BEGIN NOW The Song of Hiawatha is based on the legends and stories of END
BEGIN NOW many North American Indian tribes, but especially those of the END
BEGIN NOW Ojibway Indians of northern Michigan, Wisconsin, and Minnesota. END
BEGIN NOW They were collected by Henry Rowe Schoolcraft, the reknowned END
BEGIN NOW Schoolcraft married Jane, O-bah-bahm-wawa-ge-zhe-go-qua (The END
BEGIN NOW fur trader, and O-shau-gus-coday-way-qua (The Woman of the Green END
BEGIN NOW Prairie), who was a daughter of Waub-o-jeeg (The White Fisher), END
BEGIN NOW who was Chief of the Ojibway tribe at La Pointe, Wisconsin. END
BEGIN NOW Jane and her mother are credited with having researched, END
BEGIN NOW authenticated, and compiled much of the material Schoolcraft END
BEGIN NOW included in his Algic Researches (1839) and a revision published END
BEGIN NOW in 1856 as The Myth of Hiawatha. It was this latter revision END
BEGIN NOW that Longfellow used as the basis for The Song of Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW Longfellow began Hiawatha on June 25, 1854, he completed it END
BEGIN NOW soon as the poem was published its popularity was assured. END
BEGIN NOW However, it also was severely criticized as a plagiary of the END
BEGIN NOW Finnish epic poem Kalevala. Longfellow made no secret of the END
BEGIN NOW fact that he had used the meter of the Kalevala; but as for the END
BEGIN NOW legends, he openly gave credit to Schoolcraft in his notes to the END
BEGIN NOW I would add a personal note here. My father's roots include END
BEGIN NOW Ojibway Indians: his mother, Margaret Caroline Davenport, was a END
BEGIN NOW daughter of Susan des Carreaux, O-gee-em-a-qua (The Chief Woman), END
BEGIN NOW Finally, my mother used to rock me to sleep reading portions of END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha to me, especially: END
BEGIN NOW Wah-wah-taysee, little fire-fly, END
BEGIN NOW Little, flitting, white-fire insect END
BEGIN NOW Little, dancing, white-fire creature, END
BEGIN NOW Light me with your little candle, END
BEGIN NOW Ere upon my bed I lay me, END
BEGIN NOW Ere in sleep I close my eyelids! END
BEGIN NOW Should you ask me, whence these stories? END
BEGIN NOW Whence these legends and traditions, END
BEGIN NOW With the odors of the forest END
BEGIN NOW With the dew and damp of meadows, END
BEGIN NOW With the curling smoke of wigwams, END
BEGIN NOW With the rushing of great rivers, END
BEGIN NOW With their frequent repetitions, END
BEGIN NOW And their wild reverberations END
BEGIN NOW As of thunder in the mountains? END
BEGIN NOW I should answer, I should tell you, END
BEGIN NOW From the forests and the prairies, END
BEGIN NOW From the great lakes of the Northland, END
BEGIN NOW From the land of the Ojibways, END
BEGIN NOW From the land of the Dacotahs, END
BEGIN NOW From the mountains, moors, and fen-lands END
BEGIN NOW Where the heron, the Shuh-shuh-gah, END
BEGIN NOW Feeds among the reeds and rushes. END
BEGIN NOW I repeat them as I heard them END
BEGIN NOW From the lips of Nawadaha, END
BEGIN NOW The musician, the sweet singer. END
BEGIN NOW Should you ask where Nawadaha END
BEGIN NOW Found these songs so wild and wayward, END
BEGIN NOW Found these legends and traditions, END
BEGIN NOW I should answer, I should tell you, END
BEGIN NOW In the bird's-nests of the forest, END
BEGIN NOW In the lodges of the beaver, END
BEGIN NOW In the hoofprint of the bison, END
BEGIN NOW In the eyry of the eagle! END
BEGIN NOW All the wild-fowl sang them to him, END
BEGIN NOW In the moorlands and the fen-lands, END
BEGIN NOW In the melancholy marshes; END
BEGIN NOW Chetowaik, the plover, sang them, END
BEGIN NOW Mahng, the loon, the wild-goose, Wawa, END
BEGIN NOW The blue heron, the Shuh-shuh-gah, END
BEGIN NOW And the grouse, the Mushkodasa! END
BEGIN NOW If still further you should ask me, END
BEGIN NOW Tell us of this Nawadaha, END
BEGIN NOW I should answer your inquiries END
BEGIN NOW Straightway in such words as follow. END
BEGIN NOW In the vale of Tawasentha, END
BEGIN NOW In the green and silent valley, END
BEGIN NOW By the pleasant water-courses, END
BEGIN NOW Dwelt the singer Nawadaha. END
BEGIN NOW Round about the Indian village END
BEGIN NOW Spread the meadows and the corn-fields, END
BEGIN NOW And beyond them stood the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Stood the groves of singing pine-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Green in Summer, white in Winter, END
BEGIN NOW Ever sighing, ever singing. END
BEGIN NOW And the pleasant water-courses, END
BEGIN NOW You could trace them through the valley, END
BEGIN NOW By the rushing in the Spring-time, END
BEGIN NOW By the alders in the Summer, END
BEGIN NOW By the white fog in the Autumn, END
BEGIN NOW By the black line in the Winter; END
BEGIN NOW And beside them dwelt the singer, END
BEGIN NOW In the vale of Tawasentha, END
BEGIN NOW In the green and silent valley. END
BEGIN NOW There he sang of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Sang his wondrous birth and being, END
BEGIN NOW How he prayed and how be fasted, END
BEGIN NOW How he lived, and toiled, and suffered, END
BEGIN NOW That the tribes of men might prosper, END
BEGIN NOW That he might advance his people! END
BEGIN NOW Ye who love the haunts of Nature, END
BEGIN NOW Love the sunshine of the meadow, END
BEGIN NOW Love the shadow of the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Love the wind among the branches, END
BEGIN NOW And the rain-shower and the snow-storm, END
BEGIN NOW And the rushing of great rivers END
BEGIN NOW Through their palisades of pine-trees, END
BEGIN NOW And the thunder in the mountains, END
BEGIN NOW Whose innumerable echoes END
BEGIN NOW Flap like eagles in their eyries;-- END
BEGIN NOW Listen to these wild traditions, END
BEGIN NOW To this Song of Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Ye who love a nation's legends, END
BEGIN NOW Love the ballads of a people, END
BEGIN NOW That like voices from afar off END
BEGIN NOW Call to us to pause and listen, END
BEGIN NOW Speak in tones so plain and childlike, END
BEGIN NOW Scarcely can the ear distinguish END
BEGIN NOW Whether they are sung or spoken;-- END
BEGIN NOW Listen to this Indian Legend, END
BEGIN NOW To this Song of Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Ye whose hearts are fresh and simple, END
BEGIN NOW Who have faith in God and Nature, END
BEGIN NOW Who believe that in all ages END
BEGIN NOW Every human heart is human, END
BEGIN NOW That in even savage bosoms END
BEGIN NOW There are longings, yearnings, strivings END
BEGIN NOW For the good they comprehend not, END
BEGIN NOW That the feeble hands and helpless, END
BEGIN NOW Groping blindly in the darkness, END
BEGIN NOW Touch God's right hand in that darkness END
BEGIN NOW And are lifted up and strengthened;-- END
BEGIN NOW Listen to this simple story, END
BEGIN NOW To this Song of Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Ye, who sometimes, in your rambles END
BEGIN NOW Through the green lanes of the country, END
BEGIN NOW Where the tangled barberry-bushes END
BEGIN NOW Hang their tufts of crimson berries END
BEGIN NOW Over stone walls gray with mosses, END
BEGIN NOW Pause by some neglected graveyard, END
BEGIN NOW For a while to muse, and ponder END
BEGIN NOW On a half-effaced inscription, END
BEGIN NOW Written with little skill of song-craft, END
BEGIN NOW Homely phrases, but each letter END
BEGIN NOW Full of hope and yet of heart-break, END
BEGIN NOW Full of all the tender pathos END
BEGIN NOW Stay and read this rude inscription, END
BEGIN NOW Read this Song of Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW On the great Red Pipe-stone Quarry, END
BEGIN NOW Gitche Manito, the mighty, END
BEGIN NOW He the Master of Life, descending, END
BEGIN NOW On the red crags of the quarry END
BEGIN NOW Stood erect, and called the nations, END
BEGIN NOW Called the tribes of men together. END
BEGIN NOW From his footprints flowed a river, END
BEGIN NOW Leaped into the light of morning, END
BEGIN NOW O'er the precipice plunging downward END
BEGIN NOW Gleamed like Ishkoodah, the comet. END
BEGIN NOW And the Spirit, stooping earthward, END
BEGIN NOW With his finger on the meadow END
BEGIN NOW Traced a winding pathway for it, END
BEGIN NOW Saying to it, "Run in this way! END
BEGIN NOW From the red stone of the quarry END
BEGIN NOW With his hand he broke a fragment, END
BEGIN NOW Moulded it into a pipe-head, END
BEGIN NOW Shaped and fashioned it with figures; END
BEGIN NOW From the margin of the river END
BEGIN NOW Took a long reed for a pipe-stem, END
BEGIN NOW With its dark green leaves upon it; END
BEGIN NOW Filled the pipe with bark of willow, END
BEGIN NOW With the bark of the red willow; END
BEGIN NOW Breathed upon the neighboring forest, END
BEGIN NOW Made its great boughs chafe together, END
BEGIN NOW Till in flame they burst and kindled; END
BEGIN NOW And erect upon the mountains, END
BEGIN NOW Gitche Manito, the mighty, END
BEGIN NOW Smoked the calumet, the Peace-Pipe, END
BEGIN NOW As a signal to the nations. END
BEGIN NOW And the smoke rose slowly, slowly, END
BEGIN NOW Through the tranquil air of morning, END
BEGIN NOW First a single line of darkness, END
BEGIN NOW Then a denser, bluer vapor, END
BEGIN NOW Then a snow-white cloud unfolding, END
BEGIN NOW Like the tree-tops of the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Ever rising, rising, rising, END
BEGIN NOW Till it touched the top of heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Till it broke against the heaven, END
BEGIN NOW And rolled outward all around it. END
BEGIN NOW From the groves of Tuscaloosa, END
BEGIN NOW From the far-off Rocky Mountains, END
BEGIN NOW From the Northern lakes and rivers END
BEGIN NOW All the tribes beheld the signal, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the distant smoke ascending, END
BEGIN NOW And the Prophets of the nations END
BEGIN NOW By the signal of the Peace-Pipe, END
BEGIN NOW Bending like a wand of willow, END
BEGIN NOW Waving like a hand that beckons, END
BEGIN NOW Gitche Manito, the mighty, END
BEGIN NOW Calls the tribes of men together, END
BEGIN NOW Calls the warriors to his council! END
BEGIN NOW Down the rivers, o'er the prairies, END
BEGIN NOW Came the warriors of the nations, END
BEGIN NOW All the warriors drawn together END
BEGIN NOW By the signal of the Peace-Pipe, END
BEGIN NOW To the great Red Pipe-stone Quarry, END
BEGIN NOW And they stood there on the meadow, END
BEGIN NOW With their weapons and their war-gear, END
BEGIN NOW Painted like the leaves of Autumn, END
BEGIN NOW Painted like the sky of morning, END
BEGIN NOW Wildly glaring at each other; END
BEGIN NOW In their faces stern defiance, END
BEGIN NOW In their hearts the feuds of ages, END
BEGIN NOW The hereditary hatred, END
BEGIN NOW The ancestral thirst of vengeance. END
BEGIN NOW Gitche Manito, the mighty, END
BEGIN NOW The creator of the nations, END
BEGIN NOW Looked upon them with compassion, END
BEGIN NOW With paternal love and pity; END
BEGIN NOW Looked upon their wrath and wrangling END
BEGIN NOW But as quarrels among children, END
BEGIN NOW But as feuds and fights of children! END
BEGIN NOW Over them he stretched his right hand, END
BEGIN NOW To subdue their stubborn natures, END
BEGIN NOW To allay their thirst and fever, END
BEGIN NOW By the shadow of his right hand; END
BEGIN NOW Spake to them with voice majestic END
BEGIN NOW As the sound of far-off waters, END
BEGIN NOW Falling into deep abysses, END
BEGIN NOW Warning, chiding, spake in this wise: END
BEGIN NOW O my children! my poor children! END
BEGIN NOW Listen to the words of wisdom, END
BEGIN NOW Listen to the words of warning, END
BEGIN NOW From the lips of the Great Spirit, END
BEGIN NOW From the Master of Life, who made you! END
BEGIN NOW I have given you lands to hunt in, END
BEGIN NOW I have given you streams to fish in, END
BEGIN NOW I have given you bear and bison, END
BEGIN NOW I have given you roe and reindeer, END
BEGIN NOW I have given you brant and beaver, END
BEGIN NOW Filled the marshes full of wild-fowl, END
BEGIN NOW Filled the rivers full of fishes: END
BEGIN NOW Why then are you not contented? END
BEGIN NOW Why then will you hunt each other? END
BEGIN NOW I am weary of your quarrels, END
BEGIN NOW Weary of your wars and bloodshed, END
BEGIN NOW Weary of your prayers for vengeance, END
BEGIN NOW Of your wranglings and dissensions; END
BEGIN NOW All your strength is in your union, END
BEGIN NOW All your danger is in discord; END
BEGIN NOW Therefore be at peace henceforward, END
BEGIN NOW And as brothers live together. END
BEGIN NOW I will send a Prophet to you, END
BEGIN NOW A Deliverer of the nations, END
BEGIN NOW Who shall guide you and shall teach you, END
BEGIN NOW Who shall toil and suffer with you. END
BEGIN NOW If you listen to his counsels, END
BEGIN NOW You will multiply and prosper; END
BEGIN NOW If his warnings pass unheeded, END
BEGIN NOW You will fade away and perish! END
BEGIN NOW Bathe now in the stream before you, END
BEGIN NOW Wash the war-paint from your faces, END
BEGIN NOW Wash the blood-stains from your fingers, END
BEGIN NOW Bury your war-clubs and your weapons, END
BEGIN NOW Break the red stone from this quarry, END
BEGIN NOW Mould and make it into Peace-Pipes, END
BEGIN NOW Take the reeds that grow beside you, END
BEGIN NOW Deck them with your brightest feathers, END
BEGIN NOW Smoke the calumet together, END
BEGIN NOW And as brothers live henceforward! END
BEGIN NOW Then upon the ground the warriors END
BEGIN NOW Threw their cloaks and shirts of deer-skin, END
BEGIN NOW Threw their weapons and their war-gear, END
BEGIN NOW Leaped into the rushing river, END
BEGIN NOW Washed the war-paint from their faces. END
BEGIN NOW Clear above them flowed the water, END
BEGIN NOW Clear and limpid from the footprints END
BEGIN NOW Of the Master of Life descending; END
BEGIN NOW Dark below them flowed the water, END
BEGIN NOW Soiled and stained with streaks of crimson, END
BEGIN NOW As if blood were mingled with it! END
BEGIN NOW From the river came the warriors, END
BEGIN NOW Clean and washed from all their war-paint; END
BEGIN NOW On the banks their clubs they buried, END
BEGIN NOW Buried all their warlike weapons. END
BEGIN NOW Gitche Manito, the mighty, END
BEGIN NOW The Great Spirit, the creator, END
BEGIN NOW Smiled upon his helpless children! END
BEGIN NOW And in silence all the warriors END
BEGIN NOW Broke the red stone of the quarry, END
BEGIN NOW Smoothed and formed it into Peace-Pipes, END
BEGIN NOW Broke the long reeds by the river, END
BEGIN NOW Decked them with their brightest feathers, END
BEGIN NOW And departed each one homeward, END
BEGIN NOW While the Master of Life, ascending, END
BEGIN NOW Through the opening of cloud-curtains, END
BEGIN NOW Through the doorways of the heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Vanished from before their faces, END
BEGIN NOW In the smoke that rolled around him, END
BEGIN NOW Cried the warriors, cried the old men, END
BEGIN NOW When he came in triumph homeward END
BEGIN NOW With the sacred Belt of Wampum, END
BEGIN NOW From the regions of the North-Wind, END
BEGIN NOW From the kingdom of Wabasso, END
BEGIN NOW From the land of the White Rabbit. END
BEGIN NOW He had stolen the Belt of Wampum END
BEGIN NOW From the neck of Mishe-Mokwa, END
BEGIN NOW From the Great Bear of the mountains, END
BEGIN NOW From the terror of the nations, END
BEGIN NOW As he lay asleep and cumbrous END
BEGIN NOW On the summit of the mountains, END
BEGIN NOW Like a rock with mosses on it, END
BEGIN NOW Spotted brown and gray with mosses. END
BEGIN NOW Silently he stole upon him END
BEGIN NOW Till the red nails of the monster END
BEGIN NOW Almost touched him, almost scared him, END
BEGIN NOW Till the hot breath of his nostrils END
BEGIN NOW Warmed the hands of Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW As he drew the Belt of Wampum END
BEGIN NOW Over the round ears, that heard not, END
BEGIN NOW Over the small eyes, that saw not, END
BEGIN NOW Over the long nose and nostrils, END
BEGIN NOW The black muffle of the nostrils, END
BEGIN NOW Out of which the heavy breathing END
BEGIN NOW Warmed the hands of Mudjekeewis. END
BEGIN NOW Then he swung aloft his war-club, END
BEGIN NOW Shouted loud and long his war-cry, END
BEGIN NOW Smote the mighty Mishe-Mokwa END
BEGIN NOW In the middle of the forehead, END
BEGIN NOW Right between the eyes he smote him. END
BEGIN NOW With the heavy blow bewildered, END
BEGIN NOW Rose the Great Bear of the mountains; END
BEGIN NOW But his knees beneath him trembled, END
BEGIN NOW And he whimpered like a woman, END
BEGIN NOW As he reeled and staggered forward, END
BEGIN NOW As he sat upon his haunches; END
BEGIN NOW And the mighty Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW Standing fearlessly before him, END
BEGIN NOW Taunted him in loud derision, END
BEGIN NOW Spake disdainfully in this wise: END
BEGIN NOW Hark you, Bear! you are a coward; END
BEGIN NOW And no Brave, as you pretended; END
BEGIN NOW Else you would not cry and whimper END
BEGIN NOW Like a miserable woman! END
BEGIN NOW Bear! you know our tribes are hostile, END
BEGIN NOW Long have been at war together; END
BEGIN NOW Now you find that we are strongest, END
BEGIN NOW You go sneaking in the forest, END
BEGIN NOW You go hiding in the mountains! END
BEGIN NOW Had you conquered me in battle END
BEGIN NOW Not a groan would I have uttered; END
BEGIN NOW But you, Bear! sit here and whimper, END
BEGIN NOW And disgrace your tribe by crying, END
BEGIN NOW Like a wretched Shaugodaya, END
BEGIN NOW Like a cowardly old woman! END
BEGIN NOW Then again he raised his war-club, END
BEGIN NOW Smote again the Mishe-Mokwa END
BEGIN NOW In the middle of his forehead, END
BEGIN NOW Broke his skull, as ice is broken END
BEGIN NOW When one goes to fish in Winter. END
BEGIN NOW Thus was slain the Mishe-Mokwa, END
BEGIN NOW He the Great Bear of the mountains, END
BEGIN NOW He the terror of the nations. END
BEGIN NOW With a shout exclaimed the people, END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth he shall be the West-Wind, END
BEGIN NOW And hereafter and forever END
BEGIN NOW Shall he hold supreme dominion END
BEGIN NOW Over all the winds of heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Call him no more Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW Thus was Mudjekeewis chosen END
BEGIN NOW For himself he kept the West-Wind, END
BEGIN NOW Gave the others to his children; END
BEGIN NOW Unto Wabun gave the East-Wind, END
BEGIN NOW And the North-Wind, wild and cruel, END
BEGIN NOW To the fierce Kabibonokka. END
BEGIN NOW Young and beautiful was Wabun; END
BEGIN NOW He it was who brought the morning, END
BEGIN NOW He it was whose silver arrows END
BEGIN NOW Chased the dark o'er hill and valley; END
BEGIN NOW He it was whose cheeks were painted END
BEGIN NOW With the brightest streaks of crimson, END
BEGIN NOW And whose voice awoke the village, END
BEGIN NOW Called the deer, and called the hunter. END
BEGIN NOW Though the birds sang gayly to him, END
BEGIN NOW Though the wild-flowers of the meadow END
BEGIN NOW Filled the air with odors for him; END
BEGIN NOW Though the forests and the rivers END
BEGIN NOW Sang and shouted at his coming, END
BEGIN NOW Still his heart was sad within him, END
BEGIN NOW For he was alone in heaven. END
BEGIN NOW But one morning, gazing earthward, END
BEGIN NOW While the village still was sleeping, END
BEGIN NOW And the fog lay on the river, END
BEGIN NOW Like a ghost, that goes at sunrise, END
BEGIN NOW He beheld a maiden walking END
BEGIN NOW All alone upon a meadow, END
BEGIN NOW Gathering water-flags and rushes END
BEGIN NOW By a river in the meadow. END
BEGIN NOW Every morning, gazing earthward, END
BEGIN NOW Still the first thing he beheld there END
BEGIN NOW Was her blue eyes looking at him, END
BEGIN NOW Two blue lakes among the rushes. END
BEGIN NOW And he loved the lonely maiden, END
BEGIN NOW Who thus waited for his coming; END
BEGIN NOW For they both were solitary, END
BEGIN NOW She on earth and he in heaven. END
BEGIN NOW And he wooed her with caresses, END
BEGIN NOW Wooed her with his smile of sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW With his flattering words he wooed her, END
BEGIN NOW With his sighing and his singing, END
BEGIN NOW Gentlest whispers in the branches, END
BEGIN NOW Softest music, sweetest odors, END
BEGIN NOW Till he drew her to his bosom, END
BEGIN NOW Folded in his robes of crimson, END
BEGIN NOW Till into a star he changed her, END
BEGIN NOW Trembling still upon his bosom; END
BEGIN NOW And forever in the heavens END
BEGIN NOW They are seen together walking, END
BEGIN NOW But the fierce Kabibonokka END
BEGIN NOW Had his dwelling among icebergs, END
BEGIN NOW In the everlasting snow-drifts, END
BEGIN NOW In the kingdom of Wabasso, END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the White Rabbit. END
BEGIN NOW He it was whose hand in Autumn END
BEGIN NOW Painted all the trees with scarlet, END
BEGIN NOW Stained the leaves with red and yellow; END
BEGIN NOW He it was who sent the snow-flake, END
BEGIN NOW Sifting, hissing through the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Froze the ponds, the lakes, the rivers, END
BEGIN NOW Drove the loon and sea-gull southward, END
BEGIN NOW Drove the cormorant and curlew END
BEGIN NOW To their nests of sedge and sea-tang END
BEGIN NOW In the realms of Shawondasee. END
BEGIN NOW Once the fierce Kabibonokka END
BEGIN NOW Issued from his lodge of snow-drifts END
BEGIN NOW From his home among the icebergs, END
BEGIN NOW And his hair, with snow besprinkled, END
BEGIN NOW Streamed behind him like a river, END
BEGIN NOW Like a black and wintry river, END
BEGIN NOW As he howled and hurried southward, END
BEGIN NOW Over frozen lakes and moorlands. END
BEGIN NOW There among the reeds and rushes END
BEGIN NOW Found he Shingebis, the diver, END
BEGIN NOW Trailing strings of fish behind him, END
BEGIN NOW O'er the frozen fens and moorlands, END
BEGIN NOW Lingering still among the moorlands, END
BEGIN NOW Though his tribe had long departed END
BEGIN NOW To the land of Shawondasee. END
BEGIN NOW Cried the fierce Kabibonokka, END
BEGIN NOW Who is this that dares to brave me? END
BEGIN NOW Dares to stay in my dominions, END
BEGIN NOW When the Wawa has departed, END
BEGIN NOW When the wild-goose has gone southward, END
BEGIN NOW And the heron, the Shuh-shuh-gah, END
BEGIN NOW Long ago departed southward? END
BEGIN NOW I will go into his wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW I will put his smouldering fire out! END
BEGIN NOW And at night Kabibonokka, END
BEGIN NOW To the lodge came wild and wailing, END
BEGIN NOW Heaped the snow in drifts about it, END
BEGIN NOW Shouted down into the smoke-flue, END
BEGIN NOW Shook the lodge-poles in his fury, END
BEGIN NOW Flapped the curtain of the door-way. END
BEGIN NOW Shingebis, the diver, feared not, END
BEGIN NOW Shingebis, the diver, cared not; END
BEGIN NOW Four great logs had he for firewood, END
BEGIN NOW One for each moon of the winter, END
BEGIN NOW And for food the fishes served him. END
BEGIN NOW By his blazing fire he sat there, END
BEGIN NOW Warm and merry, eating, laughing, END
BEGIN NOW You are but my fellow-mortal! END
BEGIN NOW Then Kabibonokka entered, END
BEGIN NOW And though Shingebis, the diver, END
BEGIN NOW Felt his presence by the coldness, END
BEGIN NOW Felt his icy breath upon him, END
BEGIN NOW Still he did not cease his singing, END
BEGIN NOW Still he did not leave his laughing, END
BEGIN NOW Only turned the log a little, END
BEGIN NOW Only made the fire burn brighter, END
BEGIN NOW Made the sparks fly up the smoke-flue. END
BEGIN NOW From Kabibonokka's forehead, END
BEGIN NOW From his snow-besprinkled tresses, END
BEGIN NOW Drops of sweat fell fast and heavy, END
BEGIN NOW Making dints upon the ashes, END
BEGIN NOW As along the eaves of lodges, END
BEGIN NOW As from drooping boughs of hemlock, END
BEGIN NOW Drips the melting snow in spring-time, END
BEGIN NOW Making hollows in the snow-drifts. END
BEGIN NOW Till at last he rose defeated, END
BEGIN NOW Could not bear the heat and laughter, END
BEGIN NOW Could not bear the merry singing, END
BEGIN NOW But rushed headlong through the door-way, END
BEGIN NOW Stamped upon the crusted snow-drifts, END
BEGIN NOW Stamped upon the lakes and rivers, END
BEGIN NOW Made the snow upon them harder, END
BEGIN NOW Made the ice upon them thicker, END
BEGIN NOW Challenged Shingebis, the diver, END
BEGIN NOW To come forth and wrestle with him, END
BEGIN NOW To come forth and wrestle naked END
BEGIN NOW On the frozen fens and moorlands. END
BEGIN NOW Forth went Shingebis, the diver, END
BEGIN NOW Wrestled all night with the North-Wind, END
BEGIN NOW Wrestled naked on the moorlands END
BEGIN NOW With the fierce Kabibonokka, END
BEGIN NOW Till his panting breath grew fainter, END
BEGIN NOW Till his frozen grasp grew feebler, END
BEGIN NOW Till he reeled and staggered backward, END
BEGIN NOW And retreated, baffled, beaten, END
BEGIN NOW To the kingdom of Wabasso, END
BEGIN NOW To the land of the White Rabbit, END
BEGIN NOW Hearing still the gusty laughter, END
BEGIN NOW Hearing Shingebis, the diver, END
BEGIN NOW You are but my fellow-mortal! END
BEGIN NOW Shawondasee, fat and lazy, END
BEGIN NOW Had his dwelling far to southward, END
BEGIN NOW In the drowsy, dreamy sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW In the never-ending Summer. END
BEGIN NOW He it was who sent the wood-birds, END
BEGIN NOW Sent the robin, the Opechee, END
BEGIN NOW Sent the bluebird, the Owaissa, END
BEGIN NOW Sent the Shawshaw, sent the swallow, END
BEGIN NOW Sent the wild-goose, Wawa, northward, END
BEGIN NOW Sent the melons and tobacco, END
BEGIN NOW And the grapes in purple clusters. END
BEGIN NOW From his pipe the smoke ascending END
BEGIN NOW Filled the sky with haze and vapor, END
BEGIN NOW Filled the air with dreamy softness, END
BEGIN NOW Gave a twinkle to the water, END
BEGIN NOW Touched the rugged hills with smoothness, END
BEGIN NOW Brought the tender Indian Summer END
BEGIN NOW To the melancholy north-land, END
BEGIN NOW In the dreary Moon of Snow-shoes. END
BEGIN NOW Listless, careless Shawondasee! END
BEGIN NOW In his life he had one shadow, END
BEGIN NOW In his heart one sorrow had he. END
BEGIN NOW Once, as he was gazing northward, END
BEGIN NOW Far away upon a prairie END
BEGIN NOW He beheld a maiden standing, END
BEGIN NOW Saw a tall and slender maiden END
BEGIN NOW All alone upon a prairie; END
BEGIN NOW Brightest green were all her garments, END
BEGIN NOW And her hair was like the sunshine. END
BEGIN NOW Day by day he gazed upon her, END
BEGIN NOW Day by day he sighed with passion, END
BEGIN NOW Day by day his heart within him END
BEGIN NOW Grew more hot with love and longing END
BEGIN NOW For the maid with yellow tresses. END
BEGIN NOW But he was too fat and lazy END
BEGIN NOW To bestir himself and woo her. END
BEGIN NOW Yes, too indolent and easy END
BEGIN NOW To pursue her and persuade her; END
BEGIN NOW So he only gazed upon her, END
BEGIN NOW Only sat and sighed with passion END
BEGIN NOW For the maiden of the prairie. END
BEGIN NOW Till one morning, looking northward, END
BEGIN NOW He beheld her yellow tresses END
BEGIN NOW Changed and covered o'er with whiteness, END
BEGIN NOW Covered as with whitest snow-flakes. END
BEGIN NOW Ah! my brother from the North-land, END
BEGIN NOW From the kingdom of Wabasso, END
BEGIN NOW From the land of the White Rabbit! END
BEGIN NOW You have stolen the maiden from me, END
BEGIN NOW You have laid your hand upon her, END
BEGIN NOW You have wooed and won my maiden, END
BEGIN NOW With your stories of the North-land! END
BEGIN NOW Thus the wretched Shawondasee END
BEGIN NOW Breathed into the air his sorrow; END
BEGIN NOW And the South-Wind o'er the prairie END
BEGIN NOW Wandered warm with sighs of passion, END
BEGIN NOW With the sighs of Shawondasee, END
BEGIN NOW Till the air seemed full of snow-flakes, END
BEGIN NOW Full of thistle-down the prairie, END
BEGIN NOW And the maid with hair like sunshine END
BEGIN NOW Vanished from his sight forever; END
BEGIN NOW Never more did Shawondasee END
BEGIN NOW See the maid with yellow tresses! END
BEGIN NOW Poor, deluded Shawondasee! END
BEGIN NOW 'T was no woman that you gazed at, END
BEGIN NOW 'T was no maiden that you sighed for, END
BEGIN NOW 'T was the prairie dandelion END
BEGIN NOW That through all the dreamy Summer END
BEGIN NOW You had gazed at with such longing, END
BEGIN NOW You had sighed for with such passion, END
BEGIN NOW And had puffed away forever, END
BEGIN NOW Blown into the air with sighing. END
BEGIN NOW Ah! deluded Shawondasee! END
BEGIN NOW Thus the Four Winds were divided END
BEGIN NOW Thus the sons of Mudjekeewis END
BEGIN NOW Had their stations in the heavens, END
BEGIN NOW At the corners of the heavens; END
BEGIN NOW For himself the West-Wind only END
BEGIN NOW Kept the mighty Mudjekeewis. END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha's Childhood END
BEGIN NOW Downward through the evening twilight, END
BEGIN NOW In the days that are forgotten, END
BEGIN NOW In the unremembered ages, END
BEGIN NOW From the full moon fell Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Fell the beautiful Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW She a wife, but not a mother. END
BEGIN NOW She was sporting with her women, END
BEGIN NOW Swinging in a swing of grape-vines, END
BEGIN NOW When her rival the rejected, END
BEGIN NOW Full of jealousy and hatred, END
BEGIN NOW Cut the leafy swing asunder, END
BEGIN NOW Cut in twain the twisted grape-vines, END
BEGIN NOW And Nokomis fell affrighted END
BEGIN NOW Downward through the evening twilight, END
BEGIN NOW On the Muskoday, the meadow, END
BEGIN NOW On the prairie full of blossoms. END
BEGIN NOW See! a star falls!" said the people; END
BEGIN NOW From the sky a star is falling! END
BEGIN NOW There among the ferns and mosses, END
BEGIN NOW There among the prairie lilies, END
BEGIN NOW On the Muskoday, the meadow, END
BEGIN NOW In the moonlight and the starlight, END
BEGIN NOW Fair Nokomis bore a daughter. END
BEGIN NOW And she called her name Wenonah, END
BEGIN NOW As the first-born of her daughters. END
BEGIN NOW And the daughter of Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Grew up like the prairie lilies, END
BEGIN NOW Grew a tall and slender maiden, END
BEGIN NOW With the beauty of the moonlight, END
BEGIN NOW With the beauty of the starlight. END
BEGIN NOW And Nokomis warned her often, END
BEGIN NOW Saying oft, and oft repeating, END
BEGIN NOW Oh, beware of Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW Listen not to what he tells you; END
BEGIN NOW Lie not down upon the meadow, END
BEGIN NOW Stoop not down among the lilies, END
BEGIN NOW Lest the West-Wind come and harm you! END
BEGIN NOW But she heeded not the warning, END
BEGIN NOW Heeded not those words of wisdom, END
BEGIN NOW And the West-Wind came at evening, END
BEGIN NOW Walking lightly o'er the prairie, END
BEGIN NOW Whispering to the leaves and blossoms, END
BEGIN NOW Bending low the flowers and grasses, END
BEGIN NOW Found the beautiful Wenonah, END
BEGIN NOW Lying there among the lilies, END
BEGIN NOW Wooed her with his words of sweetness, END
BEGIN NOW Wooed her with his soft caresses, END
BEGIN NOW Till she bore a son in sorrow, END
BEGIN NOW Bore a son of love and sorrow. END
BEGIN NOW Thus was born my Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Thus was born the child of wonder; END
BEGIN NOW But the daughter of Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha's gentle mother, END
BEGIN NOW In her anguish died deserted END
BEGIN NOW By the West-Wind, false and faithless, END
BEGIN NOW By the heartless Mudjekeewis. END
BEGIN NOW For her daughter long and loudly END
BEGIN NOW Wailed and wept the sad Nokomis; END
BEGIN NOW Oh that I were dead!" she murmured, END
BEGIN NOW Oh that I were dead, as thou art! END
BEGIN NOW No more work, and no more weeping, END
BEGIN NOW By the shores of Gitche Gumee, END
BEGIN NOW By the shining Big-Sea-Water, END
BEGIN NOW Stood the wigwam of Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Dark behind it rose the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Rose the black and gloomy pine-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Rose the firs with cones upon them; END
BEGIN NOW Bright before it beat the water, END
BEGIN NOW Beat the clear and sunny water, END
BEGIN NOW Beat the shining Big-Sea-Water. END
BEGIN NOW There the wrinkled old Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Nursed the little Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Rocked him in his linden cradle, END
BEGIN NOW Bedded soft in moss and rushes, END
BEGIN NOW Safely bound with reindeer sinews; END
BEGIN NOW Stilled his fretful wail by saying, END
BEGIN NOW Hush! the Naked Bear will hear thee! END
BEGIN NOW Lulled him into slumber, singing, END
BEGIN NOW Ewa-yea! my little owlet! END
BEGIN NOW Who is this, that lights the wigwam? END
BEGIN NOW With his great eyes lights the wigwam? END
BEGIN NOW Ewa-yea! my little owlet! END
BEGIN NOW Many things Nokomis taught him END
BEGIN NOW Of the stars that shine in heaven; END
BEGIN NOW Showed him Ishkoodah, the comet, END
BEGIN NOW Ishkoodah, with fiery tresses; END
BEGIN NOW Showed the Death-Dance of the spirits, END
BEGIN NOW Warriors with their plumes and war-clubs, END
BEGIN NOW Flaring far away to northward END
BEGIN NOW In the frosty nights of Winter; END
BEGIN NOW Showed the broad white road in heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Pathway of the ghosts, the shadows, END
BEGIN NOW Running straight across the heavens, END
BEGIN NOW Crowded with the ghosts, the shadows. END
BEGIN NOW At the door on summer evenings END
BEGIN NOW Sat the little Hiawatha; END
BEGIN NOW Heard the whispering of the pine-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the lapping of the waters, END
BEGIN NOW Sounds of music, words of wonder; END
BEGIN NOW Minne-wawa! said the Pine-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Mudway-aushka! said the water. END
BEGIN NOW Saw the fire-fly, Wah-wah-taysee, END
BEGIN NOW Flitting through the dusk of evening, END
BEGIN NOW With the twinkle of its candle END
BEGIN NOW Lighting up the brakes and bushes, END
BEGIN NOW And he sang the song of children, END
BEGIN NOW Sang the song Nokomis taught him: END
BEGIN NOW Wah-wah-taysee, little fire-fly, END
BEGIN NOW Little, flitting, white-fire insect, END
BEGIN NOW Little, dancing, white-fire creature, END
BEGIN NOW Light me with your little candle, END
BEGIN NOW Ere upon my bed I lay me, END
BEGIN NOW Ere in sleep I close my eyelids! END
BEGIN NOW Saw the moon rise from the water END
BEGIN NOW Rippling, rounding from the water, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the flecks and shadows on it, END
BEGIN NOW Whispered, "What is that, Nokomis? END
BEGIN NOW And the good Nokomis answered: END
BEGIN NOW Once a warrior, very angry, END
BEGIN NOW Seized his grandmother, and threw her END
BEGIN NOW Up into the sky at midnight; END
BEGIN NOW Right against the moon he threw her; END
BEGIN NOW 'T is her body that you see there. END
BEGIN NOW Saw the rainbow in the heaven, END
BEGIN NOW In the eastern sky, the rainbow, END
BEGIN NOW Whispered, "What is that, Nokomis? END
BEGIN NOW And the good Nokomis answered: END
BEGIN NOW 'T is the heaven of flowers you see there; END
BEGIN NOW All the wild-flowers of the forest, END
BEGIN NOW All the lilies of the prairie, END
BEGIN NOW When on earth they fade and perish, END
BEGIN NOW Blossom in that heaven above us. END
BEGIN NOW When he heard the owls at midnight, END
BEGIN NOW Hooting, laughing in the forest, END
BEGIN NOW What is that?" he cried in terror, END
BEGIN NOW What is that," he said, Nokomis? END
BEGIN NOW And the good Nokomis answered: END
BEGIN NOW That is but the owl and owlet, END
BEGIN NOW Talking in their native language, END
BEGIN NOW Talking, scolding at each other. END
BEGIN NOW Then the little Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Learned of every bird its language, END
BEGIN NOW Learned their names and all their secrets, END
BEGIN NOW How they built their nests in Summer, END
BEGIN NOW Where they hid themselves in Winter, END
BEGIN NOW Talked with them whene'er he met them, END
BEGIN NOW Called them "Hiawatha's Chickens. END
BEGIN NOW Of all beasts he learned the language, END
BEGIN NOW Learned their names and all their secrets, END
BEGIN NOW How the beavers built their lodges, END
BEGIN NOW Where the squirrels hid their acorns, END
BEGIN NOW How the reindeer ran so swiftly, END
BEGIN NOW Why the rabbit was so timid, END
BEGIN NOW Talked with them whene'er he met them, END
BEGIN NOW Called them "Hiawatha's Brothers. END
BEGIN NOW Then Iagoo, the great boaster, END
BEGIN NOW He the marvellous story-teller, END
BEGIN NOW He the traveller and the talker, END
BEGIN NOW He the friend of old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW From a branch of ash he made it, END
BEGIN NOW From an oak-bough made the arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Tipped with flint, and winged with feathers, END
BEGIN NOW And the cord he made of deer-skin. END
BEGIN NOW Then he said to Hiawatha: END
BEGIN NOW Go, my son, into the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Where the red deer herd together, END
BEGIN NOW Kill for us a famous roebuck, END
BEGIN NOW Kill for us a deer with antlers! END
BEGIN NOW Forth into the forest straightway END
BEGIN NOW All alone walked Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Proudly, with his bow and arrows; END
BEGIN NOW And the birds sang round him, o'er him, END
BEGIN NOW Do not shoot us, Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Sang the robin, the Opechee, END
BEGIN NOW Sang the bluebird, the Owaissa, END
BEGIN NOW Do not shoot us, Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Up the oak-tree, close beside him, END
BEGIN NOW Sprang the squirrel, Adjidaumo, END
BEGIN NOW In and out among the branches, END
BEGIN NOW Coughed and chattered from the oak-tree, END
BEGIN NOW Laughed, and said between his laughing, END
BEGIN NOW Do not shoot me, Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW And the rabbit from his pathway END
BEGIN NOW Leaped aside, and at a distance END
BEGIN NOW Sat erect upon his haunches, END
BEGIN NOW Half in fear and half in frolic, END
BEGIN NOW Saying to the little hunter, END
BEGIN NOW Do not shoot me, Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW But he heeded not, nor heard them, END
BEGIN NOW For his thoughts were with the red deer; END
BEGIN NOW On their tracks his eyes were fastened, END
BEGIN NOW Leading downward to the river, END
BEGIN NOW To the ford across the river, END
BEGIN NOW And as one in slumber walked he. END
BEGIN NOW Hidden in the alder-bushes, END
BEGIN NOW There he waited till the deer came, END
BEGIN NOW Till he saw two antlers lifted, END
BEGIN NOW Saw two eyes look from the thicket, END
BEGIN NOW Saw two nostrils point to windward, END
BEGIN NOW And a deer came down the pathway, END
BEGIN NOW Flecked with leafy light and shadow. END
BEGIN NOW And his heart within him fluttered, END
BEGIN NOW Trembled like the leaves above him, END
BEGIN NOW Like the birch-leaf palpitated, END
BEGIN NOW As the deer came down the pathway. END
BEGIN NOW Then, upon one knee uprising, END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha aimed an arrow; END
BEGIN NOW Scarce a twig moved with his motion, END
BEGIN NOW Scarce a leaf was stirred or rustled, END
BEGIN NOW But the wary roebuck started, END
BEGIN NOW Stamped with all his hoofs together, END
BEGIN NOW Listened with one foot uplifted, END
BEGIN NOW Leaped as if to meet the arrow; END
BEGIN NOW Ah! the singing, fatal arrow, END
BEGIN NOW Like a wasp it buzzed and stung him! END
BEGIN NOW Dead he lay there in the forest, END
BEGIN NOW By the ford across the river; END
BEGIN NOW Beat his timid heart no longer, END
BEGIN NOW But the heart of Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Throbbed and shouted and exulted, END
BEGIN NOW As he bore the red deer homeward, END
BEGIN NOW Hailed his coming with applauses. END
BEGIN NOW From the red deer's hide Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Made a cloak for Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW From the red deer's flesh Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Made a banquet to his honor. END
BEGIN NOW All the village came and feasted, END
BEGIN NOW All the guests praised Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Called him Strong-Heart, Soan-ge-taha! END
BEGIN NOW Called him Loon-Heart, Mahn-go-taysee! END
BEGIN NOW Out of childhood into manhood END
BEGIN NOW Now had grown my Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Skilled in all the craft of hunters, END
BEGIN NOW Learned in all the lore of old men, END
BEGIN NOW In all youthful sports and pastimes, END
BEGIN NOW In all manly arts and labors. END
BEGIN NOW Swift of foot was Hiawatha; END
BEGIN NOW He could shoot an arrow from him, END
BEGIN NOW And run forward with such fleetness, END
BEGIN NOW That the arrow fell behind him! END
BEGIN NOW He could shoot ten arrows upward, END
BEGIN NOW Shoot them with such strength and swiftness, END
BEGIN NOW That the tenth had left the bow-string END
BEGIN NOW Ere the first to earth had fallen! END
BEGIN NOW He had mittens, Minjekahwun, END
BEGIN NOW Magic mittens made of deer-skin; END
BEGIN NOW When upon his hands he wore them, END
BEGIN NOW He could smite the rocks asunder, END
BEGIN NOW He could grind them into powder. END
BEGIN NOW He had moccasins enchanted, END
BEGIN NOW Magic moccasins of deer-skin; END
BEGIN NOW When he bound them round his ankles, END
BEGIN NOW When upon his feet he tied them, END
BEGIN NOW At each stride a mile he measured! END
BEGIN NOW Much he questioned old Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Of his father Mudjekeewis; END
BEGIN NOW Learned from her the fatal secret END
BEGIN NOW Of the beauty of his mother, END
BEGIN NOW Of the falsehood of his father; END
BEGIN NOW And his heart was hot within him, END
BEGIN NOW Like a living coal his heart was. END
BEGIN NOW Then he said to old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW I will go to Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW See how fares it with my father, END
BEGIN NOW At the doorways of the West-Wind, END
BEGIN NOW At the portals of the Sunset! END
BEGIN NOW From his lodge went Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Dressed for travel, armed for hunting; END
BEGIN NOW Dressed in deer-skin shirt and leggings, END
BEGIN NOW Richly wrought with quills and wampum; END
BEGIN NOW On his head his eagle-feathers, END
BEGIN NOW Round his waist his belt of wampum, END
BEGIN NOW In his hand his bow of ash-wood, END
BEGIN NOW Strung with sinews of the reindeer; END
BEGIN NOW In his quiver oaken arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Tipped with jasper, winged with feathers; END
BEGIN NOW With his mittens, Minjekahwun, END
BEGIN NOW With his moccasins enchanted. END
BEGIN NOW Warning said the old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Go not forth, O Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW To the kingdom of the West-Wind, END
BEGIN NOW To the realms of Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW Lest he harm you with his magic, END
BEGIN NOW Lest he kill you with his cunning! END
BEGIN NOW But the fearless Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Heeded not her woman's warning; END
BEGIN NOW Forth he strode into the forest, END
BEGIN NOW At each stride a mile he measured; END
BEGIN NOW Lurid seemed the sky above him, END
BEGIN NOW Lurid seemed the earth beneath him, END
BEGIN NOW Hot and close the air around him, END
BEGIN NOW Filled with smoke and fiery vapors, END
BEGIN NOW As of burning woods and prairies, END
BEGIN NOW For his heart was hot within him, END
BEGIN NOW Like a living coal his heart was. END
BEGIN NOW So he journeyed westward, westward, END
BEGIN NOW Left the fleetest deer behind him, END
BEGIN NOW Left the antelope and bison; END
BEGIN NOW Crossed the rushing Esconaba, END
BEGIN NOW Crossed the mighty Mississippi, END
BEGIN NOW Passed the land of Crows and Foxes, END
BEGIN NOW Passed the dwellings of the Blackfeet, END
BEGIN NOW Came unto the Rocky Mountains, END
BEGIN NOW To the kingdom of the West-Wind, END
BEGIN NOW Where upon the gusty summits END
BEGIN NOW Sat the ancient Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW Ruler of the winds of heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Filled with awe was Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW At the aspect of his father. END
BEGIN NOW On the air about him wildly END
BEGIN NOW Tossed and streamed his cloudy tresses, END
BEGIN NOW Gleamed like drifting snow his tresses, END
BEGIN NOW Glared like Ishkoodah, the comet, END
BEGIN NOW Like the star with fiery tresses. END
BEGIN NOW Filled with joy was Mudjekeewis END
BEGIN NOW When he looked on Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Saw his youth rise up before him END
BEGIN NOW In the face of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the beauty of Wenonah END
BEGIN NOW From the grave rise up before him. END
BEGIN NOW Welcome! said he, Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW To the kingdom of the West-Wind END
BEGIN NOW Long have I been waiting for you END
BEGIN NOW Youth is lovely, age is lonely, END
BEGIN NOW Youth is fiery, age is frosty; END
BEGIN NOW You bring back the days departed, END
BEGIN NOW You bring back my youth of passion, END
BEGIN NOW And the beautiful Wenonah! END
BEGIN NOW Many days they talked together, END
BEGIN NOW Questioned, listened, waited, answered; END
BEGIN NOW Much the mighty Mudjekeewis END
BEGIN NOW Boasted of his ancient prowess, END
BEGIN NOW Of his perilous adventures, END
BEGIN NOW His indomitable courage, END
BEGIN NOW His invulnerable body. END
BEGIN NOW Listening to his father's boasting; END
BEGIN NOW With a smile he sat and listened, END
BEGIN NOW Uttered neither threat nor menace, END
BEGIN NOW Neither word nor look betrayed him, END
BEGIN NOW But his heart was hot within him, END
BEGIN NOW Like a living coal his heart was. END
BEGIN NOW Then he said, "O Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW Is there nothing that can harm you? END
BEGIN NOW Nothing that you are afraid of? END
BEGIN NOW And the mighty Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW Grand and gracious in his boasting, END
BEGIN NOW Answered, saying, "There is nothing, END
BEGIN NOW Nothing but the black rock yonder, END
BEGIN NOW Nothing but the fatal Wawbeek! END
BEGIN NOW And he looked at Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW With a wise look and benignant, END
BEGIN NOW With a countenance paternal, END
BEGIN NOW Looked with pride upon the beauty END
BEGIN NOW Of his tall and graceful figure, END
BEGIN NOW Is there anything can harm you? END
BEGIN NOW Anything you are afraid of? END
BEGIN NOW But the wary Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Paused awhile, as if uncertain, END
BEGIN NOW Held his peace, as if resolving, END
BEGIN NOW And then answered, "There is nothing, END
BEGIN NOW Nothing but the bulrush yonder, END
BEGIN NOW Nothing but the great Apukwa! END
BEGIN NOW And as Mudjekeewis, rising, END
BEGIN NOW Stretched his hand to pluck the bulrush, END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha cried in terror, END
BEGIN NOW Cried in well-dissembled terror, END
BEGIN NOW Kago! kago! do not touch it! END
BEGIN NOW Ah, kaween!" said Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW No indeed, I will not touch it! END
BEGIN NOW Then they talked of other matters; END
BEGIN NOW First of Hiawatha's brothers, END
BEGIN NOW Then of Hiawatha's mother, END
BEGIN NOW Of the beautiful Wenonah, END
BEGIN NOW Of her birth upon the meadow, END
BEGIN NOW Of her death, as old Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Had remembered and related. END
BEGIN NOW And he cried, "O Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW It was you who killed Wenonah, END
BEGIN NOW Took her young life and her beauty, END
BEGIN NOW Trampled it beneath your footsteps; END
BEGIN NOW You confess it! you confess it! END
BEGIN NOW And the mighty Mudjekeewis END
BEGIN NOW Tossed upon the wind his tresses, END
BEGIN NOW Bowed his hoary head in anguish, END
BEGIN NOW With a silent nod assented. END
BEGIN NOW Then up started Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW And with threatening look and gesture END
BEGIN NOW Laid his hand upon the black rock, END
BEGIN NOW On the fatal Wawbeek laid it, END
BEGIN NOW With his mittens, Minjekahwun, END
BEGIN NOW Rent the jutting crag asunder, END
BEGIN NOW Smote and crushed it into fragments, END
BEGIN NOW Hurled them madly at his father, END
BEGIN NOW The remorseful Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW For his heart was hot within him, END
BEGIN NOW Like a living coal his heart was. END
BEGIN NOW But the ruler of the West-Wind END
BEGIN NOW Blew the fragments backward from him, END
BEGIN NOW With the breathing of his nostrils, END
BEGIN NOW With the tempest of his anger, END
BEGIN NOW Blew them back at his assailant; END
BEGIN NOW Seized the bulrush, the Apukwa, END
BEGIN NOW Dragged it with its roots and fibres END
BEGIN NOW From the margin of the meadow, END
BEGIN NOW From its ooze the giant bulrush; END
BEGIN NOW Long and loud laughed Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Then began the deadly conflict, END
BEGIN NOW Hand to hand among the mountains; END
BEGIN NOW From his eyry screamed the eagle, END
BEGIN NOW The Keneu, the great war-eagle, END
BEGIN NOW Sat upon the crags around them, END
BEGIN NOW Wheeling flapped his wings above them. END
BEGIN NOW Like a tall tree in the tempest END
BEGIN NOW Bent and lashed the giant bulrush; END
BEGIN NOW And in masses huge and heavy END
BEGIN NOW Crashing fell the fatal Wawbeek; END
BEGIN NOW Till the earth shook with the tumult END
BEGIN NOW And confusion of the battle, END
BEGIN NOW And the air was full of shoutings, END
BEGIN NOW And the thunder of the mountains, END
BEGIN NOW Starting, answered, Baim-wawa! END
BEGIN NOW Back retreated Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW Rushing westward o'er the mountains, END
BEGIN NOW Stumbling westward down the mountains, END
BEGIN NOW Three whole days retreated fighting, END
BEGIN NOW Still pursued by Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW To the doorways of the West-Wind, END
BEGIN NOW To the portals of the Sunset, END
BEGIN NOW To the earth's remotest border, END
BEGIN NOW Where into the empty spaces END
BEGIN NOW Sinks the sun, as a flamingo END
BEGIN NOW Drops into her nest at nightfall END
BEGIN NOW In the melancholy marshes. END
BEGIN NOW Hold! at length cried Mudjekeewis, END
BEGIN NOW Hold, my son, my Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW 'T is impossible to kill me, END
BEGIN NOW For you cannot kill the immortal END
BEGIN NOW I have put you to this trial, END
BEGIN NOW But to know and prove your courage; END
BEGIN NOW Now receive the prize of valor! END
BEGIN NOW Go back to your home and people, END
BEGIN NOW Live among them, toil among them, END
BEGIN NOW Cleanse the earth from all that harms it, END
BEGIN NOW Clear the fishing-grounds and rivers, END
BEGIN NOW Slay all monsters and magicians, END
BEGIN NOW All the Wendigoes, the giants, END
BEGIN NOW All the serpents, the Kenabeeks, END
BEGIN NOW As I slew the Mishe-Mokwa, END
BEGIN NOW Slew the Great Bear of the mountains. END
BEGIN NOW And at last when Death draws near you, END
BEGIN NOW When the awful eyes of Pauguk END
BEGIN NOW Glare upon you in the darkness, END
BEGIN NOW I will share my kingdom with you, END
BEGIN NOW Ruler shall you be thenceforward END
BEGIN NOW Of the home-wind, the Keewaydin. END
BEGIN NOW Thus was fought that famous battle END
BEGIN NOW In the dreadful days of Shah-shah, END
BEGIN NOW In the days long since departed, END
BEGIN NOW In the kingdom of the West-Wind. END
BEGIN NOW Still the hunter sees its traces END
BEGIN NOW Scattered far o'er hill and valley; END
BEGIN NOW Sees the giant bulrush growing END
BEGIN NOW By the ponds and water-courses, END
BEGIN NOW Sees the masses of the Wawbeek END
BEGIN NOW Lying still in every valley. END
BEGIN NOW Homeward now went Hiawatha; END
BEGIN NOW Pleasant was the landscape round him, END
BEGIN NOW Pleasant was the air above him, END
BEGIN NOW For the bitterness of anger END
BEGIN NOW Had departed wholly from him, END
BEGIN NOW From his brain the thought of vengeance, END
BEGIN NOW From his heart the burning fever. END
BEGIN NOW Only once his pace he slackened, END
BEGIN NOW Only once he paused or halted, END
BEGIN NOW Paused to purchase heads of arrows END
BEGIN NOW Of the ancient Arrow-maker, END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the Dacotahs, END
BEGIN NOW Flash and gleam among the oak-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Laugh and leap into the valley. END
BEGIN NOW There the ancient Arrow-maker END
BEGIN NOW Made his arrow-heads of sandstone, END
BEGIN NOW Arrow-heads of chalcedony, END
BEGIN NOW Arrow-heads of flint and jasper, END
BEGIN NOW Smoothed and sharpened at the edges, END
BEGIN NOW Hard and polished, keen and costly. END
BEGIN NOW With him dwelt his dark-eyed daughter, END
BEGIN NOW With her moods of shade and sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW Eyes that smiled and frowned alternate, END
BEGIN NOW Feet as rapid as the river, END
BEGIN NOW Tresses flowing like the water, END
BEGIN NOW And as musical a laughter: END
BEGIN NOW And he named her from the river, END
BEGIN NOW From the water-fall he named her, END
BEGIN NOW Was it then for heads of arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Arrow-heads of chalcedony, END
BEGIN NOW Arrow-heads of flint and jasper, END
BEGIN NOW That my Hiawatha halted END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the Dacotahs? END
BEGIN NOW Was it not to see the maiden, END
BEGIN NOW See the face of Laughing Water END
BEGIN NOW Peeping from behind the curtain, END
BEGIN NOW Hear the rustling of her garments END
BEGIN NOW From behind the waving curtain, END
BEGIN NOW As one sees the Minnehaha END
BEGIN NOW Gleaming, glancing through the branches, END
BEGIN NOW As one hears the Laughing Water END
BEGIN NOW From behind its screen of branches? END
BEGIN NOW Who shall say what thoughts and visions END
BEGIN NOW Fill the fiery brains of young men? END
BEGIN NOW Who shall say what dreams of beauty END
BEGIN NOW Filled the heart of Hiawatha? END
BEGIN NOW All he told to old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW When he reached the lodge at sunset, END
BEGIN NOW Was the meeting with his father, END
BEGIN NOW Was his fight with Mudjekeewis; END
BEGIN NOW Not a word he said of arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Not a word of Laughing Water. END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha's Fasting END
BEGIN NOW You shall hear how Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Prayed and fasted in the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Not for greater skill in hunting, END
BEGIN NOW Not for greater craft in fishing, END
BEGIN NOW Not for triumphs in the battle, END
BEGIN NOW And renown among the warriors, END
BEGIN NOW But for profit of the people, END
BEGIN NOW For advantage of the nations. END
BEGIN NOW First he built a lodge for fasting, END
BEGIN NOW Built a wigwam in the forest, END
BEGIN NOW By the shining Big-Sea-Water, END
BEGIN NOW In the blithe and pleasant Spring-time, END
BEGIN NOW In the Moon of Leaves he built it, END
BEGIN NOW And, with dreams and visions many, END
BEGIN NOW Seven whole days and nights he fasted. END
BEGIN NOW On the first day of his fasting END
BEGIN NOW Through the leafy woods he wandered; END
BEGIN NOW Saw the deer start from the thicket, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the rabbit in his burrow, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the pheasant, Bena, drumming, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the squirrel, Adjidaumo, END
BEGIN NOW Rattling in his hoard of acorns, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the pigeon, the Omeme, END
BEGIN NOW Building nests among the pinetrees, END
BEGIN NOW And in flocks the wild-goose, Wawa, END
BEGIN NOW Flying to the fen-lands northward, END
BEGIN NOW Whirring, wailing far above him. END
BEGIN NOW Master of Life!" he cried, desponding, END
BEGIN NOW Must our lives depend on these things? END
BEGIN NOW On the next day of his fasting END
BEGIN NOW By the river's brink he wandered, END
BEGIN NOW Through the Muskoday, the meadow, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the wild rice, Mahnomonee, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the blueberry, Meenahga, END
BEGIN NOW And the strawberry, Odahmin, END
BEGIN NOW And the gooseberry, Shahbomin, END
BEGIN NOW And the grape-vine, the Bemahgut, END
BEGIN NOW Trailing o'er the alder-branches, END
BEGIN NOW Filling all the air with fragrance! END
BEGIN NOW Master of Life!" he cried, desponding, END
BEGIN NOW Must our lives depend on these things? END
BEGIN NOW On the third day of his fasting END
BEGIN NOW By the lake he sat and pondered, END
BEGIN NOW By the still, transparent water; END
BEGIN NOW Saw the sturgeon, Nahma, leaping, END
BEGIN NOW Scattering drops like beads of wampum, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the yellow perch, the Sahwa, END
BEGIN NOW Like a sunbeam in the water, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the pike, the Maskenozha, END
BEGIN NOW And the herring, Okahahwis, END
BEGIN NOW And the Shawgashee, the crawfish! END
BEGIN NOW Master of Life!" he cried, desponding, END
BEGIN NOW Must our lives depend on these things? END
BEGIN NOW On the fourth day of his fasting END
BEGIN NOW In his lodge he lay exhausted; END
BEGIN NOW From his couch of leaves and branches END
BEGIN NOW Gazing with half-open eyelids, END
BEGIN NOW Full of shadowy dreams and visions, END
BEGIN NOW On the dizzy, swimming landscape, END
BEGIN NOW On the gleaming of the water, END
BEGIN NOW On the splendor of the sunset. END
BEGIN NOW And he saw a youth approaching, END
BEGIN NOW Dressed in garments green and yellow, END
BEGIN NOW Coming through the purple twilight, END
BEGIN NOW Through the splendor of the sunset; END
BEGIN NOW Plumes of green bent o'er his forehead, END
BEGIN NOW And his hair was soft and golden. END
BEGIN NOW Standing at the open doorway, END
BEGIN NOW Long he looked at Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Looked with pity and compassion END
BEGIN NOW On his wasted form and features, END
BEGIN NOW And, in accents like the sighing END
BEGIN NOW Of the South-Wind in the tree-tops, END
BEGIN NOW All your prayers are heard in heaven, END
BEGIN NOW For you pray not like the others; END
BEGIN NOW Not for greater skill in hunting, END
BEGIN NOW Not for greater craft in fishing, END
BEGIN NOW Not for triumph in the battle, END
BEGIN NOW Nor renown among the warriors, END
BEGIN NOW But for profit of the people, END
BEGIN NOW For advantage of the nations. END
BEGIN NOW From the Master of Life descending, END
BEGIN NOW I, the friend of man, Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW Come to warn you and instruct you, END
BEGIN NOW How by struggle and by labor END
BEGIN NOW You shall gain what you have prayed for. END
BEGIN NOW Rise up from your bed of branches, END
BEGIN NOW Rise, O youth, and wrestle with me! END
BEGIN NOW Faint with famine, Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Started from his bed of branches, END
BEGIN NOW From the twilight of his wigwam END
BEGIN NOW Forth into the flush of sunset END
BEGIN NOW Came, and wrestled with Mondamin; END
BEGIN NOW At his touch he felt new courage END
BEGIN NOW Throbbing in his brain and bosom, END
BEGIN NOW Felt new life and hope and vigor END
BEGIN NOW Run through every nerve and fibre. END
BEGIN NOW So they wrestled there together END
BEGIN NOW In the glory of the sunset, END
BEGIN NOW And the more they strove and struggled, END
BEGIN NOW Stronger still grew Hiawatha; END
BEGIN NOW Till the darkness fell around them, END
BEGIN NOW And the heron, the Shuh-shuh-gah, END
BEGIN NOW From her nest among the pine-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Gave a cry of lamentation, END
BEGIN NOW Gave a scream of pain and famine. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is enough!" then said Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW Smiling upon Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW But tomorrow, when the sun sets, END
BEGIN NOW I will come again to try you. END
BEGIN NOW And he vanished, and was seen not; END
BEGIN NOW Whether sinking as the rain sinks, END
BEGIN NOW Whether rising as the mists rise, END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha saw not, knew not, END
BEGIN NOW Only saw that he had vanished, END
BEGIN NOW Leaving him alone and fainting, END
BEGIN NOW With the misty lake below him, END
BEGIN NOW And the reeling stars above him. END
BEGIN NOW On the morrow and the next day, END
BEGIN NOW When the sun through heaven descending, END
BEGIN NOW Like a red and burning cinder END
BEGIN NOW From the hearth of the Great Spirit, END
BEGIN NOW Fell into the western waters, END
BEGIN NOW Came Mondamin for the trial, END
BEGIN NOW For the strife with Hiawatha; END
BEGIN NOW Came as silent as the dew comes, END
BEGIN NOW From the empty air appearing, END
BEGIN NOW Into empty air returning, END
BEGIN NOW Taking shape when earth it touches, END
BEGIN NOW But invisible to all men END
BEGIN NOW In its coming and its going. END
BEGIN NOW Thrice they wrestled there together END
BEGIN NOW In the glory of the sunset, END
BEGIN NOW Till the darkness fell around them, END
BEGIN NOW Till the heron, the Shuh-shuh-gah, END
BEGIN NOW From her nest among the pine-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Uttered her loud cry of famine, END
BEGIN NOW And Mondamin paused to listen. END
BEGIN NOW Tall and beautiful he stood there, END
BEGIN NOW In his garments green and yellow; END
BEGIN NOW To and fro his plumes above him, END
BEGIN NOW Waved and nodded with his breathing, END
BEGIN NOW And the sweat of the encounter END
BEGIN NOW Stood like drops of dew upon him. END
BEGIN NOW And he cried, "O Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Bravely have you wrestled with me, END
BEGIN NOW Thrice have wrestled stoutly with me, END
BEGIN NOW And the Master of Life, who sees us, END
BEGIN NOW He will give to you the triumph! END
BEGIN NOW Then he smiled, and said: To-morrow END
BEGIN NOW Is the last day of your conflict, END
BEGIN NOW Is the last day of your fasting. END
BEGIN NOW You will conquer and o'ercome me; END
BEGIN NOW Where the rain may fall upon me, END
BEGIN NOW Where the sun may come and warm me; END
BEGIN NOW Strip these garments, green and yellow, END
BEGIN NOW Strip this nodding plumage from me, END
BEGIN NOW Lay me in the earth, and make it END
BEGIN NOW Soft and loose and light above me. END
BEGIN NOW Let no hand disturb my slumber, END
BEGIN NOW Let no weed nor worm molest me, END
BEGIN NOW Let not Kahgahgee, the raven, END
BEGIN NOW Come to haunt me and molest me, END
BEGIN NOW Only come yourself to watch me, END
BEGIN NOW Till I wake, and start, and quicken, END
BEGIN NOW Till I leap into the sunshine END
BEGIN NOW And thus saying, he departed; END
BEGIN NOW Peacefully slept Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW But he heard the Wawonaissa, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the whippoorwill complaining, END
BEGIN NOW Perched upon his lonely wigwam; END
BEGIN NOW Heard the rushing Sebowisha, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the rivulet rippling near him, END
BEGIN NOW Talking to the darksome forest; END
BEGIN NOW Heard the sighing of the branches, END
BEGIN NOW As they lifted and subsided END
BEGIN NOW At the passing of the night-wind, END
BEGIN NOW Heard them, as one hears in slumber END
BEGIN NOW Far-off murmurs, dreamy whispers: END
BEGIN NOW Peacefully slept Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW On the morrow came Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW On the seventh day of his fasting, END
BEGIN NOW Came with food for Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Came imploring and bewailing, END
BEGIN NOW Lest his hunger should o'ercome him, END
BEGIN NOW Lest his fasting should be fatal. END
BEGIN NOW But he tasted not, and touched not, END
BEGIN NOW Only said to her, Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Wait until the sun is setting, END
BEGIN NOW Till the darkness falls around us, END
BEGIN NOW Till the heron, the Shuh-shuh-gah, END
BEGIN NOW Crying from the desolate marshes, END
BEGIN NOW Tells us that the day is ended. END
BEGIN NOW Homeward weeping went Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Fearing lest his strength should fail him, END
BEGIN NOW Lest his fasting should be fatal. END
BEGIN NOW He meanwhile sat weary waiting END
BEGIN NOW For the coming of Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW Till the shadows, pointing eastward, END
BEGIN NOW Lengthened over field and forest, END
BEGIN NOW Till the sun dropped from the heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Floating on the waters westward, END
BEGIN NOW As a red leaf in the Autumn END
BEGIN NOW Falls and floats upon the water, END
BEGIN NOW Falls and sinks into its bosom. END
BEGIN NOW And behold! the young Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW With his soft and shining tresses, END
BEGIN NOW With his garments green and yellow, END
BEGIN NOW With his long and glossy plumage, END
BEGIN NOW Stood and beckoned at the doorway. END
BEGIN NOW And as one in slumber walking, END
BEGIN NOW Pale and haggard, but undaunted, END
BEGIN NOW From the wigwam Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Came and wrestled with Mondamin. END
BEGIN NOW Round about him spun the landscape, END
BEGIN NOW Sky and forest reeled together, END
BEGIN NOW And his strong heart leaped within him, END
BEGIN NOW As the sturgeon leaps and struggles END
BEGIN NOW In a net to break its meshes. END
BEGIN NOW Like a ring of fire around him END
BEGIN NOW Blazed and flared the red horizon, END
BEGIN NOW And a hundred suns seemed looking END
BEGIN NOW At the combat of the wrestlers. END
BEGIN NOW Suddenly upon the greensward END
BEGIN NOW All alone stood Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Panting with his wild exertion, END
BEGIN NOW Palpitating with the struggle; END
BEGIN NOW And before him breathless, lifeless, END
BEGIN NOW Lay the youth, with hair dishevelled, END
BEGIN NOW Plumage torn, and garments tattered, END
BEGIN NOW Dead he lay there in the sunset. END
BEGIN NOW And victorious Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Made the grave as he commanded, END
BEGIN NOW Stripped the garments from Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW Stripped his tattered plumage from him, END
BEGIN NOW Laid him in the earth, and made it END
BEGIN NOW Soft and loose and light above him; END
BEGIN NOW And the heron, the Shuh-shuh-gah, END
BEGIN NOW From the melancholy moorlands, END
BEGIN NOW Gave a cry of lamentation, END
BEGIN NOW Gave a cry of pain and anguish! END
BEGIN NOW Homeward then went Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW To the lodge of old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW And the seven days of his fasting END
BEGIN NOW Were accomplished and completed. END
BEGIN NOW But the place was not forgotten END
BEGIN NOW Where he wrestled with Mondamin; END
BEGIN NOW Nor forgotten nor neglected END
BEGIN NOW Was the grave where lay Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW Sleeping in the rain and sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW Where his scattered plumes and garments END
BEGIN NOW Faded in the rain and sunshine. END
BEGIN NOW Go to wait and watch beside it; END
BEGIN NOW Kept the dark mould soft above it, END
BEGIN NOW Kept it clean from weeds and insects, END
BEGIN NOW Drove away, with scoffs and shoutings, END
BEGIN NOW Kahgahgee, the king of ravens. END
BEGIN NOW Till at length a small green feather END
BEGIN NOW From the earth shot slowly upward, END
BEGIN NOW Then another and another, END
BEGIN NOW And before the Summer ended END
BEGIN NOW Stood the maize in all its beauty, END
BEGIN NOW With its shining robes about it, END
BEGIN NOW And its long, soft, yellow tresses; END
BEGIN NOW And in rapture Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Cried aloud, "It is Mondamin! END
BEGIN NOW Yes, the friend of man, Mondamin! END
BEGIN NOW Then he called to old Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW And Iagoo, the great boaster, END
BEGIN NOW Showed them where the maize was growing, END
BEGIN NOW Told them of his wondrous vision, END
BEGIN NOW Of his wrestling and his triumph, END
BEGIN NOW Of this new gift to the nations, END
BEGIN NOW Which should be their food forever. END
BEGIN NOW And still later, when the Autumn END
BEGIN NOW Changed the long, green leaves to yellow, END
BEGIN NOW And the soft and juicy kernels END
BEGIN NOW Grew like wampum hard and yellow, END
BEGIN NOW Then the ripened ears he gathered, END
BEGIN NOW Stripped the withered husks from off them, END
BEGIN NOW As he once had stripped the wrestler, END
BEGIN NOW Gave the first Feast of Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW And made known unto the people END
BEGIN NOW This new gift of the Great Spirit. END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha's Friends END
BEGIN NOW Two good friends had Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Singled out from all the others, END
BEGIN NOW Bound to him in closest union, END
BEGIN NOW And to whom he gave the right hand END
BEGIN NOW Of his heart, in joy and sorrow; END
BEGIN NOW Chibiabos, the musician, END
BEGIN NOW And the very strong man, Kwasind. END
BEGIN NOW Straight between them ran the pathway, END
BEGIN NOW Never grew the grass upon it; END
BEGIN NOW Singing birds, that utter falsehoods, END
BEGIN NOW Story-tellers, mischief-makers, END
BEGIN NOW Found no eager ear to listen, END
BEGIN NOW Could not breed ill-will between them, END
BEGIN NOW For they kept each other's counsel, END
BEGIN NOW Spake with naked hearts together, END
BEGIN NOW Pondering much and much contriving END
BEGIN NOW How the tribes of men might prosper. END
BEGIN NOW Most beloved by Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Was the gentle Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW He the best of all musicians, END
BEGIN NOW He the sweetest of all singers. END
BEGIN NOW Beautiful and childlike was he, END
BEGIN NOW Brave as man is, soft as woman, END
BEGIN NOW Pliant as a wand of willow, END
BEGIN NOW Stately as a deer with antlers. END
BEGIN NOW When he sang, the village listened; END
BEGIN NOW All the warriors gathered round him, END
BEGIN NOW All the women came to hear him; END
BEGIN NOW Now he stirred their souls to passion, END
BEGIN NOW Now he melted them to pity. END
BEGIN NOW From the hollow reeds he fashioned END
BEGIN NOW Flutes so musical and mellow, END
BEGIN NOW That the brook, the Sebowisha, END
BEGIN NOW Ceased to murmur in the woodland, END
BEGIN NOW That the wood-birds ceased from singing, END
BEGIN NOW And the squirrel, Adjidaumo, END
BEGIN NOW Ceased his chatter in the oak-tree, END
BEGIN NOW And the rabbit, the Wabasso, END
BEGIN NOW Sat upright to look and listen. END
BEGIN NOW Yes, the brook, the Sebowisha, END
BEGIN NOW Pausing, said, "O Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW Teach my waves to flow in music, END
BEGIN NOW Softly as your words in singing! END
BEGIN NOW Yes, the bluebird, the Owaissa, END
BEGIN NOW Envious, said, "O Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW Teach me tones as wild and wayward, END
BEGIN NOW Teach me songs as full of frenzy! END
BEGIN NOW Yes, the robin, the Opechee, END
BEGIN NOW Joyous, said, "O Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW Teach me tones as sweet and tender, END
BEGIN NOW Teach me songs as full of gladness! END
BEGIN NOW And the whippoorwill, Wawonaissa, END
BEGIN NOW Sobbing, said, "O Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW Teach me tones as melancholy, END
BEGIN NOW Teach me songs as full of sadness! END
BEGIN NOW All the many sounds of nature END
BEGIN NOW Borrowed sweetness from his singing; END
BEGIN NOW All the hearts of men were softened END
BEGIN NOW By the pathos of his music; END
BEGIN NOW For he sang of peace and freedom, END
BEGIN NOW Sang of beauty, love, and longing; END
BEGIN NOW Sang of death, and life undying END
BEGIN NOW In the kingdom of Ponemah, END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the Hereafter. END
BEGIN NOW Very dear to Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Was the gentle Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW He the best of all musicians, END
BEGIN NOW He the sweetest of all singers; END
BEGIN NOW For his gentleness he loved him, END
BEGIN NOW And the magic of his singing. END
BEGIN NOW Dear, too, unto Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Was the very strong man, Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW He the strongest of all mortals, END
BEGIN NOW He the mightiest among many; END
BEGIN NOW For his very strength he loved him, END
BEGIN NOW For his strength allied to goodness. END
BEGIN NOW Idle in his youth was Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW Very listless, dull, and dreamy, END
BEGIN NOW Never played with other children, END
BEGIN NOW Never fished and never hunted, END
BEGIN NOW Not like other children was he; END
BEGIN NOW But they saw that much he fasted, END
BEGIN NOW Much his Manito entreated, END
BEGIN NOW Much besought his Guardian Spirit. END
BEGIN NOW Lazy Kwasind!" said his mother, END
BEGIN NOW In my work you never help me! END
BEGIN NOW In the Summer you are roaming END
BEGIN NOW Idly in the fields and forests; END
BEGIN NOW In the Winter you are cowering END
BEGIN NOW O'er the firebrands in the wigwam! END
BEGIN NOW In the coldest days of Winter END
BEGIN NOW I must break the ice for fishing; END
BEGIN NOW With my nets you never help me! END
BEGIN NOW At the door my nets are hanging, END
BEGIN NOW Dripping, freezing with the water; END
BEGIN NOW Go and wring them, Yenadizze! END
BEGIN NOW Go and dry them in the sunshine! END
BEGIN NOW Slowly, from the ashes, Kwasind END
BEGIN NOW Rose, but made no angry answer; END
BEGIN NOW From the lodge went forth in silence, END
BEGIN NOW Took the nets, that hung together, END
BEGIN NOW Dripping, freezing at the doorway; END
BEGIN NOW Like a wisp of straw he wrung them, END
BEGIN NOW Like a wisp of straw he broke them, END
BEGIN NOW Could not wring them without breaking, END
BEGIN NOW Such the strength was in his fingers. END
BEGIN NOW Lazy Kwasind!" said his father, END
BEGIN NOW In the hunt you never help me; END
BEGIN NOW Every bow you touch is broken, END
BEGIN NOW Snapped asunder every arrow; END
BEGIN NOW Yet come with me to the forest, END
BEGIN NOW You shall bring the hunting homeward. END
BEGIN NOW Down a narrow pass they wandered, END
BEGIN NOW Where a brooklet led them onward, END
BEGIN NOW Where the trail of deer and bison END
BEGIN NOW Marked the soft mud on the margin, END
BEGIN NOW Till they found all further passage END
BEGIN NOW Shut against them, barred securely END
BEGIN NOW By the trunks of trees uprooted, END
BEGIN NOW Lying lengthwise, lying crosswise, END
BEGIN NOW And forbidding further passage. END
BEGIN NOW We must go back," said the old man, END
BEGIN NOW O'er these logs we cannot clamber; END
BEGIN NOW Not a woodchuck could get through them, END
BEGIN NOW Not a squirrel clamber o'er them! END
BEGIN NOW And straightway his pipe he lighted, END
BEGIN NOW And sat down to smoke and ponder. END
BEGIN NOW But before his pipe was finished, END
BEGIN NOW Lo! the path was cleared before him; END
BEGIN NOW All the trunks had Kwasind lifted, END
BEGIN NOW To the right hand, to the left hand, END
BEGIN NOW Shot the pine-trees swift as arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Hurled the cedars light as lances. END
BEGIN NOW Lazy Kwasind!" said the young men, END
BEGIN NOW As they sported in the meadow: END
BEGIN NOW Why stand idly looking at us, END
BEGIN NOW Leaning on the rock behind you? END
BEGIN NOW Come and wrestle with the others, END
BEGIN NOW Let us pitch the quoit together! END
BEGIN NOW Lazy Kwasind made no answer, END
BEGIN NOW To their challenge made no answer, END
BEGIN NOW Only rose, and slowly turning, END
BEGIN NOW Seized the huge rock in his fingers, END
BEGIN NOW Tore it from its deep foundation, END
BEGIN NOW Poised it in the air a moment, END
BEGIN NOW Pitched it sheer into the river, END
BEGIN NOW Sheer into the swift Pauwating, END
BEGIN NOW Where it still is seen in Summer. END
BEGIN NOW Once as down that foaming river, END
BEGIN NOW Down the rapids of Pauwating, END
BEGIN NOW Kwasind sailed with his companions, END
BEGIN NOW In the stream he saw a beaver, END
BEGIN NOW Struggling with the rushing currents, END
BEGIN NOW Rising, sinking in the water. END
BEGIN NOW Without speaking, without pausing, END
BEGIN NOW Kwasind leaped into the river, END
BEGIN NOW Plunged beneath the bubbling surface, END
BEGIN NOW Through the whirlpools chased the beaver, END
BEGIN NOW Followed him among the islands, END
BEGIN NOW Stayed so long beneath the water, END
BEGIN NOW That his terrified companions END
BEGIN NOW Cried, "Alas! good-by to Kwasind! END
BEGIN NOW We shall never more see Kwasind! END
BEGIN NOW But he reappeared triumphant, END
BEGIN NOW And upon his shining shoulders END
BEGIN NOW Brought the beaver, dead and dripping, END
BEGIN NOW And these two, as I have told you, END
BEGIN NOW Were the friends of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Chibiabos, the musician, END
BEGIN NOW And the very strong man, Kwasind. END
BEGIN NOW Long they lived in peace together, END
BEGIN NOW Spake with naked hearts together, END
BEGIN NOW Pondering much and much contriving END
BEGIN NOW How the tribes of men might prosper. END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha's Sailing END
BEGIN NOW Give me of your bark, O Birch-tree! END
BEGIN NOW Of your yellow bark, O Birch-tree! END
BEGIN NOW Growing by the rushing river, END
BEGIN NOW Tall and stately in the valley! END
BEGIN NOW I a light canoe will build me, END
BEGIN NOW Build a swift Cheemaun for sailing, END
BEGIN NOW That shall float upon the river, END
BEGIN NOW Like a yellow leaf in Autumn, END
BEGIN NOW Like a yellow water-lily! END
BEGIN NOW Lay aside your cloak, O Birch-tree! END
BEGIN NOW Lay aside your white-skin wrapper, END
BEGIN NOW For the Summer-time is coming, END
BEGIN NOW And the sun is warm in heaven, END
BEGIN NOW And you need no white-skin wrapper! END
BEGIN NOW Thus aloud cried Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW In the solitary forest, END
BEGIN NOW By the rushing Taquamenaw, END
BEGIN NOW When the birds were singing gayly, END
BEGIN NOW In the Moon of Leaves were singing, END
BEGIN NOW And the sun, from sleep awaking, END
BEGIN NOW Started up and said, "Behold me! END
BEGIN NOW Gheezis, the great Sun, behold me! END
BEGIN NOW And the tree with all its branches END
BEGIN NOW Rustled in the breeze of morning, END
BEGIN NOW Saying, with a sigh of patience, END
BEGIN NOW Take my cloak, O Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW With his knife the tree he girdled; END
BEGIN NOW Just beneath its lowest branches, END
BEGIN NOW Just above the roots, he cut it, END
BEGIN NOW Till the sap came oozing outward; END
BEGIN NOW Down the trunk, from top to bottom, END
BEGIN NOW Sheer he cleft the bark asunder, END
BEGIN NOW With a wooden wedge he raised it, END
BEGIN NOW Stripped it from the trunk unbroken. END
BEGIN NOW Give me of your boughs, O Cedar! END
BEGIN NOW Of your strong and pliant branches, END
BEGIN NOW My canoe to make more steady, END
BEGIN NOW Make more strong and firm beneath me! END
BEGIN NOW Through the summit of the Cedar END
BEGIN NOW Went a sound, a cry of horror, END
BEGIN NOW Went a murmur of resistance; END
BEGIN NOW But it whispered, bending downward, END
BEGIN NOW Take my boughs, O Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Down he hewed the boughs of cedar, END
BEGIN NOW Shaped them straightway to a frame-work, END
BEGIN NOW Like two bows he formed and shaped them, END
BEGIN NOW Like two bended bows together. END
BEGIN NOW Give me of your roots, O Tamarack! END
BEGIN NOW Of your fibrous roots, O Larch-tree! END
BEGIN NOW My canoe to bind together, END
BEGIN NOW So to bind the ends together END
BEGIN NOW That the water may not enter, END
BEGIN NOW That the river may not wet me! END
BEGIN NOW And the Larch, with all its fibres, END
BEGIN NOW Shivered in the air of morning, END
BEGIN NOW Touched his forehead with its tassels, END
BEGIN NOW Slid, with one long sigh of sorrow. END
BEGIN NOW Take them all, O Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW From the earth he tore the fibres, END
BEGIN NOW Tore the tough roots of the Larch-tree, END
BEGIN NOW Closely sewed the bark together, END
BEGIN NOW Bound it closely to the frame-work. END
BEGIN NOW Give me of your balm, O Fir-tree! END
BEGIN NOW Of your balsam and your resin, END
BEGIN NOW So to close the seams together END
BEGIN NOW That the water may not enter, END
BEGIN NOW That the river may not wet me! END
BEGIN NOW And the Fir-tree, tall and sombre, END
BEGIN NOW Sobbed through all its robes of darkness, END
BEGIN NOW Rattled like a shore with pebbles, END
BEGIN NOW Answered wailing, answered weeping, END
BEGIN NOW Take my balm, O Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW And he took the tears of balsam, END
BEGIN NOW Took the resin of the Fir-tree, END
BEGIN NOW Smeared therewith each seam and fissure, END
BEGIN NOW Made each crevice safe from water. END
BEGIN NOW Give me of your quills, O Hedgehog! END
BEGIN NOW All your quills, O Kagh, the Hedgehog! END
BEGIN NOW I will make a necklace of them, END
BEGIN NOW Make a girdle for my beauty, END
BEGIN NOW And two stars to deck her bosom! END
BEGIN NOW From a hollow tree the Hedgehog END
BEGIN NOW With his sleepy eyes looked at him, END
BEGIN NOW Shot his shining quills, like arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Saying with a drowsy murmur, END
BEGIN NOW Through the tangle of his whiskers, END
BEGIN NOW Take my quills, O Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW From the ground the quills he gathered, END
BEGIN NOW All the little shining arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Stained them red and blue and yellow, END
BEGIN NOW With the juice of roots and berries; END
BEGIN NOW Into his canoe he wrought them, END
BEGIN NOW Round its waist a shining girdle, END
BEGIN NOW Round its bows a gleaming necklace, END
BEGIN NOW On its breast two stars resplendent. END
BEGIN NOW Thus the Birch Canoe was builded END
BEGIN NOW In the valley, by the river, END
BEGIN NOW In the bosom of the forest; END
BEGIN NOW And the forest's life was in it, END
BEGIN NOW All its mystery and its magic, END
BEGIN NOW All the lightness of the birch-tree, END
BEGIN NOW All the toughness of the cedar, END
BEGIN NOW All the larch's supple sinews; END
BEGIN NOW And it floated on the river END
BEGIN NOW Like a yellow leaf in Autumn, END
BEGIN NOW Like a yellow water-lily. END
BEGIN NOW Paddles none had Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Paddles none he had or needed, END
BEGIN NOW For his thoughts as paddles served him, END
BEGIN NOW And his wishes served to guide him; END
BEGIN NOW Swift or slow at will he glided, END
BEGIN NOW Veered to right or left at pleasure. END
BEGIN NOW Then he called aloud to Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW To his friend, the strong man, Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW Saying, "Help me clear this river END
BEGIN NOW Of its sunken logs and sand-bars. END
BEGIN NOW Straight into the river Kwasind END
BEGIN NOW Plunged as if he were an otter, END
BEGIN NOW Dived as if he were a beaver, END
BEGIN NOW Stood up to his waist in water, END
BEGIN NOW To his arm-pits in the river, END
BEGIN NOW Swam and scouted in the river, END
BEGIN NOW Tugged at sunken logs and branches, END
BEGIN NOW With his hands he scooped the sand-bars, END
BEGIN NOW With his feet the ooze and tangle. END
BEGIN NOW And thus sailed my Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Down the rushing Taquamenaw, END
BEGIN NOW Sailed through all its bends and windings, END
BEGIN NOW Sailed through all its deeps and shallows, END
BEGIN NOW While his friend, the strong man, Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW Swam the deeps, the shallows waded. END
BEGIN NOW Up and down the river went they, END
BEGIN NOW In and out among its islands, END
BEGIN NOW Cleared its bed of root and sand-bar, END
BEGIN NOW Dragged the dead trees from its channel, END
BEGIN NOW Made its passage safe and certain, END
BEGIN NOW Made a pathway for the people, END
BEGIN NOW From its springs among the mountains, END
BEGIN NOW To the waters of Pauwating, END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha's Fishing END
BEGIN NOW Forth upon the Gitche Gumee, END
BEGIN NOW On the shining Big-Sea-Water, END
BEGIN NOW With his fishing-line of cedar, END
BEGIN NOW Of the twisted bark of cedar, END
BEGIN NOW Forth to catch the sturgeon Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW In his birch canoe exulting END
BEGIN NOW All alone went Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW Through the clear, transparent water END
BEGIN NOW He could see the fishes swimming END
BEGIN NOW Far down in the depths below him; END
BEGIN NOW See the yellow perch, the Sahwa, END
BEGIN NOW Like a sunbeam in the water, END
BEGIN NOW See the Shawgashee, the craw-fish, END
BEGIN NOW Like a spider on the bottom, END
BEGIN NOW On the white and sandy bottom. END
BEGIN NOW At the stern sat Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW With his fishing-line of cedar; END
BEGIN NOW In his plumes the breeze of morning END
BEGIN NOW Played as in the hemlock branches; END
BEGIN NOW On the bows, with tail erected, END
BEGIN NOW Sat the squirrel, Adjidaumo; END
BEGIN NOW In his fur the breeze of morning END
BEGIN NOW Played as in the prairie grasses. END
BEGIN NOW On the white sand of the bottom END
BEGIN NOW Lay the monster Mishe-Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW Lay the sturgeon, King of Fishes; END
BEGIN NOW Through his gills he breathed the water, END
BEGIN NOW With his fins he fanned and winnowed, END
BEGIN NOW With his tail he swept the sand-floor. END
BEGIN NOW There he lay in all his armor; END
BEGIN NOW On each side a shield to guard him, END
BEGIN NOW Plates of bone upon his forehead, END
BEGIN NOW Down his sides and back and shoulders END
BEGIN NOW Plates of bone with spines projecting END
BEGIN NOW Painted was he with his war-paints, END
BEGIN NOW Stripes of yellow, red, and azure, END
BEGIN NOW Spots of brown and spots of sable; END
BEGIN NOW And he lay there on the bottom, END
BEGIN NOW Fanning with his fins of purple, END
BEGIN NOW As above him Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW In his birch canoe came sailing, END
BEGIN NOW With his fishing-line of cedar. END
BEGIN NOW Take my bait," cried Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Dawn into the depths beneath him, END
BEGIN NOW Take my bait, O Sturgeon, Nahma! END
BEGIN NOW Come up from below the water, END
BEGIN NOW Let us see which is the stronger! END
BEGIN NOW And he dropped his line of cedar END
BEGIN NOW Through the clear, transparent water, END
BEGIN NOW Waited vainly for an answer, END
BEGIN NOW Long sat waiting for an answer, END
BEGIN NOW And repeating loud and louder, END
BEGIN NOW Take my bait, O King of Fishes! END
BEGIN NOW Quiet lay the sturgeon, Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW Fanning slowly in the water, END
BEGIN NOW Listening to his call and clamor, END
BEGIN NOW His unnecessary tumult, END
BEGIN NOW Till he wearied of the shouting; END
BEGIN NOW And he said to the Kenozha, END
BEGIN NOW To the pike, the Maskenozha, END
BEGIN NOW Take the bait of this rude fellow, END
BEGIN NOW Break the line of Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW In his fingers Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Felt the loose line jerk and tighten, END
BEGIN NOW As he drew it in, it tugged so END
BEGIN NOW That the birch canoe stood endwise, END
BEGIN NOW Like a birch log in the water, END
BEGIN NOW With the squirrel, Adjidaumo, END
BEGIN NOW Perched and frisking on the summit. END
BEGIN NOW Full of scorn was Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW When he saw the fish rise upward, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the pike, the Maskenozha, END
BEGIN NOW Coming nearer, nearer to him, END
BEGIN NOW And he shouted through the water, END
BEGIN NOW Esa! esa! shame upon you! END
BEGIN NOW You are but the pike, Kenozha, END
BEGIN NOW You are not the fish I wanted, END
BEGIN NOW Reeling downward to the bottom END
BEGIN NOW Sank the pike in great confusion, END
BEGIN NOW And the mighty sturgeon, Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW Said to Ugudwash, the sun-fish, END
BEGIN NOW To the bream, with scales of crimson, END
BEGIN NOW Take the bait of this great boaster, END
BEGIN NOW Break the line of Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Slowly upward, wavering, gleaming, END
BEGIN NOW Rose the Ugudwash, the sun-fish, END
BEGIN NOW Seized the line of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Swung with all his weight upon it, END
BEGIN NOW Made a whirlpool in the water, END
BEGIN NOW Whirled the birch canoe in circles, END
BEGIN NOW Round and round in gurgling eddies, END
BEGIN NOW Till the circles in the water END
BEGIN NOW Reached the far-off sandy beaches, END
BEGIN NOW Till the water-flags and rushes END
BEGIN NOW Nodded on the distant margins. END
BEGIN NOW But when Hiawatha saw him END
BEGIN NOW Slowly rising through the water, END
BEGIN NOW Lifting up his disk refulgent, END
BEGIN NOW Loud he shouted in derision, END
BEGIN NOW Esa! esa! shame upon you! END
BEGIN NOW You are Ugudwash, the sun-fish, END
BEGIN NOW You are not the fish I wanted, END
BEGIN NOW Slowly downward, wavering, gleaming, END
BEGIN NOW Sank the Ugudwash, the sun-fish, END
BEGIN NOW And again the sturgeon, Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the shout of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Heard his challenge of defiance, END
BEGIN NOW The unnecessary tumult, END
BEGIN NOW Ringing far across the water. END
BEGIN NOW From the white sand of the bottom END
BEGIN NOW Up he rose with angry gesture, END
BEGIN NOW Quivering in each nerve and fibre, END
BEGIN NOW Clashing all his plates of armor, END
BEGIN NOW Gleaming bright with all his war-paint; END
BEGIN NOW In his wrath he darted upward, END
BEGIN NOW Flashing leaped into the sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW Opened his great jaws, and swallowed END
BEGIN NOW Both canoe and Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW Down into that darksome cavern END
BEGIN NOW Plunged the headlong Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW As a log on some black river END
BEGIN NOW Shoots and plunges down the rapids, END
BEGIN NOW Found himself in utter darkness, END
BEGIN NOW Groped about in helpless wonder, END
BEGIN NOW Till he felt a great heart beating, END
BEGIN NOW Throbbing in that utter darkness. END
BEGIN NOW And he smote it in his anger, END
BEGIN NOW With his fist, the heart of Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW Felt the mighty King of Fishes END
BEGIN NOW Shudder through each nerve and fibre, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the water gurgle round him END
BEGIN NOW As he leaped and staggered through it, END
BEGIN NOW Sick at heart, and faint and weary. END
BEGIN NOW Crosswise then did Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Drag his birch-canoe for safety, END
BEGIN NOW Lest from out the jaws of Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW In the turmoil and confusion, END
BEGIN NOW Forth he might be hurled and perish. END
BEGIN NOW And the squirrel, Adjidaumo, END
BEGIN NOW Frisked and chatted very gayly, END
BEGIN NOW Toiled and tugged with Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Till the labor was completed. END
BEGIN NOW Then said Hiawatha to him, END
BEGIN NOW O my little friend, the squirrel, END
BEGIN NOW Bravely have you toiled to help me; END
BEGIN NOW Take the thanks of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW And the name which now he gives you; END
BEGIN NOW For hereafter and forever END
BEGIN NOW Boys shall call you Adjidaumo, END
BEGIN NOW Tail-in-air the boys shall call you! END
BEGIN NOW And again the sturgeon, Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW Gasped and quivered in the water, END
BEGIN NOW Then was still, and drifted landward END
BEGIN NOW Till he grated on the pebbles, END
BEGIN NOW Till the listening Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Heard him grate upon the margin, END
BEGIN NOW Felt him strand upon the pebbles, END
BEGIN NOW Knew that Nahma, King of Fishes, END
BEGIN NOW Lay there dead upon the margin. END
BEGIN NOW Then he heard a clang and flapping, END
BEGIN NOW As of many wings assembling, END
BEGIN NOW Heard a screaming and confusion, END
BEGIN NOW As of birds of prey contending, END
BEGIN NOW Saw a gleam of light above him, END
BEGIN NOW Shining through the ribs of Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the glittering eyes of sea-gulls, END
BEGIN NOW Of Kayoshk, the sea-gulls, peering, END
BEGIN NOW Gazing at him through the opening, END
BEGIN NOW Heard them saying to each other, END
BEGIN NOW 'T is our brother, Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW And he shouted from below them, END
BEGIN NOW Cried exulting from the caverns: END
BEGIN NOW O ye sea-gulls! O my brothers! END
BEGIN NOW I have slain the sturgeon, Nahma; END
BEGIN NOW Make the rifts a little larger, END
BEGIN NOW With your claws the openings widen, END
BEGIN NOW Set me free from this dark prison, END
BEGIN NOW And henceforward and forever END
BEGIN NOW Men shall speak of your achievements, END
BEGIN NOW Calling you Kayoshk, the sea-gulls, END
BEGIN NOW And the wild and clamorous sea-gulls END
BEGIN NOW Toiled with beak and claws together, END
BEGIN NOW Made the rifts and openings wider END
BEGIN NOW In the mighty ribs of Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW And from peril and from prison, END
BEGIN NOW From the body of the sturgeon, END
BEGIN NOW From the peril of the water, END
BEGIN NOW They released my Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW He was standing near his wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW On the margin of the water, END
BEGIN NOW And he called to old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Called and beckoned to Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Pointed to the sturgeon, Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW Lying lifeless on the pebbles, END
BEGIN NOW With the sea-gulls feeding on him. END
BEGIN NOW I have slain the Mishe-Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW Slain the King of Fishes!" said he; END
BEGIN NOW Look! the sea-gulls feed upon him, END
BEGIN NOW Yes, my friends Kayoshk, the sea-gulls; END
BEGIN NOW Drive them not away, Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW They have saved me from great peril END
BEGIN NOW In the body of the sturgeon, END
BEGIN NOW Wait until their meal is ended, END
BEGIN NOW Till their craws are full with feasting, END
BEGIN NOW Till they homeward fly, at sunset, END
BEGIN NOW To their nests among the marshes; END
BEGIN NOW Then bring all your pots and kettles, END
BEGIN NOW And make oil for us in Winter. END
BEGIN NOW And she waited till the sun set, END
BEGIN NOW Till the pallid moon, the Night-sun, END
BEGIN NOW Rose above the tranquil water, END
BEGIN NOW Till Kayoshk, the sated sea-gulls, END
BEGIN NOW From their banquet rose with clamor, END
BEGIN NOW And across the fiery sunset END
BEGIN NOW Winged their way to far-off islands, END
BEGIN NOW To their nests among the rushes. END
BEGIN NOW To his sleep went Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW And Nokomis to her labor, END
BEGIN NOW Toiling patient in the moonlight, END
BEGIN NOW Till the sun and moon changed places, END
BEGIN NOW Till the sky was red with sunrise, END
BEGIN NOW And Kayoshk, the hungry sea-gulls, END
BEGIN NOW Came back from the reedy islands, END
BEGIN NOW Clamorous for their morning banquet. END
BEGIN NOW Three whole days and nights alternate END
BEGIN NOW Old Nokomis and the sea-gulls END
BEGIN NOW Stripped the oily flesh of Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW Till the waves washed through the rib-bones, END
BEGIN NOW Till the sea-gulls came no longer, END
BEGIN NOW And upon the sands lay nothing END
BEGIN NOW But the skeleton of Nahma. END
BEGIN NOW On the shores of Gitche Gumee, END
BEGIN NOW Of the shining Big-Sea-Water, END
BEGIN NOW Stood Nokomis, the old woman, END
BEGIN NOW Pointing with her finger westward, END
BEGIN NOW O'er the water pointing westward, END
BEGIN NOW To the purple clouds of sunset. END
BEGIN NOW Fiercely the red sun descending END
BEGIN NOW Burned his way along the heavens, END
BEGIN NOW Set the sky on fire behind him, END
BEGIN NOW As war-parties, when retreating, END
BEGIN NOW Burn the prairies on their war-trail; END
BEGIN NOW And the moon, the Night-sun, eastward, END
BEGIN NOW Suddenly starting from his ambush, END
BEGIN NOW Followed fast those bloody footprints, END
BEGIN NOW Followed in that fiery war-trail, END
BEGIN NOW With its glare upon his features. END
BEGIN NOW And Nokomis, the old woman, END
BEGIN NOW Pointing with her finger westward, END
BEGIN NOW Spake these words to Hiawatha: END
BEGIN NOW Yonder dwells the great Pearl-Feather, END
BEGIN NOW Guarded by his fiery serpents, END
BEGIN NOW Guarded by the black pitch-water. END
BEGIN NOW You can see his fiery serpents, END
BEGIN NOW The Kenabeek, the great serpents, END
BEGIN NOW Coiling, playing in the water; END
BEGIN NOW You can see the black pitch-water END
BEGIN NOW Stretching far away beyond them, END
BEGIN NOW To the purple clouds of sunset! END
BEGIN NOW He it was who slew my father, END
BEGIN NOW By his wicked wiles and cunning, END
BEGIN NOW When he from the moon descended, END
BEGIN NOW When he came on earth to seek me. END
BEGIN NOW He, the mightiest of Magicians, END
BEGIN NOW Sends the fever from the marshes, END
BEGIN NOW Sends the pestilential vapors, END
BEGIN NOW Sends the poisonous exhalations, END
BEGIN NOW Sends the white fog from the fen-lands, END
BEGIN NOW Sends disease and death among us! END
BEGIN NOW Take your bow, O Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Take your arrows, jasper-headed, END
BEGIN NOW Take your war-club, Puggawaugun, END
BEGIN NOW And your mittens, Minjekahwun, END
BEGIN NOW And your birch-canoe for sailing, END
BEGIN NOW So to smear its sides, that swiftly END
BEGIN NOW You may pass the black pitch-water; END
BEGIN NOW Slay this merciless magician, END
BEGIN NOW Save the people from the fever END
BEGIN NOW That he breathes across the fen-lands, END
BEGIN NOW And avenge my father's murder! END
BEGIN NOW Straightway then my Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Armed himself with all his war-gear, END
BEGIN NOW Launched his birch-canoe for sailing; END
BEGIN NOW With his palm its sides he patted, END
BEGIN NOW Said with glee, "Cheemaun, my darling, END
BEGIN NOW O my Birch-canoe! leap forward, END
BEGIN NOW Where you see the fiery serpents, END
BEGIN NOW Where you see the black pitch-water! END
BEGIN NOW Forward leaped Cheemaun exulting, END
BEGIN NOW And the noble Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Sang his war-song wild and woful, END
BEGIN NOW And above him the war-eagle, END
BEGIN NOW The Keneu, the great war-eagle, END
BEGIN NOW Master of all fowls with feathers, END
BEGIN NOW Screamed and hurtled through the heavens. END
BEGIN NOW Soon he reached the fiery serpents, END
BEGIN NOW The Kenabeek, the great serpents, END
BEGIN NOW Lying huge upon the water, END
BEGIN NOW Sparkling, rippling in the water, END
BEGIN NOW Lying coiled across the passage, END
BEGIN NOW With their blazing crests uplifted, END
BEGIN NOW Breathing fiery fogs and vapors, END
BEGIN NOW So that none could pass beyond them. END
BEGIN NOW But the fearless Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Cried aloud, and spake in this wise, END
BEGIN NOW Let me pass my way, Kenabeek, END
BEGIN NOW Let me go upon my journey! END
BEGIN NOW And they answered, hissing fiercely, END
BEGIN NOW With their fiery breath made answer: END
BEGIN NOW Back, go back! O Shaugodaya! END
BEGIN NOW Back to old Nokomis, Faint-heart! END
BEGIN NOW Then the angry Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Raised his mighty bow of ash-tree, END
BEGIN NOW Seized his arrows, jasper-headed, END
BEGIN NOW Shot them fast among the serpents; END
BEGIN NOW Every twanging of the bow-string END
BEGIN NOW Was a war-cry and a death-cry, END
BEGIN NOW Every whizzing of an arrow END
BEGIN NOW Was a death-song of Kenabeek. END
BEGIN NOW Weltering in the bloody water, END
BEGIN NOW Dead lay all the fiery serpents, END
BEGIN NOW And among them Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Harmless sailed, and cried exulting: END
BEGIN NOW Onward, O Cheemaun, my darling! END
BEGIN NOW Onward to the black pitch-water! END
BEGIN NOW Then he took the oil of Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW And the bows and sides anointed, END
BEGIN NOW Smeared them well with oil, that swiftly END
BEGIN NOW He might pass the black pitch-water. END
BEGIN NOW All night long he sailed upon it, END
BEGIN NOW Sailed upon that sluggish water, END
BEGIN NOW Covered with its mould of ages, END
BEGIN NOW Black with rotting water-rushes, END
BEGIN NOW Rank with flags and leaves of lilies, END
BEGIN NOW Stagnant, lifeless, dreary, dismal, END
BEGIN NOW Lighted by the shimmering moonlight, END
BEGIN NOW And by will-o'-the-wisps illumined, END
BEGIN NOW Fires by ghosts of dead men kindled, END
BEGIN NOW In their weary night-encampments. END
BEGIN NOW All the air was white with moonlight, END
BEGIN NOW All the water black with shadow, END
BEGIN NOW And around him the Suggema, END
BEGIN NOW The mosquito, sang his war-song, END
BEGIN NOW And the fire-flies, Wah-wah-taysee, END
BEGIN NOW Waved their torches to mislead him; END
BEGIN NOW And the bull-frog, the Dahinda, END
BEGIN NOW Thrust his head into the moonlight, END
BEGIN NOW Fixed his yellow eyes upon him, END
BEGIN NOW Sobbed and sank beneath the surface; END
BEGIN NOW And anon a thousand whistles, END
BEGIN NOW Answered over all the fen-lands, END
BEGIN NOW And the heron, the Shuh-shuh-gah, END
BEGIN NOW Far off on the reedy margin, END
BEGIN NOW Heralded the hero's coming. END
BEGIN NOW Westward thus fared Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Toward the realm of Megissogwon, END
BEGIN NOW Toward the land of the Pearl-Feather, END
BEGIN NOW Till the level moon stared at him END
BEGIN NOW In his face stared pale and haggard, END
BEGIN NOW Till the sun was hot behind him, END
BEGIN NOW Till it burned upon his shoulders, END
BEGIN NOW And before him on the upland END
BEGIN NOW He could see the Shining Wigwam END
BEGIN NOW Of the mightiest of Magicians. END
BEGIN NOW Then once more Cheemaun he patted, END
BEGIN NOW To his birch-canoe said, Onward! END
BEGIN NOW And it stirred in all its fibres, END
BEGIN NOW And with one great bound of triumph END
BEGIN NOW Leaped across the water-lilies, END
BEGIN NOW Leaped through tangled flags and rushes, END
BEGIN NOW And upon the beach beyond them END
BEGIN NOW Dry-shod landed Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW Straight he took his bow of ash-tree, END
BEGIN NOW On the sand one end he rested, END
BEGIN NOW With his knee he pressed the middle, END
BEGIN NOW Stretched the faithful bow-string tighter, END
BEGIN NOW Took an arrow, jasperheaded, END
BEGIN NOW Sent it singing as a herald, END
BEGIN NOW As a bearer of his message, END
BEGIN NOW Of his challenge loud and lofty: END
BEGIN NOW Come forth from your lodge, Pearl-Feather! END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha waits your coming! END
BEGIN NOW Straightway from the Shining Wigwam END
BEGIN NOW Came the mighty Megissogwon, END
BEGIN NOW Tall of stature, broad of shoulder, END
BEGIN NOW Dark and terrible in aspect, END
BEGIN NOW Clad from head to foot in wampum, END
BEGIN NOW Armed with all his warlike weapons, END
BEGIN NOW Painted like the sky of morning, END
BEGIN NOW Streaked with crimson, blue, and yellow, END
BEGIN NOW Crested with great eagle-feathers, END
BEGIN NOW Streaming upward, streaming outward. END
BEGIN NOW Well I know you, Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Cried he in a voice of thunder, END
BEGIN NOW In a tone of loud derision. END
BEGIN NOW Hasten back, O Shaugodaya! END
BEGIN NOW Hasten back among the women, END
BEGIN NOW Back to old Nokomis, Faint-heart! END
BEGIN NOW I will slay you as you stand there, END
BEGIN NOW As of old I slew her father! END
BEGIN NOW But my Hiawatha answered, END
BEGIN NOW Nothing daunted, fearing nothing: END
BEGIN NOW Big words do not smite like war-clubs, END
BEGIN NOW Boastful breath is not a bow-string, END
BEGIN NOW Taunts are not so sharp as arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Deeds are better things than words are, END
BEGIN NOW Actions mightier than boastings! END
BEGIN NOW Then began the greatest battle END
BEGIN NOW That the sun had ever looked on, END
BEGIN NOW That the war-birds ever witnessed. END
BEGIN NOW All a Summer's day it lasted, END
BEGIN NOW From the sunrise to the sunset; END
BEGIN NOW For the shafts of Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Harmless hit the shirt of wampum, END
BEGIN NOW Harmless fell the blows he dealt it END
BEGIN NOW With his mittens, Minjekahwun, END
BEGIN NOW Harmless fell the heavy war-club; END
BEGIN NOW It could dash the rocks asunder, END
BEGIN NOW But it could not break the meshes END
BEGIN NOW Of that magic shirt of wampum. END
BEGIN NOW Till at sunset Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Leaning on his bow of ash-tree, END
BEGIN NOW Wounded, weary, and desponding, END
BEGIN NOW With his mighty war-club broken, END
BEGIN NOW With his mittens torn and tattered, END
BEGIN NOW And three useless arrows only, END
BEGIN NOW Paused to rest beneath a pine-tree, END
BEGIN NOW From whose branches trailed the mosses, END
BEGIN NOW And whose trunk was coated over END
BEGIN NOW With the Dead-man's Moccasin-leather, END
BEGIN NOW With the fungus white and yellow. END
BEGIN NOW Suddenly from the boughs above him END
BEGIN NOW Sang the Mama, the woodpecker: END
BEGIN NOW Aim your arrows, Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW At the head of Megissogwon, END
BEGIN NOW Strike the tuft of hair upon it, END
BEGIN NOW At their roots the long black tresses; END
BEGIN NOW There alone can he be wounded! END
BEGIN NOW Winged with feathers, tipped with jasper, END
BEGIN NOW Swift flew Hiawatha's arrow, END
BEGIN NOW Just as Megissogwon, stooping, END
BEGIN NOW Raised a heavy stone to throw it. END
BEGIN NOW Full upon the crown it struck him, END
BEGIN NOW At the roots of his long tresses, END
BEGIN NOW And he reeled and staggered forward, END
BEGIN NOW Plunging like a wounded bison, END
BEGIN NOW Yes, like Pezhekee, the bison, END
BEGIN NOW When the snow is on the prairie. END
BEGIN NOW Swifter flew the second arrow, END
BEGIN NOW In the pathway of the other, END
BEGIN NOW Piercing deeper than the other, END
BEGIN NOW Wounding sorer than the other; END
BEGIN NOW And the knees of Megissogwon END
BEGIN NOW Shook like windy reeds beneath him, END
BEGIN NOW Bent and trembled like the rushes. END
BEGIN NOW But the third and latest arrow END
BEGIN NOW Swiftest flew, and wounded sorest, END
BEGIN NOW And the mighty Megissogwon END
BEGIN NOW Saw the fiery eyes of Pauguk, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the eyes of Death glare at him, END
BEGIN NOW Heard his voice call in the darkness; END
BEGIN NOW At the feet of Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Lifeless lay the great Pearl-Feather, END
BEGIN NOW Lay the mightiest of Magicians. END
BEGIN NOW Then the grateful Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Called the Mama, the woodpecker, END
BEGIN NOW From his perch among the branches END
BEGIN NOW Of the melancholy pine-tree, END
BEGIN NOW And, in honor of his service, END
BEGIN NOW Stained with blood the tuft of feathers END
BEGIN NOW On the little head of Mama; END
BEGIN NOW Even to this day he wears it, END
BEGIN NOW Wears the tuft of crimson feathers, END
BEGIN NOW As a symbol of his service. END
BEGIN NOW Then he stripped the shirt of wampum END
BEGIN NOW From the back of Megissogwon, END
BEGIN NOW As a trophy of the battle, END
BEGIN NOW As a signal of his conquest. END
BEGIN NOW On the shore he left the body, END
BEGIN NOW Half on land and half in water, END
BEGIN NOW In the sand his feet were buried, END
BEGIN NOW And his face was in the water. END
BEGIN NOW And above him, wheeled and clamored END
BEGIN NOW The Keneu, the great war-eagle, END
BEGIN NOW Sailing round in narrower circles, END
BEGIN NOW Hovering nearer, nearer, nearer. END
BEGIN NOW From the wigwam Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Bore the wealth of Megissogwon, END
BEGIN NOW All his wealth of skins and wampum, END
BEGIN NOW Furs of bison and of beaver, END
BEGIN NOW Furs of sable and of ermine, END
BEGIN NOW Wampum belts and strings and pouches, END
BEGIN NOW Quivers wrought with beads of wampum, END
BEGIN NOW Filled with arrows, silver-headed. END
BEGIN NOW Homeward then he sailed exulting, END
BEGIN NOW Homeward through the black pitch-water, END
BEGIN NOW Homeward through the weltering serpents, END
BEGIN NOW With the trophies of the battle, END
BEGIN NOW With a shout and song of triumph. END
BEGIN NOW On the shore stood old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW On the shore stood Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW And the very strong man, Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW Waiting for the hero's coming, END
BEGIN NOW Listening to his songs of triumph. END
BEGIN NOW And the people of the village END
BEGIN NOW Welcomed him with songs and dances, END
BEGIN NOW Made a joyous feast, and shouted: END
BEGIN NOW He has slain the great Pearl-Feather, END
BEGIN NOW Slain the mightiest of Magicians, END
BEGIN NOW Him, who sent the fiery fever, END
BEGIN NOW Sent the white fog from the fen-lands, END
BEGIN NOW Sent disease and death among us! END
BEGIN NOW Ever dear to Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Was the memory of Mama! END
BEGIN NOW And in token of his friendship, END
BEGIN NOW As a mark of his remembrance, END
BEGIN NOW He adorned and decked his pipe-stem END
BEGIN NOW With the crimson tuft of feathers, END
BEGIN NOW With the blood-red crest of Mama. END
BEGIN NOW But the wealth of Megissogwon, END
BEGIN NOW All the trophies of the battle, END
BEGIN NOW He divided with his people, END
BEGIN NOW Shared it equally among them. END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha's Wooing END
BEGIN NOW As unto the bow the cord is, END
BEGIN NOW So unto the man is woman; END
BEGIN NOW Though she bends him, she obeys him, END
BEGIN NOW Though she draws him, yet she follows; END
BEGIN NOW Useless each without the other! END
BEGIN NOW Thus the youthful Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Said within himself and pondered, END
BEGIN NOW Much perplexed by various feelings, END
BEGIN NOW Listless, longing, hoping, fearing, END
BEGIN NOW Dreaming still of Minnehaha, END
BEGIN NOW Of the lovely Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the Dacotahs. END
BEGIN NOW Wed a maiden of your people, END
BEGIN NOW Warning said the old Nokomis; END
BEGIN NOW Go not eastward, go not westward, END
BEGIN NOW For a stranger, whom we know not! END
BEGIN NOW Like a fire upon the hearth-stone END
BEGIN NOW Is a neighbor's homely daughter, END
BEGIN NOW Like the starlight or the moonlight END
BEGIN NOW Is the handsomest of strangers! END
BEGIN NOW Thus dissuading spake Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW And my Hiawatha answered END
BEGIN NOW Only this: "Dear old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Very pleasant is the firelight, END
BEGIN NOW But I like the starlight better, END
BEGIN NOW Better do I like the moonlight! END
BEGIN NOW Gravely then said old Nokomis: END
BEGIN NOW Bring not here an idle maiden, END
BEGIN NOW Bring not here a useless woman, END
BEGIN NOW Hands unskilful, feet unwilling; END
BEGIN NOW Bring a wife with nimble fingers, END
BEGIN NOW Heart and hand that move together, END
BEGIN NOW Feet that run on willing errands! END
BEGIN NOW Smiling answered Hiawatha: END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the Dacotahs END
BEGIN NOW Lives the Arrow-maker's daughter, END
BEGIN NOW Handsomest of all the women. END
BEGIN NOW I will bring her to your wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW She shall run upon your errands, END
BEGIN NOW Be your starlight, moonlight, firelight, END
BEGIN NOW Be the sunlight of my people! END
BEGIN NOW Still dissuading said Nokomis: END
BEGIN NOW Bring not to my lodge a stranger END
BEGIN NOW From the land of the Dacotahs! END
BEGIN NOW Very fierce are the Dacotahs, END
BEGIN NOW Often is there war between us, END
BEGIN NOW There are feuds yet unforgotten, END
BEGIN NOW Wounds that ache and still may open! END
BEGIN NOW Laughing answered Hiawatha: END
BEGIN NOW For that reason, if no other, END
BEGIN NOW Would I wed the fair Dacotah, END
BEGIN NOW That our tribes might be united, END
BEGIN NOW That old feuds might be forgotten, END
BEGIN NOW And old wounds be healed forever! END
BEGIN NOW Thus departed Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW To the land of the Dacotahs, END
BEGIN NOW To the land of handsome women; END
BEGIN NOW Striding over moor and meadow, END
BEGIN NOW Through interminable forests, END
BEGIN NOW Through uninterrupted silence. END
BEGIN NOW With his moccasins of magic, END
BEGIN NOW At each stride a mile he measured; END
BEGIN NOW Yet the way seemed long before him, END
BEGIN NOW And his heart outran his footsteps; END
BEGIN NOW And he journeyed without resting, END
BEGIN NOW Till he heard the cataract's laughter, END
BEGIN NOW Calling to him through the silence. END
BEGIN NOW Pleasant is the sound!" he murmured, END
BEGIN NOW Pleasant is the voice that calls me! END
BEGIN NOW On the outskirts of the forests, END
BEGIN NOW 'Twixt the shadow and the sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW Herds of fallow deer were feeding, END
BEGIN NOW But they saw not Hiawatha; END
BEGIN NOW To his bow he whispered, "Fail not! END
BEGIN NOW To his arrow whispered, "Swerve not! END
BEGIN NOW Sent it singing on its errand, END
BEGIN NOW To the red heart of the roebuck; END
BEGIN NOW Threw the deer across his shoulder, END
BEGIN NOW And sped forward without pausing. END
BEGIN NOW At the doorway of his wigwam END
BEGIN NOW Sat the ancient Arrow-maker, END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the Dacotahs, END
BEGIN NOW Making arrow-heads of jasper, END
BEGIN NOW Arrow-heads of chalcedony. END
BEGIN NOW At his side, in all her beauty, END
BEGIN NOW Sat the lovely Minnehaha, END
BEGIN NOW Sat his daughter, Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW Plaiting mats of flags and rushes END
BEGIN NOW Of the past the old man's thoughts were, END
BEGIN NOW And the maiden's of the future. END
BEGIN NOW He was thinking, as he sat there, END
BEGIN NOW Of the days when with such arrows END
BEGIN NOW He had struck the deer and bison, END
BEGIN NOW On the Muskoday, the meadow; END
BEGIN NOW Shot the wild goose, flying southward END
BEGIN NOW On the wing, the clamorous Wawa; END
BEGIN NOW Thinking of the great war-parties, END
BEGIN NOW How they came to buy his arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Could not fight without his arrows. END
BEGIN NOW Ah, no more such noble warriors END
BEGIN NOW Could be found on earth as they were! END
BEGIN NOW Now the men were all like women, END
BEGIN NOW Only used their tongues for weapons! END
BEGIN NOW She was thinking of a hunter, END
BEGIN NOW From another tribe and country, END
BEGIN NOW Young and tall and very handsome, END
BEGIN NOW Who one morning, in the Spring-time, END
BEGIN NOW Came to buy her father's arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Sat and rested in the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Lingered long about the doorway, END
BEGIN NOW Looking back as he departed. END
BEGIN NOW She had heard her father praise him, END
BEGIN NOW Praise his courage and his wisdom; END
BEGIN NOW Would he come again for arrows END
BEGIN NOW On the mat her hands lay idle, END
BEGIN NOW And her eyes were very dreamy. END
BEGIN NOW Through their thoughts they heard a footstep, END
BEGIN NOW Heard a rustling in the branches, END
BEGIN NOW And with glowing cheek and forehead, END
BEGIN NOW With the deer upon his shoulders, END
BEGIN NOW Suddenly from out the woodlands END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha stood before them. END
BEGIN NOW Straight the ancient Arrow-maker END
BEGIN NOW Looked up gravely from his labor, END
BEGIN NOW Laid aside the unfinished arrow, END
BEGIN NOW Bade him enter at the doorway, END
BEGIN NOW Saying, as he rose to meet him, END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha, you are welcome! END
BEGIN NOW At the feet of Laughing Water END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha laid his burden, END
BEGIN NOW Threw the red deer from his shoulders; END
BEGIN NOW And the maiden looked up at him, END
BEGIN NOW Looked up from her mat of rushes, END
BEGIN NOW Said with gentle look and accent, END
BEGIN NOW You are welcome, Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Very spacious was the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Made of deer-skins dressed and whitened, END
BEGIN NOW Drawn and painted on its curtains, END
BEGIN NOW And so tall the doorway, hardly END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha stooped to enter, END
BEGIN NOW Hardly touched his eagle-feathers END
BEGIN NOW As he entered at the doorway. END
BEGIN NOW Then uprose the Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW From the ground fair Minnehaha, END
BEGIN NOW Laid aside her mat unfinished, END
BEGIN NOW Brought forth food and set before them, END
BEGIN NOW Water brought them from the brooklet, END
BEGIN NOW Gave them food in earthen vessels, END
BEGIN NOW Gave them drink in bowls of bass-wood, END
BEGIN NOW Listened while the guest was speaking, END
BEGIN NOW Listened while her father answered, END
BEGIN NOW But not once her lips she opened, END
BEGIN NOW Not a single word she uttered. END
BEGIN NOW Yes, as in a dream she listened END
BEGIN NOW To the words of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW As he talked of old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Who had nursed him in his childhood, END
BEGIN NOW As he told of his companions, END
BEGIN NOW Chibiabos, the musician, END
BEGIN NOW And the very strong man, Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW And of happiness and plenty END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the Ojibways, END
BEGIN NOW In the pleasant land and peaceful. END
BEGIN NOW After many years of warfare, END
BEGIN NOW Many years of strife and bloodshed, END
BEGIN NOW There is peace between the Ojibways END
BEGIN NOW And the tribe of the Dacotahs. END
BEGIN NOW Thus continued Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW And then added, speaking slowly, END
BEGIN NOW That this peace may last forever, END
BEGIN NOW And our hands be clasped more closely, END
BEGIN NOW And our hearts be more united, END
BEGIN NOW Give me as my wife this maiden, END
BEGIN NOW Loveliest of Dacotah women! END
BEGIN NOW And the ancient Arrow-maker END
BEGIN NOW Paused a moment ere he answered, END
BEGIN NOW Smoked a little while in silence, END
BEGIN NOW Looked at Hiawatha proudly, END
BEGIN NOW Fondly looked at Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW And made answer very gravely: END
BEGIN NOW Yes, if Minnehaha wishes; END
BEGIN NOW Let your heart speak, Minnehaha! END
BEGIN NOW And the lovely Laughing Water END
BEGIN NOW Seemed more lovely as she stood there, END
BEGIN NOW Neither willing nor reluctant, END
BEGIN NOW As she went to Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Softly took the seat beside him, END
BEGIN NOW While she said, and blushed to say it, END
BEGIN NOW I will follow you, my husband! END
BEGIN NOW This was Hiawatha's wooing! END
BEGIN NOW Thus it was he won the daughter END
BEGIN NOW Of the ancient Arrow-maker, END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the Dacotahs! END
BEGIN NOW From the wigwam he departed, END
BEGIN NOW Leading with him Laughing Water; END
BEGIN NOW Hand in hand they went together, END
BEGIN NOW Through the woodland and the meadow, END
BEGIN NOW Left the old man standing lonely END
BEGIN NOW At the doorway of his wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Calling to them from the distance, END
BEGIN NOW Crying to them from afar off, END
BEGIN NOW Fare thee well, O Minnehaha! END
BEGIN NOW And the ancient Arrow-maker END
BEGIN NOW Turned again unto his labor, END
BEGIN NOW Sat down by his sunny doorway, END
BEGIN NOW Murmuring to himself, and saying: END
BEGIN NOW Thus it is our daughters leave us, END
BEGIN NOW Those we love, and those who love us! END
BEGIN NOW Just when they have learned to help us, END
BEGIN NOW When we are old and lean upon them, END
BEGIN NOW Comes a youth with flaunting feathers, END
BEGIN NOW With his flute of reeds, a stranger END
BEGIN NOW Wanders piping through the village, END
BEGIN NOW Beckons to the fairest maiden, END
BEGIN NOW And she follows where he leads her, END
BEGIN NOW Leaving all things for the stranger! END
BEGIN NOW Pleasant was the journey homeward, END
BEGIN NOW Through interminable forests, END
BEGIN NOW Over meadow, over mountain, END
BEGIN NOW Over river, hill, and hollow. END
BEGIN NOW Short it seemed to Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Though they journeyed very slowly, END
BEGIN NOW Though his pace he checked and slackened END
BEGIN NOW To the steps of Laughing Water. END
BEGIN NOW Over wide and rushing rivers END
BEGIN NOW In his arms he bore the maiden; END
BEGIN NOW Light he thought her as a feather, END
BEGIN NOW As the plume upon his head-gear; END
BEGIN NOW Cleared the tangled pathway for her, END
BEGIN NOW Bent aside the swaying branches, END
BEGIN NOW Made at night a lodge of branches, END
BEGIN NOW And a bed with boughs of hemlock, END
BEGIN NOW And a fire before the doorway END
BEGIN NOW With the dry cones of the pine-tree. END
BEGIN NOW All the travelling winds went with them, END
BEGIN NOW O'er the meadows, through the forest; END
BEGIN NOW All the stars of night looked at them, END
BEGIN NOW Watched with sleepless eyes their slumber; END
BEGIN NOW From his ambush in the oak-tree END
BEGIN NOW Peeped the squirrel, Adjidaumo, END
BEGIN NOW Watched with eager eyes the lovers; END
BEGIN NOW And the rabbit, the Wabasso, END
BEGIN NOW Scampered from the path before them, END
BEGIN NOW Peering, peeping from his burrow, END
BEGIN NOW Sat erect upon his haunches, END
BEGIN NOW Watched with curious eyes the lovers. END
BEGIN NOW Pleasant was the journey homeward! END
BEGIN NOW All the birds sang loud and sweetly END
BEGIN NOW Songs of happiness and heart's-ease; END
BEGIN NOW Sang the bluebird, the Owaissa, END
BEGIN NOW Happy are you, Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Having such a wife to love you! END
BEGIN NOW Sang the robin, the Opechee, END
BEGIN NOW Happy are you, Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW Having such a noble husband! END
BEGIN NOW From the sky the sun benignant END
BEGIN NOW Looked upon them through the branches, END
BEGIN NOW Saying to them, "O my children, END
BEGIN NOW Love is sunshine, hate is shadow, END
BEGIN NOW Life is checkered shade and sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW Rule by love, O Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW From the sky the moon looked at them, END
BEGIN NOW Filled the lodge with mystic splendors, END
BEGIN NOW Whispered to them, "O my children, END
BEGIN NOW Day is restless, night is quiet, END
BEGIN NOW Man imperious, woman feeble; END
BEGIN NOW Half is mine, although I follow; END
BEGIN NOW Rule by patience, Laughing Water! END
BEGIN NOW Thus it was they journeyed homeward; END
BEGIN NOW Thus it was that Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW To the lodge of old Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Brought the moonlight, starlight, firelight, END
BEGIN NOW Brought the sunshine of his people, END
BEGIN NOW Handsomest of all the women END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the Dacotahs, END
BEGIN NOW In the land of handsome women. END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha's Wedding-Feast END
BEGIN NOW You shall hear how Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW How the handsome Yenadizze END
BEGIN NOW Danced at Hiawatha's wedding; END
BEGIN NOW How the gentle Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW He the sweetest of musicians, END
BEGIN NOW Sang his songs of love and longing; END
BEGIN NOW How Iagoo, the great boaster, END
BEGIN NOW He the marvellous story-teller, END
BEGIN NOW Told his tales of strange adventure, END
BEGIN NOW That the feast might be more joyous, END
BEGIN NOW That the time might pass more gayly, END
BEGIN NOW And the guests be more contented. END
BEGIN NOW Sumptuous was the feast Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Made at Hiawatha's wedding; END
BEGIN NOW All the bowls were made of bass-wood, END
BEGIN NOW White and polished very smoothly, END
BEGIN NOW All the spoons of horn of bison, END
BEGIN NOW Black and polished very smoothly. END
BEGIN NOW She had sent through all the village END
BEGIN NOW Messengers with wands of willow, END
BEGIN NOW As a sign of invitation, END
BEGIN NOW As a token of the feasting; END
BEGIN NOW And the wedding guests assembled, END
BEGIN NOW Clad in all their richest raiment, END
BEGIN NOW Robes of fur and belts of wampum, END
BEGIN NOW Splendid with their paint and plumage, END
BEGIN NOW Beautiful with beads and tassels. END
BEGIN NOW First they ate the sturgeon, Nahma, END
BEGIN NOW And the pike, the Maskenozha, END
BEGIN NOW Caught and cooked by old Nokomis; END
BEGIN NOW Then on pemican they feasted, END
BEGIN NOW Pemican and buffalo marrow, END
BEGIN NOW Haunch of deer and hump of bison, END
BEGIN NOW Yellow cakes of the Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW And the wild rice of the river. END
BEGIN NOW But the gracious Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW And the lovely Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW And the careful old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Tasted not the food before them, END
BEGIN NOW Only waited on the others END
BEGIN NOW Only served their guests in silence. END
BEGIN NOW And when all the guests had finished, END
BEGIN NOW Old Nokomis, brisk and busy, END
BEGIN NOW From an ample pouch of otter, END
BEGIN NOW Filled the red-stone pipes for smoking END
BEGIN NOW With tobacco from the South-land, END
BEGIN NOW Mixed with bark of the red willow, END
BEGIN NOW And with herbs and leaves of fragrance. END
BEGIN NOW Then she said, "O Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Dance for us your merry dances, END
BEGIN NOW Dance the Beggar's Dance to please us, END
BEGIN NOW That the feast may be more joyous, END
BEGIN NOW That the time may pass more gayly, END
BEGIN NOW And our guests be more contented! END
BEGIN NOW Then the handsome Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW He the idle Yenadizze, END
BEGIN NOW He the merry mischief-maker, END
BEGIN NOW Whom the people called the Storm-Fool, END
BEGIN NOW Rose among the guests assembled. END
BEGIN NOW Skilled was he in sports and pastimes, END
BEGIN NOW In the merry dance of snow-shoes, END
BEGIN NOW In the play of quoits and ball-play; END
BEGIN NOW Skilled was he in games of hazard, END
BEGIN NOW In all games of skill and hazard, END
BEGIN NOW Kuntassoo, the Game of Plum-stones. END
BEGIN NOW Though the warriors called him Faint-Heart, END
BEGIN NOW Called him coward, Shaugodaya, END
BEGIN NOW Idler, gambler, Yenadizze, END
BEGIN NOW Little heeded he their jesting, END
BEGIN NOW Little cared he for their insults, END
BEGIN NOW For the women and the maidens END
BEGIN NOW Loved the handsome Pau-Puk-Keewis. END
BEGIN NOW He was dressed in shirt of doeskin, END
BEGIN NOW White and soft, and fringed with ermine, END
BEGIN NOW All inwrought with beads of wampum; END
BEGIN NOW He was dressed in deer-skin leggings, END
BEGIN NOW Fringed with hedgehog quills and ermine, END
BEGIN NOW And in moccasins of buck-skin, END
BEGIN NOW Thick with quills and beads embroidered. END
BEGIN NOW On his head were plumes of swan's down, END
BEGIN NOW On his heels were tails of foxes, END
BEGIN NOW In one hand a fan of feathers, END
BEGIN NOW And a pipe was in the other. END
BEGIN NOW Barred with streaks of red and yellow, END
BEGIN NOW Streaks of blue and bright vermilion, END
BEGIN NOW Shone the face of Pau-Puk-Keewis. END
BEGIN NOW From his forehead fell his tresses, END
BEGIN NOW Smooth, and parted like a woman's, END
BEGIN NOW Shining bright with oil, and plaited, END
BEGIN NOW Hung with braids of scented grasses, END
BEGIN NOW As among the guests assembled, END
BEGIN NOW To the sound of flutes and singing, END
BEGIN NOW To the sound of drums and voices, END
BEGIN NOW Rose the handsome Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW And began his mystic dances. END
BEGIN NOW First he danced a solemn measure, END
BEGIN NOW Very slow in step and gesture, END
BEGIN NOW In and out among the pine-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Through the shadows and the sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW Treading softly like a panther. END
BEGIN NOW Then more swiftly and still swifter, END
BEGIN NOW Whirling, spinning round in circles, END
BEGIN NOW Leaping o'er the guests assembled, END
BEGIN NOW Eddying round and round the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Till the leaves went whirling with him, END
BEGIN NOW Till the dust and wind together END
BEGIN NOW Swept in eddies round about him. END
BEGIN NOW Then along the sandy margin END
BEGIN NOW Of the lake, the Big-Sea-Water, END
BEGIN NOW On he sped with frenzied gestures, END
BEGIN NOW Stamped upon the sand, and tossed it END
BEGIN NOW Wildly in the air around him; END
BEGIN NOW Till the wind became a whirlwind, END
BEGIN NOW Till the sand was blown and sifted END
BEGIN NOW Like great snowdrifts o'er the landscape, END
BEGIN NOW Heaping all the shores with Sand Dunes, END
BEGIN NOW Thus the merry Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Danced his Beggar's Dance to please them, END
BEGIN NOW And, returning, sat down laughing END
BEGIN NOW There among the guests assembled, END
BEGIN NOW Sat and fanned himself serenely END
BEGIN NOW With his fan of turkey-feathers. END
BEGIN NOW Then they said to Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW To the friend of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW To the sweetest of all singers, END
BEGIN NOW To the best of all musicians, END
BEGIN NOW Songs of love and songs of longing, END
BEGIN NOW That the feast may be more joyous, END
BEGIN NOW That the time may pass more gayly, END
BEGIN NOW And our guests be more contented! END
BEGIN NOW And the gentle Chibiabos END
BEGIN NOW Sang in accents sweet and tender, END
BEGIN NOW Sang in tones of deep emotion, END
BEGIN NOW Songs of love and songs of longing; END
BEGIN NOW Looking still at Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Looking at fair Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW Sang he softly, sang in this wise: END
BEGIN NOW Onaway! Awake, beloved! END
BEGIN NOW Thou the wild-flower of the forest! END
BEGIN NOW Thou the wild-bird of the prairie! END
BEGIN NOW Thou with eyes so soft and fawn-like! END
BEGIN NOW If thou only lookest at me, END
BEGIN NOW I am happy, I am happy, END
BEGIN NOW As the lilies of the prairie, END
BEGIN NOW When they feel the dew upon them! END
BEGIN NOW Sweet thy breath is as the fragrance END
BEGIN NOW Of the wild-flowers in the morning, END
BEGIN NOW As their fragrance is at evening, END
BEGIN NOW In the Moon when leaves are falling. END
BEGIN NOW Does not all the blood within me END
BEGIN NOW Leap to meet thee, leap to meet thee, END
BEGIN NOW As the springs to meet the sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW In the Moon when nights are brightest? END
BEGIN NOW Onaway! my heart sings to thee, END
BEGIN NOW Sings with joy when thou art near me, END
BEGIN NOW As the sighing, singing branches END
BEGIN NOW In the pleasant Moon of Strawberries! END
BEGIN NOW When thou art not pleased, beloved, END
BEGIN NOW Then my heart is sad and darkened, END
BEGIN NOW As the shining river darkens END
BEGIN NOW When the clouds drop shadows on it! END
BEGIN NOW When thou smilest, my beloved, END
BEGIN NOW Then my troubled heart is brightened, END
BEGIN NOW As in sunshine gleam the ripples END
BEGIN NOW That the cold wind makes in rivers. END
BEGIN NOW Smiles the earth, and smile the waters, END
BEGIN NOW Smile the cloudless skies above us, END
BEGIN NOW But I lose the way of smiling END
BEGIN NOW When thou art no longer near me! END
BEGIN NOW I myself, myself! behold me! END
BEGIN NOW Blood of my beating heart, behold me! END
BEGIN NOW Oh awake, awake, beloved! END
BEGIN NOW Onaway! awake, beloved! END
BEGIN NOW Thus the gentle Chibiabos END
BEGIN NOW Sang his song of love and longing; END
BEGIN NOW And Iagoo, the great boaster, END
BEGIN NOW He the marvellous story-teller, END
BEGIN NOW He the friend of old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Jealous of the sweet musician, END
BEGIN NOW Jealous of the applause they gave him, END
BEGIN NOW Saw in all the eyes around him, END
BEGIN NOW Saw in all their looks and gestures, END
BEGIN NOW That the wedding guests assembled END
BEGIN NOW Longed to hear his pleasant stories, END
BEGIN NOW His immeasurable falsehoods. END
BEGIN NOW Very boastful was Iagoo; END
BEGIN NOW Never heard he an adventure END
BEGIN NOW But himself had met a greater; END
BEGIN NOW Never any deed of daring END
BEGIN NOW But himself had done a bolder; END
BEGIN NOW Never any marvellous story END
BEGIN NOW But himself could tell a stranger. END
BEGIN NOW Would you listen to his boasting, END
BEGIN NOW Would you only give him credence, END
BEGIN NOW No one ever shot an arrow END
BEGIN NOW Half so far and high as he had; END
BEGIN NOW Ever caught so many fishes, END
BEGIN NOW Ever killed so many reindeer, END
BEGIN NOW Ever trapped so many beaver! END
BEGIN NOW None could run so fast as he could, END
BEGIN NOW None could dive so deep as he could, END
BEGIN NOW None could swim so far as he could; END
BEGIN NOW None had made so many journeys, END
BEGIN NOW None had seen so many wonders, END
BEGIN NOW As this wonderful Iagoo, END
BEGIN NOW As this marvellous story-teller! END
BEGIN NOW Thus his name became a by-word END
BEGIN NOW And a jest among the people; END
BEGIN NOW And whene'er a boastful hunter END
BEGIN NOW Praised his own address too highly, END
BEGIN NOW Or a warrior, home returning, END
BEGIN NOW Talked too much of his achievements, END
BEGIN NOW All his hearers cried, Iagoo! END
BEGIN NOW Here's Iagoo come among us! END
BEGIN NOW He it was who carved the cradle END
BEGIN NOW Of the little Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Carved its framework out of linden, END
BEGIN NOW Bound it strong with reindeer sinews; END
BEGIN NOW He it was who taught him later END
BEGIN NOW How to make his bows and arrows, END
BEGIN NOW How to make the bows of ash-tree, END
BEGIN NOW And the arrows of the oak-tree. END
BEGIN NOW So among the guests assembled END
BEGIN NOW At my Hiawatha's wedding END
BEGIN NOW Sat Iagoo, old and ugly, END
BEGIN NOW Sat the marvellous story-teller. END
BEGIN NOW And they said, "O good Iagoo, END
BEGIN NOW Tell us now a tale of wonder, END
BEGIN NOW Tell us of some strange adventure, END
BEGIN NOW That the feast may be more joyous, END
BEGIN NOW That the time may pass more gayly, END
BEGIN NOW And our guests be more contented! END
BEGIN NOW And Iagoo answered straightway, END
BEGIN NOW You shall hear a tale of wonder, END
BEGIN NOW You shall hear the strange adventures END
BEGIN NOW From the Evening Star descending. END
BEGIN NOW Can it be the sun descending END
BEGIN NOW O'er the level plain of water? END
BEGIN NOW Or the Red Swan floating, flying, END
BEGIN NOW Wounded by the magic arrow, END
BEGIN NOW Staining all the waves with crimson, END
BEGIN NOW With the crimson of its life-blood, END
BEGIN NOW Filling all the air with splendor, END
BEGIN NOW With the splendor of its plumage? END
BEGIN NOW Yes; it is the sun descending, END
BEGIN NOW Sinking down into the water; END
BEGIN NOW All the sky is stained with purple, END
BEGIN NOW All the water flushed with crimson! END
BEGIN NOW No; it is the Red Swan floating, END
BEGIN NOW Diving down beneath the water; END
BEGIN NOW To the sky its wings are lifted, END
BEGIN NOW With its blood the waves are reddened! END
BEGIN NOW Melts and trembles through the purple, END
BEGIN NOW Hangs suspended in the twilight. END
BEGIN NOW No; it is a bead of wampum END
BEGIN NOW On the robes of the Great Spirit END
BEGIN NOW As he passes through the twilight, END
BEGIN NOW Walks in silence through the heavens. END
BEGIN NOW This with joy beheld Iagoo END
BEGIN NOW And he said in haste: "Behold it! END
BEGIN NOW See the sacred Star of Evening! END
BEGIN NOW You shall hear a tale of wonder, END
BEGIN NOW Hear the story of Osseo, END
BEGIN NOW Once, in days no more remembered, END
BEGIN NOW Ages nearer the beginning, END
BEGIN NOW When the heavens were closer to us, END
BEGIN NOW And the Gods were more familiar, END
BEGIN NOW In the North-land lived a hunter, END
BEGIN NOW With ten young and comely daughters, END
BEGIN NOW Tall and lithe as wands of willow; END
BEGIN NOW Only Oweenee, the youngest, END
BEGIN NOW She the wilful and the wayward, END
BEGIN NOW She the silent, dreamy maiden, END
BEGIN NOW Was the fairest of the sisters. END
BEGIN NOW All these women married warriors, END
BEGIN NOW Married brave and haughty husbands; END
BEGIN NOW Only Oweenee, the youngest, END
BEGIN NOW Laughed and flouted all her lovers, END
BEGIN NOW All her young and handsome suitors, END
BEGIN NOW And then married old Osseo, END
BEGIN NOW Old Osseo, poor and ugly, END
BEGIN NOW Broken with age and weak with coughing, END
BEGIN NOW Always coughing like a squirrel. END
BEGIN NOW Ah, but beautiful within him END
BEGIN NOW Was the spirit of Osseo, END
BEGIN NOW From the Evening Star descended, END
BEGIN NOW Star of tenderness and passion! END
BEGIN NOW All its fire was in his bosom, END
BEGIN NOW All its beauty in his spirit, END
BEGIN NOW All its mystery in his being, END
BEGIN NOW All its splendor in his language! END
BEGIN NOW And her lovers, the rejected, END
BEGIN NOW Handsome men with belts of wampum, END
BEGIN NOW Handsome men with paint and feathers. END
BEGIN NOW Pointed at her in derision, END
BEGIN NOW Followed her with jest and laughter. END
BEGIN NOW But she said: 'I care not for you, END
BEGIN NOW Care not for your belts of wampum, END
BEGIN NOW Care not for your paint and feathers, END
BEGIN NOW Care not for your jests and laughter; END
BEGIN NOW I am happy with Osseo!' END
BEGIN NOW Once to some great feast invited, END
BEGIN NOW Through the damp and dusk of evening, END
BEGIN NOW Walked together the ten sisters, END
BEGIN NOW Walked together with their husbands; END
BEGIN NOW Slowly followed old Osseo, END
BEGIN NOW With fair Oweenee beside him; END
BEGIN NOW All the others chatted gayly, END
BEGIN NOW These two only walked in silence. END
BEGIN NOW At the western sky Osseo END
BEGIN NOW Gazed intent, as if imploring, END
BEGIN NOW Often stopped and gazed imploring END
BEGIN NOW At the trembling Star of Evening, END
BEGIN NOW At the tender Star of Woman; END
BEGIN NOW And they heard him murmur softly, END
BEGIN NOW 'Ah, showain nemeshin, Nosa! END
BEGIN NOW Pity, pity me, my father!' END
BEGIN NOW 'Listen!' said the eldest sister, END
BEGIN NOW 'He is praying to his father! END
BEGIN NOW What a pity that the old man END
BEGIN NOW Does not stumble in the pathway, END
BEGIN NOW Does not break his neck by falling!' END
BEGIN NOW And they laughed till all the forest END
BEGIN NOW Rang with their unseemly laughter. END
BEGIN NOW On their pathway through the woodlands END
BEGIN NOW Lay an oak, by storms uprooted, END
BEGIN NOW Lay the great trunk of an oak-tree, END
BEGIN NOW Buried half in leaves and mosses, END
BEGIN NOW Mouldering, crumbling, huge and hollow. END
BEGIN NOW And Osseo, when he saw it, END
BEGIN NOW Gave a shout, a cry of anguish, END
BEGIN NOW Leaped into its yawning cavern, END
BEGIN NOW At one end went in an old man, END
BEGIN NOW Wasted, wrinkled, old, and ugly; END
BEGIN NOW From the other came a young man, END
BEGIN NOW Tall and straight and strong and handsome. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Osseo was transfigured, END
BEGIN NOW Thus restored to youth and beauty; END
BEGIN NOW But, alas for good Osseo, END
BEGIN NOW And for Oweenee, the faithful! END
BEGIN NOW Strangely, too, was she transfigured. END
BEGIN NOW Changed into a weak old woman, END
BEGIN NOW With a staff she tottered onward, END
BEGIN NOW Wasted, wrinkled, old, and ugly! END
BEGIN NOW And the sisters and their husbands END
BEGIN NOW Laughed until the echoing forest END
BEGIN NOW Rang with their unseemly laughter. END
BEGIN NOW But Osseo turned not from her, END
BEGIN NOW Walked with slower step beside her, END
BEGIN NOW Took her hand, as brown and withered END
BEGIN NOW As an oak-leaf is in Winter, END
BEGIN NOW Called her sweetheart, Nenemoosha, END
BEGIN NOW Soothed her with soft words of kindness, END
BEGIN NOW Till they reached the lodge of feasting, END
BEGIN NOW Till they sat down in the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW To the tender Star of Woman. END
BEGIN NOW Wrapt in visions, lost in dreaming, END
BEGIN NOW At the banquet sat Osseo; END
BEGIN NOW All were merry, all were happy, END
BEGIN NOW All were joyous but Osseo. END
BEGIN NOW Neither food nor drink he tasted, END
BEGIN NOW Neither did he speak nor listen; END
BEGIN NOW But as one bewildered sat he, END
BEGIN NOW Looking dreamily and sadly, END
BEGIN NOW First at Oweenee, then upward END
BEGIN NOW At the gleaming sky above them. END
BEGIN NOW Then a voice was heard, a whisper, END
BEGIN NOW Coming from the starry distance, END
BEGIN NOW Coming from the empty vastness, END
BEGIN NOW Low, and musical, and tender; END
BEGIN NOW And the voice said: 'O Osseo! END
BEGIN NOW O my son, my best beloved! END
BEGIN NOW Broken are the spells that bound you, END
BEGIN NOW All the charms of the magicians, END
BEGIN NOW All the magic powers of evil; END
BEGIN NOW Come to me; ascend, Osseo! END
BEGIN NOW 'Taste the food that stands before you: END
BEGIN NOW It is blessed and enchanted, END
BEGIN NOW It has magic virtues in it, END
BEGIN NOW It will change you to a spirit. END
BEGIN NOW All your bowls and all your kettles END
BEGIN NOW Shall be wood and clay no longer; END
BEGIN NOW But the bowls be changed to wampum, END
BEGIN NOW And the kettles shall be silver; END
BEGIN NOW They shall shine like shells of scarlet, END
BEGIN NOW Like the fire shall gleam and glimmer. END
BEGIN NOW 'And the women shall no longer END
BEGIN NOW Bear the dreary doom of labor, END
BEGIN NOW But be changed to birds, and glisten END
BEGIN NOW With the beauty of the starlight, END
BEGIN NOW Painted with the dusky splendors END
BEGIN NOW Of the skies and clouds of evening!' END
BEGIN NOW What Osseo heard as whispers, END
BEGIN NOW What as words he comprehended, END
BEGIN NOW Was but music to the others, END
BEGIN NOW Music as of birds afar off, END
BEGIN NOW Of the whippoorwill afar off, END
BEGIN NOW Of the lonely Wawonaissa END
BEGIN NOW Singing in the darksome forest. END
BEGIN NOW Then the lodge began to tremble, END
BEGIN NOW Straight began to shake and tremble, END
BEGIN NOW And they felt it rising, rising, END
BEGIN NOW Slowly through the air ascending, END
BEGIN NOW From the darkness of the tree-tops END
BEGIN NOW Forth into the dewy starlight, END
BEGIN NOW Till it passed the topmost branches; END
BEGIN NOW And behold! the wooden dishes END
BEGIN NOW All were changed to shells of scarlet! END
BEGIN NOW And behold! the earthen kettles END
BEGIN NOW All were changed to bowls of silver! END
BEGIN NOW And the roof-poles of the wigwam END
BEGIN NOW Were as glittering rods of silver, END
BEGIN NOW And the roof of bark upon them END
BEGIN NOW As the shining shards of beetles. END
BEGIN NOW Then Osseo gazed around him, END
BEGIN NOW And he saw the nine fair sisters, END
BEGIN NOW All the sisters and their husbands, END
BEGIN NOW Changed to birds of various plumage. END
BEGIN NOW Some were jays and some were magpies, END
BEGIN NOW Others thrushes, others blackbirds; END
BEGIN NOW And they hopped, and sang, and twittered, END
BEGIN NOW Perked and fluttered all their feathers, END
BEGIN NOW Strutted in their shining plumage, END
BEGIN NOW And their tails like fans unfolded. END
BEGIN NOW Only Oweenee, the youngest, END
BEGIN NOW Was not changed, but sat in silence, END
BEGIN NOW Wasted, wrinkled, old, and ugly, END
BEGIN NOW Looking sadly at the others; END
BEGIN NOW Till Osseo, gazing upward, END
BEGIN NOW Gave another cry of anguish, END
BEGIN NOW Such a cry as he had uttered END
BEGIN NOW By the oak-tree in the forest. END
BEGIN NOW Then returned her youth and beauty, END
BEGIN NOW And her soiled and tattered garments END
BEGIN NOW Were transformed to robes of ermine, END
BEGIN NOW And her staff became a feather, END
BEGIN NOW Yes, a shining silver feather! END
BEGIN NOW And again the wigwam trembled, END
BEGIN NOW Swayed and rushed through airy currents, END
BEGIN NOW Through transparent cloud and vapor, END
BEGIN NOW And amid celestial splendors END
BEGIN NOW On the Evening Star alighted, END
BEGIN NOW As a snow-flake falls on snow-flake, END
BEGIN NOW As a leaf drops on a river, END
BEGIN NOW As the thistledown on water. END
BEGIN NOW Forth with cheerful words of welcome END
BEGIN NOW Came the father of Osseo, END
BEGIN NOW He with radiant locks of silver, END
BEGIN NOW He with eyes serene and tender. END
BEGIN NOW And he said: `My son, Osseo, END
BEGIN NOW Hang the cage of birds you bring there, END
BEGIN NOW Hang the cage with rods of silver, END
BEGIN NOW And the birds with glistening feathers, END
BEGIN NOW At the doorway of my wigwam.' END
BEGIN NOW At the door he hung the bird-cage, END
BEGIN NOW And they entered in and gladly END
BEGIN NOW Listened to Osseo's father, END
BEGIN NOW As he said: `O my Osseo! END
BEGIN NOW I have had compassion on you, END
BEGIN NOW Given you back your youth and beauty, END
BEGIN NOW Into birds of various plumage END
BEGIN NOW Changed your sisters and their husbands; END
BEGIN NOW Changed them thus because they mocked you END
BEGIN NOW In the figure of the old man, END
BEGIN NOW In that aspect sad and wrinkled, END
BEGIN NOW Could not see your heart of passion, END
BEGIN NOW Could not see your youth immortal; END
BEGIN NOW Only Oweenee, the faithful, END
BEGIN NOW Saw your naked heart and loved you. END
BEGIN NOW `In the lodge that glimmers yonder, END
BEGIN NOW In the little star that twinkles END
BEGIN NOW Through the vapors, on the left hand, END
BEGIN NOW Lives the envious Evil Spirit, END
BEGIN NOW The Wabeno, the magician, END
BEGIN NOW Who transformed you to an old man. END
BEGIN NOW Take heed lest his beams fall on you, END
BEGIN NOW For the rays he darts around him END
BEGIN NOW Are the power of his enchantment, END
BEGIN NOW Are the arrows that he uses.' END
BEGIN NOW Many years, in peace and quiet, END
BEGIN NOW On the peaceful Star of Evening END
BEGIN NOW Dwelt Osseo with his father; END
BEGIN NOW Many years, in song and flutter, END
BEGIN NOW At the doorway of the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Hung the cage with rods of silver, END
BEGIN NOW And fair Oweenee, the faithful, END
BEGIN NOW Bore a son unto Osseo, END
BEGIN NOW With the beauty of his mother, END
BEGIN NOW With the courage of his father. END
BEGIN NOW And the boy grew up and prospered, END
BEGIN NOW And Osseo, to delight him, END
BEGIN NOW Made him little bows and arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Opened the great cage of silver, END
BEGIN NOW And let loose his aunts and uncles, END
BEGIN NOW All those birds with glossy feathers, END
BEGIN NOW For his little son to shoot at. END
BEGIN NOW Round and round they wheeled and darted, END
BEGIN NOW Filled the Evening Star with music, END
BEGIN NOW With their songs of joy and freedom END
BEGIN NOW Filled the Evening Star with splendor, END
BEGIN NOW With the fluttering of their plumage; END
BEGIN NOW Till the boy, the little hunter, END
BEGIN NOW Bent his bow and shot an arrow, END
BEGIN NOW Shot a swift and fatal arrow, END
BEGIN NOW And a bird, with shining feathers, END
BEGIN NOW At his feet fell wounded sorely. END
BEGIN NOW But, O wondrous transformation! END
BEGIN NOW `T was no bird he saw before him, END
BEGIN NOW `T was a beautiful young woman, END
BEGIN NOW With the arrow in her bosom! END
BEGIN NOW When her blood fell on the planet, END
BEGIN NOW On the sacred Star of Evening, END
BEGIN NOW Broken was the spell of magic, END
BEGIN NOW Powerless was the strange enchantment, END
BEGIN NOW And the youth, the fearless bowman, END
BEGIN NOW Suddenly felt himself descending, END
BEGIN NOW Held by unseen hands, but sinking END
BEGIN NOW Downward through the empty spaces, END
BEGIN NOW Downward through the clouds and vapors, END
BEGIN NOW Till he rested on an island, END
BEGIN NOW On an island, green and grassy, END
BEGIN NOW After him he saw descending END
BEGIN NOW All the birds with shining feathers, END
BEGIN NOW Fluttering, falling, wafted downward, END
BEGIN NOW Like the painted leaves of Autumn; END
BEGIN NOW And the lodge with poles of silver, END
BEGIN NOW With its roof like wings of beetles, END
BEGIN NOW Like the shining shards of beetles, END
BEGIN NOW By the winds of heaven uplifted, END
BEGIN NOW Slowly sank upon the island, END
BEGIN NOW Bringing back the good Osseo, END
BEGIN NOW Bringing Oweenee, the faithful. END
BEGIN NOW Then the birds, again transfigured, END
BEGIN NOW Reassumed the shape of mortals, END
BEGIN NOW Took their shape, but not their stature; END
BEGIN NOW They remained as Little People, END
BEGIN NOW Like the pygmies, the Puk-Wudjies, END
BEGIN NOW And on pleasant nights of Summer, END
BEGIN NOW When the Evening Star was shining, END
BEGIN NOW Hand in hand they danced together END
BEGIN NOW On the island's craggy headlands, END
BEGIN NOW On the sand-beach low and level. END
BEGIN NOW Still their glittering lodge is seen there, END
BEGIN NOW On the tranquil Summer evenings, END
BEGIN NOW And upon the shore the fisher END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes hears their happy voices, END
BEGIN NOW Sees them dancing in the starlight ! END
BEGIN NOW When the story was completed, END
BEGIN NOW When the wondrous tale was ended, END
BEGIN NOW Looking round upon his listeners, END
BEGIN NOW Solemnly Iagoo added: END
BEGIN NOW There are great men, I have known such, END
BEGIN NOW Whom their people understand not, END
BEGIN NOW Whom they even make a jest of, END
BEGIN NOW Scoff and jeer at in derision. END
BEGIN NOW From the story of Osseo END
BEGIN NOW Let us learn the fate of jesters! END
BEGIN NOW All the wedding guests delighted END
BEGIN NOW Listened to the marvellous story, END
BEGIN NOW Listened laughing and applauding, END
BEGIN NOW And they whispered to each other: END
BEGIN NOW Does he mean himself, I wonder? END
BEGIN NOW And are we the aunts and uncles? END
BEGIN NOW Then again sang Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW Sang a song of love and longing, END
BEGIN NOW In those accents sweet and tender, END
BEGIN NOW In those tones of pensive sadness, END
BEGIN NOW Sang a maiden's lamentation END
BEGIN NOW For her lover, her Algonquin. END
BEGIN NOW When I think of my beloved, END
BEGIN NOW Ah me! think of my beloved, END
BEGIN NOW When my heart is thinking of him, END
BEGIN NOW O my sweetheart, my Algonquin! END
BEGIN NOW Ah me! when I parted from him, END
BEGIN NOW Round my neck he hung the wampum, END
BEGIN NOW As a pledge, the snow-white wampum, END
BEGIN NOW O my sweetheart, my Algonquin! END
BEGIN NOW 'I will go with you,' he whispered, END
BEGIN NOW 'Ah me! to your native country; END
BEGIN NOW Let me go with you,' he whispered, END
BEGIN NOW 'O my sweetheart, my Algonquin!' END
BEGIN NOW 'Far away, away,' I answered, END
BEGIN NOW 'Very far away,' I answered, END
BEGIN NOW 'Ah me! is my native country, END
BEGIN NOW O my sweetheart, my Algonquin!' END
BEGIN NOW When I looked back to behold him, END
BEGIN NOW Where we parted, to behold him, END
BEGIN NOW After me he still was gazing, END
BEGIN NOW O my sweetheart, my Algonquin! END
BEGIN NOW By the tree he still was standing, END
BEGIN NOW By the fallen tree was standing, END
BEGIN NOW That had dropped into the water, END
BEGIN NOW O my sweetheart, my Algonquin! END
BEGIN NOW When I think of my beloved, END
BEGIN NOW Ah me! think of my beloved, END
BEGIN NOW When my heart is thinking of him, END
BEGIN NOW O my sweetheart, my Algonquin! END
BEGIN NOW Such was Hiawatha's Wedding, END
BEGIN NOW Such the dance of Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Such the story of Iagoo, END
BEGIN NOW Such the songs of Chibiabos; END
BEGIN NOW Thus the wedding banquet ended, END
BEGIN NOW And the wedding guests departed, END
BEGIN NOW Leaving Hiawatha happy END
BEGIN NOW With the night and Minnehaha. END
BEGIN NOW Of the happy days that followed, END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the Ojibways, END
BEGIN NOW In the pleasant land and peaceful! END
BEGIN NOW Sing the mysteries of Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW Buried was the bloody hatchet, END
BEGIN NOW Buried was the dreadful war-club, END
BEGIN NOW Buried were all warlike weapons, END
BEGIN NOW And the war-cry was forgotten. END
BEGIN NOW There was peace among the nations; END
BEGIN NOW Unmolested roved the hunters, END
BEGIN NOW Built the birch canoe for sailing, END
BEGIN NOW Caught the fish in lake and river, END
BEGIN NOW Shot the deer and trapped the beaver; END
BEGIN NOW Unmolested worked the women, END
BEGIN NOW Made their sugar from the maple, END
BEGIN NOW Gathered wild rice in the meadows, END
BEGIN NOW Dressed the skins of deer and beaver. END
BEGIN NOW All around the happy village END
BEGIN NOW Stood the maize-fields, green and shining, END
BEGIN NOW Waved the green plumes of Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW Waved his soft and sunny tresses, END
BEGIN NOW Filling all the land with plenty. END
BEGIN NOW `T was the women who in Spring-time END
BEGIN NOW Planted the broad fields and fruitful, END
BEGIN NOW Buried in the earth Mondamin; END
BEGIN NOW `T was the women who in Autumn END
BEGIN NOW Stripped the yellow husks of harvest, END
BEGIN NOW Stripped the garments from Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW Even as Hiawatha taught them. END
BEGIN NOW Once, when all the maize was planted, END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha, wise and thoughtful, END
BEGIN NOW Spake and said to Minnehaha, END
BEGIN NOW To his wife, the Laughing Water: END
BEGIN NOW You shall bless to-night the cornfields, END
BEGIN NOW Draw a magic circle round them, END
BEGIN NOW To protect them from destruction, END
BEGIN NOW Blast of mildew, blight of insect, END
BEGIN NOW Wagemin, the thief of cornfields, END
BEGIN NOW Paimosaid, who steals the maize-ear. END
BEGIN NOW In the night, when all is silence, END
BEGIN NOW In the night, when all is darkness, END
BEGIN NOW Shuts the doors of all the wigwams, END
BEGIN NOW So that not an ear can hear you, END
BEGIN NOW So that not an eye can see you, END
BEGIN NOW Rise up from your bed in silence, END
BEGIN NOW Lay aside your garments wholly, END
BEGIN NOW Walk around the fields you planted, END
BEGIN NOW Round the borders of the cornfields, END
BEGIN NOW Covered by your tresses only, END
BEGIN NOW Robed with darkness as a garment. END
BEGIN NOW Thus the fields shall be more fruitful, END
BEGIN NOW And the passing of your footsteps END
BEGIN NOW Draw a magic circle round them, END
BEGIN NOW So that neither blight nor mildew, END
BEGIN NOW Neither burrowing worm nor insect, END
BEGIN NOW Shall pass o'er the magic circle; END
BEGIN NOW Not the dragon-fly, Kwo-ne-she, END
BEGIN NOW Nor the spider, Subbekashe, END
BEGIN NOW Nor the grasshopper, Pah-puk-keena; END
BEGIN NOW Nor the mighty caterpillar, END
BEGIN NOW Way-muk-kwana, with the bear-skin, END
BEGIN NOW King of all the caterpillars! END
BEGIN NOW On the tree-tops near the cornfields END
BEGIN NOW Sat the hungry crows and ravens, END
BEGIN NOW With his band of black marauders. END
BEGIN NOW And they laughed at Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Till the tree-tops shook with laughter, END
BEGIN NOW With their melancholy laughter, END
BEGIN NOW At the words of Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW Hear him!" said they; "hear the Wise Man, END
BEGIN NOW Hear the plots of Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW When the noiseless night descended END
BEGIN NOW Broad and dark o'er field and forest, END
BEGIN NOW When the mournful Wawonaissa END
BEGIN NOW Sorrowing sang among the hemlocks, END
BEGIN NOW Shut the doors of all the wigwams, END
BEGIN NOW From her bed rose Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW Laid aside her garments wholly, END
BEGIN NOW And with darkness clothed and guarded, END
BEGIN NOW Unashamed and unaffrighted, END
BEGIN NOW Walked securely round the cornfields, END
BEGIN NOW Drew the sacred, magic circle END
BEGIN NOW Of her footprints round the cornfields. END
BEGIN NOW No one but the Midnight only END
BEGIN NOW Saw her beauty in the darkness, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the panting of her bosom END
BEGIN NOW Guskewau, the darkness, wrapped her END
BEGIN NOW Closely in his sacred mantle, END
BEGIN NOW So that none might see her beauty, END
BEGIN NOW So that none might boast, "I saw her! END
BEGIN NOW On the morrow, as the day dawned, END
BEGIN NOW Gathered all his black marauders, END
BEGIN NOW Crows and blackbirds, jays and ravens, END
BEGIN NOW Clamorous on the dusky tree-tops, END
BEGIN NOW And descended, fast and fearless, END
BEGIN NOW On the fields of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW On the grave of the Mondamin. END
BEGIN NOW We will drag Mondamin," said they, END
BEGIN NOW From the grave where he is buried, END
BEGIN NOW Spite of all the magic circles END
BEGIN NOW Laughing Water draws around it, END
BEGIN NOW Spite of all the sacred footprints END
BEGIN NOW Minnehaha stamps upon it! END
BEGIN NOW But the wary Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Ever thoughtful, careful, watchful, END
BEGIN NOW Had o'erheard the scornful laughter END
BEGIN NOW When they mocked him from the tree-tops. END
BEGIN NOW Kaw! he said, "my friends the ravens! END
BEGIN NOW I will teach you all a lesson END
BEGIN NOW That shall not be soon forgotten! END
BEGIN NOW He had risen before the daybreak, END
BEGIN NOW He had spread o'er all the cornfields END
BEGIN NOW Snares to catch the black marauders, END
BEGIN NOW And was lying now in ambush END
BEGIN NOW In the neighboring grove of pine-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Waiting for the crows and blackbirds, END
BEGIN NOW Waiting for the jays and ravens. END
BEGIN NOW Soon they came with caw and clamor, END
BEGIN NOW Rush of wings and cry of voices, END
BEGIN NOW To their work of devastation, END
BEGIN NOW Settling down upon the cornfields, END
BEGIN NOW Delving deep with beak and talon, END
BEGIN NOW For the body of Mondamin. END
BEGIN NOW And with all their craft and cunning, END
BEGIN NOW All their skill in wiles of warfare, END
BEGIN NOW They perceived no danger near them, END
BEGIN NOW Till their claws became entangled, END
BEGIN NOW Till they found themselves imprisoned END
BEGIN NOW In the snares of Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW From his place of ambush came he, END
BEGIN NOW Striding terrible among them, END
BEGIN NOW And so awful was his aspect END
BEGIN NOW That the bravest quailed with terror. END
BEGIN NOW Without mercy he destroyed them END
BEGIN NOW Right and left, by tens and twenties, END
BEGIN NOW And their wretched, lifeless bodies END
BEGIN NOW Hung aloft on poles for scarecrows END
BEGIN NOW Round the consecrated cornfields, END
BEGIN NOW As a signal of his vengeance, END
BEGIN NOW As a warning to marauders. END
BEGIN NOW Only Kahgahgee, the leader, END
BEGIN NOW He alone was spared among them END
BEGIN NOW As a hostage for his people. END
BEGIN NOW With his prisoner-string he bound him, END
BEGIN NOW Led him captive to his wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Tied him fast with cords of elm-bark END
BEGIN NOW To the ridge-pole of his wigwam. END
BEGIN NOW Kahgahgee, my raven!" said he, END
BEGIN NOW You the leader of the robbers, END
BEGIN NOW You the plotter of this mischief, END
BEGIN NOW The contriver of this outrage, END
BEGIN NOW I will keep you, I will hold you, END
BEGIN NOW As a hostage for your people, END
BEGIN NOW As a pledge of good behavior! END
BEGIN NOW And he left him, grim and sulky, END
BEGIN NOW Sitting in the morning sunshine END
BEGIN NOW On the summit of the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Croaking fiercely his displeasure, END
BEGIN NOW Flapping his great sable pinions, END
BEGIN NOW Vainly struggling for his freedom, END
BEGIN NOW Vainly calling on his people! END
BEGIN NOW Summer passed, and Shawondasee END
BEGIN NOW Breathed his sighs o'er all the landscape, END
BEGIN NOW From the South-land sent his ardor, END
BEGIN NOW Wafted kisses warm and tender; END
BEGIN NOW And the maize-field grew and ripened, END
BEGIN NOW Till it stood in all the splendor END
BEGIN NOW Of its garments green and yellow, END
BEGIN NOW Of its tassels and its plumage, END
BEGIN NOW And the maize-ears full and shining END
BEGIN NOW Gleamed from bursting sheaths of verdure. END
BEGIN NOW Then Nokomis, the old woman, END
BEGIN NOW Spake, and said to Minnehaha: END
BEGIN NOW 'T is the Moon when, leaves are falling; END
BEGIN NOW All the wild rice has been gathered, END
BEGIN NOW And the maize is ripe and ready; END
BEGIN NOW Let us gather in the harvest, END
BEGIN NOW Let us wrestle with Mondamin, END
BEGIN NOW Strip him of his plumes and tassels, END
BEGIN NOW Of his garments green and yellow! END
BEGIN NOW And the merry Laughing Water END
BEGIN NOW Went rejoicing from the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW With Nokomis, old and wrinkled, END
BEGIN NOW And they called the women round them, END
BEGIN NOW Called the young men and the maidens, END
BEGIN NOW To the harvest of the cornfields, END
BEGIN NOW To the husking of the maize-ear. END
BEGIN NOW On the border of the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Underneath the fragrant pine-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Sat the old men and the warriors END
BEGIN NOW Smoking in the pleasant shadow. END
BEGIN NOW In uninterrupted silence END
BEGIN NOW Looked they at the gamesome labor END
BEGIN NOW Of the young men and the women; END
BEGIN NOW Listened to their noisy talking, END
BEGIN NOW To their laughter and their singing, END
BEGIN NOW Heard them chattering like the magpies, END
BEGIN NOW Heard them laughing like the blue-jays, END
BEGIN NOW Heard them singing like the robins. END
BEGIN NOW And whene'er some lucky maiden END
BEGIN NOW Found a red ear in the husking, END
BEGIN NOW Found a maize-ear red as blood is, END
BEGIN NOW Nushka! cried they all together, END
BEGIN NOW Nushka! you shall have a sweetheart, END
BEGIN NOW You shall have a handsome husband! END
BEGIN NOW Ugh! the old men all responded END
BEGIN NOW From their seats beneath the pine-trees. END
BEGIN NOW And whene'er a youth or maiden END
BEGIN NOW Found a crooked ear in husking, END
BEGIN NOW Found a maize-ear in the husking END
BEGIN NOW Blighted, mildewed, or misshapen, END
BEGIN NOW Then they laughed and sang together, END
BEGIN NOW Crept and limped about the cornfields, END
BEGIN NOW Mimicked in their gait and gestures END
BEGIN NOW Some old man, bent almost double, END
BEGIN NOW Singing singly or together: END
BEGIN NOW Wagemin, the thief of cornfields! END
BEGIN NOW Paimosaid, who steals the maize-ear! END
BEGIN NOW Till the cornfields rang with laughter, END
BEGIN NOW Till from Hiawatha's wigwam END
BEGIN NOW Screamed and quivered in his anger, END
BEGIN NOW And from all the neighboring tree-tops END
BEGIN NOW Cawed and croaked the black marauders. END
BEGIN NOW Ugh! the old men all responded, END
BEGIN NOW From their seats beneath the pine-trees! END
BEGIN NOW In those days said Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Lo! how all things fade and perish! END
BEGIN NOW From the memory of the old men END
BEGIN NOW Pass away the great traditions, END
BEGIN NOW The achievements of the warriors, END
BEGIN NOW The adventures of the hunters, END
BEGIN NOW All the wisdom of the Medas, END
BEGIN NOW All the craft of the Wabenos, END
BEGIN NOW All the marvellous dreams and visions END
BEGIN NOW Great men die and are forgotten, END
BEGIN NOW Wise men speak; their words of wisdom END
BEGIN NOW Perish in the ears that hear them, END
BEGIN NOW Do not reach the generations END
BEGIN NOW That, as yet unborn, are waiting END
BEGIN NOW In the great, mysterious darkness END
BEGIN NOW Of the speechless days that shall be! END
BEGIN NOW On the grave-posts of our fathers END
BEGIN NOW Are no signs, no figures painted; END
BEGIN NOW Who are in those graves we know not, END
BEGIN NOW Only know they are our fathers. END
BEGIN NOW Of what kith they are and kindred, END
BEGIN NOW From what old, ancestral Totem, END
BEGIN NOW They descended, this we know not, END
BEGIN NOW Only know they are our fathers. END
BEGIN NOW Face to face we speak together, END
BEGIN NOW But we cannot speak when absent, END
BEGIN NOW Cannot send our voices from us END
BEGIN NOW To the friends that dwell afar off; END
BEGIN NOW Cannot send a secret message, END
BEGIN NOW But the bearer learns our secret, END
BEGIN NOW May pervert it, may betray it, END
BEGIN NOW May reveal it unto others. END
BEGIN NOW Thus said Hiawatha, walking END
BEGIN NOW In the solitary forest, END
BEGIN NOW Pondering, musing in the forest, END
BEGIN NOW On the welfare of his people. END
BEGIN NOW From his pouch he took his colors, END
BEGIN NOW Took his paints of different colors, END
BEGIN NOW On the smooth bark of a birch-tree END
BEGIN NOW Painted many shapes and figures, END
BEGIN NOW Wonderful and mystic figures, END
BEGIN NOW And each figure had a meaning, END
BEGIN NOW Each some word or thought suggested. END
BEGIN NOW He, the Master of Life, was painted END
BEGIN NOW As an egg, with points projecting END
BEGIN NOW To the four winds of the heavens. END
BEGIN NOW Was the meaning of this symbol. END
BEGIN NOW He the dreadful Spirit of Evil, END
BEGIN NOW As a serpent was depicted, END
BEGIN NOW As Kenabeek, the great serpent. END
BEGIN NOW Very crafty, very cunning, END
BEGIN NOW Is the creeping Spirit of Evil, END
BEGIN NOW Was the meaning of this symbol. END
BEGIN NOW Life and Death he drew as circles, END
BEGIN NOW Life was white, but Death was darkened; END
BEGIN NOW Sun and moon and stars he painted, END
BEGIN NOW Man and beast, and fish and reptile, END
BEGIN NOW Forests, mountains, lakes, and rivers. END
BEGIN NOW For the earth he drew a straight line, END
BEGIN NOW For the sky a bow above it; END
BEGIN NOW White the space between for daytime, END
BEGIN NOW Filled with little stars for night-time; END
BEGIN NOW On the left a point for sunrise, END
BEGIN NOW On the right a point for sunset, END
BEGIN NOW On the top a point for noontide, END
BEGIN NOW And for rain and cloudy weather END
BEGIN NOW Waving lines descending from it. END
BEGIN NOW Footprints pointing towards a wigwam END
BEGIN NOW Were a sign of invitation, END
BEGIN NOW Were a sign of guests assembling; END
BEGIN NOW Bloody hands with palms uplifted END
BEGIN NOW Were a symbol of destruction, END
BEGIN NOW Were a hostile sign and symbol. END
BEGIN NOW All these things did Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Show unto his wondering people, END
BEGIN NOW And interpreted their meaning, END
BEGIN NOW And he said: "Behold, your grave-posts END
BEGIN NOW Have no mark, no sign, nor symbol, END
BEGIN NOW Go and paint them all with figures; END
BEGIN NOW Each one with its household symbol, END
BEGIN NOW With its own ancestral Totem; END
BEGIN NOW So that those who follow after END
BEGIN NOW May distinguish them and know them. END
BEGIN NOW And they painted on the grave-posts END
BEGIN NOW On the graves yet unforgotten, END
BEGIN NOW Each his own ancestral Totem, END
BEGIN NOW Each the symbol of his household; END
BEGIN NOW Each inverted as a token END
BEGIN NOW That the owner was departed, END
BEGIN NOW That the chief who bore the symbol END
BEGIN NOW Lay beneath in dust and ashes. END
BEGIN NOW And the Medicine-men, the Medas, END
BEGIN NOW Painted upon bark and deer-skin END
BEGIN NOW Figures for the songs they chanted, END
BEGIN NOW For each song a separate symbol, END
BEGIN NOW Figures mystical and awful, END
BEGIN NOW Figures strange and brightly colored; END
BEGIN NOW And each figure had its meaning, END
BEGIN NOW Each some magic song suggested. END
BEGIN NOW Flashing light through all the heaven; END
BEGIN NOW With his bloody crest erected, END
BEGIN NOW Creeping, looking into heaven; END
BEGIN NOW In the sky the sun, that listens, END
BEGIN NOW And the moon eclipsed and dying; END
BEGIN NOW Owl and eagle, crane and hen-hawk, END
BEGIN NOW And the cormorant, bird of magic; END
BEGIN NOW Headless men, that walk the heavens, END
BEGIN NOW Bodies lying pierced with arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Bloody hands of death uplifted, END
BEGIN NOW Flags on graves, and great war-captains END
BEGIN NOW Grasping both the earth and heaven! END
BEGIN NOW Such as these the shapes they painted END
BEGIN NOW On the birch-bark and the deer-skin; END
BEGIN NOW Songs of war and songs of hunting, END
BEGIN NOW Songs of medicine and of magic, END
BEGIN NOW All were written in these figures, END
BEGIN NOW For each figure had its meaning, END
BEGIN NOW Each its separate song recorded. END
BEGIN NOW Nor forgotten was the Love-Song, END
BEGIN NOW The most subtle of all medicines, END
BEGIN NOW The most potent spell of magic, END
BEGIN NOW Dangerous more than war or hunting! END
BEGIN NOW Thus the Love-Song was recorded, END
BEGIN NOW Symbol and interpretation. END
BEGIN NOW First a human figure standing, END
BEGIN NOW Painted in the brightest scarlet; END
BEGIN NOW `T is the lover, the musician, END
BEGIN NOW And the meaning is, "My painting END
BEGIN NOW Makes me powerful over others. END
BEGIN NOW Then the figure seated, singing, END
BEGIN NOW Playing on a drum of magic, END
BEGIN NOW And the interpretation, Listen! END
BEGIN NOW `T is my voice you hear, my singing! END
BEGIN NOW Then the same red figure seated END
BEGIN NOW In the shelter of a wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW And the meaning of the symbol, END
BEGIN NOW I will come and sit beside you END
BEGIN NOW In the mystery of my passion! END
BEGIN NOW Then two figures, man and woman, END
BEGIN NOW Standing hand in hand together END
BEGIN NOW With their hands so clasped together END
BEGIN NOW That they seemed in one united, END
BEGIN NOW And the words thus represented END
BEGIN NOW Are, "I see your heart within you, END
BEGIN NOW And your cheeks are red with blushes! END
BEGIN NOW Next the maiden on an island, END
BEGIN NOW In the centre of an Island; END
BEGIN NOW And the song this shape suggested END
BEGIN NOW Was, "Though you were at a distance, END
BEGIN NOW Were upon some far-off island, END
BEGIN NOW Such the spell I cast upon you, END
BEGIN NOW Such the magic power of passion, END
BEGIN NOW I could straightway draw you to me! END
BEGIN NOW Then the figure of the maiden END
BEGIN NOW Sleeping, and the lover near her, END
BEGIN NOW Whispering to her in her slumbers, END
BEGIN NOW Saying, "Though you were far from me END
BEGIN NOW In the land of Sleep and Silence, END
BEGIN NOW Still the voice of love would reach you! END
BEGIN NOW And the last of all the figures END
BEGIN NOW Was a heart within a circle, END
BEGIN NOW Drawn within a magic circle; END
BEGIN NOW And the image had this meaning: END
BEGIN NOW Naked lies your heart before me, END
BEGIN NOW To your naked heart I whisper! END
BEGIN NOW Thus it was that Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW In his wisdom, taught the people END
BEGIN NOW All the mysteries of painting, END
BEGIN NOW On the smooth bark of the birch-tree, END
BEGIN NOW On the white skin of the reindeer, END
BEGIN NOW On the grave-posts of the village. END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha's Lamentation END
BEGIN NOW In those days the Evil Spirits, END
BEGIN NOW All the Manitos of mischief, END
BEGIN NOW Fearing Hiawatha's wisdom, END
BEGIN NOW And his love for Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW Jealous of their faithful friendship, END
BEGIN NOW And their noble words and actions, END
BEGIN NOW Made at length a league against them, END
BEGIN NOW To molest them and destroy them. END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha, wise and wary, END
BEGIN NOW Often said to Chibiabos, END
BEGIN NOW O my brother! do not leave me, END
BEGIN NOW Lest the Evil Spirits harm you! END
BEGIN NOW Chibiabos, young and heedless, END
BEGIN NOW Laughing shook his coal-black tresses, END
BEGIN NOW Answered ever sweet and childlike, END
BEGIN NOW Do not fear for me, O brother! END
BEGIN NOW Harm and evil come not near me! END
BEGIN NOW Once when Peboan, the Winter, END
BEGIN NOW Roofed with ice the Big-Sea-Water, END
BEGIN NOW When the snow-flakes, whirling downward, END
BEGIN NOW Hissed among the withered oak-leaves, END
BEGIN NOW Changed the pine-trees into wigwams, END
BEGIN NOW Covered all the earth with silence, END
BEGIN NOW Armed with arrows, shod with snow-shoes, END
BEGIN NOW Heeding not his brother's warning, END
BEGIN NOW Forth to hunt the deer with antlers END
BEGIN NOW All alone went Chibiabos. END
BEGIN NOW Right across the Big-Sea-Water END
BEGIN NOW Sprang with speed the deer before him. END
BEGIN NOW With the wind and snow he followed, END
BEGIN NOW O'er the treacherous ice he followed, END
BEGIN NOW Wild with all the fierce commotion END
BEGIN NOW And the rapture of the hunting. END
BEGIN NOW But beneath, the Evil Spirits END
BEGIN NOW Lay in ambush, waiting for him, END
BEGIN NOW Broke the treacherous ice beneath him, END
BEGIN NOW Dragged him downward to the bottom, END
BEGIN NOW Buried in the sand his body. END
BEGIN NOW Unktahee, the god of water, END
BEGIN NOW Drowned him in the deep abysses END
BEGIN NOW Of the lake of Gitche Gumee. END
BEGIN NOW From the headlands Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Sent forth such a wail of anguish, END
BEGIN NOW Such a fearful lamentation, END
BEGIN NOW That the bison paused to listen, END
BEGIN NOW And the wolves howled from the prairies, END
BEGIN NOW And the thunder in the distance END
BEGIN NOW Starting answered Baim-wawa! END
BEGIN NOW Then his face with black he painted, END
BEGIN NOW With his robe his head he covered, END
BEGIN NOW In his wigwam sat lamenting, END
BEGIN NOW Seven long weeks he sat lamenting, END
BEGIN NOW Uttering still this moan of sorrow: END
BEGIN NOW He is dead, the sweet musician! END
BEGIN NOW He the sweetest of all singers! END
BEGIN NOW He has gone from us forever, END
BEGIN NOW He has moved a little nearer END
BEGIN NOW To the Master of all music, END
BEGIN NOW To the Master of all singing! END
BEGIN NOW O my brother, Chibiabos! END
BEGIN NOW And the melancholy fir-trees END
BEGIN NOW Waved their dark green fans above him, END
BEGIN NOW Waved their purple cones above him, END
BEGIN NOW Sighing with him to console him, END
BEGIN NOW Mingling with his lamentation END
BEGIN NOW Their complaining, their lamenting. END
BEGIN NOW Came the Spring, and all the forest END
BEGIN NOW Looked in vain for Chibiabos; END
BEGIN NOW Sighed the rivulet, Sebowisha, END
BEGIN NOW Sighed the rushes in the meadow. END
BEGIN NOW From the tree-tops sang the bluebird, END
BEGIN NOW Sang the bluebird, the Owaissa, END
BEGIN NOW He is dead, the sweet musician! END
BEGIN NOW From the wigwam sang the robin, END
BEGIN NOW Sang the robin, the Opechee, END
BEGIN NOW He is dead, the sweetest singer! END
BEGIN NOW And at night through all the forest END
BEGIN NOW Went the whippoorwill complaining, END
BEGIN NOW Wailing went the Wawonaissa, END
BEGIN NOW He is dead, the sweet musician! END
BEGIN NOW He the sweetest of all singers! END
BEGIN NOW Then the Medicine-men, the Medas, END
BEGIN NOW The magicians, the Wabenos, END
BEGIN NOW Came to visit Hiawatha; END
BEGIN NOW Built a Sacred Lodge beside him, END
BEGIN NOW To appease him, to console him, END
BEGIN NOW Walked in silent, grave procession, END
BEGIN NOW Bearing each a pouch of healing, END
BEGIN NOW Skin of beaver, lynx, or otter, END
BEGIN NOW Filled with magic roots and simples, END
BEGIN NOW Filled with very potent medicines. END
BEGIN NOW When he heard their steps approaching, END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha ceased lamenting, END
BEGIN NOW Called no more on Chibiabos; END
BEGIN NOW Naught he questioned, naught he answered, END
BEGIN NOW But his mournful head uncovered, END
BEGIN NOW From his face the mourning colors END
BEGIN NOW Washed he slowly and in silence, END
BEGIN NOW Slowly and in silence followed END
BEGIN NOW There a magic drink they gave him, END
BEGIN NOW Made of Nahma-wusk, the spearmint, END
BEGIN NOW And Wabeno-wusk, the yarrow, END
BEGIN NOW Roots of power, and herbs of healing; END
BEGIN NOW Beat their drums, and shook their rattles; END
BEGIN NOW Chanted singly and in chorus, END
BEGIN NOW Mystic songs like these, they chanted. END
BEGIN NOW I myself, myself! behold me! END
BEGIN NOW `T is the great Gray Eagle talking; END
BEGIN NOW Come, ye white crows, come and hear him! END
BEGIN NOW The loud-speaking thunder helps me; END
BEGIN NOW All the unseen spirits help me; END
BEGIN NOW I can hear their voices calling, END
BEGIN NOW All around the sky I hear them! END
BEGIN NOW I can blow you strong, my brother, END
BEGIN NOW I can heal you, Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Hi-au-ha! replied the chorus, END
BEGIN NOW Wayha-way! the mystic chorus. END
BEGIN NOW Friends of mine are all the serpents! END
BEGIN NOW Hear me shake my skin of hen-hawk! END
BEGIN NOW Mahng, the white loon, I can kill him; END
BEGIN NOW I can shoot your heart and kill it! END
BEGIN NOW I can blow you strong, my brother, END
BEGIN NOW I can heal you, Hiawatha ! END
BEGIN NOW Hi-au-ha! replied the chorus, END
BEGIN NOW Wayhaway! the mystic chorus. END
BEGIN NOW I myself, myself! the prophet! END
BEGIN NOW When I speak the wigwam trembles, END
BEGIN NOW Shakes the Sacred Lodge with terror, END
BEGIN NOW Hands unseen begin to shake it! END
BEGIN NOW When I walk, the sky I tread on END
BEGIN NOW Bends and makes a noise beneath me! END
BEGIN NOW I can blow you strong, my brother! END
BEGIN NOW Rise and speak, O Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Hi-au-ha! replied the chorus, END
BEGIN NOW Way-ha-way! the mystic chorus. END
BEGIN NOW Then they shook their medicine-pouches END
BEGIN NOW O'er the head of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Danced their medicine-dance around him; END
BEGIN NOW And upstarting wild and haggard, END
BEGIN NOW Like a man from dreams awakened, END
BEGIN NOW He was healed of all his madness. END
BEGIN NOW As the clouds are swept from heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Straightway from his brain departed END
BEGIN NOW All his moody melancholy; END
BEGIN NOW As the ice is swept from rivers, END
BEGIN NOW Straightway from his heart departed END
BEGIN NOW All his sorrow and affliction. END
BEGIN NOW Then they summoned Chibiabos END
BEGIN NOW From his grave beneath the waters, END
BEGIN NOW From the sands of Gitche Gumee END
BEGIN NOW Summoned Hiawatha's brother. END
BEGIN NOW And so mighty was the magic END
BEGIN NOW Of that cry and invocation, END
BEGIN NOW That he heard it as he lay there END
BEGIN NOW From the sand he rose and listened, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the music and the singing, END
BEGIN NOW Came, obedient to the summons, END
BEGIN NOW To the doorway of the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW But to enter they forbade him. END
BEGIN NOW Through the door a burning fire-brand; END
BEGIN NOW Ruler o'er the dead, they made him, END
BEGIN NOW Telling him a fire to kindle END
BEGIN NOW For all those that died thereafter, END
BEGIN NOW Camp-fires for their night encampments END
BEGIN NOW On their solitary journey END
BEGIN NOW To the kingdom of Ponemah, END
BEGIN NOW To the land of the Hereafter. END
BEGIN NOW From the village of his childhood, END
BEGIN NOW From the homes of those who knew him, END
BEGIN NOW Passing silent through the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Like a smoke-wreath wafted sideways, END
BEGIN NOW Slowly vanished Chibiabos! END
BEGIN NOW Where he passed, the branches moved not, END
BEGIN NOW Where he trod, the grasses bent not, END
BEGIN NOW And the fallen leaves of last year END
BEGIN NOW Made no sound beneath his footstep. END
BEGIN NOW Four whole days he journeyed onward END
BEGIN NOW Down the pathway of the dead men; END
BEGIN NOW On the dead-man's strawberry feasted, END
BEGIN NOW Crossed the melancholy river, END
BEGIN NOW On the swinging log he crossed it, END
BEGIN NOW Came unto the Lake of Silver, END
BEGIN NOW In the Stone Canoe was carried END
BEGIN NOW To the land of ghosts and shadows. END
BEGIN NOW On that journey, moving slowly, END
BEGIN NOW Many weary spirits saw he, END
BEGIN NOW Panting under heavy burdens, END
BEGIN NOW Laden with war-clubs, bows and arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Robes of fur, and pots and kettles, END
BEGIN NOW And with food that friends had given END
BEGIN NOW For that solitary journey. END
BEGIN NOW Ay! why do the living," said they, END
BEGIN NOW Lay such heavy burdens on us! END
BEGIN NOW Better were it to go naked, END
BEGIN NOW Better were it to go fasting, END
BEGIN NOW Than to bear such heavy burdens END
BEGIN NOW On our long and weary journey! END
BEGIN NOW Forth then issued Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Wandered eastward, wandered westward, END
BEGIN NOW Teaching men the use of simples END
BEGIN NOW And the antidotes for poisons, END
BEGIN NOW And the cure of all diseases. END
BEGIN NOW Thus was first made known to mortals END
BEGIN NOW All the mystery of Medamin, END
BEGIN NOW All the sacred art of healing. END
BEGIN NOW You shall hear how Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW He, the handsome Yenadizze, END
BEGIN NOW Whom the people called the Storm-Fool, END
BEGIN NOW Vexed the village with disturbance; END
BEGIN NOW You shall hear of all his mischief, END
BEGIN NOW And his flight from Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW And his wondrous transmigrations, END
BEGIN NOW And the end of his adventures. END
BEGIN NOW On the shores of Gitche Gumee, END
BEGIN NOW On the dunes of Nagow Wudjoo, END
BEGIN NOW By the shining Big-Sea-Water END
BEGIN NOW Stood the lodge of Pau-Puk-Keewis. END
BEGIN NOW It was he who in his frenzy END
BEGIN NOW Whirled these drifting sands together, END
BEGIN NOW On the dunes of Nagow Wudjoo, END
BEGIN NOW When, among the guests assembled, END
BEGIN NOW He so merrily and madly END
BEGIN NOW Danced at Hiawatha's wedding, END
BEGIN NOW Danced the Beggar's Dance to please them. END
BEGIN NOW Now, in search of new adventures, END
BEGIN NOW From his lodge went Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Came with speed into the village, END
BEGIN NOW Found the young men all assembled END
BEGIN NOW In the lodge of old Iagoo, END
BEGIN NOW Listening to his monstrous stories, END
BEGIN NOW To his wonderful adventures. END
BEGIN NOW He was telling them the story END
BEGIN NOW How he made a hole in heaven, END
BEGIN NOW How he climbed up into heaven, END
BEGIN NOW And let out the summer-weather, END
BEGIN NOW The perpetual, pleasant Summer; END
BEGIN NOW How the Otter first essayed it; END
BEGIN NOW Tried in turn the great achievement, END
BEGIN NOW From the summit of the mountain END
BEGIN NOW Smote their fists against the heavens, END
BEGIN NOW Smote against the sky their foreheads, END
BEGIN NOW Cracked the sky, but could not break it; END
BEGIN NOW How the Wolverine, uprising, END
BEGIN NOW Made him ready for the encounter, END
BEGIN NOW Bent his knees down, like a squirrel, END
BEGIN NOW Drew his arms back, like a cricket. END
BEGIN NOW Once he leaped," said old Iagoo, END
BEGIN NOW Once he leaped, and lo! above him END
BEGIN NOW Bent the sky, as ice in rivers END
BEGIN NOW When the waters rise beneath it; END
BEGIN NOW Twice he leaped, and lo! above him END
BEGIN NOW Cracked the sky, as ice in rivers END
BEGIN NOW When the freshet is at highest! END
BEGIN NOW Thrice he leaped, and lo! above him END
BEGIN NOW Broke the shattered sky asunder, END
BEGIN NOW And he disappeared within it, END
BEGIN NOW With a bound went in behind him! END
BEGIN NOW Hark you!" shouted Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW As he entered at the doorway; END
BEGIN NOW I am tired of all this talking, END
BEGIN NOW Tired of old Iagoo's stories, END
BEGIN NOW Tired of Hiawatha's wisdom. END
BEGIN NOW Here is something to amuse you, END
BEGIN NOW Better than this endless talking. END
BEGIN NOW Then from out his pouch of wolf-skin END
BEGIN NOW Forth he drew, with solemn manner, END
BEGIN NOW All the game of Bowl and Counters, END
BEGIN NOW Pugasaing, with thirteen pieces. END
BEGIN NOW White on one side were they painted, END
BEGIN NOW And vermilion on the other; END
BEGIN NOW Two Kenabeeks or great serpents, END
BEGIN NOW Two Ininewug or wedge-men, END
BEGIN NOW One great war-club, Pugamaugun, END
BEGIN NOW And one slender fish, the Keego, END
BEGIN NOW Four round pieces, Ozawabeeks, END
BEGIN NOW And three Sheshebwug or ducklings. END
BEGIN NOW All were made of bone and painted, END
BEGIN NOW All except the Ozawabeeks; END
BEGIN NOW These were brass, on one side burnished, END
BEGIN NOW And were black upon the other. END
BEGIN NOW In a wooden bowl he placed them, END
BEGIN NOW Shook and jostled them together, END
BEGIN NOW Threw them on the ground before him, END
BEGIN NOW Thus exclaiming and explaining: END
BEGIN NOW Red side up are all the pieces, END
BEGIN NOW And one great Kenabeek standing END
BEGIN NOW On the bright side of a brass piece, END
BEGIN NOW On a burnished Ozawabeek; END
BEGIN NOW Thirteen tens and eight are counted. END
BEGIN NOW Then again he shook the pieces, END
BEGIN NOW Shook and jostled them together, END
BEGIN NOW Threw them on the ground before him, END
BEGIN NOW Still exclaiming and explaining: END
BEGIN NOW White are both the great Kenabeeks, END
BEGIN NOW White the Ininewug, the wedge-men, END
BEGIN NOW Red are all the other pieces; END
BEGIN NOW Five tens and an eight are counted. END
BEGIN NOW Thus he taught the game of hazard, END
BEGIN NOW Thus displayed it and explained it, END
BEGIN NOW Running through its various chances, END
BEGIN NOW Various changes, various meanings: END
BEGIN NOW Twenty curious eyes stared at him, END
BEGIN NOW Full of eagerness stared at him. END
BEGIN NOW Many games," said old Iagoo, END
BEGIN NOW Many games of skill and hazard END
BEGIN NOW Have I seen in different nations, END
BEGIN NOW Have I played in different countries. END
BEGIN NOW He who plays with old Iagoo END
BEGIN NOW Must have very nimble fingers; END
BEGIN NOW Though you think yourself so skilful, END
BEGIN NOW I can beat you, Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW I can even give you lessons END
BEGIN NOW In your game of Bowl and Counters! END
BEGIN NOW So they sat and played together, END
BEGIN NOW All the old men and the young men, END
BEGIN NOW Played for dresses, weapons, wampum, END
BEGIN NOW Played till midnight, played till morning, END
BEGIN NOW Played until the Yenadizze, END
BEGIN NOW Till the cunning Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Of their treasures had despoiled them, END
BEGIN NOW Of the best of all their dresses, END
BEGIN NOW Shirts of deer-skin, robes of ermine, END
BEGIN NOW Belts of wampum, crests of feathers, END
BEGIN NOW Warlike weapons, pipes and pouches. END
BEGIN NOW Twenty eyes glared wildly at him, END
BEGIN NOW Like the eyes of wolves glared at him. END
BEGIN NOW Said the lucky Pau-Puk-Keewis: END
BEGIN NOW In my wigwam I am lonely, END
BEGIN NOW In my wanderings and adventures END
BEGIN NOW I have need of a companion, END
BEGIN NOW Fain would have a Meshinauwa, END
BEGIN NOW An attendant and pipe-bearer. END
BEGIN NOW I will venture all these winnings, END
BEGIN NOW All these garments heaped about me, END
BEGIN NOW All this wampum, all these feathers, END
BEGIN NOW On a single throw will venture END
BEGIN NOW All against the young man yonder! END
BEGIN NOW `T was a youth of sixteen summers, END
BEGIN NOW `T was a nephew of Iagoo; END
BEGIN NOW Face-in-a-Mist, the people called him. END
BEGIN NOW As the fire burns in a pipe-head END
BEGIN NOW Dusky red beneath the ashes, END
BEGIN NOW So beneath his shaggy eyebrows END
BEGIN NOW Glowed the eyes of old Iagoo. END
BEGIN NOW Ugh! he answered very fiercely; END
BEGIN NOW Ugh! they answered all and each one. END
BEGIN NOW Seized the wooden bowl the old man, END
BEGIN NOW Closely in his bony fingers END
BEGIN NOW Clutched the fatal bowl, Onagon, END
BEGIN NOW Shook it fiercely and with fury, END
BEGIN NOW Made the pieces ring together END
BEGIN NOW As he threw them down before him. END
BEGIN NOW Red were both the great Kenabeeks, END
BEGIN NOW Red the Ininewug, the wedge-men, END
BEGIN NOW Red the Sheshebwug, the ducklings, END
BEGIN NOW Black the four brass Ozawabeeks, END
BEGIN NOW White alone the fish, the Keego; END
BEGIN NOW Only five the pieces counted! END
BEGIN NOW Then the smiling Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Shook the bowl and threw the pieces; END
BEGIN NOW Lightly in the air he tossed them, END
BEGIN NOW And they fell about him scattered; END
BEGIN NOW Dark and bright the Ozawabeeks, END
BEGIN NOW Red and white the other pieces, END
BEGIN NOW And upright among the others END
BEGIN NOW One Ininewug was standing, END
BEGIN NOW Even as crafty Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Stood alone among the players, END
BEGIN NOW Saying, "Five tens! mine the game is, END
BEGIN NOW Twenty eyes glared at him fiercely, END
BEGIN NOW Like the eyes of wolves glared at him, END
BEGIN NOW As he turned and left the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW By the nephew of Iagoo, END
BEGIN NOW By the tall and graceful stripling, END
BEGIN NOW Bearing in his arms the winnings, END
BEGIN NOW Shirts of deer-skin, robes of ermine, END
BEGIN NOW Belts of wampum, pipes and weapons. END
BEGIN NOW Carry them," said Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Pointing with his fan of feathers, END
BEGIN NOW To my wigwam far to eastward, END
BEGIN NOW On the dunes of Nagow Wudjoo! END
BEGIN NOW Hot and red with smoke and gambling END
BEGIN NOW Were the eyes of Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW As he came forth to the freshness END
BEGIN NOW Of the pleasant Summer morning. END
BEGIN NOW All the birds were singing gayly, END
BEGIN NOW All the streamlets flowing swiftly, END
BEGIN NOW And the heart of Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Sang with pleasure as the birds sing, END
BEGIN NOW Beat with triumph like the streamlets, END
BEGIN NOW As he wandered through the village, END
BEGIN NOW In the early gray of morning, END
BEGIN NOW With his fan of turkey-feathers, END
BEGIN NOW With his plumes and tufts of swan's down, END
BEGIN NOW Till he reached the farthest wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Reached the lodge of Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW Silent was it and deserted; END
BEGIN NOW No one met him at the doorway, END
BEGIN NOW No one came to bid him welcome; END
BEGIN NOW But the birds were singing round it, END
BEGIN NOW In and out and round the doorway, END
BEGIN NOW Hopping, singing, fluttering, feeding, END
BEGIN NOW And aloft upon the ridge-pole END
BEGIN NOW Sat with fiery eyes, and, screaming, END
BEGIN NOW Flapped his wings at Pau-Puk-Keewis. END
BEGIN NOW All are gone! the lodge is empty! END
BEGIN NOW Thus it was spake Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW In his heart resolving mischief END
BEGIN NOW Gone is wary Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Gone the silly Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW Gone Nokomis, the old woman, END
BEGIN NOW And the lodge is left unguarded! END
BEGIN NOW By the neck he seized the raven, END
BEGIN NOW Whirled it round him like a rattle, END
BEGIN NOW Like a medicine-pouch he shook it, END
BEGIN NOW Strangled Kahgahgee, the raven, END
BEGIN NOW From the ridge-pole of the wigwam END
BEGIN NOW Left its lifeless body hanging, END
BEGIN NOW As an insult to its master, END
BEGIN NOW As a taunt to Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW With a stealthy step he entered, END
BEGIN NOW Round the lodge in wild disorder END
BEGIN NOW Threw the household things about him, END
BEGIN NOW Piled together in confusion END
BEGIN NOW Bowls of wood and earthen kettles, END
BEGIN NOW Robes of buffalo and beaver, END
BEGIN NOW Skins of otter, lynx, and ermine, END
BEGIN NOW As an insult to Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW As a taunt to Minnehaha. END
BEGIN NOW Then departed Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Whistling, singing through the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Whistling gayly to the squirrels, END
BEGIN NOW Who from hollow boughs above him END
BEGIN NOW Dropped their acorn-shells upon him, END
BEGIN NOW Singing gayly to the wood birds, END
BEGIN NOW Who from out the leafy darkness END
BEGIN NOW Answered with a song as merry. END
BEGIN NOW Then he climbed the rocky headlands, END
BEGIN NOW Looking o'er the Gitche Gumee, END
BEGIN NOW Perched himself upon their summit, END
BEGIN NOW Waiting full of mirth and mischief END
BEGIN NOW The return of Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW Stretched upon his back he lay there; END
BEGIN NOW Far below him splashed the waters, END
BEGIN NOW Plashed and washed the dreamy waters; END
BEGIN NOW Far above him swam the heavens, END
BEGIN NOW Swam the dizzy, dreamy heavens; END
BEGIN NOW Round him hovered, fluttered, rustled END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha's mountain chickens, END
BEGIN NOW Flock-wise swept and wheeled about him, END
BEGIN NOW Almost brushed him with their pinions. END
BEGIN NOW And he killed them as he lay there, END
BEGIN NOW Slaughtered them by tens and twenties, END
BEGIN NOW Threw their bodies down the headland, END
BEGIN NOW Threw them on the beach below him, END
BEGIN NOW Till at length Kayoshk, the sea-gull, END
BEGIN NOW Perched upon a crag above them, END
BEGIN NOW He is slaying us by hundreds! END
BEGIN NOW Send a message to our brother, END
BEGIN NOW Tidings send to Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Full of wrath was Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW When he came into the village, END
BEGIN NOW Found the people in confusion, END
BEGIN NOW Heard of all the misdemeanors, END
BEGIN NOW All the malice and the mischief, END
BEGIN NOW Of the cunning Pau-Puk-Keewis. END
BEGIN NOW Hard his breath came through his nostrils, END
BEGIN NOW Through his teeth he buzzed and muttered END
BEGIN NOW Words of anger and resentment, END
BEGIN NOW Hot and humming, like a hornet. END
BEGIN NOW I will slay this Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Slay this mischief-maker!" said he. END
BEGIN NOW Not so long and wide the world is, END
BEGIN NOW Not so rude and rough the way is, END
BEGIN NOW That my wrath shall not attain him, END
BEGIN NOW That my vengeance shall not reach him! END
BEGIN NOW Then in swift pursuit departed END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha and the hunters END
BEGIN NOW On the trail of Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Through the forest, where he passed it, END
BEGIN NOW To the headlands where he rested; END
BEGIN NOW But they found not Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Only in the trampled grasses, END
BEGIN NOW In the whortleberry-bushes, END
BEGIN NOW Found the couch where he had rested, END
BEGIN NOW Found the impress of his body. END
BEGIN NOW From the lowlands far beneath them, END
BEGIN NOW From the Muskoday, the meadow, END
BEGIN NOW Pau-Puk-Keewis, turning backward, END
BEGIN NOW Made a gesture of defiance, END
BEGIN NOW Made a gesture of derision; END
BEGIN NOW And aloud cried Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW From the summit of the mountains: END
BEGIN NOW Not so long and wide the world is, END
BEGIN NOW Not so rude and rough the way is, END
BEGIN NOW But my wrath shall overtake you, END
BEGIN NOW And my vengeance shall attain you! END
BEGIN NOW Over rock and over river, END
BEGIN NOW Through bush, and brake, and forest, END
BEGIN NOW Ran the cunning Pau-Puk-Keewis; END
BEGIN NOW Like an antelope he bounded, END
BEGIN NOW Till he came unto a streamlet END
BEGIN NOW In the middle of the forest, END
BEGIN NOW To a streamlet still and tranquil, END
BEGIN NOW That had overflowed its margin, END
BEGIN NOW To a dam made by the beavers, END
BEGIN NOW To a pond of quiet water, END
BEGIN NOW Where knee-deep the trees were standing, END
BEGIN NOW Where the water lilies floated, END
BEGIN NOW Where the rushes waved and whispered. END
BEGIN NOW On the dam stood Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW On the dam of trunks and branches, END
BEGIN NOW O'er whose summit flowed the streamlet. END
BEGIN NOW From the bottom rose the beaver, END
BEGIN NOW Looked with two great eyes of wonder, END
BEGIN NOW Eyes that seemed to ask a question, END
BEGIN NOW At the stranger, Pau-Puk-Keewis. END
BEGIN NOW On the dam stood Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW O'er his ankles flowed the streamlet, END
BEGIN NOW Flowed the bright and silvery water, END
BEGIN NOW And he spake unto the beaver, END
BEGIN NOW With a smile he spake in this wise: END
BEGIN NOW O my friend Ahmeek, the beaver, END
BEGIN NOW Cool and pleasant is the water; END
BEGIN NOW Let me dive into the water, END
BEGIN NOW Let me rest there in your lodges; END
BEGIN NOW Change me, too, into a beaver! END
BEGIN NOW Cautiously replied the beaver, END
BEGIN NOW With reserve he thus made answer: END
BEGIN NOW Let me first consult the others, END
BEGIN NOW Let me ask the other beavers. END
BEGIN NOW Down he sank into the water, END
BEGIN NOW Heavily sank he, as a stone sinks, END
BEGIN NOW Down among the leaves and branches, END
BEGIN NOW Brown and matted at the bottom. END
BEGIN NOW On the dam stood Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW O'er his ankles flowed the streamlet, END
BEGIN NOW Dashed upon the stones beneath him, END
BEGIN NOW Spread serene and calm before him, END
BEGIN NOW And the sunshine and the shadows END
BEGIN NOW Fell in flecks and gleams upon him, END
BEGIN NOW Fell in little shining patches, END
BEGIN NOW Through the waving, rustling branches. END
BEGIN NOW From the bottom rose the beavers, END
BEGIN NOW Silently above the surface END
BEGIN NOW Rose one head and then another, END
BEGIN NOW Till the pond seemed full of beavers, END
BEGIN NOW Full of black and shining faces. END
BEGIN NOW To the beavers Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Spake entreating, said in this wise: END
BEGIN NOW Very pleasant is your dwelling, END
BEGIN NOW O my friends! and safe from danger; END
BEGIN NOW Can you not, with all your cunning, END
BEGIN NOW All your wisdom and contrivance, END
BEGIN NOW Change me, too, into a beaver? END
BEGIN NOW Yes! replied Ahmeek, the beaver, END
BEGIN NOW He the King of all the beavers, END
BEGIN NOW Let yourself slide down among us, END
BEGIN NOW Down into the tranquil water. END
BEGIN NOW Down into the pond among them END
BEGIN NOW Silently sank Pau-Puk-Keewis; END
BEGIN NOW Black became his shirt of deer-skin, END
BEGIN NOW Black his moccasins and leggings, END
BEGIN NOW In a broad black tail behind him END
BEGIN NOW Spread his fox-tails and his fringes; END
BEGIN NOW He was changed into a beaver. END
BEGIN NOW Make me large," said Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Make me large and make me larger, END
BEGIN NOW Larger than the other beavers. END
BEGIN NOW Yes, the beaver chief responded, END
BEGIN NOW When our lodge below you enter, END
BEGIN NOW In our wigwam we will make you END
BEGIN NOW Ten times larger than the others. END
BEGIN NOW Thus into the clear, brown water END
BEGIN NOW Silently sank Pau-Puk-Keewis: END
BEGIN NOW Found the bottom covered over END
BEGIN NOW With the trunks of trees and branches, END
BEGIN NOW Hoards of food against the winter, END
BEGIN NOW Piles and heaps against the famine; END
BEGIN NOW Found the lodge with arching doorway, END
BEGIN NOW Leading into spacious chambers. END
BEGIN NOW Here they made him large and larger, END
BEGIN NOW Made him largest of the beavers, END
BEGIN NOW Ten times larger than the others. END
BEGIN NOW You shall be our ruler," said they; END
BEGIN NOW Chief and King of all the beavers. END
BEGIN NOW But not long had Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Sat in state among the beavers, END
BEGIN NOW When there came a voice, of warning END
BEGIN NOW From the watchman at his station END
BEGIN NOW In the water-flags and lilies, END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha with his hunters! END
BEGIN NOW Then they heard a cry above them, END
BEGIN NOW Heard a shouting and a tramping, END
BEGIN NOW Heard a crashing and a rushing, END
BEGIN NOW And the water round and o'er them END
BEGIN NOW Sank and sucked away in eddies, END
BEGIN NOW And they knew their dam was broken. END
BEGIN NOW On the lodge's roof the hunters END
BEGIN NOW Leaped, and broke it all asunder; END
BEGIN NOW Streamed the sunshine through the crevice, END
BEGIN NOW Sprang the beavers through the doorway, END
BEGIN NOW Hid themselves in deeper water, END
BEGIN NOW In the channel of the streamlet; END
BEGIN NOW But the mighty Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Could not pass beneath the doorway; END
BEGIN NOW He was puffed with pride and feeding, END
BEGIN NOW He was swollen like a bladder. END
BEGIN NOW Through the roof looked Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Cried aloud, "O Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Vain are all your craft and cunning, END
BEGIN NOW Vain your manifold disguises! END
BEGIN NOW Well I know you, Pau-Puk-Keewis! END
BEGIN NOW With their clubs they beat and bruised him, END
BEGIN NOW Beat to death poor Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Pounded him as maize is pounded, END
BEGIN NOW Till his skull was crushed to pieces. END
BEGIN NOW Six tall hunters, lithe and limber, END
BEGIN NOW Bore him home on poles and branches, END
BEGIN NOW Bore the body of the beaver; END
BEGIN NOW But the ghost, the Jeebi in him, END
BEGIN NOW Thought and felt as Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Still lived on as Pau-Puk-Keewis. END
BEGIN NOW And it fluttered, strove, and struggled, END
BEGIN NOW Waving hither, waving thither, END
BEGIN NOW As the curtains of a wigwam END
BEGIN NOW Struggle with their thongs of deer-skin, END
BEGIN NOW When the wintry wind is blowing; END
BEGIN NOW Till it drew itself together, END
BEGIN NOW Till it rose up from the body, END
BEGIN NOW Till it took the form and features END
BEGIN NOW Of the cunning Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Vanishing into the forest. END
BEGIN NOW But the wary Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Saw the figure ere it vanished, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the form of Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Glide into the soft blue shadow END
BEGIN NOW Of the pine-trees of the forest; END
BEGIN NOW Toward the squares of white beyond it, END
BEGIN NOW Toward an opening in the forest. END
BEGIN NOW Like a wind it rushed and panted, END
BEGIN NOW Bending all the boughs before it, END
BEGIN NOW And behind it, as the rain comes, END
BEGIN NOW Came the steps of Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW To a lake with many islands END
BEGIN NOW Came the breathless Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Where among the water-lilies END
BEGIN NOW Pishnekuh, the brant, were sailing; END
BEGIN NOW Through the tufts of rushes floating, END
BEGIN NOW Steering through the reedy Islands. END
BEGIN NOW Now their broad black beaks they lifted, END
BEGIN NOW Now they plunged beneath the water, END
BEGIN NOW Now they darkened in the shadow, END
BEGIN NOW Now they brightened in the sunshine. END
BEGIN NOW Pishnekuh! cried Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Pishnekuh! my brothers!" said he, END
BEGIN NOW Change me to a brant with plumage, END
BEGIN NOW With a shining neck and feathers, END
BEGIN NOW Make me large, and make me larger, END
BEGIN NOW Ten times larger than the others. END
BEGIN NOW Straightway to a brant they changed him, END
BEGIN NOW With two huge and dusky pinions, END
BEGIN NOW With a bosom smooth and rounded, END
BEGIN NOW With a bill like two great paddles, END
BEGIN NOW Made him larger than the others, END
BEGIN NOW Ten times larger than the largest, END
BEGIN NOW Just as, shouting from the forest, END
BEGIN NOW On the shore stood Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW Up they rose with cry and clamor, END
BEGIN NOW With a whir and beat of pinions, END
BEGIN NOW Rose up from the reedy Islands, END
BEGIN NOW From the water-flags and lilies. END
BEGIN NOW And they said to Pau-Puk-Keewis: END
BEGIN NOW In your flying, look not downward, END
BEGIN NOW Take good heed and look not downward, END
BEGIN NOW Lest some strange mischance should happen, END
BEGIN NOW Lest some great mishap befall you! END
BEGIN NOW Fast and far they fled to northward, END
BEGIN NOW Fast and far through mist and sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW Fed among the moors and fen-lands, END
BEGIN NOW Slept among the reeds and rushes. END
BEGIN NOW On the morrow as they journeyed, END
BEGIN NOW Buoyed and lifted by the South-wind, END
BEGIN NOW Wafted onward by the South-wind, END
BEGIN NOW Blowing fresh and strong behind them, END
BEGIN NOW Rose a sound of human voices, END
BEGIN NOW Rose a clamor from beneath them, END
BEGIN NOW From the lodges of a village, END
BEGIN NOW From the people miles beneath them. END
BEGIN NOW For the people of the village END
BEGIN NOW Saw the flock of brant with wonder, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the wings of Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Flapping far up in the ether, END
BEGIN NOW Broader than two doorway curtains. END
BEGIN NOW Pau-Puk-Keewis heard the shouting, END
BEGIN NOW Knew the voice of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Knew the outcry of Iagoo, END
BEGIN NOW And, forgetful of the warning, END
BEGIN NOW Drew his neck in, and looked downward, END
BEGIN NOW And the wind that blew behind him END
BEGIN NOW Caught his mighty fan of feathers, END
BEGIN NOW Sent him wheeling, whirling downward! END
BEGIN NOW All in vain did Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Struggle to regain his balance! END
BEGIN NOW Whirling round and round and downward, END
BEGIN NOW He beheld in turn the village END
BEGIN NOW And in turn the flock above him, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the village coming nearer, END
BEGIN NOW And the flock receding farther, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the voices growing louder, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the shouting and the laughter; END
BEGIN NOW Saw no more the flocks above him, END
BEGIN NOW Only saw the earth beneath him; END
BEGIN NOW Dead out of the empty heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Dead among the shouting people, END
BEGIN NOW With a heavy sound and sullen, END
BEGIN NOW Fell the brant with broken pinions. END
BEGIN NOW But his soul, his ghost, his shadow, END
BEGIN NOW Still survived as Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Took again the form and features END
BEGIN NOW Of the handsome Yenadizze, END
BEGIN NOW And again went rushing onward, END
BEGIN NOW Followed fast by Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Crying: "Not so wide the world is, END
BEGIN NOW Not so long and rough the way is, END
BEGIN NOW But my wrath shall overtake you, END
BEGIN NOW But my vengeance shall attain you! END
BEGIN NOW And so near he came, so near him, END
BEGIN NOW That his hand was stretched to seize him, END
BEGIN NOW His right hand to seize and hold him, END
BEGIN NOW When the cunning Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Whirled and spun about in circles, END
BEGIN NOW Fanned the air into a whirlwind, END
BEGIN NOW Danced the dust and leaves about him, END
BEGIN NOW And amid the whirling eddies END
BEGIN NOW Sprang into a hollow oak-tree, END
BEGIN NOW Changed himself into a serpent, END
BEGIN NOW Gliding out through root and rubbish. END
BEGIN NOW With his right hand Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Smote amain the hollow oak-tree, END
BEGIN NOW Rent it into shreds and splinters, END
BEGIN NOW Left it lying there in fragments. END
BEGIN NOW But in vain; for Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Once again in human figure, END
BEGIN NOW Full in sight ran on before him, END
BEGIN NOW Sped away in gust and whirlwind, END
BEGIN NOW On the shores of Gitche Gumee, END
BEGIN NOW Came unto the rocky headlands, END
BEGIN NOW To the Pictured Rocks of sandstone, END
BEGIN NOW Looking over lake and landscape. END
BEGIN NOW Opened wide his rocky doorways, END
BEGIN NOW Opened wide his deep abysses, END
BEGIN NOW Giving Pau-Puk-Keewis shelter END
BEGIN NOW In his caverns dark and dreary, END
BEGIN NOW Bidding Pau-Puk-Keewis welcome END
BEGIN NOW To his gloomy lodge of sandstone. END
BEGIN NOW There without stood Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Found the doorways closed against him, END
BEGIN NOW With his mittens, Minjekahwun, END
BEGIN NOW Smote great caverns in the sandstone, END
BEGIN NOW Cried aloud in tones of thunder, END
BEGIN NOW Opened not, and made no answer END
BEGIN NOW From the silent crags of sandstone, END
BEGIN NOW From the gloomy rock abysses. END
BEGIN NOW Then he raised his hands to heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Called imploring on the tempest, END
BEGIN NOW Called Waywassimo, the lightning, END
BEGIN NOW And the thunder, Annemeekee; END
BEGIN NOW And they came with night and darkness, END
BEGIN NOW Sweeping down the Big-Sea-Water END
BEGIN NOW From the distant Thunder Mountains; END
BEGIN NOW And the trembling Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Heard the footsteps of the thunder, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the red eyes of the lightning, END
BEGIN NOW Was afraid, and crouched and trembled. END
BEGIN NOW Then Waywassimo, the lightning, END
BEGIN NOW Smote the doorways of the caverns, END
BEGIN NOW With his war-club smote the doorways, END
BEGIN NOW Smote the jutting crags of sandstone, END
BEGIN NOW And the thunder, Annemeekee, END
BEGIN NOW Shouted down into the caverns, END
BEGIN NOW And the crags fell, and beneath them END
BEGIN NOW Dead among the rocky ruins END
BEGIN NOW Lay the cunning Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Lay the handsome Yenadizze, END
BEGIN NOW Slain in his own human figure. END
BEGIN NOW Ended were his wild adventures, END
BEGIN NOW Ended were his tricks and gambols, END
BEGIN NOW Ended all his craft and cunning, END
BEGIN NOW Ended all his mischief-making, END
BEGIN NOW All his gambling and his dancing, END
BEGIN NOW All his wooing of the maidens. END
BEGIN NOW Then the noble Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Took his soul, his ghost, his shadow, END
BEGIN NOW Spake and said: "O Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW Never more in human figure END
BEGIN NOW Shall you search for new adventures; END
BEGIN NOW Never more with jest and laughter END
BEGIN NOW Dance the dust and leaves in whirlwinds; END
BEGIN NOW But above there in the heavens END
BEGIN NOW You shall soar and sail in circles; END
BEGIN NOW I will change you to an eagle, END
BEGIN NOW To Keneu, the great war-eagle, END
BEGIN NOW Chief of all the fowls with feathers, END
BEGIN NOW Chief of Hiawatha's chickens. END
BEGIN NOW And the name of Pau-Puk-Keewis END
BEGIN NOW Lingers still among the people, END
BEGIN NOW Lingers still among the singers, END
BEGIN NOW And among the story-tellers; END
BEGIN NOW And in Winter, when the snow-flakes END
BEGIN NOW Whirl in eddies round the lodges, END
BEGIN NOW When the wind in gusty tumult END
BEGIN NOW O'er the smoke-flue pipes and whistles, END
BEGIN NOW There, they cry, "comes Pau-Puk-Keewis, END
BEGIN NOW He is dancing through the village, END
BEGIN NOW He is gathering in his harvest! END
BEGIN NOW Far and wide among the nations END
BEGIN NOW Spread the name and fame of Kwasind; END
BEGIN NOW No man dared to strive with Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW No man could compete with Kwasind. END
BEGIN NOW But the mischievous Puk-Wudjies, END
BEGIN NOW They the envious Little People, END
BEGIN NOW They the fairies and the pygmies, END
BEGIN NOW Plotted and conspired against him. END
BEGIN NOW If this hateful Kwasind," said they, END
BEGIN NOW If this great, outrageous fellow END
BEGIN NOW Goes on thus a little longer, END
BEGIN NOW Tearing everything he touches, END
BEGIN NOW Rending everything to pieces, END
BEGIN NOW Filling all the world with wonder, END
BEGIN NOW What becomes of the Puk-Wudjies? END
BEGIN NOW Who will care for the Puk-Wudjies? END
BEGIN NOW He will tread us down like mushrooms, END
BEGIN NOW Drive us all into the water, END
BEGIN NOW Give our bodies to be eaten END
BEGIN NOW By the wicked Nee-ba-naw-baigs, END
BEGIN NOW By the Spirits of the water! END
BEGIN NOW So the angry Little People END
BEGIN NOW All conspired against the Strong Man, END
BEGIN NOW All conspired to murder Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW Yes, to rid the world of Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW The audacious, overbearing, END
BEGIN NOW Heartless, haughty, dangerous Kwasind! END
BEGIN NOW Now this wondrous strength of Kwasind END
BEGIN NOW In his crown alone was seated; END
BEGIN NOW In his crown too was his weakness; END
BEGIN NOW There alone could he be wounded, END
BEGIN NOW Nowhere else could weapon pierce him, END
BEGIN NOW Nowhere else could weapon harm him. END
BEGIN NOW Even there the only weapon END
BEGIN NOW That could wound him, that could slay him, END
BEGIN NOW Was the seed-cone of the pine-tree, END
BEGIN NOW Was the blue cone of the fir-tree. END
BEGIN NOW This was Kwasind's fatal secret, END
BEGIN NOW Known to no man among mortals; END
BEGIN NOW But the cunning Little People, END
BEGIN NOW The Puk-Wudjies, knew the secret, END
BEGIN NOW Knew the only way to kill him. END
BEGIN NOW So they gathered cones together, END
BEGIN NOW Gathered seed-cones of the pine-tree, END
BEGIN NOW Gathered blue cones of the fir-tree, END
BEGIN NOW In the woods by Taquamenaw, END
BEGIN NOW Brought them to the river's margin, END
BEGIN NOW Heaped them in great piles together, END
BEGIN NOW Where the red rocks from the margin END
BEGIN NOW Jutting overhang the river. END
BEGIN NOW There they lay in wait for Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW The malicious Little People. END
BEGIN NOW `T was an afternoon in Summer; END
BEGIN NOW Very hot and still the air was, END
BEGIN NOW Very smooth the gliding river, END
BEGIN NOW Motionless the sleeping shadows: END
BEGIN NOW Insects glistened in the sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW Insects skated on the water, END
BEGIN NOW Filled the drowsy air with buzzing, END
BEGIN NOW With a far resounding war-cry. END
BEGIN NOW Down the river came the Strong Man, END
BEGIN NOW In his birch canoe came Kwasind, END
BEGIN NOW Floating slowly down the current END
BEGIN NOW Of the sluggish Taquamenaw, END
BEGIN NOW Very languid with the weather, END
BEGIN NOW Very sleepy with the silence. END
BEGIN NOW From the overhanging branches, END
BEGIN NOW From the tassels of the birch-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Soft the Spirit of Sleep descended; END
BEGIN NOW By his airy hosts surrounded, END
BEGIN NOW His invisible attendants, END
BEGIN NOW Like a burnished Dush-kwo-ne-she, END
BEGIN NOW Like a dragon-fly, he hovered END
BEGIN NOW O'er the drowsy head of Kwasind. END
BEGIN NOW To his ear there came a murmur END
BEGIN NOW As of waves upon a sea-shore, END
BEGIN NOW As of far-off tumbling waters, END
BEGIN NOW As of winds among the pine-trees; END
BEGIN NOW And he felt upon his forehead END
BEGIN NOW Blows of little airy war-clubs, END
BEGIN NOW Wielded by the slumbrous legions END
BEGIN NOW As of some one breathing on him. END
BEGIN NOW At the first blow of their war-clubs, END
BEGIN NOW Fell a drowsiness on Kwasind; END
BEGIN NOW At the second blow they smote him, END
BEGIN NOW Motionless his paddle rested; END
BEGIN NOW At the third, before his vision END
BEGIN NOW Reeled the landscape Into darkness, END
BEGIN NOW Very sound asleep was Kwasind. END
BEGIN NOW So he floated down the river, END
BEGIN NOW Like a blind man seated upright, END
BEGIN NOW Floated down the Taquamenaw, END
BEGIN NOW Underneath the trembling birch-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Underneath the wooded headlands, END
BEGIN NOW Underneath the war encampment END
BEGIN NOW Of the pygmies, the Puk-Wudjies. END
BEGIN NOW There they stood, all armed and waiting, END
BEGIN NOW Hurled the pine-cones down upon him, END
BEGIN NOW Struck him on his brawny shoulders, END
BEGIN NOW On his crown defenceless struck him. END
BEGIN NOW Death to Kwasind!" was the sudden END
BEGIN NOW War-cry of the Little People. END
BEGIN NOW And he sideways swayed and tumbled, END
BEGIN NOW Sideways fell into the river, END
BEGIN NOW Plunged beneath the sluggish water END
BEGIN NOW Headlong, as an otter plunges; END
BEGIN NOW And the birch canoe, abandoned, END
BEGIN NOW Drifted empty down the river, END
BEGIN NOW Bottom upward swerved and drifted: END
BEGIN NOW Nothing more was seen of Kwasind. END
BEGIN NOW But the memory of the Strong Man END
BEGIN NOW Lingered long among the people, END
BEGIN NOW And whenever through the forest END
BEGIN NOW Raged and roared the wintry tempest, END
BEGIN NOW And the branches, tossed and troubled, END
BEGIN NOW Creaked and groaned and split asunder, END
BEGIN NOW Kwasind! cried they; "that is Kwasind! END
BEGIN NOW He is gathering in his fire-wood! END
BEGIN NOW Never stoops the soaring vulture END
BEGIN NOW On his quarry in the desert, END
BEGIN NOW On the sick or wounded bison, END
BEGIN NOW But another vulture, watching END
BEGIN NOW From his high aerial look-out, END
BEGIN NOW Sees the downward plunge, and follows; END
BEGIN NOW And a third pursues the second, END
BEGIN NOW Coming from the invisible ether, END
BEGIN NOW First a speck, and then a vulture, END
BEGIN NOW Till the air is dark with pinions. END
BEGIN NOW So disasters come not singly; END
BEGIN NOW But as if they watched and waited, END
BEGIN NOW Scanning one another's motions, END
BEGIN NOW When the first descends, the others END
BEGIN NOW Follow, follow, gathering flock-wise END
BEGIN NOW Round their victim, sick and wounded, END
BEGIN NOW First a shadow, then a sorrow, END
BEGIN NOW Till the air is dark with anguish. END
BEGIN NOW Now, o'er all the dreary North-land, END
BEGIN NOW Breathing on the lakes and rivers, END
BEGIN NOW Into stone had changed their waters. END
BEGIN NOW From his hair he shook the snow-flakes, END
BEGIN NOW Till the plains were strewn with whiteness, END
BEGIN NOW One uninterrupted level, END
BEGIN NOW As if, stooping, the Creator END
BEGIN NOW With his hand had smoothed them over. END
BEGIN NOW Through the forest, wide and wailing, END
BEGIN NOW Roamed the hunter on his snow-shoes; END
BEGIN NOW In the village worked the women, END
BEGIN NOW Pounded maize, or dressed the deer-skin; END
BEGIN NOW And the young men played together END
BEGIN NOW On the ice the noisy ball-play, END
BEGIN NOW On the plain the dance of snow-shoes. END
BEGIN NOW One dark evening, after sundown, END
BEGIN NOW In her wigwam Laughing Water END
BEGIN NOW Sat with old Nokomis, waiting END
BEGIN NOW For the steps of Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Homeward from the hunt returning. END
BEGIN NOW On their faces gleamed the firelight, END
BEGIN NOW Painting them with streaks of crimson, END
BEGIN NOW In the eyes of old Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Glimmered like the watery moonlight, END
BEGIN NOW In the eyes of Laughing Water END
BEGIN NOW Glistened like the sun in water; END
BEGIN NOW And behind them crouched their shadows END
BEGIN NOW In the corners of the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW And the smoke in wreaths above them END
BEGIN NOW Climbed and crowded through the smoke-flue. END
BEGIN NOW Then the curtain of the doorway END
BEGIN NOW From without was slowly lifted; END
BEGIN NOW Brighter glowed the fire a moment, END
BEGIN NOW And a moment swerved the smoke-wreath, END
BEGIN NOW As two women entered softly, END
BEGIN NOW Passed the doorway uninvited, END
BEGIN NOW Without word of salutation, END
BEGIN NOW Without sign of recognition, END
BEGIN NOW Sat down in the farthest corner, END
BEGIN NOW Crouching low among the shadows. END
BEGIN NOW From their aspect and their garments, END
BEGIN NOW Strangers seemed they in the village; END
BEGIN NOW Very pale and haggard were they, END
BEGIN NOW As they sat there sad and silent, END
BEGIN NOW Trembling, cowering with the shadows. END
BEGIN NOW Was it the wind above the smoke-flue, END
BEGIN NOW Muttering down into the wigwam? END
BEGIN NOW Was it the owl, the Koko-koho, END
BEGIN NOW Hooting from the dismal forest? END
BEGIN NOW Sure a voice said in the silence: END
BEGIN NOW These are corpses clad in garments, END
BEGIN NOW These are ghosts that come to haunt you, END
BEGIN NOW From the kingdom of Ponemah, END
BEGIN NOW From the land of the Hereafter! END
BEGIN NOW Homeward now came Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW From his hunting in the forest, END
BEGIN NOW With the snow upon his tresses, END
BEGIN NOW And the red deer on his shoulders. END
BEGIN NOW At the feet of Laughing Water END
BEGIN NOW Down he threw his lifeless burden; END
BEGIN NOW Nobler, handsomer she thought him, END
BEGIN NOW Than when first he came to woo her, END
BEGIN NOW First threw down the deer before her, END
BEGIN NOW As a token of his wishes, END
BEGIN NOW As a promise of the future. END
BEGIN NOW Then he turned and saw the strangers, END
BEGIN NOW Cowering, crouching with the shadows; END
BEGIN NOW Said within himself, "Who are they? END
BEGIN NOW What strange guests has Minnehaha? END
BEGIN NOW But he questioned not the strangers, END
BEGIN NOW Only spake to bid them welcome END
BEGIN NOW To his lodge, his food, his fireside. END
BEGIN NOW When the evening meal was ready, END
BEGIN NOW And the deer had been divided, END
BEGIN NOW Both the pallid guests, the strangers, END
BEGIN NOW Springing from among the shadows, END
BEGIN NOW Seized upon the choicest portions, END
BEGIN NOW Seized the white fat of the roebuck, END
BEGIN NOW Set apart for Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW For the wife of Hiawatha; END
BEGIN NOW Without asking, without thanking, END
BEGIN NOW Eagerly devoured the morsels, END
BEGIN NOW Flitted back among the shadows END
BEGIN NOW In the corner of the wigwam. END
BEGIN NOW Not a word spake Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Not a motion made Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Not a gesture Laughing Water; END
BEGIN NOW Not a change came o'er their features; END
BEGIN NOW Only Minnehaha softly END
BEGIN NOW Whispered, saying, "They are famished; END
BEGIN NOW Let them do what best delights them; END
BEGIN NOW Let them eat, for they are famished. END
BEGIN NOW Many a daylight dawned and darkened, END
BEGIN NOW Many a night shook off the daylight END
BEGIN NOW As the pine shakes off the snow-flakes END
BEGIN NOW From the midnight of its branches; END
BEGIN NOW Day by day the guests unmoving END
BEGIN NOW Sat there silent in the wigwam; END
BEGIN NOW But by night, in storm or starlight, END
BEGIN NOW Forth they went into the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Bringing fire-wood to the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Bringing pine-cones for the burning, END
BEGIN NOW Always sad and always silent. END
BEGIN NOW And whenever Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Came from fishing or from hunting, END
BEGIN NOW When the evening meal was ready, END
BEGIN NOW And the food had been divided, END
BEGIN NOW Gliding from their darksome corner, END
BEGIN NOW Came the pallid guests, the strangers, END
BEGIN NOW Seized upon the choicest portions END
BEGIN NOW Set aside for Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW And without rebuke or question END
BEGIN NOW Flitted back among the shadows. END
BEGIN NOW Never once had Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW By a word or look reproved them; END
BEGIN NOW Never once had old Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Made a gesture of impatience; END
BEGIN NOW Never once had Laughing Water END
BEGIN NOW Shown resentment at the outrage. END
BEGIN NOW All had they endured in silence, END
BEGIN NOW That the rights of guest and stranger, END
BEGIN NOW That the virtue of free-giving, END
BEGIN NOW By a look might not be lessened, END
BEGIN NOW By a word might not be broken. END
BEGIN NOW Once at midnight Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Ever wakeful, ever watchful, END
BEGIN NOW In the wigwam, dimly lighted END
BEGIN NOW By the brands that still were burning, END
BEGIN NOW By the glimmering, flickering firelight END
BEGIN NOW Heard a sighing, oft repeated, END
BEGIN NOW From his couch rose Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW From his shaggy hides of bison, END
BEGIN NOW Pushed aside the deer-skin curtain, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the pallid guests, the shadows, END
BEGIN NOW Sitting upright on their couches, END
BEGIN NOW Weeping in the silent midnight. END
BEGIN NOW And he said: "O guests! why is it END
BEGIN NOW That your hearts are so afflicted, END
BEGIN NOW That you sob so in the midnight? END
BEGIN NOW Has perchance the old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Has my wife, my Minnehaha, END
BEGIN NOW Wronged or grieved you by unkindness, END
BEGIN NOW Failed in hospitable duties? END
BEGIN NOW Then the shadows ceased from weeping, END
BEGIN NOW Ceased from sobbing and lamenting, END
BEGIN NOW And they said, with gentle voices: END
BEGIN NOW We are ghosts of the departed, END
BEGIN NOW Souls of those who once were with you. END
BEGIN NOW From the realms of Chibiabos END
BEGIN NOW Hither have we come to try you, END
BEGIN NOW Hither have we come to warn you. END
BEGIN NOW Cries of grief and lamentation END
BEGIN NOW Cries of anguish from the living, END
BEGIN NOW Calling back their friends departed, END
BEGIN NOW Sadden us with useless sorrow. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore have we come to try you; END
BEGIN NOW No one knows us, no one heeds us. END
BEGIN NOW We are but a burden to you, END
BEGIN NOW And we see that the departed END
BEGIN NOW Have no place among the living. END
BEGIN NOW Think of this, O Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Speak of it to all the people, END
BEGIN NOW That henceforward and forever END
BEGIN NOW They no more with lamentations END
BEGIN NOW Sadden the souls of the departed END
BEGIN NOW Do not lay such heavy burdens END
BEGIN NOW In the graves of those you bury, END
BEGIN NOW Not such weight of furs and wampum, END
BEGIN NOW Not such weight of pots and kettles, END
BEGIN NOW For the spirits faint beneath them. END
BEGIN NOW Only give them food to carry, END
BEGIN NOW Only give them fire to light them. END
BEGIN NOW Four days is the spirit's journey END
BEGIN NOW To the land of ghosts and shadows, END
BEGIN NOW Four its lonely night encampments; END
BEGIN NOW Four times must their fires be lighted. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore, when the dead are buried, END
BEGIN NOW Let a fire, as night approaches, END
BEGIN NOW Four times on the grave be kindled, END
BEGIN NOW That the soul upon its journey END
BEGIN NOW May not lack the cheerful firelight, END
BEGIN NOW May not grope about in darkness. END
BEGIN NOW Farewell, noble Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW We have put you to the trial, END
BEGIN NOW To the proof have put your patience, END
BEGIN NOW By the insult of our presence, END
BEGIN NOW By the outrage of our actions. END
BEGIN NOW We have found you great and noble. END
BEGIN NOW Fail not in the greater trial, END
BEGIN NOW Faint not in the harder struggle. END
BEGIN NOW When they ceased, a sudden darkness END
BEGIN NOW Fell and filled the silent wigwam. END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha heard a rustle END
BEGIN NOW As of garments trailing by him, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the curtain of the doorway END
BEGIN NOW Lifted by a hand he saw not, END
BEGIN NOW Felt the cold breath of the night air, END
BEGIN NOW For a moment saw the starlight; END
BEGIN NOW But he saw the ghosts no longer, END
BEGIN NOW Saw no more the wandering spirits END
BEGIN NOW From the kingdom of Ponemah, END
BEGIN NOW From the land of the Hereafter. END
BEGIN NOW Oh the long and dreary Winter! END
BEGIN NOW Oh the cold and cruel Winter! END
BEGIN NOW Ever thicker, thicker, thicker END
BEGIN NOW Froze the ice on lake and river, END
BEGIN NOW Ever deeper, deeper, deeper END
BEGIN NOW Fell the snow o'er all the landscape, END
BEGIN NOW Fell the covering snow, and drifted END
BEGIN NOW Through the forest, round the village. END
BEGIN NOW Hardly from his buried wigwam END
BEGIN NOW Could the hunter force a passage; END
BEGIN NOW With his mittens and his snow-shoes END
BEGIN NOW Vainly walked he through the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Sought for bird or beast and found none, END
BEGIN NOW Saw no track of deer or rabbit, END
BEGIN NOW In the snow beheld no footprints, END
BEGIN NOW In the ghastly, gleaming forest END
BEGIN NOW Fell, and could not rise from weakness, END
BEGIN NOW Perished there from cold and hunger. END
BEGIN NOW Oh the famine and the fever! END
BEGIN NOW Oh the wasting of the famine! END
BEGIN NOW Oh the blasting of the fever! END
BEGIN NOW Oh the wailing of the children! END
BEGIN NOW Oh the anguish of the women! END
BEGIN NOW All the earth was sick and famished; END
BEGIN NOW Hungry was the air around them, END
BEGIN NOW Hungry was the sky above them, END
BEGIN NOW And the hungry stars in heaven END
BEGIN NOW Like the eyes of wolves glared at them! END
BEGIN NOW Into Hiawatha's wigwam END
BEGIN NOW Came two other guests, as silent END
BEGIN NOW As the ghosts were, and as gloomy, END
BEGIN NOW Waited not to be invited END
BEGIN NOW Did not parley at the doorway END
BEGIN NOW Sat there without word of welcome END
BEGIN NOW In the seat of Laughing Water; END
BEGIN NOW Looked with haggard eyes and hollow END
BEGIN NOW At the face of Laughing Water. END
BEGIN NOW And the foremost said: "Behold me! END
BEGIN NOW And the other said: "Behold me! END
BEGIN NOW And the lovely Minnehaha END
BEGIN NOW Shuddered as they looked upon her, END
BEGIN NOW Shuddered at the words they uttered, END
BEGIN NOW Lay down on her bed in silence, END
BEGIN NOW Hid her face, but made no answer; END
BEGIN NOW Lay there trembling, freezing, burning END
BEGIN NOW At the looks they cast upon her, END
BEGIN NOW At the fearful words they uttered. END
BEGIN NOW Forth into the empty forest END
BEGIN NOW Rushed the maddened Hiawatha; END
BEGIN NOW In his heart was deadly sorrow, END
BEGIN NOW In his face a stony firmness; END
BEGIN NOW On his brow the sweat of anguish END
BEGIN NOW Started, but it froze and fell not. END
BEGIN NOW Wrapped in furs and armed for hunting, END
BEGIN NOW With his mighty bow of ash-tree, END
BEGIN NOW With his quiver full of arrows, END
BEGIN NOW With his mittens, Minjekahwun, END
BEGIN NOW Into the vast and vacant forest END
BEGIN NOW On his snow-shoes strode he forward. END
BEGIN NOW Cried he with his face uplifted END
BEGIN NOW In that bitter hour of anguish, END
BEGIN NOW Give your children food, O father! END
BEGIN NOW Give us food, or we must perish! END
BEGIN NOW Give me food for Minnehaha, END
BEGIN NOW For my dying Minnehaha! END
BEGIN NOW Through the far-resounding forest, END
BEGIN NOW Through the forest vast and vacant END
BEGIN NOW Rang that cry of desolation, END
BEGIN NOW But there came no other answer END
BEGIN NOW Than the echo of his crying, END
BEGIN NOW Than the echo of the woodlands, END
BEGIN NOW All day long roved Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW In that melancholy forest, END
BEGIN NOW Through the shadow of whose thickets, END
BEGIN NOW In the pleasant days of Summer, END
BEGIN NOW Of that ne'er forgotten Summer, END
BEGIN NOW He had brought his young wife homeward END
BEGIN NOW From the land of the Dacotahs; END
BEGIN NOW When the birds sang in the thickets, END
BEGIN NOW And the streamlets laughed and glistened, END
BEGIN NOW And the air was full of fragrance, END
BEGIN NOW And the lovely Laughing Water END
BEGIN NOW Said with voice that did not tremble, END
BEGIN NOW I will follow you, my husband! END
BEGIN NOW In the wigwam with Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW With those gloomy guests that watched her, END
BEGIN NOW She was lying, the Beloved, END
BEGIN NOW She, the dying Minnehaha. END
BEGIN NOW Hark! she said; "I hear a rushing, END
BEGIN NOW Hear a roaring and a rushing, END
BEGIN NOW Calling to me from a distance! END
BEGIN NOW No, my child!" said old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW `T is the night-wind in the pine-trees! END
BEGIN NOW Look! she said; "I see my father END
BEGIN NOW Standing lonely at his doorway, END
BEGIN NOW Beckoning to me from his wigwam END
BEGIN NOW In the land of the Dacotahs! END
BEGIN NOW No, my child!" said old Nokomis. END
BEGIN NOW `T is the smoke, that waves and beckons! END
BEGIN NOW Ah! said she, "the eyes of Pauguk END
BEGIN NOW Glare upon me in the darkness, END
BEGIN NOW I can feel his icy fingers END
BEGIN NOW Clasping mine amid the darkness! END
BEGIN NOW And the desolate Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Far away amid the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Miles away among the mountains, END
BEGIN NOW Heard that sudden cry of anguish, END
BEGIN NOW Heard the voice of Minnehaha END
BEGIN NOW Calling to him in the darkness, END
BEGIN NOW Over snow-fields waste and pathless, END
BEGIN NOW Under snow-encumbered branches, END
BEGIN NOW Homeward hurried Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Empty-handed, heavy-hearted, END
BEGIN NOW Heard Nokomis moaning, wailing: END
BEGIN NOW Would that I had perished for you, END
BEGIN NOW Would that I were dead as you are! END
BEGIN NOW And he rushed into the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the old Nokomis slowly END
BEGIN NOW Rocking to and fro and moaning, END
BEGIN NOW Saw his lovely Minnehaha END
BEGIN NOW Lying dead and cold before him, END
BEGIN NOW And his bursting heart within him END
BEGIN NOW Uttered such a cry of anguish, END
BEGIN NOW That the forest moaned and shuddered, END
BEGIN NOW That the very stars in heaven END
BEGIN NOW Shook and trembled with his anguish. END
BEGIN NOW Then he sat down, still and speechless, END
BEGIN NOW At the feet of Laughing Water, END
BEGIN NOW At those willing feet, that never END
BEGIN NOW More would lightly run to meet him, END
BEGIN NOW Never more would lightly follow. END
BEGIN NOW With both hands his face he covered, END
BEGIN NOW Seven long days and nights he sat there, END
BEGIN NOW As if in a swoon he sat there, END
BEGIN NOW Speechless, motionless, unconscious END
BEGIN NOW Of the daylight or the darkness. END
BEGIN NOW Then they buried Minnehaha; END
BEGIN NOW In the snow a grave they made her END
BEGIN NOW In the forest deep and darksome END
BEGIN NOW Underneath the moaning hemlocks; END
BEGIN NOW Clothed her in her richest garments END
BEGIN NOW Wrapped her in her robes of ermine, END
BEGIN NOW Covered her with snow, like ermine; END
BEGIN NOW Thus they buried Minnehaha. END
BEGIN NOW And at night a fire was lighted, END
BEGIN NOW On her grave four times was kindled, END
BEGIN NOW For her soul upon its journey END
BEGIN NOW From his doorway Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Saw it burning in the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Lighting up the gloomy hemlocks; END
BEGIN NOW From his sleepless bed uprising, END
BEGIN NOW Stood and watched it at the doorway, END
BEGIN NOW That it might not be extinguished, END
BEGIN NOW Might not leave her in the darkness. END
BEGIN NOW Farewell! said he, Minnehaha! END
BEGIN NOW All my heart is buried with you, END
BEGIN NOW All my thoughts go onward with you! END
BEGIN NOW Come not back again to labor, END
BEGIN NOW Come not back again to suffer, END
BEGIN NOW Wear the heart and waste the body. END
BEGIN NOW Soon my task will be completed, END
BEGIN NOW Soon your footsteps I shall follow END
BEGIN NOW The White Man's Foot END
BEGIN NOW In his lodge beside a river, END
BEGIN NOW Close beside a frozen river, END
BEGIN NOW Sat an old man, sad and lonely. END
BEGIN NOW White his hair was as a snow-drift; END
BEGIN NOW Dull and low his fire was burning, END
BEGIN NOW And the old man shook and trembled, END
BEGIN NOW In his tattered white-skin-wrapper, END
BEGIN NOW Hearing nothing but the tempest END
BEGIN NOW As it roared along the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Seeing nothing but the snow-storm, END
BEGIN NOW As it whirled and hissed and drifted. END
BEGIN NOW All the coals were white with ashes, END
BEGIN NOW And the fire was slowly dying, END
BEGIN NOW As a young man, walking lightly, END
BEGIN NOW At the open doorway entered. END
BEGIN NOW Red with blood of youth his cheeks were, END
BEGIN NOW Soft his eyes, as stars in Spring-time, END
BEGIN NOW Bound his forehead was with grasses; END
BEGIN NOW Bound and plumed with scented grasses, END
BEGIN NOW On his lips a smile of beauty, END
BEGIN NOW Filling all the lodge with sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW In his hand a bunch of blossoms END
BEGIN NOW Filling all the lodge with sweetness. END
BEGIN NOW Ah, my son!" exclaimed the old man, END
BEGIN NOW Happy are my eyes to see you. END
BEGIN NOW Sit here on the mat beside me, END
BEGIN NOW Sit here by the dying embers, END
BEGIN NOW Let us pass the night together, END
BEGIN NOW Tell me of your strange adventures, END
BEGIN NOW Of the lands where you have travelled; END
BEGIN NOW I will tell you of my prowess, END
BEGIN NOW Of my many deeds of wonder. END
BEGIN NOW From his pouch he drew his peace-pipe, END
BEGIN NOW Very old and strangely fashioned; END
BEGIN NOW Made of red stone was the pipe-head, END
BEGIN NOW And the stem a reed with feathers; END
BEGIN NOW Filled the pipe with bark of willow, END
BEGIN NOW Placed a burning coal upon it, END
BEGIN NOW Gave it to his guest, the stranger, END
BEGIN NOW And began to speak in this wise: END
BEGIN NOW When I blow my breath about me, END
BEGIN NOW When I breathe upon the landscape, END
BEGIN NOW Motionless are all the rivers, END
BEGIN NOW Hard as stone becomes the water! END
BEGIN NOW And the young man answered, smiling: END
BEGIN NOW When I blow my breath about me, END
BEGIN NOW When I breathe upon the landscape, END
BEGIN NOW Flowers spring up o'er all the meadows, END
BEGIN NOW Singing, onward rush the rivers! END
BEGIN NOW When I shake my hoary tresses, END
BEGIN NOW Said the old man darkly frowning, END
BEGIN NOW All the land with snow is covered; END
BEGIN NOW All the leaves from all the branches END
BEGIN NOW Fall and fade and die and wither, END
BEGIN NOW For I breathe, and lo! they are not. END
BEGIN NOW From the waters and the marshes, END
BEGIN NOW Rise the wild goose and the heron, END
BEGIN NOW Fly away to distant regions, END
BEGIN NOW For I speak, and lo! they are not. END
BEGIN NOW And where'er my footsteps wander, END
BEGIN NOW All the wild beasts of the forest END
BEGIN NOW Hide themselves in holes and caverns, END
BEGIN NOW And the earth becomes as flintstone! END
BEGIN NOW When I shake my flowing ringlets, END
BEGIN NOW Said the young man, softly laughing, END
BEGIN NOW Showers of rain fall warm and welcome, END
BEGIN NOW Plants lift up their heads rejoicing, END
BEGIN NOW Back unto their lakes and marshes END
BEGIN NOW Come the wild goose and the heron, END
BEGIN NOW Homeward shoots the arrowy swallow, END
BEGIN NOW Sing the bluebird and the robin, END
BEGIN NOW And where'er my footsteps wander, END
BEGIN NOW All the meadows wave with blossoms, END
BEGIN NOW All the woodlands ring with music, END
BEGIN NOW All the trees are dark with foliage! END
BEGIN NOW While they spake, the night departed: END
BEGIN NOW From the distant realms of Wabun, END
BEGIN NOW From his shining lodge of silver, END
BEGIN NOW Like a warrior robed and painted, END
BEGIN NOW Came the sun, and said, "Behold me END
BEGIN NOW Gheezis, the great sun, behold me! END
BEGIN NOW Then the old man's tongue was speechless END
BEGIN NOW And the air grew warm and pleasant, END
BEGIN NOW And upon the wigwam sweetly END
BEGIN NOW Sang the bluebird and the robin, END
BEGIN NOW And the stream began to murmur, END
BEGIN NOW And a scent of growing grasses END
BEGIN NOW Through the lodge was gently wafted. END
BEGIN NOW And Segwun, the youthful stranger, END
BEGIN NOW More distinctly in the daylight END
BEGIN NOW Saw the icy face before him; END
BEGIN NOW From his eyes the tears were flowing, END
BEGIN NOW As from melting lakes the streamlets, END
BEGIN NOW And his body shrunk and dwindled END
BEGIN NOW As the shouting sun ascended, END
BEGIN NOW Till into the air it faded, END
BEGIN NOW Till into the ground it vanished, END
BEGIN NOW And the young man saw before him, END
BEGIN NOW On the hearth-stone of the wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Where the fire had smoked and smouldered, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the earliest flower of Spring-time, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the Beauty of the Spring-time, END
BEGIN NOW Saw the Miskodeed in blossom. END
BEGIN NOW Thus it was that in the North-land END
BEGIN NOW After that unheard-of coldness, END
BEGIN NOW That intolerable Winter, END
BEGIN NOW Came the Spring with all its splendor, END
BEGIN NOW All its birds and all its blossoms, END
BEGIN NOW All its flowers and leaves and grasses. END
BEGIN NOW Sailing on the wind to northward, END
BEGIN NOW Flying in great flocks, like arrows, END
BEGIN NOW Like huge arrows shot through heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Passed the swan, the Mahnahbezee, END
BEGIN NOW Speaking almost as a man speaks; END
BEGIN NOW And in long lines waving, bending END
BEGIN NOW Like a bow-string snapped asunder, END
BEGIN NOW Came the white goose, Waw-be-wawa; END
BEGIN NOW And in pairs, or singly flying, END
BEGIN NOW Mahng the loon, with clangorous pinions, END
BEGIN NOW The blue heron, the Shuh-shuh-gah, END
BEGIN NOW And the grouse, the Mushkodasa. END
BEGIN NOW In the thickets and the meadows END
BEGIN NOW Piped the bluebird, the Owaissa, END
BEGIN NOW On the summit of the lodges END
BEGIN NOW Sang the robin, the Opechee, END
BEGIN NOW In the covert of the pine-trees END
BEGIN NOW Cooed the pigeon, the Omemee; END
BEGIN NOW And the sorrowing Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Speechless in his infinite sorrow, END
BEGIN NOW Heard their voices calling to him, END
BEGIN NOW Went forth from his gloomy doorway, END
BEGIN NOW Stood and gazed into the heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Gazed upon the earth and waters. END
BEGIN NOW From his wanderings far to eastward, END
BEGIN NOW From the regions of the morning, END
BEGIN NOW From the shining land of Wabun, END
BEGIN NOW Homeward now returned Iagoo, END
BEGIN NOW The great traveller, the great boaster, END
BEGIN NOW Full of new and strange adventures, END
BEGIN NOW Marvels many and many wonders. END
BEGIN NOW And the people of the village END
BEGIN NOW Listened to him as he told them END
BEGIN NOW Of his marvellous adventures, END
BEGIN NOW Laughing answered him in this wise: END
BEGIN NOW Ugh! it is indeed Iagoo! END
BEGIN NOW No one else beholds such wonders! END
BEGIN NOW He had seen, he said, a water END
BEGIN NOW Bigger than the Big-Sea-Water, END
BEGIN NOW Broader than the Gitche Gumee, END
BEGIN NOW Bitter so that none could drink it! END
BEGIN NOW At each other looked the warriors, END
BEGIN NOW Looked the women at each other, END
BEGIN NOW Smiled, and said, "It cannot be so! END
BEGIN NOW Kaw! they said, "it cannot be so! END
BEGIN NOW O'er it, said he, o'er this water END
BEGIN NOW Came a great canoe with pinions, END
BEGIN NOW A canoe with wings came flying, END
BEGIN NOW Bigger than a grove of pine-trees, END
BEGIN NOW Taller than the tallest tree-tops! END
BEGIN NOW And the old men and the women END
BEGIN NOW Kaw! they said, "we don't believe it! END
BEGIN NOW From its mouth, he said, to greet him, END
BEGIN NOW Came Waywassimo, the lightning, END
BEGIN NOW Came the thunder, Annemeekee! END
BEGIN NOW And the warriors and the women END
BEGIN NOW Laughed aloud at poor Iagoo; END
BEGIN NOW Kaw! they said, "what tales you tell us! END
BEGIN NOW In it, said he, came a people, END
BEGIN NOW In the great canoe with pinions END
BEGIN NOW Came, he said, a hundred warriors; END
BEGIN NOW Painted white were all their faces END
BEGIN NOW And with hair their chins were covered! END
BEGIN NOW And the warriors and the women END
BEGIN NOW Laughed and shouted in derision, END
BEGIN NOW Like the ravens on the tree-tops, END
BEGIN NOW Like the crows upon the hemlocks. END
BEGIN NOW Kaw! they said, "what lies you tell us! END
BEGIN NOW Do not think that we believe them! END
BEGIN NOW Only Hiawatha laughed not, END
BEGIN NOW But he gravely spake and answered END
BEGIN NOW To their jeering and their jesting: END
BEGIN NOW True is all Iagoo tells us; END
BEGIN NOW I have seen it in a vision, END
BEGIN NOW Seen the great canoe with pinions, END
BEGIN NOW Seen the people with white faces, END
BEGIN NOW Seen the coming of this bearded END
BEGIN NOW People of the wooden vessel END
BEGIN NOW From the regions of the morning, END
BEGIN NOW From the shining land of Wabun. END
BEGIN NOW Sends them hither on his errand. END
BEGIN NOW Sends them to us with his message. END
BEGIN NOW Wheresoe'er they move, before them END
BEGIN NOW Swarms the stinging fly, the Ahmo, END
BEGIN NOW Swarms the bee, the honey-maker; END
BEGIN NOW Wheresoe'er they tread, beneath them END
BEGIN NOW Springs a flower unknown among us, END
BEGIN NOW Springs the White-man's Foot in blossom. END
BEGIN NOW Let us welcome, then, the strangers, END
BEGIN NOW Hail them as our friends and brothers, END
BEGIN NOW And the heart's right hand of friendship END
BEGIN NOW Give them when they come to see us. END
BEGIN NOW Said this to me in my vision. END
BEGIN NOW I beheld, too, in that vision END
BEGIN NOW All the secrets of the future, END
BEGIN NOW Of the distant days that shall be. END
BEGIN NOW I beheld the westward marches END
BEGIN NOW Of the unknown, crowded nations. END
BEGIN NOW All the land was full of people, END
BEGIN NOW Restless, struggling, toiling, striving, END
BEGIN NOW Speaking many tongues, yet feeling END
BEGIN NOW But one heart-beat in their bosoms. END
BEGIN NOW In the woodlands rang their axes, END
BEGIN NOW Smoked their towns in all the valleys, END
BEGIN NOW Over all the lakes and rivers END
BEGIN NOW Rushed their great canoes of thunder. END
BEGIN NOW Then a darker, drearier vision END
BEGIN NOW Passed before me, vague and cloud-like; END
BEGIN NOW I beheld our nation scattered, END
BEGIN NOW All forgetful of my counsels, END
BEGIN NOW Weakened, warring with each other: END
BEGIN NOW Saw the remnants of our people END
BEGIN NOW Sweeping westward, wild and woful, END
BEGIN NOW Like the cloud-rack of a tempest, END
BEGIN NOW Like the withered leaves of Autumn! END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha's Departure END
BEGIN NOW By the shore of Gitche Gumee, END
BEGIN NOW By the shining Big-Sea-Water, END
BEGIN NOW At the doorway of his wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW In the pleasant Summer morning, END
BEGIN NOW Hiawatha stood and waited. END
BEGIN NOW All the air was full of freshness, END
BEGIN NOW All the earth was bright and joyous, END
BEGIN NOW And before him, through the sunshine, END
BEGIN NOW Westward toward the neighboring forest END
BEGIN NOW Passed in golden swarms the Ahmo, END
BEGIN NOW Passed the bees, the honey-makers, END
BEGIN NOW Burning, singing in the sunshine. END
BEGIN NOW Bright above him shone the heavens, END
BEGIN NOW Level spread the lake before him; END
BEGIN NOW From its bosom leaped the sturgeon, END
BEGIN NOW Sparkling, flashing in the sunshine; END
BEGIN NOW On its margin the great forest END
BEGIN NOW Stood reflected in the water, END
BEGIN NOW Every tree-top had its shadow, END
BEGIN NOW Motionless beneath the water. END
BEGIN NOW From the brow of Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Gone was every trace of sorrow, END
BEGIN NOW As the fog from off the water, END
BEGIN NOW As the mist from off the meadow. END
BEGIN NOW With a smile of joy and triumph, END
BEGIN NOW With a look of exultation, END
BEGIN NOW As of one who in a vision END
BEGIN NOW Sees what is to be, but is not, END
BEGIN NOW Stood and waited Hiawatha. END
BEGIN NOW Toward the sun his hands were lifted, END
BEGIN NOW Both the palms spread out against it, END
BEGIN NOW And between the parted fingers END
BEGIN NOW Fell the sunshine on his features, END
BEGIN NOW Flecked with light his naked shoulders, END
BEGIN NOW As it falls and flecks an oak-tree END
BEGIN NOW Through the rifted leaves and branches. END
BEGIN NOW O'er the water floating, flying, END
BEGIN NOW Something in the hazy distance, END
BEGIN NOW Something in the mists of morning, END
BEGIN NOW Loomed and lifted from the water, END
BEGIN NOW Now seemed floating, now seemed flying, END
BEGIN NOW Coming nearer, nearer, nearer. END
BEGIN NOW Was it Shingebis the diver? END
BEGIN NOW Or the pelican, the Shada? END
BEGIN NOW Or the heron, the Shuh-shuh-gah? END
BEGIN NOW Or the white goose, Waw-be-wawa, END
BEGIN NOW With the water dripping, flashing, END
BEGIN NOW From its glossy neck and feathers? END
BEGIN NOW It was neither goose nor diver, END
BEGIN NOW Neither pelican nor heron, END
BEGIN NOW O'er the water floating, flying, END
BEGIN NOW Through the shining mist of morning, END
BEGIN NOW But a birch canoe with paddles, END
BEGIN NOW Rising, sinking on the water, END
BEGIN NOW Dripping, flashing in the sunshine; END
BEGIN NOW And within it came a people END
BEGIN NOW From the distant land of Wabun, END
BEGIN NOW From the farthest realms of morning END
BEGIN NOW Came the Black-Robe chief, the Prophet, END
BEGIN NOW He the Priest of Prayer, the Pale-face, END
BEGIN NOW With his guides and his companions. END
BEGIN NOW And the noble Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW With his hands aloft extended, END
BEGIN NOW Held aloft in sign of welcome, END
BEGIN NOW Waited, full of exultation, END
BEGIN NOW Till the birch canoe with paddles END
BEGIN NOW Grated on the shining pebbles, END
BEGIN NOW Stranded on the sandy margin, END
BEGIN NOW Till the Black-Robe chief, the Pale-face, END
BEGIN NOW With the cross upon his bosom, END
BEGIN NOW Landed on the sandy margin. END
BEGIN NOW Then the joyous Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Cried aloud and spake in this wise: END
BEGIN NOW Beautiful is the sun, O strangers, END
BEGIN NOW When you come so far to see us! END
BEGIN NOW All our town in peace awaits you, END
BEGIN NOW All our doors stand open for you; END
BEGIN NOW You shall enter all our wigwams, END
BEGIN NOW For the heart's right hand we give you. END
BEGIN NOW Never bloomed the earth so gayly, END
BEGIN NOW Never shone the sun so brightly, END
BEGIN NOW As to-day they shine and blossom END
BEGIN NOW When you come so far to see us! END
BEGIN NOW Never was our lake so tranquil, END
BEGIN NOW Nor so free from rocks, and sand-bars; END
BEGIN NOW For your birch canoe in passing END
BEGIN NOW Has removed both rock and sand-bar. END
BEGIN NOW Never before had our tobacco END
BEGIN NOW Such a sweet and pleasant flavor, END
BEGIN NOW Never the broad leaves of our cornfields END
BEGIN NOW Were so beautiful to look on, END
BEGIN NOW As they seem to us this morning, END
BEGIN NOW When you come so far to see us! END
BEGIN NOW And the Black-Robe chief made answer, END
BEGIN NOW Stammered in his speech a little, END
BEGIN NOW Speaking words yet unfamiliar: END
BEGIN NOW Peace be with you, Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Peace be with you and your people, END
BEGIN NOW Peace of prayer, and peace of pardon, END
BEGIN NOW Then the generous Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Led the strangers to his wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW Seated them on skins of bison, END
BEGIN NOW Seated them on skins of ermine, END
BEGIN NOW And the careful old Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Brought them food in bowls of basswood, END
BEGIN NOW Water brought in birchen dippers, END
BEGIN NOW And the calumet, the peace-pipe, END
BEGIN NOW Filled and lighted for their smoking. END
BEGIN NOW All the old men of the village, END
BEGIN NOW All the warriors of the nation, END
BEGIN NOW The magicians, the Wabenos, END
BEGIN NOW And the Medicine-men, the Medas, END
BEGIN NOW Came to bid the strangers welcome; END
BEGIN NOW It is well", they said, "O brothers, END
BEGIN NOW That you come so far to see us! END
BEGIN NOW In a circle round the doorway, END
BEGIN NOW With their pipes they sat in silence, END
BEGIN NOW Waiting to behold the strangers, END
BEGIN NOW Waiting to receive their message; END
BEGIN NOW Till the Black-Robe chief, the Pale-face, END
BEGIN NOW From the wigwam came to greet them, END
BEGIN NOW Stammering in his speech a little, END
BEGIN NOW Speaking words yet unfamiliar; END
BEGIN NOW It is well," they said, "O brother, END
BEGIN NOW That you come so far to see us! END
BEGIN NOW Then the Black-Robe chief, the Prophet, END
BEGIN NOW Told his message to the people, END
BEGIN NOW Told the purport of his mission, END
BEGIN NOW Told them of the Virgin Mary, END
BEGIN NOW And her blessed Son, the Saviour, END
BEGIN NOW How in distant lands and ages END
BEGIN NOW He had lived on earth as we do; END
BEGIN NOW How he fasted, prayed, and labored; END
BEGIN NOW Mocked him, scourged him, crucified him; END
BEGIN NOW How he rose from where they laid him, END
BEGIN NOW Walked again with his disciples, END
BEGIN NOW And ascended into heaven. END
BEGIN NOW And the chiefs made answer, saying: END
BEGIN NOW We have listened to your message, END
BEGIN NOW We have heard your words of wisdom, END
BEGIN NOW We will think on what you tell us. END
BEGIN NOW It is well for us, O brothers, END
BEGIN NOW That you come so far to see us! END
BEGIN NOW Then they rose up and departed END
BEGIN NOW Each one homeward to his wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW To the young men and the women END
BEGIN NOW Told the story of the strangers END
BEGIN NOW Whom the Master of Life had sent them END
BEGIN NOW From the shining land of Wabun. END
BEGIN NOW Heavy with the heat and silence END
BEGIN NOW Grew the afternoon of Summer; END
BEGIN NOW With a drowsy sound the forest END
BEGIN NOW Whispered round the sultry wigwam, END
BEGIN NOW With a sound of sleep the water END
BEGIN NOW Rippled on the beach below it; END
BEGIN NOW From the cornfields shrill and ceaseless END
BEGIN NOW Sang the grasshopper, Pah-puk-keena; END
BEGIN NOW And the guests of Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Weary with the heat of Summer, END
BEGIN NOW Slumbered in the sultry wigwam. END
BEGIN NOW Slowly o'er the simmering landscape END
BEGIN NOW Fell the evening's dusk and coolness, END
BEGIN NOW And the long and level sunbeams END
BEGIN NOW Shot their spears into the forest, END
BEGIN NOW Breaking through its shields of shadow, END
BEGIN NOW Rushed into each secret ambush, END
BEGIN NOW Searched each thicket, dingle, hollow; END
BEGIN NOW Still the guests of Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Slumbered in the silent wigwam. END
BEGIN NOW From his place rose Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Bade farewell to old Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW Spake in whispers, spake in this wise, END
BEGIN NOW Did not wake the guests, that slumbered. END
BEGIN NOW I am going, O Nokomis, END
BEGIN NOW On a long and distant journey, END
BEGIN NOW To the portals of the Sunset. END
BEGIN NOW To the regions of the home-wind, END
BEGIN NOW But these guests I leave behind me, END
BEGIN NOW In your watch and ward I leave them; END
BEGIN NOW See that never harm comes near them, END
BEGIN NOW See that never fear molests them, END
BEGIN NOW Never danger nor suspicion, END
BEGIN NOW Never want of food or shelter, END
BEGIN NOW In the lodge of Hiawatha! END
BEGIN NOW Forth into the village went he, END
BEGIN NOW Bade farewell to all the warriors, END
BEGIN NOW Bade farewell to all the young men, END
BEGIN NOW Spake persuading, spake in this wise: END
BEGIN NOW I am going, O my people, END
BEGIN NOW On a long and distant journey; END
BEGIN NOW Many moons and many winters END
BEGIN NOW Will have come, and will have vanished, END
BEGIN NOW Ere I come again to see you. END
BEGIN NOW But my guests I leave behind me; END
BEGIN NOW Listen to their words of wisdom, END
BEGIN NOW Listen to the truth they tell you, END
BEGIN NOW For the Master of Life has sent them END
BEGIN NOW From the land of light and morning! END
BEGIN NOW On the shore stood Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW Turned and waved his hand at parting; END
BEGIN NOW On the clear and luminous water END
BEGIN NOW Launched his birch canoe for sailing, END
BEGIN NOW From the pebbles of the margin END
BEGIN NOW Shoved it forth into the water; END
BEGIN NOW Whispered to it, "Westward! westward! END
BEGIN NOW And with speed it darted forward. END
BEGIN NOW And the evening sun descending END
BEGIN NOW Set the clouds on fire with redness, END
BEGIN NOW Burned the broad sky, like a prairie, END
BEGIN NOW Left upon the level water END
BEGIN NOW One long track and trail of splendor, END
BEGIN NOW Down whose stream, as down a river, END
BEGIN NOW Westward, westward Hiawatha END
BEGIN NOW Sailed into the fiery sunset, END
BEGIN NOW Sailed into the purple vapors, END
BEGIN NOW Sailed into the dusk of evening: END
BEGIN NOW And the people from the margin END
BEGIN NOW Watched him floating, rising, sinking, END
BEGIN NOW Till the birch canoe seemed lifted END
BEGIN NOW High into that sea of splendor, END
BEGIN NOW Till it sank into the vapors END
BEGIN NOW Like the new moon slowly, slowly END
BEGIN NOW Sinking in the purple distance. END
BEGIN NOW And they said, "Farewell forever! END
BEGIN NOW And the forests, dark and lonely, END
BEGIN NOW Moved through all their depths of darkness, END
BEGIN NOW And the waves upon the margin END
BEGIN NOW Rising, rippling on the pebbles, END
BEGIN NOW And the heron, the Shuh-shuh-gah, END
BEGIN NOW From her haunts among the fen-lands, END
BEGIN NOW Thus departed Hiawatha, END
BEGIN NOW In the glory of the sunset, END
BEGIN NOW In the purple mists of evening, END
BEGIN NOW To the regions of the home-wind, END
