BEGIN NOW Puggawau'gun, a war-club END
BEGIN NOW Puk-Wudj'ies, little wild men of the END
BEGIN NOW woods; pygmies END
BEGIN NOW Sah-sah-je'wun, rapids END
BEGIN NOW Sha'da, the pelican END
BEGIN NOW Shahbo'min, the gooseberry END
BEGIN NOW Shah-shah, long ago END
BEGIN NOW Shaugoda'ya, a coward END
BEGIN NOW Shawgashee', the craw-fish END
BEGIN NOW Shawonda'see, the South-Wind END
BEGIN NOW Shaw-shaw, the swallow END
BEGIN NOW Shesh'ebwug, ducks; pieces in the Game END
BEGIN NOW Shin'gebis, the diver, or grebe END
BEGIN NOW Showain'neme'shin, pity me END
BEGIN NOW Shuh-shuh-gah', the blue heron END
BEGIN NOW Soan-ge-ta'ha, strong-hearted END
BEGIN NOW Subbeka'she, the spider END
BEGIN NOW Sugge'me, the mosquito END
BEGIN NOW To'tem, family coat-of-arms END
BEGIN NOW Ugudwash', the sun-fish END
BEGIN NOW Wabas'so, the rabbit, the North END
BEGIN NOW Wabe'no, a magician, a juggler END
BEGIN NOW Wabe'no-wusk, yarrow END
BEGIN NOW Wa'bun, the East-Wind END
BEGIN NOW Wa'bun An'nung, the Star of the East, END
BEGIN NOW Wahono'win, a cry of lamentation END
BEGIN NOW Wah-wah-tay'see, the fire-fly END
BEGIN NOW Waubewy'on, a white skin wrapper END
BEGIN NOW Wa'wa, the wild goose END
BEGIN NOW Waw-be-wa'wa, the white goose END
BEGIN NOW Wawonais'sa, the whippoorwill END
BEGIN NOW Way-muk-kwa'na, the caterpillar END
BEGIN NOW Weno'nah, the eldest daughter; Hiawatha's mother, END
BEGIN NOW daughter of Nokomis END
BEGIN NOW Yenadiz'ze, an idler and gambler; an END
BEGIN NOW Indian dandy END
BEGIN NOW Of that Forbidden Tree, whose mortal tast END
BEGIN NOW Brought Death into the World, and all our woe, END
BEGIN NOW With loss of EDEN, till one greater Man END
BEGIN NOW Restore us, and regain the blissful Seat, END
BEGIN NOW Sing Heav'nly Muse, that on the secret top END
BEGIN NOW Of OREB, or of SINAI, didst inspire END
BEGIN NOW That Shepherd, who first taught the chosen Seed, END
BEGIN NOW In the Beginning how the Heav'ns and Earth END
BEGIN NOW Rose out of CHAOS: Or if SION Hill END
BEGIN NOW Delight thee more, and SILOA'S Brook that flow'd END
BEGIN NOW Fast by the Oracle of God; I thence END
BEGIN NOW Invoke thy aid to my adventrous Song, END
BEGIN NOW That with no middle flight intends to soar END
BEGIN NOW Above th' AONIAN Mount, while it pursues END
BEGIN NOW Things unattempted yet in Prose or Rhime. END
BEGIN NOW And chiefly Thou O Spirit, that dost prefer END
BEGIN NOW Before all Temples th' upright heart and pure, END
BEGIN NOW Instruct me, for Thou know'st; Thou from the first END
BEGIN NOW Wast present, and with mighty wings outspread END
BEGIN NOW Dove-like satst brooding on the vast Abyss END
BEGIN NOW And mad'st it pregnant: What in me is dark END
BEGIN NOW Illumine, what is low raise and support; END
BEGIN NOW That to the highth of this great Argument END
BEGIN NOW I may assert th' Eternal Providence, END
BEGIN NOW And justifie the wayes of God to men. END
BEGIN NOW Say first, for Heav'n hides nothing from thy view END
BEGIN NOW Nor the deep Tract of Hell, say first what cause END
BEGIN NOW Mov'd our Grand Parents in that happy State, END
BEGIN NOW Favour'd of Heav'n so highly, to fall off END
BEGIN NOW From their Creator, and transgress his Will END
BEGIN NOW For one restraint, Lords of the World besides? END
BEGIN NOW Who first seduc'd them to that fowl revolt? END
BEGIN NOW Th' infernal Serpent; he it was, whose guile END
BEGIN NOW Stird up with Envy and Revenge, deceiv'd END
BEGIN NOW The Mother of Mankinde, what time his Pride END
BEGIN NOW Had cast him out from Heav'n, with all his Host END
BEGIN NOW Of Rebel Angels, by whose aid aspiring END
BEGIN NOW To set himself in Glory above his Peers, END
BEGIN NOW He trusted to have equal'd the most High, END
BEGIN NOW If he oppos'd; and with ambitious aim END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd impious War in Heav'n and Battel proud END
BEGIN NOW With vain attempt. Him the Almighty Power END
BEGIN NOW Hurld headlong flaming from th' Ethereal Skie END
BEGIN NOW With hideous ruine and combustion down END
BEGIN NOW To bottomless perdition, there to dwell END
BEGIN NOW In Adamantine Chains and penal Fire, END
BEGIN NOW Who durst defie th' Omnipotent to Arms. END
BEGIN NOW Nine times the Space that measures Day and Night END
BEGIN NOW To mortal men, he with his horrid crew END
BEGIN NOW Lay vanquisht, rowling in the fiery Gulfe END
BEGIN NOW Confounded though immortal: But his doom END
BEGIN NOW Reserv'd him to more wrath; for now the thought END
BEGIN NOW Both of lost happiness and lasting pain END
BEGIN NOW Torments him; round he throws his baleful eyes END
BEGIN NOW That witness'd huge affliction and dismay END
BEGIN NOW Mixt with obdurate pride and stedfast hate: END
BEGIN NOW At once as far as Angels kenn he views END
BEGIN NOW The dismal Situation waste and wilde, END
BEGIN NOW A Dungeon horrible, on all sides round END
BEGIN NOW As one great Furnace flam'd, yet from those flames END
BEGIN NOW No light, but rather darkness visible END
BEGIN NOW Serv'd only to discover sights of woe, END
BEGIN NOW Regions of sorrow, doleful shades, where peace END
BEGIN NOW And rest can never dwell, hope never comes END
BEGIN NOW That comes to all; but torture without end END
BEGIN NOW Still urges, and a fiery Deluge, fed END
BEGIN NOW With ever-burning Sulphur unconsum'd: END
BEGIN NOW Such place Eternal Justice had prepar'd END
BEGIN NOW For those rebellious, here their Prison ordain'd END
BEGIN NOW In utter darkness, and their portion set END
BEGIN NOW As far remov'd from God and light of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW As from the Center thrice to th' utmost Pole. END
BEGIN NOW O how unlike the place from whence they fell! END
BEGIN NOW There the companions of his fall, o'rewhelm'd END
BEGIN NOW With Floods and Whirlwinds of tempestuous fire, END
BEGIN NOW He soon discerns, and weltring by his side END
BEGIN NOW One next himself in power, and next in crime, END
BEGIN NOW Long after known in PALESTINE, and nam'd END
BEGIN NOW BEELZEBUB. To whom th' Arch-Enemy, END
BEGIN NOW And thence in Heav'n call'd Satan, with bold words END
BEGIN NOW Breaking the horrid silence thus began. END
BEGIN NOW If thou beest he; But O how fall'n! how chang'd END
BEGIN NOW From him, who in the happy Realms of Light END
BEGIN NOW Cloth'd with transcendent brightnes didst outshine END
BEGIN NOW Myriads though bright: If he whom mutual league, END
BEGIN NOW United thoughts and counsels, equal hope, END
BEGIN NOW And hazard in the Glorious Enterprize, END
BEGIN NOW Joynd with me once, now misery hath joynd END
BEGIN NOW In equal ruin: into what Pit thou seest END
BEGIN NOW From what highth fal'n, so much the stronger provd END
BEGIN NOW He with his Thunder: and till then who knew END
BEGIN NOW The force of those dire Arms? yet not for those END
BEGIN NOW Nor what the Potent Victor in his rage END
BEGIN NOW Can else inflict do I repent or change, END
BEGIN NOW Though chang'd in outward lustre; that fixt mind END
BEGIN NOW And high disdain, from sence of injur'd merit, END
BEGIN NOW That with the mightiest rais'd me to contend, END
BEGIN NOW And to the fierce contention brought along END
BEGIN NOW Innumerable force of Spirits arm'd END
BEGIN NOW That durst dislike his reign, and me preferring, END
BEGIN NOW His utmost power with adverse power oppos'd END
BEGIN NOW In dubious Battel on the Plains of Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW And shook his throne. What though the field be lost? END
BEGIN NOW All is not lost; the unconquerable Will, END
BEGIN NOW And study of revenge, immortal hate, END
BEGIN NOW And courage never to submit or yield: END
BEGIN NOW And what is else not to be overcome? END
BEGIN NOW That Glory never shall his wrath or might END
BEGIN NOW Extort from me. To bow and sue for grace END
BEGIN NOW With suppliant knee, and deifie his power END
BEGIN NOW Who from the terrour of this Arm so late END
BEGIN NOW Doubted his Empire, that were low indeed, END
BEGIN NOW That were an ignominy and shame beneath END
BEGIN NOW This downfall; since by Fate the strength of Gods END
BEGIN NOW And this Empyreal substance cannot fail, END
BEGIN NOW Since through experience of this great event END
BEGIN NOW In Arms not worse, in foresight much advanc't, END
BEGIN NOW We may with more successful hope resolve END
BEGIN NOW To wage by force or guile eternal Warr END
BEGIN NOW Irreconcileable, to our grand Foe, END
BEGIN NOW Who now triumphs, and in th' excess of joy END
BEGIN NOW Sole reigning holds the Tyranny of Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW So spake th' Apostate Angel, though in pain, END
BEGIN NOW Vaunting aloud, but rackt with deep despare: END
BEGIN NOW And him thus answer'd soon his bold Compeer. END
BEGIN NOW O Prince, O Chief of many Throned Powers, END
BEGIN NOW That led th' imbattelld Seraphim to Warr END
BEGIN NOW Under thy conduct, and in dreadful deeds END
BEGIN NOW Fearless, endanger'd Heav'ns perpetual King; END
BEGIN NOW And put to proof his high Supremacy, END
BEGIN NOW Whether upheld by strength, or Chance, or Fate, END
BEGIN NOW Too well I see and rue the dire event, END
BEGIN NOW That with sad overthrow and foul defeat END
BEGIN NOW Hath lost us Heav'n, and all this mighty Host END
BEGIN NOW In horrible destruction laid thus low, END
BEGIN NOW As far as Gods and Heav'nly Essences END
BEGIN NOW Can Perish: for the mind and spirit remains END
BEGIN NOW Invincible, and vigour soon returns, END
BEGIN NOW Though all our Glory extinct, and happy state END
BEGIN NOW Here swallow'd up in endless misery. END
BEGIN NOW But what if he our Conquerour, (whom I now END
BEGIN NOW Of force believe Almighty, since no less END
BEGIN NOW Then such could hav orepow'rd such force as ours) END
BEGIN NOW Have left us this our spirit and strength intire END
BEGIN NOW Strongly to suffer and support our pains, END
BEGIN NOW That we may so suffice his vengeful ire, END
BEGIN NOW Or do him mightier service as his thralls END
BEGIN NOW By right of Warr, what e're his business be END
BEGIN NOW Here in the heart of Hell to work in Fire, END
BEGIN NOW Or do his Errands in the gloomy Deep; END
BEGIN NOW What can it then avail though yet we feel END
BEGIN NOW Strength undiminisht, or eternal being END
BEGIN NOW To undergo eternal punishment? END
BEGIN NOW Whereto with speedy words th' Arch-fiend reply'd. END
BEGIN NOW Fall'n Cherube, to be weak is miserable END
BEGIN NOW Doing or Suffering: but of this be sure, END
BEGIN NOW To do ought good never will be our task, END
BEGIN NOW But ever to do ill our sole delight, END
BEGIN NOW As being the contrary to his high will END
BEGIN NOW Whom we resist. If then his Providence END
BEGIN NOW Out of our evil seek to bring forth good, END
BEGIN NOW Our labour must be to pervert that end, END
BEGIN NOW And out of good still to find means of evil; END
BEGIN NOW Which oft times may succeed, so as perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Shall grieve him, if I fail not, and disturb END
BEGIN NOW His inmost counsels from their destind aim. END
BEGIN NOW But see the angry Victor hath recall'd END
BEGIN NOW His Ministers of vengeance and pursuit END
BEGIN NOW Back to the Gates of Heav'n: The Sulphurous Hail END
BEGIN NOW Shot after us in storm, oreblown hath laid END
BEGIN NOW The fiery Surge, that from the Precipice END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'n receiv'd us falling, and the Thunder, END
BEGIN NOW Wing'd with red Lightning and impetuous rage, END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps hath spent his shafts, and ceases now END
BEGIN NOW To bellow through the vast and boundless Deep. END
BEGIN NOW Let us not slip th' occasion, whether scorn, END
BEGIN NOW Or satiate fury yield it from our Foe. END
BEGIN NOW Seest thou yon dreary Plain, forlorn and wilde, END
BEGIN NOW The seat of desolation, voyd of light, END
BEGIN NOW Save what the glimmering of these livid flames END
BEGIN NOW Casts pale and dreadful? Thither let us tend END
BEGIN NOW From off the tossing of these fiery waves, END
BEGIN NOW There rest, if any rest can harbour there, END
BEGIN NOW And reassembling our afflicted Powers, END
BEGIN NOW Consult how we may henceforth most offend END
BEGIN NOW Our Enemy, our own loss how repair, END
BEGIN NOW How overcome this dire Calamity, END
BEGIN NOW What reinforcement we may gain from Hope, END
BEGIN NOW If not what resolution from despare. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Satan talking to his neerest Mate END
BEGIN NOW With Head up-lift above the wave, and Eyes END
BEGIN NOW That sparkling blaz'd, his other Parts besides END
BEGIN NOW Prone on the Flood, extended long and large END
BEGIN NOW Lay floating many a rood, in bulk as huge END
BEGIN NOW As whom the Fables name of monstrous size, END
BEGIN NOW TITANIAN, or EARTH-BORN, that warr'd on JOVE, END
BEGIN NOW BRIARIOS or TYPHON, whom the Den END
BEGIN NOW By ancient TARSUS held, or that Sea-beast END
BEGIN NOW LEVIATHAN, which God of all his works END
BEGIN NOW Created hugest that swim th' Ocean stream: END
BEGIN NOW Him haply slumbring on the NORWAY foam END
BEGIN NOW The Pilot of some small night-founder'd Skiff, END
BEGIN NOW Deeming some Island, oft, as Sea-men tell, END
BEGIN NOW With fixed Anchor in his skaly rind END
BEGIN NOW Moors by his side under the Lee, while Night END
BEGIN NOW Invests the Sea, and wished Morn delayes: END
BEGIN NOW So stretcht out huge in length the Arch-fiend lay END
BEGIN NOW Chain'd on the burning Lake, nor ever thence END
BEGIN NOW Had ris'n or heav'd his head, but that the will END
BEGIN NOW And high permission of all-ruling Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Left him at large to his own dark designs, END
BEGIN NOW That with reiterated crimes he might END
BEGIN NOW Heap on himself damnation, while he sought END
BEGIN NOW Evil to others, and enrag'd might see END
BEGIN NOW How all his malice serv'd but to bring forth END
BEGIN NOW Infinite goodness, grace and mercy shewn END
BEGIN NOW On Man by him seduc't, but on himself END
BEGIN NOW Treble confusion, wrath and vengeance pour'd. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith upright he rears from off the Pool END
BEGIN NOW His mighty Stature; on each hand the flames END
BEGIN NOW Drivn backward slope their pointing spires, & rowld END
BEGIN NOW In billows, leave i'th' midst a horrid Vale. END
BEGIN NOW Then with expanded wings he stears his flight END
BEGIN NOW Aloft, incumbent on the dusky Air END
BEGIN NOW That felt unusual weight, till on dry Land END
BEGIN NOW He lights, if it were Land that ever burn'd END
BEGIN NOW With solid, as the Lake with liquid fire; END
BEGIN NOW And such appear'd in hue, as when the force END
BEGIN NOW Of subterranean wind transports a Hill END
BEGIN NOW Torn from PELORUS, or the shatter'd side END
BEGIN NOW Of thundring AETNA, whose combustible END
BEGIN NOW And fewel'd entrals thence conceiving Fire, END
BEGIN NOW Sublim'd with Mineral fury, aid the Winds, END
BEGIN NOW And leave a singed bottom all involv'd END
BEGIN NOW With stench and smoak: Such resting found the sole END
BEGIN NOW Of unblest feet. Him followed his next Mate, END
BEGIN NOW Both glorying to have scap't the STYGIAN flood END
BEGIN NOW As Gods, and by their own recover'd strength, END
BEGIN NOW Not by the sufferance of supernal Power. END
BEGIN NOW Is this the Region, this the Soil, the Clime, END
BEGIN NOW Said then the lost Arch Angel, this the seat END
BEGIN NOW That we must change for Heav'n, this mournful gloom END
BEGIN NOW For that celestial light? Be it so, since hee END
BEGIN NOW Who now is Sovran can dispose and bid END
BEGIN NOW What shall be right: fardest from him is best END
BEGIN NOW Whom reason hath equald, force hath made supream END
BEGIN NOW Above his equals. Farewel happy Fields END
BEGIN NOW Where Joy for ever dwells: Hail horrours, hail END
BEGIN NOW Infernal world, and thou profoundest Hell END
BEGIN NOW Receive thy new Possessor: One who brings END
BEGIN NOW A mind not to be chang'd by Place or Time. END
BEGIN NOW The mind is its own place, and in it self END
BEGIN NOW Can make a Heav'n of Hell, a Hell of Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW What matter where, if I be still the same, END
BEGIN NOW And what I should be, all but less then hee END
BEGIN NOW Whom Thunder hath made greater? Here at least END
BEGIN NOW We shall be free; th' Almighty hath not built END
BEGIN NOW Here for his envy, will not drive us hence: END
BEGIN NOW Here we may reign secure, and in my choyce END
BEGIN NOW To reign is worth ambition though in Hell: END
BEGIN NOW Better to reign in Hell, then serve in Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW But wherefore let we then our faithful friends, END
BEGIN NOW Th' associates and copartners of our loss END
BEGIN NOW Lye thus astonisht on th' oblivious Pool, END
BEGIN NOW And call them not to share with us their part END
BEGIN NOW In this unhappy Mansion, or once more END
BEGIN NOW With rallied Arms to try what may be yet END
BEGIN NOW Regaind in Heav'n, or what more lost in Hell? END
BEGIN NOW So SATAN spake, and him BEELZEBUB END
BEGIN NOW Thus answer'd. Leader of those Armies bright, END
BEGIN NOW Which but th' Omnipotent none could have foyld, END
BEGIN NOW If once they hear that voyce, their liveliest pledge END
BEGIN NOW Of hope in fears and dangers, heard so oft END
BEGIN NOW In worst extreams, and on the perilous edge END
BEGIN NOW Of battel when it rag'd, in all assaults END
BEGIN NOW Their surest signal, they will soon resume END
BEGIN NOW New courage and revive, though now they lye END
BEGIN NOW Groveling and prostrate on yon Lake of Fire, END
BEGIN NOW As we erewhile, astounded and amaz'd, END
BEGIN NOW No wonder, fall'n such a pernicious highth. END
BEGIN NOW He scarce had ceas't when the superiour Fiend END
BEGIN NOW Was moving toward the shore; his ponderous shield END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal temper, massy, large and round, END
BEGIN NOW Behind him cast; the broad circumference END
BEGIN NOW Hung on his shoulders like the Moon, whose Orb END
BEGIN NOW Through Optic Glass the TUSCAN Artist views END
BEGIN NOW At Ev'ning from the top of FESOLE, END
BEGIN NOW Or in VALDARNO, to descry new Lands, END
BEGIN NOW Rivers or Mountains in her spotty Globe. END
BEGIN NOW His Spear, to equal which the tallest Pine END
BEGIN NOW Hewn on NORWEGIAN hills, to be the Mast END
BEGIN NOW Of some great Ammiral, were but a wand, END
BEGIN NOW He walkt with to support uneasie steps END
BEGIN NOW Over the burning Marle, not like those steps END
BEGIN NOW On Heavens Azure, and the torrid Clime END
BEGIN NOW Smote on him sore besides, vaulted with Fire; END
BEGIN NOW Nathless he so endur'd, till on the Beach END
BEGIN NOW Of that inflamed Sea, he stood and call'd END
BEGIN NOW His Legions, Angel Forms, who lay intrans't END
BEGIN NOW Thick as Autumnal Leaves that strow the Brooks END
BEGIN NOW In VALLOMBROSA, where th' ETRURIAN shades END
BEGIN NOW High overarch't imbowr; or scatterd sedge END
BEGIN NOW Afloat, when with fierce Winds ORION arm'd END
BEGIN NOW Hath vext the Red-Sea Coast, whose waves orethrew END
BEGIN NOW BUSIRIS and his MEMPHIAN Chivalrie, END
BEGIN NOW VVhile with perfidious hatred they pursu'd END
BEGIN NOW The Sojourners of GOSHEN, who beheld END
BEGIN NOW From the safe shore their floating Carkases END
BEGIN NOW And broken Chariot Wheels, so thick bestrown END
BEGIN NOW Abject and lost lay these, covering the Flood, END
BEGIN NOW Under amazement of their hideous change. END
BEGIN NOW He call'd so loud, that all the hollow Deep END
BEGIN NOW Of Hell resounded. Princes, Potentates, END
BEGIN NOW Warriers, the Flowr of Heav'n, once yours, now lost, END
BEGIN NOW If such astonishment as this can sieze END
BEGIN NOW Eternal spirits; or have ye chos'n this place END
BEGIN NOW After the toyl of Battel to repose END
BEGIN NOW Your wearied vertue, for the ease you find END
BEGIN NOW To slumber here, as in the Vales of Heav'n? END
BEGIN NOW Or in this abject posture have ye sworn END
BEGIN NOW To adore the Conquerour? who now beholds END
BEGIN NOW Cherube and Seraph rowling in the Flood END
BEGIN NOW With scatter'd Arms and Ensigns, till anon END
BEGIN NOW His swift pursuers from Heav'n Gates discern END
BEGIN NOW Th' advantage, and descending tread us down END
BEGIN NOW Thus drooping, or with linked Thunderbolts END
BEGIN NOW Transfix us to the bottom of this Gulfe. END
BEGIN NOW Awake, arise, or be for ever fall'n. END
BEGIN NOW They heard, and were abasht, and up they sprung END
BEGIN NOW Upon the wing, as when men wont to watch END
BEGIN NOW On duty, sleeping found by whom they dread, END
BEGIN NOW Rouse and bestir themselves ere well awake. END
BEGIN NOW Nor did they not perceave the evil plight END
BEGIN NOW In which they were, or the fierce pains not feel; END
BEGIN NOW Yet to their Generals Voyce they soon obeyd END
BEGIN NOW Innumerable. As when the potent Rod END
BEGIN NOW Wav'd round the Coast, up call'd a pitchy cloud END
BEGIN NOW Of LOCUSTS, warping on the Eastern Wind, END
BEGIN NOW That ore the Realm of impious PHAROAH hung END
BEGIN NOW Like Night, and darken'd all the Land of NILE: END
BEGIN NOW So numberless were those bad Angels seen END
BEGIN NOW Hovering on wing under the Cope of Hell END
BEGIN NOW 'Twixt upper, nether, and surrounding Fires; END
BEGIN NOW Till, as a signal giv'n, th' uplifted Spear END
BEGIN NOW Of their great Sultan waving to direct END
BEGIN NOW Thir course, in even ballance down they light END
BEGIN NOW On the firm brimstone, and fill all the Plain; END
BEGIN NOW A multitude, like which the populous North END
BEGIN NOW Pour'd never from her frozen loyns, to pass END
BEGIN NOW RHENE or the DANAW, when her barbarous Sons END
BEGIN NOW Came like a Deluge on the South, and spread END
BEGIN NOW Beneath GIBRALTAR to the LYBIAN sands. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith from every Squadron and each Band END
BEGIN NOW The Heads and Leaders thither hast where stood END
BEGIN NOW Their great Commander; Godlike shapes and forms END
BEGIN NOW Excelling human, Princely Dignities, END
BEGIN NOW And Powers that earst in Heaven sat on Thrones; END
BEGIN NOW Though of their Names in heav'nly Records now END
BEGIN NOW Be no memorial, blotted out and ras'd END
BEGIN NOW By thir Rebellion, from the Books of Life. END
BEGIN NOW Nor had they yet among the Sons of EVE END
BEGIN NOW Got them new Names, till wandring ore the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Through Gods high sufferance for the tryal of man, END
BEGIN NOW By falsities and lyes the greatest part END
BEGIN NOW Of Mankind they corrupted to forsake END
BEGIN NOW God their Creator, and th' invisible END
BEGIN NOW Glory of him, that made them, to transform END
BEGIN NOW Oft to the Image of a Brute, adorn'd END
BEGIN NOW With gay Religions full of Pomp and Gold, END
BEGIN NOW And Devils to adore for Deities: END
BEGIN NOW Then were they known to men by various Names, END
BEGIN NOW And various Idols through the Heathen World. END
BEGIN NOW Say, Muse, their Names then known, who first, who last, END
BEGIN NOW Rous'd from the slumber, on that fiery Couch, END
BEGIN NOW At thir great Emperors call, as next in worth END
BEGIN NOW Came singly where he stood on the bare strand, END
BEGIN NOW While the promiscuous croud stood yet aloof? END
BEGIN NOW The chief were those who from the Pit of Hell END
BEGIN NOW Roaming to seek their prey on earth, durst fix END
BEGIN NOW Their Seats long after next the Seat of God, END
BEGIN NOW Their Altars by his Altar, Gods ador'd END
BEGIN NOW Among the Nations round, and durst abide END
BEGIN NOW JEHOVAH thundring out of SION, thron'd END
BEGIN NOW Between the Cherubim; yea, often plac'd END
BEGIN NOW Within his Sanctuary it self their Shrines, END
BEGIN NOW Abominations; and with cursed things END
BEGIN NOW His holy Rites, and solemn Feasts profan'd, END
BEGIN NOW And with their darkness durst affront his light. END
BEGIN NOW First MOLOCH, horrid King besmear'd with blood END
BEGIN NOW Of human sacrifice, and parents tears, END
BEGIN NOW Though for the noyse of Drums and Timbrels loud END
BEGIN NOW Their childrens cries unheard, that past through fire END
BEGIN NOW To his grim Idol. Him the AMMONITE END
BEGIN NOW Worshipt in RABBA and her watry Plain, END
BEGIN NOW In ARGOB and in BASAN, to the stream END
BEGIN NOW Of utmost ARNON. Nor content with such END
BEGIN NOW Audacious neighbourhood, the wisest heart END
BEGIN NOW Of SOLOMON he led by fraud to build END
BEGIN NOW His Temple right against the Temple of God END
BEGIN NOW On that opprobrious Hill, and made his Grove END
BEGIN NOW The pleasant Vally of HINNOM, TOPHET thence END
BEGIN NOW And black GEHENNA call'd, the Type of Hell. END
BEGIN NOW Next CHEMOS, th' obscene dread of MOABS Sons, END
BEGIN NOW From AROER to NEBO, and the wild END
BEGIN NOW Of Southmost ABARIM; in HESEBON END
BEGIN NOW And HERONAIM, SEONS Realm, beyond END
BEGIN NOW The flowry Dale of SIBMA clad with Vines, END
BEGIN NOW PEOR his other Name, when he entic'd END
BEGIN NOW ISRAEL in SITTIM on their march from NILE END
BEGIN NOW To do him wanton rites, which cost them woe. END
BEGIN NOW Yet thence his lustful Orgies he enlarg'd END
BEGIN NOW Even to that Hill of scandal, by the Grove END
BEGIN NOW Of MOLOCH homicide, lust hard by hate; END
BEGIN NOW Till good JOSIAH drove them thence to Hell. END
BEGIN NOW With these came they, who from the bordring flood END
BEGIN NOW Of old EUPHRATES to the Brook that parts END
BEGIN NOW Of BAALIM and ASHTAROTH, those male, END
BEGIN NOW These Feminine. For Spirits when they please END
BEGIN NOW Can either Sex assume, or both; so soft END
BEGIN NOW And uncompounded is their Essence pure, END
BEGIN NOW Not ti'd or manacl'd with joynt or limb, END
BEGIN NOW Nor founded on the brittle strength of bones, END
BEGIN NOW Like cumbrous flesh; but in what shape they choose END
BEGIN NOW Dilated or condens't, bright or obscure, END
BEGIN NOW Can execute their aerie purposes, END
BEGIN NOW And works of love or enmity fulfill. END
BEGIN NOW For those the Race of ISRAEL oft forsook END
BEGIN NOW Their living strength, and unfrequented left END
BEGIN NOW His righteous Altar, bowing lowly down END
BEGIN NOW To bestial Gods; for which their heads as low END
BEGIN NOW Bow'd down in Battel, sunk before the Spear END
BEGIN NOW Of despicable foes. With these in troop END
BEGIN NOW Came ASTORETH, whom the PHOENICIANS call'd END
BEGIN NOW ASTARTE, Queen of Heav'n, with crescent Horns; END
BEGIN NOW To whose bright Image nightly by the Moon END
BEGIN NOW SIDONIAN Virgins paid their Vows and Songs, END
BEGIN NOW In SION also not unsung, where stood END
BEGIN NOW Her Temple on th' offensive Mountain, built END
BEGIN NOW By that uxorious King, whose heart though large, END
BEGIN NOW Beguil'd by fair Idolatresses, fell END
BEGIN NOW To Idols foul. THAMMUZ came next behind, END
BEGIN NOW Whose annual wound in LEBANON allur'd END
BEGIN NOW The SYRIAN Damsels to lament his fate END
BEGIN NOW In amorous dittyes all a Summers day, END
BEGIN NOW While smooth ADONIS from his native Rock END
BEGIN NOW Ran purple to the Sea, suppos'd with blood END
BEGIN NOW Of THAMMUZ yearly wounded: the Love-tale END
BEGIN NOW Infected SIONS daughters with like heat, END
BEGIN NOW Whose wanton passions in the sacred Porch END
BEGIN NOW EZEKIEL saw, when by the Vision led END
BEGIN NOW His eye survay'd the dark Idolatries END
BEGIN NOW Of alienated JUDAH. Next came one END
BEGIN NOW Who mourn'd in earnest, when the Captive Ark END
BEGIN NOW Maim'd his brute Image, head and hands lopt off END
BEGIN NOW In his own Temple, on the grunsel edge, END
BEGIN NOW Where he fell flat, and sham'd his Worshipers: END
BEGIN NOW And downward Fish: yet had his Temple high END
BEGIN NOW Rear'd in AZOTUS, dreaded through the Coast END
BEGIN NOW And ACCARON and GAZA's frontier bounds. END
BEGIN NOW Him follow'd RIMMON, whose delightful Seat END
BEGIN NOW Was fair DAMASCUS, on the fertil Banks END
BEGIN NOW Of ABBANA and PHARPHAR, lucid streams. END
BEGIN NOW He also against the house of God was bold: END
BEGIN NOW A Leper once he lost and gain'd a King, END
BEGIN NOW AHAZ his sottish Conquerour, whom he drew END
BEGIN NOW Gods Altar to disparage and displace END
BEGIN NOW For one of SYRIAN mode, whereon to burn END
BEGIN NOW His odious offrings, and adore the Gods END
BEGIN NOW Whom he had vanquisht. After these appear'd END
BEGIN NOW A crew who under Names of old Renown, END
BEGIN NOW OSIRIS, ISIS, ORUS and their Train END
BEGIN NOW With monstrous shapes and sorceries abus'd END
BEGIN NOW Thir wandring Gods disguis'd in brutish forms END
BEGIN NOW Rather then human. Nor did ISRAEL scape END
BEGIN NOW Th' infection when their borrow'd Gold compos'd END
BEGIN NOW The Calf in OREB: and the Rebel King END
BEGIN NOW Doubl'd that sin in BETHEL and in DAN, END
BEGIN NOW Lik'ning his Maker to the Grazed Ox, END
BEGIN NOW JEHOVAH, who in one Night when he pass'd END
BEGIN NOW Both her first born and all her bleating Gods. END
BEGIN NOW BELIAL came last, then whom a Spirit more lewd END
BEGIN NOW Fell not from Heaven, or more gross to love END
BEGIN NOW Vice for it self: To him no Temple stood END
BEGIN NOW Or Altar smoak'd; yet who more oft then hee END
BEGIN NOW In Temples and at Altars, when the Priest END
BEGIN NOW Turns Atheist, as did ELY'S Sons, who fill'd END
BEGIN NOW With lust and violence the house of God. END
BEGIN NOW In Courts and Palaces he also Reigns END
BEGIN NOW And in luxurious Cities, where the noyse END
BEGIN NOW Of riot ascends above thir loftiest Towrs, END
BEGIN NOW And injury and outrage: And when Night END
BEGIN NOW Darkens the Streets, then wander forth the Sons END
BEGIN NOW Of BELIAL, flown with insolence and wine. END
BEGIN NOW Witness the Streets of SODOM, and that night END
BEGIN NOW In GIBEAH, when hospitable Dores END
BEGIN NOW Yielded thir Matrons to prevent worse rape. END
BEGIN NOW These were the prime in order and in might; END
BEGIN NOW The rest were long to tell, though far renown'd, END
BEGIN NOW Th' IONIAN Gods, of JAVANS Issue held END
BEGIN NOW Gods, yet confest later then Heav'n and Earth END
BEGIN NOW Thir boasted Parents; TITAN Heav'ns first born END
BEGIN NOW With his enormous brood, and birthright seis'd END
BEGIN NOW By younger SATURN, he from mightier JOVE END
BEGIN NOW His own and RHEA'S Son like measure found; END
BEGIN NOW So JOVE usurping reign'd: these first in CREET END
BEGIN NOW And IDA known, thence on the Snowy top END
BEGIN NOW Of cold OLYMPUS rul'd the middle Air END
BEGIN NOW Thir highest Heav'n; or on the DELPHIAN Cliff, END
BEGIN NOW Or in DODONA, and through all the bounds END
BEGIN NOW Of DORIC Land; or who with SATURN old END
BEGIN NOW Fled over ADRIA to th' HESPERIAN Fields, END
BEGIN NOW And ore the CELTIC roam'd the utmost Isles. END
BEGIN NOW All these and more came flocking; but with looks END
BEGIN NOW Down cast and damp, yet such wherein appear'd END
BEGIN NOW Obscure som glimps of joy, to have found thir chief END
BEGIN NOW Not in despair, to have found themselves not lost END
BEGIN NOW In loss it self; which on his count'nance cast END
BEGIN NOW Like doubtful hue: but he his wonted pride END
BEGIN NOW Soon recollecting, with high words, that bore END
BEGIN NOW Semblance of worth not substance, gently rais'd END
BEGIN NOW Their fainted courage, and dispel'd their fears. END
BEGIN NOW Then strait commands that at the warlike sound END
BEGIN NOW Of Trumpets loud and Clarions be upreard END
BEGIN NOW His mighty Standard; that proud honour claim'd END
BEGIN NOW AZAZEL as his right, a Cherube tall: END
BEGIN NOW Who forthwith from the glittering Staff unfurld END
BEGIN NOW Th' Imperial Ensign, which full high advanc't END
BEGIN NOW Shon like a Meteor streaming to the Wind END
BEGIN NOW With Gemms and Golden lustre rich imblaz'd, END
BEGIN NOW Seraphic arms and Trophies: all the while END
BEGIN NOW Sonorous mettal blowing Martial sounds: END
BEGIN NOW At which the universal Host upsent END
BEGIN NOW A shout that tore Hells Concave, and beyond END
BEGIN NOW Frighted the Reign of CHAOS and old Night. END
BEGIN NOW All in a moment through the gloom were seen END
BEGIN NOW Ten thousand Banners rise into the Air END
BEGIN NOW With Orient Colours waving: with them rose END
BEGIN NOW A Forrest huge of Spears: and thronging Helms END
BEGIN NOW Appear'd, and serried Shields in thick array END
BEGIN NOW Of depth immeasurable: Anon they move END
BEGIN NOW In perfect PHALANX to the Dorian mood END
BEGIN NOW Of Flutes and soft Recorders; such as rais'd END
BEGIN NOW To highth of noblest temper Hero's old END
BEGIN NOW Arming to Battel, and in stead of rage END
BEGIN NOW Deliberate valour breath'd, firm and unmov'd END
BEGIN NOW With dread of death to flight or foul retreat, END
BEGIN NOW Nor wanting power to mitigate and swage END
BEGIN NOW With solemn touches, troubl'd thoughts, and chase END
BEGIN NOW Anguish and doubt and fear and sorrow and pain END
BEGIN NOW From mortal or immortal minds. Thus they END
BEGIN NOW Breathing united force with fixed thought END
BEGIN NOW Mov'd on in silence to soft Pipes that charm'd END
BEGIN NOW Thir painful steps o're the burnt soyle; and now END
BEGIN NOW Advanc't in view they stand, a horrid Front END
BEGIN NOW Of dreadful length and dazling Arms, in guise END
BEGIN NOW Of Warriers old with order'd Spear and Shield, END
BEGIN NOW Awaiting what command thir mighty Chief END
BEGIN NOW Had to impose: He through the armed Files END
BEGIN NOW Darts his experienc't eye, and soon traverse END
BEGIN NOW The whole Battalion views, thir order due, END
BEGIN NOW Thir visages and stature as of Gods, END
BEGIN NOW Thir number last he summs. And now his heart END
BEGIN NOW Distends with pride, and hardning in his strength END
BEGIN NOW Glories: For never since created man, END
BEGIN NOW Met such imbodied force, as nam'd with these END
BEGIN NOW Could merit more then that small infantry END
BEGIN NOW Warr'd on by Cranes: though all the Giant brood END
BEGIN NOW Of PHLEGRA with th' Heroic Race were joyn'd END
BEGIN NOW That fought at THEB'S and ILIUM, on each side END
BEGIN NOW Mixt with auxiliar Gods; and what resounds END
BEGIN NOW In Fable or ROMANCE of UTHERS Son END
BEGIN NOW Begirt with BRITISH and ARMORIC Knights; END
BEGIN NOW And all who since, Baptiz'd or Infidel END
BEGIN NOW Or whom BISERTA sent from AFRIC shore END
BEGIN NOW When CHARLEMAIN with all his Peerage fell END
BEGIN NOW By FONTARABBIA. Thus far these beyond END
BEGIN NOW Compare of mortal prowess, yet observ'd END
BEGIN NOW Thir dread Commander: he above the rest END
BEGIN NOW In shape and gesture proudly eminent END
BEGIN NOW Stood like a Towr; his form had yet not lost END
BEGIN NOW All her Original brightness, nor appear'd END
BEGIN NOW Less then Arch Angel ruind, and th' excess END
BEGIN NOW Of Glory obscur'd: As when the Sun new ris'n END
BEGIN NOW Looks through the Horizontal misty Air END
BEGIN NOW Shorn of his Beams, or from behind the Moon END
BEGIN NOW In dim Eclips disastrous twilight sheds END
BEGIN NOW On half the Nations, and with fear of change END
BEGIN NOW Perplexes Monarchs. Dark'n'd so, yet shon END
BEGIN NOW Above them all th' Arch Angel: but his face END
BEGIN NOW Deep scars of Thunder had intrencht, and care END
BEGIN NOW Sat on his faded cheek, but under Browes END
BEGIN NOW Of dauntless courage, and considerate Pride END
BEGIN NOW Waiting revenge: cruel his eye, but cast END
BEGIN NOW Signs of remorse and passion to behold END
BEGIN NOW The fellows of his crime, the followers rather END
BEGIN NOW (Far other once beheld in bliss) condemn'd END
BEGIN NOW For ever now to have their lot in pain, END
BEGIN NOW Millions of Spirits for his fault amerc't END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'n, and from Eternal Splendors flung END
BEGIN NOW For his revolt, yet faithfull how they stood, END
BEGIN NOW Thir Glory witherd. As when Heavens Fire END
BEGIN NOW Hath scath'd the Forrest Oaks, or Mountain Pines, END
BEGIN NOW With singed top their stately growth though bare END
BEGIN NOW Stands on the blasted Heath. He now prepar'd END
BEGIN NOW To speak; whereat their doubl'd Ranks they bend END
BEGIN NOW From Wing to Wing, and half enclose him round END
BEGIN NOW With all his Peers: attention held them mute. END
BEGIN NOW Thrice he assayd, and thrice in spite of scorn, END
BEGIN NOW Tears such as Angels weep, burst forth: at last END
BEGIN NOW Words interwove with sighs found out their way. END
BEGIN NOW O Myriads of immortal Spirits, O Powers END
BEGIN NOW Matchless, but with th' Almighty, and that strife END
BEGIN NOW Was not inglorious, though th' event was dire, END
BEGIN NOW As this place testifies, and this dire change END
BEGIN NOW Hateful to utter: but what power of mind END
BEGIN NOW Foreseeing or presaging, from the Depth END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledge past or present, could have fear'd, END
BEGIN NOW How such united force of Gods, how such END
BEGIN NOW As stood like these, could ever know repulse? END
BEGIN NOW For who can yet beleeve, though after loss, END
BEGIN NOW That all these puissant Legions, whose exile END
BEGIN NOW Hath emptied Heav'n, shall faile to re-ascend END
BEGIN NOW Self-rais'd, and repossess their native seat. END
BEGIN NOW For me, be witness all the Host of Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW If counsels different, or danger shun'd END
BEGIN NOW By me, have lost our hopes. But he who reigns END
BEGIN NOW Monarch in Heav'n, till then as one secure END
BEGIN NOW Sat on his Throne, upheld by old repute, END
BEGIN NOW Consent or custome, and his Regal State END
BEGIN NOW Put forth at full, but still his strength conceal'd, END
BEGIN NOW Which tempted our attempt, and wrought our fall. END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth his might we know, and know our own END
BEGIN NOW So as not either to provoke, or dread END
BEGIN NOW New warr, provok't; our better part remains END
BEGIN NOW To work in close design, by fraud or guile END
BEGIN NOW What force effected not: that he no less END
BEGIN NOW At length from us may find, who overcomes END
BEGIN NOW By force, hath overcome but half his foe. END
BEGIN NOW Space may produce new Worlds; whereof so rife END
BEGIN NOW There went a fame in Heav'n that he ere long END
BEGIN NOW Intended to create, and therein plant END
BEGIN NOW A generation, whom his choice regard END
BEGIN NOW Should favour equal to the Sons of Heaven: END
BEGIN NOW Thither, if but to prie, shall be perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Our first eruption, thither or elsewhere: END
BEGIN NOW For this Infernal Pit shall never hold END
BEGIN NOW Long under darkness cover. But these thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Full Counsel must mature: Peace is despaird, END
BEGIN NOW For who can think Submission? Warr then, Warr END
BEGIN NOW Open or understood must be resolv'd. END
BEGIN NOW He spake: and to confirm his words, out-flew END
BEGIN NOW Millions of flaming swords, drawn from the thighs END
BEGIN NOW Of mighty Cherubim; the sudden blaze END
BEGIN NOW Far round illumin'd hell: highly they rag'd END
BEGIN NOW Against the Highest, and fierce with grasped arm's END
BEGIN NOW Clash'd on their sounding shields the din of war, END
BEGIN NOW Hurling defiance toward the vault of Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW There stood a Hill not far whose griesly top END
BEGIN NOW Belch'd fire and rowling smoak; the rest entire END
BEGIN NOW Shon with a glossie scurff, undoubted sign END
BEGIN NOW That in his womb was hid metallic Ore, END
BEGIN NOW The work of Sulphur. Thither wing'd with speed END
BEGIN NOW A numerous Brigad hasten'd. As when bands END
BEGIN NOW Forerun the Royal Camp, to trench a Field, END
BEGIN NOW Or cast a Rampart. MAMMON led them on, END
BEGIN NOW MAMMON, the least erected Spirit that fell END
BEGIN NOW From heav'n, for ev'n in heav'n his looks & thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Were always downward bent, admiring more END
BEGIN NOW The riches of Heav'ns pavement, trod'n Gold, END
BEGIN NOW Then aught divine or holy else enjoy'd END
BEGIN NOW In vision beatific: by him first END
BEGIN NOW Men also, and by his suggestion taught, END
BEGIN NOW Ransack'd the Center, and with impious hands END
BEGIN NOW Rifl'd the bowels of thir mother Earth END
BEGIN NOW For Treasures better hid. Soon had his crew END
BEGIN NOW Op'nd into the Hill a spacious wound END
BEGIN NOW And dig'd out ribs of Gold. Let none admire END
BEGIN NOW That riches grow in Hell; that soyle may best END
BEGIN NOW Deserve the pretious bane. And here let those END
BEGIN NOW Who boast in mortal things, and wondring tell END
BEGIN NOW Of BABEL, and the works of MEMPHIAN Kings, END
BEGIN NOW Learn how thir greatest Monuments of Fame, END
BEGIN NOW And Strength and Art are easily outdone END
BEGIN NOW By Spirits reprobate, and in an hour END
BEGIN NOW What in an age they with incessant toyle END
BEGIN NOW And hands innumerable scarce perform END
BEGIN NOW Nigh on the Plain in many cells prepar'd, END
BEGIN NOW That underneath had veins of liquid fire END
BEGIN NOW Sluc'd from the Lake, a second multitude END
BEGIN NOW With wondrous Art founded the massie Ore, END
BEGIN NOW Severing each kinde, and scum'd the Bullion dross: END
BEGIN NOW A third as soon had form'd within the ground END
BEGIN NOW A various mould, and from the boyling cells END
BEGIN NOW By strange conveyance fill'd each hollow nook, END
BEGIN NOW As in an Organ from one blast of wind END
BEGIN NOW To many a row of Pipes the sound-board breaths. END
BEGIN NOW Anon out of the earth a Fabrick huge END
BEGIN NOW Rose like an Exhalation, with the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of Dulcet Symphonies and voices sweet, END
BEGIN NOW Built like a Temple, where PILASTERS round END
BEGIN NOW Were set, and Doric pillars overlaid END
BEGIN NOW With Golden Architrave; nor did there want END
BEGIN NOW Cornice or Freeze, with bossy Sculptures grav'n, END
BEGIN NOW The Roof was fretted Gold. Not BABILON, END
BEGIN NOW Nor great ALCAIRO such magnificence END
BEGIN NOW Equal'd in all thir glories, to inshrine END
BEGIN NOW BELUS or SERAPIS thir Gods, or seat END
BEGIN NOW In wealth and luxurie. Th' ascending pile END
BEGIN NOW Stood fixt her stately highth, and strait the dores END
BEGIN NOW Op'ning thir brazen foulds discover wide END
BEGIN NOW Within, her ample spaces, o're the smooth END
BEGIN NOW And level pavement: from the arched roof END
BEGIN NOW Pendant by suttle Magic many a row END
BEGIN NOW Of Starry Lamps and blazing Cressets fed END
BEGIN NOW With Naphtha and ASPHALTUS yeilded light END
BEGIN NOW As from a sky. The hasty multitude END
BEGIN NOW Admiring enter'd, and the work some praise END
BEGIN NOW And some the Architect: his hand was known END
BEGIN NOW In Heav'n by many a Towred structure high, END
BEGIN NOW Where Scepter'd Angels held thir residence, END
BEGIN NOW And sat as Princes, whom the supreme King END
BEGIN NOW Exalted to such power, and gave to rule, END
BEGIN NOW Each in his Herarchie, the Orders bright. END
BEGIN NOW Nor was his name unheard or unador'd END
BEGIN NOW In ancient Greece; and in AUSONIAN land END
BEGIN NOW Men call'd him MULCIBER; and how he fell END
BEGIN NOW From Heav'n, they fabl'd, thrown by angry JOVE END
BEGIN NOW Sheer o're the Chrystal Battlements: from Morn END
BEGIN NOW To Noon he fell, from Noon to dewy Eve, END
BEGIN NOW A Summers day; and with the setting Sun END
BEGIN NOW Dropt from the Zenith like a falling Star, END
BEGIN NOW On LEMNOS th' AEGAEAN Ile: thus they relate, END
BEGIN NOW Erring; for he with this rebellious rout END
BEGIN NOW Fell long before; nor aught avail'd him now END
BEGIN NOW To have built in Heav'n high Towrs; nor did he scape END
BEGIN NOW By all his Engins, but was headlong sent END
BEGIN NOW With his industrious crew to build in hell. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while the winged Haralds by command END
BEGIN NOW Of Sovran power, with awful Ceremony END
BEGIN NOW And Trumpets sound throughout the Host proclaim END
BEGIN NOW A solemn Councel forthwith to be held END
BEGIN NOW At PANDAEMONIUM, the high Capital END
BEGIN NOW Of Satan and his Peers: thir summons call'd END
BEGIN NOW From every and Band squared Regiment END
BEGIN NOW By place or choice the worthiest; they anon END
BEGIN NOW With hundreds and with thousands trooping came END
BEGIN NOW Attended: all access was throng'd, the Gates END
BEGIN NOW And Porches wide, but chief the spacious Hall END
BEGIN NOW (Though like a cover'd field, where Champions bold END
BEGIN NOW Wont ride in arm'd, and at the Soldans chair END
BEGIN NOW Defi'd the best of Panim chivalry END
BEGIN NOW To mortal combat or carreer with Lance) END
BEGIN NOW Thick swarm'd, both on the ground and in the air, END
BEGIN NOW Brusht with the hiss of russling wings. As Bees END
BEGIN NOW In spring time, when the Sun with Taurus rides, END
BEGIN NOW Poure forth thir populous youth about the Hive END
BEGIN NOW In clusters; they among fresh dews and flowers END
BEGIN NOW Flie to and fro, or on the smoothed Plank, END
BEGIN NOW The suburb of thir Straw-built Cittadel, END
BEGIN NOW New rub'd with Baume, expatiate and confer END
BEGIN NOW Thir State affairs. So thick the aerie crowd END
BEGIN NOW Swarm'd and were straitn'd; till the Signal giv'n, END
BEGIN NOW Behold a wonder! they but now who seemd END
BEGIN NOW In bigness to surpass Earths Giant Sons END
BEGIN NOW Now less then smallest Dwarfs, in narrow room END
BEGIN NOW Throng numberless, like that Pigmean Race END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the INDIAN Mount, or Faerie Elves, END
BEGIN NOW Whose midnight Revels, by a Forrest side END
BEGIN NOW Or Fountain fome belated Peasant sees, END
BEGIN NOW Or dreams he sees, while over head the Moon END
BEGIN NOW Sits Arbitress, and neerer to the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Wheels her pale course, they on thir mirth & dance END
BEGIN NOW Intent, with jocond Music charm his ear; END
BEGIN NOW At once with joy and fear his heart rebounds. END
BEGIN NOW Thus incorporeal Spirits to smallest forms END
BEGIN NOW Reduc'd thir shapes immense, and were at large, END
BEGIN NOW Though without number still amidst the Hall END
BEGIN NOW Of that infernal Court. But far within END
BEGIN NOW And in thir own dimensions like themselves END
BEGIN NOW The great Seraphic Lords and Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW In close recess and secret conclave sat END
BEGIN NOW A thousand Demy-Gods on golden seat's, END
BEGIN NOW Frequent and full. After short silence then END
BEGIN NOW And summons read, the great consult began. END
BEGIN NOW High on a Throne of Royal State, which far END
BEGIN NOW Outshon the wealth of ORMUS and of IND, END
BEGIN NOW Or where the gorgeous East with richest hand END
BEGIN NOW Showrs on her Kings BARBARIC Pearl & Gold, END
BEGIN NOW Satan exalted sat, by merit rais'd END
BEGIN NOW To that bad eminence; and from despair END
BEGIN NOW Thus high uplifted beyond hope, aspires END
BEGIN NOW Beyond thus high, insatiate to pursue END
BEGIN NOW Vain Warr with Heav'n, and by success untaught END
BEGIN NOW His proud imaginations thus displaid. END
BEGIN NOW Powers and Dominions, Deities of Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW For since no deep within her gulf can hold END
BEGIN NOW Immortal vigor, though opprest and fall'n, END
BEGIN NOW I give not Heav'n for lost. From this descent END
BEGIN NOW Celestial vertues rising, will appear END
BEGIN NOW More glorious and more dread then from no fall, END
BEGIN NOW And trust themselves to fear no second fate: END
BEGIN NOW Mee though just right, and the fixt Laws of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Did first create your Leader, next, free choice, END
BEGIN NOW With what besides, in Counsel or in Fight, END
BEGIN NOW Hath bin achievd of merit, yet this loss END
BEGIN NOW Thus farr at least recover'd, hath much more END
BEGIN NOW Establisht in a safe unenvied Throne END
BEGIN NOW Yeilded with full consent. The happier state END
BEGIN NOW In Heav'n, which follows dignity, might draw END
BEGIN NOW Envy from each inferior; but who here END
BEGIN NOW Will envy whom the highest place exposes END
BEGIN NOW Formost to stand against the Thunderers aime END
BEGIN NOW Your bulwark, and condemns to greatest share END
BEGIN NOW Of endless pain? where there is then no good END
BEGIN NOW For which to strive, no strife can grow up there END
BEGIN NOW From Faction; for none sure will claim in hell END
BEGIN NOW Precedence, none, whose portion is so small END
BEGIN NOW Of present pain, that with ambitious mind END
BEGIN NOW Will covet more. With this advantage then END
BEGIN NOW To union, and firm Faith, and firm accord, END
BEGIN NOW More then can be in Heav'n, we now return END
BEGIN NOW To claim our just inheritance of old, END
BEGIN NOW Surer to prosper then prosperity END
BEGIN NOW Could have assur'd us; and by what best way, END
BEGIN NOW Whether of open Warr or covert guile, END
BEGIN NOW We now debate; who can advise, may speak. END
BEGIN NOW He ceas'd, and next him MOLOC, Scepter'd King END
BEGIN NOW Stood up, the strongest and the fiercest Spirit END
BEGIN NOW That fought in Heav'n; now fiercer by despair: END
BEGIN NOW His trust was with th' Eternal to be deem'd END
BEGIN NOW Equal in strength, and rather then be less END
BEGIN NOW Car'd not to be at all; with that care lost END
BEGIN NOW Went all his fear: of God, or Hell, or worse END
BEGIN NOW He reckd not, and these words thereafter spake. END
BEGIN NOW My sentence is for open Warr: Of Wiles, END
BEGIN NOW More unexpert, I boast not: them let those END
BEGIN NOW Contrive who need, or when they need, not now. END
BEGIN NOW For while they sit contriving, shall the rest, END
BEGIN NOW Millions that stand in Arms, and longing wait END
BEGIN NOW The Signal to ascend, sit lingring here END
BEGIN NOW Heav'ns fugitives, and for thir dwelling place END
BEGIN NOW Accept this dark opprobrious Den of shame, END
BEGIN NOW By our delay? no, let us rather choose END
BEGIN NOW Arm'd with Hell flames and fury all at once END
BEGIN NOW O're Heav'ns high Towrs to force resistless way, END
BEGIN NOW Turning our Tortures into horrid Arms END
BEGIN NOW Against the Torturer; when to meet the noise END
BEGIN NOW Of his Almighty Engin he shall hear END
BEGIN NOW Black fire and horror shot with equal rage END
BEGIN NOW Among his Angels; and his Throne it self END
BEGIN NOW Mixt with TARTAREAN Sulphur, and strange fire, END
BEGIN NOW His own invented Torments. But perhaps END
BEGIN NOW The way seems difficult and steep to scale END
BEGIN NOW With upright wing against a higher foe. END
BEGIN NOW Let such bethink them, if the sleepy drench END
BEGIN NOW Of that forgetful Lake benumme not still, END
BEGIN NOW That in our proper motion we ascend END
BEGIN NOW Up to our native seat: descent and fall END
BEGIN NOW To us is adverse. Who but felt of late END
BEGIN NOW When the fierce Foe hung on our brok'n Rear END
BEGIN NOW Insulting, and pursu'd us through the Deep, END
BEGIN NOW With what compulsion and laborious flight END
BEGIN NOW We sunk thus low? Th' ascent is easie then; END
BEGIN NOW Th' event is fear'd; should we again provoke END
BEGIN NOW Our stronger, some worse way his wrath may find END
BEGIN NOW To our destruction: if there be in Hell END
BEGIN NOW Fear to be worse destroy'd: what can be worse END
BEGIN NOW Then to dwell here, driv'n out from bliss, condemn'd END
BEGIN NOW In this abhorred deep to utter woe; END
BEGIN NOW Where pain of unextinguishable fire END
BEGIN NOW Must exercise us without hope of end END
BEGIN NOW The Vassals of his anger, when the Scourge END
BEGIN NOW Inexorably, and the torturing houre END
BEGIN NOW Calls us to Penance? More destroy'd then thus END
BEGIN NOW We should be quite abolisht and expire. END
BEGIN NOW What fear we then? what doubt we to incense END
BEGIN NOW His utmost ire? which to the highth enrag'd, END
BEGIN NOW Will either quite consume us, and reduce END
BEGIN NOW To nothing this essential, happier farr END
BEGIN NOW Then miserable to have eternal being: END
BEGIN NOW Or if our substance be indeed Divine, END
BEGIN NOW And cannot cease to be, we are at worst END
BEGIN NOW On this side nothing; and by proof we feel END
BEGIN NOW Our power sufficient to disturb his Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW And with perpetual inrodes to Allarme, END
BEGIN NOW Though inaccessible, his fatal Throne: END
BEGIN NOW He ended frowning, and his look denounc'd END
BEGIN NOW Desperate revenge, and Battel dangerous END
BEGIN NOW To less then Gods. On th' other side up rose END
BEGIN NOW BELIAL, in act more graceful and humane; END
BEGIN NOW A fairer person lost not Heav'n; he seemd END
BEGIN NOW For dignity compos'd and high exploit: END
BEGIN NOW But all was false and hollow; though his Tongue END
BEGIN NOW Dropt Manna, and could make the worse appear END
BEGIN NOW The better reason, to perplex and dash END
BEGIN NOW Maturest Counsels: for his thoughts were low; END
BEGIN NOW To vice industrious, but to Nobler deeds END
BEGIN NOW Timorous and slothful: yet he pleas'd the eare, END
BEGIN NOW And with perswasive accent thus began. END
BEGIN NOW I should be much for open Warr, O Peers, END
BEGIN NOW As not behind in hate; if what was urg'd END
BEGIN NOW Main reason to perswade immediate Warr, END
BEGIN NOW Did not disswade me most, and seem to cast END
BEGIN NOW Ominous conjecture on the whole success: END
BEGIN NOW When he who most excels in fact of Arms, END
BEGIN NOW In what he counsels and in what excels END
BEGIN NOW Mistrustful, grounds his courage on despair END
BEGIN NOW And utter dissolution, as the scope END
BEGIN NOW Of all his aim, after some dire revenge. END
BEGIN NOW First, what Revenge? the Towrs of Heav'n are fill'd END
BEGIN NOW With Armed watch, that render all access END
BEGIN NOW Impregnable; oft on the bordering Deep END
BEGIN NOW Encamp thir Legions, or with obscure wing END
BEGIN NOW Scout farr and wide into the Realm of night, END
BEGIN NOW Scorning surprize. Or could we break our way END
BEGIN NOW By force, and at our heels all Hell should rise END
BEGIN NOW With blackest Insurrection, to confound END
BEGIN NOW Heav'ns purest Light, yet our great Enemie END
BEGIN NOW All incorruptible would on his Throne END
BEGIN NOW Sit unpolluted, and th' Ethereal mould END
BEGIN NOW Incapable of stain would soon expel END
BEGIN NOW Her mischief, and purge off the baser fire END
BEGIN NOW Victorious. Thus repuls'd, our final hope END
BEGIN NOW Is flat despair: we must exasperate END
BEGIN NOW Th' Almighty Victor to spend all his rage, END
BEGIN NOW And that must end us, that must be our cure, END
BEGIN NOW To be no more; sad cure; for who would loose, END
BEGIN NOW Though full of pain, this intellectual being, END
BEGIN NOW Those thoughts that wander through Eternity, END
BEGIN NOW To perish rather, swallowd up and lost END
BEGIN NOW In the wide womb of uncreated night, END
BEGIN NOW Devoid of sense and motion? and who knows, END
BEGIN NOW Let this be good, whether our angry Foe END
BEGIN NOW Can give it, or will ever? how he can END
BEGIN NOW Is doubtful; that he never will is sure. END
BEGIN NOW Will he, so wise, let loose at once his ire, END
BEGIN NOW Belike through impotence, or unaware, END
BEGIN NOW To give his Enemies thir wish, and end END
BEGIN NOW Them in his anger, whom his anger saves END
BEGIN NOW To punish endless? wherefore cease we then? END
BEGIN NOW Say they who counsel Warr, we are decreed, END
BEGIN NOW Reserv'd and destin'd to Eternal woe; END
BEGIN NOW Whatever doing, what can we suffer more, END
BEGIN NOW What can we suffer worse? is this then worst, END
BEGIN NOW Thus sitting, thus consulting, thus in Arms? END
BEGIN NOW What when we fled amain, pursu'd and strook END
BEGIN NOW With Heav'ns afflicting Thunder, and besought END
BEGIN NOW The Deep to shelter us? this Hell then seem'd END
BEGIN NOW A refuge from those wounds: or when we lay END
BEGIN NOW Chain'd on the burning Lake? that sure was worse. END
BEGIN NOW What if the breath that kindl'd those grim fires END
BEGIN NOW Awak'd should blow them into sevenfold rage END
BEGIN NOW And plunge us in the Flames? or from above END
BEGIN NOW Should intermitted vengeance Arme again END
BEGIN NOW His red right hand to plague us? what if all END
BEGIN NOW Her stores were op'n'd, and this Firmament END
BEGIN NOW Of Hell should spout her Cataracts of Fire, END
BEGIN NOW Impendent horrors, threatning hideous fall END
BEGIN NOW One day upon our heads; while we perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Designing or exhorting glorious Warr, END
BEGIN NOW Caught in a fierie Tempest shall be hurl'd END
BEGIN NOW Each on his rock transfixt, the sport and prey END
BEGIN NOW Of racking whirlwinds, or for ever sunk END
BEGIN NOW Under yon boyling Ocean, wrapt in Chains; END
BEGIN NOW There to converse with everlasting groans, END
BEGIN NOW Unrespited, unpitied, unrepreevd, END
BEGIN NOW Ages of hopeless end; this would be worse. END
BEGIN NOW Warr therefore, open or conceal'd, alike END
BEGIN NOW My voice disswades; for what can force or guile END
BEGIN NOW With him, or who deceive his mind, whose eye END
BEGIN NOW Views all things at one view? he from heav'ns highth END
BEGIN NOW All these our motions vain, sees and derides; END
BEGIN NOW Not more Almighty to resist our might END
BEGIN NOW Then wise to frustrate all our plots and wiles. END
BEGIN NOW Shall we then live thus vile, the race of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Thus trampl'd, thus expell'd to suffer here END
BEGIN NOW Chains & these Torments? better these then worse END
BEGIN NOW By my advice; since fate inevitable END
BEGIN NOW The Victors will. To suffer, as to doe, END
BEGIN NOW Our strength is equal, nor the Law unjust END
BEGIN NOW That so ordains: this was at first resolv'd, END
BEGIN NOW If we were wise, against so great a foe END
BEGIN NOW Contending, and so doubtful what might fall. END
BEGIN NOW I laugh, when those who at the Spear are bold END
BEGIN NOW And vent'rous, if that fail them, shrink and fear END
BEGIN NOW What yet they know must follow, to endure END
BEGIN NOW Exile, or ignominy, or bonds, or pain, END
BEGIN NOW The sentence of thir Conquerour: This is now END
BEGIN NOW Our doom; which if we can sustain and bear, END
BEGIN NOW Our Supream Foe in time may much remit END
BEGIN NOW His anger, and perhaps thus farr remov'd END
BEGIN NOW Not mind us not offending, satisfi'd END
BEGIN NOW With what is punish't; whence these raging fires END
BEGIN NOW Will slack'n, if his breath stir not thir flames. END
BEGIN NOW Our purer essence then will overcome END
BEGIN NOW Thir noxious vapour, or enur'd not feel, END
BEGIN NOW Or chang'd at length, and to the place conformd END
BEGIN NOW In temper and in nature, will receive END
BEGIN NOW Familiar the fierce heat, and void of pain; END
BEGIN NOW This horror will grow milde, this darkness light, END
BEGIN NOW Besides what hope the never-ending flight END
BEGIN NOW Of future days may bring, what chance, what change END
BEGIN NOW Worth waiting, since our present lot appeers END
BEGIN NOW For happy though but ill, for ill not worst, END
BEGIN NOW If we procure not to our selves more woe. END
BEGIN NOW Thus BELIAL with words cloath'd in reasons garb END
BEGIN NOW Counsel'd ignoble ease, and peaceful sloath, END
BEGIN NOW Not peace: and after him thus MAMMON spake. END
BEGIN NOW Either to disinthrone the King of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW We warr, if warr be best, or to regain END
BEGIN NOW Our own right lost: him to unthrone we then END
BEGIN NOW May hope, when everlasting Fate shall yeild END
BEGIN NOW To fickle Chance, and CHAOS judge the strife: END
BEGIN NOW The former vain to hope argues as vain END
BEGIN NOW The latter: for what place can be for us END
BEGIN NOW Within Heav'ns bound, unless Heav'ns Lord supream END
BEGIN NOW We overpower? Suppose he should relent END
BEGIN NOW And publish Grace to all, on promise made END
BEGIN NOW Of new Subjection; with what eyes could we END
BEGIN NOW Stand in his presence humble, and receive END
BEGIN NOW Strict Laws impos'd, to celebrate his Throne END
BEGIN NOW With warbl'd Hymns, and to his Godhead sing END
BEGIN NOW Forc't Halleluiah's; while he Lordly sits END
BEGIN NOW Our envied Sovran, and his Altar breathes END
BEGIN NOW Our servile offerings. This must be our task END
BEGIN NOW In Heav'n, this our delight; how wearisom END
BEGIN NOW Eternity so spent in worship paid END
BEGIN NOW To whom we hate. Let us not then pursue END
BEGIN NOW By force impossible, by leave obtain'd END
BEGIN NOW Unacceptable, though in Heav'n, our state END
BEGIN NOW Of splendid vassalage, but rather seek END
BEGIN NOW Our own good from our selves, and from our own END
BEGIN NOW Live to our selves, though in this vast recess, END
BEGIN NOW Free, and to none accountable, preferring END
BEGIN NOW Hard liberty before the easie yoke END
BEGIN NOW Of servile Pomp. Our greatness will appear END
BEGIN NOW Then most conspicuous, when great things of small, END
BEGIN NOW Useful of hurtful, prosperous of adverse END
BEGIN NOW We can create, and in what place so e're END
BEGIN NOW Thrive under evil, and work ease out of pain END
BEGIN NOW Through labour and endurance. This deep world END
BEGIN NOW Of darkness do we dread? How oft amidst END
BEGIN NOW Thick clouds and dark doth Heav'ns all-ruling Sire END
BEGIN NOW Choose to reside, his Glory unobscur'd, END
BEGIN NOW And with the Majesty of darkness round END
BEGIN NOW Covers his Throne; from whence deep thunders roar END
BEGIN NOW Must'ring thir rage, and Heav'n resembles Hell? END
BEGIN NOW As he our Darkness, cannot we his Light END
BEGIN NOW Imitate when we please? This Desart soile END
BEGIN NOW Wants not her hidden lustre, Gemms and Gold; END
BEGIN NOW Nor want we skill or art, from whence to raise END
BEGIN NOW Magnificence; and what can Heav'n shew more? END
BEGIN NOW Our torments also may in length of time END
BEGIN NOW Become our Elements, these piercing Fires END
BEGIN NOW As soft as now severe, our temper chang'd END
BEGIN NOW Into their temper; which must needs remove END
BEGIN NOW The sensible of pain. All things invite END
BEGIN NOW To peaceful Counsels, and the settl'd State END
BEGIN NOW Of order, how in safety best we may END
BEGIN NOW Compose our present evils, with regard END
BEGIN NOW Of what we are and where, dismissing quite END
BEGIN NOW All thoughts of Warr: ye have what I advise. END
BEGIN NOW He scarce had finisht, when such murmur filld END
BEGIN NOW Th' Assembly, as when hollow Rocks retain END
BEGIN NOW The sound of blustring winds, which all night long END
BEGIN NOW Had rous'd the Sea, now with hoarse cadence lull END
BEGIN NOW Sea-faring men orewatcht, whose Bark by chance END
BEGIN NOW Or Pinnace anchors in a craggy Bay END
BEGIN NOW After the Tempest: Such applause was heard END
BEGIN NOW As MAMMON ended, and his Sentence pleas'd, END
BEGIN NOW Advising peace: for such another Field END
BEGIN NOW They dreaded worse then Hell: so much the fear END
BEGIN NOW Of Thunder and the Sword of MICHAEL END
BEGIN NOW Wrought still within them; and no less desire END
BEGIN NOW To found this nether Empire, which might rise END
BEGIN NOW By pollicy, and long process of time, END
BEGIN NOW In emulation opposite to Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW Which when BEELZEBUB perceiv'd, then whom, END
BEGIN NOW SATAN except, none higher sat, with grave END
BEGIN NOW Aspect he rose, and in his rising seem'd END
BEGIN NOW A Pillar of State; deep on his Front engraven END
BEGIN NOW Deliberation sat and publick care; END
BEGIN NOW And Princely counsel in his face yet shon, END
BEGIN NOW Majestick though in ruin: sage he stood END
BEGIN NOW With ATLANTEAN shoulders fit to bear END
BEGIN NOW The weight of mightiest Monarchies; his look END
BEGIN NOW Drew audience and attention still as Night END
BEGIN NOW Or Summers Noon-tide air, while thus he spake. END
BEGIN NOW Thrones and imperial Powers, off-spring of heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal Vertues; or these Titles now END
BEGIN NOW Must we renounce, and changing stile be call'd END
BEGIN NOW Princes of Hell? for so the popular vote END
BEGIN NOW Inclines, here to continue, and build up here END
BEGIN NOW A growing Empire; doubtless; while we dream, END
BEGIN NOW And know not that the King of Heav'n hath doom'd END
BEGIN NOW This place our dungeon, not our safe retreat END
BEGIN NOW Beyond his Potent arm, to live exempt END
BEGIN NOW From Heav'ns high jurisdiction, in new League END
BEGIN NOW Banded against his Throne, but to remaine END
BEGIN NOW In strictest bondage, though thus far remov'd, END
BEGIN NOW Under th' inevitable curb, reserv'd END
BEGIN NOW His captive multitude: For he, be sure, END
BEGIN NOW In highth or depth, still first and last will Reign END
BEGIN NOW Sole King, and of his Kingdom loose no part END
BEGIN NOW By our revolt, but over Hell extend END
BEGIN NOW His Empire, and with Iron Scepter rule END
BEGIN NOW Us here, as with his Golden those in Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW What sit we then projecting Peace and Warr? END
BEGIN NOW Warr hath determin'd us, and foild with loss END
BEGIN NOW Irreparable; tearms of peace yet none END
BEGIN NOW Voutsaf't or sought; for what peace will be giv'n END
BEGIN NOW To us enslav'd, but custody severe, END
BEGIN NOW And stripes, and arbitrary punishment END
BEGIN NOW Inflicted? and what peace can we return, END
BEGIN NOW But to our power hostility and hate, END
BEGIN NOW Untam'd reluctance, and revenge though slow, END
BEGIN NOW Yet ever plotting how the Conquerour least END
BEGIN NOW May reap his conquest, and may least rejoyce END
BEGIN NOW In doing what we most in suffering feel? END
BEGIN NOW Nor will occasion want, nor shall we need END
BEGIN NOW With dangerous expedition to invade END
BEGIN NOW Heav'n, whose high walls fear no assault or Siege, END
BEGIN NOW Or ambush from the Deep. What if we find END
BEGIN NOW Some easier enterprize? There is a place END
BEGIN NOW (If ancient and prophetic fame in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Err not) another World, the happy seat END
BEGIN NOW Of som new Race call'd MAN, about this time END
BEGIN NOW To be created like to us, though less END
BEGIN NOW In power and excellence, but favour'd more END
BEGIN NOW Of him who rules above; so was his will END
BEGIN NOW Pronounc'd among the Gods, and by an Oath, END
BEGIN NOW That shook Heav'ns whol circumference, confirm'd. END
BEGIN NOW Thither let us bend all our thoughts, to learn END
BEGIN NOW What creatures there inhabit, of what mould, END
BEGIN NOW Or substance, how endu'd, and what thir Power, END
BEGIN NOW And where thir weakness, how attempted best, END
BEGIN NOW By force or suttlety: Though Heav'n be shut, END
BEGIN NOW And Heav'ns high Arbitrator sit secure END
BEGIN NOW In his own strength, this place may lye expos'd END
BEGIN NOW The utmost border of his Kingdom, left END
BEGIN NOW To their defence who hold it: here perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Som advantagious act may be achiev'd END
BEGIN NOW By sudden onset, either with Hell fire END
BEGIN NOW To waste his whole Creation, or possess END
BEGIN NOW All as our own, and drive as we were driven, END
BEGIN NOW The punie habitants, or if not drive, END
BEGIN NOW Seduce them to our Party, that thir God END
BEGIN NOW May prove thir foe, and with repenting hand END
BEGIN NOW Abolish his own works. This would surpass END
BEGIN NOW Common revenge, and interrupt his joy END
BEGIN NOW In our Confusion, and our Joy upraise END
BEGIN NOW In his disturbance; when his darling Sons END
BEGIN NOW Hurl'd headlong to partake with us, shall curse END
BEGIN NOW Thir frail Originals, and faded bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Faded so soon. Advise if this be worth END
BEGIN NOW Attempting, or to sit in darkness here END
BEGIN NOW Hatching vain Empires. Thus BEELZEBUB END
BEGIN NOW Pleaded his devilish Counsel, first devis'd END
BEGIN NOW By SATAN, and in part propos'd: for whence, END
BEGIN NOW But from the Author of all ill could Spring END
BEGIN NOW So deep a malice, to confound the race END
BEGIN NOW Of mankind in one root, and Earth with Hell END
BEGIN NOW To mingle and involve, done all to spite END
BEGIN NOW The great Creatour? But thir spite still serves END
BEGIN NOW His glory to augment. The bold design END
BEGIN NOW Pleas'd highly those infernal States, and joy END
BEGIN NOW Sparkl'd in all thir eyes; with full assent END
BEGIN NOW They vote: whereat his speech he thus renews. END
BEGIN NOW Well have ye judg'd, well ended long debate, END
BEGIN NOW Synod of Gods, and like to what ye are, END
BEGIN NOW Great things resolv'd; which from the lowest deep END
BEGIN NOW Will once more lift us up, in spight of Fate, END
BEGIN NOW Neerer our ancient Seat; perhaps in view END
BEGIN NOW Of those bright confines, whence with neighbouring Arms END
BEGIN NOW And opportune excursion we may chance END
BEGIN NOW Re-enter Heav'n; or else in some milde Zone END
BEGIN NOW Dwell not unvisited of Heav'ns fair Light END
BEGIN NOW Secure, and at the brightning Orient beam END
BEGIN NOW Purge off this gloom; the soft delicious Air, END
BEGIN NOW To heal the scarr of these corrosive Fires END
BEGIN NOW Shall breath her balme. But first whom shall we send END
BEGIN NOW In search of this new world, whom shall we find END
BEGIN NOW Sufficient? who shall tempt with wandring feet END
BEGIN NOW The dark unbottom'd infinite Abyss END
BEGIN NOW And through the palpable obscure find out END
BEGIN NOW His uncouth way, or spread his aerie flight END
BEGIN NOW Upborn with indefatigable wings END
BEGIN NOW Over the vast abrupt, ere he arrive END
BEGIN NOW The happy Ile; what strength, what art can then END
BEGIN NOW Suffice, or what evasion bear him safe END
BEGIN NOW Through the strict Senteries and Stations thick END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels watching round? Here he had need END
BEGIN NOW All circumspection, and we now no less END
BEGIN NOW Choice in our suffrage; for on whom we send, END
BEGIN NOW The weight of all and our last hope relies. END
BEGIN NOW This said, he sat; and expectation held END
BEGIN NOW His look suspence, awaiting who appeer'd END
BEGIN NOW To second, or oppose, or undertake END
BEGIN NOW The perilous attempt: but all sat mute, END
BEGIN NOW Pondering the danger with deep thoughts; & each END
BEGIN NOW In others count'nance red his own dismay END
BEGIN NOW Astonisht: none among the choice and prime END
BEGIN NOW Of those Heav'n-warring Champions could be found END
BEGIN NOW So hardie as to proffer or accept END
BEGIN NOW Alone the dreadful voyage; till at last END
BEGIN NOW SATAN, whom now transcendent glory rais'd END
BEGIN NOW Above his fellows, with Monarchal pride END
BEGIN NOW Conscious of highest worth, unmov'd thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW O Progeny of Heav'n, Empyreal Thrones, END
BEGIN NOW With reason hath deep silence and demurr END
BEGIN NOW Seis'd us, though undismaid: long is the way END
BEGIN NOW And hard, that out of Hell leads up to Light; END
BEGIN NOW Our prison strong, this huge convex of Fire, END
BEGIN NOW Outrageous to devour, immures us round END
BEGIN NOW Ninefold, and gates of burning Adamant END
BEGIN NOW Barr'd over us prohibit all egress. END
BEGIN NOW These past, if any pass, the void profound END
BEGIN NOW Of unessential Night receives him next END
BEGIN NOW Wide gaping, and with utter loss of being END
BEGIN NOW Threatens him, plung'd in that abortive gulf. END
BEGIN NOW If thence he scape into what ever world, END
BEGIN NOW Or unknown Region, what remains him less END
BEGIN NOW Then unknown dangers and as hard escape. END
BEGIN NOW But I should ill become this Throne, O Peers, END
BEGIN NOW And this Imperial Sov'ranty, adorn'd END
BEGIN NOW With splendor, arm'd with power, if aught propos'd END
BEGIN NOW And judg'd of public moment, in the shape END
BEGIN NOW Of difficulty or danger could deterre END
BEGIN NOW Me from attempting. Wherefore do I assume END
BEGIN NOW These Royalties, and not refuse to Reign, END
BEGIN NOW Refusing to accept as great a share END
BEGIN NOW Of hazard as of honour, due alike END
BEGIN NOW To him who Reigns, and so much to him due END
BEGIN NOW Of hazard more, as he above the rest END
BEGIN NOW High honourd sits? Go therfore mighty powers, END
BEGIN NOW Terror of Heav'n, though fall'n; intend at home, END
BEGIN NOW While here shall be our home, what best may ease END
BEGIN NOW The present misery, and render Hell END
BEGIN NOW More tollerable; if there be cure or charm END
BEGIN NOW To respite or deceive, or slack the pain END
BEGIN NOW Of this ill Mansion: intermit no watch END
BEGIN NOW Against a wakeful Foe, while I abroad END
BEGIN NOW Through all the coasts of dark destruction seek END
BEGIN NOW Deliverance for us all: this enterprize END
BEGIN NOW None shall partake with me. Thus saying rose END
BEGIN NOW The Monarch, and prevented all reply, END
BEGIN NOW Prudent, least from his resolution rais'd END
BEGIN NOW Others among the chief might offer now END
BEGIN NOW (Certain to be refus'd) what erst they feard; END
BEGIN NOW And so refus'd might in opinion stand END
BEGIN NOW His rivals, winning cheap the high repute END
BEGIN NOW Which he through hazard huge must earn. But they END
BEGIN NOW Dreaded not more th' adventure then his voice END
BEGIN NOW Forbidding; and at once with him they rose; END
BEGIN NOW Thir rising all at once was as the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of Thunder heard remote. Towards him they bend END
BEGIN NOW With awful reverence prone; and as a God END
BEGIN NOW Extoll him equal to the highest in Heav'n: END
BEGIN NOW Nor fail'd they to express how much they prais'd, END
BEGIN NOW That for the general safety he despis'd END
BEGIN NOW His own: for neither do the Spirits damn'd END
BEGIN NOW Loose all thir vertue; least bad men should boast END
BEGIN NOW Thir specious deeds on earth, which glory excites, END
BEGIN NOW Or close ambition varnisht o're with zeal. END
BEGIN NOW Thus they thir doubtful consultations dark END
BEGIN NOW Ended rejoycing in thir matchless Chief: END
BEGIN NOW As when from mountain tops the dusky clouds END
BEGIN NOW Ascending, while the North wind sleeps, o'respread END
BEGIN NOW Heav'ns chearful face, the lowring Element END
BEGIN NOW Scowls ore the dark'nd lantskip Snow, or showre; END
BEGIN NOW If chance the radiant Sun with farewell sweet END
BEGIN NOW Extend his ev'ning beam, the fields revive, END
BEGIN NOW The birds thir notes renew, and bleating herds END
BEGIN NOW Attest thir joy, that hill and valley rings. END
BEGIN NOW O shame to men! Devil with Devil damn'd END
BEGIN NOW Firm concord holds, men onely disagree END
BEGIN NOW Of Creatures rational, though under hope END
BEGIN NOW Of heavenly Grace: and God proclaiming peace, END
BEGIN NOW Yet live in hatred, enmitie, and strife END
BEGIN NOW Among themselves, and levie cruel warres, END
BEGIN NOW Wasting the Earth, each other to destroy: END
BEGIN NOW As if (which might induce us to accord) END
BEGIN NOW Man had not hellish foes anow besides, END
BEGIN NOW That day and night for his destruction waite. END
BEGIN NOW The STYGIAN Councel thus dissolv'd; and forth END
BEGIN NOW In order came the grand infernal Peers, END
BEGIN NOW Midst came thir mighty Paramount, and seemd END
BEGIN NOW Alone th' Antagonist of Heav'n, nor less END
BEGIN NOW Then Hells dread Emperour with pomp Supream, END
BEGIN NOW And God-like imitated State; him round END
BEGIN NOW A Globe of fierie Seraphim inclos'd END
BEGIN NOW With bright imblazonrie, and horrent Arms. END
BEGIN NOW Then of thir Session ended they bid cry END
BEGIN NOW With Trumpets regal sound the great result: END
BEGIN NOW Toward the four winds four speedy Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW Put to thir mouths the sounding Alchymie END
BEGIN NOW By Haralds voice explain'd: the hollow Abyss END
BEGIN NOW Heard farr and wide, and all the host of Hell END
BEGIN NOW With deafning shout, return'd them loud acclaim. END
BEGIN NOW Thence more at ease thir minds and somwhat rais'd END
BEGIN NOW By false presumptuous hope, the ranged powers END
BEGIN NOW Disband, and wandring, each his several way END
BEGIN NOW Pursues, as inclination or sad choice END
BEGIN NOW Leads him perplext, where he may likeliest find END
BEGIN NOW Truce to his restless thoughts, and entertain END
BEGIN NOW The irksome hours, till his great Chief return. END
BEGIN NOW Part on the Plain, or in the Air sublime END
BEGIN NOW Upon the wing, or in swift race contend, END
BEGIN NOW As at th' Olympian Games or PYTHIAN fields; END
BEGIN NOW Part curb thir fierie Steeds, or shun the Goal END
BEGIN NOW With rapid wheels, or fronted Brigads form. END
BEGIN NOW As when to warn proud Cities warr appears END
BEGIN NOW Wag'd in the troubl'd Skie, and Armies rush END
BEGIN NOW To Battel in the Clouds, before each Van END
BEGIN NOW Pric forth the Aerie Knights, and couch thir spears END
BEGIN NOW Till thickest Legions close; with feats of Arms END
BEGIN NOW From either end of Heav'n the welkin burns. END
BEGIN NOW Others with vast TYPHOEAN rage more fell END
BEGIN NOW Rend up both Rocks and Hills, and ride the Air END
BEGIN NOW In whirlwind; Hell scarce holds the wilde uproar. END
BEGIN NOW As when ALCIDES from OEALIA Crown'd END
BEGIN NOW With conquest, felt th' envenom'd robe, and tore END
BEGIN NOW Through pain up by the roots THESSALIAN Pines, END
BEGIN NOW And LICHAS from the top of OETA threw END
BEGIN NOW Into th' EUBOIC Sea. Others more milde, END
BEGIN NOW Retreated in a silent valley, sing END
BEGIN NOW With notes Angelical to many a Harp END
BEGIN NOW Thir own Heroic deeds and hapless fall END
BEGIN NOW By doom of Battel; and complain that Fate END
BEGIN NOW Free Vertue should enthrall to Force or Chance. END
BEGIN NOW Thir song was partial, but the harmony END
BEGIN NOW (What could it less when Spirits immortal sing?) END
BEGIN NOW Suspended Hell, and took with ravishment END
BEGIN NOW The thronging audience. In discourse more sweet END
BEGIN NOW (For Eloquence the Soul, Song charms the Sense,) END
BEGIN NOW Others apart sat on a Hill retir'd, END
BEGIN NOW In thoughts more elevate, and reason'd high END
BEGIN NOW Fixt Fate, free will, foreknowledge absolute, END
BEGIN NOW And found no end, in wandring mazes lost. END
BEGIN NOW Of good and evil much they argu'd then, END
BEGIN NOW Of happiness and final misery, END
BEGIN NOW Passion and Apathie, and glory and shame, END
BEGIN NOW Vain wisdom all, and false Philosophie: END
BEGIN NOW Yet with a pleasing sorcerie could charm END
BEGIN NOW Pain for a while or anguish, and excite END
BEGIN NOW Fallacious hope, or arm th' obdured brest END
BEGIN NOW With stubborn patience as with triple steel. END
BEGIN NOW Another part in Squadrons and gross Bands, END
BEGIN NOW On bold adventure to discover wide END
BEGIN NOW That dismal world, if any Clime perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Might yeild them easier habitation, bend END
BEGIN NOW Four ways thir flying March, along the Banks END
BEGIN NOW Of four infernal Rivers that disgorge END
BEGIN NOW Into the burning Lake thir baleful streams; END
BEGIN NOW Abhorred STYX the flood of deadly hate, END
BEGIN NOW Sad ACHERON of sorrow, black and deep; END
BEGIN NOW COCYTUS, nam'd of lamentation loud END
BEGIN NOW Heard on the ruful stream; fierce PHLEGETON END
BEGIN NOW Whose waves of torrent fire inflame with rage. END
BEGIN NOW Farr off from these a slow and silent stream, END
BEGIN NOW LETHE the River of Oblivion roules END
BEGIN NOW Her watrie Labyrinth, whereof who drinks, END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith his former state and being forgets, END
BEGIN NOW Forgets both joy and grief, pleasure and pain. END
BEGIN NOW Beyond this flood a frozen Continent END
BEGIN NOW Lies dark and wilde, beat with perpetual storms END
BEGIN NOW Of Whirlwind and dire Hail, which on firm land END
BEGIN NOW Thaws not, but gathers heap, and ruin seems END
BEGIN NOW Of ancient pile; all else deep snow and ice, END
BEGIN NOW A gulf profound as that SERBONIAN Bog END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt DAMIATA and mount CASIUS old, END
BEGIN NOW Where Armies whole have sunk: the parching Air END
BEGIN NOW Burns frore, and cold performs th' effect of Fire. END
BEGIN NOW Thither by harpy-footed Furies hail'd, END
BEGIN NOW At certain revolutions all the damn'd END
BEGIN NOW Are brought: and feel by turns the bitter change END
BEGIN NOW Of fierce extreams, extreams by change more fierce, END
BEGIN NOW From Beds of raging Fire to starve in Ice END
BEGIN NOW Thir soft Ethereal warmth, and there to pine END
BEGIN NOW Immovable, infixt, and frozen round, END
BEGIN NOW Periods of time, thence hurried back to fire. END
BEGIN NOW They ferry over this LETHEAN Sound END
BEGIN NOW Both to and fro, thir sorrow to augment, END
BEGIN NOW And wish and struggle, as they pass, to reach END
BEGIN NOW The tempting stream, with one small drop to loose END
BEGIN NOW In sweet forgetfulness all pain and woe, END
BEGIN NOW All in one moment, and so neer the brink; END
BEGIN NOW But fate withstands, and to oppose th' attempt END
BEGIN NOW MEDUSA with GORGONIAN terror guards END
BEGIN NOW The Ford, and of it self the water flies END
BEGIN NOW All taste of living wight, as once it fled END
BEGIN NOW The lip of TANTALUS. Thus roving on END
BEGIN NOW In confus'd march forlorn, th' adventrous Bands END
BEGIN NOW With shuddring horror pale, and eyes agast END
BEGIN NOW View'd first thir lamentable lot, and found END
BEGIN NOW No rest: through many a dark and drearie Vaile END
BEGIN NOW They pass'd, and many a Region dolorous, END
BEGIN NOW O're many a Frozen, many a Fierie Alpe, END
BEGIN NOW Rocks, Caves, Lakes, Fens, Bogs, Dens, and shades of death, END
BEGIN NOW A Universe of death, which God by curse END
BEGIN NOW Created evil, for evil only good, END
BEGIN NOW Where all life dies, death lives, and nature breeds, END
BEGIN NOW Perverse, all monstrous, all prodigious things, END
BEGIN NOW Abominable, inutterable, and worse END
BEGIN NOW Then Fables yet have feign'd, or fear conceiv'd, END
BEGIN NOW Mean while the Adversary of God and Man, END
BEGIN NOW SATAN with thoughts inflam'd of highest design, END
BEGIN NOW Puts on swift wings, and toward the Gates of Hell END
BEGIN NOW Explores his solitary flight; som times END
BEGIN NOW He scours the right hand coast, som times the left, END
BEGIN NOW Now shaves with level wing the Deep, then soares END
BEGIN NOW Up to the fiery concave touring high. END
BEGIN NOW As when farr off at Sea a Fleet descri'd END
BEGIN NOW Hangs in the Clouds, by AEQUINOCTIAL Winds END
BEGIN NOW Close sailing from BENGALA, or the Iles END
BEGIN NOW Of TERNATE and TIDORE, whence Merchants bring END
BEGIN NOW Thir spicie Drugs: they on the trading Flood END
BEGIN NOW Through the wide ETHIOPIAN to the Cape END
BEGIN NOW Ply stemming nightly toward the Pole. So seem'd END
BEGIN NOW Farr off the flying Fiend: at last appeer END
BEGIN NOW Hell bounds high reaching to the horrid Roof, END
BEGIN NOW And thrice threefold the Gates; three folds were Brass END
BEGIN NOW Three Iron, three of Adamantine Rock, END
BEGIN NOW Impenitrable, impal'd with circling fire, END
BEGIN NOW Yet unconsum'd. Before the Gates there sat END
BEGIN NOW On either side a formidable shape; END
BEGIN NOW The one seem'd Woman to the waste, and fair, END
BEGIN NOW But ended foul in many a scaly fould END
BEGIN NOW Voluminous and vast, a Serpent arm'd END
BEGIN NOW With mortal sting: about her middle round END
BEGIN NOW A cry of Hell Hounds never ceasing bark'd END
BEGIN NOW With wide CERBEREAN mouths full loud, and rung END
BEGIN NOW A hideous Peal: yet, when they list, would creep, END
BEGIN NOW If aught disturb'd thir noyse, into her woomb, END
BEGIN NOW And kennel there, yet there still bark'd and howl'd END
BEGIN NOW Within unseen. Farr less abhorrd then these END
BEGIN NOW Vex'd SCYLLA bathing in the Sea that parts END
BEGIN NOW CALABRIA from the hoarce TRINACRIAN shore: END
BEGIN NOW Nor uglier follow the Night-Hag, when call'd END
BEGIN NOW In secret, riding through the Air she comes END
BEGIN NOW Lur'd with the smell of infant blood, to dance END
BEGIN NOW With LAPLAND Witches, while the labouring Moon END
BEGIN NOW Eclipses at thir charms. The other shape, END
BEGIN NOW If shape it might be call'd that shape had none END
BEGIN NOW Distinguishable in member, joynt, or limb, END
BEGIN NOW Or substance might be call'd that shadow seem'd, END
BEGIN NOW For each seem'd either; black it stood as Night, END
BEGIN NOW Fierce as ten Furies, terrible as Hell, END
BEGIN NOW And shook a dreadful Dart; what seem'd his head END
BEGIN NOW The likeness of a Kingly Crown had on. END
BEGIN NOW SATAN was now at hand, and from his seat END
BEGIN NOW The Monster moving onward came as fast, END
BEGIN NOW With horrid strides, Hell trembled as he strode. END
BEGIN NOW Th' undaunted Fiend what this might be admir'd, END
BEGIN NOW Admir'd, not fear'd; God and his Son except, END
BEGIN NOW Created thing naught vallu'd he nor shun'd; END
BEGIN NOW And with disdainful look thus first began. END
BEGIN NOW Whence and what art thou, execrable shape, END
BEGIN NOW That dar'st, though grim and terrible, advance END
BEGIN NOW Thy miscreated Front athwart my way END
BEGIN NOW To yonder Gates? through them I mean to pass, END
BEGIN NOW That be assur'd, without leave askt of thee: END
BEGIN NOW Retire, or taste thy folly, and learn by proof, END
BEGIN NOW Hell-born, not to contend with Spirits of Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Goblin full of wrauth reply'd, END
BEGIN NOW Art thou that Traitor Angel, art thou hee, END
BEGIN NOW Who first broke peace in Heav'n and Faith, till then END
BEGIN NOW Unbrok'n, and in proud rebellious Arms END
BEGIN NOW Drew after him the third part of Heav'ns Sons END
BEGIN NOW Conjur'd against the highest, for which both Thou END
BEGIN NOW And they outcast from God, are here condemn'd END
BEGIN NOW To waste Eternal daies in woe and pain? END
BEGIN NOW And reck'n'st thou thy self with Spirits of Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW Hell-doomd, and breath'st defiance here and scorn, END
BEGIN NOW Where I reign King, and to enrage thee more, END
BEGIN NOW Thy King and Lord? Back to thy punishment, END
BEGIN NOW False fugitive, and to thy speed add wings, END
BEGIN NOW Least with a whip of Scorpions I pursue END
BEGIN NOW Thy lingring, or with one stroke of this Dart END
BEGIN NOW Strange horror seise thee, and pangs unfelt before. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the grieslie terrour, and in shape, END
BEGIN NOW So speaking and so threatning, grew ten fold END
BEGIN NOW More dreadful and deform: on th' other side END
BEGIN NOW Incenc't with indignation SATAN stood END
BEGIN NOW Unterrifi'd, and like a Comet burn'd, END
BEGIN NOW That fires the length of OPHIUCUS huge END
BEGIN NOW In th' Artick Sky, and from his horrid hair END
BEGIN NOW Level'd his deadly aime; thir fatall hands END
BEGIN NOW No second stroke intend, and such a frown END
BEGIN NOW Each cast at th' other, as when two black Clouds END
BEGIN NOW With Heav'ns Artillery fraught, come rattling on END
BEGIN NOW Over the CASPIAN, then stand front to front END
BEGIN NOW Hov'ring a space, till Winds the signal blow END
BEGIN NOW To joyn thir dark Encounter in mid air: END
BEGIN NOW So frownd the mighty Combatants, that Hell END
BEGIN NOW Grew darker at thir frown, so matcht they stood; END
BEGIN NOW For never but once more was either like END
BEGIN NOW To meet so great a foe: and now great deeds END
BEGIN NOW Had been achiev'd, whereof all Hell had rung, END
BEGIN NOW Had not the Snakie Sorceress that sat END
BEGIN NOW Fast by Hell Gate, and kept the fatal Key, END
BEGIN NOW Ris'n, and with hideous outcry rush'd between. END
BEGIN NOW O Father, what intends thy hand, she cry'd, END
BEGIN NOW Against thy only Son? What fury O Son, END
BEGIN NOW Possesses thee to bend that mortal Dart END
BEGIN NOW Against thy Fathers head? and know'st for whom; END
BEGIN NOW For him who sits above and laughs the while END
BEGIN NOW At thee ordain'd his drudge, to execute END
BEGIN NOW What e're his wrath, which he calls Justice, bids, END
BEGIN NOW His wrath which one day will destroy ye both. END
BEGIN NOW She spake, and at her words the hellish Pest END
BEGIN NOW Forbore, then these to her SATAN return'd: END
BEGIN NOW So strange thy outcry, and thy words so strange END
BEGIN NOW Thou interposest, that my sudden hand END
BEGIN NOW Prevented spares to tell thee yet by deeds END
BEGIN NOW What it intends; till first I know of thee, END
BEGIN NOW What thing thou art, thus double-form'd, and why END
BEGIN NOW In this infernal Vaile first met thou call'st END
BEGIN NOW Me Father, and that Fantasm call'st my Son? END
BEGIN NOW I know thee not, nor ever saw till now END
BEGIN NOW Sight more detestable then him and thee. END
BEGIN NOW T' whom thus the Portress of Hell Gate reply'd; END
BEGIN NOW Hast thou forgot me then, and do I seem END
BEGIN NOW Now in thine eye so foul, once deemd so fair END
BEGIN NOW In Heav'n, when at th' Assembly, and in sight END
BEGIN NOW Of all the Seraphim with thee combin'd END
BEGIN NOW In bold conspiracy against Heav'ns King, END
BEGIN NOW All on a sudden miserable pain END
BEGIN NOW Surpris'd thee, dim thine eyes, and dizzie swumm END
BEGIN NOW In darkness, while thy head flames thick and fast END
BEGIN NOW Threw forth, till on the left side op'ning wide, END
BEGIN NOW Likest to thee in shape and count'nance bright, END
BEGIN NOW Then shining heav'nly fair, a Goddess arm'd END
BEGIN NOW Out of thy head I sprung: amazement seis'd END
BEGIN NOW All th' Host of Heav'n; back they recoild affraid END
BEGIN NOW At first, and call'd me SIN, and for a Sign END
BEGIN NOW Portentous held me; but familiar grown, END
BEGIN NOW I pleas'd, and with attractive graces won END
BEGIN NOW The most averse, thee chiefly, who full oft END
BEGIN NOW Thy self in me thy perfect image viewing END
BEGIN NOW Becam'st enamour'd, and such joy thou took'st END
BEGIN NOW With me in secret, that my womb conceiv'd END
BEGIN NOW A growing burden. Mean while Warr arose, END
BEGIN NOW And fields were fought in Heav'n; wherein remaind END
BEGIN NOW (For what could else) to our Almighty Foe END
BEGIN NOW Cleer Victory, to our part loss and rout END
BEGIN NOW Through all the Empyrean: down they fell END
BEGIN NOW Driv'n headlong from the Pitch of Heaven, down END
BEGIN NOW Into this Deep, and in the general fall END
BEGIN NOW I also; at which time this powerful Key END
BEGIN NOW Into my hand was giv'n, with charge to keep END
BEGIN NOW These Gates for ever shut, which none can pass END
BEGIN NOW Without my op'ning. Pensive here I sat END
BEGIN NOW Alone, but long I sat not, till my womb END
BEGIN NOW Pregnant by thee, and now excessive grown END
BEGIN NOW Prodigious motion felt and rueful throes. END
BEGIN NOW At last this odious offspring whom thou seest END
BEGIN NOW Thine own begotten, breaking violent way END
BEGIN NOW Tore through my entrails, that with fear and pain END
BEGIN NOW Distorted, all my nether shape thus grew END
BEGIN NOW Transform'd: but he my inbred enemie END
BEGIN NOW Forth issu'd, brandishing his fatal Dart END
BEGIN NOW Made to destroy: I fled, and cry'd out DEATH; END
BEGIN NOW Hell trembl'd at the hideous Name, and sigh'd END
BEGIN NOW From all her Caves, and back resounded DEATH. END
BEGIN NOW I fled, but he pursu'd (though more, it seems, END
BEGIN NOW Inflam'd with lust then rage) and swifter far, END
BEGIN NOW Me overtook his mother all dismaid, END
BEGIN NOW And in embraces forcible and foule END
BEGIN NOW Ingendring with me, of that rape begot END
BEGIN NOW These yelling Monsters that with ceasless cry END
BEGIN NOW Surround me, as thou sawst, hourly conceiv'd END
BEGIN NOW And hourly born, with sorrow infinite END
BEGIN NOW To me, for when they list into the womb END
BEGIN NOW That bred them they return, and howle and gnaw END
BEGIN NOW My Bowels, their repast; then bursting forth END
BEGIN NOW Afresh with conscious terrours vex me round, END
BEGIN NOW That rest or intermission none I find. END
BEGIN NOW Before mine eyes in opposition sits END
BEGIN NOW Grim DEATH my Son and foe, who sets them on, END
BEGIN NOW And me his Parent would full soon devour END
BEGIN NOW For want of other prey, but that he knows END
BEGIN NOW His end with mine involvd; and knows that I END
BEGIN NOW Should prove a bitter Morsel, and his bane, END
BEGIN NOW When ever that shall be; so Fate pronounc'd. END
BEGIN NOW But thou O Father, I forewarn thee, shun END
BEGIN NOW His deadly arrow; neither vainly hope END
BEGIN NOW To be invulnerable in those bright Arms, END
BEGIN NOW Though temper'd heav'nly, for that mortal dint, END
BEGIN NOW Save he who reigns above, none can resist. END
BEGIN NOW She finish'd, and the suttle Fiend his lore END
BEGIN NOW Soon learnd, now milder, and thus answerd smooth. END
BEGIN NOW Dear Daughter, since thou claim'st me for thy Sire, END
BEGIN NOW And my fair Son here showst me, the dear pledge END
BEGIN NOW Of dalliance had with thee in Heav'n, and joys END
BEGIN NOW Then sweet, now sad to mention, through dire change END
BEGIN NOW Befalln us unforeseen, unthought of, know END
BEGIN NOW I come no enemie, but to set free END
BEGIN NOW From out this dark and dismal house of pain, END
BEGIN NOW Both him and thee, and all the heav'nly Host END
BEGIN NOW Of Spirits that in our just pretenses arm'd END
BEGIN NOW Fell with us from on high: from them I go END
BEGIN NOW This uncouth errand sole, and one for all END
BEGIN NOW My self expose, with lonely steps to tread END
BEGIN NOW Th' unfounded deep, & through the void immense END
BEGIN NOW To search with wandring quest a place foretold END
BEGIN NOW Should be, and, by concurring signs, ere now END
BEGIN NOW Created vast and round, a place of bliss END
BEGIN NOW In the Pourlieues of Heav'n, and therein plac't END
BEGIN NOW A race of upstart Creatures, to supply END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps our vacant room, though more remov'd, END
BEGIN NOW Least Heav'n surcharg'd with potent multitude END
BEGIN NOW Might hap to move new broiles: Be this or aught END
BEGIN NOW Then this more secret now design'd, I haste END
BEGIN NOW To know, and this once known, shall soon return, END
BEGIN NOW And bring ye to the place where Thou and Death END
BEGIN NOW Shall dwell at ease, and up and down unseen END
BEGIN NOW Wing silently the buxom Air, imbalm'd END
BEGIN NOW With odours; there ye shall be fed and fill'd END
BEGIN NOW Immeasurably, all things shall be your prey. END
BEGIN NOW He ceas'd, for both seemd highly pleasd, and Death END
BEGIN NOW Grinnd horrible a gastly smile, to hear END
BEGIN NOW His famine should be fill'd, and blest his mawe END
BEGIN NOW Destin'd to that good hour: no less rejoyc'd END
BEGIN NOW His mother bad, and thus bespake her Sire. END
BEGIN NOW The key of this infernal Pit by due, END
BEGIN NOW And by command of Heav'ns all-powerful King END
BEGIN NOW I keep, by him forbidden to unlock END
BEGIN NOW These Adamantine Gates; against all force END
BEGIN NOW Death ready stands to interpose his dart, END
BEGIN NOW Fearless to be o'rematcht by living might. END
BEGIN NOW But what ow I to his commands above END
BEGIN NOW Who hates me, and hath hither thrust me down END
BEGIN NOW Into this gloom of TARTARUS profound, END
BEGIN NOW To sit in hateful Office here confin'd, END
BEGIN NOW Inhabitant of Heav'n, and heav'nlie-born, END
BEGIN NOW Here in perpetual agonie and pain, END
BEGIN NOW With terrors and with clamors compasst round END
BEGIN NOW Of mine own brood, that on my bowels feed: END
BEGIN NOW Thou art my Father, thou my Author, thou END
BEGIN NOW My being gav'st me; whom should I obey END
BEGIN NOW But thee, whom follow? thou wilt bring me soon END
BEGIN NOW To that new world of light and bliss, among END
BEGIN NOW The Gods who live at ease, where I shall Reign END
BEGIN NOW At thy right hand voluptuous, as beseems END
BEGIN NOW Thy daughter and thy darling, without end. END
BEGIN NOW Thus saying, from her side the fatal Key, END
BEGIN NOW Sad instrument of all our woe, she took; END
BEGIN NOW And towards the Gate rouling her bestial train, END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith the huge Porcullis high up drew, END
BEGIN NOW Which but her self not all the STYGIAN powers END
BEGIN NOW Could once have mov'd; then in the key-hole turns END
BEGIN NOW Th' intricate wards, and every Bolt and Bar END
BEGIN NOW Of massie Iron or sollid Rock with ease END
BEGIN NOW Unfast'ns: on a sudden op'n flie END
BEGIN NOW With impetuous recoile and jarring sound END
BEGIN NOW Th' infernal dores, and on thir hinges great END
BEGIN NOW Harsh Thunder, that the lowest bottom shook END
BEGIN NOW Of EREBUS. She op'nd, but to shut END
BEGIN NOW Excel'd her power; the Gates wide op'n stood, END
BEGIN NOW That with extended wings a Bannerd Host END
BEGIN NOW Under spread Ensigns marching might pass through END
BEGIN NOW With Horse and Chariots rankt in loose array; END
BEGIN NOW So wide they stood, and like a Furnace mouth END
BEGIN NOW Cast forth redounding smoak and ruddy flame. END
BEGIN NOW Before thir eyes in sudden view appear END
BEGIN NOW The secrets of the hoarie deep, a dark END
BEGIN NOW Illimitable Ocean without bound, END
BEGIN NOW Without dimension, where length, breadth, and highth, END
BEGIN NOW And time and place are lost; where eldest Night END
BEGIN NOW And CHAOS, Ancestors of Nature, hold END
BEGIN NOW Eternal ANARCHIE, amidst the noise END
BEGIN NOW Of endless warrs and by confusion stand. END
BEGIN NOW For hot, cold, moist, and dry, four Champions fierce END
BEGIN NOW Strive here for Maistrie, and to Battel bring END
BEGIN NOW Thir embryon Atoms; they around the flag END
BEGIN NOW Of each his faction, in thir several Clanns, END
BEGIN NOW Light-arm'd or heavy, sharp, smooth, swift or slow, END
BEGIN NOW Swarm populous, unnumber'd as the Sands END
BEGIN NOW Of BARCA or CYRENE'S torrid soil, END
BEGIN NOW Levied to side with warring Winds, and poise END
BEGIN NOW Thir lighter wings. To whom these most adhere, END
BEGIN NOW Hee rules a moment; CHAOS Umpire sits, END
BEGIN NOW And by decision more imbroiles the fray END
BEGIN NOW By which he Reigns: next him high Arbiter END
BEGIN NOW CHANCE governs all. Into this wilde Abyss, END
BEGIN NOW The Womb of nature and perhaps her Grave, END
BEGIN NOW Of neither Sea, nor Shore, nor Air, nor Fire, END
BEGIN NOW But all these in thir pregnant causes mixt END
BEGIN NOW Confus'dly, and which thus must ever fight, END
BEGIN NOW Unless th' Almighty Maker them ordain END
BEGIN NOW His dark materials to create more Worlds, END
BEGIN NOW Into this wilde Abyss the warie fiend END
BEGIN NOW Stood on the brink of Hell and look'd a while, END
BEGIN NOW Pondering his Voyage; for no narrow frith END
BEGIN NOW He had to cross. Nor was his eare less peal'd END
BEGIN NOW With noises loud and ruinous (to compare END
BEGIN NOW Great things with small) then when BELLONA storms, END
BEGIN NOW With all her battering Engines bent to rase END
BEGIN NOW Som Capital City, or less then if this frame END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'n were falling, and these Elements END
BEGIN NOW In mutinie had from her Axle torn END
BEGIN NOW The stedfast Earth. At last his Sail-broad Vannes END
BEGIN NOW He spreads for flight, and in the surging smoak END
BEGIN NOW Uplifted spurns the ground, thence many a League END
BEGIN NOW As in a cloudy Chair ascending rides END
BEGIN NOW Audacious, but that seat soon failing, meets END
BEGIN NOW A vast vacuitie: all unawares END
BEGIN NOW Fluttring his pennons vain plumb down he drops END
BEGIN NOW Ten thousand fadom deep, and to this hour END
BEGIN NOW Down had been falling, had not by ill chance END
BEGIN NOW The strong rebuff of som tumultuous cloud END
BEGIN NOW Instinct with Fire and Nitre hurried him END
BEGIN NOW As many miles aloft: that furie stay'd, END
BEGIN NOW Quencht in a Boggie SYRTIS, neither Sea, END
BEGIN NOW Nor good dry Land: nigh founderd on he fares, END
BEGIN NOW Treading the crude consistence, half on foot, END
BEGIN NOW Half flying; behoves him now both Oare and Saile. END
BEGIN NOW As when a Gryfon through the Wilderness END
BEGIN NOW With winged course ore Hill or moarie Dale, END
BEGIN NOW Pursues the ARIMASPIAN, who by stelth END
BEGIN NOW Had from his wakeful custody purloind END
BEGIN NOW The guarded Gold: So eagerly the fiend END
BEGIN NOW Ore bog or steep, through strait, rough, dense, or rare, END
BEGIN NOW With head, hands, wings, or feet pursues his way, END
BEGIN NOW And swims or sinks, or wades, or creeps, or flyes: END
BEGIN NOW At length a universal hubbub wilde END
BEGIN NOW Of stunning sounds and voices all confus'd END
BEGIN NOW Born through the hollow dark assaults his eare END
BEGIN NOW With loudest vehemence: thither he plyes, END
BEGIN NOW Undaunted to meet there what ever power END
BEGIN NOW Or Spirit of the nethermost Abyss END
BEGIN NOW Might in that noise reside, of whom to ask END
BEGIN NOW Which way the neerest coast of darkness lyes END
BEGIN NOW Bordering on light; when strait behold the Throne END
BEGIN NOW Of CHAOS, and his dark Pavilion spread END
BEGIN NOW Wide on the wasteful Deep; with him Enthron'd END
BEGIN NOW Sat Sable-vested Night, eldest of things, END
BEGIN NOW The consort of his Reign; and by them stood END
BEGIN NOW ORCUS and ADES, and the dreaded name END
BEGIN NOW Of DEMOGORGON; Rumor next and Chance, END
BEGIN NOW And Tumult and Confusion all imbroild, END
BEGIN NOW And Discord with a thousand various mouths. END
BEGIN NOW T' whom SATAN turning boldly, thus. Ye Powers END
BEGIN NOW And Spirits of this nethermost Abyss, END
BEGIN NOW CHAOS and ANCIENT NIGHT, I come no Spie, END
BEGIN NOW With purpose to explore or to disturb END
BEGIN NOW The secrets of your Realm, but by constraint END
BEGIN NOW Wandring this darksome desart, as my way END
BEGIN NOW Lies through your spacious Empire up to light, END
BEGIN NOW Alone, and without guide, half lost, I seek END
BEGIN NOW What readiest path leads where your gloomie bounds END
BEGIN NOW Confine with Heav'n; or if som other place END
BEGIN NOW From your Dominion won, th' Ethereal King END
BEGIN NOW Possesses lately, thither to arrive END
BEGIN NOW I travel this profound, direct my course; END
BEGIN NOW Directed, no mean recompence it brings END
BEGIN NOW To your behoof, if I that Region lost, END
BEGIN NOW All usurpation thence expell'd, reduce END
BEGIN NOW To her original darkness and your sway END
BEGIN NOW (Which is my present journey) and once more END
BEGIN NOW Erect the Standerd there of ANCIENT NIGHT; END
BEGIN NOW Yours be th' advantage all, mine the revenge. END
BEGIN NOW Thus SATAN; and him thus the Anarch old END
BEGIN NOW With faultring speech and visage incompos'd END
BEGIN NOW Answer'd. I know thee, stranger, who thou art, END
BEGIN NOW That mighty leading Angel, who of late END
BEGIN NOW Made head against Heav'ns King, though overthrown. END
BEGIN NOW I saw and heard, for such a numerous host END
BEGIN NOW Fled not in silence through the frighted deep END
BEGIN NOW With ruin upon ruin, rout on rout, END
BEGIN NOW Confusion worse confounded; and Heav'n Gates END
BEGIN NOW Pourd out by millions her victorious Bands END
BEGIN NOW Pursuing. I upon my Frontieres here END
BEGIN NOW Keep residence; if all I can will serve, END
BEGIN NOW That little which is left so to defend END
BEGIN NOW Encroacht on still through our intestine broiles END
BEGIN NOW Weakning the Scepter of old Night: first Hell END
BEGIN NOW Your dungeon stretching far and wide beneath; END
BEGIN NOW Now lately Heaven and Earth, another World END
BEGIN NOW Hung ore my Realm, link'd in a golden Chain END
BEGIN NOW To that side Heav'n from whence your Legions fell: END
BEGIN NOW If that way be your walk, you have not farr; END
BEGIN NOW So much the neerer danger; goe and speed; END
BEGIN NOW Havock and spoil and ruin are my gain. END
BEGIN NOW He ceas'd; and SATAN staid not to reply, END
BEGIN NOW But glad that now his Sea should find a shore, END
BEGIN NOW With fresh alacritie and force renew'd END
BEGIN NOW Springs upward like a Pyramid of fire END
BEGIN NOW Into the wilde expanse, and through the shock END
BEGIN NOW Of fighting Elements, on all sides round END
BEGIN NOW Environ'd wins his way; harder beset END
BEGIN NOW And more endanger'd, then when ARGO pass'd END
BEGIN NOW Through BOSPORUS betwixt the justling Rocks: END
BEGIN NOW Or when ULYSSES on the Larbord shunnd END
BEGIN NOW CHARYBDIS, and by th' other whirlpool steard. END
BEGIN NOW So he with difficulty and labour hard END
BEGIN NOW Mov'd on, with difficulty and labour hee; END
BEGIN NOW But hee once past, soon after when man fell, END
BEGIN NOW Strange alteration! Sin and Death amain END
BEGIN NOW Following his track, such was the will of Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW Pav'd after him a broad and beat'n way END
BEGIN NOW Over the dark Abyss, whose boiling Gulf END
BEGIN NOW Tamely endur'd a Bridge of wondrous length END
BEGIN NOW From Hell continu'd reaching th' utmost Orbe END
BEGIN NOW Of this frail World; by which the Spirits perverse END
BEGIN NOW With easie intercourse pass to and fro END
BEGIN NOW To tempt or punish mortals, except whom END
BEGIN NOW God and good Angels guard by special grace. END
BEGIN NOW But now at last the sacred influence END
BEGIN NOW Of light appears, and from the walls of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Shoots farr into the bosom of dim Night END
BEGIN NOW A glimmering dawn; here Nature first begins END
BEGIN NOW Her fardest verge, and CHAOS to retire END
BEGIN NOW As from her outmost works a brok'n foe END
BEGIN NOW With tumult less and with less hostile din, END
BEGIN NOW That SATAN with less toil, and now with ease END
BEGIN NOW Wafts on the calmer wave by dubious light END
BEGIN NOW And like a weather-beaten Vessel holds END
BEGIN NOW Gladly the Port, though Shrouds and Tackle torn; END
BEGIN NOW Or in the emptier waste, resembling Air, END
BEGIN NOW Weighs his spread wings, at leasure to behold END
BEGIN NOW Farr off th' Empyreal Heav'n, extended wide END
BEGIN NOW In circuit, undetermind square or round, END
BEGIN NOW With Opal Towrs and Battlements adorn'd END
BEGIN NOW Of living Saphire, once his native Seat; END
BEGIN NOW And fast by hanging in a golden Chain END
BEGIN NOW This pendant world, in bigness as a Starr END
BEGIN NOW Of smallest Magnitude close by the Moon. END
BEGIN NOW Thither full fraught with mischievous revenge, END
BEGIN NOW Accurst, and in a cursed hour he hies. END
BEGIN NOW HAil holy light, ofspring of Heav'n first-born, END
BEGIN NOW Or of th' Eternal Coeternal beam END
BEGIN NOW May I express thee unblam'd? since God is light, END
BEGIN NOW And never but in unapproached light END
BEGIN NOW Dwelt from Eternitie, dwelt then in thee, END
BEGIN NOW Bright effluence of bright essence increate. END
BEGIN NOW Or hear'st thou rather pure Ethereal stream, END
BEGIN NOW Whose Fountain who shall tell? before the Sun, END
BEGIN NOW Before the Heavens thou wert, and at the voice END
BEGIN NOW Of God, as with a Mantle didst invest END
BEGIN NOW The rising world of waters dark and deep, END
BEGIN NOW Won from the void and formless infinite. END
BEGIN NOW Thee I re-visit now with bolder wing, END
BEGIN NOW Escap't the STYGIAN Pool, though long detain'd END
BEGIN NOW In that obscure sojourn, while in my flight END
BEGIN NOW Through utter and through middle darkness borne END
BEGIN NOW With other notes then to th' ORPHEAN Lyre END
BEGIN NOW Taught by the heav'nly Muse to venture down END
BEGIN NOW The dark descent, and up to reascend, END
BEGIN NOW Though hard and rare: thee I revisit safe, END
BEGIN NOW And feel thy sovran vital Lamp; but thou END
BEGIN NOW Revisit'st not these eyes, that rowle in vain END
BEGIN NOW To find thy piercing ray, and find no dawn; END
BEGIN NOW So thick a drop serene hath quencht thir Orbs, END
BEGIN NOW Or dim suffusion veild. Yet not the more END
BEGIN NOW Cease I to wander where the Muses haunt END
BEGIN NOW Cleer Spring, or shadie Grove, or Sunnie Hill, END
BEGIN NOW Smit with the love of sacred song; but chief END
BEGIN NOW Thee SION and the flowrie Brooks beneath END
BEGIN NOW That wash thy hallowd feet, and warbling flow, END
BEGIN NOW Nightly I visit: nor somtimes forget END
BEGIN NOW Those other two equal'd with me in Fate, END
BEGIN NOW So were I equal'd with them in renown, END
BEGIN NOW And TIRESIAS and PHINEUS Prophets old. END
BEGIN NOW Then feed on thoughts, that voluntarie move END
BEGIN NOW Harmonious numbers; as the wakeful Bird END
BEGIN NOW Sings darkling, and in shadiest Covert hid END
BEGIN NOW Tunes her nocturnal Note. Thus with the Year END
BEGIN NOW Seasons return, but not to me returns END
BEGIN NOW Day, or the sweet approach of Ev'n or Morn, END
BEGIN NOW Or sight of vernal bloom, or Summers Rose, END
BEGIN NOW Or flocks, or herds, or human face divine; END
BEGIN NOW But cloud in stead, and ever-during dark END
BEGIN NOW Surrounds me, from the chearful waies of men END
BEGIN NOW Cut off, and for the book of knowledg fair END
BEGIN NOW Presented with a Universal blanc END
BEGIN NOW Of Natures works to mee expung'd and ras'd, END
BEGIN NOW And wisdome at one entrance quite shut out. END
BEGIN NOW So much the rather thou Celestial light END
BEGIN NOW Shine inward, and the mind through all her powers END
BEGIN NOW Irradiate, there plant eyes, all mist from thence END
BEGIN NOW Purge and disperse, that I may see and tell END
BEGIN NOW Of things invisible to mortal sight. END
BEGIN NOW Now had the Almighty Father from above, END
BEGIN NOW From the pure Empyrean where he sits END
BEGIN NOW High Thron'd above all highth, bent down his eye, END
BEGIN NOW His own works and their works at once to view: END
BEGIN NOW Stood thick as Starrs, and from his sight receiv'd END
BEGIN NOW Beatitude past utterance; on his right END
BEGIN NOW The radiant image of his Glory sat, END
BEGIN NOW His onely Son; On Earth he first beheld END
BEGIN NOW Our two first Parents, yet the onely two END
BEGIN NOW Of mankind, in the happie Garden plac't, END
BEGIN NOW Reaping immortal fruits of joy and love, END
BEGIN NOW Uninterrupted joy, unrivald love END
BEGIN NOW In blissful solitude; he then survey'd END
BEGIN NOW Hell and the Gulf between, and SATAN there END
BEGIN NOW Coasting the wall of Heav'n on this side Night END
BEGIN NOW In the dun Air sublime, and ready now END
BEGIN NOW To stoop with wearied wings, and willing feet END
BEGIN NOW On the bare outside of this World, that seem'd END
BEGIN NOW Firm land imbosom'd without Firmament, END
BEGIN NOW Uncertain which, in Ocean or in Air. END
BEGIN NOW Him God beholding from his prospect high, END
BEGIN NOW Wherein past, present, future he beholds, END
BEGIN NOW Thus to his onely Son foreseeing spake. END
BEGIN NOW Onely begotten Son, seest thou what rage END
BEGIN NOW Transports our adversarie, whom no bounds END
BEGIN NOW Prescrib'd, no barrs of Hell, nor all the chains END
BEGIN NOW Heapt on him there, nor yet the main Abyss END
BEGIN NOW Wide interrupt can hold; so bent he seems END
BEGIN NOW On desperat revenge, that shall redound END
BEGIN NOW Upon his own rebellious head. And now END
BEGIN NOW Through all restraint broke loose he wings his way END
BEGIN NOW Not farr off Heav'n, in the Precincts of light, END
BEGIN NOW Directly towards the new created World, END
BEGIN NOW And Man there plac't, with purpose to assay END
BEGIN NOW If him by force he can destroy, or worse, END
BEGIN NOW By som false guile pervert; and shall pervert; END
BEGIN NOW For man will heark'n to his glozing lyes, END
BEGIN NOW And easily transgress the sole Command, END
BEGIN NOW Sole pledge of his obedience: So will fall END
BEGIN NOW Hee and his faithless Progenie: whose fault? END
BEGIN NOW Whose but his own? ingrate, he had of mee END
BEGIN NOW All he could have; I made him just and right, END
BEGIN NOW Sufficient to have stood, though free to fall. END
BEGIN NOW Such I created all th' Ethereal Powers END
BEGIN NOW And Spirits, both them who stood & them who faild; END
BEGIN NOW Freely they stood who stood, and fell who fell. END
BEGIN NOW Not free, what proof could they have givn sincere END
BEGIN NOW Of true allegiance, constant Faith or Love, END
BEGIN NOW Where onely what they needs must do, appeard, END
BEGIN NOW Not what they would? what praise could they receive? END
BEGIN NOW What pleasure I from such obedience paid, END
BEGIN NOW When Will and Reason (Reason also is choice) END
BEGIN NOW Useless and vain, of freedom both despoild, END
BEGIN NOW Made passive both, had servd necessitie, END
BEGIN NOW Not mee. They therefore as to right belongd, END
BEGIN NOW So were created, nor can justly accuse END
BEGIN NOW Thir maker, or thir making, or thir Fate; END
BEGIN NOW As if Predestination over-rul'd END
BEGIN NOW Thir will, dispos'd by absolute Decree END
BEGIN NOW Or high foreknowledge; they themselves decreed END
BEGIN NOW Thir own revolt, not I: if I foreknew, END
BEGIN NOW Foreknowledge had no influence on their fault, END
BEGIN NOW Which had no less prov'd certain unforeknown. END
BEGIN NOW So without least impulse or shadow of Fate, END
BEGIN NOW Or aught by me immutablie foreseen, END
BEGIN NOW They trespass, Authors to themselves in all END
BEGIN NOW Both what they judge and what they choose; for so END
BEGIN NOW I formd them free, and free they must remain, END
BEGIN NOW Till they enthrall themselves: I else must change END
BEGIN NOW Thir nature, and revoke the high Decree END
BEGIN NOW Unchangeable, Eternal, which ordain'd END
BEGIN NOW Thir freedom, they themselves ordain'd thir fall. END
BEGIN NOW The first sort by thir own suggestion fell, END
BEGIN NOW Self-tempted, self-deprav'd: Man falls deceiv'd END
BEGIN NOW By the other first: Man therefore shall find grace, END
BEGIN NOW The other none: in Mercy and Justice both, END
BEGIN NOW Through Heav'n and Earth, so shall my glorie excel, END
BEGIN NOW But Mercy first and last shall brightest shine. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while God spake, ambrosial fragrance fill'd END
BEGIN NOW All Heav'n, and in the blessed Spirits elect END
BEGIN NOW Sense of new joy ineffable diffus'd: END
BEGIN NOW Beyond compare the Son of God was seen END
BEGIN NOW Most glorious, in him all his Father shon END
BEGIN NOW Substantially express'd, and in his face END
BEGIN NOW Divine compassion visibly appeerd, END
BEGIN NOW Love without end, and without measure Grace, END
BEGIN NOW Which uttering thus he to his Father spake. END
BEGIN NOW O Father, gracious was that word which clos'd END
BEGIN NOW Thy sovran sentence, that Man should find grace; END
BEGIN NOW For which both Heav'n and Earth shall high extoll END
BEGIN NOW Thy praises, with th' innumerable sound END
BEGIN NOW Of Hymns and sacred Songs, wherewith thy Throne END
BEGIN NOW Encompass'd shall resound thee ever blest. END
BEGIN NOW For should Man finally be lost, should Man END
BEGIN NOW Thy creature late so lov'd, thy youngest Son END
BEGIN NOW Fall circumvented thus by fraud, though joynd END
BEGIN NOW With his own folly? that be from thee farr, END
BEGIN NOW That farr be from thee, Father, who art Judge END
BEGIN NOW Of all things made, and judgest onely right. END
BEGIN NOW Or shall the Adversarie thus obtain END
BEGIN NOW His end, and frustrate thine, shall he fulfill END
BEGIN NOW His malice, and thy goodness bring to naught, END
BEGIN NOW Or proud return though to his heavier doom, END
BEGIN NOW Yet with revenge accomplish't and to Hell END
BEGIN NOW Draw after him the whole Race of mankind, END
BEGIN NOW By him corrupted? or wilt thou thy self END
BEGIN NOW Abolish thy Creation, and unmake, END
BEGIN NOW For him, what for thy glorie thou hast made? END
BEGIN NOW So should thy goodness and thy greatness both END
BEGIN NOW Be questiond and blaspheam'd without defence. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the great Creatour thus reply'd. END
BEGIN NOW O Son, in whom my Soul hath chief delight, END
BEGIN NOW Son of my bosom, Son who art alone END
BEGIN NOW My word, my wisdom, and effectual might, END
BEGIN NOW All hast thou spok'n as my thoughts are, all END
BEGIN NOW As my Eternal purpose hath decreed: END
BEGIN NOW Man shall not quite be lost, but sav'd who will, END
BEGIN NOW Yet not of will in him, but grace in me END
BEGIN NOW Freely voutsaft; once more I will renew END
BEGIN NOW His lapsed powers, though forfeit and enthrall'd END
BEGIN NOW By sin to foul exorbitant desires; END
BEGIN NOW Upheld by me, yet once more he shall stand END
BEGIN NOW On even ground against his mortal foe, END
BEGIN NOW By me upheld, that he may know how frail END
BEGIN NOW His fall'n condition is, and to me ow END
BEGIN NOW All his deliv'rance, and to none but me. END
BEGIN NOW Some I have chosen of peculiar grace END
BEGIN NOW Elect above the rest; so is my will: END
BEGIN NOW The rest shall hear me call, and oft be warnd END
BEGIN NOW Thir sinful state, and to appease betimes END
BEGIN NOW Th' incensed Deitie, while offerd grace END
BEGIN NOW Invites; for I will cleer thir senses dark, END
BEGIN NOW What may suffice, and soft'n stonie hearts END
BEGIN NOW To pray, repent, and bring obedience due. END
BEGIN NOW To prayer, repentance, and obedience due, END
BEGIN NOW Though but endevord with sincere intent, END
BEGIN NOW Mine eare shall not be slow, mine eye not shut. END
BEGIN NOW And I will place within them as a guide END
BEGIN NOW My Umpire CONSCIENCE, whom if they will hear, END
BEGIN NOW Light after light well us'd they shall attain, END
BEGIN NOW And to the end persisting, safe arrive. END
BEGIN NOW This my long sufferance and my day of grace END
BEGIN NOW They who neglect and scorn, shall never taste; END
BEGIN NOW But hard be hard'nd, blind be blinded more, END
BEGIN NOW That they may stumble on, and deeper fall; END
BEGIN NOW And none but such from mercy I exclude. END
BEGIN NOW But yet all is not don; Man disobeying, END
BEGIN NOW Disloyal breaks his fealtie, and sinns END
BEGIN NOW Against the high Supremacie of Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW Affecting God-head, and so loosing all, END
BEGIN NOW To expiate his Treason hath naught left, END
BEGIN NOW But to destruction sacred and devote, END
BEGIN NOW He with his whole posteritie must die, END
BEGIN NOW Die hee or Justice must; unless for him END
BEGIN NOW Som other able, and as willing, pay END
BEGIN NOW The rigid satisfaction, death for death. END
BEGIN NOW Say Heav'nly Powers, where shall we find such love, END
BEGIN NOW Which of ye will be mortal to redeem END
BEGIN NOW Mans mortal crime, and just th' unjust to save, END
BEGIN NOW Dwels in all Heaven charitie so deare? END
BEGIN NOW He ask'd, but all the Heav'nly Quire stood mute, END
BEGIN NOW And silence was in Heav'n: on mans behalf END
BEGIN NOW Patron or Intercessor none appeerd, END
BEGIN NOW Much less that durst upon his own head draw END
BEGIN NOW The deadly forfeiture, and ransom set. END
BEGIN NOW And now without redemption all mankind END
BEGIN NOW Must have bin lost, adjudg'd to Death and Hell END
BEGIN NOW By doom severe, had not the Son of God, END
BEGIN NOW In whom the fulness dwels of love divine, END
BEGIN NOW His dearest mediation thus renewd. END
BEGIN NOW Father, thy word is past, man shall find grace; END
BEGIN NOW And shall grace not find means, that finds her way, END
BEGIN NOW The speediest of thy winged messengers, END
BEGIN NOW To visit all thy creatures, and to all END
BEGIN NOW Comes unprevented, unimplor'd, unsought, END
BEGIN NOW Happie for man, so coming; he her aide END
BEGIN NOW Can never seek, once dead in sins and lost; END
BEGIN NOW Attonement for himself or offering meet, END
BEGIN NOW Indebted and undon, hath none to bring: END
BEGIN NOW Behold mee then, mee for him, life for life END
BEGIN NOW I offer, on mee let thine anger fall; END
BEGIN NOW Account mee man; I for his sake will leave END
BEGIN NOW Thy bosom, and this glorie next to thee END
BEGIN NOW Freely put off, and for him lastly die END
BEGIN NOW Well pleas'd, on me let Death wreck all his rage; END
BEGIN NOW Under his gloomie power I shall not long END
BEGIN NOW Lie vanquisht; thou hast givn me to possess END
BEGIN NOW Life in my self for ever, by thee I live, END
BEGIN NOW Though now to Death I yeild, and am his due END
BEGIN NOW All that of me can die, yet that debt paid, END
BEGIN NOW Thou wilt not leave me in the loathsom grave END
BEGIN NOW His prey, nor suffer my unspotted Soule END
BEGIN NOW For ever with corruption there to dwell; END
BEGIN NOW But I shall rise Victorious, and subdue END
BEGIN NOW My Vanquisher, spoild of his vanted spoile; END
BEGIN NOW Death his deaths wound shall then receive, & stoop END
BEGIN NOW Inglorious, of his mortall sting disarm'd. END
BEGIN NOW I through the ample Air in Triumph high END
BEGIN NOW Shall lead Hell Captive maugre Hell, and show END
BEGIN NOW The powers of darkness bound. Thou at the sight END
BEGIN NOW Pleas'd, out of Heaven shalt look down and smile, END
BEGIN NOW While by thee rais'd I ruin all my Foes, END
BEGIN NOW Death last, and with his Carcass glut the Grave: END
BEGIN NOW Then with the multitude of my redeemd END
BEGIN NOW Shall enter Heaven long absent, and returne, END
BEGIN NOW Father, to see thy face, wherein no cloud END
BEGIN NOW Of anger shall remain, but peace assur'd, END
BEGIN NOW And reconcilement; wrauth shall be no more END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth, but in thy presence Joy entire. END
BEGIN NOW His words here ended, but his meek aspect END
BEGIN NOW Silent yet spake, and breath'd immortal love END
BEGIN NOW To mortal men, above which only shon END
BEGIN NOW Filial obedience: as a sacrifice END
BEGIN NOW Glad to be offer'd, he attends the will END
BEGIN NOW Of his great Father. Admiration seis'd END
BEGIN NOW All Heav'n, what this might mean, & whither tend END
BEGIN NOW Wondring; but soon th' Almighty thus reply'd: END
BEGIN NOW O thou in Heav'n and Earth the only peace END
BEGIN NOW Found out for mankind under wrauth, O thou END
BEGIN NOW My sole complacence! well thou know'st how dear, END
BEGIN NOW To me are all my works, nor Man the least END
BEGIN NOW Though last created, that for him I spare END
BEGIN NOW Thee from my bosom and right hand, to save, END
BEGIN NOW By loosing thee a while, the whole Race lost. END
BEGIN NOW Thou therefore whom thou only canst redeeme, END
BEGIN NOW Thir Nature also to thy Nature joyne; END
BEGIN NOW And be thy self Man among men on Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Made flesh, when time shall be, of Virgin seed, END
BEGIN NOW By wondrous birth: Be thou in ADAMS room END
BEGIN NOW The Head of all mankind, though ADAMS Son. END
BEGIN NOW As in him perish all men, so in thee END
BEGIN NOW As from a second root shall be restor'd, END
BEGIN NOW As many as are restor'd, without thee none. END
BEGIN NOW His crime makes guiltie all his Sons, thy merit END
BEGIN NOW Imputed shall absolve them who renounce END
BEGIN NOW Thir own both righteous and unrighteous deeds, END
BEGIN NOW And live in thee transplanted, and from thee END
BEGIN NOW Receive new life. So Man, as is most just, END
BEGIN NOW Shall satisfie for Man, be judg'd and die, END
BEGIN NOW And dying rise, and rising with him raise END
BEGIN NOW His Brethren, ransomd with his own dear life. END
BEGIN NOW So Heav'nly love shal outdoo Hellish hate, END
BEGIN NOW Giving to death, and dying to redeeme, END
BEGIN NOW So dearly to redeem what Hellish hate END
BEGIN NOW So easily destroy'd, and still destroyes END
BEGIN NOW In those who, when they may, accept not grace. END
BEGIN NOW Nor shalt thou by descending to assume END
BEGIN NOW Mans Nature, less'n or degrade thine owne. END
BEGIN NOW Because thou hast, though Thron'd in highest bliss END
BEGIN NOW Equal to God, and equally enjoying END
BEGIN NOW God-like fruition, quitted all to save END
BEGIN NOW A World from utter loss, and hast been found END
BEGIN NOW By Merit more then Birthright Son of God, END
BEGIN NOW Found worthiest to be so by being Good, END
BEGIN NOW Farr more then Great or High; because in thee END
BEGIN NOW Love hath abounded more then Glory abounds, END
BEGIN NOW Therefore thy Humiliation shall exalt END
BEGIN NOW With thee thy Manhood also to this Throne; END
BEGIN NOW Here shalt thou sit incarnate, here shalt Reigne END
BEGIN NOW Both God and Man, Son both of God and Man, END
BEGIN NOW Anointed universal King; all Power END
BEGIN NOW I give thee, reign for ever, and assume END
BEGIN NOW Thy Merits; under thee as Head Supream END
BEGIN NOW Thrones, Princedoms, Powers, Dominions I reduce: END
BEGIN NOW All knees to thee shall bow, of them that bide END
BEGIN NOW In Heaven, or Earth, or under Earth in Hell; END
BEGIN NOW When thou attended gloriously from Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Shalt in the Skie appeer, and from thee send END
BEGIN NOW The summoning Arch-Angels to proclaime END
BEGIN NOW Thy dread Tribunal: forthwith from all Windes END
BEGIN NOW The living, and forthwith the cited dead END
BEGIN NOW Of all past Ages to the general Doom END
BEGIN NOW Shall hast'n, such a peal shall rouse thir sleep. END
BEGIN NOW Then all thy Saints assembl'd, thou shalt judge END
BEGIN NOW Bad men and Angels, they arraignd shall sink END
BEGIN NOW Beneath thy Sentence; Hell, her numbers full, END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth shall be for ever shut. Mean while END
BEGIN NOW The World shall burn, and from her ashes spring END
BEGIN NOW New Heav'n and Earth, wherein the just shall dwell END
BEGIN NOW And after all thir tribulations long END
BEGIN NOW See golden days, fruitful of golden deeds, END
BEGIN NOW With Joy and Love triumphing, and fair Truth. END
BEGIN NOW Then thou thy regal Scepter shalt lay by, END
BEGIN NOW For regal Scepter then no more shall need, END
BEGIN NOW God shall be All in All. But all ye Gods, END
BEGIN NOW Adore him, who to compass all this dies, END
BEGIN NOW Adore the Son, and honour him as mee. END
BEGIN NOW No sooner had th' Almighty ceas't, but all END
BEGIN NOW The multitude of Angels with a shout END
BEGIN NOW Loud as from numbers without number, sweet END
BEGIN NOW As from blest voices, uttering joy, Heav'n rung END
BEGIN NOW With Jubilee, and loud Hosanna's fill'd END
BEGIN NOW Th' eternal Regions: lowly reverent END
BEGIN NOW Towards either Throne they bow, & to the ground END
BEGIN NOW With solemn adoration down they cast END
BEGIN NOW Thir Crowns inwove with Amarant and Gold, END
BEGIN NOW Immortal Amarant, a Flour which once END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise, fast by the Tree of Life END
BEGIN NOW Began to bloom, but soon for mans offence END
BEGIN NOW To Heav'n remov'd where first it grew, there grows, END
BEGIN NOW And flours aloft shading the Fount of Life, END
BEGIN NOW And where the river of Bliss through midst of Heavn END
BEGIN NOW Rowls o're ELISIAN Flours her Amber stream; END
BEGIN NOW With these that never fade the Spirits Elect END
BEGIN NOW Bind thir resplendent locks inwreath'd with beams, END
BEGIN NOW Now in loose Garlands thick thrown off, the bright END
BEGIN NOW Pavement that like a Sea of Jasper shon END
BEGIN NOW Impurpl'd with Celestial Roses smil'd. END
BEGIN NOW Then Crown'd again thir gold'n Harps they took, END
BEGIN NOW Harps ever tun'd, that glittering by their side END
BEGIN NOW Like Quivers hung, and with Praeamble sweet END
BEGIN NOW Of charming symphonie they introduce END
BEGIN NOW Thir sacred Song, and waken raptures high; END
BEGIN NOW No voice exempt, no voice but well could joine END
BEGIN NOW Melodious part, such concord is in Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW Thee Father first they sung Omnipotent, END
BEGIN NOW Eternal King; thee Author of all being, END
BEGIN NOW Fountain of Light, thy self invisible END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the glorious brightness where thou sit'st END
BEGIN NOW Thron'd inaccessible, but when thou shad'st END
BEGIN NOW The full blaze of thy beams, and through a cloud END
BEGIN NOW Drawn round about thee like a radiant Shrine, END
BEGIN NOW Dark with excessive bright thy skirts appeer, END
BEGIN NOW Yet dazle Heav'n, that brightest Seraphim END
BEGIN NOW Approach not, but with both wings veil thir eyes. END
BEGIN NOW Thee next they sang of all Creation first, END
BEGIN NOW In whose conspicuous count'nance, without cloud END
BEGIN NOW Made visible, th' Almighty Father shines, END
BEGIN NOW Whom else no Creature can behold; on thee END
BEGIN NOW Impresst the effulgence of his Glorie abides, END
BEGIN NOW Transfus'd on thee his ample Spirit rests. END
BEGIN NOW Hee Heav'n of Heavens and all the Powers therein END
BEGIN NOW By thee created, and by thee threw down END
BEGIN NOW Th' aspiring Dominations: thou that day END
BEGIN NOW Thy Fathers dreadful Thunder didst not spare, END
BEGIN NOW Nor stop thy flaming Chariot wheels, that shook END
BEGIN NOW Heav'ns everlasting Frame, while o're the necks END
BEGIN NOW Thou drov'st of warring Angels disarraid. END
BEGIN NOW Back from pursuit thy Powers with loud acclaime END
BEGIN NOW Thee only extold, Son of thy Fathers might, END
BEGIN NOW To execute fierce vengeance on his foes, END
BEGIN NOW Not so on Man; him through their malice fall'n, END
BEGIN NOW Father of Mercie and Grace, thou didst not doome END
BEGIN NOW So strictly, but much more to pitie encline: END
BEGIN NOW No sooner did thy dear and onely Son END
BEGIN NOW Perceive thee purpos'd not to doom frail Man END
BEGIN NOW So strictly, but much more to pitie enclin'd, END
BEGIN NOW He to appease thy wrauth, and end the strife END
BEGIN NOW Of Mercy and Justice in thy face discern'd, END
BEGIN NOW Regardless of the Bliss wherein hee sat END
BEGIN NOW Second to thee, offerd himself to die END
BEGIN NOW For mans offence. O unexampl'd love, END
BEGIN NOW Love no where to be found less then Divine! END
BEGIN NOW Shall be the copious matter of my Song END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth, and never shall my Harp thy praise END
BEGIN NOW Forget, nor from thy Fathers praise disjoine. END
BEGIN NOW Thus they in Heav'n, above the starry Sphear, END
BEGIN NOW Thir happie hours in joy and hymning spent. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while upon the firm opacous Globe END
BEGIN NOW Of this round World, whose first convex divides END
BEGIN NOW The luminous inferior Orbs, enclos'd END
BEGIN NOW From CHAOS and th' inroad of Darkness old, END
BEGIN NOW SATAN alighted walks: a Globe farr off END
BEGIN NOW It seem'd, now seems a boundless Continent END
BEGIN NOW Dark, waste, and wild, under the frown of Night END
BEGIN NOW Starless expos'd, and ever-threatning storms END
BEGIN NOW Of CHAOS blustring round, inclement skie; END
BEGIN NOW Save on that side which from the wall of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Though distant farr som small reflection gaines END
BEGIN NOW Of glimmering air less vext with tempest loud: END
BEGIN NOW Here walk'd the Fiend at large in spacious field. END
BEGIN NOW As when a Vultur on IMAUS bred, END
BEGIN NOW Whose snowie ridge the roving TARTAR bounds, END
BEGIN NOW Dislodging from a Region scarce of prey END
BEGIN NOW To gorge the flesh of Lambs or yeanling Kids END
BEGIN NOW On Hills where Flocks are fed, flies toward the Springs END
BEGIN NOW But in his way lights on the barren plaines END
BEGIN NOW With Sails and Wind thir canie Waggons light: END
BEGIN NOW So on this windie Sea of Land, the Fiend END
BEGIN NOW Walk'd up and down alone bent on his prey, END
BEGIN NOW Alone, for other Creature in this place END
BEGIN NOW Living or liveless to be found was none, END
BEGIN NOW None yet, but store hereafter from the earth END
BEGIN NOW Up hither like Aereal vapours flew END
BEGIN NOW Of all things transitorie and vain, when Sin END
BEGIN NOW With vanity had filld the works of men: END
BEGIN NOW Both all things vain, and all who in vain things END
BEGIN NOW Built thir fond hopes of Glorie or lasting fame, END
BEGIN NOW Or happiness in this or th' other life; END
BEGIN NOW All who have thir reward on Earth, the fruits END
BEGIN NOW Of painful Superstition and blind Zeal, END
BEGIN NOW Naught seeking but the praise of men, here find END
BEGIN NOW Fit retribution, emptie as thir deeds; END
BEGIN NOW All th' unaccomplisht works of Natures hand, END
BEGIN NOW Abortive, monstrous, or unkindly mixt, END
BEGIN NOW Dissolvd on earth, fleet hither, and in vain, END
BEGIN NOW Till final dissolution, wander here, END
BEGIN NOW Not in the neighbouring Moon, as some have dreamd; END
BEGIN NOW Those argent Fields more likely habitants, END
BEGIN NOW Translated Saints, or middle Spirits hold END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt th' Angelical and Human kinde: END
BEGIN NOW Hither of ill-joynd Sons and Daughters born END
BEGIN NOW First from the ancient World those Giants came END
BEGIN NOW With many a vain exploit, though then renownd: END
BEGIN NOW The builders next of BABEL on the Plain END
BEGIN NOW Of SENNAAR, and still with vain designe END
BEGIN NOW New BABELS, had they wherewithall, would build: END
BEGIN NOW Others came single; hee who to be deemd END
BEGIN NOW A God, leap'd fondly into AETNA flames, END
BEGIN NOW EMPEDOCLES, and hee who to enjoy END
BEGIN NOW PLATO'S ELYSIUM, leap'd into the Sea, END
BEGIN NOW CLEOMBROTUS, and many more too long, END
BEGIN NOW White, Black and Grey, with all thir trumperie. END
BEGIN NOW Here Pilgrims roam, that stray'd so farr to seek END
BEGIN NOW In GOLGOTHA him dead, who lives in Heav'n; END
BEGIN NOW And they who to be sure of Paradise END
BEGIN NOW Dying put on the weeds of DOMINIC, END
BEGIN NOW Or in FRANCISCAN think to pass disguis'd; END
BEGIN NOW They pass the Planets seven, and pass the fixt, END
BEGIN NOW And that Crystalline Sphear whose ballance weighs END
BEGIN NOW The Trepidation talkt, and that first mov'd; END
BEGIN NOW And now Saint PETER at Heav'ns Wicket seems END
BEGIN NOW To wait them with his Keys, and now at foot END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'ns ascent they lift thir Feet, when loe END
BEGIN NOW A violent cross wind from either Coast END
BEGIN NOW Blows them transverse ten thousand Leagues awry END
BEGIN NOW Into the devious Air; then might ye see END
BEGIN NOW Cowles, Hoods and Habits with thir wearers tost END
BEGIN NOW And flutterd into Raggs, then Reliques, Beads, END
BEGIN NOW The sport of Winds: all these upwhirld aloft END
BEGIN NOW Fly o're the backside of the World farr off END
BEGIN NOW Into a LIMBO large and broad, since calld END
BEGIN NOW The Paradise of Fools, to few unknown END
BEGIN NOW Long after, now unpeopl'd, and untrod; END
BEGIN NOW All this dark Globe the Fiend found as he pass'd, END
BEGIN NOW And long he wanderd, till at last a gleame END
BEGIN NOW Of dawning light turnd thither-ward in haste END
BEGIN NOW His travell'd steps; farr distant hee descries END
BEGIN NOW Ascending by degrees magnificent END
BEGIN NOW Up to the wall of Heaven a Structure high, END
BEGIN NOW At top whereof, but farr more rich appeerd END
BEGIN NOW The work as of a Kingly Palace Gate END
BEGIN NOW Imbellisht, thick with sparkling orient Gemmes END
BEGIN NOW The Portal shon, inimitable on Earth END
BEGIN NOW By Model, or by shading Pencil drawn. END
BEGIN NOW The Stairs were such as whereon JACOB saw END
BEGIN NOW Angels ascending and descending, bands END
BEGIN NOW Of Guardians bright, when he from ESAU fled END
BEGIN NOW To PADAN-ARAM in the field of LUZ, END
BEGIN NOW Dreaming by night under the open Skie, END
BEGIN NOW And waking cri'd, This is the Gate of Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW Each Stair mysteriously was meant, nor stood END
BEGIN NOW There alwaies, but drawn up to Heav'n somtimes END
BEGIN NOW Viewless, and underneath a bright Sea flow'd END
BEGIN NOW Of Jasper, or of liquid Pearle, whereon END
BEGIN NOW Who after came from Earth, sayling arriv'd, END
BEGIN NOW Wafted by Angels, or flew o're the Lake END
BEGIN NOW Rapt in a Chariot drawn by fiery Steeds. END
BEGIN NOW The Stairs were then let down, whether to dare END
BEGIN NOW The Fiend by easie ascent, or aggravate END
BEGIN NOW His sad exclusion from the dores of Bliss. END
BEGIN NOW Direct against which op'nd from beneath, END
BEGIN NOW Just o're the blissful seat of Paradise, END
BEGIN NOW A passage down to th' Earth, a passage wide, END
BEGIN NOW Wider by farr then that of after-times END
BEGIN NOW Over Mount SION, and, though that were large, END
BEGIN NOW Over the PROMIS'D LAND to God so dear, END
BEGIN NOW By which, to visit oft those happy Tribes, END
BEGIN NOW On high behests his Angels to and fro END
BEGIN NOW Pass'd frequent, and his eye with choice regard END
BEGIN NOW From PANEAS the fount of JORDANS flood END
BEGIN NOW So wide the op'ning seemd, where bounds were set END
BEGIN NOW To darkness, such as bound the Ocean wave. END
BEGIN NOW SATAN from hence now on the lower stair END
BEGIN NOW That scal'd by steps of Gold to Heav'n Gate END
BEGIN NOW Looks down with wonder at the sudden view END
BEGIN NOW Of all this World at once. As when a Scout END
BEGIN NOW Through dark and desart wayes with peril gone END
BEGIN NOW All night; at last by break of chearful dawne END
BEGIN NOW Obtains the brow of some high-climbing Hill, END
BEGIN NOW Which to his eye discovers unaware END
BEGIN NOW The goodly prospect of some forein land END
BEGIN NOW First-seen, or some renownd Metropolis END
BEGIN NOW With glistering Spires and Pinnacles adornd, END
BEGIN NOW Which now the Rising Sun guilds with his beams. END
BEGIN NOW Such wonder seis'd, though after Heaven seen, END
BEGIN NOW The Spirit maligne, but much more envy seis'd END
BEGIN NOW At sight of all this World beheld so faire. END
BEGIN NOW Round he surveys, and well might, where he stood END
BEGIN NOW So high above the circling Canopie END
BEGIN NOW Of Nights extended shade; from Eastern Point END
BEGIN NOW Of LIBRA to the fleecie Starr that bears END
BEGIN NOW Beyond th' HORIZON; then from Pole to Pole END
BEGIN NOW He views in bredth, and without longer pause END
BEGIN NOW Down right into the Worlds first Region throws END
BEGIN NOW His flight precipitant, and windes with ease END
BEGIN NOW Through the pure marble Air his oblique way END
BEGIN NOW Amongst innumerable Starrs, that shon END
BEGIN NOW Stars distant, but nigh hand seemd other Worlds, END
BEGIN NOW Or other Worlds they seemd, or happy Iles, END
BEGIN NOW Like those HESPERIAN Gardens fam'd of old, END
BEGIN NOW Fortunate Fields, and Groves and flourie Vales, END
BEGIN NOW Thrice happy Iles, but who dwelt happy there END
BEGIN NOW He stayd not to enquire: above them all END
BEGIN NOW The golden Sun in splendor likest Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Allur'd his eye: Thither his course he bends END
BEGIN NOW Through the calm Firmament; but up or downe END
BEGIN NOW By center, or eccentric, hard to tell, END
BEGIN NOW Or Longitude, where the great Luminarie END
BEGIN NOW Alooff the vulgar Constellations thick, END
BEGIN NOW That from his Lordly eye keep distance due, END
BEGIN NOW Dispenses Light from farr; they as they move END
BEGIN NOW Thir Starry dance in numbers that compute END
BEGIN NOW Days, months, and years, towards his all-chearing Lamp END
BEGIN NOW Turn swift their various motions, or are turnd END
BEGIN NOW By his Magnetic beam, that gently warms END
BEGIN NOW The Univers, and to each inward part END
BEGIN NOW With gentle penetration, though unseen, END
BEGIN NOW Shoots invisible vertue even to the deep: END
BEGIN NOW So wondrously was set his Station bright. END
BEGIN NOW There lands the Fiend, a spot like which perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Astronomer in the Sun's lucent Orbe END
BEGIN NOW Through his glaz'd Optic Tube yet never saw. END
BEGIN NOW The place he found beyond expression bright, END
BEGIN NOW Compar'd with aught on Earth, Medal or Stone; END
BEGIN NOW Not all parts like, but all alike informd END
BEGIN NOW With radiant light, as glowing Iron with fire; END
BEGIN NOW If mettal, part seemd Gold, part Silver cleer; END
BEGIN NOW If stone, Carbuncle most or Chrysolite, END
BEGIN NOW Rubie or Topaz, to the Twelve that shon END
BEGIN NOW In AARONS Brest-plate, and a stone besides END
BEGIN NOW Imagind rather oft then elsewhere seen, END
BEGIN NOW That stone, or like to that which here below END
BEGIN NOW Philosophers in vain so long have sought, END
BEGIN NOW In vain, though by thir powerful Art they binde END
BEGIN NOW Volatil HERMES, and call up unbound END
BEGIN NOW In various shapes old PROTEUS from the Sea, END
BEGIN NOW Draind through a Limbec to his Native forme. END
BEGIN NOW What wonder then if fields and regions here END
BEGIN NOW Breathe forth ELIXIR pure, and Rivers run END
BEGIN NOW Potable Gold, when with one vertuous touch END
BEGIN NOW Th' Arch-chimic Sun so farr from us remote END
BEGIN NOW Produces with Terrestrial Humor mixt END
BEGIN NOW Here in the dark so many precious things END
BEGIN NOW Of colour glorious and effect so rare? END
BEGIN NOW Here matter new to gaze the Devil met END
BEGIN NOW Undazl'd, farr and wide his eye commands, END
BEGIN NOW For sight no obstacle found here, nor shade, END
BEGIN NOW But all Sun-shine, as when his Beams at Noon END
BEGIN NOW Culminate from th' AEQUATOR, as they now END
BEGIN NOW Shot upward still direct, whence no way round END
BEGIN NOW Shadow from body opaque can fall, and the Aire, END
BEGIN NOW No where so cleer, sharp'nd his visual ray END
BEGIN NOW To objects distant farr, whereby he soon END
BEGIN NOW Saw within kenn a glorious Angel stand, END
BEGIN NOW The same whom JOHN saw also in the Sun: END
BEGIN NOW His back was turnd, but not his brightness hid; END
BEGIN NOW Of beaming sunnie Raies, a golden tiar END
BEGIN NOW Circl'd his Head, nor less his Locks behind END
BEGIN NOW Illustrious on his Shoulders fledge with wings END
BEGIN NOW Lay waving round; on som great charge imploy'd END
BEGIN NOW Hee seemd, or fixt in cogitation deep. END
BEGIN NOW Glad was the Spirit impure as now in hope END
BEGIN NOW To find who might direct his wandring flight END
BEGIN NOW To Paradise the happie seat of Man, END
BEGIN NOW His journies end and our beginning woe. END
BEGIN NOW But first he casts to change his proper shape, END
BEGIN NOW Which else might work him danger or delay: END
BEGIN NOW And now a stripling Cherube he appeers, END
BEGIN NOW Not of the prime, yet such as in his face END
BEGIN NOW Youth smil'd Celestial, and to every Limb END
BEGIN NOW Sutable grace diffus'd, so well he feignd; END
BEGIN NOW Under a Coronet his flowing haire END
BEGIN NOW In curles on either cheek plaid, wings he wore END
BEGIN NOW Of many a colourd plume sprinkl'd with Gold, END
BEGIN NOW His habit fit for speed succinct, and held END
BEGIN NOW Before his decent steps a Silver wand. END
BEGIN NOW He drew not nigh unheard, the Angel bright, END
BEGIN NOW Ere he drew nigh, his radiant visage turnd, END
BEGIN NOW Admonisht by his eare, and strait was known END
BEGIN NOW Th' Arch-Angel URIEL, one of the seav'n END
BEGIN NOW Who in Gods presence, neerest to his Throne END
BEGIN NOW Stand ready at command, and are his Eyes END
BEGIN NOW That run through all the Heav'ns, or down to th' Earth END
BEGIN NOW Bear his swift errands over moist and dry, END
BEGIN NOW O're Sea and Land: him SATAN thus accostes; END
BEGIN NOW URIEL, for thou of those seav'n Spirits that stand END
BEGIN NOW In sight of God's high Throne, gloriously bright, END
BEGIN NOW The first art wont his great authentic will END
BEGIN NOW Interpreter through highest Heav'n to bring, END
BEGIN NOW Where all his Sons thy Embassie attend; END
BEGIN NOW And here art likeliest by supream decree END
BEGIN NOW Like honour to obtain, and as his Eye END
BEGIN NOW To visit oft this new Creation round; END
BEGIN NOW Unspeakable desire to see, and know END
BEGIN NOW All these his wondrous works, but chiefly Man, END
BEGIN NOW His chief delight and favour, him for whom END
BEGIN NOW All these his works so wondrous he ordaind, END
BEGIN NOW Hath brought me from the Quires of Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW Alone thus wandring. Brightest Seraph tell END
BEGIN NOW In which of all these shining Orbes hath Man END
BEGIN NOW His fixed seat, or fixed seat hath none, END
BEGIN NOW But all these shining Orbes his choice to dwell; END
BEGIN NOW That I may find him, and with secret gaze, END
BEGIN NOW Or open admiration him behold END
BEGIN NOW On whom the great Creator hath bestowd END
BEGIN NOW Worlds, and on whom hath all these graces powrd; END
BEGIN NOW That both in him and all things, as is meet, END
BEGIN NOW The Universal Maker we may praise; END
BEGIN NOW Who justly hath drivn out his Rebell Foes END
BEGIN NOW To deepest Hell, and to repair that loss END
BEGIN NOW Created this new happie Race of Men END
BEGIN NOW To serve him better: wise are all his wayes. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the false dissembler unperceivd; END
BEGIN NOW For neither Man nor Angel can discern END
BEGIN NOW Hypocrisie, the only evil that walks END
BEGIN NOW Invisible, except to God alone, END
BEGIN NOW By his permissive will, through Heav'n and Earth: END
BEGIN NOW And oft though wisdom wake, suspicion sleeps END
BEGIN NOW At wisdoms Gate, and to simplicitie END
BEGIN NOW Resigns her charge, while goodness thinks no ill END
BEGIN NOW Where no ill seems: Which now for once beguil'd END
BEGIN NOW URIEL, though Regent of the Sun, and held END
BEGIN NOW The sharpest sighted Spirit of all in Heav'n; END
BEGIN NOW Who to the fraudulent Impostor foule END
BEGIN NOW In his uprightness answer thus returnd. END
BEGIN NOW Faire Angel, thy desire which tends to know END
BEGIN NOW The works of God, thereby to glorifie END
BEGIN NOW The great Work-Maister, leads to no excess END
BEGIN NOW That reaches blame, but rather merits praise END
BEGIN NOW The more it seems excess, that led thee hither END
BEGIN NOW From thy Empyreal Mansion thus alone, END
BEGIN NOW To witness with thine eyes what some perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Contented with report heare onely in heav'n: END
BEGIN NOW For wonderful indeed are all his works, END
BEGIN NOW Pleasant to know, and worthiest to be all END
BEGIN NOW Had in remembrance alwayes with delight; END
BEGIN NOW But what created mind can comprehend END
BEGIN NOW Thir number, or the wisdom infinite END
BEGIN NOW That brought them forth, but hid thir causes deep. END
BEGIN NOW I saw when at his Word the formless Mass, END
BEGIN NOW This worlds material mould, came to a heap: END
BEGIN NOW Confusion heard his voice, and wilde uproar END
BEGIN NOW Stood rul'd, stood vast infinitude confin'd; END
BEGIN NOW Till at his second bidding darkness fled, END
BEGIN NOW Light shon, and order from disorder sprung: END
BEGIN NOW Swift to thir several Quarters hasted then END
BEGIN NOW The cumbrous Elements, Earth, Flood, Aire, Fire, END
BEGIN NOW And this Ethereal quintessence of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Flew upward, spirited with various forms, END
BEGIN NOW That rowld orbicular, and turnd to Starrs END
BEGIN NOW Numberless, as thou seest, and how they move; END
BEGIN NOW Each had his place appointed, each his course, END
BEGIN NOW The rest in circuit walles this Universe. END
BEGIN NOW Look downward on that Globe whose hither side END
BEGIN NOW With light from hence, though but reflected, shines; END
BEGIN NOW That place is Earth the seat of Man, that light END
BEGIN NOW His day, which else as th' other Hemisphere END
BEGIN NOW Night would invade, but there the neighbouring Moon END
BEGIN NOW (So call that opposite fair Starr) her aide END
BEGIN NOW Timely interposes, and her monthly round END
BEGIN NOW Still ending, still renewing, through mid Heav'n; END
BEGIN NOW With borrowd light her countenance triform END
BEGIN NOW Hence fills and empties to enlighten th' Earth, END
BEGIN NOW And in her pale dominion checks the night. END
BEGIN NOW That spot to which I point is PARADISE, END
BEGIN NOW ADAMS abode, those loftie shades his Bowre. END
BEGIN NOW Thy way thou canst not miss, me mine requires. END
BEGIN NOW Thus said, he turnd, and SATAN bowing low, END
BEGIN NOW As to superior Spirits is wont in Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Where honour due and reverence none neglects, END
BEGIN NOW Took leave, and toward the coast of Earth beneath, END
BEGIN NOW Down from th' Ecliptic, sped with hop'd success, END
BEGIN NOW Throws his steep flight with many an Aerie wheele, END
BEGIN NOW Nor staid, till on NIPHATES top he lights. END
BEGIN NOW O For that warning voice, which he who saw END
BEGIN NOW Th' APOCALYPS, heard cry in Heaven aloud, END
BEGIN NOW Then when the Dragon, put to second rout, END
BEGIN NOW Came furious down to be reveng'd on men, END
BEGIN NOW While time was, our first Parents had bin warnd END
BEGIN NOW The coming of thir secret foe, and scap'd END
BEGIN NOW Haply so scap'd his mortal snare; for now END
BEGIN NOW SATAN, now first inflam'd with rage, came down, END
BEGIN NOW The Tempter ere th' Accuser of man-kind, END
BEGIN NOW To wreck on innocent frail man his loss END
BEGIN NOW Of that first Battel, and his flight to Hell: END
BEGIN NOW Yet not rejoycing in his speed, though bold, END
BEGIN NOW Far off and fearless, nor with cause to boast, END
BEGIN NOW Begins his dire attempt, which nigh the birth END
BEGIN NOW Now rowling, boiles in his tumultuous brest, END
BEGIN NOW And like a devillish Engine back recoiles END
BEGIN NOW Upon himself; horror and doubt distract END
BEGIN NOW His troubl'd thoughts, and from the bottom stirr END
BEGIN NOW The Hell within him, for within him Hell END
BEGIN NOW He brings, and round about him, nor from Hell END
BEGIN NOW One step no more then from himself can fly END
BEGIN NOW By change of place: Now conscience wakes despair END
BEGIN NOW That slumberd, wakes the bitter memorie END
BEGIN NOW Of what he was, what is, and what must be END
BEGIN NOW Worse; of worse deeds worse sufferings must ensue. END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes towards EDEN which now in his view END
BEGIN NOW Lay pleasant, his grievd look he fixes sad, END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes towards Heav'n and the full-blazing Sun, END
BEGIN NOW Which now sat high in his Meridian Towre: END
BEGIN NOW Then much revolving, thus in sighs began. END
BEGIN NOW O thou that with surpassing Glory crownd, END
BEGIN NOW Look'st from thy sole Dominion like the God END
BEGIN NOW Of this new World; at whose sight all the Starrs END
BEGIN NOW Hide thir diminisht heads; to thee I call, END
BEGIN NOW But with no friendly voice, and add thy name END
BEGIN NOW O Sun, to tell thee how I hate thy beams END
BEGIN NOW That bring to my remembrance from what state END
BEGIN NOW I fell, how glorious once above thy Spheare; END
BEGIN NOW Till Pride and worse Ambition threw me down END
BEGIN NOW Warring in Heav'n against Heav'ns matchless King: END
BEGIN NOW Ah wherefore! he deservd no such return END
BEGIN NOW From me, whom he created what I was END
BEGIN NOW In that bright eminence, and with his good END
BEGIN NOW Upbraided none; nor was his service hard. END
BEGIN NOW What could be less then to afford him praise, END
BEGIN NOW The easiest recompence, and pay him thanks, END
BEGIN NOW How due! yet all his good prov'd ill in me, END
BEGIN NOW And wrought but malice; lifted up so high END
BEGIN NOW I sdeind subjection, and thought one step higher END
BEGIN NOW Would set me highest, and in a moment quit END
BEGIN NOW The debt immense of endless gratitude, END
BEGIN NOW So burthensome, still paying, still to ow; END
BEGIN NOW Forgetful what from him I still receivd, END
BEGIN NOW And understood not that a grateful mind END
BEGIN NOW By owing owes not, but still pays, at once END
BEGIN NOW Indebted and dischargd; what burden then? END
BEGIN NOW O had his powerful Destiny ordaind END
BEGIN NOW Me some inferiour Angel, I had stood END
BEGIN NOW Then happie; no unbounded hope had rais'd END
BEGIN NOW Ambition. Yet why not? som other Power END
BEGIN NOW As great might have aspir'd, and me though mean END
BEGIN NOW Drawn to his part; but other Powers as great END
BEGIN NOW Fell not, but stand unshak'n, from within END
BEGIN NOW Or from without, to all temptations arm'd. END
BEGIN NOW Hadst thou the same free Will and Power to stand? END
BEGIN NOW Thou hadst: whom hast thou then or what to accuse, END
BEGIN NOW But Heav'ns free Love dealt equally to all? END
BEGIN NOW Be then his Love accurst, since love or hate, END
BEGIN NOW To me alike, it deals eternal woe. END
BEGIN NOW Nay curs'd be thou; since against his thy will END
BEGIN NOW Chose freely what it now so justly rues. END
BEGIN NOW Me miserable! which way shall I flie END
BEGIN NOW Infinite wrauth, and infinite despaire? END
BEGIN NOW Which way I flie is Hell; my self am Hell; END
BEGIN NOW And in the lowest deep a lower deep END
BEGIN NOW Still threatning to devour me opens wide, END
BEGIN NOW To which the Hell I suffer seems a Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW O then at last relent: is there no place END
BEGIN NOW Left for Repentance, none for Pardon left? END
BEGIN NOW None left but by submission; and that word END
BEGIN NOW DISDAIN forbids me, and my dread of shame END
BEGIN NOW Among the spirits beneath, whom I seduc'd END
BEGIN NOW With other promises and other vaunts END
BEGIN NOW Then to submit, boasting I could subdue END
BEGIN NOW Th' Omnipotent. Ay me, they little know END
BEGIN NOW How dearly I abide that boast so vaine, END
BEGIN NOW Under what torments inwardly I groane; END
BEGIN NOW While they adore me on the Throne of Hell, END
BEGIN NOW With Diadem and Scepter high advanc'd END
BEGIN NOW The lower still I fall, onely Supream END
BEGIN NOW In miserie; such joy Ambition findes. END
BEGIN NOW But say I could repent and could obtaine END
BEGIN NOW By Act of Grace my former state; how soon END
BEGIN NOW Would highth recal high thoughts, how soon unsay END
BEGIN NOW What feign'd submission swore: ease would recant END
BEGIN NOW Vows made in pain, as violent and void. END
BEGIN NOW For never can true reconcilement grow END
BEGIN NOW Where wounds of deadly hate have peirc'd so deep: END
BEGIN NOW Which would but lead me to a worse relapse END
BEGIN NOW And heavier fall: so should I purchase deare END
BEGIN NOW Short intermission bought with double smart. END
BEGIN NOW This knows my punisher; therefore as farr END
BEGIN NOW From granting hee, as I from begging peace: END
BEGIN NOW All hope excluded thus, behold in stead END
BEGIN NOW Of us out-cast, exil'd, his new delight, END
BEGIN NOW Mankind created, and for him this World. END
BEGIN NOW So farwel Hope, and with Hope farwel Fear, END
BEGIN NOW Farwel Remorse: all Good to me is lost; END
BEGIN NOW Evil be thou my Good; by thee at least END
BEGIN NOW Divided Empire with Heav'ns King I hold END
BEGIN NOW By thee, and more then half perhaps will reigne; END
BEGIN NOW As Man ere long, and this new World shall know. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while he spake, each passion dimm'd his face END
BEGIN NOW Thrice chang'd with pale, ire, envie and despair, END
BEGIN NOW Which marrd his borrow'd visage, and betraid END
BEGIN NOW Him counterfet, if any eye beheld. END
BEGIN NOW For heav'nly mindes from such distempers foule END
BEGIN NOW Are ever cleer. Whereof hee soon aware, END
BEGIN NOW Each perturbation smooth'd with outward calme, END
BEGIN NOW Artificer of fraud; and was the first END
BEGIN NOW That practisd falshood under saintly shew, END
BEGIN NOW Deep malice to conceale, couch't with revenge: END
BEGIN NOW Yet not anough had practisd to deceive END
BEGIN NOW URIEL once warnd; whose eye pursu'd him down END
BEGIN NOW The way he went, and on th' ASSYRIAN mount END
BEGIN NOW Saw him disfigur'd, more then could befall END
BEGIN NOW Spirit of happie sort: his gestures fierce END
BEGIN NOW He markd and mad demeanour, then alone, END
BEGIN NOW As he suppos'd, all unobserv'd, unseen. END
BEGIN NOW So on he fares, and to the border comes END
BEGIN NOW Of EDEN, where delicious Paradise, END
BEGIN NOW Now nearer, Crowns with her enclosure green, END
BEGIN NOW As with a rural mound the champain head END
BEGIN NOW Of a steep wilderness, whose hairie sides END
BEGIN NOW With thicket overgrown, grottesque and wilde, END
BEGIN NOW Access deni'd; and over head up grew END
BEGIN NOW Insuperable highth of loftiest shade, END
BEGIN NOW Cedar, and Pine, and Firr, and branching Palm, END
BEGIN NOW A Silvan Scene, and as the ranks ascend END
BEGIN NOW Shade above shade, a woodie Theatre END
BEGIN NOW Of stateliest view. Yet higher then thir tops END
BEGIN NOW The verdurous wall of Paradise up sprung: END
BEGIN NOW Which to our general Sire gave prospect large END
BEGIN NOW Into his neather Empire neighbouring round. END
BEGIN NOW And higher then that Wall a circling row END
BEGIN NOW Of goodliest Trees loaden with fairest Fruit, END
BEGIN NOW Blossoms and Fruits at once of golden hue END
BEGIN NOW Appeerd, with gay enameld colours mixt: END
BEGIN NOW On which the Sun more glad impress'd his beams END
BEGIN NOW Then in fair Evening Cloud, or humid Bow, END
BEGIN NOW When God hath showrd the earth; so lovely seemd END
BEGIN NOW That Lantskip: And of pure now purer aire END
BEGIN NOW Meets his approach, and to the heart inspires END
BEGIN NOW Vernal delight and joy, able to drive END
BEGIN NOW All sadness but despair: now gentle gales END
BEGIN NOW Fanning thir odoriferous wings dispense END
BEGIN NOW Native perfumes, and whisper whence they stole END
BEGIN NOW Those balmie spoiles. As when to them who saile END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the CAPE OF HOPE, and now are past END
BEGIN NOW MOZAMBIC, off at Sea North-East windes blow END
BEGIN NOW SABEAN Odours from the spicie shoare END
BEGIN NOW Of ARABIE the blest, with such delay END
BEGIN NOW Well pleas'd they slack thir course, and many a League END
BEGIN NOW Cheard with the grateful smell old Ocean smiles. END
BEGIN NOW So entertaind those odorous sweets the Fiend END
BEGIN NOW Who came thir bane, though with them better pleas'd END
BEGIN NOW Then ASMODEUS with the fishie fume, END
BEGIN NOW That drove him, though enamourd, from the Spouse END
BEGIN NOW Of TOBITS Son, and with a vengeance sent END
BEGIN NOW Now to th' ascent of that steep savage Hill END
BEGIN NOW SATAN had journied on, pensive and slow; END
BEGIN NOW But further way found none, so thick entwin'd, END
BEGIN NOW As one continu'd brake, the undergrowth END
BEGIN NOW Of shrubs and tangling bushes had perplext END
BEGIN NOW All path of Man or Beast that past that way: END
BEGIN NOW One Gate there onely was, and that look'd East END
BEGIN NOW On th' other side: which when th' arch-fellon saw END
BEGIN NOW Due entrance he disdaind, and in contempt, END
BEGIN NOW At one slight bound high overleap'd all bound END
BEGIN NOW Of Hill or highest Wall, and sheer within END
BEGIN NOW Lights on his feet. As when a prowling Wolfe, END
BEGIN NOW Whom hunger drives to seek new haunt for prey, END
BEGIN NOW Watching where Shepherds pen thir Flocks at eeve END
BEGIN NOW In hurdl'd Cotes amid the field secure, END
BEGIN NOW Leaps o're the fence with ease into the Fould: END
BEGIN NOW Or as a Thief bent to unhoord the cash END
BEGIN NOW Of some rich Burgher, whose substantial dores, END
BEGIN NOW Cross-barrd and bolted fast, fear no assault, END
BEGIN NOW In at the window climbes, or o're the tiles; END
BEGIN NOW So clomb this first grand Thief into Gods Fould: END
BEGIN NOW So since into his Church lewd Hirelings climbe. END
BEGIN NOW Thence up he flew, and on the Tree of Life, END
BEGIN NOW The middle Tree and highest there that grew, END
BEGIN NOW Sat like a Cormorant; yet not true Life END
BEGIN NOW Thereby regaind, but sat devising Death END
BEGIN NOW To them who liv'd; nor on the vertue thought END
BEGIN NOW Of that life-giving Plant, but only us'd END
BEGIN NOW For prospect, what well us'd had bin the pledge END
BEGIN NOW Of immortalitie. So little knows END
BEGIN NOW Any, but God alone, to value right END
BEGIN NOW The good before him, but perverts best things END
BEGIN NOW To worst abuse, or to thir meanest use. END
BEGIN NOW Beneath him with new wonder now he views END
BEGIN NOW To all delight of human sense expos'd END
BEGIN NOW In narrow room Natures whole wealth, yea more, END
BEGIN NOW A Heaven on Earth, for blissful Paradise END
BEGIN NOW Of God the Garden was, by him in the East END
BEGIN NOW Of EDEN planted; EDEN stretchd her Line END
BEGIN NOW From AURAN Eastward to the Royal Towrs END
BEGIN NOW Of great SELEUCIA, built by GRECIAN Kings, END
BEGIN NOW Or where the Sons of EDEN long before END
BEGIN NOW Dwelt in TELASSAR: in this pleasant soile END
BEGIN NOW His farr more pleasant Garden God ordaind; END
BEGIN NOW Out of the fertil ground he caus'd to grow END
BEGIN NOW All Trees of noblest kind for sight, smell, taste; END
BEGIN NOW And all amid them stood the Tree of Life, END
BEGIN NOW High eminent, blooming Ambrosial Fruit END
BEGIN NOW Of vegetable Gold; and next to Life END
BEGIN NOW Our Death the Tree of Knowledge grew fast by, END
BEGIN NOW Knowledge of Good bought dear by knowing ill. END
BEGIN NOW Southward through EDEN went a River large, END
BEGIN NOW Nor chang'd his course, but through the shaggie hill END
BEGIN NOW Pass'd underneath ingulft, for God had thrown END
BEGIN NOW That Mountain as his Garden mould high rais'd END
BEGIN NOW Upon the rapid current, which through veins END
BEGIN NOW Of porous Earth with kindly thirst up drawn, END
BEGIN NOW Rose a fresh Fountain, and with many a rill END
BEGIN NOW Waterd the Garden; thence united fell END
BEGIN NOW Down the steep glade, and met the neather Flood, END
BEGIN NOW Which from his darksom passage now appeers, END
BEGIN NOW And now divided into four main Streams, END
BEGIN NOW Runs divers, wandring many a famous Realme END
BEGIN NOW And Country whereof here needs no account, END
BEGIN NOW But rather to tell how, if Art could tell, END
BEGIN NOW How from that Saphire Fount the crisped Brooks, END
BEGIN NOW Rowling on Orient Pearl and sands of Gold, END
BEGIN NOW With mazie error under pendant shades END
BEGIN NOW Ran Nectar, visiting each plant, and fed END
BEGIN NOW Flours worthy of Paradise which not nice Art END
BEGIN NOW In Beds and curious Knots, but Nature boon END
BEGIN NOW Powrd forth profuse on Hill and Dale and Plaine, END
BEGIN NOW Both where the morning Sun first warmly smote END
BEGIN NOW The open field, and where the unpierc't shade END
BEGIN NOW Imbround the noontide Bowrs: Thus was this place, END
BEGIN NOW A happy rural seat of various view; END
BEGIN NOW Groves whose rich Trees wept odorous Gumms and Balme, END
BEGIN NOW Others whose fruit burnisht with Golden Rinde END
BEGIN NOW Hung amiable, HESPERIAN Fables true, END
BEGIN NOW If true, here onely, and of delicious taste: END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt them Lawns, or level Downs, and Flocks END
BEGIN NOW Grasing the tender herb, were interpos'd, END
BEGIN NOW Or palmie hilloc, or the flourie lap END
BEGIN NOW Of som irriguous Valley spread her store, END
BEGIN NOW Flours of all hue, and without Thorn the Rose: END
BEGIN NOW Another side, umbrageous Grots and Caves END
BEGIN NOW Of coole recess, o're which the mantling Vine END
BEGIN NOW Layes forth her purple Grape, and gently creeps END
BEGIN NOW Luxuriant; mean while murmuring waters fall END
BEGIN NOW Down the slope hills, disperst, or in a Lake, END
BEGIN NOW That to the fringed Bank with Myrtle crownd, END
BEGIN NOW Her chrystall mirror holds, unite thir streams. END
BEGIN NOW The Birds thir quire apply; aires, vernal aires, END
BEGIN NOW Breathing the smell of field and grove, attune END
BEGIN NOW The trembling leaves, while Universal PAN END
BEGIN NOW Knit with the GRACES and the HOURS in dance END
BEGIN NOW Led on th' Eternal Spring. Not that faire field END
BEGIN NOW Of ENNA, where PROSERPIN gathring flours END
BEGIN NOW Her self a fairer Floure by gloomie DIS END
BEGIN NOW Was gatherd, which cost CERES all that pain END
BEGIN NOW To seek her through the world; nor that sweet Grove END
BEGIN NOW Of DAPHNE by ORONTES, and th' inspir'd END
BEGIN NOW CASTALIAN Spring might with this Paradise END
BEGIN NOW Of EDEN strive; nor that NYSEIAN Ile END
BEGIN NOW Girt with the River TRITON, where old CHAM, END
BEGIN NOW Whom Gentiles AMMON call and LIBYAN JOVE, END
BEGIN NOW Hid AMALTHEA and her Florid Son END
BEGIN NOW Young BACCHUS from his Stepdame RHEA'S eye; END
BEGIN NOW Nor where ABASSIN Kings thir issue Guard, END
BEGIN NOW Mount AMARA, though this by som suppos'd END
BEGIN NOW True Paradise under the ETHIOP Line END
BEGIN NOW By NILUS head, enclos'd with shining Rock, END
BEGIN NOW A whole dayes journey high, but wide remote END
BEGIN NOW From this ASSYRIAN Garden, where the Fiend END
BEGIN NOW Saw undelighted all delight, all kind END
BEGIN NOW Of living Creatures new to sight and strange: END
BEGIN NOW Two of far nobler shape erect and tall, END
BEGIN NOW Godlike erect, with native Honour clad END
BEGIN NOW In naked Majestie seemd Lords of all, END
BEGIN NOW And worthie seemd, for in thir looks Divine END
BEGIN NOW The image of thir glorious Maker shon, END
BEGIN NOW Truth, Wisdome, Sanctitude severe and pure, END
BEGIN NOW Severe, but in true filial freedom plac't; END
BEGIN NOW Whence true autoritie in men; though both END
BEGIN NOW Not equal, as thir sex not equal seemd; END
BEGIN NOW For contemplation hee and valour formd, END
BEGIN NOW For softness shee and sweet attractive Grace, END
BEGIN NOW Hee for God only, shee for God in him: END
BEGIN NOW His fair large Front and Eye sublime declar'd END
BEGIN NOW Absolute rule; and Hyacinthin Locks END
BEGIN NOW Round from his parted forelock manly hung END
BEGIN NOW Clustring, but not beneath his shoulders broad: END
BEGIN NOW Shee as a vail down to the slender waste END
BEGIN NOW Her unadorned golden tresses wore END
BEGIN NOW Dissheveld, but in wanton ringlets wav'd END
BEGIN NOW As the Vine curles her tendrils, which impli'd END
BEGIN NOW Subjection, but requir'd with gentle sway, END
BEGIN NOW And by her yeilded, by him best receivd, END
BEGIN NOW Yeilded with coy submission, modest pride, END
BEGIN NOW And sweet reluctant amorous delay. END
BEGIN NOW Nor those mysterious parts were then conceald, END
BEGIN NOW Then was not guiltie shame, dishonest shame END
BEGIN NOW Of natures works, honor dishonorable, END
BEGIN NOW Sin-bred, how have ye troubl'd all mankind END
BEGIN NOW With shews instead, meer shews of seeming pure, END
BEGIN NOW And banisht from mans life his happiest life, END
BEGIN NOW Simplicitie and spotless innocence. END
BEGIN NOW So passd they naked on, nor shund the sight END
BEGIN NOW Of God or Angel, for they thought no ill: END
BEGIN NOW So hand in hand they passd, the lovliest pair END
BEGIN NOW That ever since in loves imbraces met, END
BEGIN NOW ADAM the goodliest man of men since borne END
BEGIN NOW His Sons, the fairest of her Daughters EVE. END
BEGIN NOW Under a tuft of shade that on a green END
BEGIN NOW Stood whispering soft, by a fresh Fountain side END
BEGIN NOW They sat them down, and after no more toil END
BEGIN NOW Of thir sweet Gardning labour then suffic'd END
BEGIN NOW To recommend coole ZEPHYR, and made ease END
BEGIN NOW More easie, wholsom thirst and appetite END
BEGIN NOW More grateful, to thir Supper Fruits they fell, END
BEGIN NOW Nectarine Fruits which the compliant boughes END
BEGIN NOW Yeilded them, side-long as they sat recline END
BEGIN NOW On the soft downie Bank damaskt with flours: END
BEGIN NOW The savourie pulp they chew, and in the rinde END
BEGIN NOW Still as they thirsted scoop the brimming stream; END
BEGIN NOW Nor gentle purpose, nor endearing smiles END
BEGIN NOW Wanted, nor youthful dalliance as beseems END
BEGIN NOW Fair couple, linkt in happie nuptial League, END
BEGIN NOW Alone as they. About them frisking playd END
BEGIN NOW All Beasts of th' Earth, since wilde, and of all chase END
BEGIN NOW Sporting the Lion rampd, and in his paw END
BEGIN NOW Dandl'd the Kid; Bears, Tygers, Ounces, Pards END
BEGIN NOW Gambold before them, th' unwieldy Elephant END
BEGIN NOW To make them mirth us'd all his might, & wreathd END
BEGIN NOW His Lithe Proboscis; close the Serpent sly END
BEGIN NOW Insinuating, wove with Gordian twine END
BEGIN NOW His breaded train, and of his fatal guile END
BEGIN NOW Gave proof unheeded; others on the grass END
BEGIN NOW Coucht, and now fild with pasture gazing sat, END
BEGIN NOW Or Bedward ruminating: for the Sun END
BEGIN NOW Declin'd was hasting now with prone carreer END
BEGIN NOW To th' Ocean Iles, and in th' ascending Scale END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'n the Starrs that usher Evening rose: END
BEGIN NOW When SATAN still in gaze, as first he stood, END
BEGIN NOW Scarce thus at length faild speech recoverd sad. END
BEGIN NOW O Hell! what doe mine eyes with grief behold, END
BEGIN NOW Into our room of bliss thus high advanc't END
BEGIN NOW Creatures of other mould, earth-born perhaps, END
BEGIN NOW Not Spirits, yet to heav'nly Spirits bright END
BEGIN NOW Little inferior; whom my thoughts pursue END
BEGIN NOW With wonder, and could love, so lively shines END
BEGIN NOW In them Divine resemblance, and such grace END
BEGIN NOW The hand that formd them on thir shape hath pourd. END
BEGIN NOW Ah gentle pair, yee little think how nigh END
BEGIN NOW Your change approaches, when all these delights END
BEGIN NOW Will vanish and deliver ye to woe, END
BEGIN NOW More woe, the more your taste is now of joy; END
BEGIN NOW Happie, but for so happie ill secur'd END
BEGIN NOW Long to continue, and this high seat your Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Ill fenc't for Heav'n to keep out such a foe END
BEGIN NOW As now is enterd; yet no purpos'd foe END
BEGIN NOW To you whom I could pittie thus forlorne END
BEGIN NOW Though I unpittied: League with you I seek, END
BEGIN NOW And mutual amitie so streight, so close, END
BEGIN NOW That I with you must dwell, or you with me END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth; my dwelling haply may not please END
BEGIN NOW Like this fair Paradise, your sense, yet such END
BEGIN NOW Accept your Makers work; he gave it me, END
BEGIN NOW Which I as freely give; Hell shall unfould, END
BEGIN NOW To entertain you two, her widest Gates, END
BEGIN NOW And send forth all her Kings; there will be room, END
BEGIN NOW Not like these narrow limits, to receive END
BEGIN NOW Your numerous ofspring; if no better place, END
BEGIN NOW Thank him who puts me loath to this revenge END
BEGIN NOW On you who wrong me not for him who wrongd. END
BEGIN NOW And should I at your harmless innocence END
BEGIN NOW Melt, as I doe, yet public reason just, END
BEGIN NOW Honour and Empire with revenge enlarg'd, END
BEGIN NOW By conquering this new World, compels me now END
BEGIN NOW To do what else though damnd I should abhorre. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Fiend, and with necessitie, END
BEGIN NOW The Tyrants plea, excus'd his devilish deeds. END
BEGIN NOW Then from his loftie stand on that high Tree END
BEGIN NOW Down he alights among the sportful Herd END
BEGIN NOW Of those fourfooted kindes, himself now one, END
BEGIN NOW Now other, as thir shape servd best his end END
BEGIN NOW Neerer to view his prey, and unespi'd END
BEGIN NOW To mark what of thir state he more might learn END
BEGIN NOW By word or action markt: about them round END
BEGIN NOW A Lion now he stalkes with fierie glare, END
BEGIN NOW Then as a Tiger, who by chance hath spi'd END
BEGIN NOW In some Purlieu two gentle Fawnes at play, END
BEGIN NOW Strait couches close, then rising changes oft END
BEGIN NOW His couchant watch, as one who chose his ground END
BEGIN NOW Whence rushing he might surest seise them both END
BEGIN NOW Grip't in each paw: when ADAM first of men END
BEGIN NOW To first of women EVE thus moving speech, END
BEGIN NOW Turnd him all eare to heare new utterance flow. END
BEGIN NOW Sole partner and sole part of all these joyes, END
BEGIN NOW Dearer thy self then all; needs must the Power END
BEGIN NOW That made us, and for us this ample World END
BEGIN NOW Be infinitly good, and of his good END
BEGIN NOW As liberal and free as infinite, END
BEGIN NOW That rais'd us from the dust and plac't us here END
BEGIN NOW In all this happiness, who at his hand END
BEGIN NOW Have nothing merited, nor can performe END
BEGIN NOW Aught whereof hee hath need, hee who requires END
BEGIN NOW From us no other service then to keep END
BEGIN NOW This one, this easie charge, of all the Trees END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise that beare delicious fruit END
BEGIN NOW So various, not to taste that onely Tree END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledge, planted by the Tree of Life, END
BEGIN NOW So neer grows Death to Life, what ere Death is, END
BEGIN NOW Som dreadful thing no doubt; for well thou knowst END
BEGIN NOW God hath pronounc't it death to taste that Tree, END
BEGIN NOW The only sign of our obedience left END
BEGIN NOW Among so many signes of power and rule END
BEGIN NOW Conferrd upon us, and Dominion giv'n END
BEGIN NOW Over all other Creatures that possesse END
BEGIN NOW Earth, Aire, and Sea. Then let us not think hard END
BEGIN NOW One easie prohibition, who enjoy END
BEGIN NOW Free leave so large to all things else, and choice END
BEGIN NOW Unlimited of manifold delights: END
BEGIN NOW But let us ever praise him, and extoll END
BEGIN NOW His bountie, following our delightful task END
BEGIN NOW To prune these growing Plants, & tend these Flours, END
BEGIN NOW Which were it toilsom, yet with thee were sweet. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Eve repli'd. O thou for whom END
BEGIN NOW And from whom I was formd flesh of thy flesh, END
BEGIN NOW And without whom am to no end, my Guide END
BEGIN NOW And Head, what thou hast said is just and right. END
BEGIN NOW For wee to him indeed all praises owe, END
BEGIN NOW And daily thanks, I chiefly who enjoy END
BEGIN NOW So farr the happier Lot, enjoying thee END
BEGIN NOW Preeminent by so much odds, while thou END
BEGIN NOW Like consort to thy self canst no where find. END
BEGIN NOW That day I oft remember, when from sleep END
BEGIN NOW I first awak't, and found my self repos'd END
BEGIN NOW Under a shade on flours, much wondring where END
BEGIN NOW And what I was, whence thither brought, and how. END
BEGIN NOW Not distant far from thence a murmuring sound END
BEGIN NOW Of waters issu'd from a Cave and spread END
BEGIN NOW Into a liquid Plain, then stood unmov'd END
BEGIN NOW Pure as th' expanse of Heav'n; I thither went END
BEGIN NOW With unexperienc't thought, and laid me downe END
BEGIN NOW On the green bank, to look into the cleer END
BEGIN NOW Smooth Lake, that to me seemd another Skie. END
BEGIN NOW As I bent down to look, just opposite, END
BEGIN NOW A Shape within the watry gleam appeerd END
BEGIN NOW Bending to look on me, I started back, END
BEGIN NOW It started back, but pleasd I soon returnd, END
BEGIN NOW Pleas'd it returnd as soon with answering looks END
BEGIN NOW Of sympathie and love, there I had fixt END
BEGIN NOW Mine eyes till now, and pin'd with vain desire, END
BEGIN NOW Had not a voice thus warnd me, What thou seest, END
BEGIN NOW What there thou seest fair Creature is thy self, END
BEGIN NOW With thee it came and goes: but follow me, END
BEGIN NOW And I will bring thee where no shadow staies END
BEGIN NOW Thy coming, and thy soft imbraces, hee END
BEGIN NOW Whose image thou art, him thou shall enjoy END
BEGIN NOW Inseparablie thine, to him shalt beare END
BEGIN NOW Multitudes like thy self, and thence be call'd END
BEGIN NOW Mother of human Race: what could I doe, END
BEGIN NOW But follow strait, invisibly thus led? END
BEGIN NOW Till I espi'd thee, fair indeed and tall, END
BEGIN NOW Under a Platan, yet methought less faire, END
BEGIN NOW Less winning soft, less amiablie milde, END
BEGIN NOW Then that smooth watry image; back I turnd, END
BEGIN NOW Thou following cryd'st aloud, Return fair EVE, END
BEGIN NOW Whom fli'st thou? whom thou fli'st, of him thou art, END
BEGIN NOW His flesh, his bone; to give thee being I lent END
BEGIN NOW Out of my side to thee, neerest my heart END
BEGIN NOW Substantial Life, to have thee by my side END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth an individual solace dear; END
BEGIN NOW Part of my Soul I seek thee, and thee claim END
BEGIN NOW My other half: with that thy gentle hand END
BEGIN NOW Seisd mine, I yeilded, and from that time see END
BEGIN NOW How beauty is excelld by manly grace END
BEGIN NOW And wisdom, which alone is truly fair. END
BEGIN NOW So spake our general Mother, and with eyes END
BEGIN NOW Of conjugal attraction unreprov'd, END
BEGIN NOW And meek surrender, half imbracing leand END
BEGIN NOW On our first Father, half her swelling Breast END
BEGIN NOW Naked met his under the flowing Gold END
BEGIN NOW Of her loose tresses hid: he in delight END
BEGIN NOW Both of her Beauty and submissive Charms END
BEGIN NOW Smil'd with superior Love, as JUPITER END
BEGIN NOW On JUNO smiles, when he impregns the Clouds END
BEGIN NOW That shed MAY Flowers; and press'd her Matron lip END
BEGIN NOW With kisses pure: aside the Devil turnd END
BEGIN NOW For envie, yet with jealous leer maligne END
BEGIN NOW Ey'd them askance, and to himself thus plaind. END
BEGIN NOW Sight hateful, sight tormenting! thus these two END
BEGIN NOW Imparadis't in one anothers arms END
BEGIN NOW The happier EDEN, shall enjoy thir fill END
BEGIN NOW Of bliss on bliss, while I to Hell am thrust, END
BEGIN NOW Where neither joy nor love, but fierce desire, END
BEGIN NOW Among our other torments not the least, END
BEGIN NOW Still unfulfill'd with pain of longing pines; END
BEGIN NOW Yet let me not forget what I have gain'd END
BEGIN NOW From thir own mouths; all is not theirs it seems: END
BEGIN NOW One fatal Tree there stands of Knowledge call'd, END
BEGIN NOW Forbidden them to taste: Knowledge forbidd'n? END
BEGIN NOW Suspicious, reasonless. Why should thir Lord END
BEGIN NOW Envie them that? can it be sin to know, END
BEGIN NOW Can it be death? and do they onely stand END
BEGIN NOW By Ignorance, is that thir happie state, END
BEGIN NOW The proof of thir obedience and thir faith? END
BEGIN NOW O fair foundation laid whereon to build END
BEGIN NOW Thir ruine! Hence I will excite thir minds END
BEGIN NOW With more desire to know, and to reject END
BEGIN NOW Envious commands, invented with designe END
BEGIN NOW To keep them low whom knowledge might exalt END
BEGIN NOW Equal with Gods; aspiring to be such, END
BEGIN NOW They taste and die: what likelier can ensue? END
BEGIN NOW But first with narrow search I must walk round END
BEGIN NOW This Garden, and no corner leave unspi'd; END
BEGIN NOW A chance but chance may lead where I may meet END
BEGIN NOW Some wandring Spirit of Heav'n, by Fountain side, END
BEGIN NOW Or in thick shade retir'd, from him to draw END
BEGIN NOW What further would be learnt. Live while ye may, END
BEGIN NOW Yet happie pair; enjoy, till I return, END
BEGIN NOW Short pleasures, for long woes are to succeed. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, his proud step he scornful turn'd, END
BEGIN NOW But with sly circumspection, and began END
BEGIN NOW Through wood, through waste, o're hil, o're dale his roam. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while in utmost Longitude, where Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW With Earth and Ocean meets, the setting Sun END
BEGIN NOW Slowly descended, and with right aspect END
BEGIN NOW Against the eastern Gate of Paradise END
BEGIN NOW Leveld his eevning Rayes: it was a Rock END
BEGIN NOW Of Alablaster, pil'd up to the Clouds, END
BEGIN NOW Conspicuous farr, winding with one ascent END
BEGIN NOW Accessible from Earth, one entrance high; END
BEGIN NOW The rest was craggie cliff, that overhung END
BEGIN NOW Still as it rose, impossible to climbe. END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt these rockie Pillars GABRIEL sat END
BEGIN NOW Chief of th' Angelic Guards, awaiting night; END
BEGIN NOW About him exercis'd Heroic Games END
BEGIN NOW Th' unarmed Youth of Heav'n, but nigh at hand END
BEGIN NOW Hung high with Diamond flaming, and with Gold. END
BEGIN NOW Thither came URIEL, gliding through the Eeven END
BEGIN NOW On a Sun beam, swift as a shooting Starr END
BEGIN NOW In AUTUMN thwarts the night, when vapors fir'd END
BEGIN NOW Impress the Air, and shews the Mariner END
BEGIN NOW From what point of his Compass to beware END
BEGIN NOW Impetuous winds: he thus began in haste. END
BEGIN NOW GABRIEL, to thee thy cours by Lot hath giv'n END
BEGIN NOW Charge and strict watch that to this happie place END
BEGIN NOW No evil thing approach or enter in; END
BEGIN NOW This day at highth of Noon came to my Spheare END
BEGIN NOW A Spirit, zealous, as he seem'd, to know END
BEGIN NOW More of th' Almighties works, and chiefly Man END
BEGIN NOW Gods latest Image: I describ'd his way END
BEGIN NOW Bent all on speed, and markt his Aerie Gate; END
BEGIN NOW But in the Mount that lies from EDEN North, END
BEGIN NOW Where he first lighted, soon discernd his looks END
BEGIN NOW Alien from Heav'n, with passions foul obscur'd: END
BEGIN NOW Mine eye pursu'd him still, but under shade END
BEGIN NOW Lost sight of him; one of the banisht crew END
BEGIN NOW I fear, hath ventur'd from the deep, to raise END
BEGIN NOW New troubles; him thy care must be to find. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the winged Warriour thus returnd: END
BEGIN NOW URIEL, no wonder if thy perfet sight, END
BEGIN NOW Amid the Suns bright circle where thou sitst, END
BEGIN NOW See farr and wide: in at this Gate none pass END
BEGIN NOW The vigilance here plac't, but such as come END
BEGIN NOW Well known from Heav'n; and since Meridian hour END
BEGIN NOW No Creature thence: if Spirit of other sort, END
BEGIN NOW So minded, have oreleapt these earthie bounds END
BEGIN NOW On purpose, hard thou knowst it to exclude END
BEGIN NOW Spiritual substance with corporeal barr. END
BEGIN NOW But if within the circuit of these walks END
BEGIN NOW In whatsoever shape he lurk, of whom END
BEGIN NOW Thou telst, by morrow dawning I shall know. END
BEGIN NOW So promis'd hee, and URIEL to his charge END
BEGIN NOW Returnd on that bright beam, whose point now raisd END
BEGIN NOW Bore him slope downward to the Sun now fall'n END
BEGIN NOW Beneath th' AZORES; whither the prime Orb, END
BEGIN NOW Incredible how swift, had thither rowl'd END
BEGIN NOW Diurnal, or this less volubil Earth END
BEGIN NOW By shorter flight to th' East, had left him there END
BEGIN NOW Arraying with reflected Purple and Gold END
BEGIN NOW The Clouds that on his Western Throne attend: END
BEGIN NOW Now came still Eevning on, and Twilight gray END
BEGIN NOW Had in her sober Liverie all things clad; END
BEGIN NOW Silence accompanied, for Beast and Bird, END
BEGIN NOW They to thir grassie Couch, these to thir Nests END
BEGIN NOW Were slunk, all but the wakeful Nightingale; END
BEGIN NOW She all night long her amorous descant sung; END
BEGIN NOW Silence was pleas'd: now glow'd the Firmament END
BEGIN NOW With living Saphirs: HESPERUS that led END
BEGIN NOW The starrie Host, rode brightest, till the Moon END
BEGIN NOW Rising in clouded Majestie, at length END
BEGIN NOW Apparent Queen unvaild her peerless light, END
BEGIN NOW And o're the dark her Silver Mantle threw. END
BEGIN NOW When ADAM thus to EVE: Fair Consort, th' hour END
BEGIN NOW Of night, and all things now retir'd to rest END
BEGIN NOW Mind us of like repose, since God hath set END
BEGIN NOW Labour and rest, as day and night to men END
BEGIN NOW Successive, and the timely dew of sleep END
BEGIN NOW Now falling with soft slumbrous weight inclines END
BEGIN NOW Our eye-lids; other Creatures all day long END
BEGIN NOW Rove idle unimploid, and less need rest; END
BEGIN NOW Man hath his daily work of body or mind END
BEGIN NOW Appointed, which declares his Dignitie, END
BEGIN NOW And the regard of Heav'n on all his waies; END
BEGIN NOW While other Animals unactive range, END
BEGIN NOW And of thir doings God takes no account. END
BEGIN NOW Tomorrow ere fresh Morning streak the East END
BEGIN NOW With first approach of light, we must be ris'n, END
BEGIN NOW And at our pleasant labour, to reform END
BEGIN NOW Yon flourie Arbors, yonder Allies green, END
BEGIN NOW Our walks at noon, with branches overgrown, END
BEGIN NOW That mock our scant manuring, and require END
BEGIN NOW More hands then ours to lop thir wanton growth: END
BEGIN NOW Those Blossoms also, and those dropping Gumms, END
BEGIN NOW That lie bestrowne unsightly and unsmooth, END
BEGIN NOW Ask riddance, if we mean to tread with ease; END
BEGIN NOW Mean while, as Nature wills, Night bids us rest. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus EVE with perfet beauty adornd. END
BEGIN NOW My Author and Disposer, what thou bidst END
BEGIN NOW Unargu'd I obey; so God ordains, END
BEGIN NOW God is thy Law, thou mine: to know no more END
BEGIN NOW Is womans happiest knowledge and her praise. END
BEGIN NOW With thee conversing I forget all time, END
BEGIN NOW All seasons and thir change, all please alike. END
BEGIN NOW Sweet is the breath of morn, her rising sweet, END
BEGIN NOW With charm of earliest Birds; pleasant the Sun END
BEGIN NOW When first on this delightful Land he spreads END
BEGIN NOW His orient Beams, on herb, tree, fruit, and flour, END
BEGIN NOW Glistring with dew; fragrant the fertil earth END
BEGIN NOW After soft showers; and sweet the coming on END
BEGIN NOW Of grateful Eevning milde, then silent Night END
BEGIN NOW With this her solemn Bird and this fair Moon, END
BEGIN NOW And these the Gemms of Heav'n, her starrie train: END
BEGIN NOW But neither breath of Morn when she ascends END
BEGIN NOW With charm of earliest Birds, nor rising Sun END
BEGIN NOW On this delightful land, nor herb, fruit, floure, END
BEGIN NOW Glistring with dew, nor fragrance after showers, END
BEGIN NOW Nor grateful Evening mild, nor silent Night END
BEGIN NOW With this her solemn Bird, nor walk by Moon, END
BEGIN NOW Or glittering Starr-light without thee is sweet. END
BEGIN NOW But wherfore all night long shine these, for whom END
BEGIN NOW This glorious sight, when sleep hath shut all eyes? END
BEGIN NOW To whom our general Ancestor repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Daughter of God and Man, accomplisht EVE, END
BEGIN NOW Those have thir course to finish, round the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW By morrow Eevning, and from Land to Land END
BEGIN NOW In order, though to Nations yet unborn, END
BEGIN NOW Ministring light prepar'd, they set and rise; END
BEGIN NOW Least total darkness should by Night regaine END
BEGIN NOW Her old possession, and extinguish life END
BEGIN NOW In Nature and all things, which these soft fires END
BEGIN NOW Not only enlighten, but with kindly heate END
BEGIN NOW Of various influence foment and warme, END
BEGIN NOW Temper or nourish, or in part shed down END
BEGIN NOW Thir stellar vertue on all kinds that grow END
BEGIN NOW On Earth, made hereby apter to receive END
BEGIN NOW Perfection from the Suns more potent Ray. END
BEGIN NOW These then, though unbeheld in deep of night, END
BEGIN NOW Shine not in vain, nor think, though men were none, END
BEGIN NOW That heav'n would want spectators, God want praise; END
BEGIN NOW Millions of spiritual Creatures walk the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Unseen, both when we wake, and when we sleep: END
BEGIN NOW All these with ceasless praise his works behold END
BEGIN NOW Both day and night: how often from the steep END
BEGIN NOW Of echoing Hill or Thicket have we heard END
BEGIN NOW Celestial voices to the midnight air, END
BEGIN NOW Sole, or responsive each to others note END
BEGIN NOW Singing thir great Creator: oft in bands END
BEGIN NOW While they keep watch, or nightly rounding walk END
BEGIN NOW With Heav'nly touch of instrumental sounds END
BEGIN NOW In full harmonic number joind, thir songs END
BEGIN NOW Divide the night, and lift our thoughts to Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Thus talking hand in hand alone they pass'd END
BEGIN NOW On to thir blissful Bower; it was a place END
BEGIN NOW Chos'n by the sovran Planter, when he fram'd END
BEGIN NOW All things to mans delightful use; the roofe END
BEGIN NOW Of thickest covert was inwoven shade END
BEGIN NOW Laurel and Mirtle, and what higher grew END
BEGIN NOW Of firm and fragrant leaf; on either side END
BEGIN NOW ACANTHUS, and each odorous bushie shrub END
BEGIN NOW Fenc'd up the verdant wall; each beauteous flour, END
BEGIN NOW IRIS all hues, Roses, and Gessamin END
BEGIN NOW Rear'd high thir flourisht heads between, and wrought END
BEGIN NOW Mosaic; underfoot the Violet, END
BEGIN NOW Crocus, and Hyacinth with rich inlay END
BEGIN NOW Broiderd the ground, more colour'd then with stone END
BEGIN NOW Of costliest Emblem: other Creature here END
BEGIN NOW Beast, Bird, Insect, or Worm durst enter none; END
BEGIN NOW Such was thir awe of man. In shadier Bower END
BEGIN NOW More sacred and sequesterd, though but feignd, END
BEGIN NOW PAN or SILVANUS never slept, nor Nymph, END
BEGIN NOW Nor FAUNUS haunted. Here in close recess END
BEGIN NOW With Flowers, Garlands, and sweet-smelling Herbs END
BEGIN NOW Espoused EVE deckt first her Nuptial Bed, END
BEGIN NOW And heav'nly Quires the Hymenaean sung, END
BEGIN NOW What day the genial Angel to our Sire END
BEGIN NOW Brought her in naked beauty more adorn'd, END
BEGIN NOW More lovely then PANDORA, whom the Gods END
BEGIN NOW Endowd with all thir gifts, and O too like END
BEGIN NOW In sad event, when to the unwiser Son END
BEGIN NOW Mankind with her faire looks, to be aveng'd END
BEGIN NOW On him who had stole JOVES authentic fire. END
BEGIN NOW Thus at thir shadie Lodge arriv'd, both stood, END
BEGIN NOW Both turnd, and under op'n Skie ador'd END
BEGIN NOW The God that made both Skie, Air, Earth & Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Which they beheld, the Moons resplendent Globe END
BEGIN NOW And starrie Pole: Thou also mad'st the Night, END
BEGIN NOW Maker Omnipotent, and thou the Day, END
BEGIN NOW Which we in our appointed work imployd END
BEGIN NOW Have finisht happie in our mutual help END
BEGIN NOW And mutual love, the Crown of all our bliss END
BEGIN NOW Ordain'd by thee, and this delicious place END
BEGIN NOW For us too large, where thy abundance wants END
BEGIN NOW Partakers, and uncropt falls to the ground. END
BEGIN NOW But thou hast promis'd from us two a Race END
BEGIN NOW To fill the Earth, who shall with us extoll END
BEGIN NOW Thy goodness infinite, both when we wake, END
BEGIN NOW And when we seek, as now, thy gift of sleep. END
BEGIN NOW This said unanimous, and other Rites END
BEGIN NOW Observing none, but adoration pure END
BEGIN NOW Which God likes best, into thir inmost bower END
BEGIN NOW Handed they went; and eas'd the putting off END
BEGIN NOW These troublesom disguises which wee wear, END
BEGIN NOW Strait side by side were laid, nor turnd I weene END
BEGIN NOW ADAM from his fair Spouse, nor EVE the Rites END
BEGIN NOW Mysterious of connubial Love refus'd: END
BEGIN NOW Whatever Hypocrites austerely talk END
BEGIN NOW Of puritie and place and innocence, END
BEGIN NOW Defaming as impure what God declares END
BEGIN NOW Pure, and commands to som, leaves free to all. END
BEGIN NOW Our Maker bids increase, who bids abstain END
BEGIN NOW Haile wedded Love, mysterious Law, true source END
BEGIN NOW Of human ofspring, sole proprietie, END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise of all things common else. END
BEGIN NOW By thee adulterous lust was driv'n from men END
BEGIN NOW Among the bestial herds to raunge, by thee END
BEGIN NOW Relations dear, and all the Charities END
BEGIN NOW Of Father, Son, and Brother first were known. END
BEGIN NOW Farr be it, that I should write thee sin or blame, END
BEGIN NOW Or think thee unbefitting holiest place, END
BEGIN NOW Perpetual Fountain of Domestic sweets, END
BEGIN NOW Whose Bed is undefil'd and chast pronounc't, END
BEGIN NOW Present, or past, as Saints and Patriarchs us'd. END
BEGIN NOW Here Love his golden shafts imploies, here lights END
BEGIN NOW His constant Lamp, and waves his purple wings, END
BEGIN NOW Reigns here and revels; not in the bought smile END
BEGIN NOW Of Harlots, loveless, joyless, unindeard, END
BEGIN NOW Casual fruition, nor in Court Amours END
BEGIN NOW Mixt Dance, or wanton Mask, or Midnight Bal, END
BEGIN NOW Or Serenate, which the starv'd Lover sings END
BEGIN NOW To his proud fair, best quitted with disdain. END
BEGIN NOW These lulld by Nightingales imbraceing slept, END
BEGIN NOW And on thir naked limbs the flourie roof END
BEGIN NOW Showrd Roses, which the Morn repair'd. Sleep on, END
BEGIN NOW Blest pair; and O yet happiest if ye seek END
BEGIN NOW No happier state, and know to know no more. END
BEGIN NOW Now had night measur'd with her shaddowie Cone END
BEGIN NOW Half way up Hill this vast Sublunar Vault, END
BEGIN NOW And from thir Ivorie Port the Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW Forth issuing at th' accustomd hour stood armd END
BEGIN NOW To thir night watches in warlike Parade, END
BEGIN NOW When GABRIEL to his next in power thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW UZZIEL, half these draw off, and coast the South END
BEGIN NOW With strictest watch; these other wheel the North, END
BEGIN NOW Our circuit meets full West. As flame they part END
BEGIN NOW Half wheeling to the Shield, half to the Spear. END
BEGIN NOW From these, two strong and suttle Spirits he calld END
BEGIN NOW That neer him stood, and gave them thus in charge. END
BEGIN NOW ITHURIEL and ZEPHON, with wingd speed END
BEGIN NOW Search through this Garden, leav unsearcht no nook, END
BEGIN NOW But chiefly where those two fair Creatures Lodge, END
BEGIN NOW Now laid perhaps asleep secure of harme. END
BEGIN NOW This Eevning from the Sun's decline arriv'd END
BEGIN NOW Who tells of som infernal Spirit seen END
BEGIN NOW Hitherward bent (who could have thought?) escap'd END
BEGIN NOW The barrs of Hell, on errand bad no doubt: END
BEGIN NOW Such where ye find, seise fast, and hither bring. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, on he led his radiant Files, END
BEGIN NOW Daz'ling the Moon; these to the Bower direct END
BEGIN NOW In search of whom they sought: him there they found END
BEGIN NOW Squat like a Toad, close at the eare of EVE; END
BEGIN NOW Assaying by his Devilish art to reach END
BEGIN NOW The Organs of her Fancie, and with them forge END
BEGIN NOW Illusions as he list, Phantasms and Dreams, END
BEGIN NOW Or if, inspiring venom, he might taint END
BEGIN NOW Th' animal Spirits that from pure blood arise END
BEGIN NOW Like gentle breaths from Rivers pure, thence raise END
BEGIN NOW At least distemperd, discontented thoughts, END
BEGIN NOW Vain hopes, vain aimes, inordinate desires END
BEGIN NOW Blown up with high conceits ingendring pride. END
BEGIN NOW Him thus intent ITHURIEL with his Spear END
BEGIN NOW Touch'd lightly; for no falshood can endure END
BEGIN NOW Touch of Celestial temper, but returns END
BEGIN NOW Of force to its own likeness: up he starts END
BEGIN NOW Discoverd and surpriz'd. As when a spark END
BEGIN NOW Lights on a heap of nitrous Powder, laid END
BEGIN NOW Fit for the Tun som Magazin to store END
BEGIN NOW Against a rumord Warr, the Smuttie graine END
BEGIN NOW With sudden blaze diffus'd, inflames the Aire: END
BEGIN NOW So started up in his own shape the Fiend. END
BEGIN NOW Back stept those two fair Angels half amaz'd END
BEGIN NOW So sudden to behold the grieslie King; END
BEGIN NOW Yet thus, unmovd with fear, accost him soon. END
BEGIN NOW Which of those rebell Spirits adjudg'd to Hell END
BEGIN NOW Com'st thou, escap'd thy prison, and transform'd, END
BEGIN NOW Why satst thou like an enemie in waite END
BEGIN NOW Here watching at the head of these that sleep? END
BEGIN NOW Know ye not then said SATAN, filld with scorn, END
BEGIN NOW Know ye not me? ye knew me once no mate END
BEGIN NOW For you, there sitting where ye durst not soare; END
BEGIN NOW Not to know mee argues your selves unknown, END
BEGIN NOW The lowest of your throng; or if ye know, END
BEGIN NOW Why ask ye, and superfluous begin END
BEGIN NOW Your message, like to end as much in vain? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus ZEPHON, answering scorn with scorn. END
BEGIN NOW Think not, revolted Spirit, thy shape the same, END
BEGIN NOW Or undiminisht brightness, to be known END
BEGIN NOW As when thou stoodst in Heav'n upright and pure; END
BEGIN NOW That Glorie then, when thou no more wast good, END
BEGIN NOW Departed from thee, and thou resembl'st now END
BEGIN NOW Thy sin and place of doom obscure and foule. END
BEGIN NOW But come, for thou, be sure, shalt give account END
BEGIN NOW To him who sent us, whose charge is to keep END
BEGIN NOW This place inviolable, and these from harm. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Cherube, and his grave rebuke END
BEGIN NOW Severe in youthful beautie, added grace END
BEGIN NOW Invincible: abasht the Devil stood, END
BEGIN NOW And felt how awful goodness is, and saw END
BEGIN NOW Vertue in her shape how lovly, saw, and pin'd END
BEGIN NOW His loss; but chiefly to find here observd END
BEGIN NOW His lustre visibly impar'd; yet seemd END
BEGIN NOW Undaunted. If I must contend, said he, END
BEGIN NOW Best with the best, the Sender not the sent, END
BEGIN NOW Or all at once; more glorie will be wonn, END
BEGIN NOW Or less be lost. Thy fear, said ZEPHON bold, END
BEGIN NOW Will save us trial what the least can doe END
BEGIN NOW Single against thee wicked, and thence weak. END
BEGIN NOW The Fiend repli'd not, overcome with rage; END
BEGIN NOW But like a proud Steed reind, went hautie on, END
BEGIN NOW Chaumping his iron curb: to strive or flie END
BEGIN NOW He held it vain; awe from above had quelld END
BEGIN NOW His heart, not else dismai'd. Now drew they nigh END
BEGIN NOW The western point, where those half-rounding guards END
BEGIN NOW Just met, & closing stood in squadron joind END
BEGIN NOW Awaiting next command. To whom thir Chief END
BEGIN NOW GABRIEL from the Front thus calld aloud. END
BEGIN NOW O friends, I hear the tread of nimble feet END
BEGIN NOW Hasting this way, and now by glimps discerne END
BEGIN NOW ITHURIEL and ZEPHON through the shade, END
BEGIN NOW And with them comes a third of Regal port, END
BEGIN NOW But faded splendor wan; who by his gate END
BEGIN NOW And fierce demeanour seems the Prince of Hell, END
BEGIN NOW Not likely to part hence without contest; END
BEGIN NOW Stand firm, for in his look defiance lours. END
BEGIN NOW He scarce had ended, when those two approachd END
BEGIN NOW And brief related whom they brought, wher found, END
BEGIN NOW How busied, in what form and posture coucht. END
BEGIN NOW To whom with stern regard thus GABRIEL spake. END
BEGIN NOW Why hast thou, SATAN, broke the bounds prescrib'd END
BEGIN NOW To thy transgressions, and disturbd the charge END
BEGIN NOW Of others, who approve not to transgress END
BEGIN NOW By thy example, but have power and right END
BEGIN NOW To question thy bold entrance on this place; END
BEGIN NOW Imploi'd it seems to violate sleep, and those END
BEGIN NOW Whose dwelling God hath planted here in bliss? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus SATAN with contemptuous brow. END
BEGIN NOW GABRIEL, thou hadst in Heav'n th' esteem of wise, END
BEGIN NOW And such I held thee; but this question askt END
BEGIN NOW Puts me in doubt. Lives ther who loves his pain? END
BEGIN NOW Who would not, finding way, break loose from Hell, END
BEGIN NOW Though thither doomd? Thou wouldst thy self, no doubt, END
BEGIN NOW And boldly venture to whatever place END
BEGIN NOW Farthest from pain, where thou mightst hope to change END
BEGIN NOW Torment with ease, & soonest recompence END
BEGIN NOW Dole with delight, which in this place I sought; END
BEGIN NOW To thee no reason; who knowst only good, END
BEGIN NOW But evil hast not tri'd: and wilt object END
BEGIN NOW His will who bound us? let him surer barr END
BEGIN NOW His Iron Gates, if he intends our stay END
BEGIN NOW In that dark durance: thus much what was askt. END
BEGIN NOW The rest is true, they found me where they say; END
BEGIN NOW But that implies not violence or harme. END
BEGIN NOW Thus hee in scorn. The warlike Angel mov'd, END
BEGIN NOW Disdainfully half smiling thus repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW O loss of one in Heav'n to judge of wise, END
BEGIN NOW Since SATAN fell, whom follie overthrew, END
BEGIN NOW And now returns him from his prison scap't, END
BEGIN NOW Gravely in doubt whether to hold them wise END
BEGIN NOW Or not, who ask what boldness brought him hither END
BEGIN NOW Unlicenc't from his bounds in Hell prescrib'd; END
BEGIN NOW So wise he judges it to fly from pain END
BEGIN NOW However, and to scape his punishment. END
BEGIN NOW So judge thou still, presumptuous, till the wrauth, END
BEGIN NOW Which thou incurr'st by flying, meet thy flight END
BEGIN NOW Seavenfold, and scourge that wisdom back to Hell, END
BEGIN NOW Which taught thee yet no better, that no pain END
BEGIN NOW Can equal anger infinite provok't. END
BEGIN NOW But wherefore thou alone? wherefore with thee END
BEGIN NOW Came not all Hell broke loose? is pain to them END
BEGIN NOW Less pain, less to be fled, or thou then they END
BEGIN NOW Less hardie to endure? courageous Chief, END
BEGIN NOW The first in flight from pain, had'st thou alleg'd END
BEGIN NOW To thy deserted host this cause of flight, END
BEGIN NOW Thou surely hadst not come sole fugitive. END
BEGIN NOW To which the Fiend thus answerd frowning stern. END
BEGIN NOW Not that I less endure, or shrink from pain, END
BEGIN NOW Insulting Angel, well thou knowst I stood END
BEGIN NOW Thy fiercest, when in Battel to thy aide END
BEGIN NOW The blasting volied Thunder made all speed END
BEGIN NOW And seconded thy else not dreaded Spear. END
BEGIN NOW But still thy words at random, as before, END
BEGIN NOW Argue thy inexperience what behooves END
BEGIN NOW From hard assaies and ill successes past END
BEGIN NOW A faithful Leader, not to hazard all END
BEGIN NOW Through wayes of danger by himself untri'd. END
BEGIN NOW I therefore, I alone first undertook END
BEGIN NOW To wing the desolate Abyss, and spie END
BEGIN NOW This new created World, whereof in Hell END
BEGIN NOW Fame is not silent, here in hope to find END
BEGIN NOW Better abode, and my afflicted Powers END
BEGIN NOW To settle here on Earth, or in mid Aire; END
BEGIN NOW Though for possession put to try once more END
BEGIN NOW What thou and thy gay Legions dare against; END
BEGIN NOW Whose easier business were to serve thir Lord END
BEGIN NOW High up in Heav'n, with songs to hymne his Throne, END
BEGIN NOW And practis'd distances to cringe, not fight. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the warriour Angel soon repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW To say and strait unsay, pretending first END
BEGIN NOW Wise to flie pain, professing next the Spie, END
BEGIN NOW Argues no Leader, but a lyar trac't, END
BEGIN NOW SATAN, and couldst thou faithful add? O name, END
BEGIN NOW O sacred name of faithfulness profan'd! END
BEGIN NOW Faithful to whom? to thy rebellious crew? END
BEGIN NOW Armie of Fiends, fit body to fit head; END
BEGIN NOW Was this your discipline and faith ingag'd, END
BEGIN NOW Your military obedience, to dissolve END
BEGIN NOW Allegeance to th' acknowledg'd Power supream? END
BEGIN NOW And thou sly hypocrite, who now wouldst seem END
BEGIN NOW Patron of liberty, who more then thou END
BEGIN NOW Once fawn'd, and cring'd, and servilly ador'd END
BEGIN NOW Heav'ns awful Monarch? wherefore but in hope END
BEGIN NOW To dispossess him, and thy self to reigne? END
BEGIN NOW But mark what I arreede thee now, avant; END
BEGIN NOW Flie thither whence thou fledst: if from this houre END
BEGIN NOW Within these hallowd limits thou appeer, END
BEGIN NOW Back to th' infernal pit I drag thee chaind, END
BEGIN NOW And Seale thee so, as henceforth not to scorne END
BEGIN NOW The facil gates of hell too slightly barrd. END
BEGIN NOW So threatn'd hee, but SATAN to no threats END
BEGIN NOW Gave heed, but waxing more in rage repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Then when I am thy captive talk of chaines, END
BEGIN NOW Proud limitarie Cherube, but ere then END
BEGIN NOW Farr heavier load thy self expect to feel END
BEGIN NOW From my prevailing arme, though Heavens King END
BEGIN NOW Ride on thy wings, and thou with thy Compeers, END
BEGIN NOW Us'd to the yoak, draw'st his triumphant wheels END
BEGIN NOW In progress through the rode of Heav'n Star-pav'd. END
BEGIN NOW While thus he spake, th' Angelic Squadron bright END
BEGIN NOW Turnd fierie red, sharpning in mooned hornes END
BEGIN NOW Thir Phalanx, and began to hemm him round END
BEGIN NOW With ported Spears, as thick as when a field END
BEGIN NOW Of CERES ripe for harvest waving bends END
BEGIN NOW Her bearded Grove of ears, which way the wind END
BEGIN NOW Swayes them; the careful Plowman doubting stands END
BEGIN NOW Least on the threshing floore his hopeful sheaves END
BEGIN NOW Prove chaff. On th' other side SATAN allarm'd END
BEGIN NOW Collecting all his might dilated stood, END
BEGIN NOW Like TENERIFF or ATLAS unremov'd: END
BEGIN NOW His stature reacht the Skie, and on his Crest END
BEGIN NOW Sat horror Plum'd; nor wanted in his graspe END
BEGIN NOW What seemd both Spear and Shield: now dreadful deeds END
BEGIN NOW Might have ensu'd, nor onely Paradise END
BEGIN NOW In this commotion, but the Starrie Cope END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'n perhaps, or all the Elements END
BEGIN NOW At least had gon to rack, disturbd and torne END
BEGIN NOW With violence of this conflict, had not soon END
BEGIN NOW Th' Eternal to prevent such horrid fray END
BEGIN NOW Hung forth in Heav'n his golden Scales, yet seen END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt ASTREA and the SCORPION signe, END
BEGIN NOW Wherein all things created first he weighd, END
BEGIN NOW The pendulous round Earth with ballanc't Aire END
BEGIN NOW In counterpoise, now ponders all events, END
BEGIN NOW Battels and Realms: in these he put two weights END
BEGIN NOW The sequel each of parting and of fight; END
BEGIN NOW The latter quick up flew, and kickt the beam; END
BEGIN NOW Which GABRIEL spying, thus bespake the Fiend. END
BEGIN NOW SATAN, I know thy strength, and thou knowst mine, END
BEGIN NOW Neither our own but giv'n; what follie then END
BEGIN NOW To boast what Arms can doe, since thine no more END
BEGIN NOW Then Heav'n permits, nor mine, though doubld now END
BEGIN NOW To trample thee as mire: for proof look up, END
BEGIN NOW And read thy Lot in yon celestial Sign END
BEGIN NOW Where thou art weigh'd, & shown how light, how weak, END
BEGIN NOW If thou resist. The Fiend lookt up and knew END
BEGIN NOW His mounted scale aloft: nor more; but fled END
BEGIN NOW Murmuring, and with him fled the shades of night. END
BEGIN NOW Now Morn her rosie steps in th' Eastern Clime END
BEGIN NOW Advancing, sow'd the Earth with Orient Pearle, END
BEGIN NOW When ADAM wak't, so customd, for his sleep END
BEGIN NOW Was Aerie light, from pure digestion bred, END
BEGIN NOW And temperat vapors bland, which th' only sound END
BEGIN NOW Of leaves and fuming rills, AURORA's fan, END
BEGIN NOW Lightly dispers'd, and the shrill Matin Song END
BEGIN NOW Of Birds on every bough; so much the more END
BEGIN NOW His wonder was to find unwak'nd EVE END
BEGIN NOW With Tresses discompos'd, and glowing Cheek, END
BEGIN NOW As through unquiet rest: he on his side END
BEGIN NOW Leaning half-rais'd, with looks of cordial Love END
BEGIN NOW Hung over her enamour'd, and beheld END
BEGIN NOW Beautie, which whether waking or asleep, END
BEGIN NOW Shot forth peculiar Graces; then with voice END
BEGIN NOW Milde, as when ZEPHYRUS on FLORA breathes, END
BEGIN NOW Her hand soft touching, whisperd thus. Awake END
BEGIN NOW My fairest, my espous'd, my latest found, END
BEGIN NOW Heav'ns last best gift, my ever new delight, END
BEGIN NOW Awake, the morning shines, and the fresh field END
BEGIN NOW Calls us, we lose the prime, to mark how spring END
BEGIN NOW Our tended Plants, how blows the Citron Grove, END
BEGIN NOW What drops the Myrrhe, & what the balmie Reed, END
BEGIN NOW How Nature paints her colours, how the Bee END
BEGIN NOW Sits on the Bloom extracting liquid sweet. END
BEGIN NOW Such whispering wak'd her, but with startl'd eye END
BEGIN NOW On ADAM, whom imbracing, thus she spake. END
BEGIN NOW O Sole in whom my thoughts find all repose, END
BEGIN NOW My Glorie, my Perfection, glad I see END
BEGIN NOW Thy face, and Morn return'd, for I this Night, END
BEGIN NOW Such night till this I never pass'd, have dream'd, END
BEGIN NOW If dream'd, not as I oft am wont, of thee, END
BEGIN NOW Works of day pass't, or morrows next designe, END
BEGIN NOW But of offence and trouble, which my mind END
BEGIN NOW Knew never till this irksom night; methought END
BEGIN NOW Close at mine ear one call'd me forth to walk END
BEGIN NOW With gentle voice, I thought it thine; it said, END
BEGIN NOW Why sleepst thou EVE? now is the pleasant time, END
BEGIN NOW The cool, the silent, save where silence yields END
BEGIN NOW To the night-warbling Bird, that now awake END
BEGIN NOW Tunes sweetest his love-labor'd song; now reignes END
BEGIN NOW Full Orb'd the Moon, and with more pleasing light END
BEGIN NOW Shadowie sets off the face of things; in vain, END
BEGIN NOW If none regard; Heav'n wakes with all his eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Whom to behold but thee, Natures desire, END
BEGIN NOW In whose sight all things joy, with ravishment END
BEGIN NOW Attracted by thy beauty still to gaze. END
BEGIN NOW I rose as at thy call, but found thee not; END
BEGIN NOW To find thee I directed then my walk; END
BEGIN NOW And on, methought, alone I pass'd through ways END
BEGIN NOW That brought me on a sudden to the Tree END
BEGIN NOW Of interdicted Knowledge: fair it seem'd, END
BEGIN NOW Much fairer to my Fancie then by day: END
BEGIN NOW And as I wondring lookt, beside it stood END
BEGIN NOW One shap'd & wing'd like one of those from Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW By us oft seen; his dewie locks distill'd END
BEGIN NOW Ambrosia; on that Tree he also gaz'd; END
BEGIN NOW And O fair Plant, said he, with fruit surcharg'd, END
BEGIN NOW Deigns none to ease thy load and taste thy sweet, END
BEGIN NOW Nor God, nor Man; is Knowledge so despis'd? END
BEGIN NOW Or envie, or what reserve forbids to taste? END
BEGIN NOW Forbid who will, none shall from me withhold END
BEGIN NOW Longer thy offerd good, why else set here? END
BEGIN NOW This said he paus'd not, but with ventrous Arme END
BEGIN NOW He pluckt, he tasted; mee damp horror chil'd END
BEGIN NOW At such bold words voucht with a deed so bold: END
BEGIN NOW But he thus overjoy'd, O Fruit Divine, END
BEGIN NOW Sweet of thy self, but much more sweet thus cropt, END
BEGIN NOW Forbidd'n here, it seems, as onely fit END
BEGIN NOW For Gods, yet able to make Gods of Men: END
BEGIN NOW And why not Gods of Men, since good, the more END
BEGIN NOW Communicated, more abundant growes, END
BEGIN NOW The Author not impair'd, but honourd more? END
BEGIN NOW Here, happie Creature, fair Angelic EVE, END
BEGIN NOW Partake thou also; happie though thou art, END
BEGIN NOW Happier thou mayst be, worthier canst not be: END
BEGIN NOW Taste this, and be henceforth among the Gods END
BEGIN NOW Thy self a Goddess, not to Earth confind, END
BEGIN NOW But somtimes in the Air, as wee, somtimes END
BEGIN NOW Ascend to Heav'n, by merit thine, and see END
BEGIN NOW What life the Gods live there, and such live thou. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, he drew nigh, and to me held, END
BEGIN NOW Even to my mouth of that same fruit held part END
BEGIN NOW Which he had pluckt; the pleasant savourie smell END
BEGIN NOW So quick'nd appetite, that I, methought, END
BEGIN NOW Could not but taste. Forthwith up to the Clouds END
BEGIN NOW With him I flew, and underneath beheld END
BEGIN NOW The Earth outstretcht immense, a prospect wide END
BEGIN NOW And various: wondring at my flight and change END
BEGIN NOW To this high exaltation; suddenly END
BEGIN NOW My Guide was gon, and I, me thought, sunk down, END
BEGIN NOW And fell asleep; but O how glad I wak'd END
BEGIN NOW To find this but a dream! Thus EVE her Night END
BEGIN NOW Related, and thus ADAM answerd sad. END
BEGIN NOW Best Image of my self and dearer half, END
BEGIN NOW The trouble of thy thoughts this night in sleep END
BEGIN NOW Affects me equally; nor can I like END
BEGIN NOW This uncouth dream, of evil sprung I fear; END
BEGIN NOW Yet evil whence? in thee can harbour none, END
BEGIN NOW Created pure. But know that in the Soule END
BEGIN NOW Are many lesser Faculties that serve END
BEGIN NOW Reason as chief; among these Fansie next END
BEGIN NOW Her office holds; of all external things, END
BEGIN NOW Which the five watchful Senses represent, END
BEGIN NOW She forms Imaginations, Aerie shapes, END
BEGIN NOW Which Reason joyning or disjoyning, frames END
BEGIN NOW All what we affirm or what deny, and call END
BEGIN NOW Our knowledge or opinion; then retires END
BEGIN NOW Into her private Cell when Nature rests. END
BEGIN NOW Oft in her absence mimic Fansie wakes END
BEGIN NOW To imitate her; but misjoyning shapes, END
BEGIN NOW Wilde work produces oft, and most in dreams, END
BEGIN NOW Ill matching words and deeds long past or late. END
BEGIN NOW Som such resemblances methinks I find END
BEGIN NOW Of our last Eevnings talk, in this thy dream, END
BEGIN NOW But with addition strange; yet be not sad. END
BEGIN NOW Evil into the mind of God or Man END
BEGIN NOW May come and go, so unapprov'd, and leave END
BEGIN NOW No spot or blame behind: Which gives me hope END
BEGIN NOW That what in sleep thou didst abhorr to dream, END
BEGIN NOW Waking thou never wilt consent to do. END
BEGIN NOW Be not disheart'nd then, nor cloud those looks END
BEGIN NOW That wont to be more chearful and serene END
BEGIN NOW Then when fair Morning first smiles on the World, END
BEGIN NOW And let us to our fresh imployments rise END
BEGIN NOW That open now thir choicest bosom'd smells END
BEGIN NOW Reservd from night, and kept for thee in store. END
BEGIN NOW So cheard he his fair Spouse, and she was cheard, END
BEGIN NOW But silently a gentle tear let fall END
BEGIN NOW From either eye, and wip'd them with her haire; END
BEGIN NOW Two other precious drops that ready stood, END
BEGIN NOW Each in thir chrystal sluce, hee ere they fell END
BEGIN NOW Kiss'd as the gracious signs of sweet remorse END
BEGIN NOW And pious awe, that feard to have offended. END
BEGIN NOW So all was cleard, and to the Field they haste. END
BEGIN NOW But first from under shadie arborous roof, END
BEGIN NOW Soon as they forth were come to open sight END
BEGIN NOW Of day-spring, and the Sun, who scarce up risen END
BEGIN NOW With wheels yet hov'ring o're the Ocean brim, END
BEGIN NOW Shot paralel to the earth his dewie ray, END
BEGIN NOW Discovering in wide Lantskip all the East END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise and EDENS happie Plains, END
BEGIN NOW Lowly they bow'd adoring, and began END
BEGIN NOW Thir Orisons, each Morning duly paid END
BEGIN NOW In various style, for neither various style END
BEGIN NOW Nor holy rapture wanted they to praise END
BEGIN NOW Thir Maker, in fit strains pronounc't or sung END
BEGIN NOW Unmeditated, such prompt eloquence END
BEGIN NOW Flowd from thir lips, in Prose or numerous Verse, END
BEGIN NOW More tuneable then needed Lute or Harp END
BEGIN NOW To add more sweetness, and they thus began. END
BEGIN NOW These are thy glorious works, Parent of good, END
BEGIN NOW Almightie, thine this universal Frame, END
BEGIN NOW Thus wondrous fair; thy self how wondrous then! END
BEGIN NOW Unspeakable, who sitst above these Heavens END
BEGIN NOW To us invisible or dimly seen END
BEGIN NOW In these thy lowest works, yet these declare END
BEGIN NOW Thy goodness beyond thought, and Power Divine: END
BEGIN NOW Speak yee who best can tell, ye Sons of light, END
BEGIN NOW Angels, for yee behold him, and with songs END
BEGIN NOW And choral symphonies, Day without Night, END
BEGIN NOW Circle his Throne rejoycing, yee in Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW On Earth joyn all yee Creatures to extoll END
BEGIN NOW Him first, him last, him midst, and without end. END
BEGIN NOW Fairest of Starrs, last in the train of Night, END
BEGIN NOW If better thou belong not to the dawn, END
BEGIN NOW Sure pledge of day, that crownst the smiling Morn END
BEGIN NOW With thy bright Circlet, praise him in thy Spheare END
BEGIN NOW While day arises, that sweet hour of Prime. END
BEGIN NOW Thou Sun, of this great World both Eye and Soule, END
BEGIN NOW Acknowledge him thy Greater, sound his praise END
BEGIN NOW In thy eternal course, both when thou climb'st, END
BEGIN NOW And when high Noon hast gaind, & when thou fallst. END
BEGIN NOW Moon, that now meetst the orient Sun, now fli'st END
BEGIN NOW With the fixt Starrs, fixt in thir Orb that flies, END
BEGIN NOW And yee five other wandring Fires that move END
BEGIN NOW In mystic Dance not without Song, resound END
BEGIN NOW His praise, who out of Darkness call'd up Light. END
BEGIN NOW Aire, and ye Elements the eldest birth END
BEGIN NOW Of Natures Womb, that in quaternion run END
BEGIN NOW Perpetual Circle, multiform; and mix END
BEGIN NOW And nourish all things, let your ceasless change END
BEGIN NOW Varie to our great Maker still new praise. END
BEGIN NOW Ye Mists and Exhalations that now rise END
BEGIN NOW From Hill or steaming Lake, duskie or grey, END
BEGIN NOW Till the Sun paint your fleecie skirts with Gold, END
BEGIN NOW In honour to the Worlds great Author rise, END
BEGIN NOW Whether to deck with Clouds the uncolourd skie, END
BEGIN NOW Or wet the thirstie Earth with falling showers, END
BEGIN NOW Rising or falling still advance his praise. END
BEGIN NOW His praise ye Winds, that from four Quarters blow, END
BEGIN NOW Breath soft or loud; and wave your tops, ye Pines, END
BEGIN NOW With every Plant, in sign of Worship wave. END
BEGIN NOW Fountains and yee, that warble, as ye flow, END
BEGIN NOW Melodious murmurs, warbling tune his praise. END
BEGIN NOW Joyn voices all ye living Souls, ye Birds, END
BEGIN NOW That singing up to Heaven Gate ascend, END
BEGIN NOW Bear on your wings and in your notes his praise; END
BEGIN NOW Yee that in Waters glide, and yee that walk END
BEGIN NOW The Earth, and stately tread, or lowly creep; END
BEGIN NOW Witness if I be silent, Morn or Eeven, END
BEGIN NOW To Hill, or Valley, Fountain, or fresh shade END
BEGIN NOW Made vocal by my Song, and taught his praise. END
BEGIN NOW Hail universal Lord, be bounteous still END
BEGIN NOW To give us onely good; and if the night END
BEGIN NOW Have gathered aught of evil or conceald, END
BEGIN NOW Disperse it, as now light dispels the dark. END
BEGIN NOW So pray'd they innocent, and to thir thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Firm peace recoverd soon and wonted calm. END
BEGIN NOW On to thir mornings rural work they haste END
BEGIN NOW Among sweet dewes and flours; where any row END
BEGIN NOW Of Fruit-trees overwoodie reachd too farr END
BEGIN NOW Thir pamperd boughes, and needed hands to check END
BEGIN NOW Fruitless imbraces: or they led the Vine END
BEGIN NOW To wed her Elm; she spous'd about him twines END
BEGIN NOW Her mariageable arms, and with her brings END
BEGIN NOW Her dowr th' adopted Clusters, to adorn END
BEGIN NOW His barren leaves. Them thus imploid beheld END
BEGIN NOW With pittie Heav'ns high King, and to him call'd END
BEGIN NOW RAPHAEL, the sociable Spirit, that deign'd END
BEGIN NOW To travel with TOBIAS, and secur'd END
BEGIN NOW His marriage with the seaventimes-wedded Maid. END
BEGIN NOW RAPHAEL, said hee, thou hear'st what stir on Earth END
BEGIN NOW SATAN from Hell scap't through the darksom Gulf END
BEGIN NOW Hath raisd in Paradise, and how disturbd END
BEGIN NOW This night the human pair, how he designes END
BEGIN NOW In them at once to ruin all mankind. END
BEGIN NOW Go therefore, half this day as friend with friend END
BEGIN NOW Converse with ADAM, in what Bowre or shade END
BEGIN NOW Thou find'st him from the heat of Noon retir'd, END
BEGIN NOW To respit his day-labour with repast, END
BEGIN NOW Or with repose; and such discourse bring on, END
BEGIN NOW As may advise him of his happie state, END
BEGIN NOW Happiness in his power left free to will, END
BEGIN NOW Left to his own free Will, his Will though free, END
BEGIN NOW Yet mutable; whence warne him to beware END
BEGIN NOW He swerve not too secure: tell him withall END
BEGIN NOW His danger, and from whom, what enemie END
BEGIN NOW Late falln himself from Heav'n, is plotting now END
BEGIN NOW The fall of others from like state of bliss; END
BEGIN NOW By violence, no, for that shall be withstood, END
BEGIN NOW But by deceit and lies; this let him know, END
BEGIN NOW Least wilfully transgressing he pretend END
BEGIN NOW Surprisal, unadmonisht, unforewarnd. END
BEGIN NOW So spake th' Eternal Father, and fulfilld END
BEGIN NOW All Justice: nor delaid the winged Saint END
BEGIN NOW After his charge receivd, but from among END
BEGIN NOW Thousand Celestial Ardors, where he stood END
BEGIN NOW Vaild with his gorgeous wings, up springing light END
BEGIN NOW Flew through the midst of Heav'n; th' angelic Quires END
BEGIN NOW On each hand parting, to his speed gave way END
BEGIN NOW Through all th' Empyreal road; till at the Gate END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'n arriv'd, the gate self-opend wide END
BEGIN NOW On golden Hinges turning, as by work END
BEGIN NOW Divine the sov'ran Architect had fram'd. END
BEGIN NOW From hence, no cloud, or, to obstruct his sight, END
BEGIN NOW Starr interpos'd, however small he sees, END
BEGIN NOW Not unconform to other shining Globes, END
BEGIN NOW Earth and the Gard'n of God, with Cedars crownd END
BEGIN NOW Above all Hills. As when by night the Glass END
BEGIN NOW Of GALILEO, less assur'd, observes END
BEGIN NOW Or Pilot from amidst the CYCLADES END
BEGIN NOW DELOS or SAMOS first appeering kenns END
BEGIN NOW A cloudy spot. Down thither prone in flight END
BEGIN NOW He speeds, and through the vast Ethereal Skie END
BEGIN NOW Sailes between worlds & worlds, with steddie wing END
BEGIN NOW Now on the polar windes, then with quick Fann END
BEGIN NOW Winnows the buxom Air; till within soare END
BEGIN NOW Of Towring Eagles, to all the Fowles he seems END
BEGIN NOW A PHOENIX, gaz'd by all, as that sole Bird END
BEGIN NOW When to enshrine his reliques in the Sun's END
BEGIN NOW At once on th' Eastern cliff of Paradise END
BEGIN NOW He lights, and to his proper shape returns END
BEGIN NOW A Seraph wingd; six wings he wore, to shade END
BEGIN NOW His lineaments Divine; the pair that clad END
BEGIN NOW Each shoulder broad, came mantling o're his brest END
BEGIN NOW With regal Ornament; the middle pair END
BEGIN NOW Girt like a Starrie Zone his waste, and round END
BEGIN NOW Skirted his loines and thighes with downie Gold END
BEGIN NOW And colours dipt in Heav'n; the third his feet END
BEGIN NOW Shaddowd from either heele with featherd maile END
BEGIN NOW Skie-tinctur'd grain. Like MAIA'S son he stood, END
BEGIN NOW And shook his Plumes, that Heav'nly fragrance filld END
BEGIN NOW The circuit wide. Strait knew him all the bands END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels under watch; and to his state, END
BEGIN NOW And to his message high in honour rise; END
BEGIN NOW For on som message high they guessd him bound. END
BEGIN NOW Thir glittering Tents he passd, and now is come END
BEGIN NOW Into the blissful field, through Groves of Myrrhe, END
BEGIN NOW And flouring Odours, Cassia, Nard, and Balme; END
BEGIN NOW A Wilderness of sweets; for Nature here END
BEGIN NOW Wantond as in her prime, and plaid at will END
BEGIN NOW Her Virgin Fancies, pouring forth more sweet, END
BEGIN NOW Wilde above rule or art; enormous bliss. END
BEGIN NOW Him through the spicie Forrest onward com END
BEGIN NOW ADAM discernd, as in the dore he sat END
BEGIN NOW Of his coole Bowre, while now the mounted Sun END
BEGIN NOW Shot down direct his fervid Raies, to warme END
BEGIN NOW Earths inmost womb, more warmth then ADAM need; END
BEGIN NOW And EVE within, due at her hour prepar'd END
BEGIN NOW For dinner savourie fruits, of taste to please END
BEGIN NOW True appetite, and not disrelish thirst END
BEGIN NOW Of nectarous draughts between, from milkie stream, END
BEGIN NOW Berrie or Grape: to whom thus ADAM call'd. END
BEGIN NOW Haste hither EVE, and worth thy sight behold END
BEGIN NOW Eastward among those Trees, what glorious shape END
BEGIN NOW Comes this way moving; seems another Morn END
BEGIN NOW Ris'n on mid-noon; som great behest from Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW To us perhaps he brings, and will voutsafe END
BEGIN NOW This day to be our Guest. But goe with speed, END
BEGIN NOW And what thy stores contain, bring forth and poure END
BEGIN NOW Abundance, fit to honour and receive END
BEGIN NOW Our Heav'nly stranger; well we may afford END
BEGIN NOW Our givers thir own gifts, and large bestow END
BEGIN NOW From large bestowd, where Nature multiplies END
BEGIN NOW Her fertil growth, and by disburd'ning grows END
BEGIN NOW More fruitful, which instructs us not to spare. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus EVE. ADAM, earths hallowd mould, END
BEGIN NOW Of God inspir'd, small store will serve, where store, END
BEGIN NOW All seasons, ripe for use hangs on the stalk; END
BEGIN NOW Save what by frugal storing firmness gains END
BEGIN NOW To nourish, and superfluous moist consumes: END
BEGIN NOW But I will haste and from each bough and break, END
BEGIN NOW Each Plant & juciest Gourd will pluck such choice END
BEGIN NOW To entertain our Angel guest, as hee END
BEGIN NOW Beholding shall confess that here on Earth END
BEGIN NOW God hath dispenst his bounties as in Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, with dispatchful looks in haste END
BEGIN NOW She turns, on hospitable thoughts intent END
BEGIN NOW What choice to chuse for delicacie best, END
BEGIN NOW What order, so contriv'd as not to mix END
BEGIN NOW Tastes, not well joynd, inelegant, but bring END
BEGIN NOW Taste after taste upheld with kindliest change, END
BEGIN NOW Bestirs her then, and from each tender stalk END
BEGIN NOW Whatever Earth all-bearing Mother yeilds END
BEGIN NOW In INDIA East or West, or middle shoare END
BEGIN NOW In PONTUS or the PUNIC Coast, or where END
BEGIN NOW ALCINOUS reign'd, fruit of all kindes, in coate, END
BEGIN NOW Rough, or smooth rin'd, or bearded husk, or shell END
BEGIN NOW She gathers, Tribute large, and on the board END
BEGIN NOW Heaps with unsparing hand; for drink the Grape END
BEGIN NOW She crushes, inoffensive moust, and meathes END
BEGIN NOW From many a berrie, and from sweet kernels prest END
BEGIN NOW She tempers dulcet creams, nor these to hold END
BEGIN NOW Wants her fit vessels pure, then strews the ground END
BEGIN NOW With Rose and Odours from the shrub unfum'd. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while our Primitive great Sire, to meet END
BEGIN NOW His god-like Guest, walks forth, without more train END
BEGIN NOW Accompani'd then with his own compleat END
BEGIN NOW Perfections, in himself was all his state, END
BEGIN NOW More solemn then the tedious pomp that waits END
BEGIN NOW On Princes, when thir rich Retinue long END
BEGIN NOW Of Horses led, and Grooms besmeard with Gold END
BEGIN NOW Dazles the croud, and sets them all agape. END
BEGIN NOW Neerer his presence ADAM though not awd, END
BEGIN NOW Yet with submiss approach and reverence meek, END
BEGIN NOW As to a superior Nature, bowing low, END
BEGIN NOW Thus said. Native of Heav'n, for other place END
BEGIN NOW None can then Heav'n such glorious shape contain; END
BEGIN NOW Since by descending from the Thrones above, END
BEGIN NOW Those happie places thou hast deignd a while END
BEGIN NOW To want, and honour these, voutsafe with us END
BEGIN NOW Two onely, who yet by sov'ran gift possess END
BEGIN NOW This spacious ground, in yonder shadie Bowre END
BEGIN NOW To rest, and what the Garden choicest bears END
BEGIN NOW To sit and taste, till this meridian heat END
BEGIN NOW Be over, and the Sun more coole decline. END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus the Angelic Vertue answerd milde. END
BEGIN NOW ADAM, I therefore came, nor art thou such END
BEGIN NOW Created, or such place hast here to dwell, END
BEGIN NOW As may not oft invite, though Spirits of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW To visit thee; lead on then where thy Bowre END
BEGIN NOW Oreshades; for these mid-hours, till Eevning rise END
BEGIN NOW I have at will. So to the Silvan Lodge END
BEGIN NOW They came, that like POMONA'S Arbour smil'd END
BEGIN NOW With flourets deck't and fragrant smells; but EVE END
BEGIN NOW Undeckt, save with her self more lovely fair END
BEGIN NOW Then Wood-Nymph, or the fairest Goddess feign'd END
BEGIN NOW Of three that in Mount IDA naked strove, END
BEGIN NOW Stood to entertain her guest from Heav'n; no vaile END
BEGIN NOW Shee needed, Vertue-proof, no thought infirme END
BEGIN NOW Alterd her cheek. On whom the Angel HAILE END
BEGIN NOW Bestowd, the holy salutation us'd END
BEGIN NOW Long after to blest MARIE, second EVE. END
BEGIN NOW Haile Mother of Mankind, whose fruitful Womb END
BEGIN NOW Shall fill the World more numerous with thy Sons END
BEGIN NOW Then with these various fruits the Trees of God END
BEGIN NOW Have heap'd this Table. Rais'd of grassie terf END
BEGIN NOW Thir Table was, and mossie seats had round, END
BEGIN NOW And on her ample Square from side to side END
BEGIN NOW All AUTUMN pil'd, though SPRING and AUTUMN here END
BEGIN NOW Danc'd hand in hand. A while discourse they hold; END
BEGIN NOW No fear lest Dinner coole; when thus began END
BEGIN NOW Our Authour. Heav'nly stranger, please to taste END
BEGIN NOW These bounties which our Nourisher, from whom END
BEGIN NOW All perfet good unmeasur'd out, descends, END
BEGIN NOW To us for food and for delight hath caus'd END
BEGIN NOW The Earth to yeild; unsavourie food perhaps END
BEGIN NOW To spiritual Natures; only this I know, END
BEGIN NOW That one Celestial Father gives to all. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Angel. Therefore what he gives END
BEGIN NOW (Whose praise be ever sung) to man in part END
BEGIN NOW Spiritual, may of purest Spirits be found END
BEGIN NOW No ingrateful food: and food alike those pure END
BEGIN NOW Intelligential substances require END
BEGIN NOW As doth your Rational; and both contain END
BEGIN NOW Within them every lower facultie END
BEGIN NOW Of sense, whereby they hear, see, smell, touch, taste, END
BEGIN NOW Tasting concoct, digest, assimilate, END
BEGIN NOW And corporeal to incorporeal turn. END
BEGIN NOW For know, whatever was created, needs END
BEGIN NOW To be sustaind and fed; of Elements END
BEGIN NOW The grosser feeds the purer, earth the sea, END
BEGIN NOW Earth and the Sea feed Air, the Air those Fires END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal, and as lowest first the Moon; END
BEGIN NOW Whence in her visage round those spots, unpurg'd END
BEGIN NOW Vapours not yet into her substance turnd. END
BEGIN NOW Nor doth the Moon no nourishment exhale END
BEGIN NOW From her moist Continent to higher Orbes. END
BEGIN NOW The Sun that light imparts to all, receives END
BEGIN NOW From all his alimental recompence END
BEGIN NOW In humid exhalations, and at Even END
BEGIN NOW Sups with the Ocean: though in Heav'n the Trees END
BEGIN NOW Of life ambrosial frutage bear, and vines END
BEGIN NOW Yeild Nectar, though from off the boughs each Morn END
BEGIN NOW We brush mellifluous Dewes, and find the ground END
BEGIN NOW Cover'd with pearly grain: yet God hath here END
BEGIN NOW Varied his bounty so with new delights, END
BEGIN NOW As may compare with Heaven; and to taste END
BEGIN NOW Think not I shall be nice. So down they sat, END
BEGIN NOW And to thir viands fell, nor seemingly END
BEGIN NOW The Angel, nor in mist, the common gloss END
BEGIN NOW Of Theologians, but with keen dispatch END
BEGIN NOW Of real hunger, and concoctive heate END
BEGIN NOW To transubstantiate; what redounds, transpires END
BEGIN NOW Through Spirits with ease; nor wonder; if by fire END
BEGIN NOW Of sooty coal the Empiric Alchimist END
BEGIN NOW Can turn, or holds it possible to turn END
BEGIN NOW Metals of drossiest Ore to perfet Gold END
BEGIN NOW As from the Mine. Mean while at Table EVE END
BEGIN NOW Ministerd naked, and thir flowing cups END
BEGIN NOW With pleasant liquors crown'd: O innocence END
BEGIN NOW Deserving Paradise! if ever, then, END
BEGIN NOW Then had the Sons of God excuse to have bin END
BEGIN NOW Enamour'd at that sight; but in those hearts END
BEGIN NOW Love unlibidinous reign'd, nor jealousie END
BEGIN NOW Was understood, the injur'd Lovers Hell. END
BEGIN NOW Thus when with meats & drinks they had suffic'd, END
BEGIN NOW Not burd'nd Nature, sudden mind arose END
BEGIN NOW In ADAM, not to let th' occasion pass END
BEGIN NOW Given him by this great Conference to know END
BEGIN NOW Of things above his World, and of thir being END
BEGIN NOW Who dwell in Heav'n, whose excellence he saw END
BEGIN NOW Transcend his own so farr, whose radiant forms END
BEGIN NOW Divine effulgence, whose high Power so far END
BEGIN NOW Exceeded human, and his wary speech END
BEGIN NOW Thus to th' Empyreal Minister he fram'd. END
BEGIN NOW Inhabitant with God, now know I well END
BEGIN NOW Thy favour, in this honour done to man, END
BEGIN NOW Under whose lowly roof thou hast voutsaf't END
BEGIN NOW To enter, and these earthly fruits to taste, END
BEGIN NOW Food not of Angels, yet accepted so, END
BEGIN NOW As that more willingly thou couldst not seem END
BEGIN NOW At Heav'ns high feasts to have fed: yet what compare? END
BEGIN NOW To whom the winged Hierarch repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW O ADAM, one Almightie is, from whom END
BEGIN NOW All things proceed, and up to him return, END
BEGIN NOW If not deprav'd from good, created all END
BEGIN NOW Such to perfection, one first matter all, END
BEGIN NOW Indu'd with various forms, various degrees END
BEGIN NOW Of substance, and in things that live, of life; END
BEGIN NOW But more refin'd, more spiritous, and pure, END
BEGIN NOW As neerer to him plac't or neerer tending END
BEGIN NOW Each in thir several active Sphears assignd, END
BEGIN NOW Till body up to spirit work, in bounds END
BEGIN NOW Proportiond to each kind. So from the root END
BEGIN NOW Springs lighter the green stalk, from thence the leaves END
BEGIN NOW More aerie, last the bright consummate floure END
BEGIN NOW Spirits odorous breathes: flours and thir fruit END
BEGIN NOW Mans nourishment, by gradual scale sublim'd END
BEGIN NOW To vital Spirits aspire, to animal, END
BEGIN NOW To intellectual, give both life and sense, END
BEGIN NOW Fansie and understanding, whence the soule END
BEGIN NOW Reason receives, and reason is her being, END
BEGIN NOW Discursive, or Intuitive; discourse END
BEGIN NOW Is oftest yours, the latter most is ours, END
BEGIN NOW Differing but in degree, of kind the same. END
BEGIN NOW Wonder not then, what God for you saw good END
BEGIN NOW If I refuse not, but convert, as you, END
BEGIN NOW To proper substance; time may come when men END
BEGIN NOW With Angels may participate, and find END
BEGIN NOW No inconvenient Diet, nor too light Fare: END
BEGIN NOW And from these corporal nutriments perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Your bodies may at last turn all to Spirit END
BEGIN NOW Improv'd by tract of time, and wingd ascend END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal, as wee, or may at choice END
BEGIN NOW Here or in Heav'nly Paradises dwell; END
BEGIN NOW If ye be found obedient, and retain END
BEGIN NOW Unalterably firm his love entire END
BEGIN NOW Whose progenie you are. Mean while enjoy END
BEGIN NOW Your fill what happiness this happie state END
BEGIN NOW Can comprehend, incapable of more. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Patriarch of mankind repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW O favourable spirit, propitious guest, END
BEGIN NOW Well hast thou taught the way that might direct END
BEGIN NOW Our knowledge, and the scale of Nature set END
BEGIN NOW From center to circumference, whereon END
BEGIN NOW In contemplation of created things END
BEGIN NOW By steps we may ascend to God. But say, END
BEGIN NOW What meant that caution joind, IF YE BE FOUND END
BEGIN NOW OBEDIENT? can wee want obedience then END
BEGIN NOW To him, or possibly his love desert END
BEGIN NOW Who formd us from the dust, and plac'd us here END
BEGIN NOW Full to the utmost measure of what bliss END
BEGIN NOW Human desires can seek or apprehend? END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Angel. Son of Heav'n and Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Attend: That thou art happie, owe to God; END
BEGIN NOW That thou continu'st such, owe to thy self, END
BEGIN NOW That is, to thy obedience; therein stand. END
BEGIN NOW This was that caution giv'n thee; be advis'd. END
BEGIN NOW God made thee perfet, not immutable; END
BEGIN NOW And good he made thee, but to persevere END
BEGIN NOW He left it in thy power, ordaind thy will END
BEGIN NOW By nature free, not over-rul'd by Fate END
BEGIN NOW Inextricable, or strict necessity; END
BEGIN NOW Our voluntarie service he requires, END
BEGIN NOW Not our necessitated, such with him END
BEGIN NOW Findes no acceptance, nor can find, for how END
BEGIN NOW Can hearts, not free, be tri'd whether they serve END
BEGIN NOW Willing or no, who will but what they must END
BEGIN NOW By Destinie, and can no other choose? END
BEGIN NOW My self and all th' Angelic Host that stand END
BEGIN NOW In sight of God enthron'd, our happie state END
BEGIN NOW Hold, as you yours, while our obedience holds; END
BEGIN NOW On other surety none; freely we serve. END
BEGIN NOW Because wee freely love, as in our will END
BEGIN NOW To love or not; in this we stand or fall: END
BEGIN NOW And som are fall'n, to disobedience fall'n, END
BEGIN NOW And so from Heav'n to deepest Hell; O fall END
BEGIN NOW From what high state of bliss into what woe! END
BEGIN NOW To whom our great Progenitor. Thy words END
BEGIN NOW Attentive, and with more delighted eare END
BEGIN NOW Divine instructer, I have heard, then when END
BEGIN NOW Cherubic Songs by night from neighbouring Hills END
BEGIN NOW Aereal Music send: nor knew I not END
BEGIN NOW To be both will and deed created free; END
BEGIN NOW Yet that we never shall forget to love END
BEGIN NOW Our maker, and obey him whose command END
BEGIN NOW Single, is yet so just, my constant thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Assur'd me and still assure: though what thou tellst END
BEGIN NOW Hath past in Heav'n, som doubt within me move, END
BEGIN NOW But more desire to hear, if thou consent, END
BEGIN NOW The full relation, which must needs be strange, END
BEGIN NOW Worthy of Sacred silence to be heard; END
BEGIN NOW And we have yet large day, for scarce the Sun END
BEGIN NOW Hath finisht half his journey, and scarce begins END
BEGIN NOW His other half in the great Zone of Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW Thus ADAM made request, and RAPHAEL END
BEGIN NOW After short pause assenting, thus began. END
BEGIN NOW High matter thou injoinst me, O prime of men, END
BEGIN NOW Sad task and hard, for how shall I relate END
BEGIN NOW To human sense th' invisible exploits END
BEGIN NOW Of warring Spirits; how without remorse END
BEGIN NOW The ruin of so many glorious once END
BEGIN NOW And perfet while they stood; how last unfould END
BEGIN NOW The secrets of another world, perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Not lawful to reveal? yet for thy good END
BEGIN NOW This is dispenc't, and what surmounts the reach END
BEGIN NOW Of human sense, I shall delineate so, END
BEGIN NOW By lik'ning spiritual to corporal forms, END
BEGIN NOW As may express them best, though what if Earth END
BEGIN NOW Be but the shaddow of Heav'n, and things therein END
BEGIN NOW Each to other like, more then on earth is thought? END
BEGIN NOW As yet this world was not, and CHAOS wilde END
BEGIN NOW Reignd where these Heav'ns now rowl, where Earth now rests END
BEGIN NOW Upon her Center pois'd, when on a day END
BEGIN NOW (For Time, though in Eternitie, appli'd END
BEGIN NOW To motion, measures all things durable END
BEGIN NOW By present, past, and future) on such day END
BEGIN NOW As Heav'ns great Year brings forth, th' Empyreal Host END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels by Imperial summons call'd, END
BEGIN NOW Innumerable before th' Almighties Throne END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith from all the ends of Heav'n appeerd END
BEGIN NOW Under thir Hierarchs in orders bright END
BEGIN NOW Ten thousand thousand Ensignes high advanc'd, END
BEGIN NOW Standards, and Gonfalons twixt Van and Reare END
BEGIN NOW Streame in the Aire, and for distinction serve END
BEGIN NOW Or in thir glittering Tissues bear imblaz'd END
BEGIN NOW Holy Memorials, acts of Zeale and Love END
BEGIN NOW Recorded eminent. Thus when in Orbes END
BEGIN NOW Of circuit inexpressible they stood, END
BEGIN NOW Orb within Orb, the Father infinite, END
BEGIN NOW By whom in bliss imbosom'd sat the Son, END
BEGIN NOW Amidst as from a flaming Mount, whoseop END
BEGIN NOW Brightness had made invisible, thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW Hear my Decree, which unrevok't shall stand. END
BEGIN NOW This day I have begot whom I declare END
BEGIN NOW My onely Son, and on this holy Hill END
BEGIN NOW Him have anointed, whom ye now behold END
BEGIN NOW At my right hand; your Head I him appoint; END
BEGIN NOW And by my Self have sworn to him shall bow END
BEGIN NOW All knees in Heav'n, and shall confess him Lord: END
BEGIN NOW Under his great Vice-gerent Reign abide END
BEGIN NOW United as one individual Soule END
BEGIN NOW For ever happie: him who disobeyes END
BEGIN NOW Mee disobeyes, breaks union, and that day END
BEGIN NOW Cast out from God and blessed vision, falls END
BEGIN NOW Into utter darkness, deep ingulft, his place END
BEGIN NOW Ordaind without redemption, without end. END
BEGIN NOW So spake th' Omnipotent, and with his words END
BEGIN NOW All seemd well pleas'd, all seem'd, but were not all. END
BEGIN NOW That day, as other solem dayes, they spent END
BEGIN NOW In song and dance about the sacred Hill, END
BEGIN NOW Mystical dance, which yonder starrie Spheare END
BEGIN NOW Of Planets and of fixt in all her Wheeles END
BEGIN NOW Resembles nearest, mazes intricate, END
BEGIN NOW Eccentric, intervolv'd, yet regular END
BEGIN NOW Then most, when most irregular they seem: END
BEGIN NOW And in thir motions harmonie Divine END
BEGIN NOW So smooths her charming tones, that Gods own ear END
BEGIN NOW Listens delighted. Eevning approachd END
BEGIN NOW (For we have also our Eevning and our Morn, END
BEGIN NOW We ours for change delectable, not need) END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith from dance to sweet repast they turn END
BEGIN NOW Desirous, all in Circles as they stood, END
BEGIN NOW Tables are set, and on a sudden pil'd END
BEGIN NOW With Angels Food, and rubied Nectar flows: END
BEGIN NOW In Pearl, in Diamond, and massie Gold, END
BEGIN NOW Fruit of delicious Vines, the growth of Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW They eat, they drink, and with refection sweet END
BEGIN NOW Are fill'd, before th' all bounteous King, who showrd END
BEGIN NOW With copious hand, rejoycing in thir joy. END
BEGIN NOW Now when ambrosial Night with Clouds exhal'd END
BEGIN NOW From that high mount of God, whence light & shade END
BEGIN NOW Spring both, the face of brightest Heav'n had changd END
BEGIN NOW To grateful Twilight (for Night comes not there END
BEGIN NOW In darker veile) and roseat Dews dispos'd END
BEGIN NOW All but the unsleeping eyes of God to rest, END
BEGIN NOW Wide over all the Plain, and wider farr END
BEGIN NOW Then all this globous Earth in Plain outspred, END
BEGIN NOW (Such are the Courts of God) Th' Angelic throng END
BEGIN NOW Disperst in Bands and Files thir Camp extend END
BEGIN NOW By living Streams among the Trees of Life, END
BEGIN NOW Pavilions numberless, and sudden reard, END
BEGIN NOW Celestial Tabernacles, where they slept END
BEGIN NOW Fannd with coole Winds, save those who in thir course END
BEGIN NOW Melodious Hymns about the sovran Throne END
BEGIN NOW Alternate all night long: but not so wak'd END
BEGIN NOW SATAN, so call him now, his former name END
BEGIN NOW Is heard no more Heav'n; he of the first, END
BEGIN NOW If not the first Arch-Angel, great in Power, END
BEGIN NOW In favour and praeeminence, yet fraught END
BEGIN NOW With envie against the Son of God, that day END
BEGIN NOW Honourd by his great Father, and proclaimd END
BEGIN NOW MESSIAH King anointed, could not beare END
BEGIN NOW Through pride that sight, and thought himself impaird. END
BEGIN NOW Deep malice thence conceiving & disdain, END
BEGIN NOW Soon as midnight brought on the duskie houre END
BEGIN NOW Friendliest to sleep and silence, he resolv'd END
BEGIN NOW With all his Legions to dislodge, and leave END
BEGIN NOW Unworshipt, unobey'd the Throne supream END
BEGIN NOW Contemptuous, and his next subordinate END
BEGIN NOW Awak'ning, thus to him in secret spake. END
BEGIN NOW Sleepst thou Companion dear, what sleep can close END
BEGIN NOW Thy eye-lids? and remembrest what Decree END
BEGIN NOW Of yesterday, so late hath past the lips END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'ns Almightie. Thou to me thy thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Wast wont, I mine to thee was wont to impart; END
BEGIN NOW Both waking we were one; how then can now END
BEGIN NOW Thy sleep dissent? new Laws thou seest impos'd; END
BEGIN NOW New Laws from him who reigns, new minds may raise END
BEGIN NOW In us who serve, new Counsels, to debate END
BEGIN NOW What doubtful may ensue, more in this place END
BEGIN NOW To utter is not safe. Assemble thou END
BEGIN NOW Of all those Myriads which we lead the chief; END
BEGIN NOW Tell them that by command, ere yet dim Night END
BEGIN NOW Her shadowie Cloud withdraws, I am to haste, END
BEGIN NOW And all who under me thir Banners wave, END
BEGIN NOW Homeward with flying march where we possess END
BEGIN NOW The Quarters of the North, there to prepare END
BEGIN NOW Fit entertainment to receive our King END
BEGIN NOW The great MESSIAH, and his new commands, END
BEGIN NOW Who speedily through all the Hierarchies END
BEGIN NOW Intends to pass triumphant, and give Laws. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the false Arch-Angel, and infus'd END
BEGIN NOW Bad influence into th' unwarie brest END
BEGIN NOW Of his Associate; hee together calls, END
BEGIN NOW Or several one by one, the Regent Powers, END
BEGIN NOW Under him Regent, tells, as he was taught, END
BEGIN NOW That the most High commanding, now ere Night, END
BEGIN NOW Now ere dim Night had disincumberd Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW The great Hierarchal Standard was to move; END
BEGIN NOW Tells the suggested cause, and casts between END
BEGIN NOW Ambiguous words and jealousies, to sound END
BEGIN NOW Or taint integritie; but all obey'd END
BEGIN NOW The wonted signal, and superior voice END
BEGIN NOW Of thir great Potentate; for great indeed END
BEGIN NOW His name, and high was his degree in Heav'n; END
BEGIN NOW His count'nance, as the Morning Starr that guides END
BEGIN NOW The starrie flock, allur'd them, and with lyes END
BEGIN NOW Drew after him the third part of Heav'ns Host: END
BEGIN NOW Mean while th' Eternal eye, whose sight discernes END
BEGIN NOW Abstrusest thoughts, from forth his holy Mount END
BEGIN NOW And from within the golden Lamps that burne END
BEGIN NOW Nightly before him, saw without thir light END
BEGIN NOW Rebellion rising, saw in whom, how spred END
BEGIN NOW Among the sons of Morn, what multitudes END
BEGIN NOW Were banded to oppose his high Decree; END
BEGIN NOW And smiling to his onely Son thus said. END
BEGIN NOW Son, thou in whom my glory I behold END
BEGIN NOW In full resplendence, Heir of all my might, END
BEGIN NOW Neerly it now concernes us to be sure END
BEGIN NOW Of our Omnipotence, and with what Arms END
BEGIN NOW We mean to hold what anciently we claim END
BEGIN NOW Of Deitie or Empire, such a foe END
BEGIN NOW Is rising, who intends to erect his Throne END
BEGIN NOW Equal to ours, throughout the spacious North; END
BEGIN NOW Nor so content, hath in his thought to trie END
BEGIN NOW In battel, what our Power is, or our right. END
BEGIN NOW Let us advise, and to this hazard draw END
BEGIN NOW With speed what force is left, and all imploy END
BEGIN NOW In our defence, lest unawares we lose END
BEGIN NOW This our high place, our Sanctuarie, our Hill. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Son with calm aspect and cleer END
BEGIN NOW Light'ning Divine, ineffable, serene, END
BEGIN NOW Made answer. Mightie Father, thou thy foes END
BEGIN NOW Justly hast in derision, and secure END
BEGIN NOW Laugh'st at thir vain designes and tumults vain, END
BEGIN NOW Matter to mee of Glory, whom thir hate END
BEGIN NOW Illustrates, when they see all Regal Power END
BEGIN NOW Giv'n me to quell thir pride, and in event END
BEGIN NOW Know whether I be dextrous to subdue END
BEGIN NOW Thy Rebels, or be found the worst in Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Son, but SATAN with his Powers END
BEGIN NOW Farr was advanc't on winged speed, an Host END
BEGIN NOW Or Starrs of Morning, Dew-drops, which the Sun END
BEGIN NOW Impearls on every leaf and every flouer. END
BEGIN NOW Regions they pass'd, the mightie Regencies END
BEGIN NOW In thir triple Degrees, Regions to which END
BEGIN NOW All thy Dominion, ADAM, is no more END
BEGIN NOW Then what this Garden is to all the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW And all the Sea, from one entire globose END
BEGIN NOW Stretcht into Longitude; which having pass'd END
BEGIN NOW At length into the limits of the North END
BEGIN NOW They came, and SATAN to his Royal seat END
BEGIN NOW High on a Hill, far blazing, as a Mount END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd on a Mount, with Pyramids and Towrs END
BEGIN NOW From Diamond Quarries hew'n, & Rocks of Gold, END
BEGIN NOW The Palace of great LUCIFER, (so call END
BEGIN NOW Interpreted) which not long after, hee END
BEGIN NOW Affecting all equality with God, END
BEGIN NOW In imitation of that Mount whereon END
BEGIN NOW MESSIAH was declar'd in sight of Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW The Mountain of the Congregation call'd; END
BEGIN NOW For thither he assembl'd all his Train, END
BEGIN NOW Pretending so commanded to consult END
BEGIN NOW About the great reception of thir King, END
BEGIN NOW Thither to come, and with calumnious Art END
BEGIN NOW Of counterfeted truth thus held thir ears. END
BEGIN NOW If these magnific Titles yet remain END
BEGIN NOW Not meerly titular, since by Decree END
BEGIN NOW Another now hath to himself ingross't END
BEGIN NOW All Power, and us eclipst under the name END
BEGIN NOW Of King anointed, for whom all this haste END
BEGIN NOW Of midnight march, and hurried meeting here, END
BEGIN NOW This onely to consult how we may best END
BEGIN NOW With what may be devis'd of honours new END
BEGIN NOW Receive him coming to receive from us END
BEGIN NOW Knee-tribute yet unpaid, prostration vile, END
BEGIN NOW Too much to one, but double how endur'd, END
BEGIN NOW To one and to his image now proclaim'd? END
BEGIN NOW But what if better counsels might erect END
BEGIN NOW Our minds and teach us to cast off this Yoke? END
BEGIN NOW Will ye submit your necks, and chuse to bend END
BEGIN NOW The supple knee? ye will not, if I trust END
BEGIN NOW To know ye right, or if ye know your selves END
BEGIN NOW Natives and Sons of Heav'n possest before END
BEGIN NOW By none, and if not equal all, yet free, END
BEGIN NOW Equally free; for Orders and Degrees END
BEGIN NOW Jarr not with liberty, but well consist. END
BEGIN NOW Who can in reason then or right assume END
BEGIN NOW Monarchie over such as live by right END
BEGIN NOW His equals, if in power and splendor less, END
BEGIN NOW In freedome equal? or can introduce END
BEGIN NOW Law and Edict on us, who without law END
BEGIN NOW Erre not, much less for this to be our Lord, END
BEGIN NOW And look for adoration to th' abuse END
BEGIN NOW Of those Imperial Titles which assert END
BEGIN NOW Our being ordain'd to govern, not to serve? END
BEGIN NOW Thus farr his bold discourse without controule END
BEGIN NOW Had audience, when among the Seraphim END
BEGIN NOW ABDIEL, then whom none with more zeale ador'd END
BEGIN NOW The Deitie, and divine commands obei'd, END
BEGIN NOW Stood up, and in a flame of zeale severe END
BEGIN NOW The current of his fury thus oppos'd. END
BEGIN NOW O argument blasphemous, false and proud! END
BEGIN NOW Words which no eare ever to hear in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Expected, least of all from thee, ingrate END
BEGIN NOW In place thy self so high above thy Peeres. END
BEGIN NOW Canst thou with impious obloquie condemne END
BEGIN NOW The just Decree of God, pronounc't and sworn, END
BEGIN NOW That to his only Son by right endu'd END
BEGIN NOW With Regal Scepter, every Soule in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Shall bend the knee, and in that honour due END
BEGIN NOW Confess him rightful King? unjust thou saist END
BEGIN NOW Flatly unjust, to binde with Laws the free, END
BEGIN NOW And equal over equals to let Reigne, END
BEGIN NOW One over all with unsucceeded power. END
BEGIN NOW Shalt thou give Law to God, shalt thou dispute END
BEGIN NOW With him the points of libertie, who made END
BEGIN NOW Thee what thou art, & formd the Pow'rs of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Such as he pleasd, and circumscrib'd thir being? END
BEGIN NOW Yet by experience taught we know how good, END
BEGIN NOW And of our good, and of our dignitie END
BEGIN NOW How provident he is, how farr from thought END
BEGIN NOW To make us less, bent rather to exalt END
BEGIN NOW Our happie state under one Head more neer END
BEGIN NOW United. But to grant it thee unjust, END
BEGIN NOW That equal over equals Monarch Reigne: END
BEGIN NOW Thy self though great & glorious dost thou count, END
BEGIN NOW Or all Angelic Nature joind in one, END
BEGIN NOW Equal to him begotten Son, by whom END
BEGIN NOW As by his Word the mighty Father made END
BEGIN NOW All things, ev'n thee, and all the Spirits of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW By him created in thir bright degrees, END
BEGIN NOW Crownd them with Glory, & to thir Glory nam'd END
BEGIN NOW Essential Powers, nor by his Reign obscur'd, END
BEGIN NOW But more illustrious made, since he the Head END
BEGIN NOW One of our number thus reduc't becomes, END
BEGIN NOW His Laws our Laws, all honour to him done END
BEGIN NOW Returns our own. Cease then this impious rage, END
BEGIN NOW And tempt not these; but hast'n to appease END
BEGIN NOW Th' incensed Father, and th' incensed Son, END
BEGIN NOW While Pardon may be found in time besought. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the fervent Angel, but his zeale END
BEGIN NOW None seconded, as out of season judg'd, END
BEGIN NOW Or singular and rash, whereat rejoic'd END
BEGIN NOW Th' Apostat, and more haughty thus repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW That we were formd then saist thou? & the work END
BEGIN NOW Of secondarie hands, by task transferd END
BEGIN NOW From Father to his Son? strange point and new! END
BEGIN NOW Doctrin which we would know whence learnt: who saw END
BEGIN NOW When this creation was? rememberst thou END
BEGIN NOW Thy making, while the Maker gave thee being? END
BEGIN NOW We know no time when we were not as now; END
BEGIN NOW Know none before us, self-begot, self-rais'd END
BEGIN NOW By our own quick'ning power, when fatal course END
BEGIN NOW Had circl'd his full Orbe, the birth mature END
BEGIN NOW Of this our native Heav'n, Ethereal Sons. END
BEGIN NOW Our puissance is our own, our own right hand END
BEGIN NOW Shall teach us highest deeds, by proof to try END
BEGIN NOW Who is our equal: then thou shalt behold END
BEGIN NOW Whether by supplication we intend END
BEGIN NOW Address, and to begirt th' Almighty Throne END
BEGIN NOW Beseeching or besieging. This report, END
BEGIN NOW These tidings carrie to th' anointed King; END
BEGIN NOW And fly, ere evil intercept thy flight. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and as the sound of waters deep END
BEGIN NOW Hoarce murmur echo'd to his words applause END
BEGIN NOW Through the infinite Host, nor less for that END
BEGIN NOW The flaming Seraph fearless, though alone END
BEGIN NOW Encompass'd round with foes, thus answerd bold. END
BEGIN NOW O alienate from God, O spirit accurst, END
BEGIN NOW Forsak'n of all good; I see thy fall END
BEGIN NOW Determind, and thy hapless crew involv'd END
BEGIN NOW In this perfidious fraud, contagion spred END
BEGIN NOW Both of thy crime and punishment: henceforth END
BEGIN NOW No more be troubl'd how to quit the yoke END
BEGIN NOW Of Gods MESSIAH; those indulgent Laws END
BEGIN NOW Will not be now voutsaf't, other Decrees END
BEGIN NOW Against thee are gon forth without recall; END
BEGIN NOW That Golden Scepter which thou didst reject END
BEGIN NOW Is now an Iron Rod to bruise and breake END
BEGIN NOW Thy disobedience. Well thou didst advise, END
BEGIN NOW Yet not for thy advise or threats I fly END
BEGIN NOW These wicked Tents devoted, least the wrauth END
BEGIN NOW Impendent, raging into sudden flame END
BEGIN NOW Distinguish not: for soon expect to feel END
BEGIN NOW His Thunder on thy head, devouring fire. END
BEGIN NOW Then who created thee lamenting learne, END
BEGIN NOW When who can uncreate thee thou shalt know. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Seraph ABDIEL faithful found, END
BEGIN NOW Among the faithless, faithful only hee; END
BEGIN NOW Among innumerable false, unmov'd, END
BEGIN NOW Unshak'n, unseduc'd, unterrifi'd END
BEGIN NOW His Loyaltie he kept, his Love, his Zeale; END
BEGIN NOW Nor number, nor example with him wrought END
BEGIN NOW To swerve from truth, or change his constant mind END
BEGIN NOW Though single. From amidst them forth he passd, END
BEGIN NOW Long way through hostile scorn, which he susteind END
BEGIN NOW Superior, nor of violence fear'd aught; END
BEGIN NOW And with retorted scorn his back he turn'd END
BEGIN NOW On those proud Towrs to swift destruction doom'd. END
BEGIN NOW All night the dreadless Angel unpursu'd END
BEGIN NOW Through Heav'ns wide Champain held his way, till Morn, END
BEGIN NOW Wak't by the circling Hours, with rosie hand END
BEGIN NOW Unbarr'd the gates of Light. There is a Cave END
BEGIN NOW Within the Mount of God, fast by his Throne, END
BEGIN NOW Where light and darkness in perpetual round END
BEGIN NOW Lodge and dislodge by turns, which makes through Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Grateful vicissitude, like Day and Night; END
BEGIN NOW Light issues forth, and at the other dore END
BEGIN NOW Obsequious darkness enters, till her houre END
BEGIN NOW To veile the Heav'n, though darkness there might well END
BEGIN NOW Seem twilight here; and now went forth the Morn END
BEGIN NOW Such as in highest Heav'n, arrayd in Gold END
BEGIN NOW Empyreal, from before her vanisht Night, END
BEGIN NOW Shot through with orient Beams: when all the Plain END
BEGIN NOW Coverd with thick embatteld Squadrons bright, END
BEGIN NOW Chariots and flaming Armes, and fierie Steeds END
BEGIN NOW Reflecting blaze on blaze, first met his view: END
BEGIN NOW Warr he perceav'd, warr in procinct, and found END
BEGIN NOW Already known what he for news had thought END
BEGIN NOW To have reported: gladly then he mixt END
BEGIN NOW Among those friendly Powers who him receav'd END
BEGIN NOW With joy and acclamations loud, that one END
BEGIN NOW That of so many Myriads fall'n, yet one END
BEGIN NOW Returnd not lost: On to the sacred hill END
BEGIN NOW They led him high applauded, and present END
BEGIN NOW Before the seat supream; from whence a voice END
BEGIN NOW From midst a Golden Cloud thus milde was heard. END
BEGIN NOW Servant of God, well done, well hast thou fought END
BEGIN NOW The better fight, who single hast maintaind END
BEGIN NOW Against revolted multitudes the Cause END
BEGIN NOW Of Truth, in word mightier then they in Armes; END
BEGIN NOW And for the testimonie of Truth hast born END
BEGIN NOW Universal reproach, far worse to beare END
BEGIN NOW Then violence: for this was all thy care END
BEGIN NOW To stand approv'd in sight of God, though Worlds END
BEGIN NOW Judg'd thee perverse: the easier conquest now END
BEGIN NOW Remains thee, aided by this host of friends, END
BEGIN NOW Back on thy foes more glorious to return END
BEGIN NOW Then scornd thou didst depart, and to subdue END
BEGIN NOW By force, who reason for thir Law refuse, END
BEGIN NOW Right reason for thir Law, and for thir King END
BEGIN NOW MESSIAH, who by right of merit Reigns. END
BEGIN NOW Goe MICHAEL of Celestial Armies Prince, END
BEGIN NOW And thou in Military prowess next END
BEGIN NOW GABRIEL, lead forth to Battel these my Sons END
BEGIN NOW Invincible, lead forth my armed Saints END
BEGIN NOW By Thousands and by Millions rang'd for fight; END
BEGIN NOW Equal in number to that Godless crew END
BEGIN NOW Rebellious, them with Fire and hostile Arms END
BEGIN NOW Fearless assault, and to the brow of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Pursuing drive them out from God and bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Into thir place of punishment, the Gulf END
BEGIN NOW Of TARTARUS, which ready opens wide END
BEGIN NOW His fiery CHAOS to receave thir fall. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Sovran voice, and Clouds began END
BEGIN NOW To darken all the Hill, and smoak to rowl END
BEGIN NOW In duskie wreathes, reluctant flames, the signe END
BEGIN NOW Of wrauth awak't: nor with less dread the loud END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal Trumpet from on high gan blow: END
BEGIN NOW At which command the Powers Militant, END
BEGIN NOW That stood for Heav'n, in mighty Quadrate joyn'd END
BEGIN NOW Of Union irresistible, mov'd on END
BEGIN NOW In silence thir bright Legions, to the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of instrumental Harmonie that breath'd END
BEGIN NOW Heroic Ardor to advent'rous deeds END
BEGIN NOW Under thir God-like Leaders, in the Cause END
BEGIN NOW Of God and his MESSIAH. On they move END
BEGIN NOW Indissolubly firm; nor obvious Hill, END
BEGIN NOW Nor streit'ning Vale, nor Wood, nor Stream divides END
BEGIN NOW Thir perfet ranks; for high above the ground END
BEGIN NOW Thir march was, and the passive Air upbore END
BEGIN NOW Thir nimble tread; as when the total kind END
BEGIN NOW Of Birds in orderly array on wing END
BEGIN NOW Came summond over EDEN to receive END
BEGIN NOW Thir names of thee; so over many a tract END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'n they march'd, and many a Province wide END
BEGIN NOW Tenfold the length of this terrene: at last END
BEGIN NOW Farr in th' Horizon to the North appeer'd END
BEGIN NOW From skirt to skirt a fierie Region, stretcht END
BEGIN NOW In battailous aspect, and neerer view END
BEGIN NOW Bristl'd with upright beams innumerable END
BEGIN NOW Of rigid Spears, and Helmets throng'd, and Shields END
BEGIN NOW Various, with boastful Argument portraid, END
BEGIN NOW The banded Powers of SATAN hasting on END
BEGIN NOW With furious expedition; for they weend END
BEGIN NOW That self same day by fight, or by surprize END
BEGIN NOW To set the envier of his State, the proud END
BEGIN NOW Aspirer, but thir thoughts prov'd fond and vain END
BEGIN NOW In the mid way: though strange to us it seemd END
BEGIN NOW At first, that Angel should with Angel warr, END
BEGIN NOW And in fierce hosting meet, who wont to meet END
BEGIN NOW So oft in Festivals of joy and love END
BEGIN NOW Unanimous, as sons of one great Sire END
BEGIN NOW Hymning th' Eternal Father: but the shout END
BEGIN NOW Of Battel now began, and rushing sound END
BEGIN NOW Of onset ended soon each milder thought. END
BEGIN NOW High in the midst exalted as a God END
BEGIN NOW Th' Apostat in his Sun-bright Chariot sate END
BEGIN NOW Idol of Majestie Divine, enclos'd END
BEGIN NOW With Flaming Cherubim, and golden Shields; END
BEGIN NOW Then lighted from his gorgeous Throne, for now END
BEGIN NOW 'Twixt Host and Host but narrow space was left, END
BEGIN NOW A dreadful interval, and Front to Front END
BEGIN NOW Presented stood in terrible array END
BEGIN NOW Of hideous length: before the cloudie Van, END
BEGIN NOW On the rough edge of battel ere it joyn'd, END
BEGIN NOW SATAN with vast and haughtie strides advanc't, END
BEGIN NOW Came towring, armd in Adamant and Gold; END
BEGIN NOW ABDIEL that sight endur'd not, where he stood END
BEGIN NOW Among the mightiest, bent on highest deeds, END
BEGIN NOW And thus his own undaunted heart explores. END
BEGIN NOW O Heav'n! that such resemblance of the Highest END
BEGIN NOW Should yet remain, where faith and realtie END
BEGIN NOW Remain not; wherfore should not strength & might END
BEGIN NOW There fail where Vertue fails, or weakest prove END
BEGIN NOW Where boldest; though to sight unconquerable? END
BEGIN NOW His puissance, trusting in th' Almightie's aide, END
BEGIN NOW I mean to try, whose Reason I have tri'd END
BEGIN NOW Unsound and false; nor is it aught but just, END
BEGIN NOW That he who in debate of Truth hath won, END
BEGIN NOW Should win in Arms, in both disputes alike END
BEGIN NOW Victor; though brutish that contest and foule, END
BEGIN NOW When Reason hath to deal with force, yet so END
BEGIN NOW Most reason is that Reason overcome. END
BEGIN NOW So pondering, and from his armed Peers END
BEGIN NOW Forth stepping opposite, half way he met END
BEGIN NOW His daring foe, at this prevention more END
BEGIN NOW Incens't, and thus securely him defi'd. END
BEGIN NOW Proud, art thou met? thy hope was to have reacht END
BEGIN NOW The highth of thy aspiring unoppos'd, END
BEGIN NOW The Throne of God unguarded, and his side END
BEGIN NOW Abandond at the terror of thy Power END
BEGIN NOW Or potent tongue; fool, not to think how vain END
BEGIN NOW Against th' Omnipotent to rise in Arms; END
BEGIN NOW Who out of smallest things could without end END
BEGIN NOW Have rais'd incessant Armies to defeat END
BEGIN NOW Thy folly; or with solitarie hand END
BEGIN NOW Reaching beyond all limit, at one blow END
BEGIN NOW Unaided could have finisht thee, and whelmd END
BEGIN NOW Thy Legions under darkness; but thou seest END
BEGIN NOW All are not of thy Train; there be who Faith END
BEGIN NOW Prefer, and Pietie to God, though then END
BEGIN NOW To thee not visible, when I alone END
BEGIN NOW Seemd in thy World erroneous to dissent END
BEGIN NOW From all: my Sect thou seest, now learn too late END
BEGIN NOW How few somtimes may know, when thousands err. END
BEGIN NOW Whom the grand foe with scornful eye askance END
BEGIN NOW Thus answerd. Ill for thee, but in wisht houre END
BEGIN NOW Of my revenge, first sought for thou returnst END
BEGIN NOW From flight, seditious Angel, to receave END
BEGIN NOW Thy merited reward, the first assay END
BEGIN NOW Of this right hand provok't, since first that tongue END
BEGIN NOW Inspir'd with contradiction durst oppose END
BEGIN NOW A third part of the Gods, in Synod met END
BEGIN NOW Thir Deities to assert, who while they feel END
BEGIN NOW Vigour Divine within them, can allow END
BEGIN NOW Omnipotence to none. But well thou comst END
BEGIN NOW Before thy fellows, ambitious to win END
BEGIN NOW From me som Plume, that thy success may show END
BEGIN NOW Destruction to the rest: this pause between END
BEGIN NOW (Unanswerd least thou boast) to let thee know; END
BEGIN NOW At first I thought that Libertie and Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW To heav'nly Soules had bin all one; but now END
BEGIN NOW I see that most through sloth had rather serve, END
BEGIN NOW Ministring Spirits, traind up in Feast and Song; END
BEGIN NOW Such hast thou arm'd, the Minstrelsie of Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW Servilitie with freedom to contend, END
BEGIN NOW As both thir deeds compar'd this day shall prove. END
BEGIN NOW To whom in brief thus ABDIEL stern repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Apostat, still thou errst, nor end wilt find END
BEGIN NOW Of erring, from the path of truth remote: END
BEGIN NOW Unjustly thou deprav'st it with the name END
BEGIN NOW Of SERVITUDE to serve whom God ordains, END
BEGIN NOW Or Nature; God and Nature bid the same, END
BEGIN NOW When he who rules is worthiest, and excells END
BEGIN NOW Them whom he governs. This is servitude, END
BEGIN NOW To serve th' unwise, or him who hath rebelld END
BEGIN NOW Against his worthier, as thine now serve thee, END
BEGIN NOW Thy self not free, but to thy self enthrall'd; END
BEGIN NOW Yet leudly dar'st our ministring upbraid. END
BEGIN NOW Reign thou in Hell thy Kingdom, let mee serve END
BEGIN NOW In Heav'n God ever blessed, and his Divine END
BEGIN NOW Behests obey, worthiest to be obey'd, END
BEGIN NOW Yet Chains in Hell, not Realms expect: mean while END
BEGIN NOW From mee returnd, as erst thou saidst, from flight, END
BEGIN NOW This greeting on thy impious Crest receive. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, a noble stroke he lifted high, END
BEGIN NOW Which hung not, but so swift with tempest fell END
BEGIN NOW On the proud Crest of SATAN, that no sight, END
BEGIN NOW Nor motion of swift thought, less could his Shield END
BEGIN NOW Such ruin intercept: ten paces huge END
BEGIN NOW He back recoild; the tenth on bended knee END
BEGIN NOW His massie Spear upstaid; as if on Earth END
BEGIN NOW Winds under ground or waters forcing way END
BEGIN NOW Sidelong, had push't a Mountain from his seat END
BEGIN NOW Half sunk with all his Pines. Amazement seis'd END
BEGIN NOW The Rebel Thrones, but greater rage to see END
BEGIN NOW Thus foil'd thir mightiest, ours joy filld, and shout, END
BEGIN NOW Presage of Victorie and fierce desire END
BEGIN NOW Of Battel: whereat MICHAEL bid sound END
BEGIN NOW Th' Arch-Angel trumpet; through the vast of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW It sounded, and the faithful Armies rung END
BEGIN NOW HOSANNA to the Highest: nor stood at gaze END
BEGIN NOW The adverse Legions, nor less hideous joyn'd END
BEGIN NOW The horrid shock: now storming furie rose, END
BEGIN NOW And clamour such as heard in Heav'n till now END
BEGIN NOW Was never, Arms on Armour clashing bray'd END
BEGIN NOW Horrible discord, and the madding Wheeles END
BEGIN NOW Of brazen Chariots rag'd; dire was the noise END
BEGIN NOW Of conflict; over head the dismal hiss END
BEGIN NOW Of fiery Darts in flaming volies flew, END
BEGIN NOW And flying vaulted either Host with fire. END
BEGIN NOW Sounder fierie Cope together rush'd END
BEGIN NOW Both Battels maine, with ruinous assault END
BEGIN NOW And inextinguishable rage; all Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Resounded, and had Earth bin then, all Earth END
BEGIN NOW Had to her Center shook. What wonder? when END
BEGIN NOW Millions of fierce encountring Angels fought END
BEGIN NOW On either side, the least of whom could weild END
BEGIN NOW These Elements, and arm him with the force END
BEGIN NOW Of all thir Regions: how much more of Power END
BEGIN NOW Armie against Armie numberless to raise END
BEGIN NOW Dreadful combustion warring, and disturb, END
BEGIN NOW Though not destroy, thir happie Native seat; END
BEGIN NOW From his strong hold of Heav'n high over-rul'd END
BEGIN NOW And limited thir might; though numberd such END
BEGIN NOW As each divided Legion might have seemd END
BEGIN NOW A numerous Host, in strength each armed hand END
BEGIN NOW A Legion; led in fight, yet Leader seemd END
BEGIN NOW Each Warriour single as in Chief, expert END
BEGIN NOW When to advance, or stand, or turn the sway END
BEGIN NOW Of Battel, open when, and when to close END
BEGIN NOW The ridges of grim Warr; no thought of flight, END
BEGIN NOW None of retreat, no unbecoming deed END
BEGIN NOW That argu'd fear; each on himself reli'd, END
BEGIN NOW As onely in his arm the moment lay END
BEGIN NOW Of victorie; deeds of eternal fame END
BEGIN NOW Were don, but infinite: for wide was spred END
BEGIN NOW That Warr and various; somtimes on firm ground END
BEGIN NOW A standing fight, then soaring on main wing END
BEGIN NOW Tormented all the Air; all Air seemd then END
BEGIN NOW Conflicting Fire: long time in eeven scale END
BEGIN NOW The Battel hung; till SATAN, who that day END
BEGIN NOW Prodigious power had shewn, and met in Armes END
BEGIN NOW No equal, raunging through the dire attack END
BEGIN NOW Of fighting Seraphim confus'd, at length END
BEGIN NOW Saw where the Sword of MICHAEL smote, and fell'd END
BEGIN NOW Squadrons at once, with huge two-handed sway END
BEGIN NOW Brandisht aloft the horrid edge came down END
BEGIN NOW Wide wasting; such destruction to withstand END
BEGIN NOW He hasted, and oppos'd the rockie Orb END
BEGIN NOW Of tenfold Adamant, his ample Shield END
BEGIN NOW A vast circumference: At his approach END
BEGIN NOW The great Arch-Angel from his warlike toile END
BEGIN NOW Surceas'd, and glad as hoping here to end END
BEGIN NOW Intestine War in Heav'n, the arch foe subdu'd END
BEGIN NOW Or Captive drag'd in Chains, with hostile frown END
BEGIN NOW And visage all enflam'd first thus began. END
BEGIN NOW Author of evil, unknown till thy revolt, END
BEGIN NOW Unnam'd in Heav'n, now plenteous, as thou seest END
BEGIN NOW These Acts of hateful strife, hateful to all, END
BEGIN NOW Though heaviest by just measure on thy self END
BEGIN NOW And thy adherents: how hast thou disturb'd END
BEGIN NOW Heav'ns blessed peace, and into Nature brought END
BEGIN NOW Miserie, uncreated till the crime END
BEGIN NOW Of thy Rebellion? how hast thou instill'd END
BEGIN NOW Thy malice into thousands, once upright END
BEGIN NOW And faithful, now prov'd false. But think not here END
BEGIN NOW To trouble Holy Rest; Heav'n casts thee out END
BEGIN NOW From all her Confines. Heav'n the seat of bliss END
BEGIN NOW Brooks not the works of violence and Warr. END
BEGIN NOW Hence then, and evil go with thee along END
BEGIN NOW Thy ofspring, to the place of evil, Hell, END
BEGIN NOW Thou and thy wicked crew; there mingle broiles, END
BEGIN NOW Ere this avenging Sword begin thy doome, END
BEGIN NOW Or som more sudden vengeance wing'd from God END
BEGIN NOW Precipitate thee with augmented paine. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Prince of Angels; to whom thus END
BEGIN NOW The Adversarie. Nor think thou with wind END
BEGIN NOW Of airie threats to aw whom yet with deeds END
BEGIN NOW Thou canst not. Hast thou turnd the least of these END
BEGIN NOW To flight, or if to fall, but that they rise END
BEGIN NOW Unvanquisht, easier to transact with mee END
BEGIN NOW That thou shouldst hope, imperious, & with threats END
BEGIN NOW To chase me hence? erre not that so shall end END
BEGIN NOW The strife which thou call'st evil, but wee style END
BEGIN NOW The strife of Glorie: which we mean to win, END
BEGIN NOW Or turn this Heav'n it self into the Hell END
BEGIN NOW Thou fablest, here however to dwell free, END
BEGIN NOW If not to reign: mean while thy utmost force, END
BEGIN NOW And join him nam'd ALMIGHTIE to thy aid, END
BEGIN NOW I flie not, but have sought thee farr and nigh. END
BEGIN NOW They ended parle, and both addrest for fight END
BEGIN NOW Unspeakable; for who, though with the tongue END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels, can relate, or to what things END
BEGIN NOW Liken on Earth conspicuous, that may lift END
BEGIN NOW Human imagination to such highth END
BEGIN NOW Of Godlike Power: for likest Gods they seemd, END
BEGIN NOW Stood they or mov'd, in stature, motion, arms END
BEGIN NOW Fit to decide the Empire of great Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW Now wav'd thir fierie Swords, and in the Aire END
BEGIN NOW Made horrid Circles; two broad Suns thir Shields END
BEGIN NOW Blaz'd opposite, while expectation stood END
BEGIN NOW In horror; from each hand with speed retir'd END
BEGIN NOW Where erst was thickest fight, th' Angelic throng, END
BEGIN NOW And left large field, unsafe within the wind END
BEGIN NOW Of such commotion, such as to set forth END
BEGIN NOW Great things by small, If Natures concord broke, END
BEGIN NOW Among the Constellations warr were sprung, END
BEGIN NOW Two Planets rushing from aspect maligne END
BEGIN NOW Of fiercest opposition in mid Skie, END
BEGIN NOW Should combat, and thir jarring Sphears confound. END
BEGIN NOW Together both with next to Almightie Arme, END
BEGIN NOW Uplifted imminent one stroke they aim'd END
BEGIN NOW That might determine, and not need repeate, END
BEGIN NOW As not of power, at once; nor odds appeerd END
BEGIN NOW In might or swift prevention; but the sword END
BEGIN NOW Of MICHAEL from the Armorie of God END
BEGIN NOW Was giv'n him temperd so, that neither keen END
BEGIN NOW Nor solid might resist that edge: it met END
BEGIN NOW The sword of SATAN with steep force to smite END
BEGIN NOW Descending, and in half cut sheere, nor staid, END
BEGIN NOW But with swift wheele reverse, deep entring shar'd END
BEGIN NOW All his right side; then SATAN first knew pain, END
BEGIN NOW And writh'd him to and fro convolv'd; so sore END
BEGIN NOW The griding sword with discontinuous wound END
BEGIN NOW Pass'd through him, but th' Ethereal substance clos'd END
BEGIN NOW Not long divisible, and from the gash END
BEGIN NOW A stream of Nectarous humor issuing flow'd END
BEGIN NOW Sanguin, such as Celestial Spirits may bleed, END
BEGIN NOW And all his Armour staind ere while so bright. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith on all sides to his aide was run END
BEGIN NOW By Angels many and strong, who interpos'd END
BEGIN NOW Defence, while others bore him on thir Shields END
BEGIN NOW Back to his Chariot; where it stood retir'd END
BEGIN NOW From off the files of warr; there they him laid END
BEGIN NOW Gnashing for anguish and despite and shame END
BEGIN NOW To find himself not matchless, and his pride END
BEGIN NOW Humbl'd by such rebuke, so farr beneath END
BEGIN NOW His confidence to equal God in power. END
BEGIN NOW Yet soon he heal'd; for Spirits that live throughout END
BEGIN NOW Vital in every part, not as frail man END
BEGIN NOW Cannot but by annihilating die; END
BEGIN NOW Nor in thir liquid texture mortal wound END
BEGIN NOW Receive, no more then can the fluid Aire: END
BEGIN NOW All Heart they live, all Head, all Eye, all Eare, END
BEGIN NOW All Intellect, all Sense, and as they please, END
BEGIN NOW They Limb themselves, and colour, shape or size END
BEGIN NOW Assume, as likes them best, condense or rare. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while in other parts like deeds deservd END
BEGIN NOW Memorial, where the might of GABRIEL fought, END
BEGIN NOW And with fierce Ensignes pierc'd the deep array END
BEGIN NOW Of MOLOC furious King, who him defi'd, END
BEGIN NOW And at his Chariot wheeles to drag him bound END
BEGIN NOW Threatn'd, nor from the Holie One of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Refrein'd his tongue blasphemous; but anon END
BEGIN NOW Down clov'n to the waste, with shatterd Armes END
BEGIN NOW And uncouth paine fled bellowing. On each wing END
BEGIN NOW URIEL and RAPHAEL his vaunting foe, END
BEGIN NOW Though huge, and in a Rock of Diamond Armd, END
BEGIN NOW Vanquish'd ADRAMELEC, and ASMADAI, END
BEGIN NOW Two potent Thrones, that to be less then Gods END
BEGIN NOW Disdain'd, but meaner thoughts learnd in thir flight, END
BEGIN NOW Mangl'd with gastly wounds through Plate and Maile. END
BEGIN NOW Nor stood unmindful ABDIEL to annoy END
BEGIN NOW The Atheist crew, but with redoubl'd blow END
BEGIN NOW ARIEL and ARIOC, and the violence END
BEGIN NOW Of RAMIEL scorcht and blasted overthrew. END
BEGIN NOW I might relate of thousands, and thir names END
BEGIN NOW Eternize here on Earth; but those elect END
BEGIN NOW Angels contented with thir fame in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Seek not the praise of men: the other sort END
BEGIN NOW In might though wondrous and in Acts of Warr, END
BEGIN NOW Nor of Renown less eager, yet by doome END
BEGIN NOW Canceld from Heav'n and sacred memorie, END
BEGIN NOW Nameless in dark oblivion let them dwell. END
BEGIN NOW For strength from Truth divided and from Just, END
BEGIN NOW Illaudable, naught merits but dispraise END
BEGIN NOW And ignominie, yet to glorie aspires END
BEGIN NOW Vain glorious, and through infamie seeks fame: END
BEGIN NOW Therfore Eternal silence be thir doome. END
BEGIN NOW And now thir mightiest quelld, the battel swerv'd, END
BEGIN NOW With many an inrode gor'd; deformed rout END
BEGIN NOW Enter'd, and foul disorder; all the ground END
BEGIN NOW With shiverd armour strow'n, and on a heap END
BEGIN NOW Chariot and Charioter lay overturnd END
BEGIN NOW And fierie foaming Steeds; what stood, recoyld END
BEGIN NOW Orewearied, through the faint Satanic Host END
BEGIN NOW Defensive scarse, or with pale fear surpris'd, END
BEGIN NOW Then first with fear surpris'd and sense of paine END
BEGIN NOW Fled ignominious, to such evil brought END
BEGIN NOW By sinne of disobedience, till that hour END
BEGIN NOW Not liable to fear or flight or paine. END
BEGIN NOW Far otherwise th' inviolable Saints END
BEGIN NOW In Cubic Phalanx firm advanc't entire, END
BEGIN NOW Invulnerable, impenitrably arm'd: END
BEGIN NOW Such high advantages thir innocence END
BEGIN NOW Gave them above thir foes, not to have sinnd, END
BEGIN NOW Not to have disobei'd; in fight they stood END
BEGIN NOW Unwearied, unobnoxious to be pain'd END
BEGIN NOW By wound, though from thir place by violence mov'd. END
BEGIN NOW Now Night her course began, and over Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Inducing darkness, grateful truce impos'd, END
BEGIN NOW And silence on the odious dinn of Warr: END
BEGIN NOW Under her Cloudie covert both retir'd, END
BEGIN NOW Victor and Vanquisht: on the foughten field END
BEGIN NOW MICHAEL and his Angels prevalent END
BEGIN NOW Encamping, plac'd in Guard thir Watches round, END
BEGIN NOW Cherubic waving fires: on th' other part END
BEGIN NOW SATAN with his rebellious disappeerd, END
BEGIN NOW Far in the dark dislodg'd, and void of rest, END
BEGIN NOW His Potentates to Councel call'd by night; END
BEGIN NOW And in the midst thus undismai'd began. END
BEGIN NOW O now in danger tri'd, now known in Armes END
BEGIN NOW Not to be overpowerd, Companions deare, END
BEGIN NOW Found worthy not of Libertie alone, END
BEGIN NOW Too mean pretense, but what we more affect, END
BEGIN NOW Honour, Dominion, Glorie, and renowne, END
BEGIN NOW Who have sustaind one day in doubtful fight, END
BEGIN NOW (And if one day, why not Eternal dayes?) END
BEGIN NOW What Heavens Lord had powerfullest to send END
BEGIN NOW Against us from about his Throne, and judg'd END
BEGIN NOW Sufficient to subdue us to his will, END
BEGIN NOW But proves not so: then fallible, it seems, END
BEGIN NOW Of future we may deem him, though till now END
BEGIN NOW Omniscient thought. True is, less firmly arm'd, END
BEGIN NOW Some disadvantage we endur'd and paine, END
BEGIN NOW Till now not known, but known as soon contemnd, END
BEGIN NOW Since now we find this our Empyreal forme END
BEGIN NOW Incapable of mortal injurie END
BEGIN NOW Imperishable, and though peirc'd with wound, END
BEGIN NOW Soon closing, and by native vigour heal'd. END
BEGIN NOW Of evil then so small as easie think END
BEGIN NOW The remedie; perhaps more valid Armes, END
BEGIN NOW Weapons more violent, when next we meet, END
BEGIN NOW May serve to better us, and worse our foes, END
BEGIN NOW Or equal what between us made the odds, END
BEGIN NOW In Nature none: if other hidden cause END
BEGIN NOW Left them Superiour, while we can preserve END
BEGIN NOW Unhurt our mindes, and understanding sound, END
BEGIN NOW Due search and consultation will disclose. END
BEGIN NOW He sat; and in th' assembly next upstood END
BEGIN NOW NISROC, of Principalities the prime; END
BEGIN NOW As one he stood escap't from cruel fight, END
BEGIN NOW Sore toild, his riv'n Armes to havoc hewn, END
BEGIN NOW And cloudie in aspect thus answering spake. END
BEGIN NOW Deliverer from new Lords, leader to free END
BEGIN NOW Enjoyment of our right as Gods; yet hard END
BEGIN NOW For Gods, and too unequal work we find END
BEGIN NOW Against unequal armes to fight in paine, END
BEGIN NOW Against unpaind, impassive; from which evil END
BEGIN NOW Ruin must needs ensue; for what availes END
BEGIN NOW Valour or strength, though matchless, quelld with pain END
BEGIN NOW Which all subdues, and makes remiss the hands END
BEGIN NOW Of Mightiest. Sense of pleasure we may well END
BEGIN NOW Spare out of life perhaps, and not repine, END
BEGIN NOW But live content, which is the calmest life: END
BEGIN NOW But pain is perfet miserie, the worst END
BEGIN NOW Of evils, and excessive, overturnes END
BEGIN NOW All patience. He who therefore can invent END
BEGIN NOW With what more forcible we may offend END
BEGIN NOW Our yet unwounded Enemies, or arme END
BEGIN NOW Our selves with like defence, to mee deserves END
BEGIN NOW No less then for deliverance what we owe. END
BEGIN NOW Whereto with look compos'd SATAN repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Not uninvented that, which thou aright END
BEGIN NOW Beleivst so main to our success, I bring; END
BEGIN NOW Which of us who beholds the bright surface END
BEGIN NOW Of this Ethereous mould whereon we stand, END
BEGIN NOW This continent of spacious Heav'n, adornd END
BEGIN NOW Whose Eye so superficially surveyes END
BEGIN NOW These things, as not to mind from whence they grow END
BEGIN NOW Deep under ground, materials dark and crude, END
BEGIN NOW Of spiritous and fierie spume, till toucht END
BEGIN NOW With Heav'ns ray, and temperd they shoot forth END
BEGIN NOW So beauteous, op'ning to the ambient light. END
BEGIN NOW These in thir dark Nativitie the Deep END
BEGIN NOW Shall yeild us, pregnant with infernal flame, END
BEGIN NOW Which into hallow Engins long and round END
BEGIN NOW Thick-rammd, at th' other bore with touch of fire END
BEGIN NOW Dilated and infuriate shall send forth END
BEGIN NOW From far with thundring noise among our foes END
BEGIN NOW Such implements of mischief as shall dash END
BEGIN NOW To pieces, and orewhelm whatever stands END
BEGIN NOW Adverse, that they shall fear we have disarmd END
BEGIN NOW The Thunderer of his only dreaded bolt. END
BEGIN NOW Nor long shall be our labour, yet ere dawne, END
BEGIN NOW Effect shall end our wish. Mean while revive; END
BEGIN NOW Abandon fear; to strength and counsel joind END
BEGIN NOW Think nothing hard, much less to be despaird. END
BEGIN NOW He ended, and his words thir drooping chere END
BEGIN NOW Enlightn'd, and thir languisht hope reviv'd. END
BEGIN NOW Th' invention all admir'd, and each, how hee END
BEGIN NOW To be th' inventer miss'd, so easie it seemd END
BEGIN NOW Once found, which yet unfound most would have thought END
BEGIN NOW Impossible: yet haply of thy Race END
BEGIN NOW In future dayes, if Malice should abound, END
BEGIN NOW Some one intent on mischief, or inspir'd END
BEGIN NOW With dev'lish machination might devise END
BEGIN NOW Like instrument to plague the Sons of men END
BEGIN NOW For sin, on warr and mutual slaughter bent. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith from Councel to the work they flew, END
BEGIN NOW None arguing stood, innumerable hands END
BEGIN NOW Were ready, in a moment up they turnd END
BEGIN NOW Wide the Celestial soile, and saw beneath END
BEGIN NOW Th' originals of Nature in thir crude END
BEGIN NOW They found, they mingl'd, and with suttle Art, END
BEGIN NOW Concocted and adusted they reduc'd END
BEGIN NOW To blackest grain, and into store conveyd: END
BEGIN NOW Part hidd'n veins diggd up (nor hath this Earth END
BEGIN NOW Entrails unlike) of Mineral and Stone, END
BEGIN NOW Whereof to found thir Engins and thir Balls END
BEGIN NOW Of missive ruin; part incentive reed END
BEGIN NOW Provide, pernicious with one touch to fire. END
BEGIN NOW So all ere day spring, under conscious Night END
BEGIN NOW Secret they finish'd, and in order set, END
BEGIN NOW With silent circumspection unespi'd. END
BEGIN NOW Now when fair Morn Orient in Heav'n appeerd END
BEGIN NOW Up rose the Victor Angels, and to Arms END
BEGIN NOW The matin Trumpet Sung: in Arms they stood END
BEGIN NOW Of Golden Panoplie, refulgent Host, END
BEGIN NOW Soon banded; others from the dawning Hills END
BEGIN NOW Lookd round, and Scouts each Coast light-armed scoure, END
BEGIN NOW Each quarter, to descrie the distant foe, END
BEGIN NOW Where lodg'd, or whither fled, or if for fight, END
BEGIN NOW In motion or in alt: him soon they met END
BEGIN NOW Under spred Ensignes moving nigh, in slow END
BEGIN NOW But firm Battalion; back with speediest Sail END
BEGIN NOW ZEPHIEL, of Cherubim the swiftest wing, END
BEGIN NOW Came flying, and in mid Aire aloud thus cri'd. END
BEGIN NOW Arme, Warriours, Arme for fight, the foe at hand, END
BEGIN NOW Whom fled we thought, will save us long pursuit END
BEGIN NOW This day, fear not his flight; so thick a Cloud END
BEGIN NOW He comes, and settl'd in his face I see END
BEGIN NOW Sad resolution and secure: let each END
BEGIN NOW His Adamantine coat gird well, and each END
BEGIN NOW Fit well his Helme, gripe fast his orbed Shield, END
BEGIN NOW Born eevn or high, for this day will pour down, END
BEGIN NOW If I conjecture aught, no drizling showr, END
BEGIN NOW But ratling storm of Arrows barbd with fire. END
BEGIN NOW So warnd he them aware themselves, and soon END
BEGIN NOW In order, quit of all impediment; END
BEGIN NOW Instant without disturb they took Allarm, END
BEGIN NOW And onward move Embattelld; when behold END
BEGIN NOW Not distant far with heavie pace the Foe END
BEGIN NOW Approaching gross and huge; in hollow Cube END
BEGIN NOW Training his devilish Enginrie, impal'd END
BEGIN NOW On every side with shaddowing Squadrons Deep, END
BEGIN NOW To hide the fraud. At interview both stood END
BEGIN NOW A while, but suddenly at head appeerd END
BEGIN NOW SATAN: And thus was heard Commanding loud. END
BEGIN NOW Vangard, to Right and Left the Front unfould; END
BEGIN NOW That all may see who hate us, how we seek END
BEGIN NOW Peace and composure, and with open brest END
BEGIN NOW Stand readie to receive them, if they like END
BEGIN NOW Our overture, and turn not back perverse; END
BEGIN NOW But that I doubt, however witness Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Heav'n witness thou anon, while we discharge END
BEGIN NOW Freely our part: yee who appointed stand END
BEGIN NOW Do as you have in charge, and briefly touch END
BEGIN NOW What we propound, and loud that all may hear. END
BEGIN NOW So scoffing in ambiguous words, he scarce END
BEGIN NOW Had ended; when to Right and Left the Front END
BEGIN NOW Divided, and to either Flank retir'd. END
BEGIN NOW Which to our eyes discoverd new and strange, END
BEGIN NOW A triple-mounted row of Pillars laid END
BEGIN NOW On Wheels (for like to Pillars most they seem'd END
BEGIN NOW Or hollow'd bodies made of Oak or Firr END
BEGIN NOW With branches lopt, in Wood or Mountain fell'd) END
BEGIN NOW Brass, Iron, Stonie mould, had not thir mouthes END
BEGIN NOW With hideous orifice gap't on us wide, END
BEGIN NOW Portending hollow truce; at each behind END
BEGIN NOW A Seraph stood, and in his hand a Reed END
BEGIN NOW Stood waving tipt with fire; while we suspense, END
BEGIN NOW Collected stood within our thoughts amus'd, END
BEGIN NOW Not long, for sudden all at once thir Reeds END
BEGIN NOW Put forth, and to a narrow vent appli'd END
BEGIN NOW With nicest touch. Immediate in a flame, END
BEGIN NOW But soon obscur'd with smoak, all Heav'n appeerd, END
BEGIN NOW From those deep-throated Engins belcht, whose roar END
BEGIN NOW Emboweld with outragious noise the Air, END
BEGIN NOW And all her entrails tore, disgorging foule END
BEGIN NOW Thir devillish glut, chaind Thunderbolts and Hail END
BEGIN NOW Of Iron Globes, which on the Victor Host END
BEGIN NOW Level'd, with such impetuous furie smote, END
BEGIN NOW That whom they hit, none on thir feet might stand, END
BEGIN NOW Though standing else as Rocks, but down they fell END
BEGIN NOW By thousands, Angel on Arch-Angel rowl'd; END
BEGIN NOW The sooner for thir Arms, unarm'd they might END
BEGIN NOW Have easily as Spirits evaded swift END
BEGIN NOW By quick contraction or remove; but now END
BEGIN NOW Foule dissipation follow'd and forc't rout; END
BEGIN NOW Nor serv'd it to relax thir serried files. END
BEGIN NOW What should they do? if on they rusht, repulse END
BEGIN NOW Repeated, and indecent overthrow END
BEGIN NOW Doubl'd, would render them yet more despis'd, END
BEGIN NOW And to thir foes a laughter; for in view END
BEGIN NOW Stood rankt of Seraphim another row END
BEGIN NOW In posture to displode thir second tire END
BEGIN NOW Of Thunder: back defeated to return END
BEGIN NOW They worse abhorr'd. SATAN beheld thir plight, END
BEGIN NOW And to his Mates thus in derision call'd. END
BEGIN NOW O Friends, why come not on these Victors proud? END
BEGIN NOW Ere while they fierce were coming, and when wee, END
BEGIN NOW To entertain them fair with open Front END
BEGIN NOW And Brest, (what could we more?) propounded terms END
BEGIN NOW Of composition, strait they chang'd thir minds, END
BEGIN NOW Flew off, and into strange vagaries fell, END
BEGIN NOW As they would dance, yet for a dance they seemd END
BEGIN NOW Somwhat extravagant and wilde, perhaps END
BEGIN NOW For joy of offerd peace: but I suppose END
BEGIN NOW If our proposals once again were heard END
BEGIN NOW We should compel them to a quick result. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus BELIAL in like gamesom mood. END
BEGIN NOW Leader, the terms we sent were terms of weight, END
BEGIN NOW Of hard contents, and full of force urg'd home, END
BEGIN NOW Such as we might perceive amus'd them all, END
BEGIN NOW And stumbl'd many, who receives them right, END
BEGIN NOW Had need from head to foot well understand; END
BEGIN NOW Not understood, this gift they have besides, END
BEGIN NOW They shew us when our foes walk not upright. END
BEGIN NOW So they among themselves in pleasant veine END
BEGIN NOW Stood scoffing, highthn'd in thir thoughts beyond END
BEGIN NOW All doubt of Victorie, eternal might END
BEGIN NOW To match with thir inventions they presum'd END
BEGIN NOW So easie, and of his Thunder made a scorn, END
BEGIN NOW And all his Host derided, while they stood END
BEGIN NOW A while in trouble; but they stood not long, END
BEGIN NOW Rage prompted them at length, & found them arms END
BEGIN NOW Against such hellish mischief fit to oppose. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith (behold the excellence, the power END
BEGIN NOW Which God hath in his mighty Angels plac'd) END
BEGIN NOW Thir Arms away they threw, and to the Hills END
BEGIN NOW (For Earth hath this variety from Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Of pleasure situate in Hill and Dale) END
BEGIN NOW Light as the Lightning glimps they ran, they flew, END
BEGIN NOW From thir foundations loosning to and fro END
BEGIN NOW They pluckt the seated Hills with all thir load, END
BEGIN NOW Rocks, Waters, Woods, and by the shaggie tops END
BEGIN NOW Up lifting bore them in thir hands: Amaze, END
BEGIN NOW Be sure, and terrour seis'd the rebel Host, END
BEGIN NOW When coming towards them so dread they saw END
BEGIN NOW The bottom of the Mountains upward turn'd, END
BEGIN NOW Till on those cursed Engins triple-row END
BEGIN NOW They saw them whelmd, and all thir confidence END
BEGIN NOW Under the weight of Mountains buried deep, END
BEGIN NOW Themselves invaded next, and on thir heads END
BEGIN NOW Main Promontories flung, which in the Air END
BEGIN NOW Came shadowing, and opprest whole Legions arm'd, END
BEGIN NOW Thir armor help'd thir harm, crush't in and brus'd END
BEGIN NOW Into thir substance pent, which wrought them pain END
BEGIN NOW Implacable, and many a dolorous groan, END
BEGIN NOW Long strugling underneath, ere they could wind END
BEGIN NOW Out of such prison, though Spirits of purest light, END
BEGIN NOW Purest at first, now gross by sinning grown. END
BEGIN NOW The rest in imitation to like Armes END
BEGIN NOW Betook them, and the neighbouring Hills uptore; END
BEGIN NOW So Hills amid the Air encounterd Hills END
BEGIN NOW Hurl'd to and fro with jaculation dire, END
BEGIN NOW That under ground they fought in dismal shade; END
BEGIN NOW Infernal noise; Warr seem'd a civil Game END
BEGIN NOW To this uproar; horrid confusion heapt END
BEGIN NOW Upon confusion rose: and now all Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Had gone to wrack, with ruin overspred, END
BEGIN NOW Had not th' Almightie Father where he sits END
BEGIN NOW Shrin'd in his Sanctuarie of Heav'n secure, END
BEGIN NOW Consulting on the sum of things, foreseen END
BEGIN NOW This tumult, and permitted all, advis'd: END
BEGIN NOW That his great purpose he might so fulfill, END
BEGIN NOW To honour his Anointed Son aveng'd END
BEGIN NOW Upon his enemies, and to declare END
BEGIN NOW All power on him transferr'd: whence to his Son END
BEGIN NOW Th' Assessor of his Throne he thus began. END
BEGIN NOW Effulgence of my Glorie, Son belov'd, END
BEGIN NOW Son in whose face invisible is beheld END
BEGIN NOW Visibly, what by Deitie I am, END
BEGIN NOW And in whose hand what by Decree I doe, END
BEGIN NOW Second Omnipotence, two dayes are past, END
BEGIN NOW Two dayes, as we compute the dayes of Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW Since MICHAEL and his Powers went forth to tame END
BEGIN NOW These disobedient; sore hath been thir fight, END
BEGIN NOW As likeliest was, when two such Foes met arm'd; END
BEGIN NOW For to themselves I left them, and thou knowst, END
BEGIN NOW Equal in their Creation they were form'd, END
BEGIN NOW Save what sin hath impaird, which yet hath wrought END
BEGIN NOW Insensibly, for I suspend thir doom; END
BEGIN NOW Whence in perpetual fight they needs must last END
BEGIN NOW Endless, and no solution will be found: END
BEGIN NOW Warr wearied hath perform'd what Warr can do, END
BEGIN NOW And to disorder'd rage let loose the reines, END
BEGIN NOW With Mountains as with Weapons arm'd, which makes END
BEGIN NOW Wild work in Heav'n, and dangerous to the maine. END
BEGIN NOW Two dayes are therefore past, the third is thine; END
BEGIN NOW For thee I have ordain'd it, and thus farr END
BEGIN NOW Have sufferd, that the Glorie may be thine END
BEGIN NOW Of ending this great Warr, since none but Thou END
BEGIN NOW Can end it. Into thee such Vertue and Grace END
BEGIN NOW Immense I have transfus'd, that all may know END
BEGIN NOW In Heav'n and Hell thy Power above compare, END
BEGIN NOW And this perverse Commotion governd thus, END
BEGIN NOW To manifest thee worthiest to be Heir END
BEGIN NOW Of all things, to be Heir and to be King END
BEGIN NOW By Sacred Unction, thy deserved right. END
BEGIN NOW Go then thou Mightiest in thy Fathers might, END
BEGIN NOW Ascend my Chariot, guide the rapid Wheeles END
BEGIN NOW That shake Heav'ns basis, bring forth all my Warr, END
BEGIN NOW Gird on, and Sword upon thy puissant Thigh; END
BEGIN NOW Pursue these sons of Darkness, drive them out END
BEGIN NOW From all Heav'ns bounds into the utter Deep: END
BEGIN NOW There let them learn, as likes them, to despise END
BEGIN NOW God and MESSIAH his anointed King. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and on his Son with Rayes direct END
BEGIN NOW Shon full, he all his Father full exprest END
BEGIN NOW Ineffably into his face receiv'd, END
BEGIN NOW And thus the filial Godhead answering spake. END
BEGIN NOW O Father, O Supream of heav'nly Thrones, END
BEGIN NOW First, Highest, Holiest, Best, thou alwayes seekst END
BEGIN NOW To glorifie thy Son, I alwayes thee, END
BEGIN NOW As is most just; this I my Glorie account, END
BEGIN NOW My exaltation, and my whole delight, END
BEGIN NOW That thou in me well pleas'd, declarst thy will END
BEGIN NOW Fulfill'd, which to fulfil is all my bliss. END
BEGIN NOW Scepter and Power, thy giving, I assume, END
BEGIN NOW And gladlier shall resign, when in the end END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt be All in All, and I in thee END
BEGIN NOW For ever, and in mee all whom thou lov'st: END
BEGIN NOW But whom thou hat'st, I hate, and can put on END
BEGIN NOW Thy terrors, as I put thy mildness on, END
BEGIN NOW Image of thee in all things; and shall soon, END
BEGIN NOW Armd with thy might, rid heav'n of these rebell'd, END
BEGIN NOW To thir prepar'd ill Mansion driven down END
BEGIN NOW To chains of Darkness, and th' undying Worm, END
BEGIN NOW That from thy just obedience could revolt, END
BEGIN NOW Whom to obey is happiness entire. END
BEGIN NOW Then shall thy Saints unmixt, and from th' impure END
BEGIN NOW Farr separate, circling thy holy Mount END
BEGIN NOW Unfained HALLELUIAHS to thee sing, END
BEGIN NOW Hymns of high praise, and I among them chief. END
BEGIN NOW So said, he o're his Scepter bowing, rose END
BEGIN NOW From the right hand of Glorie where he sate, END
BEGIN NOW And the third sacred Morn began to shine END
BEGIN NOW Dawning through Heav'n: forth rush'd with whirlwind sound END
BEGIN NOW Flashing thick flames, Wheele within Wheele undrawn, END
BEGIN NOW It self instinct with Spirit, but convoyd END
BEGIN NOW By four Cherubic shapes, four Faces each END
BEGIN NOW Had wondrous, as with Starrs thir bodies all END
BEGIN NOW And Wings were set with Eyes, with Eyes the Wheels END
BEGIN NOW Of Beril, and careering Fires between; END
BEGIN NOW Over thir heads a chrystal Firmament, END
BEGIN NOW Whereon a Saphir Throne, inlaid with pure END
BEGIN NOW Amber, and colours of the showrie Arch. END
BEGIN NOW Hee in Celestial Panoplie all armd END
BEGIN NOW Of radiant URIM, work divinely wrought, END
BEGIN NOW Ascended, at his right hand Victorie END
BEGIN NOW Sate Eagle-wing'd, beside him hung his Bow END
BEGIN NOW And Quiver with three-bolted Thunder stor'd, END
BEGIN NOW And from about him fierce Effusion rowld END
BEGIN NOW Of smoak and bickering flame, and sparkles dire; END
BEGIN NOW Attended with ten thousand thousand Saints, END
BEGIN NOW He onward came, farr off his coming shon, END
BEGIN NOW And twentie thousand (I thir number heard) END
BEGIN NOW Chariots of God, half on each hand were seen: END
BEGIN NOW Hee on the wings of Cherub rode sublime END
BEGIN NOW On the Crystallin Skie, in Saphir Thron'd. END
BEGIN NOW Illustrious farr and wide, but by his own END
BEGIN NOW First seen, them unexpected joy surpriz'd, END
BEGIN NOW When the great Ensign of MESSIAH blaz'd END
BEGIN NOW Aloft by Angels born, his Sign in Heav'n: END
BEGIN NOW Under whose Conduct MICHAEL soon reduc'd END
BEGIN NOW His Armie, circumfus'd on either Wing, END
BEGIN NOW Under thir Head imbodied all in one. END
BEGIN NOW Before him Power Divine his way prepar'd; END
BEGIN NOW At his command the uprooted Hills retir'd END
BEGIN NOW Each to his place, they heard his voice and went END
BEGIN NOW Obsequious, Heav'n his wonted face renewd, END
BEGIN NOW And with fresh Flourets Hill and Valley smil'd. END
BEGIN NOW This saw his hapless Foes, but stood obdur'd, END
BEGIN NOW And to rebellious fight rallied thir Powers END
BEGIN NOW Insensate, hope conceiving from despair. END
BEGIN NOW In heav'nly Spirits could such perverseness dwell? END
BEGIN NOW But to convince the proud what Signs availe, END
BEGIN NOW Or Wonders move th' obdurate to relent? END
BEGIN NOW They hard'nd more by what might most reclame, END
BEGIN NOW Grieving to see his Glorie, at the sight END
BEGIN NOW Took envie, and aspiring to his highth, END
BEGIN NOW Stood reimbattell'd fierce, by force or fraud END
BEGIN NOW Weening to prosper, and at length prevaile END
BEGIN NOW Against God and MESSIAH, or to fall END
BEGIN NOW In universal ruin last, and now END
BEGIN NOW To final Battel drew, disdaining flight, END
BEGIN NOW Or faint retreat; when the great Son of God END
BEGIN NOW To all his Host on either hand thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW Stand still in bright array ye Saints, here stand END
BEGIN NOW Ye Angels arm'd, this day from Battel rest; END
BEGIN NOW Faithful hath been your Warfare, and of God END
BEGIN NOW Accepted, fearless in his righteous Cause, END
BEGIN NOW And as ye have receivd, so have ye don END
BEGIN NOW Invincibly; but of this cursed crew END
BEGIN NOW The punishment to other hand belongs, END
BEGIN NOW Vengeance is his, or whose he sole appoints; END
BEGIN NOW Number to this dayes work is not ordain'd END
BEGIN NOW Nor multitude, stand onely and behold END
BEGIN NOW Gods indignation on these Godless pourd END
BEGIN NOW By mee; not you but mee they have despis'd, END
BEGIN NOW Yet envied; against mee is all thir rage, END
BEGIN NOW Because the Father, t' whom in Heav'n supream END
BEGIN NOW Kingdom and Power and Glorie appertains, END
BEGIN NOW Hath honourd me according to his will. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore to mee thir doom he hath assig'n'd; END
BEGIN NOW That they may have thir wish, to trie with mee END
BEGIN NOW In Battel which the stronger proves, they all, END
BEGIN NOW Or I alone against them, since by strength END
BEGIN NOW They measure all, of other excellence END
BEGIN NOW Not emulous, nor care who them excells; END
BEGIN NOW Nor other strife with them do I voutsafe. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Son, and into terrour chang'd END
BEGIN NOW His count'nance too severe to be beheld END
BEGIN NOW And full of wrauth bent on his Enemies. END
BEGIN NOW At once the Four spred out thir Starrie wings END
BEGIN NOW With dreadful shade contiguous, and the Orbes END
BEGIN NOW Of his fierce Chariot rowld, as with the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of torrent Floods, or of a numerous Host. END
BEGIN NOW Hee on his impious Foes right onward drove, END
BEGIN NOW Gloomie as Night; under his burning Wheeles END
BEGIN NOW The stedfast Empyrean shook throughout, END
BEGIN NOW All but the Throne it self of God. Full soon END
BEGIN NOW Among them he arriv'd; in his right hand END
BEGIN NOW Grasping ten thousand Thunders, which he sent END
BEGIN NOW Before him, such as in thir Soules infix'd END
BEGIN NOW Plagues; they astonisht all resistance lost, END
BEGIN NOW All courage; down thir idle weapons drop'd; END
BEGIN NOW O're Shields and Helmes, and helmed heads he rode END
BEGIN NOW Of Thrones and mighty Seraphim prostrate, END
BEGIN NOW That wish'd the Mountains now might be again END
BEGIN NOW Thrown on them as a shelter from his ire. END
BEGIN NOW Nor less on either side tempestuous fell END
BEGIN NOW His arrows, from the fourfold-visag'd Foure, END
BEGIN NOW Distinct with eyes, and from the living Wheels, END
BEGIN NOW Distinct alike with multitude of eyes, END
BEGIN NOW One Spirit in them rul'd, and every eye END
BEGIN NOW Glar'd lightning, and shot forth pernicious fire END
BEGIN NOW Among th' accurst, that witherd all thir strength, END
BEGIN NOW And of thir wonted vigour left them draind, END
BEGIN NOW Exhausted, spiritless, afflicted, fall'n. END
BEGIN NOW Yet half his strength he put not forth, but check'd END
BEGIN NOW His Thunder in mid Volie, for he meant END
BEGIN NOW Not to destroy, but root them out of Heav'n: END
BEGIN NOW The overthrown he rais'd, and as a Heard END
BEGIN NOW Of Goats or timerous flock together throngd END
BEGIN NOW Drove them before him Thunder-struck, pursu'd END
BEGIN NOW With terrors and with furies to the bounds END
BEGIN NOW And Chrystall wall of Heav'n, which op'ning wide, END
BEGIN NOW Rowld inward, and a spacious Gap disclos'd END
BEGIN NOW Into the wastful Deep; the monstrous sight END
BEGIN NOW Strook them with horror backward, but far worse END
BEGIN NOW Urg'd them behind; headlong themselvs they threw END
BEGIN NOW Down from the verge of Heav'n, Eternal wrauth END
BEGIN NOW Burnt after them to the bottomless pit. END
BEGIN NOW Hell heard th' unsufferable noise, Hell saw END
BEGIN NOW Heav'n ruining from Heav'n and would have fled END
BEGIN NOW Affrighted; but strict Fate had cast too deep END
BEGIN NOW Her dark foundations, and too fast had bound. END
BEGIN NOW Nine dayes they fell; confounded CHAOS roard, END
BEGIN NOW And felt tenfold confusion in thir fall END
BEGIN NOW Through his wilde Anarchie, so huge a rout END
BEGIN NOW Incumberd him with ruin: Hell at last END
BEGIN NOW Yawning receavd them whole, and on them clos'd, END
BEGIN NOW Hell thir fit habitation fraught with fire END
BEGIN NOW Unquenchable, the house of woe and paine. END
BEGIN NOW Disburd'nd Heav'n rejoic'd, and soon repaird END
BEGIN NOW Her mural breach, returning whence it rowld. END
BEGIN NOW Sole Victor from th' expulsion of his Foes END
BEGIN NOW MESSIAH his triumphal Chariot turnd: END
BEGIN NOW To meet him all his Saints, who silent stood END
BEGIN NOW Eye witnesses of his Almightie Acts, END
BEGIN NOW With Jubilie advanc'd; and as they went, END
BEGIN NOW Shaded with branching Palme, each order bright, END
BEGIN NOW Sung Triumph, and him sung Victorious King, END
BEGIN NOW Son, Heire, and Lord, to him Dominion giv'n, END
BEGIN NOW Worthiest to Reign: he celebrated rode END
BEGIN NOW Triumphant through mid Heav'n, into the Courts END
BEGIN NOW And Temple of his mightie Father Thron'd END
BEGIN NOW On high; who into Glorie him receav'd, END
BEGIN NOW Where now he sits at the right hand of bliss. END
BEGIN NOW Thus measuring things in Heav'n by things on Earth END
BEGIN NOW At thy request, and that thou maist beware END
BEGIN NOW By what is past, to thee I have reveal'd END
BEGIN NOW What might have else to human Race bin hid; END
BEGIN NOW The discord which befel, and Warr in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Among th' Angelic Powers, and the deep fall END
BEGIN NOW Of those too high aspiring, who rebelld END
BEGIN NOW With SATAN, hee who envies now thy state, END
BEGIN NOW Who now is plotting how he may seduce END
BEGIN NOW Thee also from obedience, that with him END
BEGIN NOW Bereavd of happiness thou maist partake END
BEGIN NOW His punishment, Eternal miserie; END
BEGIN NOW Which would be all his solace and revenge, END
BEGIN NOW As a despite don against the most High, END
BEGIN NOW Thee once to gaine Companion of his woe. END
BEGIN NOW But list'n not to his Temptations, warne END
BEGIN NOW Thy weaker; let it profit thee to have heard END
BEGIN NOW By terrible Example the reward END
BEGIN NOW Of disobedience; firm they might have stood, END
BEGIN NOW Yet fell; remember, and fear to transgress. END
BEGIN NOW Descend from Heav'n URANIA, by that name END
BEGIN NOW If rightly thou art call'd, whose Voice divine END
BEGIN NOW Following, above th' OLYMPIAN Hill I soare, END
BEGIN NOW Above the flight of PEGASEAN wing. END
BEGIN NOW The meaning, not the Name I call: for thou END
BEGIN NOW Nor of the Muses nine, nor on the top END
BEGIN NOW Of old OLYMPUS dwell'st, but Heav'nlie borne, END
BEGIN NOW Before the Hills appeerd, or Fountain flow'd, END
BEGIN NOW Thou with Eternal wisdom didst converse, END
BEGIN NOW Wisdom thy Sister, and with her didst play END
BEGIN NOW In presence of th' Almightie Father, pleas'd END
BEGIN NOW With thy Celestial Song. Up led by thee END
BEGIN NOW Into the Heav'n of Heav'ns I have presum'd, END
BEGIN NOW An Earthlie Guest, and drawn Empyreal Aire, END
BEGIN NOW Thy tempring; with like safetie guided down END
BEGIN NOW Least from this flying Steed unrein'd, (as once END
BEGIN NOW BELLEROPHON, though from a lower Clime) END
BEGIN NOW Dismounted, on th' ALEIAN Field I fall END
BEGIN NOW Erroneous, there to wander and forlorne. END
BEGIN NOW Half yet remaines unsung, but narrower bound END
BEGIN NOW Within the visible Diurnal Spheare; END
BEGIN NOW Standing on Earth, not rapt above the Pole, END
BEGIN NOW More safe I Sing with mortal voice, unchang'd END
BEGIN NOW To hoarce or mute, though fall'n on evil dayes, END
BEGIN NOW On evil dayes though fall'n, and evil tongues; END
BEGIN NOW In darkness, and with dangers compast rouud, END
BEGIN NOW And solitude; yet not alone, while thou END
BEGIN NOW Visit'st my slumbers Nightly, or when Morn END
BEGIN NOW Purples the East: still govern thou my Song, END
BEGIN NOW URANIA, and fit audience find, though few. END
BEGIN NOW But drive farr off the barbarous dissonance END
BEGIN NOW Of BACCHUS and his Revellers, the Race END
BEGIN NOW Of that wilde Rout that tore the THRACIAN Bard END
BEGIN NOW In RHODOPE, where Woods and Rocks had Eares END
BEGIN NOW To rapture, till the savage clamor dround END
BEGIN NOW Both Harp and Voice; nor could the Muse defend END
BEGIN NOW Her Son. So fail not thou, who thee implores: END
BEGIN NOW For thou art Heav'nlie, shee an empty dreame. END
BEGIN NOW Say Goddess, what ensu'd when RAPHAEL, END
BEGIN NOW The affable Arch-angel, had forewarn'd END
BEGIN NOW ADAM by dire example to beware END
BEGIN NOW Apostasie, by what befell in Heaven END
BEGIN NOW To those Apostates, least the like befall END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise to ADAM or his Race, END
BEGIN NOW Charg'd not to touch the interdicted Tree, END
BEGIN NOW If they transgress, and slight that sole command, END
BEGIN NOW So easily obeyd amid the choice END
BEGIN NOW Of all tasts else to please thir appetite, END
BEGIN NOW Though wandring. He with his consorted EVE END
BEGIN NOW The storie heard attentive, and was fill'd END
BEGIN NOW With admiration, and deep Muse to heare END
BEGIN NOW Of things so high and strange, things to thir thought END
BEGIN NOW So unimaginable as hate in Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW And Warr so neer the Peace of God in bliss END
BEGIN NOW With such confusion: but the evil soon END
BEGIN NOW Driv'n back redounded as a flood on those END
BEGIN NOW From whom it sprung, impossible to mix END
BEGIN NOW With Blessedness. Whence ADAM soon repeal'd END
BEGIN NOW The doubts that in his heart arose: and now END
BEGIN NOW Led on, yet sinless, with desire to know END
BEGIN NOW What neerer might concern him, how this World END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'n and Earth conspicuous first began, END
BEGIN NOW When, and whereof created, for what cause, END
BEGIN NOW What within EDEN or without was done END
BEGIN NOW Before his memorie, as one whose drouth END
BEGIN NOW Yet scarce allay'd still eyes the current streame, END
BEGIN NOW Whose liquid murmur heard new thirst excites, END
BEGIN NOW Proceeded thus to ask his Heav'nly Guest. END
BEGIN NOW Great things, and full of wonder in our eares, END
BEGIN NOW Farr differing from this World, thou hast reveal'd END
BEGIN NOW Divine Interpreter, by favour sent END
BEGIN NOW Down from the Empyrean to forewarne END
BEGIN NOW Us timely of what might else have bin our loss, END
BEGIN NOW Unknown, which human knowledg could not reach: END
BEGIN NOW For which to the infinitly Good we owe END
BEGIN NOW Immortal thanks, and his admonishment END
BEGIN NOW Receave with solemne purpose to observe END
BEGIN NOW Immutably his sovran will, the end END
BEGIN NOW Of what we are. But since thou hast voutsaf't END
BEGIN NOW Gently for our instruction to impart END
BEGIN NOW Things above Earthly thought, which yet concernd END
BEGIN NOW Our knowing, as to highest wisdom seemd, END
BEGIN NOW Deign to descend now lower, and relate END
BEGIN NOW What may no less perhaps availe us known, END
BEGIN NOW How first began this Heav'n which we behold END
BEGIN NOW Distant so high, with moving Fires adornd END
BEGIN NOW Innumerable, and this which yeelds or fills END
BEGIN NOW All space, the ambient Aire wide interfus'd END
BEGIN NOW Imbracing round this florid Earth, what cause END
BEGIN NOW Mov'd the Creator in his holy Rest END
BEGIN NOW Through all Eternitie so late to build END
BEGIN NOW In CHAOS, and the work begun, how soon END
BEGIN NOW Absolv'd, if unforbid thou maist unfould END
BEGIN NOW What wee, not to explore the secrets aske END
BEGIN NOW Of his Eternal Empire, but the more END
BEGIN NOW To magnifie his works, the more we know. END
BEGIN NOW And the great Light of Day yet wants to run END
BEGIN NOW Much of his Race though steep, suspens in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Held by thy voice, thy potent voice he heares, END
BEGIN NOW And longer will delay to heare thee tell END
BEGIN NOW His Generation, and the rising Birth END
BEGIN NOW Of Nature from the unapparent Deep: END
BEGIN NOW Haste to thy audience, Night with her will bring END
BEGIN NOW Silence, and Sleep listning to thee will watch, END
BEGIN NOW Or we can bid his absence, till thy Song END
BEGIN NOW End, and dismiss thee ere the Morning shine. END
BEGIN NOW Thus ADAM his illustrous Guest besought: END
BEGIN NOW And thus the Godlike Angel answerd milde. END
BEGIN NOW This also thy request with caution askt END
BEGIN NOW Obtaine: though to recount Almightie works END
BEGIN NOW What words or tongue of Seraph can suffice, END
BEGIN NOW Or heart of man suffice to comprehend? END
BEGIN NOW Yet what thou canst attain, which best may serve END
BEGIN NOW To glorifie the Maker, and inferr END
BEGIN NOW Thee also happier, shall not be withheld END
BEGIN NOW Thy hearing, such Commission from above END
BEGIN NOW I have receav'd, to answer thy desire END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledge within bounds; beyond abstain END
BEGIN NOW To ask, nor let thine own inventions hope END
BEGIN NOW Things not reveal'd, which th' invisible King, END
BEGIN NOW Onely Omniscient, hath supprest in Night, END
BEGIN NOW To none communicable in Earth or Heaven: END
BEGIN NOW Anough is left besides to search and know. END
BEGIN NOW But Knowledge is as food, and needs no less END
BEGIN NOW Her Temperance over Appetite, to know END
BEGIN NOW In measure what the mind may well contain, END
BEGIN NOW Oppresses else with Surfet, and soon turns END
BEGIN NOW Know then, that after LUCIFER from Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW (So call him, brighter once amidst the Host END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels, then that Starr the Starrs among) END
BEGIN NOW Fell with his flaming Legions through the Deep END
BEGIN NOW Into his place, and the great Son returnd END
BEGIN NOW Victorious with his Saints, th' Omnipotent END
BEGIN NOW Eternal Father from his Throne beheld END
BEGIN NOW Thir multitude, and to his Son thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW At least our envious Foe hath fail'd, who thought END
BEGIN NOW All like himself rebellious, by whose aid END
BEGIN NOW This inaccessible high strength, the seat END
BEGIN NOW Of Deitie supream, us dispossest, END
BEGIN NOW He trusted to have seis'd, and into fraud END
BEGIN NOW Drew many, whom thir place knows here no more; END
BEGIN NOW Yet farr the greater part have kept, I see, END
BEGIN NOW Thir station, Heav'n yet populous retaines END
BEGIN NOW Number sufficient to possess her Realmes END
BEGIN NOW Though wide, and this high Temple to frequent END
BEGIN NOW With Ministeries due and solemn Rites: END
BEGIN NOW But least his heart exalt him in the harme END
BEGIN NOW Already done, to have dispeopl'd Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW My damage fondly deem'd, I can repaire END
BEGIN NOW That detriment, if such it be to lose END
BEGIN NOW Self-lost, and in a moment will create END
BEGIN NOW Of men innumerable, there to dwell, END
BEGIN NOW Not here, till by degrees of merit rais'd END
BEGIN NOW They open to themselves at length the way END
BEGIN NOW Up hither, under long obedience tri'd, END
BEGIN NOW And Earth be chang'd to Heavn, & Heav'n to Earth, END
BEGIN NOW One Kingdom, Joy and Union without end. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while inhabit laxe, ye Powers of Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW And thou my Word, begotten Son, by thee END
BEGIN NOW This I perform, speak thou, and be it don: END
BEGIN NOW My overshadowing Spirit and might with thee END
BEGIN NOW I send along, ride forth, and bid the Deep END
BEGIN NOW Within appointed bounds be Heav'n and Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Boundless the Deep, because I am who fill END
BEGIN NOW Infinitude, nor vacuous the space. END
BEGIN NOW Though I uncircumscrib'd my self retire, END
BEGIN NOW And put not forth my goodness, which is free END
BEGIN NOW To act or not, Necessitie and Chance END
BEGIN NOW Approach not mee, and what I will is Fate. END
BEGIN NOW So spake th' Almightie, and to what he spake END
BEGIN NOW His Word, the Filial Godhead, gave effect. END
BEGIN NOW Immediate are the Acts of God, more swift END
BEGIN NOW Then time or motion, but to human ears END
BEGIN NOW Cannot without process of speech be told, END
BEGIN NOW So told as earthly notion can receave. END
BEGIN NOW Great triumph and rejoycing was in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW When such was heard declar'd the Almightie's will; END
BEGIN NOW Glorie they sung to the most High, good will END
BEGIN NOW To future men, and in thir dwellings peace: END
BEGIN NOW Glorie to him whose just avenging ire END
BEGIN NOW Had driven out th' ungodly from his sight END
BEGIN NOW And th' habitations of the just; to him END
BEGIN NOW Glorie and praise, whose wisdom had ordain'd END
BEGIN NOW Good out of evil to create, in stead END
BEGIN NOW Of Spirits maligne a better Race to bring END
BEGIN NOW Into thir vacant room, and thence diffuse END
BEGIN NOW His good to Worlds and Ages infinite. END
BEGIN NOW So sang the Hierarchies: Mean while the Son END
BEGIN NOW On his great Expedition now appeer'd, END
BEGIN NOW Girt with Omnipotence, with Radiance crown'd END
BEGIN NOW Immense, and all his Father in him shon. END
BEGIN NOW About his Chariot numberless were pour'd END
BEGIN NOW And Vertues, winged Spirits, and Chariots wing'd, END
BEGIN NOW From the Armoury of God, where stand of old END
BEGIN NOW Myriads between two brazen Mountains lodg'd END
BEGIN NOW Against a solemn day, harnest at hand, END
BEGIN NOW Celestial Equipage; and now came forth END
BEGIN NOW Spontaneous, for within them Spirit livd, END
BEGIN NOW Attendant on thir Lord: Heav'n op'nd wide END
BEGIN NOW Her ever during Gates, Harmonious sound END
BEGIN NOW On golden Hinges moving, to let forth END
BEGIN NOW The King of Glorie in his powerful Word END
BEGIN NOW And Spirit coming to create new Worlds. END
BEGIN NOW On heav'nly ground they stood, and from the shore END
BEGIN NOW They view'd the vast immeasurable Abyss END
BEGIN NOW Outrageous as a Sea, dark, wasteful, wilde, END
BEGIN NOW Up from the bottom turn'd by furious windes END
BEGIN NOW And surging waves, as Mountains to assault END
BEGIN NOW Heav'ns highth, and with the Center mix the Pole. END
BEGIN NOW Silence, ye troubl'd waves, and thou Deep, peace, END
BEGIN NOW Said then th' Omnific Word, your discord end: END
BEGIN NOW Nor staid, but on the Wings of Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW Uplifted, in Paternal Glorie rode END
BEGIN NOW Farr into CHAOS, and the World unborn; END
BEGIN NOW For CHAOS heard his voice: him all his Traine END
BEGIN NOW Follow'd in bright procession to behold END
BEGIN NOW Creation, and the wonders of his might. END
BEGIN NOW Then staid the fervid Wheeles, and in his hand END
BEGIN NOW He took the golden Compasses, prepar'd END
BEGIN NOW In Gods Eternal store, to circumscribe END
BEGIN NOW This Universe, and all created things: END
BEGIN NOW One foot he center'd, and the other turn'd END
BEGIN NOW Round through the vast profunditie obscure, END
BEGIN NOW And said, thus farr extend, thus farr thy bounds, END
BEGIN NOW This be thy just Circumference, O World. END
BEGIN NOW Thus God the Heav'n created, thus the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Matter unform'd and void: Darkness profound END
BEGIN NOW Cover'd th' Abyss: but on the watrie calme END
BEGIN NOW His brooding wings the Spirit of God outspred, END
BEGIN NOW And vital vertue infus'd, and vital warmth END
BEGIN NOW Throughout the fluid Mass, but downward purg'd END
BEGIN NOW The black tartareous cold infernal dregs END
BEGIN NOW Adverse to life: then founded, then conglob'd END
BEGIN NOW Like things to like, the rest to several place END
BEGIN NOW Disparted, and between spun out the Air, END
BEGIN NOW And Earth self-ballanc't on her Center hung. END
BEGIN NOW Let ther be Light, said God, and forthwith Light END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal, first of things, quintessence pure END
BEGIN NOW Sprung from the Deep, and from her Native East END
BEGIN NOW To journie through the airie gloom began, END
BEGIN NOW Sphear'd in a radiant Cloud, for yet the Sun END
BEGIN NOW Was not; shee in a cloudie Tabernacle END
BEGIN NOW Sojourn'd the while. God saw the Light was good; END
BEGIN NOW And light from darkness by the Hemisphere END
BEGIN NOW He nam'd. Thus was the first Day Eev'n and Morn: END
BEGIN NOW Nor past uncelebrated, nor unsung END
BEGIN NOW By the Celestial Quires, when Orient Light END
BEGIN NOW Exhaling first from Darkness they beheld; END
BEGIN NOW Birth-day of Heav'n and Earth; with joy and shout END
BEGIN NOW The hollow Universal Orb they fill'd, END
BEGIN NOW And touch't thir Golden Harps, & hymning prais'd END
BEGIN NOW God and his works, Creatour him they sung, END
BEGIN NOW Both when first Eevning was, and when first Morn. END
BEGIN NOW Again, God said, let ther be Firmament END
BEGIN NOW Amid the Waters, and let it divide END
BEGIN NOW The Waters from the Waters: and God made END
BEGIN NOW The Firmament, expanse of liquid, pure, END
BEGIN NOW Transparent, Elemental Air, diffus'd END
BEGIN NOW In circuit to the uttermost convex END
BEGIN NOW Of this great Round: partition firm and sure, END
BEGIN NOW The Waters underneath from those above END
BEGIN NOW Built on circumfluous Waters calme, in wide END
BEGIN NOW Crystallin Ocean, and the loud misrule END
BEGIN NOW Of CHAOS farr remov'd, least fierce extreames END
BEGIN NOW Contiguous might distemper the whole frame: END
BEGIN NOW And Heav'n he nam'd the Firmament: So Eev'n END
BEGIN NOW And Morning CHORUS sung the second Day. END
BEGIN NOW The Earth was form'd, but in the Womb as yet END
BEGIN NOW Of Waters, Embryon immature involv'd, END
BEGIN NOW Appeer'd not: over all the face of Earth END
BEGIN NOW Main Ocean flow'd, not idle, but with warme END
BEGIN NOW Prolific humour soft'ning all her Globe, END
BEGIN NOW Fermented the great Mother to conceave, END
BEGIN NOW Satiate with genial moisture, when God said END
BEGIN NOW Be gather'd now ye Waters under Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Into one place, and let dry Land appeer. END
BEGIN NOW Immediately the Mountains huge appeer END
BEGIN NOW Emergent, and thir broad bare backs upheave END
BEGIN NOW Into the Clouds, thir tops ascend the Skie: END
BEGIN NOW So high as heav'd the tumid Hills, so low END
BEGIN NOW Down sunk a hollow bottom broad and deep, END
BEGIN NOW Capacious bed of Waters: thither they END
BEGIN NOW Hasted with glad precipitance, uprowld END
BEGIN NOW As drops on dust conglobing from the drie; END
BEGIN NOW Part rise in crystal Wall, or ridge direct, END
BEGIN NOW For haste; such flight the great command impress'd END
BEGIN NOW On the swift flouds: as Armies at the call END
BEGIN NOW Of Trumpet (for of Armies thou hast heard) END
BEGIN NOW Troop to thir Standard, so the watrie throng, END
BEGIN NOW Wave rowling after Wave, where way they found, END
BEGIN NOW If steep, with torrent rapture, if through Plaine, END
BEGIN NOW Soft-ebbing; nor withstood them Rock or Hill, END
BEGIN NOW But they, or under ground, or circuit wide END
BEGIN NOW With Serpent errour wandring, found thir way, END
BEGIN NOW And on the washie Oose deep Channels wore; END
BEGIN NOW Easie, e're God had bid the ground be drie, END
BEGIN NOW All but within those banks, where Rivers now END
BEGIN NOW Stream, and perpetual draw thir humid traine. END
BEGIN NOW The dry Land, Earth, and the great receptacle END
BEGIN NOW Of congregated Waters he call'd Seas: END
BEGIN NOW And saw that it was good, and said, Let th' Earth END
BEGIN NOW Put forth the verdant Grass, Herb yeilding Seed, END
BEGIN NOW And Fruit Tree yeilding Fruit after her kind; END
BEGIN NOW Whose Seed is in her self upon the Earth. END
BEGIN NOW He scarce had said, when the bare Earth, till then END
BEGIN NOW Desert and bare, unsightly, unadorn'd, END
BEGIN NOW Brought forth the tender Grass, whose verdure clad END
BEGIN NOW Her Universal Face with pleasant green, END
BEGIN NOW Then Herbs of every leaf, that sudden flour'd END
BEGIN NOW Op'ning thir various colours, and made gay END
BEGIN NOW Her bosom smelling sweet: and these scarce blown, END
BEGIN NOW Forth flourish't thick the clustring Vine, forth crept END
BEGIN NOW The smelling Gourd, up stood the cornie Reed END
BEGIN NOW Embattell'd in her field: add the humble Shrub, END
BEGIN NOW And Bush with frizl'd hair implicit: last END
BEGIN NOW Rose as in Dance the stately Trees, and spred END
BEGIN NOW Thir branches hung with copious Fruit; or gemm'd END
BEGIN NOW Thir Blossoms: with high Woods the Hills were crownd, END
BEGIN NOW With tufts the vallies & each fountain side, END
BEGIN NOW With borders long the Rivers. That Earth now END
BEGIN NOW Seemd like to Heav'n, a seat where Gods might dwell, END
BEGIN NOW Or wander with delight, and love to haunt END
BEGIN NOW Her sacred shades: though God had yet not rain'd END
BEGIN NOW Upon the Earth, and man to till the ground END
BEGIN NOW None was, but from the Earth a dewie Mist END
BEGIN NOW Went up and waterd all the ground, and each END
BEGIN NOW Plant of the field, which e're it was in the Earth END
BEGIN NOW God made, and every Herb, before it grew END
BEGIN NOW On the green stemm; God saw that it was good: END
BEGIN NOW So Eev'n and Morn recorded the Third Day. END
BEGIN NOW Again th' Almightie spake: Let there be Lights END
BEGIN NOW High in th' expanse of Heaven to divide END
BEGIN NOW The Day from Night; and let them be for Signes, END
BEGIN NOW For Seasons, and for Dayes, and circling Years, END
BEGIN NOW And let them be for Lights as I ordaine END
BEGIN NOW Thir Office in the Firmament of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW To give Light on the Earth; and it was so. END
BEGIN NOW And God made two great Lights, great for thir use END
BEGIN NOW To Man, the greater to have rule by Day, END
BEGIN NOW The less by Night alterne: and made the Starrs, END
BEGIN NOW And set them in the Firmament of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW To illuminate the Earth, and rule the Day END
BEGIN NOW In thir vicissitude, and rule the Night, END
BEGIN NOW And Light from Darkness to divide. God saw, END
BEGIN NOW Surveying his great Work, that it was good: END
BEGIN NOW For of Celestial Bodies first the Sun END
BEGIN NOW A mightie Spheare he fram'd, unlightsom first, END
BEGIN NOW Though of Ethereal Mould: then form'd the Moon END
BEGIN NOW Globose, and everie magnitude of Starrs, END
BEGIN NOW And sowd with Starrs the Heav'n thick as a field: END
BEGIN NOW Of Light by farr the greater part he took, END
BEGIN NOW Transplanted from her cloudie Shrine, and plac'd END
BEGIN NOW In the Suns Orb, made porous to receive END
BEGIN NOW And drink the liquid Light, firm to retaine END
BEGIN NOW Her gather'd beams, great Palace now of Light. END
BEGIN NOW Hither as to thir Fountain other Starrs END
BEGIN NOW Repairing, in thir gold'n Urns draw Light, END
BEGIN NOW And hence the Morning Planet guilds his horns; END
BEGIN NOW By tincture or reflection they augment END
BEGIN NOW Thir small peculiar, though from human sight END
BEGIN NOW So farr remote, with diminution seen. END
BEGIN NOW First in his East the glorious Lamp was seen, END
BEGIN NOW Regent of Day, and all th' Horizon round END
BEGIN NOW Invested with bright Rayes, jocond to run END
BEGIN NOW His Longitude through Heav'ns high rode: the gray END
BEGIN NOW Dawn, and the PLEIADES before him danc'd END
BEGIN NOW Shedding sweet influence: less bright the Moon, END
BEGIN NOW But opposite in leveld West was set END
BEGIN NOW His mirror, with full face borrowing her Light END
BEGIN NOW From him, for other light she needed none END
BEGIN NOW In that aspect, and still that distance keepes END
BEGIN NOW Till night, then in the East her turn she shines, END
BEGIN NOW Revolvd on Heav'ns great Axle, and her Reign END
BEGIN NOW With thousand lesser Lights dividual holds, END
BEGIN NOW With thousand thousand Starres, that then appeer'd END
BEGIN NOW Spangling the Hemisphere: then first adornd END
BEGIN NOW With thir bright Luminaries that Set and Rose, END
BEGIN NOW Glad Eevning & glad Morn crownd the fourth day. END
BEGIN NOW And God said, let the Waters generate END
BEGIN NOW Reptil with Spawn abundant, living Soule: END
BEGIN NOW And let Fowle flie above the Earth, with wings END
BEGIN NOW Displayd on the op'n Firmament of Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW And God created the great Whales, and each END
BEGIN NOW Soul living, each that crept, which plenteously END
BEGIN NOW The waters generated by thir kindes, END
BEGIN NOW And every Bird of wing after his kinde; END
BEGIN NOW And saw that it was good, and bless'd them, saying, END
BEGIN NOW Be fruitful, multiply, and in the Seas END
BEGIN NOW And Lakes and running Streams the waters fill; END
BEGIN NOW And let the Fowle be multiply'd on the Earth. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith the Sounds and Seas, each Creek & Bay END
BEGIN NOW With Frie innumerable swarme, and Shoales END
BEGIN NOW Of Fish that with thir Finns and shining Scales END
BEGIN NOW Glide under the green Wave, in Sculles that oft END
BEGIN NOW Bank the mid Sea: part single or with mate END
BEGIN NOW Graze the Sea weed thir pasture, & through Groves END
BEGIN NOW Of Coral stray, or sporting with quick glance END
BEGIN NOW Show to the Sun thir wav'd coats dropt with Gold, END
BEGIN NOW Or in thir Pearlie shells at ease, attend END
BEGIN NOW Moist nutriment, or under Rocks thir food END
BEGIN NOW In jointed Armour watch: on smooth the Seale, END
BEGIN NOW And bended Dolphins play: part huge of bulk END
BEGIN NOW Wallowing unweildie, enormous in thir Gate END
BEGIN NOW Tempest the Ocean: there Leviathan END
BEGIN NOW Hugest of living Creatures, on the Deep END
BEGIN NOW Stretcht like a Promontorie sleeps or swimmes, END
BEGIN NOW And seems a moving Land, and at his Gilles END
BEGIN NOW Draws in, and at his Trunck spouts out a Sea. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while the tepid Caves, and Fens and shoares END
BEGIN NOW Thir Brood as numerous hatch, from the Egg that soon END
BEGIN NOW Bursting with kindly rupture forth disclos'd END
BEGIN NOW Thir callow young, but featherd soon and fledge END
BEGIN NOW They summ'd thir Penns, and soaring th' air sublime END
BEGIN NOW With clang despis'd the ground, under a cloud END
BEGIN NOW In prospect; there the Eagle and the Stork END
BEGIN NOW On Cliffs and Cedar tops thir Eyries build: END
BEGIN NOW Part loosly wing the Region, part more wise END
BEGIN NOW In common, rang'd in figure wedge thir way, END
BEGIN NOW Intelligent of seasons, and set forth END
BEGIN NOW Thir Aierie Caravan high over Sea's END
BEGIN NOW Flying, and over Lands with mutual wing END
BEGIN NOW Easing thir flight; so stears the prudent Crane END
BEGIN NOW Her annual Voiage, born on Windes; the Aire END
BEGIN NOW Floats, as they pass, fann'd with unnumber'd plumes: END
BEGIN NOW From Branch to Branch the smaller Birds with song END
BEGIN NOW Solac'd the Woods, and spred thir painted wings END
BEGIN NOW Till Ev'n, nor then the solemn Nightingal END
BEGIN NOW Ceas'd warbling, but all night tun'd her soft layes: END
BEGIN NOW Others on Silver Lakes and Rivers Bath'd END
BEGIN NOW Thir downie Brest; the Swan with Arched neck END
BEGIN NOW Between her white wings mantling proudly, Rowes END
BEGIN NOW Her state with Oarie feet: yet oft they quit END
BEGIN NOW The Dank, and rising on stiff Pennons, towre END
BEGIN NOW The mid Aereal Skie: Others on ground END
BEGIN NOW Walk'd firm; the crested Cock whose clarion sounds END
BEGIN NOW The silent hours, and th' other whose gay Traine END
BEGIN NOW Adorns him, colour'd with the Florid hue END
BEGIN NOW Of Rainbows and Starrie Eyes. The Waters thus END
BEGIN NOW With Fish replenisht, and the Aire with Fowle, END
BEGIN NOW Ev'ning and Morn solemniz'd the Fift day. END
BEGIN NOW The Sixt, and of Creation last arose END
BEGIN NOW With Eevning Harps and Mattin, when God said, END
BEGIN NOW Let th' Earth bring forth Fowle living in her kinde, END
BEGIN NOW Cattel and Creeping things, and Beast of the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Each in their kinde. The Earth obey'd, and strait END
BEGIN NOW Op'ning her fertil Woomb teem'd at a Birth END
BEGIN NOW Innumerous living Creatures, perfet formes, END
BEGIN NOW Limb'd and full grown: out of the ground up-rose END
BEGIN NOW As from his Laire the wilde Beast where he wonns END
BEGIN NOW In Forrest wilde, in Thicket, Brake, or Den; END
BEGIN NOW Among the Trees in Pairs they rose, they walk'd: END
BEGIN NOW The Cattel in the Fields and Meddowes green: END
BEGIN NOW Those rare and solitarie, these in flocks END
BEGIN NOW Pasturing at once, and in broad Herds upsprung: END
BEGIN NOW The grassie Clods now Calv'd, now half appeer'd END
BEGIN NOW The Tawnie Lion, pawing to get free END
BEGIN NOW His hinder parts, then springs as broke from Bonds, END
BEGIN NOW And Rampant shakes his Brinded main; the Ounce, END
BEGIN NOW Rising, the crumbl'd Earth above them threw END
BEGIN NOW In Hillocks; the swift Stag from under ground END
BEGIN NOW Bore up his branching head: scarse from his mould END
BEGIN NOW BEHEMOTH biggest born of Earth upheav'd END
BEGIN NOW His vastness: Fleec't the Flocks and bleating rose, END
BEGIN NOW As Plants: ambiguous between Sea and Land END
BEGIN NOW The River Horse and scalie Crocodile. END
BEGIN NOW At once came forth whatever creeps the ground, END
BEGIN NOW Insect or Worme; those wav'd thir limber fans END
BEGIN NOW For wings, and smallest Lineaments exact END
BEGIN NOW In all the Liveries dect of Summers pride END
BEGIN NOW With spots of Gold and Purple, azure and green: END
BEGIN NOW These as a line thir long dimension drew, END
BEGIN NOW Streaking the ground with sinuous trace; not all END
BEGIN NOW Minims of Nature; some of Serpent kinde END
BEGIN NOW Wondrous in length and corpulence involv'd END
BEGIN NOW Thir Snakie foulds, and added wings. First crept END
BEGIN NOW The Parsimonious Emmet, provident END
BEGIN NOW Of future, in small room large heart enclos'd, END
BEGIN NOW Pattern of just equalitie perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Hereafter, join'd in her popular Tribes END
BEGIN NOW Of Commonaltie: swarming next appeer'd END
BEGIN NOW The Femal Bee that feeds her Husband Drone END
BEGIN NOW Deliciously, and builds her waxen Cells END
BEGIN NOW With Honey stor'd: the rest are numberless, END
BEGIN NOW And thou thir Natures know'st, and gav'st them Names, END
BEGIN NOW Needlest to thee repeaed; nor unknown END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent suttl'st Beast of all the field, END
BEGIN NOW Of huge extent somtimes, with brazen Eyes END
BEGIN NOW And hairie Main terrific, though to thee END
BEGIN NOW Not noxious, but obedient at thy call. END
BEGIN NOW Now Heav'n in all her Glorie shon, and rowld END
BEGIN NOW Her motions, as the great first-Movers hand END
BEGIN NOW First wheeld thir course; Earth in her rich attire END
BEGIN NOW Consummate lovly smil'd; Aire, Water, Earth, END
BEGIN NOW By Fowl, Fish, Beast, was flown, was swum, was walkt END
BEGIN NOW Frequent; and of the Sixt day yet remain'd; END
BEGIN NOW There wanted yet the Master work, the end END
BEGIN NOW Of all yet don; a Creature who not prone END
BEGIN NOW And Brute as other Creatures, but endu'd END
BEGIN NOW With Sanctitie of Reason, might erect END
BEGIN NOW His Stature, and upright with Front serene END
BEGIN NOW Govern the rest, self-knowing, and from thence END
BEGIN NOW Magnanimous to correspond with Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW But grateful to acknowledge whence his good END
BEGIN NOW Descends, thither with heart and voice and eyes END
BEGIN NOW Directed in Devotion, to adore END
BEGIN NOW And worship God Supream, who made him chief END
BEGIN NOW Of all his works: therefore the Omnipotent END
BEGIN NOW Eternal Father (For where is not hee END
BEGIN NOW Present) thus to his Son audibly spake. END
BEGIN NOW Let us make now Man in our image, Man END
BEGIN NOW In our similitude, and let them rule END
BEGIN NOW Beast of the Field, and over all the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW And every creeping thing that creeps the ground. END
BEGIN NOW This said, he formd thee, ADAM, thee O Man END
BEGIN NOW Dust of the ground, and in thy nostrils breath'd END
BEGIN NOW The breath of Life; in his own Image hee END
BEGIN NOW Created thee, in the Image of God END
BEGIN NOW Express, and thou becam'st a living Soul. END
BEGIN NOW Male he created thee, but thy consort END
BEGIN NOW Femal for Race; then bless'd Mankinde, and said, END
BEGIN NOW Be fruitful, multiplie, and fill the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Subdue it, and throughout Dominion hold END
BEGIN NOW And every living thing that moves on the Earth. END
BEGIN NOW Wherever thus created, for no place END
BEGIN NOW Is yet distinct by name, thence, as thou know'st END
BEGIN NOW He brought thee into this delicious Grove, END
BEGIN NOW This Garden, planted with the Trees of God, END
BEGIN NOW Delectable both to behold and taste; END
BEGIN NOW And freely all thir pleasant fruit for food END
BEGIN NOW Gave thee, all sorts are here that all th' Earth yeelds, END
BEGIN NOW Varietie without end; but of the Tree END
BEGIN NOW Which tasted works knowledge of Good and Evil, END
BEGIN NOW Thou mai'st not; in the day thou eat'st, thou di'st; END
BEGIN NOW Death is the penaltie impos'd, beware, END
BEGIN NOW And govern well thy appetite, least sin END
BEGIN NOW Surprise thee, and her black attendant Death. END
BEGIN NOW Here finish'd hee, and all that he had made END
BEGIN NOW View'd, and behold all was entirely good; END
BEGIN NOW So Ev'n and Morn accomplish'd the Sixt day: END
BEGIN NOW Yet not till the Creator from his work END
BEGIN NOW Desisting, though unwearied, up returnd END
BEGIN NOW Up to the Heav'n of Heav'ns his high abode, END
BEGIN NOW Thence to behold this new created World END
BEGIN NOW Th' addition of his Empire, how it shew'd END
BEGIN NOW In prospect from his Throne, how good, how faire, END
BEGIN NOW Answering his great Idea. Up he rode END
BEGIN NOW Followd with acclamation and the sound END
BEGIN NOW Symphonious of ten thousand Harpes that tun'd END
BEGIN NOW Angelic harmonies: the Earth, the Aire END
BEGIN NOW Resounded, (thou remember'st, for thou heardst) END
BEGIN NOW The Heav'ns and all the Constellations rung, END
BEGIN NOW The Planets in thir stations list'ning stood, END
BEGIN NOW While the bright Pomp ascended jubilant. END
BEGIN NOW Open, ye everlasting Gates, they sung, END
BEGIN NOW Open, ye Heav'ns, your living dores; let in END
BEGIN NOW The great Creator from his work returnd END
BEGIN NOW Magnificent, his Six days work, a World; END
BEGIN NOW Open, and henceforth oft; for God will deigne END
BEGIN NOW To visit oft the dwellings of just Men END
BEGIN NOW Delighted, and with frequent intercourse END
BEGIN NOW Thither will send his winged Messengers END
BEGIN NOW On errands of supernal Grace. So sung END
BEGIN NOW The glorious Train ascending: He through Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW That open'd wide her blazing Portals, led END
BEGIN NOW To Gods Eternal house direct the way, END
BEGIN NOW A broad and ample rode, whose dust is Gold END
BEGIN NOW And pavement Starrs, as Starrs to thee appeer, END
BEGIN NOW Seen in the Galaxie, that Milkie way END
BEGIN NOW Which nightly as a circling Zone thou seest END
BEGIN NOW Pouderd with Starrs. And now on Earth the Seaventh END
BEGIN NOW Eev'ning arose in EDEN, for the Sun END
BEGIN NOW Was set, and twilight from the East came on, END
BEGIN NOW Forerunning Night; when at the holy mount END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'ns high-seated top, th' Impereal Throne END
BEGIN NOW Of Godhead, fixt for ever firm and sure, END
BEGIN NOW The Filial Power arriv'd, and sate him down END
BEGIN NOW With his great Father (for he also went END
BEGIN NOW Invisible, yet staid (such priviledge END
BEGIN NOW Hath Omnipresence) and the work ordain'd, END
BEGIN NOW Author and end of all things, and from work END
BEGIN NOW Now resting, bless'd and hallowd the Seav'nth day, END
BEGIN NOW As resting on that day from all his work, END
BEGIN NOW But not in silence holy kept; the Harp END
BEGIN NOW Had work and rested not, the solemn Pipe, END
BEGIN NOW And Dulcimer, all Organs of sweet stop, END
BEGIN NOW All sounds on Fret by String or Golden Wire END
BEGIN NOW Temper'd soft Tunings, intermixt with Voice END
BEGIN NOW Choral or Unison: of incense Clouds END
BEGIN NOW Fuming from Golden Censers hid the Mount. END
BEGIN NOW Creation and the Six dayes acts they sung, END
BEGIN NOW Great are thy works, JEHOVAH, infinite END
BEGIN NOW Thy power; what thought can measure thee or tongue END
BEGIN NOW Relate thee; greater now in thy return END
BEGIN NOW Then from the Giant Angels; thee that day END
BEGIN NOW Thy Thunders magnifi'd; but to create END
BEGIN NOW Is greater then created to destroy. END
BEGIN NOW Who can impair thee, mighty King, or bound END
BEGIN NOW Thy Empire? easily the proud attempt END
BEGIN NOW Of Spirits apostat and thir Counsels vaine END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast repeld, while impiously they thought END
BEGIN NOW Thee to diminish, and from thee withdraw END
BEGIN NOW The number of thy worshippers. Who seekes END
BEGIN NOW To lessen thee, against his purpose serves END
BEGIN NOW To manifest the more thy might: his evil END
BEGIN NOW Thou usest, and from thence creat'st more good. END
BEGIN NOW Witness this new-made World, another Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW From Heaven Gate not farr, founded in view END
BEGIN NOW On the cleer HYALINE, the Glassie Sea; END
BEGIN NOW Of amplitude almost immense, with Starr's END
BEGIN NOW Numerous, and every Starr perhaps a World END
BEGIN NOW Of destind habitation; but thou know'st END
BEGIN NOW Thir seasons: among these the seat of men, END
BEGIN NOW Earth with her nether Ocean circumfus'd, END
BEGIN NOW Thir pleasant dwelling place. Thrice happie men, END
BEGIN NOW And sons of men, whom God hath thus advanc't, END
BEGIN NOW Created in his Image, there to dwell END
BEGIN NOW And worship him, and in reward to rule END
BEGIN NOW And multiply a Race of Worshippers END
BEGIN NOW Holy and just: thrice happie if they know END
BEGIN NOW Thir happiness, and persevere upright. END
BEGIN NOW So sung they, and the Empyrean rung, END
BEGIN NOW With HALLELUIAHS: Thus was Sabbath kept. END
BEGIN NOW And thy request think now fulfill'd, that ask'd END
BEGIN NOW How first this World and face of things began, END
BEGIN NOW And what before thy memorie was don END
BEGIN NOW From the beginning, that posteritie END
BEGIN NOW Informd by thee might know; if else thou seekst END
BEGIN NOW Aught, not surpassing human measure, say. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus ADAM gratefully repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW What thanks sufficient, or what recompence END
BEGIN NOW Equal have I to render thee, Divine END
BEGIN NOW Hystorian, who thus largely hast allayd END
BEGIN NOW The thirst I had of knowledge, and voutsaf't END
BEGIN NOW This friendly condescention to relate END
BEGIN NOW Things else by me unsearchable, now heard END
BEGIN NOW VVith wonder, but delight, and, as is due, END
BEGIN NOW With glorie attributed to the high END
BEGIN NOW Creator; some thing yet of doubt remaines, END
BEGIN NOW VVhich onely thy solution can resolve. END
BEGIN NOW VVhen I behold this goodly Frame, this VVorld END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'n and Earth consisting, and compute, END
BEGIN NOW Thir magnitudes, this Earth a spot, a graine, END
BEGIN NOW An Atom, with the Firmament compar'd END
BEGIN NOW And all her numberd Starrs, that seem to rowle END
BEGIN NOW Spaces incomprehensible (for such END
BEGIN NOW Thir distance argues and thir swift return END
BEGIN NOW Diurnal) meerly to officiate light END
BEGIN NOW Round this opacous Earth, this punctual spot, END
BEGIN NOW One day and night; in all thir vast survey END
BEGIN NOW Useless besides, reasoning I oft admire, END
BEGIN NOW How Nature wise and frugal could commit END
BEGIN NOW Such disproportions, with superfluous hand END
BEGIN NOW So many nobler Bodies to create, END
BEGIN NOW Greater so manifold to this one use, END
BEGIN NOW For aught appeers, and on thir Orbs impose END
BEGIN NOW Such restless revolution day by day END
BEGIN NOW Repeated, while the sedentarie Earth, END
BEGIN NOW That better might with farr less compass move, END
BEGIN NOW Serv'd by more noble then her self, attaines END
BEGIN NOW Her end without least motion, and receaves, END
BEGIN NOW As Tribute such a sumless journey brought END
BEGIN NOW Of incorporeal speed, her warmth and light; END
BEGIN NOW Speed, to describe whose swiftness Number failes. END
BEGIN NOW So spake our Sire, and by his count'nance seemd END
BEGIN NOW Entring on studious thoughts abstruse, which EVE END
BEGIN NOW Perceaving where she sat retir'd in sight, END
BEGIN NOW With lowliness Majestic from her seat, END
BEGIN NOW And Grace that won who saw to wish her stay, END
BEGIN NOW Rose, and went forth among her Fruits and Flours, END
BEGIN NOW To visit how they prosper'd, bud and bloom, END
BEGIN NOW Her Nurserie; they at her coming sprung END
BEGIN NOW And toucht by her fair tendance gladlier grew. END
BEGIN NOW Yet went she not, as not with such discourse END
BEGIN NOW Delighted, or not capable her eare END
BEGIN NOW Of what was high: such pleasure she reserv'd, END
BEGIN NOW ADAM relating, she sole Auditress; END
BEGIN NOW Her Husband the Relater she preferr'd END
BEGIN NOW Chose rather; hee, she knew would intermix END
BEGIN NOW Grateful digressions, and solve high dispute END
BEGIN NOW With conjugal Caresses, from his Lip END
BEGIN NOW Not Words alone pleas'd her. O when meet now END
BEGIN NOW Such pairs, in Love and mutual Honour joyn'd? END
BEGIN NOW With Goddess-like demeanour forth she went; END
BEGIN NOW Not unattended, for on her as Queen END
BEGIN NOW A pomp of winning Graces waited still, END
BEGIN NOW And from about her shot Darts of desire END
BEGIN NOW Into all Eyes to wish her still in sight. END
BEGIN NOW And RAPHAEL now to ADAM's doubt propos'd END
BEGIN NOW Benevolent and facil thus repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW To ask or search I blame thee not, for Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Is as the Book of God before thee set, END
BEGIN NOW Wherein to read his wondrous Works, and learne END
BEGIN NOW This to attain, whether Heav'n move or Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Imports not, if thou reck'n right, the rest END
BEGIN NOW From Man or Angel the great Architect END
BEGIN NOW Did wisely to conceal, and not divulge END
BEGIN NOW His secrets to be scann'd by them who ought END
BEGIN NOW Rather admire; or if they list to try END
BEGIN NOW Conjecture, he his Fabric of the Heav'ns END
BEGIN NOW Hath left to thir disputes, perhaps to move END
BEGIN NOW His laughter at thir quaint Opinions wide END
BEGIN NOW Hereafter, when they come to model Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW And calculate the Starrs, how they will weild END
BEGIN NOW The mightie frame, how build, unbuild, contrive END
BEGIN NOW To save appeerances, how gird the Sphear END
BEGIN NOW With Centric and Eccentric scribl'd o're, END
BEGIN NOW Alreadie by thy reasoning this I guess, END
BEGIN NOW Who art to lead thy ofspring, and supposest END
BEGIN NOW That Bodies bright and greater should not serve END
BEGIN NOW The less not bright, nor Heav'n such journies run, END
BEGIN NOW Earth sitting still, when she alone receaves END
BEGIN NOW The benefit: consider first, that Great END
BEGIN NOW Or Bright inferrs not Excellence: the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Though, in comparison of Heav'n, so small, END
BEGIN NOW Nor glistering, may of solid good containe END
BEGIN NOW More plenty then the Sun that barren shines, END
BEGIN NOW Whose vertue on it self workes no effect, END
BEGIN NOW But in the fruitful Earth; there first receavd END
BEGIN NOW His beams, unactive else, thir vigor find. END
BEGIN NOW Yet not to Earth are those bright Luminaries END
BEGIN NOW Officious, but to thee Earths habitant. END
BEGIN NOW And for the Heav'ns wide Circuit, let it speak END
BEGIN NOW The Makers high magnificence, who built END
BEGIN NOW So spacious, and his Line stretcht out so farr; END
BEGIN NOW That Man may know he dwells not in his own; END
BEGIN NOW An Edifice too large for him to fill, END
BEGIN NOW Lodg'd in a small partition, and the rest END
BEGIN NOW Ordain'd for uses to his Lord best known. END
BEGIN NOW The swiftness of those Circles attribute, END
BEGIN NOW Though numberless, to his Omnipotence, END
BEGIN NOW That to corporeal substances could adde END
BEGIN NOW Speed almost Spiritual; mee thou thinkst not slow, END
BEGIN NOW Who since the Morning hour set out from Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Where God resides, and ere mid-day arriv'd END
BEGIN NOW In EDEN, distance inexpressible END
BEGIN NOW By Numbers that have name. But this I urge, END
BEGIN NOW Admitting Motion in the Heav'ns, to shew END
BEGIN NOW Invalid that which thee to doubt it mov'd; END
BEGIN NOW Not that I so affirm, though so it seem END
BEGIN NOW To thee who hast thy dwelling here on Earth. END
BEGIN NOW God to remove his wayes from human sense, END
BEGIN NOW Plac'd Heav'n from Earth so farr, that earthly sight, END
BEGIN NOW If it presume, might erre in things too high, END
BEGIN NOW And no advantage gaine. What if the Sun END
BEGIN NOW Be Center to the World, and other Starrs END
BEGIN NOW By his attractive vertue and thir own END
BEGIN NOW Incited, dance about him various rounds? END
BEGIN NOW Thir wandring course now high, now low, then hid, END
BEGIN NOW Progressive, retrograde, or standing still, END
BEGIN NOW In six thou seest, and what if sev'nth to these END
BEGIN NOW The Planet Earth, so stedfast though she seem, END
BEGIN NOW Insensibly three different Motions move? END
BEGIN NOW Which else to several Sphears thou must ascribe, END
BEGIN NOW Mov'd contrarie with thwart obliquities, END
BEGIN NOW Or save the Sun his labour, and that swift END
BEGIN NOW Nocturnal and Diurnal rhomb suppos'd, END
BEGIN NOW Invisible else above all Starrs, the Wheele END
BEGIN NOW Of Day and Night; which needs not thy beleefe, END
BEGIN NOW If Earth industrious of her self fetch Day END
BEGIN NOW Travelling East, and with her part averse END
BEGIN NOW From the Suns beam meet Night, her other part END
BEGIN NOW Still luminous by his ray. What if that light END
BEGIN NOW Sent from her through the wide transpicuous aire, END
BEGIN NOW To the terrestrial Moon be as a Starr END
BEGIN NOW This Earth? reciprocal, if Land be there, END
BEGIN NOW Feilds and Inhabitants: Her spots thou seest END
BEGIN NOW As Clouds, and Clouds may rain, and Rain produce END
BEGIN NOW Fruits in her soft'nd Soile, for some to eate END
BEGIN NOW Allotted there; and other Suns perhaps END
BEGIN NOW With thir attendant Moons thou wilt descrie END
BEGIN NOW Which two great Sexes animate the World, END
BEGIN NOW Stor'd in each Orb perhaps with some that live. END
BEGIN NOW For such vast room in Nature unpossest END
BEGIN NOW By living Soule, desert and desolate, END
BEGIN NOW Onely to shine, yet scarce to contribute END
BEGIN NOW Each Orb a glimps of Light, conveyd so farr END
BEGIN NOW Down to this habitable, which returnes END
BEGIN NOW Light back to them, is obvious to dispute. END
BEGIN NOW But whether thus these things, or whether not, END
BEGIN NOW Whether the Sun predominant in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Rise on the Earth, or Earth rise on the Sun, END
BEGIN NOW Hee from the East his flaming rode begin, END
BEGIN NOW Or Shee from West her silent course advance END
BEGIN NOW With inoffensive pace that spinning sleeps END
BEGIN NOW On her soft Axle, while she paces Eev'n, END
BEGIN NOW And bears thee soft with the smooth Air along, END
BEGIN NOW Sollicit not thy thoughts with matters hid, END
BEGIN NOW Leave them to God above, him serve and feare; END
BEGIN NOW Of other Creatures, as him pleases best, END
BEGIN NOW Wherever plac't, let him dispose: joy thou END
BEGIN NOW In what he gives to thee, this Paradise END
BEGIN NOW And thy faire EVE; Heav'n is for thee too high END
BEGIN NOW To know what passes there; be lowlie wise: END
BEGIN NOW Think onely what concernes thee and thy being; END
BEGIN NOW Dream not of other Worlds, what Creatures there END
BEGIN NOW Live, in what state, condition or degree, END
BEGIN NOW Contented that thus farr hath been reveal'd END
BEGIN NOW Not of Earth onely but of highest Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus ADAM cleerd of doubt, repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW How fully hast thou satisfi'd mee, pure END
BEGIN NOW Intelligence of Heav'n, Angel serene, END
BEGIN NOW And freed from intricacies, taught to live, END
BEGIN NOW The easiest way, nor with perplexing thoughts END
BEGIN NOW To interrupt the sweet of Life, from which END
BEGIN NOW God hath bid dwell farr off all anxious cares, END
BEGIN NOW And not molest us, unless we our selves END
BEGIN NOW Seek them with wandring thoughts, and notions vaine. END
BEGIN NOW But apt the Mind or Fancie is to roave END
BEGIN NOW Uncheckt, and of her roaving is no end; END
BEGIN NOW Till warn'd, or by experience taught, she learne, END
BEGIN NOW That not to know at large of things remote END
BEGIN NOW From use, obscure and suttle, but to know END
BEGIN NOW That which before us lies in daily life, END
BEGIN NOW Is the prime Wisdom, what is more, is fume, END
BEGIN NOW Or emptiness, or fond impertinence, END
BEGIN NOW And renders us in things that most concerne END
BEGIN NOW Unpractis'd, unprepar'd, and still to seek. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore from this high pitch let us descend END
BEGIN NOW A lower flight, and speak of things at hand END
BEGIN NOW Useful, whence haply mention may arise END
BEGIN NOW Of somthing not unseasonable to ask END
BEGIN NOW By sufferance, and thy wonted favour deign'd. END
BEGIN NOW Thee I have heard relating what was don END
BEGIN NOW Ere my remembrance: now hear mee relate END
BEGIN NOW My Storie, which perhaps thou hast not heard; END
BEGIN NOW And Day is yet not spent; till then thou seest END
BEGIN NOW How suttly to detaine thee I devise, END
BEGIN NOW Inviting thee to hear while I relate, END
BEGIN NOW Fond, were it not in hope of thy reply: END
BEGIN NOW For while I sit with thee, I seem in Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW And sweeter thy discourse is to my eare END
BEGIN NOW Then Fruits of Palm-tree pleasantest to thirst END
BEGIN NOW And hunger both, from labour, at the houre END
BEGIN NOW Of sweet repast; they satiate, and soon fill, END
BEGIN NOW Though pleasant, but thy words with Grace Divine END
BEGIN NOW Imbu'd, bring to thir sweetness no satietie. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus RAPHAEL answer'd heav'nly meek. END
BEGIN NOW Nor are thy lips ungraceful, Sire of men, END
BEGIN NOW Nor tongue ineloquent; for God on thee END
BEGIN NOW Abundantly his gifts hath also pour'd, END
BEGIN NOW Inward and outward both, his image faire: END
BEGIN NOW Speaking or mute all comliness and grace END
BEGIN NOW Attends thee, and each word, each motion formes. END
BEGIN NOW Nor less think wee in Heav'n of thee on Earth END
BEGIN NOW Then of our fellow servant, and inquire END
BEGIN NOW Gladly into the wayes of God with Man: END
BEGIN NOW For God we see hath honour'd thee, and set END
BEGIN NOW On Man his equal Love: say therefore on; END
BEGIN NOW For I that Day was absent, as befell, END
BEGIN NOW Bound on a voyage uncouth and obscure, END
BEGIN NOW Farr on excursion toward the Gates of Hell; END
BEGIN NOW Squar'd in full Legion (such command we had) END
BEGIN NOW To see that none thence issu'd forth a spie, END
BEGIN NOW Or enemie, while God was in his work, END
BEGIN NOW Least hee incenst at such eruption bold, END
BEGIN NOW Destruction with Creation might have mixt. END
BEGIN NOW Not that they durst without his leave attempt, END
BEGIN NOW But us he sends upon his high behests END
BEGIN NOW For state, as Sovran King, and to enure END
BEGIN NOW Our prompt obedience. Fast we found, fast shut END
BEGIN NOW The dismal Gates, and barricado'd strong; END
BEGIN NOW But long ere our approaching heard within END
BEGIN NOW Noise, other then the sound of Dance or Song, END
BEGIN NOW Torment, and lowd lament, and furious rage. END
BEGIN NOW Glad we return'd up to the coasts of Light END
BEGIN NOW Ere Sabbath Eev'ning: so we had in charge. END
BEGIN NOW But thy relation now; for I attend, END
BEGIN NOW Pleas'd with thy words no less then thou with mine. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Godlike Power, and thus our Sire. END
BEGIN NOW For Man to tell how human Life began END
BEGIN NOW Is hard; for who himself beginning knew? END
BEGIN NOW Desire with thee still longer to converse END
BEGIN NOW Induc'd me. As new wak't from soundest sleep END
BEGIN NOW Soft on the flourie herb I found me laid END
BEGIN NOW In Balmie Sweat, which with his Beames the Sun END
BEGIN NOW Soon dri'd, and on the reaking moisture fed. END
BEGIN NOW Strait toward Heav'n my wondring Eyes I turnd, END
BEGIN NOW And gaz'd a while the ample Skie, till rais'd END
BEGIN NOW By quick instinctive motion up I sprung, END
BEGIN NOW As thitherward endevoring, and upright END
BEGIN NOW Stood on my feet; about me round I saw END
BEGIN NOW Hill, Dale, and shadie Woods, and sunnie Plaines, END
BEGIN NOW And liquid Lapse of murmuring Streams; by these, END
BEGIN NOW Creatures that livd, and movd, and walk'd, or flew, END
BEGIN NOW Birds on the branches warbling; all things smil'd, END
BEGIN NOW With fragrance and with joy my heart oreflow'd. END
BEGIN NOW My self I then perus'd, and Limb by Limb END
BEGIN NOW Survey'd, and sometimes went, and sometimes ran END
BEGIN NOW With supple joints, as lively vigour led: END
BEGIN NOW But who I was, or where, or from what cause, END
BEGIN NOW Knew not; to speak I tri'd, and forthwith spake, END
BEGIN NOW My Tongue obey'd and readily could name END
BEGIN NOW What e're I saw. Thou Sun, said I, faire Light, END
BEGIN NOW And thou enlight'nd Earth, so fresh and gay, END
BEGIN NOW And ye that live and move, fair Creatures, tell, END
BEGIN NOW Tell, if ye saw, how came I thus, how here? END
BEGIN NOW Not of my self; by some great Maker then, END
BEGIN NOW In goodness and in power praeeminent; END
BEGIN NOW Tell me, how may I know him, how adore, END
BEGIN NOW From whom I have that thus I move and live, END
BEGIN NOW And feel that I am happier then I know. END
BEGIN NOW While thus I call'd, and stray'd I knew not whither, END
BEGIN NOW From where I first drew Aire, and first beheld END
BEGIN NOW This happie Light, when answer none return'd, END
BEGIN NOW On a green shadie Bank profuse of Flours END
BEGIN NOW Pensive I sate me down; there gentle sleep END
BEGIN NOW First found me, and with soft oppression seis'd END
BEGIN NOW My droused sense, untroubl'd, though I thought END
BEGIN NOW I then was passing to my former state END
BEGIN NOW Insensible, and forthwith to dissolve: END
BEGIN NOW When suddenly stood at my Head a dream, END
BEGIN NOW Whose inward apparition gently mov'd END
BEGIN NOW My Fancy to believe I yet had being, END
BEGIN NOW And livd: One came, methought, of shape Divine, END
BEGIN NOW And said, thy Mansion wants thee, ADAM, rise, END
BEGIN NOW First Man, of Men innumerable ordain'd END
BEGIN NOW First Father, call'd by thee I come thy Guide END
BEGIN NOW To the Garden of bliss, thy seat prepar'd. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, by the hand he took me rais'd, END
BEGIN NOW And over Fields and Waters, as in Aire END
BEGIN NOW Smooth sliding without step, last led me up END
BEGIN NOW A woodie Mountain; whose high top was plaine, END
BEGIN NOW A Circuit wide, enclos'd, with goodliest Trees END
BEGIN NOW Planted, with Walks, and Bowers, that what I saw END
BEGIN NOW Of Earth before scarse pleasant seemd. Each Tree END
BEGIN NOW Load'n with fairest Fruit, that hung to the Eye END
BEGIN NOW Tempting, stirr'd in me sudden appetite END
BEGIN NOW To pluck and eate; whereat I wak'd, and found END
BEGIN NOW Before mine Eyes all real, as the dream END
BEGIN NOW Had lively shadowd: Here had new begun END
BEGIN NOW My wandring, had not hee who was my Guide END
BEGIN NOW Up hither, from among the Trees appeer'd, END
BEGIN NOW Presence Divine. Rejoycing, but with aw END
BEGIN NOW In adoration at his feet I fell END
BEGIN NOW Submiss: he rear'd me, & Whom thou soughtst I am, END
BEGIN NOW Said mildely, Author of all this thou seest END
BEGIN NOW Above, or round about thee or beneath. END
BEGIN NOW This Paradise I give thee, count it thine END
BEGIN NOW To Till and keep, and of the Fruit to eate: END
BEGIN NOW Of every Tree that in the Garden growes END
BEGIN NOW Eate freely with glad heart; fear here no dearth: END
BEGIN NOW But of the Tree whose operation brings END
BEGIN NOW Knowledg of good and ill, which I have set END
BEGIN NOW Remember what I warne thee, shun to taste, END
BEGIN NOW And shun the bitter consequence: for know, END
BEGIN NOW The day thou eat'st thereof, my sole command END
BEGIN NOW Transgrest, inevitably thou shalt dye; END
BEGIN NOW From that day mortal, and this happie State END
BEGIN NOW Shalt loose, expell'd from hence into a World END
BEGIN NOW Of woe and sorrow. Sternly he pronounc'd END
BEGIN NOW The rigid interdiction, which resounds END
BEGIN NOW Yet dreadful in mine eare, though in my choice END
BEGIN NOW Not to incur; but soon his cleer aspect END
BEGIN NOW Return'd and gratious purpose thus renew'd. END
BEGIN NOW Not onely these fair bounds, but all the Earth END
BEGIN NOW To thee and to thy Race I give; as Lords END
BEGIN NOW Possess it, and all things that therein live, END
BEGIN NOW Or live in Sea, or Aire, Beast, Fish, and Fowle. END
BEGIN NOW In signe whereof each Bird and Beast behold END
BEGIN NOW After thir kindes; I bring them to receave END
BEGIN NOW From thee thir Names, and pay thee fealtie END
BEGIN NOW With low subjection; understand the same END
BEGIN NOW Of Fish within thir watry residence, END
BEGIN NOW Not hither summond, since they cannot change END
BEGIN NOW Thir Element to draw the thinner Aire. END
BEGIN NOW As thus he spake, each Bird and Beast behold END
BEGIN NOW Approaching two and two, These cowring low END
BEGIN NOW With blandishment, each Bird stoop'd on his wing. END
BEGIN NOW I nam'd them, as they pass'd, and understood END
BEGIN NOW Thir Nature, with such knowledg God endu'd END
BEGIN NOW My sudden apprehension: but in these END
BEGIN NOW I found not what me thought I wanted still; END
BEGIN NOW And to the Heav'nly vision thus presum'd. END
BEGIN NOW O by what Name, for thou above all these, END
BEGIN NOW Above mankinde, or aught then mankinde higher, END
BEGIN NOW Surpassest farr my naming, how may I END
BEGIN NOW Adore thee, Author of this Universe, END
BEGIN NOW And all this good to man, for whose well being END
BEGIN NOW So amply, and with hands so liberal END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast provided all things: but with mee END
BEGIN NOW I see not who partakes. In solitude END
BEGIN NOW What happiness, who can enjoy alone, END
BEGIN NOW Or all enjoying, what contentment find? END
BEGIN NOW Thus I presumptuous; and the vision bright, END
BEGIN NOW As with a smile more bright'nd, thus repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW What call'st thou solitude, is not the Earth END
BEGIN NOW With various living creatures, and the Aire END
BEGIN NOW Replenisht, and all these at thy command END
BEGIN NOW To come and play before thee, know'st thou not END
BEGIN NOW Thir language and thir wayes, they also know, END
BEGIN NOW And reason not contemptibly; with these END
BEGIN NOW Find pastime, and beare rule; thy Realm is large. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Universal Lord, and seem'd END
BEGIN NOW So ordering. I with leave of speech implor'd, END
BEGIN NOW And humble deprecation thus repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Let not my words offend thee, Heav'nly Power, END
BEGIN NOW My Maker, be propitious while I speak. END
BEGIN NOW Hast thou not made me here thy substitute, END
BEGIN NOW And these inferiour farr beneath me set? END
BEGIN NOW Among unequals what societie END
BEGIN NOW Can sort, what harmonie or true delight? END
BEGIN NOW Which must be mutual, in proportion due END
BEGIN NOW Giv'n and receiv'd; but in disparitie END
BEGIN NOW The one intense, the other still remiss END
BEGIN NOW Cannot well suite with either, but soon prove END
BEGIN NOW Tedious alike: Of fellowship I speak END
BEGIN NOW Such as I seek, fit to participate END
BEGIN NOW All rational delight, wherein the brute END
BEGIN NOW Cannot be human consort; they rejoyce END
BEGIN NOW Each with thir kinde, Lion with Lioness; END
BEGIN NOW So fitly them in pairs thou hast combin'd; END
BEGIN NOW Much less can Bird with Beast, or Fish with Fowle END
BEGIN NOW So well converse, nor with the Ox the Ape; END
BEGIN NOW Wors then can Man with Beast, and least of all. END
BEGIN NOW Whereto th' Almighty answer'd, not displeas'd. END
BEGIN NOW A nice and suttle happiness I see END
BEGIN NOW Thou to thy self proposest, in the choice END
BEGIN NOW Of thy Associates, ADAM, and wilt taste END
BEGIN NOW No pleasure, though in pleasure, solitarie. END
BEGIN NOW What thinkst thou then of mee, and this my State, END
BEGIN NOW Seem I to thee sufficiently possest END
BEGIN NOW Of happiness, or not? who am alone END
BEGIN NOW From all Eternitie, for none I know END
BEGIN NOW Second to mee or like, equal much less. END
BEGIN NOW How have I then with whom to hold converse END
BEGIN NOW Save with the Creatures which I made, and those END
BEGIN NOW To me inferiour, infinite descents END
BEGIN NOW Beneath what other Creatures are to thee? END
BEGIN NOW He ceas'd, I lowly answer'd. To attaine END
BEGIN NOW The highth and depth of thy Eternal wayes END
BEGIN NOW All human thoughts come short, Supream of things; END
BEGIN NOW Thou in thy self art perfet, and in thee END
BEGIN NOW Is no deficience found; not so is Man, END
BEGIN NOW But in degree, the cause of his desire END
BEGIN NOW By conversation with his like to help, END
BEGIN NOW Or solace his defects. No need that thou END
BEGIN NOW Shouldst propagat, already infinite; END
BEGIN NOW And through all numbers absolute, though One; END
BEGIN NOW But Man by number is to manifest END
BEGIN NOW His single imperfection, and beget END
BEGIN NOW Like of his like, his Image multipli'd, END
BEGIN NOW In unitie defective, which requires END
BEGIN NOW Collateral love, and deerest amitie. END
BEGIN NOW Thou in thy secresie although alone, END
BEGIN NOW Best with thy self accompanied, seek'st not END
BEGIN NOW Social communication, yet so pleas'd, END
BEGIN NOW Canst raise thy Creature to what highth thou wilt END
BEGIN NOW Of Union or Communion, deifi'd; END
BEGIN NOW I by conversing cannot these erect END
BEGIN NOW From prone, nor in thir wayes complacence find. END
BEGIN NOW Thus I embold'nd spake, and freedom us'd END
BEGIN NOW Permissive, and acceptance found, which gain'd END
BEGIN NOW This answer from the gratious voice Divine. END
BEGIN NOW Thus farr to try thee, ADAM, I was pleas'd, END
BEGIN NOW And finde thee knowing not of Beasts alone, END
BEGIN NOW Which thou hast rightly nam'd, but of thy self, END
BEGIN NOW Expressing well the spirit within thee free, END
BEGIN NOW My Image, not imparted to the Brute, END
BEGIN NOW Whose fellowship therefore unmeet for thee END
BEGIN NOW Good reason was thou freely shouldst dislike, END
BEGIN NOW And be so minded still; I, ere thou spak'st, END
BEGIN NOW Knew it not good for Man to be alone, END
BEGIN NOW And no such companie as then thou saw'st END
BEGIN NOW Intended thee, for trial onely brought, END
BEGIN NOW To see how thou could'st judge of fit and meet: END
BEGIN NOW What next I bring shall please thee, be assur'd, END
BEGIN NOW Thy likeness, thy fit help, thy other self, END
BEGIN NOW Thy wish, exactly to thy hearts desire. END
BEGIN NOW Hee ended, or I heard no more, for now END
BEGIN NOW My earthly by his Heav'nly overpowerd, END
BEGIN NOW Which it had long stood under, streind to the highth END
BEGIN NOW In that celestial Colloquie sublime, END
BEGIN NOW As with an object that excels the sense, END
BEGIN NOW Dazl'd and spent, sunk down, and sought repair END
BEGIN NOW Of sleep, which instantly fell on me, call'd END
BEGIN NOW By Nature as in aide, and clos'd mine eyes. END
BEGIN NOW Mine eyes he clos'd, but op'n left the Cell END
BEGIN NOW Of Fancie my internal sight, by which END
BEGIN NOW Abstract as in a transe methought I saw, END
BEGIN NOW Though sleeping, where I lay, and saw the shape END
BEGIN NOW Still glorious before whom awake I stood; END
BEGIN NOW Who stooping op'nd my left side, and took END
BEGIN NOW From thence a Rib, with cordial spirits warme, END
BEGIN NOW And Life-blood streaming fresh; wide was the wound, END
BEGIN NOW But suddenly with flesh fill'd up & heal'd: END
BEGIN NOW The Rib he formd and fashond with his hands; END
BEGIN NOW Under his forming hands a Creature grew, END
BEGIN NOW Manlike, but different sex, so lovly faire, END
BEGIN NOW That what seemd fair in all the World, seemd now END
BEGIN NOW Mean, or in her summd up, in her containd END
BEGIN NOW And in her looks, which from that time infus'd END
BEGIN NOW Sweetness into my heart, unfelt before, END
BEGIN NOW And into all things from her Aire inspir'd END
BEGIN NOW The spirit of love and amorous delight. END
BEGIN NOW She disappeerd, and left me dark, I wak'd END
BEGIN NOW To find her, or for ever to deplore END
BEGIN NOW Her loss, and other pleasures all abjure: END
BEGIN NOW When out of hope, behold her, not farr off, END
BEGIN NOW Such as I saw her in my dream, adornd END
BEGIN NOW With what all Earth or Heaven could bestow END
BEGIN NOW To make her amiable: On she came, END
BEGIN NOW Led by her Heav'nly Maker, though unseen, END
BEGIN NOW And guided by his voice, nor uninformd END
BEGIN NOW Of nuptial Sanctitie and marriage Rites: END
BEGIN NOW Grace was in all her steps, Heav'n in her Eye, END
BEGIN NOW In every gesture dignitie and love. END
BEGIN NOW I overjoyd could not forbear aloud. END
BEGIN NOW This turn hath made amends; thou hast fulfill'd END
BEGIN NOW Thy words, Creator bounteous and benigne, END
BEGIN NOW Giver of all things faire, but fairest this END
BEGIN NOW Of all thy gifts, nor enviest. I now see END
BEGIN NOW Extracted; for this cause he shall forgoe END
BEGIN NOW Father and Mother, and to his Wife adhere; END
BEGIN NOW And they shall be one Flesh, one Heart, one Soule. END
BEGIN NOW She heard me thus, and though divinely brought, END
BEGIN NOW Her vertue and the conscience of her worth, END
BEGIN NOW That would be woo'd, and not unsought be won, END
BEGIN NOW Not obvious, not obtrusive, but retir'd, END
BEGIN NOW The more desirable, or to say all, END
BEGIN NOW Nature her self, though pure of sinful thought, END
BEGIN NOW Wrought in her so, that seeing me, she turn'd; END
BEGIN NOW I follow'd her, she what was Honour knew, END
BEGIN NOW And with obsequious Majestie approv'd END
BEGIN NOW My pleaded reason. To the Nuptial Bowre END
BEGIN NOW I led her blushing like the Morn: all Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW And happie Constellations on that houre END
BEGIN NOW Shed thir selectest influence; the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Gave sign of gratulation, and each Hill; END
BEGIN NOW Joyous the Birds; fresh Gales and gentle Aires END
BEGIN NOW Whisper'd it to the Woods, and from thir wings END
BEGIN NOW Flung Rose, flung Odours from the spicie Shrub, END
BEGIN NOW Disporting, till the amorous Bird of Night END
BEGIN NOW Sung Spousal, and bid haste the Eevning Starr END
BEGIN NOW On his Hill top, to light the bridal Lamp. END
BEGIN NOW Thus I have told thee all my State, and brought END
BEGIN NOW My Storie to the sum of earthly bliss END
BEGIN NOW Which I enjoy, and must confess to find END
BEGIN NOW In all things else delight indeed, but such END
BEGIN NOW As us'd or not, works in the mind no change, END
BEGIN NOW Nor vehement desire, these delicacies END
BEGIN NOW I mean of Taste, Sight, Smell, Herbs, Fruits, & Flours, END
BEGIN NOW Walks, and the melodie of Birds; but here END
BEGIN NOW Farr otherwise, transported I behold, END
BEGIN NOW Transported touch; here passion first I felt, END
BEGIN NOW Commotion strange, in all enjoyments else END
BEGIN NOW Superiour and unmov'd, here onely weake END
BEGIN NOW Against the charm of Beauties powerful glance. END
BEGIN NOW Or Nature faild in mee, and left some part END
BEGIN NOW Not proof enough such Object to sustain, END
BEGIN NOW Or from my side subducting, took perhaps END
BEGIN NOW More then enough; at least on her bestow'd END
BEGIN NOW Too much of Ornament, in outward shew END
BEGIN NOW Elaborate, of inward less exact. END
BEGIN NOW For well I understand in the prime end END
BEGIN NOW Of Nature her th' inferiour, in the mind END
BEGIN NOW And inward Faculties, which most excell, END
BEGIN NOW In outward also her resembling less END
BEGIN NOW His Image who made both, and less expressing END
BEGIN NOW The character of that Dominion giv'n END
BEGIN NOW O're other Creatures; yet when I approach END
BEGIN NOW Her loveliness, so absolute she seems END
BEGIN NOW And in her self compleat, so well to know END
BEGIN NOW Her own, that what she wills to do or say, END
BEGIN NOW Seems wisest, vertuousest, discreetest, best; END
BEGIN NOW All higher knowledge in her presence falls END
BEGIN NOW Degraded, Wisdom in discourse with her END
BEGIN NOW Looses discount'nanc't, and like folly shewes; END
BEGIN NOW Authoritie and Reason on her waite, END
BEGIN NOW As one intended first, not after made END
BEGIN NOW Occasionally; and to consummate all, END
BEGIN NOW Greatness of mind and nobleness thir seat END
BEGIN NOW Build in her loveliest, and create an awe END
BEGIN NOW About her, as a guard Angelic plac't. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Angel with contracted brow. END
BEGIN NOW Accuse not Nature, she hath don her part; END
BEGIN NOW Do thou but thine, and be not diffident END
BEGIN NOW Of Wisdom, she deserts thee not, if thou END
BEGIN NOW Dismiss not her, when most thou needst her nigh, END
BEGIN NOW By attributing overmuch to things END
BEGIN NOW Less excellent, as thou thy self perceav'st. END
BEGIN NOW For what admir'st thou, what transports thee so, END
BEGIN NOW An outside? fair no doubt, and worthy well END
BEGIN NOW Thy cherishing, thy honouring, and thy love, END
BEGIN NOW Not thy subjection: weigh with her thy self; END
BEGIN NOW Then value: Oft times nothing profits more END
BEGIN NOW Then self-esteem, grounded on just and right END
BEGIN NOW Well manag'd; of that skill the more thou know'st, END
BEGIN NOW The more she will acknowledge thee her Head, END
BEGIN NOW And to realities yeild all her shows; END
BEGIN NOW Made so adorn for thy delight the more, END
BEGIN NOW So awful, that with honour thou maist love END
BEGIN NOW Thy mate, who sees when thou art seen least wise. END
BEGIN NOW But if the sense of touch whereby mankind END
BEGIN NOW Is propagated seem such dear delight END
BEGIN NOW Beyond all other, think the same voutsaf't END
BEGIN NOW To Cattel and each Beast; which would not be END
BEGIN NOW To them made common & divulg'd, if aught END
BEGIN NOW Therein enjoy'd were worthy to subdue END
BEGIN NOW The Soule of Man, or passion in him move. END
BEGIN NOW What higher in her societie thou findst END
BEGIN NOW Attractive, human, rational, love still; END
BEGIN NOW In loving thou dost well, in passion not, END
BEGIN NOW Wherein true Love consists not; love refines END
BEGIN NOW The thoughts, and heart enlarges, hath his seat END
BEGIN NOW In Reason, and is judicious, is the scale END
BEGIN NOW By which to heav'nly Love thou maist ascend, END
BEGIN NOW Not sunk in carnal pleasure, for which cause END
BEGIN NOW Among the Beasts no Mate for thee was found. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus half abash't ADAM repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Neither her out-side formd so fair, nor aught END
BEGIN NOW In procreation common to all kindes END
BEGIN NOW (Though higher of the genial Bed by far, END
BEGIN NOW And with mysterious reverence I deem) END
BEGIN NOW So much delights me, as those graceful acts, END
BEGIN NOW Those thousand decencies that daily flow END
BEGIN NOW From all her words and actions, mixt with Love END
BEGIN NOW And sweet compliance, which declare unfeign'd END
BEGIN NOW Union of Mind, or in us both one Soule; END
BEGIN NOW Harmonie to behold in wedded pair END
BEGIN NOW More grateful then harmonious sound to the eare. END
BEGIN NOW Yet these subject not; I to thee disclose END
BEGIN NOW What inward thence I feel, not therefore foild, END
BEGIN NOW Who meet with various objects, from the sense END
BEGIN NOW Variously representing; yet still free END
BEGIN NOW Approve the best, and follow what I approve. END
BEGIN NOW To love thou blam'st me not, for love thou saist END
BEGIN NOW Leads up to Heav'n, is both the way and guide; END
BEGIN NOW Bear with me then, if lawful what I ask; END
BEGIN NOW Love not the heav'nly Spirits, and how thir Love END
BEGIN NOW Express they, by looks onely, or do they mix END
BEGIN NOW Irradiance, virtual or immediate touch? END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Angel with a smile that glow'd END
BEGIN NOW Celestial rosie red, Loves proper hue, END
BEGIN NOW Answer'd. Let it suffice thee that thou know'st END
BEGIN NOW Us happie, and without Love no happiness. END
BEGIN NOW Whatever pure thou in the body enjoy'st END
BEGIN NOW (And pure thou wert created) we enjoy END
BEGIN NOW In eminence, and obstacle find none END
BEGIN NOW Of membrane, joynt, or limb, exclusive barrs: END
BEGIN NOW Easier then Air with Air, if Spirits embrace, END
BEGIN NOW Total they mix, Union of Pure with Pure END
BEGIN NOW Desiring; nor restrain'd conveyance need END
BEGIN NOW As Flesh to mix with Flesh, or Soul with Soul. END
BEGIN NOW But I can now no more; the parting Sun END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the Earths green Cape and verdant Isles END
BEGIN NOW HESPEREAN sets, my Signal to depart. END
BEGIN NOW Be strong, live happie, and love, but first of all END
BEGIN NOW Him whom to love is to obey, and keep END
BEGIN NOW His great command; take heed least Passion sway END
BEGIN NOW Thy Judgement to do aught, which else free Will END
BEGIN NOW Would not admit; thine and of all thy Sons END
BEGIN NOW The weal or woe in thee is plac't; beware. END
BEGIN NOW I in thy persevering shall rejoyce, END
BEGIN NOW And all the Blest: stand fast; to stand or fall END
BEGIN NOW Free in thine own Arbitrement it lies. END
BEGIN NOW Perfet within, no outward aid require; END
BEGIN NOW And all temptation to transgress repel. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, he arose; whom ADAM thus END
BEGIN NOW Follow'd with benediction. Since to part, END
BEGIN NOW Go heavenly Guest, Ethereal Messenger, END
BEGIN NOW Sent from whose sovran goodness I adore. END
BEGIN NOW Gentle to me and affable hath been END
BEGIN NOW Thy condescension, and shall be honour'd ever END
BEGIN NOW With grateful Memorie: thou to mankind END
BEGIN NOW Be good and friendly still, and oft return. END
BEGIN NOW So parted they, the Angel up to Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW From the thick shade, and ADAM to his Bowre. END
BEGIN NOW No more of talk where God or Angel Guest END
BEGIN NOW With Man, as with his Friend, familiar us'd END
BEGIN NOW To sit indulgent, and with him partake END
BEGIN NOW Rural repast, permitting him the while END
BEGIN NOW Venial discourse unblam'd: I now must change END
BEGIN NOW Those Notes to Tragic; foul distrust, and breach END
BEGIN NOW Disloyal on the part of Man, revolt END
BEGIN NOW And disobedience: On the part of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Now alienated, distance and distaste, END
BEGIN NOW Anger and just rebuke, and judgement giv'n, END
BEGIN NOW That brought into this World a world of woe, END
BEGIN NOW Sinne and her shadow Death, and Miserie END
BEGIN NOW Deaths Harbinger: Sad task, yet argument END
BEGIN NOW Not less but more Heroic then the wrauth END
BEGIN NOW Of stern ACHILLES on his Foe pursu'd END
BEGIN NOW Thrice Fugitive about TROY Wall; or rage END
BEGIN NOW Of TURNUS for LAVINIA disespous'd, END
BEGIN NOW Or NEPTUN'S ire or JUNO'S, that so long END
BEGIN NOW Perplex'd the GREEK and CYTHEREA'S Son; END
BEGIN NOW If answerable style I can obtaine END
BEGIN NOW Of my Celestial Patroness, who deignes END
BEGIN NOW Her nightly visitation unimplor'd, END
BEGIN NOW And dictates to me slumbring, or inspires END
BEGIN NOW Easie my unpremeditated Verse: END
BEGIN NOW Since first this subject for Heroic Song END
BEGIN NOW Pleas'd me long choosing, and beginning late; END
BEGIN NOW Not sedulous by Nature to indite END
BEGIN NOW Warrs, hitherto the onely Argument END
BEGIN NOW Heroic deem'd, chief maistrie to dissect END
BEGIN NOW With long and tedious havoc fabl'd Knights END
BEGIN NOW In Battels feign'd; the better fortitude END
BEGIN NOW Unsung; or to describe Races and Games, END
BEGIN NOW Or tilting Furniture, emblazon'd Shields, END
BEGIN NOW Impreses quaint, Caparisons and Steeds; END
BEGIN NOW Bases and tinsel Trappings, gorgious Knights END
BEGIN NOW At Joust and Torneament; then marshal'd Feast END
BEGIN NOW Serv'd up in Hall with Sewers, and Seneshals; END
BEGIN NOW The skill of Artifice or Office mean, END
BEGIN NOW Not that which justly gives Heroic name END
BEGIN NOW To Person or to Poem. Mee of these END
BEGIN NOW Nor skilld nor studious, higher Argument END
BEGIN NOW Remaines, sufficient of it self to raise END
BEGIN NOW That name, unless an age too late, or cold END
BEGIN NOW Climat, or Years damp my intended wing END
BEGIN NOW Deprest, and much they may, if all be mine, END
BEGIN NOW Not Hers who brings it nightly to my Ear. END
BEGIN NOW The Sun was sunk, and after him the Starr END
BEGIN NOW Of HESPERUS, whose Office is to bring END
BEGIN NOW Twilight upon the Earth, short Arbiter END
BEGIN NOW Twixt Day and Night, and now from end to end END
BEGIN NOW Nights Hemisphere had veild the Horizon round: END
BEGIN NOW When SATAN who late fled before the threats END
BEGIN NOW Of GABRIEL out of EDEN, now improv'd END
BEGIN NOW In meditated fraud and malice, bent END
BEGIN NOW On mans destruction, maugre what might hap END
BEGIN NOW Of heavier on himself, fearless return'd. END
BEGIN NOW By Night he fled, and at Midnight return'd END
BEGIN NOW From compassing the Earth, cautious of day, END
BEGIN NOW Since URIEL Regent of the Sun descri'd END
BEGIN NOW His entrance, and forewarnd the Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW That kept thir watch; thence full of anguish driv'n, END
BEGIN NOW The space of seven continu'd Nights he rode END
BEGIN NOW With darkness, thrice the Equinoctial Line END
BEGIN NOW He circl'd, four times cross'd the Carr of Night END
BEGIN NOW From Pole to Pole, traversing each Colure; END
BEGIN NOW On the eighth return'd, and on the Coast averse END
BEGIN NOW From entrance or Cherubic Watch, by stealth END
BEGIN NOW Found unsuspected way. There was a place, END
BEGIN NOW Now not, though Sin, not Time, first wraught the change, END
BEGIN NOW Where TIGRIS at the foot of Paradise END
BEGIN NOW Into a Gulf shot under ground, till part END
BEGIN NOW In with the River sunk, and with it rose END
BEGIN NOW Satan involv'd in rising Mist, then sought END
BEGIN NOW Where to lie hid; Sea he had searcht and Land END
BEGIN NOW From EDEN over PONTUS, and the Poole END
BEGIN NOW MAEOTIS, up beyond the River OB; END
BEGIN NOW Downward as farr Antartic; and in length END
BEGIN NOW West from ORANTES to the Ocean barr'd END
BEGIN NOW At DARIEN, thence to the Land where flowes END
BEGIN NOW GANGES and INDUS: thus the Orb he roam'd END
BEGIN NOW With narrow search; and with inspection deep END
BEGIN NOW Consider'd every Creature, which of all END
BEGIN NOW Most opportune might serve his Wiles, and found END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent suttlest Beast of all the Field. END
BEGIN NOW Him after long debate, irresolute END
BEGIN NOW Of thoughts revolv'd, his final sentence chose END
BEGIN NOW Fit Vessel, fittest Imp of fraud, in whom END
BEGIN NOW To enter, and his dark suggestions hide END
BEGIN NOW From sharpest sight: for in the wilie Snake, END
BEGIN NOW Whatever sleights none would suspicious mark, END
BEGIN NOW As from his wit and native suttletie END
BEGIN NOW Proceeding, which in other Beasts observ'd END
BEGIN NOW Doubt might beget of Diabolic pow'r END
BEGIN NOW Active within beyond the sense of brute. END
BEGIN NOW Thus he resolv'd, but first from inward griefe END
BEGIN NOW His bursting passion into plaints thus pour'd: END
BEGIN NOW O Earth, how like to Heav'n, if not preferrd END
BEGIN NOW More justly, Seat worthier of Gods, as built END
BEGIN NOW With second thoughts, reforming what was old! END
BEGIN NOW For what God after better worse would build? END
BEGIN NOW Terrestrial Heav'n, danc't round by other Heav'ns END
BEGIN NOW That shine, yet bear thir bright officious Lamps, END
BEGIN NOW Light above Light, for thee alone, as seems, END
BEGIN NOW In thee concentring all thir precious beams END
BEGIN NOW Of sacred influence: As God in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Is Center, yet extends to all, so thou END
BEGIN NOW Centring receav'st from all those Orbs; in thee, END
BEGIN NOW Not in themselves, all thir known vertue appeers END
BEGIN NOW Productive in Herb, Plant, and nobler birth END
BEGIN NOW Of Creatures animate with gradual life END
BEGIN NOW Of Growth, Sense, Reason, all summ'd up in Man. END
BEGIN NOW With what delight could I have walkt thee round END
BEGIN NOW If I could joy in aught, sweet interchange END
BEGIN NOW Now Land, now Sea, & Shores with Forrest crownd, END
BEGIN NOW Rocks, Dens, and Caves; but I in none of these END
BEGIN NOW Find place or refuge; and the more I see END
BEGIN NOW Pleasures about me, so much more I feel END
BEGIN NOW Torment within me, as from the hateful siege END
BEGIN NOW Of contraries; all good to me becomes END
BEGIN NOW Bane, and in Heav'n much worse would be my state. END
BEGIN NOW But neither here seek I, no nor in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW To dwell, unless by maistring Heav'ns Supreame; END
BEGIN NOW Nor hope to be my self less miserable END
BEGIN NOW By what I seek, but others to make such END
BEGIN NOW As I though thereby worse to me redound: END
BEGIN NOW For onely in destroying I finde ease END
BEGIN NOW To my relentless thoughts; and him destroyd, END
BEGIN NOW Or won to what may work his utter loss, END
BEGIN NOW For whom all this was made, all this will soon END
BEGIN NOW Follow, as to him linkt in weal or woe, END
BEGIN NOW In wo then; that destruction wide may range: END
BEGIN NOW To mee shall be the glorie sole among END
BEGIN NOW The infernal Powers, in one day to have marr'd END
BEGIN NOW What he ALMIGHTIE styl'd, six Nights and Days END
BEGIN NOW Continu'd making, and who knows how long END
BEGIN NOW Before had bin contriving, though perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Not longer then since I in one Night freed END
BEGIN NOW From servitude inglorious welnigh half END
BEGIN NOW Th' Angelic Name, and thinner left the throng END
BEGIN NOW Of his adorers: hee to be aveng'd, END
BEGIN NOW And to repaire his numbers thus impair'd, END
BEGIN NOW Whether such vertue spent of old now faild END
BEGIN NOW More Angels to Create, if they at least END
BEGIN NOW Are his Created or to spite us more, END
BEGIN NOW Determin'd to advance into our room END
BEGIN NOW A Creature form'd of Earth, and him endow, END
BEGIN NOW Exalted from so base original, END
BEGIN NOW With Heav'nly spoils, our spoils: What he decreed END
BEGIN NOW He effected; Man he made, and for him built END
BEGIN NOW Magnificent this World, and Earth his seat, END
BEGIN NOW Him Lord pronounc'd, and, O indignitie! END
BEGIN NOW Subjected to his service Angel wings, END
BEGIN NOW And flaming Ministers to watch and tend END
BEGIN NOW Thir earthlie Charge: Of these the vigilance END
BEGIN NOW I dread, and to elude, thus wrapt in mist END
BEGIN NOW Of midnight vapor glide obscure, and prie END
BEGIN NOW In every Bush and Brake, where hap may finde END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent sleeping, in whose mazie foulds END
BEGIN NOW To hide me, and the dark intent I bring. END
BEGIN NOW O foul descent! that I who erst contended END
BEGIN NOW With Gods to sit the highest, am now constraind END
BEGIN NOW Into a Beast, and mixt with bestial slime, END
BEGIN NOW This essence to incarnate and imbrute, END
BEGIN NOW That to the hight of Deitie aspir'd; END
BEGIN NOW But what will not Ambition and Revenge END
BEGIN NOW Descend to? who aspires must down as low END
BEGIN NOW As high he soard, obnoxious first or last END
BEGIN NOW To basest things. Revenge, at first though sweet, END
BEGIN NOW Bitter ere long back on it self recoiles; END
BEGIN NOW Let it; I reck not, so it light well aim'd, END
BEGIN NOW Since higher I fall short, on him who next END
BEGIN NOW Provokes my envie, this new Favorite END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'n, this Man of Clay, Son of despite, END
BEGIN NOW Whom us the more to spite his Maker rais'd END
BEGIN NOW From dust: spite then with spite is best repaid. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, through each Thicket Danck or Drie, END
BEGIN NOW Like a black mist low creeping, he held on END
BEGIN NOW His midnight search, where soonest he might finde END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent: him fast sleeping soon he found END
BEGIN NOW In Labyrinth of many a round self-rowl'd, END
BEGIN NOW His head the midst, well stor'd with suttle wiles: END
BEGIN NOW Not yet in horrid Shade or dismal Den, END
BEGIN NOW Not nocent yet, but on the grassie Herbe END
BEGIN NOW Fearless unfeard he slept: in at his Mouth END
BEGIN NOW The Devil enterd, and his brutal sense, END
BEGIN NOW In heart or head, possessing soon inspir'd END
BEGIN NOW With act intelligential; but his sleep END
BEGIN NOW Disturbd not, waiting close th' approach of Morn. END
BEGIN NOW Now whenas sacred Light began to dawne END
BEGIN NOW In EDEN on the humid Flours, that breathd END
BEGIN NOW Thir morning Incense, when all things that breath, END
BEGIN NOW From th' Earths great Altar send up silent praise END
BEGIN NOW To the Creator, and his Nostrils fill END
BEGIN NOW With gratefull Smell, forth came the human pair END
BEGIN NOW And joynd thir vocal Worship to the Quire END
BEGIN NOW Of Creatures wanting voice, that done, partake END
BEGIN NOW The season, prime for sweetest Sents and Aires: END
BEGIN NOW Then commune how that day they best may ply END
BEGIN NOW Thir growing work: for much thir work outgrew END
BEGIN NOW The hands dispatch of two Gardning so wide. END
BEGIN NOW And EVE first to her Husband thus began. END
BEGIN NOW ADAM, well may we labour still to dress END
BEGIN NOW This Garden, still to tend Plant, Herb and Flour. END
BEGIN NOW Our pleasant task enjoyn'd, but till more hands END
BEGIN NOW Aid us, the work under our labour grows, END
BEGIN NOW Luxurious by restraint; what we by day END
BEGIN NOW Lop overgrown, or prune, or prop, or bind, END
BEGIN NOW One night or two with wanton growth derides END
BEGIN NOW Tending to wilde. Thou therefore now advise END
BEGIN NOW Or hear what to my mind first thoughts present, END
BEGIN NOW Let us divide our labours, thou where choice END
BEGIN NOW Leads thee, or where most needs, whether to wind END
BEGIN NOW The Woodbine round this Arbour, or direct END
BEGIN NOW The clasping Ivie where to climb, while I END
BEGIN NOW In yonder Spring of Roses intermixt END
BEGIN NOW With Myrtle, find what to redress till Noon: END
BEGIN NOW For while so near each other thus all day END
BEGIN NOW Our task we choose, what wonder if no near END
BEGIN NOW Looks intervene and smiles, or object new END
BEGIN NOW Casual discourse draw on, which intermits END
BEGIN NOW Our dayes work brought to little, though begun END
BEGIN NOW Early, and th' hour of Supper comes unearn'd. END
BEGIN NOW To whom mild answer ADAM thus return'd. END
BEGIN NOW Sole EVE, Associate sole, to me beyond END
BEGIN NOW Compare above all living Creatures deare, END
BEGIN NOW Well hast thou motion'd, wel thy thoughts imployd END
BEGIN NOW How we might best fulfill the work which here END
BEGIN NOW God hath assign'd us, nor of me shalt pass END
BEGIN NOW Unprais'd: for nothing lovelier can be found END
BEGIN NOW In woman, then to studie houshold good, END
BEGIN NOW And good workes in her Husband to promote. END
BEGIN NOW Yet not so strictly hath our Lord impos'd END
BEGIN NOW Labour, as to debarr us when we need END
BEGIN NOW Refreshment, whether food, or talk between, END
BEGIN NOW Food of the mind, or this sweet intercourse END
BEGIN NOW Of looks and smiles, for smiles from Reason flow, END
BEGIN NOW To brute deni'd, and are of Love the food, END
BEGIN NOW Love not the lowest end of human life. END
BEGIN NOW For not to irksom toile, but to delight END
BEGIN NOW He made us, and delight to Reason joyn'd. END
BEGIN NOW These paths and Bowers doubt not but our joynt END
BEGIN NOW Will keep from Wilderness with ease, as wide END
BEGIN NOW As we need walk, till younger hands ere long END
BEGIN NOW Assist us: But if much converse perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Thee satiate, to short absence I could yeild. END
BEGIN NOW For solitude somtimes is best societie, END
BEGIN NOW And short retirement urges sweet returne. END
BEGIN NOW But other doubt possesses me, least harm END
BEGIN NOW Befall thee sever'd from me; for thou knowst END
BEGIN NOW What hath bin warn'd us, what malicious Foe END
BEGIN NOW Envying our happiness, and of his own END
BEGIN NOW Despairing, seeks to work us woe and shame END
BEGIN NOW By sly assault; and somwhere nigh at hand END
BEGIN NOW Watches, no doubt, with greedy hope to find END
BEGIN NOW His wish and best advantage, us asunder, END
BEGIN NOW Hopeless to circumvent us joynd, where each END
BEGIN NOW To other speedie aide might lend at need; END
BEGIN NOW Whether his first design be to withdraw END
BEGIN NOW Our fealtie from God, or to disturb END
BEGIN NOW Conjugal Love, then which perhaps no bliss END
BEGIN NOW Enjoy'd by us excites his envie more; END
BEGIN NOW Or this, or worse, leave not the faithful side END
BEGIN NOW That gave thee being, stil shades thee and protects. END
BEGIN NOW The Wife, where danger or dishonour lurks, END
BEGIN NOW Safest and seemliest by her Husband staies, END
BEGIN NOW Who guards her, or with her the worst endures. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Virgin Majestie of EVE, END
BEGIN NOW As one who loves, and some unkindness meets, END
BEGIN NOW With sweet austeer composure thus reply'd. END
BEGIN NOW Ofspring of Heav'n and Earth, and all Earths Lord, END
BEGIN NOW That such an enemie we have, who seeks END
BEGIN NOW Our ruin, both by thee informd I learne, END
BEGIN NOW And from the parting Angel over-heard END
BEGIN NOW As in a shadie nook I stood behind, END
BEGIN NOW Just then returnd at shut of Evening Flours. END
BEGIN NOW But that thou shouldst my firmness therefore doubt END
BEGIN NOW To God or thee, because we have a foe END
BEGIN NOW May tempt it, I expected not to hear. END
BEGIN NOW His violence thou fearst not, being such, END
BEGIN NOW As wee, not capable of death or paine, END
BEGIN NOW Can either not receave, or can repell. END
BEGIN NOW His fraud is then thy fear, which plain inferrs END
BEGIN NOW Thy equal fear that my firm Faith and Love END
BEGIN NOW Can by his fraud be shak'n or seduc't; END
BEGIN NOW Thoughts, which how found they harbour in thy Brest, END
BEGIN NOW ADAM, misthought of her to thee so dear? END
BEGIN NOW To whom with healing words ADAM reply'd. END
BEGIN NOW Daughter of God and Man, immortal EVE, END
BEGIN NOW For such thou art, from sin and blame entire: END
BEGIN NOW Not diffident of thee do I dissuade END
BEGIN NOW Thy absence from my sight, but to avoid END
BEGIN NOW Th' attempt it self, intended by our Foe. END
BEGIN NOW For hee who tempts, though in vain, at least asperses END
BEGIN NOW The tempted with dishonour foul, suppos'd END
BEGIN NOW Not incorruptible of Faith, not prooff END
BEGIN NOW Against temptation: thou thy self with scorne END
BEGIN NOW And anger wouldst resent the offer'd wrong, END
BEGIN NOW Though ineffectual found: misdeem not then, END
BEGIN NOW If such affront I labour to avert END
BEGIN NOW From thee alone, which on us both at once END
BEGIN NOW The Enemie, though bold, will hardly dare, END
BEGIN NOW Or daring, first on mee th' assault shall light. END
BEGIN NOW Nor thou his malice and false guile contemn; END
BEGIN NOW Suttle he needs must be, who could seduce END
BEGIN NOW Angels, nor think superfluous others aid. END
BEGIN NOW I from the influence of thy looks receave END
BEGIN NOW Access in every Vertue, in thy sight END
BEGIN NOW More wise, more watchful, stronger, if need were END
BEGIN NOW Of outward strength; while shame, thou looking on, END
BEGIN NOW Shame to be overcome or over-reacht END
BEGIN NOW Would utmost vigor raise, and rais'd unite. END
BEGIN NOW Why shouldst not thou like sense within thee feel END
BEGIN NOW When I am present, and thy trial choose END
BEGIN NOW With me, best witness of thy Vertue tri'd. END
BEGIN NOW So spake domestick ADAM in his care END
BEGIN NOW And Matrimonial Love, but EVE, who thought END
BEGIN NOW Less attributed to her Faith sincere, END
BEGIN NOW Thus her reply with accent sweet renewd. END
BEGIN NOW If this be our condition, thus to dwell END
BEGIN NOW In narrow circuit strait'nd by a Foe, END
BEGIN NOW Suttle or violent, we not endu'd END
BEGIN NOW Single with like defence, wherever met, END
BEGIN NOW How are we happie, still in fear of harm? END
BEGIN NOW But harm precedes not sin: onely our Foe END
BEGIN NOW Tempting affronts us with his foul esteem END
BEGIN NOW Of our integritie: his foul esteeme END
BEGIN NOW Sticks no dishonor on our Front, but turns END
BEGIN NOW Foul on himself; then wherfore shund or feard END
BEGIN NOW By us? who rather double honour gaine END
BEGIN NOW From his surmise prov'd false, finde peace within, END
BEGIN NOW Favour from Heav'n, our witness from th' event. END
BEGIN NOW And what is Faith, Love, Vertue unassaid END
BEGIN NOW Alone, without exterior help sustaind? END
BEGIN NOW Let us not then suspect our happie State END
BEGIN NOW Left so imperfet by the Maker wise, END
BEGIN NOW As not secure to single or combin'd. END
BEGIN NOW Fraile is our happiness, if this be so, END
BEGIN NOW And EDEN were no EDEN thus expos'd. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus ADAM fervently repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW O Woman, best are all things as the will END
BEGIN NOW Of God ordaind them, his creating hand END
BEGIN NOW Nothing imperfet or deficient left END
BEGIN NOW Of all that he Created, much less Man, END
BEGIN NOW Or ought that might his happie State secure, END
BEGIN NOW Secure from outward force; within himself END
BEGIN NOW The danger lies, yet lies within his power: END
BEGIN NOW Against his will he can receave no harme. END
BEGIN NOW But God left free the Will, for what obeyes END
BEGIN NOW Reason, is free, and Reason he made right, END
BEGIN NOW But bid her well beware, and still erect, END
BEGIN NOW Least by some faire appeering good surpris'd END
BEGIN NOW She dictate false, and missinforme the Will END
BEGIN NOW To do what God expresly hath forbid. END
BEGIN NOW Not then mistrust, but tender love enjoynes, END
BEGIN NOW That I should mind thee oft, and mind thou me. END
BEGIN NOW Firm we subsist, yet possible to swerve, END
BEGIN NOW Since Reason not impossibly may meet END
BEGIN NOW Some specious object by the Foe subornd, END
BEGIN NOW And fall into deception unaware, END
BEGIN NOW Not keeping strictest watch, as she was warnd. END
BEGIN NOW Seek not temptation then, which to avoide END
BEGIN NOW Were better, and most likelie if from mee END
BEGIN NOW Thou sever not; Trial will come unsought. END
BEGIN NOW Wouldst thou approve thy constancie, approve END
BEGIN NOW First thy obedience; th' other who can know, END
BEGIN NOW Not seeing thee attempted, who attest? END
BEGIN NOW But if thou think, trial unsought may finde END
BEGIN NOW Us both securer then thus warnd thou seemst, END
BEGIN NOW Go; for thy stay, not free, absents thee more; END
BEGIN NOW Go in thy native innocence, relie END
BEGIN NOW On what thou hast of vertue, summon all, END
BEGIN NOW For God towards thee hath done his part, do thine. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Patriarch of Mankinde, but EVE END
BEGIN NOW Persisted, yet submiss, though last, repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW With thy permission then, and thus forewarnd END
BEGIN NOW Chiefly by what thy own last reasoning words END
BEGIN NOW Touchd onely, that our trial, when least sought, END
BEGIN NOW May finde us both perhaps farr less prepar'd, END
BEGIN NOW The willinger I goe, nor much expect END
BEGIN NOW A Foe so proud will first the weaker seek; END
BEGIN NOW So bent, the more shall shame him his repulse. END
BEGIN NOW Thus saying, from her Husbands hand her hand END
BEGIN NOW Soft she withdrew, and like a Wood-Nymph light END
BEGIN NOW OREAD or DRYAD, or of DELIA's Traine, END
BEGIN NOW Betook her to the Groves, but DELIA's self END
BEGIN NOW In gate surpass'd and Goddess-like deport, END
BEGIN NOW Though not as shee with Bow and Quiver armd, END
BEGIN NOW But with such Gardning Tools as Are yet rude, END
BEGIN NOW Guiltless of fire had formd, or Angels brought, END
BEGIN NOW To PALES, or POMONA, thus adornd, END
BEGIN NOW Likest she seemd, POMONA when she fled END
BEGIN NOW VERTUMNUS, or to CERES in her Prime, END
BEGIN NOW Yet Virgin of PROSERPINA from JOVE. END
BEGIN NOW Her long with ardent look his EYE pursu'd END
BEGIN NOW Delighted, but desiring more her stay. END
BEGIN NOW Oft he to her his charge of quick returne, END
BEGIN NOW Repeated, shee to him as oft engag'd END
BEGIN NOW To be returnd by Noon amid the Bowre, END
BEGIN NOW And all things in best order to invite END
BEGIN NOW Noontide repast, or Afternoons repose. END
BEGIN NOW O much deceav'd, much failing, hapless EVE, END
BEGIN NOW Of thy presum'd return! event perverse! END
BEGIN NOW Thou never from that houre in Paradise END
BEGIN NOW Foundst either sweet repast, or found repose; END
BEGIN NOW Such ambush hid among sweet Flours and Shades END
BEGIN NOW Waited with hellish rancor imminent END
BEGIN NOW To intercept thy way, or send thee back END
BEGIN NOW For now, and since first break of dawne the Fiend, END
BEGIN NOW Meer Serpent in appearance, forth was come, END
BEGIN NOW And on his Quest, where likeliest he might finde END
BEGIN NOW The onely two of Mankinde, but in them END
BEGIN NOW The whole included Race, his purposd prey. END
BEGIN NOW In Bowre and Field he sought, where any tuft END
BEGIN NOW Of Grove or Garden-Plot more pleasant lay, END
BEGIN NOW Thir tendance or Plantation for delight, END
BEGIN NOW By Fountain or by shadie Rivulet END
BEGIN NOW He sought them both, but wish'd his hap might find END
BEGIN NOW EVE separate, he wish'd, but not with hope END
BEGIN NOW Of what so seldom chanc'd, when to his wish, END
BEGIN NOW Beyond his hope, EVE separate he spies, END
BEGIN NOW Veild in a Cloud of Fragrance, where she stood, END
BEGIN NOW Half spi'd, so thick the Roses bushing round END
BEGIN NOW About her glowd, oft stooping to support END
BEGIN NOW Each Flour of slender stalk, whose head though gay END
BEGIN NOW Carnation, Purple, Azure, or spect with Gold, END
BEGIN NOW Hung drooping unsustaind, them she upstaies END
BEGIN NOW Gently with Mirtle band, mindless the while, END
BEGIN NOW Her self, though fairest unsupported Flour, END
BEGIN NOW From her best prop so farr, and storn so nigh. END
BEGIN NOW Neererhe drew, and many a walk travers'd END
BEGIN NOW Of stateliest Covert, Cedar, Pine, or Palme, END
BEGIN NOW Then voluble and bold, now hid, now seen END
BEGIN NOW Among thick-wov'n Arborets and Flours END
BEGIN NOW Imborderd on each Bank, the hand of EVE: END
BEGIN NOW Spot more delicious then those Gardens feign'd END
BEGIN NOW Or of reviv'd ADONIS, or renownd END
BEGIN NOW ALCINOUS, host of old LAERTES Son, END
BEGIN NOW Or that, not Mystic, where the Sapient King END
BEGIN NOW Much hee the Place admir'd, the Person more. END
BEGIN NOW As one who long in populous City pent, END
BEGIN NOW Where Houses thick and Sewers annoy the Aire, END
BEGIN NOW Forth issuing on a Summers Morn, to breathe END
BEGIN NOW Among the pleasant Villages and Farmes END
BEGIN NOW Adjoynd, from each thing met conceaves delight, END
BEGIN NOW The smell of Grain, or tedded Grass, or Kine, END
BEGIN NOW Or Dairie, each rural sight, each rural sound; END
BEGIN NOW If chance with Nymphlike step fair Virgin pass, END
BEGIN NOW What pleasing seemd, for her now pleases more, END
BEGIN NOW She most, and in her look summs all Delight. END
BEGIN NOW Such Pleasure took the Serpent to behold END
BEGIN NOW This Flourie Plat, the sweet recess of EVE END
BEGIN NOW Thus earlie, thus alone; her Heav'nly forme END
BEGIN NOW Angelic, but more soft, and Feminine, END
BEGIN NOW Her graceful Innocence, her every Aire END
BEGIN NOW Of gesture or lest action overawd END
BEGIN NOW His Malice, and with rapine sweet bereav'd END
BEGIN NOW His fierceness of the fierce intent it brought: END
BEGIN NOW That space the Evil one abstracted stood END
BEGIN NOW From his own evil, and for the time remaind END
BEGIN NOW Stupidly good, of enmitie disarm'd, END
BEGIN NOW Of guile, of hate, of envie, of revenge; END
BEGIN NOW But the hot Hell that alwayes in him burnes, END
BEGIN NOW Though in mid Heav'n, soon ended his delight, END
BEGIN NOW And tortures him now more, the more he sees END
BEGIN NOW Of pleasure not for him ordain'd: then soon END
BEGIN NOW Fierce hate he recollects, and all his thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Of mischief, gratulating, thus excites. END
BEGIN NOW Thoughts, whither have he led me, with what sweet END
BEGIN NOW Compulsion thus transported to forget END
BEGIN NOW What hither brought us, hate, not love, nor hope END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise for Hell, hope here to taste END
BEGIN NOW Of pleasure, but all pleasure to destroy, END
BEGIN NOW Save what is in destroying, other joy END
BEGIN NOW To me is lost. Then let me not let pass END
BEGIN NOW Occasion which now smiles, behold alone END
BEGIN NOW The Woman, opportune to all attempts, END
BEGIN NOW Her Husband, for I view far round, not nigh, END
BEGIN NOW Whose higher intellectual more I shun, END
BEGIN NOW And strength, of courage hautie, and of limb END
BEGIN NOW Heroic built, though of terrestrial mould, END
BEGIN NOW Foe not informidable, exempt from wound, END
BEGIN NOW I not; so much hath Hell debas'd, and paine END
BEGIN NOW Infeebl'd me, to what I was in Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW Shee fair, divinely fair, fit Love for Gods, END
BEGIN NOW Not terrible, though terrour be in Love END
BEGIN NOW And beautie, not approacht by stronger hate, END
BEGIN NOW Hate stronger, under shew of Love well feign'd, END
BEGIN NOW The way which to her ruin now I tend. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Enemie of Mankind, enclos'd END
BEGIN NOW In Serpent, Inmate bad, and toward EVE END
BEGIN NOW Address'd his way, not with indented wave, END
BEGIN NOW Prone on the ground, as since, but on his reare, END
BEGIN NOW Circular base of rising foulds, that tour'd END
BEGIN NOW Fould above fould a surging Maze, his Head END
BEGIN NOW Crested aloft, and Carbuncle his Eyes; END
BEGIN NOW With burnisht Neck of verdant Gold, erect END
BEGIN NOW Amidst his circling Spires, that on the grass END
BEGIN NOW Floted redundant: pleasing was his shape, END
BEGIN NOW And lovely, never since of Serpent kind END
BEGIN NOW Lovelier, not those that in ILLYRIA chang'd END
BEGIN NOW HERMIONE and CADMUS, or the God END
BEGIN NOW In EPIDAURUS; nor to which transformd END
BEGIN NOW Hee with OLYMPIAS, this with her who bore END
BEGIN NOW SCIPIO the highth of ROME. With tract oblique END
BEGIN NOW At first, as one who sought access, but feard END
BEGIN NOW To interrupt, side-long he works his way. END
BEGIN NOW As when a Ship by skilful Stearsman wrought END
BEGIN NOW Nigh Rivers mouth or Foreland, where the Wind END
BEGIN NOW Veres oft, as oft so steers, and shifts her Saile; END
BEGIN NOW So varied hee, and of his tortuous Traine END
BEGIN NOW Curld many a wanton wreath in sight of EVE, END
BEGIN NOW To lure her Eye; shee busied heard the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of rusling Leaves, but minded not, as us'd END
BEGIN NOW To such disport before her through the Field, END
BEGIN NOW From every Beast, more duteous at her call, END
BEGIN NOW Then at CIRCEAN call the Herd disguis'd. END
BEGIN NOW Hee boulder now, uncall'd before her stood; END
BEGIN NOW But as in gaze admiring: Oft he bowd END
BEGIN NOW His turret Crest, and sleek enamel'd Neck, END
BEGIN NOW Fawning, and lick'd the ground whereon she trod. END
BEGIN NOW The Eye of EVE to mark his play; he glad END
BEGIN NOW Of her attention gaind, with Serpent Tongue END
BEGIN NOW Organic, or impulse of vocal Air, END
BEGIN NOW His fraudulent temptation thus began. END
BEGIN NOW Wonder not, sovran Mistress, if perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Thou canst, who art sole Wonder, much less arm END
BEGIN NOW Thy looks, the Heav'n of mildness, with disdain, END
BEGIN NOW Displeas'd that I approach thee thus, and gaze END
BEGIN NOW Insatiate, I thus single; nor have feard END
BEGIN NOW Thy awful brow, more awful thus retir'd. END
BEGIN NOW Fairest resemblance of thy Maker faire, END
BEGIN NOW Thee all living things gaze on, all things thine END
BEGIN NOW By gift, and thy Celestial Beautie adore END
BEGIN NOW With ravishment beheld, there best beheld END
BEGIN NOW Where universally admir'd; but here END
BEGIN NOW In this enclosure wild, these Beasts among, END
BEGIN NOW Beholders rude, and shallow to discerne END
BEGIN NOW Half what in thee is fair, one man except, END
BEGIN NOW Who sees thee? (and what is one?) who shouldst be seen END
BEGIN NOW A Goddess among Gods, ador'd and serv'd END
BEGIN NOW By Angels numberless, thy daily Train. END
BEGIN NOW So gloz'd the Tempter, and his Proem tun'd; END
BEGIN NOW Into the Heart of EVE his words made way, END
BEGIN NOW Though at the voice much marveling; at length END
BEGIN NOW Not unamaz'd she thus in answer spake. END
BEGIN NOW What may this mean? Language of Man pronounc't END
BEGIN NOW By Tongue of Brute, and human sense exprest? END
BEGIN NOW The first at lest of these I thought deni'd END
BEGIN NOW To Beasts, whom God on their Creation-Day END
BEGIN NOW Created mute to all articulat sound; END
BEGIN NOW The latter I demurre, for in thir looks END
BEGIN NOW Much reason, and in thir actions oft appeers. END
BEGIN NOW Thee, Serpent, suttlest beast of all the field END
BEGIN NOW I knew, but not with human voice endu'd; END
BEGIN NOW Redouble then this miracle, and say, END
BEGIN NOW How cam'st thou speakable of mute, and how END
BEGIN NOW To me so friendly grown above the rest END
BEGIN NOW Of brutal kind, that daily are in sight? END
BEGIN NOW Say, for such wonder claims attention due. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the guileful Tempter thus reply'd. END
BEGIN NOW Empress of this fair World, resplendent EVE, END
BEGIN NOW Easie to mee it is to tell thee all END
BEGIN NOW What thou commandst, and right thou shouldst be obeyd: END
BEGIN NOW I was at first as other Beasts that graze END
BEGIN NOW The trodden Herb, of abject thoughts and low, END
BEGIN NOW As was my food, nor aught but food discern'd END
BEGIN NOW Or Sex, and apprehended nothing high: END
BEGIN NOW Till on a day roaving the field, I chanc'd END
BEGIN NOW A goodly Tree farr distant to behold END
BEGIN NOW Loaden with fruit of fairest colours mixt, END
BEGIN NOW Ruddie and Gold: I nearer drew to gaze; END
BEGIN NOW When from the boughes a savorie odour blow'n, END
BEGIN NOW Grateful to appetite, more pleas'd my sense END
BEGIN NOW Then smell of sweetest Fenel, or the Teats END
BEGIN NOW Of Ewe or Goat dropping with Milk at Eevn, END
BEGIN NOW Unsuckt of Lamb or Kid, that tend thir play. END
BEGIN NOW To satisfie the sharp desire I had END
BEGIN NOW Of tasting those fair Apples, I resolv'd END
BEGIN NOW Not to deferr; hunger and thirst at once, END
BEGIN NOW Powerful perswaders, quick'nd at the scent END
BEGIN NOW Of that alluring fruit, urg'd me so keene. END
BEGIN NOW About the Mossie Trunk I wound me soon, END
BEGIN NOW For high from ground the branches would require END
BEGIN NOW Thy utmost reach or ADAMS: Round the Tree END
BEGIN NOW All other Beasts that saw, with like desire END
BEGIN NOW Longing and envying stood, but could not reach. END
BEGIN NOW Amid the Tree now got, where plentie hung END
BEGIN NOW Tempting so nigh, to pluck and eat my fill END
BEGIN NOW I spar'd not, for such pleasure till that hour END
BEGIN NOW At Feed or Fountain never had I found. END
BEGIN NOW Sated at length, ere long I might perceave END
BEGIN NOW Strange alteration in me, to degree END
BEGIN NOW Of Reason in my inward Powers, and Speech END
BEGIN NOW Wanted not long, though to this shape retaind. END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth to Speculations high or deep END
BEGIN NOW I turnd my thoughts, and with capacious mind END
BEGIN NOW Considerd all things visible in Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW Or Earth, or Middle, all things fair and good; END
BEGIN NOW But all that fair and good in thy Divine END
BEGIN NOW Semblance, and in thy Beauties heav'nly Ray END
BEGIN NOW United I beheld; no Fair to thine END
BEGIN NOW Equivalent or second, which compel'd END
BEGIN NOW Mee thus, though importune perhaps, to come END
BEGIN NOW And gaze, and worship thee of right declar'd END
BEGIN NOW Sovran of Creatures, universal Dame. END
BEGIN NOW So talk'd the spirited sly Snake; and EVE END
BEGIN NOW Yet more amaz'd unwarie thus reply'd. END
BEGIN NOW Serpent, thy overpraising leaves in doubt END
BEGIN NOW The vertue of that Fruit, in thee first prov'd: END
BEGIN NOW But say, where grows the Tree, from hence how far? END
BEGIN NOW For many are the Trees of God that grow END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise, and various, yet unknown END
BEGIN NOW To us, in such abundance lies our choice, END
BEGIN NOW As leaves a greater store of Fruit untoucht, END
BEGIN NOW Still hanging incorruptible, till men END
BEGIN NOW Grow up to thir provision, and more hands END
BEGIN NOW Help to disburden Nature of her Bearth. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the wilie Adder, blithe and glad. END
BEGIN NOW Empress, the way is readie, and not long, END
BEGIN NOW Fast by a Fountain, one small Thicket past END
BEGIN NOW Of blowing Myrrh and Balme; if thou accept END
BEGIN NOW My conduct, I can bring thee thither soon. END
BEGIN NOW Lead then, said EVE. Hee leading swiftly rowld END
BEGIN NOW In tangles, and make intricate seem strait, END
BEGIN NOW To mischief swift. Hope elevates, and joy END
BEGIN NOW Bright'ns his Crest, as when a wandring Fire END
BEGIN NOW Compact of unctuous vapor, which the Night END
BEGIN NOW Condenses, and the cold invirons round, END
BEGIN NOW Kindl'd through agitation to a Flame, END
BEGIN NOW Which oft, they say, some evil Spirit attends, END
BEGIN NOW Hovering and blazing with delusive Light, END
BEGIN NOW Misleads th' amaz'd Night-wanderer from his way END
BEGIN NOW To Boggs and Mires, & oft through Pond or Poole, END
BEGIN NOW There swallow'd up and lost, from succour farr. END
BEGIN NOW So glister'd the dire Snake and into fraud END
BEGIN NOW Led EVE our credulous Mother, to the Tree END
BEGIN NOW Of prohibition, root of all our woe; END
BEGIN NOW Which when she saw, thus to her guide she spake. END
BEGIN NOW Serpent, we might have spar'd our coming hither, END
BEGIN NOW Fruitless to me, though Fruit be here to excess, END
BEGIN NOW The credit of whose vertue rest with thee, END
BEGIN NOW Wondrous indeed, if cause of such effects. END
BEGIN NOW But of this Tree we may not taste nor touch; END
BEGIN NOW God so commanded, and left that Command END
BEGIN NOW Sole Daughter of his voice; the rest, we live END
BEGIN NOW Law to our selves, our Reason is our Law. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Tempter guilefully repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Indeed? hath God then said that of the Fruit END
BEGIN NOW Of all these Garden Trees ye shall not eate, END
BEGIN NOW Yet Lords declar'd of all in Earth or Aire? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus EVE yet sinless. Of the Fruit END
BEGIN NOW Of each Tree in the Garden we may eate, END
BEGIN NOW But of the Fruit of this fair Tree amidst END
BEGIN NOW The Garden, God hath said, Ye shall not eate END
BEGIN NOW Thereof, nor shall ye touch it, least ye die. END
BEGIN NOW She scarse had said, though brief, when now more bold END
BEGIN NOW The Tempter, but with shew of Zeale and Love END
BEGIN NOW To Man, and indignation at his wrong, END
BEGIN NOW New part puts on, and as to passion mov'd, END
BEGIN NOW Fluctuats disturbd, yet comely, and in act END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd, as of som great matter to begin. END
BEGIN NOW As when of old som Orator renound END
BEGIN NOW In ATHENS or free ROME, where Eloquence END
BEGIN NOW Flourishd, since mute, to som great cause addrest, END
BEGIN NOW Stood in himself collected, while each part, END
BEGIN NOW Motion, each act won audience ere the tongue, END
BEGIN NOW Somtimes in highth began, as no delay END
BEGIN NOW Of Preface brooking through his Zeal of Right. END
BEGIN NOW So standing, moving, or to highth upgrown END
BEGIN NOW The Tempter all impassiond thus began. END
BEGIN NOW O Sacred, Wise, and Wisdom-giving Plant, END
BEGIN NOW Mother of Science, Now I feel thy Power END
BEGIN NOW Within me cleere, not onely to discerne END
BEGIN NOW Things in thir Causes, but to trace the wayes END
BEGIN NOW Of highest Agents, deemd however wise. END
BEGIN NOW Queen of this Universe, doe not believe END
BEGIN NOW Those rigid threats of Death; ye shall not Die: END
BEGIN NOW How should ye? by the Fruit? it gives you Life END
BEGIN NOW To Knowledge? By the Threatner, look on mee, END
BEGIN NOW Mee who have touch'd and tasted, yet both live, END
BEGIN NOW And life more perfet have attaind then Fate END
BEGIN NOW Meant mee, by ventring higher then my Lot. END
BEGIN NOW Shall that be shut to Man, which to the Beast END
BEGIN NOW Is open? or will God incense his ire END
BEGIN NOW For such a pretty Trespass, and not praise END
BEGIN NOW Rather your dauntless vertue, whom the pain END
BEGIN NOW Of Death denounc't, whatever thing Death be, END
BEGIN NOW Deterrd not from atchieving what might leade END
BEGIN NOW To happier life, knowledge of Good and Evil; END
BEGIN NOW Of good, how just? of evil, if what is evil END
BEGIN NOW Be real, why not known, since easier shunnd? END
BEGIN NOW God therefore cannot hurt ye, and be just; END
BEGIN NOW Not just, not God; not feard then, nor obeid: END
BEGIN NOW Your feare it self of Death removes the feare. END
BEGIN NOW Why then was this forbid? Why but to awe, END
BEGIN NOW Why but to keep ye low and ignorant, END
BEGIN NOW His worshippers; he knows that in the day END
BEGIN NOW Ye Eate thereof, your Eyes that seem so cleere, END
BEGIN NOW Yet are but dim, shall perfetly be then END
BEGIN NOW Op'nd and cleerd, and ye shall be as Gods, END
BEGIN NOW Knowing both Good and Evil as they know. END
BEGIN NOW That ye should be as Gods, since I as Man, END
BEGIN NOW Internal Man, is but proportion meet, END
BEGIN NOW I of brute human, yee of human Gods. END
BEGIN NOW So ye shalt die perhaps, by putting off END
BEGIN NOW Human, to put on Gods, death to be wisht, END
BEGIN NOW Though threat'nd, which no worse then this can bring END
BEGIN NOW And what are Gods that Man may not become END
BEGIN NOW As they, participating God-like food? END
BEGIN NOW The Gods are first, and that advantage use END
BEGIN NOW On our belief, that all from them proceeds, END
BEGIN NOW I question it, for this fair Earth I see, END
BEGIN NOW Warm'd by the Sun, producing every kind, END
BEGIN NOW Them nothing: If they all things, who enclos'd END
BEGIN NOW Knowledge of Good and Evil in this Tree, END
BEGIN NOW That whoso eats thereof, forthwith attains END
BEGIN NOW Wisdom without their leave? and wherein lies END
BEGIN NOW Th' offence, that Man should thus attain to know? END
BEGIN NOW What can your knowledge hurt him, or this Tree END
BEGIN NOW Impart against his will if all be his? END
BEGIN NOW Or is it envie, and can envie dwell END
BEGIN NOW In heav'nly brests? these, these and many more END
BEGIN NOW Causes import your need of this fair Fruit. END
BEGIN NOW Goddess humane, reach then, and freely taste. END
BEGIN NOW He ended, and his words replete with guile END
BEGIN NOW Into her heart too easie entrance won: END
BEGIN NOW Fixt on the Fruit she gaz'd, which to behold END
BEGIN NOW Might tempt alone, and in her ears the sound END
BEGIN NOW Yet rung of his perswasive words, impregn'd END
BEGIN NOW With Reason, to her seeming, and with Truth; END
BEGIN NOW Meanwhile the hour of Noon drew on, and wak'd END
BEGIN NOW An eager appetite, rais'd by the smell END
BEGIN NOW So savorie of that Fruit, which with desire, END
BEGIN NOW Inclinable now grown to touch or taste, END
BEGIN NOW Sollicited her longing eye; yet first END
BEGIN NOW Pausing a while, thus to her self she mus'd. END
BEGIN NOW Great are thy Vertues, doubtless, best of Fruits, END
BEGIN NOW Though kept from Man, & worthy to be admir'd, END
BEGIN NOW Whose taste, too long forborn, at first assay END
BEGIN NOW Gave elocution to the mute, and taught END
BEGIN NOW The Tongue not made for Speech to speak thy praise: END
BEGIN NOW Thy praise hee also who forbids thy use, END
BEGIN NOW Conceales not from us, naming thee the Tree END
BEGIN NOW Of Knowledge, knowledge both of good and evil; END
BEGIN NOW Forbids us then to taste, but his forbidding END
BEGIN NOW Commends thee more, while it inferrs the good END
BEGIN NOW By thee communicated, and our want: END
BEGIN NOW For good unknown, sure is not had, or had END
BEGIN NOW And yet unknown, is as not had at all. END
BEGIN NOW In plain then, what forbids he but to know, END
BEGIN NOW Forbids us good, forbids us to be wise? END
BEGIN NOW Such prohibitions binde not. But if Death END
BEGIN NOW Bind us with after-bands, what profits then END
BEGIN NOW Our inward freedom? In the day we eate END
BEGIN NOW Of this fair Fruit, our doom is, we shall die. END
BEGIN NOW How dies the Serpent? hee hath eat'n and lives, END
BEGIN NOW And knows, and speaks, and reasons, and discernes, END
BEGIN NOW Irrational till then. For us alone END
BEGIN NOW Was death invented? or to us deni'd END
BEGIN NOW This intellectual food, for beasts reserv'd? END
BEGIN NOW For Beasts it seems: yet that one Beast which first END
BEGIN NOW Hath tasted, envies not, but brings with joy END
BEGIN NOW The good befall'n him, Author unsuspect, END
BEGIN NOW Friendly to man, farr from deceit or guile. END
BEGIN NOW What fear I then, rather what know to feare END
BEGIN NOW Under this ignorance of Good and Evil, END
BEGIN NOW Here grows the Cure of all, this Fruit Divine, END
BEGIN NOW Fair to the Eye, inviting to the Taste, END
BEGIN NOW Of vertue to make wise: what hinders then END
BEGIN NOW To reach, and feed at once both Bodie and Mind? END
BEGIN NOW So saying, her rash hand in evil hour END
BEGIN NOW Forth reaching to the Fruit, she pluck'd, she eat: END
BEGIN NOW Earth felt the wound, and Nature from her seat END
BEGIN NOW Sighing through all her Works gave signs of woe, END
BEGIN NOW That all was lost. Back to the Thicket slunk END
BEGIN NOW The guiltie Serpent, and well might, for EVE END
BEGIN NOW Intent now wholly on her taste, naught else END
BEGIN NOW Regarded, such delight till then, as seemd, END
BEGIN NOW In Fruit she never tasted, whether true END
BEGIN NOW Or fansied so, through expectation high END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledg, nor was God-head from her thought. END
BEGIN NOW Greedily she ingorg'd without restraint, END
BEGIN NOW And knew not eating Death: Satiate at length, END
BEGIN NOW And hight'nd as with Wine, jocond and boon, END
BEGIN NOW Thus to her self she pleasingly began. END
BEGIN NOW O Sovran, vertuous, precious of all Trees END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise, of operation blest END
BEGIN NOW To Sapience, hitherto obscur'd, infam'd, END
BEGIN NOW And thy fair Fruit let hang, as to no end END
BEGIN NOW Created; but henceforth my early care, END
BEGIN NOW Not without Song, each Morning, and due praise END
BEGIN NOW Shall tend thee, and the fertil burden ease END
BEGIN NOW Of thy full branches offer'd free to all; END
BEGIN NOW Till dieted by thee I grow mature END
BEGIN NOW In knowledge, as the Gods who all things know; END
BEGIN NOW Though others envie what they cannot give; END
BEGIN NOW For had the gift bin theirs, it had not here END
BEGIN NOW Thus grown. Experience, next to thee I owe, END
BEGIN NOW Best guide; not following thee, I had remaind END
BEGIN NOW In ignorance, thou op'nst Wisdoms way, END
BEGIN NOW And giv'st access, though secret she retire. END
BEGIN NOW And I perhaps am secret; Heav'n is high, END
BEGIN NOW High and remote to see from thence distinct END
BEGIN NOW Each thing on Earth; and other care perhaps END
BEGIN NOW May have diverted from continual watch END
BEGIN NOW Our great Forbidder, safe with all his Spies END
BEGIN NOW About him. But to ADAM in what sort END
BEGIN NOW Shall I appeer? shall I to him make known END
BEGIN NOW As yet my change, and give him to partake END
BEGIN NOW Full happiness with mee, or rather not, END
BEGIN NOW But keep the odds of Knowledge in my power END
BEGIN NOW Without Copartner? so to add what wants END
BEGIN NOW In Femal Sex, the more to draw his Love, END
BEGIN NOW And render me more equal, and perhaps END
BEGIN NOW A thing not undesireable, somtime END
BEGIN NOW Superior; for inferior who is free? END
BEGIN NOW This may be well: but what if God have seen, END
BEGIN NOW And Death ensue? then I shall be no more, END
BEGIN NOW And ADAM wedded to another EVE, END
BEGIN NOW Shall live with her enjoying, I extinct; END
BEGIN NOW A death to think. Confirm'd then I resolve, END
BEGIN NOW ADAM shall share with me in bliss or woe: END
BEGIN NOW So dear I love him, that with him all deaths END
BEGIN NOW I could endure; without him live no life. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, from the Tree her step she turnd, END
BEGIN NOW But first low Reverence don, as to the power END
BEGIN NOW That dwelt within, whose presence had infus'd END
BEGIN NOW Into the plant sciential sap, deriv'd END
BEGIN NOW From Nectar, drink of Gods. ADAM the while END
BEGIN NOW Waiting desirous her return, had wove END
BEGIN NOW Of choicest Flours a Garland to adorne END
BEGIN NOW Her Tresses, and her rural labours crown END
BEGIN NOW As Reapers oft are wont thir Harvest Queen. END
BEGIN NOW Great joy he promis'd to his thoughts, and new END
BEGIN NOW Solace in her return, so long delay'd; END
BEGIN NOW Yet oft his heart, divine of somthing ill, END
BEGIN NOW Misgave him; hee the faultring measure felt; END
BEGIN NOW And forth to meet her went, the way she took END
BEGIN NOW That Morn when first they parted; by the Tree END
BEGIN NOW Of Knowledge he must pass, there he her met, END
BEGIN NOW Scarse from the Tree returning; in her hand END
BEGIN NOW A bough of fairest fruit that downie smil'd, END
BEGIN NOW New gatherd, and ambrosial smell diffus'd. END
BEGIN NOW To him she hasted, in her face excuse END
BEGIN NOW Came Prologue, and Apologie to prompt, END
BEGIN NOW Which with bland words at will she thus addrest. END
BEGIN NOW Hast thou not wonderd, ADAM, at my stay? END
BEGIN NOW Thee I have misst, and thought it long, depriv'd END
BEGIN NOW Thy presence, agonie of love till now END
BEGIN NOW Not felt, nor shall be twice, for never more END
BEGIN NOW Mean I to trie, what rash untri'd I sought, END
BEGIN NOW The paine of absence from thy sight. But strange END
BEGIN NOW Hath bin the cause, and wonderful to heare: END
BEGIN NOW This Tree is not as we are told, a Tree END
BEGIN NOW Of danger tasted, nor to evil unknown END
BEGIN NOW Op'ning the way, but of Divine effect END
BEGIN NOW To open Eyes, and make them Gods who taste; END
BEGIN NOW And hath bin tasted such; the Serpent wise, END
BEGIN NOW Or not restraind as wee, or not obeying, END
BEGIN NOW Hath eat'n of the fruit, and is become, END
BEGIN NOW Not dead, as we are threatn'd, but thenceforth END
BEGIN NOW Endu'd with human voice and human sense, END
BEGIN NOW Reasoning to admiration, and with mee END
BEGIN NOW Perswasively hath so prevaild, that I END
BEGIN NOW Have also tasted, and have also found END
BEGIN NOW Th' effects to correspond, opener mine Eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Dimm erst, dilated Spirits, ampler Heart, END
BEGIN NOW And growing up to Godhead; which for thee END
BEGIN NOW Chiefly I sought, without thee can despise. END
BEGIN NOW For bliss, as thou hast part, to me is bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Tedious, unshar'd with thee, and odious soon. END
BEGIN NOW Thou therefore also taste, that equal Lot END
BEGIN NOW May joyne us, equal Joy, as equal Love; END
BEGIN NOW Least thou not tasting, different degree END
BEGIN NOW Disjoyne us, and I then too late renounce END
BEGIN NOW Deitie for thee, when Fate will not permit. END
BEGIN NOW Thus EVE with Countnance blithe her storie told; END
BEGIN NOW But in her Cheek distemper flushing glowd. END
BEGIN NOW On th' other side, ADAM, soon as he heard END
BEGIN NOW The fatal Trespass don by EVE, amaz'd, END
BEGIN NOW Astonied stood and Blank, while horror chill END
BEGIN NOW Ran through his veins, and all his joynts relax'd; END
BEGIN NOW From his slack hand the Garland wreath'd for EVE END
BEGIN NOW Down drop'd, and all the faded Roses shed: END
BEGIN NOW Speechless he stood and pale, till thus at length END
BEGIN NOW First to himself he inward silence broke. END
BEGIN NOW O fairest of Creation, last and best END
BEGIN NOW Of all Gods Works, Creature in whom excell'd END
BEGIN NOW Whatever can to fight or thought be found, END
BEGIN NOW Holy, divine, good, amiable, or sweet! END
BEGIN NOW How art thou lost, how on a sudden lost, END
BEGIN NOW Defac't, deflourd, and now to Death devote? END
BEGIN NOW Rather how hast thou yeelded to transgress END
BEGIN NOW The strict forbiddance, how to violate END
BEGIN NOW The sacred Fruit forbidd'n! som cursed fraud END
BEGIN NOW Of Enemie hath beguil'd thee, yet unknown, END
BEGIN NOW And mee with thee hath ruind, for with thee END
BEGIN NOW Certain my resolution is to Die; END
BEGIN NOW How can I live without thee, how forgoe END
BEGIN NOW Thy sweet Converse and Love so dearly joyn'd, END
BEGIN NOW To live again in these wilde Woods forlorn? END
BEGIN NOW Should God create another EVE, and I END
BEGIN NOW Another Rib afford, yet loss of thee END
BEGIN NOW Would never from my heart; no no, I feel END
BEGIN NOW The Link of Nature draw me: Flesh of Flesh, END
BEGIN NOW Bone of my Bone thou art, and from thy State END
BEGIN NOW Mine never shall be parted, bliss or woe. END
BEGIN NOW So having said, as one from sad dismay END
BEGIN NOW Recomforted, and after thoughts disturbd END
BEGIN NOW Submitting to what seemd remediless, END
BEGIN NOW Thus in calme mood his Words to EVE he turnd. END
BEGIN NOW Bold deed thou hast presum'd, adventrous EVE, END
BEGIN NOW And peril great provok't, who thus hast dar'd END
BEGIN NOW Had it bin onely coveting to Eye END
BEGIN NOW That sacred Fruit, sacred to abstinence, END
BEGIN NOW Much more to taste it under banne to touch. END
BEGIN NOW But past who can recall, or don undoe? END
BEGIN NOW Not God omnipotent, for Fate, yet so END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps thou shalt not Die, perhaps the Fact END
BEGIN NOW Is not so hainous now, foretasted Fruit, END
BEGIN NOW Profan'd first by the Serpent, by him first END
BEGIN NOW Made common and unhallowd: ere one tastes; END
BEGIN NOW Nor yet on him found deadly; he yet lives, END
BEGIN NOW Lives, as thou saidst, and gaines to live as Man END
BEGIN NOW Higher degree of Life, inducement strong END
BEGIN NOW To us, as likely tasting to attaine END
BEGIN NOW Proportional ascent, which cannot be END
BEGIN NOW But to be Gods, or Angels Demi-gods. END
BEGIN NOW Nor can I think that God, Creator wise, END
BEGIN NOW Though threatning, will in earnest so destroy END
BEGIN NOW Us his prime Creatures, dignifi'd so high, END
BEGIN NOW Set over all his Works, which in our Fall, END
BEGIN NOW For us created, needs with us must faile, END
BEGIN NOW Dependent made; so God shall uncreate, END
BEGIN NOW Be frustrate, do, undo, and labour loose, END
BEGIN NOW Not well conceav'd of God, who though his Power END
BEGIN NOW Creation could repeate, yet would be loath END
BEGIN NOW Us to abolish, least the Adversary END
BEGIN NOW Triumph and say; Fickle their State whom God END
BEGIN NOW Most Favors, who can please him long? Mee first END
BEGIN NOW He ruind, now Mankind; whom will he next? END
BEGIN NOW Matter of scorne, not to be given the Foe. END
BEGIN NOW However I with thee have fixt my Lot, END
BEGIN NOW Certain to undergoe like doom, if Death END
BEGIN NOW Consort with thee, Death is to mee as Life; END
BEGIN NOW So forcible within my heart I feel END
BEGIN NOW The Bond of Nature draw me to my owne, END
BEGIN NOW My own in thee, for what thou art is mine; END
BEGIN NOW Our State cannot be severd, we are one, END
BEGIN NOW One Flesh; to loose thee were to loose my self. END
BEGIN NOW So ADAM, and thus EVE to him repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW O glorious trial of exceeding Love, END
BEGIN NOW Illustrious evidence, example high! END
BEGIN NOW Ingaging me to emulate, but short END
BEGIN NOW Of thy perfection, how shall I attaine, END
BEGIN NOW ADAM, from whose deare side I boast me sprung, END
BEGIN NOW And gladly of our Union heare thee speak, END
BEGIN NOW One Heart, one Soul in both; whereof good prooff END
BEGIN NOW This day affords, declaring thee resolvd, END
BEGIN NOW Rather then Death or aught then Death more dread END
BEGIN NOW Shall separate us, linkt in Love so deare, END
BEGIN NOW To undergoe with mee one Guilt, one Crime, END
BEGIN NOW If any be, of tasting this fair Fruit, END
BEGIN NOW Whose vertue, for of good still good proceeds, END
BEGIN NOW Direct, or by occasion hath presented END
BEGIN NOW This happie trial of thy Love, which else END
BEGIN NOW So eminently never had bin known. END
BEGIN NOW Were it I thought Death menac't would ensue END
BEGIN NOW This my attempt, I would sustain alone END
BEGIN NOW The worst, and not perswade thee, rather die END
BEGIN NOW Deserted, then oblige thee with a fact END
BEGIN NOW Pernicious to thy Peace, chiefly assur'd END
BEGIN NOW Remarkably so late of thy so true, END
BEGIN NOW So faithful Love unequald; but I feel END
BEGIN NOW Farr otherwise th' event, not Death, but Life END
BEGIN NOW Augmented, op'nd Eyes, new Hopes, new Joyes, END
BEGIN NOW Taste so Divine, that what of sweet before END
BEGIN NOW Hath toucht my sense, flat seems to this, and harsh. END
BEGIN NOW On my experience, ADAM, freely taste, END
BEGIN NOW And fear of Death deliver to the Windes. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, she embrac'd him, and for joy END
BEGIN NOW Tenderly wept, much won that he his Love END
BEGIN NOW Had so enobl'd, as of choice to incurr END
BEGIN NOW Divine displeasure for her sake, or Death. END
BEGIN NOW In recompence (for such compliance bad END
BEGIN NOW Such recompence best merits) from the bough END
BEGIN NOW She gave him of that fair enticing Fruit END
BEGIN NOW With liberal hand: he scrupl'd not to eat END
BEGIN NOW Against his better knowledge, not deceav'd, END
BEGIN NOW But fondly overcome with Femal charm. END
BEGIN NOW Earth trembl'd from her entrails, as again END
BEGIN NOW In pangs, and Nature gave a second groan, END
BEGIN NOW Skie lowr'd, and muttering Thunder, som sad drops END
BEGIN NOW Wept at compleating of the mortal Sin END
BEGIN NOW Original; while ADAM took no thought, END
BEGIN NOW Eating his fill, nor EVE to iterate END
BEGIN NOW Her former trespass fear'd, the more to soothe END
BEGIN NOW Him with her lov'd societie, that now END
BEGIN NOW As with new Wine intoxicated both END
BEGIN NOW They swim in mirth, and fansie that they feel END
BEGIN NOW Divinitie within them breeding wings END
BEGIN NOW Wherewith to scorn the Earth: but that false Fruit END
BEGIN NOW Farr other operation first displaid, END
BEGIN NOW Carnal desire enflaming, hee on EVE END
BEGIN NOW Began to cast lascivious Eyes, she him END
BEGIN NOW As wantonly repaid; in Lust they burne: END
BEGIN NOW Till ADAM thus 'gan EVE to dalliance move. END
BEGIN NOW EVE, now I see thou art exact of taste, END
BEGIN NOW And elegant, of Sapience no small part, END
BEGIN NOW Since to each meaning savour we apply, END
BEGIN NOW And Palate call judicious; I the praise END
BEGIN NOW Yeild thee, so well this day thou hast purvey'd. END
BEGIN NOW Much pleasure we have lost, while we abstain'd END
BEGIN NOW From this delightful Fruit, nor known till now END
BEGIN NOW True relish, tasting; if such pleasure be END
BEGIN NOW In things to us forbidden, it might be wish'd, END
BEGIN NOW For this one Tree had bin forbidden ten. END
BEGIN NOW But come, so well refresh't, now let us play, END
BEGIN NOW As meet is, after such delicious Fare; END
BEGIN NOW For never did thy Beautie since the day END
BEGIN NOW I saw thee first and wedded thee, adorn'd END
BEGIN NOW With all perfections, so enflame my sense END
BEGIN NOW With ardor to enjoy thee, fairer now END
BEGIN NOW Then ever, bountie of this vertuous Tree. END
BEGIN NOW So said he, and forbore not glance or toy END
BEGIN NOW Of amorous intent, well understood END
BEGIN NOW Of EVE, whose Eye darted contagious Fire. END
BEGIN NOW Her hand he seis'd, and to a shadie bank, END
BEGIN NOW Thick overhead with verdant roof imbowr'd END
BEGIN NOW He led her nothing loath; Flours were the Couch, END
BEGIN NOW And Hyacinth, Earths freshest softest lap. END
BEGIN NOW There they thir fill of Love and Loves disport END
BEGIN NOW Took largely, of thir mutual guilt the Seale, END
BEGIN NOW The solace of thir sin, till dewie sleep END
BEGIN NOW Oppress'd them, wearied with thir amorous play. END
BEGIN NOW Soon as the force of that fallacious Fruit, END
BEGIN NOW That with exhilerating vapour bland END
BEGIN NOW About thir spirits had plaid, and inmost powers END
BEGIN NOW Made erre, was now exhal'd, and grosser sleep END
BEGIN NOW Bred of unkindly fumes, with conscious dreams END
BEGIN NOW Encumberd, now had left them, up they rose END
BEGIN NOW As from unrest, and each the other viewing, END
BEGIN NOW Soon found thir Eyes how op'nd, and thir minds END
BEGIN NOW How dark'nd; innocence, that as a veile END
BEGIN NOW Had shadow'd them from knowing ill, was gon, END
BEGIN NOW Just confidence, and native righteousness, END
BEGIN NOW And honour from about them, naked left END
BEGIN NOW To guiltie shame hee cover'd, but his Robe END
BEGIN NOW Uncover'd more. So rose the DANITE strong END
BEGIN NOW HERCULEAN SAMSON from the Harlot-lap END
BEGIN NOW Shorn of his strength, They destitute and bare END
BEGIN NOW Of all thir vertue: silent, and in face END
BEGIN NOW Confounded long they sate, as struck'n mute, END
BEGIN NOW Till ADAM, though not less then EVE abasht, END
BEGIN NOW At length gave utterance to these words constraind. END
BEGIN NOW O EVE, in evil hour thou didst give care END
BEGIN NOW To that false Worm, of whomsoever taught END
BEGIN NOW To counterfet Mans voice, true in our Fall, END
BEGIN NOW False in our promis'd Rising; since our Eyes END
BEGIN NOW Op'nd we find indeed, and find we know END
BEGIN NOW Both Good and Evil, Good lost and Evil got, END
BEGIN NOW Bad Fruit of Knowledge, if this be to know, END
BEGIN NOW Which leaves us naked thus, of Honour void, END
BEGIN NOW Our wonted Ornaments now soild and staind, END
BEGIN NOW And in our Faces evident the signes END
BEGIN NOW Of foul concupiscence; whence evil store; END
BEGIN NOW Even shame, the last of evils; of the first END
BEGIN NOW Be sure then. How shall I behold the face END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth of God or Angel, earst with joy END
BEGIN NOW And rapture so oft beheld? those heav'nly shapes END
BEGIN NOW Will dazle now this earthly, with thir blaze END
BEGIN NOW Insufferably bright. O might I here END
BEGIN NOW In solitude live savage, in some glad END
BEGIN NOW Obscur'd, where highest Woods impenetrable END
BEGIN NOW To Starr or Sun-light, spread thir umbrage broad, END
BEGIN NOW And brown as Evening: Cover me ye Pines, END
BEGIN NOW Ye Cedars, with innumerable boughs END
BEGIN NOW Hide me, where I may never see them more. END
BEGIN NOW But let us now, as in bad plight, devise END
BEGIN NOW What best may for the present serve to hide END
BEGIN NOW The Parts of each from other, that seem most END
BEGIN NOW To shame obnoxious, and unseemliest seen, END
BEGIN NOW Some Tree whose broad smooth Leaves together sowd, END
BEGIN NOW And girded on our loyns, may cover round END
BEGIN NOW Those middle parts, that this new commer, Shame, END
BEGIN NOW There sit not, and reproach us as unclean. END
BEGIN NOW So counsel'd hee, and both together went END
BEGIN NOW Into the thickest Wood, there soon they chose END
BEGIN NOW The Figtree, not that kind for Fruit renown'd, END
BEGIN NOW But such as at this day to INDIANS known END
BEGIN NOW In MALABAR or DECAN spreds her Armes END
BEGIN NOW Braunching so broad and long, that in the ground END
BEGIN NOW The bended Twigs take root, and Daughters grow END
BEGIN NOW About the Mother Tree, a Pillard shade END
BEGIN NOW High overarch't, and echoing Walks between; END
BEGIN NOW There oft the INDIAN Herdsman shunning heate END
BEGIN NOW Shelters in coole, and tends his pasturing Herds END
BEGIN NOW At Loopholes cut through thickest shade: Those Leaves END
BEGIN NOW They gatherd, broad as AMAZONIAN Targe, END
BEGIN NOW And with what skill they had, together sowd, END
BEGIN NOW To gird thir waste, vain Covering if to hide END
BEGIN NOW Thir guilt and dreaded shame; O how unlike END
BEGIN NOW To that first naked Glorie. Such of late END
BEGIN NOW COLUMBUS found th' AMERICAN to girt END
BEGIN NOW With featherd Cincture, naked else and wilde END
BEGIN NOW Among the Trees on Iles and woodie Shores. END
BEGIN NOW Thus fenc't, and as they thought, thir shame in part END
BEGIN NOW Coverd, but not at rest or ease of Mind, END
BEGIN NOW They sate them down to weep, nor onely Teares END
BEGIN NOW Raind at thir Eyes, but high Winds worse within END
BEGIN NOW Began to rise, high Passions, Anger, Hate, END
BEGIN NOW Mistrust, Suspicion, Discord, and shook sore END
BEGIN NOW Thir inward State of Mind, calme Region once END
BEGIN NOW And full of Peace, now tost and turbulent: END
BEGIN NOW For Understanding rul'd not, and the Will END
BEGIN NOW Heard not her lore, both in subjection now END
BEGIN NOW To sensual Appetite, who from beneathe END
BEGIN NOW Usurping over sovran Reason claimd END
BEGIN NOW Superior sway: From thus distemperd brest, END
BEGIN NOW ADAM, estrang'd in look and alterd stile, END
BEGIN NOW Speech intermitted thus to EVE renewd. END
BEGIN NOW Would thou hadst heark'nd to my words, & stai'd END
BEGIN NOW With me, as I besought thee, when that strange END
BEGIN NOW Desire of wandring this unhappie Morn, END
BEGIN NOW I know not whence possessd thee; we had then END
BEGIN NOW Remaind still happie, not as now, despoild END
BEGIN NOW Of all our good, sham'd, naked, miserable. END
BEGIN NOW Let none henceforth seek needless cause to approve END
BEGIN NOW The Faith they owe; when earnestly they seek END
BEGIN NOW Such proof, conclude, they then begin to faile. END
BEGIN NOW To whom soon mov'd with touch of blame thus EVE. END
BEGIN NOW What words have past thy Lips, ADAM severe, END
BEGIN NOW Imput'st thou that to my default, or will END
BEGIN NOW Of wandering, as thou call'st it, which who knows END
BEGIN NOW But might as ill have happ'nd thou being by, END
BEGIN NOW Or to thy self perhaps: hadst thou bin there, END
BEGIN NOW Or bere th' attempt, thou couldst not have discernd END
BEGIN NOW Fraud in the Serpent, speaking as he spake; END
BEGIN NOW No ground of enmitie between us known, END
BEGIN NOW Why hee should mean me ill, or seek to harme. END
BEGIN NOW Was I to have never parted from thy side? END
BEGIN NOW As good have grown there still a liveless Rib. END
BEGIN NOW Being as I am, why didst not thou the Head END
BEGIN NOW Command me absolutely not to go, END
BEGIN NOW Going into such danger as thou saidst? END
BEGIN NOW Too facil then thou didst not much gainsay, END
BEGIN NOW Nay, didst permit, approve, and fair dismiss. END
BEGIN NOW Hadst thou bin firm and fixt in thy dissent, END
BEGIN NOW Neither had I transgress'd, nor thou with mee. END
BEGIN NOW To whom then first incenst ADAM repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Is this the Love, is the recompence END
BEGIN NOW Of mine to thee, ingrateful EVE, exprest END
BEGIN NOW Immutable when thou wert lost, not I, END
BEGIN NOW Who might have liv'd and joyd immortal bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Yet willingly chose rather Death with thee: END
BEGIN NOW And am I now upbraided, as the cause END
BEGIN NOW Of thy transgressing? not enough severe, END
BEGIN NOW It seems, in thy restraint: what could I more? END
BEGIN NOW I warn'd thee, I admonish'd thee, foretold END
BEGIN NOW The danger, and the lurking Enemie END
BEGIN NOW That lay in wait; beyond this had bin force, END
BEGIN NOW And force upon free Will hath here no place. END
BEGIN NOW But confidence then bore thee on, secure END
BEGIN NOW Either to meet no danger, or to finde END
BEGIN NOW Matter of glorious trial; and perhaps END
BEGIN NOW I also err'd in overmuch admiring END
BEGIN NOW What seemd in thee so perfet, that I thought END
BEGIN NOW No evil durst attempt thee, but I rue END
BEGIN NOW That errour now, which is become my crime, END
BEGIN NOW And thou th' accuser. Thus it shall befall END
BEGIN NOW Him who to worth in Women overtrusting END
BEGIN NOW Lets her Will rule; restraint she will not brook, END
BEGIN NOW And left to her self, if evil thence ensue, END
BEGIN NOW Shee first his weak indulgence will accuse. END
BEGIN NOW Thus they in mutual accusation spent END
BEGIN NOW The fruitless hours, but neither self-condemning END
BEGIN NOW And of thir vain contest appeer'd no end. END
BEGIN NOW Meanwhile the hainous and despightfull act END
BEGIN NOW Of SATAN done in Paradise, and how END
BEGIN NOW Hee in the Serpent had perverted EVE, END
BEGIN NOW Her Husband shee, to taste the fatall fruit, END
BEGIN NOW Was known in Heav'n; for what can scape the Eye END
BEGIN NOW Of God All-seeing, or deceave his Heart END
BEGIN NOW Omniscient, who in all things wise and just, END
BEGIN NOW Hinder'd not SATAN to attempt the minde END
BEGIN NOW Of Man, with strength entire, and free Will arm'd, END
BEGIN NOW Complete to have discover'd and repulst END
BEGIN NOW Whatever wiles of Foe or seeming Friend. END
BEGIN NOW For still they knew, and ought to have still remember'd END
BEGIN NOW The high Injunction not to taste that Fruit, END
BEGIN NOW Whoever tempted; which they not obeying, END
BEGIN NOW Incurr'd, what could they less, the penaltie, END
BEGIN NOW And manifold in sin, deserv'd to fall. END
BEGIN NOW Up into Heav'n from Paradise in hast END
BEGIN NOW Th' Angelic Guards ascended, mute and sad END
BEGIN NOW For Man, for of his state by this they knew, END
BEGIN NOW Much wondring how the suttle Fiend had stoln END
BEGIN NOW Entrance unseen. Soon as th' unwelcome news END
BEGIN NOW From Earth arriv'd at Heaven Gate, displeas'd END
BEGIN NOW All were who heard, dim sadness did not spare END
BEGIN NOW That time Celestial visages, yet mixt END
BEGIN NOW With pitie, violated not thir bliss. END
BEGIN NOW About the new-arriv'd, in multitudes END
BEGIN NOW Th' ethereal People ran, to hear and know END
BEGIN NOW How all befell: they towards the Throne Supream END
BEGIN NOW Accountable made haste to make appear END
BEGIN NOW With righteous plea, thir utmost vigilance, END
BEGIN NOW And easily approv'd; when the most High END
BEGIN NOW Eternal Father from his secret Cloud, END
BEGIN NOW Amidst in Thunder utter'd thus his voice. END
BEGIN NOW Assembl'd Angels, and ye Powers return'd END
BEGIN NOW From unsuccessful charge, be not dismaid, END
BEGIN NOW Nor troubl'd at these tidings from the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Which your sincerest care could not prevent, END
BEGIN NOW Foretold so lately what would come to pass, END
BEGIN NOW When first this Tempter cross'd the Gulf from Hell. END
BEGIN NOW I told ye then he should prevail and speed END
BEGIN NOW On his bad Errand, Man should be seduc't END
BEGIN NOW And flatter'd out of all, believing lies END
BEGIN NOW Against his Maker; no Decree of mine END
BEGIN NOW Concurring to necessitate his Fall, END
BEGIN NOW Or touch with lightest moment of impulse END
BEGIN NOW His free Will, to her own inclining left END
BEGIN NOW In eevn scale. But fall'n he is, and now END
BEGIN NOW What rests, but that the mortal Sentence pass END
BEGIN NOW On his transgression, Death denounc't that day, END
BEGIN NOW Which he presumes already vain and void, END
BEGIN NOW Because not yet inflicted, as he fear'd, END
BEGIN NOW By some immediate stroak; but soon shall find END
BEGIN NOW Forbearance no acquittance ere day end. END
BEGIN NOW Justice shall not return as bountie scorn'd. END
BEGIN NOW But whom send I to judge them? whom but thee END
BEGIN NOW Vicegerent Son, to thee I have transferr'd END
BEGIN NOW All Judgement, whether in Heav'n, or Earth; or Hell. END
BEGIN NOW Easie it may be seen that I intend END
BEGIN NOW Mercie collegue with Justice, sending thee END
BEGIN NOW Mans Friend, his Mediator, his design'd END
BEGIN NOW Both Ransom and Redeemer voluntarie, END
BEGIN NOW And destin'd Man himself to judge Man fall'n. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Father, and unfoulding bright END
BEGIN NOW Toward the right hand his Glorie, on the Son END
BEGIN NOW Blaz'd forth unclouded Deitie; he full END
BEGIN NOW Resplendent all his Father manifest END
BEGIN NOW Express'd, and thus divinely answer'd milde. END
BEGIN NOW Father Eternal, thine is to decree, END
BEGIN NOW Mine both in Heav'n and Earth to do thy will END
BEGIN NOW Supream, that thou in mee thy Son belov'd END
BEGIN NOW Mayst ever rest well pleas'd. I go to judge END
BEGIN NOW On Earth these thy transgressors, but thou knowst, END
BEGIN NOW Whoever judg'd, the worst on mee must light, END
BEGIN NOW When time shall be, for so I undertook END
BEGIN NOW Before thee; and not repenting, this obtaine END
BEGIN NOW Of right, that I may mitigate thir doom END
BEGIN NOW On me deriv'd, yet I shall temper so END
BEGIN NOW Justice with Mercie, as may illustrate most END
BEGIN NOW Them fully satisfied, and thee appease. END
BEGIN NOW Attendance none shall need, nor Train, where none END
BEGIN NOW Are to behold the Judgement, but the judg'd, END
BEGIN NOW Those two; the third best absent is condemn'd, END
BEGIN NOW Convict by flight, and Rebel to all Law END
BEGIN NOW Conviction to the Serpent none belongs. END
BEGIN NOW Thus saying, from his radiant Seat he rose END
BEGIN NOW Of high collateral glorie: him Thrones and Powers, END
BEGIN NOW Princedoms, and Dominations ministrant END
BEGIN NOW Accompanied to Heaven Gate, from whence END
BEGIN NOW EDEN and all the Coast in prospect lay. END
BEGIN NOW Down he descended strait; the speed of Gods END
BEGIN NOW Time counts not, though with swiftest minutes wing'd. END
BEGIN NOW Now was the Sun in Western cadence low END
BEGIN NOW From Noon, and gentle Aires due at thir hour END
BEGIN NOW To fan the Earth now wak'd, and usher in END
BEGIN NOW The Eevning coole when he from wrauth more coole END
BEGIN NOW Came the mild Judge and Intercessor both END
BEGIN NOW To sentence Man: the voice of God they heard END
BEGIN NOW Now walking in the Garden, by soft windes END
BEGIN NOW Brought to thir Ears, while day declin'd, they heard END
BEGIN NOW And from his presence hid themselves among END
BEGIN NOW The thickest Trees, both Man and Wife, till God END
BEGIN NOW Approaching, thus to ADAM call'd aloud. END
BEGIN NOW Where art thou ADAM, wont with joy to meet END
BEGIN NOW My coming seen far off? I miss thee here, END
BEGIN NOW Not pleas'd, thus entertaind with solitude, END
BEGIN NOW Where obvious dutie erewhile appear'd unsaught: END
BEGIN NOW Or come I less conspicuous, or what change END
BEGIN NOW Absents thee, or what chance detains? Come forth. END
BEGIN NOW He came, and with him EVE, more loth, though first END
BEGIN NOW To offend, discount'nanc't both, and discompos'd; END
BEGIN NOW Love was not in thir looks, either to God END
BEGIN NOW Or to each other, but apparent guilt, END
BEGIN NOW And shame, and perturbation, and despaire, END
BEGIN NOW Anger, and obstinacie, and hate, and guile. END
BEGIN NOW Whence ADAM faultring long, thus answer'd brief. END
BEGIN NOW I heard thee in the Garden, and of thy voice END
BEGIN NOW Affraid, being naked, hid my self. To whom END
BEGIN NOW The gracious Judge without revile repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW My voice thou oft hast heard, and hast not fear'd, END
BEGIN NOW But still rejoyc't, how is it now become END
BEGIN NOW So dreadful to thee? that thou art naked, who END
BEGIN NOW Hath told thee? hast thou eaten of the Tree END
BEGIN NOW Whereof I gave thee charge thou shouldst not eat? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus ADAM sore beset repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW O Heav'n! in evil strait this day I stand END
BEGIN NOW Before my Judge, either to undergoe END
BEGIN NOW My self the total Crime, or to accuse END
BEGIN NOW My other self, the partner of my life; END
BEGIN NOW Whose failing, while her Faith to me remaines, END
BEGIN NOW I should conceal, and not expose to blame END
BEGIN NOW By my complaint; but strict necessitie END
BEGIN NOW Subdues me, and calamitous constraint, END
BEGIN NOW Least on my head both sin and punishment, END
BEGIN NOW However insupportable, be all END
BEGIN NOW Devolv'd; though should I hold my peace, yet thou END
BEGIN NOW Wouldst easily detect what I conceale. END
BEGIN NOW This Woman whom thou mad'st to be my help, END
BEGIN NOW And gav'st me as thy perfet gift, so good, END
BEGIN NOW So fit, so acceptable, so Divine, END
BEGIN NOW That from her hand I could suspect no ill, END
BEGIN NOW And what she did, whatever in it self, END
BEGIN NOW Her doing seem'd to justifie the deed; END
BEGIN NOW Shee gave me of the Tree, and I did eate. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the sovran Presence thus repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Was shee thy God, that her thou didst obey END
BEGIN NOW Before his voice, or was shee made thy guide, END
BEGIN NOW Superior, or but equal, that to her END
BEGIN NOW Thou did'st resigne thy Manhood, and the Place END
BEGIN NOW Wherein God set thee above her made of thee, END
BEGIN NOW And for thee, whose perfection farr excell'd END
BEGIN NOW Hers in all real dignitie: Adornd END
BEGIN NOW She was indeed, and lovely to attract END
BEGIN NOW Were such as under Government well seem'd, END
BEGIN NOW Unseemly to beare rule, which was thy part END
BEGIN NOW And person, had'st thou known thy self aright. END
BEGIN NOW So having said, he thus to EVE in few: END
BEGIN NOW Say Woman, what is this which thou hast done? END
BEGIN NOW To whom sad EVE with shame nigh overwhelm'd, END
BEGIN NOW Confessing soon, yet not before her Judge END
BEGIN NOW Bold or loquacious, thus abasht repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent me beguil'd and I did eate. END
BEGIN NOW Which when the Lord God heard, without delay END
BEGIN NOW To Judgement he proceeded on th' accus'd END
BEGIN NOW Serpent though brute, unable to transferre END
BEGIN NOW The Guilt on him who made him instrument END
BEGIN NOW Of mischief, and polluted from the end END
BEGIN NOW Of his Creation; justly then accurst, END
BEGIN NOW As vitiated in Nature: more to know END
BEGIN NOW Concern'd not Man (since he no further knew) END
BEGIN NOW Nor alter'd his offence; yet God at last END
BEGIN NOW To Satan first in sin his doom apply'd, END
BEGIN NOW Though in mysterious terms, judg'd as then best: END
BEGIN NOW And on the Serpent thus his curse let fall. END
BEGIN NOW Because thou hast done this, thou art accurst END
BEGIN NOW Above all Cattel, each Beast of the Field; END
BEGIN NOW Upon thy Belly groveling thou shalt goe, END
BEGIN NOW And dust shalt eat all the days of thy Life. END
BEGIN NOW Between Thee and the Woman I will put END
BEGIN NOW Enmitie, and between thine and her Seed; END
BEGIN NOW Her Seed shall bruise thy head, thou bruise his heel. END
BEGIN NOW So spake this Oracle, then verifi'd END
BEGIN NOW When JESUS son of MARY second EVE, END
BEGIN NOW Saw Satan fall like Lightning down from Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW Prince of the Aire; then rising from his Grave END
BEGIN NOW Spoild Principalities and Powers, triumpht END
BEGIN NOW In open shew, and with ascention bright END
BEGIN NOW Captivity led captive through the Aire, END
BEGIN NOW The Realme it self of Satan long usurpt, END
BEGIN NOW Whom he shall tread at last under our feet; END
BEGIN NOW Eevn hee who now foretold his fatal bruise, END
BEGIN NOW And to the Woman thus his Sentence turn'd. END
BEGIN NOW Thy sorrow I will greatly multiplie END
BEGIN NOW By thy Conception; Children thou shalt bring END
BEGIN NOW In sorrow forth, and to thy Husbands will END
BEGIN NOW Thine shall submit, hee over thee shall rule. END
BEGIN NOW On ADAM last thus judgement he pronounc'd. END
BEGIN NOW Because thou hast heark'nd to the voice of thy Wife, END
BEGIN NOW And eaten of the Tree concerning which END
BEGIN NOW I charg'd thee, saying: Thou shalt not eate thereof, END
BEGIN NOW Curs'd is the ground for thy sake, thou in sorrow END
BEGIN NOW Shalt eate thereof all the days of thy Life; END
BEGIN NOW Thornes also and Thistles it shall bring thee forth END
BEGIN NOW Unbid, and thou shalt eate th' Herb of th' Field, END
BEGIN NOW In the sweat of thy Face shalt thou eate Bread, END
BEGIN NOW Till thou return unto the ground, for thou END
BEGIN NOW Out of the ground wast taken, know thy Birth, END
BEGIN NOW For dust thou art, and shalt to dust returne. END
BEGIN NOW So judg'd he Man, both Judge and Saviour sent, END
BEGIN NOW And th' instant stroke of Death denounc't that day END
BEGIN NOW Remov'd farr off; then pittying how they stood END
BEGIN NOW Before him naked to the aire, that now END
BEGIN NOW Must suffer change, disdain'd not to begin END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth the forme of servant to assume, END
BEGIN NOW As when he wash'd his servants feet, so now END
BEGIN NOW As Father of his Familie he clad END
BEGIN NOW Thir nakedness with Skins of Beasts, or slain, END
BEGIN NOW Or as the Snake with youthful Coate repaid; END
BEGIN NOW And thought not much to cloath his Enemies: END
BEGIN NOW Nor hee thir outward onely with the Skins END
BEGIN NOW Of Beasts, but inward nakedness, much more END
BEGIN NOW Opprobrious, with his Robe of righteousness, END
BEGIN NOW Araying cover'd from his Fathers sight. END
BEGIN NOW To him with swift ascent he up returnd, END
BEGIN NOW Into his blissful bosom reassum'd END
BEGIN NOW In glory as of old, to him appeas'd END
BEGIN NOW All, though all-knowing, what had past with Man END
BEGIN NOW Recounted, mixing intercession sweet. END
BEGIN NOW Meanwhile ere thus was sin'd and judg'd on Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Within the Gates of Hell sate Sin and Death, END
BEGIN NOW In counterview within the Gates, that now END
BEGIN NOW Stood open wide, belching outrageous flame END
BEGIN NOW Farr into CHAOS, since the Fiend pass'd through, END
BEGIN NOW Sin opening, who thus now to Death began. END
BEGIN NOW O Son, why sit we here each other viewing END
BEGIN NOW Idlely, while Satan our great Author thrives END
BEGIN NOW In other Worlds, and happier Seat provides END
BEGIN NOW For us his ofspring deare? It cannot be END
BEGIN NOW But that success attends him; if mishap, END
BEGIN NOW Ere this he had return'd, with fury driv'n END
BEGIN NOW By his Avenger, since no place like this END
BEGIN NOW Can fit his punishment, or their revenge. END
BEGIN NOW Methinks I feel new strength within me rise, END
BEGIN NOW Wings growing, and Dominion giv'n me large END
BEGIN NOW Beyond this Deep; whatever drawes me on, END
BEGIN NOW Or sympathie, or som connatural force END
BEGIN NOW Powerful at greatest distance to unite END
BEGIN NOW With secret amity things of like kinde END
BEGIN NOW By secretest conveyance. Thou my Shade END
BEGIN NOW Inseparable must with mee along: END
BEGIN NOW For Death from Sin no power can separate. END
BEGIN NOW But least the difficultie of passing back END
BEGIN NOW Stay his returne perhaps over this Gulfe END
BEGIN NOW Impassable, impervious, let us try END
BEGIN NOW Adventrous work, yet to thy power and mine END
BEGIN NOW Not unagreeable, to found a path END
BEGIN NOW Over this Maine from Hell to that new World END
BEGIN NOW Where Satan now prevailes, a Monument END
BEGIN NOW Of merit high to all th' infernal Host, END
BEGIN NOW Easing thir passage hence, for intercourse, END
BEGIN NOW Or transmigration, as thir lot shall lead. END
BEGIN NOW Nor can I miss the way, so strongly drawn END
BEGIN NOW By this new felt attraction and instinct. END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus the meager Shadow answerd soon. END
BEGIN NOW Goe whither Fate and inclination strong END
BEGIN NOW Leads thee, I shall not lag behinde, nor erre END
BEGIN NOW The way, thou leading, such a sent I draw END
BEGIN NOW Of carnage, prey innumerable, and taste END
BEGIN NOW The savour of Death from all things there that live: END
BEGIN NOW Nor shall I to the work thou enterprisest END
BEGIN NOW Be wanting, but afford thee equal aid. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, with delight he snuff'd the smell END
BEGIN NOW Of mortal change on Earth. As when a flock END
BEGIN NOW Of ravenous Fowl, though many a League remote, END
BEGIN NOW Where Armies lie encampt, come flying, lur'd END
BEGIN NOW With sent of living Carcasses design'd END
BEGIN NOW For death, the following day, in bloodie fight. END
BEGIN NOW So sented the grim Feature, and upturn'd END
BEGIN NOW His Nostril wide into the murkie Air, END
BEGIN NOW Sagacious of his Quarrey from so farr. END
BEGIN NOW Then Both from out Hell Gates into the waste END
BEGIN NOW Wide Anarchie of CHAOS damp and dark END
BEGIN NOW Flew divers, & with Power (thir Power was great) END
BEGIN NOW Hovering upon the Waters; what they met END
BEGIN NOW Solid or slimie, as in raging Sea END
BEGIN NOW Tost up and down, together crowded drove END
BEGIN NOW From each side shoaling towards the mouth of Hell. END
BEGIN NOW As when two Polar Winds blowing adverse END
BEGIN NOW Upon the CRONIAN Sea, together drive END
BEGIN NOW Mountains of Ice, that stop th' imagin'd way END
BEGIN NOW Beyond PETSORA Eastward, to the rich END
BEGIN NOW CATHAIAN Coast. The aggregated Soyle END
BEGIN NOW Death with his Mace petrific, cold and dry, END
BEGIN NOW As with a Trident smote, and fix't as firm END
BEGIN NOW As DELOS floating once; the rest his look END
BEGIN NOW Bound with GORGONIAN rigor not to move, END
BEGIN NOW And with ASPHALTIC slime; broad as the Gate, END
BEGIN NOW Deep to the Roots of Hell the gather'd beach END
BEGIN NOW They fasten'd, and the Mole immense wraught on END
BEGIN NOW Over the foaming deep high Archt, a Bridge END
BEGIN NOW Of length prodigious joyning to the Wall END
BEGIN NOW Immoveable of this now fenceless world END
BEGIN NOW Forfeit to Death; from hence a passage broad, END
BEGIN NOW Smooth, easie, inoffensive down to Hell. END
BEGIN NOW So, if great things to small may be compar'd, END
BEGIN NOW XERXES, the Libertie of GREECE to yoke, END
BEGIN NOW From SUSA his MEMNONIAN Palace high END
BEGIN NOW Came to the Sea, and over HELLESPONT END
BEGIN NOW Bridging his way, EUROPE with ASIA joyn'd, END
BEGIN NOW And scourg'd with many a stroak th' indignant waves. END
BEGIN NOW Now had they brought the work by wondrous Art END
BEGIN NOW Pontifical, a ridge of pendent Rock END
BEGIN NOW Over the vext Abyss, following the track END
BEGIN NOW Of SATAN, to the selfsame place where hee END
BEGIN NOW First lighted from his Wing, and landed safe END
BEGIN NOW From out of CHAOS to the outside bare END
BEGIN NOW Of this round World: with Pinns of Adamant END
BEGIN NOW And Chains they made all fast, too fast they made END
BEGIN NOW And durable; and now in little space END
BEGIN NOW The Confines met of Empyrean Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW And of this World, and on the left hand Hell END
BEGIN NOW With long reach interpos'd; three sev'ral wayes END
BEGIN NOW In sight, to each of these three places led. END
BEGIN NOW And now thir way to Earth they had descri'd, END
BEGIN NOW To Paradise first tending, when behold END
BEGIN NOW SATAN in likeness of an Angel bright END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the CENTAURE and the SCORPION stearing END
BEGIN NOW His ZENITH, while the Sun in ARIES rose: END
BEGIN NOW Disguis'd he came, but those his Children dear END
BEGIN NOW Thir Parent soon discern'd, though in disguise. END
BEGIN NOW Hee, after EVE seduc't, unminded slunk END
BEGIN NOW Into the Wood fast by, and changing shape END
BEGIN NOW To observe the sequel, saw his guileful act END
BEGIN NOW By EVE, though all unweeting, seconded END
BEGIN NOW Upon her Husband, saw thir shame that sought END
BEGIN NOW Vain covertures; but when he saw descend END
BEGIN NOW The Son of God to judge them, terrifi'd END
BEGIN NOW Hee fled, not hoping to escape, but shun END
BEGIN NOW The present, fearing guiltie what his wrauth END
BEGIN NOW Might suddenly inflict; that past, return'd END
BEGIN NOW By Night, and listning where the hapless Paire END
BEGIN NOW Sate in thir sad discourse, and various plaint, END
BEGIN NOW Thence gatherd his own doom, which understood END
BEGIN NOW Not instant, but of future time. With joy END
BEGIN NOW And tidings fraught, to Hell he now return'd, END
BEGIN NOW And at the brink of CHAOS, neer the foot END
BEGIN NOW Of this new wondrous Pontifice, unhop't END
BEGIN NOW Met who to meet him came, his Ofspring dear. END
BEGIN NOW Great joy was at thir meeting, and at sight END
BEGIN NOW Of that stupendious Bridge his joy encreas'd. END
BEGIN NOW Long hee admiring stood, till Sin, his faire END
BEGIN NOW Inchanting Daughter, thus the silence broke. END
BEGIN NOW O Parent, these are thy magnific deeds, END
BEGIN NOW Thy Trophies, which thou view'st as not thine own, END
BEGIN NOW Thou art thir Author and prime Architect: END
BEGIN NOW For I no sooner in my Heart divin'd, END
BEGIN NOW My Heart, which by a secret harmonie END
BEGIN NOW Still moves with thine, joyn'd in connexion sweet, END
BEGIN NOW That thou on Earth hadst prosper'd, which thy looks END
BEGIN NOW Now also evidence, but straight I felt END
BEGIN NOW Though distant from thee Worlds between, yet felt END
BEGIN NOW That I must after thee with this thy Son; END
BEGIN NOW Such fatal consequence unites us three: END
BEGIN NOW Hell could no longer hold us in her bounds, END
BEGIN NOW Nor this unvoyageable Gulf obscure END
BEGIN NOW Detain from following thy illustrious track. END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast atchiev'd our libertie, confin'd END
BEGIN NOW Within Hell Gates till now, thou us impow'rd END
BEGIN NOW To fortifie thus farr, and overlay END
BEGIN NOW With this portentous Bridge the dark Abyss. END
BEGIN NOW Thine now is all this World, thy vertue hath won END
BEGIN NOW What thy hands builded not, thy Wisdom gain'd END
BEGIN NOW With odds what Warr hath lost, and fully aveng'd END
BEGIN NOW Our foile in Heav'n; here thou shalt Monarch reign, END
BEGIN NOW There didst not; there let him still Victor sway, END
BEGIN NOW As Battel hath adjudg'd, from this new World END
BEGIN NOW Retiring, by his own doom alienated, END
BEGIN NOW And henceforth Monarchie with thee divide END
BEGIN NOW Of all things, parted by th' Empyreal bounds, END
BEGIN NOW His Quadrature, from thy Orbicular World, END
BEGIN NOW Or trie thee now more dang'rous to his Throne. END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus the Prince of Darkness answerd glad. END
BEGIN NOW Fair Daughter, and thou Son and Grandchild both, END
BEGIN NOW High proof ye now have giv'n to be the Race END
BEGIN NOW Of SATAN (for I glorie in the name, END
BEGIN NOW Antagonist of Heav'ns Almightie King) END
BEGIN NOW Amply have merited of me, of all END
BEGIN NOW Th' Infernal Empire, that so neer Heav'ns dore END
BEGIN NOW Triumphal with triumphal act have met, END
BEGIN NOW Mine with this glorious Work, & made one Realm END
BEGIN NOW Hell and this World, one Realm, one Continent END
BEGIN NOW Of easie thorough-fare. Therefore while I END
BEGIN NOW Descend through Darkness, on your Rode with ease END
BEGIN NOW To my associate Powers, them to acquaint END
BEGIN NOW With these successes, and with them rejoyce, END
BEGIN NOW You two this way, among those numerous Orbs END
BEGIN NOW All yours, right down to Paradise descend; END
BEGIN NOW There dwell & Reign in bliss, thence on the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Dominion exercise and in the Aire, END
BEGIN NOW Chiefly on Man, sole Lord of all declar'd, END
BEGIN NOW Him first make sure your thrall, and lastly kill. END
BEGIN NOW My Substitutes I send ye, and Create END
BEGIN NOW Plenipotent on Earth, of matchless might END
BEGIN NOW Issuing from mee: on your joynt vigor now END
BEGIN NOW My hold of this new Kingdom all depends, END
BEGIN NOW Through Sin to Death expos'd by my exploit. END
BEGIN NOW If your joynt power prevaile, th' affaires of Hell END
BEGIN NOW No detriment need feare, goe and be strong. END
BEGIN NOW So saying he dismiss'd them, they with speed END
BEGIN NOW Thir course through thickest Constellations held END
BEGIN NOW Spreading thir bane; the blasted Starrs lookt wan, END
BEGIN NOW And Planets, Planet-strook, real Eclips END
BEGIN NOW Then sufferd. Th' other way SATAN went down END
BEGIN NOW The Causey to Hell Gate; on either side END
BEGIN NOW Disparted CHAOS over built exclaimd, END
BEGIN NOW And with rebounding surge the barrs assaild, END
BEGIN NOW That scorn'd his indignation: through the Gate, END
BEGIN NOW Wide open and unguarded, SATAN pass'd, END
BEGIN NOW And all about found desolate; for those END
BEGIN NOW Appointed to sit there, had left thir charge, END
BEGIN NOW Flown to the upper World; the rest were all END
BEGIN NOW Farr to the inland retir'd, about the walls END
BEGIN NOW Of PANDEMONIUM, Citie and proud seate END
BEGIN NOW Of LUCIFER, so by allusion calld, END
BEGIN NOW Of that bright Starr to SATAN paragond. END
BEGIN NOW There kept thir Watch the Legions, while the Grand END
BEGIN NOW In Council sate, sollicitous what chance END
BEGIN NOW Might intercept thir Emperour sent, so hee END
BEGIN NOW Departing gave command, and they observ'd. END
BEGIN NOW As when the TARTAR from his RUSSIAN Foe END
BEGIN NOW By ASTRACAN over the Snowie Plaines END
BEGIN NOW Retires, or BACTRIAN Sophi from the hornes END
BEGIN NOW Of TURKISH Crescent, leaves all waste beyond END
BEGIN NOW The Realme of ALADULE, in his retreate END
BEGIN NOW To TAURIS or CASBEEN. So these the late END
BEGIN NOW Heav'n-banisht Host, left desert utmost Hell END
BEGIN NOW Many a dark League, reduc't in careful Watch END
BEGIN NOW Round thir Metropolis, and now expecting END
BEGIN NOW Each hour their great adventurer from the search END
BEGIN NOW Of Forrein Worlds: he through the midst unmarkt, END
BEGIN NOW In shew plebeian Angel militant END
BEGIN NOW Of lowest order, past; and from the dore END
BEGIN NOW Of that PLUTONIAN Hall, invisible END
BEGIN NOW Ascended his high Throne, which under state END
BEGIN NOW Of richest texture spred, at th' upper end END
BEGIN NOW Was plac't in regal lustre. Down a while END
BEGIN NOW He sate, and round about him saw unseen: END
BEGIN NOW At last as from a Cloud his fulgent head END
BEGIN NOW And shape Starr bright appeer'd, or brighter, clad END
BEGIN NOW With what permissive glory since his fall END
BEGIN NOW Was left him, or false glitter: All amaz'd END
BEGIN NOW At that so sudden blaze the STYGIAN throng END
BEGIN NOW Bent thir aspect, and whom they wish'd beheld, END
BEGIN NOW Thir mighty Chief returnd: loud was th' acclaime: END
BEGIN NOW Forth rush'd in haste the great consulting Peers, END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd from thir dark DIVAN, and with like joy END
BEGIN NOW Congratulant approach'd him, who with hand END
BEGIN NOW Silence, and with these words attention won. END
BEGIN NOW For in possession such, not onely of right, END
BEGIN NOW I call ye and declare ye now, returnd END
BEGIN NOW Successful beyond hope, to lead ye forth END
BEGIN NOW Triumphant out of this infernal Pit END
BEGIN NOW Abominable, accurst, the house of woe, END
BEGIN NOW And Dungeon of our Tyrant: Now possess, END
BEGIN NOW As Lords, a spacious World, to our native Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Little inferiour, by my adventure hard END
BEGIN NOW With peril great atchiev'd. Long were to tell END
BEGIN NOW What I have don, what sufferd, with what paine END
BEGIN NOW Voyag'd the unreal, vast, unbounded deep END
BEGIN NOW Of horrible confusion, over which END
BEGIN NOW By Sin and Death a broad way now is pav'd END
BEGIN NOW To expedite your glorious march; but I END
BEGIN NOW Toild out my uncouth passage, forc't to ride END
BEGIN NOW Th' untractable Abysse, plung'd in the womb END
BEGIN NOW Of unoriginal NIGHT and CHAOS wilde, END
BEGIN NOW That jealous of thir secrets fiercely oppos'd END
BEGIN NOW My journey strange, with clamorous uproare END
BEGIN NOW Protesting Fate supreame; thence how I found END
BEGIN NOW The new created World, which fame in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Long had foretold, a Fabrick wonderful END
BEGIN NOW Of absolute perfection, therein Man END
BEGIN NOW Plac't in a Paradise, by our exile END
BEGIN NOW Made happie: Him by fraud I have seduc'd END
BEGIN NOW From his Creator, and the more to increase END
BEGIN NOW Your wonder, with an Apple; he thereat END
BEGIN NOW Offended, worth your laughter, hath giv'n up END
BEGIN NOW Both his beloved Man and all his World, END
BEGIN NOW To Sin and Death a prey, and so to us, END
BEGIN NOW Without our hazard, labour or allarme, END
BEGIN NOW To range in, and to dwell, and over Man END
BEGIN NOW To rule, as over all he should have rul'd. END
BEGIN NOW True is, mee also he hath judg'd, or rather END
BEGIN NOW Mee not, but the brute Serpent in whose shape END
BEGIN NOW Man I deceav'd: that which to mee belongs, END
BEGIN NOW Is enmity, which he will put between END
BEGIN NOW Mee and Mankinde; I am to bruise his heel; END
BEGIN NOW His Seed, when is not set, shall bruise my head: END
BEGIN NOW A World who would not purchase with a bruise, END
BEGIN NOW Or much more grievous pain? Ye have th' account END
BEGIN NOW Of my performance: What remaines, ye Gods, END
BEGIN NOW But up and enter now into full bliss. END
BEGIN NOW So having said, a while he stood, expecting END
BEGIN NOW Thir universal shout and high applause END
BEGIN NOW To fill his eare, when contrary he hears END
BEGIN NOW On all sides, from innumerable tongues END
BEGIN NOW A dismal universal hiss, the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of public scorn; he wonderd, but not long END
BEGIN NOW Had leasure, wondring at himself now more; END
BEGIN NOW His Visage drawn he felt to sharp and spare, END
BEGIN NOW His Armes clung to his Ribs, his Leggs entwining END
BEGIN NOW Each other, till supplanted down he fell END
BEGIN NOW A monstrous Serpent on his Belly prone, END
BEGIN NOW Reluctant, but in vaine, a greater power END
BEGIN NOW Now rul'd him, punisht in the shape he sin'd, END
BEGIN NOW According to his doom: he would have spoke, END
BEGIN NOW But hiss for hiss returnd with forked tongue END
BEGIN NOW To forked tongue, for now were all transform'd END
BEGIN NOW Alike, to Serpents all as accessories END
BEGIN NOW To his bold Riot: dreadful was the din END
BEGIN NOW Of hissing through the Hall, thick swarming now END
BEGIN NOW With complicated monsters, head and taile, END
BEGIN NOW Scorpion and Asp, and AMPHISBAENA dire, END
BEGIN NOW CERASTES hornd, HYDRUS, and ELLOPS drear, END
BEGIN NOW And DIPSAS (Not so thick swarm'd once the Soil END
BEGIN NOW Bedropt with blood of Gorgon, or the Isle END
BEGIN NOW OPHIUSA) but still greatest hee the midst, END
BEGIN NOW Now Dragon grown, larger then whom the Sun END
BEGIN NOW Ingenderd in the PYTHIAN Vale on slime, END
BEGIN NOW Huge PYTHON, and his Power no less he seem'd END
BEGIN NOW Above the rest still to retain; they all END
BEGIN NOW Him follow'd issuing forth to th' open Field, END
BEGIN NOW Where all yet left of that revolted Rout END
BEGIN NOW Heav'n-fall'n, in station stood or just array, END
BEGIN NOW Sublime with expectation when to see END
BEGIN NOW In Triumph issuing forth thir glorious Chief; END
BEGIN NOW They saw, but other sight instead, a crowd END
BEGIN NOW Of ugly Serpents; horror on them fell, END
BEGIN NOW And horrid sympathie; for what they saw, END
BEGIN NOW They felt themselvs now changing; down thir arms, END
BEGIN NOW Down fell both Spear and Shield, down they as fast, END
BEGIN NOW And the dire hiss renew'd, and the dire form END
BEGIN NOW Catcht by Contagion, like in punishment, END
BEGIN NOW As in thir crime. Thus was th' applause they meant, END
BEGIN NOW Turnd to exploding hiss, triumph to shame END
BEGIN NOW Cast on themselves from thir own mouths. There stood END
BEGIN NOW A Grove hard by, sprung up with this thir change, END
BEGIN NOW His will who reigns above, to aggravate END
BEGIN NOW Thir penance, laden with fair Fruit, like that END
BEGIN NOW VVhich grew in Paradise, the bait of EVE END
BEGIN NOW Us'd by the Tempter: on that prospect strange END
BEGIN NOW Thir earnest eyes they fix'd, imagining END
BEGIN NOW For one forbidden Tree a multitude END
BEGIN NOW Now ris'n, to work them furder woe or shame; END
BEGIN NOW Yet parcht with scalding thurst and hunger fierce, END
BEGIN NOW Though to delude them sent, could not abstain, END
BEGIN NOW But on they rould in heaps, and up the Trees END
BEGIN NOW Climbing, sat thicker then the snakie locks END
BEGIN NOW That curld MEGAERA: greedily they pluck'd END
BEGIN NOW The Frutage fair to sight, like that which grew END
BEGIN NOW Neer that bituminous Lake where SODOM flam'd; END
BEGIN NOW This more delusive, not the touch, but taste END
BEGIN NOW Deceav'd; they fondly thinking to allay END
BEGIN NOW Thir appetite with gust, instead of Fruit END
BEGIN NOW Chewd bitter Ashes, which th' offended taste END
BEGIN NOW VVith spattering noise rejected: oft they assayd, END
BEGIN NOW Hunger and thirst constraining, drugd as oft, END
BEGIN NOW VVith hatefullest disrelish writh'd thir jaws END
BEGIN NOW VVith foot and cinders fill'd; so oft they fell END
BEGIN NOW Into the same illusion, not as Man END
BEGIN NOW Whom they triumph'd once lapst. Thus were they plagu'd END
BEGIN NOW And worn with Famin, long and ceasless hiss, END
BEGIN NOW Till thir lost shape, permitted, they resum'd, END
BEGIN NOW Yearly enjoynd, some say, to undergo END
BEGIN NOW This annual humbling certain number'd days, END
BEGIN NOW To dash thir pride, and joy for Man seduc't. END
BEGIN NOW However some tradition they dispers'd END
BEGIN NOW Among the Heathen of thir purchase got, END
BEGIN NOW And Fabl'd how the Serpent, whom they calld END
BEGIN NOW OPHION with EURYNOME, the wide- END
BEGIN NOW Encroaching EVE perhaps, had first the rule END
BEGIN NOW Of high OLYMPUS, thence by SATURN driv'n END
BEGIN NOW And OPS, ere yet DICTAEAN JOVE was born. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while in Paradise the hellish pair END
BEGIN NOW Too soon arriv'd, SIN there in power before, END
BEGIN NOW Once actual, now in body, and to dwell END
BEGIN NOW Habitual habitant; behind her DEATH END
BEGIN NOW Close following pace for pace, not mounted yet END
BEGIN NOW On his pale Horse: to whom SIN thus began. END
BEGIN NOW Second of SATAN sprung, all conquering Death, END
BEGIN NOW What thinkst thou of our Empire now, though earnd END
BEGIN NOW With travail difficult, not better farr END
BEGIN NOW Then stil at Hels dark threshold to have sate watch, END
BEGIN NOW Unnam'd, undreaded, and thy self half starv'd? END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus the Sin-born Monster answerd soon. END
BEGIN NOW To mee, who with eternal Famin pine, END
BEGIN NOW There best, where most with ravin I may meet; END
BEGIN NOW Which here, though plenteous, all too little seems END
BEGIN NOW To stuff this Maw, this vast unhide-bound Corps. END
BEGIN NOW To whom th' incestuous Mother thus repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Thou therefore on these Herbs, and Fruits, & Flours END
BEGIN NOW Feed first, on each Beast next, and Fish, and Fowle, END
BEGIN NOW No homely morsels, and whatever thing END
BEGIN NOW The Sithe of Time mowes down, devour unspar'd, END
BEGIN NOW Till I in Man residing through the Race, END
BEGIN NOW His thoughts, his looks, words, actions all infect, END
BEGIN NOW And season him thy last and sweetest prey. END
BEGIN NOW This said, they both betook them several wayes, END
BEGIN NOW Both to destroy, or unimmortal make END
BEGIN NOW All kinds, and for destruction to mature END
BEGIN NOW Sooner or later; which th' Almightie seeing, END
BEGIN NOW From his transcendent Seat the Saints among, END
BEGIN NOW To those bright Orders utterd thus his voice. END
BEGIN NOW See with what heat these Dogs of Hell advance END
BEGIN NOW To waste and havoc yonder VVorld, which I END
BEGIN NOW So fair and good created, and had still END
BEGIN NOW Kept in that state, had not the folly of Man END
BEGIN NOW Let in these wastful Furies, who impute END
BEGIN NOW Folly to mee, so doth the Prince of Hell END
BEGIN NOW And his Adherents, that with so much ease END
BEGIN NOW I suffer them to enter and possess END
BEGIN NOW A place so heav'nly, and conniving seem END
BEGIN NOW To gratifie my scornful Enemies, END
BEGIN NOW That laugh, as if transported with some fit END
BEGIN NOW Of Passion, I to them had quitted all, END
BEGIN NOW At random yeilded up to their misrule; END
BEGIN NOW And know not that I call'd and drew them thither END
BEGIN NOW My Hell-hounds, to lick up the draff and filth END
BEGIN NOW Which mans polluting Sin with taint hath shed END
BEGIN NOW On what was pure, till cramm'd and gorg'd, nigh burst END
BEGIN NOW With suckt and glutted offal, at one fling END
BEGIN NOW Of thy victorious Arm, well-pleasing Son, END
BEGIN NOW Both SIN, and DEATH, and yawning GRAVE at last END
BEGIN NOW Through CHAOS hurld, obstruct the mouth of Hell END
BEGIN NOW For ever, and seal up his ravenous Jawes. END
BEGIN NOW Then Heav'n and Earth renewd shall be made pure END
BEGIN NOW To sanctitie that shall receive no staine: END
BEGIN NOW Till then the Curse pronounc't on both precedes. END
BEGIN NOW Hee ended, and the heav'nly Audience loud END
BEGIN NOW Sung HALLELUIA, as the sound of Seas, END
BEGIN NOW Through multitude that sung: Just are thy ways, END
BEGIN NOW Who can extenuate thee? Next, to the Son, END
BEGIN NOW Destin'd restorer of Mankind, by whom END
BEGIN NOW New Heav'n and Earth shall to the Ages rise, END
BEGIN NOW Or down from Heav'n descend. Such was thir song, END
BEGIN NOW While the Creator calling forth by name END
BEGIN NOW His mightie Angels gave them several charge, END
BEGIN NOW As sorted best with present things. The Sun END
BEGIN NOW Had first his precept so to move, so shine, END
BEGIN NOW As might affect the Earth with cold and heat END
BEGIN NOW Scarce tollerable, and from the North to call END
BEGIN NOW Decrepit Winter, from the South to bring END
BEGIN NOW Solstitial summers heat. To the blanc Moone END
BEGIN NOW Her office they prescrib'd, to th' other five END
BEGIN NOW Thir planetarie motions and aspects END
BEGIN NOW Of noxious efficacie, and when to joyne END
BEGIN NOW In Synod unbenigne, and taught the fixt END
BEGIN NOW Thir influence malignant when to showre, END
BEGIN NOW Which of them rising with the Sun, or falling, END
BEGIN NOW Should prove tempestuous: To the Winds they set END
BEGIN NOW Thir corners, when with bluster to confound END
BEGIN NOW Sea, Aire, and Shoar, the Thunder when to rowle END
BEGIN NOW With terror through the dark Aereal Hall. END
BEGIN NOW Some say he bid his Angels turne ascanse END
BEGIN NOW The Poles of Earth twice ten degrees and more END
BEGIN NOW From the Suns Axle; they with labour push'd END
BEGIN NOW Was bid turn Reines from th' Equinoctial Rode END
BEGIN NOW Like distant breadth to TAURUS with the Seav'n END
BEGIN NOW ATLANTICK Sisters, and the SPARTAN Twins END
BEGIN NOW Up to the TROPIC Crab; thence down amaine END
BEGIN NOW By LEO and the VIRGIN and the SCALES, END
BEGIN NOW As deep as CAPRICORNE, to bring in change END
BEGIN NOW Of Seasons to each Clime; else had the Spring END
BEGIN NOW Perpetual smil'd on Earth with vernant Flours, END
BEGIN NOW Equal in Days and Nights, except to those END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the Polar Circles; to them Day END
BEGIN NOW Had unbenighted shon, while the low Sun END
BEGIN NOW To recompence his distance, in thir sight END
BEGIN NOW Had rounded still th' HORIZON, and not known END
BEGIN NOW Or East or West, which had forbid the Snow END
BEGIN NOW From cold ESTOTILAND, and South as farr END
BEGIN NOW Beneath MAGELLAN. At that tasted Fruit END
BEGIN NOW The Sun, as from THYESTEAN Banquet, turn'd END
BEGIN NOW His course intended; else how had the World END
BEGIN NOW Inhabited, though sinless, more then now, END
BEGIN NOW Avoided pinching cold and scorching heate? END
BEGIN NOW These changes in the Heav'ns, though slow, produc'd END
BEGIN NOW Like change on Sea and Land, sideral blast, END
BEGIN NOW Vapour, and Mist, and Exhalation hot, END
BEGIN NOW Corrupt and Pestilent: Now from the North END
BEGIN NOW Of NORUMBEGA, and the SAMOED shoar END
BEGIN NOW Bursting thir brazen Dungeon, armd with ice END
BEGIN NOW And snow and haile and stormie gust and flaw, END
BEGIN NOW And THRASCIAS rend the Woods and Seas upturn; END
BEGIN NOW With adverse blast up-turns them from the South END
BEGIN NOW NOTUS and AFER black with thundrous Clouds END
BEGIN NOW From SERRALIONA; thwart of these as fierce END
BEGIN NOW Forth rush the LEVANT and the PONENT VVindes END
BEGIN NOW EURUS and ZEPHIR with thir lateral noise, END
BEGIN NOW SIROCCO, and LIBECCHIO. Thus began END
BEGIN NOW Outrage from liveless things; but Discord first END
BEGIN NOW Daughter of Sin, among th' irrational, END
BEGIN NOW Death introduc'd through fierce antipathie: END
BEGIN NOW Beast now with Beast gan war, & Fowle with Fowle, END
BEGIN NOW And Fish with Fish; to graze the Herb all leaving, END
BEGIN NOW Devourd each other; nor stood much in awe END
BEGIN NOW Of Man, but fled him, or with count'nance grim END
BEGIN NOW Glar'd on him passing: these were from without END
BEGIN NOW The growing miseries, which ADAM saw END
BEGIN NOW Alreadie in part, though hid in gloomiest shade, END
BEGIN NOW To sorrow abandond, but worse felt within, END
BEGIN NOW And in a troubl'd Sea of passion tost, END
BEGIN NOW Thus to disburd'n sought with sad complaint. END
BEGIN NOW O miserable of happie! is this the end END
BEGIN NOW Of this new glorious World, and mee so late END
BEGIN NOW The Glory of that Glory, who now becom END
BEGIN NOW Accurst of blessed, hide me from the face END
BEGIN NOW Of God, whom to behold was then my highth END
BEGIN NOW Of happiness: yet well, if here would end END
BEGIN NOW The miserie, I deserv'd it, and would beare END
BEGIN NOW My own deservings; but this will not serve; END
BEGIN NOW All that I eate or drink, or shall beget, END
BEGIN NOW Is propagated curse. O voice once heard END
BEGIN NOW Now death to heare! for what can I encrease END
BEGIN NOW Or multiplie, but curses on my head? END
BEGIN NOW Who of all Ages to succeed, but feeling END
BEGIN NOW The evil on him brought by me, will curse END
BEGIN NOW My Head, Ill fare our Ancestor impure, END
BEGIN NOW For this we may thank ADAM; but his thanks END
BEGIN NOW Shall be the execration; so besides END
BEGIN NOW Mine own that bide upon me, all from mee END
BEGIN NOW Shall with a fierce reflux on mee redound, END
BEGIN NOW On mee as on thir natural center light END
BEGIN NOW Heavie, though in thir place. O fleeting joyes END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise, deare bought with lasting woes! END
BEGIN NOW Did I request thee, Maker, from my Clay END
BEGIN NOW To mould me Man, did I sollicite thee END
BEGIN NOW From darkness to promote me, or here place END
BEGIN NOW In this delicious Garden? as my Will END
BEGIN NOW Concurd not to my being, it were but right END
BEGIN NOW And equal to reduce me to my dust, END
BEGIN NOW Desirous to resigne, and render back END
BEGIN NOW All I receav'd, unable to performe END
BEGIN NOW Thy terms too hard, by which I was to hold END
BEGIN NOW The good I sought not. To the loss of that, END
BEGIN NOW Sufficient penaltie, why hast thou added END
BEGIN NOW The sense of endless woes? inexplicable END
BEGIN NOW Thy Justice seems; yet to say truth, too late, END
BEGIN NOW I thus contest; then should have been refusd END
BEGIN NOW Those terms whatever, when they were propos'd: END
BEGIN NOW Thou didst accept them; wilt thou enjoy the good, END
BEGIN NOW Then cavil the conditions? and though God END
BEGIN NOW Made thee without thy leave, what if thy Son END
BEGIN NOW Prove disobedient, and reprov'd, retort, END
BEGIN NOW Wherefore didst thou beget me? I sought it not: END
BEGIN NOW Wouldst thou admit for his contempt of thee END
BEGIN NOW That proud excuse? yet him not thy election, END
BEGIN NOW But Natural necessity begot. END
BEGIN NOW God made thee of choice his own, and of his own END
BEGIN NOW To serve him, thy reward was of his grace, END
BEGIN NOW Thy punishment then justly is at his Will. END
BEGIN NOW Be it so, for I submit, his doom is fair, END
BEGIN NOW That dust I am, and shall to dust returne: END
BEGIN NOW O welcom hour whenever! why delayes END
BEGIN NOW His hand to execute what his Decree END
BEGIN NOW Fixd on this day? why do I overlive, END
BEGIN NOW Why am I mockt with death, and length'nd out END
BEGIN NOW To deathless pain? how gladly would I meet END
BEGIN NOW Mortalitie my sentence, and be Earth END
BEGIN NOW Insensible, how glad would lay me down END
BEGIN NOW As in my Mothers lap? there I should rest END
BEGIN NOW And sleep secure; his dreadful voice no more END
BEGIN NOW Would Thunder in my ears, no fear of worse END
BEGIN NOW To mee and to my ofspring would torment me END
BEGIN NOW With cruel expectation. Yet one doubt END
BEGIN NOW Pursues me still, least all I cannot die, END
BEGIN NOW Least that pure breath of Life, the Spirit of Man END
BEGIN NOW Which God inspir'd, cannot together perish END
BEGIN NOW With this corporeal Clod; then in the Grave, END
BEGIN NOW Or in some other dismal place, who knows END
BEGIN NOW But I shall die a living Death? O thought END
BEGIN NOW Horrid, if true! yet why? it was but breath END
BEGIN NOW Of Life that sinn'd; what dies but what had life END
BEGIN NOW And sin? the Bodie properly hath neither. END
BEGIN NOW All of me then shall die: let this appease END
BEGIN NOW The doubt, since humane reach no further knows. END
BEGIN NOW For though the Lord of all be infinite, END
BEGIN NOW Is his wrauth also? be it, man is not so, END
BEGIN NOW But mortal doom'd. How can he exercise END
BEGIN NOW Wrath without end on Man whom Death must end? END
BEGIN NOW Can he make deathless Death? that were to make END
BEGIN NOW Strange contradiction, which to God himself END
BEGIN NOW Impossible is held, as Argument END
BEGIN NOW Of weakness, not of Power. Will he, draw out, END
BEGIN NOW For angers sake, finite to infinite END
BEGIN NOW In punisht man, to satisfie his rigour END
BEGIN NOW Satisfi'd never; that were to extend END
BEGIN NOW His Sentence beyond dust and Natures Law, END
BEGIN NOW By which all Causes else according still END
BEGIN NOW To the reception of thir matter act, END
BEGIN NOW Not to th' extent of thir own Spheare. But say END
BEGIN NOW That Death be not one stroak, as I suppos'd, END
BEGIN NOW Bereaving sense, but endless miserie END
BEGIN NOW From this day onward, which I feel begun END
BEGIN NOW Both in me, and without me, and so last END
BEGIN NOW To perpetuitie; Ay me, that fear END
BEGIN NOW Comes thundring back with dreadful revolution END
BEGIN NOW On my defensless head; both Death and I END
BEGIN NOW Am found Eternal, and incorporate both, END
BEGIN NOW Nor I on my part single, in mee all END
BEGIN NOW Posteritie stands curst: Fair Patrimonie END
BEGIN NOW That I must leave ye, Sons; O were I able END
BEGIN NOW To waste it all my self, and leave ye none! END
BEGIN NOW So disinherited how would ye bless END
BEGIN NOW Me now your Curse! Ah, why should all mankind END
BEGIN NOW For one mans fault thus guiltless be condemn'd, END
BEGIN NOW If guiltless? But from mee what can proceed, END
BEGIN NOW But all corrupt, both Mind and Will deprav'd, END
BEGIN NOW Not to do onely, but to will the same END
BEGIN NOW With me? how can they acquitted stand END
BEGIN NOW In sight of God? Him after all Disputes END
BEGIN NOW Forc't I absolve: all my evasions vain END
BEGIN NOW And reasonings, though through Mazes, lead me still END
BEGIN NOW But to my own conviction: first and last END
BEGIN NOW On mee, mee onely, as the sourse and spring END
BEGIN NOW Of all corruption, all the blame lights due; END
BEGIN NOW So might the wrauth, Fond wish! couldst thou support END
BEGIN NOW That burden heavier then the Earth to bear, END
BEGIN NOW Then all the world much heavier, though divided END
BEGIN NOW With that bad Woman? Thus what thou desir'st, END
BEGIN NOW And what thou fearst, alike destroyes all hope END
BEGIN NOW Of refuge, and concludes thee miserable END
BEGIN NOW Beyond all past example and future, END
BEGIN NOW To SATAN onely like both crime and doom. END
BEGIN NOW O Conscience, into what Abyss of fears END
BEGIN NOW And horrors hast thou driv'n me; out of which END
BEGIN NOW I find no way, from deep to deeper plung'd! END
BEGIN NOW Thus ADAM to himself lamented loud END
BEGIN NOW Through the still Night, now now, as ere man fell, END
BEGIN NOW Wholsom and cool, and mild, but with black Air END
BEGIN NOW Accompanied, with damps and dreadful gloom, END
BEGIN NOW Which to his evil Conscience represented END
BEGIN NOW All things with double terror: On the ground END
BEGIN NOW Outstretcht he lay, on the cold ground, and oft END
BEGIN NOW Curs'd his Creation, Death as oft accus'd END
BEGIN NOW The day of his offence. Why comes not Death, END
BEGIN NOW Said hee, with one thrice acceptable stroke END
BEGIN NOW To end me? Shall Truth fail to keep her word, END
BEGIN NOW Justice Divine not hast'n to be just? END
BEGIN NOW But Death comes not at call, Justice Divine END
BEGIN NOW Mends not her slowest pace for prayers or cries. END
BEGIN NOW VVith other echo farr I taught your Shades END
BEGIN NOW To answer, and resound farr other Song. END
BEGIN NOW VVhom thus afflicted when sad EVE beheld, END
BEGIN NOW Desolate where she sate, approaching nigh, END
BEGIN NOW Soft words to his fierce passion she assay'd: END
BEGIN NOW But her with stern regard he thus repell'd. END
BEGIN NOW Out of my sight, thou Serpent, that name best END
BEGIN NOW Befits thee with him leagu'd, thy self as false END
BEGIN NOW And hateful; nothing wants, but that thy shape, END
BEGIN NOW Like his, and colour Serpentine may shew END
BEGIN NOW Thy inward fraud, to warn all Creatures from thee END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth; least that too heav'nly form, pretended END
BEGIN NOW To hellish falshood, snare them. But for thee END
BEGIN NOW I had persisted happie, had not thy pride END
BEGIN NOW And wandring vanitie, when lest was safe, END
BEGIN NOW Rejected my forewarning, and disdain'd END
BEGIN NOW Not to be trusted, longing to be seen END
BEGIN NOW Though by the Devil himself, him overweening END
BEGIN NOW To over-reach, but with the Serpent meeting END
BEGIN NOW Fool'd and beguil'd, by him thou, I by thee, END
BEGIN NOW To trust thee from my side, imagin'd wise, END
BEGIN NOW Constant, mature, proof against all assaults, END
BEGIN NOW And understood not all was but a shew END
BEGIN NOW Rather then solid vertu, all but a Rib END
BEGIN NOW Crooked by nature, bent, as now appears, END
BEGIN NOW More to the part sinister from me drawn, END
BEGIN NOW Well if thrown out, as supernumerarie END
BEGIN NOW To my just number found. O why did God, END
BEGIN NOW Creator wise, that peopl'd highest Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW With Spirits Masculine, create at last END
BEGIN NOW This noveltie on Earth, this fair defect END
BEGIN NOW Of Nature, and not fill the World at once END
BEGIN NOW With Men as Angels without Feminine, END
BEGIN NOW Or find some other way to generate END
BEGIN NOW Mankind? this mischief had not then befall'n, END
BEGIN NOW And more that shall befall, innumerable END
BEGIN NOW Disturbances on Earth through Femal snares, END
BEGIN NOW And straight conjunction with this Sex: for either END
BEGIN NOW He never shall find out fit Mate, but such END
BEGIN NOW As some misfortune brings him, or mistake, END
BEGIN NOW Or whom he wishes most shall seldom gain END
BEGIN NOW Through her perverseness, but shall see her gaind END
BEGIN NOW By a farr worse, or if she love, withheld END
BEGIN NOW By Parents, or his happiest choice too late END
BEGIN NOW Shall meet, alreadie linkt and Wedlock-bound END
BEGIN NOW To a fell Adversarie, his hate or shame: END
BEGIN NOW Which infinite calamitie shall cause END
BEGIN NOW To humane life, and houshold peace confound. END
BEGIN NOW He added not, and from her turn'd, but EVE END
BEGIN NOW Not so repulst, with Tears that ceas'd not flowing, END
BEGIN NOW And tresses all disorderd, at his feet END
BEGIN NOW Fell humble, and imbracing them, besaught END
BEGIN NOW His peace, and thus proceeded in her plaint. END
BEGIN NOW Forsake me not thus, ADAM, witness Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW What love sincere, and reverence in my heart END
BEGIN NOW I beare thee, and unweeting have offended, END
BEGIN NOW Unhappilie deceav'd; thy suppliant END
BEGIN NOW I beg, and clasp thy knees; bereave me not, END
BEGIN NOW Whereon I live, thy gentle looks, thy aid, END
BEGIN NOW Thy counsel in this uttermost distress, END
BEGIN NOW My onely strength and stay: forlorn of thee, END
BEGIN NOW Whither shall I betake me, where subsist? END
BEGIN NOW While yet we live, scarse one short hour perhaps, END
BEGIN NOW Between us two let there be peace, both joyning, END
BEGIN NOW As joyn'd in injuries, one enmitie END
BEGIN NOW Against a Foe by doom express assign'd us, END
BEGIN NOW That cruel Serpent: On me exercise not END
BEGIN NOW Thy hatred for this miserie befall'n, END
BEGIN NOW On me already lost, mee then thy self END
BEGIN NOW More miserable; both have sin'd, but thou END
BEGIN NOW Against God onely, I against God and thee, END
BEGIN NOW And to the place of judgement will return, END
BEGIN NOW There with my cries importune Heaven, that all END
BEGIN NOW The sentence from thy head remov'd may light END
BEGIN NOW On me, sole cause to thee of all this woe, END
BEGIN NOW Mee mee onely just object of his ire. END
BEGIN NOW She ended weeping, and her lowlie plight, END
BEGIN NOW Immoveable till peace obtain'd from fault END
BEGIN NOW Acknowledg'd and deplor'd, in ADAM wraught END
BEGIN NOW Commiseration; soon his heart relented END
BEGIN NOW Towards her, his life so late and sole delight, END
BEGIN NOW Now at his feet submissive in distress, END
BEGIN NOW Creature so faire his reconcilement seeking, END
BEGIN NOW His counsel whom she had displeas'd, his aide; END
BEGIN NOW As one disarm'd, his anger all he lost, END
BEGIN NOW And thus with peaceful words uprais'd her soon. END
BEGIN NOW Unwarie, and too desirous, as before, END
BEGIN NOW So now of what thou knowst not, who desir'st END
BEGIN NOW The punishment all on thy self; alas, END
BEGIN NOW Beare thine own first, ill able to sustaine END
BEGIN NOW His full wrauth whose thou feelst as yet lest part, END
BEGIN NOW And my displeasure bearst so ill. If Prayers END
BEGIN NOW Could alter high Decrees, I to that place END
BEGIN NOW Would speed before thee, and be louder heard, END
BEGIN NOW That on my head all might be visited, END
BEGIN NOW Thy frailtie and infirmer Sex forgiv'n, END
BEGIN NOW To me committed and by me expos'd. END
BEGIN NOW But rise, let us no more contend, nor blame END
BEGIN NOW Each other, blam'd enough elsewhere, but strive END
BEGIN NOW In offices of Love, how we may light'n END
BEGIN NOW Each others burden in our share of woe; END
BEGIN NOW Since this days Death denounc't, if ought I see, END
BEGIN NOW Will prove no sudden, but a slow-pac't evill, END
BEGIN NOW A long days dying to augment our paine, END
BEGIN NOW And to our Seed (O hapless Seed!) deriv'd. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus EVE, recovering heart, repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW ADAM, by sad experiment I know END
BEGIN NOW How little weight my words with thee can finde, END
BEGIN NOW Found so erroneous, thence by just event END
BEGIN NOW Found so unfortunate; nevertheless, END
BEGIN NOW Restor'd by thee, vile as I am, to place END
BEGIN NOW Of new acceptance, hopeful to regaine END
BEGIN NOW Thy Love, the sole contentment of my heart, END
BEGIN NOW Living or dying from thee I will not hide END
BEGIN NOW What thoughts in my unquiet brest are ris'n, END
BEGIN NOW Tending to som relief of our extremes, END
BEGIN NOW Or end, though sharp and sad, yet tolerable, END
BEGIN NOW As in our evils, and of easier choice. END
BEGIN NOW If care of our descent perplex us most, END
BEGIN NOW Which must be born to certain woe, devourd END
BEGIN NOW By Death at last, and miserable it is END
BEGIN NOW To be to others cause of misery, END
BEGIN NOW Our own begotten, and of our Loines to bring END
BEGIN NOW Into this cursed World a woful Race, END
BEGIN NOW That after wretched Life must be at last END
BEGIN NOW Food for so foule a Monster, in thy power END
BEGIN NOW It lies, yet ere Conception to prevent END
BEGIN NOW The Race unblest, to being yet unbegot. END
BEGIN NOW Childless thou art, Childless remaine: END
BEGIN NOW So Death shall be deceav'd his glut, and with us two END
BEGIN NOW Be forc'd to satisfie his Rav'nous Maw. END
BEGIN NOW But if thou judge it hard and difficult, END
BEGIN NOW Conversing, looking, loving, to abstain END
BEGIN NOW From Loves due Rites, Nuptial embraces sweet, END
BEGIN NOW And with desire to languish without hope, END
BEGIN NOW Before the present object languishing END
BEGIN NOW With like desire, which would be miserie END
BEGIN NOW And torment less then none of what we dread, END
BEGIN NOW Then both our selves and Seed at once to free END
BEGIN NOW From what we fear for both, let us make short, END
BEGIN NOW Let us seek Death, or hee not found, supply END
BEGIN NOW With our own hands his Office on our selves; END
BEGIN NOW Why stand we longer shivering under feares, END
BEGIN NOW That shew no end but Death, and have the power, END
BEGIN NOW Of many wayes to die the shortest choosing, END
BEGIN NOW Destruction with destruction to destroy. END
BEGIN NOW She ended heer, or vehement despaire END
BEGIN NOW Broke off the rest; so much of Death her thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Had entertaind, as di'd her Cheeks with pale. END
BEGIN NOW But ADAM with such counsel nothing sway'd, END
BEGIN NOW To better hopes his more attentive minde END
BEGIN NOW Labouring had rais'd, and thus to EVE repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW EVE, thy contempt of life and pleasure seems END
BEGIN NOW To argue in thee somthing more sublime END
BEGIN NOW And excellent then what thy minde contemnes; END
BEGIN NOW But self-destruction therefore saught, refutes END
BEGIN NOW That excellence thought in thee, and implies, END
BEGIN NOW Not thy contempt, but anguish and regret END
BEGIN NOW For loss of life and pleasure overlov'd. END
BEGIN NOW Or if thou covet death, as utmost end END
BEGIN NOW Of miserie, so thinking to evade END
BEGIN NOW The penaltie pronounc't, doubt not but God END
BEGIN NOW Hath wiselier arm'd his vengeful ire then so END
BEGIN NOW To be forestall'd; much more I fear least Death END
BEGIN NOW So snatcht will not exempt us from the paine END
BEGIN NOW We are by doom to pay; rather such acts END
BEGIN NOW Of contumacie will provoke the highest END
BEGIN NOW To make death in us live: Then let us seek END
BEGIN NOW Som safer resolution, which methinks END
BEGIN NOW I have in view, calling to minde with heed END
BEGIN NOW Part of our Sentence, that thy Seed shall bruise END
BEGIN NOW The Serpents head; piteous amends, unless END
BEGIN NOW Be meant, whom I conjecture, our grand Foe END
BEGIN NOW SATAN, who in the Serpent hath contriv'd END
BEGIN NOW Against us this deceit: to crush his head END
BEGIN NOW Would be revenge indeed; which will be lost END
BEGIN NOW By death brought on our selves, or childless days END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd, as thou proposest; so our Foe END
BEGIN NOW Shall scape his punishment ordain'd, and wee END
BEGIN NOW Instead shall double ours upon our heads. END
BEGIN NOW No more be mention'd then of violence END
BEGIN NOW Against our selves, and wilful barrenness, END
BEGIN NOW That cuts us off from hope, and savours onely END
BEGIN NOW Rancor and pride, impatience and despite, END
BEGIN NOW Reluctance against God and his just yoke END
BEGIN NOW Laid on our Necks. Remember with what mild END
BEGIN NOW And gracious temper he both heard and judg'd END
BEGIN NOW Without wrauth or reviling; wee expected END
BEGIN NOW Immediate dissolution, which we thought END
BEGIN NOW Was meant by Death that day, when lo, to thee END
BEGIN NOW Pains onely in Child-bearing were foretold, END
BEGIN NOW And bringing forth, soon recompenc't with joy, END
BEGIN NOW Fruit of thy Womb: On mee the Curse aslope END
BEGIN NOW Glanc'd on the ground, with labour I must earne END
BEGIN NOW My bread; what harm? Idleness had bin worse; END
BEGIN NOW My labour will sustain me; and least Cold END
BEGIN NOW Or Heat should injure us, his timely care END
BEGIN NOW Hath unbesaught provided, and his hands END
BEGIN NOW Cloath'd us unworthie, pitying while he judg'd; END
BEGIN NOW How much more, if we pray him, will his ear END
BEGIN NOW Be open, and his heart to pitie incline, END
BEGIN NOW And teach us further by what means to shun END
BEGIN NOW Th' inclement Seasons, Rain, Ice, Hail and Snow, END
BEGIN NOW Which now the Skie with various Face begins END
BEGIN NOW To shew us in this Mountain, while the Winds END
BEGIN NOW Blow moist and keen, shattering the graceful locks END
BEGIN NOW Of these fair spreading Trees; which bids us seek END
BEGIN NOW Som better shroud, som better warmth to cherish END
BEGIN NOW Our Limbs benumm'd, ere this diurnal Starr END
BEGIN NOW Leave cold the Night, how we his gather'd beams END
BEGIN NOW Reflected, may with matter sere foment, END
BEGIN NOW Or by collision of two bodies grinde END
BEGIN NOW The Air attrite to Fire, as late the Clouds END
BEGIN NOW Justling or pusht with Winds rude in thir shock END
BEGIN NOW Tine the slant Lightning, whose thwart flame driv'n down END
BEGIN NOW Kindles the gummie bark of Firr or Pine, END
BEGIN NOW And sends a comfortable heat from farr, END
BEGIN NOW Which might supplie the Sun: such Fire to use, END
BEGIN NOW And what may else be remedie or cure END
BEGIN NOW To evils which our own misdeeds have wrought, END
BEGIN NOW Hee will instruct us praying, and of Grace END
BEGIN NOW Beseeching him, so as we need not fear END
BEGIN NOW To pass commodiously this life, sustain'd END
BEGIN NOW By him with many comforts, till we end END
BEGIN NOW In dust, our final rest and native home. END
BEGIN NOW What better can we do, then to the place END
BEGIN NOW Repairing where he judg'd us, prostrate fall END
BEGIN NOW Before him reverent, and there confess END
BEGIN NOW Humbly our faults, and pardon beg, with tears END
BEGIN NOW VVatering the ground, and with our sighs the Air END
BEGIN NOW Frequenting, sent from hearts contrite, in sign END
BEGIN NOW Of sorrow unfeign'd, and humiliation meek. END
BEGIN NOW Undoubtedly he will relent and turn END
BEGIN NOW From his displeasure; in whose look serene, END
BEGIN NOW VVhen angry most he seem'd and most severe, END
BEGIN NOW VVhat else but favor, grace, and mercie shon? END
BEGIN NOW So spake our Father penitent, nor EVE END
BEGIN NOW Felt less remorse: they forthwith to the place END
BEGIN NOW Repairing where he judg'd them prostrate fell END
BEGIN NOW Before him reverent, and both confess'd END
BEGIN NOW Humbly thir faults, and pardon beg'd, with tears END
BEGIN NOW VVatering the ground, and with thir sighs the Air END
BEGIN NOW Frequenting, sent from hearts contrite, in sign END
BEGIN NOW Of sorrow unfeign'd, and humiliation meek. END
BEGIN NOW Thus they in lowliest plight repentant stood END
BEGIN NOW Praying, for from the Mercie-seat above END
BEGIN NOW Prevenient Grace descending had remov'd END
BEGIN NOW The stonie from thir hearts, and made new flesh END
BEGIN NOW Regenerat grow instead, that sighs now breath'd END
BEGIN NOW Unutterable, which the Spirit of prayer END
BEGIN NOW Inspir'd, and wing'd for Heav'n with speedier flight END
BEGIN NOW Then loudest Oratorie: yet thir port END
BEGIN NOW Not of mean suiters, nor important less END
BEGIN NOW Seem'd thir Petition, then when th' ancient Pair END
BEGIN NOW In Fables old, less ancient yet then these, END
BEGIN NOW DEUCALION and chaste PYRRHA to restore END
BEGIN NOW The Race of Mankind drownd, before the Shrine END
BEGIN NOW Of THEMIS stood devout. To Heav'n thir prayers END
BEGIN NOW Flew up, nor missed the way, by envious windes END
BEGIN NOW Blow'n vagabond or frustrate: in they passd END
BEGIN NOW Dimentionless through Heav'nly dores; then clad END
BEGIN NOW With incense, where the Golden Altar fum'd, END
BEGIN NOW By thir great Intercessor, came in sight END
BEGIN NOW Before the Fathers Throne: Them the glad Son END
BEGIN NOW Presenting, thus to intercede began. END
BEGIN NOW See Father, what first fruits on Earth are sprung END
BEGIN NOW From thy implanted Grace in Man, these Sighs END
BEGIN NOW And Prayers, which in this Golden Censer, mixt END
BEGIN NOW With Incense, I thy Priest before thee bring, END
BEGIN NOW Fruits of more pleasing savour from thy seed END
BEGIN NOW Sow'n with contrition in his heart, then those END
BEGIN NOW Which his own hand manuring all the Trees END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise could have produc't, ere fall'n END
BEGIN NOW From innocence. Now therefore bend thine eare END
BEGIN NOW To supplication, heare his sighs though mute; END
BEGIN NOW Unskilful with what words to pray, let mee END
BEGIN NOW Interpret for him, mee his Advocate END
BEGIN NOW And propitiation, all his works on mee END
BEGIN NOW Good or not good ingraft, my Merit those END
BEGIN NOW Shall perfet, and for these my Death shall pay. END
BEGIN NOW Accept me, and in mee from these receave END
BEGIN NOW The smell of peace toward Mankinde, let him live END
BEGIN NOW Before thee reconcil'd, at least his days END
BEGIN NOW Numberd, though sad, till Death, his doom (which I END
BEGIN NOW To mitigate thus plead, not to reverse) END
BEGIN NOW To better life shall yeeld him, where with mee END
BEGIN NOW All my redeemd may dwell in joy and bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Made one with me as I with thee am one. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Father, without Cloud, serene. END
BEGIN NOW All thy request for Man, accepted Son, END
BEGIN NOW Obtain, all thy request was my Decree: END
BEGIN NOW But longer in that Paradise to dwell, END
BEGIN NOW The Law I gave to Nature him forbids: END
BEGIN NOW Those pure immortal Elements that know END
BEGIN NOW No gross, no unharmoneous mixture foule, END
BEGIN NOW Eject him tainted now, and purge him off END
BEGIN NOW As a distemper, gross to aire as gross, END
BEGIN NOW And mortal food, as may dispose him best END
BEGIN NOW For dissolution wrought by Sin, that first END
BEGIN NOW Distemperd all things, and of incorrupt END
BEGIN NOW Corrupted. I at first with two fair gifts END
BEGIN NOW Created him endowd, with Happiness END
BEGIN NOW And Immortalitie: that fondly lost, END
BEGIN NOW This other serv'd but to eternize woe; END
BEGIN NOW Till I provided Death; so Death becomes END
BEGIN NOW His final remedie, and after Life END
BEGIN NOW Tri'd in sharp tribulation, and refin'd END
BEGIN NOW By Faith and faithful works, to second Life, END
BEGIN NOW Wak't in the renovation of the just, END
BEGIN NOW Resignes him up with Heav'n and Earth renewd. END
BEGIN NOW But let us call to Synod all the Blest END
BEGIN NOW Through Heav'ns wide bounds; from them I will not hide END
BEGIN NOW My judgments, how with Mankind I proceed, END
BEGIN NOW As how with peccant Angels late they saw; END
BEGIN NOW And in thir state, though firm, stood more confirmd. END
BEGIN NOW He ended, and the Son gave signal high END
BEGIN NOW To the bright Minister that watchd, hee blew END
BEGIN NOW His Trumpet, heard in OREB since perhaps END
BEGIN NOW When God descended, and perhaps once more END
BEGIN NOW To sound at general Doom. Th' Angelic blast END
BEGIN NOW Filld all the Regions: from thir blissful Bowrs END
BEGIN NOW Of AMARANTIN Shade, Fountain or Spring, END
BEGIN NOW By the waters of Life, where ere they sate END
BEGIN NOW In fellowships of joy: the Sons of Light END
BEGIN NOW Hasted, resorting to the Summons high, END
BEGIN NOW And took thir Seats; till from his Throne supream END
BEGIN NOW Th' Almighty thus pronounced his sovran Will. END
BEGIN NOW O Sons, like one of us Man is become END
BEGIN NOW To know both Good and Evil, since his taste END
BEGIN NOW Of that defended Fruit; but let him boast END
BEGIN NOW His knowledge of Good lost, and Evil got, END
BEGIN NOW Happier, had it suffic'd him to have known END
BEGIN NOW Good by it self, and Evil not at all. END
BEGIN NOW He sorrows now, repents, and prayes contrite, END
BEGIN NOW My motions in him, longer then they move, END
BEGIN NOW His heart I know, how variable and vain END
BEGIN NOW Self-left. Least therefore his now bolder hand END
BEGIN NOW Reach also of the Tree of Life, and eat, END
BEGIN NOW And live for ever, dream at least to live END
BEGIN NOW Forever, to remove him I decree, END
BEGIN NOW And send him from the Garden forth to Till END
BEGIN NOW The Ground whence he was taken, fitter soile. END
BEGIN NOW MICHAEL, this my behest have thou in charge, END
BEGIN NOW Take to thee from among the Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW Thy choice of flaming Warriours, least the Fiend END
BEGIN NOW Or in behalf of Man, or to invade END
BEGIN NOW Vacant possession som new trouble raise: END
BEGIN NOW Hast thee, and from the Paradise of God END
BEGIN NOW Without remorse drive out the sinful Pair, END
BEGIN NOW From hallowd ground th' unholie, and denounce END
BEGIN NOW To them and to thir Progenie from thence END
BEGIN NOW Perpetual banishment. Yet least they faint END
BEGIN NOW At the sad Sentence rigorously urg'd, END
BEGIN NOW For I behold them soft'nd and with tears END
BEGIN NOW Bewailing thir excess, all terror hide. END
BEGIN NOW If patiently thy bidding they obey, END
BEGIN NOW Dismiss them not disconsolate; reveale END
BEGIN NOW To ADAM what shall come in future dayes, END
BEGIN NOW As I shall thee enlighten, intermix END
BEGIN NOW My Cov'nant in the Womans seed renewd; END
BEGIN NOW So send them forth, though sorrowing, yet in peace: END
BEGIN NOW And on the East side of the Garden place, END
BEGIN NOW Where entrance up from EDEN easiest climbes, END
BEGIN NOW Cherubic watch, and of a Sword the flame END
BEGIN NOW Wide waving, all approach farr off to fright, END
BEGIN NOW And guard all passage to the Tree of Life: END
BEGIN NOW Least Paradise a receptacle prove END
BEGIN NOW To Spirits foule, and all my Trees thir prey, END
BEGIN NOW With whose stol'n Fruit Man once more to delude. END
BEGIN NOW He ceas'd; and th' Archangelic Power prepar'd END
BEGIN NOW For swift descent, with him the Cohort bright END
BEGIN NOW Of watchful Cherubim; four faces each END
BEGIN NOW Had, like a double JANUS, all thir shape END
BEGIN NOW Spangl'd with eyes more numerous then those END
BEGIN NOW Of ARGUS, and more wakeful then to drouze, END
BEGIN NOW Charm'd with ARCADIAN Pipe, the Pastoral Reed END
BEGIN NOW Of HERMES, or his opiate Rod. Meanwhile END
BEGIN NOW To resalute the World with sacred Light END
BEGIN NOW LEUCOTHEA wak'd, and with fresh dews imbalmd END
BEGIN NOW The Earth, when ADAM and first Matron EVE END
BEGIN NOW Had ended now thir Orisons, and found, END
BEGIN NOW Strength added from above, new hope to spring END
BEGIN NOW Out of despaire, joy, but with fear yet linkt; END
BEGIN NOW Which thus to EVE his welcome words renewd. END
BEGIN NOW EVE, easily may Faith admit, that all END
BEGIN NOW The good which we enjoy, from Heav'n descends END
BEGIN NOW But that from us ought should ascend to Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW So prevalent as to concerne the mind END
BEGIN NOW Of God high blest, or to incline his will, END
BEGIN NOW Hard to belief may seem; yet this will Prayer, END
BEGIN NOW Or one short sigh of humane breath, up-borne END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n to the Seat of God. For since I saught END
BEGIN NOW By Prayer th' offended Deitie to appease, END
BEGIN NOW Kneel'd and before him humbl'd all my heart, END
BEGIN NOW Methought I saw him placable and mild, END
BEGIN NOW Bending his eare; perswasion in me grew END
BEGIN NOW That I was heard with favour; peace returnd END
BEGIN NOW Home to my brest, and to my memorie END
BEGIN NOW His promise, that thy Seed shall bruise our Foe; END
BEGIN NOW Which then not minded in dismay, yet now END
BEGIN NOW Assures me that the bitterness of death END
BEGIN NOW Is past, and we shall live. Whence Haile to thee, END
BEGIN NOW EVE rightly call'd, Mother of all Mankind, END
BEGIN NOW Mother of all things living, since by thee END
BEGIN NOW Man is to live, and all things live for Man. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus EVE with sad demeanour meek. END
BEGIN NOW Ill worthie I such title should belong END
BEGIN NOW To me transgressour, who for thee ordaind END
BEGIN NOW A help, became thy snare; to mee reproach END
BEGIN NOW Rather belongs, distrust and all dispraise: END
BEGIN NOW But infinite in pardon was my Judge, END
BEGIN NOW That I who first brought Death on all, am grac't END
BEGIN NOW The sourse of life; next favourable thou, END
BEGIN NOW Who highly thus to entitle me voutsaf't, END
BEGIN NOW Farr other name deserving. But the Field END
BEGIN NOW To labour calls us now with sweat impos'd, END
BEGIN NOW Though after sleepless Night; for see the Morn, END
BEGIN NOW All unconcern'd with our unrest, begins END
BEGIN NOW Her rosie progress smiling; let us forth, END
BEGIN NOW I never from thy side henceforth to stray, END
BEGIN NOW Wherere our days work lies, though now enjoind END
BEGIN NOW Laborious, till day droop; while here we dwell, END
BEGIN NOW What can be toilsom in these pleasant Walkes? END
BEGIN NOW Here let us live, though in fall'n state, content. END
BEGIN NOW So spake, so wish'd much-humbl'd EVE, but Fate END
BEGIN NOW Subscrib'd not; Nature first gave Signs, imprest END
BEGIN NOW On Bird, Beast, Aire, Aire suddenly eclips'd END
BEGIN NOW After short blush of Morn; nigh in her sight END
BEGIN NOW The Bird of JOVE, stoopt from his aerie tour, END
BEGIN NOW Two Birds of gayest plume before him drove: END
BEGIN NOW Down from a Hill the Beast that reigns in Woods, END
BEGIN NOW First Hunter then, pursu'd a gentle brace, END
BEGIN NOW Direct to th' Eastern Gate was bent thir flight. END
BEGIN NOW ADAM observ'd, and with his Eye the chase END
BEGIN NOW Pursuing, not unmov'd to EVE thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW O EVE, some furder change awaits us nigh, END
BEGIN NOW Which Heav'n by these mute signs in Nature shews END
BEGIN NOW Forerunners of his purpose, or to warn END
BEGIN NOW Us haply too secure of our discharge END
BEGIN NOW From penaltie, because from death releast END
BEGIN NOW Some days; how long, and what till then our life, END
BEGIN NOW Who knows, or more then this, that we are dust, END
BEGIN NOW And thither must return and be no more. END
BEGIN NOW VVhy else this double object in our sight END
BEGIN NOW Of flight pursu'd in th' Air and ore the ground END
BEGIN NOW One way the self-same hour? why in the East END
BEGIN NOW Darkness ere Dayes mid-course, and Morning light END
BEGIN NOW More orient in yon VVestern Cloud that draws END
BEGIN NOW O're the blew Firmament a radiant white, END
BEGIN NOW And slow descends, with somthing heav'nly fraught. END
BEGIN NOW He err'd not, for by this the heav'nly Bands END
BEGIN NOW Down from a Skie of Jasper lighted now END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise, and on a Hill made alt, END
BEGIN NOW A glorious Apparition, had not doubt END
BEGIN NOW And carnal fear that day dimm'd ADAMS eye. END
BEGIN NOW Not that more glorious, when the Angels met END
BEGIN NOW JACOB in MAHANAIM, where he saw END
BEGIN NOW The field Pavilion'd with his Guardians bright; END
BEGIN NOW Nor that which on the flaming Mount appeerd END
BEGIN NOW In DOTHAN, cover'd with a Camp of Fire, END
BEGIN NOW Against the SYRIAN King, who to surprize END
BEGIN NOW One man, Assassin-like had levied Warr, END
BEGIN NOW Warr unproclam'd. The Princely Hierarch END
BEGIN NOW In thir bright stand, there left his Powers to seise END
BEGIN NOW Possession of the Garden; hee alone, END
BEGIN NOW To finde where ADAM shelterd, took his way, END
BEGIN NOW Not unperceav'd of ADAM, who to EVE, END
BEGIN NOW While the great Visitant approachd, thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW EVE, now expect great tidings, which perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Of us will soon determin, or impose END
BEGIN NOW New Laws to be observ'd; for I descrie END
BEGIN NOW From yonder blazing Cloud that veils the Hill END
BEGIN NOW One of the heav'nly Host, and by his Gate END
BEGIN NOW None of the meanest, some great Potentate END
BEGIN NOW Or of the Thrones above, such Majestie END
BEGIN NOW Invests him coming; yet not terrible, END
BEGIN NOW That I should fear, nor sociably mild, END
BEGIN NOW As RAPHAEL, that I should much confide, END
BEGIN NOW But solemn and sublime, whom not to offend, END
BEGIN NOW With reverence I must meet, and thou retire. END
BEGIN NOW He ended; and th' Arch-Angel soon drew nigh, END
BEGIN NOW Not in his shape Celestial, but as Man END
BEGIN NOW Clad to meet Man; over his lucid Armes END
BEGIN NOW A militarie Vest of purple flowd END
BEGIN NOW Livelier then MELIBOEAN, or the graine END
BEGIN NOW Of SARRA, worn by Kings and Hero's old END
BEGIN NOW In time of Truce; IRIS had dipt the wooff; END
BEGIN NOW His starrie Helme unbuckl'd shew'd him prime END
BEGIN NOW In Manhood where Youth ended; by his side END
BEGIN NOW As in a glistering ZODIAC hung the Sword, END
BEGIN NOW Satans dire dread, and in his hand the Spear. END
BEGIN NOW ADAM bowd low, hee Kingly from his State END
BEGIN NOW Inclin'd not, but his coming thus declar'd. END
BEGIN NOW ADAM, Heav'ns high behest no Preface needs: END
BEGIN NOW Sufficient that thy Prayers are heard, and Death, END
BEGIN NOW Then due by sentence when thou didst transgress, END
BEGIN NOW Defeated of his seisure many dayes END
BEGIN NOW Giv'n thee of Grace, wherein thou may'st repent, END
BEGIN NOW And one bad act with many deeds well done END
BEGIN NOW Mayst cover: well may then thy Lord appeas'd END
BEGIN NOW Redeem thee quite from Deaths rapacious claimes; END
BEGIN NOW But longer in this Paradise to dwell END
BEGIN NOW Permits not; to remove thee I am come, END
BEGIN NOW And send thee from the Garden forth to till END
BEGIN NOW The ground whence thou wast tak'n, fitter Soile. END
BEGIN NOW He added not, for ADAM at the newes END
BEGIN NOW Heart-strook with chilling gripe of sorrow stood, END
BEGIN NOW That all his senses bound; EVE, who unseen END
BEGIN NOW Yet all had heard, with audible lament END
BEGIN NOW Discover'd soon the place of her retire. END
BEGIN NOW O unexpected stroke, worse then of Death! END
BEGIN NOW Must I thus leave thee Paradise? thus leave END
BEGIN NOW Thee Native Soile, these happie Walks and Shades, END
BEGIN NOW Fit haunt of Gods? where I had hope to spend, END
BEGIN NOW Quiet though sad, the respit of that day END
BEGIN NOW That must be mortal to us both. O flours, END
BEGIN NOW That never will in other Climate grow, END
BEGIN NOW My early visitation, and my last END
BEGIN NOW At Eev'n, which I bred up with tender hand END
BEGIN NOW From the first op'ning bud, and gave ye Names, END
BEGIN NOW Who now shall reare ye to the Sun, or ranke END
BEGIN NOW Your Tribes, and water from th' ambrosial Fount? END
BEGIN NOW Thee lastly nuptial Bowre, by mee adornd END
BEGIN NOW With what to sight or smell was sweet; from thee END
BEGIN NOW How shall I part, and whither wander down END
BEGIN NOW Into a lower World, to this obscure END
BEGIN NOW And wilde, how shall we breath in other Aire END
BEGIN NOW Less pure, accustomd to immortal Fruits? END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus the Angel interrupted milde. END
BEGIN NOW Lament not EVE, but patiently resigne END
BEGIN NOW What justly thou hast lost; nor set thy heart, END
BEGIN NOW Thus over fond, on that which is not thine; END
BEGIN NOW Thy going is not lonely, with thee goes END
BEGIN NOW Thy Husband, him to follow thou art bound; END
BEGIN NOW Where he abides, think there thy native soile. END
BEGIN NOW ADAM by this from the cold sudden damp END
BEGIN NOW Recovering, and his scatterd spirits returnd, END
BEGIN NOW To MICHAEL thus his humble words addressd. END
BEGIN NOW Celestial, whether among the Thrones, or nam'd END
BEGIN NOW Of them the Highest, for such of shape may seem END
BEGIN NOW Prince above Princes, gently hast thou tould END
BEGIN NOW Thy message, which might else in telling wound, END
BEGIN NOW And in performing end us; what besides END
BEGIN NOW Of sorrow and dejection and despair END
BEGIN NOW Our frailtie can sustain, thy tidings bring, END
BEGIN NOW Departure from this happy place, our sweet END
BEGIN NOW Recess, and onely consolation left END
BEGIN NOW Familiar to our eyes, all places else END
BEGIN NOW Inhospitable appeer and desolate, END
BEGIN NOW Nor knowing us nor known: and if by prayer END
BEGIN NOW Incessant I could hope to change the will END
BEGIN NOW Of him who all things can, I would not cease END
BEGIN NOW To wearie him with my assiduous cries: END
BEGIN NOW But prayer against his absolute Decree END
BEGIN NOW No more availes then breath against the winde, END
BEGIN NOW Blown stifling back on him that breaths it forth: END
BEGIN NOW Therefore to his great bidding I submit. END
BEGIN NOW This most afflicts me, that departing hence, END
BEGIN NOW As from his face I shall be hid, deprivd END
BEGIN NOW His blessed count'nance; here I could frequent, END
BEGIN NOW With worship, place by place where he voutsaf'd END
BEGIN NOW Presence Divine, and to my Sons relate; END
BEGIN NOW On this Mount he appeerd, under this Tree END
BEGIN NOW Stood visible, among these Pines his voice END
BEGIN NOW I heard, here with him at this Fountain talk'd: END
BEGIN NOW So many grateful Altars I would reare END
BEGIN NOW Of grassie Terfe, and pile up every Stone END
BEGIN NOW Of lustre from the brook, in memorie, END
BEGIN NOW Or monument to Ages, and thereon END
BEGIN NOW Offer sweet smelling Gumms & Fruits and Flours: END
BEGIN NOW In yonder nether World where shall I seek END
BEGIN NOW His bright appearances, or footstep trace? END
BEGIN NOW For though I fled him angrie, yet recall'd END
BEGIN NOW To life prolongd and promisd Race, I now END
BEGIN NOW Gladly behold though but his utmost skirts END
BEGIN NOW Of glory, and farr off his steps adore. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus MICHAEL with regard benigne. END
BEGIN NOW ADAM, thou know'st Heav'n his, and all the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Not this Rock onely; his Omnipresence fills END
BEGIN NOW Land, Sea, and Aire, and every kinde that lives, END
BEGIN NOW Fomented by his virtual power and warmd: END
BEGIN NOW All th' Earth he gave thee to possess and rule, END
BEGIN NOW No despicable gift; surmise not then END
BEGIN NOW His presence to these narrow bounds confin'd END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise or EDEN: this had been END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps thy Capital Seate, from whence had spred END
BEGIN NOW All generations, and had hither come END
BEGIN NOW From all the ends of th' Earth, to celebrate END
BEGIN NOW And reverence thee thir great Progenitor. END
BEGIN NOW But this praeeminence thou hast lost, brought down END
BEGIN NOW To dwell on eeven ground now with thy Sons: END
BEGIN NOW Yet doubt not but in Vallie and in Plaine END
BEGIN NOW God is as here, and will be found alike END
BEGIN NOW Present, and of his presence many a signe END
BEGIN NOW Still following thee, still compassing thee round END
BEGIN NOW With goodness and paternal Love, his Face END
BEGIN NOW Express, and of his steps the track Divine. END
BEGIN NOW Which that thou mayst beleeve, and be confirmd, END
BEGIN NOW Ere thou from hence depart, know I am sent END
BEGIN NOW To shew thee what shall come in future dayes END
BEGIN NOW To thee and to thy Ofspring; good with bad END
BEGIN NOW Expect to hear, supernal Grace contending END
BEGIN NOW With sinfulness of Men; thereby to learn END
BEGIN NOW True patience, and to temper joy with fear END
BEGIN NOW And pious sorrow, equally enur'd END
BEGIN NOW By moderation either state to beare, END
BEGIN NOW Prosperous or adverse: so shalt thou lead END
BEGIN NOW Safest thy life, and best prepar'd endure END
BEGIN NOW Thy mortal passage when it comes. Ascend END
BEGIN NOW This Hill; let EVE (for I have drencht her eyes) END
BEGIN NOW Here sleep below while thou to foresight wak'st, END
BEGIN NOW As once thou slepst, while Shee to life was formd. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus ADAM gratefully repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Ascend, I follow thee, safe Guide, the path END
BEGIN NOW Thou lead'st me, and to the hand of Heav'n submit, END
BEGIN NOW However chast'ning, to the evil turne END
BEGIN NOW My obvious breast, arming to overcom END
BEGIN NOW By suffering, and earne rest from labour won, END
BEGIN NOW If so I may attain. So both ascend END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise the highest, from whose top END
BEGIN NOW The Hemisphere of Earth in cleerest Ken END
BEGIN NOW Stretcht out to amplest reach of prospect lay. END
BEGIN NOW Not higher that Hill nor wider looking round, END
BEGIN NOW Whereon for different cause the Tempter set END
BEGIN NOW Our second ADAM in the Wilderness, END
BEGIN NOW To shew him all Earths Kingdomes and thir Glory. END
BEGIN NOW His Eye might there command wherever stood END
BEGIN NOW City of old or modern Fame, the Seat END
BEGIN NOW Of mightiest Empire, from the destind Walls END
BEGIN NOW To PAQUIN of SINAEAN Kings, and thence END
BEGIN NOW To AGRA and LAHOR of great MOGUL END
BEGIN NOW Down to the golden CHERSONESE, or where END
BEGIN NOW The PERSIAN in ECBATAN sate, or since END
BEGIN NOW In MOSCO, or the Sultan in BIZANCE, END
BEGIN NOW TURCHESTAN-born; nor could his eye not ken END
BEGIN NOW Th' Empire of NEGUS to his utmost Port END
BEGIN NOW ERCOCO and the less Maritine Kings END
BEGIN NOW And SOFALA thought OPHIR, to the Realme END
BEGIN NOW Of CONGO, and ANGOLA fardest South; END
BEGIN NOW Or thence from NIGER Flood to ATLAS Mount END
BEGIN NOW The Kingdoms of ALMANSOR, FEZ, and SUS, END
BEGIN NOW On EUROPE thence, and where ROME was to sway END
BEGIN NOW The VVorld: in Spirit perhaps he also saw END
BEGIN NOW Rich MEXICO the seat of MOTEZUME, END
BEGIN NOW And CUSCO in PERU, the richer seat END
BEGIN NOW Of ATABALIPA, and yet unspoil'd END
BEGIN NOW GUIANA, whose great Citie GERYONS Sons END
BEGIN NOW Call EL DORADO: but to nobler sights END
BEGIN NOW MICHAEL from ADAMS eyes the Filme remov'd END
BEGIN NOW VVhich that false Fruit that promis'd clearer sight END
BEGIN NOW Had bred; then purg'd with Euphrasie and Rue END
BEGIN NOW The visual Nerve, for he had much to see; END
BEGIN NOW And from the VVell of Life three drops instill'd. END
BEGIN NOW So deep the power of these Ingredients pierc'd, END
BEGIN NOW Eevn to the inmost seat of mental sight, END
BEGIN NOW That ADAM now enforc't to close his eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Sunk down and all his Spirits became intranst: END
BEGIN NOW But him the gentle Angel by the hand END
BEGIN NOW Soon rais'd, and his attention thus recall'd. END
BEGIN NOW ADAM, now ope thine eyes, and first behold END
BEGIN NOW Th' effects which thy original crime hath wrought END
BEGIN NOW In some to spring from thee, who never touch'd END
BEGIN NOW Th' excepted Tree, nor with the Snake conspir'd, END
BEGIN NOW Nor sinn'd thy sin, yet from that sin derive END
BEGIN NOW Corruption to bring forth more violent deeds. END
BEGIN NOW His eyes he op'nd, and beheld a field, END
BEGIN NOW Part arable and tilth, whereon were Sheaves END
BEGIN NOW New reapt, the other part sheep-walks and foulds; END
BEGIN NOW Ith' midst an Altar as the Land-mark stood END
BEGIN NOW Rustic, of grassie sord; thither anon END
BEGIN NOW A sweatie Reaper from his Tillage brought END
BEGIN NOW First Fruits, the green Eare, and the yellow Sheaf, END
BEGIN NOW Uncull'd, as came to hand; a Shepherd next END
BEGIN NOW More meek came with the Firstlings of his Flock END
BEGIN NOW Choicest and best; then sacrificing, laid END
BEGIN NOW The Inwards and thir Fat, with Incense strew'd, END
BEGIN NOW On the cleft Wood, and all due Rites perform'd. END
BEGIN NOW His Offring soon propitious Fire from Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Consum'd with nimble glance, and grateful steame; END
BEGIN NOW The others not, for his was not sincere; END
BEGIN NOW Whereat hee inlie rag'd, and as they talk'd, END
BEGIN NOW Smote him into the Midriff with a stone END
BEGIN NOW That beat out life; he fell, and deadly pale END
BEGIN NOW Groand out his Soul with gushing bloud effus'd. END
BEGIN NOW Much at that sight was ADAM in his heart END
BEGIN NOW Dismai'd, and thus in haste to th' Angel cri'd. END
BEGIN NOW O Teacher, some great mischief hath befall'n END
BEGIN NOW To that meek man, who well had sacrific'd; END
BEGIN NOW Is Pietie thus and pure Devotion paid? END
BEGIN NOW T' whom MICHAEL thus, hee also mov'd, repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW These two are Brethren, ADAM, and to come END
BEGIN NOW Out of thy loyns; th' unjust the just hath slain, END
BEGIN NOW For envie that his Brothers Offering found END
BEGIN NOW From Heav'n acceptance; but the bloodie Fact END
BEGIN NOW Will be aveng'd, and th' others Faith approv'd END
BEGIN NOW Loose no reward, though here thou see him die, END
BEGIN NOW Rowling in dust and gore. To which our Sire. END
BEGIN NOW Alas, both for the deed and for the cause! END
BEGIN NOW But have I now seen Death? Is this the way END
BEGIN NOW I must return to native dust? O sight END
BEGIN NOW Of terrour, foul and ugly to behold, END
BEGIN NOW Horrid to think, how horrible to feel! END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus MICHAEL. Death thou hast seen END
BEGIN NOW In his first shape on man; but many shapes END
BEGIN NOW Of Death, and many are the wayes that lead END
BEGIN NOW To his grim Cave, all dismal; yet to sense END
BEGIN NOW More terrible at th' entrance then within. END
BEGIN NOW Some, as thou saw'st, by violent stroke shall die, END
BEGIN NOW By Fire, Flood, Famin, by Intemperance more END
BEGIN NOW In Meats and Drinks, which on the Earth shal bring END
BEGIN NOW Diseases dire, of which a monstrous crew END
BEGIN NOW Before thee shall appear; that thou mayst know END
BEGIN NOW What miserie th' inabstinence of EVE END
BEGIN NOW Shall bring on men. Immediately a place END
BEGIN NOW Before his eyes appeard, sad, noysom, dark, END
BEGIN NOW A Lazar-house it seemd, wherein were laid END
BEGIN NOW Numbers of all diseas'd, all maladies END
BEGIN NOW Of gastly Spasm, or racking torture, qualmes END
BEGIN NOW Of heart-sick Agonie, all feavorous kinds, END
BEGIN NOW Convulsions, Epilepsies, fierce Catarrhs, END
BEGIN NOW Intestin Stone and Ulcer, Colic pangs, END
BEGIN NOW Dropsies, and Asthma's, and Joint-racking Rheums. END
BEGIN NOW Dire was the tossing, deep the groans, despair END
BEGIN NOW Tended the sick busiest from Couch to Couch; END
BEGIN NOW And over them triumphant Death his Dart END
BEGIN NOW Shook, but delaid to strike, though oft invok't END
BEGIN NOW With vows, as thir chief good, and final hope. END
BEGIN NOW Sight so deform what heart of Rock could long END
BEGIN NOW Drie-ey'd behold? ADAM could not, but wept, END
BEGIN NOW Though not of Woman born; compassion quell'd END
BEGIN NOW His best of Man, and gave him up to tears END
BEGIN NOW A space, till firmer thoughts restraind excess, END
BEGIN NOW And scarce recovering words his plaint renew'd. END
BEGIN NOW O miserable Mankind, to what fall END
BEGIN NOW Degraded, to what wretched state reserv'd? END
BEGIN NOW Better end heer unborn. Why is life giv'n END
BEGIN NOW To be thus wrested from us? rather why END
BEGIN NOW Obtruded on us thus? who if we knew END
BEGIN NOW What we receive, would either not accept END
BEGIN NOW Life offer'd, or soon beg to lay it down, END
BEGIN NOW Glad to be so dismist in peace. Can thus END
BEGIN NOW Th' Image of God in man created once END
BEGIN NOW So goodly and erect, though faultie since, END
BEGIN NOW To such unsightly sufferings be debas't END
BEGIN NOW Under inhuman pains? Why should not Man, END
BEGIN NOW Retaining still Divine similitude END
BEGIN NOW In part, from such deformities be free, END
BEGIN NOW And for his Makers Image sake exempt? END
BEGIN NOW Thir Makers Image, answerd MICHAEL, then END
BEGIN NOW Forsook them, when themselves they villifi'd END
BEGIN NOW To serve ungovern'd appetite, and took END
BEGIN NOW His Image whom they serv'd, a brutish vice, END
BEGIN NOW Inductive mainly to the sin of EVE. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore so abject is thir punishment, END
BEGIN NOW Disfiguring not Gods likeness, but thir own, END
BEGIN NOW Or if his likeness, by themselves defac't END
BEGIN NOW While they pervert pure Natures healthful rules END
BEGIN NOW To loathsom sickness, worthily, since they END
BEGIN NOW Gods Image did not reverence in themselves. END
BEGIN NOW I yeild it just, said ADAM, and submit. END
BEGIN NOW But is there yet no other way, besides END
BEGIN NOW These painful passages, how we may come END
BEGIN NOW To Death, and mix with our connatural dust? END
BEGIN NOW There is, said MICHAEL, if thou well observe END
BEGIN NOW The rule of not too much, by temperance taught END
BEGIN NOW In what thou eatst and drinkst, seeking from thence END
BEGIN NOW Due nourishment, not gluttonous delight, END
BEGIN NOW Till many years over thy head return: END
BEGIN NOW So maist thou live, till like ripe Fruit thou drop END
BEGIN NOW Into thy Mothers lap, or be with ease END
BEGIN NOW Gatherd, not harshly pluckt, for death mature: END
BEGIN NOW This is old age; but then thou must outlive END
BEGIN NOW Thy youth, thy strength, thy beauty, which will change END
BEGIN NOW To witherd weak & gray; thy Senses then END
BEGIN NOW Obtuse, all taste of pleasure must forgoe, END
BEGIN NOW To what thou hast, and for the Aire of youth END
BEGIN NOW Hopeful and cheerful, in thy blood will reigne END
BEGIN NOW A melancholly damp of cold and dry END
BEGIN NOW To waigh thy spirits down, and last consume END
BEGIN NOW The Balme of Life. To whom our Ancestor. END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth I flie not Death, nor would prolong END
BEGIN NOW Life much, bent rather how I may be quit END
BEGIN NOW Fairest and easiest of this combrous charge, END
BEGIN NOW Which I must keep till my appointed day END
BEGIN NOW Of rendring up. MICHAEL to him repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW Nor love thy Life, nor hate; but what thou livst END
BEGIN NOW Live well, how long or short permit to Heav'n: END
BEGIN NOW And now prepare thee for another sight. END
BEGIN NOW He lookd and saw a spacious Plaine, whereon END
BEGIN NOW Were Tents of various hue; by some were herds END
BEGIN NOW Of Cattel grazing: others, whence the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of Instruments that made melodious chime END
BEGIN NOW Was heard, of Harp and Organ; and who moovd END
BEGIN NOW Thir stops and chords was seen: his volant touch END
BEGIN NOW Instinct through all proportions low and high END
BEGIN NOW Fled and pursu'd transverse the resonant fugue. END
BEGIN NOW In other part stood one who at the Forge END
BEGIN NOW Labouring, two massie clods of Iron and Brass END
BEGIN NOW Had melted (whether found where casual fire END
BEGIN NOW Had wasted woods on Mountain or in Vale, END
BEGIN NOW Down to the veins of Earth, thence gliding hot END
BEGIN NOW To som Caves mouth, or whether washt by stream END
BEGIN NOW From underground) the liquid Ore he dreind END
BEGIN NOW Into fit moulds prepar'd; from which he formd END
BEGIN NOW First his own Tooles; then, what might else be wrought END
BEGIN NOW Fulfil or grav'n in mettle. After these, END
BEGIN NOW But on the hether side a different sort END
BEGIN NOW From the high neighbouring Hills, which was thir Seat, END
BEGIN NOW Down to the Plain descended: by thir guise END
BEGIN NOW Just men they seemd, and all thir study bent END
BEGIN NOW To worship God aright, and know his works END
BEGIN NOW Not hid, nor those things lost which might preserve END
BEGIN NOW Freedom and Peace to men: they on the Plain END
BEGIN NOW Long had not walkt, when from the Tents behold END
BEGIN NOW A Beavie of fair Women, richly gay END
BEGIN NOW In Gems and wanton dress; to the Harp they sung END
BEGIN NOW Soft amorous Ditties, and in dance came on: END
BEGIN NOW The Men though grave, ey'd them, and let thir eyes END
BEGIN NOW Rove without rein, till in the amorous Net END
BEGIN NOW Fast caught, they lik'd, and each his liking chose; END
BEGIN NOW And now of love they treat till th' Eevning Star END
BEGIN NOW Loves Harbinger appeerd; then all in heat END
BEGIN NOW They light the Nuptial Torch, and bid invoke END
BEGIN NOW Hymen, then first to marriage Rites invok't; END
BEGIN NOW With Feast and Musick all the Tents resound. END
BEGIN NOW Such happy interview and fair event END
BEGIN NOW Of love & youth not lost, Songs, Garlands, Flours, END
BEGIN NOW And charming Symphonies attach'd the heart END
BEGIN NOW Of ADAM, soon enclin'd to admit delight, END
BEGIN NOW The bent of Nature; which he thus express'd. END
BEGIN NOW True opener of mine eyes, prime Angel blest, END
BEGIN NOW Much better seems this Vision, and more hope END
BEGIN NOW Of peaceful dayes portends, then those two past; END
BEGIN NOW Those were of hate and death, or pain much worse, END
BEGIN NOW Here Nature seems fulfilld in all her ends. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus MICHAEL. Judg not what is best END
BEGIN NOW By pleasure, though to Nature seeming meet, END
BEGIN NOW Created, as thou art, to nobler end END
BEGIN NOW Holie and pure, conformitie divine. END
BEGIN NOW Those Tents thou sawst so pleasant, were the Tents END
BEGIN NOW Of wickedness, wherein shall dwell his Race END
BEGIN NOW Who slew his Brother; studious they appere END
BEGIN NOW Of Arts that polish Life, Inventers rare, END
BEGIN NOW Unmindful of thir Maker, though his Spirit END
BEGIN NOW Taught them, but they his gifts acknowledg'd none. END
BEGIN NOW Yet they a beauteous ofspring shall beget; END
BEGIN NOW For that fair femal Troop thou sawst, that seemd END
BEGIN NOW Of Goddesses, so blithe, so smooth, so gay, END
BEGIN NOW Yet empty of all good wherein consists END
BEGIN NOW Womans domestic honour and chief praise; END
BEGIN NOW Bred onely and completed to the taste END
BEGIN NOW Of lustful apperence, to sing, to dance, END
BEGIN NOW To dress, and troule the Tongue, and roule the Eye. END
BEGIN NOW To these that sober Race of Men, whose lives END
BEGIN NOW Religious titl'd them the Sons of God, END
BEGIN NOW Shall yeild up all thir vertue, all thir fame END
BEGIN NOW Ignobly, to the trains and to the smiles END
BEGIN NOW Of these fair Atheists, and now swim in joy, END
BEGIN NOW (Erelong to swim at larg) and laugh; for which END
BEGIN NOW The world erelong a world of tears must weepe. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus ADAM of short joy bereft. END
BEGIN NOW O pittie and shame, that they who to live well END
BEGIN NOW Enterd so faire, should turn aside to tread END
BEGIN NOW Paths indirect, or in the mid way faint! END
BEGIN NOW But still I see the tenor of Mans woe END
BEGIN NOW Holds on the same, from Woman to begin. END
BEGIN NOW From Mans effeminate slackness it begins, END
BEGIN NOW Said th' Angel, who should better hold his place END
BEGIN NOW By wisdome, and superiour gifts receavd. END
BEGIN NOW But now prepare thee for another Scene. END
BEGIN NOW He lookd and saw wide Territorie spred END
BEGIN NOW Before him, Towns, and rural works between, END
BEGIN NOW Cities of Men with lofty Gates and Towrs, END
BEGIN NOW Concours in Arms, fierce Faces threatning Warr, END
BEGIN NOW Giants of mightie Bone, and bould emprise; END
BEGIN NOW Part wield thir Arms, part courb the foaming Steed, END
BEGIN NOW Single or in Array of Battel rang'd END
BEGIN NOW Both Horse and Foot, nor idely mustring stood; END
BEGIN NOW One way a Band select from forage drives END
BEGIN NOW A herd of Beeves, faire Oxen and faire Kine END
BEGIN NOW From a fat Meddow ground; or fleecy Flock, END
BEGIN NOW Ewes and thir bleating Lambs over the Plaine, END
BEGIN NOW Thir Bootie; scarce with Life the Shepherds flye, END
BEGIN NOW But call in aide, which tacks a bloody Fray; END
BEGIN NOW With cruel Tournament the Squadrons joine; END
BEGIN NOW Where Cattel pastur'd late, now scatterd lies END
BEGIN NOW With Carcasses and Arms th' ensanguind Field END
BEGIN NOW Deserted: Others to a Citie strong END
BEGIN NOW Lay Siege, encampt; by Batterie, Scale, and Mine, END
BEGIN NOW Assaulting; others from the Wall defend END
BEGIN NOW With Dart and Jav'lin, Stones and sulfurous Fire; END
BEGIN NOW On each hand slaughter and gigantic deeds. END
BEGIN NOW In other part the scepter'd Haralds call END
BEGIN NOW To Council in the Citie Gates: anon END
BEGIN NOW Grey-headed men and grave, with Warriours mixt, END
BEGIN NOW Assemble, and Harangues are heard, but soon END
BEGIN NOW In factious opposition, till at last END
BEGIN NOW Of middle Age one rising, eminent END
BEGIN NOW In wise deport, spake much of Right and Wrong, END
BEGIN NOW And Judgement from above: him old and young END
BEGIN NOW Exploded, and had seiz'd with violent hands, END
BEGIN NOW Had not a Cloud descending snatch'd him thence END
BEGIN NOW Unseen amid the throng: so violence END
BEGIN NOW Through all the Plain, and refuge none was found. END
BEGIN NOW ADAM was all in tears, and to his guide END
BEGIN NOW Lamenting turnd full sad; O what are these, END
BEGIN NOW Deaths Ministers, not Men, who thus deal Death END
BEGIN NOW Inhumanly to men, and multiply END
BEGIN NOW Ten thousand fould the sin of him who slew END
BEGIN NOW His Brother; for of whom such massacher END
BEGIN NOW Make they but of thir Brethren, men of men? END
BEGIN NOW But who was that Just Man, whom had not Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Rescu'd, had in his Righteousness bin lost? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus MICHAEL; These are the product END
BEGIN NOW Of those ill-mated Marriages thou saw'st; END
BEGIN NOW Where good with bad were matcht, who of themselves END
BEGIN NOW Abhor to joyn; and by imprudence mixt, END
BEGIN NOW Produce prodigious Births of bodie or mind. END
BEGIN NOW Such were these Giants, men of high renown; END
BEGIN NOW For in those dayes Might onely shall be admir'd, END
BEGIN NOW And Valour and Heroic Vertu call'd; END
BEGIN NOW To overcome in Battel, and subdue END
BEGIN NOW Nations, and bring home spoils with infinite END
BEGIN NOW Man-slaughter, shall be held the highest pitch END
BEGIN NOW Of human Glorie, and for Glorie done END
BEGIN NOW Of triumph, to be styl'd great Conquerours, END
BEGIN NOW Destroyers rightlier call'd and Plagues of men. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Fame shall be achiev'd, renown on Earth, END
BEGIN NOW And what most merits fame in silence hid. END
BEGIN NOW But hee the seventh from thee, whom thou beheldst END
BEGIN NOW The onely righteous in a World perverse, END
BEGIN NOW And therefore hated, therefore so beset END
BEGIN NOW With Foes for daring single to be just, END
BEGIN NOW And utter odious Truth, that God would come END
BEGIN NOW To judge them with his Saints: Him the most High END
BEGIN NOW Rapt in a balmie Cloud with winged Steeds END
BEGIN NOW Did, as thou sawst, receave, to walk with God END
BEGIN NOW High in Salvation and the Climes of bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Exempt from Death; to shew thee what reward END
BEGIN NOW Awaits the good, the rest what punishment; END
BEGIN NOW Which now direct thine eyes and soon behold. END
BEGIN NOW He look'd, & saw the face of things quite chang'd; END
BEGIN NOW The brazen Throat of Warr had ceast to roar, END
BEGIN NOW All now was turn'd to jollitie and game, END
BEGIN NOW To luxurie and riot, feast and dance, END
BEGIN NOW Marrying or prostituting, as befell, END
BEGIN NOW Rape or Adulterie, where passing faire END
BEGIN NOW Allurd them; thence from Cups to civil Broiles. END
BEGIN NOW At length a Reverend Sire among them came, END
BEGIN NOW And of thir doings great dislike declar'd, END
BEGIN NOW And testifi'd against thir wayes; hee oft END
BEGIN NOW Frequented thir Assemblies, whereso met, END
BEGIN NOW Triumphs or Festivals, and to them preachd END
BEGIN NOW In prison under Judgements imminent: END
BEGIN NOW But all in vain: which when he saw, he ceas'd END
BEGIN NOW Contending, and remov'd his Tents farr off; END
BEGIN NOW Then from the Mountain hewing Timber tall, END
BEGIN NOW Began to build a Vessel of huge bulk, END
BEGIN NOW Measur'd by Cubit, length, & breadth, and highth, END
BEGIN NOW Smeard round with Pitch, and in the side a dore END
BEGIN NOW Contriv'd, and of provisions laid in large END
BEGIN NOW For Man and Beast: when loe a wonder strange! END
BEGIN NOW Of everie Beast, and Bird, and Insect small END
BEGIN NOW Came seavens, and pairs, and enterd in, as taught END
BEGIN NOW Thir order; last the Sire, and his three Sons END
BEGIN NOW With thir four Wives, and God made fast the dore. END
BEGIN NOW Meanwhile the Southwind rose, & with black wings END
BEGIN NOW Wide hovering, all the Clouds together drove END
BEGIN NOW From under Heav'n; the Hills to their supplie END
BEGIN NOW Vapour, and Exhalation dusk and moist, END
BEGIN NOW Sent up amain; and now the thick'nd Skie END
BEGIN NOW Like a dark Ceeling stood; down rush'd the Rain END
BEGIN NOW Impetuous, and continu'd till the Earth END
BEGIN NOW No more was seen; the floating Vessel swum END
BEGIN NOW Uplifted; and secure with beaked prow END
BEGIN NOW Rode tilting o're the Waves, all dwellings else END
BEGIN NOW Flood overwhelmd, and them with all thir pomp END
BEGIN NOW Deep under water rould; Sea cover'd Sea, END
BEGIN NOW Sea without shoar; and in thir Palaces END
BEGIN NOW Where luxurie late reign'd, Sea-monsters whelp'd END
BEGIN NOW And stabl'd; of Mankind, so numerous late, END
BEGIN NOW All left, in one small bottom swum imbark't. END
BEGIN NOW How didst thou grieve then, ADAM, to behold END
BEGIN NOW The end of all thy Ofspring, end so sad, END
BEGIN NOW Depopulation; thee another Floud, END
BEGIN NOW Of tears and sorrow a Floud thee also drown'd, END
BEGIN NOW And sunk thee as thy Sons; till gently reard END
BEGIN NOW By th' Angel, on thy feet thou stoodst at last, END
BEGIN NOW Though comfortless, as when a Father mourns END
BEGIN NOW His Childern, all in view destroyd at once; END
BEGIN NOW And scarce to th' Angel utterdst thus thy plaint. END
BEGIN NOW O Visions ill foreseen! better had I END
BEGIN NOW Liv'd ignorant of future, so had borne END
BEGIN NOW My part of evil onely, each dayes lot END
BEGIN NOW Anough to bear; those now, that were dispenst END
BEGIN NOW The burd'n of many Ages, on me light END
BEGIN NOW At once, by my foreknowledge gaining Birth END
BEGIN NOW Abortive, to torment me ere thir being, END
BEGIN NOW With thought that they must be. Let no man seek END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth to be foretold what shall befall END
BEGIN NOW Him or his Childern, evil he may be sure, END
BEGIN NOW Which neither his foreknowing can prevent, END
BEGIN NOW And hee the future evil shall no less END
BEGIN NOW In apprehension then in substance feel END
BEGIN NOW Grievous to bear: but that care now is past, END
BEGIN NOW Man is not whom to warne: those few escap't END
BEGIN NOW Famin and anguish will at last consume END
BEGIN NOW Wandring that watrie Desert: I had hope END
BEGIN NOW When violence was ceas't, and Warr on Earth, END
BEGIN NOW All would have then gon well, peace would have crownd END
BEGIN NOW With length of happy days the race of man; END
BEGIN NOW But I was farr deceav'd; for now I see END
BEGIN NOW Peace to corrupt no less then Warr to waste. END
BEGIN NOW How comes it thus? unfould, Celestial Guide, END
BEGIN NOW And whether here the Race of man will end. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus MICHAEL. Those whom last thou sawst END
BEGIN NOW In triumph and luxurious wealth, are they END
BEGIN NOW First seen in acts of prowess eminent END
BEGIN NOW And great exploits, but of true vertu void; END
BEGIN NOW Who having spilt much blood, and don much waste END
BEGIN NOW Subduing Nations, and achievd thereby END
BEGIN NOW Fame in the World, high titles, and rich prey, END
BEGIN NOW Shall change thir course to pleasure, ease, and sloth, END
BEGIN NOW Surfet, and lust, till wantonness and pride END
BEGIN NOW Raise out of friendship hostil deeds in Peace. END
BEGIN NOW The conquerd also, and enslav'd by Warr END
BEGIN NOW Shall with thir freedom lost all vertu loose END
BEGIN NOW And feare of God, from whom thir pietie feign'd END
BEGIN NOW In sharp contest of Battel found no aide END
BEGIN NOW Against invaders; therefore coold in zeale END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth shall practice how to live secure, END
BEGIN NOW Worldlie or dissolute, on what thir Lords END
BEGIN NOW Shall leave them to enjoy; for th' Earth shall bear END
BEGIN NOW More then anough, that temperance may be tri'd: END
BEGIN NOW So all shall turn degenerate, all deprav'd, END
BEGIN NOW Justice and Temperance, Truth and Faith forgot; END
BEGIN NOW One Man except, the onely Son of light END
BEGIN NOW In a dark Age, against example good, END
BEGIN NOW Against allurement, custom, and a World END
BEGIN NOW Offended; fearless of reproach and scorn, END
BEGIN NOW Or violence, hee of thir wicked wayes END
BEGIN NOW Shall them admonish, and before them set END
BEGIN NOW The paths of righteousness, how much more safe, END
BEGIN NOW And full of peace, denouncing wrauth to come END
BEGIN NOW On thir impenitence; and shall returne END
BEGIN NOW Of them derided, but of God observd END
BEGIN NOW The one just Man alive; by his command END
BEGIN NOW Shall build a wondrous Ark, as thou beheldst, END
BEGIN NOW To save himself and houshold from amidst END
BEGIN NOW A World devote to universal rack. END
BEGIN NOW No sooner hee with them of Man and Beast END
BEGIN NOW Select for life shall in the Ark be lodg'd, END
BEGIN NOW And shelterd round, but all the Cataracts END
BEGIN NOW Of Heav'n set open on the Earth shall powre END
BEGIN NOW Raine day and night, all fountaines of the Deep END
BEGIN NOW Broke up, shall heave the Ocean to usurp END
BEGIN NOW Beyond all bounds, till inundation rise END
BEGIN NOW Above the highest Hills: then shall this Mount END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise by might of Waves be moovd END
BEGIN NOW Out of his place, pushd by the horned floud, END
BEGIN NOW With all his verdure spoil'd, and Trees adrift END
BEGIN NOW Down the great River to the op'ning Gulf, END
BEGIN NOW And there take root an Iland salt and bare, END
BEGIN NOW The haunt of Seales and Orcs, and Sea-mews clang. END
BEGIN NOW To teach thee that God attributes to place END
BEGIN NOW No sanctitie, if none be thither brought END
BEGIN NOW By Men who there frequent, or therein dwell. END
BEGIN NOW And now what further shall ensue, behold. END
BEGIN NOW He lookd, and saw the Ark hull on the floud, END
BEGIN NOW Which now abated, for the Clouds were fled, END
BEGIN NOW Drivn by a keen North-winde, that blowing drie END
BEGIN NOW Wrinkl'd the face of Deluge, as decai'd; END
BEGIN NOW And the cleer Sun on his wide watrie Glass END
BEGIN NOW Gaz'd hot, and of the fresh Wave largely drew, END
BEGIN NOW As after thirst, which made thir flowing shrink END
BEGIN NOW From standing lake to tripping ebbe, that stole END
BEGIN NOW With soft foot towards the deep, who now had stopt END
BEGIN NOW His Sluces, as the Heav'n his windows shut. END
BEGIN NOW The Ark no more now flotes, but seems on ground END
BEGIN NOW Fast on the top of som high mountain fixt. END
BEGIN NOW And now the tops of Hills as Rocks appeer; END
BEGIN NOW With clamor thence the rapid Currents drive END
BEGIN NOW Towards the retreating Sea thir furious tyde. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith from out the Arke a Raven flies, END
BEGIN NOW And after him, the surer messenger, END
BEGIN NOW A Dove sent forth once and agen to spie END
BEGIN NOW Green Tree or ground whereon his foot may light; END
BEGIN NOW The second time returning, in his Bill END
BEGIN NOW An Olive leafe he brings, pacific signe: END
BEGIN NOW Anon drie ground appeers, and from his Arke END
BEGIN NOW The ancient Sire descends with all his Train; END
BEGIN NOW Then with uplifted hands, and eyes devout, END
BEGIN NOW Grateful to Heav'n, over his head beholds END
BEGIN NOW A dewie Cloud, and in the Cloud a Bow END
BEGIN NOW Conspicuous with three lifted colours gay, END
BEGIN NOW Betok'ning peace from God, and Cov'nant new. END
BEGIN NOW Whereat the heart of ADAM erst so sad END
BEGIN NOW Greatly rejoyc'd, and thus his joy broke forth. END
BEGIN NOW O thou that future things canst represent END
BEGIN NOW As present, Heav'nly instructer, I revive END
BEGIN NOW At this last sight, assur'd that Man shall live END
BEGIN NOW With all the Creatures, and thir seed preserve. END
BEGIN NOW Farr less I now lament for one whole World END
BEGIN NOW Of wicked Sons destroyd, then I rejoyce END
BEGIN NOW For one Man found so perfet and so just, END
BEGIN NOW That God voutsafes to raise another World END
BEGIN NOW From him, and all his anger to forget. END
BEGIN NOW But say, what mean those colourd streaks in Heavn, END
BEGIN NOW Distended as the Brow of God appeas'd, END
BEGIN NOW Or serve they as a flourie verge to binde END
BEGIN NOW The fluid skirts of that same watrie Cloud, END
BEGIN NOW Least it again dissolve and showr the Earth? END
BEGIN NOW To whom th' Archangel. Dextrously thou aim'st; END
BEGIN NOW So willingly doth God remit his Ire, END
BEGIN NOW Though late repenting him of Man deprav'd, END
BEGIN NOW Griev'd at his heart, when looking down he saw END
BEGIN NOW The whole Earth fill'd with violence, and all flesh END
BEGIN NOW Corrupting each thir way; yet those remoov'd, END
BEGIN NOW Such grace shall one just Man find in his sight, END
BEGIN NOW That he relents, not to blot out mankind, END
BEGIN NOW And makes a Covenant never to destroy END
BEGIN NOW The Earth again by flood, nor let the Sea END
BEGIN NOW Surpass his bounds, nor Rain to drown the World END
BEGIN NOW With Man therein or Beast; but when he brings END
BEGIN NOW Over the Earth a Cloud, will therein set END
BEGIN NOW His triple-colour'd Bow, whereon to look END
BEGIN NOW And call to mind his Cov'nant: Day and Night, END
BEGIN NOW Seed time and Harvest, Heat and hoary Frost END
BEGIN NOW Shall hold thir course, till fire purge all things new, END
BEGIN NOW Both Heav'n and Earth, wherein the just shall dwell. END
BEGIN NOW Thus thou hast seen one World begin and end; END
BEGIN NOW And Man as from a second stock proceed. END
BEGIN NOW Much thou hast yet to see, but I perceave END
BEGIN NOW Thy mortal sight to faile; objects divine END
BEGIN NOW Must needs impaire and wearie human sense: END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth what is to com I will relate, END
BEGIN NOW Thou therefore give due audience, and attend. END
BEGIN NOW This second sours of Men, while yet but few, END
BEGIN NOW And while the dread of judgement past remains END
BEGIN NOW Fresh in thir mindes, fearing the Deitie, END
BEGIN NOW With some regard to what is just and right END
BEGIN NOW Shall lead thir lives, and multiplie apace, END
BEGIN NOW Labouring the soile, and reaping plenteous crop, END
BEGIN NOW Corn wine and oyle; and from the herd or flock, END
BEGIN NOW Oft sacrificing Bullock, Lamb, or Kid, END
BEGIN NOW With large Wine-offerings pour'd, and sacred Feast END
BEGIN NOW Shal spend thir dayes in joy unblam'd, and dwell END
BEGIN NOW Long time in peace by Families and Tribes END
BEGIN NOW Under paternal rule; till one shall rise END
BEGIN NOW Of proud ambitious heart, who not content END
BEGIN NOW With fair equalitie, fraternal state, END
BEGIN NOW Will arrogate Dominion undeserv'd END
BEGIN NOW Over his brethren, and quite dispossess END
BEGIN NOW Concord and law of Nature from the Earth; END
BEGIN NOW Hunting (and Men not Beasts shall be his game) END
BEGIN NOW With Warr and hostile snare such as refuse END
BEGIN NOW Subjection to his Empire tyrannous: END
BEGIN NOW A mightie Hunter thence he shall be styl'd END
BEGIN NOW Before the Lord, as in despite of Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW Or from Heav'n claming second Sovrantie; END
BEGIN NOW And from Rebellion shall derive his name, END
BEGIN NOW Though of Rebellion others he accuse. END
BEGIN NOW Hee with a crew, whom like Ambition joyns END
BEGIN NOW With him or under him to tyrannize, END
BEGIN NOW Marching from EDEN towards the West, shall finde END
BEGIN NOW The Plain, wherein a black bituminous gurge END
BEGIN NOW Boiles out from under ground, the mouth of Hell; END
BEGIN NOW Of Brick, and of that stuff they cast to build END
BEGIN NOW A Citie & Towre, whose top may reach to Heav'n; END
BEGIN NOW And get themselves a name, least far disperst END
BEGIN NOW In foraign Lands thir memorie be lost, END
BEGIN NOW Regardless whether good or evil fame. END
BEGIN NOW But God who oft descends to visit men END
BEGIN NOW Unseen, and through thir habitations walks END
BEGIN NOW To mark thir doings, them beholding soon, END
BEGIN NOW Comes down to see thir Citie, ere the Tower END
BEGIN NOW Obstruct Heav'n Towrs, and in derision sets END
BEGIN NOW Upon thir Tongues a various Spirit to rase END
BEGIN NOW Quite out thir Native Language, and instead END
BEGIN NOW To sow a jangling noise of words unknown: END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith a hideous gabble rises loud END
BEGIN NOW Among the Builders; each to other calls END
BEGIN NOW Not understood, till hoarse, and all in rage, END
BEGIN NOW As mockt they storm; great laughter was in Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW And looking down, to see the hubbub strange END
BEGIN NOW And hear the din; thus was the building left END
BEGIN NOW Ridiculous, and the work Confusion nam'd. END
BEGIN NOW Whereto thus ADAM fatherly displeas'd. END
BEGIN NOW O execrable Son so to aspire END
BEGIN NOW Above his Brethren, to himself affirming END
BEGIN NOW Authoritie usurpt, from God not giv'n: END
BEGIN NOW He gave us onely over Beast, Fish, Fowl END
BEGIN NOW Dominion absolute; that right we hold END
BEGIN NOW By his donation; but Man over men END
BEGIN NOW He made not Lord; such title to himself END
BEGIN NOW Reserving, human left from human free. END
BEGIN NOW But this Usurper his encroachment proud END
BEGIN NOW Stayes not on Man; to God his Tower intends END
BEGIN NOW Siege and defiance: Wretched man! what food END
BEGIN NOW Will he convey up thither to sustain END
BEGIN NOW Himself and his rash Armie, where thin Aire END
BEGIN NOW Above the Clouds will pine his entrails gross, END
BEGIN NOW And famish him of Breath, if not of Bread? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus MICHAEL. Justly thou abhorr'st END
BEGIN NOW That Son, who on the quiet state of men END
BEGIN NOW Such trouble brought, affecting to subdue END
BEGIN NOW Rational Libertie; yet know withall, END
BEGIN NOW Since thy original lapse, true Libertie END
BEGIN NOW Is lost, which alwayes with right Reason dwells END
BEGIN NOW Twinn'd, and from her hath no dividual being: END
BEGIN NOW Reason in man obscur'd, or not obeyd, END
BEGIN NOW Immediately inordinate desires END
BEGIN NOW And upstart Passions catch the Government END
BEGIN NOW From Reason, and to servitude reduce END
BEGIN NOW Man till then free. Therefore since hee permits END
BEGIN NOW Within himself unworthie Powers to reign END
BEGIN NOW Over free Reason, God in Judgement just END
BEGIN NOW Subjects him from without to violent Lords; END
BEGIN NOW Who oft as undeservedly enthrall END
BEGIN NOW His outward freedom: Tyrannie must be, END
BEGIN NOW Though to the Tyrant thereby no excuse. END
BEGIN NOW Yet somtimes Nations will decline so low END
BEGIN NOW From vertue, which is reason, that no wrong, END
BEGIN NOW But Justice, and some fatal curse annext END
BEGIN NOW Deprives them of thir outward libertie, END
BEGIN NOW Thir inward lost: Witness th' irreverent Son END
BEGIN NOW Of him who built the Ark, who for the shame END
BEGIN NOW Don to his Father, heard this heavie curse, END
BEGIN NOW SERVANT OF SERVANTS, on his vitious Race. END
BEGIN NOW Thus will this latter, as the former World, END
BEGIN NOW Still tend from bad to worse, till God at last END
BEGIN NOW Wearied with their iniquities, withdraw END
BEGIN NOW His presence from among them, and avert END
BEGIN NOW His holy Eyes; resolving from thenceforth END
BEGIN NOW To leave them to thir own polluted wayes; END
BEGIN NOW And one peculiar Nation to select END
BEGIN NOW From all the rest, of whom to be invok'd, END
BEGIN NOW A Nation from one faithful man to spring: END
BEGIN NOW Him on this side EUPHRATES yet residing, END
BEGIN NOW Bred up in Idol-worship; O that men END
BEGIN NOW (Canst thou believe?) should be so stupid grown, END
BEGIN NOW While yet the Patriark liv'd, who scap'd the Flood, END
BEGIN NOW As to forsake the living God, and fall END
BEGIN NOW To-worship thir own work in Wood and Stone END
BEGIN NOW For Gods! yet him God the most High voutsafes END
BEGIN NOW To call by Vision from his Fathers house, END
BEGIN NOW His kindred and false Gods, into a Land END
BEGIN NOW Which he will shew him, and from him will raise END
BEGIN NOW A mightie Nation, and upon him showre END
BEGIN NOW His benediction so, that in his Seed END
BEGIN NOW All Nations shall be blest; hee straight obeys, END
BEGIN NOW Not knowing to what Land, yet firm believes: END
BEGIN NOW I see him, but thou canst not, with what Faith END
BEGIN NOW He leaves his Gods, his Friends, and native Soile END
BEGIN NOW UR of CHALDAEA, passing now the Ford END
BEGIN NOW To HARAN, after him a cumbrous Train END
BEGIN NOW Of Herds and Flocks, and numerous servitude; END
BEGIN NOW Not wandring poor, but trusting all his wealth END
BEGIN NOW With God, who call'd him, in a land unknown. END
BEGIN NOW CANAAN he now attains, I see his Tents END
BEGIN NOW Pitcht about SECHEM, and the neighbouring Plaine END
BEGIN NOW Of MOREB; there by promise he receaves END
BEGIN NOW Gift to his Progenie of all that Land; END
BEGIN NOW From HAMATH Northward to the Desert South END
BEGIN NOW (Things by thir names I call, though yet unnam'd) END
BEGIN NOW From HERMON East to the great Western Sea, END
BEGIN NOW Mount HERMON, yonder Sea, each place behold END
BEGIN NOW In prospect, as I point them; on the shoare END
BEGIN NOW Mount CARMEL; here the double-founted stream END
BEGIN NOW JORDAN, true limit Eastward; but his Sons END
BEGIN NOW Shall dwell to SENIR, that long ridge of Hills. END
BEGIN NOW This ponder, that all Nations of the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Shall in his Seed be blessed; by that Seed END
BEGIN NOW Is meant thy great deliverer, who shall bruise END
BEGIN NOW The Serpents head; whereof to thee anon END
BEGIN NOW Plainlier shall be reveald. This Patriarch blest, END
BEGIN NOW Whom FAITHFUL ABRAHAM due time shall call, END
BEGIN NOW A Son, and of his Son a Grand-childe leaves, END
BEGIN NOW Like him in faith, in wisdom, and renown; END
BEGIN NOW The Grandchilde with twelve Sons increast, departs END
BEGIN NOW From CANAAN, to a Land hereafter call'd END
BEGIN NOW See where it flows, disgorging at seaven mouthes END
BEGIN NOW Into the Sea: to sojourn in that Land END
BEGIN NOW He comes invited by a yonger Son END
BEGIN NOW In time of dearth, a Son whose worthy deeds END
BEGIN NOW Raise him to be the second in that Realme END
BEGIN NOW Of PHARAO: there he dies, and leaves his Race END
BEGIN NOW Growing into a Nation, and now grown END
BEGIN NOW Suspected to a sequent King, who seeks END
BEGIN NOW To stop thir overgrowth, as inmate guests END
BEGIN NOW Too numerous; whence of guests he makes them slaves END
BEGIN NOW Inhospitably, and kills thir infant Males: END
BEGIN NOW Till by two brethren (those two brethren call END
BEGIN NOW MOSES and AARON) sent from God to claime END
BEGIN NOW His people from enthralment, they return END
BEGIN NOW With glory and spoile back to thir promis'd Land. END
BEGIN NOW But first the lawless Tyrant, who denies END
BEGIN NOW To know thir God, or message to regard, END
BEGIN NOW Must be compelld by Signes and Judgements dire; END
BEGIN NOW To blood unshed the Rivers must be turnd, END
BEGIN NOW Frogs, Lice and Flies must all his Palace fill END
BEGIN NOW With loath'd intrusion, and fill all the land; END
BEGIN NOW His Cattel must of Rot and Murren die, END
BEGIN NOW Botches and blaines must all his flesh imboss, END
BEGIN NOW And all his people; Thunder mixt with Haile, END
BEGIN NOW And wheel on th' Earth, devouring where it rouls; END
BEGIN NOW What it devours not, Herb, or Fruit, or Graine, END
BEGIN NOW A darksom Cloud of Locusts swarming down END
BEGIN NOW Must eat, and on the ground leave nothing green: END
BEGIN NOW Darkness must overshadow all his bounds, END
BEGIN NOW Palpable darkness, and blot out three dayes; END
BEGIN NOW Last with one midnight stroke all the first-born END
BEGIN NOW This River-dragon tam'd at length submits END
BEGIN NOW To let his sojourners depart, and oft END
BEGIN NOW Humbles his stubborn heart, but still as Ice END
BEGIN NOW More hard'nd after thaw, till in his rage END
BEGIN NOW Pursuing whom he late dismissd, the Sea END
BEGIN NOW Swallows him with his Host, but them lets pass END
BEGIN NOW As on drie land between two christal walls, END
BEGIN NOW Aw'd by the rod of MOSES so to stand END
BEGIN NOW Divided, till his rescu'd gain thir shoar: END
BEGIN NOW Such wondrous power God to his Saint will lend, END
BEGIN NOW Though present in his Angel, who shall goe END
BEGIN NOW Before them in a Cloud, and Pillar of Fire, END
BEGIN NOW To guide them in thir journey, and remove END
BEGIN NOW Behinde them, while th' obdurat King pursues: END
BEGIN NOW All night he will pursue, but his approach END
BEGIN NOW Darkness defends between till morning Watch; END
BEGIN NOW Then through the Firey Pillar and the Cloud END
BEGIN NOW God looking forth will trouble all his Host END
BEGIN NOW And craze thir Chariot wheels: when by command END
BEGIN NOW MOSES once more his potent Rod extends END
BEGIN NOW Over the Sea; the Sea his Rod obeys; END
BEGIN NOW On thir imbattelld ranks the Waves return, END
BEGIN NOW And overwhelm thir Warr: the Race elect END
BEGIN NOW Safe towards CANAAN from the shoar advance END
BEGIN NOW Through the wilde Desert, not the readiest way, END
BEGIN NOW Least entring on the CANAANITE allarmd END
BEGIN NOW Warr terrifie them inexpert, and feare END
BEGIN NOW Inglorious life with servitude; for life END
BEGIN NOW To noble and ignoble is more sweet END
BEGIN NOW Untraind in Armes, where rashness leads not on. END
BEGIN NOW This also shall they gain by thir delay END
BEGIN NOW In the wide Wilderness, there they shall found END
BEGIN NOW Thir government, and thir great Senate choose END
BEGIN NOW Through the twelve Tribes, to rule by Laws ordaind: END
BEGIN NOW God from the Mount of SINAI, whose gray top END
BEGIN NOW Shall tremble, he descending, will himself END
BEGIN NOW In Thunder Lightning and loud Trumpets sound END
BEGIN NOW Ordaine them Lawes; part such as appertaine END
BEGIN NOW To civil Justice, part religious Rites END
BEGIN NOW Of sacrifice, informing them, by types END
BEGIN NOW And shadowes, of that destind Seed to bruise END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent, by what meanes he shall achieve END
BEGIN NOW Mankinds deliverance. But the voice of God END
BEGIN NOW To mortal eare is dreadful; they beseech END
BEGIN NOW That MOSES might report to them his will, END
BEGIN NOW And terror cease; he grants them thir desire, END
BEGIN NOW Instructed that to God is no access END
BEGIN NOW Without Mediator, whose high Office now END
BEGIN NOW MOSES in figure beares, to introduce END
BEGIN NOW One greater, of whose day he shall foretell, END
BEGIN NOW And all the Prophets in thir Age the times END
BEGIN NOW Of great MESSIAH shall sing. Thus Laws and Rites END
BEGIN NOW Establisht, such delight hath God in Men END
BEGIN NOW Obedient to his will, that he voutsafes END
BEGIN NOW Among them to set up his Tabernacle, END
BEGIN NOW The holy One with mortal Men to dwell: END
BEGIN NOW By his prescript a Sanctuary is fram'd END
BEGIN NOW Of Cedar, overlaid with Gold, therein END
BEGIN NOW The Records of his Cov'nant, over these END
BEGIN NOW A Mercie-seat of Gold between the wings END
BEGIN NOW Of two bright Cherubim, before him burn END
BEGIN NOW Seaven Lamps as in a Zodiac representing END
BEGIN NOW The Heav'nly fires; over the Tent a Cloud END
BEGIN NOW Shall rest by Day, a fierie gleame by Night, END
BEGIN NOW Save when they journie, and at length they come, END
BEGIN NOW Promisd to ABRAHAM and his Seed: the rest END
BEGIN NOW Were long to tell, how many Battels fought, END
BEGIN NOW How many Kings destroyd, and Kingdoms won, END
BEGIN NOW Or how the Sun shall in mid Heav'n stand still END
BEGIN NOW A day entire, and Nights due course adjourne, END
BEGIN NOW Mans voice commanding, Sun in GIBEON stand, END
BEGIN NOW And thou Moon in the vale of AIALON, END
BEGIN NOW Till ISRAEL overcome; so call the third END
BEGIN NOW From ABRAHAM, Son of ISAAC, and from him END
BEGIN NOW His whole descent, who thus shall CANAAN win. END
BEGIN NOW Here ADAM interpos'd. O sent from Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW Enlightner of my darkness, gracious things END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast reveald, those chiefly which concerne END
BEGIN NOW Just ABRAHAM and his Seed: now first I finde END
BEGIN NOW Mine eyes true op'ning, and my heart much eas'd, END
BEGIN NOW Erwhile perplext with thoughts what would becom END
BEGIN NOW His day, in whom all Nations shall be blest, END
BEGIN NOW Favour unmerited by me, who sought END
BEGIN NOW Forbidd'n knowledge by forbidd'n means. END
BEGIN NOW This yet I apprehend not, why to those END
BEGIN NOW Among whom God will deigne to dwell on Earth END
BEGIN NOW So many and so various Laws are giv'n; END
BEGIN NOW So many Laws argue so many sins END
BEGIN NOW Among them; how can God with such reside? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus MICHAEL. Doubt not but that sin END
BEGIN NOW Will reign among them, as of thee begot; END
BEGIN NOW And therefore was Law given them to evince END
BEGIN NOW Thir natural pravitie, by stirring up END
BEGIN NOW Sin against Law to fight; that when they see END
BEGIN NOW Law can discover sin, but not remove, END
BEGIN NOW Save by those shadowie expiations weak, END
BEGIN NOW The bloud of Bulls and Goats, they may conclude END
BEGIN NOW Some bloud more precious must be paid for Man, END
BEGIN NOW Just for unjust, that in such righteousness END
BEGIN NOW To them by Faith imputed, they may finde END
BEGIN NOW Justification towards God, and peace END
BEGIN NOW Of Conscience, which the Law by Ceremonies END
BEGIN NOW Cannot appease, nor Man the moral part END
BEGIN NOW Perform, and not performing cannot live. END
BEGIN NOW So Law appears imperfet, and but giv'n END
BEGIN NOW With purpose to resign them in full time END
BEGIN NOW Up to a better Cov'nant, disciplin'd END
BEGIN NOW From shadowie Types to Truth, from Flesh to Spirit, END
BEGIN NOW From imposition of strict Laws, to free END
BEGIN NOW Acceptance of large Grace, from servil fear END
BEGIN NOW To filial, works of Law to works of Faith. END
BEGIN NOW And therefore shall not MOSES, though of God END
BEGIN NOW Highly belov'd, being but the Minister END
BEGIN NOW Of Law, his people into CANAAN lead; END
BEGIN NOW But JOSHUA whom the Gentiles JESUS call, END
BEGIN NOW His Name and Office bearing, who shall quell END
BEGIN NOW The adversarie Serpent, and bring back END
BEGIN NOW Through the worlds wilderness long wanderd man END
BEGIN NOW Safe to eternal Paradise of rest. END
BEGIN NOW Meanwhile they in thir earthly CANAAN plac't END
BEGIN NOW Long time shall dwell and prosper, but when sins END
BEGIN NOW National interrupt thir public peace, END
BEGIN NOW Provoking God to raise them enemies: END
BEGIN NOW From whom as oft he saves them penitent END
BEGIN NOW By Judges first, then under Kings; of whom END
BEGIN NOW The second, both for pietie renownd END
BEGIN NOW And puissant deeds, a promise shall receive END
BEGIN NOW Irrevocable, that his Regal Throne END
BEGIN NOW For ever shall endure; the like shall sing END
BEGIN NOW Of DAVID (so I name this King) shall rise END
BEGIN NOW A Son, the Womans Seed to thee foretold, END
BEGIN NOW Foretold to ABRAHAM, as in whom shall trust END
BEGIN NOW All Nations, and to Kings foretold, of Kings END
BEGIN NOW The last, for of his Reign shall be no end. END
BEGIN NOW But first a long succession must ensue, END
BEGIN NOW And his next Son for Wealth and Wisdom fam'd, END
BEGIN NOW The clouded Ark of God till then in Tents END
BEGIN NOW Wandring, shall in a glorious Temple enshrine. END
BEGIN NOW Such follow him, as shall be registerd END
BEGIN NOW Part good, part bad, of bad the longer scrowle, END
BEGIN NOW Whose foul Idolatries, and other faults END
BEGIN NOW Heapt to the popular summe, will so incense END
BEGIN NOW God, as to leave them, and expose thir Land, END
BEGIN NOW Thir Citie, his Temple, and his holy Ark END
BEGIN NOW With all his sacred things, a scorn and prey END
BEGIN NOW To that proud Citie, whose high Walls thou saw'st END
BEGIN NOW Left in confusion, BABYLON thence call'd. END
BEGIN NOW There in captivitie he lets them dwell END
BEGIN NOW The space of seventie years, then brings them back, END
BEGIN NOW Remembring mercie, and his Cov'nant sworn END
BEGIN NOW To DAVID, stablisht as the dayes of Heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW Returnd from BABYLON by leave of Kings END
BEGIN NOW Thir Lords, whom God dispos'd, the house of God END
BEGIN NOW They first re-edifie, and for a while END
BEGIN NOW In mean estate live moderate, till grown END
BEGIN NOW In wealth and multitude, factious they grow; END
BEGIN NOW But first among the Priests dissension springs, END
BEGIN NOW Men who attend the Altar, and should most END
BEGIN NOW Endeavour Peace: thir strife pollution brings END
BEGIN NOW Upon the Temple it self: at last they seise END
BEGIN NOW The Scepter, and regard not DAVIDS Sons, END
BEGIN NOW Then loose it to a stranger, that the true END
BEGIN NOW Anointed King MESSIAH might be born END
BEGIN NOW Barr'd of his right; yet at his Birth a Starr END
BEGIN NOW Unseen before in Heav'n proclaims him com, END
BEGIN NOW And guides the Eastern Sages, who enquire END
BEGIN NOW His place, to offer Incense, Myrrh, and Gold; END
BEGIN NOW His place of birth a solemn Angel tells END
BEGIN NOW To simple Shepherds, keeping watch by night; END
BEGIN NOW They gladly thither haste, and by a Quire END
BEGIN NOW Of squadrond Angels hear his Carol sung. END
BEGIN NOW The Power of the most High; he shall ascend END
BEGIN NOW The Throne hereditarie, and bound his Reign END
BEGIN NOW With earths wide bounds, his glory with the Heav'ns. END
BEGIN NOW He ceas'd, discerning ADAM with such joy END
BEGIN NOW Surcharg'd, as had like grief bin dew'd in tears, END
BEGIN NOW Without the vent of words, which these he breathd. END
BEGIN NOW O Prophet of glad tidings, finisher END
BEGIN NOW Of utmost hope! now clear I understand END
BEGIN NOW What oft my steddiest thoughts have searcht in vain, END
BEGIN NOW Why our great expectation should be call'd END
BEGIN NOW The seed of Woman: Virgin Mother, Haile, END
BEGIN NOW High in the love of Heav'n, yet from my Loynes END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt proceed, and from thy Womb the Son END
BEGIN NOW Of God most High; So God with man unites. END
BEGIN NOW Needs must the Serpent now his capital bruise END
BEGIN NOW Expect with mortal paine: say where and when END
BEGIN NOW Thir fight, what stroke shall bruise the Victors heel. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus MICHAEL. Dream not of thir fight, END
BEGIN NOW As of a Duel, or the local wounds END
BEGIN NOW Of head or heel: not therefore joynes the Son END
BEGIN NOW Manhood to God-head, with more strength to foil END
BEGIN NOW Thy enemie; nor so is overcome END
BEGIN NOW SATAN, whose fall from Heav'n, a deadlier bruise, END
BEGIN NOW Disabl'd not to give thee thy deaths wound: END
BEGIN NOW Which hee, who comes thy Saviour, shall recure, END
BEGIN NOW Not by destroying SATAN, but his works END
BEGIN NOW In thee and in thy Seed: nor can this be, END
BEGIN NOW But by fulfilling that which thou didst want, END
BEGIN NOW Obedience to the Law of God, impos'd END
BEGIN NOW On penaltie of death, and suffering death, END
BEGIN NOW The penaltie to thy transgression due, END
BEGIN NOW And due to theirs which out of thine will grow: END
BEGIN NOW So onely can high Justice rest appaid. END
BEGIN NOW The Law of God exact he shall fulfill END
BEGIN NOW Both by obedience and by love, though love END
BEGIN NOW Alone fulfill the Law; thy punishment END
BEGIN NOW He shall endure by coming in the Flesh END
BEGIN NOW To a reproachful life and cursed death, END
BEGIN NOW Proclaiming Life to all who shall believe END
BEGIN NOW In his redemption, and that his obedience END
BEGIN NOW Imputed becomes theirs by Faith, his merits END
BEGIN NOW To save them, not thir own, though legal works. END
BEGIN NOW For this he shall live hated, be blasphem'd, END
BEGIN NOW Seis'd on by force, judg'd, and to death condemnd END
BEGIN NOW A shameful and accurst, naild to the Cross END
BEGIN NOW By his own Nation, slaine for bringing Life; END
BEGIN NOW But to the Cross he nailes thy Enemies, END
BEGIN NOW The Law that is against thee, and the sins END
BEGIN NOW Of all mankinde, with him there crucifi'd, END
BEGIN NOW Never to hurt them more who rightly trust END
BEGIN NOW In this his satisfaction; so he dies, END
BEGIN NOW But soon revives, Death over him no power END
BEGIN NOW Shall long usurp; ere the third dawning light END
BEGIN NOW Returne, the Starres of Morn shall see him rise END
BEGIN NOW Out of his grave, fresh as the dawning light, END
BEGIN NOW Thy ransom paid, which Man from death redeems, END
BEGIN NOW His death for Man, as many as offerd Life END
BEGIN NOW Neglect not, and the benefit imbrace END
BEGIN NOW By Faith not void of works: this God-like act END
BEGIN NOW Annuls thy doom, the death thou shouldst have dy'd, END
BEGIN NOW In sin for ever lost from life; this act END
BEGIN NOW Shall bruise the head of SATAN, crush his strength END
BEGIN NOW Defeating Sin and Death, his two maine armes, END
BEGIN NOW And fix farr deeper in his head thir stings END
BEGIN NOW Then temporal death shall bruise the Victors heel, END
BEGIN NOW Or theirs whom he redeems, a death like sleep, END
BEGIN NOW A gentle wafting to immortal Life. END
BEGIN NOW Nor after resurrection shall he stay END
BEGIN NOW Longer on Earth then certaine times to appeer END
BEGIN NOW Still follow'd him; to them shall leave in charge END
BEGIN NOW To teach all nations what of him they learn'd END
BEGIN NOW And his Salvation, them who shall beleeve END
BEGIN NOW Baptizing in the profluent streame, the signe END
BEGIN NOW Of washing them from guilt of sin to Life END
BEGIN NOW Pure, and in mind prepar'd, if so befall, END
BEGIN NOW For death, like that which the redeemer dy'd. END
BEGIN NOW All Nations they shall teach; for from that day END
BEGIN NOW Not onely to the Sons of ABRAHAMS Loines END
BEGIN NOW Salvation shall be Preacht, but to the Sons END
BEGIN NOW Of ABRAHAMS Faith wherever through the world; END
BEGIN NOW So in his seed all Nations shall be blest. END
BEGIN NOW Then to the Heav'n of Heav'ns he shall ascend END
BEGIN NOW With victory, triumphing through the aire END
BEGIN NOW Over his foes and thine; there shall surprise END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent, Prince of aire, and drag in Chaines END
BEGIN NOW Through all his realme, & there confounded leave; END
BEGIN NOW Then enter into glory, and resume END
BEGIN NOW His Seat at Gods right hand, exalted high END
BEGIN NOW Above all names in Heav'n; and thence shall come, END
BEGIN NOW When this worlds dissolution shall be ripe, END
BEGIN NOW With glory and power to judge both quick & dead, END
BEGIN NOW To judge th' unfaithful dead, but to reward END
BEGIN NOW His faithful, and receave them into bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Whether in Heav'n or Earth, for then the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Shall all be Paradise, far happier place END
BEGIN NOW Then this of EDEN, and far happier daies. END
BEGIN NOW So spake th' Archangel MICHAEL, then paus'd, END
BEGIN NOW As at the Worlds great period; and our Sire END
BEGIN NOW Replete with joy and wonder thus repli'd. END
BEGIN NOW O goodness infinite, goodness immense! END
BEGIN NOW That all this good of evil shall produce, END
BEGIN NOW And evil turn to good; more wonderful END
BEGIN NOW Then that which by creation first brought forth END
BEGIN NOW Light out of darkness! full of doubt I stand, END
BEGIN NOW Whether I should repent me now of sin END
BEGIN NOW By mee done and occasiond, or rejoyce END
BEGIN NOW Much more, that much more good thereof shall spring, END
BEGIN NOW To God more glory, more good will to Men END
BEGIN NOW From God, and over wrauth grace shall abound. END
BEGIN NOW But say, if our deliverer up to Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Must reascend, what will betide the few END
BEGIN NOW His faithful, left among th' unfaithful herd, END
BEGIN NOW The enemies of truth; who then shall guide END
BEGIN NOW His people, who defend? will they not deale END
BEGIN NOW Wors with his followers then with him they dealt? END
BEGIN NOW Be sure they will, said th' Angel; but from Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Hee to his own a Comforter will send, END
BEGIN NOW The promise of the Father, who shall dwell END
BEGIN NOW His Spirit within them, and the Law of Faith END
BEGIN NOW Working through love, upon thir hearts shall write, END
BEGIN NOW To guide them in all truth, and also arme END
BEGIN NOW With spiritual Armour, able to resist END
BEGIN NOW SATANS assaults, and quench his fierie darts END
BEGIN NOW What Man can do against them, not affraid, END
BEGIN NOW Though to the death, against such cruelties END
BEGIN NOW With inward consolations recompenc't, END
BEGIN NOW And oft supported so as shall amaze END
BEGIN NOW Thir proudest persecuters: for the Spirit END
BEGIN NOW Powrd first on his Apostles, whom he sends END
BEGIN NOW To evangelize the Nations, then on all END
BEGIN NOW Baptiz'd, shall them with wondrous gifts endue END
BEGIN NOW To speak all Tongues, and do all Miracles, END
BEGIN NOW As did thir Lord before them. Thus they win END
BEGIN NOW Great numbers of each Nation to receave END
BEGIN NOW With joy the tidings brought from Heav'n: at length END
BEGIN NOW Thir Ministry perform'd, and race well run, END
BEGIN NOW Thir doctrine and thir story written left, END
BEGIN NOW They die; but in thir room, as they forewarne, END
BEGIN NOW Wolves shall succeed for teachers, grievous Wolves, END
BEGIN NOW Who all the sacred mysteries of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW To thir own vile advantages shall turne END
BEGIN NOW Of lucre and ambition, and the truth END
BEGIN NOW With superstitions and traditions taint, END
BEGIN NOW Left onely in those written Records pure, END
BEGIN NOW Though not but by the Spirit understood. END
BEGIN NOW Then shall they seek to avail themselves of names, END
BEGIN NOW Places and titles, and with these to joine END
BEGIN NOW Secular power, though feigning still to act END
BEGIN NOW By spiritual, to themselves appropriating END
BEGIN NOW The Spirit of God, promisd alike and giv'n END
BEGIN NOW To all Beleevers; and from that pretense, END
BEGIN NOW Spiritual Lawes by carnal power shall force END
BEGIN NOW On every conscience; Laws which none shall finde END
BEGIN NOW Left them inrould, or what the Spirit within END
BEGIN NOW Shall on the heart engrave. What will they then END
BEGIN NOW But force the Spirit of Grace it self, and binde END
BEGIN NOW His consort Libertie; what, but unbuild END
BEGIN NOW His living Temples, built by Faith to stand, END
BEGIN NOW Thir own Faith not anothers: for on Earth END
BEGIN NOW Who against Faith and Conscience can be heard END
BEGIN NOW Infallible? yet many will presume: END
BEGIN NOW Whence heavie persecution shall arise END
BEGIN NOW On all who in the worship persevere END
BEGIN NOW Of Spirit and Truth; the rest, farr greater part, END
BEGIN NOW Will deem in outward Rites and specious formes END
BEGIN NOW Religion satisfi'd; Truth shall retire END
BEGIN NOW Bestuck with slandrous darts, and works of Faith END
BEGIN NOW Rarely be found: so shall the World goe on, END
BEGIN NOW To good malignant, to bad men benigne, END
BEGIN NOW Under her own waight groaning, till the day END
BEGIN NOW Appeer of respiration to the just, END
BEGIN NOW And vengeance to the wicked, at return END
BEGIN NOW Of him so lately promis'd to thy aid, END
BEGIN NOW The Womans seed, obscurely then foretold, END
BEGIN NOW Now amplier known thy Saviour and thy Lord, END
BEGIN NOW Last in the Clouds from Heav'n to be reveald END
BEGIN NOW In glory of the Father, to dissolve END
BEGIN NOW SATAN with his perverted World, then raise END
BEGIN NOW From the conflagrant mass, purg'd and refin'd, END
BEGIN NOW New Heav'ns, new Earth, Ages of endless date END
BEGIN NOW Founded in righteousness and peace and love, END
BEGIN NOW To bring forth fruits Joy and eternal Bliss. END
BEGIN NOW He ended; and thus ADAM last reply'd. END
BEGIN NOW How soon hath thy prediction, Seer blest, END
BEGIN NOW Measur'd this transient World, the Race of time, END
BEGIN NOW Till time stand fixt: beyond is all abyss, END
BEGIN NOW Eternitie, whose end no eye can reach. END
BEGIN NOW Greatly instructed I shall hence depart, END
BEGIN NOW Greatly in peace of thought, and have my fill END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledge, what this vessel can containe; END
BEGIN NOW Beyond which was my folly to aspire. END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth I learne, that to obey is best, END
BEGIN NOW And love with feare the onely God, to walk END
BEGIN NOW As in his presence, ever to observe END
BEGIN NOW His providence, and on him sole depend, END
BEGIN NOW Merciful over all his works, with good END
BEGIN NOW Still overcoming evil, and by small END
BEGIN NOW Accomplishing great things, by things deemd weak END
BEGIN NOW Subverting worldly strong, and worldly wise END
BEGIN NOW By simply meek; that suffering for Truths sake END
BEGIN NOW Is fortitude to highest victorie, END
BEGIN NOW And to the faithful Death the Gate of Life; END
BEGIN NOW Taught this by his example whom I now END
BEGIN NOW Acknowledge my Redeemer ever blest. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus also th' Angel last repli'd: END
BEGIN NOW This having learnt, thou hast attaind the summe END
BEGIN NOW Of wisdom; hope no higher, though all the Starrs END
BEGIN NOW Thou knewst by name, and all th' ethereal Powers, END
BEGIN NOW All secrets of the deep, all Natures works, END
BEGIN NOW Or works of God in Heav'n, Air, Earth, or Sea, END
BEGIN NOW And all the riches of this World enjoydst, END
BEGIN NOW And all the rule, one Empire; onely add END
BEGIN NOW Deeds to thy knowledge answerable, add Faith, END
BEGIN NOW By name to come call'd Charitie, the soul END
BEGIN NOW Of all the rest: then wilt thou not be loath END
BEGIN NOW To leave this Paradise, but shalt possess END
BEGIN NOW A Paradise within thee, happier farr. END
BEGIN NOW Let us descend now therefore from this top END
BEGIN NOW Of Speculation; for the hour precise END
BEGIN NOW Exacts our parting hence; and see the Guards, END
BEGIN NOW By mee encampt on yonder Hill, expect END
BEGIN NOW Thir motion, at whose Front a flaming Sword, END
BEGIN NOW In signal of remove, waves fiercely round; END
BEGIN NOW We may no longer stay: go, waken Eve; END
BEGIN NOW Her also I with gentle Dreams have calm'd END
BEGIN NOW Portending good, and all her spirits compos'd END
BEGIN NOW To meek submission: thou at season fit END
BEGIN NOW Let her with thee partake what thou hast heard, END
BEGIN NOW Chiefly what may concern her Faith to know, END
BEGIN NOW The great deliverance by her Seed to come END
BEGIN NOW That ye may live, which will be many dayes, END
BEGIN NOW Both in one Faith unanimous though sad, END
BEGIN NOW With cause for evils past, yet much more cheer'd END
BEGIN NOW With meditation on the happie end. END
BEGIN NOW He ended, and they both descend the Hill; END
BEGIN NOW Descended, ADAM to the Bowre where EVE END
BEGIN NOW Lay sleeping ran before, but found her wak't; END
BEGIN NOW And thus with words not sad she him receav'd. END
BEGIN NOW Whence thou returnst, & whither wentst, I know; END
BEGIN NOW For God is also in sleep, and Dreams advise, END
BEGIN NOW Which he hath sent propitious, some great good END
BEGIN NOW Presaging, since with sorrow and hearts distress END
BEGIN NOW VVearied I fell asleep: but now lead on; END
BEGIN NOW In mee is no delay; with thee to goe, END
BEGIN NOW Is to stay here; without thee here to stay, END
BEGIN NOW Is to go hence unwilling; thou to mee END
BEGIN NOW Art all things under Heav'n, all places thou, END
BEGIN NOW VVho for my wilful crime art banisht hence. END
BEGIN NOW This further consolation yet secure END
BEGIN NOW I carry hence; though all by mee is lost, END
BEGIN NOW Such favour I unworthie am voutsaft, END
BEGIN NOW By mee the Promis'd Seed shall all restore. END
BEGIN NOW So spake our Mother EVE, and ADAM heard END
BEGIN NOW VVell pleas'd, but answer'd not; for now too nigh END
BEGIN NOW Th' Archangel stood, and from the other Hill END
BEGIN NOW To thir fixt Station, all in bright array END
BEGIN NOW The Cherubim descended; on the ground END
BEGIN NOW Gliding meteorous, as Ev'ning Mist END
BEGIN NOW Ris'n from a River o're the marish glides, END
BEGIN NOW And gathers ground fast at the Labourers heel END
BEGIN NOW Homeward returning. High in Front advanc't, END
BEGIN NOW The brandisht Sword of God before them blaz'd END
BEGIN NOW Fierce as a Comet; which with torrid heat, END
BEGIN NOW And vapour as the LIBYAN Air adust, END
BEGIN NOW Began to parch that temperate Clime; whereat END
BEGIN NOW In either hand the hastning Angel caught END
BEGIN NOW Our lingring Parents, and to th' Eastern Gate END
BEGIN NOW Let them direct, and down the Cliff as fast END
BEGIN NOW To the subjected Plaine; then disappeer'd. END
BEGIN NOW They looking back, all th' Eastern side beheld END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise, so late thir happie seat, END
BEGIN NOW Wav'd over by that flaming Brand, the Gate END
BEGIN NOW With dreadful Faces throng'd and fierie Armes: END
BEGIN NOW Som natural tears they drop'd, but wip'd them soon; END
BEGIN NOW The World was all before them, where to choose END
BEGIN NOW Thir place of rest, and Providence thir guide: END
BEGIN NOW They hand in hand with wandring steps and slow, END
BEGIN NOW Through EDEN took thir solitarie way. END
BEGIN NOW Of Man's first disobedience, and the fruit END
BEGIN NOW Of that forbidden tree whose mortal taste END
BEGIN NOW Brought death into the World, and all our woe, END
BEGIN NOW With loss of Eden, till one greater Man END
BEGIN NOW Restore us, and regain the blissful seat, END
BEGIN NOW Sing, Heavenly Muse, that, on the secret top END
BEGIN NOW Of Oreb, or of Sinai, didst inspire END
BEGIN NOW That shepherd who first taught the chosen seed END
BEGIN NOW In the beginning how the heavens and earth END
BEGIN NOW Rose out of Chaos: or, if Sion hill END
BEGIN NOW Delight thee more, and Siloa's brook that flowed END
BEGIN NOW Fast by the oracle of God, I thence END
BEGIN NOW Invoke thy aid to my adventurous song, END
BEGIN NOW That with no middle flight intends to soar END
BEGIN NOW Above th' Aonian mount, while it pursues END
BEGIN NOW Things unattempted yet in prose or rhyme. END
BEGIN NOW And chiefly thou, O Spirit, that dost prefer END
BEGIN NOW Before all temples th' upright heart and pure, END
BEGIN NOW Instruct me, for thou know'st; thou from the first END
BEGIN NOW Wast present, and, with mighty wings outspread, END
BEGIN NOW Dove-like sat'st brooding on the vast Abyss, END
BEGIN NOW And mad'st it pregnant: what in me is dark END
BEGIN NOW Illumine, what is low raise and support; END
BEGIN NOW That, to the height of this great argument, END
BEGIN NOW I may assert Eternal Providence, END
BEGIN NOW And justify the ways of God to men. END
BEGIN NOW Say first--for Heaven hides nothing from thy view, END
BEGIN NOW Nor the deep tract of Hell--say first what cause END
BEGIN NOW Moved our grand parents, in that happy state, END
BEGIN NOW Favoured of Heaven so highly, to fall off END
BEGIN NOW From their Creator, and transgress his will END
BEGIN NOW For one restraint, lords of the World besides. END
BEGIN NOW Who first seduced them to that foul revolt? END
BEGIN NOW Th' infernal Serpent; he it was whose guile, END
BEGIN NOW Stirred up with envy and revenge, deceived END
BEGIN NOW The mother of mankind, what time his pride END
BEGIN NOW Had cast him out from Heaven, with all his host END
BEGIN NOW Of rebel Angels, by whose aid, aspiring END
BEGIN NOW To set himself in glory above his peers, END
BEGIN NOW He trusted to have equalled the Most High, END
BEGIN NOW If he opposed, and with ambitious aim END
BEGIN NOW Against the throne and monarchy of God, END
BEGIN NOW Raised impious war in Heaven and battle proud, END
BEGIN NOW With vain attempt. Him the Almighty Power END
BEGIN NOW Hurled headlong flaming from th' ethereal sky, END
BEGIN NOW With hideous ruin and combustion, down END
BEGIN NOW To bottomless perdition, there to dwell END
BEGIN NOW In adamantine chains and penal fire, END
BEGIN NOW Who durst defy th' Omnipotent to arms. END
BEGIN NOW Nine times the space that measures day and night END
BEGIN NOW To mortal men, he, with his horrid crew, END
BEGIN NOW Lay vanquished, rolling in the fiery gulf, END
BEGIN NOW Confounded, though immortal. But his doom END
BEGIN NOW Reserved him to more wrath; for now the thought END
BEGIN NOW Both of lost happiness and lasting pain END
BEGIN NOW Torments him: round he throws his baleful eyes, END
BEGIN NOW That witnessed huge affliction and dismay, END
BEGIN NOW Mixed with obdurate pride and steadfast hate. END
BEGIN NOW At once, as far as Angels ken, he views END
BEGIN NOW The dismal situation waste and wild. END
BEGIN NOW A dungeon horrible, on all sides round, END
BEGIN NOW As one great furnace flamed; yet from those flames END
BEGIN NOW No light; but rather darkness visible END
BEGIN NOW Served only to discover sights of woe, END
BEGIN NOW Regions of sorrow, doleful shades, where peace END
BEGIN NOW And rest can never dwell, hope never comes END
BEGIN NOW That comes to all, but torture without end END
BEGIN NOW Still urges, and a fiery deluge, fed END
BEGIN NOW With ever-burning sulphur unconsumed. END
BEGIN NOW Such place Eternal Justice has prepared END
BEGIN NOW For those rebellious; here their prison ordained END
BEGIN NOW In utter darkness, and their portion set, END
BEGIN NOW As far removed from God and light of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW As from the centre thrice to th' utmost pole. END
BEGIN NOW Oh how unlike the place from whence they fell! END
BEGIN NOW There the companions of his fall, o'erwhelmed END
BEGIN NOW With floods and whirlwinds of tempestuous fire, END
BEGIN NOW He soon discerns; and, weltering by his side, END
BEGIN NOW One next himself in power, and next in crime, END
BEGIN NOW Long after known in Palestine, and named END
BEGIN NOW Beelzebub. To whom th' Arch-Enemy, END
BEGIN NOW And thence in Heaven called Satan, with bold words END
BEGIN NOW Breaking the horrid silence, thus began:-- END
BEGIN NOW If thou beest he--but O how fallen! how changed END
BEGIN NOW From him who, in the happy realms of light END
BEGIN NOW Clothed with transcendent brightness, didst outshine END
BEGIN NOW Myriads, though bright!--if he whom mutual league, END
BEGIN NOW United thoughts and counsels, equal hope END
BEGIN NOW And hazard in the glorious enterprise END
BEGIN NOW Joined with me once, now misery hath joined END
BEGIN NOW In equal ruin; into what pit thou seest END
BEGIN NOW From what height fallen: so much the stronger proved END
BEGIN NOW He with his thunder; and till then who knew END
BEGIN NOW The force of those dire arms? Yet not for those, END
BEGIN NOW Nor what the potent Victor in his rage END
BEGIN NOW Can else inflict, do I repent, or change, END
BEGIN NOW Though changed in outward lustre, that fixed mind, END
BEGIN NOW And high disdain from sense of injured merit, END
BEGIN NOW That with the Mightiest raised me to contend, END
BEGIN NOW And to the fierce contentions brought along END
BEGIN NOW Innumerable force of Spirits armed, END
BEGIN NOW That durst dislike his reign, and, me preferring, END
BEGIN NOW His utmost power with adverse power opposed END
BEGIN NOW In dubious battle on the plains of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW And shook his throne. What though the field be lost? END
BEGIN NOW All is not lost--the unconquerable will, END
BEGIN NOW And study of revenge, immortal hate, END
BEGIN NOW And courage never to submit or yield: END
BEGIN NOW And what is else not to be overcome? END
BEGIN NOW That glory never shall his wrath or might END
BEGIN NOW Extort from me. To bow and sue for grace END
BEGIN NOW With suppliant knee, and deify his power END
BEGIN NOW Who, from the terror of this arm, so late END
BEGIN NOW Doubted his empire--that were low indeed; END
BEGIN NOW That were an ignominy and shame beneath END
BEGIN NOW This downfall; since, by fate, the strength of Gods, END
BEGIN NOW And this empyreal sybstance, cannot fail; END
BEGIN NOW Since, through experience of this great event, END
BEGIN NOW In arms not worse, in foresight much advanced, END
BEGIN NOW We may with more successful hope resolve END
BEGIN NOW To wage by force or guile eternal war, END
BEGIN NOW Irreconcilable to our grand Foe, END
BEGIN NOW Who now triumphs, and in th' excess of joy END
BEGIN NOW Sole reigning holds the tyranny of Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW So spake th' apostate Angel, though in pain, END
BEGIN NOW Vaunting aloud, but racked with deep despair; END
BEGIN NOW And him thus answered soon his bold compeer:-- END
BEGIN NOW O Prince, O Chief of many throned Powers END
BEGIN NOW That led th' embattled Seraphim to war END
BEGIN NOW Under thy conduct, and, in dreadful deeds END
BEGIN NOW Fearless, endangered Heaven's perpetual King, END
BEGIN NOW And put to proof his high supremacy, END
BEGIN NOW Whether upheld by strength, or chance, or fate, END
BEGIN NOW Too well I see and rue the dire event END
BEGIN NOW That, with sad overthrow and foul defeat, END
BEGIN NOW Hath lost us Heaven, and all this mighty host END
BEGIN NOW In horrible destruction laid thus low, END
BEGIN NOW As far as Gods and heavenly Essences END
BEGIN NOW Can perish: for the mind and spirit remains END
BEGIN NOW Invincible, and vigour soon returns, END
BEGIN NOW Though all our glory extinct, and happy state END
BEGIN NOW Here swallowed up in endless misery. END
BEGIN NOW But what if he our Conqueror (whom I now END
BEGIN NOW Of force believe almighty, since no less END
BEGIN NOW Than such could have o'erpowered such force as ours) END
BEGIN NOW Have left us this our spirit and strength entire, END
BEGIN NOW Strongly to suffer and support our pains, END
BEGIN NOW That we may so suffice his vengeful ire, END
BEGIN NOW Or do him mightier service as his thralls END
BEGIN NOW By right of war, whate'er his business be, END
BEGIN NOW Here in the heart of Hell to work in fire, END
BEGIN NOW Or do his errands in the gloomy Deep? END
BEGIN NOW What can it the avail though yet we feel END
BEGIN NOW Strength undiminished, or eternal being END
BEGIN NOW To undergo eternal punishment? END
BEGIN NOW Whereto with speedy words th' Arch-Fiend replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Fallen Cherub, to be weak is miserable, END
BEGIN NOW Doing or suffering: but of this be sure-- END
BEGIN NOW To do aught good never will be our task, END
BEGIN NOW But ever to do ill our sole delight, END
BEGIN NOW As being the contrary to his high will END
BEGIN NOW Whom we resist. If then his providence END
BEGIN NOW Out of our evil seek to bring forth good, END
BEGIN NOW Our labour must be to pervert that end, END
BEGIN NOW And out of good still to find means of evil; END
BEGIN NOW Which ofttimes may succeed so as perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Shall grieve him, if I fail not, and disturb END
BEGIN NOW His inmost counsels from their destined aim. END
BEGIN NOW But see! the angry Victor hath recalled END
BEGIN NOW His ministers of vengeance and pursuit END
BEGIN NOW Back to the gates of Heaven: the sulphurous hail, END
BEGIN NOW Shot after us in storm, o'erblown hath laid END
BEGIN NOW The fiery surge that from the precipice END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven received us falling; and the thunder, END
BEGIN NOW Winged with red lightning and impetuous rage, END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps hath spent his shafts, and ceases now END
BEGIN NOW To bellow through the vast and boundless Deep. END
BEGIN NOW Let us not slip th' occasion, whether scorn END
BEGIN NOW Or satiate fury yield it from our Foe. END
BEGIN NOW Seest thou yon dreary plain, forlorn and wild, END
BEGIN NOW The seat of desolation, void of light, END
BEGIN NOW Save what the glimmering of these livid flames END
BEGIN NOW Casts pale and dreadful? Thither let us tend END
BEGIN NOW From off the tossing of these fiery waves; END
BEGIN NOW There rest, if any rest can harbour there; END
BEGIN NOW And, re-assembling our afflicted powers, END
BEGIN NOW Consult how we may henceforth most offend END
BEGIN NOW Our enemy, our own loss how repair, END
BEGIN NOW How overcome this dire calamity, END
BEGIN NOW What reinforcement we may gain from hope, END
BEGIN NOW If not, what resolution from despair. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Satan, talking to his nearest mate, END
BEGIN NOW With head uplift above the wave, and eyes END
BEGIN NOW That sparkling blazed; his other parts besides END
BEGIN NOW Prone on the flood, extended long and large, END
BEGIN NOW Lay floating many a rood, in bulk as huge END
BEGIN NOW As whom the fables name of monstrous size, END
BEGIN NOW Titanian or Earth-born, that warred on Jove, END
BEGIN NOW Briareos or Typhon, whom the den END
BEGIN NOW By ancient Tarsus held, or that sea-beast END
BEGIN NOW Leviathan, which God of all his works END
BEGIN NOW Created hugest that swim th' ocean-stream. END
BEGIN NOW Him, haply slumbering on the Norway foam, END
BEGIN NOW The pilot of some small night-foundered skiff, END
BEGIN NOW Deeming some island, oft, as seamen tell, END
BEGIN NOW With fixed anchor in his scaly rind, END
BEGIN NOW Moors by his side under the lee, while night END
BEGIN NOW Invests the sea, and wished morn delays. END
BEGIN NOW So stretched out huge in length the Arch-fiend lay, END
BEGIN NOW Chained on the burning lake; nor ever thence END
BEGIN NOW Had risen, or heaved his head, but that the will END
BEGIN NOW And high permission of all-ruling Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Left him at large to his own dark designs, END
BEGIN NOW That with reiterated crimes he might END
BEGIN NOW Heap on himself damnation, while he sought END
BEGIN NOW Evil to others, and enraged might see END
BEGIN NOW How all his malice served but to bring forth END
BEGIN NOW Infinite goodness, grace, and mercy, shewn END
BEGIN NOW On Man by him seduced, but on himself END
BEGIN NOW Treble confusion, wrath, and vengeance poured. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith upright he rears from off the pool END
BEGIN NOW His mighty stature; on each hand the flames END
BEGIN NOW Driven backward slope their pointing spires, and rolled END
BEGIN NOW In billows, leave i' th' midst a horrid vale. END
BEGIN NOW Then with expanded wings he steers his flight END
BEGIN NOW Aloft, incumbent on the dusky air, END
BEGIN NOW That felt unusual weight; till on dry land END
BEGIN NOW He lights--if it were land that ever burned END
BEGIN NOW With solid, as the lake with liquid fire, END
BEGIN NOW And such appeared in hue as when the force END
BEGIN NOW Of subterranean wind transports a hill END
BEGIN NOW Torn from Pelorus, or the shattered side END
BEGIN NOW Of thundering Etna, whose combustible END
BEGIN NOW And fuelled entrails, thence conceiving fire, END
BEGIN NOW Sublimed with mineral fury, aid the winds, END
BEGIN NOW And leave a singed bottom all involved END
BEGIN NOW With stench and smoke. Such resting found the sole END
BEGIN NOW Of unblest feet. Him followed his next mate; END
BEGIN NOW Both glorying to have scaped the Stygian flood END
BEGIN NOW As gods, and by their own recovered strength, END
BEGIN NOW Not by the sufferance of supernal Power. END
BEGIN NOW Is this the region, this the soil, the clime, END
BEGIN NOW Said then the lost Archangel, "this the seat END
BEGIN NOW That we must change for Heaven?--this mournful gloom END
BEGIN NOW For that celestial light? Be it so, since he END
BEGIN NOW Who now is sovereign can dispose and bid END
BEGIN NOW What shall be right: farthest from him is best END
BEGIN NOW Whom reason hath equalled, force hath made supreme END
BEGIN NOW Above his equals. Farewell, happy fields, END
BEGIN NOW Where joy for ever dwells! Hail, horrors! hail, END
BEGIN NOW Infernal world! and thou, profoundest Hell, END
BEGIN NOW Receive thy new possessor--one who brings END
BEGIN NOW A mind not to be changed by place or time. END
BEGIN NOW The mind is its own place, and in itself END
BEGIN NOW Can make a Heaven of Hell, a Hell of Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW What matter where, if I be still the same, END
BEGIN NOW And what I should be, all but less than he END
BEGIN NOW Whom thunder hath made greater? Here at least END
BEGIN NOW We shall be free; th' Almighty hath not built END
BEGIN NOW Here for his envy, will not drive us hence: END
BEGIN NOW Here we may reign secure; and, in my choice, END
BEGIN NOW To reign is worth ambition, though in Hell: END
BEGIN NOW Better to reign in Hell than serve in Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW But wherefore let we then our faithful friends, END
BEGIN NOW Th' associates and co-partners of our loss, END
BEGIN NOW Lie thus astonished on th' oblivious pool, END
BEGIN NOW And call them not to share with us their part END
BEGIN NOW In this unhappy mansion, or once more END
BEGIN NOW With rallied arms to try what may be yet END
BEGIN NOW Regained in Heaven, or what more lost in Hell? END
BEGIN NOW So Satan spake; and him Beelzebub END
BEGIN NOW Thus answered:--"Leader of those armies bright END
BEGIN NOW Which, but th' Omnipotent, none could have foiled! END
BEGIN NOW If once they hear that voice, their liveliest pledge END
BEGIN NOW Of hope in fears and dangers--heard so oft END
BEGIN NOW In worst extremes, and on the perilous edge END
BEGIN NOW Of battle, when it raged, in all assaults END
BEGIN NOW Their surest signal--they will soon resume END
BEGIN NOW New courage and revive, though now they lie END
BEGIN NOW Grovelling and prostrate on yon lake of fire, END
BEGIN NOW As we erewhile, astounded and amazed; END
BEGIN NOW No wonder, fallen such a pernicious height! END
BEGIN NOW He scare had ceased when the superior Fiend END
BEGIN NOW Was moving toward the shore; his ponderous shield, END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal temper, massy, large, and round, END
BEGIN NOW Behind him cast. The broad circumference END
BEGIN NOW Hung on his shoulders like the moon, whose orb END
BEGIN NOW Through optic glass the Tuscan artist views END
BEGIN NOW At evening, from the top of Fesole, END
BEGIN NOW Or in Valdarno, to descry new lands, END
BEGIN NOW Rivers, or mountains, in her spotty globe. END
BEGIN NOW His spear--to equal which the tallest pine END
BEGIN NOW Hewn on Norwegian hills, to be the mast END
BEGIN NOW Of some great ammiral, were but a wand-- END
BEGIN NOW He walked with, to support uneasy steps END
BEGIN NOW Over the burning marl, not like those steps END
BEGIN NOW On Heaven's azure; and the torrid clime END
BEGIN NOW Smote on him sore besides, vaulted with fire. END
BEGIN NOW Nathless he so endured, till on the beach END
BEGIN NOW Of that inflamed sea he stood, and called END
BEGIN NOW His legions--Angel Forms, who lay entranced END
BEGIN NOW Thick as autumnal leaves that strow the brooks END
BEGIN NOW In Vallombrosa, where th' Etrurian shades END
BEGIN NOW High over-arched embower; or scattered sedge END
BEGIN NOW Afloat, when with fierce winds Orion armed END
BEGIN NOW Hath vexed the Red-Sea coast, whose waves o'erthrew END
BEGIN NOW Busiris and his Memphian chivalry, END
BEGIN NOW While with perfidious hatred they pursued END
BEGIN NOW The sojourners of Goshen, who beheld END
BEGIN NOW From the safe shore their floating carcases END
BEGIN NOW And broken chariot-wheels. So thick bestrown, END
BEGIN NOW Abject and lost, lay these, covering the flood, END
BEGIN NOW Under amazement of their hideous change. END
BEGIN NOW He called so loud that all the hollow deep END
BEGIN NOW Of Hell resounded:--"Princes, Potentates, END
BEGIN NOW Warriors, the Flower of Heaven--once yours; now lost, END
BEGIN NOW If such astonishment as this can seize END
BEGIN NOW Eternal Spirits! Or have ye chosen this place END
BEGIN NOW After the toil of battle to repose END
BEGIN NOW Your wearied virtue, for the ease you find END
BEGIN NOW To slumber here, as in the vales of Heaven? END
BEGIN NOW Or in this abject posture have ye sworn END
BEGIN NOW To adore the Conqueror, who now beholds END
BEGIN NOW Cherub and Seraph rolling in the flood END
BEGIN NOW With scattered arms and ensigns, till anon END
BEGIN NOW His swift pursuers from Heaven-gates discern END
BEGIN NOW Th' advantage, and, descending, tread us down END
BEGIN NOW Thus drooping, or with linked thunderbolts END
BEGIN NOW Transfix us to the bottom of this gulf? END
BEGIN NOW Awake, arise, or be for ever fallen! END
BEGIN NOW They heard, and were abashed, and up they sprung END
BEGIN NOW Upon the wing, as when men wont to watch END
BEGIN NOW On duty, sleeping found by whom they dread, END
BEGIN NOW Rouse and bestir themselves ere well awake. END
BEGIN NOW Nor did they not perceive the evil plight END
BEGIN NOW In which they were, or the fierce pains not feel; END
BEGIN NOW Yet to their General's voice they soon obeyed END
BEGIN NOW Innumerable. As when the potent rod END
BEGIN NOW Waved round the coast, up-called a pitchy cloud END
BEGIN NOW Of locusts, warping on the eastern wind, END
BEGIN NOW That o'er the realm of impious Pharaoh hung END
BEGIN NOW Like Night, and darkened all the land of Nile; END
BEGIN NOW So numberless were those bad Angels seen END
BEGIN NOW Hovering on wing under the cope of Hell, END
BEGIN NOW 'Twixt upper, nether, and surrounding fires; END
BEGIN NOW Till, as a signal given, th' uplifted spear END
BEGIN NOW Of their great Sultan waving to direct END
BEGIN NOW Their course, in even balance down they light END
BEGIN NOW On the firm brimstone, and fill all the plain: END
BEGIN NOW A multitude like which the populous North END
BEGIN NOW Poured never from her frozen loins to pass END
BEGIN NOW Rhene or the Danaw, when her barbarous sons END
BEGIN NOW Came like a deluge on the South, and spread END
BEGIN NOW Beneath Gibraltar to the Libyan sands. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith, form every squadron and each band, END
BEGIN NOW The heads and leaders thither haste where stood END
BEGIN NOW Their great Commander--godlike Shapes, and Forms END
BEGIN NOW Excelling human; princely Dignities; END
BEGIN NOW And Powers that erst in Heaven sat on thrones, END
BEGIN NOW Though on their names in Heavenly records now END
BEGIN NOW Be no memorial, blotted out and rased END
BEGIN NOW By their rebellion from the Books of Life. END
BEGIN NOW Nor had they yet among the sons of Eve END
BEGIN NOW Got them new names, till, wandering o'er the earth, END
BEGIN NOW Through God's high sufferance for the trial of man, END
BEGIN NOW By falsities and lies the greatest part END
BEGIN NOW Of mankind they corrupted to forsake END
BEGIN NOW God their Creator, and th' invisible END
BEGIN NOW Glory of him that made them to transform END
BEGIN NOW Oft to the image of a brute, adorned END
BEGIN NOW With gay religions full of pomp and gold, END
BEGIN NOW And devils to adore for deities: END
BEGIN NOW Then were they known to men by various names, END
BEGIN NOW And various idols through the heathen world. END
BEGIN NOW Say, Muse, their names then known, who first, who last, END
BEGIN NOW Roused from the slumber on that fiery couch, END
BEGIN NOW At their great Emperor's call, as next in worth END
BEGIN NOW Came singly where he stood on the bare strand, END
BEGIN NOW While the promiscuous crowd stood yet aloof? END
BEGIN NOW The chief were those who, from the pit of Hell END
BEGIN NOW Roaming to seek their prey on Earth, durst fix END
BEGIN NOW Their seats, long after, next the seat of God, END
BEGIN NOW Their altars by his altar, gods adored END
BEGIN NOW Among the nations round, and durst abide END
BEGIN NOW Jehovah thundering out of Sion, throned END
BEGIN NOW Between the Cherubim; yea, often placed END
BEGIN NOW Within his sanctuary itself their shrines, END
BEGIN NOW Abominations; and with cursed things END
BEGIN NOW His holy rites and solemn feasts profaned, END
BEGIN NOW And with their darkness durst affront his light. END
BEGIN NOW First, Moloch, horrid king, besmeared with blood END
BEGIN NOW Of human sacrifice, and parents' tears; END
BEGIN NOW Though, for the noise of drums and timbrels loud, END
BEGIN NOW Their children's cries unheard that passed through fire END
BEGIN NOW To his grim idol. Him the Ammonite END
BEGIN NOW Worshiped in Rabba and her watery plain, END
BEGIN NOW In Argob and in Basan, to the stream END
BEGIN NOW Of utmost Arnon. Nor content with such END
BEGIN NOW Audacious neighbourhood, the wisest heart END
BEGIN NOW Of Solomon he led by fraud to build END
BEGIN NOW His temple right against the temple of God END
BEGIN NOW On that opprobrious hill, and made his grove END
BEGIN NOW The pleasant valley of Hinnom, Tophet thence END
BEGIN NOW And black Gehenna called, the type of Hell. END
BEGIN NOW Next Chemos, th' obscene dread of Moab's sons, END
BEGIN NOW From Aroar to Nebo and the wild END
BEGIN NOW Of southmost Abarim; in Hesebon END
BEGIN NOW And Horonaim, Seon's real, beyond END
BEGIN NOW The flowery dale of Sibma clad with vines, END
BEGIN NOW Peor his other name, when he enticed END
BEGIN NOW Israel in Sittim, on their march from Nile, END
BEGIN NOW To do him wanton rites, which cost them woe. END
BEGIN NOW Yet thence his lustful orgies he enlarged END
BEGIN NOW Even to that hill of scandal, by the grove END
BEGIN NOW Of Moloch homicide, lust hard by hate, END
BEGIN NOW Till good Josiah drove them thence to Hell. END
BEGIN NOW With these came they who, from the bordering flood END
BEGIN NOW Of old Euphrates to the brook that parts END
BEGIN NOW Of Baalim and Ashtaroth--those male, END
BEGIN NOW These feminine. For Spirits, when they please, END
BEGIN NOW Can either sex assume, or both; so soft END
BEGIN NOW And uncompounded is their essence pure, END
BEGIN NOW Not tried or manacled with joint or limb, END
BEGIN NOW Nor founded on the brittle strength of bones, END
BEGIN NOW Like cumbrous flesh; but, in what shape they choose, END
BEGIN NOW Dilated or condensed, bright or obscure, END
BEGIN NOW Can execute their airy purposes, END
BEGIN NOW And works of love or enmity fulfil. END
BEGIN NOW For those the race of Israel oft forsook END
BEGIN NOW Their Living Strength, and unfrequented left END
BEGIN NOW His righteous altar, bowing lowly down END
BEGIN NOW To bestial gods; for which their heads as low END
BEGIN NOW Bowed down in battle, sunk before the spear END
BEGIN NOW Of despicable foes. With these in troop END
BEGIN NOW Came Astoreth, whom the Phoenicians called END
BEGIN NOW Astarte, queen of heaven, with crescent horns; END
BEGIN NOW To whose bright image nightly by the moon END
BEGIN NOW Sidonian virgins paid their vows and songs; END
BEGIN NOW In Sion also not unsung, where stood END
BEGIN NOW Her temple on th' offensive mountain, built END
BEGIN NOW By that uxorious king whose heart, though large, END
BEGIN NOW Beguiled by fair idolatresses, fell END
BEGIN NOW To idols foul. Thammuz came next behind, END
BEGIN NOW Whose annual wound in Lebanon allured END
BEGIN NOW The Syrian damsels to lament his fate END
BEGIN NOW In amorous ditties all a summer's day, END
BEGIN NOW While smooth Adonis from his native rock END
BEGIN NOW Ran purple to the sea, supposed with blood END
BEGIN NOW Of Thammuz yearly wounded: the love-tale END
BEGIN NOW Infected Sion's daughters with like heat, END
BEGIN NOW Whose wanton passions in the sacred porch END
BEGIN NOW Ezekiel saw, when, by the vision led, END
BEGIN NOW His eye surveyed the dark idolatries END
BEGIN NOW Of alienated Judah. Next came one END
BEGIN NOW Who mourned in earnest, when the captive ark END
BEGIN NOW Maimed his brute image, head and hands lopt off, END
BEGIN NOW In his own temple, on the grunsel-edge, END
BEGIN NOW Where he fell flat and shamed his worshippers: END
BEGIN NOW And downward fish; yet had his temple high END
BEGIN NOW Reared in Azotus, dreaded through the coast END
BEGIN NOW And Accaron and Gaza's frontier bounds. END
BEGIN NOW Him followed Rimmon, whose delightful seat END
BEGIN NOW Was fair Damascus, on the fertile banks END
BEGIN NOW Of Abbana and Pharphar, lucid streams. END
BEGIN NOW He also against the house of God was bold: END
BEGIN NOW A leper once he lost, and gained a king-- END
BEGIN NOW Ahaz, his sottish conqueror, whom he drew END
BEGIN NOW God's altar to disparage and displace END
BEGIN NOW For one of Syrian mode, whereon to burn END
BEGIN NOW His odious offerings, and adore the gods END
BEGIN NOW Whom he had vanquished. After these appeared END
BEGIN NOW A crew who, under names of old renown-- END
BEGIN NOW Osiris, Isis, Orus, and their train-- END
BEGIN NOW With monstrous shapes and sorceries abused END
BEGIN NOW Their wandering gods disguised in brutish forms END
BEGIN NOW Rather than human. Nor did Israel scape END
BEGIN NOW Th' infection, when their borrowed gold composed END
BEGIN NOW The calf in Oreb; and the rebel king END
BEGIN NOW Doubled that sin in Bethel and in Dan, END
BEGIN NOW Likening his Maker to the grazed ox-- END
BEGIN NOW Jehovah, who, in one night, when he passed END
BEGIN NOW Both her first-born and all her bleating gods. END
BEGIN NOW Belial came last; than whom a Spirit more lewd END
BEGIN NOW Fell not from Heaven, or more gross to love END
BEGIN NOW Vice for itself. To him no temple stood END
BEGIN NOW Or altar smoked; yet who more oft than he END
BEGIN NOW In temples and at altars, when the priest END
BEGIN NOW Turns atheist, as did Eli's sons, who filled END
BEGIN NOW With lust and violence the house of God? END
BEGIN NOW In courts and palaces he also reigns, END
BEGIN NOW And in luxurious cities, where the noise END
BEGIN NOW Of riot ascends above their loftiest towers, END
BEGIN NOW And injury and outrage; and, when night END
BEGIN NOW Darkens the streets, then wander forth the sons END
BEGIN NOW Of Belial, flown with insolence and wine. END
BEGIN NOW Witness the streets of Sodom, and that night END
BEGIN NOW In Gibeah, when the hospitable door END
BEGIN NOW Exposed a matron, to avoid worse rape. END
BEGIN NOW These were the prime in order and in might: END
BEGIN NOW The rest were long to tell; though far renowned END
BEGIN NOW Th' Ionian gods--of Javan's issue held END
BEGIN NOW Gods, yet confessed later than Heaven and Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Their boasted parents;--Titan, Heaven's first-born, END
BEGIN NOW With his enormous brood, and birthright seized END
BEGIN NOW By younger Saturn: he from mightier Jove, END
BEGIN NOW His own and Rhea's son, like measure found; END
BEGIN NOW So Jove usurping reigned. These, first in Crete END
BEGIN NOW And Ida known, thence on the snowy top END
BEGIN NOW Of cold Olympus ruled the middle air, END
BEGIN NOW Their highest heaven; or on the Delphian cliff, END
BEGIN NOW Or in Dodona, and through all the bounds END
BEGIN NOW Of Doric land; or who with Saturn old END
BEGIN NOW Fled over Adria to th' Hesperian fields, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er the Celtic roamed the utmost Isles. END
BEGIN NOW All these and more came flocking; but with looks END
BEGIN NOW Downcast and damp; yet such wherein appeared END
BEGIN NOW Obscure some glimpse of joy to have found their Chief END
BEGIN NOW Not in despair, to have found themselves not lost END
BEGIN NOW In loss itself; which on his countenance cast END
BEGIN NOW Like doubtful hue. But he, his wonted pride END
BEGIN NOW Soon recollecting, with high words, that bore END
BEGIN NOW Semblance of worth, not substance, gently raised END
BEGIN NOW Their fainting courage, and dispelled their fears. END
BEGIN NOW Then straight commands that, at the warlike sound END
BEGIN NOW Of trumpets loud and clarions, be upreared END
BEGIN NOW His mighty standard. That proud honour claimed END
BEGIN NOW Azazel as his right, a Cherub tall: END
BEGIN NOW Who forthwith from the glittering staff unfurled END
BEGIN NOW Th' imperial ensign; which, full high advanced, END
BEGIN NOW Shone like a meteor streaming to the wind, END
BEGIN NOW With gems and golden lustre rich emblazed, END
BEGIN NOW Seraphic arms and trophies; all the while END
BEGIN NOW Sonorous metal blowing martial sounds: END
BEGIN NOW At which the universal host up-sent END
BEGIN NOW A shout that tore Hell's concave, and beyond END
BEGIN NOW Frighted the reign of Chaos and old Night. END
BEGIN NOW All in a moment through the gloom were seen END
BEGIN NOW Ten thousand banners rise into the air, END
BEGIN NOW With orient colours waving: with them rose END
BEGIN NOW A forest huge of spears; and thronging helms END
BEGIN NOW Appeared, and serried shields in thick array END
BEGIN NOW Of depth immeasurable. Anon they move END
BEGIN NOW In perfect phalanx to the Dorian mood END
BEGIN NOW Of flutes and soft recorders--such as raised END
BEGIN NOW To height of noblest temper heroes old END
BEGIN NOW Arming to battle, and instead of rage END
BEGIN NOW Deliberate valour breathed, firm, and unmoved END
BEGIN NOW With dread of death to flight or foul retreat; END
BEGIN NOW Nor wanting power to mitigate and swage END
BEGIN NOW With solemn touches troubled thoughts, and chase END
BEGIN NOW Anguish and doubt and fear and sorrow and pain END
BEGIN NOW From mortal or immortal minds. Thus they, END
BEGIN NOW Breathing united force with fixed thought, END
BEGIN NOW Moved on in silence to soft pipes that charmed END
BEGIN NOW Their painful steps o'er the burnt soil. And now END
BEGIN NOW Advanced in view they stand--a horrid front END
BEGIN NOW Of dreadful length and dazzling arms, in guise END
BEGIN NOW Of warriors old, with ordered spear and shield, END
BEGIN NOW Awaiting what command their mighty Chief END
BEGIN NOW Had to impose. He through the armed files END
BEGIN NOW Darts his experienced eye, and soon traverse END
BEGIN NOW The whole battalion views--their order due, END
BEGIN NOW Their visages and stature as of gods; END
BEGIN NOW Their number last he sums. And now his heart END
BEGIN NOW Distends with pride, and, hardening in his strength, END
BEGIN NOW Glories: for never, since created Man, END
BEGIN NOW Met such embodied force as, named with these, END
BEGIN NOW Could merit more than that small infantry END
BEGIN NOW Warred on by cranes--though all the giant brood END
BEGIN NOW Of Phlegra with th' heroic race were joined END
BEGIN NOW That fought at Thebes and Ilium, on each side END
BEGIN NOW Mixed with auxiliar gods; and what resounds END
BEGIN NOW In fable or romance of Uther's son, END
BEGIN NOW Begirt with British and Armoric knights; END
BEGIN NOW And all who since, baptized or infidel, END
BEGIN NOW Or whom Biserta sent from Afric shore END
BEGIN NOW When Charlemain with all his peerage fell END
BEGIN NOW By Fontarabbia. Thus far these beyond END
BEGIN NOW Compare of mortal prowess, yet observed END
BEGIN NOW Their dread Commander. He, above the rest END
BEGIN NOW In shape and gesture proudly eminent, END
BEGIN NOW Stood like a tower. His form had yet not lost END
BEGIN NOW All her original brightness, nor appeared END
BEGIN NOW Less than Archangel ruined, and th' excess END
BEGIN NOW Of glory obscured: as when the sun new-risen END
BEGIN NOW Looks through the horizontal misty air END
BEGIN NOW Shorn of his beams, or, from behind the moon, END
BEGIN NOW In dim eclipse, disastrous twilight sheds END
BEGIN NOW On half the nations, and with fear of change END
BEGIN NOW Perplexes monarchs. Darkened so, yet shone END
BEGIN NOW Above them all th' Archangel: but his face END
BEGIN NOW Deep scars of thunder had intrenched, and care END
BEGIN NOW Sat on his faded cheek, but under brows END
BEGIN NOW Of dauntless courage, and considerate pride END
BEGIN NOW Waiting revenge. Cruel his eye, but cast END
BEGIN NOW Signs of remorse and passion, to behold END
BEGIN NOW The fellows of his crime, the followers rather END
BEGIN NOW (Far other once beheld in bliss), condemned END
BEGIN NOW For ever now to have their lot in pain-- END
BEGIN NOW Millions of Spirits for his fault amerced END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven, and from eternal splendours flung END
BEGIN NOW For his revolt--yet faithful how they stood, END
BEGIN NOW Their glory withered; as, when heaven's fire END
BEGIN NOW Hath scathed the forest oaks or mountain pines, END
BEGIN NOW With singed top their stately growth, though bare, END
BEGIN NOW Stands on the blasted heath. He now prepared END
BEGIN NOW To speak; whereat their doubled ranks they bend END
BEGIN NOW From wing to wing, and half enclose him round END
BEGIN NOW With all his peers: attention held them mute. END
BEGIN NOW Thrice he assayed, and thrice, in spite of scorn, END
BEGIN NOW Tears, such as Angels weep, burst forth: at last END
BEGIN NOW Words interwove with sighs found out their way:-- END
BEGIN NOW O myriads of immortal Spirits! O Powers END
BEGIN NOW Matchless, but with th' Almighty!--and that strife END
BEGIN NOW Was not inglorious, though th' event was dire, END
BEGIN NOW As this place testifies, and this dire change, END
BEGIN NOW Hateful to utter. But what power of mind, END
BEGIN NOW Forseeing or presaging, from the depth END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledge past or present, could have feared END
BEGIN NOW How such united force of gods, how such END
BEGIN NOW As stood like these, could ever know repulse? END
BEGIN NOW For who can yet believe, though after loss, END
BEGIN NOW That all these puissant legions, whose exile END
BEGIN NOW Hath emptied Heaven, shall fail to re-ascend, END
BEGIN NOW Self-raised, and repossess their native seat? END
BEGIN NOW For me, be witness all the host of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW If counsels different, or danger shunned END
BEGIN NOW By me, have lost our hopes. But he who reigns END
BEGIN NOW Monarch in Heaven till then as one secure END
BEGIN NOW Sat on his throne, upheld by old repute, END
BEGIN NOW Consent or custom, and his regal state END
BEGIN NOW Put forth at full, but still his strength concealed-- END
BEGIN NOW Which tempted our attempt, and wrought our fall. END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth his might we know, and know our own, END
BEGIN NOW So as not either to provoke, or dread END
BEGIN NOW New war provoked: our better part remains END
BEGIN NOW To work in close design, by fraud or guile, END
BEGIN NOW What force effected not; that he no less END
BEGIN NOW At length from us may find, who overcomes END
BEGIN NOW By force hath overcome but half his foe. END
BEGIN NOW Space may produce new Worlds; whereof so rife END
BEGIN NOW There went a fame in Heaven that he ere long END
BEGIN NOW Intended to create, and therein plant END
BEGIN NOW A generation whom his choice regard END
BEGIN NOW Should favour equal to the Sons of Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Thither, if but to pry, shall be perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Our first eruption--thither, or elsewhere; END
BEGIN NOW For this infernal pit shall never hold END
BEGIN NOW Celestial Spirits in bondage, nor th' Abyss END
BEGIN NOW Long under darkness cover. But these thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Full counsel must mature. Peace is despaired; END
BEGIN NOW For who can think submission? War, then, war END
BEGIN NOW Open or understood, must be resolved. END
BEGIN NOW He spake; and, to confirm his words, outflew END
BEGIN NOW Millions of flaming swords, drawn from the thighs END
BEGIN NOW Of mighty Cherubim; the sudden blaze END
BEGIN NOW Far round illumined Hell. Highly they raged END
BEGIN NOW Against the Highest, and fierce with grasped arms END
BEGIN NOW Clashed on their sounding shields the din of war, END
BEGIN NOW Hurling defiance toward the vault of Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW There stood a hill not far, whose grisly top END
BEGIN NOW Belched fire and rolling smoke; the rest entire END
BEGIN NOW Shone with a glossy scurf--undoubted sign END
BEGIN NOW That in his womb was hid metallic ore, END
BEGIN NOW The work of sulphur. Thither, winged with speed, END
BEGIN NOW A numerous brigade hastened: as when bands END
BEGIN NOW Forerun the royal camp, to trench a field, END
BEGIN NOW Or cast a rampart. Mammon led them on-- END
BEGIN NOW Mammon, the least erected Spirit that fell END
BEGIN NOW From Heaven; for even in Heaven his looks and thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Were always downward bent, admiring more END
BEGIN NOW The riches of heaven's pavement, trodden gold, END
BEGIN NOW Than aught divine or holy else enjoyed END
BEGIN NOW In vision beatific. By him first END
BEGIN NOW Men also, and by his suggestion taught, END
BEGIN NOW Ransacked the centre, and with impious hands END
BEGIN NOW Rifled the bowels of their mother Earth END
BEGIN NOW For treasures better hid. Soon had his crew END
BEGIN NOW Opened into the hill a spacious wound, END
BEGIN NOW And digged out ribs of gold. Let none admire END
BEGIN NOW That riches grow in Hell; that soil may best END
BEGIN NOW Deserve the precious bane. And here let those END
BEGIN NOW Who boast in mortal things, and wondering tell END
BEGIN NOW Of Babel, and the works of Memphian kings, END
BEGIN NOW Learn how their greatest monuments of fame END
BEGIN NOW And strength, and art, are easily outdone END
BEGIN NOW By Spirits reprobate, and in an hour END
BEGIN NOW What in an age they, with incessant toil END
BEGIN NOW And hands innumerable, scarce perform. END
BEGIN NOW Nigh on the plain, in many cells prepared, END
BEGIN NOW That underneath had veins of liquid fire END
BEGIN NOW Sluiced from the lake, a second multitude END
BEGIN NOW With wondrous art founded the massy ore, END
BEGIN NOW Severing each kind, and scummed the bullion-dross. END
BEGIN NOW A third as soon had formed within the ground END
BEGIN NOW A various mould, and from the boiling cells END
BEGIN NOW By strange conveyance filled each hollow nook; END
BEGIN NOW As in an organ, from one blast of wind, END
BEGIN NOW To many a row of pipes the sound-board breathes. END
BEGIN NOW Anon out of the earth a fabric huge END
BEGIN NOW Rose like an exhalation, with the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of dulcet symphonies and voices sweet-- END
BEGIN NOW Built like a temple, where pilasters round END
BEGIN NOW Were set, and Doric pillars overlaid END
BEGIN NOW With golden architrave; nor did there want END
BEGIN NOW Cornice or frieze, with bossy sculptures graven; END
BEGIN NOW The roof was fretted gold. Not Babylon END
BEGIN NOW Nor great Alcairo such magnificence END
BEGIN NOW Equalled in all their glories, to enshrine END
BEGIN NOW Belus or Serapis their gods, or seat END
BEGIN NOW In wealth and luxury. Th' ascending pile END
BEGIN NOW Stood fixed her stately height, and straight the doors, END
BEGIN NOW Opening their brazen folds, discover, wide END
BEGIN NOW Within, her ample spaces o'er the smooth END
BEGIN NOW And level pavement: from the arched roof, END
BEGIN NOW Pendent by subtle magic, many a row END
BEGIN NOW Of starry lamps and blazing cressets, fed END
BEGIN NOW With naptha and asphaltus, yielded light END
BEGIN NOW As from a sky. The hasty multitude END
BEGIN NOW Admiring entered; and the work some praise, END
BEGIN NOW And some the architect. His hand was known END
BEGIN NOW In Heaven by many a towered structure high, END
BEGIN NOW Where sceptred Angels held their residence, END
BEGIN NOW And sat as Princes, whom the supreme King END
BEGIN NOW Exalted to such power, and gave to rule, END
BEGIN NOW Each in his Hierarchy, the Orders bright. END
BEGIN NOW Nor was his name unheard or unadored END
BEGIN NOW In ancient Greece; and in Ausonian land END
BEGIN NOW Men called him Mulciber; and how he fell END
BEGIN NOW From Heaven they fabled, thrown by angry Jove END
BEGIN NOW Sheer o'er the crystal battlements: from morn END
BEGIN NOW To noon he fell, from noon to dewy eve, END
BEGIN NOW A summer's day, and with the setting sun END
BEGIN NOW Dropt from the zenith, like a falling star, END
BEGIN NOW On Lemnos, th' Aegaean isle. Thus they relate, END
BEGIN NOW Erring; for he with this rebellious rout END
BEGIN NOW Fell long before; nor aught availed him now END
BEGIN NOW To have built in Heaven high towers; nor did he scape END
BEGIN NOW By all his engines, but was headlong sent, END
BEGIN NOW With his industrious crew, to build in Hell. END
BEGIN NOW Meanwhile the winged Heralds, by command END
BEGIN NOW Of sovereign power, with awful ceremony END
BEGIN NOW And trumpet's sound, throughout the host proclaim END
BEGIN NOW A solemn council forthwith to be held END
BEGIN NOW At Pandemonium, the high capital END
BEGIN NOW Of Satan and his peers. Their summons called END
BEGIN NOW From every band and squared regiment END
BEGIN NOW By place or choice the worthiest: they anon END
BEGIN NOW With hundreds and with thousands trooping came END
BEGIN NOW Attended. All access was thronged; the gates END
BEGIN NOW And porches wide, but chief the spacious hall END
BEGIN NOW (Though like a covered field, where champions bold END
BEGIN NOW Wont ride in armed, and at the Soldan's chair END
BEGIN NOW Defied the best of Paynim chivalry END
BEGIN NOW To mortal combat, or career with lance), END
BEGIN NOW Thick swarmed, both on the ground and in the air, END
BEGIN NOW Brushed with the hiss of rustling wings. As bees END
BEGIN NOW In spring-time, when the Sun with Taurus rides. END
BEGIN NOW Pour forth their populous youth about the hive END
BEGIN NOW In clusters; they among fresh dews and flowers END
BEGIN NOW Fly to and fro, or on the smoothed plank, END
BEGIN NOW The suburb of their straw-built citadel, END
BEGIN NOW New rubbed with balm, expatiate, and confer END
BEGIN NOW Their state-affairs: so thick the airy crowd END
BEGIN NOW Swarmed and were straitened; till, the signal given, END
BEGIN NOW Behold a wonder! They but now who seemed END
BEGIN NOW In bigness to surpass Earth's giant sons, END
BEGIN NOW Now less than smallest dwarfs, in narrow room END
BEGIN NOW Throng numberless--like that pygmean race END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the Indian mount; or faery elves, END
BEGIN NOW Whose midnight revels, by a forest-side END
BEGIN NOW Or fountain, some belated peasant sees, END
BEGIN NOW Or dreams he sees, while overhead the Moon END
BEGIN NOW Sits arbitress, and nearer to the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Wheels her pale course: they, on their mirth and dance END
BEGIN NOW Intent, with jocund music charm his ear; END
BEGIN NOW At once with joy and fear his heart rebounds. END
BEGIN NOW Thus incorporeal Spirits to smallest forms END
BEGIN NOW Reduced their shapes immense, and were at large, END
BEGIN NOW Though without number still, amidst the hall END
BEGIN NOW Of that infernal court. But far within, END
BEGIN NOW And in their own dimensions like themselves, END
BEGIN NOW The great Seraphic Lords and Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW In close recess and secret conclave sat, END
BEGIN NOW A thousand demi-gods on golden seats, END
BEGIN NOW Frequent and full. After short silence then, END
BEGIN NOW And summons read, the great consult began. END
BEGIN NOW High on a throne of royal state, which far END
BEGIN NOW Outshone the wealth or Ormus and of Ind, END
BEGIN NOW Or where the gorgeous East with richest hand END
BEGIN NOW Showers on her kings barbaric pearl and gold, END
BEGIN NOW Satan exalted sat, by merit raised END
BEGIN NOW To that bad eminence; and, from despair END
BEGIN NOW Thus high uplifted beyond hope, aspires END
BEGIN NOW Beyond thus high, insatiate to pursue END
BEGIN NOW Vain war with Heaven; and, by success untaught, END
BEGIN NOW His proud imaginations thus displayed:-- END
BEGIN NOW For, since no deep within her gulf can hold END
BEGIN NOW Immortal vigour, though oppressed and fallen, END
BEGIN NOW I give not Heaven for lost: from this descent END
BEGIN NOW Celestial Virtues rising will appear END
BEGIN NOW More glorious and more dread than from no fall, END
BEGIN NOW And trust themselves to fear no second fate!-- END
BEGIN NOW Me though just right, and the fixed laws of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Did first create your leader--next, free choice END
BEGIN NOW With what besides in council or in fight END
BEGIN NOW Hath been achieved of merit--yet this loss, END
BEGIN NOW Thus far at least recovered, hath much more END
BEGIN NOW Established in a safe, unenvied throne, END
BEGIN NOW Yielded with full consent. The happier state END
BEGIN NOW In Heaven, which follows dignity, might draw END
BEGIN NOW Envy from each inferior; but who here END
BEGIN NOW Will envy whom the highest place exposes END
BEGIN NOW Foremost to stand against the Thunderer's aim END
BEGIN NOW Your bulwark, and condemns to greatest share END
BEGIN NOW Of endless pain? Where there is, then, no good END
BEGIN NOW For which to strive, no strife can grow up there END
BEGIN NOW From faction: for none sure will claim in Hell END
BEGIN NOW Precedence; none whose portion is so small END
BEGIN NOW Of present pain that with ambitious mind END
BEGIN NOW Will covet more! With this advantage, then, END
BEGIN NOW To union, and firm faith, and firm accord, END
BEGIN NOW More than can be in Heaven, we now return END
BEGIN NOW To claim our just inheritance of old, END
BEGIN NOW Surer to prosper than prosperity END
BEGIN NOW Could have assured us; and by what best way, END
BEGIN NOW Whether of open war or covert guile, END
BEGIN NOW We now debate. Who can advise may speak. END
BEGIN NOW He ceased; and next him Moloch, sceptred king, END
BEGIN NOW Stood up--the strongest and the fiercest Spirit END
BEGIN NOW That fought in Heaven, now fiercer by despair. END
BEGIN NOW His trust was with th' Eternal to be deemed END
BEGIN NOW Equal in strength, and rather than be less END
BEGIN NOW Cared not to be at all; with that care lost END
BEGIN NOW Went all his fear: of God, or Hell, or worse, END
BEGIN NOW He recked not, and these words thereafter spake:-- END
BEGIN NOW My sentence is for open war. Of wiles, END
BEGIN NOW More unexpert, I boast not: them let those END
BEGIN NOW Contrive who need, or when they need; not now. END
BEGIN NOW For, while they sit contriving, shall the rest-- END
BEGIN NOW Millions that stand in arms, and longing wait END
BEGIN NOW The signal to ascend--sit lingering here, END
BEGIN NOW Heaven's fugitives, and for their dwelling-place END
BEGIN NOW Accept this dark opprobrious den of shame, END
BEGIN NOW The prison of his tyranny who reigns END
BEGIN NOW By our delay? No! let us rather choose, END
BEGIN NOW Armed with Hell-flames and fury, all at once END
BEGIN NOW O'er Heaven's high towers to force resistless way, END
BEGIN NOW Turning our tortures into horrid arms END
BEGIN NOW Against the Torturer; when, to meet the noise END
BEGIN NOW Of his almighty engine, he shall hear END
BEGIN NOW Infernal thunder, and, for lightning, see END
BEGIN NOW Black fire and horror shot with equal rage END
BEGIN NOW Among his Angels, and his throne itself END
BEGIN NOW Mixed with Tartarean sulphur and strange fire, END
BEGIN NOW His own invented torments. But perhaps END
BEGIN NOW The way seems difficult, and steep to scale END
BEGIN NOW With upright wing against a higher foe! END
BEGIN NOW Let such bethink them, if the sleepy drench END
BEGIN NOW Of that forgetful lake benumb not still, END
BEGIN NOW That in our proper motion we ascend END
BEGIN NOW Up to our native seat; descent and fall END
BEGIN NOW To us is adverse. Who but felt of late, END
BEGIN NOW When the fierce foe hung on our broken rear END
BEGIN NOW Insulting, and pursued us through the Deep, END
BEGIN NOW With what compulsion and laborious flight END
BEGIN NOW We sunk thus low? Th' ascent is easy, then; END
BEGIN NOW Th' event is feared! Should we again provoke END
BEGIN NOW Our stronger, some worse way his wrath may find END
BEGIN NOW To our destruction, if there be in Hell END
BEGIN NOW Fear to be worse destroyed! What can be worse END
BEGIN NOW Than to dwell here, driven out from bliss, condemned END
BEGIN NOW In this abhorred deep to utter woe! END
BEGIN NOW Where pain of unextinguishable fire END
BEGIN NOW Must exercise us without hope of end END
BEGIN NOW The vassals of his anger, when the scourge END
BEGIN NOW Inexorably, and the torturing hour, END
BEGIN NOW Calls us to penance? More destroyed than thus, END
BEGIN NOW We should be quite abolished, and expire. END
BEGIN NOW What fear we then? what doubt we to incense END
BEGIN NOW His utmost ire? which, to the height enraged, END
BEGIN NOW Will either quite consume us, and reduce END
BEGIN NOW To nothing this essential--happier far END
BEGIN NOW Than miserable to have eternal being!-- END
BEGIN NOW Or, if our substance be indeed divine, END
BEGIN NOW And cannot cease to be, we are at worst END
BEGIN NOW On this side nothing; and by proof we feel END
BEGIN NOW Our power sufficient to disturb his Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW And with perpetual inroads to alarm, END
BEGIN NOW Though inaccessible, his fatal throne: END
BEGIN NOW Which, if not victory, is yet revenge. END
BEGIN NOW He ended frowning, and his look denounced END
BEGIN NOW Desperate revenge, and battle dangerous END
BEGIN NOW To less than gods. On th' other side up rose END
BEGIN NOW Belial, in act more graceful and humane. END
BEGIN NOW A fairer person lost not Heaven; he seemed END
BEGIN NOW For dignity composed, and high exploit. END
BEGIN NOW But all was false and hollow; though his tongue END
BEGIN NOW Dropped manna, and could make the worse appear END
BEGIN NOW The better reason, to perplex and dash END
BEGIN NOW Maturest counsels: for his thoughts were low-- END
BEGIN NOW To vice industrious, but to nobler deeds END
BEGIN NOW Timorous and slothful. Yet he pleased the ear, END
BEGIN NOW And with persuasive accent thus began:-- END
BEGIN NOW I should be much for open war, O Peers, END
BEGIN NOW As not behind in hate, if what was urged END
BEGIN NOW Main reason to persuade immediate war END
BEGIN NOW Did not dissuade me most, and seem to cast END
BEGIN NOW Ominous conjecture on the whole success; END
BEGIN NOW When he who most excels in fact of arms, END
BEGIN NOW In what he counsels and in what excels END
BEGIN NOW Mistrustful, grounds his courage on despair END
BEGIN NOW And utter dissolution, as the scope END
BEGIN NOW Of all his aim, after some dire revenge. END
BEGIN NOW First, what revenge? The towers of Heaven are filled END
BEGIN NOW With armed watch, that render all access END
BEGIN NOW Impregnable: oft on the bordering Deep END
BEGIN NOW Encamp their legions, or with obscure wing END
BEGIN NOW Scout far and wide into the realm of Night, END
BEGIN NOW Scorning surprise. Or, could we break our way END
BEGIN NOW By force, and at our heels all Hell should rise END
BEGIN NOW With blackest insurrection to confound END
BEGIN NOW Heaven's purest light, yet our great Enemy, END
BEGIN NOW All incorruptible, would on his throne END
BEGIN NOW Sit unpolluted, and th' ethereal mould, END
BEGIN NOW Incapable of stain, would soon expel END
BEGIN NOW Her mischief, and purge off the baser fire, END
BEGIN NOW Victorious. Thus repulsed, our final hope END
BEGIN NOW Is flat despair: we must exasperate END
BEGIN NOW Th' Almighty Victor to spend all his rage; END
BEGIN NOW And that must end us; that must be our cure-- END
BEGIN NOW To be no more. Sad cure! for who would lose, END
BEGIN NOW Though full of pain, this intellectual being, END
BEGIN NOW Those thoughts that wander through eternity, END
BEGIN NOW To perish rather, swallowed up and lost END
BEGIN NOW In the wide womb of uncreated Night, END
BEGIN NOW Devoid of sense and motion? And who knows, END
BEGIN NOW Let this be good, whether our angry Foe END
BEGIN NOW Can give it, or will ever? How he can END
BEGIN NOW Is doubtful; that he never will is sure. END
BEGIN NOW Will he, so wise, let loose at once his ire, END
BEGIN NOW Belike through impotence or unaware, END
BEGIN NOW To give his enemies their wish, and end END
BEGIN NOW Them in his anger whom his anger saves END
BEGIN NOW To punish endless? "Wherefore cease we, then? END
BEGIN NOW Say they who counsel war; "we are decreed, END
BEGIN NOW Reserved, and destined to eternal woe; END
BEGIN NOW Whatever doing, what can we suffer more, END
BEGIN NOW What can we suffer worse?" Is this, then, worst-- END
BEGIN NOW Thus sitting, thus consulting, thus in arms? END
BEGIN NOW What when we fled amain, pursued and struck END
BEGIN NOW With Heaven's afflicting thunder, and besought END
BEGIN NOW The Deep to shelter us? This Hell then seemed END
BEGIN NOW A refuge from those wounds. Or when we lay END
BEGIN NOW Chained on the burning lake? That sure was worse. END
BEGIN NOW What if the breath that kindled those grim fires, END
BEGIN NOW Awaked, should blow them into sevenfold rage, END
BEGIN NOW And plunge us in the flames; or from above END
BEGIN NOW Should intermitted vengeance arm again END
BEGIN NOW His red right hand to plague us? What if all END
BEGIN NOW Her stores were opened, and this firmament END
BEGIN NOW Of Hell should spout her cataracts of fire, END
BEGIN NOW Impendent horrors, threatening hideous fall END
BEGIN NOW One day upon our heads; while we perhaps, END
BEGIN NOW Designing or exhorting glorious war, END
BEGIN NOW Caught in a fiery tempest, shall be hurled, END
BEGIN NOW Each on his rock transfixed, the sport and prey END
BEGIN NOW Or racking whirlwinds, or for ever sunk END
BEGIN NOW Under yon boiling ocean, wrapt in chains, END
BEGIN NOW There to converse with everlasting groans, END
BEGIN NOW Unrespited, unpitied, unreprieved, END
BEGIN NOW Ages of hopeless end? This would be worse. END
BEGIN NOW War, therefore, open or concealed, alike END
BEGIN NOW My voice dissuades; for what can force or guile END
BEGIN NOW With him, or who deceive his mind, whose eye END
BEGIN NOW Views all things at one view? He from Heaven's height END
BEGIN NOW All these our motions vain sees and derides, END
BEGIN NOW Not more almighty to resist our might END
BEGIN NOW Than wise to frustrate all our plots and wiles. END
BEGIN NOW Shall we, then, live thus vile--the race of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Thus trampled, thus expelled, to suffer here END
BEGIN NOW Chains and these torments? Better these than worse, END
BEGIN NOW By my advice; since fate inevitable END
BEGIN NOW Subdues us, and omnipotent decree, END
BEGIN NOW The Victor's will. To suffer, as to do, END
BEGIN NOW Our strength is equal; nor the law unjust END
BEGIN NOW That so ordains. This was at first resolved, END
BEGIN NOW If we were wise, against so great a foe END
BEGIN NOW Contending, and so doubtful what might fall. END
BEGIN NOW I laugh when those who at the spear are bold END
BEGIN NOW And venturous, if that fail them, shrink, and fear END
BEGIN NOW What yet they know must follow--to endure END
BEGIN NOW Exile, or igominy, or bonds, or pain, END
BEGIN NOW The sentence of their Conqueror. This is now END
BEGIN NOW Our doom; which if we can sustain and bear, END
BEGIN NOW Our Supreme Foe in time may much remit END
BEGIN NOW His anger, and perhaps, thus far removed, END
BEGIN NOW Not mind us not offending, satisfied END
BEGIN NOW With what is punished; whence these raging fires END
BEGIN NOW Will slacken, if his breath stir not their flames. END
BEGIN NOW Our purer essence then will overcome END
BEGIN NOW Their noxious vapour; or, inured, not feel; END
BEGIN NOW Or, changed at length, and to the place conformed END
BEGIN NOW In temper and in nature, will receive END
BEGIN NOW Familiar the fierce heat; and, void of pain, END
BEGIN NOW This horror will grow mild, this darkness light; END
BEGIN NOW Besides what hope the never-ending flight END
BEGIN NOW Of future days may bring, what chance, what change END
BEGIN NOW Worth waiting--since our present lot appears END
BEGIN NOW For happy though but ill, for ill not worst, END
BEGIN NOW If we procure not to ourselves more woe. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Belial, with words clothed in reason's garb, END
BEGIN NOW Counselled ignoble ease and peaceful sloth, END
BEGIN NOW Not peace; and after him thus Mammon spake:-- END
BEGIN NOW Either to disenthrone the King of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW We war, if war be best, or to regain END
BEGIN NOW Our own right lost. Him to unthrone we then END
BEGIN NOW May hope, when everlasting Fate shall yield END
BEGIN NOW To fickle Chance, and Chaos judge the strife. END
BEGIN NOW The former, vain to hope, argues as vain END
BEGIN NOW The latter; for what place can be for us END
BEGIN NOW Within Heaven's bound, unless Heaven's Lord supreme END
BEGIN NOW We overpower? Suppose he should relent END
BEGIN NOW And publish grace to all, on promise made END
BEGIN NOW Of new subjection; with what eyes could we END
BEGIN NOW Stand in his presence humble, and receive END
BEGIN NOW Strict laws imposed, to celebrate his throne END
BEGIN NOW With warbled hymns, and to his Godhead sing END
BEGIN NOW Forced hallelujahs, while he lordly sits END
BEGIN NOW Our envied sovereign, and his altar breathes END
BEGIN NOW Ambrosial odours and ambrosial flowers, END
BEGIN NOW Our servile offerings? This must be our task END
BEGIN NOW In Heaven, this our delight. How wearisome END
BEGIN NOW Eternity so spent in worship paid END
BEGIN NOW To whom we hate! Let us not then pursue, END
BEGIN NOW By force impossible, by leave obtained END
BEGIN NOW Unacceptable, though in Heaven, our state END
BEGIN NOW Of splendid vassalage; but rather seek END
BEGIN NOW Our own good from ourselves, and from our own END
BEGIN NOW Live to ourselves, though in this vast recess, END
BEGIN NOW Free and to none accountable, preferring END
BEGIN NOW Hard liberty before the easy yoke END
BEGIN NOW Of servile pomp. Our greatness will appear END
BEGIN NOW Then most conspicuous when great things of small, END
BEGIN NOW Useful of hurtful, prosperous of adverse, END
BEGIN NOW We can create, and in what place soe'er END
BEGIN NOW Thrive under evil, and work ease out of pain END
BEGIN NOW Through labour and endurance. This deep world END
BEGIN NOW Of darkness do we dread? How oft amidst END
BEGIN NOW Thick clouds and dark doth Heaven's all-ruling Sire END
BEGIN NOW Choose to reside, his glory unobscured, END
BEGIN NOW And with the majesty of darkness round END
BEGIN NOW Covers his throne, from whence deep thunders roar. END
BEGIN NOW Mustering their rage, and Heaven resembles Hell! END
BEGIN NOW As he our darkness, cannot we his light END
BEGIN NOW Imitate when we please? This desert soil END
BEGIN NOW Wants not her hidden lustre, gems and gold; END
BEGIN NOW Nor want we skill or art from whence to raise END
BEGIN NOW Magnificence; and what can Heaven show more? END
BEGIN NOW Our torments also may, in length of time, END
BEGIN NOW Become our elements, these piercing fires END
BEGIN NOW As soft as now severe, our temper changed END
BEGIN NOW Into their temper; which must needs remove END
BEGIN NOW The sensible of pain. All things invite END
BEGIN NOW To peaceful counsels, and the settled state END
BEGIN NOW Of order, how in safety best we may END
BEGIN NOW Compose our present evils, with regard END
BEGIN NOW Of what we are and where, dismissing quite END
BEGIN NOW All thoughts of war. Ye have what I advise. END
BEGIN NOW He scarce had finished, when such murmur filled END
BEGIN NOW Th' assembly as when hollow rocks retain END
BEGIN NOW The sound of blustering winds, which all night long END
BEGIN NOW Had roused the sea, now with hoarse cadence lull END
BEGIN NOW Seafaring men o'erwatched, whose bark by chance END
BEGIN NOW Or pinnace, anchors in a craggy bay END
BEGIN NOW After the tempest. Such applause was heard END
BEGIN NOW As Mammon ended, and his sentence pleased, END
BEGIN NOW Advising peace: for such another field END
BEGIN NOW They dreaded worse than Hell; so much the fear END
BEGIN NOW Of thunder and the sword of Michael END
BEGIN NOW Wrought still within them; and no less desire END
BEGIN NOW To found this nether empire, which might rise, END
BEGIN NOW By policy and long process of time, END
BEGIN NOW In emulation opposite to Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Which when Beelzebub perceived--than whom, END
BEGIN NOW Satan except, none higher sat--with grave END
BEGIN NOW Aspect he rose, and in his rising seemed END
BEGIN NOW A pillar of state. Deep on his front engraven END
BEGIN NOW Deliberation sat, and public care; END
BEGIN NOW And princely counsel in his face yet shone, END
BEGIN NOW Majestic, though in ruin. Sage he stood END
BEGIN NOW With Atlantean shoulders, fit to bear END
BEGIN NOW The weight of mightiest monarchies; his look END
BEGIN NOW Drew audience and attention still as night END
BEGIN NOW Or summer's noontide air, while thus he spake:-- END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal Virtues! or these titles now END
BEGIN NOW Must we renounce, and, changing style, be called END
BEGIN NOW Princes of Hell? for so the popular vote END
BEGIN NOW Inclines--here to continue, and build up here END
BEGIN NOW A growing empire; doubtless! while we dream, END
BEGIN NOW And know not that the King of Heaven hath doomed END
BEGIN NOW This place our dungeon, not our safe retreat END
BEGIN NOW Beyond his potent arm, to live exempt END
BEGIN NOW From Heaven's high jurisdiction, in new league END
BEGIN NOW Banded against his throne, but to remain END
BEGIN NOW In strictest bondage, though thus far removed, END
BEGIN NOW Under th' inevitable curb, reserved END
BEGIN NOW His captive multitude. For he, to be sure, END
BEGIN NOW In height or depth, still first and last will reign END
BEGIN NOW Sole king, and of his kingdom lose no part END
BEGIN NOW By our revolt, but over Hell extend END
BEGIN NOW His empire, and with iron sceptre rule END
BEGIN NOW Us here, as with his golden those in Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW What sit we then projecting peace and war? END
BEGIN NOW War hath determined us and foiled with loss END
BEGIN NOW Irreparable; terms of peace yet none END
BEGIN NOW Vouchsafed or sought; for what peace will be given END
BEGIN NOW To us enslaved, but custody severe, END
BEGIN NOW And stripes and arbitrary punishment END
BEGIN NOW Inflicted? and what peace can we return, END
BEGIN NOW But, to our power, hostility and hate, END
BEGIN NOW Untamed reluctance, and revenge, though slow, END
BEGIN NOW Yet ever plotting how the Conqueror least END
BEGIN NOW May reap his conquest, and may least rejoice END
BEGIN NOW In doing what we most in suffering feel? END
BEGIN NOW Nor will occasion want, nor shall we need END
BEGIN NOW With dangerous expedition to invade END
BEGIN NOW Heaven, whose high walls fear no assault or siege, END
BEGIN NOW Or ambush from the Deep. What if we find END
BEGIN NOW Some easier enterprise? There is a place END
BEGIN NOW (If ancient and prophetic fame in Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Err not)--another World, the happy seat END
BEGIN NOW Of some new race, called Man, about this time END
BEGIN NOW To be created like to us, though less END
BEGIN NOW In power and excellence, but favoured more END
BEGIN NOW Of him who rules above; so was his will END
BEGIN NOW Pronounced among the Gods, and by an oath END
BEGIN NOW That shook Heaven's whole circumference confirmed. END
BEGIN NOW Thither let us bend all our thoughts, to learn END
BEGIN NOW What creatures there inhabit, of what mould END
BEGIN NOW Or substance, how endued, and what their power END
BEGIN NOW And where their weakness: how attempted best, END
BEGIN NOW By force of subtlety. Though Heaven be shut, END
BEGIN NOW And Heaven's high Arbitrator sit secure END
BEGIN NOW In his own strength, this place may lie exposed, END
BEGIN NOW The utmost border of his kingdom, left END
BEGIN NOW To their defence who hold it: here, perhaps, END
BEGIN NOW Some advantageous act may be achieved END
BEGIN NOW By sudden onset--either with Hell-fire END
BEGIN NOW To waste his whole creation, or possess END
BEGIN NOW All as our own, and drive, as we were driven, END
BEGIN NOW The puny habitants; or, if not drive, END
BEGIN NOW Seduce them to our party, that their God END
BEGIN NOW May prove their foe, and with repenting hand END
BEGIN NOW Abolish his own works. This would surpass END
BEGIN NOW Common revenge, and interrupt his joy END
BEGIN NOW In our confusion, and our joy upraise END
BEGIN NOW In his disturbance; when his darling sons, END
BEGIN NOW Hurled headlong to partake with us, shall curse END
BEGIN NOW Their frail original, and faded bliss-- END
BEGIN NOW Faded so soon! Advise if this be worth END
BEGIN NOW Attempting, or to sit in darkness here END
BEGIN NOW Hatching vain empires." Thus Beelzebub END
BEGIN NOW Pleaded his devilish counsel--first devised END
BEGIN NOW By Satan, and in part proposed: for whence, END
BEGIN NOW But from the author of all ill, could spring END
BEGIN NOW So deep a malice, to confound the race END
BEGIN NOW Of mankind in one root, and Earth with Hell END
BEGIN NOW To mingle and involve, done all to spite END
BEGIN NOW The great Creator? But their spite still serves END
BEGIN NOW His glory to augment. The bold design END
BEGIN NOW Pleased highly those infernal States, and joy END
BEGIN NOW Sparkled in all their eyes: with full assent END
BEGIN NOW They vote: whereat his speech he thus renews:-- END
BEGIN NOW Well have ye judged, well ended long debate, END
BEGIN NOW Synod of Gods, and, like to what ye are, END
BEGIN NOW Great things resolved, which from the lowest deep END
BEGIN NOW Will once more lift us up, in spite of fate, END
BEGIN NOW Nearer our ancient seat--perhaps in view END
BEGIN NOW Of those bright confines, whence, with neighbouring arms, END
BEGIN NOW And opportune excursion, we may chance END
BEGIN NOW Re-enter Heaven; or else in some mild zone END
BEGIN NOW Dwell, not unvisited of Heaven's fair light, END
BEGIN NOW Secure, and at the brightening orient beam END
BEGIN NOW Purge off this gloom: the soft delicious air, END
BEGIN NOW To heal the scar of these corrosive fires, END
BEGIN NOW Shall breathe her balm. But, first, whom shall we send END
BEGIN NOW In search of this new World? whom shall we find END
BEGIN NOW Sufficient? who shall tempt with wandering feet END
BEGIN NOW The dark, unbottomed, infinite Abyss, END
BEGIN NOW And through the palpable obscure find out END
BEGIN NOW His uncouth way, or spread his airy flight, END
BEGIN NOW Upborne with indefatigable wings END
BEGIN NOW Over the vast abrupt, ere he arrive END
BEGIN NOW The happy Isle? What strength, what art, can then END
BEGIN NOW Suffice, or what evasion bear him safe, END
BEGIN NOW Through the strict senteries and stations thick END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels watching round? Here he had need END
BEGIN NOW All circumspection: and we now no less END
BEGIN NOW Choice in our suffrage; for on whom we send END
BEGIN NOW The weight of all, and our last hope, relies. END
BEGIN NOW This said, he sat; and expectation held END
BEGIN NOW His look suspense, awaiting who appeared END
BEGIN NOW To second, or oppose, or undertake END
BEGIN NOW The perilous attempt. But all sat mute, END
BEGIN NOW Pondering the danger with deep thoughts; and each END
BEGIN NOW In other's countenance read his own dismay, END
BEGIN NOW Astonished. None among the choice and prime END
BEGIN NOW Of those Heaven-warring champions could be found END
BEGIN NOW So hardy as to proffer or accept, END
BEGIN NOW Alone, the dreadful voyage; till, at last, END
BEGIN NOW Satan, whom now transcendent glory raised END
BEGIN NOW Above his fellows, with monarchal pride END
BEGIN NOW Conscious of highest worth, unmoved thus spake:-- END
BEGIN NOW With reason hath deep silence and demur END
BEGIN NOW Seized us, though undismayed. Long is the way END
BEGIN NOW And hard, that out of Hell leads up to light. END
BEGIN NOW Our prison strong, this huge convex of fire, END
BEGIN NOW Outrageous to devour, immures us round END
BEGIN NOW Ninefold; and gates of burning adamant, END
BEGIN NOW Barred over us, prohibit all egress. END
BEGIN NOW These passed, if any pass, the void profound END
BEGIN NOW Of unessential Night receives him next, END
BEGIN NOW Wide-gaping, and with utter loss of being END
BEGIN NOW Threatens him, plunged in that abortive gulf. END
BEGIN NOW If thence he scape, into whatever world, END
BEGIN NOW Or unknown region, what remains him less END
BEGIN NOW Than unknown dangers, and as hard escape? END
BEGIN NOW But I should ill become this throne, O Peers, END
BEGIN NOW And this imperial sovereignty, adorned END
BEGIN NOW With splendour, armed with power, if aught proposed END
BEGIN NOW And judged of public moment in the shape END
BEGIN NOW Of difficulty or danger, could deter END
BEGIN NOW Me from attempting. Wherefore do I assume END
BEGIN NOW These royalties, and not refuse to reign, END
BEGIN NOW Refusing to accept as great a share END
BEGIN NOW Of hazard as of honour, due alike END
BEGIN NOW To him who reigns, and so much to him due END
BEGIN NOW Of hazard more as he above the rest END
BEGIN NOW High honoured sits? Go, therefore, mighty Powers, END
BEGIN NOW Terror of Heaven, though fallen; intend at home, END
BEGIN NOW While here shall be our home, what best may ease END
BEGIN NOW The present misery, and render Hell END
BEGIN NOW More tolerable; if there be cure or charm END
BEGIN NOW To respite, or deceive, or slack the pain END
BEGIN NOW Of this ill mansion: intermit no watch END
BEGIN NOW Against a wakeful foe, while I abroad END
BEGIN NOW Through all the coasts of dark destruction seek END
BEGIN NOW Deliverance for us all. This enterprise END
BEGIN NOW None shall partake with me." Thus saying, rose END
BEGIN NOW The Monarch, and prevented all reply; END
BEGIN NOW Prudent lest, from his resolution raised, END
BEGIN NOW Others among the chief might offer now, END
BEGIN NOW Certain to be refused, what erst they feared, END
BEGIN NOW And, so refused, might in opinion stand END
BEGIN NOW His rivals, winning cheap the high repute END
BEGIN NOW Which he through hazard huge must earn. But they END
BEGIN NOW Dreaded not more th' adventure than his voice END
BEGIN NOW Forbidding; and at once with him they rose. END
BEGIN NOW Their rising all at once was as the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of thunder heard remote. Towards him they bend END
BEGIN NOW With awful reverence prone, and as a God END
BEGIN NOW Extol him equal to the Highest in Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Nor failed they to express how much they praised END
BEGIN NOW That for the general safety he despised END
BEGIN NOW His own: for neither do the Spirits damned END
BEGIN NOW Lose all their virtue; lest bad men should boast END
BEGIN NOW Their specious deeds on earth, which glory excites, END
BEGIN NOW Or close ambition varnished o'er with zeal. END
BEGIN NOW Thus they their doubtful consultations dark END
BEGIN NOW Ended, rejoicing in their matchless Chief: END
BEGIN NOW As, when from mountain-tops the dusky clouds END
BEGIN NOW Ascending, while the north wind sleeps, o'erspread END
BEGIN NOW Heaven's cheerful face, the louring element END
BEGIN NOW Scowls o'er the darkened landscape snow or shower, END
BEGIN NOW If chance the radiant sun, with farewell sweet, END
BEGIN NOW Extend his evening beam, the fields revive, END
BEGIN NOW The birds their notes renew, and bleating herds END
BEGIN NOW Attest their joy, that hill and valley rings. END
BEGIN NOW O shame to men! Devil with devil damned END
BEGIN NOW Firm concord holds; men only disagree END
BEGIN NOW Of creatures rational, though under hope END
BEGIN NOW Of heavenly grace, and, God proclaiming peace, END
BEGIN NOW Yet live in hatred, enmity, and strife END
BEGIN NOW Among themselves, and levy cruel wars END
BEGIN NOW Wasting the earth, each other to destroy: END
BEGIN NOW As if (which might induce us to accord) END
BEGIN NOW Man had not hellish foes enow besides, END
BEGIN NOW That day and night for his destruction wait! END
BEGIN NOW The Stygian council thus dissolved; and forth END
BEGIN NOW In order came the grand infernal Peers: END
BEGIN NOW Midst came their mighty Paramount, and seemed END
BEGIN NOW Alone th' antagonist of Heaven, nor less END
BEGIN NOW Than Hell's dread Emperor, with pomp supreme, END
BEGIN NOW And god-like imitated state: him round END
BEGIN NOW A globe of fiery Seraphim enclosed END
BEGIN NOW With bright emblazonry, and horrent arms. END
BEGIN NOW Then of their session ended they bid cry END
BEGIN NOW With trumpet's regal sound the great result: END
BEGIN NOW Toward the four winds four speedy Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW Put to their mouths the sounding alchemy, END
BEGIN NOW By herald's voice explained; the hollow Abyss END
BEGIN NOW Heard far and wide, and all the host of Hell END
BEGIN NOW With deafening shout returned them loud acclaim. END
BEGIN NOW Thence more at ease their minds, and somewhat raised END
BEGIN NOW By false presumptuous hope, the ranged Powers END
BEGIN NOW Disband; and, wandering, each his several way END
BEGIN NOW Pursues, as inclination or sad choice END
BEGIN NOW Leads him perplexed, where he may likeliest find END
BEGIN NOW Truce to his restless thoughts, and entertain END
BEGIN NOW The irksome hours, till his great Chief return. END
BEGIN NOW Part on the plain, or in the air sublime, END
BEGIN NOW Upon the wing or in swift race contend, END
BEGIN NOW As at th' Olympian games or Pythian fields; END
BEGIN NOW Part curb their fiery steeds, or shun the goal END
BEGIN NOW With rapid wheels, or fronted brigades form: END
BEGIN NOW As when, to warn proud cities, war appears END
BEGIN NOW Waged in the troubled sky, and armies rush END
BEGIN NOW To battle in the clouds; before each van END
BEGIN NOW Prick forth the airy knights, and couch their spears, END
BEGIN NOW Till thickest legions close; with feats of arms END
BEGIN NOW From either end of heaven the welkin burns. END
BEGIN NOW Others, with vast Typhoean rage, more fell, END
BEGIN NOW Rend up both rocks and hills, and ride the air END
BEGIN NOW In whirlwind; Hell scarce holds the wild uproar:-- END
BEGIN NOW As when Alcides, from Oechalia crowned END
BEGIN NOW With conquest, felt th' envenomed robe, and tore END
BEGIN NOW Through pain up by the roots Thessalian pines, END
BEGIN NOW And Lichas from the top of Oeta threw END
BEGIN NOW Into th' Euboic sea. Others, more mild, END
BEGIN NOW Retreated in a silent valley, sing END
BEGIN NOW With notes angelical to many a harp END
BEGIN NOW Their own heroic deeds, and hapless fall END
BEGIN NOW By doom of battle, and complain that Fate END
BEGIN NOW Free Virtue should enthrall to Force or Chance. END
BEGIN NOW Their song was partial; but the harmony END
BEGIN NOW (What could it less when Spirits immortal sing?) END
BEGIN NOW Suspended Hell, and took with ravishment END
BEGIN NOW The thronging audience. In discourse more sweet END
BEGIN NOW (For Eloquence the Soul, Song charms the Sense) END
BEGIN NOW Others apart sat on a hill retired, END
BEGIN NOW In thoughts more elevate, and reasoned high END
BEGIN NOW Fixed fate, free will, foreknowledge absolute, END
BEGIN NOW And found no end, in wandering mazes lost. END
BEGIN NOW Of good and evil much they argued then, END
BEGIN NOW Of happiness and final misery, END
BEGIN NOW Passion and apathy, and glory and shame: END
BEGIN NOW Vain wisdom all, and false philosophy!-- END
BEGIN NOW Yet, with a pleasing sorcery, could charm END
BEGIN NOW Pain for a while or anguish, and excite END
BEGIN NOW Fallacious hope, or arm th' obdured breast END
BEGIN NOW With stubborn patience as with triple steel. END
BEGIN NOW Another part, in squadrons and gross bands, END
BEGIN NOW On bold adventure to discover wide END
BEGIN NOW That dismal world, if any clime perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Might yield them easier habitation, bend END
BEGIN NOW Four ways their flying march, along the banks END
BEGIN NOW Of four infernal rivers, that disgorge END
BEGIN NOW Into the burning lake their baleful streams-- END
BEGIN NOW Abhorred Styx, the flood of deadly hate; END
BEGIN NOW Sad Acheron of sorrow, black and deep; END
BEGIN NOW Cocytus, named of lamentation loud END
BEGIN NOW Heard on the rueful stream; fierce Phlegeton, END
BEGIN NOW Whose waves of torrent fire inflame with rage. END
BEGIN NOW Far off from these, a slow and silent stream, END
BEGIN NOW Lethe, the river of oblivion, rolls END
BEGIN NOW Her watery labyrinth, whereof who drinks END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith his former state and being forgets-- END
BEGIN NOW Forgets both joy and grief, pleasure and pain. END
BEGIN NOW Beyond this flood a frozen continent END
BEGIN NOW Lies dark and wild, beat with perpetual storms END
BEGIN NOW Of whirlwind and dire hail, which on firm land END
BEGIN NOW Thaws not, but gathers heap, and ruin seems END
BEGIN NOW Of ancient pile; all else deep snow and ice, END
BEGIN NOW A gulf profound as that Serbonian bog END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt Damiata and Mount Casius old, END
BEGIN NOW Where armies whole have sunk: the parching air END
BEGIN NOW Burns frore, and cold performs th' effect of fire. END
BEGIN NOW Thither, by harpy-footed Furies haled, END
BEGIN NOW At certain revolutions all the damned END
BEGIN NOW Are brought; and feel by turns the bitter change END
BEGIN NOW Of fierce extremes, extremes by change more fierce, END
BEGIN NOW From beds of raging fire to starve in ice END
BEGIN NOW Their soft ethereal warmth, and there to pine END
BEGIN NOW Immovable, infixed, and frozen round END
BEGIN NOW Periods of time,--thence hurried back to fire. END
BEGIN NOW They ferry over this Lethean sound END
BEGIN NOW Both to and fro, their sorrow to augment, END
BEGIN NOW And wish and struggle, as they pass, to reach END
BEGIN NOW The tempting stream, with one small drop to lose END
BEGIN NOW In sweet forgetfulness all pain and woe, END
BEGIN NOW All in one moment, and so near the brink; END
BEGIN NOW But Fate withstands, and, to oppose th' attempt, END
BEGIN NOW Medusa with Gorgonian terror guards END
BEGIN NOW The ford, and of itself the water flies END
BEGIN NOW All taste of living wight, as once it fled END
BEGIN NOW The lip of Tantalus. Thus roving on END
BEGIN NOW In confused march forlorn, th' adventurous bands, END
BEGIN NOW With shuddering horror pale, and eyes aghast, END
BEGIN NOW Viewed first their lamentable lot, and found END
BEGIN NOW No rest. Through many a dark and dreary vale END
BEGIN NOW They passed, and many a region dolorous, END
BEGIN NOW O'er many a frozen, many a fiery alp, END
BEGIN NOW Rocks, caves, lakes, fens, bogs, dens, and shades of death-- END
BEGIN NOW A universe of death, which God by curse END
BEGIN NOW Created evil, for evil only good; END
BEGIN NOW Where all life dies, death lives, and Nature breeds, END
BEGIN NOW Perverse, all monstrous, all prodigious things, END
BEGIN NOW Obominable, inutterable, and worse END
BEGIN NOW Than fables yet have feigned or fear conceived, END
BEGIN NOW Gorgons, and Hydras, and Chimeras dire. END
BEGIN NOW Satan, with thoughts inflamed of highest design, END
BEGIN NOW Puts on swift wings, and toward the gates of Hell END
BEGIN NOW Explores his solitary flight: sometimes END
BEGIN NOW He scours the right hand coast, sometimes the left; END
BEGIN NOW Now shaves with level wing the deep, then soars END
BEGIN NOW Up to the fiery concave towering high. END
BEGIN NOW As when far off at sea a fleet descried END
BEGIN NOW Hangs in the clouds, by equinoctial winds END
BEGIN NOW Close sailing from Bengala, or the isles END
BEGIN NOW Of Ternate and Tidore, whence merchants bring END
BEGIN NOW Their spicy drugs; they on the trading flood, END
BEGIN NOW Through the wide Ethiopian to the Cape, END
BEGIN NOW Ply stemming nightly toward the pole: so seemed END
BEGIN NOW Far off the flying Fiend. At last appear END
BEGIN NOW Hell-bounds, high reaching to the horrid roof, END
BEGIN NOW And thrice threefold the gates; three folds were brass, END
BEGIN NOW Three iron, three of adamantine rock, END
BEGIN NOW Impenetrable, impaled with circling fire, END
BEGIN NOW Yet unconsumed. Before the gates there sat END
BEGIN NOW On either side a formidable Shape. END
BEGIN NOW The one seemed woman to the waist, and fair, END
BEGIN NOW But ended foul in many a scaly fold, END
BEGIN NOW Voluminous and vast--a serpent armed END
BEGIN NOW With mortal sting. About her middle round END
BEGIN NOW A cry of Hell-hounds never-ceasing barked END
BEGIN NOW With wide Cerberean mouths full loud, and rung END
BEGIN NOW A hideous peal; yet, when they list, would creep, END
BEGIN NOW If aught disturbed their noise, into her womb, END
BEGIN NOW And kennel there; yet there still barked and howled END
BEGIN NOW Within unseen. Far less abhorred than these END
BEGIN NOW Vexed Scylla, bathing in the sea that parts END
BEGIN NOW Calabria from the hoarse Trinacrian shore; END
BEGIN NOW Nor uglier follow the night-hag, when, called END
BEGIN NOW In secret, riding through the air she comes, END
BEGIN NOW Lured with the smell of infant blood, to dance END
BEGIN NOW With Lapland witches, while the labouring moon END
BEGIN NOW Eclipses at their charms. The other Shape-- END
BEGIN NOW If shape it might be called that shape had none END
BEGIN NOW Distinguishable in member, joint, or limb; END
BEGIN NOW Or substance might be called that shadow seemed, END
BEGIN NOW For each seemed either--black it stood as Night, END
BEGIN NOW Fierce as ten Furies, terrible as Hell, END
BEGIN NOW And shook a dreadful dart: what seemed his head END
BEGIN NOW The likeness of a kingly crown had on. END
BEGIN NOW Satan was now at hand, and from his seat END
BEGIN NOW The monster moving onward came as fast END
BEGIN NOW With horrid strides; Hell trembled as he strode. END
BEGIN NOW Th' undaunted Fiend what this might be admired-- END
BEGIN NOW Admired, not feared (God and his Son except, END
BEGIN NOW Created thing naught valued he nor shunned), END
BEGIN NOW And with disdainful look thus first began:-- END
BEGIN NOW Whence and what art thou, execrable Shape, END
BEGIN NOW That dar'st, though grim and terrible, advance END
BEGIN NOW Thy miscreated front athwart my way END
BEGIN NOW To yonder gates? Through them I mean to pass, END
BEGIN NOW That be assured, without leave asked of thee. END
BEGIN NOW Retire; or taste thy folly, and learn by proof, END
BEGIN NOW Hell-born, not to contend with Spirits of Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Goblin, full of wrath, replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Art thou that traitor Angel? art thou he, END
BEGIN NOW Who first broke peace in Heaven and faith, till then END
BEGIN NOW Unbroken, and in proud rebellious arms END
BEGIN NOW Drew after him the third part of Heaven's sons, END
BEGIN NOW Conjured against the Highest--for which both thou END
BEGIN NOW And they, outcast from God, are here condemned END
BEGIN NOW To waste eternal days in woe and pain? END
BEGIN NOW And reckon'st thou thyself with Spirits of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Hell-doomed, and breath'st defiance here and scorn, END
BEGIN NOW Where I reign king, and, to enrage thee more, END
BEGIN NOW Thy king and lord? Back to thy punishment, END
BEGIN NOW False fugitive; and to thy speed add wings, END
BEGIN NOW Lest with a whip of scorpions I pursue END
BEGIN NOW Thy lingering, or with one stroke of this dart END
BEGIN NOW Strange horror seize thee, and pangs unfelt before. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the grisly Terror, and in shape, END
BEGIN NOW So speaking and so threatening, grew tenfold, END
BEGIN NOW More dreadful and deform. On th' other side, END
BEGIN NOW Incensed with indignation, Satan stood END
BEGIN NOW Unterrified, and like a comet burned, END
BEGIN NOW That fires the length of Ophiuchus huge END
BEGIN NOW In th' arctic sky, and from his horrid hair END
BEGIN NOW Shakes pestilence and war. Each at the head END
BEGIN NOW Levelled his deadly aim; their fatal hands END
BEGIN NOW No second stroke intend; and such a frown END
BEGIN NOW Each cast at th' other as when two black clouds, END
BEGIN NOW With heaven's artillery fraught, came rattling on END
BEGIN NOW Over the Caspian,--then stand front to front END
BEGIN NOW Hovering a space, till winds the signal blow END
BEGIN NOW To join their dark encounter in mid-air. END
BEGIN NOW So frowned the mighty combatants that Hell END
BEGIN NOW Grew darker at their frown; so matched they stood; END
BEGIN NOW For never but once more was wither like END
BEGIN NOW To meet so great a foe. And now great deeds END
BEGIN NOW Had been achieved, whereof all Hell had rung, END
BEGIN NOW Had not the snaky Sorceress, that sat END
BEGIN NOW Fast by Hell-gate and kept the fatal key, END
BEGIN NOW Risen, and with hideous outcry rushed between. END
BEGIN NOW O father, what intends thy hand," she cried, END
BEGIN NOW Against thy only son? What fury, O son, END
BEGIN NOW Possesses thee to bend that mortal dart END
BEGIN NOW Against thy father's head? And know'st for whom? END
BEGIN NOW For him who sits above, and laughs the while END
BEGIN NOW At thee, ordained his drudge to execute END
BEGIN NOW Whate'er his wrath, which he calls justice, bids-- END
BEGIN NOW His wrath, which one day will destroy ye both! END
BEGIN NOW She spake, and at her words the hellish Pest END
BEGIN NOW Forbore: then these to her Satan returned:-- END
BEGIN NOW So strange thy outcry, and thy words so strange END
BEGIN NOW Thou interposest, that my sudden hand, END
BEGIN NOW Prevented, spares to tell thee yet by deeds END
BEGIN NOW What it intends, till first I know of thee END
BEGIN NOW What thing thou art, thus double-formed, and why, END
BEGIN NOW In this infernal vale first met, thou call'st END
BEGIN NOW Me father, and that phantasm call'st my son. END
BEGIN NOW I know thee not, nor ever saw till now END
BEGIN NOW Sight more detestable than him and thee. END
BEGIN NOW T' whom thus the Portress of Hell-gate replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Hast thou forgot me, then; and do I seem END
BEGIN NOW Now in thine eye so foul?--once deemed so fair END
BEGIN NOW In Heaven, when at th' assembly, and in sight END
BEGIN NOW Of all the Seraphim with thee combined END
BEGIN NOW In bold conspiracy against Heaven's King, END
BEGIN NOW All on a sudden miserable pain END
BEGIN NOW Surprised thee, dim thine eyes and dizzy swum END
BEGIN NOW In darkness, while thy head flames thick and fast END
BEGIN NOW Threw forth, till on the left side opening wide, END
BEGIN NOW Likest to thee in shape and countenance bright, END
BEGIN NOW Then shining heavenly fair, a goddess armed, END
BEGIN NOW Out of thy head I sprung. Amazement seized END
BEGIN NOW All th' host of Heaven; back they recoiled afraid END
BEGIN NOW At first, and called me Sin, and for a sign END
BEGIN NOW Portentous held me; but, familiar grown, END
BEGIN NOW I pleased, and with attractive graces won END
BEGIN NOW The most averse--thee chiefly, who, full oft END
BEGIN NOW Thyself in me thy perfect image viewing, END
BEGIN NOW Becam'st enamoured; and such joy thou took'st END
BEGIN NOW With me in secret that my womb conceived END
BEGIN NOW A growing burden. Meanwhile war arose, END
BEGIN NOW And fields were fought in Heaven: wherein remained END
BEGIN NOW (For what could else?) to our Almighty Foe END
BEGIN NOW Clear victory; to our part loss and rout END
BEGIN NOW Through all the Empyrean. Down they fell, END
BEGIN NOW Driven headlong from the pitch of Heaven, down END
BEGIN NOW Into this Deep; and in the general fall END
BEGIN NOW I also: at which time this powerful key END
BEGIN NOW Into my hands was given, with charge to keep END
BEGIN NOW These gates for ever shut, which none can pass END
BEGIN NOW Without my opening. Pensive here I sat END
BEGIN NOW Alone; but long I sat not, till my womb, END
BEGIN NOW Pregnant by thee, and now excessive grown, END
BEGIN NOW Prodigious motion felt and rueful throes. END
BEGIN NOW At last this odious offspring whom thou seest, END
BEGIN NOW Thine own begotten, breaking violent way, END
BEGIN NOW Tore through my entrails, that, with fear and pain END
BEGIN NOW Distorted, all my nether shape thus grew END
BEGIN NOW Transformed: but he my inbred enemy END
BEGIN NOW Forth issued, brandishing his fatal dart, END
BEGIN NOW Made to destroy. I fled, and cried out Death! END
BEGIN NOW Hell trembled at the hideous name, and sighed END
BEGIN NOW From all her caves, and back resounded Death! END
BEGIN NOW I fled; but he pursued (though more, it seems, END
BEGIN NOW Inflamed with lust than rage), and, swifter far, END
BEGIN NOW Me overtook, his mother, all dismayed, END
BEGIN NOW And, in embraces forcible and foul END
BEGIN NOW Engendering with me, of that rape begot END
BEGIN NOW These yelling monsters, that with ceaseless cry END
BEGIN NOW Surround me, as thou saw'st--hourly conceived END
BEGIN NOW And hourly born, with sorrow infinite END
BEGIN NOW To me; for, when they list, into the womb END
BEGIN NOW That bred them they return, and howl, and gnaw END
BEGIN NOW My bowels, their repast; then, bursting forth END
BEGIN NOW Afresh, with conscious terrors vex me round, END
BEGIN NOW That rest or intermission none I find. END
BEGIN NOW Before mine eyes in opposition sits END
BEGIN NOW Grim Death, my son and foe, who set them on, END
BEGIN NOW And me, his parent, would full soon devour END
BEGIN NOW For want of other prey, but that he knows END
BEGIN NOW His end with mine involved, and knows that I END
BEGIN NOW Should prove a bitter morsel, and his bane, END
BEGIN NOW Whenever that shall be: so Fate pronounced. END
BEGIN NOW But thou, O father, I forewarn thee, shun END
BEGIN NOW His deadly arrow; neither vainly hope END
BEGIN NOW To be invulnerable in those bright arms, END
BEGIN NOW Through tempered heavenly; for that mortal dint, END
BEGIN NOW Save he who reigns above, none can resist. END
BEGIN NOW She finished; and the subtle Fiend his lore END
BEGIN NOW Soon learned, now milder, and thus answered smooth:-- END
BEGIN NOW Dear daughter--since thou claim'st me for thy sire, END
BEGIN NOW And my fair son here show'st me, the dear pledge END
BEGIN NOW Of dalliance had with thee in Heaven, and joys END
BEGIN NOW Then sweet, now sad to mention, through dire change END
BEGIN NOW Befallen us unforeseen, unthought-of--know, END
BEGIN NOW I come no enemy, but to set free END
BEGIN NOW From out this dark and dismal house of pain END
BEGIN NOW Both him and thee, and all the heavenly host END
BEGIN NOW Of Spirits that, in our just pretences armed, END
BEGIN NOW Fell with us from on high. From them I go END
BEGIN NOW This uncouth errand sole, and one for all END
BEGIN NOW Myself expose, with lonely steps to tread END
BEGIN NOW Th' unfounded Deep, and through the void immense END
BEGIN NOW To search, with wandering quest, a place foretold END
BEGIN NOW Should be--and, by concurring signs, ere now END
BEGIN NOW Created vast and round--a place of bliss END
BEGIN NOW In the purlieus of Heaven; and therein placed END
BEGIN NOW A race of upstart creatures, to supply END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps our vacant room, though more removed, END
BEGIN NOW Lest Heaven, surcharged with potent multitude, END
BEGIN NOW Might hap to move new broils. Be this, or aught END
BEGIN NOW Than this more secret, now designed, I haste END
BEGIN NOW To know; and, this once known, shall soon return, END
BEGIN NOW And bring ye to the place where thou and Death END
BEGIN NOW Shall dwell at ease, and up and down unseen END
BEGIN NOW Wing silently the buxom air, embalmed END
BEGIN NOW With odours. There ye shall be fed and filled END
BEGIN NOW Immeasurably; all things shall be your prey. END
BEGIN NOW He ceased; for both seemed highly pleased, and Death END
BEGIN NOW Grinned horrible a ghastly smile, to hear END
BEGIN NOW His famine should be filled, and blessed his maw END
BEGIN NOW Destined to that good hour. No less rejoiced END
BEGIN NOW His mother bad, and thus bespake her sire:-- END
BEGIN NOW The key of this infernal Pit, by due END
BEGIN NOW And by command of Heaven's all-powerful King, END
BEGIN NOW I keep, by him forbidden to unlock END
BEGIN NOW These adamantine gates; against all force END
BEGIN NOW Death ready stands to interpose his dart, END
BEGIN NOW Fearless to be o'ermatched by living might. END
BEGIN NOW But what owe I to his commands above, END
BEGIN NOW Who hates me, and hath hither thrust me down END
BEGIN NOW Into this gloom of Tartarus profound, END
BEGIN NOW To sit in hateful office here confined, END
BEGIN NOW Inhabitant of Heaven and heavenly born-- END
BEGIN NOW Here in perpetual agony and pain, END
BEGIN NOW With terrors and with clamours compassed round END
BEGIN NOW Of mine own brood, that on my bowels feed? END
BEGIN NOW Thou art my father, thou my author, thou END
BEGIN NOW My being gav'st me; whom should I obey END
BEGIN NOW But thee? whom follow? Thou wilt bring me soon END
BEGIN NOW To that new world of light and bliss, among END
BEGIN NOW The gods who live at ease, where I shall reign END
BEGIN NOW At thy right hand voluptuous, as beseems END
BEGIN NOW Thy daughter and thy darling, without end. END
BEGIN NOW Thus saying, from her side the fatal key, END
BEGIN NOW Sad instrument of all our woe, she took; END
BEGIN NOW And, towards the gate rolling her bestial train, END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith the huge portcullis high up-drew, END
BEGIN NOW Which, but herself, not all the Stygian Powers END
BEGIN NOW Could once have moved; then in the key-hole turns END
BEGIN NOW Th' intricate wards, and every bolt and bar END
BEGIN NOW Of massy iron or solid rock with ease END
BEGIN NOW Unfastens. On a sudden open fly, END
BEGIN NOW With impetuous recoil and jarring sound, END
BEGIN NOW Th' infernal doors, and on their hinges grate END
BEGIN NOW Harsh thunder, that the lowest bottom shook END
BEGIN NOW Of Erebus. She opened; but to shut END
BEGIN NOW Excelled her power: the gates wide open stood, END
BEGIN NOW That with extended wings a bannered host, END
BEGIN NOW Under spread ensigns marching, might pass through END
BEGIN NOW With horse and chariots ranked in loose array; END
BEGIN NOW So wide they stood, and like a furnace-mouth END
BEGIN NOW Cast forth redounding smoke and ruddy flame. END
BEGIN NOW Before their eyes in sudden view appear END
BEGIN NOW The secrets of the hoary Deep--a dark END
BEGIN NOW Illimitable ocean, without bound, END
BEGIN NOW Without dimension; where length, breadth, and height, END
BEGIN NOW And time, and place, are lost; where eldest Night END
BEGIN NOW And Chaos, ancestors of Nature, hold END
BEGIN NOW Eternal anarchy, amidst the noise END
BEGIN NOW Of endless wars, and by confusion stand. END
BEGIN NOW For Hot, Cold, Moist, and Dry, four champions fierce, END
BEGIN NOW Strive here for mastery, and to battle bring END
BEGIN NOW Their embryon atoms: they around the flag END
BEGIN NOW Of each his faction, in their several clans, END
BEGIN NOW Light-armed or heavy, sharp, smooth, swift, or slow, END
BEGIN NOW Swarm populous, unnumbered as the sands END
BEGIN NOW Of Barca or Cyrene's torrid soil, END
BEGIN NOW Levied to side with warring winds, and poise END
BEGIN NOW Their lighter wings. To whom these most adhere END
BEGIN NOW He rules a moment: Chaos umpire sits, END
BEGIN NOW And by decision more embroils the fray END
BEGIN NOW By which he reigns: next him, high arbiter, END
BEGIN NOW Chance governs all. Into this wild Abyss, END
BEGIN NOW The womb of Nature, and perhaps her grave, END
BEGIN NOW Of neither sea, nor shore, nor air, nor fire, END
BEGIN NOW But all these in their pregnant causes mixed END
BEGIN NOW Confusedly, and which thus must ever fight, END
BEGIN NOW Unless th' Almighty Maker them ordain END
BEGIN NOW His dark materials to create more worlds-- END
BEGIN NOW Into this wild Abyss the wary Fiend END
BEGIN NOW Stood on the brink of Hell and looked a while, END
BEGIN NOW Pondering his voyage; for no narrow frith END
BEGIN NOW He had to cross. Nor was his ear less pealed END
BEGIN NOW With noises loud and ruinous (to compare END
BEGIN NOW Great things with small) than when Bellona storms END
BEGIN NOW With all her battering engines, bent to rase END
BEGIN NOW Some capital city; or less than if this frame END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven were falling, and these elements END
BEGIN NOW In mutiny had from her axle torn END
BEGIN NOW The steadfast Earth. At last his sail-broad vans END
BEGIN NOW He spread for flight, and, in the surging smoke END
BEGIN NOW Uplifted, spurns the ground; thence many a league, END
BEGIN NOW As in a cloudy chair, ascending rides END
BEGIN NOW Audacious; but, that seat soon failing, meets END
BEGIN NOW A vast vacuity. All unawares, END
BEGIN NOW Fluttering his pennons vain, plumb-down he drops END
BEGIN NOW Ten thousand fathom deep, and to this hour END
BEGIN NOW Down had been falling, had not, by ill chance, END
BEGIN NOW The strong rebuff of some tumultuous cloud, END
BEGIN NOW Instinct with fire and nitre, hurried him END
BEGIN NOW As many miles aloft. That fury stayed-- END
BEGIN NOW Quenched in a boggy Syrtis, neither sea, END
BEGIN NOW Nor good dry land--nigh foundered, on he fares, END
BEGIN NOW Treading the crude consistence, half on foot, END
BEGIN NOW Half flying; behoves him now both oar and sail. END
BEGIN NOW As when a gryphon through the wilderness END
BEGIN NOW With winged course, o'er hill or moory dale, END
BEGIN NOW Pursues the Arimaspian, who by stealth END
BEGIN NOW Had from his wakeful custody purloined END
BEGIN NOW The guarded gold; so eagerly the Fiend END
BEGIN NOW O'er bog or steep, through strait, rough, dense, or rare, END
BEGIN NOW With head, hands, wings, or feet, pursues his way, END
BEGIN NOW And swims, or sinks, or wades, or creeps, or flies. END
BEGIN NOW At length a universal hubbub wild END
BEGIN NOW Of stunning sounds, and voices all confused, END
BEGIN NOW Borne through the hollow dark, assaults his ear END
BEGIN NOW With loudest vehemence. Thither he plies END
BEGIN NOW Undaunted, to meet there whatever Power END
BEGIN NOW Or Spirit of the nethermost Abyss END
BEGIN NOW Might in that noise reside, of whom to ask END
BEGIN NOW Which way the nearest coast of darkness lies END
BEGIN NOW Bordering on light; when straight behold the throne END
BEGIN NOW Of Chaos, and his dark pavilion spread END
BEGIN NOW Wide on the wasteful Deep! With him enthroned END
BEGIN NOW Sat sable-vested Night, eldest of things, END
BEGIN NOW The consort of his reign; and by them stood END
BEGIN NOW Orcus and Ades, and the dreaded name END
BEGIN NOW Of Demogorgon; Rumour next, and Chance, END
BEGIN NOW And Tumult, and Confusion, all embroiled, END
BEGIN NOW And Discord with a thousand various mouths. END
BEGIN NOW T' whom Satan, turning boldly, thus:--"Ye Powers END
BEGIN NOW And Spirits of this nethermost Abyss, END
BEGIN NOW Chaos and ancient Night, I come no spy END
BEGIN NOW With purpose to explore or to disturb END
BEGIN NOW The secrets of your realm; but, by constraint END
BEGIN NOW Wandering this darksome desert, as my way END
BEGIN NOW Lies through your spacious empire up to light, END
BEGIN NOW Alone and without guide, half lost, I seek, END
BEGIN NOW What readiest path leads where your gloomy bounds END
BEGIN NOW Confine with Heaven; or, if some other place, END
BEGIN NOW From your dominion won, th' Ethereal King END
BEGIN NOW Possesses lately, thither to arrive END
BEGIN NOW I travel this profound. Direct my course: END
BEGIN NOW Directed, no mean recompense it brings END
BEGIN NOW To your behoof, if I that region lost, END
BEGIN NOW All usurpation thence expelled, reduce END
BEGIN NOW To her original darkness and your sway END
BEGIN NOW (Which is my present journey), and once more END
BEGIN NOW Erect the standard there of ancient Night. END
BEGIN NOW Yours be th' advantage all, mine the revenge! END
BEGIN NOW Thus Satan; and him thus the Anarch old, END
BEGIN NOW With faltering speech and visage incomposed, END
BEGIN NOW Answered: "I know thee, stranger, who thou art-- END
BEGIN NOW That mighty leading Angel, who of late END
BEGIN NOW Made head against Heaven's King, though overthrown. END
BEGIN NOW I saw and heard; for such a numerous host END
BEGIN NOW Fled not in silence through the frighted Deep, END
BEGIN NOW With ruin upon ruin, rout on rout, END
BEGIN NOW Confusion worse confounded; and Heaven-gates END
BEGIN NOW Poured out by millions her victorious bands, END
BEGIN NOW Pursuing. I upon my frontiers here END
BEGIN NOW Keep residence; if all I can will serve END
BEGIN NOW That little which is left so to defend, END
BEGIN NOW Encroached on still through our intestine broils END
BEGIN NOW Weakening the sceptre of old Night: first, Hell, END
BEGIN NOW Your dungeon, stretching far and wide beneath; END
BEGIN NOW Now lately Heaven and Earth, another world END
BEGIN NOW Hung o'er my realm, linked in a golden chain END
BEGIN NOW To that side Heaven from whence your legions fell! END
BEGIN NOW If that way be your walk, you have not far; END
BEGIN NOW So much the nearer danger. Go, and speed; END
BEGIN NOW Havoc, and spoil, and ruin, are my gain. END
BEGIN NOW He ceased; and Satan stayed not to reply, END
BEGIN NOW But, glad that now his sea should find a shore, END
BEGIN NOW With fresh alacrity and force renewed END
BEGIN NOW Springs upward, like a pyramid of fire, END
BEGIN NOW Into the wild expanse, and through the shock END
BEGIN NOW Of fighting elements, on all sides round END
BEGIN NOW Environed, wins his way; harder beset END
BEGIN NOW And more endangered than when Argo passed END
BEGIN NOW Through Bosporus betwixt the justling rocks, END
BEGIN NOW Or when Ulysses on the larboard shunned END
BEGIN NOW Charybdis, and by th' other whirlpool steered. END
BEGIN NOW So he with difficulty and labour hard END
BEGIN NOW Moved on, with difficulty and labour he; END
BEGIN NOW But, he once passed, soon after, when Man fell, END
BEGIN NOW Strange alteration! Sin and Death amain, END
BEGIN NOW Following his track (such was the will of Heaven) END
BEGIN NOW Paved after him a broad and beaten way END
BEGIN NOW Over the dark Abyss, whose boiling gulf END
BEGIN NOW Tamely endured a bridge of wondrous length, END
BEGIN NOW From Hell continued, reaching th' utmost orb END
BEGIN NOW Of this frail World; by which the Spirits perverse END
BEGIN NOW With easy intercourse pass to and fro END
BEGIN NOW To tempt or punish mortals, except whom END
BEGIN NOW God and good Angels guard by special grace. END
BEGIN NOW But now at last the sacred influence END
BEGIN NOW Of light appears, and from the walls of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Shoots far into the bosom of dim Night END
BEGIN NOW A glimmering dawn. Here Nature first begins END
BEGIN NOW Her farthest verge, and Chaos to retire, END
BEGIN NOW As from her outmost works, a broken foe, END
BEGIN NOW With tumult less and with less hostile din; END
BEGIN NOW That Satan with less toil, and now with ease, END
BEGIN NOW Wafts on the calmer wave by dubious light, END
BEGIN NOW And, like a weather-beaten vessel, holds END
BEGIN NOW Gladly the port, though shrouds and tackle torn; END
BEGIN NOW Or in the emptier waste, resembling air, END
BEGIN NOW Weighs his spread wings, at leisure to behold END
BEGIN NOW Far off th' empyreal Heaven, extended wide END
BEGIN NOW In circuit, undetermined square or round, END
BEGIN NOW With opal towers and battlements adorned END
BEGIN NOW Of living sapphire, once his native seat; END
BEGIN NOW And, fast by, hanging in a golden chain, END
BEGIN NOW This pendent World, in bigness as a star END
BEGIN NOW Of smallest magnitude close by the moon. END
BEGIN NOW Thither, full fraught with mischievous revenge, END
BEGIN NOW Accursed, and in a cursed hour, he hies. END
BEGIN NOW Hail, holy Light, offspring of Heaven firstborn, END
BEGIN NOW Or of the Eternal coeternal beam END
BEGIN NOW May I express thee unblam'd? since God is light, END
BEGIN NOW And never but in unapproached light END
BEGIN NOW Dwelt from eternity, dwelt then in thee END
BEGIN NOW Bright effluence of bright essence increate. END
BEGIN NOW Or hear'st thou rather pure ethereal stream, END
BEGIN NOW Whose fountain who shall tell? before the sun, END
BEGIN NOW Before the Heavens thou wert, and at the voice END
BEGIN NOW Of God, as with a mantle, didst invest END
BEGIN NOW The rising world of waters dark and deep, END
BEGIN NOW Won from the void and formless infinite. END
BEGIN NOW Thee I re-visit now with bolder wing, END
BEGIN NOW Escap'd the Stygian pool, though long detain'd END
BEGIN NOW In that obscure sojourn, while in my flight END
BEGIN NOW Through utter and through middle darkness borne, END
BEGIN NOW With other notes than to the Orphean lyre END
BEGIN NOW I sung of Chaos and eternal Night; END
BEGIN NOW Taught by the heavenly Muse to venture down END
BEGIN NOW The dark descent, and up to re-ascend, END
BEGIN NOW Though hard and rare: Thee I revisit safe, END
BEGIN NOW And feel thy sovran vital lamp; but thou END
BEGIN NOW Revisit'st not these eyes, that roll in vain END
BEGIN NOW To find thy piercing ray, and find no dawn; END
BEGIN NOW So thick a drop serene hath quench'd their orbs, END
BEGIN NOW Or dim suffusion veil'd. Yet not the more END
BEGIN NOW Cease I to wander, where the Muses haunt, END
BEGIN NOW Clear spring, or shady grove, or sunny hill, END
BEGIN NOW Smit with the love of sacred song; but chief END
BEGIN NOW Thee, Sion, and the flowery brooks beneath, END
BEGIN NOW That wash thy hallow'd feet, and warbling flow, END
BEGIN NOW Nightly I visit: nor sometimes forget END
BEGIN NOW So were I equall'd with them in renown, END
BEGIN NOW Thy sovran command, that Man should find grace; END
BEGIN NOW Blind Thamyris, and blind Maeonides, END
BEGIN NOW And Tiresias, and Phineus, prophets old: END
BEGIN NOW Then feed on thoughts, that voluntary move END
BEGIN NOW Harmonious numbers; as the wakeful bird END
BEGIN NOW Sings darkling, and in shadiest covert hid END
BEGIN NOW Tunes her nocturnal note. Thus with the year END
BEGIN NOW Seasons return; but not to me returns END
BEGIN NOW Day, or the sweet approach of even or morn, END
BEGIN NOW Or sight of vernal bloom, or summer's rose, END
BEGIN NOW Or flocks, or herds, or human face divine; END
BEGIN NOW But cloud instead, and ever-during dark END
BEGIN NOW Surrounds me, from the cheerful ways of men END
BEGIN NOW Cut off, and for the book of knowledge fair END
BEGIN NOW Presented with a universal blank END
BEGIN NOW Of nature's works to me expung'd and ras'd, END
BEGIN NOW And wisdom at one entrance quite shut out. END
BEGIN NOW So much the rather thou, celestial Light, END
BEGIN NOW Shine inward, and the mind through all her powers END
BEGIN NOW Irradiate; there plant eyes, all mist from thence END
BEGIN NOW Purge and disperse, that I may see and tell END
BEGIN NOW Of things invisible to mortal sight. END
BEGIN NOW Now had the Almighty Father from above, END
BEGIN NOW From the pure empyrean where he sits END
BEGIN NOW High thron'd above all highth, bent down his eye END
BEGIN NOW His own works and their works at once to view: END
BEGIN NOW Stood thick as stars, and from his sight receiv'd END
BEGIN NOW Beatitude past utterance; on his right END
BEGIN NOW The radiant image of his glory sat, END
BEGIN NOW His only son; on earth he first beheld END
BEGIN NOW Our two first parents, yet the only two END
BEGIN NOW Of mankind in the happy garden plac'd END
BEGIN NOW Reaping immortal fruits of joy and love, END
BEGIN NOW Uninterrupted joy, unrivall'd love, END
BEGIN NOW In blissful solitude; he then survey'd END
BEGIN NOW Hell and the gulf between, and Satan there END
BEGIN NOW Coasting the wall of Heaven on this side Night END
BEGIN NOW In the dun air sublime, and ready now END
BEGIN NOW To stoop with wearied wings, and willing feet, END
BEGIN NOW On the bare outside of this world, that seem'd END
BEGIN NOW Firm land imbosom'd, without firmament, END
BEGIN NOW Uncertain which, in ocean or in air. END
BEGIN NOW Him God beholding from his prospect high, END
BEGIN NOW Wherein past, present, future, he beholds, END
BEGIN NOW Thus to his only Son foreseeing spake. END
BEGIN NOW Only begotten Son, seest thou what rage END
BEGIN NOW Transports our Adversary? whom no bounds END
BEGIN NOW Prescrib'd no bars of Hell, nor all the chains END
BEGIN NOW Heap'd on him there, nor yet the main abyss END
BEGIN NOW Wide interrupt, can hold; so bent he seems END
BEGIN NOW On desperate revenge, that shall redound END
BEGIN NOW Upon his own rebellious head. And now, END
BEGIN NOW Through all restraint broke loose, he wings his way END
BEGIN NOW Not far off Heaven, in the precincts of light, END
BEGIN NOW Directly towards the new created world, END
BEGIN NOW And man there plac'd, with purpose to assay END
BEGIN NOW If him by force he can destroy, or, worse, END
BEGIN NOW By some false guile pervert; and shall pervert; END
BEGIN NOW For man will hearken to his glozing lies, END
BEGIN NOW And easily transgress the sole command, END
BEGIN NOW Sole pledge of his obedience: So will fall END
BEGIN NOW He and his faithless progeny: Whose fault? END
BEGIN NOW Whose but his own? ingrate, he had of me END
BEGIN NOW All he could have; I made him just and right, END
BEGIN NOW Sufficient to have stood, though free to fall. END
BEGIN NOW Such I created all the ethereal Powers END
BEGIN NOW And Spirits, both them who stood, and them who fail'd; END
BEGIN NOW Freely they stood who stood, and fell who fell. END
BEGIN NOW Not free, what proof could they have given sincere END
BEGIN NOW Of true allegiance, constant faith or love, END
BEGIN NOW Where only what they needs must do appear'd, END
BEGIN NOW Not what they would? what praise could they receive? END
BEGIN NOW What pleasure I from such obedience paid, END
BEGIN NOW When will and reason (reason also is choice) END
BEGIN NOW Useless and vain, of freedom both despoil'd, END
BEGIN NOW Made passive both, had serv'd necessity, END
BEGIN NOW Not me. They therefore, as to right belong'd, END
BEGIN NOW So were created, nor can justly accuse END
BEGIN NOW Their Maker, or their making, or their fate, END
BEGIN NOW As if predestination over-rul'd END
BEGIN NOW Their will dispos'd by absolute decree END
BEGIN NOW Or high foreknowledge they themselves decreed END
BEGIN NOW Their own revolt, not I; if I foreknew, END
BEGIN NOW Foreknowledge had no influence on their fault, END
BEGIN NOW Which had no less proved certain unforeknown. END
BEGIN NOW So without least impulse or shadow of fate, END
BEGIN NOW Or aught by me immutably foreseen, END
BEGIN NOW They trespass, authors to themselves in all END
BEGIN NOW Both what they judge, and what they choose; for so END
BEGIN NOW I form'd them free: and free they must remain, END
BEGIN NOW Till they enthrall themselves; I else must change END
BEGIN NOW Their nature, and revoke the high decree END
BEGIN NOW Unchangeable, eternal, which ordain'd END
BEGIN NOW Their freedom: they themselves ordain'd their fall. END
BEGIN NOW The first sort by their own suggestion fell, END
BEGIN NOW Self-tempted, self-deprav'd: Man falls, deceiv'd END
BEGIN NOW By the other first: Man therefore shall find grace, END
BEGIN NOW The other none: In mercy and justice both, END
BEGIN NOW Through Heaven and Earth, so shall my glory excel; END
BEGIN NOW But Mercy, first and last, shall brightest shine. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while God spake, ambrosial fragrance fill'd END
BEGIN NOW All Heaven, and in the blessed Spirits elect END
BEGIN NOW Sense of new joy ineffable diffus'd. END
BEGIN NOW Beyond compare the Son of God was seen END
BEGIN NOW Most glorious; in him all his Father shone END
BEGIN NOW Substantially express'd; and in his face END
BEGIN NOW Divine compassion visibly appear'd, END
BEGIN NOW Love without end, and without measure grace, END
BEGIN NOW Which uttering, thus he to his Father spake. END
BEGIN NOW O Father, gracious was that word which clos'd END
BEGIN NOW Thy sovran command, that Man should find grace; END
BEGIN NOW For which both Heaven and earth shall high extol END
BEGIN NOW Thy praises, with the innumerable sound END
BEGIN NOW Of hymns and sacred songs, wherewith thy throne END
BEGIN NOW Encompass'd shall resound thee ever blest. END
BEGIN NOW For should Man finally be lost, should Man, END
BEGIN NOW Thy creature late so lov'd, thy youngest son, END
BEGIN NOW Fall circumvented thus by fraud, though join'd END
BEGIN NOW With his own folly? that be from thee far, END
BEGIN NOW That far be from thee, Father, who art judge END
BEGIN NOW Of all things made, and judgest only right. END
BEGIN NOW Or shall the Adversary thus obtain END
BEGIN NOW His end, and frustrate thine? shall he fulfill END
BEGIN NOW His malice, and thy goodness bring to nought, END
BEGIN NOW Or proud return, though to his heavier doom, END
BEGIN NOW Yet with revenge accomplish'd, and to Hell END
BEGIN NOW Draw after him the whole race of mankind, END
BEGIN NOW By him corrupted? or wilt thou thyself END
BEGIN NOW Abolish thy creation, and unmake END
BEGIN NOW For him, what for thy glory thou hast made? END
BEGIN NOW So should thy goodness and thy greatness both END
BEGIN NOW Be question'd and blasphem'd without defence. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the great Creator thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW O son, in whom my soul hath chief delight, END
BEGIN NOW Son of my bosom, Son who art alone. END
BEGIN NOW My word, my wisdom, and effectual might, END
BEGIN NOW All hast thou spoken as my thoughts are, all END
BEGIN NOW As my eternal purpose hath decreed; END
BEGIN NOW Man shall not quite be lost, but sav'd who will; END
BEGIN NOW Yet not of will in him, but grace in me END
BEGIN NOW Freely vouchsaf'd; once more I will renew END
BEGIN NOW His lapsed powers, though forfeit; and enthrall'd END
BEGIN NOW By sin to foul exorbitant desires; END
BEGIN NOW Upheld by me, yet once more he shall stand END
BEGIN NOW On even ground against his mortal foe; END
BEGIN NOW By me upheld, that he may know how frail END
BEGIN NOW His fallen condition is, and to me owe END
BEGIN NOW All his deliverance, and to none but me. END
BEGIN NOW Some I have chosen of peculiar grace, END
BEGIN NOW Elect above the rest; so is my will: END
BEGIN NOW The rest shall hear me call, and oft be warn'd END
BEGIN NOW Their sinful state, and to appease betimes END
BEGIN NOW The incensed Deity, while offer'd grace END
BEGIN NOW Invites; for I will clear their senses dark, END
BEGIN NOW What may suffice, and soften stony hearts END
BEGIN NOW To pray, repent, and bring obedience due. END
BEGIN NOW To prayer, repentance, and obedience due, END
BEGIN NOW Though but endeavour'd with sincere intent, END
BEGIN NOW Mine ear shall not be slow, mine eye not shut. END
BEGIN NOW And I will place within them as a guide, END
BEGIN NOW My umpire Conscience; whom if they will hear, END
BEGIN NOW Light after light, well us'd, they shall attain, END
BEGIN NOW And to the end, persisting, safe arrive. END
BEGIN NOW This my long sufferance, and my day of grace, END
BEGIN NOW They who neglect and scorn, shall never taste; END
BEGIN NOW But hard be harden'd, blind be blinded more, END
BEGIN NOW That they may stumble on, and deeper fall; END
BEGIN NOW And none but such from mercy I exclude. END
BEGIN NOW But yet all is not done; Man disobeying, END
BEGIN NOW Disloyal, breaks his fealty, and sins END
BEGIN NOW Against the high supremacy of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Affecting God-head, and, so losing all, END
BEGIN NOW To expiate his treason hath nought left, END
BEGIN NOW But to destruction sacred and devote, END
BEGIN NOW He, with his whole posterity, must die, END
BEGIN NOW Die he or justice must; unless for him END
BEGIN NOW Some other able, and as willing, pay END
BEGIN NOW The rigid satisfaction, death for death. END
BEGIN NOW Say, heavenly Powers, where shall we find such love? END
BEGIN NOW Which of you will be mortal, to redeem END
BEGIN NOW Man's mortal crime, and just the unjust to save? END
BEGIN NOW Dwells in all Heaven charity so dear? END
BEGIN NOW He ask'd, but all the heavenly quire stood mute, END
BEGIN NOW And silence was in Heaven: on Man's behalf END
BEGIN NOW Patron or intercessour none appear'd, END
BEGIN NOW Much less that durst upon his own head draw END
BEGIN NOW The deadly forfeiture, and ransom set. END
BEGIN NOW And now without redemption all mankind END
BEGIN NOW Must have been lost, adjudg'd to Death and Hell END
BEGIN NOW By doom severe, had not the Son of God, END
BEGIN NOW In whom the fulness dwells of love divine, END
BEGIN NOW His dearest mediation thus renew'd. END
BEGIN NOW Father, thy word is past, Man shall find grace; END
BEGIN NOW And shall grace not find means, that finds her way, END
BEGIN NOW The speediest of thy winged messengers, END
BEGIN NOW To visit all thy creatures, and to all END
BEGIN NOW Comes unprevented, unimplor'd, unsought? END
BEGIN NOW Happy for Man, so coming; he her aid END
BEGIN NOW Can never seek, once dead in sins, and lost; END
BEGIN NOW Atonement for himself, or offering meet, END
BEGIN NOW Indebted and undone, hath none to bring; END
BEGIN NOW Behold me then: me for him, life for life END
BEGIN NOW I offer: on me let thine anger fall; END
BEGIN NOW Account me Man; I for his sake will leave END
BEGIN NOW Thy bosom, and this glory next to thee END
BEGIN NOW Freely put off, and for him lastly die END
BEGIN NOW Well pleased; on me let Death wreak all his rage. END
BEGIN NOW Under his gloomy power I shall not long END
BEGIN NOW Lie vanquished. Thou hast given me to possess END
BEGIN NOW Life in myself for ever; by thee I live; END
BEGIN NOW Though now to Death I yield, and am his due, END
BEGIN NOW All that of me can die, yet, that debt paid, END
BEGIN NOW Thou wilt not leave me in the loathsome grave END
BEGIN NOW His prey, nor suffer my unspotted soul END
BEGIN NOW For ever with corruption there to dwell; END
BEGIN NOW But I shall rise victorious, and subdue END
BEGIN NOW My vanquisher, spoiled of his vaunted spoil. END
BEGIN NOW Death his death's wound shall then receive, and stoop END
BEGIN NOW Inglorious, of his mortal sting disarmed; END
BEGIN NOW I through the ample air in triumph high END
BEGIN NOW Shall lead Hell captive maugre Hell, and show END
BEGIN NOW The powers of darkness bound. Thou, at the sight END
BEGIN NOW Pleased, out of Heaven shalt look down and smile, END
BEGIN NOW While, by thee raised, I ruin all my foes; END
BEGIN NOW Death last, and with his carcase glut the grave; END
BEGIN NOW Then, with the multitude of my redeemed, END
BEGIN NOW Shall enter Heaven, long absent, and return, END
BEGIN NOW Father, to see thy face, wherein no cloud END
BEGIN NOW Of anger shall remain, but peace assured END
BEGIN NOW And reconcilement: wrath shall be no more END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth, but in thy presence joy entire. END
BEGIN NOW His words here ended; but his meek aspect END
BEGIN NOW Silent yet spake, and breathed immortal love END
BEGIN NOW To mortal men, above which only shone END
BEGIN NOW Filial obedience: as a sacrifice END
BEGIN NOW Glad to be offered, he attends the will END
BEGIN NOW Of his great Father. Admiration seized END
BEGIN NOW All Heaven, what this might mean, and whither tend, END
BEGIN NOW Wondering; but soon th' Almighty thus replied: END
BEGIN NOW O thou in Heaven and Earth the only peace END
BEGIN NOW Found out for mankind under wrath, O thou END
BEGIN NOW My sole complacence! Well thou know'st how dear END
BEGIN NOW To me are all my works; nor Man the least, END
BEGIN NOW Though last created, that for him I spare END
BEGIN NOW Thee from my bosom and right hand, to save, END
BEGIN NOW By losing thee a while, the whole race lost. END
BEGIN NOW Thou, therefore, whom thou only canst redeem, END
BEGIN NOW Their nature also to thy nature join; END
BEGIN NOW And be thyself Man among men on Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Made flesh, when time shall be, of virgin seed, END
BEGIN NOW By wondrous birth; be thou in Adam's room END
BEGIN NOW The head of all mankind, though Adam's son. END
BEGIN NOW As in him perish all men, so in thee, END
BEGIN NOW As from a second root, shall be restored END
BEGIN NOW As many as are restored, without thee none. END
BEGIN NOW His crime makes guilty all his sons; thy merit, END
BEGIN NOW Imputed, shall absolve them who renounce END
BEGIN NOW Their own both righteous and unrighteous deeds, END
BEGIN NOW And live in thee transplanted, and from thee END
BEGIN NOW Receive new life. So Man, as is most just, END
BEGIN NOW Shall satisfy for Man, be judged and die, END
BEGIN NOW And dying rise, and rising with him raise END
BEGIN NOW His brethren, ransomed with his own dear life. END
BEGIN NOW So heavenly love shall outdo hellish hate, END
BEGIN NOW Giving to death, and dying to redeem, END
BEGIN NOW So dearly to redeem what hellish hate END
BEGIN NOW So easily destroyed, and still destroys END
BEGIN NOW In those who, when they may, accept not grace. END
BEGIN NOW Nor shalt thou, by descending to assume END
BEGIN NOW Man's nature, lessen or degrade thine own. END
BEGIN NOW Because thou hast, though throned in highest bliss END
BEGIN NOW Equal to God, and equally enjoying END
BEGIN NOW God-like fruition, quitted all, to save END
BEGIN NOW A world from utter loss, and hast been found END
BEGIN NOW By merit more than birthright Son of God, END
BEGIN NOW Found worthiest to be so by being good, END
BEGIN NOW Far more than great or high; because in thee END
BEGIN NOW Love hath abounded more than glory abounds; END
BEGIN NOW Therefore thy humiliation shall exalt END
BEGIN NOW With thee thy manhood also to this throne: END
BEGIN NOW Here shalt thou sit incarnate, here shalt reign END
BEGIN NOW Both God and Man, Son both of God and Man, END
BEGIN NOW Anointed universal King; all power END
BEGIN NOW I give thee; reign for ever, and assume END
BEGIN NOW Thy merits; under thee, as head supreme, END
BEGIN NOW Thrones, Princedoms, Powers, Dominions, I reduce: END
BEGIN NOW All knees to thee shall bow, of them that bide END
BEGIN NOW In Heaven, or Earth, or under Earth in Hell. END
BEGIN NOW When thou, attended gloriously from Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Shalt in the sky appear, and from thee send END
BEGIN NOW The summoning Arch-Angels to proclaim END
BEGIN NOW Thy dread tribunal; forthwith from all winds, END
BEGIN NOW The living, and forthwith the cited dead END
BEGIN NOW Of all past ages, to the general doom END
BEGIN NOW Shall hasten; such a peal shall rouse their sleep. END
BEGIN NOW Then, all thy saints assembled, thou shalt judge END
BEGIN NOW Bad Men and Angels; they, arraigned, shall sink END
BEGIN NOW Beneath thy sentence; Hell, her numbers full, END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth shall be for ever shut. Mean while END
BEGIN NOW The world shall burn, and from her ashes spring END
BEGIN NOW New Heaven and Earth, wherein the just shall dwell, END
BEGIN NOW And, after all their tribulations long, END
BEGIN NOW See golden days, fruitful of golden deeds, END
BEGIN NOW With joy and peace triumphing, and fair truth. END
BEGIN NOW Then thou thy regal scepter shalt lay by, END
BEGIN NOW For regal scepter then no more shall need, END
BEGIN NOW God shall be all in all. But, all ye Gods, END
BEGIN NOW Adore him, who to compass all this dies; END
BEGIN NOW Adore the Son, and honour him as me. END
BEGIN NOW No sooner had the Almighty ceased, but all END
BEGIN NOW The multitude of Angels, with a shout END
BEGIN NOW Loud as from numbers without number, sweet END
BEGIN NOW As from blest voices, uttering joy, Heaven rung END
BEGIN NOW With jubilee, and loud Hosannas filled END
BEGIN NOW The eternal regions: Lowly reverent END
BEGIN NOW Towards either throne they bow, and to the ground END
BEGIN NOW With solemn adoration down they cast END
BEGIN NOW Their crowns inwove with amarant and gold; END
BEGIN NOW Immortal amarant, a flower which once END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise, fast by the tree of life, END
BEGIN NOW Began to bloom; but soon for man's offence END
BEGIN NOW To Heaven removed, where first it grew, there grows, END
BEGIN NOW And flowers aloft shading the fount of life, END
BEGIN NOW And where the river of bliss through midst of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Rolls o'er Elysian flowers her amber stream; END
BEGIN NOW With these that never fade the Spirits elect END
BEGIN NOW Bind their resplendent locks inwreathed with beams; END
BEGIN NOW Now in loose garlands thick thrown off, the bright END
BEGIN NOW Pavement, that like a sea of jasper shone, END
BEGIN NOW Impurpled with celestial roses smiled. END
BEGIN NOW Then, crowned again, their golden harps they took, END
BEGIN NOW Harps ever tuned, that glittering by their side END
BEGIN NOW Like quivers hung, and with preamble sweet END
BEGIN NOW Of charming symphony they introduce END
BEGIN NOW Their sacred song, and waken raptures high; END
BEGIN NOW No voice exempt, no voice but well could join END
BEGIN NOW Melodious part, such concord is in Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Thee, Father, first they sung Omnipotent, END
BEGIN NOW Eternal King; the Author of all being, END
BEGIN NOW Fountain of light, thyself invisible END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the glorious brightness where thou sit'st END
BEGIN NOW Throned inaccessible, but when thou shadest END
BEGIN NOW The full blaze of thy beams, and, through a cloud END
BEGIN NOW Drawn round about thee like a radiant shrine, END
BEGIN NOW Dark with excessive bright thy skirts appear, END
BEGIN NOW Yet dazzle Heaven, that brightest Seraphim END
BEGIN NOW Approach not, but with both wings veil their eyes. END
BEGIN NOW Thee next they sang of all creation first, END
BEGIN NOW In whose conspicuous countenance, without cloud END
BEGIN NOW Made visible, the Almighty Father shines, END
BEGIN NOW Whom else no creature can behold; on thee END
BEGIN NOW Impressed the effulgence of his glory abides, END
BEGIN NOW Transfused on thee his ample Spirit rests. END
BEGIN NOW He Heaven of Heavens and all the Powers therein END
BEGIN NOW By thee created; and by thee threw down END
BEGIN NOW The aspiring Dominations: Thou that day END
BEGIN NOW Thy Father's dreadful thunder didst not spare, END
BEGIN NOW Nor stop thy flaming chariot-wheels, that shook END
BEGIN NOW Heaven's everlasting frame, while o'er the necks END
BEGIN NOW Thou drovest of warring Angels disarrayed. END
BEGIN NOW Back from pursuit thy Powers with loud acclaim END
BEGIN NOW Thee only extolled, Son of thy Father's might, END
BEGIN NOW To execute fierce vengeance on his foes, END
BEGIN NOW Not so on Man: Him through their malice fallen, END
BEGIN NOW Father of mercy and grace, thou didst not doom END
BEGIN NOW So strictly, but much more to pity incline: END
BEGIN NOW No sooner did thy dear and only Son END
BEGIN NOW Perceive thee purposed not to doom frail Man END
BEGIN NOW So strictly, but much more to pity inclined, END
BEGIN NOW He to appease thy wrath, and end the strife END
BEGIN NOW Of mercy and justice in thy face discerned, END
BEGIN NOW Regardless of the bliss wherein he sat END
BEGIN NOW Second to thee, offered himself to die END
BEGIN NOW For Man's offence. O unexampled love, END
BEGIN NOW Love no where to be found less than Divine! END
BEGIN NOW Hail, Son of God, Saviour of Men! Thy name END
BEGIN NOW Shall be the copious matter of my song END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth, and never shall my heart thy praise END
BEGIN NOW Forget, nor from thy Father's praise disjoin. END
BEGIN NOW Thus they in Heaven, above the starry sphere, END
BEGIN NOW Their happy hours in joy and hymning spent. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while upon the firm opacous globe END
BEGIN NOW Of this round world, whose first convex divides END
BEGIN NOW The luminous inferiour orbs, enclosed END
BEGIN NOW From Chaos, and the inroad of Darkness old, END
BEGIN NOW Satan alighted walks: A globe far off END
BEGIN NOW It seemed, now seems a boundless continent END
BEGIN NOW Dark, waste, and wild, under the frown of Night END
BEGIN NOW Starless exposed, and ever-threatening storms END
BEGIN NOW Of Chaos blustering round, inclement sky; END
BEGIN NOW Save on that side which from the wall of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Though distant far, some small reflection gains END
BEGIN NOW Of glimmering air less vexed with tempest loud: END
BEGIN NOW Here walked the Fiend at large in spacious field. END
BEGIN NOW As when a vultur on Imaus bred, END
BEGIN NOW Whose snowy ridge the roving Tartar bounds, END
BEGIN NOW Dislodging from a region scarce of prey END
BEGIN NOW To gorge the flesh of lambs or yeanling kids, END
BEGIN NOW On hills where flocks are fed, flies toward the springs END
BEGIN NOW Of Ganges or Hydaspes, Indian streams; END
BEGIN NOW But in his way lights on the barren plains END
BEGIN NOW Of Sericana, where Chineses drive END
BEGIN NOW With sails and wind their cany waggons light: END
BEGIN NOW So, on this windy sea of land, the Fiend END
BEGIN NOW Walked up and down alone, bent on his prey; END
BEGIN NOW Alone, for other creature in this place, END
BEGIN NOW Living or lifeless, to be found was none; END
BEGIN NOW None yet, but store hereafter from the earth END
BEGIN NOW Up hither like aereal vapours flew END
BEGIN NOW Of all things transitory and vain, when sin END
BEGIN NOW With vanity had filled the works of men: END
BEGIN NOW Both all things vain, and all who in vain things END
BEGIN NOW Built their fond hopes of glory or lasting fame, END
BEGIN NOW Or happiness in this or the other life; END
BEGIN NOW All who have their reward on earth, the fruits END
BEGIN NOW Of painful superstition and blind zeal, END
BEGIN NOW Nought seeking but the praise of men, here find END
BEGIN NOW Fit retribution, empty as their deeds; END
BEGIN NOW All the unaccomplished works of Nature's hand, END
BEGIN NOW Abortive, monstrous, or unkindly mixed, END
BEGIN NOW Dissolved on earth, fleet hither, and in vain, END
BEGIN NOW Till final dissolution, wander here; END
BEGIN NOW Not in the neighbouring moon as some have dreamed; END
BEGIN NOW Those argent fields more likely habitants, END
BEGIN NOW Translated Saints, or middle Spirits hold END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the angelical and human kind. END
BEGIN NOW Hither of ill-joined sons and daughters born END
BEGIN NOW First from the ancient world those giants came END
BEGIN NOW With many a vain exploit, though then renowned: END
BEGIN NOW The builders next of Babel on the plain END
BEGIN NOW Of Sennaar, and still with vain design, END
BEGIN NOW New Babels, had they wherewithal, would build: END
BEGIN NOW Others came single; he, who, to be deemed END
BEGIN NOW A God, leaped fondly into Aetna flames, END
BEGIN NOW Empedocles; and he, who, to enjoy END
BEGIN NOW Plato's Elysium, leaped into the sea, END
BEGIN NOW Cleombrotus; and many more too long, END
BEGIN NOW White, black, and gray, with all their trumpery. END
BEGIN NOW Here pilgrims roam, that strayed so far to seek END
BEGIN NOW In Golgotha him dead, who lives in Heaven; END
BEGIN NOW And they, who to be sure of Paradise, END
BEGIN NOW Dying, put on the weeds of Dominick, END
BEGIN NOW Or in Franciscan think to pass disguised; END
BEGIN NOW They pass the planets seven, and pass the fixed, END
BEGIN NOW And that crystalling sphere whose balance weighs END
BEGIN NOW The trepidation talked, and that first moved; END
BEGIN NOW And now Saint Peter at Heaven's wicket seems END
BEGIN NOW To wait them with his keys, and now at foot END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven's ascent they lift their feet, when lo END
BEGIN NOW A violent cross wind from either coast END
BEGIN NOW Blows them transverse, ten thousand leagues awry END
BEGIN NOW Into the devious air: Then might ye see END
BEGIN NOW Cowls, hoods, and habits, with their wearers, tost END
BEGIN NOW And fluttered into rags; then reliques, beads, END
BEGIN NOW Indulgences, dispenses, pardons, bulls, END
BEGIN NOW The sport of winds: All these, upwhirled aloft, END
BEGIN NOW Fly o'er the backside of the world far off END
BEGIN NOW Into a Limbo large and broad, since called END
BEGIN NOW The Paradise of Fools, to few unknown END
BEGIN NOW Long after; now unpeopled, and untrod. END
BEGIN NOW All this dark globe the Fiend found as he passed, END
BEGIN NOW And long he wandered, till at last a gleam END
BEGIN NOW Of dawning light turned thither-ward in haste END
BEGIN NOW His travelled steps: far distant he descries END
BEGIN NOW Ascending by degrees magnificent END
BEGIN NOW Up to the wall of Heaven a structure high; END
BEGIN NOW At top whereof, but far more rich, appeared END
BEGIN NOW The work as of a kingly palace-gate, END
BEGIN NOW With frontispiece of diamond and gold END
BEGIN NOW Embellished; thick with sparkling orient gems END
BEGIN NOW The portal shone, inimitable on earth END
BEGIN NOW By model, or by shading pencil, drawn. END
BEGIN NOW These stairs were such as whereon Jacob saw END
BEGIN NOW Angels ascending and descending, bands END
BEGIN NOW Of guardians bright, when he from Esau fled END
BEGIN NOW To Padan-Aram, in the field of Luz END
BEGIN NOW Dreaming by night under the open sky END
BEGIN NOW And waking cried, This is the gate of Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Each stair mysteriously was meant, nor stood END
BEGIN NOW There always, but drawn up to Heaven sometimes END
BEGIN NOW Viewless; and underneath a bright sea flowed END
BEGIN NOW Of jasper, or of liquid pearl, whereon END
BEGIN NOW Who after came from earth, failing arrived END
BEGIN NOW Wafted by Angels, or flew o'er the lake END
BEGIN NOW Rapt in a chariot drawn by fiery steeds. END
BEGIN NOW The stairs were then let down, whether to dare END
BEGIN NOW The Fiend by easy ascent, or aggravate END
BEGIN NOW His sad exclusion from the doors of bliss: END
BEGIN NOW Direct against which opened from beneath, END
BEGIN NOW Just o'er the blissful seat of Paradise, END
BEGIN NOW A passage down to the Earth, a passage wide, END
BEGIN NOW Wider by far than that of after-times END
BEGIN NOW Over mount Sion, and, though that were large, END
BEGIN NOW Over the Promised Land to God so dear; END
BEGIN NOW By which, to visit oft those happy tribes, END
BEGIN NOW On high behests his angels to and fro END
BEGIN NOW Passed frequent, and his eye with choice regard END
BEGIN NOW From Paneas, the fount of Jordan's flood, END
BEGIN NOW To Beersaba, where the Holy Land END
BEGIN NOW So wide the opening seemed, where bounds were set END
BEGIN NOW To darkness, such as bound the ocean wave. END
BEGIN NOW Satan from hence, now on the lower stair, END
BEGIN NOW That scaled by steps of gold to Heaven-gate, END
BEGIN NOW Looks down with wonder at the sudden view END
BEGIN NOW Of all this world at once. As when a scout, END
BEGIN NOW Through dark and desert ways with peril gone END
BEGIN NOW All night; at last by break of cheerful dawn END
BEGIN NOW Obtains the brow of some high-climbing hill, END
BEGIN NOW Which to his eye discovers unaware END
BEGIN NOW The goodly prospect of some foreign land END
BEGIN NOW First seen, or some renowned metropolis END
BEGIN NOW With glistering spires and pinnacles adorned, END
BEGIN NOW Which now the rising sun gilds with his beams: END
BEGIN NOW Such wonder seised, though after Heaven seen, END
BEGIN NOW The Spirit malign, but much more envy seised, END
BEGIN NOW At sight of all this world beheld so fair. END
BEGIN NOW Round he surveys (and well might, where he stood END
BEGIN NOW So high above the circling canopy END
BEGIN NOW Of night's extended shade,) from eastern point END
BEGIN NOW Of Libra to the fleecy star that bears END
BEGIN NOW Andromeda far off Atlantick seas END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the horizon; then from pole to pole END
BEGIN NOW He views in breadth, and without longer pause END
BEGIN NOW Down right into the world's first region throws END
BEGIN NOW His flight precipitant, and winds with ease END
BEGIN NOW Through the pure marble air his oblique way END
BEGIN NOW Amongst innumerable stars, that shone END
BEGIN NOW Stars distant, but nigh hand seemed other worlds; END
BEGIN NOW Or other worlds they seemed, or happy isles, END
BEGIN NOW Like those Hesperian gardens famed of old, END
BEGIN NOW Fortunate fields, and groves, and flowery vales, END
BEGIN NOW Thrice happy isles; but who dwelt happy there END
BEGIN NOW He staid not to inquire: Above them all END
BEGIN NOW The golden sun, in splendour likest Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Allured his eye; thither his course he bends END
BEGIN NOW Through the calm firmament, (but up or down, END
BEGIN NOW By center, or eccentrick, hard to tell, END
BEGIN NOW Or longitude,) where the great luminary END
BEGIN NOW Aloof the vulgar constellations thick, END
BEGIN NOW That from his lordly eye keep distance due, END
BEGIN NOW Dispenses light from far; they, as they move END
BEGIN NOW Their starry dance in numbers that compute END
BEGIN NOW Days, months, and years, towards his all-cheering lamp END
BEGIN NOW Turn swift their various motions, or are turned END
BEGIN NOW By his magnetick beam, that gently warms END
BEGIN NOW The universe, and to each inward part END
BEGIN NOW With gentle penetration, though unseen, END
BEGIN NOW Shoots invisible virtue even to the deep; END
BEGIN NOW So wonderously was set his station bright. END
BEGIN NOW There lands the Fiend, a spot like which perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Astronomer in the sun's lucent orb END
BEGIN NOW Through his glazed optick tube yet never saw. END
BEGIN NOW The place he found beyond expression bright, END
BEGIN NOW Compared with aught on earth, metal or stone; END
BEGIN NOW Not all parts like, but all alike informed END
BEGIN NOW With radiant light, as glowing iron with fire; END
BEGIN NOW If metal, part seemed gold, part silver clear; END
BEGIN NOW If stone, carbuncle most or chrysolite, END
BEGIN NOW Ruby or topaz, to the twelve that shone END
BEGIN NOW In Aaron's breast-plate, and a stone besides END
BEGIN NOW Imagined rather oft than elsewhere seen, END
BEGIN NOW That stone, or like to that which here below END
BEGIN NOW Philosophers in vain so long have sought, END
BEGIN NOW In vain, though by their powerful art they bind END
BEGIN NOW Volatile Hermes, and call up unbound END
BEGIN NOW In various shapes old Proteus from the sea, END
BEGIN NOW Drained through a limbeck to his native form. END
BEGIN NOW What wonder then if fields and regions here END
BEGIN NOW Breathe forth Elixir pure, and rivers run END
BEGIN NOW Potable gold, when with one virtuous touch END
BEGIN NOW The arch-chemick sun, so far from us remote, END
BEGIN NOW Produces, with terrestrial humour mixed, END
BEGIN NOW Here in the dark so many precious things END
BEGIN NOW Of colour glorious, and effect so rare? END
BEGIN NOW Here matter new to gaze the Devil met END
BEGIN NOW Undazzled; far and wide his eye commands; END
BEGIN NOW For sight no obstacle found here, nor shade, END
BEGIN NOW But all sun-shine, as when his beams at noon END
BEGIN NOW Culminate from the equator, as they now END
BEGIN NOW Shot upward still direct, whence no way round END
BEGIN NOW Shadow from body opaque can fall; and the air, END
BEGIN NOW No where so clear, sharpened his visual ray END
BEGIN NOW To objects distant far, whereby he soon END
BEGIN NOW Saw within ken a glorious Angel stand, END
BEGIN NOW The same whom John saw also in the sun: END
BEGIN NOW His back was turned, but not his brightness hid; END
BEGIN NOW Of beaming sunny rays a golden tiar END
BEGIN NOW Circled his head, nor less his locks behind END
BEGIN NOW Illustrious on his shoulders fledge with wings END
BEGIN NOW Lay waving round; on some great charge employed END
BEGIN NOW He seemed, or fixed in cogitation deep. END
BEGIN NOW Glad was the Spirit impure, as now in hope END
BEGIN NOW To find who might direct his wandering flight END
BEGIN NOW To Paradise, the happy seat of Man, END
BEGIN NOW His journey's end and our beginning woe. END
BEGIN NOW But first he casts to change his proper shape, END
BEGIN NOW Which else might work him danger or delay: END
BEGIN NOW And now a stripling Cherub he appears, END
BEGIN NOW Not of the prime, yet such as in his face END
BEGIN NOW Youth smiled celestial, and to every limb END
BEGIN NOW Suitable grace diffused, so well he feigned: END
BEGIN NOW Under a coronet his flowing hair END
BEGIN NOW In curls on either cheek played; wings he wore END
BEGIN NOW Of many a coloured plume, sprinkled with gold; END
BEGIN NOW His habit fit for speed succinct, and held END
BEGIN NOW Before his decent steps a silver wand. END
BEGIN NOW He drew not nigh unheard; the Angel bright, END
BEGIN NOW Ere he drew nigh, his radiant visage turned, END
BEGIN NOW Admonished by his ear, and straight was known END
BEGIN NOW The Arch-Angel Uriel, one of the seven END
BEGIN NOW Who in God's presence, nearest to his throne, END
BEGIN NOW Stand ready at command, and are his eyes END
BEGIN NOW That run through all the Heavens, or down to the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Bear his swift errands over moist and dry, END
BEGIN NOW O'er sea and land: him Satan thus accosts. END
BEGIN NOW Uriel, for thou of those seven Spirits that stand END
BEGIN NOW In sight of God's high throne, gloriously bright, END
BEGIN NOW The first art wont his great authentick will END
BEGIN NOW Interpreter through highest Heaven to bring, END
BEGIN NOW Where all his sons thy embassy attend; END
BEGIN NOW And here art likeliest by supreme decree END
BEGIN NOW Like honour to obtain, and as his eye END
BEGIN NOW To visit oft this new creation round; END
BEGIN NOW Unspeakable desire to see, and know END
BEGIN NOW All these his wonderous works, but chiefly Man, END
BEGIN NOW His chief delight and favour, him for whom END
BEGIN NOW All these his works so wonderous he ordained, END
BEGIN NOW Hath brought me from the quires of Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW Alone thus wandering. Brightest Seraph, tell END
BEGIN NOW In which of all these shining orbs hath Man END
BEGIN NOW His fixed seat, or fixed seat hath none, END
BEGIN NOW But all these shining orbs his choice to dwell; END
BEGIN NOW That I may find him, and with secret gaze END
BEGIN NOW Or open admiration him behold, END
BEGIN NOW On whom the great Creator hath bestowed END
BEGIN NOW Worlds, and on whom hath all these graces poured; END
BEGIN NOW That both in him and all things, as is meet, END
BEGIN NOW The universal Maker we may praise; END
BEGIN NOW Who justly hath driven out his rebel foes END
BEGIN NOW To deepest Hell, and, to repair that loss, END
BEGIN NOW Created this new happy race of Men END
BEGIN NOW To serve him better: Wise are all his ways. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the false dissembler unperceived; END
BEGIN NOW For neither Man nor Angel can discern END
BEGIN NOW Hypocrisy, the only evil that walks END
BEGIN NOW Invisible, except to God alone, END
BEGIN NOW By his permissive will, through Heaven and Earth: END
BEGIN NOW And oft, though wisdom wake, suspicion sleeps END
BEGIN NOW At wisdom's gate, and to simplicity END
BEGIN NOW Resigns her charge, while goodness thinks no ill END
BEGIN NOW Where no ill seems: Which now for once beguiled END
BEGIN NOW Uriel, though regent of the sun, and held END
BEGIN NOW The sharpest-sighted Spirit of all in Heaven; END
BEGIN NOW Who to the fraudulent impostor foul, END
BEGIN NOW In his uprightness, answer thus returned. END
BEGIN NOW Fair Angel, thy desire, which tends to know END
BEGIN NOW The works of God, thereby to glorify END
BEGIN NOW The great Work-master, leads to no excess END
BEGIN NOW That reaches blame, but rather merits praise END
BEGIN NOW The more it seems excess, that led thee hither END
BEGIN NOW From thy empyreal mansion thus alone, END
BEGIN NOW To witness with thine eyes what some perhaps, END
BEGIN NOW Contented with report, hear only in Heaven: END
BEGIN NOW For wonderful indeed are all his works, END
BEGIN NOW Pleasant to know, and worthiest to be all END
BEGIN NOW Had in remembrance always with delight; END
BEGIN NOW But what created mind can comprehend END
BEGIN NOW Their number, or the wisdom infinite END
BEGIN NOW That brought them forth, but hid their causes deep? END
BEGIN NOW I saw when at his word the formless mass, END
BEGIN NOW This world's material mould, came to a heap: END
BEGIN NOW Confusion heard his voice, and wild uproar END
BEGIN NOW Stood ruled, stood vast infinitude confined; END
BEGIN NOW Till at his second bidding Darkness fled, END
BEGIN NOW Light shone, and order from disorder sprung: END
BEGIN NOW Swift to their several quarters hasted then END
BEGIN NOW The cumbrous elements, earth, flood, air, fire; END
BEGIN NOW And this ethereal quintessence of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Flew upward, spirited with various forms, END
BEGIN NOW That rolled orbicular, and turned to stars END
BEGIN NOW Numberless, as thou seest, and how they move; END
BEGIN NOW Each had his place appointed, each his course; END
BEGIN NOW The rest in circuit walls this universe. END
BEGIN NOW Look downward on that globe, whose hither side END
BEGIN NOW With light from hence, though but reflected, shines; END
BEGIN NOW That place is Earth, the seat of Man; that light END
BEGIN NOW His day, which else, as the other hemisphere, END
BEGIN NOW Night would invade; but there the neighbouring moon END
BEGIN NOW (So call that opposite fair star) her aid END
BEGIN NOW Timely interposes, and her monthly round END
BEGIN NOW Still ending, still renewing, through mid Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW With borrowed light her countenance triform END
BEGIN NOW Hence fills and empties to enlighten the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW And in her pale dominion checks the night. END
BEGIN NOW That spot, to which I point, is Paradise, END
BEGIN NOW Adam's abode; those lofty shades, his bower. END
BEGIN NOW Thy way thou canst not miss, me mine requires. END
BEGIN NOW Thus said, he turned; and Satan, bowing low, END
BEGIN NOW As to superiour Spirits is wont in Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Where honour due and reverence none neglects, END
BEGIN NOW Took leave, and toward the coast of earth beneath, END
BEGIN NOW Down from the ecliptick, sped with hoped success, END
BEGIN NOW Throws his steep flight in many an aery wheel; END
BEGIN NOW Nor staid, till on Niphates' top he lights. END
BEGIN NOW O, for that warning voice, which he, who saw END
BEGIN NOW The Apocalypse, heard cry in Heaven aloud, END
BEGIN NOW Then when the Dragon, put to second rout, END
BEGIN NOW Came furious down to be revenged on men, END
BEGIN NOW Woe to the inhabitants on earth! that now, END
BEGIN NOW While time was, our first parents had been warned END
BEGIN NOW The coming of their secret foe, and 'scaped, END
BEGIN NOW Haply so 'scaped his mortal snare: For now END
BEGIN NOW Satan, now first inflamed with rage, came down, END
BEGIN NOW The tempter ere the accuser of mankind, END
BEGIN NOW To wreak on innocent frail Man his loss END
BEGIN NOW Of that first battle, and his flight to Hell: END
BEGIN NOW Yet, not rejoicing in his speed, though bold END
BEGIN NOW Far off and fearless, nor with cause to boast, END
BEGIN NOW Begins his dire attempt; which nigh the birth END
BEGIN NOW Now rolling boils in his tumultuous breast, END
BEGIN NOW And like a devilish engine back recoils END
BEGIN NOW Upon himself; horrour and doubt distract END
BEGIN NOW His troubled thoughts, and from the bottom stir END
BEGIN NOW The Hell within him; for within him Hell END
BEGIN NOW He brings, and round about him, nor from Hell END
BEGIN NOW One step, no more than from himself, can fly END
BEGIN NOW By change of place: Now conscience wakes despair, END
BEGIN NOW That slumbered; wakes the bitter memory END
BEGIN NOW Of what he was, what is, and what must be END
BEGIN NOW Worse; of worse deeds worse sufferings must ensue. END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes towards Eden, which now in his view END
BEGIN NOW Lay pleasant, his grieved look he fixes sad; END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes towards Heaven, and the full-blazing sun, END
BEGIN NOW Which now sat high in his meridian tower: END
BEGIN NOW Then, much revolving, thus in sighs began. END
BEGIN NOW O thou, that, with surpassing glory crowned, END
BEGIN NOW Lookest from thy sole dominion like the God END
BEGIN NOW Of this new world; at whose sight all the stars END
BEGIN NOW Hide their diminished heads; to thee I call, END
BEGIN NOW But with no friendly voice, and add thy name, END
BEGIN NOW Of Sun! to tell thee how I hate thy beams, END
BEGIN NOW That bring to my remembrance from what state END
BEGIN NOW I fell, how glorious once above thy sphere; END
BEGIN NOW Till pride and worse ambition threw me down END
BEGIN NOW Warring in Heaven against Heaven's matchless King: END
BEGIN NOW Ah, wherefore! he deserved no such return END
BEGIN NOW From me, whom he created what I was END
BEGIN NOW In that bright eminence, and with his good END
BEGIN NOW Upbraided none; nor was his service hard. END
BEGIN NOW What could be less than to afford him praise, END
BEGIN NOW The easiest recompence, and pay him thanks, END
BEGIN NOW How due! yet all his good proved ill in me, END
BEGIN NOW And wrought but malice; lifted up so high END
BEGIN NOW I 'sdeined subjection, and thought one step higher END
BEGIN NOW Would set me highest, and in a moment quit END
BEGIN NOW The debt immense of endless gratitude, END
BEGIN NOW So burdensome still paying, still to owe, END
BEGIN NOW Forgetful what from him I still received, END
BEGIN NOW And understood not that a grateful mind END
BEGIN NOW By owing owes not, but still pays, at once END
BEGIN NOW Indebted and discharged; what burden then END
BEGIN NOW O, had his powerful destiny ordained END
BEGIN NOW Me some inferiour Angel, I had stood END
BEGIN NOW Then happy; no unbounded hope had raised END
BEGIN NOW Ambition! Yet why not some other Power END
BEGIN NOW As great might have aspired, and me, though mean, END
BEGIN NOW Drawn to his part; but other Powers as great END
BEGIN NOW Fell not, but stand unshaken, from within END
BEGIN NOW Or from without, to all temptations armed. END
BEGIN NOW Hadst thou the same free will and power to stand? END
BEGIN NOW Thou hadst: whom hast thou then or what to accuse, END
BEGIN NOW But Heaven's free love dealt equally to all? END
BEGIN NOW Be then his love accursed, since love or hate, END
BEGIN NOW To me alike, it deals eternal woe. END
BEGIN NOW Nay, cursed be thou; since against his thy will END
BEGIN NOW Chose freely what it now so justly rues. END
BEGIN NOW Me miserable! which way shall I fly END
BEGIN NOW Infinite wrath, and infinite despair? END
BEGIN NOW Which way I fly is Hell; myself am Hell; END
BEGIN NOW And, in the lowest deep, a lower deep END
BEGIN NOW Still threatening to devour me opens wide, END
BEGIN NOW To which the Hell I suffer seems a Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW O, then, at last relent: Is there no place END
BEGIN NOW Left for repentance, none for pardon left? END
BEGIN NOW None left but by submission; and that word END
BEGIN NOW Disdain forbids me, and my dread of shame END
BEGIN NOW Among the Spirits beneath, whom I seduced END
BEGIN NOW With other promises and other vaunts END
BEGIN NOW Than to submit, boasting I could subdue END
BEGIN NOW The Omnipotent. Ay me! they little know END
BEGIN NOW How dearly I abide that boast so vain, END
BEGIN NOW Under what torments inwardly I groan, END
BEGIN NOW While they adore me on the throne of Hell. END
BEGIN NOW With diadem and scepter high advanced, END
BEGIN NOW The lower still I fall, only supreme END
BEGIN NOW In misery: Such joy ambition finds. END
BEGIN NOW But say I could repent, and could obtain, END
BEGIN NOW By act of grace, my former state; how soon END
BEGIN NOW Would highth recall high thoughts, how soon unsay END
BEGIN NOW What feigned submission swore? Ease would recant END
BEGIN NOW Vows made in pain, as violent and void. END
BEGIN NOW For never can true reconcilement grow, END
BEGIN NOW Where wounds of deadly hate have pierced so deep: END
BEGIN NOW Which would but lead me to a worse relapse END
BEGIN NOW And heavier fall: so should I purchase dear END
BEGIN NOW Short intermission bought with double smart. END
BEGIN NOW This knows my Punisher; therefore as far END
BEGIN NOW From granting he, as I from begging, peace; END
BEGIN NOW All hope excluded thus, behold, instead END
BEGIN NOW Of us out-cast, exil'd, his new delight, END
BEGIN NOW Mankind created, and for him this world. END
BEGIN NOW So farewell, hope; and with hope farewell, fear; END
BEGIN NOW Farewell, remorse! all good to me is lost; END
BEGIN NOW Evil, be thou my good; by thee at least END
BEGIN NOW Divided empire with Heaven's King I hold, END
BEGIN NOW By thee, and more than half perhaps will reign; END
BEGIN NOW As Man ere long, and this new world, shall know. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while he spake, each passion dimmed his face END
BEGIN NOW Thrice changed with pale, ire, envy, and despair; END
BEGIN NOW Which marred his borrowed visage, and betrayed END
BEGIN NOW Him counterfeit, if any eye beheld. END
BEGIN NOW For heavenly minds from such distempers foul END
BEGIN NOW Are ever clear. Whereof he soon aware, END
BEGIN NOW Each perturbation smoothed with outward calm, END
BEGIN NOW Artificer of fraud; and was the first END
BEGIN NOW That practised falsehood under saintly show, END
BEGIN NOW Deep malice to conceal, couched with revenge: END
BEGIN NOW Yet not enough had practised to deceive END
BEGIN NOW Uriel once warned; whose eye pursued him down END
BEGIN NOW The way he went, and on the Assyrian mount END
BEGIN NOW Saw him disfigured, more than could befall END
BEGIN NOW Spirit of happy sort; his gestures fierce END
BEGIN NOW He marked and mad demeanour, then alone, END
BEGIN NOW As he supposed, all unobserved, unseen. END
BEGIN NOW So on he fares, and to the border comes END
BEGIN NOW Of Eden, where delicious Paradise, END
BEGIN NOW Now nearer, crowns with her enclosure green, END
BEGIN NOW As with a rural mound, the champaign head END
BEGIN NOW Of a steep wilderness, whose hairy sides END
BEGIN NOW With thicket overgrown, grotesque and wild, END
BEGIN NOW Access denied; and overhead upgrew END
BEGIN NOW Insuperable height of loftiest shade, END
BEGIN NOW Cedar, and pine, and fir, and branching palm, END
BEGIN NOW A sylvan scene, and, as the ranks ascend, END
BEGIN NOW Shade above shade, a woody theatre END
BEGIN NOW Of stateliest view. Yet higher than their tops END
BEGIN NOW The verdurous wall of Paradise upsprung; END
BEGIN NOW Which to our general sire gave prospect large END
BEGIN NOW Into his nether empire neighbouring round. END
BEGIN NOW And higher than that wall a circling row END
BEGIN NOW Of goodliest trees, loaden with fairest fruit, END
BEGIN NOW Blossoms and fruits at once of golden hue, END
BEGIN NOW Appeared, with gay enamelled colours mixed: END
BEGIN NOW On which the sun more glad impressed his beams END
BEGIN NOW Than in fair evening cloud, or humid bow, END
BEGIN NOW When God hath showered the earth; so lovely seemed END
BEGIN NOW That landskip: And of pure now purer air END
BEGIN NOW Meets his approach, and to the heart inspires END
BEGIN NOW Vernal delight and joy, able to drive END
BEGIN NOW All sadness but despair: Now gentle gales, END
BEGIN NOW Fanning their odoriferous wings, dispense END
BEGIN NOW Native perfumes, and whisper whence they stole END
BEGIN NOW Those balmy spoils. As when to them who fail END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the Cape of Hope, and now are past END
BEGIN NOW Mozambick, off at sea north-east winds blow END
BEGIN NOW Sabean odours from the spicy shore END
BEGIN NOW Of Araby the blest; with such delay END
BEGIN NOW Well pleased they slack their course, and many a league END
BEGIN NOW Cheered with the grateful smell old Ocean smiles: END
BEGIN NOW So entertained those odorous sweets the Fiend, END
BEGIN NOW Who came their bane; though with them better pleased END
BEGIN NOW Than Asmodeus with the fishy fume END
BEGIN NOW That drove him, though enamoured, from the spouse END
BEGIN NOW Of Tobit's son, and with a vengeance sent END
BEGIN NOW Now to the ascent of that steep savage hill END
BEGIN NOW Satan had journeyed on, pensive and slow; END
BEGIN NOW But further way found none, so thick entwined, END
BEGIN NOW As one continued brake, the undergrowth END
BEGIN NOW Of shrubs and tangling bushes had perplexed END
BEGIN NOW All path of man or beast that passed that way. END
BEGIN NOW One gate there only was, and that looked east END
BEGIN NOW On the other side: which when the arch-felon saw, END
BEGIN NOW Due entrance he disdained; and, in contempt, END
BEGIN NOW At one flight bound high over-leaped all bound END
BEGIN NOW Of hill or highest wall, and sheer within END
BEGIN NOW Lights on his feet. As when a prowling wolf, END
BEGIN NOW Whom hunger drives to seek new haunt for prey, END
BEGIN NOW Watching where shepherds pen their flocks at eve END
BEGIN NOW In hurdled cotes amid the field secure, END
BEGIN NOW Leaps o'er the fence with ease into the fold: END
BEGIN NOW Or as a thief, bent to unhoard the cash END
BEGIN NOW Of some rich burgher, whose substantial doors, END
BEGIN NOW Cross-barred and bolted fast, fear no assault, END
BEGIN NOW In at the window climbs, or o'er the tiles: END
BEGIN NOW So clomb this first grand thief into God's fold; END
BEGIN NOW So since into his church lewd hirelings climb. END
BEGIN NOW Thence up he flew, and on the tree of life, END
BEGIN NOW The middle tree and highest there that grew, END
BEGIN NOW Sat like a cormorant; yet not true life END
BEGIN NOW Thereby regained, but sat devising death END
BEGIN NOW To them who lived; nor on the virtue thought END
BEGIN NOW Of that life-giving plant, but only used END
BEGIN NOW For prospect, what well used had been the pledge END
BEGIN NOW Of immortality. So little knows END
BEGIN NOW Any, but God alone, to value right END
BEGIN NOW The good before him, but perverts best things END
BEGIN NOW To worst abuse, or to their meanest use. END
BEGIN NOW Beneath him with new wonder now he views, END
BEGIN NOW To all delight of human sense exposed, END
BEGIN NOW In narrow room, Nature's whole wealth, yea more, END
BEGIN NOW A Heaven on Earth: For blissful Paradise END
BEGIN NOW Of God the garden was, by him in the east END
BEGIN NOW Of Eden planted; Eden stretched her line END
BEGIN NOW From Auran eastward to the royal towers END
BEGIN NOW Of great Seleucia, built by Grecian kings, END
BEGIN NOW Or where the sons of Eden long before END
BEGIN NOW Dwelt in Telassar: In this pleasant soil END
BEGIN NOW His far more pleasant garden God ordained; END
BEGIN NOW Out of the fertile ground he caused to grow END
BEGIN NOW All trees of noblest kind for sight, smell, taste; END
BEGIN NOW And all amid them stood the tree of life, END
BEGIN NOW High eminent, blooming ambrosial fruit END
BEGIN NOW Of vegetable gold; and next to life, END
BEGIN NOW Our death, the tree of knowledge, grew fast by, END
BEGIN NOW Knowledge of good bought dear by knowing ill. END
BEGIN NOW Southward through Eden went a river large, END
BEGIN NOW Nor changed his course, but through the shaggy hill END
BEGIN NOW Passed underneath ingulfed; for God had thrown END
BEGIN NOW That mountain as his garden-mould high raised END
BEGIN NOW Upon the rapid current, which, through veins END
BEGIN NOW Of porous earth with kindly thirst up-drawn, END
BEGIN NOW Rose a fresh fountain, and with many a rill END
BEGIN NOW Watered the garden; thence united fell END
BEGIN NOW Down the steep glade, and met the nether flood, END
BEGIN NOW Which from his darksome passage now appears, END
BEGIN NOW And now, divided into four main streams, END
BEGIN NOW Runs diverse, wandering many a famous realm END
BEGIN NOW And country, whereof here needs no account; END
BEGIN NOW But rather to tell how, if Art could tell, END
BEGIN NOW How from that sapphire fount the crisped brooks, END
BEGIN NOW Rolling on orient pearl and sands of gold, END
BEGIN NOW With mazy errour under pendant shades END
BEGIN NOW Ran nectar, visiting each plant, and fed END
BEGIN NOW Flowers worthy of Paradise, which not nice Art END
BEGIN NOW In beds and curious knots, but Nature boon END
BEGIN NOW Poured forth profuse on hill, and dale, and plain, END
BEGIN NOW Both where the morning sun first warmly smote END
BEGIN NOW The open field, and where the unpierced shade END
BEGIN NOW Imbrowned the noontide bowers: Thus was this place END
BEGIN NOW A happy rural seat of various view; END
BEGIN NOW Groves whose rich trees wept odorous gums and balm, END
BEGIN NOW Others whose fruit, burnished with golden rind, END
BEGIN NOW Hung amiable, Hesperian fables true, END
BEGIN NOW If true, here only, and of delicious taste: END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt them lawns, or level downs, and flocks END
BEGIN NOW Grazing the tender herb, were interposed, END
BEGIN NOW Or palmy hillock; or the flowery lap END
BEGIN NOW Of some irriguous valley spread her store, END
BEGIN NOW Flowers of all hue, and without thorn the rose: END
BEGIN NOW Another side, umbrageous grots and caves END
BEGIN NOW Of cool recess, o'er which the mantling vine END
BEGIN NOW Lays forth her purple grape, and gently creeps END
BEGIN NOW Luxuriant; mean while murmuring waters fall END
BEGIN NOW Down the slope hills, dispersed, or in a lake, END
BEGIN NOW That to the fringed bank with myrtle crowned END
BEGIN NOW Her crystal mirrour holds, unite their streams. END
BEGIN NOW The birds their quire apply; airs, vernal airs, END
BEGIN NOW Breathing the smell of field and grove, attune END
BEGIN NOW The trembling leaves, while universal Pan, END
BEGIN NOW Knit with the Graces and the Hours in dance, END
BEGIN NOW Led on the eternal Spring. Not that fair field END
BEGIN NOW Of Enna, where Proserpine gathering flowers, END
BEGIN NOW Herself a fairer flower by gloomy Dis END
BEGIN NOW Was gathered, which cost Ceres all that pain END
BEGIN NOW To seek her through the world; nor that sweet grove END
BEGIN NOW Of Daphne by Orontes, and the inspired END
BEGIN NOW Castalian spring, might with this Paradise END
BEGIN NOW Of Eden strive; nor that Nyseian isle END
BEGIN NOW Girt with the river Triton, where old Cham, END
BEGIN NOW Whom Gentiles Ammon call and Libyan Jove, END
BEGIN NOW Hid Amalthea, and her florid son END
BEGIN NOW Young Bacchus, from his stepdame Rhea's eye; END
BEGIN NOW Nor where Abassin kings their issue guard, END
BEGIN NOW Mount Amara, though this by some supposed END
BEGIN NOW True Paradise under the Ethiop line END
BEGIN NOW By Nilus' head, enclosed with shining rock, END
BEGIN NOW A whole day's journey high, but wide remote END
BEGIN NOW From this Assyrian garden, where the Fiend END
BEGIN NOW Saw, undelighted, all delight, all kind END
BEGIN NOW Of living creatures, new to sight, and strange END
BEGIN NOW Two of far nobler shape, erect and tall, END
BEGIN NOW Godlike erect, with native honour clad END
BEGIN NOW In naked majesty seemed lords of all: END
BEGIN NOW And worthy seemed; for in their looks divine END
BEGIN NOW The image of their glorious Maker shone, END
BEGIN NOW Truth, wisdom, sanctitude severe and pure, END
BEGIN NOW (Severe, but in true filial freedom placed,) END
BEGIN NOW Whence true authority in men; though both END
BEGIN NOW Not equal, as their sex not equal seemed; END
BEGIN NOW For contemplation he and valour formed; END
BEGIN NOW For softness she and sweet attractive grace; END
BEGIN NOW He for God only, she for God in him: END
BEGIN NOW His fair large front and eye sublime declared END
BEGIN NOW Absolute rule; and hyacinthine locks END
BEGIN NOW Round from his parted forelock manly hung END
BEGIN NOW Clustering, but not beneath his shoulders broad: END
BEGIN NOW She, as a veil, down to the slender waist END
BEGIN NOW Her unadorned golden tresses wore END
BEGIN NOW Dishevelled, but in wanton ringlets waved END
BEGIN NOW As the vine curls her tendrils, which implied END
BEGIN NOW Subjection, but required with gentle sway, END
BEGIN NOW And by her yielded, by him best received, END
BEGIN NOW Yielded with coy submission, modest pride, END
BEGIN NOW And sweet, reluctant, amorous delay. END
BEGIN NOW Nor those mysterious parts were then concealed; END
BEGIN NOW Then was not guilty shame, dishonest shame END
BEGIN NOW Of nature's works, honour dishonourable, END
BEGIN NOW Sin-bred, how have ye troubled all mankind END
BEGIN NOW With shows instead, mere shows of seeming pure, END
BEGIN NOW And banished from man's life his happiest life, END
BEGIN NOW Simplicity and spotless innocence! END
BEGIN NOW So passed they naked on, nor shunned the sight END
BEGIN NOW Of God or Angel; for they thought no ill: END
BEGIN NOW So hand in hand they passed, the loveliest pair, END
BEGIN NOW That ever since in love's embraces met; END
BEGIN NOW Adam the goodliest man of men since born END
BEGIN NOW His sons, the fairest of her daughters Eve. END
BEGIN NOW Under a tuft of shade that on a green END
BEGIN NOW Stood whispering soft, by a fresh fountain side END
BEGIN NOW They sat them down; and, after no more toil END
BEGIN NOW Of their sweet gardening labour than sufficed END
BEGIN NOW To recommend cool Zephyr, and made ease END
BEGIN NOW More easy, wholesome thirst and appetite END
BEGIN NOW More grateful, to their supper-fruits they fell, END
BEGIN NOW Nectarine fruits which the compliant boughs END
BEGIN NOW Yielded them, side-long as they sat recline END
BEGIN NOW On the soft downy bank damasked with flowers: END
BEGIN NOW The savoury pulp they chew, and in the rind, END
BEGIN NOW Still as they thirsted, scoop the brimming stream; END
BEGIN NOW Nor gentle purpose, nor endearing smiles END
BEGIN NOW Wanted, nor youthful dalliance, as beseems END
BEGIN NOW Fair couple, linked in happy nuptial league, END
BEGIN NOW Alone as they. About them frisking played END
BEGIN NOW All beasts of the earth, since wild, and of all chase END
BEGIN NOW In wood or wilderness, forest or den; END
BEGIN NOW Sporting the lion ramped, and in his paw END
BEGIN NOW Dandled the kid; bears, tigers, ounces, pards, END
BEGIN NOW Gambolled before them; the unwieldy elephant, END
BEGIN NOW To make them mirth, used all his might, and wreathed END
BEGIN NOW His lithe proboscis; close the serpent sly, END
BEGIN NOW Insinuating, wove with Gordian twine END
BEGIN NOW His braided train, and of his fatal guile END
BEGIN NOW Gave proof unheeded; others on the grass END
BEGIN NOW Couched, and now filled with pasture gazing sat, END
BEGIN NOW Or bedward ruminating; for the sun, END
BEGIN NOW Declined, was hasting now with prone career END
BEGIN NOW To the ocean isles, and in the ascending scale END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven the stars that usher evening rose: END
BEGIN NOW When Satan still in gaze, as first he stood, END
BEGIN NOW Scarce thus at length failed speech recovered sad. END
BEGIN NOW O Hell! what do mine eyes with grief behold! END
BEGIN NOW Into our room of bliss thus high advanced END
BEGIN NOW Creatures of other mould, earth-born perhaps, END
BEGIN NOW Not Spirits, yet to heavenly Spirits bright END
BEGIN NOW Little inferiour; whom my thoughts pursue END
BEGIN NOW With wonder, and could love, so lively shines END
BEGIN NOW In them divine resemblance, and such grace END
BEGIN NOW The hand that formed them on their shape hath poured. END
BEGIN NOW Ah! gentle pair, ye little think how nigh END
BEGIN NOW Your change approaches, when all these delights END
BEGIN NOW Will vanish, and deliver ye to woe; END
BEGIN NOW More woe, the more your taste is now of joy; END
BEGIN NOW Happy, but for so happy ill secured END
BEGIN NOW Long to continue, and this high seat your Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Ill fenced for Heaven to keep out such a foe END
BEGIN NOW As now is entered; yet no purposed foe END
BEGIN NOW To you, whom I could pity thus forlorn, END
BEGIN NOW Though I unpitied: League with you I seek, END
BEGIN NOW And mutual amity, so strait, so close, END
BEGIN NOW That I with you must dwell, or you with me END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth; my dwelling haply may not please, END
BEGIN NOW Like this fair Paradise, your sense; yet such END
BEGIN NOW Accept your Maker's work; he gave it me, END
BEGIN NOW Which I as freely give: Hell shall unfold, END
BEGIN NOW To entertain you two, her widest gates, END
BEGIN NOW And send forth all her kings; there will be room, END
BEGIN NOW Not like these narrow limits, to receive END
BEGIN NOW Your numerous offspring; if no better place, END
BEGIN NOW Thank him who puts me loth to this revenge END
BEGIN NOW On you who wrong me not for him who wronged. END
BEGIN NOW And should I at your harmless innocence END
BEGIN NOW Melt, as I do, yet publick reason just, END
BEGIN NOW Honour and empire with revenge enlarged, END
BEGIN NOW By conquering this new world, compels me now END
BEGIN NOW To do what else, though damned, I should abhor. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Fiend, and with necessity, END
BEGIN NOW The tyrant's plea, excused his devilish deeds. END
BEGIN NOW Then from his lofty stand on that high tree END
BEGIN NOW Down he alights among the sportful herd END
BEGIN NOW Of those four-footed kinds, himself now one, END
BEGIN NOW Now other, as their shape served best his end END
BEGIN NOW Nearer to view his prey, and, unespied, END
BEGIN NOW To mark what of their state he more might learn, END
BEGIN NOW By word or action marked. About them round END
BEGIN NOW A lion now he stalks with fiery glare; END
BEGIN NOW Then as a tiger, who by chance hath spied END
BEGIN NOW In some purlieu two gentle fawns at play, END
BEGIN NOW Straight couches close, then, rising, changes oft END
BEGIN NOW His couchant watch, as one who chose his ground, END
BEGIN NOW Whence rushing, he might surest seize them both, END
BEGIN NOW Griped in each paw: when, Adam first of men END
BEGIN NOW To first of women Eve thus moving speech, END
BEGIN NOW Turned him, all ear to hear new utterance flow. END
BEGIN NOW Sole partner, and sole part, of all these joys, END
BEGIN NOW Dearer thyself than all; needs must the Power END
BEGIN NOW That made us, and for us this ample world, END
BEGIN NOW Be infinitely good, and of his good END
BEGIN NOW As liberal and free as infinite; END
BEGIN NOW That raised us from the dust, and placed us here END
BEGIN NOW In all this happiness, who at his hand END
BEGIN NOW Have nothing merited, nor can perform END
BEGIN NOW Aught whereof he hath need; he who requires END
BEGIN NOW From us no other service than to keep END
BEGIN NOW This one, this easy charge, of all the trees END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise that bear delicious fruit END
BEGIN NOW So various, not to taste that only tree END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledge, planted by the tree of life; END
BEGIN NOW So near grows death to life, whate'er death is, END
BEGIN NOW Some dreadful thing no doubt; for well thou knowest END
BEGIN NOW God hath pronounced it death to taste that tree, END
BEGIN NOW The only sign of our obedience left, END
BEGIN NOW Among so many signs of power and rule END
BEGIN NOW Conferred upon us, and dominion given END
BEGIN NOW Over all other creatures that possess END
BEGIN NOW Earth, air, and sea. Then let us not think hard END
BEGIN NOW One easy prohibition, who enjoy END
BEGIN NOW Free leave so large to all things else, and choice END
BEGIN NOW Unlimited of manifold delights: END
BEGIN NOW But let us ever praise him, and extol END
BEGIN NOW His bounty, following our delightful task, END
BEGIN NOW To prune these growing plants, and tend these flowers, END
BEGIN NOW Which were it toilsome, yet with thee were sweet. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Eve replied. O thou for whom END
BEGIN NOW And from whom I was formed, flesh of thy flesh, END
BEGIN NOW And without whom am to no end, my guide END
BEGIN NOW And head! what thou hast said is just and right. END
BEGIN NOW For we to him indeed all praises owe, END
BEGIN NOW And daily thanks; I chiefly, who enjoy END
BEGIN NOW So far the happier lot, enjoying thee END
BEGIN NOW Pre-eminent by so much odds, while thou END
BEGIN NOW Like consort to thyself canst no where find. END
BEGIN NOW That day I oft remember, when from sleep END
BEGIN NOW I first awaked, and found myself reposed END
BEGIN NOW Under a shade on flowers, much wondering where END
BEGIN NOW And what I was, whence thither brought, and how. END
BEGIN NOW Not distant far from thence a murmuring sound END
BEGIN NOW Of waters issued from a cave, and spread END
BEGIN NOW Into a liquid plain, then stood unmoved END
BEGIN NOW Pure as the expanse of Heaven; I thither went END
BEGIN NOW With unexperienced thought, and laid me down END
BEGIN NOW On the green bank, to look into the clear END
BEGIN NOW Smooth lake, that to me seemed another sky. END
BEGIN NOW As I bent down to look, just opposite END
BEGIN NOW A shape within the watery gleam appeared, END
BEGIN NOW Bending to look on me: I started back, END
BEGIN NOW It started back; but pleased I soon returned, END
BEGIN NOW Pleased it returned as soon with answering looks END
BEGIN NOW Of sympathy and love: There I had fixed END
BEGIN NOW Mine eyes till now, and pined with vain desire, END
BEGIN NOW Had not a voice thus warned me; "What thou seest, END
BEGIN NOW What there thou seest, fair Creature, is thyself; END
BEGIN NOW With thee it came and goes: but follow me, END
BEGIN NOW And I will bring thee where no shadow stays END
BEGIN NOW Thy coming, and thy soft embraces, he END
BEGIN NOW Whose image thou art; him thou shalt enjoy END
BEGIN NOW Inseparably thine, to him shalt bear END
BEGIN NOW Multitudes like thyself, and thence be called END
BEGIN NOW Mother of human race." What could I do, END
BEGIN NOW But follow straight, invisibly thus led? END
BEGIN NOW Till I espied thee, fair indeed and tall, END
BEGIN NOW Under a platane; yet methought less fair, END
BEGIN NOW Less winning soft, less amiably mild, END
BEGIN NOW Than that smooth watery image: Back I turned; END
BEGIN NOW Thou following cryedst aloud, "Return, fair Eve; END
BEGIN NOW Whom flyest thou? whom thou flyest, of him thou art, END
BEGIN NOW His flesh, his bone; to give thee being I lent END
BEGIN NOW Out of my side to thee, nearest my heart, END
BEGIN NOW Substantial life, to have thee by my side END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth an individual solace dear; END
BEGIN NOW Part of my soul I seek thee, and thee claim END
BEGIN NOW My other half:" With that thy gentle hand END
BEGIN NOW Seised mine: I yielded; and from that time see END
BEGIN NOW How beauty is excelled by manly grace, END
BEGIN NOW And wisdom, which alone is truly fair. END
BEGIN NOW So spake our general mother, and with eyes END
BEGIN NOW Of conjugal attraction unreproved, END
BEGIN NOW And meek surrender, half-embracing leaned END
BEGIN NOW On our first father; half her swelling breast END
BEGIN NOW Naked met his, under the flowing gold END
BEGIN NOW Of her loose tresses hid: he in delight END
BEGIN NOW Both of her beauty, and submissive charms, END
BEGIN NOW Smiled with superiour love, as Jupiter END
BEGIN NOW On Juno smiles, when he impregns the clouds END
BEGIN NOW That shed Mayflowers; and pressed her matron lip END
BEGIN NOW With kisses pure: Aside the Devil turned END
BEGIN NOW For envy; yet with jealous leer malign END
BEGIN NOW Eyed them askance, and to himself thus plained. END
BEGIN NOW Sight hateful, sight tormenting! thus these two, END
BEGIN NOW Imparadised in one another's arms, END
BEGIN NOW The happier Eden, shall enjoy their fill END
BEGIN NOW Of bliss on bliss; while I to Hell am thrust, END
BEGIN NOW Where neither joy nor love, but fierce desire, END
BEGIN NOW Among our other torments not the least, END
BEGIN NOW Still unfulfilled with pain of longing pines. END
BEGIN NOW Yet let me not forget what I have gained END
BEGIN NOW From their own mouths: All is not theirs, it seems; END
BEGIN NOW One fatal tree there stands, of knowledge called, END
BEGIN NOW Forbidden them to taste: Knowledge forbidden END
BEGIN NOW Suspicious, reasonless. Why should their Lord END
BEGIN NOW Envy them that? Can it be sin to know? END
BEGIN NOW Can it be death? And do they only stand END
BEGIN NOW By ignorance? Is that their happy state, END
BEGIN NOW The proof of their obedience and their faith? END
BEGIN NOW O fair foundation laid whereon to build END
BEGIN NOW Their ruin! hence I will excite their minds END
BEGIN NOW With more desire to know, and to reject END
BEGIN NOW Envious commands, invented with design END
BEGIN NOW To keep them low, whom knowledge might exalt END
BEGIN NOW Equal with Gods: aspiring to be such, END
BEGIN NOW They taste and die: What likelier can ensue END
BEGIN NOW But first with narrow search I must walk round END
BEGIN NOW This garden, and no corner leave unspied; END
BEGIN NOW A chance but chance may lead where I may meet END
BEGIN NOW Some wandering Spirit of Heaven by fountain side, END
BEGIN NOW Or in thick shade retired, from him to draw END
BEGIN NOW What further would be learned. Live while ye may, END
BEGIN NOW Yet happy pair; enjoy, till I return, END
BEGIN NOW Short pleasures, for long woes are to succeed! END
BEGIN NOW So saying, his proud step he scornful turned, END
BEGIN NOW But with sly circumspection, and began END
BEGIN NOW Through wood, through waste, o'er hill, o'er dale, his roam END
BEGIN NOW Mean while in utmost longitude, where Heaven END
BEGIN NOW With earth and ocean meets, the setting sun END
BEGIN NOW Slowly descended, and with right aspect END
BEGIN NOW Against the eastern gate of Paradise END
BEGIN NOW Levelled his evening rays: It was a rock END
BEGIN NOW Of alabaster, piled up to the clouds, END
BEGIN NOW Conspicuous far, winding with one ascent END
BEGIN NOW Accessible from earth, one entrance high; END
BEGIN NOW The rest was craggy cliff, that overhung END
BEGIN NOW Still as it rose, impossible to climb. END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt these rocky pillars Gabriel sat, END
BEGIN NOW Chief of the angelick guards, awaiting night; END
BEGIN NOW About him exercised heroick games END
BEGIN NOW The unarmed youth of Heaven, but nigh at hand END
BEGIN NOW Celestial armoury, shields, helms, and spears, END
BEGIN NOW Hung high with diamond flaming, and with gold. END
BEGIN NOW Thither came Uriel, gliding through the even END
BEGIN NOW On a sun-beam, swift as a shooting star END
BEGIN NOW In autumn thwarts the night, when vapours fired END
BEGIN NOW Impress the air, and shows the mariner END
BEGIN NOW From what point of his compass to beware END
BEGIN NOW Impetuous winds: He thus began in haste. END
BEGIN NOW Gabriel, to thee thy course by lot hath given END
BEGIN NOW Charge and strict watch, that to this happy place END
BEGIN NOW No evil thing approach or enter in. END
BEGIN NOW This day at highth of noon came to my sphere END
BEGIN NOW A Spirit, zealous, as he seemed, to know END
BEGIN NOW More of the Almighty's works, and chiefly Man, END
BEGIN NOW God's latest image: I described his way END
BEGIN NOW Bent all on speed, and marked his aery gait; END
BEGIN NOW But in the mount that lies from Eden north, END
BEGIN NOW Where he first lighted, soon discerned his looks END
BEGIN NOW Alien from Heaven, with passions foul obscured: END
BEGIN NOW Mine eye pursued him still, but under shade END
BEGIN NOW Lost sight of him: One of the banished crew, END
BEGIN NOW I fear, hath ventured from the deep, to raise END
BEGIN NOW New troubles; him thy care must be to find. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the winged warriour thus returned. END
BEGIN NOW Uriel, no wonder if thy perfect sight, END
BEGIN NOW Amid the sun's bright circle where thou sitst, END
BEGIN NOW See far and wide: In at this gate none pass END
BEGIN NOW The vigilance here placed, but such as come END
BEGIN NOW Well known from Heaven; and since meridian hour END
BEGIN NOW No creature thence: If Spirit of other sort, END
BEGIN NOW So minded, have o'er-leaped these earthly bounds END
BEGIN NOW On purpose, hard thou knowest it to exclude END
BEGIN NOW Spiritual substance with corporeal bar. END
BEGIN NOW But if within the circuit of these walks, END
BEGIN NOW In whatsoever shape he lurk, of whom END
BEGIN NOW Thou tellest, by morrow dawning I shall know. END
BEGIN NOW So promised he; and Uriel to his charge END
BEGIN NOW Returned on that bright beam, whose point now raised END
BEGIN NOW Bore him slope downward to the sun now fallen END
BEGIN NOW Beneath the Azores; whether the prime orb, END
BEGIN NOW Incredible how swift, had thither rolled END
BEGIN NOW Diurnal, or this less volubil earth, END
BEGIN NOW By shorter flight to the east, had left him there END
BEGIN NOW Arraying with reflected purple and gold END
BEGIN NOW The clouds that on his western throne attend. END
BEGIN NOW Now came still Evening on, and Twilight gray END
BEGIN NOW Had in her sober livery all things clad; END
BEGIN NOW Silence accompanied; for beast and bird, END
BEGIN NOW They to their grassy couch, these to their nests END
BEGIN NOW Were slunk, all but the wakeful nightingale; END
BEGIN NOW She all night long her amorous descant sung; END
BEGIN NOW Silence was pleased: Now glowed the firmament END
BEGIN NOW With living sapphires: Hesperus, that led END
BEGIN NOW The starry host, rode brightest, till the moon, END
BEGIN NOW Rising in clouded majesty, at length END
BEGIN NOW Apparent queen unveiled her peerless light, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er the dark her silver mantle threw. END
BEGIN NOW When Adam thus to Eve. Fair Consort, the hour END
BEGIN NOW Of night, and all things now retired to rest, END
BEGIN NOW Mind us of like repose; since God hath set END
BEGIN NOW Labour and rest, as day and night, to men END
BEGIN NOW Successive; and the timely dew of sleep, END
BEGIN NOW Now falling with soft slumbrous weight, inclines END
BEGIN NOW Our eye-lids: Other creatures all day long END
BEGIN NOW Rove idle, unemployed, and less need rest; END
BEGIN NOW Man hath his daily work of body or mind END
BEGIN NOW Appointed, which declares his dignity, END
BEGIN NOW And the regard of Heaven on all his ways; END
BEGIN NOW While other animals unactive range, END
BEGIN NOW And of their doings God takes no account. END
BEGIN NOW To-morrow, ere fresh morning streak the east END
BEGIN NOW With first approach of light, we must be risen, END
BEGIN NOW And at our pleasant labour, to reform END
BEGIN NOW Yon flowery arbours, yonder alleys green, END
BEGIN NOW Our walk at noon, with branches overgrown, END
BEGIN NOW That mock our scant manuring, and require END
BEGIN NOW More hands than ours to lop their wanton growth: END
BEGIN NOW Those blossoms also, and those dropping gums, END
BEGIN NOW That lie bestrown, unsightly and unsmooth, END
BEGIN NOW Ask riddance, if we mean to tread with ease; END
BEGIN NOW Mean while, as Nature wills, night bids us rest. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Eve, with perfect beauty adorned END
BEGIN NOW My Author and Disposer, what thou bidst END
BEGIN NOW Unargued I obey: So God ordains; END
BEGIN NOW God is thy law, thou mine: To know no more END
BEGIN NOW Is woman's happiest knowledge, and her praise. END
BEGIN NOW With thee conversing I forget all time; END
BEGIN NOW All seasons, and their change, all please alike. END
BEGIN NOW Sweet is the breath of Morn, her rising sweet, END
BEGIN NOW With charm of earliest birds: pleasant the sun, END
BEGIN NOW When first on this delightful land he spreads END
BEGIN NOW His orient beams, on herb, tree, fruit, and flower, END
BEGIN NOW Glistering with dew; fragrant the fertile earth END
BEGIN NOW After soft showers; and sweet the coming on END
BEGIN NOW Of grateful Evening mild; then silent Night, END
BEGIN NOW With this her solemn bird, and this fair moon, END
BEGIN NOW And these the gems of Heaven, her starry train: END
BEGIN NOW But neither breath of Morn, when she ascends END
BEGIN NOW With charm of earliest birds; nor rising sun END
BEGIN NOW On this delightful land; nor herb, fruit, flower, END
BEGIN NOW Glistering with dew; nor fragrance after showers; END
BEGIN NOW Nor grateful Evening mild; nor silent Night, END
BEGIN NOW With this her solemn bird, nor walk by moon, END
BEGIN NOW Or glittering star-light, without thee is sweet. END
BEGIN NOW But wherefore all night long shine these? for whom END
BEGIN NOW This glorious sight, when sleep hath shut all eyes? END
BEGIN NOW To whom our general ancestor replied. END
BEGIN NOW Daughter of God and Man, accomplished Eve, END
BEGIN NOW These have their course to finish round the earth, END
BEGIN NOW By morrow evening, and from land to land END
BEGIN NOW In order, though to nations yet unborn, END
BEGIN NOW Ministring light prepared, they set and rise; END
BEGIN NOW Lest total Darkness should by night regain END
BEGIN NOW Her old possession, and extinguish life END
BEGIN NOW In Nature and all things; which these soft fires END
BEGIN NOW Not only enlighten, but with kindly heat END
BEGIN NOW Of various influence foment and warm, END
BEGIN NOW Temper or nourish, or in part shed down END
BEGIN NOW Their stellar virtue on all kinds that grow END
BEGIN NOW On earth, made hereby apter to receive END
BEGIN NOW Perfection from the sun's more potent ray. END
BEGIN NOW These then, though unbeheld in deep of night, END
BEGIN NOW Shine not in vain; nor think, though men were none, END
BEGIN NOW That Heaven would want spectators, God want praise: END
BEGIN NOW Millions of spiritual creatures walk the earth END
BEGIN NOW Unseen, both when we wake, and when we sleep: END
BEGIN NOW All these with ceaseless praise his works behold END
BEGIN NOW Both day and night: How often from the steep END
BEGIN NOW Of echoing hill or thicket have we heard END
BEGIN NOW Celestial voices to the midnight air, END
BEGIN NOW Sole, or responsive each to others note, END
BEGIN NOW Singing their great Creator? oft in bands END
BEGIN NOW While they keep watch, or nightly rounding walk, END
BEGIN NOW With heavenly touch of instrumental sounds END
BEGIN NOW In full harmonick number joined, their songs END
BEGIN NOW Divide the night, and lift our thoughts to Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Thus talking, hand in hand alone they passed END
BEGIN NOW On to their blissful bower: it was a place END
BEGIN NOW Chosen by the sovran Planter, when he framed END
BEGIN NOW All things to Man's delightful use; the roof END
BEGIN NOW Of thickest covert was inwoven shade END
BEGIN NOW Laurel and myrtle, and what higher grew END
BEGIN NOW Of firm and fragrant leaf; on either side END
BEGIN NOW Acanthus, and each odorous bushy shrub, END
BEGIN NOW Fenced up the verdant wall; each beauteous flower, END
BEGIN NOW Iris all hues, roses, and jessamin, END
BEGIN NOW Reared high their flourished heads between, and wrought END
BEGIN NOW Mosaick; underfoot the violet, END
BEGIN NOW Crocus, and hyacinth, with rich inlay END
BEGIN NOW Broidered the ground, more coloured than with stone END
BEGIN NOW Of costliest emblem: Other creature here, END
BEGIN NOW Bird, beast, insect, or worm, durst enter none, END
BEGIN NOW Such was their awe of Man. In shadier bower END
BEGIN NOW More sacred and sequestered, though but feigned, END
BEGIN NOW Pan or Sylvanus never slept, nor Nymph END
BEGIN NOW Nor Faunus haunted. Here, in close recess, END
BEGIN NOW With flowers, garlands, and sweet-smelling herbs, END
BEGIN NOW Espoused Eve decked first her nuptial bed; END
BEGIN NOW And heavenly quires the hymenaean sung, END
BEGIN NOW What day the genial Angel to our sire END
BEGIN NOW Brought her in naked beauty more adorned, END
BEGIN NOW More lovely, than Pandora, whom the Gods END
BEGIN NOW Endowed with all their gifts, and O! too like END
BEGIN NOW In sad event, when to the unwiser son END
BEGIN NOW Mankind with her fair looks, to be avenged END
BEGIN NOW On him who had stole Jove's authentick fire. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, at their shady lodge arrived, both stood, END
BEGIN NOW Both turned, and under open sky adored END
BEGIN NOW The God that made both sky, air, earth, and heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Which they beheld, the moon's resplendent globe, END
BEGIN NOW And starry pole: Thou also madest the night, END
BEGIN NOW Maker Omnipotent, and thou the day, END
BEGIN NOW Which we, in our appointed work employed, END
BEGIN NOW Have finished, happy in our mutual help END
BEGIN NOW And mutual love, the crown of all our bliss END
BEGIN NOW Ordained by thee; and this delicious place END
BEGIN NOW For us too large, where thy abundance wants END
BEGIN NOW Partakers, and uncropt falls to the ground. END
BEGIN NOW But thou hast promised from us two a race END
BEGIN NOW To fill the earth, who shall with us extol END
BEGIN NOW Thy goodness infinite, both when we wake, END
BEGIN NOW And when we seek, as now, thy gift of sleep. END
BEGIN NOW This said unanimous, and other rites END
BEGIN NOW Observing none, but adoration pure END
BEGIN NOW Which God likes best, into their inmost bower END
BEGIN NOW Handed they went; and, eased the putting off END
BEGIN NOW These troublesome disguises which we wear, END
BEGIN NOW Straight side by side were laid; nor turned, I ween, END
BEGIN NOW Adam from his fair spouse, nor Eve the rites END
BEGIN NOW Mysterious of connubial love refused: END
BEGIN NOW Whatever hypocrites austerely talk END
BEGIN NOW Of purity, and place, and innocence, END
BEGIN NOW Defaming as impure what God declares END
BEGIN NOW Pure, and commands to some, leaves free to all. END
BEGIN NOW Our Maker bids encrease; who bids abstain END
BEGIN NOW Hail, wedded Love, mysterious law, true source END
BEGIN NOW Of human offspring, sole propriety END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise of all things common else! END
BEGIN NOW By thee adulterous Lust was driven from men END
BEGIN NOW Among the bestial herds to range; by thee END
BEGIN NOW Founded in reason, loyal, just, and pure, END
BEGIN NOW Relations dear, and all the charities END
BEGIN NOW Of father, son, and brother, first were known. END
BEGIN NOW Far be it, that I should write thee sin or blame, END
BEGIN NOW Or think thee unbefitting holiest place, END
BEGIN NOW Perpetual fountain of domestick sweets, END
BEGIN NOW Whose bed is undefiled and chaste pronounced, END
BEGIN NOW Present, or past, as saints and patriarchs used. END
BEGIN NOW Here Love his golden shafts employs, here lights END
BEGIN NOW His constant lamp, and waves his purple wings, END
BEGIN NOW Reigns here and revels; not in the bought smile END
BEGIN NOW Of harlots, loveless, joyless, unendeared, END
BEGIN NOW Casual fruition; nor in court-amours, END
BEGIN NOW Mixed dance, or wanton mask, or midnight ball, END
BEGIN NOW Or serenate, which the starved lover sings END
BEGIN NOW To his proud fair, best quitted with disdain. END
BEGIN NOW These, lulled by nightingales, embracing slept, END
BEGIN NOW And on their naked limbs the flowery roof END
BEGIN NOW Showered roses, which the morn repaired. Sleep on, END
BEGIN NOW Blest pair; and O! yet happiest, if ye seek END
BEGIN NOW No happier state, and know to know no more. END
BEGIN NOW Now had night measured with her shadowy cone END
BEGIN NOW Half way up hill this vast sublunar vault, END
BEGIN NOW And from their ivory port the Cherubim, END
BEGIN NOW Forth issuing at the accustomed hour, stood armed END
BEGIN NOW To their night watches in warlike parade; END
BEGIN NOW When Gabriel to his next in power thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW Uzziel, half these draw off, and coast the south END
BEGIN NOW With strictest watch; these other wheel the north; END
BEGIN NOW Our circuit meets full west. As flame they part, END
BEGIN NOW Half wheeling to the shield, half to the spear. END
BEGIN NOW From these, two strong and subtle Spirits he called END
BEGIN NOW That near him stood, and gave them thus in charge. END
BEGIN NOW Ithuriel and Zephon, with winged speed END
BEGIN NOW Search through this garden, leave unsearched no nook; END
BEGIN NOW But chiefly where those two fair creatures lodge, END
BEGIN NOW Now laid perhaps asleep, secure of harm. END
BEGIN NOW This evening from the sun's decline arrived, END
BEGIN NOW Who tells of some infernal Spirit seen END
BEGIN NOW Hitherward bent (who could have thought?) escaped END
BEGIN NOW The bars of Hell, on errand bad no doubt: END
BEGIN NOW Such, where ye find, seise fast, and hither bring. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, on he led his radiant files, END
BEGIN NOW Dazzling the moon; these to the bower direct END
BEGIN NOW In search of whom they sought: Him there they found END
BEGIN NOW Squat like a toad, close at the ear of Eve, END
BEGIN NOW Assaying by his devilish art to reach END
BEGIN NOW The organs of her fancy, and with them forge END
BEGIN NOW Illusions, as he list, phantasms and dreams; END
BEGIN NOW Or if, inspiring venom, he might taint END
BEGIN NOW The animal spirits, that from pure blood arise END
BEGIN NOW Like gentle breaths from rivers pure, thence raise END
BEGIN NOW At least distempered, discontented thoughts, END
BEGIN NOW Vain hopes, vain aims, inordinate desires, END
BEGIN NOW Blown up with high conceits ingendering pride. END
BEGIN NOW Him thus intent Ithuriel with his spear END
BEGIN NOW Touched lightly; for no falshood can endure END
BEGIN NOW Touch of celestial temper, but returns END
BEGIN NOW Of force to its own likeness: Up he starts END
BEGIN NOW Discovered and surprised. As when a spark END
BEGIN NOW Lights on a heap of nitrous powder, laid END
BEGIN NOW Fit for the tun some magazine to store END
BEGIN NOW Against a rumoured war, the smutty grain, END
BEGIN NOW With sudden blaze diffused, inflames the air; END
BEGIN NOW So started up in his own shape the Fiend. END
BEGIN NOW Back stept those two fair Angels, half amazed END
BEGIN NOW So sudden to behold the grisly king; END
BEGIN NOW Yet thus, unmoved with fear, accost him soon. END
BEGIN NOW Which of those rebel Spirits adjudged to Hell END
BEGIN NOW Comest thou, escaped thy prison? and, transformed, END
BEGIN NOW Why sat'st thou like an enemy in wait, END
BEGIN NOW Here watching at the head of these that sleep? END
BEGIN NOW Know ye not then said Satan, filled with scorn, END
BEGIN NOW Know ye not me? ye knew me once no mate END
BEGIN NOW For you, there sitting where ye durst not soar: END
BEGIN NOW Not to know me argues yourselves unknown, END
BEGIN NOW The lowest of your throng; or, if ye know, END
BEGIN NOW Why ask ye, and superfluous begin END
BEGIN NOW Your message, like to end as much in vain? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Zephon, answering scorn with scorn. END
BEGIN NOW Think not, revolted Spirit, thy shape the same, END
BEGIN NOW Or undiminished brightness to be known, END
BEGIN NOW As when thou stoodest in Heaven upright and pure; END
BEGIN NOW That glory then, when thou no more wast good, END
BEGIN NOW Departed from thee; and thou resemblest now END
BEGIN NOW Thy sin and place of doom obscure and foul. END
BEGIN NOW But come, for thou, be sure, shalt give account END
BEGIN NOW To him who sent us, whose charge is to keep END
BEGIN NOW This place inviolable, and these from harm. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Cherub; and his grave rebuke, END
BEGIN NOW Severe in youthful beauty, added grace END
BEGIN NOW Invincible: Abashed the Devil stood, END
BEGIN NOW And felt how awful goodness is, and saw END
BEGIN NOW Virtue in her shape how lovely; saw, and pined END
BEGIN NOW His loss; but chiefly to find here observed END
BEGIN NOW His lustre visibly impaired; yet seemed END
BEGIN NOW Undaunted. If I must contend, said he, END
BEGIN NOW Best with the best, the sender, not the sent, END
BEGIN NOW Or all at once; more glory will be won, END
BEGIN NOW Or less be lost. Thy fear, said Zephon bold, END
BEGIN NOW Will save us trial what the least can do END
BEGIN NOW Single against thee wicked, and thence weak. END
BEGIN NOW The Fiend replied not, overcome with rage; END
BEGIN NOW But, like a proud steed reined, went haughty on, END
BEGIN NOW Champing his iron curb: To strive or fly END
BEGIN NOW He held it vain; awe from above had quelled END
BEGIN NOW His heart, not else dismayed. Now drew they nigh END
BEGIN NOW The western point, where those half-rounding guards END
BEGIN NOW Just met, and closing stood in squadron joined, END
BEGIN NOW A waiting next command. To whom their Chief, END
BEGIN NOW Gabriel, from the front thus called aloud. END
BEGIN NOW O friends! I hear the tread of nimble feet END
BEGIN NOW Hasting this way, and now by glimpse discern END
BEGIN NOW Ithuriel and Zephon through the shade; END
BEGIN NOW And with them comes a third of regal port, END
BEGIN NOW But faded splendour wan; who by his gait END
BEGIN NOW And fierce demeanour seems the Prince of Hell, END
BEGIN NOW Not likely to part hence without contest; END
BEGIN NOW Stand firm, for in his look defiance lours. END
BEGIN NOW He scarce had ended, when those two approached, END
BEGIN NOW And brief related whom they brought, where found, END
BEGIN NOW How busied, in what form and posture couched. END
BEGIN NOW To whom with stern regard thus Gabriel spake. END
BEGIN NOW Why hast thou, Satan, broke the bounds prescribed END
BEGIN NOW To thy transgressions, and disturbed the charge END
BEGIN NOW Of others, who approve not to transgress END
BEGIN NOW By thy example, but have power and right END
BEGIN NOW To question thy bold entrance on this place; END
BEGIN NOW Employed, it seems, to violate sleep, and those END
BEGIN NOW Whose dwelling God hath planted here in bliss! END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Satan with contemptuous brow. END
BEGIN NOW Gabriel? thou hadst in Heaven the esteem of wise, END
BEGIN NOW And such I held thee; but this question asked END
BEGIN NOW Puts me in doubt. Lives there who loves his pain! END
BEGIN NOW Who would not, finding way, break loose from Hell, END
BEGIN NOW Though thither doomed! Thou wouldst thyself, no doubt END
BEGIN NOW And boldly venture to whatever place END
BEGIN NOW Farthest from pain, where thou mightst hope to change END
BEGIN NOW Torment with ease, and soonest recompense END
BEGIN NOW Dole with delight, which in this place I sought; END
BEGIN NOW To thee no reason, who knowest only good, END
BEGIN NOW But evil hast not tried: and wilt object END
BEGIN NOW His will who bounds us! Let him surer bar END
BEGIN NOW His iron gates, if he intends our stay END
BEGIN NOW In that dark durance: Thus much what was asked. END
BEGIN NOW The rest is true, they found me where they say; END
BEGIN NOW But that implies not violence or harm. END
BEGIN NOW Thus he in scorn. The warlike Angel moved, END
BEGIN NOW Disdainfully half smiling, thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW O loss of one in Heaven to judge of wise END
BEGIN NOW Since Satan fell, whom folly overthrew, END
BEGIN NOW And now returns him from his prison 'scaped, END
BEGIN NOW Gravely in doubt whether to hold them wise END
BEGIN NOW Or not, who ask what boldness brought him hither END
BEGIN NOW Unlicensed from his bounds in Hell prescribed; END
BEGIN NOW So wise he judges it to fly from pain END
BEGIN NOW However, and to 'scape his punishment! END
BEGIN NOW So judge thou still, presumptuous! till the wrath, END
BEGIN NOW Which thou incurrest by flying, meet thy flight END
BEGIN NOW Sevenfold, and scourge that wisdom back to Hell, END
BEGIN NOW Which taught thee yet no better, that no pain END
BEGIN NOW Can equal anger infinite provoked. END
BEGIN NOW But wherefore thou alone? wherefore with thee END
BEGIN NOW Came not all hell broke loose? or thou than they END
BEGIN NOW Less hardy to endure? Courageous Chief! END
BEGIN NOW The first in flight from pain! hadst thou alleged END
BEGIN NOW To thy deserted host this cause of flight, END
BEGIN NOW Thou surely hadst not come sole fugitive. END
BEGIN NOW To which the Fiend thus answered, frowning stern. END
BEGIN NOW Not that I less endure, or shrink from pain, END
BEGIN NOW Insulting Angel! well thou knowest I stood END
BEGIN NOW Thy fiercest, when in battle to thy aid END
BEGIN NOW The blasting vollied thunder made all speed, END
BEGIN NOW And seconded thy else not dreaded spear. END
BEGIN NOW But still thy words at random, as before, END
BEGIN NOW Argue thy inexperience what behoves END
BEGIN NOW From hard assays and ill successes past END
BEGIN NOW A faithful leader, not to hazard all END
BEGIN NOW Through ways of danger by himself untried: END
BEGIN NOW I, therefore, I alone first undertook END
BEGIN NOW To wing the desolate abyss, and spy END
BEGIN NOW This new created world, whereof in Hell END
BEGIN NOW Fame is not silent, here in hope to find END
BEGIN NOW Better abode, and my afflicted Powers END
BEGIN NOW To settle here on earth, or in mid air; END
BEGIN NOW Though for possession put to try once more END
BEGIN NOW What thou and thy gay legions dare against; END
BEGIN NOW Whose easier business were to serve their Lord END
BEGIN NOW High up in Heaven, with songs to hymn his throne, END
BEGIN NOW And practised distances to cringe, not fight, END
BEGIN NOW To whom the warriour Angel soon replied. END
BEGIN NOW To say and straight unsay, pretending first END
BEGIN NOW Wise to fly pain, professing next the spy, END
BEGIN NOW Argues no leader but a liar traced, END
BEGIN NOW Satan, and couldst thou faithful add? O name, END
BEGIN NOW O sacred name of faithfulness profaned! END
BEGIN NOW Faithful to whom? to thy rebellious crew? END
BEGIN NOW Army of Fiends, fit body to fit head. END
BEGIN NOW Was this your discipline and faith engaged, END
BEGIN NOW Your military obedience, to dissolve END
BEGIN NOW Allegiance to the acknowledged Power supreme? END
BEGIN NOW And thou, sly hypocrite, who now wouldst seem END
BEGIN NOW Patron of liberty, who more than thou END
BEGIN NOW Once fawned, and cringed, and servilely adored END
BEGIN NOW Heaven's awful Monarch? wherefore, but in hope END
BEGIN NOW To dispossess him, and thyself to reign? END
BEGIN NOW But mark what I arreed thee now, Avant; END
BEGIN NOW Fly neither whence thou fledst! If from this hour END
BEGIN NOW Within these hallowed limits thou appear, END
BEGIN NOW Back to the infernal pit I drag thee chained, END
BEGIN NOW And seal thee so, as henceforth not to scorn END
BEGIN NOW The facile gates of Hell too slightly barred. END
BEGIN NOW So threatened he; but Satan to no threats END
BEGIN NOW Gave heed, but waxing more in rage replied. END
BEGIN NOW Then when I am thy captive talk of chains, END
BEGIN NOW Proud limitary Cherub! but ere then END
BEGIN NOW Far heavier load thyself expect to feel END
BEGIN NOW From my prevailing arm, though Heaven's King END
BEGIN NOW Ride on thy wings, and thou with thy compeers, END
BEGIN NOW Us'd to the yoke, drawest his triumphant wheels END
BEGIN NOW In progress through the road of Heaven star-paved. END
BEGIN NOW While thus he spake, the angelick squadron bright END
BEGIN NOW Turned fiery red, sharpening in mooned horns END
BEGIN NOW Their phalanx, and began to hem him round END
BEGIN NOW With ported spears, as thick as when a field END
BEGIN NOW Of Ceres ripe for harvest waving bends END
BEGIN NOW Her bearded grove of ears, which way the wind END
BEGIN NOW Sways them; the careful plowman doubting stands, END
BEGIN NOW Left on the threshing floor his hopeless sheaves END
BEGIN NOW Prove chaff. On the other side, Satan, alarmed, END
BEGIN NOW Collecting all his might, dilated stood, END
BEGIN NOW Like Teneriff or Atlas, unremoved: END
BEGIN NOW His stature reached the sky, and on his crest END
BEGIN NOW Sat Horrour plumed; nor wanted in his grasp END
BEGIN NOW What seemed both spear and shield: Now dreadful deeds END
BEGIN NOW Might have ensued, nor only Paradise END
BEGIN NOW In this commotion, but the starry cope END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven perhaps, or all the elements END
BEGIN NOW At least had gone to wrack, disturbed and torn END
BEGIN NOW With violence of this conflict, had not soon END
BEGIN NOW The Eternal, to prevent such horrid fray, END
BEGIN NOW Hung forth in Heaven his golden scales, yet seen END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt Astrea and the Scorpion sign, END
BEGIN NOW Wherein all things created first he weighed, END
BEGIN NOW The pendulous round earth with balanced air END
BEGIN NOW In counterpoise, now ponders all events, END
BEGIN NOW Battles and realms: In these he put two weights, END
BEGIN NOW The sequel each of parting and of fight: END
BEGIN NOW The latter quick up flew, and kicked the beam, END
BEGIN NOW Which Gabriel spying, thus bespake the Fiend. END
BEGIN NOW Satan, I know thy strength, and thou knowest mine; END
BEGIN NOW Neither our own, but given: What folly then END
BEGIN NOW To boast what arms can do? since thine no more END
BEGIN NOW Than Heaven permits, nor mine, though doubled now END
BEGIN NOW To trample thee as mire: For proof look up, END
BEGIN NOW And read thy lot in yon celestial sign; END
BEGIN NOW Where thou art weighed, and shown how light, how weak, END
BEGIN NOW If thou resist. The Fiend looked up, and knew END
BEGIN NOW His mounted scale aloft: Nor more; but fled END
BEGIN NOW Murmuring, and with him fled the shades of night. END
BEGIN NOW Now Morn, her rosy steps in the eastern clime END
BEGIN NOW Advancing, sowed the earth with orient pearl, END
BEGIN NOW When Adam waked, so customed; for his sleep END
BEGIN NOW Was aery-light, from pure digestion bred, END
BEGIN NOW And temperate vapours bland, which the only sound END
BEGIN NOW Of leaves and fuming rills, Aurora's fan, END
BEGIN NOW Lightly dispersed, and the shrill matin song END
BEGIN NOW Of birds on every bough; so much the more END
BEGIN NOW His wonder was to find unwakened Eve END
BEGIN NOW With tresses discomposed, and glowing cheek, END
BEGIN NOW As through unquiet rest: He, on his side END
BEGIN NOW Leaning half raised, with looks of cordial love END
BEGIN NOW Hung over her enamoured, and beheld END
BEGIN NOW Beauty, which, whether waking or asleep, END
BEGIN NOW Shot forth peculiar graces; then with voice END
BEGIN NOW Mild, as when Zephyrus on Flora breathes, END
BEGIN NOW Her hand soft touching, whispered thus. Awake, END
BEGIN NOW My fairest, my espoused, my latest found, END
BEGIN NOW Heaven's last best gift, my ever new delight! END
BEGIN NOW Awake: The morning shines, and the fresh field END
BEGIN NOW Calls us; we lose the prime, to mark how spring END
BEGIN NOW Our tender plants, how blows the citron grove, END
BEGIN NOW What drops the myrrh, and what the balmy reed, END
BEGIN NOW How nature paints her colours, how the bee END
BEGIN NOW Sits on the bloom extracting liquid sweet. END
BEGIN NOW Such whispering waked her, but with startled eye END
BEGIN NOW On Adam, whom embracing, thus she spake. END
BEGIN NOW O sole in whom my thoughts find all repose, END
BEGIN NOW My glory, my perfection! glad I see END
BEGIN NOW Thy face, and morn returned; for I this night END
BEGIN NOW (Such night till this I never passed) have dreamed, END
BEGIN NOW If dreamed, not, as I oft am wont, of thee, END
BEGIN NOW Works of day past, or morrow's next design, END
BEGIN NOW But of offence and trouble, which my mind END
BEGIN NOW Knew never till this irksome night: Methought, END
BEGIN NOW Close at mine ear one called me forth to walk END
BEGIN NOW With gentle voice; I thought it thine: It said, END
BEGIN NOW Why sleepest thou, Eve? now is the pleasant time, END
BEGIN NOW The cool, the silent, save where silence yields END
BEGIN NOW To the night-warbling bird, that now awake END
BEGIN NOW Tunes sweetest his love-laboured song; now reigns END
BEGIN NOW Full-orbed the moon, and with more pleasing light END
BEGIN NOW Shadowy sets off the face of things; in vain, END
BEGIN NOW If none regard; Heaven wakes with all his eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Whom to behold but thee, Nature's desire? END
BEGIN NOW In whose sight all things joy, with ravishment END
BEGIN NOW Attracted by thy beauty still to gaze. END
BEGIN NOW I rose as at thy call, but found thee not; END
BEGIN NOW To find thee I directed then my walk; END
BEGIN NOW And on, methought, alone I passed through ways END
BEGIN NOW That brought me on a sudden to the tree END
BEGIN NOW Of interdicted knowledge: fair it seemed, END
BEGIN NOW Much fairer to my fancy than by day: END
BEGIN NOW And, as I wondering looked, beside it stood END
BEGIN NOW One shaped and winged like one of those from Heaven END
BEGIN NOW By us oft seen; his dewy locks distilled END
BEGIN NOW Ambrosia; on that tree he also gazed; END
BEGIN NOW And "O fair plant," said he, "with fruit surcharged, END
BEGIN NOW Deigns none to ease thy load, and taste thy sweet, END
BEGIN NOW Nor God, nor Man? Is knowledge so despised? END
BEGIN NOW Or envy, or what reserve forbids to taste? END
BEGIN NOW Forbid who will, none shall from me withhold END
BEGIN NOW Longer thy offered good; why else set here? END
BEGIN NOW This said, he paused not, but with venturous arm END
BEGIN NOW He plucked, he tasted; me damp horrour chilled END
BEGIN NOW At such bold words vouched with a deed so bold: END
BEGIN NOW But he thus, overjoyed; "O fruit divine, END
BEGIN NOW Sweet of thyself, but much more sweet thus cropt, END
BEGIN NOW Forbidden here, it seems, as only fit END
BEGIN NOW For Gods, yet able to make Gods of Men: END
BEGIN NOW And why not Gods of Men; since good, the more END
BEGIN NOW Communicated, more abundant grows, END
BEGIN NOW The author not impaired, but honoured more? END
BEGIN NOW Here, happy creature, fair angelick Eve! END
BEGIN NOW Partake thou also; happy though thou art, END
BEGIN NOW Happier thou mayest be, worthier canst not be: END
BEGIN NOW Taste this, and be henceforth among the Gods END
BEGIN NOW Thyself a Goddess, not to earth confined, END
BEGIN NOW But sometimes in the air, as we, sometimes END
BEGIN NOW Ascend to Heaven, by merit thine, and see END
BEGIN NOW What life the Gods live there, and such live thou! END
BEGIN NOW So saying, he drew nigh, and to me held, END
BEGIN NOW Even to my mouth of that same fruit held part END
BEGIN NOW Which he had plucked; the pleasant savoury smell END
BEGIN NOW So quickened appetite, that I, methought, END
BEGIN NOW Could not but taste. Forthwith up to the clouds END
BEGIN NOW With him I flew, and underneath beheld END
BEGIN NOW The earth outstretched immense, a prospect wide END
BEGIN NOW And various: Wondering at my flight and change END
BEGIN NOW To this high exaltation; suddenly END
BEGIN NOW My guide was gone, and I, methought, sunk down, END
BEGIN NOW And fell asleep; but O, how glad I waked END
BEGIN NOW To find this but a dream! Thus Eve her night END
BEGIN NOW Related, and thus Adam answered sad. END
BEGIN NOW Best image of myself, and dearer half, END
BEGIN NOW The trouble of thy thoughts this night in sleep END
BEGIN NOW Affects me equally; nor can I like END
BEGIN NOW This uncouth dream, of evil sprung, I fear; END
BEGIN NOW Yet evil whence? in thee can harbour none, END
BEGIN NOW Created pure. But know that in the soul END
BEGIN NOW Are many lesser faculties, that serve END
BEGIN NOW Reason as chief; among these Fancy next END
BEGIN NOW Her office holds; of all external things END
BEGIN NOW Which the five watchful senses represent, END
BEGIN NOW She forms imaginations, aery shapes, END
BEGIN NOW Which Reason, joining or disjoining, frames END
BEGIN NOW All what we affirm or what deny, and call END
BEGIN NOW Our knowledge or opinion; then retires END
BEGIN NOW Into her private cell, when nature rests. END
BEGIN NOW Oft in her absence mimick Fancy wakes END
BEGIN NOW To imitate her; but, misjoining shapes, END
BEGIN NOW Wild work produces oft, and most in dreams; END
BEGIN NOW Ill matching words and deeds long past or late. END
BEGIN NOW Some such resemblances, methinks, I find END
BEGIN NOW Of our last evening's talk, in this thy dream, END
BEGIN NOW But with addition strange; yet be not sad. END
BEGIN NOW Evil into the mind of God or Man END
BEGIN NOW May come and go, so unreproved, and leave END
BEGIN NOW No spot or blame behind: Which gives me hope END
BEGIN NOW That what in sleep thou didst abhor to dream, END
BEGIN NOW Waking thou never will consent to do. END
BEGIN NOW Be not disheartened then, nor cloud those looks, END
BEGIN NOW That wont to be more cheerful and serene, END
BEGIN NOW Than when fair morning first smiles on the world; END
BEGIN NOW And let us to our fresh employments rise END
BEGIN NOW Among the groves, the fountains, and the flowers END
BEGIN NOW That open now their choisest bosomed smells, END
BEGIN NOW Reserved from night, and kept for thee in store. END
BEGIN NOW So cheered he his fair spouse, and she was cheered; END
BEGIN NOW But silently a gentle tear let fall END
BEGIN NOW From either eye, and wiped them with her hair; END
BEGIN NOW Two other precious drops that ready stood, END
BEGIN NOW Each in their crystal sluice, he ere they fell END
BEGIN NOW Kissed, as the gracious signs of sweet remorse END
BEGIN NOW And pious awe, that feared to have offended. END
BEGIN NOW So all was cleared, and to the field they haste. END
BEGIN NOW But first, from under shady arborous roof END
BEGIN NOW Soon as they forth were come to open sight END
BEGIN NOW Of day-spring, and the sun, who, scarce up-risen, END
BEGIN NOW With wheels yet hovering o'er the ocean-brim, END
BEGIN NOW Shot parallel to the earth his dewy ray, END
BEGIN NOW Discovering in wide landskip all the east END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise and Eden's happy plains, END
BEGIN NOW Lowly they bowed adoring, and began END
BEGIN NOW Their orisons, each morning duly paid END
BEGIN NOW In various style; for neither various style END
BEGIN NOW Nor holy rapture wanted they to praise END
BEGIN NOW Their Maker, in fit strains pronounced, or sung END
BEGIN NOW Unmeditated; such prompt eloquence END
BEGIN NOW Flowed from their lips, in prose or numerous verse, END
BEGIN NOW More tuneable than needed lute or harp END
BEGIN NOW To add more sweetness; and they thus began. END
BEGIN NOW These are thy glorious works, Parent of good, END
BEGIN NOW Almighty! Thine this universal frame, END
BEGIN NOW Thus wonderous fair; Thyself how wonderous then! END
BEGIN NOW Unspeakable, who sitst above these heavens END
BEGIN NOW To us invisible, or dimly seen END
BEGIN NOW In these thy lowest works; yet these declare END
BEGIN NOW Thy goodness beyond thought, and power divine. END
BEGIN NOW Speak, ye who best can tell, ye sons of light, END
BEGIN NOW Angels; for ye behold him, and with songs END
BEGIN NOW And choral symphonies, day without night, END
BEGIN NOW Circle his throne rejoicing; ye in Heaven END
BEGIN NOW On Earth join all ye Creatures to extol END
BEGIN NOW Him first, him last, him midst, and without end. END
BEGIN NOW Fairest of stars, last in the train of night, END
BEGIN NOW If better thou belong not to the dawn, END
BEGIN NOW Sure pledge of day, that crownest the smiling morn END
BEGIN NOW With thy bright circlet, praise him in thy sphere, END
BEGIN NOW While day arises, that sweet hour of prime. END
BEGIN NOW Thou Sun, of this great world both eye and soul, END
BEGIN NOW Acknowledge him thy greater; sound his praise END
BEGIN NOW In thy eternal course, both when thou climbest, END
BEGIN NOW And when high noon hast gained, and when thou fallest. END
BEGIN NOW Moon, that now meetest the orient sun, now flyest, END
BEGIN NOW With the fixed Stars, fixed in their orb that flies; END
BEGIN NOW And ye five other wandering Fires, that move END
BEGIN NOW In mystick dance not without song, resound END
BEGIN NOW His praise, who out of darkness called up light. END
BEGIN NOW Air, and ye Elements, the eldest birth END
BEGIN NOW Of Nature's womb, that in quaternion run END
BEGIN NOW Perpetual circle, multiform; and mix END
BEGIN NOW And nourish all things; let your ceaseless change END
BEGIN NOW Vary to our great Maker still new praise. END
BEGIN NOW Ye Mists and Exhalations, that now rise END
BEGIN NOW From hill or steaming lake, dusky or gray, END
BEGIN NOW Till the sun paint your fleecy skirts with gold, END
BEGIN NOW In honour to the world's great Author rise; END
BEGIN NOW Whether to deck with clouds the uncoloured sky, END
BEGIN NOW Or wet the thirsty earth with falling showers, END
BEGIN NOW Rising or falling still advance his praise. END
BEGIN NOW His praise, ye Winds, that from four quarters blow, END
BEGIN NOW Breathe soft or loud; and, wave your tops, ye Pines, END
BEGIN NOW With every plant, in sign of worship wave. END
BEGIN NOW Fountains, and ye that warble, as ye flow, END
BEGIN NOW Melodious murmurs, warbling tune his praise. END
BEGIN NOW Join voices, all ye living Souls: Ye Birds, END
BEGIN NOW That singing up to Heaven-gate ascend, END
BEGIN NOW Bear on your wings and in your notes his praise. END
BEGIN NOW Ye that in waters glide, and ye that walk END
BEGIN NOW The earth, and stately tread, or lowly creep; END
BEGIN NOW Witness if I be silent, morn or even, END
BEGIN NOW To hill, or valley, fountain, or fresh shade, END
BEGIN NOW Made vocal by my song, and taught his praise. END
BEGIN NOW Hail, universal Lord, be bounteous still END
BEGIN NOW To give us only good; and if the night END
BEGIN NOW Have gathered aught of evil, or concealed, END
BEGIN NOW Disperse it, as now light dispels the dark! END
BEGIN NOW So prayed they innocent, and to their thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Firm peace recovered soon, and wonted calm. END
BEGIN NOW On to their morning's rural work they haste, END
BEGIN NOW Among sweet dews and flowers; where any row END
BEGIN NOW Of fruit-trees over-woody reached too far END
BEGIN NOW Their pampered boughs, and needed hands to check END
BEGIN NOW Fruitless embraces: or they led the vine END
BEGIN NOW To wed her elm; she, spoused, about him twines END
BEGIN NOW Her marriageable arms, and with him brings END
BEGIN NOW Her dower, the adopted clusters, to adorn END
BEGIN NOW His barren leaves. Them thus employed beheld END
BEGIN NOW With pity Heaven's high King, and to him called END
BEGIN NOW Raphael, the sociable Spirit, that deigned END
BEGIN NOW To travel with Tobias, and secured END
BEGIN NOW His marriage with the seventimes-wedded maid. END
BEGIN NOW Raphael, said he, thou hearest what stir on Earth END
BEGIN NOW Satan, from Hell 'scaped through the darksome gulf, END
BEGIN NOW Hath raised in Paradise; and how disturbed END
BEGIN NOW This night the human pair; how he designs END
BEGIN NOW In them at once to ruin all mankind. END
BEGIN NOW Go therefore, half this day as friend with friend END
BEGIN NOW Converse with Adam, in what bower or shade END
BEGIN NOW Thou findest him from the heat of noon retired, END
BEGIN NOW To respite his day-labour with repast, END
BEGIN NOW Or with repose; and such discourse bring on, END
BEGIN NOW As may advise him of his happy state, END
BEGIN NOW Happiness in his power left free to will, END
BEGIN NOW Left to his own free will, his will though free, END
BEGIN NOW Yet mutable; whence warn him to beware END
BEGIN NOW He swerve not, too secure: Tell him withal END
BEGIN NOW His danger, and from whom; what enemy, END
BEGIN NOW Late fallen himself from Heaven, is plotting now END
BEGIN NOW The fall of others from like state of bliss; END
BEGIN NOW By violence? no, for that shall be withstood; END
BEGIN NOW But by deceit and lies: This let him know, END
BEGIN NOW Lest, wilfully transgressing, he pretend END
BEGIN NOW Surprisal, unadmonished, unforewarned. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Eternal Father, and fulfilled END
BEGIN NOW All justice: Nor delayed the winged Saint END
BEGIN NOW After his charge received; but from among END
BEGIN NOW Thousand celestial Ardours, where he stood END
BEGIN NOW Veiled with his gorgeous wings, up springing light, END
BEGIN NOW Flew through the midst of Heaven; the angelick quires, END
BEGIN NOW On each hand parting, to his speed gave way END
BEGIN NOW Through all the empyreal road; till, at the gate END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven arrived, the gate self-opened wide END
BEGIN NOW On golden hinges turning, as by work END
BEGIN NOW Divine the sovran Architect had framed. END
BEGIN NOW From hence no cloud, or, to obstruct his sight, END
BEGIN NOW Star interposed, however small he sees, END
BEGIN NOW Not unconformed to other shining globes, END
BEGIN NOW Earth, and the garden of God, with cedars crowned END
BEGIN NOW Above all hills. As when by night the glass END
BEGIN NOW Of Galileo, less assured, observes END
BEGIN NOW Imagined lands and regions in the moon: END
BEGIN NOW Or pilot, from amidst the Cyclades END
BEGIN NOW Delos or Samos first appearing, kens END
BEGIN NOW A cloudy spot. Down thither prone in flight END
BEGIN NOW He speeds, and through the vast ethereal sky END
BEGIN NOW Sails between worlds and worlds, with steady wing END
BEGIN NOW Now on the polar winds, then with quick fan END
BEGIN NOW Winnows the buxom air; till, within soar END
BEGIN NOW Of towering eagles, to all the fowls he seems END
BEGIN NOW A phoenix, gazed by all as that sole bird, END
BEGIN NOW When, to enshrine his reliques in the Sun's END
BEGIN NOW At once on the eastern cliff of Paradise END
BEGIN NOW He lights, and to his proper shape returns END
BEGIN NOW A Seraph winged: Six wings he wore, to shade END
BEGIN NOW His lineaments divine; the pair that clad END
BEGIN NOW Each shoulder broad, came mantling o'er his breast END
BEGIN NOW With regal ornament; the middle pair END
BEGIN NOW Girt like a starry zone his waist, and round END
BEGIN NOW Skirted his loins and thighs with downy gold END
BEGIN NOW And colours dipt in Heaven; the third his feet END
BEGIN NOW Shadowed from either heel with feathered mail, END
BEGIN NOW Sky-tinctured grain. Like Maia's son he stood, END
BEGIN NOW And shook his plumes, that heavenly fragrance filled END
BEGIN NOW The circuit wide. Straight knew him all the bands END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels under watch; and to his state, END
BEGIN NOW And to his message high, in honour rise; END
BEGIN NOW For on some message high they guessed him bound. END
BEGIN NOW Their glittering tents he passed, and now is come END
BEGIN NOW Into the blissful field, through groves of myrrh, END
BEGIN NOW And flowering odours, cassia, nard, and balm; END
BEGIN NOW A wilderness of sweets; for Nature here END
BEGIN NOW Wantoned as in her prime, and played at will END
BEGIN NOW Her virgin fancies pouring forth more sweet, END
BEGIN NOW Wild above rule or art, enormous bliss. END
BEGIN NOW Him through the spicy forest onward come END
BEGIN NOW Adam discerned, as in the door he sat END
BEGIN NOW Of his cool bower, while now the mounted sun END
BEGIN NOW Shot down direct his fervid rays to warm END
BEGIN NOW Earth's inmost womb, more warmth than Adam needs: END
BEGIN NOW And Eve within, due at her hour prepared END
BEGIN NOW For dinner savoury fruits, of taste to please END
BEGIN NOW True appetite, and not disrelish thirst END
BEGIN NOW Of nectarous draughts between, from milky stream, END
BEGIN NOW Berry or grape: To whom thus Adam called. END
BEGIN NOW Haste hither, Eve, and worth thy sight behold END
BEGIN NOW Eastward among those trees, what glorious shape END
BEGIN NOW Comes this way moving; seems another morn END
BEGIN NOW Risen on mid-noon; some great behest from Heaven END
BEGIN NOW To us perhaps he brings, and will vouchsafe END
BEGIN NOW This day to be our guest. But go with speed, END
BEGIN NOW And, what thy stores contain, bring forth, and pour END
BEGIN NOW Abundance, fit to honour and receive END
BEGIN NOW Our heavenly stranger: Well we may afford END
BEGIN NOW Our givers their own gifts, and large bestow END
BEGIN NOW From large bestowed, where Nature multiplies END
BEGIN NOW Her fertile growth, and by disburthening grows END
BEGIN NOW More fruitful, which instructs us not to spare. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Eve. Adam, earth's hallowed mould, END
BEGIN NOW Of God inspired! small store will serve, where store, END
BEGIN NOW All seasons, ripe for use hangs on the stalk; END
BEGIN NOW Save what by frugal storing firmness gains END
BEGIN NOW To nourish, and superfluous moist consumes: END
BEGIN NOW But I will haste, and from each bough and brake, END
BEGIN NOW Each plant and juciest gourd, will pluck such choice END
BEGIN NOW To entertain our Angel-guest, as he END
BEGIN NOW Beholding shall confess, that here on Earth END
BEGIN NOW God hath dispensed his bounties as in Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, with dispatchful looks in haste END
BEGIN NOW She turns, on hospitable thoughts intent END
BEGIN NOW What choice to choose for delicacy best, END
BEGIN NOW What order, so contrived as not to mix END
BEGIN NOW Tastes, not well joined, inelegant, but bring END
BEGIN NOW Taste after taste upheld with kindliest change; END
BEGIN NOW Bestirs her then, and from each tender stalk END
BEGIN NOW Whatever Earth, all-bearing mother, yields END
BEGIN NOW In India East or West, or middle shore END
BEGIN NOW In Pontus or the Punick coast, or where END
BEGIN NOW Alcinous reigned, fruit of all kinds, in coat END
BEGIN NOW Rough, or smooth rind, or bearded husk, or shell, END
BEGIN NOW She gathers, tribute large, and on the board END
BEGIN NOW Heaps with unsparing hand; for drink the grape END
BEGIN NOW She crushes, inoffensive must, and meaths END
BEGIN NOW From many a berry, and from sweet kernels pressed END
BEGIN NOW She tempers dulcet creams; nor these to hold END
BEGIN NOW Wants her fit vessels pure; then strows the ground END
BEGIN NOW With rose and odours from the shrub unfumed. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while our primitive great sire, to meet END
BEGIN NOW His God-like guest, walks forth, without more train END
BEGIN NOW Accompanied than with his own complete END
BEGIN NOW Perfections; in himself was all his state, END
BEGIN NOW More solemn than the tedious pomp that waits END
BEGIN NOW On princes, when their rich retinue long END
BEGIN NOW Of horses led, and grooms besmeared with gold, END
BEGIN NOW Dazzles the croud, and sets them all agape. END
BEGIN NOW Nearer his presence Adam, though not awed, END
BEGIN NOW Yet with submiss approach and reverence meek, END
BEGIN NOW As to a superiour nature bowing low, END
BEGIN NOW Thus said. Native of Heaven, for other place END
BEGIN NOW None can than Heaven such glorious shape contain; END
BEGIN NOW Since, by descending from the thrones above, END
BEGIN NOW Those happy places thou hast deigned a while END
BEGIN NOW To want, and honour these, vouchsafe with us END
BEGIN NOW Two only, who yet by sovran gift possess END
BEGIN NOW This spacious ground, in yonder shady bower END
BEGIN NOW To rest; and what the garden choicest bears END
BEGIN NOW To sit and taste, till this meridian heat END
BEGIN NOW Be over, and the sun more cool decline. END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus the angelick Virtue answered mild. END
BEGIN NOW Adam, I therefore came; nor art thou such END
BEGIN NOW Created, or such place hast here to dwell, END
BEGIN NOW As may not oft invite, though Spirits of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW To visit thee; lead on then where thy bower END
BEGIN NOW O'ershades; for these mid-hours, till evening rise, END
BEGIN NOW I have at will. So to the sylvan lodge END
BEGIN NOW They came, that like Pomona's arbour smiled, END
BEGIN NOW With flowerets decked, and fragrant smells; but Eve, END
BEGIN NOW Undecked save with herself, more lovely fair END
BEGIN NOW Than Wood-Nymph, or the fairest Goddess feigned END
BEGIN NOW Of three that in mount Ida naked strove, END
BEGIN NOW Stood to entertain her guest from Heaven; no veil END
BEGIN NOW She needed, virtue-proof; no thought infirm END
BEGIN NOW Altered her cheek. On whom the Angel Hail END
BEGIN NOW Bestowed, the holy salutation used END
BEGIN NOW Long after to blest Mary, second Eve. END
BEGIN NOW Hail, Mother of Mankind, whose fruitful womb END
BEGIN NOW Shall fill the world more numerous with thy sons, END
BEGIN NOW Than with these various fruits the trees of God END
BEGIN NOW Have heaped this table!--Raised of grassy turf END
BEGIN NOW Their table was, and mossy seats had round, END
BEGIN NOW And on her ample square from side to side END
BEGIN NOW All autumn piled, though spring and autumn here END
BEGIN NOW Danced hand in hand. A while discourse they hold; END
BEGIN NOW No fear lest dinner cool; when thus began END
BEGIN NOW Our author. Heavenly stranger, please to taste END
BEGIN NOW These bounties, which our Nourisher, from whom END
BEGIN NOW All perfect good, unmeasured out, descends, END
BEGIN NOW To us for food and for delight hath caused END
BEGIN NOW The earth to yield; unsavoury food perhaps END
BEGIN NOW To spiritual natures; only this I know, END
BEGIN NOW That one celestial Father gives to all. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Angel. Therefore what he gives END
BEGIN NOW (Whose praise be ever sung) to Man in part END
BEGIN NOW Spiritual, may of purest Spirits be found END
BEGIN NOW No ingrateful food: And food alike those pure END
BEGIN NOW Intelligential substances require, END
BEGIN NOW As doth your rational; and both contain END
BEGIN NOW Within them every lower faculty END
BEGIN NOW Of sense, whereby they hear, see, smell, touch, taste, END
BEGIN NOW Tasting concoct, digest, assimilate, END
BEGIN NOW And corporeal to incorporeal turn. END
BEGIN NOW For know, whatever was created, needs END
BEGIN NOW To be sustained and fed: Of elements END
BEGIN NOW The grosser feeds the purer, earth the sea, END
BEGIN NOW Earth and the sea feed air, the air those fires END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal, and as lowest first the moon; END
BEGIN NOW Whence in her visage round those spots, unpurged END
BEGIN NOW Vapours not yet into her substance turned. END
BEGIN NOW Nor doth the moon no nourishment exhale END
BEGIN NOW From her moist continent to higher orbs. END
BEGIN NOW The sun that light imparts to all, receives END
BEGIN NOW From all his alimental recompence END
BEGIN NOW In humid exhalations, and at even END
BEGIN NOW Sups with the ocean. Though in Heaven the trees END
BEGIN NOW Of life ambrosial fruitage bear, and vines END
BEGIN NOW Yield nectar; though from off the boughs each morn END
BEGIN NOW We brush mellifluous dews, and find the ground END
BEGIN NOW Covered with pearly grain: Yet God hath here END
BEGIN NOW Varied his bounty so with new delights, END
BEGIN NOW As may compare with Heaven; and to taste END
BEGIN NOW Think not I shall be nice. So down they sat, END
BEGIN NOW And to their viands fell; nor seemingly END
BEGIN NOW The Angel, nor in mist, the common gloss END
BEGIN NOW Of Theologians; but with keen dispatch END
BEGIN NOW Of real hunger, and concoctive heat END
BEGIN NOW To transubstantiate: What redounds, transpires END
BEGIN NOW Through Spirits with ease; nor wonder; if by fire END
BEGIN NOW Of sooty coal the empirick alchemist END
BEGIN NOW Can turn, or holds it possible to turn, END
BEGIN NOW Metals of drossiest ore to perfect gold, END
BEGIN NOW As from the mine. Mean while at table Eve END
BEGIN NOW Ministered naked, and their flowing cups END
BEGIN NOW With pleasant liquours crowned: O innocence END
BEGIN NOW Deserving Paradise! if ever, then, END
BEGIN NOW Then had the sons of God excuse to have been END
BEGIN NOW Enamoured at that sight; but in those hearts END
BEGIN NOW Love unlibidinous reigned, nor jealousy END
BEGIN NOW Was understood, the injured lover's hell. END
BEGIN NOW Thus when with meats and drinks they had sufficed, END
BEGIN NOW Not burdened nature, sudden mind arose END
BEGIN NOW In Adam, not to let the occasion pass END
BEGIN NOW Given him by this great conference to know END
BEGIN NOW Of things above his world, and of their being END
BEGIN NOW Who dwell in Heaven, whose excellence he saw END
BEGIN NOW Transcend his own so far; whose radiant forms, END
BEGIN NOW Divine effulgence, whose high power, so far END
BEGIN NOW Exceeded human; and his wary speech END
BEGIN NOW Thus to the empyreal minister he framed. END
BEGIN NOW Inhabitant with God, now know I well END
BEGIN NOW Thy favour, in this honour done to Man; END
BEGIN NOW Under whose lowly roof thou hast vouchsafed END
BEGIN NOW To enter, and these earthly fruits to taste, END
BEGIN NOW Food not of Angels, yet accepted so, END
BEGIN NOW As that more willingly thou couldst not seem END
BEGIN NOW At Heaven's high feasts to have fed: yet what compare END
BEGIN NOW To whom the winged Hierarch replied. END
BEGIN NOW O Adam, One Almighty is, from whom END
BEGIN NOW All things proceed, and up to him return, END
BEGIN NOW If not depraved from good, created all END
BEGIN NOW Such to perfection, one first matter all, END
BEGIN NOW Endued with various forms, various degrees END
BEGIN NOW Of substance, and, in things that live, of life; END
BEGIN NOW But more refined, more spiritous, and pure, END
BEGIN NOW As nearer to him placed, or nearer tending END
BEGIN NOW Each in their several active spheres assigned, END
BEGIN NOW Till body up to spirit work, in bounds END
BEGIN NOW Proportioned to each kind. So from the root END
BEGIN NOW Springs lighter the green stalk, from thence the leaves END
BEGIN NOW More aery, last the bright consummate flower END
BEGIN NOW Spirits odorous breathes: flowers and their fruit, END
BEGIN NOW Man's nourishment, by gradual scale sublimed, END
BEGIN NOW To vital spirits aspire, to animal, END
BEGIN NOW To intellectual; give both life and sense, END
BEGIN NOW Fancy and understanding; whence the soul END
BEGIN NOW Reason receives, and reason is her being, END
BEGIN NOW Discursive, or intuitive; discourse END
BEGIN NOW Is oftest yours, the latter most is ours, END
BEGIN NOW Differing but in degree, of kind the same. END
BEGIN NOW Wonder not then, what God for you saw good END
BEGIN NOW If I refuse not, but convert, as you END
BEGIN NOW To proper substance. Time may come, when Men END
BEGIN NOW With Angels may participate, and find END
BEGIN NOW No inconvenient diet, nor too light fare; END
BEGIN NOW And from these corporal nutriments perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Your bodies may at last turn all to spirit, END
BEGIN NOW Improved by tract of time, and, winged, ascend END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal, as we; or may, at choice, END
BEGIN NOW Here or in heavenly Paradises dwell; END
BEGIN NOW If ye be found obedient, and retain END
BEGIN NOW Unalterably firm his love entire, END
BEGIN NOW Whose progeny you are. Mean while enjoy END
BEGIN NOW Your fill what happiness this happy state END
BEGIN NOW Can comprehend, incapable of more. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the patriarch of mankind replied. END
BEGIN NOW O favourable Spirit, propitious guest, END
BEGIN NOW Well hast thou taught the way that might direct END
BEGIN NOW Our knowledge, and the scale of nature set END
BEGIN NOW From center to circumference; whereon, END
BEGIN NOW In contemplation of created things, END
BEGIN NOW By steps we may ascend to God. But say, END
BEGIN NOW What meant that caution joined, If ye be found END
BEGIN NOW Obedient? Can we want obedience then END
BEGIN NOW To him, or possibly his love desert, END
BEGIN NOW Who formed us from the dust and placed us here END
BEGIN NOW Full to the utmost measure of what bliss END
BEGIN NOW Human desires can seek or apprehend? END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Angel. Son of Heaven and Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Attend! That thou art happy, owe to God; END
BEGIN NOW That thou continuest such, owe to thyself, END
BEGIN NOW That is, to thy obedience; therein stand. END
BEGIN NOW This was that caution given thee; be advised. END
BEGIN NOW God made thee perfect, not immutable; END
BEGIN NOW And good he made thee, but to persevere END
BEGIN NOW He left it in thy power; ordained thy will END
BEGIN NOW By nature free, not over-ruled by fate END
BEGIN NOW Inextricable, or strict necessity: END
BEGIN NOW Our voluntary service he requires, END
BEGIN NOW Not our necessitated; such with him END
BEGIN NOW Finds no acceptance, nor can find; for how END
BEGIN NOW Can hearts, not free, be tried whether they serve END
BEGIN NOW Willing or no, who will but what they must END
BEGIN NOW By destiny, and can no other choose? END
BEGIN NOW Myself, and all the angelick host, that stand END
BEGIN NOW In sight of God, enthroned, our happy state END
BEGIN NOW Hold, as you yours, while our obedience holds; END
BEGIN NOW On other surety none: Freely we serve, END
BEGIN NOW Because we freely love, as in our will END
BEGIN NOW To love or not; in this we stand or fall: END
BEGIN NOW And some are fallen, to disobedience fallen, END
BEGIN NOW And so from Heaven to deepest Hell; O fall END
BEGIN NOW From what high state of bliss, into what woe! END
BEGIN NOW To whom our great progenitor. Thy words END
BEGIN NOW Attentive, and with more delighted ear, END
BEGIN NOW Divine instructer, I have heard, than when END
BEGIN NOW Cherubick songs by night from neighbouring hills END
BEGIN NOW Aereal musick send: Nor knew I not END
BEGIN NOW To be both will and deed created free; END
BEGIN NOW Yet that we never shall forget to love END
BEGIN NOW Our Maker, and obey him whose command END
BEGIN NOW Single is yet so just, my constant thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Assured me, and still assure: Though what thou tellest END
BEGIN NOW Hath passed in Heaven, some doubt within me move, END
BEGIN NOW But more desire to hear, if thou consent, END
BEGIN NOW The full relation, which must needs be strange, END
BEGIN NOW Worthy of sacred silence to be heard; END
BEGIN NOW And we have yet large day, for scarce the sun END
BEGIN NOW Hath finished half his journey, and scarce begins END
BEGIN NOW His other half in the great zone of Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Adam made request; and Raphael, END
BEGIN NOW After short pause assenting, thus began. END
BEGIN NOW High matter thou enjoinest me, O prime of men, END
BEGIN NOW Sad task and hard: For how shall I relate END
BEGIN NOW To human sense the invisible exploits END
BEGIN NOW Of warring Spirits? how, without remorse, END
BEGIN NOW The ruin of so many glorious once END
BEGIN NOW And perfect while they stood? how last unfold END
BEGIN NOW The secrets of another world, perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Not lawful to reveal? yet for thy good END
BEGIN NOW This is dispensed; and what surmounts the reach END
BEGIN NOW Of human sense, I shall delineate so, END
BEGIN NOW By likening spiritual to corporal forms, END
BEGIN NOW As may express them best; though what if Earth END
BEGIN NOW Be but a shadow of Heaven, and things therein END
BEGIN NOW Each to other like, more than on earth is thought? END
BEGIN NOW As yet this world was not, and Chaos wild END
BEGIN NOW Reigned where these Heavens now roll, where Earth now rests END
BEGIN NOW Upon her center poised; when on a day END
BEGIN NOW (For time, though in eternity, applied END
BEGIN NOW To motion, measures all things durable END
BEGIN NOW By present, past, and future,) on such day END
BEGIN NOW As Heaven's great year brings forth, the empyreal host END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels by imperial summons called, END
BEGIN NOW Innumerable before the Almighty's throne END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith, from all the ends of Heaven, appeared END
BEGIN NOW Under their Hierarchs in orders bright: END
BEGIN NOW Ten thousand thousand ensigns high advanced, END
BEGIN NOW Standards and gonfalons 'twixt van and rear END
BEGIN NOW Stream in the air, and for distinction serve END
BEGIN NOW Of hierarchies, of orders, and degrees; END
BEGIN NOW Or in their glittering tissues bear imblazed END
BEGIN NOW Holy memorials, acts of zeal and love END
BEGIN NOW Recorded eminent. Thus when in orbs END
BEGIN NOW Of circuit inexpressible they stood, END
BEGIN NOW Orb within orb, the Father Infinite, END
BEGIN NOW By whom in bliss imbosomed sat the Son, END
BEGIN NOW Amidst as from a flaming mount, whose top END
BEGIN NOW Brightness had made invisible, thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW Hear, all ye Angels, progeny of light, END
BEGIN NOW Hear my decree, which unrevoked shall stand. END
BEGIN NOW This day I have begot whom I declare END
BEGIN NOW My only Son, and on this holy hill END
BEGIN NOW Him have anointed, whom ye now behold END
BEGIN NOW At my right hand; your head I him appoint; END
BEGIN NOW And by myself have sworn, to him shall bow END
BEGIN NOW All knees in Heaven, and shall confess him Lord: END
BEGIN NOW Under his great vice-gerent reign abide END
BEGIN NOW United, as one individual soul, END
BEGIN NOW For ever happy: Him who disobeys, END
BEGIN NOW Me disobeys, breaks union, and that day, END
BEGIN NOW Cast out from God and blessed vision, falls END
BEGIN NOW Into utter darkness, deep ingulfed, his place END
BEGIN NOW Ordained without redemption, without end. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Omnipotent, and with his words END
BEGIN NOW All seemed well pleased; all seemed, but were not all. END
BEGIN NOW That day, as other solemn days, they spent END
BEGIN NOW In song and dance about the sacred hill; END
BEGIN NOW Mystical dance, which yonder starry sphere END
BEGIN NOW Of planets, and of fixed, in all her wheels END
BEGIN NOW Resembles nearest, mazes intricate, END
BEGIN NOW Eccentrick, intervolved, yet regular END
BEGIN NOW Then most, when most irregular they seem; END
BEGIN NOW And in their motions harmony divine END
BEGIN NOW So smooths her charming tones, that God's own ear END
BEGIN NOW Listens delighted. Evening now approached, END
BEGIN NOW (For we have also our evening and our morn, END
BEGIN NOW We ours for change delectable, not need;) END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith from dance to sweet repast they turn END
BEGIN NOW Desirous; all in circles as they stood, END
BEGIN NOW Tables are set, and on a sudden piled END
BEGIN NOW With Angels food, and rubied nectar flows END
BEGIN NOW In pearl, in diamond, and massy gold, END
BEGIN NOW Fruit of delicious vines, the growth of Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW On flowers reposed, and with fresh flowerets crowned, END
BEGIN NOW They eat, they drink, and in communion sweet END
BEGIN NOW Quaff immortality and joy, secure END
BEGIN NOW Of surfeit, where full measure only bounds END
BEGIN NOW Excess, before the all-bounteous King, who showered END
BEGIN NOW With copious hand, rejoicing in their joy. END
BEGIN NOW Now when ambrosial night with clouds exhaled END
BEGIN NOW From that high mount of God, whence light and shade END
BEGIN NOW Spring both, the face of brightest Heaven had changed END
BEGIN NOW To grateful twilight, (for night comes not there END
BEGIN NOW In darker veil) and roseate dews disposed END
BEGIN NOW All but the unsleeping eyes of God to rest; END
BEGIN NOW Wide over all the plain, and wider far END
BEGIN NOW Than all this globous earth in plain outspread, END
BEGIN NOW (Such are the courts of God) the angelick throng, END
BEGIN NOW Dispersed in bands and files, their camp extend END
BEGIN NOW By living streams among the trees of life, END
BEGIN NOW Pavilions numberless, and sudden reared, END
BEGIN NOW Celestial tabernacles, where they slept END
BEGIN NOW Fanned with cool winds; save those, who, in their course, END
BEGIN NOW Melodious hymns about the sovran throne END
BEGIN NOW Alternate all night long: but not so waked END
BEGIN NOW Satan; so call him now, his former name END
BEGIN NOW Is heard no more in Heaven; he of the first, END
BEGIN NOW If not the first Arch-Angel, great in power, END
BEGIN NOW In favour and pre-eminence, yet fraught END
BEGIN NOW With envy against the Son of God, that day END
BEGIN NOW Honoured by his great Father, and proclaimed END
BEGIN NOW Messiah King anointed, could not bear END
BEGIN NOW Through pride that sight, and thought himself impaired. END
BEGIN NOW Deep malice thence conceiving and disdain, END
BEGIN NOW Soon as midnight brought on the dusky hour END
BEGIN NOW Friendliest to sleep and silence, he resolved END
BEGIN NOW With all his legions to dislodge, and leave END
BEGIN NOW Unworshipt, unobeyed, the throne supreme, END
BEGIN NOW Contemptuous; and his next subordinate END
BEGIN NOW Awakening, thus to him in secret spake. END
BEGIN NOW Sleepest thou, Companion dear? What sleep can close END
BEGIN NOW Thy eye-lids? and rememberest what decree END
BEGIN NOW Of yesterday, so late hath passed the lips END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven's Almighty. Thou to me thy thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Wast wont, I mine to thee was wont to impart; END
BEGIN NOW Both waking we were one; how then can now END
BEGIN NOW Thy sleep dissent? New laws thou seest imposed; END
BEGIN NOW New laws from him who reigns, new minds may raise END
BEGIN NOW In us who serve, new counsels to debate END
BEGIN NOW What doubtful may ensue: More in this place END
BEGIN NOW To utter is not safe. Assemble thou END
BEGIN NOW Of all those myriads which we lead the chief; END
BEGIN NOW Tell them, that by command, ere yet dim night END
BEGIN NOW Her shadowy cloud withdraws, I am to haste, END
BEGIN NOW And all who under me their banners wave, END
BEGIN NOW Homeward, with flying march, where we possess END
BEGIN NOW The quarters of the north; there to prepare END
BEGIN NOW Fit entertainment to receive our King, END
BEGIN NOW The great Messiah, and his new commands, END
BEGIN NOW Who speedily through all the hierarchies END
BEGIN NOW Intends to pass triumphant, and give laws. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the false Arch-Angel, and infused END
BEGIN NOW Bad influence into the unwary breast END
BEGIN NOW Of his associate: He together calls, END
BEGIN NOW Or several one by one, the regent Powers, END
BEGIN NOW Under him Regent; tells, as he was taught, END
BEGIN NOW That the Most High commanding, now ere night, END
BEGIN NOW Now ere dim night had disincumbered Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW The great hierarchal standard was to move; END
BEGIN NOW Tells the suggested cause, and casts between END
BEGIN NOW Ambiguous words and jealousies, to sound END
BEGIN NOW Or taint integrity: But all obeyed END
BEGIN NOW The wonted signal, and superiour voice END
BEGIN NOW Of their great Potentate; for great indeed END
BEGIN NOW His name, and high was his degree in Heaven; END
BEGIN NOW His countenance, as the morning-star that guides END
BEGIN NOW The starry flock, allured them, and with lies END
BEGIN NOW Drew after him the third part of Heaven's host. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while the Eternal eye, whose sight discerns END
BEGIN NOW Abstrusest thoughts, from forth his holy mount, END
BEGIN NOW And from within the golden lamps that burn END
BEGIN NOW Nightly before him, saw without their light END
BEGIN NOW Rebellion rising; saw in whom, how spread END
BEGIN NOW Among the sons of morn, what multitudes END
BEGIN NOW Were banded to oppose his high decree; END
BEGIN NOW And, smiling, to his only Son thus said. END
BEGIN NOW Son, thou in whom my glory I behold END
BEGIN NOW In full resplendence, Heir of all my might, END
BEGIN NOW Nearly it now concerns us to be sure END
BEGIN NOW Of our Omnipotence, and with what arms END
BEGIN NOW We mean to hold what anciently we claim END
BEGIN NOW Of deity or empire: Such a foe END
BEGIN NOW Is rising, who intends to erect his throne END
BEGIN NOW Equal to ours, throughout the spacious north; END
BEGIN NOW Nor so content, hath in his thought to try END
BEGIN NOW In battle, what our power is, or our right. END
BEGIN NOW Let us advise, and to this hazard draw END
BEGIN NOW With speed what force is left, and all employ END
BEGIN NOW In our defence; lest unawares we lose END
BEGIN NOW This our high place, our sanctuary, our hill. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Son with calm aspect and clear, END
BEGIN NOW Lightning divine, ineffable, serene, END
BEGIN NOW Made answer. Mighty Father, thou thy foes END
BEGIN NOW Justly hast in derision, and, secure, END
BEGIN NOW Laughest at their vain designs and tumults vain, END
BEGIN NOW Matter to me of glory, whom their hate END
BEGIN NOW Illustrates, when they see all regal power END
BEGIN NOW Given me to quell their pride, and in event END
BEGIN NOW Know whether I be dextrous to subdue END
BEGIN NOW Thy rebels, or be found the worst in Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Son; but Satan, with his Powers, END
BEGIN NOW Far was advanced on winged speed; an host END
BEGIN NOW Innumerable as the stars of night, END
BEGIN NOW Or stars of morning, dew-drops, which the sun END
BEGIN NOW Impearls on every leaf and every flower. END
BEGIN NOW Regions they passed, the mighty regencies END
BEGIN NOW In their triple degrees; regions to which END
BEGIN NOW All thy dominion, Adam, is no more END
BEGIN NOW Than what this garden is to all the earth, END
BEGIN NOW And all the sea, from one entire globose END
BEGIN NOW Stretched into longitude; which having passed, END
BEGIN NOW At length into the limits of the north END
BEGIN NOW They came; and Satan to his royal seat END
BEGIN NOW High on a hill, far blazing, as a mount END
BEGIN NOW Raised on a mount, with pyramids and towers END
BEGIN NOW From diamond quarries hewn, and rocks of gold; END
BEGIN NOW The palace of great Lucifer, (so call END
BEGIN NOW That structure in the dialect of men END
BEGIN NOW Interpreted,) which not long after, he END
BEGIN NOW Affecting all equality with God, END
BEGIN NOW In imitation of that mount whereon END
BEGIN NOW Messiah was declared in sight of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW The Mountain of the Congregation called; END
BEGIN NOW For thither he assembled all his train, END
BEGIN NOW Pretending so commanded to consult END
BEGIN NOW About the great reception of their King, END
BEGIN NOW Thither to come, and with calumnious art END
BEGIN NOW Of counterfeited truth thus held their ears. END
BEGIN NOW If these magnifick titles yet remain END
BEGIN NOW Not merely titular, since by decree END
BEGIN NOW Another now hath to himself engrossed END
BEGIN NOW All power, and us eclipsed under the name END
BEGIN NOW Of King anointed, for whom all this haste END
BEGIN NOW Of midnight-march, and hurried meeting here, END
BEGIN NOW This only to consult how we may best, END
BEGIN NOW With what may be devised of honours new, END
BEGIN NOW Receive him coming to receive from us END
BEGIN NOW Knee-tribute yet unpaid, prostration vile! END
BEGIN NOW Too much to one! but double how endured, END
BEGIN NOW To one, and to his image now proclaimed? END
BEGIN NOW But what if better counsels might erect END
BEGIN NOW Our minds, and teach us to cast off this yoke? END
BEGIN NOW Will ye submit your necks, and choose to bend END
BEGIN NOW The supple knee? Ye will not, if I trust END
BEGIN NOW To know ye right, or if ye know yourselves END
BEGIN NOW Natives and sons of Heaven possessed before END
BEGIN NOW By none; and if not equal all, yet free, END
BEGIN NOW Equally free; for orders and degrees END
BEGIN NOW Jar not with liberty, but well consist. END
BEGIN NOW Who can in reason then, or right, assume END
BEGIN NOW Monarchy over such as live by right END
BEGIN NOW His equals, if in power and splendour less, END
BEGIN NOW In freedom equal? or can introduce END
BEGIN NOW Law and edict on us, who without law END
BEGIN NOW Err not? much less for this to be our Lord, END
BEGIN NOW And look for adoration, to the abuse END
BEGIN NOW Of those imperial titles, which assert END
BEGIN NOW Our being ordained to govern, not to serve. END
BEGIN NOW Thus far his bold discourse without controul END
BEGIN NOW Had audience; when among the Seraphim END
BEGIN NOW Abdiel, than whom none with more zeal adored END
BEGIN NOW The Deity, and divine commands obeyed, END
BEGIN NOW Stood up, and in a flame of zeal severe END
BEGIN NOW The current of his fury thus opposed. END
BEGIN NOW O argument blasphemous, false, and proud! END
BEGIN NOW Words which no ear ever to hear in Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Expected, least of all from thee, Ingrate, END
BEGIN NOW In place thyself so high above thy peers. END
BEGIN NOW Canst thou with impious obloquy condemn END
BEGIN NOW The just decree of God, pronounced and sworn, END
BEGIN NOW That to his only Son, by right endued END
BEGIN NOW With regal scepter, every soul in Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Shall bend the knee, and in that honour due END
BEGIN NOW Confess him rightful King? unjust, thou sayest, END
BEGIN NOW Flatly unjust, to bind with laws the free, END
BEGIN NOW And equal over equals to let reign, END
BEGIN NOW One over all with unsucceeded power. END
BEGIN NOW Shalt thou give law to God? shalt thou dispute END
BEGIN NOW With him the points of liberty, who made END
BEGIN NOW Thee what thou art, and formed the Powers of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Such as he pleased, and circumscribed their being? END
BEGIN NOW Yet, by experience taught, we know how good, END
BEGIN NOW And of our good and of our dignity END
BEGIN NOW How provident he is; how far from thought END
BEGIN NOW To make us less, bent rather to exalt END
BEGIN NOW Our happy state, under one head more near END
BEGIN NOW United. But to grant it thee unjust, END
BEGIN NOW That equal over equals monarch reign: END
BEGIN NOW Thyself, though great and glorious, dost thou count, END
BEGIN NOW Or all angelick nature joined in one, END
BEGIN NOW Equal to him begotten Son? by whom, END
BEGIN NOW As by his Word, the Mighty Father made END
BEGIN NOW All things, even thee; and all the Spirits of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW By him created in their bright degrees, END
BEGIN NOW Crowned them with glory, and to their glory named END
BEGIN NOW Essential Powers; nor by his reign obscured, END
BEGIN NOW But more illustrious made; since he the head END
BEGIN NOW One of our number thus reduced becomes; END
BEGIN NOW His laws our laws; all honour to him done END
BEGIN NOW Returns our own. Cease then this impious rage, END
BEGIN NOW And tempt not these; but hasten to appease END
BEGIN NOW The incensed Father, and the incensed Son, END
BEGIN NOW While pardon may be found in time besought. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the fervent Angel; but his zeal END
BEGIN NOW None seconded, as out of season judged, END
BEGIN NOW Or singular and rash: Whereat rejoiced END
BEGIN NOW The Apostate, and, more haughty, thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW That we were formed then sayest thou? and the work END
BEGIN NOW Of secondary hands, by task transferred END
BEGIN NOW From Father to his Son? strange point and new! END
BEGIN NOW Doctrine which we would know whence learned: who saw END
BEGIN NOW When this creation was? rememberest thou END
BEGIN NOW Thy making, while the Maker gave thee being? END
BEGIN NOW We know no time when we were not as now; END
BEGIN NOW Know none before us, self-begot, self-raised END
BEGIN NOW By our own quickening power, when fatal course END
BEGIN NOW Had circled his full orb, the birth mature END
BEGIN NOW Of this our native Heaven, ethereal sons. END
BEGIN NOW Our puissance is our own; our own right hand END
BEGIN NOW Shall teach us highest deeds, by proof to try END
BEGIN NOW Who is our equal: Then thou shalt behold END
BEGIN NOW Whether by supplication we intend END
BEGIN NOW Address, and to begirt the almighty throne END
BEGIN NOW Beseeching or besieging. This report, END
BEGIN NOW These tidings carry to the anointed King; END
BEGIN NOW And fly, ere evil intercept thy flight. END
BEGIN NOW He said; and, as the sound of waters deep, END
BEGIN NOW Hoarse murmur echoed to his words applause END
BEGIN NOW Through the infinite host; nor less for that END
BEGIN NOW The flaming Seraph fearless, though alone END
BEGIN NOW Encompassed round with foes, thus answered bold. END
BEGIN NOW O alienate from God, O Spirit accursed, END
BEGIN NOW Forsaken of all good! I see thy fall END
BEGIN NOW Determined, and thy hapless crew involved END
BEGIN NOW In this perfidious fraud, contagion spread END
BEGIN NOW Both of thy crime and punishment: Henceforth END
BEGIN NOW No more be troubled how to quit the yoke END
BEGIN NOW Of God's Messiah; those indulgent laws END
BEGIN NOW Will not be now vouchsafed; other decrees END
BEGIN NOW Against thee are gone forth without recall; END
BEGIN NOW That golden scepter, which thou didst reject, END
BEGIN NOW Is now an iron rod to bruise and break END
BEGIN NOW Thy disobedience. Well thou didst advise; END
BEGIN NOW Yet not for thy advice or threats I fly END
BEGIN NOW These wicked tents devoted, lest the wrath END
BEGIN NOW Impendent, raging into sudden flame, END
BEGIN NOW Distinguish not: For soon expect to feel END
BEGIN NOW His thunder on thy head, devouring fire. END
BEGIN NOW Then who created thee lamenting learn, END
BEGIN NOW When who can uncreate thee thou shalt know. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Seraph Abdiel, faithful found END
BEGIN NOW Among the faithless, faithful only he; END
BEGIN NOW Among innumerable false, unmoved, END
BEGIN NOW Unshaken, unseduced, unterrified, END
BEGIN NOW His loyalty he kept, his love, his zeal; END
BEGIN NOW Nor number, nor example, with him wrought END
BEGIN NOW To swerve from truth, or change his constant mind, END
BEGIN NOW Though single. From amidst them forth he passed, END
BEGIN NOW Long way through hostile scorn, which he sustained END
BEGIN NOW Superiour, nor of violence feared aught; END
BEGIN NOW And, with retorted scorn, his back he turned END
BEGIN NOW On those proud towers to swift destruction doomed. END
BEGIN NOW All night the dreadless Angel, unpursued, END
BEGIN NOW Through Heaven's wide champain held his way; till Morn, END
BEGIN NOW Waked by the circling Hours, with rosy hand END
BEGIN NOW Unbarred the gates of light. There is a cave END
BEGIN NOW Within the mount of God, fast by his throne, END
BEGIN NOW Where light and darkness in perpetual round END
BEGIN NOW Lodge and dislodge by turns, which makes through Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Grateful vicissitude, like day and night; END
BEGIN NOW Light issues forth, and at the other door END
BEGIN NOW Obsequious darkness enters, till her hour END
BEGIN NOW To veil the Heaven, though darkness there might well END
BEGIN NOW Seem twilight here: And now went forth the Morn END
BEGIN NOW Such as in highest Heaven arrayed in gold END
BEGIN NOW Empyreal; from before her vanished Night, END
BEGIN NOW Shot through with orient beams; when all the plain END
BEGIN NOW Covered with thick embattled squadrons bright, END
BEGIN NOW Chariots, and flaming arms, and fiery steeds, END
BEGIN NOW Reflecting blaze on blaze, first met his view: END
BEGIN NOW War he perceived, war in procinct; and found END
BEGIN NOW Already known what he for news had thought END
BEGIN NOW To have reported: Gladly then he mixed END
BEGIN NOW Among those friendly Powers, who him received END
BEGIN NOW With joy and acclamations loud, that one, END
BEGIN NOW That of so many myriads fallen, yet one END
BEGIN NOW Returned not lost. On to the sacred hill END
BEGIN NOW They led him high applauded, and present END
BEGIN NOW Before the seat supreme; from whence a voice, END
BEGIN NOW From midst a golden cloud, thus mild was heard. END
BEGIN NOW Servant of God. Well done; well hast thou fought END
BEGIN NOW The better fight, who single hast maintained END
BEGIN NOW Against revolted multitudes the cause END
BEGIN NOW Of truth, in word mightier than they in arms; END
BEGIN NOW And for the testimony of truth hast borne END
BEGIN NOW Universal reproach, far worse to bear END
BEGIN NOW Than violence; for this was all thy care END
BEGIN NOW To stand approved in sight of God, though worlds END
BEGIN NOW Judged thee perverse: The easier conquest now END
BEGIN NOW Remains thee, aided by this host of friends, END
BEGIN NOW Back on thy foes more glorious to return, END
BEGIN NOW Than scorned thou didst depart; and to subdue END
BEGIN NOW By force, who reason for their law refuse, END
BEGIN NOW Right reason for their law, and for their King END
BEGIN NOW Messiah, who by right of merit reigns. END
BEGIN NOW Go, Michael, of celestial armies prince, END
BEGIN NOW And thou, in military prowess next, END
BEGIN NOW Gabriel, lead forth to battle these my sons END
BEGIN NOW Invincible; lead forth my armed Saints, END
BEGIN NOW By thousands and by millions, ranged for fight, END
BEGIN NOW Equal in number to that Godless crew END
BEGIN NOW Rebellious: Them with fire and hostile arms END
BEGIN NOW Fearless assault; and, to the brow of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Pursuing, drive them out from God and bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Into their place of punishment, the gulf END
BEGIN NOW Of Tartarus, which ready opens wide END
BEGIN NOW His fiery Chaos to receive their fall. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Sovran Voice, and clouds began END
BEGIN NOW To darken all the hill, and smoke to roll END
BEGIN NOW In dusky wreaths, reluctant flames, the sign END
BEGIN NOW Of wrath awaked; nor with less dread the loud END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal trumpet from on high 'gan blow: END
BEGIN NOW At which command the Powers militant, END
BEGIN NOW That stood for Heaven, in mighty quadrate joined END
BEGIN NOW Of union irresistible, moved on END
BEGIN NOW In silence their bright legions, to the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of instrumental harmony, that breathed END
BEGIN NOW Heroick ardour to adventurous deeds END
BEGIN NOW Under their God-like leaders, in the cause END
BEGIN NOW Of God and his Messiah. On they move END
BEGIN NOW Indissolubly firm; nor obvious hill, END
BEGIN NOW Nor straitening vale, nor wood, nor stream, divides END
BEGIN NOW Their perfect ranks; for high above the ground END
BEGIN NOW Their march was, and the passive air upbore END
BEGIN NOW Their nimble tread; as when the total kind END
BEGIN NOW Of birds, in orderly array on wing, END
BEGIN NOW Came summoned over Eden to receive END
BEGIN NOW Their names of thee; so over many a tract END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven they marched, and many a province wide, END
BEGIN NOW Tenfold the length of this terrene: At last, END
BEGIN NOW Far in the horizon to the north appeared END
BEGIN NOW From skirt to skirt a fiery region, stretched END
BEGIN NOW In battailous aspect, and nearer view END
BEGIN NOW Bristled with upright beams innumerable END
BEGIN NOW Of rigid spears, and helmets thronged, and shields END
BEGIN NOW Various, with boastful argument portrayed, END
BEGIN NOW The banded Powers of Satan hasting on END
BEGIN NOW With furious expedition; for they weened END
BEGIN NOW That self-same day, by fight or by surprise, END
BEGIN NOW To win the mount of God, and on his throne END
BEGIN NOW To set the Envier of his state, the proud END
BEGIN NOW Aspirer; but their thoughts proved fond and vain END
BEGIN NOW In the mid way: Though strange to us it seemed END
BEGIN NOW At first, that Angel should with Angel war, END
BEGIN NOW And in fierce hosting meet, who wont to meet END
BEGIN NOW So oft in festivals of joy and love END
BEGIN NOW Unanimous, as sons of one great Sire, END
BEGIN NOW Hymning the Eternal Father: But the shout END
BEGIN NOW Of battle now began, and rushing sound END
BEGIN NOW Of onset ended soon each milder thought. END
BEGIN NOW High in the midst, exalted as a God, END
BEGIN NOW The Apostate in his sun-bright chariot sat, END
BEGIN NOW Idol of majesty divine, enclosed END
BEGIN NOW With flaming Cherubim, and golden shields; END
BEGIN NOW Then lighted from his gorgeous throne, for now END
BEGIN NOW 'Twixt host and host but narrow space was left, END
BEGIN NOW A dreadful interval, and front to front END
BEGIN NOW Presented stood in terrible array END
BEGIN NOW Of hideous length: Before the cloudy van, END
BEGIN NOW On the rough edge of battle ere it joined, END
BEGIN NOW Satan, with vast and haughty strides advanced, END
BEGIN NOW Came towering, armed in adamant and gold; END
BEGIN NOW Abdiel that sight endured not, where he stood END
BEGIN NOW Among the mightiest, bent on highest deeds, END
BEGIN NOW And thus his own undaunted heart explores. END
BEGIN NOW O Heaven! that such resemblance of the Highest END
BEGIN NOW Should yet remain, where faith and realty END
BEGIN NOW Remain not: Wherefore should not strength and might END
BEGIN NOW There fail where virtue fails, or weakest prove END
BEGIN NOW Where boldest, though to fight unconquerable? END
BEGIN NOW His puissance, trusting in the Almighty's aid, END
BEGIN NOW I mean to try, whose reason I have tried END
BEGIN NOW Unsound and false; nor is it aught but just, END
BEGIN NOW That he, who in debate of truth hath won, END
BEGIN NOW Should win in arms, in both disputes alike END
BEGIN NOW Victor; though brutish that contest and foul, END
BEGIN NOW When reason hath to deal with force, yet so END
BEGIN NOW Most reason is that reason overcome. END
BEGIN NOW So pondering, and from his armed peers END
BEGIN NOW Forth stepping opposite, half-way he met END
BEGIN NOW His daring foe, at this prevention more END
BEGIN NOW Incensed, and thus securely him defied. END
BEGIN NOW Proud, art thou met? thy hope was to have reached END
BEGIN NOW The highth of thy aspiring unopposed, END
BEGIN NOW The throne of God unguarded, and his side END
BEGIN NOW Abandoned, at the terrour of thy power END
BEGIN NOW Or potent tongue: Fool! not to think how vain END
BEGIN NOW Against the Omnipotent to rise in arms; END
BEGIN NOW Who out of smallest things could, without end, END
BEGIN NOW Have raised incessant armies to defeat END
BEGIN NOW Thy folly; or with solitary hand END
BEGIN NOW Reaching beyond all limit, at one blow, END
BEGIN NOW Unaided, could have finished thee, and whelmed END
BEGIN NOW Thy legions under darkness: But thou seest END
BEGIN NOW All are not of thy train; there be, who faith END
BEGIN NOW Prefer, and piety to God, though then END
BEGIN NOW To thee not visible, when I alone END
BEGIN NOW Seemed in thy world erroneous to dissent END
BEGIN NOW From all: My sect thou seest; now learn too late END
BEGIN NOW How few sometimes may know, when thousands err. END
BEGIN NOW Whom the grand foe, with scornful eye askance, END
BEGIN NOW Thus answered. Ill for thee, but in wished hour END
BEGIN NOW Of my revenge, first sought for, thou returnest END
BEGIN NOW From flight, seditious Angel! to receive END
BEGIN NOW Thy merited reward, the first assay END
BEGIN NOW Of this right hand provoked, since first that tongue, END
BEGIN NOW Inspired with contradiction, durst oppose END
BEGIN NOW A third part of the Gods, in synod met END
BEGIN NOW Their deities to assert; who, while they feel END
BEGIN NOW Vigour divine within them, can allow END
BEGIN NOW Omnipotence to none. But well thou comest END
BEGIN NOW Before thy fellows, ambitious to win END
BEGIN NOW From me some plume, that thy success may show END
BEGIN NOW Destruction to the rest: This pause between, END
BEGIN NOW (Unanswered lest thou boast) to let thee know, END
BEGIN NOW At first I thought that Liberty and Heaven END
BEGIN NOW To heavenly souls had been all one; but now END
BEGIN NOW I see that most through sloth had rather serve, END
BEGIN NOW Ministring Spirits, trained up in feast and song! END
BEGIN NOW Such hast thou armed, the minstrelsy of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Servility with freedom to contend, END
BEGIN NOW As both their deeds compared this day shall prove. END
BEGIN NOW To whom in brief thus Abdiel stern replied. END
BEGIN NOW Apostate! still thou errest, nor end wilt find END
BEGIN NOW Of erring, from the path of truth remote: END
BEGIN NOW Unjustly thou depravest it with the name END
BEGIN NOW Of servitude, to serve whom God ordains, END
BEGIN NOW Or Nature: God and Nature bid the same, END
BEGIN NOW When he who rules is worthiest, and excels END
BEGIN NOW Them whom he governs. This is servitude, END
BEGIN NOW To serve the unwise, or him who hath rebelled END
BEGIN NOW Against his worthier, as thine now serve thee, END
BEGIN NOW Thyself not free, but to thyself enthralled; END
BEGIN NOW Yet lewdly darest our ministring upbraid. END
BEGIN NOW Reign thou in Hell, thy kingdom; let me serve END
BEGIN NOW In Heaven God ever blest, and his divine END
BEGIN NOW Behests obey, worthiest to be obeyed; END
BEGIN NOW Yet chains in Hell, not realms, expect: Mean while END
BEGIN NOW From me returned, as erst thou saidst, from flight, END
BEGIN NOW This greeting on thy impious crest receive. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, a noble stroke he lifted high, END
BEGIN NOW Which hung not, but so swift with tempest fell END
BEGIN NOW On the proud crest of Satan, that no sight, END
BEGIN NOW Nor motion of swift thought, less could his shield, END
BEGIN NOW Such ruin intercept: Ten paces huge END
BEGIN NOW He back recoiled; the tenth on bended knee END
BEGIN NOW His massy spear upstaid; as if on earth END
BEGIN NOW Winds under ground, or waters forcing way, END
BEGIN NOW Sidelong had pushed a mountain from his seat, END
BEGIN NOW Half sunk with all his pines. Amazement seised END
BEGIN NOW The rebel Thrones, but greater rage, to see END
BEGIN NOW Thus foiled their mightiest; ours joy filled, and shout, END
BEGIN NOW Presage of victory, and fierce desire END
BEGIN NOW Of battle: Whereat Michael bid sound END
BEGIN NOW The Arch-Angel trumpet; through the vast of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW It sounded, and the faithful armies rung END
BEGIN NOW Hosanna to the Highest: Nor stood at gaze END
BEGIN NOW The adverse legions, nor less hideous joined END
BEGIN NOW The horrid shock. Now storming fury rose, END
BEGIN NOW And clamour such as heard in Heaven till now END
BEGIN NOW Was never; arms on armour clashing brayed END
BEGIN NOW Horrible discord, and the madding wheels END
BEGIN NOW Of brazen chariots raged; dire was the noise END
BEGIN NOW Of conflict; over head the dismal hiss END
BEGIN NOW Of fiery darts in flaming vollies flew, END
BEGIN NOW And flying vaulted either host with fire. END
BEGIN NOW So under fiery cope together rushed END
BEGIN NOW Both battles main, with ruinous assault END
BEGIN NOW And inextinguishable rage. All Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Resounded; and had Earth been then, all Earth END
BEGIN NOW Had to her center shook. What wonder? when END
BEGIN NOW Millions of fierce encountering Angels fought END
BEGIN NOW On either side, the least of whom could wield END
BEGIN NOW These elements, and arm him with the force END
BEGIN NOW Of all their regions: How much more of power END
BEGIN NOW Army against army numberless to raise END
BEGIN NOW Dreadful combustion warring, and disturb, END
BEGIN NOW Though not destroy, their happy native seat; END
BEGIN NOW From his strong hold of Heaven, high over-ruled END
BEGIN NOW And limited their might; though numbered such END
BEGIN NOW As each divided legion might have seemed END
BEGIN NOW A numerous host; in strength each armed hand END
BEGIN NOW A legion; led in fight, yet leader seemed END
BEGIN NOW Each warriour single as in chief, expert END
BEGIN NOW When to advance, or stand, or turn the sway END
BEGIN NOW Of battle, open when, and when to close END
BEGIN NOW The ridges of grim war: No thought of flight, END
BEGIN NOW None of retreat, no unbecoming deed END
BEGIN NOW That argued fear; each on himself relied, END
BEGIN NOW As only in his arm the moment lay END
BEGIN NOW Of victory: Deeds of eternal fame END
BEGIN NOW Were done, but infinite; for wide was spread END
BEGIN NOW That war and various; sometimes on firm ground END
BEGIN NOW A standing fight, then, soaring on main wing, END
BEGIN NOW Tormented all the air; all air seemed then END
BEGIN NOW Conflicting fire. Long time in even scale END
BEGIN NOW The battle hung; till Satan, who that day END
BEGIN NOW Prodigious power had shown, and met in arms END
BEGIN NOW No equal, ranging through the dire attack END
BEGIN NOW Of fighting Seraphim confused, at length END
BEGIN NOW Saw where the sword of Michael smote, and felled END
BEGIN NOW Squadrons at once; with huge two-handed sway END
BEGIN NOW Brandished aloft, the horrid edge came down END
BEGIN NOW Wide-wasting; such destruction to withstand END
BEGIN NOW He hasted, and opposed the rocky orb END
BEGIN NOW Of tenfold adamant, his ample shield, END
BEGIN NOW A vast circumference. At his approach END
BEGIN NOW The great Arch-Angel from his warlike toil END
BEGIN NOW Surceased, and glad, as hoping here to end END
BEGIN NOW Intestine war in Heaven, the arch-foe subdued END
BEGIN NOW Or captive dragged in chains, with hostile frown END
BEGIN NOW And visage all inflamed first thus began. END
BEGIN NOW Author of evil, unknown till thy revolt, END
BEGIN NOW Unnamed in Heaven, now plenteous as thou seest END
BEGIN NOW These acts of hateful strife, hateful to all, END
BEGIN NOW Though heaviest by just measure on thyself, END
BEGIN NOW And thy adherents: How hast thou disturbed END
BEGIN NOW Heaven's blessed peace, and into nature brought END
BEGIN NOW Misery, uncreated till the crime END
BEGIN NOW Of thy rebellion! how hast thou instilled END
BEGIN NOW Thy malice into thousands, once upright END
BEGIN NOW And faithful, now proved false! But think not here END
BEGIN NOW To trouble holy rest; Heaven casts thee out END
BEGIN NOW From all her confines. Heaven, the seat of bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Brooks not the works of violence and war. END
BEGIN NOW Hence then, and evil go with thee along, END
BEGIN NOW Thy offspring, to the place of evil, Hell; END
BEGIN NOW Thou and thy wicked crew! there mingle broils, END
BEGIN NOW Ere this avenging sword begin thy doom, END
BEGIN NOW Or some more sudden vengeance, winged from God, END
BEGIN NOW Precipitate thee with augmented pain. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Prince of Angels; to whom thus END
BEGIN NOW The Adversary. Nor think thou with wind END
BEGIN NOW Of aery threats to awe whom yet with deeds END
BEGIN NOW Thou canst not. Hast thou turned the least of these END
BEGIN NOW To flight, or if to fall, but that they rise END
BEGIN NOW Unvanquished, easier to transact with me END
BEGIN NOW That thou shouldst hope, imperious, and with threats END
BEGIN NOW To chase me hence? err not, that so shall end END
BEGIN NOW The strife which thou callest evil, but we style END
BEGIN NOW The strife of glory; which we mean to win, END
BEGIN NOW Or turn this Heaven itself into the Hell END
BEGIN NOW Thou fablest; here however to dwell free, END
BEGIN NOW If not to reign: Mean while thy utmost force, END
BEGIN NOW And join him named Almighty to thy aid, END
BEGIN NOW I fly not, but have sought thee far and nigh. END
BEGIN NOW They ended parle, and both addressed for fight END
BEGIN NOW Unspeakable; for who, though with the tongue END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels, can relate, or to what things END
BEGIN NOW Liken on earth conspicuous, that may lift END
BEGIN NOW Human imagination to such highth END
BEGIN NOW Of Godlike power? for likest Gods they seemed, END
BEGIN NOW Stood they or moved, in stature, motion, arms, END
BEGIN NOW Fit to decide the empire of great Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Now waved their fiery swords, and in the air END
BEGIN NOW Made horrid circles; two broad suns their shields END
BEGIN NOW Blazed opposite, while Expectation stood END
BEGIN NOW In horrour: From each hand with speed retired, END
BEGIN NOW Where erst was thickest fight, the angelick throng, END
BEGIN NOW And left large field, unsafe within the wind END
BEGIN NOW Of such commotion; such as, to set forth END
BEGIN NOW Great things by small, if, nature's concord broke, END
BEGIN NOW Among the constellations war were sprung, END
BEGIN NOW Two planets, rushing from aspect malign END
BEGIN NOW Of fiercest opposition, in mid sky END
BEGIN NOW Should combat, and their jarring spheres confound. END
BEGIN NOW Together both with next to almighty arm END
BEGIN NOW Up-lifted imminent, one stroke they aimed END
BEGIN NOW That might determine, and not need repeat, END
BEGIN NOW As not of power at once; nor odds appeared END
BEGIN NOW In might or swift prevention: But the sword END
BEGIN NOW Of Michael from the armoury of God END
BEGIN NOW Was given him tempered so, that neither keen END
BEGIN NOW Nor solid might resist that edge: it met END
BEGIN NOW The sword of Satan, with steep force to smite END
BEGIN NOW Descending, and in half cut sheer; nor staid, END
BEGIN NOW But with swift wheel reverse, deep entering, shared END
BEGIN NOW All his right side: Then Satan first knew pain, END
BEGIN NOW And writhed him to and fro convolved; so sore END
BEGIN NOW The griding sword with discontinuous wound END
BEGIN NOW Passed through him: But the ethereal substance closed, END
BEGIN NOW Not long divisible; and from the gash END
BEGIN NOW A stream of necturous humour issuing flowed END
BEGIN NOW Sanguine, such as celestial Spirits may bleed, END
BEGIN NOW And all his armour stained, ere while so bright. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith on all sides to his aid was run END
BEGIN NOW By Angels many and strong, who interposed END
BEGIN NOW Defence, while others bore him on their shields END
BEGIN NOW Back to his chariot, where it stood retired END
BEGIN NOW From off the files of war: There they him laid END
BEGIN NOW Gnashing for anguish, and despite, and shame, END
BEGIN NOW To find himself not matchless, and his pride END
BEGIN NOW Humbled by such rebuke, so far beneath END
BEGIN NOW His confidence to equal God in power. END
BEGIN NOW Yet soon he healed; for Spirits that live throughout END
BEGIN NOW Vital in every part, not as frail man END
BEGIN NOW In entrails, heart of head, liver or reins, END
BEGIN NOW Cannot but by annihilating die; END
BEGIN NOW Nor in their liquid texture mortal wound END
BEGIN NOW Receive, no more than can the fluid air: END
BEGIN NOW All heart they live, all head, all eye, all ear, END
BEGIN NOW All intellect, all sense; and, as they please, END
BEGIN NOW They limb themselves, and colour, shape, or size END
BEGIN NOW Assume, as likes them best, condense or rare. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while in other parts like deeds deserved END
BEGIN NOW Memorial, where the might of Gabriel fought, END
BEGIN NOW And with fierce ensigns pierced the deep array END
BEGIN NOW Of Moloch, furious king; who him defied, END
BEGIN NOW And at his chariot-wheels to drag him bound END
BEGIN NOW Threatened, nor from the Holy One of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Refrained his tongue blasphemous; but anon END
BEGIN NOW Down cloven to the waist, with shattered arms END
BEGIN NOW And uncouth pain fled bellowing. On each wing END
BEGIN NOW Uriel, and Raphael, his vaunting foe, END
BEGIN NOW Though huge, and in a rock of diamond armed, END
BEGIN NOW Two potent Thrones, that to be less than Gods END
BEGIN NOW Disdained, but meaner thoughts learned in their flight, END
BEGIN NOW Mangled with ghastly wounds through plate and mail. END
BEGIN NOW Nor stood unmindful Abdiel to annoy END
BEGIN NOW The atheist crew, but with redoubled blow END
BEGIN NOW Ariel, and Arioch, and the violence END
BEGIN NOW Of Ramiel scorched and blasted, overthrew. END
BEGIN NOW I might relate of thousands, and their names END
BEGIN NOW Eternize here on earth; but those elect END
BEGIN NOW Angels, contented with their fame in Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Seek not the praise of men: The other sort, END
BEGIN NOW In might though wonderous and in acts of war, END
BEGIN NOW Nor of renown less eager, yet by doom END
BEGIN NOW Cancelled from Heaven and sacred memory, END
BEGIN NOW Nameless in dark oblivion let them dwell. END
BEGIN NOW For strength from truth divided, and from just, END
BEGIN NOW Illaudable, nought merits but dispraise END
BEGIN NOW And ignominy; yet to glory aspires END
BEGIN NOW Vain-glorious, and through infamy seeks fame: END
BEGIN NOW Therefore eternal silence be their doom. END
BEGIN NOW And now, their mightiest quelled, the battle swerved, END
BEGIN NOW With many an inroad gored; deformed rout END
BEGIN NOW Entered, and foul disorder; all the ground END
BEGIN NOW With shivered armour strown, and on a heap END
BEGIN NOW Chariot and charioteer lay overturned, END
BEGIN NOW And fiery-foaming steeds; what stood, recoiled END
BEGIN NOW O'er-wearied, through the faint Satanick host END
BEGIN NOW Defensive scarce, or with pale fear surprised, END
BEGIN NOW Then first with fear surprised, and sense of pain, END
BEGIN NOW Fled ignominious, to such evil brought END
BEGIN NOW By sin of disobedience; till that hour END
BEGIN NOW Not liable to fear, or flight, or pain. END
BEGIN NOW Far otherwise the inviolable Saints, END
BEGIN NOW In cubick phalanx firm, advanced entire, END
BEGIN NOW Invulnerable, impenetrably armed; END
BEGIN NOW Such high advantages their innocence END
BEGIN NOW Gave them above their foes; not to have sinned, END
BEGIN NOW Not to have disobeyed; in fight they stood END
BEGIN NOW Unwearied, unobnoxious to be pained END
BEGIN NOW By wound, though from their place by violence moved, END
BEGIN NOW Now Night her course began, and, over Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Inducing darkness, grateful truce imposed, END
BEGIN NOW And silence on the odious din of war: END
BEGIN NOW Under her cloudy covert both retired, END
BEGIN NOW Victor and vanquished: On the foughten field END
BEGIN NOW Michael and his Angels prevalent END
BEGIN NOW Encamping, placed in guard their watches round, END
BEGIN NOW Cherubick waving fires: On the other part, END
BEGIN NOW Satan with his rebellious disappeared, END
BEGIN NOW Far in the dark dislodged; and, void of rest, END
BEGIN NOW His potentates to council called by night; END
BEGIN NOW And in the midst thus undismayed began. END
BEGIN NOW O now in danger tried, now known in arms END
BEGIN NOW Not to be overpowered, Companions dear, END
BEGIN NOW Found worthy not of liberty alone, END
BEGIN NOW Too mean pretence! but what we more affect, END
BEGIN NOW Honour, dominion, glory, and renown; END
BEGIN NOW Who have sustained one day in doubtful fight, END
BEGIN NOW (And if one day, why not eternal days?) END
BEGIN NOW What Heaven's Lord had powerfullest to send END
BEGIN NOW Against us from about his throne, and judged END
BEGIN NOW Sufficient to subdue us to his will, END
BEGIN NOW But proves not so: Then fallible, it seems, END
BEGIN NOW Of future we may deem him, though till now END
BEGIN NOW Omniscient thought. True is, less firmly armed, END
BEGIN NOW Some disadvantage we endured and pain, END
BEGIN NOW Till now not known, but, known, as soon contemned; END
BEGIN NOW Since now we find this our empyreal form END
BEGIN NOW Incapable of mortal injury, END
BEGIN NOW Imperishable, and, though pierced with wound, END
BEGIN NOW Soon closing, and by native vigour healed. END
BEGIN NOW Of evil then so small as easy think END
BEGIN NOW The remedy; perhaps more valid arms, END
BEGIN NOW Weapons more violent, when next we meet, END
BEGIN NOW May serve to better us, and worse our foes, END
BEGIN NOW Or equal what between us made the odds, END
BEGIN NOW In nature none: If other hidden cause END
BEGIN NOW Left them superiour, while we can preserve END
BEGIN NOW Unhurt our minds, and understanding sound, END
BEGIN NOW Due search and consultation will disclose. END
BEGIN NOW He sat; and in the assembly next upstood END
BEGIN NOW Nisroch, of Principalities the prime; END
BEGIN NOW As one he stood escaped from cruel fight, END
BEGIN NOW Sore toiled, his riven arms to havock hewn, END
BEGIN NOW And cloudy in aspect thus answering spake. END
BEGIN NOW Deliverer from new Lords, leader to free END
BEGIN NOW Enjoyment of our right as Gods; yet hard END
BEGIN NOW For Gods, and too unequal work we find, END
BEGIN NOW Against unequal arms to fight in pain, END
BEGIN NOW Against unpained, impassive; from which evil END
BEGIN NOW Ruin must needs ensue; for what avails END
BEGIN NOW Valour or strength, though matchless, quelled with pain END
BEGIN NOW Which all subdues, and makes remiss the hands END
BEGIN NOW Of mightiest? Sense of pleasure we may well END
BEGIN NOW Spare out of life perhaps, and not repine, END
BEGIN NOW But live content, which is the calmest life: END
BEGIN NOW But pain is perfect misery, the worst END
BEGIN NOW Of evils, and, excessive, overturns END
BEGIN NOW All patience. He, who therefore can invent END
BEGIN NOW With what more forcible we may offend END
BEGIN NOW Our yet unwounded enemies, or arm END
BEGIN NOW Ourselves with like defence, to me deserves END
BEGIN NOW No less than for deliverance what we owe. END
BEGIN NOW Whereto with look composed Satan replied. END
BEGIN NOW Not uninvented that, which thou aright END
BEGIN NOW Believest so main to our success, I bring. END
BEGIN NOW Which of us who beholds the bright surface END
BEGIN NOW Of this ethereous mould whereon we stand, END
BEGIN NOW This continent of spacious Heaven, adorned END
BEGIN NOW With plant, fruit, flower ambrosial, gems, and gold; END
BEGIN NOW Whose eye so superficially surveys END
BEGIN NOW These things, as not to mind from whence they grow END
BEGIN NOW Deep under ground, materials dark and crude, END
BEGIN NOW Of spiritous and fiery spume, till touched END
BEGIN NOW With Heaven's ray, and tempered, they shoot forth END
BEGIN NOW So beauteous, opening to the ambient light? END
BEGIN NOW These in their dark nativity the deep END
BEGIN NOW Shall yield us, pregnant with infernal flame; END
BEGIN NOW Which, into hollow engines, long and round, END
BEGIN NOW Thick rammed, at the other bore with touch of fire END
BEGIN NOW Dilated and infuriate, shall send forth END
BEGIN NOW From far, with thundering noise, among our foes END
BEGIN NOW Such implements of mischief, as shall dash END
BEGIN NOW To pieces, and o'erwhelm whatever stands END
BEGIN NOW Adverse, that they shall fear we have disarmed END
BEGIN NOW The Thunderer of his only dreaded bolt. END
BEGIN NOW Nor long shall be our labour; yet ere dawn, END
BEGIN NOW Effect shall end our wish. Mean while revive; END
BEGIN NOW Abandon fear; to strength and counsel joined END
BEGIN NOW Think nothing hard, much less to be despaired. END
BEGIN NOW He ended, and his words their drooping cheer END
BEGIN NOW Enlightened, and their languished hope revived. END
BEGIN NOW The invention all admired, and each, how he END
BEGIN NOW To be the inventer missed; so easy it seemed END
BEGIN NOW Once found, which yet unfound most would have thought END
BEGIN NOW Impossible: Yet, haply, of thy race END
BEGIN NOW In future days, if malice should abound, END
BEGIN NOW Some one intent on mischief, or inspired END
BEGIN NOW With devilish machination, might devise END
BEGIN NOW Like instrument to plague the sons of men END
BEGIN NOW For sin, on war and mutual slaughter bent. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith from council to the work they flew; END
BEGIN NOW None arguing stood; innumerable hands END
BEGIN NOW Were ready; in a moment up they turned END
BEGIN NOW Wide the celestial soil, and saw beneath END
BEGIN NOW The originals of nature in their crude END
BEGIN NOW Conception; sulphurous and nitrous foam END
BEGIN NOW They found, they mingled, and, with subtle art, END
BEGIN NOW Concocted and adusted they reduced END
BEGIN NOW To blackest grain, and into store conveyed: END
BEGIN NOW Part hidden veins digged up (nor hath this earth END
BEGIN NOW Entrails unlike) of mineral and stone, END
BEGIN NOW Whereof to found their engines and their balls END
BEGIN NOW Of missive ruin; part incentive reed END
BEGIN NOW Provide, pernicious with one touch to fire. END
BEGIN NOW So all ere day-spring, under conscious night, END
BEGIN NOW Secret they finished, and in order set, END
BEGIN NOW With silent circumspection, unespied. END
BEGIN NOW Now when fair morn orient in Heaven appeared, END
BEGIN NOW Up rose the victor-Angels, and to arms END
BEGIN NOW The matin trumpet sung: In arms they stood END
BEGIN NOW Of golden panoply, refulgent host, END
BEGIN NOW Soon banded; others from the dawning hills END
BEGIN NOW Look round, and scouts each coast light-armed scour, END
BEGIN NOW Each quarter to descry the distant foe, END
BEGIN NOW Where lodged, or whither fled, or if for fight, END
BEGIN NOW In motion or in halt: Him soon they met END
BEGIN NOW Under spread ensigns moving nigh, in slow END
BEGIN NOW But firm battalion; back with speediest sail END
BEGIN NOW Zophiel, of Cherubim the swiftest wing, END
BEGIN NOW Came flying, and in mid air aloud thus cried. END
BEGIN NOW Arm, Warriours, arm for fight; the foe at hand, END
BEGIN NOW Whom fled we thought, will save us long pursuit END
BEGIN NOW This day; fear not his flight; so thick a cloud END
BEGIN NOW He comes, and settled in his face I see END
BEGIN NOW Sad resolution, and secure: Let each END
BEGIN NOW His adamantine coat gird well, and each END
BEGIN NOW Fit well his helm, gripe fast his orbed shield, END
BEGIN NOW Borne even or high; for this day will pour down, END
BEGIN NOW If I conjecture aught, no drizzling shower, END
BEGIN NOW But rattling storm of arrows barbed with fire. END
BEGIN NOW So warned he them, aware themselves, and soon END
BEGIN NOW In order, quit of all impediment; END
BEGIN NOW Instant without disturb they took alarm, END
BEGIN NOW And onward moved embattled: When behold! END
BEGIN NOW Not distant far with heavy pace the foe END
BEGIN NOW Approaching gross and huge, in hollow cube END
BEGIN NOW Training his devilish enginery, impaled END
BEGIN NOW On every side with shadowing squadrons deep, END
BEGIN NOW To hide the fraud. At interview both stood END
BEGIN NOW A while; but suddenly at head appeared END
BEGIN NOW Satan, and thus was heard commanding loud. END
BEGIN NOW Vanguard, to right and left the front unfold; END
BEGIN NOW That all may see who hate us, how we seek END
BEGIN NOW Peace and composure, and with open breast END
BEGIN NOW Stand ready to receive them, if they like END
BEGIN NOW Our overture; and turn not back perverse: END
BEGIN NOW But that I doubt; however witness, Heaven! END
BEGIN NOW Heaven, witness thou anon! while we discharge END
BEGIN NOW Freely our part: ye, who appointed stand END
BEGIN NOW Do as you have in charge, and briefly touch END
BEGIN NOW What we propound, and loud that all may hear! END
BEGIN NOW So scoffing in ambiguous words, he scarce END
BEGIN NOW Had ended; when to right and left the front END
BEGIN NOW Divided, and to either flank retired: END
BEGIN NOW Which to our eyes discovered, new and strange, END
BEGIN NOW A triple mounted row of pillars laid END
BEGIN NOW On wheels (for like to pillars most they seemed, END
BEGIN NOW Or hollowed bodies made of oak or fir, END
BEGIN NOW With branches lopt, in wood or mountain felled,) END
BEGIN NOW Brass, iron, stony mould, had not their mouths END
BEGIN NOW With hideous orifice gaped on us wide, END
BEGIN NOW Portending hollow truce: At each behind END
BEGIN NOW A Seraph stood, and in his hand a reed END
BEGIN NOW Stood waving tipt with fire; while we, suspense, END
BEGIN NOW Collected stood within our thoughts amused, END
BEGIN NOW Not long; for sudden all at once their reeds END
BEGIN NOW Put forth, and to a narrow vent applied END
BEGIN NOW With nicest touch. Immediate in a flame, END
BEGIN NOW But soon obscured with smoke, all Heaven appeared, END
BEGIN NOW From those deep-throated engines belched, whose roar END
BEGIN NOW Embowelled with outrageous noise the air, END
BEGIN NOW And all her entrails tore, disgorging foul END
BEGIN NOW Their devilish glut, chained thunderbolts and hail END
BEGIN NOW Of iron globes; which, on the victor host END
BEGIN NOW Levelled, with such impetuous fury smote, END
BEGIN NOW That, whom they hit, none on their feet might stand, END
BEGIN NOW Though standing else as rocks, but down they fell END
BEGIN NOW By thousands, Angel on Arch-Angel rolled; END
BEGIN NOW The sooner for their arms; unarmed, they might END
BEGIN NOW Have easily, as Spirits, evaded swift END
BEGIN NOW By quick contraction or remove; but now END
BEGIN NOW Foul dissipation followed, and forced rout; END
BEGIN NOW Nor served it to relax their serried files. END
BEGIN NOW What should they do? if on they rushed, repulse END
BEGIN NOW Repeated, and indecent overthrow END
BEGIN NOW Doubled, would render them yet more despised, END
BEGIN NOW And to their foes a laughter; for in view END
BEGIN NOW Stood ranked of Seraphim another row, END
BEGIN NOW In posture to displode their second tire END
BEGIN NOW Of thunder: Back defeated to return END
BEGIN NOW They worse abhorred. Satan beheld their plight, END
BEGIN NOW And to his mates thus in derision called. END
BEGIN NOW O Friends! why come not on these victors proud END
BEGIN NOW Ere while they fierce were coming; and when we, END
BEGIN NOW To entertain them fair with open front END
BEGIN NOW And breast, (what could we more?) propounded terms END
BEGIN NOW Of composition, straight they changed their minds, END
BEGIN NOW Flew off, and into strange vagaries fell, END
BEGIN NOW As they would dance; yet for a dance they seemed END
BEGIN NOW Somewhat extravagant and wild; perhaps END
BEGIN NOW For joy of offered peace: But I suppose, END
BEGIN NOW If our proposals once again were heard, END
BEGIN NOW We should compel them to a quick result. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Belial, in like gamesome mood. END
BEGIN NOW Leader! the terms we sent were terms of weight, END
BEGIN NOW Of hard contents, and full of force urged home; END
BEGIN NOW Such as we might perceive amused them all, END
BEGIN NOW And stumbled many: Who receives them right, END
BEGIN NOW Had need from head to foot well understand; END
BEGIN NOW Not understood, this gift they have besides, END
BEGIN NOW They show us when our foes walk not upright. END
BEGIN NOW So they among themselves in pleasant vein END
BEGIN NOW Stood scoffing, hightened in their thoughts beyond END
BEGIN NOW All doubt of victory: Eternal Might END
BEGIN NOW To match with their inventions they presumed END
BEGIN NOW So easy, and of his thunder made a scorn, END
BEGIN NOW And all his host derided, while they stood END
BEGIN NOW A while in trouble: But they stood not long; END
BEGIN NOW Rage prompted them at length, and found them arms END
BEGIN NOW Against such hellish mischief fit to oppose. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith (behold the excellence, the power, END
BEGIN NOW Which God hath in his mighty Angels placed!) END
BEGIN NOW Their arms away they threw, and to the hills END
BEGIN NOW (For Earth hath this variety from Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Of pleasure situate in hill and dale,) END
BEGIN NOW Light as the lightning glimpse they ran, they flew; END
BEGIN NOW From their foundations loosening to and fro, END
BEGIN NOW They plucked the seated hills, with all their load, END
BEGIN NOW Rocks, waters, woods, and by the shaggy tops END
BEGIN NOW Up-lifting bore them in their hands: Amaze, END
BEGIN NOW Be sure, and terrour, seized the rebel host, END
BEGIN NOW When coming towards them so dread they saw END
BEGIN NOW The bottom of the mountains upward turned; END
BEGIN NOW Till on those cursed engines' triple-row END
BEGIN NOW They saw them whelmed, and all their confidence END
BEGIN NOW Under the weight of mountains buried deep; END
BEGIN NOW Themselves invaded next, and on their heads END
BEGIN NOW Main promontories flung, which in the air END
BEGIN NOW Came shadowing, and oppressed whole legions armed; END
BEGIN NOW Their armour helped their harm, crushed in and bruised END
BEGIN NOW Into their substance pent, which wrought them pain END
BEGIN NOW Implacable, and many a dolorous groan; END
BEGIN NOW Long struggling underneath, ere they could wind END
BEGIN NOW Out of such prison, though Spirits of purest light, END
BEGIN NOW Purest at first, now gross by sinning grown. END
BEGIN NOW The rest, in imitation, to like arms END
BEGIN NOW Betook them, and the neighbouring hills uptore: END
BEGIN NOW So hills amid the air encountered hills, END
BEGIN NOW Hurled to and fro with jaculation dire; END
BEGIN NOW That under ground they fought in dismal shade; END
BEGIN NOW Infernal noise! war seemed a civil game END
BEGIN NOW To this uproar; horrid confusion heaped END
BEGIN NOW Upon confusion rose: And now all Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Had gone to wrack, with ruin overspread; END
BEGIN NOW Had not the Almighty Father, where he sits END
BEGIN NOW Shrined in his sanctuary of Heaven secure, END
BEGIN NOW Consulting on the sum of things, foreseen END
BEGIN NOW This tumult, and permitted all, advised: END
BEGIN NOW That his great purpose he might so fulfil, END
BEGIN NOW To honour his anointed Son avenged END
BEGIN NOW Upon his enemies, and to declare END
BEGIN NOW All power on him transferred: Whence to his Son, END
BEGIN NOW The Assessour of his throne, he thus began. END
BEGIN NOW Effulgence of my glory, Son beloved, END
BEGIN NOW Son, in whose face invisible is beheld END
BEGIN NOW Visibly, what by Deity I am; END
BEGIN NOW And in whose hand what by decree I do, END
BEGIN NOW Second Omnipotence! two days are past, END
BEGIN NOW Two days, as we compute the days of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Since Michael and his Powers went forth to tame END
BEGIN NOW These disobedient: Sore hath been their fight, END
BEGIN NOW As likeliest was, when two such foes met armed; END
BEGIN NOW For to themselves I left them; and thou knowest, END
BEGIN NOW Equal in their creation they were formed, END
BEGIN NOW Save what sin hath impaired; which yet hath wrought END
BEGIN NOW Insensibly, for I suspend their doom; END
BEGIN NOW Whence in perpetual fight they needs must last END
BEGIN NOW Endless, and no solution will be found: END
BEGIN NOW War wearied hath performed what war can do, END
BEGIN NOW And to disordered rage let loose the reins END
BEGIN NOW With mountains, as with weapons, armed; which makes END
BEGIN NOW Wild work in Heaven, and dangerous to the main. END
BEGIN NOW Two days are therefore past, the third is thine; END
BEGIN NOW For thee I have ordained it; and thus far END
BEGIN NOW Have suffered, that the glory may be thine END
BEGIN NOW Of ending this great war, since none but Thou END
BEGIN NOW Can end it. Into thee such virtue and grace END
BEGIN NOW Immense I have transfused, that all may know END
BEGIN NOW In Heaven and Hell thy power above compare; END
BEGIN NOW And, this perverse commotion governed thus, END
BEGIN NOW To manifest thee worthiest to be Heir END
BEGIN NOW Of all things; to be Heir, and to be King END
BEGIN NOW By sacred unction, thy deserved right. END
BEGIN NOW Go then, Thou Mightiest, in thy Father's might; END
BEGIN NOW Ascend my chariot, guide the rapid wheels END
BEGIN NOW That shake Heaven's basis, bring forth all my war, END
BEGIN NOW My bow and thunder, my almighty arms END
BEGIN NOW Gird on, and sword upon thy puissant thigh; END
BEGIN NOW Pursue these sons of darkness, drive them out END
BEGIN NOW From all Heaven's bounds into the utter deep: END
BEGIN NOW There let them learn, as likes them, to despise END
BEGIN NOW God, and Messiah his anointed King. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and on his Son with rays direct END
BEGIN NOW Shone full; he all his Father full expressed END
BEGIN NOW Ineffably into his face received; END
BEGIN NOW And thus the Filial Godhead answering spake. END
BEGIN NOW O Father, O Supreme of heavenly Thrones, END
BEGIN NOW First, Highest, Holiest, Best; thou always seek'st END
BEGIN NOW To glorify thy Son, I always thee, END
BEGIN NOW As is most just: This I my glory account, END
BEGIN NOW My exaltation, and my whole delight, END
BEGIN NOW That thou, in me well pleased, declarest thy will END
BEGIN NOW Fulfilled, which to fulfil is all my bliss. END
BEGIN NOW Scepter and power, thy giving, I assume, END
BEGIN NOW And gladlier shall resign, when in the end END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt be all in all, and I in thee END
BEGIN NOW For ever; and in me all whom thou lovest: END
BEGIN NOW But whom thou hatest, I hate, and can put on END
BEGIN NOW Thy terrours, as I put thy mildness on, END
BEGIN NOW Image of thee in all things; and shall soon, END
BEGIN NOW Armed with thy might, rid Heaven of these rebelled; END
BEGIN NOW To their prepared ill mansion driven down, END
BEGIN NOW To chains of darkness, and the undying worm; END
BEGIN NOW That from thy just obedience could revolt, END
BEGIN NOW Whom to obey is happiness entire. END
BEGIN NOW Then shall thy Saints unmixed, and from the impure END
BEGIN NOW Far separate, circling thy holy mount, END
BEGIN NOW Unfeigned Halleluiahs to thee sing, END
BEGIN NOW Hymns of high praise, and I among them Chief. END
BEGIN NOW So said, he, o'er his scepter bowing, rose END
BEGIN NOW From the right hand of Glory where he sat; END
BEGIN NOW And the third sacred morn began to shine, END
BEGIN NOW Dawning through Heaven. Forth rushed with whirlwind sound END
BEGIN NOW The chariot of Paternal Deity, END
BEGIN NOW Flashing thick flames, wheel within wheel undrawn, END
BEGIN NOW Itself instinct with Spirit, but convoyed END
BEGIN NOW By four Cherubick shapes; four faces each END
BEGIN NOW Had wonderous; as with stars, their bodies all END
BEGIN NOW And wings were set with eyes; with eyes the wheels END
BEGIN NOW Of beryl, and careering fires between; END
BEGIN NOW Over their heads a crystal firmament, END
BEGIN NOW Whereon a sapphire throne, inlaid with pure END
BEGIN NOW Amber, and colours of the showery arch. END
BEGIN NOW He, in celestial panoply all armed END
BEGIN NOW Of radiant Urim, work divinely wrought, END
BEGIN NOW Ascended; at his right hand Victory END
BEGIN NOW Sat eagle-winged; beside him hung his bow END
BEGIN NOW And quiver with three-bolted thunder stored; END
BEGIN NOW And from about him fierce effusion rolled END
BEGIN NOW Of smoke, and bickering flame, and sparkles dire: END
BEGIN NOW Attended with ten thousand thousand Saints, END
BEGIN NOW He onward came; far off his coming shone; END
BEGIN NOW And twenty thousand (I their number heard) END
BEGIN NOW Chariots of God, half on each hand, were seen; END
BEGIN NOW He on the wings of Cherub rode sublime END
BEGIN NOW On the crystalline sky, in sapphire throned, END
BEGIN NOW Illustrious far and wide; but by his own END
BEGIN NOW First seen: Them unexpected joy surprised, END
BEGIN NOW When the great ensign of Messiah blazed END
BEGIN NOW Aloft by Angels borne, his sign in Heaven; END
BEGIN NOW Under whose conduct Michael soon reduced END
BEGIN NOW His army, circumfused on either wing, END
BEGIN NOW Under their Head imbodied all in one. END
BEGIN NOW Before him Power Divine his way prepared; END
BEGIN NOW At his command the uprooted hills retired END
BEGIN NOW Each to his place; they heard his voice, and went END
BEGIN NOW Obsequious; Heaven his wonted face renewed, END
BEGIN NOW And with fresh flowerets hill and valley smiled. END
BEGIN NOW This saw his hapless foes, but stood obdured, END
BEGIN NOW And to rebellious fight rallied their Powers, END
BEGIN NOW Insensate, hope conceiving from despair. END
BEGIN NOW In heavenly Spirits could such perverseness dwell? END
BEGIN NOW But to convince the proud what signs avail, END
BEGIN NOW Or wonders move the obdurate to relent? END
BEGIN NOW They, hardened more by what might most reclaim, END
BEGIN NOW Grieving to see his glory, at the sight END
BEGIN NOW Took envy; and, aspiring to his highth, END
BEGIN NOW Stood re-embattled fierce, by force or fraud END
BEGIN NOW Weening to prosper, and at length prevail END
BEGIN NOW Against God and Messiah, or to fall END
BEGIN NOW In universal ruin last; and now END
BEGIN NOW To final battle drew, disdaining flight, END
BEGIN NOW Or faint retreat; when the great Son of God END
BEGIN NOW To all his host on either hand thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW Stand still in bright array, ye Saints; here stand, END
BEGIN NOW Ye Angels armed; this day from battle rest: END
BEGIN NOW Faithful hath been your warfare, and of God END
BEGIN NOW Accepted, fearless in his righteous cause; END
BEGIN NOW And as ye have received, so have ye done, END
BEGIN NOW Invincibly: But of this cursed crew END
BEGIN NOW The punishment to other hand belongs; END
BEGIN NOW Vengeance is his, or whose he sole appoints: END
BEGIN NOW Number to this day's work is not ordained, END
BEGIN NOW Nor multitude; stand only, and behold END
BEGIN NOW God's indignation on these godless poured END
BEGIN NOW By me; not you, but me, they have despised, END
BEGIN NOW Yet envied; against me is all their rage, END
BEGIN NOW Because the Father, to whom in Heaven s'preme END
BEGIN NOW Kingdom, and power, and glory appertains, END
BEGIN NOW Hath honoured me, according to his will. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore to me their doom he hath assigned; END
BEGIN NOW That they may have their wish, to try with me END
BEGIN NOW In battle which the stronger proves; they all, END
BEGIN NOW Or I alone against them; since by strength END
BEGIN NOW They measure all, of other excellence END
BEGIN NOW Not emulous, nor care who them excels; END
BEGIN NOW Nor other strife with them do I vouchsafe. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Son, and into terrour changed END
BEGIN NOW His countenance too severe to be beheld, END
BEGIN NOW And full of wrath bent on his enemies. END
BEGIN NOW At once the Four spread out their starry wings END
BEGIN NOW With dreadful shade contiguous, and the orbs END
BEGIN NOW Of his fierce chariot rolled, as with the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of torrent floods, or of a numerous host. END
BEGIN NOW He on his impious foes right onward drove, END
BEGIN NOW Gloomy as night; under his burning wheels END
BEGIN NOW The stedfast empyrean shook throughout, END
BEGIN NOW All but the throne itself of God. Full soon END
BEGIN NOW Among them he arrived; in his right hand END
BEGIN NOW Grasping ten thousand thunders, which he sent END
BEGIN NOW Before him, such as in their souls infixed END
BEGIN NOW Plagues: They, astonished, all resistance lost, END
BEGIN NOW All courage; down their idle weapons dropt: END
BEGIN NOW O'er shields, and helms, and helmed heads he rode END
BEGIN NOW Of Thrones and mighty Seraphim prostrate, END
BEGIN NOW That wished the mountains now might be again END
BEGIN NOW Thrown on them, as a shelter from his ire. END
BEGIN NOW Nor less on either side tempestuous fell END
BEGIN NOW His arrows, from the fourfold-visaged Four END
BEGIN NOW Distinct with eyes, and from the living wheels END
BEGIN NOW Distinct alike with multitude of eyes; END
BEGIN NOW One Spirit in them ruled; and every eye END
BEGIN NOW Glared lightning, and shot forth pernicious fire END
BEGIN NOW Among the accursed, that withered all their strength, END
BEGIN NOW And of their wonted vigour left them drained, END
BEGIN NOW Exhausted, spiritless, afflicted, fallen. END
BEGIN NOW Yet half his strength he put not forth, but checked END
BEGIN NOW His thunder in mid volley; for he meant END
BEGIN NOW Not to destroy, but root them out of Heaven: END
BEGIN NOW The overthrown he raised, and as a herd END
BEGIN NOW Of goats or timorous flock together thronged END
BEGIN NOW Drove them before him thunder-struck, pursued END
BEGIN NOW With terrours, and with furies, to the bounds END
BEGIN NOW And crystal wall of Heaven; which, opening wide, END
BEGIN NOW Rolled inward, and a spacious gap disclosed END
BEGIN NOW Into the wasteful deep: The monstrous sight END
BEGIN NOW Struck them with horrour backward, but far worse END
BEGIN NOW Urged them behind: Headlong themselves they threw END
BEGIN NOW Down from the verge of Heaven; eternal wrath END
BEGIN NOW Burnt after them to the bottomless pit. END
BEGIN NOW Hell heard the unsufferable noise, Hell saw END
BEGIN NOW Heaven ruining from Heaven, and would have fled END
BEGIN NOW Affrighted; but strict Fate had cast too deep END
BEGIN NOW Her dark foundations, and too fast had bound. END
BEGIN NOW Nine days they fell: Confounded Chaos roared, END
BEGIN NOW And felt tenfold confusion in their fall END
BEGIN NOW Through his wild anarchy, so huge a rout END
BEGIN NOW Incumbered him with ruin: Hell at last END
BEGIN NOW Yawning received them whole, and on them closed; END
BEGIN NOW Hell, their fit habitation, fraught with fire END
BEGIN NOW Unquenchable, the house of woe and pain. END
BEGIN NOW Disburdened Heaven rejoiced, and soon repaired END
BEGIN NOW Her mural breach, returning whence it rolled. END
BEGIN NOW Sole victor, from the expulsion of his foes, END
BEGIN NOW Messiah his triumphal chariot turned: END
BEGIN NOW To meet him all his Saints, who silent stood END
BEGIN NOW Eye-witnesses of his almighty acts, END
BEGIN NOW With jubilee advanced; and, as they went, END
BEGIN NOW Shaded with branching palm, each Order bright, END
BEGIN NOW Sung triumph, and him sung victorious King, END
BEGIN NOW Son, Heir, and Lord, to him dominion given, END
BEGIN NOW Worthiest to reign: He, celebrated, rode END
BEGIN NOW Triumphant through mid Heaven, into the courts END
BEGIN NOW And temple of his Mighty Father throned END
BEGIN NOW On high; who into glory him received, END
BEGIN NOW Where now he sits at the right hand of bliss. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, measuring things in Heaven by things on Earth, END
BEGIN NOW At thy request, and that thou mayest beware END
BEGIN NOW By what is past, to thee I have revealed END
BEGIN NOW What might have else to human race been hid; END
BEGIN NOW The discord which befel, and war in Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Among the angelick Powers, and the deep fall END
BEGIN NOW Of those too high aspiring, who rebelled END
BEGIN NOW With Satan; he who envies now thy state, END
BEGIN NOW Who now is plotting how he may seduce END
BEGIN NOW Thee also from obedience, that, with him END
BEGIN NOW Bereaved of happiness, thou mayest partake END
BEGIN NOW His punishment, eternal misery; END
BEGIN NOW Which would be all his solace and revenge, END
BEGIN NOW As a despite done against the Most High, END
BEGIN NOW Thee once to gain companion of his woe. END
BEGIN NOW But listen not to his temptations, warn END
BEGIN NOW Thy weaker; let it profit thee to have heard, END
BEGIN NOW By terrible example, the reward END
BEGIN NOW Of disobedience; firm they might have stood, END
BEGIN NOW Yet fell; remember, and fear to transgress. END
BEGIN NOW Descend from Heaven, Urania, by that name END
BEGIN NOW If rightly thou art called, whose voice divine END
BEGIN NOW Following, above the Olympian hill I soar, END
BEGIN NOW Above the flight of Pegasean wing! END
BEGIN NOW The meaning, not the name, I call: for thou END
BEGIN NOW Nor of the Muses nine, nor on the top END
BEGIN NOW Of old Olympus dwellest; but, heavenly-born, END
BEGIN NOW Before the hills appeared, or fountain flowed, END
BEGIN NOW Thou with eternal Wisdom didst converse, END
BEGIN NOW Wisdom thy sister, and with her didst play END
BEGIN NOW In presence of the Almighty Father, pleased END
BEGIN NOW With thy celestial song. Up led by thee END
BEGIN NOW Into the Heaven of Heavens I have presumed, END
BEGIN NOW An earthly guest, and drawn empyreal air, END
BEGIN NOW Thy tempering: with like safety guided down END
BEGIN NOW Return me to my native element: END
BEGIN NOW Lest from this flying steed unreined, (as once END
BEGIN NOW Bellerophon, though from a lower clime,) END
BEGIN NOW Dismounted, on the Aleian field I fall, END
BEGIN NOW Erroneous there to wander, and forlorn. END
BEGIN NOW Half yet remains unsung, but narrower bound END
BEGIN NOW Within the visible diurnal sphere; END
BEGIN NOW Standing on earth, not rapt above the pole, END
BEGIN NOW More safe I sing with mortal voice, unchanged END
BEGIN NOW To hoarse or mute, though fallen on evil days, END
BEGIN NOW On evil days though fallen, and evil tongues; END
BEGIN NOW In darkness, and with dangers compassed round, END
BEGIN NOW And solitude; yet not alone, while thou END
BEGIN NOW Visitest my slumbers nightly, or when morn END
BEGIN NOW Purples the east: still govern thou my song, END
BEGIN NOW Urania, and fit audience find, though few. END
BEGIN NOW But drive far off the barbarous dissonance END
BEGIN NOW Of Bacchus and his revellers, the race END
BEGIN NOW Of that wild rout that tore the Thracian bard END
BEGIN NOW In Rhodope, where woods and rocks had ears END
BEGIN NOW To rapture, till the savage clamour drowned END
BEGIN NOW Both harp and voice; nor could the Muse defend END
BEGIN NOW Her son. So fail not thou, who thee implores: END
BEGIN NOW For thou art heavenly, she an empty dream. END
BEGIN NOW Say, Goddess, what ensued when Raphael, END
BEGIN NOW The affable Arch-Angel, had forewarned END
BEGIN NOW Adam, by dire example, to beware END
BEGIN NOW Apostasy, by what befel in Heaven END
BEGIN NOW To those apostates; lest the like befall END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise to Adam or his race, END
BEGIN NOW Charged not to touch the interdicted tree, END
BEGIN NOW If they transgress, and slight that sole command, END
BEGIN NOW So easily obeyed amid the choice END
BEGIN NOW Of all tastes else to please their appetite, END
BEGIN NOW Though wandering. He, with his consorted Eve, END
BEGIN NOW The story heard attentive, and was filled END
BEGIN NOW With admiration and deep muse, to hear END
BEGIN NOW Of things so high and strange; things, to their thought END
BEGIN NOW So unimaginable, as hate in Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW And war so near the peace of God in bliss, END
BEGIN NOW With such confusion: but the evil, soon END
BEGIN NOW Driven back, redounded as a flood on those END
BEGIN NOW From whom it sprung; impossible to mix END
BEGIN NOW With blessedness. Whence Adam soon repealed END
BEGIN NOW The doubts that in his heart arose: and now END
BEGIN NOW Led on, yet sinless, with desire to know END
BEGIN NOW What nearer might concern him, how this world END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven and Earth conspicuous first began; END
BEGIN NOW When, and whereof created; for what cause; END
BEGIN NOW What within Eden, or without, was done END
BEGIN NOW Before his memory; as one whose drouth END
BEGIN NOW Yet scarce allayed still eyes the current stream, END
BEGIN NOW Whose liquid murmur heard new thirst excites, END
BEGIN NOW Proceeded thus to ask his heavenly guest. END
BEGIN NOW Great things, and full of wonder in our ears, END
BEGIN NOW Far differing from this world, thou hast revealed, END
BEGIN NOW Divine interpreter! by favour sent END
BEGIN NOW Down from the empyrean, to forewarn END
BEGIN NOW Us timely of what might else have been our loss, END
BEGIN NOW Unknown, which human knowledge could not reach; END
BEGIN NOW For which to the infinitely Good we owe END
BEGIN NOW Immortal thanks, and his admonishment END
BEGIN NOW Receive, with solemn purpose to observe END
BEGIN NOW Immutably his sovran will, the end END
BEGIN NOW Of what we are. But since thou hast vouchsafed END
BEGIN NOW Gently, for our instruction, to impart END
BEGIN NOW Things above earthly thought, which yet concerned END
BEGIN NOW Our knowing, as to highest wisdom seemed, END
BEGIN NOW Deign to descend now lower, and relate END
BEGIN NOW What may no less perhaps avail us known, END
BEGIN NOW How first began this Heaven which we behold END
BEGIN NOW Distant so high, with moving fires adorned END
BEGIN NOW Innumerable; and this which yields or fills END
BEGIN NOW All space, the ambient air wide interfused END
BEGIN NOW Embracing round this floried Earth; what cause END
BEGIN NOW Moved the Creator, in his holy rest END
BEGIN NOW Through all eternity, so late to build END
BEGIN NOW In Chaos; and the work begun, how soon END
BEGIN NOW Absolved; if unforbid thou mayest unfold END
BEGIN NOW What we, not to explore the secrets ask END
BEGIN NOW Of his eternal empire, but the more END
BEGIN NOW To magnify his works, the more we know. END
BEGIN NOW And the great light of day yet wants to run END
BEGIN NOW Much of his race though steep; suspense in Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Held by thy voice, thy potent voice, he hears, END
BEGIN NOW And longer will delay to hear thee tell END
BEGIN NOW His generation, and the rising birth END
BEGIN NOW Of Nature from the unapparent Deep: END
BEGIN NOW Or if the star of evening and the moon END
BEGIN NOW Haste to thy audience, Night with her will bring, END
BEGIN NOW Silence; and Sleep, listening to thee, will watch; END
BEGIN NOW Or we can bid his absence, till thy song END
BEGIN NOW End, and dismiss thee ere the morning shine. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Adam his illustrious guest besought: END
BEGIN NOW And thus the Godlike Angel answered mild. END
BEGIN NOW This also thy request, with caution asked, END
BEGIN NOW Obtain; though to recount almighty works END
BEGIN NOW What words or tongue of Seraph can suffice, END
BEGIN NOW Or heart of man suffice to comprehend? END
BEGIN NOW Yet what thou canst attain, which best may serve END
BEGIN NOW To glorify the Maker, and infer END
BEGIN NOW Thee also happier, shall not be withheld END
BEGIN NOW Thy hearing; such commission from above END
BEGIN NOW I have received, to answer thy desire END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledge within bounds; beyond, abstain END
BEGIN NOW To ask; nor let thine own inventions hope END
BEGIN NOW Things not revealed, which the invisible King, END
BEGIN NOW Only Omniscient, hath suppressed in night; END
BEGIN NOW To none communicable in Earth or Heaven: END
BEGIN NOW Enough is left besides to search and know. END
BEGIN NOW But knowledge is as food, and needs no less END
BEGIN NOW Her temperance over appetite, to know END
BEGIN NOW In measure what the mind may well contain; END
BEGIN NOW Oppresses else with surfeit, and soon turns END
BEGIN NOW Wisdom to folly, as nourishment to wind. END
BEGIN NOW Know then, that, after Lucifer from Heaven END
BEGIN NOW (So call him, brighter once amidst the host END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels, than that star the stars among,) END
BEGIN NOW Fell with his flaming legions through the deep END
BEGIN NOW Into his place, and the great Son returned END
BEGIN NOW Victorious with his Saints, the Omnipotent END
BEGIN NOW Eternal Father from his throne beheld END
BEGIN NOW Their multitude, and to his Son thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW At least our envious Foe hath failed, who thought END
BEGIN NOW All like himself rebellious, by whose aid END
BEGIN NOW This inaccessible high strength, the seat END
BEGIN NOW Of Deity supreme, us dispossessed, END
BEGIN NOW He trusted to have seised, and into fraud END
BEGIN NOW Drew many, whom their place knows here no more: END
BEGIN NOW Yet far the greater part have kept, I see, END
BEGIN NOW Their station; Heaven, yet populous, retains END
BEGIN NOW Number sufficient to possess her realms END
BEGIN NOW Though wide, and this high temple to frequent END
BEGIN NOW With ministeries due, and solemn rites: END
BEGIN NOW But, lest his heart exalt him in the harm END
BEGIN NOW Already done, to have dispeopled Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW My damage fondly deemed, I can repair END
BEGIN NOW That detriment, if such it be to lose END
BEGIN NOW Self-lost; and in a moment will create END
BEGIN NOW Another world, out of one man a race END
BEGIN NOW Of men innumerable, there to dwell, END
BEGIN NOW Not here; till, by degrees of merit raised, END
BEGIN NOW They open to themselves at length the way END
BEGIN NOW Up hither, under long obedience tried; END
BEGIN NOW And Earth be changed to Heaven, and Heaven to Earth, END
BEGIN NOW One kingdom, joy and union without end. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while inhabit lax, ye Powers of Heaven; END
BEGIN NOW And thou my Word, begotten Son, by thee END
BEGIN NOW This I perform; speak thou, and be it done! END
BEGIN NOW My overshadowing Spirit and Might with thee END
BEGIN NOW I send along; ride forth, and bid the Deep END
BEGIN NOW Within appointed bounds be Heaven and Earth; END
BEGIN NOW Boundless the Deep, because I Am who fill END
BEGIN NOW Infinitude, nor vacuous the space. END
BEGIN NOW Though I, uncircumscribed myself, retire, END
BEGIN NOW And put not forth my goodness, which is free END
BEGIN NOW To act or not, Necessity and Chance END
BEGIN NOW Approach not me, and what I will is Fate. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Almighty, and to what he spake END
BEGIN NOW His Word, the Filial Godhead, gave effect. END
BEGIN NOW Immediate are the acts of God, more swift END
BEGIN NOW Than time or motion, but to human ears END
BEGIN NOW Cannot without process of speech be told, END
BEGIN NOW So told as earthly notion can receive. END
BEGIN NOW Great triumph and rejoicing was in Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW When such was heard declared the Almighty's will; END
BEGIN NOW Glory they sung to the Most High, good will END
BEGIN NOW To future men, and in their dwellings peace; END
BEGIN NOW Glory to Him, whose just avenging ire END
BEGIN NOW Had driven out the ungodly from his sight END
BEGIN NOW And the habitations of the just; to Him END
BEGIN NOW Glory and praise, whose wisdom had ordained END
BEGIN NOW Good out of evil to create; instead END
BEGIN NOW Of Spirits malign, a better race to bring END
BEGIN NOW Into their vacant room, and thence diffuse END
BEGIN NOW His good to worlds and ages infinite. END
BEGIN NOW So sang the Hierarchies: Mean while the Son END
BEGIN NOW On his great expedition now appeared, END
BEGIN NOW Girt with Omnipotence, with radiance crowned END
BEGIN NOW Of Majesty Divine; sapience and love END
BEGIN NOW Immense, and all his Father in him shone. END
BEGIN NOW About his chariot numberless were poured END
BEGIN NOW And Virtues, winged Spirits, and chariots winged END
BEGIN NOW From the armoury of God; where stand of old END
BEGIN NOW Myriads, between two brazen mountains lodged END
BEGIN NOW Against a solemn day, harnessed at hand, END
BEGIN NOW Celestial equipage; and now came forth END
BEGIN NOW Spontaneous, for within them Spirit lived, END
BEGIN NOW Attendant on their Lord: Heaven opened wide END
BEGIN NOW Her ever-during gates, harmonious sound END
BEGIN NOW On golden hinges moving, to let forth END
BEGIN NOW The King of Glory, in his powerful Word END
BEGIN NOW And Spirit, coming to create new worlds. END
BEGIN NOW On heavenly ground they stood; and from the shore END
BEGIN NOW They viewed the vast immeasurable abyss END
BEGIN NOW Outrageous as a sea, dark, wasteful, wild, END
BEGIN NOW Up from the bottom turned by furious winds END
BEGIN NOW And surging waves, as mountains, to assault END
BEGIN NOW Heaven's highth, and with the center mix the pole. END
BEGIN NOW Silence, ye troubled Waves, and thou Deep, peace, END
BEGIN NOW Said then the Omnifick Word; your discord end! END
BEGIN NOW Nor staid; but, on the wings of Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW Uplifted, in paternal glory rode END
BEGIN NOW Far into Chaos, and the world unborn; END
BEGIN NOW For Chaos heard his voice: Him all his train END
BEGIN NOW Followed in bright procession, to behold END
BEGIN NOW Creation, and the wonders of his might. END
BEGIN NOW Then staid the fervid wheels, and in his hand END
BEGIN NOW He took the golden compasses, prepared END
BEGIN NOW In God's eternal store, to circumscribe END
BEGIN NOW This universe, and all created things: END
BEGIN NOW One foot he centered, and the other turned END
BEGIN NOW Round through the vast profundity obscure; END
BEGIN NOW And said, Thus far extend, thus far thy bounds, END
BEGIN NOW This be thy just circumference, O World! END
BEGIN NOW Thus God the Heaven created, thus the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Matter unformed and void: Darkness profound END
BEGIN NOW Covered the abyss: but on the watery calm END
BEGIN NOW His brooding wings the Spirit of God outspread, END
BEGIN NOW And vital virtue infused, and vital warmth END
BEGIN NOW Throughout the fluid mass; but downward purged END
BEGIN NOW The black tartareous cold infernal dregs, END
BEGIN NOW Adverse to life: then founded, then conglobed END
BEGIN NOW Like things to like; the rest to several place END
BEGIN NOW Disparted, and between spun out the air; END
BEGIN NOW And Earth self-balanced on her center hung. END
BEGIN NOW Let there be light, said God; and forthwith Light END
BEGIN NOW Ethereal, first of things, quintessence pure, END
BEGIN NOW Sprung from the deep; and from her native east END
BEGIN NOW To journey through the aery gloom began, END
BEGIN NOW Sphered in a radiant cloud, for yet the sun END
BEGIN NOW Was not; she in a cloudy tabernacle END
BEGIN NOW Sojourned the while. God saw the light was good; END
BEGIN NOW And light from darkness by the hemisphere END
BEGIN NOW Divided: light the Day, and darkness Night, END
BEGIN NOW He named. Thus was the first day even and morn: END
BEGIN NOW Nor past uncelebrated, nor unsung END
BEGIN NOW By the celestial quires, when orient light END
BEGIN NOW Exhaling first from darkness they beheld; END
BEGIN NOW Birth-day of Heaven and Earth; with joy and shout END
BEGIN NOW The hollow universal orb they filled, END
BEGIN NOW And touched their golden harps, and hymning praised END
BEGIN NOW God and his works; Creator him they sung, END
BEGIN NOW Both when first evening was, and when first morn. END
BEGIN NOW Again, God said, Let there be firmament END
BEGIN NOW Amid the waters, and let it divide END
BEGIN NOW The waters from the waters; and God made END
BEGIN NOW The firmament, expanse of liquid, pure, END
BEGIN NOW Transparent, elemental air, diffused END
BEGIN NOW In circuit to the uttermost convex END
BEGIN NOW Of this great round; partition firm and sure, END
BEGIN NOW The waters underneath from those above END
BEGIN NOW Dividing: for as earth, so he the world END
BEGIN NOW Built on circumfluous waters calm, in wide END
BEGIN NOW Crystalline ocean, and the loud misrule END
BEGIN NOW Of Chaos far removed; lest fierce extremes END
BEGIN NOW Contiguous might distemper the whole frame: END
BEGIN NOW And Heaven he named the Firmament: So even END
BEGIN NOW And morning chorus sung the second day. END
BEGIN NOW The Earth was formed, but in the womb as yet END
BEGIN NOW Of waters, embryon immature involved, END
BEGIN NOW Appeared not: over all the face of Earth END
BEGIN NOW Main ocean flowed, not idle; but, with warm END
BEGIN NOW Prolifick humour softening all her globe, END
BEGIN NOW Fermented the great mother to conceive, END
BEGIN NOW Satiate with genial moisture; when God said, END
BEGIN NOW Be gathered now ye waters under Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Into one place, and let dry land appear. END
BEGIN NOW Immediately the mountains huge appear END
BEGIN NOW Emergent, and their broad bare backs upheave END
BEGIN NOW Into the clouds; their tops ascend the sky: END
BEGIN NOW So high as heaved the tumid hills, so low END
BEGIN NOW Down sunk a hollow bottom broad and deep, END
BEGIN NOW Capacious bed of waters: Thither they END
BEGIN NOW Hasted with glad precipitance, uprolled, END
BEGIN NOW As drops on dust conglobing from the dry: END
BEGIN NOW Part rise in crystal wall, or ridge direct, END
BEGIN NOW For haste; such flight the great command impressed END
BEGIN NOW On the swift floods: As armies at the call END
BEGIN NOW Of trumpet (for of armies thou hast heard) END
BEGIN NOW Troop to their standard; so the watery throng, END
BEGIN NOW Wave rolling after wave, where way they found, END
BEGIN NOW If steep, with torrent rapture, if through plain, END
BEGIN NOW Soft-ebbing; nor withstood them rock or hill; END
BEGIN NOW But they, or under ground, or circuit wide END
BEGIN NOW With serpent errour wandering, found their way, END
BEGIN NOW And on the washy oose deep channels wore; END
BEGIN NOW Easy, ere God had bid the ground be dry, END
BEGIN NOW All but within those banks, where rivers now END
BEGIN NOW Stream, and perpetual draw their humid train. END
BEGIN NOW The dry land, Earth; and the great receptacle END
BEGIN NOW Of congregated waters, he called Seas: END
BEGIN NOW And saw that it was good; and said, Let the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Put forth the verdant grass, herb yielding seed, END
BEGIN NOW And fruit-tree yielding fruit after her kind, END
BEGIN NOW Whose seed is in herself upon the Earth. END
BEGIN NOW He scarce had said, when the bare Earth, till then END
BEGIN NOW Desart and bare, unsightly, unadorned, END
BEGIN NOW Brought forth the tender grass, whose verdure clad END
BEGIN NOW Her universal face with pleasant green; END
BEGIN NOW Then herbs of every leaf, that sudden flowered END
BEGIN NOW Opening their various colours, and made gay END
BEGIN NOW Her bosom, smelling sweet: and, these scarce blown, END
BEGIN NOW Forth flourished thick the clustering vine, forth crept END
BEGIN NOW The swelling gourd, up stood the corny reed END
BEGIN NOW Embattled in her field, and the humble shrub, END
BEGIN NOW And bush with frizzled hair implicit: Last END
BEGIN NOW Rose, as in dance, the stately trees, and spread END
BEGIN NOW Their branches hung with copious fruit, or gemmed END
BEGIN NOW Their blossoms: With high woods the hills were crowned; END
BEGIN NOW With tufts the valleys, and each fountain side; END
BEGIN NOW With borders long the rivers: that Earth now END
BEGIN NOW Seemed like to Heaven, a seat where Gods might dwell, END
BEGIN NOW Or wander with delight, and love to haunt END
BEGIN NOW Her sacred shades: though God had yet not rained END
BEGIN NOW Upon the Earth, and man to till the ground END
BEGIN NOW None was; but from the Earth a dewy mist END
BEGIN NOW Went up, and watered all the ground, and each END
BEGIN NOW Plant of the field; which, ere it was in the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW God made, and every herb, before it grew END
BEGIN NOW On the green stem: God saw that it was good: END
BEGIN NOW So even and morn recorded the third day. END
BEGIN NOW Again the Almighty spake, Let there be lights END
BEGIN NOW High in the expanse of Heaven, to divide END
BEGIN NOW The day from night; and let them be for signs, END
BEGIN NOW For seasons, and for days, and circling years; END
BEGIN NOW And let them be for lights, as I ordain END
BEGIN NOW Their office in the firmament of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW To give light on the Earth; and it was so. END
BEGIN NOW And God made two great lights, great for their use END
BEGIN NOW To Man, the greater to have rule by day, END
BEGIN NOW The less by night, altern; and made the stars, END
BEGIN NOW And set them in the firmament of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW To illuminate the Earth, and rule the day END
BEGIN NOW In their vicissitude, and rule the night, END
BEGIN NOW And light from darkness to divide. God saw, END
BEGIN NOW Surveying his great work, that it was good: END
BEGIN NOW For of celestial bodies first the sun END
BEGIN NOW A mighty sphere he framed, unlightsome first, END
BEGIN NOW Though of ethereal mould: then formed the moon END
BEGIN NOW Globose, and every magnitude of stars, END
BEGIN NOW And sowed with stars the Heaven, thick as a field: END
BEGIN NOW Of light by far the greater part he took, END
BEGIN NOW Transplanted from her cloudy shrine, and placed END
BEGIN NOW In the sun's orb, made porous to receive END
BEGIN NOW And drink the liquid light; firm to retain END
BEGIN NOW Her gathered beams, great palace now of light. END
BEGIN NOW Hither, as to their fountain, other stars END
BEGIN NOW Repairing, in their golden urns draw light, END
BEGIN NOW And hence the morning-planet gilds her horns; END
BEGIN NOW By tincture or reflection they augment END
BEGIN NOW Their small peculiar, though from human sight END
BEGIN NOW So far remote, with diminution seen, END
BEGIN NOW First in his east the glorious lamp was seen, END
BEGIN NOW Regent of day, and all the horizon round END
BEGIN NOW Invested with bright rays, jocund to run END
BEGIN NOW His longitude through Heaven's high road; the gray END
BEGIN NOW Dawn, and the Pleiades, before him danced, END
BEGIN NOW Shedding sweet influence: Less bright the moon, END
BEGIN NOW But opposite in levelled west was set, END
BEGIN NOW His mirrour, with full face borrowing her light END
BEGIN NOW From him; for other light she needed none END
BEGIN NOW In that aspect, and still that distance keeps END
BEGIN NOW Till night; then in the east her turn she shines, END
BEGIN NOW Revolved on Heaven's great axle, and her reign END
BEGIN NOW With thousand lesser lights dividual holds, END
BEGIN NOW With thousand thousand stars, that then appeared END
BEGIN NOW Spangling the hemisphere: Then first adorned END
BEGIN NOW With their bright luminaries that set and rose, END
BEGIN NOW Glad evening and glad morn crowned the fourth day. END
BEGIN NOW And God said, Let the waters generate END
BEGIN NOW Reptile with spawn abundant, living soul: END
BEGIN NOW And let fowl fly above the Earth, with wings END
BEGIN NOW Displayed on the open firmament of Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW And God created the great whales, and each END
BEGIN NOW Soul living, each that crept, which plenteously END
BEGIN NOW The waters generated by their kinds; END
BEGIN NOW And every bird of wing after his kind; END
BEGIN NOW And saw that it was good, and blessed them, saying. END
BEGIN NOW Be fruitful, multiply, and in the seas, END
BEGIN NOW And lakes, and running streams, the waters fill; END
BEGIN NOW And let the fowl be multiplied, on the Earth. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith the sounds and seas, each creek and bay, END
BEGIN NOW With fry innumerable swarm, and shoals END
BEGIN NOW Of fish that with their fins, and shining scales, END
BEGIN NOW Glide under the green wave, in sculls that oft END
BEGIN NOW Bank the mid sea: part single, or with mate, END
BEGIN NOW Graze the sea-weed their pasture, and through groves END
BEGIN NOW Of coral stray; or, sporting with quick glance, END
BEGIN NOW Show to the sun their waved coats dropt with gold; END
BEGIN NOW Or, in their pearly shells at ease, attend END
BEGIN NOW Moist nutriment; or under rocks their food END
BEGIN NOW In jointed armour watch: on smooth the seal END
BEGIN NOW And bended dolphins play: part huge of bulk END
BEGIN NOW Wallowing unwieldy, enormous in their gait, END
BEGIN NOW Tempest the ocean: there leviathan, END
BEGIN NOW Hugest of living creatures, on the deep END
BEGIN NOW Stretched like a promontory sleeps or swims, END
BEGIN NOW And seems a moving land; and at his gills END
BEGIN NOW Draws in, and at his trunk spouts out, a sea. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while the tepid caves, and fens, and shores, END
BEGIN NOW Their brood as numerous hatch, from the egg that soon END
BEGIN NOW Bursting with kindly rupture forth disclosed END
BEGIN NOW Their callow young; but feathered soon and fledge END
BEGIN NOW They summed their pens; and, soaring the air sublime, END
BEGIN NOW With clang despised the ground, under a cloud END
BEGIN NOW In prospect; there the eagle and the stork END
BEGIN NOW On cliffs and cedar tops their eyries build: END
BEGIN NOW Part loosely wing the region, part more wise END
BEGIN NOW In common, ranged in figure, wedge their way, END
BEGIN NOW Intelligent of seasons, and set forth END
BEGIN NOW Their aery caravan, high over seas END
BEGIN NOW Flying, and over lands, with mutual wing END
BEGIN NOW Easing their flight; so steers the prudent crane END
BEGIN NOW Her annual voyage, borne on winds; the air END
BEGIN NOW Floats as they pass, fanned with unnumbered plumes: END
BEGIN NOW From branch to branch the smaller birds with song END
BEGIN NOW Solaced the woods, and spread their painted wings END
BEGIN NOW Till even; nor then the solemn nightingale END
BEGIN NOW Ceased warbling, but all night tun'd her soft lays: END
BEGIN NOW Others, on silver lakes and rivers, bathed END
BEGIN NOW Their downy breast; the swan with arched neck, END
BEGIN NOW Between her white wings mantling proudly, rows END
BEGIN NOW Her state with oary feet; yet oft they quit END
BEGIN NOW The dank, and, rising on stiff pennons, tower END
BEGIN NOW The mid aereal sky: Others on ground END
BEGIN NOW Walked firm; the crested cock whose clarion sounds END
BEGIN NOW The silent hours, and the other whose gay train END
BEGIN NOW Adorns him, coloured with the florid hue END
BEGIN NOW Of rainbows and starry eyes. The waters thus END
BEGIN NOW With fish replenished, and the air with fowl, END
BEGIN NOW Evening and morn solemnized the fifth day. END
BEGIN NOW The sixth, and of creation last, arose END
BEGIN NOW With evening harps and matin; when God said, END
BEGIN NOW Let the Earth bring forth soul living in her kind, END
BEGIN NOW Cattle, and creeping things, and beast of the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Each in their kind. The Earth obeyed, and straight END
BEGIN NOW Opening her fertile womb teemed at a birth END
BEGIN NOW Innumerous living creatures, perfect forms, END
BEGIN NOW Limbed and full grown: Out of the ground up rose, END
BEGIN NOW As from his lair, the wild beast where he wons END
BEGIN NOW In forest wild, in thicket, brake, or den; END
BEGIN NOW Among the trees in pairs they rose, they walked: END
BEGIN NOW The cattle in the fields and meadows green: END
BEGIN NOW Those rare and solitary, these in flocks END
BEGIN NOW Pasturing at once, and in broad herds upsprung. END
BEGIN NOW The grassy clods now calved; now half appeared END
BEGIN NOW The tawny lion, pawing to get free END
BEGIN NOW His hinder parts, then springs as broke from bonds, END
BEGIN NOW And rampant shakes his brinded mane; the ounce, END
BEGIN NOW The libbard, and the tiger, as the mole END
BEGIN NOW Rising, the crumbled earth above them threw END
BEGIN NOW In hillocks: The swift stag from under ground END
BEGIN NOW Bore up his branching head: Scarce from his mould END
BEGIN NOW Behemoth biggest born of earth upheaved END
BEGIN NOW His vastness: Fleeced the flocks and bleating rose, END
BEGIN NOW As plants: Ambiguous between sea and land END
BEGIN NOW The river-horse, and scaly crocodile. END
BEGIN NOW At once came forth whatever creeps the ground, END
BEGIN NOW Insect or worm: those waved their limber fans END
BEGIN NOW For wings, and smallest lineaments exact END
BEGIN NOW In all the liveries decked of summer's pride END
BEGIN NOW With spots of gold and purple, azure and green: END
BEGIN NOW These, as a line, their long dimension drew, END
BEGIN NOW Streaking the ground with sinuous trace; not all END
BEGIN NOW Minims of nature; some of serpent-kind, END
BEGIN NOW Wonderous in length and corpulence, involved END
BEGIN NOW Their snaky folds, and added wings. First crept END
BEGIN NOW The parsimonious emmet, provident END
BEGIN NOW Of future; in small room large heart enclosed; END
BEGIN NOW Pattern of just equality perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Hereafter, joined in her popular tribes END
BEGIN NOW Of commonalty: Swarming next appeared END
BEGIN NOW The female bee, that feeds her husband drone END
BEGIN NOW Deliciously, and builds her waxen cells END
BEGIN NOW With honey stored: The rest are numberless, END
BEGIN NOW And thou their natures knowest, and gavest them names, END
BEGIN NOW Needless to thee repeated; nor unknown END
BEGIN NOW The serpent, subtlest beast of all the field, END
BEGIN NOW Of huge extent sometimes, with brazen eyes END
BEGIN NOW And hairy mane terrifick, though to thee END
BEGIN NOW Not noxious, but obedient at thy call. END
BEGIN NOW Now Heaven in all her glory shone, and rolled END
BEGIN NOW Her motions, as the great first Mover's hand END
BEGIN NOW First wheeled their course: Earth in her rich attire END
BEGIN NOW Consummate lovely smiled; air, water, earth, END
BEGIN NOW By fowl, fish, beast, was flown, was swum, was walked, END
BEGIN NOW Frequent; and of the sixth day yet remained: END
BEGIN NOW There wanted yet the master-work, the end END
BEGIN NOW Of all yet done; a creature, who, not prone END
BEGIN NOW And brute as other creatures, but endued END
BEGIN NOW With sanctity of reason, might erect END
BEGIN NOW His stature, and upright with front serene END
BEGIN NOW Govern the rest, self-knowing; and from thence END
BEGIN NOW Magnanimous to correspond with Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW But grateful to acknowledge whence his good END
BEGIN NOW Descends, thither with heart, and voice, and eyes END
BEGIN NOW Directed in devotion, to adore END
BEGIN NOW And worship God Supreme, who made him chief END
BEGIN NOW Of all his works: therefore the Omnipotent END
BEGIN NOW Eternal Father (for where is not he END
BEGIN NOW Present?) thus to his Son audibly spake. END
BEGIN NOW Let us make now Man in our image, Man END
BEGIN NOW In our similitude, and let them rule END
BEGIN NOW Over the fish and fowl of sea and air, END
BEGIN NOW Beast of the field, and over all the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW And every creeping thing that creeps the ground. END
BEGIN NOW This said, he formed thee, Adam, thee, O Man, END
BEGIN NOW Dust of the ground, and in thy nostrils breathed END
BEGIN NOW The breath of life; in his own image he END
BEGIN NOW Created thee, in the image of God END
BEGIN NOW Express; and thou becamest a living soul. END
BEGIN NOW Male he created thee; but thy consort END
BEGIN NOW Female, for race; then blessed mankind, and said, END
BEGIN NOW Be fruitful, multiply, and fill the Earth; END
BEGIN NOW Subdue it, and throughout dominion hold END
BEGIN NOW Over fish of the sea, and fowl of the air, END
BEGIN NOW And every living thing that moves on the Earth. END
BEGIN NOW Wherever thus created, for no place END
BEGIN NOW Is yet distinct by name, thence, as thou knowest, END
BEGIN NOW He brought thee into this delicious grove, END
BEGIN NOW This garden, planted with the trees of God, END
BEGIN NOW Delectable both to behold and taste; END
BEGIN NOW And freely all their pleasant fruit for food END
BEGIN NOW Gave thee; all sorts are here that all the Earth yields, END
BEGIN NOW Variety without end; but of the tree, END
BEGIN NOW Which, tasted, works knowledge of good and evil, END
BEGIN NOW Thou mayest not; in the day thou eatest, thou diest; END
BEGIN NOW Death is the penalty imposed; beware, END
BEGIN NOW And govern well thy appetite; lest Sin END
BEGIN NOW Surprise thee, and her black attendant Death. END
BEGIN NOW Here finished he, and all that he had made END
BEGIN NOW Viewed, and behold all was entirely good; END
BEGIN NOW So even and morn accomplished the sixth day: END
BEGIN NOW Yet not till the Creator from his work END
BEGIN NOW Desisting, though unwearied, up returned, END
BEGIN NOW Up to the Heaven of Heavens, his high abode; END
BEGIN NOW Thence to behold this new created world, END
BEGIN NOW The addition of his empire, how it showed END
BEGIN NOW In prospect from his throne, how good, how fair, END
BEGIN NOW Answering his great idea. Up he rode END
BEGIN NOW Followed with acclamation, and the sound END
BEGIN NOW Symphonious of ten thousand harps, that tuned END
BEGIN NOW Angelick harmonies: The earth, the air END
BEGIN NOW Resounded, (thou rememberest, for thou heardst,) END
BEGIN NOW The heavens and all the constellations rung, END
BEGIN NOW The planets in their station listening stood, END
BEGIN NOW While the bright pomp ascended jubilant. END
BEGIN NOW Open, ye everlasting gates! they sung, END
BEGIN NOW Open, ye Heavens! your living doors; let in END
BEGIN NOW The great Creator from his work returned END
BEGIN NOW Magnificent, his six days work, a World; END
BEGIN NOW Open, and henceforth oft; for God will deign END
BEGIN NOW To visit oft the dwellings of just men, END
BEGIN NOW Delighted; and with frequent intercourse END
BEGIN NOW Thither will send his winged messengers END
BEGIN NOW On errands of supernal grace. So sung END
BEGIN NOW The glorious train ascending: He through Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW That opened wide her blazing portals, led END
BEGIN NOW To God's eternal house direct the way; END
BEGIN NOW A broad and ample road, whose dust is gold END
BEGIN NOW And pavement stars, as stars to thee appear, END
BEGIN NOW Seen in the galaxy, that milky way, END
BEGIN NOW Which nightly, as a circling zone, thou seest END
BEGIN NOW Powdered with stars. And now on Earth the seventh END
BEGIN NOW Evening arose in Eden, for the sun END
BEGIN NOW Was set, and twilight from the east came on, END
BEGIN NOW Forerunning night; when at the holy mount END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven's high-seated top, the imperial throne END
BEGIN NOW Of Godhead, fixed for ever firm and sure, END
BEGIN NOW The Filial Power arrived, and sat him down END
BEGIN NOW With his great Father; for he also went END
BEGIN NOW Invisible, yet staid, (such privilege END
BEGIN NOW Hath Omnipresence) and the work ordained, END
BEGIN NOW Author and End of all things; and, from work END
BEGIN NOW Now resting, blessed and hallowed the seventh day, END
BEGIN NOW As resting on that day from all his work, END
BEGIN NOW But not in silence holy kept: the harp END
BEGIN NOW Had work and rested not; the solemn pipe, END
BEGIN NOW And dulcimer, all organs of sweet stop, END
BEGIN NOW All sounds on fret by string or golden wire, END
BEGIN NOW Tempered soft tunings, intermixed with voice END
BEGIN NOW Choral or unison: of incense clouds, END
BEGIN NOW Fuming from golden censers, hid the mount. END
BEGIN NOW Creation and the six days acts they sung: END
BEGIN NOW Great are thy works, Jehovah! infinite END
BEGIN NOW Thy power! what thought can measure thee, or tongue END
BEGIN NOW Relate thee! Greater now in thy return END
BEGIN NOW Than from the giant Angels: Thee that day END
BEGIN NOW Thy thunders magnified; but to create END
BEGIN NOW Is greater than created to destroy. END
BEGIN NOW Who can impair thee, Mighty King, or bound END
BEGIN NOW Thy empire! Easily the proud attempt END
BEGIN NOW Of Spirits apostate, and their counsels vain, END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast repelled; while impiously they thought END
BEGIN NOW Thee to diminish, and from thee withdraw END
BEGIN NOW The number of thy worshippers. Who seeks END
BEGIN NOW To lessen thee, against his purpose serves END
BEGIN NOW To manifest the more thy might: his evil END
BEGIN NOW Thou usest, and from thence createst more good. END
BEGIN NOW Witness this new-made world, another Heaven END
BEGIN NOW From Heaven-gate not far, founded in view END
BEGIN NOW On the clear hyaline, the glassy sea; END
BEGIN NOW Of amplitude almost immense, with stars END
BEGIN NOW Numerous, and every star perhaps a world END
BEGIN NOW Of destined habitation; but thou knowest END
BEGIN NOW Their seasons: among these the seat of Men, END
BEGIN NOW Earth, with her nether ocean circumfused, END
BEGIN NOW Their pleasant dwelling-place. Thrice happy Men, END
BEGIN NOW And sons of Men, whom God hath thus advanced! END
BEGIN NOW Created in his image, there to dwell END
BEGIN NOW And worship him; and in reward to rule END
BEGIN NOW Over his works, on earth, in sea, or air, END
BEGIN NOW And multiply a race of worshippers END
BEGIN NOW Holy and just: Thrice happy, if they know END
BEGIN NOW Their happiness, and persevere upright! END
BEGIN NOW So sung they, and the empyrean rung END
BEGIN NOW With halleluiahs: Thus was sabbath kept. END
BEGIN NOW And thy request think now fulfilled, that asked END
BEGIN NOW How first this world and face of things began, END
BEGIN NOW And what before thy memory was done END
BEGIN NOW From the beginning; that posterity, END
BEGIN NOW Informed by thee, might know: If else thou seekest END
BEGIN NOW Aught, not surpassing human measure, say. END
BEGIN NOW The Angel ended, and in Adam's ear END
BEGIN NOW So charming left his voice, that he a while END
BEGIN NOW Thought him still speaking, still stood fixed to hear; END
BEGIN NOW Then, as new waked, thus gratefully replied. END
BEGIN NOW What thanks sufficient, or what recompence END
BEGIN NOW Equal, have I to render thee, divine END
BEGIN NOW Historian, who thus largely hast allayed END
BEGIN NOW The thirst I had of knowledge, and vouchsafed END
BEGIN NOW This friendly condescension to relate END
BEGIN NOW Things, else by me unsearchable; now heard END
BEGIN NOW With wonder, but delight, and, as is due, END
BEGIN NOW With glory attributed to the high END
BEGIN NOW Creator! Something yet of doubt remains, END
BEGIN NOW Which only thy solution can resolve. END
BEGIN NOW When I behold this goodly frame, this world, END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven and Earth consisting; and compute END
BEGIN NOW Their magnitudes; this Earth, a spot, a grain, END
BEGIN NOW An atom, with the firmament compared END
BEGIN NOW And all her numbered stars, that seem to roll END
BEGIN NOW Spaces incomprehensible, (for such END
BEGIN NOW Their distance argues, and their swift return END
BEGIN NOW Diurnal,) merely to officiate light END
BEGIN NOW Round this opacous Earth, this punctual spot, END
BEGIN NOW One day and night; in all her vast survey END
BEGIN NOW Useless besides; reasoning I oft admire, END
BEGIN NOW How Nature wise and frugal could commit END
BEGIN NOW Such disproportions, with superfluous hand END
BEGIN NOW So many nobler bodies to create, END
BEGIN NOW Greater so manifold, to this one use, END
BEGIN NOW For aught appears, and on their orbs impose END
BEGIN NOW Such restless revolution day by day END
BEGIN NOW Repeated; while the sedentary Earth, END
BEGIN NOW That better might with far less compass move, END
BEGIN NOW Served by more noble than herself, attains END
BEGIN NOW Her end without least motion, and receives, END
BEGIN NOW As tribute, such a sumless journey brought END
BEGIN NOW Of incorporeal speed, her warmth and light; END
BEGIN NOW Speed, to describe whose swiftness number fails. END
BEGIN NOW So spake our sire, and by his countenance seemed END
BEGIN NOW Entering on studious thoughts abstruse; which Eve END
BEGIN NOW Perceiving, where she sat retired in sight, END
BEGIN NOW With lowliness majestick from her seat, END
BEGIN NOW And grace that won who saw to wish her stay, END
BEGIN NOW Rose, and went forth among her fruits and flowers, END
BEGIN NOW To visit how they prospered, bud and bloom, END
BEGIN NOW Her nursery; they at her coming sprung, END
BEGIN NOW And, touched by her fair tendance, gladlier grew. END
BEGIN NOW Yet went she not, as not with such discourse END
BEGIN NOW Delighted, or not capable her ear END
BEGIN NOW Of what was high: such pleasure she reserved, END
BEGIN NOW Adam relating, she sole auditress; END
BEGIN NOW Her husband the relater she preferred END
BEGIN NOW Chose rather; he, she knew, would intermix END
BEGIN NOW Grateful digressions, and solve high dispute END
BEGIN NOW With conjugal caresses: from his lip END
BEGIN NOW Not words alone pleased her. O! when meet now END
BEGIN NOW Such pairs, in love and mutual honour joined? END
BEGIN NOW With Goddess-like demeanour forth she went, END
BEGIN NOW Not unattended; for on her, as Queen, END
BEGIN NOW A pomp of winning Graces waited still, END
BEGIN NOW And from about her shot darts of desire END
BEGIN NOW Into all eyes, to wish her still in sight. END
BEGIN NOW And Raphael now, to Adam's doubt proposed, END
BEGIN NOW Benevolent and facile thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW To ask or search, I blame thee not; for Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Is as the book of God before thee set, END
BEGIN NOW Wherein to read his wonderous works, and learn END
BEGIN NOW His seasons, hours, or days, or months, or years: END
BEGIN NOW This to attain, whether Heaven move or Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Imports not, if thou reckon right; the rest END
BEGIN NOW From Man or Angel the great Architect END
BEGIN NOW Did wisely to conceal, and not divulge END
BEGIN NOW His secrets to be scanned by them who ought END
BEGIN NOW Rather admire; or, if they list to try END
BEGIN NOW Conjecture, he his fabrick of the Heavens END
BEGIN NOW Hath left to their disputes, perhaps to move END
BEGIN NOW His laughter at their quaint opinions wide END
BEGIN NOW Hereafter; when they come to model Heaven END
BEGIN NOW And calculate the stars, how they will wield END
BEGIN NOW The mighty frame; how build, unbuild, contrive END
BEGIN NOW To save appearances; how gird the sphere END
BEGIN NOW With centrick and eccentrick scribbled o'er, END
BEGIN NOW Cycle and epicycle, orb in orb: END
BEGIN NOW Already by thy reasoning this I guess, END
BEGIN NOW Who art to lead thy offspring, and supposest END
BEGIN NOW That bodies bright and greater should not serve END
BEGIN NOW The less not bright, nor Heaven such journeys run, END
BEGIN NOW Earth sitting still, when she alone receives END
BEGIN NOW The benefit: Consider first, that great END
BEGIN NOW Or bright infers not excellence: the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Though, in comparison of Heaven, so small, END
BEGIN NOW Nor glistering, may of solid good contain END
BEGIN NOW More plenty than the sun that barren shines; END
BEGIN NOW Whose virtue on itself works no effect, END
BEGIN NOW But in the fruitful Earth; there first received, END
BEGIN NOW His beams, unactive else, their vigour find. END
BEGIN NOW Yet not to Earth are those bright luminaries END
BEGIN NOW Officious; but to thee, Earth's habitant. END
BEGIN NOW And for the Heaven's wide circuit, let it speak END
BEGIN NOW The Maker's high magnificence, who built END
BEGIN NOW So spacious, and his line stretched out so far; END
BEGIN NOW That Man may know he dwells not in his own; END
BEGIN NOW An edifice too large for him to fill, END
BEGIN NOW Lodged in a small partition; and the rest END
BEGIN NOW Ordained for uses to his Lord best known. END
BEGIN NOW The swiftness of those circles attribute, END
BEGIN NOW Though numberless, to his Omnipotence, END
BEGIN NOW That to corporeal substances could add END
BEGIN NOW Speed almost spiritual: Me thou thinkest not slow, END
BEGIN NOW Who since the morning-hour set out from Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Where God resides, and ere mid-day arrived END
BEGIN NOW In Eden; distance inexpressible END
BEGIN NOW By numbers that have name. But this I urge, END
BEGIN NOW Admitting motion in the Heavens, to show END
BEGIN NOW Invalid that which thee to doubt it moved; END
BEGIN NOW Not that I so affirm, though so it seem END
BEGIN NOW To thee who hast thy dwelling here on Earth. END
BEGIN NOW God, to remove his ways from human sense, END
BEGIN NOW Placed Heaven from Earth so far, that earthly sight, END
BEGIN NOW If it presume, might err in things too high, END
BEGIN NOW And no advantage gain. What if the sun END
BEGIN NOW Be center to the world; and other stars, END
BEGIN NOW By his attractive virtue and their own END
BEGIN NOW Incited, dance about him various rounds? END
BEGIN NOW Their wandering course now high, now low, then hid, END
BEGIN NOW Progressive, retrograde, or standing still, END
BEGIN NOW In six thou seest; and what if seventh to these END
BEGIN NOW The planet earth, so stedfast though she seem, END
BEGIN NOW Insensibly three different motions move? END
BEGIN NOW Which else to several spheres thou must ascribe, END
BEGIN NOW Moved contrary with thwart obliquities; END
BEGIN NOW Or save the sun his labour, and that swift END
BEGIN NOW Nocturnal and diurnal rhomb supposed, END
BEGIN NOW Invisible else above all stars, the wheel END
BEGIN NOW Of day and night; which needs not thy belief, END
BEGIN NOW If earth, industrious of herself, fetch day END
BEGIN NOW Travelling east, and with her part averse END
BEGIN NOW From the sun's beam meet night, her other part END
BEGIN NOW Still luminous by his ray. What if that light, END
BEGIN NOW Sent from her through the wide transpicuous air, END
BEGIN NOW To the terrestrial moon be as a star, END
BEGIN NOW Enlightening her by day, as she by night END
BEGIN NOW This earth? reciprocal, if land be there, END
BEGIN NOW Fields and inhabitants: Her spots thou seest END
BEGIN NOW As clouds, and clouds may rain, and rain produce END
BEGIN NOW Fruits in her softened soil for some to eat END
BEGIN NOW Allotted there; and other suns perhaps, END
BEGIN NOW With their attendant moons, thou wilt descry, END
BEGIN NOW Communicating male and female light; END
BEGIN NOW Which two great sexes animate the world, END
BEGIN NOW Stored in each orb perhaps with some that live. END
BEGIN NOW For such vast room in Nature unpossessed END
BEGIN NOW By living soul, desart and desolate, END
BEGIN NOW Only to shine, yet scarce to contribute END
BEGIN NOW Each orb a glimpse of light, conveyed so far END
BEGIN NOW Down to this habitable, which returns END
BEGIN NOW Light back to them, is obvious to dispute. END
BEGIN NOW But whether thus these things, or whether not; END
BEGIN NOW But whether the sun, predominant in Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Rise on the earth; or earth rise on the sun; END
BEGIN NOW He from the east his flaming road begin; END
BEGIN NOW Or she from west her silent course advance, END
BEGIN NOW With inoffensive pace that spinning sleeps END
BEGIN NOW On her soft axle, while she paces even, END
BEGIN NOW And bears thee soft with the smooth hair along; END
BEGIN NOW Sollicit not thy thoughts with matters hid; END
BEGIN NOW Leave them to God above; him serve, and fear! END
BEGIN NOW Of other creatures, as him pleases best, END
BEGIN NOW Wherever placed, let him dispose; joy thou END
BEGIN NOW In what he gives to thee, this Paradise END
BEGIN NOW And thy fair Eve; Heaven is for thee too high END
BEGIN NOW To know what passes there; be lowly wise: END
BEGIN NOW Think only what concerns thee, and thy being; END
BEGIN NOW Dream not of other worlds, what creatures there END
BEGIN NOW Live, in what state, condition, or degree; END
BEGIN NOW Contented that thus far hath been revealed END
BEGIN NOW Not of Earth only, but of highest Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Adam, cleared of doubt, replied. END
BEGIN NOW How fully hast thou satisfied me, pure END
BEGIN NOW Intelligence of Heaven, Angel serene! END
BEGIN NOW And, freed from intricacies, taught to live END
BEGIN NOW The easiest way; nor with perplexing thoughts END
BEGIN NOW To interrupt the sweet of life, from which END
BEGIN NOW God hath bid dwell far off all anxious cares, END
BEGIN NOW And not molest us; unless we ourselves END
BEGIN NOW Seek them with wandering thoughts, and notions vain. END
BEGIN NOW But apt the mind or fancy is to rove END
BEGIN NOW Unchecked, and of her roving is no end; END
BEGIN NOW Till warned, or by experience taught, she learn, END
BEGIN NOW That, not to know at large of things remote END
BEGIN NOW From use, obscure and subtle; but, to know END
BEGIN NOW That which before us lies in daily life, END
BEGIN NOW Is the prime wisdom: What is more, is fume, END
BEGIN NOW Or emptiness, or fond impertinence: END
BEGIN NOW And renders us, in things that most concern, END
BEGIN NOW Unpractised, unprepared, and still to seek. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore from this high pitch let us descend END
BEGIN NOW A lower flight, and speak of things at hand END
BEGIN NOW Useful; whence, haply, mention may arise END
BEGIN NOW Of something not unseasonable to ask, END
BEGIN NOW By sufferance, and thy wonted favour, deigned. END
BEGIN NOW Thee I have heard relating what was done END
BEGIN NOW Ere my remembrance: now, hear me relate END
BEGIN NOW My story, which perhaps thou hast not heard; END
BEGIN NOW And day is not yet spent; till then thou seest END
BEGIN NOW How subtly to detain thee I devise; END
BEGIN NOW Inviting thee to hear while I relate; END
BEGIN NOW Fond! were it not in hope of thy reply: END
BEGIN NOW For, while I sit with thee, I seem in Heaven; END
BEGIN NOW And sweeter thy discourse is to my ear END
BEGIN NOW Than fruits of palm-tree pleasantest to thirst END
BEGIN NOW And hunger both, from labour, at the hour END
BEGIN NOW Of sweet repast; they satiate, and soon fill, END
BEGIN NOW Though pleasant; but thy words, with grace divine END
BEGIN NOW Imbued, bring to their sweetness no satiety. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Raphael answered heavenly meek. END
BEGIN NOW Nor are thy lips ungraceful, Sire of men, END
BEGIN NOW Nor tongue ineloquent; for God on thee END
BEGIN NOW Abundantly his gifts hath also poured END
BEGIN NOW Inward and outward both, his image fair: END
BEGIN NOW Speaking, or mute, all comeliness and grace END
BEGIN NOW Attends thee; and each word, each motion, forms; END
BEGIN NOW Nor less think we in Heaven of thee on Earth END
BEGIN NOW Than of our fellow-servant, and inquire END
BEGIN NOW Gladly into the ways of God with Man: END
BEGIN NOW For God, we see, hath honoured thee, and set END
BEGIN NOW On Man his equal love: Say therefore on; END
BEGIN NOW For I that day was absent, as befel, END
BEGIN NOW Bound on a voyage uncouth and obscure, END
BEGIN NOW Far on excursion toward the gates of Hell; END
BEGIN NOW Squared in full legion (such command we had) END
BEGIN NOW To see that none thence issued forth a spy, END
BEGIN NOW Or enemy, while God was in his work; END
BEGIN NOW Lest he, incensed at such eruption bold, END
BEGIN NOW Destruction with creation might have mixed. END
BEGIN NOW Not that they durst without his leave attempt; END
BEGIN NOW But us he sends upon his high behests END
BEGIN NOW For state, as Sovran King; and to inure END
BEGIN NOW Our prompt obedience. Fast we found, fast shut, END
BEGIN NOW The dismal gates, and barricadoed strong; END
BEGIN NOW But long ere our approaching heard within END
BEGIN NOW Noise, other than the sound of dance or song, END
BEGIN NOW Torment, and loud lament, and furious rage. END
BEGIN NOW Glad we returned up to the coasts of light END
BEGIN NOW Ere sabbath-evening: so we had in charge. END
BEGIN NOW But thy relation now; for I attend, END
BEGIN NOW Pleased with thy words no less than thou with mine. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Godlike Power, and thus our Sire. END
BEGIN NOW For Man to tell how human life began END
BEGIN NOW Is hard; for who himself beginning knew END
BEGIN NOW Desire with thee still longer to converse END
BEGIN NOW Induced me. As new waked from soundest sleep, END
BEGIN NOW Soft on the flowery herb I found me laid, END
BEGIN NOW In balmy sweat; which with his beams the sun END
BEGIN NOW Soon dried, and on the reeking moisture fed. END
BEGIN NOW Straight toward Heaven my wondering eyes I turned, END
BEGIN NOW And gazed a while the ample sky; till, raised END
BEGIN NOW By quick instinctive motion, up I sprung, END
BEGIN NOW As thitherward endeavouring, and upright END
BEGIN NOW Stood on my feet: about me round I saw END
BEGIN NOW Hill, dale, and shady woods, and sunny plains, END
BEGIN NOW And liquid lapse of murmuring streams; by these, END
BEGIN NOW Creatures that lived and moved, and walked, or flew; END
BEGIN NOW Birds on the branches warbling; all things smiled; END
BEGIN NOW With fragrance and with joy my heart o'erflowed. END
BEGIN NOW Myself I then perused, and limb by limb END
BEGIN NOW Surveyed, and sometimes went, and sometimes ran END
BEGIN NOW With supple joints, as lively vigour led: END
BEGIN NOW But who I was, or where, or from what cause, END
BEGIN NOW Knew not; to speak I tried, and forthwith spake; END
BEGIN NOW My tongue obeyed, and readily could name END
BEGIN NOW Whate'er I saw. Thou Sun, said I, fair light, END
BEGIN NOW And thou enlightened Earth, so fresh and gay, END
BEGIN NOW And ye that live and move, fair Creatures, tell, END
BEGIN NOW Tell, if ye saw, how I came thus, how here?-- END
BEGIN NOW Not of myself;--by some great Maker then, END
BEGIN NOW In goodness and in power pre-eminent: END
BEGIN NOW Tell me, how may I know him, how adore, END
BEGIN NOW From whom I have that thus I move and live, END
BEGIN NOW And feel that I am happier than I know.-- END
BEGIN NOW While thus I called, and strayed I knew not whither, END
BEGIN NOW From where I first drew air, and first beheld END
BEGIN NOW This happy light; when, answer none returned, END
BEGIN NOW On a green shady bank, profuse of flowers, END
BEGIN NOW Pensive I sat me down: There gentle sleep END
BEGIN NOW First found me, and with soft oppression seised END
BEGIN NOW My droused sense, untroubled, though I thought END
BEGIN NOW I then was passing to my former state END
BEGIN NOW Insensible, and forthwith to dissolve: END
BEGIN NOW When suddenly stood at my head a dream, END
BEGIN NOW Whose inward apparition gently moved END
BEGIN NOW My fancy to believe I yet had being, END
BEGIN NOW And lived: One came, methought, of shape divine, END
BEGIN NOW And said, "Thy mansion wants thee, Adam; rise, END
BEGIN NOW First Man, of men innumerable ordained END
BEGIN NOW First Father! called by thee, I come thy guide END
BEGIN NOW To the garden of bliss, thy seat prepared. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, by the hand he took me raised, END
BEGIN NOW And over fields and waters, as in air END
BEGIN NOW Smooth-sliding without step, last led me up END
BEGIN NOW A woody mountain; whose high top was plain, END
BEGIN NOW A circuit wide, enclosed, with goodliest trees END
BEGIN NOW Planted, with walks, and bowers; that what I saw END
BEGIN NOW Of Earth before scarce pleasant seemed. Each tree, END
BEGIN NOW Loaden with fairest fruit that hung to the eye END
BEGIN NOW Tempting, stirred in me sudden appetite END
BEGIN NOW To pluck and eat; whereat I waked, and found END
BEGIN NOW Before mine eyes all real, as the dream END
BEGIN NOW Had lively shadowed: Here had new begun END
BEGIN NOW My wandering, had not he, who was my guide END
BEGIN NOW Up hither, from among the trees appeared, END
BEGIN NOW Presence Divine. Rejoicing, but with awe, END
BEGIN NOW In adoration at his feet I fell END
BEGIN NOW Submiss: He reared me, and "Whom thou soughtest I am, END
BEGIN NOW Said mildly, "Author of all this thou seest END
BEGIN NOW Above, or round about thee, or beneath. END
BEGIN NOW This Paradise I give thee, count it thine END
BEGIN NOW To till and keep, and of the fruit to eat: END
BEGIN NOW Of every tree that in the garden grows END
BEGIN NOW Eat freely with glad heart; fear here no dearth: END
BEGIN NOW But of the tree whose operation brings END
BEGIN NOW Knowledge of good and ill, which I have set END
BEGIN NOW The pledge of thy obedience and thy faith, END
BEGIN NOW Amid the garden by the tree of life, END
BEGIN NOW Remember what I warn thee, shun to taste, END
BEGIN NOW And shun the bitter consequence: for know, END
BEGIN NOW The day thou eatest thereof, my sole command END
BEGIN NOW Transgressed, inevitably thou shalt die, END
BEGIN NOW From that day mortal; and this happy state END
BEGIN NOW Shalt lose, expelled from hence into a world END
BEGIN NOW Of woe and sorrow." Sternly he pronounced END
BEGIN NOW The rigid interdiction, which resounds END
BEGIN NOW Yet dreadful in mine ear, though in my choice END
BEGIN NOW Not to incur; but soon his clear aspect END
BEGIN NOW Returned, and gracious purpose thus renewed. END
BEGIN NOW Not only these fair bounds, but all the Earth END
BEGIN NOW To thee and to thy race I give; as lords END
BEGIN NOW Possess it, and all things that therein live, END
BEGIN NOW Or live in sea, or air; beast, fish, and fowl. END
BEGIN NOW In sign whereof, each bird and beast behold END
BEGIN NOW After their kinds; I bring them to receive END
BEGIN NOW From thee their names, and pay thee fealty END
BEGIN NOW With low subjection; understand the same END
BEGIN NOW Of fish within their watery residence, END
BEGIN NOW Not hither summoned, since they cannot change END
BEGIN NOW Their element, to draw the thinner air. END
BEGIN NOW As thus he spake, each bird and beast behold END
BEGIN NOW Approaching two and two; these cowering low END
BEGIN NOW With blandishment; each bird stooped on his wing. END
BEGIN NOW I named them, as they passed, and understood END
BEGIN NOW Their nature, with such knowledge God endued END
BEGIN NOW My sudden apprehension: But in these END
BEGIN NOW I found not what methought I wanted still; END
BEGIN NOW And to the heavenly Vision thus presumed. END
BEGIN NOW O, by what name, for thou above all these, END
BEGIN NOW Above mankind, or aught than mankind higher, END
BEGIN NOW Surpassest far my naming; how may I END
BEGIN NOW Adore thee, Author of this universe, END
BEGIN NOW And all this good to man? for whose well being END
BEGIN NOW So amply, and with hands so liberal, END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast provided all things: But with me END
BEGIN NOW I see not who partakes. In solitude END
BEGIN NOW What happiness, who can enjoy alone, END
BEGIN NOW Or, all enjoying, what contentment find? END
BEGIN NOW Thus I presumptuous; and the Vision bright, END
BEGIN NOW As with a smile more brightened, thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW What callest thou solitude? Is not the Earth END
BEGIN NOW With various living creatures, and the air END
BEGIN NOW Replenished, and all these at thy command END
BEGIN NOW To come and play before thee? Knowest thou not END
BEGIN NOW Their language and their ways? They also know, END
BEGIN NOW And reason not contemptibly: With these END
BEGIN NOW Find pastime, and bear rule; thy realm is large. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Universal Lord, and seemed END
BEGIN NOW So ordering: I, with leave of speech implored, END
BEGIN NOW And humble deprecation, thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW Let not my words offend thee, Heavenly Power; END
BEGIN NOW My Maker, be propitious while I speak. END
BEGIN NOW Hast thou not made me here thy substitute, END
BEGIN NOW And these inferiour far beneath me set? END
BEGIN NOW Among unequals what society END
BEGIN NOW Can sort, what harmony, or true delight? END
BEGIN NOW Which must be mutual, in proportion due END
BEGIN NOW Given and received; but, in disparity END
BEGIN NOW The one intense, the other still remiss, END
BEGIN NOW Cannot well suit with either, but soon prove END
BEGIN NOW Tedious alike: Of fellowship I speak END
BEGIN NOW Such as I seek, fit to participate END
BEGIN NOW All rational delight: wherein the brute END
BEGIN NOW Cannot be human consort: They rejoice END
BEGIN NOW Each with their kind, lion with lioness; END
BEGIN NOW So fitly them in pairs thou hast combined: END
BEGIN NOW Much less can bird with beast, or fish with fowl END
BEGIN NOW So well converse, nor with the ox the ape; END
BEGIN NOW Worse then can man with beast, and least of all. END
BEGIN NOW Whereto the Almighty answered, not displeased. END
BEGIN NOW A nice and subtle happiness, I see, END
BEGIN NOW Thou to thyself proposest, in the choice END
BEGIN NOW Of thy associates, Adam! and wilt taste END
BEGIN NOW No pleasure, though in pleasure, solitary. END
BEGIN NOW What thinkest thou then of me, and this my state? END
BEGIN NOW Seem I to thee sufficiently possessed END
BEGIN NOW Of happiness, or not? who am alone END
BEGIN NOW From all eternity; for none I know END
BEGIN NOW Second to me or like, equal much less. END
BEGIN NOW How have I then with whom to hold converse, END
BEGIN NOW Save with the creatures which I made, and those END
BEGIN NOW To me inferiour, infinite descents END
BEGIN NOW Beneath what other creatures are to thee? END
BEGIN NOW He ceased; I lowly answered. To attain END
BEGIN NOW The highth and depth of thy eternal ways END
BEGIN NOW All human thoughts come short, Supreme of things! END
BEGIN NOW Thou in thyself art perfect, and in thee END
BEGIN NOW Is no deficience found: Not so is Man, END
BEGIN NOW But in degree; the cause of his desire END
BEGIN NOW By conversation with his like to help END
BEGIN NOW Or solace his defects. No need that thou END
BEGIN NOW Shouldst propagate, already Infinite; END
BEGIN NOW And through all numbers absolute, though One: END
BEGIN NOW But Man by number is to manifest END
BEGIN NOW His single imperfection, and beget END
BEGIN NOW Like of his like, his image multiplied, END
BEGIN NOW In unity defective; which requires END
BEGIN NOW Collateral love, and dearest amity. END
BEGIN NOW Thou in thy secresy although alone, END
BEGIN NOW Best with thyself accompanied, seekest not END
BEGIN NOW Social communication; yet, so pleased, END
BEGIN NOW Canst raise thy creature to what highth thou wilt END
BEGIN NOW Of union or communion, deified: END
BEGIN NOW I, by conversing, cannot these erect END
BEGIN NOW From prone; nor in their ways complacence find. END
BEGIN NOW Thus I emboldened spake, and freedom used END
BEGIN NOW Permissive, and acceptance found; which gained END
BEGIN NOW This answer from the gracious Voice Divine. END
BEGIN NOW Thus far to try thee, Adam, I was pleased; END
BEGIN NOW And find thee knowing, not of beasts alone, END
BEGIN NOW Which thou hast rightly named, but of thyself; END
BEGIN NOW Expressing well the spirit within thee free, END
BEGIN NOW My image, not imparted to the brute; END
BEGIN NOW Whose fellowship therefore unmeet for thee END
BEGIN NOW Good reason was thou freely shouldst dislike; END
BEGIN NOW And be so minded still: I, ere thou spakest, END
BEGIN NOW Knew it not good for Man to be alone; END
BEGIN NOW And no such company as then thou sawest END
BEGIN NOW Intended thee; for trial only brought, END
BEGIN NOW To see how thou couldest judge of fit and meet: END
BEGIN NOW What next I bring shall please thee, be assured, END
BEGIN NOW Thy likeness, thy fit help, thy other self, END
BEGIN NOW Thy wish exactly to thy heart's desire. END
BEGIN NOW He ended, or I heard no more; for now END
BEGIN NOW My earthly by his heavenly overpowered, END
BEGIN NOW Which it had long stood under, strained to the highth END
BEGIN NOW In that celestial colloquy sublime, END
BEGIN NOW As with an object that excels the sense END
BEGIN NOW Dazzled and spent, sunk down; and sought repair END
BEGIN NOW Of sleep, which instantly fell on me, called END
BEGIN NOW By Nature as in aid, and closed mine eyes. END
BEGIN NOW Mine eyes he closed, but open left the cell END
BEGIN NOW Of fancy, my internal sight; by which, END
BEGIN NOW Abstract as in a trance, methought I saw, END
BEGIN NOW Though sleeping, where I lay, and saw the shape END
BEGIN NOW Still glorious before whom awake I stood: END
BEGIN NOW Who stooping opened my left side, and took END
BEGIN NOW From thence a rib, with cordial spirits warm, END
BEGIN NOW And life-blood streaming fresh; wide was the wound, END
BEGIN NOW But suddenly with flesh filled up and healed: END
BEGIN NOW The rib he formed and fashioned with his hands; END
BEGIN NOW Under his forming hands a creature grew, END
BEGIN NOW Man-like, but different sex; so lovely fair, END
BEGIN NOW That what seemed fair in all the world, seemed now END
BEGIN NOW Mean, or in her summed up, in her contained END
BEGIN NOW And in her looks; which from that time infused END
BEGIN NOW Sweetness into my heart, unfelt before, END
BEGIN NOW And into all things from her air inspired END
BEGIN NOW The spirit of love and amorous delight. END
BEGIN NOW She disappeared, and left me dark; I waked END
BEGIN NOW To find her, or for ever to deplore END
BEGIN NOW Her loss, and other pleasures all abjure: END
BEGIN NOW When out of hope, behold her, not far off, END
BEGIN NOW Such as I saw her in my dream, adorned END
BEGIN NOW With what all Earth or Heaven could bestow END
BEGIN NOW To make her amiable: On she came, END
BEGIN NOW Led by her heavenly Maker, though unseen, END
BEGIN NOW And guided by his voice; nor uninformed END
BEGIN NOW Of nuptial sanctity, and marriage rites: END
BEGIN NOW Grace was in all her steps, Heaven in her eye, END
BEGIN NOW In every gesture dignity and love. END
BEGIN NOW I, overjoyed, could not forbear aloud. END
BEGIN NOW This turn hath made amends; thou hast fulfilled END
BEGIN NOW Thy words, Creator bounteous and benign, END
BEGIN NOW Giver of all things fair! but fairest this END
BEGIN NOW Of all thy gifts! nor enviest. I now see END
BEGIN NOW Bone of my bone, flesh of my flesh, myself END
BEGIN NOW Before me: Woman is her name; of Man END
BEGIN NOW Extracted: for this cause he shall forego END
BEGIN NOW Father and mother, and to his wife adhere; END
BEGIN NOW And they shall be one flesh, one heart, one soul. END
BEGIN NOW She heard me thus; and though divinely brought, END
BEGIN NOW Yet innocence, and virgin modesty, END
BEGIN NOW Her virtue, and the conscience of her worth, END
BEGIN NOW That would be wooed, and not unsought be won, END
BEGIN NOW Not obvious, not obtrusive, but, retired, END
BEGIN NOW The more desirable; or, to say all, END
BEGIN NOW Nature herself, though pure of sinful thought, END
BEGIN NOW Wrought in her so, that, seeing me, she turned: END
BEGIN NOW I followed her; she what was honour knew, END
BEGIN NOW And with obsequious majesty approved END
BEGIN NOW My pleaded reason. To the nuptial bower END
BEGIN NOW I led her blushing like the morn: All Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW And happy constellations, on that hour END
BEGIN NOW Shed their selectest influence; the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Gave sign of gratulation, and each hill; END
BEGIN NOW Joyous the birds; fresh gales and gentle airs END
BEGIN NOW Whispered it to the woods, and from their wings END
BEGIN NOW Flung rose, flung odours from the spicy shrub, END
BEGIN NOW Disporting, till the amorous bird of night END
BEGIN NOW Sung spousal, and bid haste the evening-star END
BEGIN NOW On his hill top, to light the bridal lamp. END
BEGIN NOW Thus have I told thee all my state, and brought END
BEGIN NOW My story to the sum of earthly bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Which I enjoy; and must confess to find END
BEGIN NOW In all things else delight indeed, but such END
BEGIN NOW As, used or not, works in the mind no change, END
BEGIN NOW Nor vehement desire; these delicacies END
BEGIN NOW I mean of taste, sight, smell, herbs, fruits, and flowers, END
BEGIN NOW Walks, and the melody of birds: but here END
BEGIN NOW Far otherwise, transported I behold, END
BEGIN NOW Transported touch; here passion first I felt, END
BEGIN NOW Commotion strange! in all enjoyments else END
BEGIN NOW Superiour and unmoved; here only weak END
BEGIN NOW Against the charm of Beauty's powerful glance. END
BEGIN NOW Or Nature failed in me, and left some part END
BEGIN NOW Not proof enough such object to sustain; END
BEGIN NOW Or, from my side subducting, took perhaps END
BEGIN NOW More than enough; at least on her bestowed END
BEGIN NOW Too much of ornament, in outward show END
BEGIN NOW Elaborate, of inward less exact. END
BEGIN NOW For well I understand in the prime end END
BEGIN NOW Of Nature her the inferiour, in the mind END
BEGIN NOW And inward faculties, which most excel; END
BEGIN NOW In outward also her resembling less END
BEGIN NOW His image who made both, and less expressing END
BEGIN NOW The character of that dominion given END
BEGIN NOW O'er other creatures: Yet when I approach END
BEGIN NOW Her loveliness, so absolute she seems END
BEGIN NOW And in herself complete, so well to know END
BEGIN NOW Her own, that what she wills to do or say, END
BEGIN NOW Seems wisest, virtuousest, discreetest, best: END
BEGIN NOW All higher knowledge in her presence falls END
BEGIN NOW Degraded; Wisdom in discourse with her END
BEGIN NOW Loses discountenanced, and like Folly shows; END
BEGIN NOW Authority and Reason on her wait, END
BEGIN NOW As one intended first, not after made END
BEGIN NOW Occasionally; and, to consummate all, END
BEGIN NOW Greatness of mind and Nobleness their seat END
BEGIN NOW Build in her loveliest, and create an awe END
BEGIN NOW About her, as a guard angelick placed. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Angel with contracted brow. END
BEGIN NOW Accuse not Nature, she hath done her part; END
BEGIN NOW Do thou but thine; and be not diffident END
BEGIN NOW Of Wisdom; she deserts thee not, if thou END
BEGIN NOW Dismiss not her, when most thou needest her nigh, END
BEGIN NOW By attributing overmuch to things END
BEGIN NOW Less excellent, as thou thyself perceivest. END
BEGIN NOW For, what admirest thou, what transports thee so, END
BEGIN NOW An outside? fair, no doubt, and worthy well END
BEGIN NOW Thy cherishing, thy honouring, and thy love; END
BEGIN NOW Not thy subjection: Weigh with her thyself; END
BEGIN NOW Then value: Oft-times nothing profits more END
BEGIN NOW Than self-esteem, grounded on just and right END
BEGIN NOW Well managed; of that skill the more thou knowest, END
BEGIN NOW The more she will acknowledge thee her head, END
BEGIN NOW And to realities yield all her shows: END
BEGIN NOW Made so adorn for thy delight the more, END
BEGIN NOW So awful, that with honour thou mayest love END
BEGIN NOW Thy mate, who sees when thou art seen least wise. END
BEGIN NOW But if the sense of touch, whereby mankind END
BEGIN NOW Is propagated, seem such dear delight END
BEGIN NOW Beyond all other; think the same vouchsafed END
BEGIN NOW To cattle and each beast; which would not be END
BEGIN NOW To them made common and divulged, if aught END
BEGIN NOW Therein enjoyed were worthy to subdue END
BEGIN NOW The soul of man, or passion in him move. END
BEGIN NOW What higher in her society thou findest END
BEGIN NOW Attractive, human, rational, love still; END
BEGIN NOW In loving thou dost well, in passion not, END
BEGIN NOW Wherein true love consists not: Love refines END
BEGIN NOW The thoughts, and heart enlarges; hath his seat END
BEGIN NOW In reason, and is judicious; is the scale END
BEGIN NOW By which to heavenly love thou mayest ascend, END
BEGIN NOW Not sunk in carnal pleasure; for which cause, END
BEGIN NOW Among the beasts no mate for thee was found. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus, half abashed, Adam replied. END
BEGIN NOW Neither her outside formed so fair, nor aught END
BEGIN NOW In procreation common to all kinds, END
BEGIN NOW (Though higher of the genial bed by far, END
BEGIN NOW And with mysterious reverence I deem,) END
BEGIN NOW So much delights me, as those graceful acts, END
BEGIN NOW Those thousand decencies, that daily flow END
BEGIN NOW From all her words and actions mixed with love END
BEGIN NOW And sweet compliance, which declare unfeigned END
BEGIN NOW Union of mind, or in us both one soul; END
BEGIN NOW Harmony to behold in wedded pair END
BEGIN NOW More grateful than harmonious sound to the ear. END
BEGIN NOW Yet these subject not; I to thee disclose END
BEGIN NOW What inward thence I feel, not therefore foiled, END
BEGIN NOW Who meet with various objects, from the sense END
BEGIN NOW Variously representing; yet, still free, END
BEGIN NOW Approve the best, and follow what I approve. END
BEGIN NOW To love, thou blamest me not; for Love, thou sayest, END
BEGIN NOW Leads up to Heaven, is both the way and guide; END
BEGIN NOW Bear with me then, if lawful what I ask: END
BEGIN NOW Love not the heavenly Spirits, and how their love END
BEGIN NOW Express they? by looks only? or do they mix END
BEGIN NOW Irradiance, virtual or immediate touch? END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Angel, with a smile that glowed END
BEGIN NOW Celestial rosy red, Love's proper hue, END
BEGIN NOW Answered. Let it suffice thee that thou knowest END
BEGIN NOW Us happy, and without love no happiness. END
BEGIN NOW Whatever pure thou in the body enjoyest, END
BEGIN NOW (And pure thou wert created) we enjoy END
BEGIN NOW In eminence; and obstacle find none END
BEGIN NOW Of membrane, joint, or limb, exclusive bars; END
BEGIN NOW Easier than air with air, if Spirits embrace, END
BEGIN NOW Total they mix, union of pure with pure END
BEGIN NOW Desiring, nor restrained conveyance need, END
BEGIN NOW As flesh to mix with flesh, or soul with soul. END
BEGIN NOW But I can now no more; the parting sun END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the Earth's green Cape and verdant Isles END
BEGIN NOW Hesperian sets, my signal to depart. END
BEGIN NOW Be strong, live happy, and love! But, first of all, END
BEGIN NOW Him, whom to love is to obey, and keep END
BEGIN NOW His great command; take heed lest passion sway END
BEGIN NOW Thy judgement to do aught, which else free will END
BEGIN NOW Would not admit: thine, and of all thy sons, END
BEGIN NOW The weal or woe in thee is placed; beware! END
BEGIN NOW I in thy persevering shall rejoice, END
BEGIN NOW And all the Blest: Stand fast; to stand or fall END
BEGIN NOW Free in thine own arbitrement it lies. END
BEGIN NOW Perfect within, no outward aid require; END
BEGIN NOW And all temptation to transgress repel. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, he arose; whom Adam thus END
BEGIN NOW Followed with benediction. Since to part, END
BEGIN NOW Go, heavenly guest, ethereal Messenger, END
BEGIN NOW Sent from whose sovran goodness I adore! END
BEGIN NOW Gentle to me and affable hath been END
BEGIN NOW Thy condescension, and shall be honoured ever END
BEGIN NOW With grateful memory: Thou to mankind END
BEGIN NOW Be good and friendly still, and oft return! END
BEGIN NOW So parted they; the Angel up to Heaven END
BEGIN NOW From the thick shade, and Adam to his bower. END
BEGIN NOW No more of talk where God or Angel guest END
BEGIN NOW With Man, as with his friend, familiar us'd, END
BEGIN NOW To sit indulgent, and with him partake END
BEGIN NOW Rural repast; permitting him the while END
BEGIN NOW Venial discourse unblam'd. I now must change END
BEGIN NOW Those notes to tragick; foul distrust, and breach END
BEGIN NOW Disloyal on the part of Man, revolt, END
BEGIN NOW And disobedience: on the part of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Now alienated, distance and distaste, END
BEGIN NOW Anger and just rebuke, and judgement given, END
BEGIN NOW That brought into this world a world of woe, END
BEGIN NOW Sin and her shadow Death, and Misery END
BEGIN NOW Death's harbinger: Sad task! yet argument END
BEGIN NOW Not less but more heroick than the wrath END
BEGIN NOW Of stern Achilles on his foe pursued END
BEGIN NOW Thrice fugitive about Troy wall; or rage END
BEGIN NOW Of Turnus for Lavinia disespous'd; END
BEGIN NOW Or Neptune's ire, or Juno's, that so long END
BEGIN NOW Perplexed the Greek, and Cytherea's son: END
BEGIN NOW If answerable style I can obtain END
BEGIN NOW Of my celestial patroness, who deigns END
BEGIN NOW Her nightly visitation unimplor'd, END
BEGIN NOW And dictates to me slumbering; or inspires END
BEGIN NOW Easy my unpremeditated verse: END
BEGIN NOW Since first this subject for heroick song END
BEGIN NOW Pleas'd me long choosing, and beginning late; END
BEGIN NOW Not sedulous by nature to indite END
BEGIN NOW Wars, hitherto the only argument END
BEGIN NOW Heroick deem'd chief mastery to dissect END
BEGIN NOW With long and tedious havock fabled knights END
BEGIN NOW In battles feign'd; the better fortitude END
BEGIN NOW Of patience and heroick martyrdom END
BEGIN NOW Unsung; or to describe races and games, END
BEGIN NOW Or tilting furniture, imblazon'd shields, END
BEGIN NOW Impresses quaint, caparisons and steeds, END
BEGIN NOW Bases and tinsel trappings, gorgeous knights END
BEGIN NOW At joust and tournament; then marshall'd feast END
BEGIN NOW Serv'd up in hall with sewers and seneshals; END
BEGIN NOW The skill of artifice or office mean, END
BEGIN NOW Not that which justly gives heroick name END
BEGIN NOW To person, or to poem. Me, of these END
BEGIN NOW Nor skill'd nor studious, higher argument END
BEGIN NOW Remains; sufficient of itself to raise END
BEGIN NOW That name, unless an age too late, or cold END
BEGIN NOW Climate, or years, damp my intended wing END
BEGIN NOW Depress'd; and much they may, if all be mine, END
BEGIN NOW Not hers, who brings it nightly to my ear. END
BEGIN NOW The sun was sunk, and after him the star END
BEGIN NOW Of Hesperus, whose office is to bring END
BEGIN NOW Twilight upon the earth, short arbiter END
BEGIN NOW 'Twixt day and night, and now from end to end END
BEGIN NOW Night's hemisphere had veil'd the horizon round: END
BEGIN NOW When satan, who late fled before the threats END
BEGIN NOW Of Gabriel out of Eden, now improv'd END
BEGIN NOW In meditated fraud and malice, bent END
BEGIN NOW On Man's destruction, maugre what might hap END
BEGIN NOW Of heavier on himself, fearless returned END
BEGIN NOW By night he fled, and at midnight returned END
BEGIN NOW From compassing the earth; cautious of day, END
BEGIN NOW Since Uriel, regent of the sun, descried END
BEGIN NOW His entrance, and foreworned the Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW That kept their watch; thence full of anguish driven, END
BEGIN NOW The space of seven continued nights he rode END
BEGIN NOW With darkness; thrice the equinoctial line END
BEGIN NOW He circled; four times crossed the car of night END
BEGIN NOW From pole to pole, traversing each colure; END
BEGIN NOW On the eighth returned; and, on the coast averse END
BEGIN NOW From entrance or Cherubick watch, by stealth END
BEGIN NOW Found unsuspected way. There was a place, END
BEGIN NOW Now not, though sin, not time, first wrought the change, END
BEGIN NOW Where Tigris, at the foot of Paradise, END
BEGIN NOW Into a gulf shot under ground, till part END
BEGIN NOW Rose up a fountain by the tree of life: END
BEGIN NOW In with the river sunk, and with it rose END
BEGIN NOW Satan, involved in rising mist; then sought END
BEGIN NOW Where to lie hid; sea he had searched, and land, END
BEGIN NOW From Eden over Pontus and the pool END
BEGIN NOW Maeotis, up beyond the river Ob; END
BEGIN NOW Downward as far antarctick; and in length, END
BEGIN NOW West from Orontes to the ocean barred END
BEGIN NOW At Darien; thence to the land where flows END
BEGIN NOW Ganges and Indus: Thus the orb he roamed END
BEGIN NOW With narrow search; and with inspection deep END
BEGIN NOW Considered every creature, which of all END
BEGIN NOW Most opportune might serve his wiles; and found END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent subtlest beast of all the field. END
BEGIN NOW Him after long debate, irresolute END
BEGIN NOW Of thoughts revolved, his final sentence chose END
BEGIN NOW Fit vessel, fittest imp of fraud, in whom END
BEGIN NOW To enter, and his dark suggestions hide END
BEGIN NOW From sharpest sight: for, in the wily snake END
BEGIN NOW Whatever sleights, none would suspicious mark, END
BEGIN NOW As from his wit and native subtlety END
BEGIN NOW Proceeding; which, in other beasts observed, END
BEGIN NOW Doubt might beget of diabolick power END
BEGIN NOW Active within, beyond the sense of brute. END
BEGIN NOW Thus he resolved, but first from inward grief END
BEGIN NOW His bursting passion into plaints thus poured. END
BEGIN NOW More justly, seat worthier of Gods, as built END
BEGIN NOW With second thoughts, reforming what was old! END
BEGIN NOW O Earth, how like to Heaven, if not preferred END
BEGIN NOW For what God, after better, worse would build? END
BEGIN NOW Terrestrial Heaven, danced round by other Heavens END
BEGIN NOW That shine, yet bear their bright officious lamps, END
BEGIN NOW Light above light, for thee alone, as seems, END
BEGIN NOW In thee concentring all their precious beams END
BEGIN NOW Of sacred influence! As God in Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Is center, yet extends to all; so thou, END
BEGIN NOW Centring, receivest from all those orbs: in thee, END
BEGIN NOW Not in themselves, all their known virtue appears END
BEGIN NOW Productive in herb, plant, and nobler birth END
BEGIN NOW Of creatures animate with gradual life END
BEGIN NOW Of growth, sense, reason, all summed up in Man. END
BEGIN NOW With what delight could I have walked thee round, END
BEGIN NOW If I could joy in aught, sweet interchange END
BEGIN NOW Of hill, and valley, rivers, woods, and plains, END
BEGIN NOW Now land, now sea and shores with forest crowned, END
BEGIN NOW Rocks, dens, and caves! But I in none of these END
BEGIN NOW Find place or refuge; and the more I see END
BEGIN NOW Pleasures about me, so much more I feel END
BEGIN NOW Torment within me, as from the hateful siege END
BEGIN NOW Of contraries: all good to me becomes END
BEGIN NOW Bane, and in Heaven much worse would be my state. END
BEGIN NOW But neither here seek I, no nor in Heaven END
BEGIN NOW To dwell, unless by mastering Heaven's Supreme; END
BEGIN NOW Nor hope to be myself less miserable END
BEGIN NOW By what I seek, but others to make such END
BEGIN NOW As I, though thereby worse to me redound: END
BEGIN NOW For only in destroying I find ease END
BEGIN NOW To my relentless thoughts; and, him destroyed, END
BEGIN NOW Or won to what may work his utter loss, END
BEGIN NOW For whom all this was made, all this will soon END
BEGIN NOW Follow, as to him linked in weal or woe; END
BEGIN NOW In woe then; that destruction wide may range: END
BEGIN NOW To me shall be the glory sole among END
BEGIN NOW The infernal Powers, in one day to have marred END
BEGIN NOW What he, Almighty styled, six nights and days END
BEGIN NOW Continued making; and who knows how long END
BEGIN NOW Before had been contriving? though perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Not longer than since I, in one night, freed END
BEGIN NOW From servitude inglorious well nigh half END
BEGIN NOW The angelick name, and thinner left the throng END
BEGIN NOW Of his adorers: He, to be avenged, END
BEGIN NOW And to repair his numbers thus impaired, END
BEGIN NOW Whether such virtue spent of old now failed END
BEGIN NOW More Angels to create, if they at least END
BEGIN NOW Are his created, or, to spite us more, END
BEGIN NOW Determined to advance into our room END
BEGIN NOW A creature formed of earth, and him endow, END
BEGIN NOW Exalted from so base original, END
BEGIN NOW With heavenly spoils, our spoils: What he decreed, END
BEGIN NOW He effected; Man he made, and for him built END
BEGIN NOW Magnificent this world, and earth his seat, END
BEGIN NOW Him lord pronounced; and, O indignity! END
BEGIN NOW Subjected to his service angel-wings, END
BEGIN NOW And flaming ministers to watch and tend END
BEGIN NOW Their earthly charge: Of these the vigilance END
BEGIN NOW I dread; and, to elude, thus wrapt in mist END
BEGIN NOW Of midnight vapour glide obscure, and pry END
BEGIN NOW In every bush and brake, where hap may find END
BEGIN NOW The serpent sleeping; in whose mazy folds END
BEGIN NOW To hide me, and the dark intent I bring. END
BEGIN NOW O foul descent! that I, who erst contended END
BEGIN NOW With Gods to sit the highest, am now constrained END
BEGIN NOW Into a beast; and, mixed with bestial slime, END
BEGIN NOW This essence to incarnate and imbrute, END
BEGIN NOW That to the highth of Deity aspired! END
BEGIN NOW But what will not ambition and revenge END
BEGIN NOW Descend to? Who aspires, must down as low END
BEGIN NOW As high he soared; obnoxious, first or last, END
BEGIN NOW To basest things. Revenge, at first though sweet, END
BEGIN NOW Bitter ere long, back on itself recoils: END
BEGIN NOW Let it; I reck not, so it light well aimed, END
BEGIN NOW Since higher I fall short, on him who next END
BEGIN NOW Provokes my envy, this new favourite END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven, this man of clay, son of despite, END
BEGIN NOW Whom, us the more to spite, his Maker raised END
BEGIN NOW From dust: Spite then with spite is best repaid. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, through each thicket dank or dry, END
BEGIN NOW Like a black mist low-creeping, he held on END
BEGIN NOW His midnight-search, where soonest he might find END
BEGIN NOW The serpent; him fast-sleeping soon he found END
BEGIN NOW In labyrinth of many a round self-rolled, END
BEGIN NOW His head the midst, well stored with subtile wiles: END
BEGIN NOW Not yet in horrid shade or dismal den, END
BEGIN NOW Nor nocent yet; but, on the grassy herb, END
BEGIN NOW Fearless unfeared he slept: in at his mouth END
BEGIN NOW The Devil entered; and his brutal sense, END
BEGIN NOW In heart or head, possessing, soon inspired END
BEGIN NOW With act intelligential; but his sleep END
BEGIN NOW Disturbed not, waiting close the approach of morn. END
BEGIN NOW Now, when as sacred light began to dawn END
BEGIN NOW In Eden on the humid flowers, that breathed END
BEGIN NOW Their morning incense, when all things, that breathe, END
BEGIN NOW From the Earth's great altar send up silent praise END
BEGIN NOW To the Creator, and his nostrils fill END
BEGIN NOW With grateful smell, forth came the human pair, END
BEGIN NOW And joined their vocal worship to the quire END
BEGIN NOW Of creatures wanting voice; that done, partake END
BEGIN NOW The season prime for sweetest scents and airs: END
BEGIN NOW Then commune, how that day they best may ply END
BEGIN NOW Their growing work: for much their work out-grew END
BEGIN NOW The hands' dispatch of two gardening so wide, END
BEGIN NOW And Eve first to her husband thus began. END
BEGIN NOW Adam, well may we labour still to dress END
BEGIN NOW This garden, still to tend plant, herb, and flower, END
BEGIN NOW Our pleasant task enjoined; but, till more hands END
BEGIN NOW Aid us, the work under our labour grows, END
BEGIN NOW Luxurious by restraint; what we by day END
BEGIN NOW Lop overgrown, or prune, or prop, or bind, END
BEGIN NOW One night or two with wanton growth derides END
BEGIN NOW Tending to wild. Thou therefore now advise, END
BEGIN NOW Or bear what to my mind first thoughts present: END
BEGIN NOW Let us divide our labours; thou, where choice END
BEGIN NOW Leads thee, or where most needs, whether to wind END
BEGIN NOW The woodbine round this arbour, or direct END
BEGIN NOW The clasping ivy where to climb; while I, END
BEGIN NOW In yonder spring of roses intermixed END
BEGIN NOW With myrtle, find what to redress till noon: END
BEGIN NOW For, while so near each other thus all day END
BEGIN NOW Our task we choose, what wonder if so near END
BEGIN NOW Looks intervene and smiles, or object new END
BEGIN NOW Casual discourse draw on; which intermits END
BEGIN NOW Our day's work, brought to little, though begun END
BEGIN NOW Early, and the hour of supper comes unearned? END
BEGIN NOW To whom mild answer Adam thus returned. END
BEGIN NOW Sole Eve, associate sole, to me beyond END
BEGIN NOW Compare above all living creatures dear! END
BEGIN NOW Well hast thou motioned, well thy thoughts employed, END
BEGIN NOW How we might best fulfil the work which here END
BEGIN NOW God hath assigned us; nor of me shalt pass END
BEGIN NOW Unpraised: for nothing lovelier can be found END
BEGIN NOW In woman, than to study houshold good, END
BEGIN NOW And good works in her husband to promote. END
BEGIN NOW Yet not so strictly hath our Lord imposed END
BEGIN NOW Labour, as to debar us when we need END
BEGIN NOW Refreshment, whether food, or talk between, END
BEGIN NOW Food of the mind, or this sweet intercourse END
BEGIN NOW Of looks and smiles; for smiles from reason flow, END
BEGIN NOW To brute denied, and are of love the food; END
BEGIN NOW Love, not the lowest end of human life. END
BEGIN NOW For not to irksome toil, but to delight, END
BEGIN NOW He made us, and delight to reason joined. END
BEGIN NOW These paths and bowers doubt not but our joint hands END
BEGIN NOW Will keep from wilderness with ease, as wide END
BEGIN NOW As we need walk, till younger hands ere long END
BEGIN NOW Assist us; But, if much converse perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Thee satiate, to short absence I could yield: END
BEGIN NOW For solitude sometimes is best society, END
BEGIN NOW And short retirement urges sweet return. END
BEGIN NOW But other doubt possesses me, lest harm END
BEGIN NOW Befall thee severed from me; for thou knowest END
BEGIN NOW What hath been warned us, what malicious foe END
BEGIN NOW Envying our happiness, and of his own END
BEGIN NOW Despairing, seeks to work us woe and shame END
BEGIN NOW By sly assault; and somewhere nigh at hand END
BEGIN NOW Watches, no doubt, with greedy hope to find END
BEGIN NOW His wish and best advantage, us asunder; END
BEGIN NOW Hopeless to circumvent us joined, where each END
BEGIN NOW To other speedy aid might lend at need: END
BEGIN NOW Whether his first design be to withdraw END
BEGIN NOW Our fealty from God, or to disturb END
BEGIN NOW Conjugal love, than which perhaps no bliss END
BEGIN NOW Enjoyed by us excites his envy more; END
BEGIN NOW Or this, or worse, leave not the faithful side END
BEGIN NOW That gave thee being, still shades thee, and protects. END
BEGIN NOW The wife, where danger or dishonour lurks, END
BEGIN NOW Safest and seemliest by her husband stays, END
BEGIN NOW Who guards her, or with her the worst endures. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the virgin majesty of Eve, END
BEGIN NOW As one who loves, and some unkindness meets, END
BEGIN NOW With sweet austere composure thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW Offspring of Heaven and Earth, and all Earth's Lord! END
BEGIN NOW That such an enemy we have, who seeks END
BEGIN NOW Our ruin, both by thee informed I learn, END
BEGIN NOW And from the parting Angel over-heard, END
BEGIN NOW As in a shady nook I stood behind, END
BEGIN NOW Just then returned at shut of evening flowers. END
BEGIN NOW But, that thou shouldst my firmness therefore doubt END
BEGIN NOW To God or thee, because we have a foe END
BEGIN NOW May tempt it, I expected not to hear. END
BEGIN NOW His violence thou fearest not, being such END
BEGIN NOW As we, not capable of death or pain, END
BEGIN NOW Can either not receive, or can repel. END
BEGIN NOW His fraud is then thy fear; which plain infers END
BEGIN NOW Thy equal fear, that my firm faith and love END
BEGIN NOW Can by his fraud be shaken or seduced; END
BEGIN NOW Thoughts, which how found they harbour in thy breast, END
BEGIN NOW Adam, mis-thought of her to thee so dear? END
BEGIN NOW To whom with healing words Adam replied. END
BEGIN NOW Daughter of God and Man, immortal Eve! END
BEGIN NOW For such thou art; from sin and blame entire: END
BEGIN NOW Not diffident of thee do I dissuade END
BEGIN NOW Thy absence from my sight, but to avoid END
BEGIN NOW The attempt itself, intended by our foe. END
BEGIN NOW For he who tempts, though in vain, at least asperses END
BEGIN NOW The tempted with dishonour foul; supposed END
BEGIN NOW Not incorruptible of faith, not proof END
BEGIN NOW Against temptation: Thou thyself with scorn END
BEGIN NOW And anger wouldst resent the offered wrong, END
BEGIN NOW Though ineffectual found: misdeem not then, END
BEGIN NOW If such affront I labour to avert END
BEGIN NOW From thee alone, which on us both at once END
BEGIN NOW The enemy, though bold, will hardly dare; END
BEGIN NOW Or daring, first on me the assault shall light. END
BEGIN NOW Nor thou his malice and false guile contemn; END
BEGIN NOW Subtle he needs must be, who could seduce END
BEGIN NOW Angels; nor think superfluous other's aid. END
BEGIN NOW I, from the influence of thy looks, receive END
BEGIN NOW Access in every virtue; in thy sight END
BEGIN NOW More wise, more watchful, stronger, if need were END
BEGIN NOW Of outward strength; while shame, thou looking on, END
BEGIN NOW Shame to be overcome or over-reached, END
BEGIN NOW Would utmost vigour raise, and raised unite. END
BEGIN NOW Why shouldst not thou like sense within thee feel END
BEGIN NOW When I am present, and thy trial choose END
BEGIN NOW With me, best witness of thy virtue tried? END
BEGIN NOW So spake domestick Adam in his care END
BEGIN NOW And matrimonial love; but Eve, who thought END
BEGIN NOW Less attributed to her faith sincere, END
BEGIN NOW Thus her reply with accent sweet renewed. END
BEGIN NOW If this be our condition, thus to dwell END
BEGIN NOW In narrow circuit straitened by a foe, END
BEGIN NOW Subtle or violent, we not endued END
BEGIN NOW Single with like defence, wherever met; END
BEGIN NOW How are we happy, still in fear of harm? END
BEGIN NOW But harm precedes not sin: only our foe, END
BEGIN NOW Tempting, affronts us with his foul esteem END
BEGIN NOW Of our integrity: his foul esteem END
BEGIN NOW Sticks no dishonour on our front, but turns END
BEGIN NOW Foul on himself; then wherefore shunned or feared END
BEGIN NOW By us? who rather double honour gain END
BEGIN NOW From his surmise proved false; find peace within, END
BEGIN NOW Favour from Heaven, our witness, from the event. END
BEGIN NOW And what is faith, love, virtue, unassayed END
BEGIN NOW Alone, without exteriour help sustained? END
BEGIN NOW Let us not then suspect our happy state END
BEGIN NOW Left so imperfect by the Maker wise, END
BEGIN NOW As not secure to single or combined. END
BEGIN NOW Frail is our happiness, if this be so, END
BEGIN NOW And Eden were no Eden, thus exposed. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Adam fervently replied. END
BEGIN NOW O Woman, best are all things as the will END
BEGIN NOW Of God ordained them: His creating hand END
BEGIN NOW Nothing imperfect or deficient left END
BEGIN NOW Of all that he created, much less Man, END
BEGIN NOW Or aught that might his happy state secure, END
BEGIN NOW Secure from outward force; within himself END
BEGIN NOW The danger lies, yet lies within his power: END
BEGIN NOW Against his will he can receive no harm. END
BEGIN NOW But God left free the will; for what obeys END
BEGIN NOW Reason, is free; and Reason he made right, END
BEGIN NOW But bid her well be ware, and still erect; END
BEGIN NOW Lest, by some fair-appearing good surprised, END
BEGIN NOW She dictate false; and mis-inform the will END
BEGIN NOW To do what God expressly hath forbid. END
BEGIN NOW Not then mistrust, but tender love, enjoins, END
BEGIN NOW That I should mind thee oft; and mind thou me. END
BEGIN NOW Firm we subsist, yet possible to swerve; END
BEGIN NOW Since Reason not impossibly may meet END
BEGIN NOW Some specious object by the foe suborned, END
BEGIN NOW And fall into deception unaware, END
BEGIN NOW Not keeping strictest watch, as she was warned. END
BEGIN NOW Seek not temptation then, which to avoid END
BEGIN NOW Were better, and most likely if from me END
BEGIN NOW Thou sever not: Trial will come unsought. END
BEGIN NOW Wouldst thou approve thy constancy, approve END
BEGIN NOW First thy obedience; the other who can know, END
BEGIN NOW Not seeing thee attempted, who attest? END
BEGIN NOW But, if thou think, trial unsought may find END
BEGIN NOW Us both securer than thus warned thou seemest, END
BEGIN NOW Go; for thy stay, not free, absents thee more; END
BEGIN NOW Go in thy native innocence, rely END
BEGIN NOW On what thou hast of virtue; summon all! END
BEGIN NOW For God towards thee hath done his part, do thine. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the patriarch of mankind; but Eve END
BEGIN NOW Persisted; yet submiss, though last, replied. END
BEGIN NOW With thy permission then, and thus forewarned END
BEGIN NOW Chiefly by what thy own last reasoning words END
BEGIN NOW Touched only; that our trial, when least sought, END
BEGIN NOW May find us both perhaps far less prepared, END
BEGIN NOW The willinger I go, nor much expect END
BEGIN NOW A foe so proud will first the weaker seek; END
BEGIN NOW So bent, the more shall shame him his repulse. END
BEGIN NOW Thus saying, from her husband's hand her hand END
BEGIN NOW Soft she withdrew; and, like a Wood-Nymph light, END
BEGIN NOW Oread or Dryad, or of Delia's train, END
BEGIN NOW Betook her to the groves; but Delia's self END
BEGIN NOW In gait surpassed, and Goddess-like deport, END
BEGIN NOW Though not as she with bow and quiver armed, END
BEGIN NOW But with such gardening tools as Art yet rude, END
BEGIN NOW Guiltless of fire, had formed, or Angels brought. END
BEGIN NOW To Pales, or Pomona, thus adorned, END
BEGIN NOW Likest she seemed, Pomona when she fled END
BEGIN NOW Vertumnus, or to Ceres in her prime, END
BEGIN NOW Yet virgin of Proserpina from Jove. END
BEGIN NOW Her long with ardent look his eye pursued END
BEGIN NOW Delighted, but desiring more her stay. END
BEGIN NOW Oft he to her his charge of quick return END
BEGIN NOW Repeated; she to him as oft engaged END
BEGIN NOW To be returned by noon amid the bower, END
BEGIN NOW And all things in best order to invite END
BEGIN NOW Noontide repast, or afternoon's repose. END
BEGIN NOW O much deceived, much failing, hapless Eve, END
BEGIN NOW Of thy presumed return! event perverse! END
BEGIN NOW Thou never from that hour in Paradise END
BEGIN NOW Foundst either sweet repast, or sound repose; END
BEGIN NOW Such ambush, hid among sweet flowers and shades, END
BEGIN NOW Waited with hellish rancour imminent END
BEGIN NOW To intercept thy way, or send thee back END
BEGIN NOW Despoiled of innocence, of faith, of bliss! END
BEGIN NOW For now, and since first break of dawn, the Fiend, END
BEGIN NOW Mere serpent in appearance, forth was come; END
BEGIN NOW And on his quest, where likeliest he might find END
BEGIN NOW The only two of mankind, but in them END
BEGIN NOW The whole included race, his purposed prey. END
BEGIN NOW In bower and field he sought, where any tuft END
BEGIN NOW Of grove or garden-plot more pleasant lay, END
BEGIN NOW Their tendance, or plantation for delight; END
BEGIN NOW By fountain or by shady rivulet END
BEGIN NOW He sought them both, but wished his hap might find END
BEGIN NOW Eve separate; he wished, but not with hope END
BEGIN NOW Of what so seldom chanced; when to his wish, END
BEGIN NOW Beyond his hope, Eve separate he spies, END
BEGIN NOW Veiled in a cloud of fragrance, where she stood, END
BEGIN NOW Half spied, so thick the roses blushing round END
BEGIN NOW About her glowed, oft stooping to support END
BEGIN NOW Each flower of slender stalk, whose head, though gay END
BEGIN NOW Carnation, purple, azure, or specked with gold, END
BEGIN NOW Hung drooping unsustained; them she upstays END
BEGIN NOW Gently with myrtle band, mindless the while END
BEGIN NOW Herself, though fairest unsupported flower, END
BEGIN NOW From her best prop so far, and storm so nigh. END
BEGIN NOW Nearer he drew, and many a walk traversed END
BEGIN NOW Of stateliest covert, cedar, pine, or palm; END
BEGIN NOW Then voluble and bold, now hid, now seen, END
BEGIN NOW Among thick-woven arborets, and flowers END
BEGIN NOW Imbordered on each bank, the hand of Eve: END
BEGIN NOW Spot more delicious than those gardens feigned END
BEGIN NOW Or of revived Adonis, or renowned END
BEGIN NOW Alcinous, host of old Laertes' son; END
BEGIN NOW Or that, not mystick, where the sapient king END
BEGIN NOW Much he the place admired, the person more. END
BEGIN NOW As one who long in populous city pent, END
BEGIN NOW Where houses thick and sewers annoy the air, END
BEGIN NOW Forth issuing on a summer's morn, to breathe END
BEGIN NOW Among the pleasant villages and farms END
BEGIN NOW Adjoined, from each thing met conceives delight; END
BEGIN NOW The smell of grain, or tedded grass, or kine, END
BEGIN NOW Or dairy, each rural sight, each rural sound; END
BEGIN NOW If chance, with nymph-like step, fair virgin pass, END
BEGIN NOW What pleasing seemed, for her now pleases more; END
BEGIN NOW She most, and in her look sums all delight: END
BEGIN NOW Such pleasure took the Serpent to behold END
BEGIN NOW This flowery plat, the sweet recess of Eve END
BEGIN NOW Thus early, thus alone: Her heavenly form END
BEGIN NOW Angelick, but more soft, and feminine, END
BEGIN NOW Her graceful innocence, her every air END
BEGIN NOW Of gesture, or least action, overawed END
BEGIN NOW His malice, and with rapine sweet bereaved END
BEGIN NOW His fierceness of the fierce intent it brought: END
BEGIN NOW That space the Evil-one abstracted stood END
BEGIN NOW From his own evil, and for the time remained END
BEGIN NOW Stupidly good; of enmity disarmed, END
BEGIN NOW Of guile, of hate, of envy, of revenge: END
BEGIN NOW But the hot Hell that always in him burns, END
BEGIN NOW Though in mid Heaven, soon ended his delight, END
BEGIN NOW And tortures him now more, the more he sees END
BEGIN NOW Of pleasure, not for him ordained: then soon END
BEGIN NOW Fierce hate he recollects, and all his thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Of mischief, gratulating, thus excites. END
BEGIN NOW Thoughts, whither have ye led me! with what sweet END
BEGIN NOW Compulsion thus transported, to forget END
BEGIN NOW What hither brought us! hate, not love; nor hope END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise for Hell, hope here to taste END
BEGIN NOW Of pleasure; but all pleasure to destroy, END
BEGIN NOW Save what is in destroying; other joy END
BEGIN NOW To me is lost. Then, let me not let pass END
BEGIN NOW Occasion which now smiles; behold alone END
BEGIN NOW The woman, opportune to all attempts, END
BEGIN NOW Her husband, for I view far round, not nigh, END
BEGIN NOW Whose higher intellectual more I shun, END
BEGIN NOW And strength, of courage haughty, and of limb END
BEGIN NOW Heroick built, though of terrestrial mould; END
BEGIN NOW Foe not informidable! exempt from wound, END
BEGIN NOW I not; so much hath Hell debased, and pain END
BEGIN NOW Enfeebled me, to what I was in Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW She fair, divinely fair, fit love for Gods! END
BEGIN NOW Not terrible, though terrour be in love END
BEGIN NOW And beauty, not approached by stronger hate, END
BEGIN NOW Hate stronger, under show of love well feigned; END
BEGIN NOW The way which to her ruin now I tend. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the enemy of mankind, enclosed END
BEGIN NOW In serpent, inmate bad! and toward Eve END
BEGIN NOW Addressed his way: not with indented wave, END
BEGIN NOW Prone on the ground, as since; but on his rear, END
BEGIN NOW Circular base of rising folds, that towered END
BEGIN NOW Fold above fold, a surging maze! his head END
BEGIN NOW Crested aloft, and carbuncle his eyes; END
BEGIN NOW With burnished neck of verdant gold, erect END
BEGIN NOW Amidst his circling spires, that on the grass END
BEGIN NOW Floated redundant: pleasing was his shape END
BEGIN NOW And lovely; never since of serpent-kind END
BEGIN NOW Lovelier, not those that in Illyria changed, END
BEGIN NOW In Epidaurus; nor to which transformed END
BEGIN NOW Ammonian Jove, or Capitoline, was seen; END
BEGIN NOW He with Olympias; this with her who bore END
BEGIN NOW Scipio, the highth of Rome. With tract oblique END
BEGIN NOW At first, as one who sought access, but feared END
BEGIN NOW To interrupt, side-long he works his way. END
BEGIN NOW As when a ship, by skilful steersmen wrought END
BEGIN NOW Nigh river's mouth or foreland, where the wind END
BEGIN NOW Veers oft, as oft so steers, and shifts her sail: END
BEGIN NOW So varied he, and of his tortuous train END
BEGIN NOW Curled many a wanton wreath in sight of Eve, END
BEGIN NOW To lure her eye; she, busied, heard the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of rusling leaves, but minded not, as used END
BEGIN NOW To such disport before her through the field, END
BEGIN NOW From every beast; more duteous at her call, END
BEGIN NOW Than at Circean call the herd disguised. END
BEGIN NOW He, bolder now, uncalled before her stood, END
BEGIN NOW But as in gaze admiring: oft he bowed END
BEGIN NOW His turret crest, and sleek enamelled neck, END
BEGIN NOW Fawning; and licked the ground whereon she trod. END
BEGIN NOW The eye of Eve to mark his play; he, glad END
BEGIN NOW Of her attention gained, with serpent-tongue END
BEGIN NOW Organick, or impulse of vocal air, END
BEGIN NOW His fraudulent temptation thus began. END
BEGIN NOW Wonder not, sovran Mistress, if perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Thou canst, who art sole wonder! much less arm END
BEGIN NOW Thy looks, the Heaven of mildness, with disdain, END
BEGIN NOW Displeased that I approach thee thus, and gaze END
BEGIN NOW Insatiate; I thus single; nor have feared END
BEGIN NOW Thy awful brow, more awful thus retired. END
BEGIN NOW Fairest resemblance of thy Maker fair, END
BEGIN NOW Thee all things living gaze on, all things thine END
BEGIN NOW By gift, and thy celestial beauty adore END
BEGIN NOW With ravishment beheld! there best beheld, END
BEGIN NOW Where universally admired; but here END
BEGIN NOW In this enclosure wild, these beasts among, END
BEGIN NOW Beholders rude, and shallow to discern END
BEGIN NOW Half what in thee is fair, one man except, END
BEGIN NOW Who sees thee? and what is one? who should be seen END
BEGIN NOW A Goddess among Gods, adored and served END
BEGIN NOW By Angels numberless, thy daily train. END
BEGIN NOW So glozed the Tempter, and his proem tuned: END
BEGIN NOW Into the heart of Eve his words made way, END
BEGIN NOW Though at the voice much marvelling; at length, END
BEGIN NOW Not unamazed, she thus in answer spake. END
BEGIN NOW What may this mean? language of man pronounced END
BEGIN NOW By tongue of brute, and human sense expressed? END
BEGIN NOW The first, at least, of these I thought denied END
BEGIN NOW To beasts; whom God, on their creation-day, END
BEGIN NOW Created mute to all articulate sound: END
BEGIN NOW The latter I demur; for in their looks END
BEGIN NOW Much reason, and in their actions, oft appears. END
BEGIN NOW Thee, Serpent, subtlest beast of all the field END
BEGIN NOW I knew, but not with human voice endued; END
BEGIN NOW Redouble then this miracle, and say, END
BEGIN NOW How camest thou speakable of mute, and how END
BEGIN NOW To me so friendly grown above the rest END
BEGIN NOW Of brutal kind, that daily are in sight? END
BEGIN NOW Say, for such wonder claims attention due. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the guileful Tempter thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW Empress of this fair world, resplendent Eve! END
BEGIN NOW Easy to me it is to tell thee all END
BEGIN NOW What thou commandest; and right thou shouldst be obeyed: END
BEGIN NOW I was at first as other beasts that graze END
BEGIN NOW The trodden herb, of abject thoughts and low, END
BEGIN NOW As was my food; nor aught but food discerned END
BEGIN NOW Or sex, and apprehended nothing high: END
BEGIN NOW Till, on a day roving the field, I chanced END
BEGIN NOW A goodly tree far distant to behold END
BEGIN NOW Loaden with fruit of fairest colours mixed, END
BEGIN NOW Ruddy and gold: I nearer drew to gaze; END
BEGIN NOW When from the boughs a savoury odour blown, END
BEGIN NOW Grateful to appetite, more pleased my sense END
BEGIN NOW Than smell of sweetest fennel, or the teats END
BEGIN NOW Of ewe or goat dropping with milk at even, END
BEGIN NOW Unsucked of lamb or kid, that tend their play. END
BEGIN NOW To satisfy the sharp desire I had END
BEGIN NOW Of tasting those fair apples, I resolved END
BEGIN NOW Not to defer; hunger and thirst at once, END
BEGIN NOW Powerful persuaders, quickened at the scent END
BEGIN NOW Of that alluring fruit, urged me so keen. END
BEGIN NOW About the mossy trunk I wound me soon; END
BEGIN NOW For, high from ground, the branches would require END
BEGIN NOW Thy utmost reach or Adam's: Round the tree END
BEGIN NOW All other beasts that saw, with like desire END
BEGIN NOW Longing and envying stood, but could not reach. END
BEGIN NOW Amid the tree now got, where plenty hung END
BEGIN NOW Tempting so nigh, to pluck and eat my fill END
BEGIN NOW I spared not; for, such pleasure till that hour, END
BEGIN NOW At feed or fountain, never had I found. END
BEGIN NOW Sated at length, ere long I might perceive END
BEGIN NOW Strange alteration in me, to degree END
BEGIN NOW Of reason in my inward powers; and speech END
BEGIN NOW Wanted not long; though to this shape retained. END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth to speculations high or deep END
BEGIN NOW I turned my thoughts, and with capacious mind END
BEGIN NOW Considered all things visible in Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Or Earth, or Middle; all things fair and good: END
BEGIN NOW But all that fair and good in thy divine END
BEGIN NOW Semblance, and in thy beauty's heavenly ray, END
BEGIN NOW United I beheld; no fair to thine END
BEGIN NOW Equivalent or second! which compelled END
BEGIN NOW Me thus, though importune perhaps, to come END
BEGIN NOW And gaze, and worship thee of right declared END
BEGIN NOW Sovran of creatures, universal Dame! END
BEGIN NOW So talked the spirited sly Snake; and Eve, END
BEGIN NOW Yet more amazed, unwary thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW Serpent, thy overpraising leaves in doubt END
BEGIN NOW The virtue of that fruit, in thee first proved: END
BEGIN NOW But say, where grows the tree? from hence how far? END
BEGIN NOW For many are the trees of God that grow END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise, and various, yet unknown END
BEGIN NOW To us; in such abundance lies our choice, END
BEGIN NOW As leaves a greater store of fruit untouched, END
BEGIN NOW Still hanging incorruptible, till men END
BEGIN NOW Grow up to their provision, and more hands END
BEGIN NOW Help to disburden Nature of her birth. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the wily Adder, blithe and glad. END
BEGIN NOW Empress, the way is ready, and not long; END
BEGIN NOW Beyond a row of myrtles, on a flat, END
BEGIN NOW Fast by a fountain, one small thicket past END
BEGIN NOW Of blowing myrrh and balm: if thou accept END
BEGIN NOW My conduct, I can bring thee thither soon END
BEGIN NOW Lead then, said Eve. He, leading, swiftly rolled END
BEGIN NOW In tangles, and made intricate seem straight, END
BEGIN NOW To mischief swift. Hope elevates, and joy END
BEGIN NOW Brightens his crest; as when a wandering fire, END
BEGIN NOW Compact of unctuous vapour, which the night END
BEGIN NOW Condenses, and the cold environs round, END
BEGIN NOW Kindled through agitation to a flame, END
BEGIN NOW Which oft, they say, some evil Spirit attends, END
BEGIN NOW Hovering and blazing with delusive light, END
BEGIN NOW Misleads the amazed night-wanderer from his way END
BEGIN NOW To bogs and mires, and oft through pond or pool; END
BEGIN NOW There swallowed up and lost, from succour far. END
BEGIN NOW So glistered the dire Snake, and into fraud END
BEGIN NOW Led Eve, our credulous mother, to the tree END
BEGIN NOW Of prohibition, root of all our woe; END
BEGIN NOW Which when she saw, thus to her guide she spake. END
BEGIN NOW Serpent, we might have spared our coming hither, END
BEGIN NOW Fruitless to me, though fruit be here to excess, END
BEGIN NOW The credit of whose virtue rest with thee; END
BEGIN NOW Wonderous indeed, if cause of such effects. END
BEGIN NOW But of this tree we may not taste nor touch; END
BEGIN NOW God so commanded, and left that command END
BEGIN NOW Sole daughter of his voice; the rest, we live END
BEGIN NOW Law to ourselves; our reason is our law. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Tempter guilefully replied. END
BEGIN NOW Indeed! hath God then said that of the fruit END
BEGIN NOW Of all these garden-trees ye shall not eat, END
BEGIN NOW Yet Lords declared of all in earth or air? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Eve, yet sinless. Of the fruit END
BEGIN NOW Of each tree in the garden we may eat; END
BEGIN NOW But of the fruit of this fair tree amidst END
BEGIN NOW The garden, God hath said, Ye shall not eat END
BEGIN NOW Thereof, nor shall ye touch it, lest ye die. END
BEGIN NOW She scarce had said, though brief, when now more bold END
BEGIN NOW The Tempter, but with show of zeal and love END
BEGIN NOW To Man, and indignation at his wrong, END
BEGIN NOW New part puts on; and, as to passion moved, END
BEGIN NOW Fluctuates disturbed, yet comely and in act END
BEGIN NOW Raised, as of some great matter to begin. END
BEGIN NOW As when of old some orator renowned, END
BEGIN NOW In Athens or free Rome, where eloquence END
BEGIN NOW Flourished, since mute! to some great cause addressed, END
BEGIN NOW Stood in himself collected; while each part, END
BEGIN NOW Motion, each act, won audience ere the tongue; END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes in highth began, as no delay END
BEGIN NOW Of preface brooking, through his zeal of right: END
BEGIN NOW So standing, moving, or to highth up grown, END
BEGIN NOW The Tempter, all impassioned, thus began. END
BEGIN NOW O sacred, wise, and wisdom-giving Plant, END
BEGIN NOW Mother of science! now I feel thy power END
BEGIN NOW Within me clear; not only to discern END
BEGIN NOW Things in their causes, but to trace the ways END
BEGIN NOW Of highest agents, deemed however wise. END
BEGIN NOW Queen of this universe! do not believe END
BEGIN NOW Those rigid threats of death: ye shall not die: END
BEGIN NOW How should you? by the fruit? it gives you life END
BEGIN NOW To knowledge; by the threatener? look on me, END
BEGIN NOW Me, who have touched and tasted; yet both live, END
BEGIN NOW And life more perfect have attained than Fate END
BEGIN NOW Meant me, by venturing higher than my lot. END
BEGIN NOW Shall that be shut to Man, which to the Beast END
BEGIN NOW Is open? or will God incense his ire END
BEGIN NOW For such a petty trespass? and not praise END
BEGIN NOW Rather your dauntless virtue, whom the pain END
BEGIN NOW Of death denounced, whatever thing death be, END
BEGIN NOW Deterred not from achieving what might lead END
BEGIN NOW To happier life, knowledge of good and evil; END
BEGIN NOW Of good, how just? of evil, if what is evil END
BEGIN NOW Be real, why not known, since easier shunned? END
BEGIN NOW God therefore cannot hurt ye, and be just; END
BEGIN NOW Not just, not God; not feared then, nor obeyed: END
BEGIN NOW Your fear itself of death removes the fear. END
BEGIN NOW Why then was this forbid? Why, but to awe; END
BEGIN NOW Why, but to keep ye low and ignorant, END
BEGIN NOW His worshippers? He knows that in the day END
BEGIN NOW Ye eat thereof, your eyes that seem so clear, END
BEGIN NOW Yet are but dim, shall perfectly be then END
BEGIN NOW Opened and cleared, and ye shall be as Gods, END
BEGIN NOW Knowing both good and evil, as they know. END
BEGIN NOW That ye shall be as Gods, since I as Man, END
BEGIN NOW Internal Man, is but proportion meet; END
BEGIN NOW I, of brute, human; ye, of human, Gods. END
BEGIN NOW So ye shall die perhaps, by putting off END
BEGIN NOW Human, to put on Gods; death to be wished, END
BEGIN NOW Though threatened, which no worse than this can bring. END
BEGIN NOW And what are Gods, that Man may not become END
BEGIN NOW As they, participating God-like food? END
BEGIN NOW The Gods are first, and that advantage use END
BEGIN NOW On our belief, that all from them proceeds: END
BEGIN NOW I question it; for this fair earth I see, END
BEGIN NOW Warmed by the sun, producing every kind; END
BEGIN NOW Them, nothing: if they all things, who enclosed END
BEGIN NOW Knowledge of good and evil in this tree, END
BEGIN NOW That whoso eats thereof, forthwith attains END
BEGIN NOW Wisdom without their leave? and wherein lies END
BEGIN NOW The offence, that Man should thus attain to know? END
BEGIN NOW What can your knowledge hurt him, or this tree END
BEGIN NOW Impart against his will, if all be his? END
BEGIN NOW Or is it envy? and can envy dwell END
BEGIN NOW In heavenly breasts? These, these, and many more END
BEGIN NOW Causes import your need of this fair fruit. END
BEGIN NOW Goddess humane, reach then, and freely taste! END
BEGIN NOW He ended; and his words, replete with guile, END
BEGIN NOW Into her heart too easy entrance won: END
BEGIN NOW Fixed on the fruit she gazed, which to behold END
BEGIN NOW Might tempt alone; and in her ears the sound END
BEGIN NOW Yet rung of his persuasive words, impregned END
BEGIN NOW With reason, to her seeming, and with truth: END
BEGIN NOW Mean while the hour of noon drew on, and waked END
BEGIN NOW An eager appetite, raised by the smell END
BEGIN NOW So savoury of that fruit, which with desire, END
BEGIN NOW Inclinable now grown to touch or taste, END
BEGIN NOW Solicited her longing eye; yet first END
BEGIN NOW Pausing a while, thus to herself she mused. END
BEGIN NOW Great are thy virtues, doubtless, best of fruits, END
BEGIN NOW Though kept from man, and worthy to be admired; END
BEGIN NOW Whose taste, too long forborn, at first assay END
BEGIN NOW Gave elocution to the mute, and taught END
BEGIN NOW The tongue not made for speech to speak thy praise: END
BEGIN NOW Thy praise he also, who forbids thy use, END
BEGIN NOW Conceals not from us, naming thee the tree END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledge, knowledge both of good and evil; END
BEGIN NOW Forbids us then to taste! but his forbidding END
BEGIN NOW Commends thee more, while it infers the good END
BEGIN NOW By thee communicated, and our want: END
BEGIN NOW For good unknown sure is not had; or, had END
BEGIN NOW And yet unknown, is as not had at all. END
BEGIN NOW In plain then, what forbids he but to know, END
BEGIN NOW Forbids us good, forbids us to be wise? END
BEGIN NOW Such prohibitions bind not. But, if death END
BEGIN NOW Bind us with after-bands, what profits then END
BEGIN NOW Our inward freedom? In the day we eat END
BEGIN NOW Of this fair fruit, our doom is, we shall die! END
BEGIN NOW How dies the Serpent? he hath eaten and lives, END
BEGIN NOW And knows, and speaks, and reasons, and discerns, END
BEGIN NOW Irrational till then. For us alone END
BEGIN NOW Was death invented? or to us denied END
BEGIN NOW This intellectual food, for beasts reserved? END
BEGIN NOW For beasts it seems: yet that one beast which first END
BEGIN NOW Hath tasted envies not, but brings with joy END
BEGIN NOW The good befallen him, author unsuspect, END
BEGIN NOW Friendly to man, far from deceit or guile. END
BEGIN NOW What fear I then? rather, what know to fear END
BEGIN NOW Under this ignorance of good and evil, END
BEGIN NOW Of God or death, of law or penalty? END
BEGIN NOW Here grows the cure of all, this fruit divine, END
BEGIN NOW Fair to the eye, inviting to the taste, END
BEGIN NOW Of virtue to make wise: What hinders then END
BEGIN NOW To reach, and feed at once both body and mind? END
BEGIN NOW So saying, her rash hand in evil hour END
BEGIN NOW Forth reaching to the fruit, she plucked, she eat! END
BEGIN NOW Earth felt the wound; and Nature from her seat, END
BEGIN NOW Sighing through all her works, gave signs of woe, END
BEGIN NOW That all was lost. Back to the thicket slunk END
BEGIN NOW The guilty Serpent; and well might; for Eve, END
BEGIN NOW Intent now wholly on her taste, nought else END
BEGIN NOW Regarded; such delight till then, as seemed, END
BEGIN NOW In fruit she never tasted, whether true END
BEGIN NOW Or fancied so, through expectation high END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledge; not was Godhead from her thought. END
BEGIN NOW Greedily she ingorged without restraint, END
BEGIN NOW And knew not eating death: Satiate at length, END
BEGIN NOW And hightened as with wine, jocund and boon, END
BEGIN NOW Thus to herself she pleasingly began. END
BEGIN NOW O sovran, virtuous, precious of all trees END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise! of operation blest END
BEGIN NOW To sapience, hitherto obscured, infamed. END
BEGIN NOW And thy fair fruit let hang, as to no end END
BEGIN NOW Created; but henceforth my early care, END
BEGIN NOW Not without song, each morning, and due praise, END
BEGIN NOW Shall tend thee, and the fertile burden ease END
BEGIN NOW Of thy full branches offered free to all; END
BEGIN NOW Till, dieted by thee, I grow mature END
BEGIN NOW In knowledge, as the Gods, who all things know; END
BEGIN NOW Though others envy what they cannot give: END
BEGIN NOW For, had the gift been theirs, it had not here END
BEGIN NOW Thus grown. Experience, next, to thee I owe, END
BEGIN NOW Best guide; not following thee, I had remained END
BEGIN NOW In ignorance; thou openest wisdom's way, END
BEGIN NOW And givest access, though secret she retire. END
BEGIN NOW And I perhaps am secret: Heaven is high, END
BEGIN NOW High, and remote to see from thence distinct END
BEGIN NOW Each thing on Earth; and other care perhaps END
BEGIN NOW May have diverted from continual watch END
BEGIN NOW Our great Forbidder, safe with all his spies END
BEGIN NOW About him. But to Adam in what sort END
BEGIN NOW Shall I appear? shall I to him make known END
BEGIN NOW As yet my change, and give him to partake END
BEGIN NOW Full happiness with me, or rather not, END
BEGIN NOW But keeps the odds of knowledge in my power END
BEGIN NOW Without copartner? so to add what wants END
BEGIN NOW In female sex, the more to draw his love, END
BEGIN NOW And render me more equal; and perhaps, END
BEGIN NOW A thing not undesirable, sometime END
BEGIN NOW Superiour; for, inferiour, who is free END
BEGIN NOW This may be well: But what if God have seen, END
BEGIN NOW And death ensue? then I shall be no more! END
BEGIN NOW And Adam, wedded to another Eve, END
BEGIN NOW Shall live with her enjoying, I extinct; END
BEGIN NOW A death to think! Confirmed then I resolve, END
BEGIN NOW Adam shall share with me in bliss or woe: END
BEGIN NOW So dear I love him, that with him all deaths END
BEGIN NOW I could endure, without him live no life. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, from the tree her step she turned; END
BEGIN NOW But first low reverence done, as to the Power END
BEGIN NOW That dwelt within, whose presence had infused END
BEGIN NOW Into the plant sciential sap, derived END
BEGIN NOW From nectar, drink of Gods. Adam the while, END
BEGIN NOW Waiting desirous her return, had wove END
BEGIN NOW Of choicest flowers a garland, to adorn END
BEGIN NOW Her tresses, and her rural labours crown; END
BEGIN NOW As reapers oft are wont their harvest-queen. END
BEGIN NOW Great joy he promised to his thoughts, and new END
BEGIN NOW Solace in her return, so long delayed: END
BEGIN NOW Yet oft his heart, divine of something ill, END
BEGIN NOW Misgave him; he the faltering measure felt; END
BEGIN NOW And forth to meet her went, the way she took END
BEGIN NOW That morn when first they parted: by the tree END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledge he must pass; there he her met, END
BEGIN NOW Scarce from the tree returning; in her hand END
BEGIN NOW A bough of fairest fruit, that downy smiled, END
BEGIN NOW New gathered, and ambrosial smell diffused. END
BEGIN NOW To him she hasted; in her face excuse END
BEGIN NOW Came prologue, and apology too prompt; END
BEGIN NOW Which, with bland words at will, she thus addressed. END
BEGIN NOW Hast thou not wondered, Adam, at my stay? END
BEGIN NOW Thee I have missed, and thought it long, deprived END
BEGIN NOW Thy presence; agony of love till now END
BEGIN NOW Not felt, nor shall be twice; for never more END
BEGIN NOW Mean I to try, what rash untried I sought, END
BEGIN NOW The pain of absence from thy sight. But strange END
BEGIN NOW Hath been the cause, and wonderful to hear: END
BEGIN NOW This tree is not, as we are told, a tree END
BEGIN NOW Of danger tasted, nor to evil unknown END
BEGIN NOW Opening the way, but of divine effect END
BEGIN NOW To open eyes, and make them Gods who taste; END
BEGIN NOW And hath been tasted such: The serpent wise, END
BEGIN NOW Or not restrained as we, or not obeying, END
BEGIN NOW Hath eaten of the fruit; and is become, END
BEGIN NOW Not dead, as we are threatened, but thenceforth END
BEGIN NOW Endued with human voice and human sense, END
BEGIN NOW Reasoning to admiration; and with me END
BEGIN NOW Persuasively hath so prevailed, that I END
BEGIN NOW Have also tasted, and have also found END
BEGIN NOW The effects to correspond; opener mine eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Dim erst, dilated spirits, ampler heart, END
BEGIN NOW And growing up to Godhead; which for thee END
BEGIN NOW Chiefly I sought, without thee can despise. END
BEGIN NOW For bliss, as thou hast part, to me is bliss; END
BEGIN NOW Tedious, unshared with thee, and odious soon. END
BEGIN NOW Thou therefore also taste, that equal lot END
BEGIN NOW May join us, equal joy, as equal love; END
BEGIN NOW Lest, thou not tasting, different degree END
BEGIN NOW Disjoin us, and I then too late renounce END
BEGIN NOW Deity for thee, when Fate will not permit. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Eve with countenance blithe her story told; END
BEGIN NOW But in her cheek distemper flushing glowed. END
BEGIN NOW On the other side Adam, soon as he heard END
BEGIN NOW The fatal trespass done by Eve, amazed, END
BEGIN NOW Astonied stood and blank, while horrour chill END
BEGIN NOW Ran through his veins, and all his joints relaxed; END
BEGIN NOW From his slack hand the garland wreathed for Eve END
BEGIN NOW Down dropt, and all the faded roses shed: END
BEGIN NOW Speechless he stood and pale, till thus at length END
BEGIN NOW First to himself he inward silence broke. END
BEGIN NOW O fairest of Creation, last and best END
BEGIN NOW Of all God's works, Creature in whom excelled END
BEGIN NOW Whatever can to sight or thought be formed, END
BEGIN NOW Holy, divine, good, amiable, or sweet! END
BEGIN NOW How art thou lost! how on a sudden lost, END
BEGIN NOW Defaced, deflowered, and now to death devote! END
BEGIN NOW Rather, how hast thou yielded to transgress END
BEGIN NOW The strict forbiddance, how to violate END
BEGIN NOW The sacred fruit forbidden! Some cursed fraud END
BEGIN NOW Of enemy hath beguiled thee, yet unknown, END
BEGIN NOW And me with thee hath ruined; for with thee END
BEGIN NOW Certain my resolution is to die: END
BEGIN NOW How can I live without thee! how forego END
BEGIN NOW Thy sweet converse, and love so dearly joined, END
BEGIN NOW To live again in these wild woods forlorn! END
BEGIN NOW Should God create another Eve, and I END
BEGIN NOW Another rib afford, yet loss of thee END
BEGIN NOW Would never from my heart: no, no! I feel END
BEGIN NOW The link of Nature draw me: flesh of flesh, END
BEGIN NOW Bone of my bone thou art, and from thy state END
BEGIN NOW Mine never shall be parted, bliss or woe. END
BEGIN NOW So having said, as one from sad dismay END
BEGIN NOW Recomforted, and after thoughts disturbed END
BEGIN NOW Submitting to what seemed remediless, END
BEGIN NOW Thus in calm mood his words to Eve he turned. END
BEGIN NOW Bold deed thou hast presumed, adventurous Eve, END
BEGIN NOW And peril great provoked, who thus hast dared, END
BEGIN NOW Had it been only coveting to eye END
BEGIN NOW That sacred fruit, sacred to abstinence, END
BEGIN NOW Much more to taste it under ban to touch. END
BEGIN NOW But past who can recall, or done undo? END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps thou shalt not die, perhaps the fact END
BEGIN NOW Is not so heinous now, foretasted fruit, END
BEGIN NOW Profaned first by the serpent, by him first END
BEGIN NOW Made common, and unhallowed, ere our taste; END
BEGIN NOW Nor yet on him found deadly; yet he lives; END
BEGIN NOW Lives, as thou saidst, and gains to live, as Man, END
BEGIN NOW Higher degree of life; inducement strong END
BEGIN NOW To us, as likely tasting to attain END
BEGIN NOW Proportional ascent; which cannot be END
BEGIN NOW But to be Gods, or Angels, demi-Gods. END
BEGIN NOW Nor can I think that God, Creator wise, END
BEGIN NOW Though threatening, will in earnest so destroy END
BEGIN NOW Us his prime creatures, dignified so high, END
BEGIN NOW Set over all his works; which in our fall, END
BEGIN NOW For us created, needs with us must fail, END
BEGIN NOW Dependant made; so God shall uncreate, END
BEGIN NOW Be frustrate, do, undo, and labour lose; END
BEGIN NOW Not well conceived of God, who, though his power END
BEGIN NOW Creation could repeat, yet would be loth END
BEGIN NOW Us to abolish, lest the Adversary END
BEGIN NOW Triumph, and say; "Fickle their state whom God END
BEGIN NOW Most favours; who can please him long? Me first END
BEGIN NOW He ruined, now Mankind; whom will he next? END
BEGIN NOW Matter of scorn, not to be given the Foe. END
BEGIN NOW However I with thee have fixed my lot, END
BEGIN NOW Certain to undergo like doom: If death END
BEGIN NOW Consort with thee, death is to me as life; END
BEGIN NOW So forcible within my heart I feel END
BEGIN NOW The bond of Nature draw me to my own; END
BEGIN NOW My own in thee, for what thou art is mine; END
BEGIN NOW Our state cannot be severed; we are one, END
BEGIN NOW One flesh; to lose thee were to lose myself. END
BEGIN NOW So Adam; and thus Eve to him replied. END
BEGIN NOW O glorious trial of exceeding love, END
BEGIN NOW Illustrious evidence, example high! END
BEGIN NOW Engaging me to emulate; but, short END
BEGIN NOW Of thy perfection, how shall I attain, END
BEGIN NOW Adam, from whose dear side I boast me sprung, END
BEGIN NOW And gladly of our union hear thee speak, END
BEGIN NOW One heart, one soul in both; whereof good proof END
BEGIN NOW This day affords, declaring thee resolved, END
BEGIN NOW Rather than death, or aught than death more dread, END
BEGIN NOW Shall separate us, linked in love so dear, END
BEGIN NOW To undergo with me one guilt, one crime, END
BEGIN NOW If any be, of tasting this fair fruit; END
BEGIN NOW Whose virtue for of good still good proceeds, END
BEGIN NOW Direct, or by occasion, hath presented END
BEGIN NOW This happy trial of thy love, which else END
BEGIN NOW So eminently never had been known? END
BEGIN NOW Were it I thought death menaced would ensue END
BEGIN NOW This my attempt, I would sustain alone END
BEGIN NOW The worst, and not persuade thee, rather die END
BEGIN NOW Deserted, than oblige thee with a fact END
BEGIN NOW Pernicious to thy peace; chiefly assured END
BEGIN NOW Remarkably so late of thy so true, END
BEGIN NOW So faithful, love unequalled: but I feel END
BEGIN NOW Far otherwise the event; not death, but life END
BEGIN NOW Augmented, opened eyes, new hopes, new joys, END
BEGIN NOW Taste so divine, that what of sweet before END
BEGIN NOW Hath touched my sense, flat seems to this, and harsh. END
BEGIN NOW On my experience, Adam, freely taste, END
BEGIN NOW And fear of death deliver to the winds. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, she embraced him, and for joy END
BEGIN NOW Tenderly wept; much won, that he his love END
BEGIN NOW Had so ennobled, as of choice to incur END
BEGIN NOW Divine displeasure for her sake, or death. END
BEGIN NOW In recompence (for such compliance bad END
BEGIN NOW Such recompence best merits) from the bough END
BEGIN NOW She gave him of that fair enticing fruit END
BEGIN NOW With liberal hand: he scrupled not to eat, END
BEGIN NOW Against his better knowledge; not deceived, END
BEGIN NOW But fondly overcome with female charm. END
BEGIN NOW Earth trembled from her entrails, as again END
BEGIN NOW In pangs; and Nature gave a second groan; END
BEGIN NOW Sky loured; and, muttering thunder, some sad drops END
BEGIN NOW Wept at completing of the mortal sin END
BEGIN NOW Original: while Adam took no thought, END
BEGIN NOW Eating his fill; nor Eve to iterate END
BEGIN NOW Her former trespass feared, the more to sooth END
BEGIN NOW Him with her loved society; that now, END
BEGIN NOW As with new wine intoxicated both, END
BEGIN NOW They swim in mirth, and fancy that they feel END
BEGIN NOW Divinity within them breeding wings, END
BEGIN NOW Wherewith to scorn the earth: But that false fruit END
BEGIN NOW Far other operation first displayed, END
BEGIN NOW Carnal desire inflaming; he on Eve END
BEGIN NOW Began to cast lascivious eyes; she him END
BEGIN NOW As wantonly repaid; in lust they burn: END
BEGIN NOW Till Adam thus 'gan Eve to dalliance move. END
BEGIN NOW Eve, now I see thou art exact of taste, END
BEGIN NOW And elegant, of sapience no small part; END
BEGIN NOW Since to each meaning savour we apply, END
BEGIN NOW And palate call judicious; I the praise END
BEGIN NOW Yield thee, so well this day thou hast purveyed. END
BEGIN NOW Much pleasure we have lost, while we abstained END
BEGIN NOW From this delightful fruit, nor known till now END
BEGIN NOW True relish, tasting; if such pleasure be END
BEGIN NOW In things to us forbidden, it might be wished, END
BEGIN NOW For this one tree had been forbidden ten. END
BEGIN NOW But come, so well refreshed, now let us play, END
BEGIN NOW As meet is, after such delicious fare; END
BEGIN NOW For never did thy beauty, since the day END
BEGIN NOW I saw thee first and wedded thee, adorned END
BEGIN NOW With all perfections, so inflame my sense END
BEGIN NOW With ardour to enjoy thee, fairer now END
BEGIN NOW Than ever; bounty of this virtuous tree! END
BEGIN NOW So said he, and forbore not glance or toy END
BEGIN NOW Of amorous intent; well understood END
BEGIN NOW Of Eve, whose eye darted contagious fire. END
BEGIN NOW Her hand he seised; and to a shady bank, END
BEGIN NOW Thick over-head with verdant roof imbowered, END
BEGIN NOW He led her nothing loth; flowers were the couch, END
BEGIN NOW Pansies, and violets, and asphodel, END
BEGIN NOW And hyacinth; Earth's freshest softest lap. END
BEGIN NOW There they their fill of love and love's disport END
BEGIN NOW Took largely, of their mutual guilt the seal, END
BEGIN NOW The solace of their sin; till dewy sleep END
BEGIN NOW Oppressed them, wearied with their amorous play, END
BEGIN NOW Soon as the force of that fallacious fruit, END
BEGIN NOW That with exhilarating vapour bland END
BEGIN NOW About their spirits had played, and inmost powers END
BEGIN NOW Made err, was now exhaled; and grosser sleep, END
BEGIN NOW Bred of unkindly fumes, with conscious dreams END
BEGIN NOW Incumbered, now had left them; up they rose END
BEGIN NOW As from unrest; and, each the other viewing, END
BEGIN NOW Soon found their eyes how opened, and their minds END
BEGIN NOW How darkened; innocence, that as a veil END
BEGIN NOW Had shadowed them from knowing ill, was gone; END
BEGIN NOW Just confidence, and native righteousness, END
BEGIN NOW And honour, from about them, naked left END
BEGIN NOW To guilty Shame; he covered, but his robe END
BEGIN NOW Uncovered more. So rose the Danite strong, END
BEGIN NOW Herculean Samson, from the harlot-lap END
BEGIN NOW Of Philistean Dalilah, and waked END
BEGIN NOW Shorn of his strength. They destitute and bare END
BEGIN NOW Of all their virtue: Silent, and in face END
BEGIN NOW Confounded, long they sat, as strucken mute: END
BEGIN NOW Till Adam, though not less than Eve abashed, END
BEGIN NOW At length gave utterance to these words constrained. END
BEGIN NOW O Eve, in evil hour thou didst give ear END
BEGIN NOW To that false worm, of whomsoever taught END
BEGIN NOW To counterfeit Man's voice; true in our fall, END
BEGIN NOW False in our promised rising; since our eyes END
BEGIN NOW Opened we find indeed, and find we know END
BEGIN NOW Both good and evil; good lost, and evil got; END
BEGIN NOW Bad fruit of knowledge, if this be to know; END
BEGIN NOW Which leaves us naked thus, of honour void, END
BEGIN NOW Of innocence, of faith, of purity, END
BEGIN NOW Our wonted ornaments now soiled and stained, END
BEGIN NOW And in our faces evident the signs END
BEGIN NOW Of foul concupiscence; whence evil store; END
BEGIN NOW Even shame, the last of evils; of the first END
BEGIN NOW Be sure then.--How shall I behold the face END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth of God or Angel, erst with joy END
BEGIN NOW And rapture so oft beheld? Those heavenly shapes END
BEGIN NOW Will dazzle now this earthly with their blaze END
BEGIN NOW Insufferably bright. O! might I here END
BEGIN NOW In solitude live savage; in some glade END
BEGIN NOW Obscured, where highest woods, impenetrable END
BEGIN NOW To star or sun-light, spread their umbrage broad END
BEGIN NOW And brown as evening: Cover me, ye Pines! END
BEGIN NOW Ye Cedars, with innumerable boughs END
BEGIN NOW Hide me, where I may never see them more!-- END
BEGIN NOW But let us now, as in bad plight, devise END
BEGIN NOW What best may for the present serve to hide END
BEGIN NOW The parts of each from other, that seem most END
BEGIN NOW To shame obnoxious, and unseemliest seen; END
BEGIN NOW Some tree, whose broad smooth leaves together sewed, END
BEGIN NOW And girded on our loins, may cover round END
BEGIN NOW Those middle parts; that this new comer, Shame, END
BEGIN NOW There sit not, and reproach us as unclean. END
BEGIN NOW So counselled he, and both together went END
BEGIN NOW Into the thickest wood; there soon they chose END
BEGIN NOW The fig-tree; not that kind for fruit renowned, END
BEGIN NOW But such as at this day, to Indians known, END
BEGIN NOW In Malabar or Decan spreads her arms END
BEGIN NOW Branching so broad and long, that in the ground END
BEGIN NOW The bended twigs take root, and daughters grow END
BEGIN NOW About the mother tree, a pillared shade END
BEGIN NOW High over-arched, and echoing walks between: END
BEGIN NOW There oft the Indian herdsman, shunning heat, END
BEGIN NOW Shelters in cool, and tends his pasturing herds END
BEGIN NOW At loop-holes cut through thickest shade: Those leaves END
BEGIN NOW They gathered, broad as Amazonian targe; END
BEGIN NOW And, with what skill they had, together sewed, END
BEGIN NOW To gird their waist; vain covering, if to hide END
BEGIN NOW Their guilt and dreaded shame! O, how unlike END
BEGIN NOW To that first naked glory! Such of late END
BEGIN NOW Columbus found the American, so girt END
BEGIN NOW With feathered cincture; naked else, and wild END
BEGIN NOW Among the trees on isles and woody shores. END
BEGIN NOW Thus fenced, and, as they thought, their shame in part END
BEGIN NOW Covered, but not at rest or ease of mind, END
BEGIN NOW They sat them down to weep; nor only tears END
BEGIN NOW Rained at their eyes, but high winds worse within END
BEGIN NOW Began to rise, high passions, anger, hate, END
BEGIN NOW Mistrust, suspicion, discord; and shook sore END
BEGIN NOW Their inward state of mind, calm region once END
BEGIN NOW And full of peace, now tost and turbulent: END
BEGIN NOW For Understanding ruled not, and the Will END
BEGIN NOW Heard not her lore; both in subjection now END
BEGIN NOW To sensual Appetite, who from beneath END
BEGIN NOW Usurping over sovran Reason claimed END
BEGIN NOW Superiour sway: From thus distempered breast, END
BEGIN NOW Adam, estranged in look and altered style, END
BEGIN NOW Speech intermitted thus to Eve renewed. END
BEGIN NOW Would thou hadst hearkened to my words, and staid END
BEGIN NOW With me, as I besought thee, when that strange END
BEGIN NOW Desire of wandering, this unhappy morn, END
BEGIN NOW I know not whence possessed thee; we had then END
BEGIN NOW Remained still happy; not, as now, despoiled END
BEGIN NOW Of all our good; shamed, naked, miserable! END
BEGIN NOW Let none henceforth seek needless cause to approve END
BEGIN NOW The faith they owe; when earnestly they seek END
BEGIN NOW Such proof, conclude, they then begin to fail. END
BEGIN NOW To whom, soon moved with touch of blame, thus Eve. END
BEGIN NOW What words have passed thy lips, Adam severe! END
BEGIN NOW Imputest thou that to my default, or will END
BEGIN NOW Of wandering, as thou callest it, which who knows END
BEGIN NOW But might as ill have happened thou being by, END
BEGIN NOW Or to thyself perhaps? Hadst thou been there, END
BEGIN NOW Or here the attempt, thou couldst not have discerned END
BEGIN NOW Fraud in the Serpent, speaking as he spake; END
BEGIN NOW No ground of enmity between us known, END
BEGIN NOW Why he should mean me ill, or seek to harm. END
BEGIN NOW Was I to have never parted from thy side? END
BEGIN NOW As good have grown there still a lifeless rib. END
BEGIN NOW Being as I am, why didst not thou, the head, END
BEGIN NOW Command me absolutely not to go, END
BEGIN NOW Going into such danger, as thou saidst? END
BEGIN NOW Too facile then, thou didst not much gainsay; END
BEGIN NOW Nay, didst permit, approve, and fair dismiss. END
BEGIN NOW Hadst thou been firm and fixed in thy dissent, END
BEGIN NOW Neither had I transgressed, nor thou with me. END
BEGIN NOW To whom, then first incensed, Adam replied. END
BEGIN NOW Is this the love, is this the recompence END
BEGIN NOW Of mine to thee, ingrateful Eve! expressed END
BEGIN NOW Immutable, when thou wert lost, not I; END
BEGIN NOW Who might have lived, and joyed immortal bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Yet willingly chose rather death with thee? END
BEGIN NOW And am I now upbraided as the cause END
BEGIN NOW Of thy transgressing? Not enough severe, END
BEGIN NOW It seems, in thy restraint: What could I more END
BEGIN NOW I warned thee, I admonished thee, foretold END
BEGIN NOW The danger, and the lurking enemy END
BEGIN NOW That lay in wait; beyond this, had been force; END
BEGIN NOW And force upon free will hath here no place. END
BEGIN NOW But confidence then bore thee on; secure END
BEGIN NOW Either to meet no danger, or to find END
BEGIN NOW Matter of glorious trial; and perhaps END
BEGIN NOW I also erred, in overmuch admiring END
BEGIN NOW What seemed in thee so perfect, that I thought END
BEGIN NOW No evil durst attempt thee; but I rue END
BEGIN NOW The errour now, which is become my crime, END
BEGIN NOW And thou the accuser. Thus it shall befall END
BEGIN NOW Him, who, to worth in women overtrusting, END
BEGIN NOW Lets her will rule: restraint she will not brook; END
BEGIN NOW And, left to herself, if evil thence ensue, END
BEGIN NOW She first his weak indulgence will accuse. END
BEGIN NOW Thus they in mutual accusation spent END
BEGIN NOW The fruitless hours, but neither self-condemning; END
BEGIN NOW And of their vain contest appeared no end. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while the heinous and despiteful act END
BEGIN NOW Of Satan, done in Paradise; and how END
BEGIN NOW He, in the serpent, had perverted Eve, END
BEGIN NOW Her husband she, to taste the fatal fruit, END
BEGIN NOW Was known in Heaven; for what can 'scape the eye END
BEGIN NOW Of God all-seeing, or deceive his heart END
BEGIN NOW Omniscient? who, in all things wise and just, END
BEGIN NOW Hindered not Satan to attempt the mind END
BEGIN NOW Of Man, with strength entire and free will armed, END
BEGIN NOW Complete to have discovered and repulsed END
BEGIN NOW Whatever wiles of foe or seeming friend. END
BEGIN NOW For still they knew, and ought to have still remembered, END
BEGIN NOW The high injunction, not to taste that fruit, END
BEGIN NOW Whoever tempted; which they not obeying, END
BEGIN NOW (Incurred what could they less?) the penalty; END
BEGIN NOW And, manifold in sin, deserved to fall. END
BEGIN NOW Up into Heaven from Paradise in haste END
BEGIN NOW The angelick guards ascended, mute, and sad, END
BEGIN NOW For Man; for of his state by this they knew, END
BEGIN NOW Much wondering how the subtle Fiend had stolen END
BEGIN NOW Entrance unseen. Soon as the unwelcome news END
BEGIN NOW From Earth arrived at Heaven-gate, displeased END
BEGIN NOW All were who heard; dim sadness did not spare END
BEGIN NOW That time celestial visages, yet, mixed END
BEGIN NOW With pity, violated not their bliss. END
BEGIN NOW About the new-arrived, in multitudes END
BEGIN NOW The ethereal people ran, to hear and know END
BEGIN NOW How all befel: They towards the throne supreme, END
BEGIN NOW Accountable, made haste, to make appear, END
BEGIN NOW With righteous plea, their utmost vigilance END
BEGIN NOW And easily approved; when the Most High END
BEGIN NOW Eternal Father, from his secret cloud, END
BEGIN NOW Amidst in thunder uttered thus his voice. END
BEGIN NOW Assembled Angels, and ye Powers returned END
BEGIN NOW From unsuccessful charge; be not dismayed, END
BEGIN NOW Nor troubled at these tidings from the earth, END
BEGIN NOW Which your sincerest care could not prevent; END
BEGIN NOW Foretold so lately what would come to pass, END
BEGIN NOW When first this tempter crossed the gulf from Hell. END
BEGIN NOW I told ye then he should prevail, and speed END
BEGIN NOW On his bad errand; Man should be seduced, END
BEGIN NOW And flattered out of all, believing lies END
BEGIN NOW Against his Maker; no decree of mine END
BEGIN NOW Concurring to necessitate his fall, END
BEGIN NOW Or touch with lightest moment of impulse END
BEGIN NOW His free will, to her own inclining left END
BEGIN NOW In even scale. But fallen he is; and now END
BEGIN NOW What rests, but that the mortal sentence pass END
BEGIN NOW On his transgression,--death denounced that day? END
BEGIN NOW Which he presumes already vain and void, END
BEGIN NOW Because not yet inflicted, as he feared, END
BEGIN NOW By some immediate stroke; but soon shall find END
BEGIN NOW Forbearance no acquittance, ere day end. END
BEGIN NOW Justice shall not return as bounty scorned. END
BEGIN NOW But whom send I to judge them? whom but thee, END
BEGIN NOW Vicegerent Son? To thee I have transferred END
BEGIN NOW All judgement, whether in Heaven, or Earth, or Hell. END
BEGIN NOW Easy it may be seen that I intend END
BEGIN NOW Mercy colleague with justice, sending thee END
BEGIN NOW Man's friend, his Mediator, his designed END
BEGIN NOW Both ransom and Redeemer voluntary, END
BEGIN NOW And destined Man himself to judge Man fallen. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Father; and, unfolding bright END
BEGIN NOW Toward the right hand his glory, on the Son END
BEGIN NOW Blazed forth unclouded Deity: He full END
BEGIN NOW Resplendent all his Father manifest END
BEGIN NOW Expressed, and thus divinely answered mild. END
BEGIN NOW Father Eternal, thine is to decree; END
BEGIN NOW Mine, both in Heaven and Earth, to do thy will END
BEGIN NOW Supreme; that thou in me, thy Son beloved, END
BEGIN NOW Mayest ever rest well pleased. I go to judge END
BEGIN NOW On earth these thy transgressours; but thou knowest, END
BEGIN NOW Whoever judged, the worst on me must light, END
BEGIN NOW When time shall be; for so I undertook END
BEGIN NOW Before thee; and, not repenting, this obtain END
BEGIN NOW Of right, that I may mitigate their doom END
BEGIN NOW On me derived; yet I shall temper so END
BEGIN NOW Justice with mercy, as may illustrate most END
BEGIN NOW Them fully satisfied, and thee appease. END
BEGIN NOW Attendance none shall need, nor train, where none END
BEGIN NOW Are to behold the judgement, but the judged, END
BEGIN NOW Those two; the third best absent is condemned, END
BEGIN NOW Convict by flight, and rebel to all law: END
BEGIN NOW Conviction to the serpent none belongs. END
BEGIN NOW Thus saying, from his radiant seat he rose END
BEGIN NOW Of high collateral glory: Him Thrones, and Powers, END
BEGIN NOW Princedoms, and Dominations ministrant, END
BEGIN NOW Accompanied to Heaven-gate; from whence END
BEGIN NOW Eden, and all the coast, in prospect lay. END
BEGIN NOW Down he descended straight; the speed of Gods END
BEGIN NOW Time counts not, though with swiftest minutes winged. END
BEGIN NOW Now was the sun in western cadence low END
BEGIN NOW From noon, and gentle airs, due at their hour, END
BEGIN NOW To fan the earth now waked, and usher in END
BEGIN NOW The evening cool; when he, from wrath more cool, END
BEGIN NOW Came the mild Judge, and Intercessour both, END
BEGIN NOW To sentence Man: The voice of God they heard END
BEGIN NOW Now walking in the garden, by soft winds END
BEGIN NOW Brought to their ears, while day declined; they heard, END
BEGIN NOW And from his presence hid themselves among END
BEGIN NOW The thickest trees, both man and wife; till God, END
BEGIN NOW Approaching, thus to Adam called aloud. END
BEGIN NOW Where art thou, Adam, wont with joy to meet END
BEGIN NOW My coming seen far off? I miss thee here, END
BEGIN NOW Not pleased, thus entertained with solitude, END
BEGIN NOW Where obvious duty ere while appeared unsought: END
BEGIN NOW Or come I less conspicuous, or what change END
BEGIN NOW Absents thee, or what chance detains?--Come forth! END
BEGIN NOW He came; and with him Eve, more loth, though first END
BEGIN NOW To offend; discountenanced both, and discomposed; END
BEGIN NOW Love was not in their looks, either to God, END
BEGIN NOW Or to each other; but apparent guilt, END
BEGIN NOW And shame, and perturbation, and despair, END
BEGIN NOW Anger, and obstinacy, and hate, and guile. END
BEGIN NOW Whence Adam, faltering long, thus answered brief. END
BEGIN NOW I heard thee in the garden, and of thy voice END
BEGIN NOW Afraid, being naked, hid myself. To whom END
BEGIN NOW The gracious Judge without revile replied. END
BEGIN NOW My voice thou oft hast heard, and hast not feared, END
BEGIN NOW But still rejoiced; how is it now become END
BEGIN NOW So dreadful to thee? That thou art naked, who END
BEGIN NOW Hath told thee? Hast thou eaten of the tree, END
BEGIN NOW Whereof I gave thee charge thou shouldst not eat? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Adam sore beset replied. END
BEGIN NOW O Heaven! in evil strait this day I stand END
BEGIN NOW Before my Judge; either to undergo END
BEGIN NOW Myself the total crime, or to accuse END
BEGIN NOW My other self, the partner of my life; END
BEGIN NOW Whose failing, while her faith to me remains, END
BEGIN NOW I should conceal, and not expose to blame END
BEGIN NOW By my complaint: but strict necessity END
BEGIN NOW Subdues me, and calamitous constraint; END
BEGIN NOW Lest on my head both sin and punishment, END
BEGIN NOW However insupportable, be all END
BEGIN NOW Devolved; though should I hold my peace, yet thou END
BEGIN NOW Wouldst easily detect what I conceal.-- END
BEGIN NOW This Woman, whom thou madest to be my help, END
BEGIN NOW And gavest me as thy perfect gift, so good, END
BEGIN NOW So fit, so acceptable, so divine, END
BEGIN NOW That from her hand I could suspect no ill, END
BEGIN NOW And what she did, whatever in itself, END
BEGIN NOW Her doing seemed to justify the deed; END
BEGIN NOW She gave me of the tree, and I did eat. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Sovran Presence thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW Was she thy God, that her thou didst obey END
BEGIN NOW Before his voice? or was she made thy guide, END
BEGIN NOW Superiour, or but equal, that to her END
BEGIN NOW Thou didst resign thy manhood, and the place END
BEGIN NOW Wherein God set thee above her made of thee, END
BEGIN NOW And for thee, whose perfection far excelled END
BEGIN NOW Hers in all real dignity? Adorned END
BEGIN NOW She was indeed, and lovely, to attract END
BEGIN NOW Thy love, not thy subjection; and her gifts END
BEGIN NOW Were such, as under government well seemed; END
BEGIN NOW Unseemly to bear rule; which was thy part END
BEGIN NOW And person, hadst thou known thyself aright. END
BEGIN NOW So having said, he thus to Eve in few. END
BEGIN NOW Say, Woman, what is this which thou hast done? END
BEGIN NOW To whom sad Eve, with shame nigh overwhelmed, END
BEGIN NOW Confessing soon, yet not before her Judge END
BEGIN NOW Bold or loquacious, thus abashed replied. END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent me beguiled, and I did eat. END
BEGIN NOW Which when the Lord God heard, without delay END
BEGIN NOW To judgement he proceeded on the accused END
BEGIN NOW Serpent, though brute; unable to transfer END
BEGIN NOW The guilt on him, who made him instrument END
BEGIN NOW Of mischief, and polluted from the end END
BEGIN NOW Of his creation; justly then accursed, END
BEGIN NOW As vitiated in nature: More to know END
BEGIN NOW Concerned not Man, (since he no further knew) END
BEGIN NOW Nor altered his offence; yet God at last END
BEGIN NOW To Satan first in sin his doom applied, END
BEGIN NOW Though in mysterious terms, judged as then best: END
BEGIN NOW And on the Serpent thus his curse let fall. END
BEGIN NOW Because thou hast done this, thou art accursed END
BEGIN NOW Above all cattle, each beast of the field; END
BEGIN NOW Upon thy belly groveling thou shalt go, END
BEGIN NOW And dust shalt eat all the days of thy life. END
BEGIN NOW Between thee and the woman I will put END
BEGIN NOW Enmity, and between thine and her seed; END
BEGIN NOW Her seed shall bruise thy head, thou bruise his heel. END
BEGIN NOW So spake this oracle, then verified END
BEGIN NOW When Jesus, Son of Mary, second Eve, END
BEGIN NOW Saw Satan fall, like lightning, down from Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Prince of the air; then, rising from his grave END
BEGIN NOW Spoiled Principalities and Powers, triumphed END
BEGIN NOW In open show; and, with ascension bright, END
BEGIN NOW Captivity led captive through the air, END
BEGIN NOW The realm itself of Satan, long usurped; END
BEGIN NOW Whom he shall tread at last under our feet; END
BEGIN NOW Even he, who now foretold his fatal bruise; END
BEGIN NOW And to the Woman thus his sentence turned. END
BEGIN NOW Thy sorrow I will greatly multiply END
BEGIN NOW By thy conception; children thou shalt bring END
BEGIN NOW In sorrow forth; and to thy husband's will END
BEGIN NOW Thine shall submit; he over thee shall rule. END
BEGIN NOW On Adam last thus judgement he pronounced. END
BEGIN NOW Because thou hast hearkened to the voice of thy wife, END
BEGIN NOW And eaten of the tree, concerning which END
BEGIN NOW I charged thee, saying, Thou shalt not eat thereof: END
BEGIN NOW Cursed is the ground for thy sake; thou in sorrow END
BEGIN NOW Shalt eat thereof, all the days of thy life; END
BEGIN NOW Thorns also and thistles it shall bring thee forth END
BEGIN NOW Unbid; and thou shalt eat the herb of the field; END
BEGIN NOW In the sweat of thy face shalt thou eat bread, END
BEGIN NOW Till thou return unto the ground; for thou END
BEGIN NOW Out of the ground wast taken, know thy birth, END
BEGIN NOW For dust thou art, and shalt to dust return. END
BEGIN NOW So judged he Man, both Judge and Saviour sent; END
BEGIN NOW And the instant stroke of death, denounced that day, END
BEGIN NOW Removed far off; then, pitying how they stood END
BEGIN NOW Before him naked to the air, that now END
BEGIN NOW Must suffer change, disdained not to begin END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth the form of servant to assume; END
BEGIN NOW As when he washed his servants feet; so now, END
BEGIN NOW As father of his family, he clad END
BEGIN NOW Their nakedness with skins of beasts, or slain, END
BEGIN NOW Or as the snake with youthful coat repaid; END
BEGIN NOW And thought not much to clothe his enemies; END
BEGIN NOW Nor he their outward only with the skins END
BEGIN NOW Of beasts, but inward nakedness, much more. END
BEGIN NOW Opprobrious, with his robe of righteousness, END
BEGIN NOW Arraying, covered from his Father's sight. END
BEGIN NOW To him with swift ascent he up returned, END
BEGIN NOW Into his blissful bosom reassumed END
BEGIN NOW In glory, as of old; to him appeased END
BEGIN NOW All, though all-knowing, what had passed with Man END
BEGIN NOW Recounted, mixing intercession sweet. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while, ere thus was sinned and judged on Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Within the gates of Hell sat Sin and Death, END
BEGIN NOW In counterview within the gates, that now END
BEGIN NOW Stood open wide, belching outrageous flame END
BEGIN NOW Far into Chaos, since the Fiend passed through, END
BEGIN NOW Sin opening; who thus now to Death began. END
BEGIN NOW O Son, why sit we here each other viewing END
BEGIN NOW Idly, while Satan, our great author, thrives END
BEGIN NOW In other worlds, and happier seat provides END
BEGIN NOW For us, his offspring dear? It cannot be END
BEGIN NOW But that success attends him; if mishap, END
BEGIN NOW Ere this he had returned, with fury driven END
BEGIN NOW By his avengers; since no place like this END
BEGIN NOW Can fit his punishment, or their revenge. END
BEGIN NOW Methinks I feel new strength within me rise, END
BEGIN NOW Wings growing, and dominion given me large END
BEGIN NOW Beyond this deep; whatever draws me on, END
BEGIN NOW Or sympathy, or some connatural force, END
BEGIN NOW Powerful at greatest distance to unite, END
BEGIN NOW With secret amity, things of like kind, END
BEGIN NOW By secretest conveyance. Thou, my shade END
BEGIN NOW Inseparable, must with me along; END
BEGIN NOW For Death from Sin no power can separate. END
BEGIN NOW But, lest the difficulty of passing back END
BEGIN NOW Stay his return perhaps over this gulf END
BEGIN NOW Impassable, impervious; let us try END
BEGIN NOW Adventurous work, yet to thy power and mine END
BEGIN NOW Not unagreeable, to found a path END
BEGIN NOW Over this main from Hell to that new world, END
BEGIN NOW Where Satan now prevails; a monument END
BEGIN NOW Of merit high to all the infernal host, END
BEGIN NOW Easing their passage hence, for intercourse, END
BEGIN NOW Or transmigration, as their lot shall lead. END
BEGIN NOW Nor can I miss the way, so strongly drawn END
BEGIN NOW By this new-felt attraction and instinct. END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus the meager Shadow answered soon. END
BEGIN NOW Go, whither Fate, and inclination strong, END
BEGIN NOW Leads thee; I shall not lag behind, nor err END
BEGIN NOW The way, thou leading; such a scent I draw END
BEGIN NOW Of carnage, prey innumerable, and taste END
BEGIN NOW The savour of death from all things there that live: END
BEGIN NOW Nor shall I to the work thou enterprisest END
BEGIN NOW Be wanting, but afford thee equal aid. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, with delight he snuffed the smell END
BEGIN NOW Of mortal change on earth. As when a flock END
BEGIN NOW Of ravenous fowl, though many a league remote, END
BEGIN NOW Against the day of battle, to a field, END
BEGIN NOW Where armies lie encamped, come flying, lured END
BEGIN NOW With scent of living carcasses designed END
BEGIN NOW For death, the following day, in bloody fight: END
BEGIN NOW So scented the grim Feature, and upturned END
BEGIN NOW His nostril wide into the murky air; END
BEGIN NOW Sagacious of his quarry from so far. END
BEGIN NOW Then both from out Hell-gates, into the waste END
BEGIN NOW Wide anarchy of Chaos, damp and dark, END
BEGIN NOW Flew diverse; and with power (their power was great) END
BEGIN NOW Hovering upon the waters, what they met END
BEGIN NOW Solid or slimy, as in raging sea END
BEGIN NOW Tost up and down, together crouded drove, END
BEGIN NOW From each side shoaling towards the mouth of Hell; END
BEGIN NOW As when two polar winds, blowing adverse END
BEGIN NOW Upon the Cronian sea, together drive END
BEGIN NOW Mountains of ice, that stop the imagined way END
BEGIN NOW Beyond Petsora eastward, to the rich END
BEGIN NOW Cathaian coast. The aggregated soil END
BEGIN NOW Death with his mace petrifick, cold and dry, END
BEGIN NOW As with a trident, smote; and fixed as firm END
BEGIN NOW As Delos, floating once; the rest his look END
BEGIN NOW Bound with Gorgonian rigour not to move; END
BEGIN NOW And with Asphaltick slime, broad as the gate, END
BEGIN NOW Deep to the roots of Hell the gathered beach END
BEGIN NOW They fastened, and the mole immense wrought on END
BEGIN NOW Over the foaming deep high-arched, a bridge END
BEGIN NOW Of length prodigious, joining to the wall END
BEGIN NOW Immoveable of this now fenceless world, END
BEGIN NOW Forfeit to Death; from hence a passage broad, END
BEGIN NOW Smooth, easy, inoffensive, down to Hell. END
BEGIN NOW So, if great things to small may be compared, END
BEGIN NOW Xerxes, the liberty of Greece to yoke, END
BEGIN NOW From Susa, his Memnonian palace high, END
BEGIN NOW Came to the sea: and, over Hellespont END
BEGIN NOW Bridging his way, Europe with Asia joined, END
BEGIN NOW And scourged with many a stroke the indignant waves. END
BEGIN NOW Now had they brought the work by wonderous art END
BEGIN NOW Pontifical, a ridge of pendant rock, END
BEGIN NOW Over the vexed abyss, following the track END
BEGIN NOW Of Satan to the self-same place where he END
BEGIN NOW First lighted from his wing, and landed safe END
BEGIN NOW From out of Chaos, to the outside bare END
BEGIN NOW Of this round world: With pins of adamant END
BEGIN NOW And chains they made all fast, too fast they made END
BEGIN NOW And durable! And now in little space END
BEGIN NOW The confines met of empyrean Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW And of this World; and, on the left hand, Hell END
BEGIN NOW With long reach interposed; three several ways END
BEGIN NOW In sight, to each of these three places led. END
BEGIN NOW And now their way to Earth they had descried, END
BEGIN NOW To Paradise first tending; when, behold! END
BEGIN NOW Satan, in likeness of an Angel bright, END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the Centaur and the Scorpion steering END
BEGIN NOW His zenith, while the sun in Aries rose: END
BEGIN NOW Disguised he came; but those his children dear END
BEGIN NOW Their parent soon discerned, though in disguise. END
BEGIN NOW He, after Eve seduced, unminded slunk END
BEGIN NOW Into the wood fast by; and, changing shape, END
BEGIN NOW To observe the sequel, saw his guileful act END
BEGIN NOW By Eve, though all unweeting, seconded END
BEGIN NOW Upon her husband; saw their shame that sought END
BEGIN NOW Vain covertures; but when he saw descend END
BEGIN NOW The Son of God to judge them, terrified END
BEGIN NOW He fled; not hoping to escape, but shun END
BEGIN NOW The present; fearing, guilty, what his wrath END
BEGIN NOW Might suddenly inflict; that past, returned END
BEGIN NOW By night, and listening where the hapless pair END
BEGIN NOW Sat in their sad discourse, and various plaint, END
BEGIN NOW Thence gathered his own doom; which understood END
BEGIN NOW Not instant, but of future time, with joy END
BEGIN NOW And tidings fraught, to Hell he now returned; END
BEGIN NOW And at the brink of Chaos, near the foot END
BEGIN NOW Of this new wonderous pontifice, unhoped END
BEGIN NOW Met, who to meet him came, his offspring dear. END
BEGIN NOW Great joy was at their meeting, and at sight END
BEGIN NOW Of that stupendous bridge his joy encreased. END
BEGIN NOW Long he admiring stood, till Sin, his fair END
BEGIN NOW Enchanting daughter, thus the silence broke. END
BEGIN NOW O Parent, these are thy magnifick deeds, END
BEGIN NOW Thy trophies! which thou viewest as not thine own; END
BEGIN NOW Thou art their author, and prime architect: END
BEGIN NOW For I no sooner in my heart divined, END
BEGIN NOW My heart, which by a secret harmony END
BEGIN NOW Still moves with thine, joined in connexion sweet, END
BEGIN NOW That thou on earth hadst prospered, which thy looks END
BEGIN NOW Now also evidence, but straight I felt, END
BEGIN NOW Though distant from thee worlds between, yet felt, END
BEGIN NOW That I must after thee, with this thy son; END
BEGIN NOW Such fatal consequence unites us three! END
BEGIN NOW Hell could no longer hold us in our bounds, END
BEGIN NOW Nor this unvoyageable gulf obscure END
BEGIN NOW Detain from following thy illustrious track. END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast achieved our liberty, confined END
BEGIN NOW Within Hell-gates till now; thou us impowered END
BEGIN NOW To fortify thus far, and overlay, END
BEGIN NOW With this portentous bridge, the dark abyss. END
BEGIN NOW Thine now is all this world; thy virtue hath won END
BEGIN NOW What thy hands builded not; thy wisdom gained END
BEGIN NOW With odds what war hath lost, and fully avenged END
BEGIN NOW Our foil in Heaven; here thou shalt monarch reign, END
BEGIN NOW There didst not; there let him still victor sway, END
BEGIN NOW As battle hath adjudged; from this new world END
BEGIN NOW Retiring, by his own doom alienated; END
BEGIN NOW And henceforth monarchy with thee divide END
BEGIN NOW Of all things, parted by the empyreal bounds, END
BEGIN NOW His quadrature, from thy orbicular world; END
BEGIN NOW Or try thee now more dangerous to his throne. END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus the Prince of darkness answered glad. END
BEGIN NOW Fair Daughter, and thou Son and Grandchild both; END
BEGIN NOW High proof ye now have given to be the race END
BEGIN NOW Of Satan (for I glory in the name, END
BEGIN NOW Antagonist of Heaven's Almighty King,) END
BEGIN NOW Amply have merited of me, of all END
BEGIN NOW The infernal empire, that so near Heaven's door END
BEGIN NOW Triumphal with triumphal act have met, END
BEGIN NOW Mine, with this glorious work; and made one realm, END
BEGIN NOW Hell and this world, one realm, one continent END
BEGIN NOW Of easy thorough-fare. Therefore, while I END
BEGIN NOW Descend through darkness, on your road with ease, END
BEGIN NOW To my associate Powers, them to acquaint END
BEGIN NOW With these successes, and with them rejoice; END
BEGIN NOW You two this way, among these numerous orbs, END
BEGIN NOW All yours, right down to Paradise descend; END
BEGIN NOW There dwell, and reign in bliss; thence on the earth END
BEGIN NOW Dominion exercise and in the air, END
BEGIN NOW Chiefly on Man, sole lord of all declared; END
BEGIN NOW Him first make sure your thrall, and lastly kill. END
BEGIN NOW My substitutes I send ye, and create END
BEGIN NOW Plenipotent on earth, of matchless might END
BEGIN NOW Issuing from me: on your joint vigour now END
BEGIN NOW My hold of this new kingdom all depends, END
BEGIN NOW Through Sin to Death exposed by my exploit. END
BEGIN NOW If your joint power prevail, the affairs of Hell END
BEGIN NOW No detriment need fear; go, and be strong! END
BEGIN NOW So saying he dismissed them; they with speed END
BEGIN NOW Their course through thickest constellations held, END
BEGIN NOW Spreading their bane; the blasted stars looked wan, END
BEGIN NOW And planets, planet-struck, real eclipse END
BEGIN NOW Then suffered. The other way Satan went down END
BEGIN NOW The causey to Hell-gate: On either side END
BEGIN NOW Disparted Chaos overbuilt exclaimed, END
BEGIN NOW And with rebounding surge the bars assailed, END
BEGIN NOW That scorned his indignation: Through the gate, END
BEGIN NOW Wide open and unguarded, Satan passed, END
BEGIN NOW And all about found desolate; for those, END
BEGIN NOW Appointed to sit there, had left their charge, END
BEGIN NOW Flown to the upper world; the rest were all END
BEGIN NOW Far to the inland retired, about the walls END
BEGIN NOW Of Pandemonium; city and proud seat END
BEGIN NOW Of Lucifer, so by allusion called END
BEGIN NOW Of that bright star to Satan paragoned; END
BEGIN NOW There kept their watch the legions, while the Grand END
BEGIN NOW In council sat, solicitous what chance END
BEGIN NOW Might intercept their emperour sent; so he END
BEGIN NOW Departing gave command, and they observed. END
BEGIN NOW As when the Tartar from his Russian foe, END
BEGIN NOW By Astracan, over the snowy plains, END
BEGIN NOW Retires; or Bactrin Sophi, from the horns END
BEGIN NOW Of Turkish crescent, leaves all waste beyond END
BEGIN NOW The realm of Aladule, in his retreat END
BEGIN NOW To Tauris or Casbeen: So these, the late END
BEGIN NOW Heaven-banished host, left desart utmost Hell END
BEGIN NOW Many a dark league, reduced in careful watch END
BEGIN NOW Round their metropolis; and now expecting END
BEGIN NOW Each hour their great adventurer, from the search END
BEGIN NOW Of foreign worlds: He through the midst unmarked, END
BEGIN NOW In show plebeian Angel militant END
BEGIN NOW Of lowest order, passed; and from the door END
BEGIN NOW Of that Plutonian hall, invisible END
BEGIN NOW Ascended his high throne; which, under state END
BEGIN NOW Of richest texture spread, at the upper end END
BEGIN NOW Was placed in regal lustre. Down a while END
BEGIN NOW He sat, and round about him saw unseen: END
BEGIN NOW At last, as from a cloud, his fulgent head END
BEGIN NOW And shape star-bright appeared, or brighter; clad END
BEGIN NOW With what permissive glory since his fall END
BEGIN NOW Was left him, or false glitter: All amazed END
BEGIN NOW At that so sudden blaze the Stygian throng END
BEGIN NOW Bent their aspect, and whom they wished beheld, END
BEGIN NOW Their mighty Chief returned: loud was the acclaim: END
BEGIN NOW Forth rushed in haste the great consulting peers, END
BEGIN NOW Raised from their dark Divan, and with like joy END
BEGIN NOW Congratulant approached him; who with hand END
BEGIN NOW Silence, and with these words attention, won. END
BEGIN NOW For in possession such, not only of right, END
BEGIN NOW I call ye, and declare ye now; returned END
BEGIN NOW Successful beyond hope, to lead ye forth END
BEGIN NOW Triumphant out of this infernal pit END
BEGIN NOW Abominable, accursed, the house of woe, END
BEGIN NOW And dungeon of our tyrant: Now possess, END
BEGIN NOW As Lords, a spacious world, to our native Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Little inferiour, by my adventure hard END
BEGIN NOW With peril great achieved. Long were to tell END
BEGIN NOW What I have done; what suffered; with what pain END
BEGIN NOW Voyaged th' unreal, vast, unbounded deep END
BEGIN NOW Of horrible confusion; over which END
BEGIN NOW By Sin and Death a broad way now is paved, END
BEGIN NOW To expedite your glorious march; but I END
BEGIN NOW Toiled out my uncouth passage, forced to ride END
BEGIN NOW The untractable abyss, plunged in the womb END
BEGIN NOW Of unoriginal Night and Chaos wild; END
BEGIN NOW That, jealous of their secrets, fiercely opposed END
BEGIN NOW My journey strange, with clamorous uproar END
BEGIN NOW Protesting Fate supreme; thence how I found END
BEGIN NOW The new created world, which fame in Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Long had foretold, a fabrick wonderful END
BEGIN NOW Of absolute perfection! therein Man END
BEGIN NOW Placed in a Paradise, by our exile END
BEGIN NOW Made happy: Him by fraud I have seduced END
BEGIN NOW From his Creator; and, the more to encrease END
BEGIN NOW Your wonder, with an apple; he, thereat END
BEGIN NOW Offended, worth your laughter! hath given up END
BEGIN NOW Both his beloved Man, and all his world, END
BEGIN NOW To Sin and Death a prey, and so to us, END
BEGIN NOW Without our hazard, labour, or alarm; END
BEGIN NOW To range in, and to dwell, and over Man END
BEGIN NOW To rule, as over all he should have ruled. END
BEGIN NOW True is, me also he hath judged, or rather END
BEGIN NOW Me not, but the brute serpent in whose shape END
BEGIN NOW Man I deceived: that which to me belongs, END
BEGIN NOW Is enmity which he will put between END
BEGIN NOW Me and mankind; I am to bruise his heel; END
BEGIN NOW His seed, when is not set, shall bruise my head: END
BEGIN NOW A world who would not purchase with a bruise, END
BEGIN NOW Or much more grievous pain?--Ye have the account END
BEGIN NOW Of my performance: What remains, ye Gods, END
BEGIN NOW But up, and enter now into full bliss? END
BEGIN NOW So having said, a while he stood, expecting END
BEGIN NOW Their universal shout, and high applause, END
BEGIN NOW To fill his ear; when, contrary, he hears END
BEGIN NOW On all sides, from innumerable tongues, END
BEGIN NOW A dismal universal hiss, the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of publick scorn; he wondered, but not long END
BEGIN NOW Had leisure, wondering at himself now more, END
BEGIN NOW His visage drawn he felt to sharp and spare; END
BEGIN NOW His arms clung to his ribs; his legs entwining END
BEGIN NOW Each other, till supplanted down he fell END
BEGIN NOW A monstrous serpent on his belly prone, END
BEGIN NOW Reluctant, but in vain; a greater power END
BEGIN NOW Now ruled him, punished in the shape he sinned, END
BEGIN NOW According to his doom: he would have spoke, END
BEGIN NOW But hiss for hiss returned with forked tongue END
BEGIN NOW To forked tongue; for now were all transformed END
BEGIN NOW Alike, to serpents all, as accessories END
BEGIN NOW To his bold riot: Dreadful was the din END
BEGIN NOW Of hissing through the hall, thick swarming now END
BEGIN NOW With complicated monsters head and tail, END
BEGIN NOW Scorpion, and Asp, and Amphisbaena dire, END
BEGIN NOW Cerastes horned, Hydrus, and Elops drear, END
BEGIN NOW And Dipsas; (not so thick swarmed once the soil END
BEGIN NOW Bedropt with blood of Gorgon, or the isle END
BEGIN NOW Ophiusa,) but still greatest he the midst, END
BEGIN NOW Now Dragon grown, larger than whom the sun END
BEGIN NOW Ingendered in the Pythian vale or slime, END
BEGIN NOW Huge Python, and his power no less he seemed END
BEGIN NOW Above the rest still to retain; they all END
BEGIN NOW Him followed, issuing forth to the open field, END
BEGIN NOW Where all yet left of that revolted rout, END
BEGIN NOW Heaven-fallen, in station stood or just array; END
BEGIN NOW Sublime with expectation when to see END
BEGIN NOW In triumph issuing forth their glorious Chief; END
BEGIN NOW They saw, but other sight instead! a croud END
BEGIN NOW Of ugly serpents; horrour on them fell, END
BEGIN NOW And horrid sympathy; for, what they saw, END
BEGIN NOW They felt themselves, now changing; down their arms, END
BEGIN NOW Down fell both spear and shield; down they as fast; END
BEGIN NOW And the dire hiss renewed, and the dire form END
BEGIN NOW Catched, by contagion; like in punishment, END
BEGIN NOW As in their crime. Thus was the applause they meant, END
BEGIN NOW Turned to exploding hiss, triumph to shame END
BEGIN NOW Cast on themselves from their own mouths. There stood END
BEGIN NOW A grove hard by, sprung up with this their change, END
BEGIN NOW His will who reigns above, to aggravate END
BEGIN NOW Their penance, laden with fair fruit, like that END
BEGIN NOW Which grew in Paradise, the bait of Eve END
BEGIN NOW Used by the Tempter: on that prospect strange END
BEGIN NOW Their earnest eyes they fixed, imagining END
BEGIN NOW For one forbidden tree a multitude END
BEGIN NOW Now risen, to work them further woe or shame; END
BEGIN NOW Yet, parched with scalding thirst and hunger fierce, END
BEGIN NOW Though to delude them sent, could not abstain; END
BEGIN NOW But on they rolled in heaps, and, up the trees END
BEGIN NOW Climbing, sat thicker than the snaky locks END
BEGIN NOW That curled Megaera: greedily they plucked END
BEGIN NOW The fruitage fair to sight, like that which grew END
BEGIN NOW Near that bituminous lake where Sodom flamed; END
BEGIN NOW This more delusive, not the touch, but taste END
BEGIN NOW Deceived; they, fondly thinking to allay END
BEGIN NOW Their appetite with gust, instead of fruit END
BEGIN NOW Chewed bitter ashes, which the offended taste END
BEGIN NOW With spattering noise rejected: oft they assayed, END
BEGIN NOW Hunger and thirst constraining; drugged as oft, END
BEGIN NOW With hatefullest disrelish writhed their jaws, END
BEGIN NOW With soot and cinders filled; so oft they fell END
BEGIN NOW Into the same illusion, not as Man END
BEGIN NOW Whom they triumphed once lapsed. Thus were they plagued END
BEGIN NOW And worn with famine, long and ceaseless hiss, END
BEGIN NOW Till their lost shape, permitted, they resumed; END
BEGIN NOW Yearly enjoined, some say, to undergo, END
BEGIN NOW This annual humbling certain numbered days, END
BEGIN NOW To dash their pride, and joy, for Man seduced. END
BEGIN NOW However, some tradition they dispersed END
BEGIN NOW Among the Heathen, of their purchase got, END
BEGIN NOW And fabled how the Serpent, whom they called END
BEGIN NOW Ophion, with Eurynome, the wide-- END
BEGIN NOW Encroaching Eve perhaps, had first the rule END
BEGIN NOW Of high Olympus; thence by Saturn driven END
BEGIN NOW And Ops, ere yet Dictaean Jove was born. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while in Paradise the hellish pair END
BEGIN NOW Too soon arrived; Sin, there in power before, END
BEGIN NOW Once actual; now in body, and to dwell END
BEGIN NOW Habitual habitant; behind her Death, END
BEGIN NOW Close following pace for pace, not mounted yet END
BEGIN NOW On his pale horse: to whom Sin thus began. END
BEGIN NOW Second of Satan sprung, all-conquering Death! END
BEGIN NOW What thinkest thou of our empire now, though earned END
BEGIN NOW With travel difficult, not better far END
BEGIN NOW Than still at Hell's dark threshold to have sat watch, END
BEGIN NOW Unnamed, undreaded, and thyself half starved? END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus the Sin-born monster answered soon. END
BEGIN NOW To me, who with eternal famine pine, END
BEGIN NOW There best, where most with ravine I may meet; END
BEGIN NOW Which here, though plenteous, all too little seems END
BEGIN NOW To stuff this maw, this vast unhide-bound corps. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the incestuous mother thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW Thou therefore on these herbs, and fruits, and flowers, END
BEGIN NOW Feed first; on each beast next, and fish, and fowl; END
BEGIN NOW No homely morsels! and, whatever thing END
BEGIN NOW The sithe of Time mows down, devour unspared; END
BEGIN NOW Till I, in Man residing, through the race, END
BEGIN NOW His thoughts, his looks, words, actions, all infect; END
BEGIN NOW And season him thy last and sweetest prey. END
BEGIN NOW This said, they both betook them several ways, END
BEGIN NOW Both to destroy, or unimmortal make END
BEGIN NOW All kinds, and for destruction to mature END
BEGIN NOW Sooner or later; which the Almighty seeing, END
BEGIN NOW From his transcendent seat the Saints among, END
BEGIN NOW To those bright Orders uttered thus his voice. END
BEGIN NOW See, with what heat these dogs of Hell advance END
BEGIN NOW To waste and havock yonder world, which I END
BEGIN NOW So fair and good created; and had still END
BEGIN NOW Kept in that state, had not the folly of Man END
BEGIN NOW Let in these wasteful furies, who impute END
BEGIN NOW Folly to me; so doth the Prince of Hell END
BEGIN NOW And his adherents, that with so much ease END
BEGIN NOW I suffer them to enter and possess END
BEGIN NOW A place so heavenly; and, conniving, seem END
BEGIN NOW To gratify my scornful enemies, END
BEGIN NOW That laugh, as if, transported with some fit END
BEGIN NOW Of passion, I to them had quitted all, END
BEGIN NOW At random yielded up to their misrule; END
BEGIN NOW And know not that I called, and drew them thither, END
BEGIN NOW My Hell-hounds, to lick up the draff and filth END
BEGIN NOW Which Man's polluting sin with taint hath shed END
BEGIN NOW On what was pure; til, crammed and gorged, nigh burst END
BEGIN NOW With sucked and glutted offal, at one sling END
BEGIN NOW Of thy victorious arm, well-pleasing Son, END
BEGIN NOW Both Sin, and Death, and yawning Grave, at last, END
BEGIN NOW Through Chaos hurled, obstruct the mouth of Hell END
BEGIN NOW For ever, and seal up his ravenous jaws. END
BEGIN NOW Then Heaven and Earth renewed shall be made pure END
BEGIN NOW To sanctity, that shall receive no stain: END
BEGIN NOW Till then, the curse pronounced on both precedes. END
BEGIN NOW He ended, and the heavenly audience loud END
BEGIN NOW Sung Halleluiah, as the sound of seas, END
BEGIN NOW Through multitude that sung: Just are thy ways, END
BEGIN NOW Righteous are thy decrees on all thy works; END
BEGIN NOW Who can extenuate thee? Next, to the Son, END
BEGIN NOW Destined Restorer of mankind, by whom END
BEGIN NOW New Heaven and Earth shall to the ages rise, END
BEGIN NOW Or down from Heaven descend.--Such was their song; END
BEGIN NOW While the Creator, calling forth by name END
BEGIN NOW His mighty Angels, gave them several charge, END
BEGIN NOW As sorted best with present things. The sun END
BEGIN NOW Had first his precept so to move, so shine, END
BEGIN NOW As might affect the earth with cold and heat END
BEGIN NOW Scarce tolerable; and from the north to call END
BEGIN NOW Decrepit winter; from the south to bring END
BEGIN NOW Solstitial summer's heat. To the blanc moon END
BEGIN NOW Her office they prescribed; to the other five END
BEGIN NOW Their planetary motions, and aspects, END
BEGIN NOW In sextile, square, and trine, and opposite, END
BEGIN NOW Of noxious efficacy, and when to join END
BEGIN NOW In synod unbenign; and taught the fixed END
BEGIN NOW Their influence malignant when to shower, END
BEGIN NOW Which of them rising with the sun, or falling, END
BEGIN NOW Should prove tempestuous: To the winds they set END
BEGIN NOW Their corners, when with bluster to confound END
BEGIN NOW Sea, air, and shore; the thunder when to roll END
BEGIN NOW With terrour through the dark aereal hall. END
BEGIN NOW Some say, he bid his Angels turn ascanse END
BEGIN NOW The poles of earth, twice ten degrees and more, END
BEGIN NOW From the sun's axle; they with labour pushed END
BEGIN NOW Oblique the centrick globe: Some say, the sun END
BEGIN NOW Was bid turn reins from the equinoctial road END
BEGIN NOW Like distant breadth to Taurus with the seven END
BEGIN NOW Up to the Tropick Crab: thence down amain END
BEGIN NOW As deep as Capricorn; to bring in change END
BEGIN NOW Of seasons to each clime; else had the spring END
BEGIN NOW Perpetual smiled on earth with vernant flowers, END
BEGIN NOW Equal in days and nights, except to those END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the polar circles; to them day END
BEGIN NOW Had unbenighted shone, while the low sun, END
BEGIN NOW To recompense his distance, in their sight END
BEGIN NOW Had rounded still the horizon, and not known END
BEGIN NOW Or east or west; which had forbid the snow END
BEGIN NOW From cold Estotiland, and south as far END
BEGIN NOW Beneath Magellan. At that tasted fruit END
BEGIN NOW The sun, as from Thyestean banquet, turned END
BEGIN NOW His course intended; else, how had the world END
BEGIN NOW Inhabited, though sinless, more than now, END
BEGIN NOW Avoided pinching cold and scorching heat? END
BEGIN NOW These changes in the Heavens, though slow, produced END
BEGIN NOW Like change on sea and land; sideral blast, END
BEGIN NOW Vapour, and mist, and exhalation hot, END
BEGIN NOW Corrupt and pestilent: Now from the north END
BEGIN NOW Of Norumbega, and the Samoed shore, END
BEGIN NOW Bursting their brazen dungeon, armed with ice, END
BEGIN NOW And snow, and hail, and stormy gust and flaw, END
BEGIN NOW Boreas, and Caecias, and Argestes loud, END
BEGIN NOW And Thrascias, rend the woods, and seas upturn; END
BEGIN NOW With adverse blast upturns them from the south END
BEGIN NOW Notus, and Afer black with thunderous clouds END
BEGIN NOW From Serraliona; thwart of these, as fierce, END
BEGIN NOW Forth rush the Levant and the Ponent winds, END
BEGIN NOW Eurus and Zephyr, with their lateral noise, END
BEGIN NOW Sirocco and Libecchio. Thus began END
BEGIN NOW Outrage from lifeless things; but Discord first, END
BEGIN NOW Daughter of Sin, among the irrational END
BEGIN NOW Death introduced, through fierce antipathy: END
BEGIN NOW Beast now with beast 'gan war, and fowl with fowl, END
BEGIN NOW And fish with fish; to graze the herb all leaving, END
BEGIN NOW Devoured each other; nor stood much in awe END
BEGIN NOW Of Man, but fled him; or, with countenance grim, END
BEGIN NOW Glared on him passing. These were from without END
BEGIN NOW The growing miseries, which Adam saw END
BEGIN NOW Already in part, though hid in gloomiest shade, END
BEGIN NOW To sorrow abandoned, but worse felt within; END
BEGIN NOW And, in a troubled sea of passion tost, END
BEGIN NOW Thus to disburden sought with sad complaint. END
BEGIN NOW O miserable of happy! Is this the end END
BEGIN NOW Of this new glorious world, and me so late END
BEGIN NOW The glory of that glory, who now become END
BEGIN NOW Accursed, of blessed? hide me from the face END
BEGIN NOW Of God, whom to behold was then my highth END
BEGIN NOW Of happiness!--Yet well, if here would end END
BEGIN NOW The misery; I deserved it, and would bear END
BEGIN NOW My own deservings; but this will not serve: END
BEGIN NOW All that I eat or drink, or shall beget, END
BEGIN NOW Is propagated curse. O voice, once heard END
BEGIN NOW Delightfully, Encrease and multiply; END
BEGIN NOW Now death to hear! for what can I encrease, END
BEGIN NOW Or multiply, but curses on my head? END
BEGIN NOW Who of all ages to succeed, but, feeling END
BEGIN NOW The evil on him brought by me, will curse END
BEGIN NOW My head? Ill fare our ancestor impure, END
BEGIN NOW For this we may thank Adam! but his thanks END
BEGIN NOW Shall be the execration: so, besides END
BEGIN NOW Mine own that bide upon me, all from me END
BEGIN NOW Shall with a fierce reflux on me rebound; END
BEGIN NOW On me, as on their natural center, light END
BEGIN NOW Heavy, though in their place. O fleeting joys END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise, dear bought with lasting woes! END
BEGIN NOW Did I request thee, Maker, from my clay END
BEGIN NOW To mould me Man? did I solicit thee END
BEGIN NOW From darkness to promote me, or here place END
BEGIN NOW In this delicious garden? As my will END
BEGIN NOW Concurred not to my being, it were but right END
BEGIN NOW And equal to reduce me to my dust; END
BEGIN NOW Desirous to resign and render back END
BEGIN NOW All I received; unable to perform END
BEGIN NOW Thy terms too hard, by which I was to hold END
BEGIN NOW The good I sought not. To the loss of that, END
BEGIN NOW Sufficient penalty, why hast thou added END
BEGIN NOW The sense of endless woes? Inexplicable END
BEGIN NOW Thy justice seems; yet to say truth, too late END
BEGIN NOW I thus contest; then should have been refused END
BEGIN NOW Those terms whatever, when they were proposed: END
BEGIN NOW Thou didst accept them; wilt thou enjoy the good, END
BEGIN NOW Then cavil the conditions? And, though God END
BEGIN NOW Made thee without thy leave, what if thy son END
BEGIN NOW Prove disobedient, and reproved, retort, END
BEGIN NOW Wherefore didst thou beget me? I sought it not! END
BEGIN NOW Wouldst thou admit for his contempt of thee END
BEGIN NOW That proud excuse? yet him not thy election, END
BEGIN NOW But natural necessity begot. END
BEGIN NOW God made thee of choice his own, and of his own END
BEGIN NOW To serve him; thy reward was of his grace; END
BEGIN NOW Thy punishment then, justly is at his will. END
BEGIN NOW Be it so, for I submit; his doom is fair, END
BEGIN NOW That dust I am, and shall to dust return. END
BEGIN NOW O welcome hour whenever! Why delays END
BEGIN NOW His hand to execute what his decree END
BEGIN NOW Fixed on this day? Why do I overlive, END
BEGIN NOW Why am I mocked with death, and lengthened out END
BEGIN NOW To deathless pain? How gladly would I meet END
BEGIN NOW Mortality my sentence, and be earth END
BEGIN NOW Insensible! How glad would lay me down END
BEGIN NOW As in my mother's lap! There I should rest, END
BEGIN NOW And sleep secure; his dreadful voice no more END
BEGIN NOW Would thunder in my ears; no fear of worse END
BEGIN NOW To me, and to my offspring, would torment me END
BEGIN NOW With cruel expectation. Yet one doubt END
BEGIN NOW Pursues me still, lest all I cannot die; END
BEGIN NOW Lest that pure breath of life, the spirit of Man END
BEGIN NOW Which God inspired, cannot together perish END
BEGIN NOW With this corporeal clod; then, in the grave, END
BEGIN NOW Or in some other dismal place, who knows END
BEGIN NOW But I shall die a living death? O thought END
BEGIN NOW Horrid, if true! Yet why? It was but breath END
BEGIN NOW Of life that sinned; what dies but what had life END
BEGIN NOW And sin? The body properly had neither, END
BEGIN NOW All of me then shall die: let this appease END
BEGIN NOW The doubt, since human reach no further knows. END
BEGIN NOW For though the Lord of all be infinite, END
BEGIN NOW Is his wrath also? Be it, Man is not so, END
BEGIN NOW But mortal doomed. How can he exercise END
BEGIN NOW Wrath without end on Man, whom death must end? END
BEGIN NOW Can he make deathless death? That were to make END
BEGIN NOW Strange contradiction, which to God himself END
BEGIN NOW Impossible is held; as argument END
BEGIN NOW Of weakness, not of power. Will he draw out, END
BEGIN NOW For anger's sake, finite to infinite, END
BEGIN NOW In punished Man, to satisfy his rigour, END
BEGIN NOW Satisfied never? That were to extend END
BEGIN NOW His sentence beyond dust and Nature's law; END
BEGIN NOW By which all causes else, according still END
BEGIN NOW To the reception of their matter, act; END
BEGIN NOW Not to the extent of their own sphere. But say END
BEGIN NOW That death be not one stroke, as I supposed, END
BEGIN NOW Bereaving sense, but endless misery END
BEGIN NOW From this day onward; which I feel begun END
BEGIN NOW Both in me, and without me; and so last END
BEGIN NOW To perpetuity;--Ay me! that fear END
BEGIN NOW Comes thundering back with dreadful revolution END
BEGIN NOW On my defenceless head; both Death and I END
BEGIN NOW Am found eternal, and incorporate both; END
BEGIN NOW Nor I on my part single; in me all END
BEGIN NOW Posterity stands cursed: Fair patrimony END
BEGIN NOW That I must leave ye, Sons! O, were I able END
BEGIN NOW To waste it all myself, and leave ye none! END
BEGIN NOW So disinherited, how would you bless END
BEGIN NOW Me, now your curse! Ah, why should all mankind, END
BEGIN NOW For one man's fault, thus guiltless be condemned, END
BEGIN NOW It guiltless? But from me what can proceed, END
BEGIN NOW But all corrupt; both mind and will depraved END
BEGIN NOW Not to do only, but to will the same END
BEGIN NOW With me? How can they then acquitted stand END
BEGIN NOW In sight of God? Him, after all disputes, END
BEGIN NOW Forced I absolve: all my evasions vain, END
BEGIN NOW And reasonings, though through mazes, lead me still END
BEGIN NOW But to my own conviction: first and last END
BEGIN NOW On me, me only, as the source and spring END
BEGIN NOW Of all corruption, all the blame lights due; END
BEGIN NOW So might the wrath! Fond wish! couldst thou support END
BEGIN NOW That burden, heavier than the earth to bear; END
BEGIN NOW Than all the world much heavier, though divided END
BEGIN NOW With that bad Woman? Thus, what thou desirest, END
BEGIN NOW And what thou fearest, alike destroys all hope END
BEGIN NOW Of refuge, and concludes thee miserable END
BEGIN NOW Beyond all past example and future; END
BEGIN NOW To Satan only like both crime and doom. END
BEGIN NOW O Conscience! into what abyss of fears END
BEGIN NOW And horrours hast thou driven me; out of which END
BEGIN NOW I find no way, from deep to deeper plunged! END
BEGIN NOW Thus Adam to himself lamented loud, END
BEGIN NOW Through the still night; not now, as ere Man fell, END
BEGIN NOW Wholesome, and cool, and mild, but with black air END
BEGIN NOW Accompanied; with damps, and dreadful gloom; END
BEGIN NOW Which to his evil conscience represented END
BEGIN NOW All things with double terrour: On the ground END
BEGIN NOW Outstretched he lay, on the cold ground; and oft END
BEGIN NOW Cursed his creation; Death as oft accused END
BEGIN NOW The day of his offence. Why comes not Death, END
BEGIN NOW Said he, with one thrice-acceptable stroke END
BEGIN NOW To end me? Shall Truth fail to keep her word, END
BEGIN NOW Justice Divine not hasten to be just? END
BEGIN NOW But Death comes not at call; Justice Divine END
BEGIN NOW Mends not her slowest pace for prayers or cries, END
BEGIN NOW O woods, O fountains, hillocks, dales, and bowers! END
BEGIN NOW With other echo late I taught your shades END
BEGIN NOW To answer, and resound far other song.-- END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus afflicted when sad Eve beheld, END
BEGIN NOW Desolate where she sat, approaching nigh, END
BEGIN NOW Soft words to his fierce passion she assayed: END
BEGIN NOW But her with stern regard he thus repelled. END
BEGIN NOW Out of my sight, thou Serpent! That name best END
BEGIN NOW Befits thee with him leagued, thyself as false END
BEGIN NOW And hateful; nothing wants, but that thy shape, END
BEGIN NOW Like his, and colour serpentine, may show END
BEGIN NOW Thy inward fraud; to warn all creatures from thee END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth; lest that too heavenly form, pretended END
BEGIN NOW To hellish falshood, snare them! But for thee END
BEGIN NOW I had persisted happy; had not thy pride END
BEGIN NOW And wandering vanity, when least was safe, END
BEGIN NOW Rejected my forewarning, and disdained END
BEGIN NOW Not to be trusted; longing to be seen, END
BEGIN NOW Though by the Devil himself; him overweening END
BEGIN NOW To over-reach; but, with the serpent meeting, END
BEGIN NOW Fooled and beguiled; by him thou, I by thee END
BEGIN NOW To trust thee from my side; imagined wise, END
BEGIN NOW Constant, mature, proof against all assaults; END
BEGIN NOW And understood not all was but a show, END
BEGIN NOW Rather than solid virtue; all but a rib END
BEGIN NOW Crooked by nature, bent, as now appears, END
BEGIN NOW More to the part sinister, from me drawn; END
BEGIN NOW Well if thrown out, as supernumerary END
BEGIN NOW To my just number found. O! why did God, END
BEGIN NOW Creator wise, that peopled highest Heaven END
BEGIN NOW With Spirits masculine, create at last END
BEGIN NOW This novelty on earth, this fair defect END
BEGIN NOW Of nature, and not fill the world at once END
BEGIN NOW With Men, as Angels, without feminine; END
BEGIN NOW Or find some other way to generate END
BEGIN NOW Mankind? This mischief had not been befallen, END
BEGIN NOW And more that shall befall; innumerable END
BEGIN NOW Disturbances on earth through female snares, END
BEGIN NOW And strait conjunction with this sex: for either END
BEGIN NOW He never shall find out fit mate, but such END
BEGIN NOW As some misfortune brings him, or mistake; END
BEGIN NOW Or whom he wishes most shall seldom gain END
BEGIN NOW Through her perverseness, but shall see her gained END
BEGIN NOW By a far worse; or, if she love, withheld END
BEGIN NOW By parents; or his happiest choice too late END
BEGIN NOW Shall meet, already linked and wedlock-bound END
BEGIN NOW To a fell adversary, his hate or shame: END
BEGIN NOW Which infinite calamity shall cause END
BEGIN NOW To human life, and houshold peace confound. END
BEGIN NOW He added not, and from her turned; but Eve, END
BEGIN NOW Not so repulsed, with tears that ceased not flowing END
BEGIN NOW And tresses all disordered, at his feet END
BEGIN NOW Fell humble; and, embracing them, besought END
BEGIN NOW His peace, and thus proceeded in her plaint. END
BEGIN NOW Forsake me not thus, Adam! witness Heaven END
BEGIN NOW What love sincere, and reverence in my heart END
BEGIN NOW I bear thee, and unweeting have offended, END
BEGIN NOW Unhappily deceived! Thy suppliant END
BEGIN NOW I beg, and clasp thy knees; bereave me not, END
BEGIN NOW Whereon I live, thy gentle looks, thy aid, END
BEGIN NOW Thy counsel, in this uttermost distress, END
BEGIN NOW My only strength and stay: Forlorn of thee, END
BEGIN NOW Whither shall I betake me, where subsist? END
BEGIN NOW While yet we live, scarce one short hour perhaps, END
BEGIN NOW Between us two let there be peace; both joining, END
BEGIN NOW As joined in injuries, one enmity END
BEGIN NOW Against a foe by doom express assigned us, END
BEGIN NOW That cruel Serpent: On me exercise not END
BEGIN NOW Thy hatred for this misery befallen; END
BEGIN NOW On me already lost, me than thyself END
BEGIN NOW More miserable! Both have sinned; but thou END
BEGIN NOW Against God only; I against God and thee; END
BEGIN NOW And to the place of judgement will return, END
BEGIN NOW There with my cries importune Heaven; that all END
BEGIN NOW The sentence, from thy head removed, may light END
BEGIN NOW On me, sole cause to thee of all this woe; END
BEGIN NOW Me, me only, just object of his ire! END
BEGIN NOW She ended weeping; and her lowly plight, END
BEGIN NOW Immoveable, till peace obtained from fault END
BEGIN NOW Acknowledged and deplored, in Adam wrought END
BEGIN NOW Commiseration: Soon his heart relented END
BEGIN NOW Towards her, his life so late, and sole delight, END
BEGIN NOW Now at his feet submissive in distress; END
BEGIN NOW Creature so fair his reconcilement seeking, END
BEGIN NOW His counsel, whom she had displeased, his aid: END
BEGIN NOW As one disarmed, his anger all he lost, END
BEGIN NOW And thus with peaceful words upraised her soon. END
BEGIN NOW Unwary, and too desirous, as before, END
BEGIN NOW So now of what thou knowest not, who desirest END
BEGIN NOW The punishment all on thyself; alas! END
BEGIN NOW Bear thine own first, ill able to sustain END
BEGIN NOW His full wrath, whose thou feelest as yet least part, END
BEGIN NOW And my displeasure bearest so ill. If prayers END
BEGIN NOW Could alter high decrees, I to that place END
BEGIN NOW Would speed before thee, and be louder heard, END
BEGIN NOW That on my head all might be visited; END
BEGIN NOW Thy frailty and infirmer sex forgiven, END
BEGIN NOW To me committed, and by me exposed. END
BEGIN NOW But rise;--let us no more contend, nor blame END
BEGIN NOW Each other, blamed enough elsewhere; but strive END
BEGIN NOW In offices of love, how we may lighten END
BEGIN NOW Each other's burden, in our share of woe; END
BEGIN NOW Since this day's death denounced, if aught I see, END
BEGIN NOW Will prove no sudden, but a slow-paced evil; END
BEGIN NOW A long day's dying, to augment our pain; END
BEGIN NOW And to our seed (O hapless seed!) derived. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Eve, recovering heart, replied. END
BEGIN NOW Adam, by sad experiment I know END
BEGIN NOW How little weight my words with thee can find, END
BEGIN NOW Found so erroneous; thence by just event END
BEGIN NOW Found so unfortunate: Nevertheless, END
BEGIN NOW Restored by thee, vile as I am, to place END
BEGIN NOW Of new acceptance, hopeful to regain END
BEGIN NOW Thy love, the sole contentment of my heart END
BEGIN NOW Living or dying, from thee I will not hide END
BEGIN NOW What thoughts in my unquiet breast are risen, END
BEGIN NOW Tending to some relief of our extremes, END
BEGIN NOW Or end; though sharp and sad, yet tolerable, END
BEGIN NOW As in our evils, and of easier choice. END
BEGIN NOW If care of our descent perplex us most, END
BEGIN NOW Which must be born to certain woe, devoured END
BEGIN NOW By Death at last; and miserable it is END
BEGIN NOW To be to others cause of misery, END
BEGIN NOW Our own begotten, and of our loins to bring END
BEGIN NOW Into this cursed world a woeful race, END
BEGIN NOW That after wretched life must be at last END
BEGIN NOW Food for so foul a monster; in thy power END
BEGIN NOW It lies, yet ere conception to prevent END
BEGIN NOW The race unblest, to being yet unbegot. END
BEGIN NOW Childless thou art, childless remain: so Death END
BEGIN NOW Shall be deceived his glut, and with us two END
BEGIN NOW Be forced to satisfy his ravenous maw. END
BEGIN NOW But if thou judge it hard and difficult, END
BEGIN NOW Conversing, looking, loving, to abstain END
BEGIN NOW From love's due rights, nuptial embraces sweet; END
BEGIN NOW And with desire to languish without hope, END
BEGIN NOW Before the present object languishing END
BEGIN NOW With like desire; which would be misery END
BEGIN NOW And torment less than none of what we dread; END
BEGIN NOW Then, both ourselves and seed at once to free END
BEGIN NOW From what we fear for both, let us make short,-- END
BEGIN NOW Let us seek Death;--or, he not found, supply END
BEGIN NOW With our own hands his office on ourselves: END
BEGIN NOW Why stand we longer shivering under fears, END
BEGIN NOW That show no end but death, and have the power, END
BEGIN NOW Of many ways to die the shortest choosing, END
BEGIN NOW Destruction with destruction to destroy?-- END
BEGIN NOW She ended here, or vehement despair END
BEGIN NOW Broke off the rest: so much of death her thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Had entertained, as dyed her cheeks with pale. END
BEGIN NOW But Adam, with such counsel nothing swayed, END
BEGIN NOW To better hopes his more attentive mind END
BEGIN NOW Labouring had raised; and thus to Eve replied. END
BEGIN NOW Eve, thy contempt of life and pleasure seems END
BEGIN NOW To argue in thee something more sublime END
BEGIN NOW And excellent, than what thy mind contemns; END
BEGIN NOW But self-destruction therefore sought, refutes END
BEGIN NOW That excellence thought in thee; and implies, END
BEGIN NOW Not thy contempt, but anguish and regret END
BEGIN NOW For loss of life and pleasure overloved. END
BEGIN NOW Or if thou covet death, as utmost end END
BEGIN NOW Of misery, so thinking to evade END
BEGIN NOW The penalty pronounced; doubt not but God END
BEGIN NOW Hath wiselier armed his vengeful ire, than so END
BEGIN NOW To be forestalled; much more I fear lest death, END
BEGIN NOW So snatched, will not exempt us from the pain END
BEGIN NOW We are by doom to pay; rather, such acts END
BEGIN NOW Of contumacy will provoke the Highest END
BEGIN NOW To make death in us live: Then let us seek END
BEGIN NOW Some safer resolution, which methinks END
BEGIN NOW I have in view, calling to mind with heed END
BEGIN NOW Part of our sentence, that thy seed shall bruise END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent's head; piteous amends! unless END
BEGIN NOW Be meant, whom I conjecture, our grand foe, END
BEGIN NOW Satan; who, in the serpent, hath contrived END
BEGIN NOW Against us this deceit: To crush his head END
BEGIN NOW Would be revenge indeed! which will be lost END
BEGIN NOW By death brought on ourselves, or childless days END
BEGIN NOW Resolved, as thou proposest; so our foe END
BEGIN NOW Shal 'scape his punishment ordained, and we END
BEGIN NOW Instead shall double ours upon our heads. END
BEGIN NOW No more be mentioned then of violence END
BEGIN NOW Against ourselves; and wilful barrenness, END
BEGIN NOW That cuts us off from hope; and savours only END
BEGIN NOW Rancour and pride, impatience and despite, END
BEGIN NOW Reluctance against God and his just yoke END
BEGIN NOW Laid on our necks. Remember with what mild END
BEGIN NOW And gracious temper he both heard, and judged, END
BEGIN NOW Without wrath or reviling; we expected END
BEGIN NOW Immediate dissolution, which we thought END
BEGIN NOW Was meant by death that day; when lo! to thee END
BEGIN NOW Pains only in child-bearing were foretold, END
BEGIN NOW And bringing forth; soon recompensed with joy, END
BEGIN NOW Fruit of thy womb: On me the curse aslope END
BEGIN NOW Glanced on the ground; with labour I must earn END
BEGIN NOW My bread; what harm? Idleness had been worse; END
BEGIN NOW My labour will sustain me; and, lest cold END
BEGIN NOW Or heat should injure us, his timely care END
BEGIN NOW Hath, unbesought, provided; and his hands END
BEGIN NOW Clothed us unworthy, pitying while he judged; END
BEGIN NOW How much more, if we pray him, will his ear END
BEGIN NOW Be open, and his heart to pity incline, END
BEGIN NOW And teach us further by what means to shun END
BEGIN NOW The inclement seasons, rain, ice, hail, and snow! END
BEGIN NOW Which now the sky, with various face, begins END
BEGIN NOW To show us in this mountain; while the winds END
BEGIN NOW Blow moist and keen, shattering the graceful locks END
BEGIN NOW Of these fair spreading trees; which bids us seek END
BEGIN NOW Some better shroud, some better warmth to cherish END
BEGIN NOW Our limbs benummed, ere this diurnal star END
BEGIN NOW Leave cold the night, how we his gathered beams END
BEGIN NOW Reflected may with matter sere foment; END
BEGIN NOW Or, by collision of two bodies, grind END
BEGIN NOW The air attrite to fire; as late the clouds END
BEGIN NOW Justling, or pushed with winds, rude in their shock, END
BEGIN NOW Tine the slant lightning; whose thwart flame, driven down END
BEGIN NOW Kindles the gummy bark of fir or pine; END
BEGIN NOW And sends a comfortable heat from far, END
BEGIN NOW Which might supply the sun: Such fire to use, END
BEGIN NOW And what may else be remedy or cure END
BEGIN NOW To evils which our own misdeeds have wrought, END
BEGIN NOW He will instruct us praying, and of grace END
BEGIN NOW Beseeching him; so as we need not fear END
BEGIN NOW To pass commodiously this life, sustained END
BEGIN NOW By him with many comforts, till we end END
BEGIN NOW In dust, our final rest and native home. END
BEGIN NOW What better can we do, than, to the place END
BEGIN NOW Repairing where he judged us, prostrate fall END
BEGIN NOW Before him reverent; and there confess END
BEGIN NOW Humbly our faults, and pardon beg; with tears END
BEGIN NOW Watering the ground, and with our sighs the air END
BEGIN NOW Frequenting, sent from hearts contrite, in sign END
BEGIN NOW Of sorrow unfeigned, and humiliation meek. END
BEGIN NOW Undoubtedly he will relent, and turn END
BEGIN NOW From his displeasure; in whose look serene, END
BEGIN NOW When angry most he seemed and most severe, END
BEGIN NOW What else but favour, grace, and mercy, shone? END
BEGIN NOW So spake our father penitent; nor Eve END
BEGIN NOW Felt less remorse: they, forthwith to the place END
BEGIN NOW Repairing where he judged them, prostrate fell END
BEGIN NOW Before him reverent; and both confessed END
BEGIN NOW Humbly their faults, and pardon begged; with tears END
BEGIN NOW Watering the ground, and with their sighs the air END
BEGIN NOW Frequenting, sent from hearts contrite, in sign END
BEGIN NOW Of sorrow unfeigned, and humiliation meek. END
BEGIN NOW Thus they, in lowliest plight, repentant stood END
BEGIN NOW Praying; for from the mercy-seat above END
BEGIN NOW Prevenient grace descending had removed END
BEGIN NOW The stony from their hearts, and made new flesh END
BEGIN NOW Regenerate grow instead; that sighs now breathed END
BEGIN NOW Unutterable; which the Spirit of prayer END
BEGIN NOW Inspired, and winged for Heaven with speedier flight END
BEGIN NOW Than loudest oratory: Yet their port END
BEGIN NOW Not of mean suitors; nor important less END
BEGIN NOW Seemed their petition, than when the ancient pair END
BEGIN NOW In fables old, less ancient yet than these, END
BEGIN NOW Deucalion and chaste Pyrrha, to restore END
BEGIN NOW The race of mankind drowned, before the shrine END
BEGIN NOW Of Themis stood devout. To Heaven their prayers END
BEGIN NOW Flew up, nor missed the way, by envious winds END
BEGIN NOW Blown vagabond or frustrate: in they passed END
BEGIN NOW Dimensionless through heavenly doors; then clad END
BEGIN NOW With incense, where the golden altar fumed, END
BEGIN NOW By their great intercessour, came in sight END
BEGIN NOW Before the Father's throne: them the glad Son END
BEGIN NOW Presenting, thus to intercede began. END
BEGIN NOW See Father, what first-fruits on earth are sprung END
BEGIN NOW From thy implanted grace in Man; these sighs END
BEGIN NOW And prayers, which in this golden censer mixed END
BEGIN NOW With incense, I thy priest before thee bring; END
BEGIN NOW Fruits of more pleasing savour, from thy seed END
BEGIN NOW Sown with contrition in his heart, than those END
BEGIN NOW Which, his own hand manuring, all the trees END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise could have produced, ere fallen END
BEGIN NOW From innocence. Now therefore, bend thine ear END
BEGIN NOW To supplication; hear his sighs, though mute; END
BEGIN NOW Unskilful with what words to pray, let me END
BEGIN NOW Interpret for him; me, his advocate END
BEGIN NOW And propitiation; all his works on me, END
BEGIN NOW Good, or not good, ingraft; my merit those END
BEGIN NOW Shall perfect, and for these my death shall pay. END
BEGIN NOW Accept me; and, in me, from these receive END
BEGIN NOW The smell of peace toward mankind: let him live END
BEGIN NOW Before thee reconciled, at least his days END
BEGIN NOW Numbered, though sad; till death, his doom, (which I END
BEGIN NOW To mitigate thus plead, not to reverse,) END
BEGIN NOW To better life shall yield him: where with me END
BEGIN NOW All my redeemed may dwell in joy and bliss; END
BEGIN NOW Made one with me, as I with thee am one. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Father, without cloud, serene. END
BEGIN NOW All thy request for Man, accepted Son, END
BEGIN NOW Obtain; all thy request was my decree: END
BEGIN NOW But, longer in that Paradise to dwell, END
BEGIN NOW The law I gave to Nature him forbids: END
BEGIN NOW Those pure immortal elements, that know, END
BEGIN NOW No gross, no unharmonious mixture foul, END
BEGIN NOW Eject him, tainted now; and purge him off, END
BEGIN NOW As a distemper, gross, to air as gross, END
BEGIN NOW And mortal food; as may dispose him best END
BEGIN NOW For dissolution wrought by sin, that first END
BEGIN NOW Distempered all things, and of incorrupt END
BEGIN NOW Corrupted. I, at first, with two fair gifts END
BEGIN NOW Created him endowed; with happiness, END
BEGIN NOW And immortality: that fondly lost, END
BEGIN NOW This other served but to eternize woe; END
BEGIN NOW Till I provided death: so death becomes END
BEGIN NOW His final remedy; and, after life, END
BEGIN NOW Tried in sharp tribulation, and refined END
BEGIN NOW By faith and faithful works, to second life, END
BEGIN NOW Waked in the renovation of the just, END
BEGIN NOW Resigns him up with Heaven and Earth renewed. END
BEGIN NOW But let us call to synod all the Blest, END
BEGIN NOW Through Heaven's wide bounds: from them I will not hide END
BEGIN NOW My judgements; how with mankind I proceed, END
BEGIN NOW As how with peccant Angels late they saw, END
BEGIN NOW And in their state, though firm, stood more confirmed. END
BEGIN NOW He ended, and the Son gave signal high END
BEGIN NOW To the bright minister that watched; he blew END
BEGIN NOW His trumpet, heard in Oreb since perhaps END
BEGIN NOW When God descended, and perhaps once more END
BEGIN NOW To sound at general doom. The angelick blast END
BEGIN NOW Filled all the regions: from their blisful bowers END
BEGIN NOW Of amarantine shade, fountain or spring, END
BEGIN NOW By the waters of life, where'er they sat END
BEGIN NOW In fellowships of joy, the sons of light END
BEGIN NOW Hasted, resorting to the summons high; END
BEGIN NOW And took their seats; till from his throne supreme END
BEGIN NOW The Almighty thus pronounced his sovran will. END
BEGIN NOW O Sons, like one of us Man is become END
BEGIN NOW To know both good and evil, since his taste END
BEGIN NOW Of that defended fruit; but let him boast END
BEGIN NOW His knowledge of good lost, and evil got; END
BEGIN NOW Happier! had it sufficed him to have known END
BEGIN NOW Good by itself, and evil not at all. END
BEGIN NOW He sorrows now, repents, and prays contrite, END
BEGIN NOW My motions in him; longer than they move, END
BEGIN NOW His heart I know, how variable and vain, END
BEGIN NOW Self-left. Lest therefore his now bolder hand END
BEGIN NOW Reach also of the tree of life, and eat, END
BEGIN NOW And live for ever, dream at least to live END
BEGIN NOW For ever, to remove him I decree, END
BEGIN NOW And send him from the garden forth to till END
BEGIN NOW The ground whence he was taken, fitter soil. END
BEGIN NOW Michael, this my behest have thou in charge; END
BEGIN NOW Take to thee from among the Cherubim END
BEGIN NOW Thy choice of flaming warriours, lest the Fiend, END
BEGIN NOW Or in behalf of Man, or to invade END
BEGIN NOW Vacant possession, some new trouble raise: END
BEGIN NOW Haste thee, and from the Paradise of God END
BEGIN NOW Without remorse drive out the sinful pair; END
BEGIN NOW From hallowed ground the unholy; and denounce END
BEGIN NOW To them, and to their progeny, from thence END
BEGIN NOW Perpetual banishment. Yet, lest they faint END
BEGIN NOW At the sad sentence rigorously urged, END
BEGIN NOW (For I behold them softened, and with tears END
BEGIN NOW Bewailing their excess,) all terrour hide. END
BEGIN NOW If patiently thy bidding they obey, END
BEGIN NOW Dismiss them not disconsolate; reveal END
BEGIN NOW To Adam what shall come in future days, END
BEGIN NOW As I shall thee enlighten; intermix END
BEGIN NOW My covenant in the Woman's seed renewed; END
BEGIN NOW So send them forth, though sorrowing, yet in peace: END
BEGIN NOW And on the east side of the garden place, END
BEGIN NOW Where entrance up from Eden easiest climbs, END
BEGIN NOW Cherubick watch; and of a sword the flame END
BEGIN NOW Wide-waving; all approach far off to fright, END
BEGIN NOW And guard all passage to the tree of life: END
BEGIN NOW Lest Paradise a receptacle prove END
BEGIN NOW To Spirits foul, and all my trees their prey; END
BEGIN NOW With whose stolen fruit Man once more to delude. END
BEGIN NOW He ceased; and the arch-angelick Power prepared END
BEGIN NOW For swift descent; with him the cohort bright END
BEGIN NOW Of watchful Cherubim: four faces each END
BEGIN NOW Had, like a double Janus; all their shape END
BEGIN NOW Spangled with eyes more numerous than those END
BEGIN NOW Of Argus, and more wakeful than to drouse, END
BEGIN NOW Charmed with Arcadian pipe, the pastoral reed END
BEGIN NOW Of Hermes, or his opiate rod. Mean while, END
BEGIN NOW To re-salute the world with sacred light, END
BEGIN NOW Leucothea waked; and with fresh dews imbalmed END
BEGIN NOW The earth; when Adam and first matron Eve END
BEGIN NOW Had ended now their orisons, and found END
BEGIN NOW Strength added from above; new hope to spring END
BEGIN NOW Out of despair; joy, but with fear yet linked; END
BEGIN NOW Which thus to Eve his welcome words renewed. END
BEGIN NOW Eve, easily my faith admit, that all END
BEGIN NOW The good which we enjoy from Heaven descends; END
BEGIN NOW But, that from us aught should ascend to Heaven END
BEGIN NOW So prevalent as to concern the mind END
BEGIN NOW Of God high-blest, or to incline his will, END
BEGIN NOW Hard to belief may seem; yet this will prayer END
BEGIN NOW Or one short sigh of human breath, upborne END
BEGIN NOW Even to the seat of God. For since I sought END
BEGIN NOW By prayer the offended Deity to appease; END
BEGIN NOW Kneeled, and before him humbled all my heart; END
BEGIN NOW Methought I saw him placable and mild, END
BEGIN NOW Bending his ear; persuasion in me grew END
BEGIN NOW That I was heard with favour; peace returned END
BEGIN NOW Home to my breast, and to my memory END
BEGIN NOW His promise, that thy seed shall bruise our foe; END
BEGIN NOW Which, then not minded in dismay, yet now END
BEGIN NOW Assures me that the bitterness of death END
BEGIN NOW Is past, and we shall live. Whence hail to thee, END
BEGIN NOW Eve rightly called, mother of all mankind, END
BEGIN NOW Mother of all things living, since by thee END
BEGIN NOW Man is to live; and all things live for Man. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Eve with sad demeanour meek. END
BEGIN NOW Ill-worthy I such title should belong END
BEGIN NOW To me transgressour; who, for thee ordained END
BEGIN NOW A help, became thy snare; to me reproach END
BEGIN NOW Rather belongs, distrust, and all dispraise: END
BEGIN NOW But infinite in pardon was my Judge, END
BEGIN NOW That I, who first brought death on all, am graced END
BEGIN NOW The source of life; next favourable thou, END
BEGIN NOW Who highly thus to entitle me vouchsaf'st, END
BEGIN NOW Far other name deserving. But the field END
BEGIN NOW To labour calls us, now with sweat imposed, END
BEGIN NOW Though after sleepless night; for see! the morn, END
BEGIN NOW All unconcerned with our unrest, begins END
BEGIN NOW Her rosy progress smiling: let us forth; END
BEGIN NOW I never from thy side henceforth to stray, END
BEGIN NOW Where'er our day's work lies, though now enjoined END
BEGIN NOW Laborious, till day droop; while here we dwell, END
BEGIN NOW What can be toilsome in these pleasant walks? END
BEGIN NOW Here let us live, though in fallen state, content. END
BEGIN NOW So spake, so wished much humbled Eve; but Fate END
BEGIN NOW Subscribed not: Nature first gave signs, impressed END
BEGIN NOW On bird, beast, air; air suddenly eclipsed, END
BEGIN NOW After short blush of morn; nigh in her sight END
BEGIN NOW The bird of Jove, stooped from his aery tour, END
BEGIN NOW Two birds of gayest plume before him drove; END
BEGIN NOW Down from a hill the beast that reigns in woods, END
BEGIN NOW First hunter then, pursued a gentle brace, END
BEGIN NOW Goodliest of all the forest, hart and hind; END
BEGIN NOW Direct to the eastern gate was bent their flight. END
BEGIN NOW Adam observed, and with his eye the chase END
BEGIN NOW Pursuing, not unmoved, to Eve thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW O Eve, some further change awaits us nigh, END
BEGIN NOW Which Heaven, by these mute signs in Nature, shows END
BEGIN NOW Forerunners of his purpose; or to warn END
BEGIN NOW Us, haply too secure, of our discharge END
BEGIN NOW From penalty, because from death released END
BEGIN NOW Some days: how long, and what till then our life, END
BEGIN NOW Who knows? or more than this, that we are dust, END
BEGIN NOW And thither must return, and be no more? END
BEGIN NOW Why else this double object in our sight END
BEGIN NOW Of flight pursued in the air, and o'er the ground, END
BEGIN NOW One way the self-same hour? why in the east END
BEGIN NOW Darkness ere day's mid-course, and morning-light END
BEGIN NOW More orient in yon western cloud, that draws END
BEGIN NOW O'er the blue firmament a radiant white, END
BEGIN NOW And slow descends with something heavenly fraught? END
BEGIN NOW He erred not; for by this the heavenly bands END
BEGIN NOW Down from a sky of jasper lighted now END
BEGIN NOW In Paradise, and on a hill made halt; END
BEGIN NOW A glorious apparition, had not doubt END
BEGIN NOW And carnal fear that day dimmed Adam's eye. END
BEGIN NOW Not that more glorious, when the Angels met END
BEGIN NOW Jacob in Mahanaim, where he saw END
BEGIN NOW The field pavilioned with his guardians bright; END
BEGIN NOW Nor that, which on the flaming mount appeared END
BEGIN NOW In Dothan, covered with a camp of fire, END
BEGIN NOW Against the Syrian king, who to surprise END
BEGIN NOW One man, assassin-like, had levied war, END
BEGIN NOW War unproclaimed. The princely Hierarch END
BEGIN NOW In their bright stand there left his Powers, to seise END
BEGIN NOW Possession of the garden; he alone, END
BEGIN NOW To find where Adam sheltered, took his way, END
BEGIN NOW Not unperceived of Adam; who to Eve, END
BEGIN NOW While the great visitant approached, thus spake. END
BEGIN NOW Eve, now expect great tidings, which perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Of us will soon determine, or impose END
BEGIN NOW New laws to be observed; for I descry, END
BEGIN NOW From yonder blazing cloud that veils the hill, END
BEGIN NOW One of the heavenly host; and, by his gait, END
BEGIN NOW None of the meanest; some great Potentate END
BEGIN NOW Or of the Thrones above; such majesty END
BEGIN NOW Invests him coming! yet not terrible, END
BEGIN NOW That I should fear; nor sociably mild, END
BEGIN NOW As Raphael, that I should much confide; END
BEGIN NOW But solemn and sublime; whom not to offend, END
BEGIN NOW With reverence I must meet, and thou retire. END
BEGIN NOW He ended: and the Arch-Angel soon drew nigh, END
BEGIN NOW Not in his shape celestial, but as man END
BEGIN NOW Clad to meet man; over his lucid arms END
BEGIN NOW A military vest of purple flowed, END
BEGIN NOW Livelier than Meliboean, or the grain END
BEGIN NOW Of Sarra, worn by kings and heroes old END
BEGIN NOW In time of truce; Iris had dipt the woof; END
BEGIN NOW His starry helm unbuckled showed him prime END
BEGIN NOW In manhood where youth ended; by his side, END
BEGIN NOW As in a glistering zodiack, hung the sword, END
BEGIN NOW Satan's dire dread; and in his hand the spear. END
BEGIN NOW Adam bowed low; he, kingly, from his state END
BEGIN NOW Inclined not, but his coming thus declared. END
BEGIN NOW Adam, Heaven's high behest no preface needs: END
BEGIN NOW Sufficient that thy prayers are heard; and Death, END
BEGIN NOW Then due by sentence when thou didst transgress, END
BEGIN NOW Defeated of his seisure many days END
BEGIN NOW Given thee of grace; wherein thou mayest repent, END
BEGIN NOW And one bad act with many deeds well done END
BEGIN NOW Mayest cover: Well may then thy Lord, appeased, END
BEGIN NOW Redeem thee quite from Death's rapacious claim; END
BEGIN NOW But longer in this Paradise to dwell END
BEGIN NOW Permits not: to remove thee I am come, END
BEGIN NOW And send thee from the garden forth to till END
BEGIN NOW The ground whence thou wast taken, fitter soil. END
BEGIN NOW He added not; for Adam at the news END
BEGIN NOW Heart-struck with chilling gripe of sorrow stood, END
BEGIN NOW That all his senses bound; Eve, who unseen END
BEGIN NOW Yet all had heard, with audible lament END
BEGIN NOW Discovered soon the place of her retire. END
BEGIN NOW O unexpected stroke, worse than of Death! END
BEGIN NOW Must I thus leave thee Paradise? thus leave END
BEGIN NOW Thee, native soil! these happy walks and shades, END
BEGIN NOW Fit haunt of Gods? where I had hope to spend, END
BEGIN NOW Quiet though sad, the respite of that day END
BEGIN NOW That must be mortal to us both. O flowers, END
BEGIN NOW That never will in other climate grow, END
BEGIN NOW My early visitation, and my last END
BEGIN NOW At even, which I bred up with tender hand END
BEGIN NOW From the first opening bud, and gave ye names, END
BEGIN NOW Who now shall rear ye to the sun, or rank END
BEGIN NOW Your tribes, and water from the ambrosial fount? END
BEGIN NOW Thee lastly, nuptial bower! by me adorned END
BEGIN NOW With what to sight or smell was sweet! from thee END
BEGIN NOW How shall I part, and whither wander down END
BEGIN NOW Into a lower world; to this obscure END
BEGIN NOW And wild, how shall we breathe in other air END
BEGIN NOW Less pure, accustomed to immortal fruits? END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus the Angel interrupted mild. END
BEGIN NOW Lament not, Eve, but patiently resign END
BEGIN NOW What justly thou hast lost, nor set thy heart, END
BEGIN NOW Thus over-fond, on that which is not thine: END
BEGIN NOW Thy going is not lonely; with thee goes END
BEGIN NOW Thy husband; whom to follow thou art bound; END
BEGIN NOW Where he abides, think there thy native soil. END
BEGIN NOW Adam, by this from the cold sudden damp END
BEGIN NOW Recovering, and his scattered spirits returned, END
BEGIN NOW To Michael thus his humble words addressed. END
BEGIN NOW Celestial, whether among the Thrones, or named END
BEGIN NOW Of them the highest; for such of shape may seem END
BEGIN NOW Prince above princes! gently hast thou told END
BEGIN NOW Thy message, which might else in telling wound, END
BEGIN NOW And in performing end us; what besides END
BEGIN NOW Of sorrow, and dejection, and despair, END
BEGIN NOW Our frailty can sustain, thy tidings bring, END
BEGIN NOW Departure from this happy place, our sweet END
BEGIN NOW Recess, and only consolation left END
BEGIN NOW Familiar to our eyes! all places else END
BEGIN NOW Inhospitable appear, and desolate; END
BEGIN NOW Nor knowing us, nor known: And, if by prayer END
BEGIN NOW Incessant I could hope to change the will END
BEGIN NOW Of Him who all things can, I would not cease END
BEGIN NOW To weary him with my assiduous cries: END
BEGIN NOW But prayer against his absolute decree END
BEGIN NOW No more avails than breath against the wind, END
BEGIN NOW Blown stifling back on him that breathes it forth: END
BEGIN NOW Therefore to his great bidding I submit. END
BEGIN NOW This most afflicts me, that, departing hence, END
BEGIN NOW As from his face I shall be hid, deprived END
BEGIN NOW His blessed countenance: Here I could frequent END
BEGIN NOW With worship place by place where he vouchsafed END
BEGIN NOW Presence Divine; and to my sons relate, END
BEGIN NOW On this mount he appeared; under this tree END
BEGIN NOW Stood visible; among these pines his voice END
BEGIN NOW I heard; here with him at this fountain talked: END
BEGIN NOW So many grateful altars I would rear END
BEGIN NOW Of grassy turf, and pile up every stone END
BEGIN NOW Of lustre from the brook, in memory, END
BEGIN NOW Or monument to ages; and theron END
BEGIN NOW Offer sweet-smelling gums, and fruits, and flowers: END
BEGIN NOW In yonder nether world where shall I seek END
BEGIN NOW His bright appearances, or foot-step trace? END
BEGIN NOW For though I fled him angry, yet recalled END
BEGIN NOW To life prolonged and promised race, I now END
BEGIN NOW Gladly behold though but his utmost skirts END
BEGIN NOW Of glory; and far off his steps adore. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Michael with regard benign. END
BEGIN NOW Adam, thou knowest Heaven his, and all the Earth; END
BEGIN NOW Not this rock only; his Omnipresence fills END
BEGIN NOW Land, sea, and air, and every kind that lives, END
BEGIN NOW Fomented by his virtual power and warmed: END
BEGIN NOW All the earth he gave thee to possess and rule, END
BEGIN NOW No despicable gift; surmise not then END
BEGIN NOW His presence to these narrow bounds confined END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise, or Eden: this had been END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps thy capital seat, from whence had spread END
BEGIN NOW All generations; and had hither come END
BEGIN NOW From all the ends of the earth, to celebrate END
BEGIN NOW And reverence thee, their great progenitor. END
BEGIN NOW But this pre-eminence thou hast lost, brought down END
BEGIN NOW To dwell on even ground now with thy sons: END
BEGIN NOW Yet doubt not but in valley, and in plain, END
BEGIN NOW God is, as here; and will be found alike END
BEGIN NOW Present; and of his presence many a sign END
BEGIN NOW Still following thee, still compassing thee round END
BEGIN NOW With goodness and paternal love, his face END
BEGIN NOW Express, and of his steps the track divine. END
BEGIN NOW Which that thou mayest believe, and be confirmed END
BEGIN NOW Ere thou from hence depart; know, I am sent END
BEGIN NOW To show thee what shall come in future days END
BEGIN NOW To thee, and to thy offspring: good with bad END
BEGIN NOW Expect to hear; supernal grace contending END
BEGIN NOW With sinfulness of men; thereby to learn END
BEGIN NOW True patience, and to temper joy with fear END
BEGIN NOW And pious sorrow; equally inured END
BEGIN NOW By moderation either state to bear, END
BEGIN NOW Prosperous or adverse: so shalt thou lead END
BEGIN NOW Safest thy life, and best prepared endure END
BEGIN NOW Thy mortal passage when it comes.--Ascend END
BEGIN NOW This hill; let Eve (for I have drenched her eyes) END
BEGIN NOW Here sleep below; while thou to foresight wakest; END
BEGIN NOW As once thou sleptst, while she to life was formed. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Adam gratefully replied. END
BEGIN NOW Ascend, I follow thee, safe Guide, the path END
BEGIN NOW Thou leadest me; and to the hand of Heaven submit, END
BEGIN NOW However chastening; to the evil turn END
BEGIN NOW My obvious breast; arming to overcome END
BEGIN NOW By suffering, and earn rest from labour won, END
BEGIN NOW If so I may attain.--So both ascend END
BEGIN NOW In the visions of God. It was a hill, END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise the highest; from whose top END
BEGIN NOW The hemisphere of earth, in clearest ken, END
BEGIN NOW Stretched out to the amplest reach of prospect lay. END
BEGIN NOW Not higher that hill, nor wider looking round, END
BEGIN NOW Whereon, for different cause, the Tempter set END
BEGIN NOW Our second Adam, in the wilderness; END
BEGIN NOW To show him all Earth's kingdoms, and their glory. END
BEGIN NOW His eye might there command wherever stood END
BEGIN NOW City of old or modern fame, the seat END
BEGIN NOW Of mightiest empire, from the destined walls END
BEGIN NOW Of Cambalu, seat of Cathaian Can, END
BEGIN NOW And Samarchand by Oxus, Temir's throne, END
BEGIN NOW To Paquin of Sinaean kings; and thence END
BEGIN NOW To Agra and Lahor of great Mogul, END
BEGIN NOW Down to the golden Chersonese; or where END
BEGIN NOW The Persian in Ecbatan sat, or since END
BEGIN NOW In Hispahan; or where the Russian Ksar END
BEGIN NOW Turchestan-born; nor could his eye not ken END
BEGIN NOW The empire of Negus to his utmost port END
BEGIN NOW Ercoco, and the less maritim kings END
BEGIN NOW And Sofala, thought Ophir, to the realm END
BEGIN NOW Of Congo, and Angola farthest south; END
BEGIN NOW Or thence from Niger flood to Atlas mount END
BEGIN NOW The kingdoms of Almansor, Fez and Sus, END
BEGIN NOW On Europe thence, and where Rome was to sway END
BEGIN NOW The world: in spirit perhaps he also saw END
BEGIN NOW Rich Mexico, the seat of Montezume, END
BEGIN NOW And Cusco in Peru, the richer seat END
BEGIN NOW Of Atabalipa; and yet unspoiled END
BEGIN NOW Guiana, whose great city Geryon's sons END
BEGIN NOW Call El Dorado. But to nobler sights END
BEGIN NOW Michael from Adam's eyes the film removed, END
BEGIN NOW Which that false fruit that promised clearer sight END
BEGIN NOW Had bred; then purged with euphrasy and rue END
BEGIN NOW The visual nerve, for he had much to see; END
BEGIN NOW And from the well of life three drops instilled. END
BEGIN NOW So deep the power of these ingredients pierced, END
BEGIN NOW Even to the inmost seat of mental sight, END
BEGIN NOW That Adam, now enforced to close his eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Sunk down, and all his spirits became entranced; END
BEGIN NOW But him the gentle Angel by the hand END
BEGIN NOW Soon raised, and his attention thus recalled. END
BEGIN NOW Adam, now ope thine eyes; and first behold END
BEGIN NOW The effects, which thy original crime hath wrought END
BEGIN NOW In some to spring from thee; who never touched END
BEGIN NOW The excepted tree; nor with the snake conspired; END
BEGIN NOW Nor sinned thy sin; yet from that sin derive END
BEGIN NOW Corruption, to bring forth more violent deeds. END
BEGIN NOW His eyes he opened, and beheld a field, END
BEGIN NOW Part arable and tilth, whereon were sheaves END
BEGIN NOW New reaped; the other part sheep-walks and folds; END
BEGIN NOW I' the midst an altar as the land-mark stood, END
BEGIN NOW Rustick, of grassy sord; thither anon END
BEGIN NOW A sweaty reaper from his tillage brought END
BEGIN NOW First fruits, the green ear, and the yellow sheaf, END
BEGIN NOW Unculled, as came to hand; a shepherd next, END
BEGIN NOW More meek, came with the firstlings of his flock, END
BEGIN NOW Choicest and best; then, sacrificing, laid END
BEGIN NOW The inwards and their fat, with incense strowed, END
BEGIN NOW On the cleft wood, and all due rights performed: END
BEGIN NOW His offering soon propitious fire from Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Consumed with nimble glance, and grateful steam; END
BEGIN NOW The other's not, for his was not sincere; END
BEGIN NOW Whereat he inly raged, and, as they talked, END
BEGIN NOW Smote him into the midriff with a stone END
BEGIN NOW That beat out life; he fell; and, deadly pale, END
BEGIN NOW Groaned out his soul with gushing blood effused. END
BEGIN NOW Much at that sight was Adam in his heart END
BEGIN NOW Dismayed, and thus in haste to the Angel cried. END
BEGIN NOW O Teacher, some great mischief hath befallen END
BEGIN NOW To that meek man, who well had sacrificed; END
BEGIN NOW Is piety thus and pure devotion paid? END
BEGIN NOW To whom Michael thus, he also moved, replied. END
BEGIN NOW These two are brethren, Adam, and to come END
BEGIN NOW Out of thy loins; the unjust the just hath slain, END
BEGIN NOW For envy that his brother's offering found END
BEGIN NOW From Heaven acceptance; but the bloody fact END
BEGIN NOW Will be avenged; and the other's faith, approved, END
BEGIN NOW Lose no reward; though here thou see him die, END
BEGIN NOW Rolling in dust and gore. To which our sire. END
BEGIN NOW Alas! both for the deed, and for the cause! END
BEGIN NOW But have I now seen Death? Is this the way END
BEGIN NOW I must return to native dust? O sight END
BEGIN NOW Of terrour, foul and ugly to behold, END
BEGIN NOW Horrid to think, how horrible to feel! END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Michael. Death thou hast seen END
BEGIN NOW In his first shape on Man; but many shapes END
BEGIN NOW Of Death, and many are the ways that lead END
BEGIN NOW To his grim cave, all dismal; yet to sense END
BEGIN NOW More terrible at the entrance, than within. END
BEGIN NOW Some, as thou sawest, by violent stroke shall die; END
BEGIN NOW By fire, flood, famine, by intemperance more END
BEGIN NOW In meats and drinks, which on the earth shall bring END
BEGIN NOW Diseases dire, of which a monstrous crew END
BEGIN NOW Before thee shall appear; that thou mayest know END
BEGIN NOW What misery the inabstinence of Eve END
BEGIN NOW Shall bring on Men. Immediately a place END
BEGIN NOW Before his eyes appeared, sad, noisome, dark; END
BEGIN NOW A lazar-house it seemed; wherein were laid END
BEGIN NOW Numbers of all diseased; all maladies END
BEGIN NOW Of ghastly spasm, or racking torture, qualms END
BEGIN NOW Of heart-sick agony, all feverous kinds, END
BEGIN NOW Convulsions, epilepsies, fierce catarrhs, END
BEGIN NOW Intestine stone and ulcer, colick-pangs, END
BEGIN NOW Demoniack phrenzy, moaping melancholy, END
BEGIN NOW And moon-struck madness, pining atrophy, END
BEGIN NOW Marasmus, and wide-wasting pestilence, END
BEGIN NOW Dropsies, and asthmas, and joint-racking rheums. END
BEGIN NOW Dire was the tossing, deep the groans; Despair END
BEGIN NOW Tended the sick busiest from couch to couch; END
BEGIN NOW And over them triumphant Death his dart END
BEGIN NOW Shook, but delayed to strike, though oft invoked END
BEGIN NOW With vows, as their chief good, and final hope. END
BEGIN NOW Sight so deform what heart of rock could long END
BEGIN NOW Dry-eyed behold? Adam could not, but wept, END
BEGIN NOW Though not of woman born; compassion quelled END
BEGIN NOW His best of man, and gave him up to tears END
BEGIN NOW A space, till firmer thoughts restrained excess; END
BEGIN NOW And, scarce recovering words, his plaint renewed. END
BEGIN NOW O miserable mankind, to what fall END
BEGIN NOW Degraded, to what wretched state reserved! END
BEGIN NOW Better end here unborn. Why is life given END
BEGIN NOW To be thus wrested from us? rather, why END
BEGIN NOW Obtruded on us thus? who, if we knew END
BEGIN NOW What we receive, would either no accept END
BEGIN NOW Life offered, or soon beg to lay it down; END
BEGIN NOW Glad to be so dismissed in peace. Can thus END
BEGIN NOW The image of God in Man, created once END
BEGIN NOW So goodly and erect, though faulty since, END
BEGIN NOW To such unsightly sufferings be debased END
BEGIN NOW Under inhuman pains? Why should not Man, END
BEGIN NOW Retaining still divine similitude END
BEGIN NOW In part, from such deformities be free, END
BEGIN NOW And, for his Maker's image sake, exempt? END
BEGIN NOW Their Maker's image, answered Michael, then END
BEGIN NOW Forsook them, when themselves they vilified END
BEGIN NOW To serve ungoverned Appetite; and took END
BEGIN NOW His image whom they served, a brutish vice, END
BEGIN NOW Inductive mainly to the sin of Eve. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore so abject is their punishment, END
BEGIN NOW Disfiguring not God's likeness, but their own; END
BEGIN NOW Or if his likeness, by themselves defaced; END
BEGIN NOW While they pervert pure Nature's healthful rules END
BEGIN NOW To loathsome sickness; worthily, since they END
BEGIN NOW God's image did not reverence in themselves. END
BEGIN NOW I yield it just, said Adam, and submit. END
BEGIN NOW But is there yet no other way, besides END
BEGIN NOW These painful passages, how we may come END
BEGIN NOW To death, and mix with our connatural dust? END
BEGIN NOW There is, said Michael, if thou well observe END
BEGIN NOW The rule of Not too much; by temperance taught, END
BEGIN NOW In what thou eatest and drinkest; seeking from thence END
BEGIN NOW Due nourishment, not gluttonous delight, END
BEGIN NOW Till many years over thy head return: END
BEGIN NOW So mayest thou live; till, like ripe fruit, thou drop END
BEGIN NOW Into thy mother's lap; or be with ease END
BEGIN NOW Gathered, nor harshly plucked; for death mature: END
BEGIN NOW This is Old Age; but then, thou must outlive END
BEGIN NOW Thy youth, thy strength, thy beauty; which will change END
BEGIN NOW To withered, weak, and gray; thy senses then, END
BEGIN NOW Obtuse, all taste of pleasure must forego, END
BEGIN NOW To what thou hast; and, for the air of youth, END
BEGIN NOW Hopeful and cheerful, in thy blood will reign END
BEGIN NOW A melancholy damp of cold and dry END
BEGIN NOW To weigh thy spirits down, and last consume END
BEGIN NOW The balm of life. To whom our ancestor. END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth I fly not death, nor would prolong END
BEGIN NOW Life much; bent rather, how I may be quit, END
BEGIN NOW Fairest and easiest, of this cumbrous charge; END
BEGIN NOW Which I must keep till my appointed day END
BEGIN NOW Of rendering up, and patiently attend END
BEGIN NOW My dissolution. Michael replied. END
BEGIN NOW Nor love thy life, nor hate; but what thou livest END
BEGIN NOW Live well; how long, or short, permit to Heaven: END
BEGIN NOW And now prepare thee for another sight. END
BEGIN NOW He looked, and saw a spacious plain, whereon END
BEGIN NOW Were tents of various hue; by some, were herds END
BEGIN NOW Of cattle grazing; others, whence the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of instruments, that made melodious chime, END
BEGIN NOW Was heard, of harp and organ; and, who moved END
BEGIN NOW Their stops and chords, was seen; his volant touch, END
BEGIN NOW Instinct through all proportions, low and high, END
BEGIN NOW Fled and pursued transverse the resonant fugue. END
BEGIN NOW In other part stood one who, at the forge END
BEGIN NOW Labouring, two massy clods of iron and brass END
BEGIN NOW Had melted, (whether found where casual fire END
BEGIN NOW Had wasted woods on mountain or in vale, END
BEGIN NOW Down to the veins of earth; thence gliding hot END
BEGIN NOW To some cave's mouth; or whether washed by stream END
BEGIN NOW From underground;) the liquid ore he drained END
BEGIN NOW Into fit moulds prepared; from which he formed END
BEGIN NOW First his own tools; then, what might else be wrought END
BEGIN NOW Fusil or graven in metal. After these, END
BEGIN NOW But on the hither side, a different sort END
BEGIN NOW From the high neighbouring hills, which was their seat, END
BEGIN NOW Down to the plain descended; by their guise END
BEGIN NOW Just men they seemed, and all their study bent END
BEGIN NOW To worship God aright, and know his works END
BEGIN NOW Not hid; nor those things last, which might preserve END
BEGIN NOW Freedom and peace to Men; they on the plain END
BEGIN NOW Long had not walked, when from the tents, behold! END
BEGIN NOW A bevy of fair women, richly gay END
BEGIN NOW In gems and wanton dress; to the harp they sung END
BEGIN NOW Soft amorous ditties, and in dance came on: END
BEGIN NOW The men, though grave, eyed them; and let their eyes END
BEGIN NOW Rove without rein; till, in the amorous net END
BEGIN NOW Fast caught, they liked; and each his liking chose; END
BEGIN NOW And now of love they treat, till the evening-star, END
BEGIN NOW Love's harbinger, appeared; then, all in heat END
BEGIN NOW They light the nuptial torch, and bid invoke END
BEGIN NOW Hymen, then first to marriage rites invoked: END
BEGIN NOW With feast and musick all the tents resound. END
BEGIN NOW Such happy interview, and fair event END
BEGIN NOW Of love and youth not lost, songs, garlands, flowers, END
BEGIN NOW And charming symphonies, attached the heart END
BEGIN NOW Of Adam, soon inclined to admit delight, END
BEGIN NOW The bent of nature; which he thus expressed. END
BEGIN NOW True opener of mine eyes, prime Angel blest; END
BEGIN NOW Much better seems this vision, and more hope END
BEGIN NOW Of peaceful days portends, than those two past; END
BEGIN NOW Those were of hate and death, or pain much worse; END
BEGIN NOW Here Nature seems fulfilled in all her ends. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Michael. Judge not what is best END
BEGIN NOW By pleasure, though to nature seeming meet; END
BEGIN NOW Created, as thou art, to nobler end END
BEGIN NOW Holy and pure, conformity divine. END
BEGIN NOW Those tents thou sawest so pleasant, were the tents END
BEGIN NOW Of wickedness, wherein shall dwell his race END
BEGIN NOW Who slew his brother; studious they appear END
BEGIN NOW Of arts that polish life, inventers rare; END
BEGIN NOW Unmindful of their Maker, though his Spirit END
BEGIN NOW Taught them; but they his gifts acknowledged none. END
BEGIN NOW Yet they a beauteous offspring shall beget; END
BEGIN NOW For that fair female troop thou sawest, that seemed END
BEGIN NOW Of Goddesses, so blithe, so smooth, so gay, END
BEGIN NOW Yet empty of all good wherein consists END
BEGIN NOW Woman's domestick honour and chief praise; END
BEGIN NOW Bred only and completed to the taste END
BEGIN NOW Of lustful appetence, to sing, to dance, END
BEGIN NOW To dress, and troll the tongue, and roll the eye: END
BEGIN NOW To these that sober race of men, whose lives END
BEGIN NOW Religious titled them the sons of God, END
BEGIN NOW Shall yield up all their virtue, all their fame END
BEGIN NOW Ignobly, to the trains and to the smiles END
BEGIN NOW Of these fair atheists; and now swim in joy, END
BEGIN NOW Erelong to swim at large; and laugh, for which END
BEGIN NOW The world erelong a world of tears must weep. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Adam, of short joy bereft. END
BEGIN NOW O pity and shame, that they, who to live well END
BEGIN NOW Entered so fair, should turn aside to tread END
BEGIN NOW Paths indirect, or in the mid way faint! END
BEGIN NOW But still I see the tenour of Man's woe END
BEGIN NOW Holds on the same, from Woman to begin. END
BEGIN NOW From Man's effeminate slackness it begins, END
BEGIN NOW Said the Angel, who should better hold his place END
BEGIN NOW By wisdom, and superiour gifts received. END
BEGIN NOW But now prepare thee for another scene. END
BEGIN NOW He looked, and saw wide territory spread END
BEGIN NOW Before him, towns, and rural works between; END
BEGIN NOW Cities of men with lofty gates and towers, END
BEGIN NOW Concourse in arms, fierce faces threatening war, END
BEGIN NOW Giants of mighty bone and bold emprise; END
BEGIN NOW Part wield their arms, part curb the foaming steed, END
BEGIN NOW Single or in array of battle ranged END
BEGIN NOW Both horse and foot, nor idly mustering stood; END
BEGIN NOW One way a band select from forage drives END
BEGIN NOW A herd of beeves, fair oxen and fair kine, END
BEGIN NOW From a fat meadow ground; or fleecy flock, END
BEGIN NOW Ewes and their bleating lambs over the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Their booty; scarce with life the shepherds fly, END
BEGIN NOW But call in aid, which makes a bloody fray; END
BEGIN NOW With cruel tournament the squadrons join; END
BEGIN NOW Where cattle pastured late, now scattered lies END
BEGIN NOW With carcasses and arms the ensanguined field, END
BEGIN NOW Deserted: Others to a city strong END
BEGIN NOW Lay siege, encamped; by battery, scale, and mine, END
BEGIN NOW Assaulting; others from the wall defend END
BEGIN NOW With dart and javelin, stones, and sulphurous fire; END
BEGIN NOW On each hand slaughter, and gigantick deeds. END
BEGIN NOW In other part the sceptered heralds call END
BEGIN NOW To council, in the city-gates; anon END
BEGIN NOW Gray-headed men and grave, with warriours mixed, END
BEGIN NOW Assemble, and harangues are heard; but soon, END
BEGIN NOW In factious opposition; till at last, END
BEGIN NOW Of middle age one rising, eminent END
BEGIN NOW In wise deport, spake much of right and wrong, END
BEGIN NOW Of justice, or religion, truth, and peace, END
BEGIN NOW And judgement from above: him old and young END
BEGIN NOW Exploded, and had seized with violent hands, END
BEGIN NOW Had not a cloud descending snatched him thence END
BEGIN NOW Unseen amid the throng: so violence END
BEGIN NOW Proceeded, and oppression, and sword-law, END
BEGIN NOW Through all the plain, and refuge none was found. END
BEGIN NOW Adam was all in tears, and to his guide END
BEGIN NOW Lamenting turned full sad; O! what are these, END
BEGIN NOW Death's ministers, not men? who thus deal death END
BEGIN NOW Inhumanly to men, and multiply END
BEGIN NOW Ten thousandfold the sin of him who slew END
BEGIN NOW His brother: for of whom such massacre END
BEGIN NOW Make they, but of their brethren; men of men END
BEGIN NOW But who was that just man, whom had not Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Rescued, had in his righteousness been lost? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Michael. These are the product END
BEGIN NOW Of those ill-mated marriages thou sawest; END
BEGIN NOW Where good with bad were matched, who of themselves END
BEGIN NOW Abhor to join; and, by imprudence mixed, END
BEGIN NOW Produce prodigious births of body or mind. END
BEGIN NOW Such were these giants, men of high renown; END
BEGIN NOW For in those days might only shall be admired, END
BEGIN NOW And valour and heroick virtue called; END
BEGIN NOW To overcome in battle, and subdue END
BEGIN NOW Nations, and bring home spoils with infinite END
BEGIN NOW Man-slaughter, shall be held the highest pitch END
BEGIN NOW Of human glory; and for glory done END
BEGIN NOW Of triumph, to be styled great conquerours END
BEGIN NOW Patrons of mankind, Gods, and sons of Gods; END
BEGIN NOW Destroyers rightlier called, and plagues of men. END
BEGIN NOW Thus fame shall be achieved, renown on earth; END
BEGIN NOW And what most merits fame, in silence hid. END
BEGIN NOW But he, the seventh from thee, whom thou beheldst END
BEGIN NOW The only righteous in a world preverse, END
BEGIN NOW And therefore hated, therefore so beset END
BEGIN NOW With foes, for daring single to be just, END
BEGIN NOW And utter odious truth, that God would come END
BEGIN NOW To judge them with his Saints; him the Most High END
BEGIN NOW Rapt in a balmy cloud with winged steeds END
BEGIN NOW Did, as thou sawest, receive, to walk with God END
BEGIN NOW High in salvation and the climes of bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Exempt from death; to show thee what reward END
BEGIN NOW Awaits the good; the rest what punishment; END
BEGIN NOW Which now direct thine eyes and soon behold. END
BEGIN NOW He looked, and saw the face of things quite changed; END
BEGIN NOW The brazen throat of war had ceased to roar; END
BEGIN NOW All now was turned to jollity and game, END
BEGIN NOW To luxury and riot, feast and dance; END
BEGIN NOW Marrying or prostituting, as befel, END
BEGIN NOW Rape or adultery, where passing fair END
BEGIN NOW Allured them; thence from cups to civil broils. END
BEGIN NOW At length a reverend sire among them came, END
BEGIN NOW And of their doings great dislike declared, END
BEGIN NOW And testified against their ways; he oft END
BEGIN NOW Frequented their assemblies, whereso met, END
BEGIN NOW Triumphs or festivals; and to them preached END
BEGIN NOW Conversion and repentance, as to souls END
BEGIN NOW In prison, under judgements imminent: END
BEGIN NOW But all in vain: which when he saw, he ceased END
BEGIN NOW Contending, and removed his tents far off; END
BEGIN NOW Then, from the mountain hewing timber tall, END
BEGIN NOW Began to build a vessel of huge bulk; END
BEGIN NOW Measured by cubit, length, and breadth, and highth; END
BEGIN NOW Smeared round with pitch; and in the side a door END
BEGIN NOW Contrived; and of provisions laid in large, END
BEGIN NOW For man and beast: when lo, a wonder strange! END
BEGIN NOW Of every beast, and bird, and insect small, END
BEGIN NOW Came sevens, and pairs; and entered in as taught END
BEGIN NOW Their order: last the sire and his three sons, END
BEGIN NOW With their four wives; and God made fast the door. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while the south-wind rose, and, with black wings END
BEGIN NOW Wide-hovering, all the clouds together drove END
BEGIN NOW From under Heaven; the hills to their supply END
BEGIN NOW Vapour, and exhalation dusk and moist, END
BEGIN NOW Sent up amain; and now the thickened sky END
BEGIN NOW Like a dark ceiling stood; down rushed the rain END
BEGIN NOW Impetuous; and continued, till the earth END
BEGIN NOW No more was seen: the floating vessel swum END
BEGIN NOW Uplifted, and secure with beaked prow END
BEGIN NOW Rode tilting o'er the waves; all dwellings else END
BEGIN NOW Flood overwhelmed, and them with all their pomp END
BEGIN NOW Deep under water rolled; sea covered sea, END
BEGIN NOW Sea without shore; and in their palaces, END
BEGIN NOW Where luxury late reigned, sea-monsters whelped END
BEGIN NOW And stabled; of mankind, so numerous late, END
BEGIN NOW All left, in one small bottom swum imbarked. END
BEGIN NOW How didst thou grieve then, Adam, to behold END
BEGIN NOW The end of all thy offspring, end so sad, END
BEGIN NOW Depopulation! Thee another flood, END
BEGIN NOW Of tears and sorrow a flood, thee also drowned, END
BEGIN NOW And sunk thee as thy sons; till, gently reared END
BEGIN NOW By the Angel, on thy feet thou stoodest at last, END
BEGIN NOW Though comfortless; as when a father mourns END
BEGIN NOW His children, all in view destroyed at once; END
BEGIN NOW And scarce to the Angel utter'dst thus thy plaint. END
BEGIN NOW O visions ill foreseen! Better had I END
BEGIN NOW Lived ignorant of future! so had borne END
BEGIN NOW My part of evil only, each day's lot END
BEGIN NOW Enough to bear; those now, that were dispensed END
BEGIN NOW The burden of many ages, on me light END
BEGIN NOW At once, by my foreknowledge gaining birth END
BEGIN NOW Abortive, to torment me ere their being, END
BEGIN NOW With thought that they must be. Let no man seek END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth to be foretold, what shall befall END
BEGIN NOW Him or his children; evil he may be sure, END
BEGIN NOW Which neither his foreknowing can prevent; END
BEGIN NOW And he the future evil shall no less END
BEGIN NOW In apprehension than in substance feel, END
BEGIN NOW Grievous to bear: but that care now is past, END
BEGIN NOW Man is not whom to warn: those few escaped END
BEGIN NOW Famine and anguish will at last consume, END
BEGIN NOW Wandering that watery desart: I had hope, END
BEGIN NOW When violence was ceased, and war on earth, END
BEGIN NOW All would have then gone well; peace would have crowned END
BEGIN NOW With length of happy days the race of Man; END
BEGIN NOW But I was far deceived; for now I see END
BEGIN NOW Peace to corrupt no less than war to waste. END
BEGIN NOW How comes it thus? unfold, celestial Guide, END
BEGIN NOW And whether here the race of Man will end. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Michael. Those, whom last thou sawest END
BEGIN NOW In triumph and luxurious wealth, are they END
BEGIN NOW First seen in acts of prowess eminent END
BEGIN NOW And great exploits, but of true virtue void; END
BEGIN NOW Who, having spilt much blood, and done much wast END
BEGIN NOW Subduing nations, and achieved thereby END
BEGIN NOW Fame in the world, high titles, and rich prey; END
BEGIN NOW Shall change their course to pleasure, ease, and sloth, END
BEGIN NOW Surfeit, and lust; till wantonness and pride END
BEGIN NOW Raise out of friendship hostile deeds in peace. END
BEGIN NOW The conquered also, and enslaved by war, END
BEGIN NOW Shall, with their freedom lost, all virtue lose END
BEGIN NOW And fear of God; from whom their piety feigned END
BEGIN NOW In sharp contest of battle found no aid END
BEGIN NOW Against invaders; therefore, cooled in zeal, END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth shall practice how to live secure, END
BEGIN NOW Worldly or dissolute, on what their lords END
BEGIN NOW Shall leave them to enjoy; for the earth shall bear END
BEGIN NOW More than enough, that temperance may be tried: END
BEGIN NOW So all shall turn degenerate, all depraved; END
BEGIN NOW Justice and temperance, truth and faith, forgot; END
BEGIN NOW One man except, the only son of light END
BEGIN NOW In a dark age, against example good, END
BEGIN NOW Against allurement, custom, and a world END
BEGIN NOW Offended: fearless of reproach and scorn, END
BEGIN NOW Or violence, he of their wicked ways END
BEGIN NOW Shall them admonish; and before them set END
BEGIN NOW The paths of righteousness, how much more safe END
BEGIN NOW And full of peace; denouncing wrath to come END
BEGIN NOW On their impenitence; and shall return END
BEGIN NOW Of them derided, but of God observed END
BEGIN NOW The one just man alive; by his command END
BEGIN NOW Shall build a wonderous ark, as thou beheldst, END
BEGIN NOW To save himself, and houshold, from amidst END
BEGIN NOW A world devote to universal wrack. END
BEGIN NOW No sooner he, with them of man and beast END
BEGIN NOW Select for life, shall in the ark be lodged, END
BEGIN NOW And sheltered round; but all the cataracts END
BEGIN NOW Of Heaven set open on the Earth shall pour END
BEGIN NOW Rain, day and night; all fountains of the deep, END
BEGIN NOW Broke up, shall heave the ocean to usurp END
BEGIN NOW Beyond all bounds; till inundation rise END
BEGIN NOW Above the highest hills: Then shall this mount END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise by might of waves be moved END
BEGIN NOW Out of his place, pushed by the horned flood, END
BEGIN NOW With all his verdure spoiled, and trees adrift, END
BEGIN NOW Down the great river to the opening gulf, END
BEGIN NOW And there take root an island salt and bare, END
BEGIN NOW The haunt of seals, and orcs, and sea-mews' clang: END
BEGIN NOW To teach thee that God attributes to place END
BEGIN NOW No sanctity, if none be thither brought END
BEGIN NOW By men who there frequent, or therein dwell. END
BEGIN NOW And now, what further shall ensue, behold. END
BEGIN NOW He looked, and saw the ark hull on the flood, END
BEGIN NOW Which now abated; for the clouds were fled, END
BEGIN NOW Driven by a keen north-wind, that, blowing dry, END
BEGIN NOW Wrinkled the face of deluge, as decayed; END
BEGIN NOW And the clear sun on his wide watery glass END
BEGIN NOW Gazed hot, and of the fresh wave largely drew, END
BEGIN NOW As after thirst; which made their flowing shrink END
BEGIN NOW From standing lake to tripping ebb, that stole END
BEGIN NOW With soft foot towards the deep; who now had stopt END
BEGIN NOW His sluces, as the Heaven his windows shut. END
BEGIN NOW The ark no more now floats, but seems on ground, END
BEGIN NOW Fast on the top of some high mountain fixed. END
BEGIN NOW And now the tops of hills, as rocks, appear; END
BEGIN NOW With clamour thence the rapid currents drive, END
BEGIN NOW Towards the retreating sea, their furious tide. END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith from out the ark a raven flies, END
BEGIN NOW And after him, the surer messenger, END
BEGIN NOW A dove sent forth once and again to spy END
BEGIN NOW Green tree or ground, whereon his foot may light: END
BEGIN NOW The second time returning, in his bill END
BEGIN NOW An olive-leaf he brings, pacifick sign: END
BEGIN NOW Anon dry ground appears, and from his ark END
BEGIN NOW The ancient sire descends, with all his train; END
BEGIN NOW Then with uplifted hands, and eyes devout, END
BEGIN NOW Grateful to Heaven, over his head beholds END
BEGIN NOW A dewy cloud, and in the cloud a bow END
BEGIN NOW Conspicuous with three lifted colours gay, END
BEGIN NOW Betokening peace from God, and covenant new. END
BEGIN NOW Whereat the heart of Adam, erst so sad, END
BEGIN NOW Greatly rejoiced; and thus his joy broke forth. END
BEGIN NOW O thou, who future things canst represent END
BEGIN NOW As present, heavenly Instructer! I revive END
BEGIN NOW At this last sight; assured that Man shall live, END
BEGIN NOW With all the creatures, and their seed preserve. END
BEGIN NOW Far less I now lament for one whole world END
BEGIN NOW Of wicked sons destroyed, than I rejoice END
BEGIN NOW For one man found so perfect, and so just, END
BEGIN NOW That God vouchsafes to raise another world END
BEGIN NOW From him, and all his anger to forget. END
BEGIN NOW But say, what mean those coloured streaks in Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Distended, as the brow of God appeased? END
BEGIN NOW Or serve they, as a flowery verge, to bind END
BEGIN NOW The fluid skirts of that same watery cloud, END
BEGIN NOW Lest it again dissolve, and shower the earth? END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Arch-Angel. Dextrously thou aimest; END
BEGIN NOW So willingly doth God remit his ire, END
BEGIN NOW Though late repenting him of Man depraved; END
BEGIN NOW Grieved at his heart, when looking down he saw END
BEGIN NOW The whole earth filled with violence, and all flesh END
BEGIN NOW Corrupting each their way; yet, those removed, END
BEGIN NOW Such grace shall one just man find in his sight, END
BEGIN NOW That he relents, not to blot out mankind; END
BEGIN NOW And makes a covenant never to destroy END
BEGIN NOW The earth again by flood; nor let the sea END
BEGIN NOW Surpass his bounds; nor rain to drown the world, END
BEGIN NOW With man therein or beast; but, when he brings END
BEGIN NOW Over the earth a cloud, will therein set END
BEGIN NOW His triple-coloured bow, whereon to look, END
BEGIN NOW And call to mind his covenant: Day and night, END
BEGIN NOW Seed-time and harvest, heat and hoary frost, END
BEGIN NOW Shall hold their course; till fire purge all things new, END
BEGIN NOW Both Heaven and Earth, wherein the just shall dwell. END
BEGIN NOW As one who in his journey bates at noon, END
BEGIN NOW Though bent on speed; so here the Arch-Angel paused END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the world destroyed and world restored, END
BEGIN NOW If Adam aught perhaps might interpose; END
BEGIN NOW Then, with transition sweet, new speech resumes. END
BEGIN NOW Thus thou hast seen one world begin, and end; END
BEGIN NOW And Man, as from a second stock, proceed. END
BEGIN NOW Much thou hast yet to see; but I perceive END
BEGIN NOW Thy mortal sight to fail; objects divine END
BEGIN NOW Must needs impair and weary human sense: END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth what is to come I will relate; END
BEGIN NOW Thou therefore give due audience, and attend. END
BEGIN NOW This second source of Men, while yet but few, END
BEGIN NOW And while the dread of judgement past remains END
BEGIN NOW Fresh in their minds, fearing the Deity, END
BEGIN NOW With some regard to what is just and right END
BEGIN NOW Shall lead their lives, and multiply apace; END
BEGIN NOW Labouring the soil, and reaping plenteous crop, END
BEGIN NOW Corn, wine, and oil; and, from the herd or flock, END
BEGIN NOW Oft sacrificing bullock, lamb, or kid, END
BEGIN NOW With large wine-offerings poured, and sacred feast, END
BEGIN NOW Shall spend their days in joy unblamed; and dwell END
BEGIN NOW Long time in peace, by families and tribes, END
BEGIN NOW Under paternal rule: till one shall rise END
BEGIN NOW Of proud ambitious heart; who, not content END
BEGIN NOW With fair equality, fraternal state, END
BEGIN NOW Will arrogate dominion undeserved END
BEGIN NOW Over his brethren, and quite dispossess END
BEGIN NOW Concord and law of nature from the earth; END
BEGIN NOW Hunting (and men not beasts shall be his game) END
BEGIN NOW With war, and hostile snare, such as refuse END
BEGIN NOW Subjection to his empire tyrannous: END
BEGIN NOW A mighty hunter thence he shall be styled END
BEGIN NOW Before the Lord; as in despite of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Or from Heaven, claiming second sovranty; END
BEGIN NOW And from rebellion shall derive his name, END
BEGIN NOW Though of rebellion others he accuse. END
BEGIN NOW He with a crew, whom like ambition joins END
BEGIN NOW With him or under him to tyrannize, END
BEGIN NOW Marching from Eden towards the west, shall find END
BEGIN NOW The plain, wherein a black bituminous gurge END
BEGIN NOW Boils out from under ground, the mouth of Hell: END
BEGIN NOW Of brick, and of that stuff, they cast to build END
BEGIN NOW A city and tower, whose top may reach to Heaven; END
BEGIN NOW And get themselves a name; lest, far dispersed END
BEGIN NOW In foreign lands, their memory be lost; END
BEGIN NOW Regardless whether good or evil fame. END
BEGIN NOW But God, who oft descends to visit men END
BEGIN NOW Unseen, and through their habitations walks END
BEGIN NOW To mark their doings, them beholding soon, END
BEGIN NOW Comes down to see their city, ere the tower END
BEGIN NOW Obstruct Heaven-towers, and in derision sets END
BEGIN NOW Upon their tongues a various spirit, to rase END
BEGIN NOW Quite out their native language; and, instead, END
BEGIN NOW To sow a jangling noise of words unknown: END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith a hideous gabble rises loud, END
BEGIN NOW Among the builders; each to other calls END
BEGIN NOW Not understood; till hoarse, and all in rage, END
BEGIN NOW As mocked they storm: great laughter was in Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW And looking down, to see the hubbub strange, END
BEGIN NOW And hear the din: Thus was the building left END
BEGIN NOW Ridiculous, and the work Confusion named. END
BEGIN NOW Whereto thus Adam, fatherly displeased. END
BEGIN NOW O execrable son! so to aspire END
BEGIN NOW Above his brethren; to himself assuming END
BEGIN NOW Authority usurped, from God not given: END
BEGIN NOW He gave us only over beast, fish, fowl, END
BEGIN NOW Dominion absolute; that right we hold END
BEGIN NOW By his donation; but man over men END
BEGIN NOW He made not lord; such title to himself END
BEGIN NOW Reserving, human left from human free. END
BEGIN NOW But this usurper his encroachment proud END
BEGIN NOW Stays not on Man; to God his tower intends END
BEGIN NOW Siege and defiance: Wretched man! what food END
BEGIN NOW Will he convey up thither, to sustain END
BEGIN NOW Himself and his rash army; where thin air END
BEGIN NOW Above the clouds will pine his entrails gross, END
BEGIN NOW And famish him of breath, if not of bread? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Michael. Justly thou abhorrest END
BEGIN NOW That son, who on the quiet state of men END
BEGIN NOW Such trouble brought, affecting to subdue END
BEGIN NOW Rational liberty; yet know withal, END
BEGIN NOW Since thy original lapse, true liberty END
BEGIN NOW Is lost, which always with right reason dwells END
BEGIN NOW Twinned, and from her hath no dividual being: END
BEGIN NOW Reason in man obscured, or not obeyed, END
BEGIN NOW Immediately inordinate desires, END
BEGIN NOW And upstart passions, catch the government END
BEGIN NOW From reason; and to servitude reduce END
BEGIN NOW Man, till then free. Therefore, since he permits END
BEGIN NOW Within himself unworthy powers to reign END
BEGIN NOW Over free reason, God, in judgement just, END
BEGIN NOW Subjects him from without to violent lords; END
BEGIN NOW Who oft as undeservedly enthrall END
BEGIN NOW His outward freedom: Tyranny must be; END
BEGIN NOW Though to the tyrant thereby no excuse. END
BEGIN NOW Yet sometimes nations will decline so low END
BEGIN NOW From virtue, which is reason, that no wrong, END
BEGIN NOW But justice, and some fatal curse annexed, END
BEGIN NOW Deprives them of their outward liberty; END
BEGIN NOW Their inward lost: Witness the irreverent son END
BEGIN NOW Of him who built the ark; who, for the shame END
BEGIN NOW Done to his father, heard this heavy curse, END
BEGIN NOW Servant of servants, on his vicious race. END
BEGIN NOW Thus will this latter, as the former world, END
BEGIN NOW Still tend from bad to worse; till God at last, END
BEGIN NOW Wearied with their iniquities, withdraw END
BEGIN NOW His presence from among them, and avert END
BEGIN NOW His holy eyes; resolving from thenceforth END
BEGIN NOW To leave them to their own polluted ways; END
BEGIN NOW And one peculiar nation to select END
BEGIN NOW From all the rest, of whom to be invoked, END
BEGIN NOW A nation from one faithful man to spring: END
BEGIN NOW Him on this side Euphrates yet residing, END
BEGIN NOW Bred up in idol-worship: O, that men END
BEGIN NOW (Canst thou believe?) should be so stupid grown, END
BEGIN NOW While yet the patriarch lived, who 'scaped the flood, END
BEGIN NOW As to forsake the living God, and fall END
BEGIN NOW To worship their own work in wood and stone END
BEGIN NOW For Gods! Yet him God the Most High vouchsafes END
BEGIN NOW To call by vision, from his father's house, END
BEGIN NOW His kindred, and false Gods, into a land END
BEGIN NOW Which he will show him; and from him will raise END
BEGIN NOW A mighty nation; and upon him shower END
BEGIN NOW His benediction so, that in his seed END
BEGIN NOW All nations shall be blest: he straight obeys; END
BEGIN NOW Not knowing to what land, yet firm believes: END
BEGIN NOW I see him, but thou canst not, with what faith END
BEGIN NOW He leaves his Gods, his friends, and native soil, END
BEGIN NOW Ur of Chaldaea, passing now the ford END
BEGIN NOW To Haran; after him a cumbrous train END
BEGIN NOW Of herds and flocks, and numerous servitude; END
BEGIN NOW Not wandering poor, but trusting all his wealth END
BEGIN NOW With God, who called him, in a land unknown. END
BEGIN NOW Canaan he now attains; I see his tents END
BEGIN NOW Pitched about Sechem, and the neighbouring plain END
BEGIN NOW Of Moreh; there by promise he receives END
BEGIN NOW Gift to his progeny of all that land, END
BEGIN NOW From Hameth northward to the Desart south; END
BEGIN NOW (Things by their names I call, though yet unnamed;) END
BEGIN NOW From Hermon east to the great western Sea; END
BEGIN NOW Mount Hermon, yonder sea; each place behold END
BEGIN NOW In prospect, as I point them; on the shore END
BEGIN NOW Mount Carmel; here, the double-founted stream, END
BEGIN NOW Jordan, true limit eastward; but his sons END
BEGIN NOW Shall dwell to Senir, that long ridge of hills. END
BEGIN NOW This ponder, that all nations of the earth END
BEGIN NOW Shall in his seed be blessed: By that seed END
BEGIN NOW Is meant thy great Deliverer, who shall bruise END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent's head; whereof to thee anon END
BEGIN NOW Plainlier shall be revealed. This patriarch blest, END
BEGIN NOW Whom faithful Abraham due time shall call, END
BEGIN NOW A son, and of his son a grand-child, leaves; END
BEGIN NOW Like him in faith, in wisdom, and renown: END
BEGIN NOW The grandchild, with twelve sons increased, departs END
BEGIN NOW From Canaan to a land hereafter called END
BEGIN NOW See where it flows, disgorging at seven mouths END
BEGIN NOW Into the sea. To sojourn in that land END
BEGIN NOW He comes, invited by a younger son END
BEGIN NOW In time of dearth, a son whose worthy deeds END
BEGIN NOW Raise him to be the second in that realm END
BEGIN NOW Of Pharaoh. There he dies, and leaves his race END
BEGIN NOW Growing into a nation, and now grown END
BEGIN NOW Suspected to a sequent king, who seeks END
BEGIN NOW To stop their overgrowth, as inmate guests END
BEGIN NOW Too numerous; whence of guests he makes them slaves END
BEGIN NOW Inhospitably, and kills their infant males: END
BEGIN NOW Till by two brethren (these two brethren call END
BEGIN NOW Moses and Aaron) sent from God to claim END
BEGIN NOW His people from enthralment, they return, END
BEGIN NOW With glory and spoil, back to their promised land. END
BEGIN NOW But first, the lawless tyrant, who denies END
BEGIN NOW To know their God, or message to regard, END
BEGIN NOW Must be compelled by signs and judgements dire; END
BEGIN NOW To blood unshed the rivers must be turned; END
BEGIN NOW Frogs, lice, and flies, must all his palace fill END
BEGIN NOW With loathed intrusion, and fill all the land; END
BEGIN NOW His cattle must of rot and murren die; END
BEGIN NOW Botches and blains must all his flesh emboss, END
BEGIN NOW And all his people; thunder mixed with hail, END
BEGIN NOW And wheel on the earth, devouring where it rolls; END
BEGIN NOW What it devours not, herb, or fruit, or grain, END
BEGIN NOW A darksome cloud of locusts swarming down END
BEGIN NOW Must eat, and on the ground leave nothing green; END
BEGIN NOW Darkness must overshadow all his bounds, END
BEGIN NOW Palpable darkness, and blot out three days; END
BEGIN NOW Last, with one midnight stroke, all the first-born END
BEGIN NOW The river-dragon tamed at length submits END
BEGIN NOW To let his sojourners depart, and oft END
BEGIN NOW Humbles his stubborn heart; but still, as ice END
BEGIN NOW More hardened after thaw; till, in his rage END
BEGIN NOW Pursuing whom he late dismissed, the sea END
BEGIN NOW Swallows him with his host; but them lets pass, END
BEGIN NOW As on dry land, between two crystal walls; END
BEGIN NOW Awed by the rod of Moses so to stand END
BEGIN NOW Divided, till his rescued gain their shore: END
BEGIN NOW Such wondrous power God to his saint will lend, END
BEGIN NOW Though present in his Angel; who shall go END
BEGIN NOW Before them in a cloud, and pillar of fire; END
BEGIN NOW By day a cloud, by night a pillar of fire; END
BEGIN NOW To guide them in their journey, and remove END
BEGIN NOW Behind them, while the obdurate king pursues: END
BEGIN NOW All night he will pursue; but his approach END
BEGIN NOW Darkness defends between till morning watch; END
BEGIN NOW Then through the fiery pillar, and the cloud, END
BEGIN NOW God looking forth will trouble all his host, END
BEGIN NOW And craze their chariot-wheels: when by command END
BEGIN NOW Moses once more his potent rod extends END
BEGIN NOW Over the sea; the sea his rod obeys; END
BEGIN NOW On their embattled ranks the waves return, END
BEGIN NOW And overwhelm their war: The race elect END
BEGIN NOW Safe toward Canaan from the shore advance END
BEGIN NOW Through the wild Desart, not the readiest way; END
BEGIN NOW Lest, entering on the Canaanite alarmed, END
BEGIN NOW War terrify them inexpert, and fear END
BEGIN NOW Inglorious life with servitude; for life END
BEGIN NOW To noble and ignoble is more sweet END
BEGIN NOW Untrained in arms, where rashness leads not on. END
BEGIN NOW This also shall they gain by their delay END
BEGIN NOW In the wide wilderness; there they shall found END
BEGIN NOW Their government, and their great senate choose END
BEGIN NOW Through the twelve tribes, to rule by laws ordained: END
BEGIN NOW God from the mount of Sinai, whose gray top END
BEGIN NOW Shall tremble, he descending, will himself END
BEGIN NOW In thunder, lightning, and loud trumpets' sound, END
BEGIN NOW Ordain them laws; part, such as appertain END
BEGIN NOW To civil justice; part, religious rites END
BEGIN NOW Of sacrifice; informing them, by types END
BEGIN NOW And shadows, of that destined Seed to bruise END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent, by what means he shall achieve END
BEGIN NOW Mankind's deliverance. But the voice of God END
BEGIN NOW To mortal ear is dreadful: They beseech END
BEGIN NOW That Moses might report to them his will, END
BEGIN NOW And terrour cease; he grants what they besought, END
BEGIN NOW Instructed that to God is no access END
BEGIN NOW Without Mediator, whose high office now END
BEGIN NOW Moses in figure bears; to introduce END
BEGIN NOW One greater, of whose day he shall foretel, END
BEGIN NOW And all the Prophets in their age the times END
BEGIN NOW Of great Messiah shall sing. Thus, laws and rites END
BEGIN NOW Established, such delight hath God in Men END
BEGIN NOW Obedient to his will, that he vouchsafes END
BEGIN NOW Among them to set up his tabernacle; END
BEGIN NOW The Holy One with mortal Men to dwell: END
BEGIN NOW By his prescript a sanctuary is framed END
BEGIN NOW Of cedar, overlaid with gold; therein END
BEGIN NOW An ark, and in the ark his testimony, END
BEGIN NOW The records of his covenant; over these END
BEGIN NOW A mercy-seat of gold, between the wings END
BEGIN NOW Of two bright Cherubim; before him burn END
BEGIN NOW Seven lamps as in a zodiack representing END
BEGIN NOW The heavenly fires; over the tent a cloud END
BEGIN NOW Shall rest by day, a fiery gleam by night; END
BEGIN NOW Save when they journey, and at length they come, END
BEGIN NOW Conducted by his Angel, to the land END
BEGIN NOW Promised to Abraham and his seed:--The rest END
BEGIN NOW Were long to tell; how many battles fought END
BEGIN NOW How many kings destroyed; and kingdoms won; END
BEGIN NOW Or how the sun shall in mid Heaven stand still END
BEGIN NOW A day entire, and night's due course adjourn, END
BEGIN NOW Man's voice commanding, "Sun, in Gibeon stand, END
BEGIN NOW And thou moon in the vale of Aialon, END
BEGIN NOW Till Israel overcome!" so call the third END
BEGIN NOW From Abraham, son of Isaac; and from him END
BEGIN NOW His whole descent, who thus shall Canaan win. END
BEGIN NOW Here Adam interposed. O sent from Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Enlightener of my darkness, gracious things END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast revealed; those chiefly, which concern END
BEGIN NOW Just Abraham and his seed: now first I find END
BEGIN NOW Mine eyes true-opening, and my heart much eased; END
BEGIN NOW Erewhile perplexed with thoughts, what would become END
BEGIN NOW Of me and all mankind: But now I see END
BEGIN NOW His day, in whom all nations shall be blest; END
BEGIN NOW Favour unmerited by me, who sought END
BEGIN NOW Forbidden knowledge by forbidden means. END
BEGIN NOW This yet I apprehend not, why to those END
BEGIN NOW Among whom God will deign to dwell on earth END
BEGIN NOW So many and so various laws are given; END
BEGIN NOW So many laws argue so many sins END
BEGIN NOW Among them; how can God with such reside? END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Michael. Doubt not but that sin END
BEGIN NOW Will reign among them, as of thee begot; END
BEGIN NOW And therefore was law given them, to evince END
BEGIN NOW Their natural pravity, by stirring up END
BEGIN NOW Sin against law to fight: that when they see END
BEGIN NOW Law can discover sin, but not remove, END
BEGIN NOW Save by those shadowy expiations weak, END
BEGIN NOW The blood of bulls and goats, they may conclude END
BEGIN NOW Some blood more precious must be paid for Man; END
BEGIN NOW Just for unjust; that, in such righteousness END
BEGIN NOW To them by faith imputed, they may find END
BEGIN NOW Justification towards God, and peace END
BEGIN NOW Of conscience; which the law by ceremonies END
BEGIN NOW Cannot appease; nor Man the mortal part END
BEGIN NOW Perform; and, not performing, cannot live. END
BEGIN NOW So law appears imperfect; and but given END
BEGIN NOW With purpose to resign them, in full time, END
BEGIN NOW Up to a better covenant; disciplined END
BEGIN NOW From shadowy types to truth; from flesh to spirit; END
BEGIN NOW From imposition of strict laws to free END
BEGIN NOW Acceptance of large grace; from servile fear END
BEGIN NOW To filial; works of law to works of faith. END
BEGIN NOW And therefore shall not Moses, though of God END
BEGIN NOW Highly beloved, being but the minister END
BEGIN NOW Of law, his people into Canaan lead; END
BEGIN NOW But Joshua, whom the Gentiles Jesus call, END
BEGIN NOW His name and office bearing, who shall quell END
BEGIN NOW The adversary-Serpent, and bring back END
BEGIN NOW Through the world's wilderness long-wandered Man END
BEGIN NOW Safe to eternal Paradise of rest. END
BEGIN NOW Mean while they, in their earthly Canaan placed, END
BEGIN NOW Long time shall dwell and prosper, but when sins END
BEGIN NOW National interrupt their publick peace, END
BEGIN NOW Provoking God to raise them enemies; END
BEGIN NOW From whom as oft he saves them penitent END
BEGIN NOW By Judges first, then under Kings; of whom END
BEGIN NOW The second, both for piety renowned END
BEGIN NOW And puissant deeds, a promise shall receive END
BEGIN NOW Irrevocable, that his regal throne END
BEGIN NOW For ever shall endure; the like shall sing END
BEGIN NOW All Prophecy, that of the royal stock END
BEGIN NOW Of David (so I name this king) shall rise END
BEGIN NOW A Son, the Woman's seed to thee foretold, END
BEGIN NOW Foretold to Abraham, as in whom shall trust END
BEGIN NOW All nations; and to kings foretold, of kings END
BEGIN NOW The last; for of his reign shall be no end. END
BEGIN NOW But first, a long succession must ensue; END
BEGIN NOW And his next son, for wealth and wisdom famed, END
BEGIN NOW The clouded ark of God, till then in tents END
BEGIN NOW Wandering, shall in a glorious temple enshrine. END
BEGIN NOW Such follow him, as shall be registered END
BEGIN NOW Part good, part bad; of bad the longer scroll; END
BEGIN NOW Whose foul idolatries, and other faults END
BEGIN NOW Heaped to the popular sum, will so incense END
BEGIN NOW God, as to leave them, and expose their land, END
BEGIN NOW Their city, his temple, and his holy ark, END
BEGIN NOW With all his sacred things, a scorn and prey END
BEGIN NOW To that proud city, whose high walls thou sawest END
BEGIN NOW Left in confusion; Babylon thence called. END
BEGIN NOW There in captivity he lets them dwell END
BEGIN NOW The space of seventy years; then brings them back, END
BEGIN NOW Remembering mercy, and his covenant sworn END
BEGIN NOW To David, stablished as the days of Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Returned from Babylon by leave of kings END
BEGIN NOW Their lords, whom God disposed, the house of God END
BEGIN NOW They first re-edify; and for a while END
BEGIN NOW In mean estate live moderate; till, grown END
BEGIN NOW In wealth and multitude, factious they grow; END
BEGIN NOW But first among the priests dissention springs, END
BEGIN NOW Men who attend the altar, and should most END
BEGIN NOW Endeavour peace: their strife pollution brings END
BEGIN NOW Upon the temple itself: at last they seise END
BEGIN NOW The scepter, and regard not David's sons; END
BEGIN NOW Then lose it to a stranger, that the true END
BEGIN NOW Anointed King Messiah might be born END
BEGIN NOW Barred of his right; yet at his birth a star, END
BEGIN NOW Unseen before in Heaven, proclaims him come; END
BEGIN NOW And guides the eastern sages, who inquire END
BEGIN NOW His place, to offer incense, myrrh, and gold: END
BEGIN NOW His place of birth a solemn Angel tells END
BEGIN NOW To simple shepherds, keeping watch by night; END
BEGIN NOW They gladly thither haste, and by a quire END
BEGIN NOW Of squadroned Angels hear his carol sung. END
BEGIN NOW A virgin is his mother, but his sire END
BEGIN NOW The power of the Most High: He shall ascend END
BEGIN NOW The throne hereditary, and bound his reign END
BEGIN NOW With Earth's wide bounds, his glory with the Heavens. END
BEGIN NOW He ceased, discerning Adam with such joy END
BEGIN NOW Surcharged, as had like grief been dewed in tears, END
BEGIN NOW Without the vent of words; which these he breathed. END
BEGIN NOW O prophet of glad tidings, finisher END
BEGIN NOW Of utmost hope! now clear I understand END
BEGIN NOW What oft my steadiest thoughts have searched in vain; END
BEGIN NOW Why our great Expectation should be called END
BEGIN NOW The seed of Woman: Virgin Mother, hail, END
BEGIN NOW High in the love of Heaven; yet from my loins END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt proceed, and from thy womb the Son END
BEGIN NOW Of God Most High: so God with Man unites! END
BEGIN NOW Needs must the Serpent now his capital bruise END
BEGIN NOW Expect with mortal pain: Say where and when END
BEGIN NOW Their fight, what stroke shall bruise the victor's heel. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Michael. Dream not of their fight, END
BEGIN NOW As of a duel, or the local wounds END
BEGIN NOW Of head or heel: Not therefore joins the Son END
BEGIN NOW Manhood to Godhead, with more strength to foil END
BEGIN NOW Thy enemy; nor so is overcome END
BEGIN NOW Satan, whose fall from Heaven, a deadlier bruise, END
BEGIN NOW Disabled, not to give thee thy death's wound: END
BEGIN NOW Which he, who comes thy Saviour, shall recure, END
BEGIN NOW Not by destroying Satan, but his works END
BEGIN NOW In thee, and in thy seed: Nor can this be, END
BEGIN NOW But by fulfilling that which thou didst want, END
BEGIN NOW Obedience to the law of God, imposed END
BEGIN NOW On penalty of death, and suffering death; END
BEGIN NOW The penalty to thy transgression due, END
BEGIN NOW And due to theirs which out of thine will grow: END
BEGIN NOW So only can high Justice rest appaid. END
BEGIN NOW The law of God exact he shall fulfil END
BEGIN NOW Both by obedience and by love, though love END
BEGIN NOW Alone fulfil the law; thy punishment END
BEGIN NOW He shall endure, by coming in the flesh END
BEGIN NOW To a reproachful life, and cursed death; END
BEGIN NOW Proclaiming life to all who shall believe END
BEGIN NOW In his redemption; and that his obedience, END
BEGIN NOW Imputed, becomes theirs by faith; his merits END
BEGIN NOW To save them, not their own, though legal, works. END
BEGIN NOW For this he shall live hated, be blasphemed, END
BEGIN NOW Seised on by force, judged, and to death condemned END
BEGIN NOW A shameful and accursed, nailed to the cross END
BEGIN NOW By his own nation; slain for bringing life: END
BEGIN NOW But to the cross he nails thy enemies, END
BEGIN NOW The law that is against thee, and the sins END
BEGIN NOW Of all mankind, with him there crucified, END
BEGIN NOW Never to hurt them more who rightly trust END
BEGIN NOW In this his satisfaction; so he dies, END
BEGIN NOW But soon revives; Death over him no power END
BEGIN NOW Shall long usurp; ere the third dawning light END
BEGIN NOW Return, the stars of morn shall see him rise END
BEGIN NOW Out of his grave, fresh as the dawning light, END
BEGIN NOW Thy ransom paid, which Man from death redeems, END
BEGIN NOW His death for Man, as many as offered life END
BEGIN NOW Neglect not, and the benefit embrace END
BEGIN NOW By faith not void of works: This God-like act END
BEGIN NOW Annuls thy doom, the death thou shouldest have died, END
BEGIN NOW In sin for ever lost from life; this act END
BEGIN NOW Shall bruise the head of Satan, crush his strength, END
BEGIN NOW Defeating Sin and Death, his two main arms; END
BEGIN NOW And fix far deeper in his head their stings END
BEGIN NOW Than temporal death shall bruise the victor's heel, END
BEGIN NOW Or theirs whom he redeems; a death, like sleep, END
BEGIN NOW A gentle wafting to immortal life. END
BEGIN NOW Nor after resurrection shall he stay END
BEGIN NOW Longer on earth, than certain times to appear END
BEGIN NOW To his disciples, men who in his life END
BEGIN NOW Still followed him; to them shall leave in charge END
BEGIN NOW To teach all nations what of him they learned END
BEGIN NOW And his salvation; them who shall believe END
BEGIN NOW Baptizing in the profluent stream, the sign END
BEGIN NOW Of washing them from guilt of sin to life END
BEGIN NOW Pure, and in mind prepared, if so befall, END
BEGIN NOW For death, like that which the Redeemer died. END
BEGIN NOW All nations they shall teach; for, from that day, END
BEGIN NOW Not only to the sons of Abraham's loins END
BEGIN NOW Salvation shall be preached, but to the sons END
BEGIN NOW Of Abraham's faith wherever through the world; END
BEGIN NOW So in his seed all nations shall be blest. END
BEGIN NOW Then to the Heaven of Heavens he shall ascend END
BEGIN NOW With victory, triumphing through the air END
BEGIN NOW Over his foes and thine; there shall surprise END
BEGIN NOW The Serpent, prince of air, and drag in chains END
BEGIN NOW Through all his realm, and there confounded leave; END
BEGIN NOW Then enter into glory, and resume END
BEGIN NOW His seat at God's right hand, exalted high END
BEGIN NOW Above all names in Heaven; and thence shall come, END
BEGIN NOW When this world's dissolution shall be ripe, END
BEGIN NOW With glory and power to judge both quick and dead; END
BEGIN NOW To judge the unfaithful dead, but to reward END
BEGIN NOW His faithful, and receive them into bliss, END
BEGIN NOW Whether in Heaven or Earth; for then the Earth END
BEGIN NOW Shall all be Paradise, far happier place END
BEGIN NOW Than this of Eden, and far happier days. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Arch-Angel Michael; then paused, END
BEGIN NOW As at the world's great period; and our sire, END
BEGIN NOW Replete with joy and wonder, thus replied. END
BEGIN NOW O Goodness infinite, Goodness immense! END
BEGIN NOW That all this good of evil shall produce, END
BEGIN NOW And evil turn to good; more wonderful END
BEGIN NOW Than that which by creation first brought forth END
BEGIN NOW Light out of darkness! Full of doubt I stand, END
BEGIN NOW Whether I should repent me now of sin END
BEGIN NOW By me done, and occasioned; or rejoice END
BEGIN NOW Much more, that much more good thereof shall spring; END
BEGIN NOW To God more glory, more good-will to Men END
BEGIN NOW From God, and over wrath grace shall abound. END
BEGIN NOW But say, if our Deliverer up to Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Must re-ascend, what will betide the few END
BEGIN NOW His faithful, left among the unfaithful herd, END
BEGIN NOW The enemies of truth? Who then shall guide END
BEGIN NOW His people, who defend? Will they not deal END
BEGIN NOW Worse with his followers than with him they dealt? END
BEGIN NOW Be sure they will, said the Angel; but from Heaven END
BEGIN NOW He to his own a Comforter will send, END
BEGIN NOW The promise of the Father, who shall dwell END
BEGIN NOW His Spirit within them; and the law of faith, END
BEGIN NOW Working through love, upon their hearts shall write, END
BEGIN NOW To guide them in all truth; and also arm END
BEGIN NOW With spiritual armour, able to resist END
BEGIN NOW Satan's assaults, and quench his fiery darts; END
BEGIN NOW What man can do against them, not afraid, END
BEGIN NOW Though to the death; against such cruelties END
BEGIN NOW With inward consolations recompensed, END
BEGIN NOW And oft supported so as shall amaze END
BEGIN NOW Their proudest persecutors: For the Spirit, END
BEGIN NOW Poured first on his Apostles, whom he sends END
BEGIN NOW To evangelize the nations, then on all END
BEGIN NOW Baptized, shall them with wonderous gifts endue END
BEGIN NOW To speak all tongues, and do all miracles, END
BEGIN NOW As did their Lord before them. Thus they win END
BEGIN NOW Great numbers of each nation to receive END
BEGIN NOW With joy the tidings brought from Heaven: At length END
BEGIN NOW Their ministry performed, and race well run, END
BEGIN NOW Their doctrine and their story written left, END
BEGIN NOW They die; but in their room, as they forewarn, END
BEGIN NOW Wolves shall succeed for teachers, grievous wolves, END
BEGIN NOW Who all the sacred mysteries of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW To their own vile advantages shall turn END
BEGIN NOW Of lucre and ambition; and the truth END
BEGIN NOW With superstitions and traditions taint, END
BEGIN NOW Left only in those written records pure, END
BEGIN NOW Though not but by the Spirit understood. END
BEGIN NOW Then shall they seek to avail themselves of names, END
BEGIN NOW Places, and titles, and with these to join END
BEGIN NOW Secular power; though feigning still to act END
BEGIN NOW By spiritual, to themselves appropriating END
BEGIN NOW The Spirit of God, promised alike and given END
BEGIN NOW To all believers; and, from that pretence, END
BEGIN NOW Spiritual laws by carnal power shall force END
BEGIN NOW On every conscience; laws which none shall find END
BEGIN NOW Left them inrolled, or what the Spirit within END
BEGIN NOW Shall on the heart engrave. What will they then END
BEGIN NOW But force the Spirit of Grace itself, and bind END
BEGIN NOW His consort Liberty? what, but unbuild END
BEGIN NOW His living temples, built by faith to stand, END
BEGIN NOW Their own faith, not another's? for, on earth, END
BEGIN NOW Who against faith and conscience can be heard END
BEGIN NOW Infallible? yet many will presume: END
BEGIN NOW Whence heavy persecution shall arise END
BEGIN NOW On all, who in the worship persevere END
BEGIN NOW Of spirit and truth; the rest, far greater part, END
BEGIN NOW Will deem in outward rites and specious forms END
BEGIN NOW Religion satisfied; Truth shall retire END
BEGIN NOW Bestuck with slanderous darts, and works of faith END
BEGIN NOW Rarely be found: So shall the world go on, END
BEGIN NOW To good malignant, to bad men benign; END
BEGIN NOW Under her own weight groaning; till the day END
BEGIN NOW Appear of respiration to the just, END
BEGIN NOW And vengeance to the wicked, at return END
BEGIN NOW Of him so lately promised to thy aid, END
BEGIN NOW The Woman's Seed; obscurely then foretold, END
BEGIN NOW Now ampler known thy Saviour and thy Lord; END
BEGIN NOW Last, in the clouds, from Heaven to be revealed END
BEGIN NOW In glory of the Father, to dissolve END
BEGIN NOW Satan with his perverted world; then raise END
BEGIN NOW From the conflagrant mass, purged and refined, END
BEGIN NOW New Heavens, new Earth, ages of endless date, END
BEGIN NOW Founded in righteousness, and peace, and love; END
BEGIN NOW To bring forth fruits, joy and eternal bliss. END
BEGIN NOW He ended; and thus Adam last replied. END
BEGIN NOW How soon hath thy prediction, Seer blest, END
BEGIN NOW Measured this transient world, the race of time, END
BEGIN NOW Till time stand fixed! Beyond is all abyss, END
BEGIN NOW Eternity, whose end no eye can reach. END
BEGIN NOW Greatly-instructed I shall hence depart; END
BEGIN NOW Greatly in peace of thought; and have my fill END
BEGIN NOW Of knowledge, what this vessel can contain; END
BEGIN NOW Beyond which was my folly to aspire. END
BEGIN NOW Henceforth I learn, that to obey is best, END
BEGIN NOW And love with fear the only God; to walk END
BEGIN NOW As in his presence; ever to observe END
BEGIN NOW His providence; and on him sole depend, END
BEGIN NOW Merciful over all his works, with good END
BEGIN NOW Still overcoming evil, and by small END
BEGIN NOW Accomplishing great things, by things deemed weak END
BEGIN NOW Subverting worldly strong, and worldly wise END
BEGIN NOW By simply meek: that suffering for truth's sake END
BEGIN NOW Is fortitude to highest victory, END
BEGIN NOW And, to the faithful, death the gate of life; END
BEGIN NOW Taught this by his example, whom I now END
BEGIN NOW Acknowledge my Redeemer ever blest. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus also the Angel last replied. END
BEGIN NOW This having learned, thou hast attained the sum END
BEGIN NOW Of wisdom; hope no higher, though all the stars END
BEGIN NOW Thou knewest by name, and all the ethereal powers, END
BEGIN NOW All secrets of the deep, all Nature's works, END
BEGIN NOW Or works of God in Heaven, air, earth, or sea, END
BEGIN NOW And all the riches of this world enjoyedst, END
BEGIN NOW And all the rule, one empire; only add END
BEGIN NOW Deeds to thy knowledge answerable; add faith, END
BEGIN NOW Add virtue, patience, temperance; add love, END
BEGIN NOW By name to come called charity, the soul END
BEGIN NOW Of all the rest: then wilt thou not be loth END
BEGIN NOW To leave this Paradise, but shalt possess END
BEGIN NOW A Paradise within thee, happier far.-- END
BEGIN NOW Let us descend now therefore from this top END
BEGIN NOW Of speculation; for the hour precise END
BEGIN NOW Exacts our parting hence; and see the guards, END
BEGIN NOW By me encamped on yonder hill, expect END
BEGIN NOW Their motion; at whose front a flaming sword, END
BEGIN NOW In signal of remove, waves fiercely round: END
BEGIN NOW We may no longer stay: go, waken Eve; END
BEGIN NOW Her also I with gentle dreams have calmed END
BEGIN NOW Portending good, and all her spirits composed END
BEGIN NOW To meek submission: thou, at season fit, END
BEGIN NOW Let her with thee partake what thou hast heard; END
BEGIN NOW Chiefly what may concern her faith to know, END
BEGIN NOW The great deliverance by her seed to come END
BEGIN NOW (For by the Woman's seed) on all mankind: END
BEGIN NOW That ye may live, which will be many days, END
BEGIN NOW Both in one faith unanimous, though sad, END
BEGIN NOW With cause, for evils past; yet much more cheered END
BEGIN NOW With meditation on the happy end. END
BEGIN NOW He ended, and they both descend the hill; END
BEGIN NOW Descended, Adam to the bower, where Eve END
BEGIN NOW Lay sleeping, ran before; but found her waked; END
BEGIN NOW And thus with words not sad she him received. END
BEGIN NOW Whence thou returnest, and whither wentest, I know; END
BEGIN NOW For God is also in sleep; and dreams advise, END
BEGIN NOW Which he hath sent propitious, some great good END
BEGIN NOW Presaging, since with sorrow and heart's distress END
BEGIN NOW Wearied I fell asleep: But now lead on; END
BEGIN NOW In me is no delay; with thee to go, END
BEGIN NOW Is to stay here; without thee here to stay, END
BEGIN NOW Is to go hence unwilling; thou to me END
BEGIN NOW Art all things under Heaven, all places thou, END
BEGIN NOW Who for my wilful crime art banished hence. END
BEGIN NOW This further consolation yet secure END
BEGIN NOW I carry hence; though all by me is lost, END
BEGIN NOW Such favour I unworthy am vouchsafed, END
BEGIN NOW By me the Promised Seed shall all restore. END
BEGIN NOW So spake our mother Eve; and Adam heard END
BEGIN NOW Well pleased, but answered not: For now, too nigh END
BEGIN NOW The Arch-Angel stood; and, from the other hill END
BEGIN NOW To their fixed station, all in bright array END
BEGIN NOW The Cherubim descended; on the ground END
BEGIN NOW Gliding meteorous, as evening-mist END
BEGIN NOW Risen from a river o'er the marish glides, END
BEGIN NOW And gathers ground fast at the labourer's heel END
BEGIN NOW Homeward returning. High in front advanced, END
BEGIN NOW The brandished sword of God before them blazed, END
BEGIN NOW Fierce as a comet; which with torrid heat, END
BEGIN NOW And vapour as the Libyan air adust, END
BEGIN NOW Began to parch that temperate clime; whereat END
BEGIN NOW In either hand the hastening Angel caught END
BEGIN NOW Our lingering parents, and to the eastern gate END
BEGIN NOW Led them direct, and down the cliff as fast END
BEGIN NOW To the subjected plain; then disappeared. END
BEGIN NOW They, looking back, all the eastern side beheld END
BEGIN NOW Of Paradise, so late their happy seat, END
BEGIN NOW Waved over by that flaming brand; the gate END
BEGIN NOW With dreadful faces thronged, and fiery arms: END
BEGIN NOW Some natural tears they dropt, but wiped them soon; END
BEGIN NOW The world was all before them, where to choose END
BEGIN NOW Their place of rest, and Providence their guide: END
BEGIN NOW They, hand in hand, with wandering steps and slow, END
BEGIN NOW Through Eden took their solitary way. END
BEGIN NOW I, WHO erewhile the happy Garden sung END
BEGIN NOW By one man's disobedience lost, now sing END
BEGIN NOW Recovered Paradise to all mankind, END
BEGIN NOW By one man's firm obedience fully tried END
BEGIN NOW Through all temptation, and the Tempter foiled END
BEGIN NOW In all his wiles, defeated and repulsed, END
BEGIN NOW And Eden raised in the waste Wilderness. END
BEGIN NOW Thou Spirit, who led'st this glorious Eremite END
BEGIN NOW Into the desert, his victorious field END
BEGIN NOW Against the spiritual foe, and brought'st him thence END
BEGIN NOW By proof the undoubted Son of God, inspire, END
BEGIN NOW As thou art wont, my prompted song, else mute, END
BEGIN NOW And bear through highth or depth of Nature's bounds, END
BEGIN NOW With prosperous wing full summed, to tell of deeds END
BEGIN NOW Above heroic, though in secret done, END
BEGIN NOW And unrecorded left through many an age: END
BEGIN NOW Worthy to have not remained so long unsung. END
BEGIN NOW Now had the great Proclaimer, with a voice END
BEGIN NOW More awful than the sound of trumpet, cried END
BEGIN NOW Repentance, and Heaven's kingdom nigh at hand END
BEGIN NOW To all baptized. To his great baptism flocked END
BEGIN NOW With awe the regions round, and with them came END
BEGIN NOW From Nazareth the son of Joseph deemed END
BEGIN NOW To the flood Jordan--came as then obscure, END
BEGIN NOW Unmarked, unknown. But him the Baptist soon END
BEGIN NOW Descried, divinely warned, and witness bore END
BEGIN NOW As to his worthier, and would have resigned END
BEGIN NOW To him his heavenly office. Nor was long END
BEGIN NOW His witness unconfirmed: on him baptized END
BEGIN NOW Heaven opened, and in likeness of a Dove END
BEGIN NOW The Spirit descended, while the Father's voice END
BEGIN NOW From Heaven pronounced him his beloved Son. END
BEGIN NOW That heard the Adversary, who, roving still END
BEGIN NOW About the world, at that assembly famed END
BEGIN NOW Would not be last, and, with the voice divine END
BEGIN NOW Nigh thunder-struck, the exalted man to whom END
BEGIN NOW Such high attest was given a while surveyed END
BEGIN NOW With wonder; then, with envy fraught and rage, END
BEGIN NOW Flies to his place, nor rests, but in mid air END
BEGIN NOW To council summons all his mighty Peers, END
BEGIN NOW Within thick clouds and dark tenfold involved, END
BEGIN NOW A gloomy consistory; and them amidst, END
BEGIN NOW With looks aghast and sad, he thus bespake:-- END
BEGIN NOW O ancient Powers of Air and this wide World END
BEGIN NOW (For much more willingly I mention Air, END
BEGIN NOW This our old conquest, than remember Hell, END
BEGIN NOW Our hated habitation), well ye know END
BEGIN NOW How many ages, as the years of men, END
BEGIN NOW This Universe we have possessed, and ruled END
BEGIN NOW In manner at our will the affairs of Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Since Adam and his facile consort Eve END
BEGIN NOW Lost Paradise, deceived by me, though since END
BEGIN NOW With dread attending when that fatal wound END
BEGIN NOW Shall be inflicted by the seed of Eve END
BEGIN NOW Upon my head. Long the decrees of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Delay, for longest time to Him is short; END
BEGIN NOW And now, too soon for us, the circling hours END
BEGIN NOW This dreaded time have compassed, wherein we END
BEGIN NOW Must bide the stroke of that long-threatened wound END
BEGIN NOW (At least, if so we can, and by the head END
BEGIN NOW Broken be not intended all our power END
BEGIN NOW To be infringed, our freedom and our being END
BEGIN NOW In this fair empire won of Earth and Air)-- END
BEGIN NOW For this ill news I bring: The Woman's Seed, END
BEGIN NOW Destined to this, is late of woman born. END
BEGIN NOW His birth to our just fear gave no small cause; END
BEGIN NOW But his growth now to youth's full flower, displaying END
BEGIN NOW All virtue, grace and wisdom to achieve END
BEGIN NOW Things highest, greatest, multiplies my fear. END
BEGIN NOW Before him a great Prophet, to proclaim END
BEGIN NOW His coming, is sent harbinger, who all END
BEGIN NOW Invites, and in the consecrated stream END
BEGIN NOW Pretends to wash off sin, and fit them so END
BEGIN NOW Purified to receive him pure, or rather END
BEGIN NOW To do him honour as their King. All come, END
BEGIN NOW And he himself among them was baptized-- END
BEGIN NOW Not thence to be more pure, but to receive END
BEGIN NOW The testimony of Heaven, that who he is END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth the nations may not doubt. I saw END
BEGIN NOW The Prophet do him reverence; on him, rising END
BEGIN NOW Out of the water, Heaven above the clouds END
BEGIN NOW Unfold her crystal doors; thence on his head END
BEGIN NOW A perfet Dove descend (whate'er it meant); END
BEGIN NOW And out of Heaven the sovraign voice I heard, END
BEGIN NOW 'This is my Son beloved,--in him am pleased.' END
BEGIN NOW His mother, than, is mortal, but his Sire END
BEGIN NOW He who obtains the monarchy of Heaven; END
BEGIN NOW And what will He not do to advance his Son? END
BEGIN NOW His first-begot we know, and sore have felt, END
BEGIN NOW When his fierce thunder drove us to the Deep; END
BEGIN NOW Who this is we must learn, for Man he seems END
BEGIN NOW In all his lineaments, though in his face END
BEGIN NOW The glimpses of his Father's glory shine. END
BEGIN NOW Ye see our danger on the utmost edge END
BEGIN NOW Of hazard, which admits no long debate, END
BEGIN NOW But must with something sudden be opposed END
BEGIN NOW (Not force, but well-couched fraud, well-woven snares), END
BEGIN NOW Ere in the head of nations he appear, END
BEGIN NOW Their king, their leader, and supreme on Earth. END
BEGIN NOW I, when no other durst, sole undertook END
BEGIN NOW The dismal expedition to find out END
BEGIN NOW And ruin Adam, and the exploit performed END
BEGIN NOW Successfully: a calmer voyage now END
BEGIN NOW Will waft me; and the way found prosperous once END
BEGIN NOW Induces best to hope of like success. END
BEGIN NOW He ended, and his words impression left END
BEGIN NOW Of much amazement to the infernal crew, END
BEGIN NOW Distracted and surprised with deep dismay END
BEGIN NOW At these sad tidings. But no time was then END
BEGIN NOW For long indulgence to their fears or grief: END
BEGIN NOW Unanimous they all commit the care END
BEGIN NOW And management of this man enterprise END
BEGIN NOW To him, their great Dictator, whose attempt END
BEGIN NOW At first against mankind so well had thrived END
BEGIN NOW In Adam's overthrow, and led their march END
BEGIN NOW From Hell's deep-vaulted den to dwell in light, END
BEGIN NOW Regents, and potentates, and kings, yea gods, END
BEGIN NOW Of many a pleasant realm and province wide. END
BEGIN NOW So to the coast of Jordan he directs END
BEGIN NOW His easy steps, girded with snaky wiles, END
BEGIN NOW Where he might likeliest find this new-declared, END
BEGIN NOW This man of men, attested Son of God, END
BEGIN NOW Temptation and all guile on him to try-- END
BEGIN NOW So to subvert whom he suspected raised END
BEGIN NOW To end his reign on Earth so long enjoyed: END
BEGIN NOW But, contrary, unweeting he fulfilled END
BEGIN NOW The purposed counsel, pre-ordained and fixed, END
BEGIN NOW Of the Most High, who, in full frequence bright END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels, thus to Gabriel smiling spake:-- END
BEGIN NOW Gabriel, this day, by proof, thou shalt behold, END
BEGIN NOW Thou and all Angels conversant on Earth END
BEGIN NOW With Man or men's affairs, how I begin END
BEGIN NOW To verify that solemn message late, END
BEGIN NOW On which I sent thee to the Virgin pure END
BEGIN NOW In Galilee, that she should bear a son, END
BEGIN NOW Great in renown, and called the Son of God. END
BEGIN NOW Then told'st her, doubting how these things could be END
BEGIN NOW To her a virgin, that on her should come END
BEGIN NOW The Holy Ghost, and the power of the Highest END
BEGIN NOW O'ershadow her. This Man, born and now upgrown, END
BEGIN NOW To shew him worthy of his birth divine END
BEGIN NOW And high prediction, henceforth I expose END
BEGIN NOW To Satan; let him tempt, and now assay END
BEGIN NOW His utmost subtlety, because he boasts END
BEGIN NOW And vaunts of his great cunning to the throng END
BEGIN NOW Of his Apostasy. He might have learnt END
BEGIN NOW Less overweening, since he failed in Job, END
BEGIN NOW Whose constant perseverance overcame END
BEGIN NOW Whate'er his cruel malice could invent. END
BEGIN NOW He now shall know I can produce a man, END
BEGIN NOW Of female seed, far abler to resist END
BEGIN NOW All his solicitations, and at length END
BEGIN NOW All his vast force, and drive him back to Hell-- END
BEGIN NOW Winning by conquest what the first man lost END
BEGIN NOW By fallacy surprised. But first I mean END
BEGIN NOW To exercise him in the Wilderness; END
BEGIN NOW There he shall first lay down the rudiments END
BEGIN NOW Of his great warfare, ere I send him forth END
BEGIN NOW To conquer Sin and Death, the two grand foes. END
BEGIN NOW By humiliation and strong sufferance END
BEGIN NOW His weakness shall o'ercome Satanic strength, END
BEGIN NOW And all the world, and mass of sinful flesh; END
BEGIN NOW That all the Angels and aethereal Powers-- END
BEGIN NOW They now, and men hereafter--may discern END
BEGIN NOW From what consummate virtue I have chose END
BEGIN NOW This perfet man, by merit called my Son, END
BEGIN NOW To earn salvation for the sons of men. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Eternal Father, and all Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Admiring stood a space; then into hymns END
BEGIN NOW Burst forth, and in celestial measures moved, END
BEGIN NOW Circling the throne and singing, while the hand END
BEGIN NOW Sung with the voice, and this the argument:-- END
BEGIN NOW Victory and triumph to the Son of God, END
BEGIN NOW Now entering his great duel, not of arms, END
BEGIN NOW But to vanquish by wisdom hellish wiles! END
BEGIN NOW The Father knows the Son; therefore secure END
BEGIN NOW Ventures his filial virtue, though untried, END
BEGIN NOW Against whate'er may tempt, whate'er seduce, END
BEGIN NOW Allure, or terrify, or undermine. END
BEGIN NOW Be frustrate, all ye stratagems of Hell, END
BEGIN NOW And, devilish machinations, come to nought! END
BEGIN NOW So they in Heaven their odes and vigils tuned. END
BEGIN NOW Meanwhile the Son of God, who yet some days END
BEGIN NOW Lodged in Bethabara, where John baptized, END
BEGIN NOW Musing and much revolving in his breast END
BEGIN NOW How best the mighty work he might begin END
BEGIN NOW Of Saviour to mankind, and which way first END
BEGIN NOW Publish his godlike office now mature, END
BEGIN NOW One day forth walked alone, the Spirit leading END
BEGIN NOW And his deep thoughts, the better to converse END
BEGIN NOW With solitude, till, far from track of men, END
BEGIN NOW Thought following thought, and step by step led on, END
BEGIN NOW He entered now the bordering Desert wild, END
BEGIN NOW And, with dark shades and rocks environed round, END
BEGIN NOW His holy meditations thus pursued:-- END
BEGIN NOW O what a multitude of thoughts at once END
BEGIN NOW Awakened in me swarm, while I consider END
BEGIN NOW What from within I feel myself, and hear END
BEGIN NOW What from without comes often to my ears, END
BEGIN NOW Ill sorting with my present state compared! END
BEGIN NOW When I was yet a child, no childish play END
BEGIN NOW To me was pleasing; all my mind was set END
BEGIN NOW Serious to learn and know, and thence to do, END
BEGIN NOW What might be public good; myself I thought END
BEGIN NOW Born to that end, born to promote all truth, END
BEGIN NOW All righteous things. Therefore, above my years, END
BEGIN NOW The Law of God I read, and found it sweet; END
BEGIN NOW Made it my whole delight, and in it grew END
BEGIN NOW To such perfection that, ere yet my age END
BEGIN NOW Had measured twice six years, at our great Feast END
BEGIN NOW I went into the Temple, there to hear END
BEGIN NOW The teachers of our Law, and to propose END
BEGIN NOW What might improve my knowledge or their own, END
BEGIN NOW And was admired by all. Yet this not all END
BEGIN NOW To which my spirit aspired. Victorious deeds END
BEGIN NOW Flamed in my heart, heroic acts--one while END
BEGIN NOW To rescue Israel from the Roman yoke; END
BEGIN NOW Then to subdue and quell, o'er all the earth, END
BEGIN NOW Brute violence and proud tyrannic power, END
BEGIN NOW Till truth were freed, and equity restored: END
BEGIN NOW Yet held it more humane, more heavenly, first END
BEGIN NOW By winning words to conquer willing hearts, END
BEGIN NOW And make persuasion do the work of fear; END
BEGIN NOW At least to try, and teach the erring soul, END
BEGIN NOW Not wilfully misdoing, but unware END
BEGIN NOW Misled; the stubborn only to subdue. END
BEGIN NOW These growing thoughts my mother soon perceiving, END
BEGIN NOW By words at times cast forth, inly rejoiced, END
BEGIN NOW And said to me apart, 'High are thy thoughts, END
BEGIN NOW O Son! but nourish them, and let them soar END
BEGIN NOW To what highth sacred virtue and true worth END
BEGIN NOW Can raise them, though above example high; END
BEGIN NOW By matchless deeds express thy matchless Sire. END
BEGIN NOW For know, thou art no son of mortal man; END
BEGIN NOW Though men esteem thee low of parentage, END
BEGIN NOW Thy Father is the Eternal King who rules END
BEGIN NOW All Heaven and Earth, Angels and sons of men. END
BEGIN NOW A messenger from God foretold thy birth END
BEGIN NOW Conceived in me a virgin; he foretold END
BEGIN NOW Thou shouldst be great, and sit on David's throne, END
BEGIN NOW And of thy kingdom there should be no end. END
BEGIN NOW At thy nativity a glorious quire END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels, in the fields of Bethlehem, sung END
BEGIN NOW To shepherds, watching at their folds by night, END
BEGIN NOW And told them the Messiah now was born, END
BEGIN NOW Where they might see him; and to thee they came, END
BEGIN NOW Directed to the manger where thou lay'st; END
BEGIN NOW For in the inn was left no better room. END
BEGIN NOW A Star, not seen before, in heaven appearing, END
BEGIN NOW Guided the Wise Men thither from the East, END
BEGIN NOW To honour thee with incense, myrrh, and gold; END
BEGIN NOW By whose bright course led on they found the place, END
BEGIN NOW Affirming it thy star, new-graven in heaven, END
BEGIN NOW By which they knew thee King of Israel born. END
BEGIN NOW Just Simeon and prophetic Anna, warned END
BEGIN NOW By vision, found thee in the Temple, and spake, END
BEGIN NOW Before the altar and the vested priest, END
BEGIN NOW Like things of thee to all that present stood.' END
BEGIN NOW This having heart, straight I again revolved END
BEGIN NOW The Law and Prophets, searching what was writ END
BEGIN NOW Concerning the Messiah, to our scribes END
BEGIN NOW Known partly, and soon found of whom they spake END
BEGIN NOW I am--this chiefly, that my way must lie END
BEGIN NOW Through many a hard assay, even to the death, END
BEGIN NOW Ere I the promised kingdom can attain, END
BEGIN NOW Or work redemption for mankind, whose sins' END
BEGIN NOW Full weight must be transferred upon my head. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, neither thus disheartened or dismayed, END
BEGIN NOW The time prefixed I waited; when behold END
BEGIN NOW The Baptist (of whose birth I oft had heard, END
BEGIN NOW Not knew by sight) now come, who was to come END
BEGIN NOW Before Messiah, and his way prepare! END
BEGIN NOW I, as all others, to his baptism came, END
BEGIN NOW Which I believed was from above; but he END
BEGIN NOW Straight knew me, and with loudest voice proclaimed END
BEGIN NOW Me him (for it was shewn him so from Heaven)-- END
BEGIN NOW Me him whose harbinger he was; and first END
BEGIN NOW Refused on me his baptism to confer, END
BEGIN NOW As much his greater, and was hardly won. END
BEGIN NOW But, as I rose out of the laving stream, END
BEGIN NOW Heaven opened her eternal doors, from whence END
BEGIN NOW The Spirit descended on me like a Dove; END
BEGIN NOW And last, the sum of all, my Father's voice, END
BEGIN NOW Audibly heard from Heaven, pronounced me his, END
BEGIN NOW Me his beloved Son, in whom alone END
BEGIN NOW He was well pleased: by which I knew the time END
BEGIN NOW Now full, that I no more should live obscure, END
BEGIN NOW But openly begin, as best becomes END
BEGIN NOW The authority which I derived from Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW And now by some strong motion I am led END
BEGIN NOW Into this wilderness; to what intent END
BEGIN NOW I learn not yet. Perhaps I need not know; END
BEGIN NOW For what concerns my knowledge God reveals. END
BEGIN NOW So spake our Morning Star, then in his rise, END
BEGIN NOW And, looking round, on every side beheld END
BEGIN NOW A pathless desert, dusk with horrid shades. END
BEGIN NOW The way he came, not having marked return, END
BEGIN NOW Was difficult, by human steps untrod; END
BEGIN NOW And he still on was led, but with such thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Accompanied of things past and to come END
BEGIN NOW Lodged in his breast as well might recommend END
BEGIN NOW Such solitude before choicest society. END
BEGIN NOW Full forty days he passed--whether on hill END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes, anon in shady vale, each night END
BEGIN NOW Under the covert of some ancient oak END
BEGIN NOW Or cedar to defend him from the dew, END
BEGIN NOW Or harboured in one cave, is not revealed; END
BEGIN NOW Nor tasted human food, nor hunger felt, END
BEGIN NOW Till those days ended; hungered then at last END
BEGIN NOW Among wild beasts. They at his sight grew mild, END
BEGIN NOW Nor sleeping him nor waking harmed; his walk END
BEGIN NOW The fiery serpent fled and noxious worm; END
BEGIN NOW The lion and fierce tiger glared aloof. END
BEGIN NOW But now an aged man in rural weeds, END
BEGIN NOW Following, as seemed, the quest of some stray eye, END
BEGIN NOW Or withered sticks to gather, which might serve END
BEGIN NOW Against a winter's day, when winds blow keen, END
BEGIN NOW To warm him wet returned from field at eve, END
BEGIN NOW He saw approach; who first with curious eye END
BEGIN NOW Perused him, then with words thus uttered spake:-- END
BEGIN NOW Sir, what ill chance hath brought thee to this place, END
BEGIN NOW So far from path or road of men, who pass END
BEGIN NOW In troop or caravan? for single none END
BEGIN NOW Durst ever, who returned, and dropt not here END
BEGIN NOW His carcass, pined with hunger and with droughth. END
BEGIN NOW I ask the rather, and the more admire, END
BEGIN NOW For that to me thou seem'st the man whom late END
BEGIN NOW Our new baptizing Prophet at the ford END
BEGIN NOW Of Jordan honoured so, and called thee Son END
BEGIN NOW Of God. I saw and heard, for we sometimes END
BEGIN NOW Who dwell this wild, constrained by want, come forth END
BEGIN NOW To town or village nigh (nighest is far), END
BEGIN NOW Where aught we hear, and curious are to hear, END
BEGIN NOW What happens new; fame also finds us out. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Son of God:--"Who brought me hither END
BEGIN NOW Will bring me hence; no other guide I seek. END
BEGIN NOW By miracle he may," replied the swain; END
BEGIN NOW What other way I see not; for we here END
BEGIN NOW Live on tough roots and stubs, to thirst inured END
BEGIN NOW More than the camel, and to drink go far-- END
BEGIN NOW Men to much misery and hardship born. END
BEGIN NOW But, if thou be the Son of God, command END
BEGIN NOW That out of these hard stones be made thee bread; END
BEGIN NOW So shalt thou save thyself, and us relieve END
BEGIN NOW With food, whereof we wretched seldom taste. END
BEGIN NOW He ended, and the Son of God replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Think'st thou such force in bread? Is it not written END
BEGIN NOW (For I discern thee other than thou seem'st), END
BEGIN NOW Man lives not by bread only, but each word END
BEGIN NOW Proceeding from the mouth of God, who fed END
BEGIN NOW Our fathers here with manna? In the Mount END
BEGIN NOW Moses was forty days, nor eat nor drank; END
BEGIN NOW And forty days Eliah without food END
BEGIN NOW Wandered this barren waste; the same I now. END
BEGIN NOW Why dost thou, then, suggest to me distrust END
BEGIN NOW Knowing who I am, as I know who thou art? END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus answered the Arch-Fiend, now undisguised:-- END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis true, I am that Spirit unfortunate END
BEGIN NOW Who, leagued with millions more in rash revolt, END
BEGIN NOW Kept not my happy station, but was driven END
BEGIN NOW With them from bliss to the bottomless Deep-- END
BEGIN NOW Yet to that hideous place not so confined END
BEGIN NOW By rigour unconniving but that oft, END
BEGIN NOW Leaving my dolorous prison, I enjoy END
BEGIN NOW Large liberty to round this globe of Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Or range in the Air; nor from the Heaven of Heavens END
BEGIN NOW Hath he excluded my resort sometimes. END
BEGIN NOW I came, among the Sons of God, when he END
BEGIN NOW Gave up into my hands Uzzean Job, END
BEGIN NOW To prove him, and illustrate his high worth; END
BEGIN NOW And, when to all his Angels he proposed END
BEGIN NOW To draw the proud king Ahab into fraud, END
BEGIN NOW That he might fall in Ramoth, they demurring, END
BEGIN NOW I undertook that office, and the tongues END
BEGIN NOW Of all his flattering prophets glibbed with lies END
BEGIN NOW To his destruction, as I had in charge: END
BEGIN NOW For what he bids I do. Though I have lost END
BEGIN NOW Much lustre of my native brightness, lost END
BEGIN NOW To be beloved of God, I have not lost END
BEGIN NOW To love, at least contemplate and admire, END
BEGIN NOW What I see excellent in good, or fair, END
BEGIN NOW Or virtuous; I should so have lost all sense. END
BEGIN NOW What can be then less in me than desire END
BEGIN NOW To see thee and approach thee, whom I know END
BEGIN NOW Declared the Son of God, to hear attent END
BEGIN NOW Thy wisdom, and behold thy godlike deeds? END
BEGIN NOW Men generally think me much a foe END
BEGIN NOW To all mankind. Why should I? they to me END
BEGIN NOW Never did wrong or violence. By them END
BEGIN NOW I lost not what I lost; rather by them END
BEGIN NOW I gained what I have gained, and with them dwell END
BEGIN NOW Copartner in these regions of the World, END
BEGIN NOW If not disposer--lend them oft my aid, END
BEGIN NOW Oft my advice by presages and signs, END
BEGIN NOW And answers, oracles, portents, and dreams, END
BEGIN NOW Whereby they may direct their future life. END
BEGIN NOW Envy, they say, excites me, thus to gain END
BEGIN NOW Companions of my misery and woe! END
BEGIN NOW At first it may be; but, long since with woe END
BEGIN NOW Nearer acquainted, now I feel by proof END
BEGIN NOW That fellowship in pain divides not smart, END
BEGIN NOW Nor lightens aught each man's peculiar load; END
BEGIN NOW Small consolation, then, were Man adjoined. END
BEGIN NOW This wounds me most (what can it less?) that Man, END
BEGIN NOW Man fallen, shall be restored, I never more. END
BEGIN NOW To whom our Saviour sternly thus replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Deservedly thou griev'st, composed of lies END
BEGIN NOW From the beginning, and in lies wilt end, END
BEGIN NOW Who boast'st release from Hell, and leave to come END
BEGIN NOW Into the Heaven of Heavens. Thou com'st, indeed, END
BEGIN NOW As a poor miserable captive thrall END
BEGIN NOW Comes to the place where he before had sat END
BEGIN NOW Among the prime in splendour, now deposed, END
BEGIN NOW Ejected, emptied, gazed, unpitied, shunned, END
BEGIN NOW A spectacle of ruin, or of scorn, END
BEGIN NOW To all the host of Heaven. The happy place END
BEGIN NOW Imparts to thee no happiness, no joy-- END
BEGIN NOW Rather inflames thy torment, representing END
BEGIN NOW Lost bliss, to thee no more communicable; END
BEGIN NOW So never more in Hell than when in Heaven. END
BEGIN NOW But thou art serviceable to Heaven's King! END
BEGIN NOW Wilt thou impute to obedience what thy fear END
BEGIN NOW Extorts, or pleasure to do ill excites? END
BEGIN NOW What but thy malice moved thee to misdeem END
BEGIN NOW Of righteous Job, then cruelly to afflict him END
BEGIN NOW With all inflictions? but his patience won. END
BEGIN NOW The other service was thy chosen task, END
BEGIN NOW To be a liar in four hundred mouths; END
BEGIN NOW For lying is thy sustenance, thy food. END
BEGIN NOW Yet thou pretend'st to truth! all oracles END
BEGIN NOW By thee are given, and what confessed more true END
BEGIN NOW Among the nations? That hath been thy craft, END
BEGIN NOW By mixing somewhat true to vent more lies. END
BEGIN NOW But what have been thy answers? what but dark, END
BEGIN NOW Ambiguous, and with double sense deluding, END
BEGIN NOW Which they who asked have seldom understood, END
BEGIN NOW And, not well understood, as good not known? END
BEGIN NOW Who ever, by consulting at thy shrine, END
BEGIN NOW Returned the wiser, or the more instruct END
BEGIN NOW To fly or follow what concerned him most, END
BEGIN NOW And run not sooner to his fatal snare? END
BEGIN NOW For God hath justly given the nations up END
BEGIN NOW To thy delusions; justly, since they fell END
BEGIN NOW Idolatrous. But, when his purpose is END
BEGIN NOW Among them to declare his providence, END
BEGIN NOW To thee not known, whence hast thou then thy truth, END
BEGIN NOW But from him, or his Angels president END
BEGIN NOW In every province, who, themselves disdaining END
BEGIN NOW To approach thy temples, give thee in command END
BEGIN NOW To thy adorers? Thou, with trembling fear, END
BEGIN NOW Or like a fawning parasite, obey'st; END
BEGIN NOW Then to thyself ascrib'st the truth foretold. END
BEGIN NOW But this thy glory shall be soon retrenched; END
BEGIN NOW No more shalt thou by oracling abuse END
BEGIN NOW The Gentiles; henceforth oracles are ceased, END
BEGIN NOW And thou no more with pomp and sacrifice END
BEGIN NOW Shalt be enquired at Delphos or elsewhere-- END
BEGIN NOW At least in vain, for they shall find thee mute. END
BEGIN NOW God hath now sent his living Oracle END
BEGIN NOW Into the world to teach his final will, END
BEGIN NOW And sends his Spirit of Truth henceforth to dwell END
BEGIN NOW In pious hearts, an inward oracle END
BEGIN NOW To all truth requisite for men to know. END
BEGIN NOW So spake our Saviour; but the subtle Fiend, END
BEGIN NOW Though inly stung with anger and disdain, END
BEGIN NOW Dissembled, and this answer smooth returned:-- END
BEGIN NOW Sharply thou hast insisted on rebuke, END
BEGIN NOW And urged me hard with doings which not will, END
BEGIN NOW But misery, hath wrested from me. Where END
BEGIN NOW Easily canst thou find one miserable, END
BEGIN NOW And not inforced oft-times to part from truth, END
BEGIN NOW If it may stand him more in stead to lie, END
BEGIN NOW Say and unsay, feign, flatter, or abjure? END
BEGIN NOW But thou art placed above me; thou art Lord; END
BEGIN NOW From thee I can, and must, submiss, endure END
BEGIN NOW Cheek or reproof, and glad to scape so quit. END
BEGIN NOW Hard are the ways of truth, and rough to walk, END
BEGIN NOW Smooth on the tongue discoursed, pleasing to the ear, END
BEGIN NOW And tunable as sylvan pipe or song; END
BEGIN NOW What wonder, then, if I delight to hear END
BEGIN NOW Her dictates from thy mouth? most men admire END
BEGIN NOW Virtue who follow not her lore. Permit me END
BEGIN NOW To hear thee when I come (since no man comes), END
BEGIN NOW And talk at least, though I despair to attain. END
BEGIN NOW Thy Father, who is holy, wise, and pure, END
BEGIN NOW Suffers the hypocrite or atheous priest END
BEGIN NOW To tread his sacred courts, and minister END
BEGIN NOW About his altar, handling holy things, END
BEGIN NOW Praying or vowing, and voutsafed his voice END
BEGIN NOW To Balaam reprobate, a prophet yet END
BEGIN NOW Inspired: disdain not such access to me. END
BEGIN NOW To whom our Saviour, with unaltered brow:-- END
BEGIN NOW Thy coming hither, though I know thy scope, END
BEGIN NOW I bid not, or forbid. Do as thou find'st END
BEGIN NOW Permission from above; thou canst not more. END
BEGIN NOW He added not; and Satan, bowling low END
BEGIN NOW His gray dissimulation, disappeared, END
BEGIN NOW Into thin air diffused: for now began END
BEGIN NOW Night with her sullen wing to double-shade END
BEGIN NOW The desert; fowls in their clay nests were couched; END
BEGIN NOW And now wild beasts came forth the woods to roam. END
BEGIN NOW MEANWHILE the new-baptized, who yet remained END
BEGIN NOW At Jordan with the Baptist, and had seen END
BEGIN NOW Him whom they heard so late expressly called END
BEGIN NOW Jesus Messiah, Son of God, declared, END
BEGIN NOW And on that high authority had believed, END
BEGIN NOW And with him talked, and with him lodged--I mean END
BEGIN NOW Andrew and Simon, famous after known, END
BEGIN NOW With others, though in Holy Writ not named-- END
BEGIN NOW Now missing him, their joy so lately found, END
BEGIN NOW So lately found and so abruptly gone, END
BEGIN NOW Began to doubt, and doubted many days, END
BEGIN NOW And, as the days increased, increased their doubt. END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes they thought he might be only shewn, END
BEGIN NOW And for a time caught up to God, as once END
BEGIN NOW Moses was in the Mount and missing long, END
BEGIN NOW And the great Thisbite, who on fiery wheels END
BEGIN NOW Rode up to Heaven, yet once again to come. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore, as those young prophets then with care END
BEGIN NOW Sought lost Eliah, so in each place these END
BEGIN NOW Nigh to Bethabara--in Jericho END
BEGIN NOW The city of palms, AEnon, and Salem old, END
BEGIN NOW Machaerus, and each town or city walled END
BEGIN NOW On this side the broad lake Genezaret, END
BEGIN NOW Or in Peraea--but returned in vain. END
BEGIN NOW Then on the bank of Jordan, by a creek, END
BEGIN NOW Where winds with reeds and osiers whispering play, END
BEGIN NOW Plain fishermen (no greater men them call), END
BEGIN NOW Close in a cottage low together got, END
BEGIN NOW Their unexpected loss and plaints outbreathed:-- END
BEGIN NOW Alas, from what high hope to what relapse END
BEGIN NOW Unlooked for are we fallen! Our eyes beheld END
BEGIN NOW Messiah certainly now come, so long END
BEGIN NOW Expected of our fathers; we have heard END
BEGIN NOW His words, his wisdom full of grace and truth. END
BEGIN NOW 'Now, now, for sure, deliverance is at hand; END
BEGIN NOW The kingdom shall to Israel be restored:' END
BEGIN NOW Thus we rejoiced, but soon our joy is turned END
BEGIN NOW Into perplexity and new amaze. END
BEGIN NOW For whither is he gone? what accident END
BEGIN NOW Hath rapt him from us? will he now retire END
BEGIN NOW After appearance, and again prolong END
BEGIN NOW Our expectation? God of Israel, END
BEGIN NOW Send thy Messiah forth; the time is come. END
BEGIN NOW Behold the kings of the earth, how they oppress END
BEGIN NOW Thy Chosen, to what highth their power unjust END
BEGIN NOW They have exalted, and behind them cast END
BEGIN NOW All fear of Thee; arise, and vindicate END
BEGIN NOW Thy glory; free thy people from their yoke! END
BEGIN NOW But let us wait; thus far He hath performed-- END
BEGIN NOW Sent his Anointed, and to us revealed him END
BEGIN NOW By his great Prophet pointed at and shown END
BEGIN NOW In public, and with him we have conversed. END
BEGIN NOW Let us be glad of this, and all our fears END
BEGIN NOW Lay on his providence; He will not fail, END
BEGIN NOW Nor will withdraw him now, nor will recall-- END
BEGIN NOW Mock us with his blest sight, then snatch him hence: END
BEGIN NOW Soon we shall see our hope, our joy, return. END
BEGIN NOW Thus they out of their plaints new hope resume END
BEGIN NOW To find whom at the first they found unsought. END
BEGIN NOW But to his mother Mary, when she saw END
BEGIN NOW Others returned from baptism, not her Son, END
BEGIN NOW Nor left at Jordan tidings of him none, END
BEGIN NOW Within her breast though calm, her breast though pure, END
BEGIN NOW Motherly cares and fears got head, and raised END
BEGIN NOW Some troubled thoughts, which she in sighs thus clad:-- END
BEGIN NOW Oh, what avails me now that honour high, END
BEGIN NOW To have conceived of God, or that salute, END
BEGIN NOW 'Hail, highly favoured, among women blest!' END
BEGIN NOW While I to sorrows am no less advanced, END
BEGIN NOW And fears as eminent above the lot END
BEGIN NOW Of other women, by the birth I bore: END
BEGIN NOW In such a season born, when scarce a shed END
BEGIN NOW Could be obtained to shelter him or me END
BEGIN NOW From the bleak air? A stable was our warmth, END
BEGIN NOW A manger his; yet soon enforced to fly END
BEGIN NOW Were dead, who sought his life, and, missing, filled END
BEGIN NOW With infant blood the streets of Bethlehem. END
BEGIN NOW Hath been our dwelling many years; his life END
BEGIN NOW Private, unactive, calm, contemplative, END
BEGIN NOW Little suspicious to any king. But now, END
BEGIN NOW Full grown to man, acknowledged, as I hear, END
BEGIN NOW By John the Baptist, and in public shewn, END
BEGIN NOW Son owned from Heaven by his Father's voice, END
BEGIN NOW I looked for some great change. To honour? no; END
BEGIN NOW But trouble, as old Simeon plain foretold, END
BEGIN NOW That to the fall and rising he should be END
BEGIN NOW Of many in Israel, and to a sign END
BEGIN NOW Spoken against--that through my very soul END
BEGIN NOW A sword shall pierce. This is my favoured lot, END
BEGIN NOW My exaltation to afflictions high! END
BEGIN NOW Afflicted I may be, it seems, and blest! END
BEGIN NOW I will not argue that, nor will repine. END
BEGIN NOW But where delays he now? Some great intent END
BEGIN NOW Conceals him. When twelve years he scarce had seen, END
BEGIN NOW I lost him, but so found as well I saw END
BEGIN NOW He could not lose himself, but went about END
BEGIN NOW His Father's business. What he meant I mused-- END
BEGIN NOW Since understand; much more his absence now END
BEGIN NOW Thus long to some great purpose he obscures. END
BEGIN NOW But I to wait with patience am inured; END
BEGIN NOW My heart hath been a storehouse long of things END
BEGIN NOW And sayings laid up, pretending strange events. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Mary, pondering oft, and oft to mind END
BEGIN NOW Recalling what remarkably had passed END
BEGIN NOW Since first her Salutation heard, with thoughts END
BEGIN NOW Meekly composed awaited the fulfilling: END
BEGIN NOW The while her Son, tracing the desert wild, END
BEGIN NOW Sole, but with holiest meditations fed, END
BEGIN NOW Into himself descended, and at once END
BEGIN NOW All his great work to come before him set-- END
BEGIN NOW How to begin, how to accomplish best END
BEGIN NOW His end of being on Earth, and mission high. END
BEGIN NOW For Satan, with sly preface to return, END
BEGIN NOW Had left him vacant, and with speed was gone END
BEGIN NOW Up to the middle region of thick air, END
BEGIN NOW Where all his Potentates in council sate. END
BEGIN NOW There, without sign of boast, or sign of joy, END
BEGIN NOW Solicitous and blank, he thus began:-- END
BEGIN NOW Princes, Heaven's ancient Sons, AEthereal Thrones-- END
BEGIN NOW Daemonian Spirits now, from the element END
BEGIN NOW Each of his reign allotted, rightlier called END
BEGIN NOW Powers of Fire, Air, Water, and Earth beneath END
BEGIN NOW (So may we hold our place and these mild seats END
BEGIN NOW Without new trouble!)--such an enemy END
BEGIN NOW Is risen to invade us, who no less END
BEGIN NOW Threatens than our expulsion down to Hell. END
BEGIN NOW I, as I undertook, and with the vote END
BEGIN NOW Consenting in full frequence was impowered, END
BEGIN NOW Have found him, viewed him, tasted him; but find END
BEGIN NOW Far other labour to be undergone END
BEGIN NOW Than when I dealt with Adam, first of men, END
BEGIN NOW Though Adam by his wife's allurement fell, END
BEGIN NOW However to this Man inferior far-- END
BEGIN NOW If he be Man by mother's side, at least END
BEGIN NOW With more than human gifts from Heaven adorned, END
BEGIN NOW Perfections absolute, graces divine, END
BEGIN NOW And amplitude of mind to greatest deeds. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore I am returned, lest confidence END
BEGIN NOW Of my success with Eve in Paradise END
BEGIN NOW Deceive ye to persuasion over-sure END
BEGIN NOW Of like succeeding here. I summon all END
BEGIN NOW Rather to be in readiness with hand END
BEGIN NOW Or counsel to assist, lest I, who erst END
BEGIN NOW Thought none my equal, now be overmatched. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the old Serpent, doubting, and from all END
BEGIN NOW With clamour was assured their utmost aid END
BEGIN NOW At his command; when from amidst them rose END
BEGIN NOW Belial, the dissolutest Spirit that fell, END
BEGIN NOW The sensualest, and, after Asmodai, END
BEGIN NOW The fleshliest Incubus, and thus advised:-- END
BEGIN NOW Set women in his eye and in his walk, END
BEGIN NOW Among daughters of men the fairest found. END
BEGIN NOW Many are in each region passing fair END
BEGIN NOW As the noon sky, more like to goddesses END
BEGIN NOW Than mortal creatures, graceful and discreet, END
BEGIN NOW Expert in amorous arts, enchanting tongues END
BEGIN NOW Persuasive, virgin majesty with mild END
BEGIN NOW And sweet allayed, yet terrible to approach, END
BEGIN NOW Skilled to retire, and in retiring draw END
BEGIN NOW Hearts after them tangled in amorous nets. END
BEGIN NOW Such object hath the power to soften and tame END
BEGIN NOW Severest temper, smooth the rugged'st brow, END
BEGIN NOW Enerve, and with voluptuous hope dissolve, END
BEGIN NOW Draw out with credulous desire, and lead END
BEGIN NOW At will the manliest, resolutest breast, END
BEGIN NOW As the magnetic hardest iron draws. END
BEGIN NOW Women, when nothing else, beguiled the heart END
BEGIN NOW Of wisest Solomon, and made him build, END
BEGIN NOW And made him bow, to the gods of his wives. END
BEGIN NOW To whom quick answer Satan thus returned:-- END
BEGIN NOW Belial, in much uneven scale thou weigh'st END
BEGIN NOW All others by thyself. Because of old END
BEGIN NOW Thou thyself doat'st on womankind, admiring END
BEGIN NOW Their shape, their colour, and attractive grace, END
BEGIN NOW None are, thou think'st, but taken with such toys. END
BEGIN NOW Before the Flood, thou, with thy lusty crew, END
BEGIN NOW False titled Sons of God, roaming the Earth, END
BEGIN NOW Cast wanton eyes on the daughters of men, END
BEGIN NOW And coupled with them, and begot a race. END
BEGIN NOW Have we not seen, or by relation heard, END
BEGIN NOW In courts and regal chambers how thou lurk'st, END
BEGIN NOW In wood or grove, by mossy fountain-side, END
BEGIN NOW In valley or green meadow, to waylay END
BEGIN NOW Some beauty rare, Calisto, Clymene, END
BEGIN NOW Or Amymone, Syrinx, many more END
BEGIN NOW Too long--then lay'st thy scapes on names adored, END
BEGIN NOW Satyr, or Faun, or Silvan? But these haunts END
BEGIN NOW Delight not all. Among the sons of men END
BEGIN NOW How many have with a smile made small account END
BEGIN NOW Of beauty and her lures, easily scorned END
BEGIN NOW All her assaults, on worthier things intent! END
BEGIN NOW Remember that Pellean conqueror, END
BEGIN NOW A youth, how all the beauties of the East END
BEGIN NOW He slightly viewed, and slightly overpassed; END
BEGIN NOW How he surnamed of Africa dismissed, END
BEGIN NOW In his prime youth, the fair Iberian maid. END
BEGIN NOW For Solomon, he lived at ease, and, full END
BEGIN NOW Of honour, wealth, high fare, aimed not beyond END
BEGIN NOW Higher design than to enjoy his state; END
BEGIN NOW Thence to the bait of women lay exposed. END
BEGIN NOW But he whom we attempt is wiser far END
BEGIN NOW Than Solomon, of more exalted mind, END
BEGIN NOW Made and set wholly on the accomplishment END
BEGIN NOW Of greatest things. What woman will you find, END
BEGIN NOW Though of this age the wonder and the fame, END
BEGIN NOW On whom his leisure will voutsafe an eye END
BEGIN NOW Of fond desire? Or should she, confident, END
BEGIN NOW As sitting queen adored on Beauty's throne, END
BEGIN NOW Descend with all her winning charms begirt END
BEGIN NOW To enamour, as the zone of Venus once END
BEGIN NOW Wrought that effect on Jove (so fables tell), END
BEGIN NOW How would one look from his majestic brow, END
BEGIN NOW Seated as on the top of Virtue's hill, END
BEGIN NOW Discountenance her despised, and put to rout END
BEGIN NOW All her array, her female pride deject, END
BEGIN NOW Or turn to reverent awe! For Beauty stands END
BEGIN NOW In the admiration only of weak minds END
BEGIN NOW Led captive; cease to admire, and all her plumes END
BEGIN NOW Fall flat, and shrink into a trivial toy, END
BEGIN NOW At every sudden slighting quite abashed. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore with manlier objects we must try END
BEGIN NOW His constancy--with such as have more shew END
BEGIN NOW Of worth, of honour, glory, and popular praise END
BEGIN NOW (Rocks whereon greatest men have oftest wrecked); END
BEGIN NOW Or that which only seems to satisfy END
BEGIN NOW Lawful desires of nature, not beyond. END
BEGIN NOW And now I know he hungers, where no food END
BEGIN NOW Is to be found, in the wide Wilderness: END
BEGIN NOW The rest commit to me; I shall let pass END
BEGIN NOW No advantage, and his strength as oft assay. END
BEGIN NOW He ceased, and heard their grant in loud acclaim; END
BEGIN NOW Then forthwith to him takes a chosen band END
BEGIN NOW Of Spirits likest to himself in guile, END
BEGIN NOW To be at hand and at his beck appear, END
BEGIN NOW If cause were to unfold some active scene END
BEGIN NOW Of various persons, each to know his part; END
BEGIN NOW Then to the desert takes with these his flight, END
BEGIN NOW Where still, from shade to shade, the Son of God, END
BEGIN NOW After forty days' fasting, had remained, END
BEGIN NOW Now hungering first, and to himself thus said:-- END
BEGIN NOW Where will this end? Four times ten days I have passed END
BEGIN NOW Wandering this woody maze, and human food END
BEGIN NOW Nor tasted, nor had appetite. That fast END
BEGIN NOW To virtue I impute not, or count part END
BEGIN NOW Of what I suffer here. If nature need not, END
BEGIN NOW Or God support nature without repast, END
BEGIN NOW Though needing, what praise is it to endure? END
BEGIN NOW But now I feel I hunger; which declares END
BEGIN NOW Nature hath need of what she asks. Yet God END
BEGIN NOW Can satisfy that need some other way, END
BEGIN NOW Though hunger still remain. So it remain END
BEGIN NOW Without this body's wasting, I content me, END
BEGIN NOW And from the sting of famine fear no harm; END
BEGIN NOW Nor mind it, fed with better thoughts, that feed END
BEGIN NOW Me hungering more to do my Father's will. END
BEGIN NOW It was the hour of night, when thus the Son END
BEGIN NOW Communed in silent walk, then laid him down END
BEGIN NOW Under the hospitable covert nigh END
BEGIN NOW Of trees thick interwoven. There he slept, END
BEGIN NOW And dreamed, as appetite is wont to dream, END
BEGIN NOW Of meats and drinks, nature's refreshment sweet. END
BEGIN NOW Him thought he by the brook of Cherith stood, END
BEGIN NOW And saw the ravens with their horny beaks END
BEGIN NOW Food to Elijah bringing even and morn-- END
BEGIN NOW Though ravenous, taught to abstain from what they brought; END
BEGIN NOW He saw the Prophet also, how he fled END
BEGIN NOW Into the desert, and how there he slept END
BEGIN NOW Under a juniper--then how, awaked, END
BEGIN NOW He found his supper on the coals prepared, END
BEGIN NOW And by the Angel was bid rise and eat, END
BEGIN NOW And eat the second time after repose, END
BEGIN NOW The strength whereof sufficed him forty days: END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes that with Elijah he partook, END
BEGIN NOW Or as a guest with Daniel at his pulse. END
BEGIN NOW Thus wore out night; and now the harald Lark END
BEGIN NOW Left his ground-nest, high towering to descry END
BEGIN NOW The Morn's approach, and greet her with his song. END
BEGIN NOW As lightly from his grassy couch up rose END
BEGIN NOW Our Saviour, and found all was but a dream; END
BEGIN NOW Fasting he went to sleep, and fasting waked. END
BEGIN NOW Up to a hill anon his steps he reared, END
BEGIN NOW From whose high top to ken the prospect round, END
BEGIN NOW If cottage were in view, sheep-cote, or herd; END
BEGIN NOW But cottage, herd, or sheep-cote, none he saw-- END
BEGIN NOW Only in a bottom saw a pleasant grove, END
BEGIN NOW With chaunt of tuneful birds resounding loud. END
BEGIN NOW Thither he bent his way, determined there END
BEGIN NOW To rest at noon, and entered soon the shade END
BEGIN NOW High-roofed, and walks beneath, and alleys brown, END
BEGIN NOW That opened in the midst a woody scene; END
BEGIN NOW Nature's own work it seemed (Nature taught Art), END
BEGIN NOW And, to a superstitious eye, the haunt END
BEGIN NOW Of wood-gods and wood-nymphs. He viewed it round; END
BEGIN NOW When suddenly a man before him stood, END
BEGIN NOW Not rustic as before, but seemlier clad, END
BEGIN NOW As one in city or court or palace bred, END
BEGIN NOW And with fair speech these words to him addressed:-- END
BEGIN NOW With granted leave officious I return, END
BEGIN NOW But much more wonder that the Son of God END
BEGIN NOW In this wild solitude so long should bide, END
BEGIN NOW Of all things destitute, and, well I know, END
BEGIN NOW Not without hunger. Others of some note, END
BEGIN NOW As story tells, have trod this wilderness: END
BEGIN NOW The fugitive Bond-woman, with her son, END
BEGIN NOW Outcast Nebaioth, yet found here relief END
BEGIN NOW By a providing Angel; all the race END
BEGIN NOW Of Israel here had famished, had not God END
BEGIN NOW Rained from heaven manna; and that Prophet bold, END
BEGIN NOW Native of Thebez, wandering here, was fed END
BEGIN NOW Twice by a voice inviting him to eat. END
BEGIN NOW Of thee those forty days none hath regard, END
BEGIN NOW Forty and more deserted here indeed. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Jesus:--"What conclud'st thou hence? END
BEGIN NOW They all had need; I, as thou seest, have none. END
BEGIN NOW How hast thou hunger then?" Satan replied. END
BEGIN NOW Tell me, if food were now before thee set, END
BEGIN NOW Wouldst thou not eat?" "Thereafter as I like END
BEGIN NOW the giver," answered Jesus. "Why should that END
BEGIN NOW Cause thy refusal?" said the subtle Fiend. END
BEGIN NOW Hast thou not right to all created things? END
BEGIN NOW Owe not all creatures, by just right, to thee END
BEGIN NOW Duty and service, nor to stay till bid, END
BEGIN NOW But tender all their power? Nor mention I END
BEGIN NOW Meats by the law unclean, or offered first END
BEGIN NOW To idols--those young Daniel could refuse; END
BEGIN NOW Nor proffered by an enemy--though who END
BEGIN NOW Would scruple that, with want oppressed? Behold, END
BEGIN NOW Nature ashamed, or, better to express, END
BEGIN NOW Troubled, that thou shouldst hunger, hath purveyed END
BEGIN NOW From all the elements her choicest store, END
BEGIN NOW To treat thee as beseems, and as her Lord END
BEGIN NOW With honour. Only deign to sit and eat. END
BEGIN NOW He spake no dream; for, as his words had end, END
BEGIN NOW Our Saviour, lifting up his eyes, beheld, END
BEGIN NOW In ample space under the broadest shade, END
BEGIN NOW A table richly spread in regal mode, END
BEGIN NOW With dishes piled and meats of noblest sort END
BEGIN NOW And savour--beasts of chase, or fowl of game, END
BEGIN NOW In pastry built, or from the spit, or boiled, END
BEGIN NOW Grisamber-steamed; all fish, from sea or shore, END
BEGIN NOW Freshet or purling brook, of shell or fin, END
BEGIN NOW And exquisitest name, for which was drained END
BEGIN NOW Pontus, and Lucrine bay, and Afric coast. END
BEGIN NOW Alas! how simple, to these cates compared, END
BEGIN NOW Was that crude Apple that diverted Eve! END
BEGIN NOW And at a stately sideboard, by the wine, END
BEGIN NOW That fragrant smell diffused, in order stood END
BEGIN NOW Tall stripling youths rich-clad, of fairer hue END
BEGIN NOW Than Ganymed or Hylas; distant more, END
BEGIN NOW Under the trees now tripped, now solemn stood, END
BEGIN NOW Nymphs of Diana's train, and Naiades END
BEGIN NOW With fruits and flowers from Amalthea's horn, END
BEGIN NOW And ladies of the Hesperides, that seemed END
BEGIN NOW Fairer than feigned of old, or fabled since END
BEGIN NOW Of faery damsels met in forest wide END
BEGIN NOW By knights of Logres, or of Lyones, END
BEGIN NOW And all the while harmonious airs were heard END
BEGIN NOW Of chiming strings or charming pipes; and winds END
BEGIN NOW Of gentlest gale Arabian odours fanned END
BEGIN NOW From their soft wings, and Flora's earliest smells. END
BEGIN NOW Such was the splendour; and the Tempter now END
BEGIN NOW His invitation earnestly renewed:-- END
BEGIN NOW What doubts the Son of God to sit and eat? END
BEGIN NOW These are not fruits forbidden; no interdict END
BEGIN NOW Defends the touching of these viands pure; END
BEGIN NOW Their taste no knowledge works, at least of evil, END
BEGIN NOW But life preserves, destroys life's enemy, END
BEGIN NOW Hunger, with sweet restorative delight. END
BEGIN NOW All these are Spirits of air, and woods, and springs, END
BEGIN NOW Thy gentle ministers, who come to pay END
BEGIN NOW Thee homage, and acknowledge thee their Lord. END
BEGIN NOW What doubt'st thou, Son of God? Sit down and eat. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Jesus temperately replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Said'st thou not that to all things I had right? END
BEGIN NOW And who withholds my power that right to use? END
BEGIN NOW Shall I receive by gift what of my own, END
BEGIN NOW When and where likes me best, I can command? END
BEGIN NOW I can at will, doubt not, as soon as thou, END
BEGIN NOW Command a table in this wilderness, END
BEGIN NOW And call swift flights of Angels ministrant, END
BEGIN NOW Arrayed in glory, on my cup to attend: END
BEGIN NOW Why shouldst thou, then, obtrude this diligence END
BEGIN NOW In vain, where no acceptance it can find? END
BEGIN NOW And with my hunger what hast thou to do? END
BEGIN NOW Thy pompous delicacies I contemn, END
BEGIN NOW And count thy specious gifts no gifts, but guiles. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus answered Satan, male-content:-- END
BEGIN NOW That I have also power to give thou seest; END
BEGIN NOW If of that power I bring thee voluntary END
BEGIN NOW What I might have bestowed on whom I pleased, END
BEGIN NOW And rather opportunely in this place END
BEGIN NOW Chose to impart to thy apparent need, END
BEGIN NOW Why shouldst thou not accept it? But I see END
BEGIN NOW What I can do or offer is suspect. END
BEGIN NOW Of these things others quickly will dispose, END
BEGIN NOW Whose pains have earned the far-fet spoil." With that END
BEGIN NOW Both table and provision vanished quite, END
BEGIN NOW With sound of harpies' wings and talons heard; END
BEGIN NOW Only the importune Tempter still remained, END
BEGIN NOW And with these words his temptation pursued:-- END
BEGIN NOW By hunger, that each other creature tames, END
BEGIN NOW Thou art not to be harmed, therefore not moved; END
BEGIN NOW Thy temperance, invincible besides, END
BEGIN NOW For no allurement yields to appetite; END
BEGIN NOW And all thy heart is set on high designs, END
BEGIN NOW High actions. But wherewith to be achieved? END
BEGIN NOW Great acts require great means of enterprise; END
BEGIN NOW Thou art unknown, unfriended, low of birth, END
BEGIN NOW A carpenter thy father known, thyself END
BEGIN NOW Bred up in poverty and straits at home, END
BEGIN NOW Lost in a desert here and hunger-bit. END
BEGIN NOW Which way, or from what hope, dost thou aspire END
BEGIN NOW To greatness? whence authority deriv'st? END
BEGIN NOW What followers, what retinue canst thou gain, END
BEGIN NOW Or at thy heels the dizzy multitude, END
BEGIN NOW Longer than thou canst feed them on thy cost? END
BEGIN NOW Money brings honour, friends, conquest, and realms. END
BEGIN NOW What raised Antipater the Edomite, END
BEGIN NOW And his son Herod placed on Juda's throne, END
BEGIN NOW Thy throne, but gold, that got him puissant friends? END
BEGIN NOW Therefore, if at great things thou wouldst arrive, END
BEGIN NOW Get riches first, get wealth, and treasure heap-- END
BEGIN NOW Not difficult, if thou hearken to me. END
BEGIN NOW Riches are mine, fortune is in my hand; END
BEGIN NOW They whom I favour thrive in wealth amain, END
BEGIN NOW While virtue, valour, wisdom, sit in want. END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Jesus patiently replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Yet wealth without these three is impotent END
BEGIN NOW To gain dominion, or to keep it gained-- END
BEGIN NOW Witness those ancient empires of the earth, END
BEGIN NOW In highth of all their flowing wealth dissolved; END
BEGIN NOW But men endued with these have oft attained, END
BEGIN NOW In lowest poverty, to highest deeds-- END
BEGIN NOW Gideon, and Jephtha, and the shepherd lad END
BEGIN NOW Whose offspring on the throne of Juda sate END
BEGIN NOW So many ages, and shall yet regain END
BEGIN NOW That seat, and reign in Israel without end. END
BEGIN NOW Among the Heathen (for throughout the world END
BEGIN NOW To me is not unknown what hath been done END
BEGIN NOW Worthy of memorial) canst thou not remember END
BEGIN NOW For I esteem those names of men so poor, END
BEGIN NOW Who could do mighty things, and could contemn END
BEGIN NOW Riches, though offered from the hand of kings. END
BEGIN NOW And what in me seems wanting but that I END
BEGIN NOW May also in this poverty as soon END
BEGIN NOW Accomplish what they did, perhaps and more? END
BEGIN NOW Extol not riches, then, the toil of fools, END
BEGIN NOW The wise man's cumbrance, if not snare; more apt END
BEGIN NOW To slacken virtue and abate her edge END
BEGIN NOW Than prompt her to do aught may merit praise. END
BEGIN NOW What if with like aversion I reject END
BEGIN NOW Riches and realms! Yet not for that a crown, END
BEGIN NOW Golden in shew, is but a wreath of thorns, END
BEGIN NOW Brings dangers, troubles, cares, and sleepless nights, END
BEGIN NOW To him who wears the regal diadem, END
BEGIN NOW When on his shoulders each man's burden lies; END
BEGIN NOW For therein stands the office of a king, END
BEGIN NOW His honour, virtue, merit, and chief praise, END
BEGIN NOW That for the public all this weight he bears. END
BEGIN NOW Yet he who reigns within himself, and rules END
BEGIN NOW Passions, desires, and fears, is more a king-- END
BEGIN NOW Which every wise and virtuous man attains; END
BEGIN NOW And who attains not, ill aspires to rule END
BEGIN NOW Cities of men, or headstrong multitudes, END
BEGIN NOW Subject himself to anarchy within, END
BEGIN NOW Or lawless passions in him, which he serves. END
BEGIN NOW But to guide nations in the way of truth END
BEGIN NOW By saving doctrine, and from error lead END
BEGIN NOW To know, and, knowing, worship God aright, END
BEGIN NOW Is yet more kingly. This attracts the soul, END
BEGIN NOW Governs the inner man, the nobler part; END
BEGIN NOW That other o'er the body only reigns, END
BEGIN NOW And oft by force--which to a generous mind END
BEGIN NOW So reigning can be no sincere delight. END
BEGIN NOW Besides, to give a kingdom hath been thought END
BEGIN NOW Greater and nobler done, and to lay down END
BEGIN NOW Far more magnanimous, than to assume. END
BEGIN NOW Riches are needless, then, both for themselves, END
BEGIN NOW And for thy reason why they should be sought-- END
BEGIN NOW To gain a sceptre, oftest better missed. END
BEGIN NOW SO spake the Son of God; and Satan stood END
BEGIN NOW A while as mute, confounded what to say, END
BEGIN NOW What to reply, confuted and convinced END
BEGIN NOW Of his weak arguing and fallacious drift; END
BEGIN NOW At length, collecting all his serpent wiles, END
BEGIN NOW With soothing words renewed, him thus accosts:-- END
BEGIN NOW I see thou know'st what is of use to know, END
BEGIN NOW What best to say canst say, to do canst do; END
BEGIN NOW Thy actions to thy words accord; thy words END
BEGIN NOW To thy large heart give utterance due; thy heart END
BEGIN NOW Contains of good, wise, just, the perfet shape. END
BEGIN NOW Should kings and nations from thy mouth consult, END
BEGIN NOW Thy counsel would be as the oracle END
BEGIN NOW Urim and Thummim, those oraculous gems END
BEGIN NOW On Aaron's breast, or tongue of Seers old END
BEGIN NOW Infallible; or, wert thou sought to deeds END
BEGIN NOW That might require the array of war, thy skill END
BEGIN NOW Of conduct would be such that all the world END
BEGIN NOW Could not sustain thy prowess, or subsist END
BEGIN NOW In battle, though against thy few in arms. END
BEGIN NOW These godlike virtues wherefore dost thou hide? END
BEGIN NOW Affecting private life, or more obscure END
BEGIN NOW In savage wilderness, wherefore deprive END
BEGIN NOW All Earth her wonder at thy acts, thyself END
BEGIN NOW The fame and glory--glory, the reward END
BEGIN NOW That sole excites to high attempts the flame END
BEGIN NOW Of most erected spirits, most tempered pure END
BEGIN NOW AEthereal, who all pleasures else despise, END
BEGIN NOW All treasures and all gain esteem as dross, END
BEGIN NOW And dignities and powers, all but the highest? END
BEGIN NOW Thy years are ripe, and over-ripe. The son END
BEGIN NOW Of Macedonian Philip had ere these END
BEGIN NOW Won Asia, and the throne of Cyrus held END
BEGIN NOW At his dispose; young Scipio had brought down END
BEGIN NOW The Carthaginian pride; young Pompey quelled END
BEGIN NOW The Pontic king, and in triumph had rode. END
BEGIN NOW Yet years, and to ripe years judgment mature, END
BEGIN NOW Quench not the thirst of glory, but augment. END
BEGIN NOW Great Julius, whom now all the world admires, END
BEGIN NOW The more he grew in years, the more inflamed END
BEGIN NOW With glory, wept that he had lived so long END
BEGIN NOW Ingloroious. But thou yet art not too late. END
BEGIN NOW To whom our Saviour calmly thus replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Thou neither dost persuade me to seek wealth END
BEGIN NOW For empire's sake, nor empire to affect END
BEGIN NOW For glory's sake, by all thy argument. END
BEGIN NOW For what is glory but the blaze of fame, END
BEGIN NOW The people's praise, if always praise unmixed? END
BEGIN NOW And what the people but a herd confused, END
BEGIN NOW A miscellaneous rabble, who extol END
BEGIN NOW Things vulgar, and, well weighed, scarce worth the praise? END
BEGIN NOW They praise and they admire they know not what, END
BEGIN NOW And know not whom, but as one leads the other; END
BEGIN NOW And what delight to be by such extolled, END
BEGIN NOW To live upon their tongues, and be their talk? END
BEGIN NOW Of whom to be dispraised were no small praise-- END
BEGIN NOW His lot who dares be singularly good. END
BEGIN NOW The intelligent among them and the wise END
BEGIN NOW Are few, and glory scarce of few is raised. END
BEGIN NOW This is true glory and renown--when God, END
BEGIN NOW Looking on the Earth, with approbation marks END
BEGIN NOW The just man, and divulges him through Heaven END
BEGIN NOW To all his Angels, who with true applause END
BEGIN NOW Recount his praises. Thus he did to Job, END
BEGIN NOW When, to extend his fame through Heaven and Earth, END
BEGIN NOW As thou to thy reproach may'st well remember, END
BEGIN NOW He asked thee, 'Hast thou seen my servant Job?' END
BEGIN NOW Famous he was in Heaven; on Earth less known, END
BEGIN NOW Where glory is false glory, attributed END
BEGIN NOW To things not glorious, men not worthy of fame. END
BEGIN NOW They err who count it glorious to subdue END
BEGIN NOW By conquest far and wide, to overrun END
BEGIN NOW Large countries, and in field great battles win, END
BEGIN NOW Great cities by assault. What do these worthies END
BEGIN NOW But rob and spoil, burn, slaughter, and enslave END
BEGIN NOW Peaceable nations, neighbouring or remote, END
BEGIN NOW Made captive, yet deserving freedom more END
BEGIN NOW Than those their conquerors, who leave behind END
BEGIN NOW Nothing but ruin wheresoe'er they rove, END
BEGIN NOW And all the flourishing works of peace destroy; END
BEGIN NOW Then swell with pride, and must be titled Gods, END
BEGIN NOW Great benefactors of mankind, Deliverers, END
BEGIN NOW Worshipped with temple, priest, and sacrifice? END
BEGIN NOW One is the son of Jove, of Mars the other; END
BEGIN NOW Till conqueror Death discover them scarce men, END
BEGIN NOW Rowling in brutish vices, and deformed, END
BEGIN NOW Violent or shameful death their due reward. END
BEGIN NOW But, if there be in glory aught of good; END
BEGIN NOW It may be means far different be attained, END
BEGIN NOW Without ambition, war, or violence-- END
BEGIN NOW By deeds of peace, by wisdom eminent, END
BEGIN NOW By patience, temperance. I mention still END
BEGIN NOW Him whom thy wrongs, with saintly patience borne, END
BEGIN NOW Made famous in a land and times obscure; END
BEGIN NOW Who names not now with honour patient Job? END
BEGIN NOW Poor Socrates, (who next more memorable?) END
BEGIN NOW By what he taught and suffered for so doing, END
BEGIN NOW For truth's sake suffering death unjust, lives now END
BEGIN NOW Equal in fame to proudest conquerors. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, if for fame and glory aught be done, END
BEGIN NOW Aught suffered--if young African for fame END
BEGIN NOW His wasted country freed from Punic rage-- END
BEGIN NOW The deed becomes unpraised, the man at least, END
BEGIN NOW And loses, though but verbal, his reward. END
BEGIN NOW Shall I seek glory, then, as vain men seek, END
BEGIN NOW Oft not deserved? I seek not mine, but His END
BEGIN NOW Who sent me, and thereby witness whence I am. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Tempter, murmuring, thus replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Think not so slight of glory, therein least END
BEGIN NOW Resembling thy great Father. He seeks glory, END
BEGIN NOW And for his glory all things made, all things END
BEGIN NOW Orders and governs; nor content in Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW By all his Angels glorified, requires END
BEGIN NOW Glory from men, from all men, good or bad, END
BEGIN NOW Wise or unwise, no difference, no exemption. END
BEGIN NOW Above all sacrifice, or hallowed gift, END
BEGIN NOW Glory he requires, and glory he receives, END
BEGIN NOW Or Barbarous, nor exception hath declared; END
BEGIN NOW From us, his foes pronounced, glory he exacts. END
BEGIN NOW To whom our Saviour fervently replied: END
BEGIN NOW And reason; since his Word all things produced, END
BEGIN NOW Though chiefly not for glory as prime end, END
BEGIN NOW But to shew forth his goodness, and impart END
BEGIN NOW His good communicable to every soul END
BEGIN NOW Freely; of whom what could He less expect END
BEGIN NOW Than glory and benediction--that is, thanks-- END
BEGIN NOW The slightest, easiest, readiest recompense END
BEGIN NOW From them who could return him nothing else, END
BEGIN NOW And, not returning that, would likeliest render END
BEGIN NOW Contempt instead, dishonour, obloquy? END
BEGIN NOW Hard recompense, unsuitable return END
BEGIN NOW For so much good, so much beneficience! END
BEGIN NOW But why should man seek glory, who of his own END
BEGIN NOW Hath nothing, and to whom nothing belongs END
BEGIN NOW But condemnation, ignominy, and shame-- END
BEGIN NOW Who, for so many benefits received, END
BEGIN NOW Turned recreant to God, ingrate and false, END
BEGIN NOW And so of all true good himself despoiled; END
BEGIN NOW Yet, sacrilegious, to himself would take END
BEGIN NOW That which to God alone of right belongs? END
BEGIN NOW Yet so much bounty is in God, such grace, END
BEGIN NOW That who advances his glory, not their own, END
BEGIN NOW Them he himself to glory will advance. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Son of God; and here again END
BEGIN NOW Satan had not to answer, but stood struck END
BEGIN NOW With guilt of his own sin--for he himself, END
BEGIN NOW Insatiable of glory, had lost all; END
BEGIN NOW Yet of another plea bethought him soon:-- END
BEGIN NOW Of glory, as thou wilt," said he, "so deem; END
BEGIN NOW Worth or not worth the seeking, let it pass. END
BEGIN NOW But to a Kingdom thou art born--ordained END
BEGIN NOW To sit upon thy father David's throne, END
BEGIN NOW By mother's side thy father, though thy right END
BEGIN NOW Be now in powerful hands, that will not part END
BEGIN NOW Easily from possession won with arms. END
BEGIN NOW Reduced a province under Roman yoke, END
BEGIN NOW Obeys Tiberius, nor is always ruled END
BEGIN NOW With temperate sway: oft have they violated END
BEGIN NOW The Temple, oft the Law, with foul affronts, END
BEGIN NOW Abominations rather, as did once END
BEGIN NOW Antiochus. And think'st thou to regain END
BEGIN NOW Thy right by sitting still, or thus retiring? END
BEGIN NOW So did not Machabeus. He indeed END
BEGIN NOW Retired unto the Desert, but with arms; END
BEGIN NOW And o'er a mighty king so oft prevailed END
BEGIN NOW That by strong hand his family obtained, END
BEGIN NOW Though priests, the crown, and David's throne usurped, END
BEGIN NOW With Modin and her suburbs once content. END
BEGIN NOW If kingdom move thee not, let move thee zeal END
BEGIN NOW And duty--zeal and duty are not slow, END
BEGIN NOW But on Occasion's forelock watchful wait: END
BEGIN NOW They themselves rather are occasion best-- END
BEGIN NOW Zeal of thy Father's house, duty to free END
BEGIN NOW Thy country from her heathen servitude. END
BEGIN NOW So shalt thou best fulfil, best verify, END
BEGIN NOW The Prophets old, who sung thy endless reign-- END
BEGIN NOW The happier reign the sooner it begins. END
BEGIN NOW Rein then; what canst thou better do the while? END
BEGIN NOW To whom our Saviour answer thus returned:-- END
BEGIN NOW All things are best fulfilled in their due time; END
BEGIN NOW And time there is for all things, Truth hath said. END
BEGIN NOW If of my reign Prophetic Writ hath told END
BEGIN NOW That it shall never end, so, when begin END
BEGIN NOW The Father in his purpose hath decreed-- END
BEGIN NOW He in whose hand all times and seasons rowl. END
BEGIN NOW What if he hath decreed that I shall first END
BEGIN NOW Be tried in humble state, and things adverse, END
BEGIN NOW By tribulations, injuries, insults, END
BEGIN NOW Contempts, and scorns, and snares, and violence, END
BEGIN NOW Suffering, abstaining, quietly expecting END
BEGIN NOW Without distrust or doubt, that He may know END
BEGIN NOW What I can suffer, how obey? Who best END
BEGIN NOW Can suffer best can do, best reign who first END
BEGIN NOW Well hath obeyed--just trial ere I merit END
BEGIN NOW My exaltation without change or end. END
BEGIN NOW But what concerns it thee when I begin END
BEGIN NOW My everlasting Kingdom? Why art thou END
BEGIN NOW Solicitous? What moves thy inquisition? END
BEGIN NOW Know'st thou not that my rising is thy fall, END
BEGIN NOW And my promotion will be thy destruction? END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Tempter, inly racked, replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Let that come when it comes. All hope is lost END
BEGIN NOW Of my reception into grace; what worse? END
BEGIN NOW For where no hope is left is left no fear. END
BEGIN NOW If there be worse, the expectation more END
BEGIN NOW Of worse torments me than the feeling can. END
BEGIN NOW I would be at the worst; worst is my port, END
BEGIN NOW My harbour, and my ultimate repose, END
BEGIN NOW The end I would attain, my final good. END
BEGIN NOW My error was my error, and my crime END
BEGIN NOW My crime; whatever, for itself condemned, END
BEGIN NOW And will alike be punished, whether thou END
BEGIN NOW Reign or reign not--though to that gentle brow END
BEGIN NOW Willingly I could fly, and hope thy reign, END
BEGIN NOW From that placid aspect and meek regard, END
BEGIN NOW Rather than aggravate my evil state, END
BEGIN NOW Would stand between me and thy Father's ire END
BEGIN NOW (Whose ire I dread more than the fire of Hell) END
BEGIN NOW A shelter and a kind of shading cool END
BEGIN NOW Interposition, as a summer's cloud. END
BEGIN NOW If I, then, to the worst that can be haste, END
BEGIN NOW Why move thy feet so slow to what is best? END
BEGIN NOW Happiest, both to thyself and all the world, END
BEGIN NOW That thou, who worthiest art, shouldst be their King! END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps thou linger'st in deep thoughts detained END
BEGIN NOW Of the enterprise so hazardous and high! END
BEGIN NOW No wonder; for, though in thee be united END
BEGIN NOW What of perfection can in Man be found, END
BEGIN NOW Or human nature can receive, consider END
BEGIN NOW Thy life hath yet been private, most part spent END
BEGIN NOW At home, scarce viewed the Galilean towns, END
BEGIN NOW And once a year Jerusalem, few days' END
BEGIN NOW Short sojourn; and what thence couldst thou observe? END
BEGIN NOW The world thou hast not seen, much less her glory, END
BEGIN NOW Empires, and monarchs, and their radiant courts-- END
BEGIN NOW Best school of best experience, quickest in sight END
BEGIN NOW In all things that to greatest actions lead. END
BEGIN NOW The wisest, unexperienced, will be ever END
BEGIN NOW Timorous, and loth, with novice modesty END
BEGIN NOW (As he who, seeking asses, found a kingdom) END
BEGIN NOW Irresolute, unhardy, unadventrous. END
BEGIN NOW But I will bring thee where thou soon shalt quit END
BEGIN NOW Those rudiments, and see before thine eyes END
BEGIN NOW The monarchies of the Earth, their pomp and state-- END
BEGIN NOW Sufficient introduction to inform END
BEGIN NOW Thee, of thyself so apt, in regal arts, END
BEGIN NOW And regal mysteries; that thou may'st know END
BEGIN NOW How best their opposition to withstand. END
BEGIN NOW With that (such power was given him then), he took END
BEGIN NOW The Son of God up to a mountain high. END
BEGIN NOW It was a mountain at whose verdant feet END
BEGIN NOW A spacious plain outstretched in circuit wide END
BEGIN NOW Lay pleasant; from his side two rivers flowed, END
BEGIN NOW The one winding, the other straight, and left between END
BEGIN NOW Fair champaign, with less rivers interveined, END
BEGIN NOW Then meeting joined their tribute to the sea. END
BEGIN NOW Fertil of corn the glebe, of oil, and wine; END
BEGIN NOW With herds the pasture thronged, with flocks the hills; END
BEGIN NOW Huge cities and high-towered, that well might seem END
BEGIN NOW The seats of mightiest monarchs; and so large END
BEGIN NOW The prospect was that here and there was room END
BEGIN NOW For barren desert, fountainless and dry. END
BEGIN NOW To this high mountain-top the Tempter brought END
BEGIN NOW Our Saviour, and new train of words began:-- END
BEGIN NOW Well have we speeded, and o'er hill and dale, END
BEGIN NOW Forest, and field, and flood, temples and towers, END
BEGIN NOW Cut shorter many a league. Here thou behold'st END
BEGIN NOW Assyria, and her empire's ancient bounds, END
BEGIN NOW Araxes and the Caspian lake; thence on END
BEGIN NOW As far as Indus east, Euphrates west, END
BEGIN NOW And oft beyond; to south the Persian bay, END
BEGIN NOW And, inaccessible, the Arabian drouth: END
BEGIN NOW Here, Nineveh, of length within her wall END
BEGIN NOW Several days' journey, built by Ninus old, END
BEGIN NOW Of that first golden monarchy the seat, END
BEGIN NOW And seat of Salmanassar, whose success END
BEGIN NOW Israel in long captivity still mourns; END
BEGIN NOW There Babylon, the wonder of all tongues, END
BEGIN NOW As ancient, but rebuilt by him who twice END
BEGIN NOW Judah and all thy father David's house END
BEGIN NOW Led captive, and Jerusalem laid waste, END
BEGIN NOW Till Cyrus set them free; Persepolis, END
BEGIN NOW His city, there thou seest, and Bactra there; END
BEGIN NOW Ecbatana her structure vast there shews, END
BEGIN NOW And Hecatompylos her hunderd gates; END
BEGIN NOW There Susa by Choaspes, amber stream, END
BEGIN NOW The drink of none but kings; of later fame, END
BEGIN NOW Built by Emathian or by Parthian hands, END
BEGIN NOW The great Seleucia, Nisibis, and there END
BEGIN NOW Turning with easy eye, thou may'st behold. END
BEGIN NOW All these the Parthian (now some ages past END
BEGIN NOW By great Arsaces led, who founded first END
BEGIN NOW That empire) under his dominion holds, END
BEGIN NOW From the luxurious kings of Antioch won. END
BEGIN NOW And just in time thou com'st to have a view END
BEGIN NOW Of his great power; for now the Parthian king END
BEGIN NOW In Ctesiphon hath gathered all his host END
BEGIN NOW Against the Scythian, whose incursions wild END
BEGIN NOW Have wasted Sogdiana; to her aid END
BEGIN NOW He marches now in haste. See, though from far, END
BEGIN NOW His thousands, in what martial equipage END
BEGIN NOW They issue forth, steel bows and shafts their arms, END
BEGIN NOW Of equal dread in flight or in pursuit-- END
BEGIN NOW All horsemen, in which fight they most excel; END
BEGIN NOW See how in warlike muster they appear, END
BEGIN NOW In rhombs, and wedges, and half-moons, and wings. END
BEGIN NOW He looked, and saw what numbers numberless END
BEGIN NOW The city gates outpoured, light-armed troops END
BEGIN NOW In coats of mail and military pride. END
BEGIN NOW In mail their horses clad, yet fleet and strong, END
BEGIN NOW Prauncing their riders bore, the flower and choice END
BEGIN NOW Of many provinces from bound to bound-- END
BEGIN NOW From Arachosia, from Candaor east, END
BEGIN NOW And Margiana, to the Hyrcanian cliffs END
BEGIN NOW Of Caucasus, and dark Iberian dales; END
BEGIN NOW From Atropatia, and the neighbouring plains END
BEGIN NOW Of Adiabene, Media, and the south END
BEGIN NOW Of Susiana, to Balsara's haven. END
BEGIN NOW He saw them in their forms of battle ranged, END
BEGIN NOW How quick they wheeled, and flying behind them shot END
BEGIN NOW Sharp sleet of arrowy showers against the face END
BEGIN NOW Of their pursuers, and overcame by flight; END
BEGIN NOW The field all iron cast a gleaming brown. END
BEGIN NOW Nor wanted clouds of foot, nor, on each horn, END
BEGIN NOW Cuirassiers all in steel for standing fight, END
BEGIN NOW Chariots, or elephants indorsed with towers END
BEGIN NOW Of archers; nor of labouring pioners END
BEGIN NOW To lay hills plain, fell woods, or valleys fill, END
BEGIN NOW Or where plain was raise hill, or overlay END
BEGIN NOW With bridges rivers proud, as with a yoke: END
BEGIN NOW Mules after these, camels and dromedaries, END
BEGIN NOW And waggons fraught with utensils of war. END
BEGIN NOW Such forces met not, nor so wide a camp, END
BEGIN NOW When Agrican, with all his northern powers, END
BEGIN NOW Besieged Albracea, as romances tell, END
BEGIN NOW The city of Gallaphrone, from thence to win END
BEGIN NOW The fairest of her sex, Angelica, END
BEGIN NOW His daughter, sought by many prowest knights, END
BEGIN NOW Both Paynim and the peers of Charlemane. END
BEGIN NOW Such and so numerous was their chivalry; END
BEGIN NOW At sight whereof the Fiend yet more presumed, END
BEGIN NOW And to our Saviour thus his words renewed:-- END
BEGIN NOW That thou may'st know I seek not to engage END
BEGIN NOW Thy virtue, and not every way secure END
BEGIN NOW On no slight grounds thy safety, hear and mark END
BEGIN NOW To what end I have brought thee hither, and shew END
BEGIN NOW All this fair sight. Thy kingdom, though foretold END
BEGIN NOW By Prophet or by Angel, unless thou END
BEGIN NOW Endeavour, as thy father David did, END
BEGIN NOW Thou never shalt obtain: prediction still END
BEGIN NOW In all things, and all men, supposes means; END
BEGIN NOW Without means used, what it predicts revokes. END
BEGIN NOW But say thou wert possessed of David's throne END
BEGIN NOW By free consent of all, none opposite, END
BEGIN NOW Long to enjoy it quiet and secure END
BEGIN NOW Between two such enclosing enemies, END
BEGIN NOW Roman and Parthian? Therefore one of these END
BEGIN NOW Thou must make sure thy own: the Parthian first, END
BEGIN NOW By my advice, as nearer, and of late END
BEGIN NOW Found able by invasion to annoy END
BEGIN NOW Thy country, and captive lead away her kings, END
BEGIN NOW Antigonus and old Hyrcanus, bound, END
BEGIN NOW Maugre the Roman. It shall be my task END
BEGIN NOW To render thee the Parthian at dispose, END
BEGIN NOW Choose which thou wilt, by conquest or by league. END
BEGIN NOW By him thou shalt regain, without him not, END
BEGIN NOW That which alone can truly reinstall thee END
BEGIN NOW In David's royal seat, his true successor-- END
BEGIN NOW Deliverance of thy brethren, those Ten Tribes END
BEGIN NOW Whose offspring in his territory yet serve END
BEGIN NOW In Habor, and among the Medes dispersed: END
BEGIN NOW The sons of Jacob, two of Joseph, lost END
BEGIN NOW Thus long from Israel, serving, as of old END
BEGIN NOW This offer sets before thee to deliver. END
BEGIN NOW These if from servitude thou shalt restore END
BEGIN NOW To their inheritance, then, nor till then, END
BEGIN NOW Thou on the throne of David in full glory, END
BEGIN NOW Shalt reign, and Rome or Caesar not need fear. END
BEGIN NOW To whom our Saviour answered thus, unmoved:-- END
BEGIN NOW Much ostentation vain of fleshly arm END
BEGIN NOW And fragile arms, much instrument of war, END
BEGIN NOW Long in preparing, soon to nothing brought, END
BEGIN NOW Before mine eyes thou hast set, and in my ear END
BEGIN NOW Vented much policy, and projects deep END
BEGIN NOW Of enemies, of aids, battles, and leagues, END
BEGIN NOW Plausible to the world, to me worth naught. END
BEGIN NOW Means I must use, thou say'st; prediction else END
BEGIN NOW Will unpredict, and fail me of the throne! END
BEGIN NOW My time, I told thee (and that time for thee END
BEGIN NOW Were better farthest off), is not yet come. END
BEGIN NOW When that comes, think not thou to find me slack END
BEGIN NOW On my part aught endeavouring, or to need END
BEGIN NOW Thy politic maxims, or that cumbersome END
BEGIN NOW Luggage of war there shewn me--argument END
BEGIN NOW Of human weakness rather than of strength. END
BEGIN NOW My brethren, as thou call'st them, those Ten Tribes, END
BEGIN NOW I must deliver, if I mean to reign END
BEGIN NOW David's true heir, and his full sceptre sway END
BEGIN NOW To just extent over all Israel's sons! END
BEGIN NOW But whence to thee this zeal? Where was it then END
BEGIN NOW For Israel, or for David, or his throne, END
BEGIN NOW When thou stood'st up his tempter to the pride END
BEGIN NOW Of numbering Israel--which cost the lives END
BEGIN NOW of threescore and ten thousand Israelites END
BEGIN NOW By three days' pestilence? Such was thy zeal END
BEGIN NOW To Israel then, the same that now to me. END
BEGIN NOW As for those captive tribes, themselves were they END
BEGIN NOW Who wrought their own captivity, fell off END
BEGIN NOW From God to worship calves, the deities END
BEGIN NOW And all the idolatries of heathen round, END
BEGIN NOW Besides their other worse than heathenish crimes; END
BEGIN NOW Nor in the land of their captivity END
BEGIN NOW Humbled themselves, or penitent besought END
BEGIN NOW The God of their forefathers, but so died END
BEGIN NOW Impenitent, and left a race behind END
BEGIN NOW Like to themselves, distinguishable scarce END
BEGIN NOW From Gentiles, but by circumcision vain, END
BEGIN NOW And God with idols in their worship joined. END
BEGIN NOW Should I of these the liberty regard, END
BEGIN NOW Who, freed, as to their ancient patrimony, END
BEGIN NOW Unhumbled, unrepentant, unreformed, END
BEGIN NOW Headlong would follow, and to their gods perhaps END
BEGIN NOW Of Bethel and of Dan? No; let them serve END
BEGIN NOW Their enemies who serve idols with God. END
BEGIN NOW Yet He at length, time to himself best known, END
BEGIN NOW Remembering Abraham, by some wondrous call END
BEGIN NOW May bring them back, repentant and sincere, END
BEGIN NOW And at their passing cleave the Assyrian flood, END
BEGIN NOW While to their native land with joy they haste, END
BEGIN NOW As the Red Sea and Jordan once he cleft, END
BEGIN NOW When to the Promised Land their fathers passed. END
BEGIN NOW To his due time and providence I leave them. END
BEGIN NOW So spake Israel's true King, and to the Fiend END
BEGIN NOW Made answer meet, that made void all his wiles. END
BEGIN NOW So fares it when with truth falsehood contends. END
BEGIN NOW Perplexed and troubled at his bad success END
BEGIN NOW The Tempter stood, nor had what to reply, END
BEGIN NOW Discovered in his fraud, thrown from his hope END
BEGIN NOW So oft, and the persuasive rhetoric END
BEGIN NOW That sleeked his tongue, and won so much on Eve, END
BEGIN NOW So little here, nay lost. But Eve was Eve; END
BEGIN NOW This far his over-match, who, self-deceived END
BEGIN NOW And rash, beforehand had no better weighed END
BEGIN NOW The strength he was to cope with, or his own. END
BEGIN NOW But--as a man who had been matchless held END
BEGIN NOW In cunning, over-reached where least he thought, END
BEGIN NOW To salve his credit, and for very spite, END
BEGIN NOW Still will be tempting him who foils him still, END
BEGIN NOW And never cease, though to his shame the more; END
BEGIN NOW Or as a swarm of flies in vintage-time, END
BEGIN NOW About the wine-press where sweet must is poured, END
BEGIN NOW Beat off, returns as oft with humming sound; END
BEGIN NOW Or surging waves against a solid rock, END
BEGIN NOW Though all to shivers dashed, the assault renew, END
BEGIN NOW (Vain battery!) and in froth or bubbles end-- END
BEGIN NOW So Satan, whom repulse upon repulse END
BEGIN NOW Met ever, and to shameful silence brought, END
BEGIN NOW Yet gives not o'er, though desperate of success, END
BEGIN NOW And his vain importunity pursues. END
BEGIN NOW He brought our Saviour to the western side END
BEGIN NOW Of that high mountain, whence he might behold END
BEGIN NOW Another plain, long, but in breadth not wide, END
BEGIN NOW Washed by the southern sea, and on the north END
BEGIN NOW To equal length backed with a ridge of hills END
BEGIN NOW That screened the fruits of the earth and seats of men END
BEGIN NOW From cold Septentrion blasts; thence in the midst END
BEGIN NOW Divided by a river, off whose banks END
BEGIN NOW On each side an Imperial City stood, END
BEGIN NOW With towers and temples proudly elevate END
BEGIN NOW On seven small hills, with palaces adorned, END
BEGIN NOW Porches and theatres, baths, aqueducts, END
BEGIN NOW Statues and trophies, and triumphal arcs, END
BEGIN NOW Gardens and groves, presented to his eyes END
BEGIN NOW Above the highth of mountains interposed-- END
BEGIN NOW By what strange parallax, or optic skill END
BEGIN NOW Of vision, multiplied through air, or glass END
BEGIN NOW Of telescope, were curious to enquire. END
BEGIN NOW And now the Tempter thus his silence broke:-- END
BEGIN NOW The city which thou seest no other deem END
BEGIN NOW Than great and glorious Rome, Queen of the Earth END
BEGIN NOW So far renowned, and with the spoils enriched END
BEGIN NOW Of nations. There the Capitol thou seest, END
BEGIN NOW Above the rest lifting his stately head END
BEGIN NOW On the Tarpeian rock, her citadel END
BEGIN NOW Impregnable; and there Mount Palatine, END
BEGIN NOW The imperial palace, compass huge, and high END
BEGIN NOW The structure, skill of noblest architects, END
BEGIN NOW With gilded battlements, conspicuous far, END
BEGIN NOW Turrets, and terraces, and glittering spires. END
BEGIN NOW Many a fair edifice besides, more like END
BEGIN NOW Houses of gods--so well I have disposed END
BEGIN NOW My aerie microscope--thou may'st behold, END
BEGIN NOW Outside and inside both, pillars and roofs END
BEGIN NOW Carved work, the hand of famed artificers END
BEGIN NOW In cedar, marble, ivory, or gold. END
BEGIN NOW Thence to the gates cast round thine eye, and see END
BEGIN NOW What conflux issuing forth, or entering in: END
BEGIN NOW Praetors, proconsuls to their provinces END
BEGIN NOW Hasting, or on return, in robes of state; END
BEGIN NOW Lictors and rods, the ensigns of their power; END
BEGIN NOW Legions and cohorts, turms of horse and wings; END
BEGIN NOW Or embassies from regions far remote, END
BEGIN NOW In various habits, on the Appian road, END
BEGIN NOW Or on the AEmilian--some from farthest south, END
BEGIN NOW Syene, and where the shadow both way falls, END
BEGIN NOW Meroe, Nilotic isle, and, more to west, END
BEGIN NOW The realm of Bocchus to the Blackmoor sea; END
BEGIN NOW From the Asian kings (and Parthian among these), END
BEGIN NOW And utmost Indian isle Taprobane, END
BEGIN NOW Dusk faces with white silken turbants wreathed; END
BEGIN NOW From Gallia, Gades, and the British west; END
BEGIN NOW Germans, and Scythians, and Sarmatians north END
BEGIN NOW Beyond Danubius to the Tauric pool. END
BEGIN NOW All nations now to Rome obedience pay-- END
BEGIN NOW To Rome's great Emperor, whose wide domain, END
BEGIN NOW In ample territory, wealth and power, END
BEGIN NOW Civility of manners, arts and arms, END
BEGIN NOW And long renown, thou justly may'st prefer END
BEGIN NOW Before the Parthian. These two thrones except, END
BEGIN NOW The rest are barbarous, and scarce worth the sight, END
BEGIN NOW Shared among petty kings too far removed; END
BEGIN NOW These having shewn thee, I have shewn thee all END
BEGIN NOW The kingdoms of the world, and all their glory. END
BEGIN NOW This Emperor hath no son, and now is old, END
BEGIN NOW Old and lascivious, and from Rome retired END
BEGIN NOW To Capreae, an island small but strong END
BEGIN NOW On the Campanian shore, with purpose there END
BEGIN NOW His horrid lusts in private to enjoy; END
BEGIN NOW Committing to a wicked favourite END
BEGIN NOW All public cares, and yet of him suspicious; END
BEGIN NOW Hated of all, and hating. With what ease, END
BEGIN NOW Endued with regal virtues as thou art, END
BEGIN NOW Appearing, and beginning noble deeds, END
BEGIN NOW Might'st thou expel this monster from his throne, END
BEGIN NOW Now made a sty, and, in his place ascending, END
BEGIN NOW A victor-people free from servile yoke! END
BEGIN NOW And with my help thou may'st; to me the power END
BEGIN NOW Is given, and by that right I give it thee. END
BEGIN NOW Aim, therefore, at no less than all the world; END
BEGIN NOW Aim at the highest; without the highest attained, END
BEGIN NOW Will be for thee no sitting, or not long, END
BEGIN NOW On David's throne, be prophesied what will. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Son of God, unmoved, replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Nor doth this grandeur and majestic shew END
BEGIN NOW Of luxury, though called magnificence, END
BEGIN NOW More than of arms before, allure mine eye, END
BEGIN NOW Much less my mind; though thou should'st add to tell END
BEGIN NOW Their sumptuous gluttonies, and gorgeous feasts END
BEGIN NOW On citron tables or Atlantic stone END
BEGIN NOW (For I have also heard, perhaps have read), END
BEGIN NOW Their wines of Setia, Cales, and Falerne, END
BEGIN NOW Chios and Crete, and how they quaff in gold, END
BEGIN NOW Crystal, and myrrhine cups, imbossed with gems END
BEGIN NOW And studs of pearl--to me should'st tell, who thirst END
BEGIN NOW And hunger still. Then embassies thou shew'st END
BEGIN NOW From nations far and nigh! What honour that, END
BEGIN NOW But tedious waste of time, to sit and hear END
BEGIN NOW So many hollow compliments and lies, END
BEGIN NOW Outlandish flatteries? Then proceed'st to talk END
BEGIN NOW Of the Emperor, how easily subdued, END
BEGIN NOW How gloriously. I shall, thou say'st, expel END
BEGIN NOW A brutish monster: what if I withal END
BEGIN NOW Expel a Devil who first made him such? END
BEGIN NOW Let his tormentor, Conscience, find him out; END
BEGIN NOW For him I was not sent, nor yet to free END
BEGIN NOW That people, victor once, now vile and base, END
BEGIN NOW Deservedly made vassal--who, once just, END
BEGIN NOW Frugal, and mild, and temperate, conquered well, END
BEGIN NOW But govern ill the nations under yoke, END
BEGIN NOW Peeling their provinces, exhausted all END
BEGIN NOW By lust and rapine; first ambitious grown END
BEGIN NOW Of triumph, that insulting vanity; END
BEGIN NOW Then cruel, by their sports to blood inured END
BEGIN NOW Of fighting beasts, and men to beasts exposed; END
BEGIN NOW Luxurious by their wealth, and greedier still, END
BEGIN NOW And from the daily Scene effeminate. END
BEGIN NOW What wise and valiant man would seek to free END
BEGIN NOW These, thus degenerate, by themselves enslaved, END
BEGIN NOW Or could of inward slaves make outward free? END
BEGIN NOW Know, therefore, when my season comes to sit END
BEGIN NOW On David's throne, it shall be like a tree END
BEGIN NOW Spreading and overshadowing all the earth, END
BEGIN NOW Or as a stone that shall to pieces dash END
BEGIN NOW All monarchies besides throughout the world; END
BEGIN NOW And of my Kingdom there shall be no end. END
BEGIN NOW Means there shall be to this; but what the means END
BEGIN NOW Is not for thee to know, nor me to tell. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Tempter, impudent, replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW I see all offers made by me how slight END
BEGIN NOW Thou valuest, because offered, and reject'st. END
BEGIN NOW Nothing will please the difficult and nice, END
BEGIN NOW Or nothing more than still to contradict. END
BEGIN NOW On the other side know also thou that I END
BEGIN NOW On what I offer set as high esteem, END
BEGIN NOW Nor what I part with mean to give for naught, END
BEGIN NOW All these, which in a moment thou behold'st, END
BEGIN NOW The kingdoms of the world, to thee I give END
BEGIN NOW (For, given to me, I give to whom I please), END
BEGIN NOW No trifle; yet with this reserve, not else-- END
BEGIN NOW On this condition, if thou wilt fall down, END
BEGIN NOW And worship me as thy superior Lord END
BEGIN NOW (Easily done), and hold them all of me; END
BEGIN NOW For what can less so great a gift deserve? END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus our Saviour answered with disdain:-- END
BEGIN NOW I never liked thy talk, thy offers less; END
BEGIN NOW Now both abhor, since thou hast dared to utter END
BEGIN NOW The abominable terms, impious condition. END
BEGIN NOW But I endure the time, till which expired END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast permission on me. It is written, END
BEGIN NOW The first of all commandments, 'Thou shalt worship END
BEGIN NOW The Lord thy God, and only Him shalt serve.' END
BEGIN NOW And dar'st thou to the Son of God propound END
BEGIN NOW To worship thee, accursed? now more accursed END
BEGIN NOW For this attempt, bolder than that on Eve, END
BEGIN NOW And more blasphemous; which expect to rue. END
BEGIN NOW The kingdoms of the world to thee were given! END
BEGIN NOW Permitted rather, and by thee usurped; END
BEGIN NOW Other donation none thou canst produce. END
BEGIN NOW If given, by whom but by the King of kings, END
BEGIN NOW God over all supreme? If given to thee, END
BEGIN NOW By thee how fairly is the Giver now END
BEGIN NOW Repaid! But gratitude in thee is lost END
BEGIN NOW Long since. Wert thou so void of fear or shame END
BEGIN NOW As offer them to me, the Son of God-- END
BEGIN NOW To me my own, on such abhorred pact, END
BEGIN NOW That I fall down and worship thee as God? END
BEGIN NOW Get thee behind me! Plain thou now appear'st END
BEGIN NOW That Evil One, Satan for ever damned. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Fiend, with fear abashed, replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Be not so sore offended, Son of God-- END
BEGIN NOW Though Sons of God both Angels are and Men-- END
BEGIN NOW If I, to try whether in higher sort END
BEGIN NOW Than these thou bear'st that title, have proposed END
BEGIN NOW What both from Men and Angels I receive, END
BEGIN NOW Nations besides from all the quartered winds-- END
BEGIN NOW God of this World invoked, and World beneath. END
BEGIN NOW Who then thou art, whose coming is foretold END
BEGIN NOW To me most fatal, me it most concerns. END
BEGIN NOW The trial hath indamaged thee no way, END
BEGIN NOW Rather more honour left and more esteem; END
BEGIN NOW Me naught advantaged, missing what I aimed. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore let pass, as they are transitory, END
BEGIN NOW The kingdoms of this world; I shall no more END
BEGIN NOW Advise thee; gain them as thou canst, or not. END
BEGIN NOW And thou thyself seem'st otherwise inclined END
BEGIN NOW Than to a worldly crown, addicted more END
BEGIN NOW To contemplation and profound dispute; END
BEGIN NOW As by that early action may be judged, END
BEGIN NOW When, slipping from thy mother's eye, thou went'st END
BEGIN NOW Alone into the Temple, there wast found END
BEGIN NOW Among the gravest Rabbies, disputant END
BEGIN NOW On points and questions fitting Moses' chair, END
BEGIN NOW Teaching, not taught. The childhood shews the man, END
BEGIN NOW As morning shews the day. Be famous, then, END
BEGIN NOW By wisdom; as thy empire must extend, END
BEGIN NOW So let extend thy mind o'er all the world END
BEGIN NOW In knowledge; all things in it comprehend. END
BEGIN NOW All knowledge is not couched in Moses' law, END
BEGIN NOW The Pentateuch, or what the Prophets wrote; END
BEGIN NOW The Gentiles also know, and write, and teach END
BEGIN NOW To admiration, led by Nature's light; END
BEGIN NOW And with the Gentiles much thou must converse, END
BEGIN NOW Ruling them by persuasion, as thou mean'st. END
BEGIN NOW Without their learning, how wilt thou with them, END
BEGIN NOW Or they with thee, hold conversation meet? END
BEGIN NOW How wilt thou reason with them, how refute END
BEGIN NOW Their idolisms, traditions, paradoxes? END
BEGIN NOW Error by his own arms is best evinced. END
BEGIN NOW Look once more, ere we leave this specular mount, END
BEGIN NOW Westward, much nearer by south-west; behold END
BEGIN NOW Where on the AEgean shore a city stands, END
BEGIN NOW Built nobly, pure the air and light the soil-- END
BEGIN NOW Athens, the eye of Greece, mother of arts END
BEGIN NOW And Eloquence, native to famous wits END
BEGIN NOW Or hospitable, in her sweet recess, END
BEGIN NOW City or suburban, studious walks and shades. END
BEGIN NOW See there the olive-grove of Academe, END
BEGIN NOW Plato's retirement, where the Attic bird END
BEGIN NOW Trills her thick-warbled notes the summer long; END
BEGIN NOW There, flowery hill, Hymettus, with the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of bees' industrious murmur, oft invites END
BEGIN NOW To studious musing; there Ilissus rowls END
BEGIN NOW His whispering stream. Within the walls then view END
BEGIN NOW The schools of ancient sages--his who bred END
BEGIN NOW Great Alexander to subdue the world, END
BEGIN NOW Lyceum there; and painted Stoa next. END
BEGIN NOW There thou shalt hear and learn the secret power END
BEGIN NOW Of harmony, in tones and numbers hit END
BEGIN NOW By voice or hand, and various-measured verse, END
BEGIN NOW AEolian charms and Dorian lyric odes, END
BEGIN NOW And his who gave them breath, but higher sung, END
BEGIN NOW Blind Melesigenes, thence Homer called, END
BEGIN NOW Whose poem Phoebus challenged for his own. END
BEGIN NOW Thence what the lofty grave Tragedians taught END
BEGIN NOW In chorus or iambic, teachers best END
BEGIN NOW Of moral prudence, with delight received END
BEGIN NOW In brief sententious precepts, while they treat END
BEGIN NOW Of fate, and chance, and change in human life, END
BEGIN NOW High actions and high passions best describing. END
BEGIN NOW Thence to the famous Orators repair, END
BEGIN NOW Those ancient whose resistless eloquence END
BEGIN NOW Wielded at will that fierce democraty, END
BEGIN NOW Shook the Arsenal, and fulmined over Greece END
BEGIN NOW To Macedon and Artaxerxes' throne. END
BEGIN NOW To sage Philosophy next lend thine ear, END
BEGIN NOW From heaven descended to the low-roofed house END
BEGIN NOW Of Socrates--see there his tenement-- END
BEGIN NOW Whom, well inspired, the Oracle pronounced END
BEGIN NOW Wisest of men; from whose mouth issued forth END
BEGIN NOW Mellifluous streams, that watered all the schools END
BEGIN NOW Of Academics old and new, with those END
BEGIN NOW Surnamed Peripatetics, and the sect END
BEGIN NOW Epicurean, and the Stoic severe. END
BEGIN NOW These here revolve, or, as thou likest, at home, END
BEGIN NOW Till time mature thee to a kingdom's weight; END
BEGIN NOW These rules will render thee a king complete END
BEGIN NOW Within thyself, much more with empire joined. END
BEGIN NOW To whom our Saviour sagely thus replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Think not but that I know these things; or, think END
BEGIN NOW I know them not, not therefore am I short END
BEGIN NOW Of knowing what I ought. He who receives END
BEGIN NOW Light from above, from the Fountain of Light, END
BEGIN NOW No other doctrine needs, though granted true; END
BEGIN NOW But these are false, or little else but dreams, END
BEGIN NOW Conjectures, fancies, built on nothing firm. END
BEGIN NOW The first and wisest of them all professed END
BEGIN NOW To know this only, that he nothing knew; END
BEGIN NOW The next to fabling fell and smooth conceits; END
BEGIN NOW A third sort doubted all things, though plain sense; END
BEGIN NOW Others in virtue placed felicity, END
BEGIN NOW But virtue joined with riches and long life; END
BEGIN NOW In corporal pleasure he, and careless ease; END
BEGIN NOW The Stoic last in philosophic pride, END
BEGIN NOW By him called virtue, and his virtuous man, END
BEGIN NOW Wise, perfect in himself, and all possessing, END
BEGIN NOW Equal to God, oft shames not to prefer, END
BEGIN NOW As fearing God nor man, contemning all END
BEGIN NOW Wealth, pleasure, pain or torment, death and life-- END
BEGIN NOW Which, when he lists, he leaves, or boasts he can; END
BEGIN NOW For all his tedious talk is but vain boast, END
BEGIN NOW Or subtle shifts conviction to evade. END
BEGIN NOW Alas! what can they teach, and not mislead, END
BEGIN NOW Ignorant of themselves, of God much more, END
BEGIN NOW And how the World began, and how Man fell, END
BEGIN NOW Degraded by himself, on grace depending? END
BEGIN NOW Much of the Soul they talk, but all awry; END
BEGIN NOW And in themselves seek virtue; and to themselves END
BEGIN NOW All glory arrogate, to God give none; END
BEGIN NOW Rather accuse him under usual names, END
BEGIN NOW Fortune and Fate, as one regardless quite END
BEGIN NOW Of mortal things. Who, therefore, seeks in these END
BEGIN NOW True wisdom finds her not, or, by delusion END
BEGIN NOW Far worse, her false resemblance only meets, END
BEGIN NOW An empty cloud. However, many books, END
BEGIN NOW Wise men have said, are wearisome; who reads END
BEGIN NOW Incessantly, and to his reading brings not END
BEGIN NOW A spirit and judgment equal or superior, END
BEGIN NOW (And what he brings what needs he elsewhere seek?) END
BEGIN NOW Uncertain and unsettled still remains, END
BEGIN NOW Deep-versed in books and shallow in himself, END
BEGIN NOW Crude or intoxicate, collecting toys END
BEGIN NOW And trifles for choice matters, worth a sponge, END
BEGIN NOW As children gathering pebbles on the shore. END
BEGIN NOW Or, if I would delight my private hours END
BEGIN NOW With music or with poem, where so soon END
BEGIN NOW As in our native language can I find END
BEGIN NOW That solace? All our Law and Story strewed END
BEGIN NOW With hymns, our Psalms with artful terms inscribed, END
BEGIN NOW Our Hebrew songs and harps, in Babylon END
BEGIN NOW That pleased so well our victor's ear, declare END
BEGIN NOW That rather Greece from us these arts derived-- END
BEGIN NOW Ill imitated while they loudest sing END
BEGIN NOW The vices of their deities, and their own, END
BEGIN NOW In fable, hymn, or song, so personating END
BEGIN NOW Their gods ridiculous, and themselves past shame. END
BEGIN NOW Remove their swelling epithetes, thick-laid END
BEGIN NOW As varnish on a harlot's cheek, the rest, END
BEGIN NOW Thin-sown with aught of profit or delight, END
BEGIN NOW Will far be found unworthy to compare END
BEGIN NOW With Sion's songs, to all true tastes excelling, END
BEGIN NOW Where God is praised aright and godlike men, END
BEGIN NOW (Such are from God inspired, not such from thee); END
BEGIN NOW Unless where moral virtue is expressed END
BEGIN NOW By light of Nature, not in all quite lost. END
BEGIN NOW Their orators thou then extoll'st as those END
BEGIN NOW The top of eloquence--statists indeed, END
BEGIN NOW And lovers of their country, as may seem; END
BEGIN NOW But herein to our Prophets far beneath, END
BEGIN NOW As men divinely taught, and better teaching END
BEGIN NOW The solid rules of civil government, END
BEGIN NOW In their majestic, unaffected style, END
BEGIN NOW Than all the oratory of Greece and Rome. END
BEGIN NOW In them is plainest taught, and easiest learnt, END
BEGIN NOW What makes a nation happy, and keeps it so, END
BEGIN NOW What ruins kingdoms, and lays cities flat; END
BEGIN NOW These only, with our Law, best form a king. END
BEGIN NOW So spake the Son of God; but Satan, now END
BEGIN NOW Quite at a loss (for all his darts were spent), END
BEGIN NOW Thus to our Saviour, with stern brow, replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Since neither wealth nor honour, arms nor arts, END
BEGIN NOW Kingdom nor empire, pleases thee, nor aught END
BEGIN NOW By me proposed in life contemplative END
BEGIN NOW Or active, tended on by glory or fame, END
BEGIN NOW What dost thou in this world? The Wilderness END
BEGIN NOW For thee is fittest place: I found thee there, END
BEGIN NOW And thither will return thee. Yet remember END
BEGIN NOW What I foretell thee; soon thou shalt have cause END
BEGIN NOW To wish thou never hadst rejected, thus END
BEGIN NOW Nicely or cautiously, my offered aid, END
BEGIN NOW Which would have set thee in short time with ease END
BEGIN NOW On David's throne, or throne of all the world, END
BEGIN NOW Now at full age, fulness of time, thy season, END
BEGIN NOW When prophecies of thee are best fulfilled. END
BEGIN NOW Now, contrary--if I read aught in heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Or heaven write aught of fate--by what the stars END
BEGIN NOW Voluminous, or single characters END
BEGIN NOW In their conjunction met, give me to spell, END
BEGIN NOW Sorrows and labours, opposition, hate, END
BEGIN NOW Attends thee; scorns, reproaches, injuries, END
BEGIN NOW Violence and stripes, and, lastly, cruel death. END
BEGIN NOW A kingdom they portend thee, but what kingdom, END
BEGIN NOW Real or allegoric, I discern not; END
BEGIN NOW Nor when: eternal sure--as without end, END
BEGIN NOW Without beginning; for no date prefixed END
BEGIN NOW Directs me in the starry rubric set. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, he took (for still he knew his power END
BEGIN NOW Not yet expired), and to the Wilderness END
BEGIN NOW Brought back, the Son of God, and left him there, END
BEGIN NOW Feigning to disappear. Darkness now rose, END
BEGIN NOW As daylight sunk, and brought in louring Night, END
BEGIN NOW Her shadowy offspring, unsubstantial both, END
BEGIN NOW Privation mere of light and absent day. END
BEGIN NOW Our Saviour, meek, and with untroubled mind END
BEGIN NOW After hisaerie jaunt, though hurried sore, END
BEGIN NOW Hungry and cold, betook him to his rest, END
BEGIN NOW Wherever, under some concourse of shades, END
BEGIN NOW Whose branching arms thick intertwined might shield END
BEGIN NOW From dews and damps of night his sheltered head; END
BEGIN NOW But, sheltered, slept in vain; for at his head END
BEGIN NOW The Tempter watched, and soon with ugly dreams END
BEGIN NOW Disturbed his sleep. And either tropic now END
BEGIN NOW 'Gan thunder, and both ends of heaven; the clouds END
BEGIN NOW From many a horrid rift abortive poured END
BEGIN NOW Fierce rain with lightning mixed, water with fire, END
BEGIN NOW In ruin reconciled; nor slept the winds END
BEGIN NOW Within their stony caves, but rushed abroad END
BEGIN NOW From the four hinges of the world, and fell END
BEGIN NOW On the vexed wilderness, whose tallest pines, END
BEGIN NOW Though rooted deep as high, and sturdiest oaks, END
BEGIN NOW Bowed their stiff necks, loaden with stormy blasts, END
BEGIN NOW Or torn up sheer. Ill wast thou shrouded then, END
BEGIN NOW O patient Son of God, yet only stood'st END
BEGIN NOW Unshaken! Nor yet staid the terror there: END
BEGIN NOW Infernal ghosts and hellish furies round END
BEGIN NOW Environed thee; some howled, some yelled, some shrieked, END
BEGIN NOW Some bent at thee their fiery darts, while thou END
BEGIN NOW Sat'st unappalled in calm and sinless peace. END
BEGIN NOW Thus passed the night so foul, till Morning fair END
BEGIN NOW Came forth with pilgrim steps, in amice grey, END
BEGIN NOW Who with her radiant finger stilled the roar END
BEGIN NOW Of thunder, chased the clouds, and laid the winds, END
BEGIN NOW And griesly spectres, which the Fiend had raised END
BEGIN NOW To tempt the Son of God with terrors dire. END
BEGIN NOW And now the sun with more effectual beams END
BEGIN NOW Had cheered the face of earth, and dried the wet END
BEGIN NOW From drooping plant, or dropping tree; the birds, END
BEGIN NOW Who all things now behold more fresh and green, END
BEGIN NOW After a night of storm so ruinous, END
BEGIN NOW Cleared up their choicest notes in bush and spray, END
BEGIN NOW To gratulate the sweet return of morn. END
BEGIN NOW Nor yet, amidst this joy and brightest morn, END
BEGIN NOW Was absent, after all his mischief done, END
BEGIN NOW The Prince of Darkness; glad would also seem END
BEGIN NOW Of this fair change, and to our Saviour came; END
BEGIN NOW Yet with no new device (they all were spent), END
BEGIN NOW Rather by this his last affront resolved, END
BEGIN NOW Desperate of better course, to vent his rage END
BEGIN NOW And mad despite to be so oft repelled. END
BEGIN NOW Him walking on a sunny hill he found, END
BEGIN NOW Backed on the north and west by a thick wood; END
BEGIN NOW Out of the wood he starts in wonted shape, END
BEGIN NOW And in a careless mood thus to him said:-- END
BEGIN NOW Fair morning yet betides thee, Son of God, END
BEGIN NOW After a dismal night. I heard the wrack, END
BEGIN NOW As earth and sky would mingle; but myself END
BEGIN NOW Was distant; and these flaws, though mortals fear them, END
BEGIN NOW As dangerous to the pillared frame of Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Or to the Earth's dark basis underneath, END
BEGIN NOW Are to the main as inconsiderable END
BEGIN NOW And harmless, if not wholesome, as a sneeze END
BEGIN NOW To man's less universe, and soon are gone. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, as being ofttimes noxious where they light END
BEGIN NOW On man, beast, plant, wasteful and turbulent, END
BEGIN NOW Like turbulencies in the affairs of men, END
BEGIN NOW Over whose heads they roar, and seem to point, END
BEGIN NOW They oft fore-signify and threaten ill. END
BEGIN NOW This tempest at this desert most was bent; END
BEGIN NOW Of men at thee, for only thou here dwell'st. END
BEGIN NOW Did I not tell thee, if thou didst reject END
BEGIN NOW The perfect season offered with my aid END
BEGIN NOW To win thy destined seat, but wilt prolong END
BEGIN NOW All to the push of fate, pursue thy way END
BEGIN NOW Of gaining David's throne no man knows when END
BEGIN NOW (For both the when and how is nowhere told), END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt be what thou art ordained, no doubt; END
BEGIN NOW For Angels have proclaimed it, but concealing END
BEGIN NOW The time and means? Each act is rightliest done END
BEGIN NOW Not when it must, but when it may be best. END
BEGIN NOW If thou observe not this, be sure to find END
BEGIN NOW What I foretold thee--many a hard assay END
BEGIN NOW Of dangers, and adversities, and pains, END
BEGIN NOW Ere thou of Israel's sceptre get fast hold; END
BEGIN NOW Whereof this ominous night that closed thee round, END
BEGIN NOW So many terrors, voices, prodigies, END
BEGIN NOW May warn thee, as a sure foregoing sign. END
BEGIN NOW So talked he, while the Son of God went on, END
BEGIN NOW And staid not, but in brief him answered thus:-- END
BEGIN NOW Me worse than wet thou find'st not; other harm END
BEGIN NOW Those terrors which thou speak'st of did me none. END
BEGIN NOW I never feared they could, though noising loud END
BEGIN NOW And threatening nigh: what they can do as signs END
BEGIN NOW Betokening or ill-boding I contemn END
BEGIN NOW As false portents, not sent from God, but thee; END
BEGIN NOW Who, knowing I shall reign past thy preventing, END
BEGIN NOW Obtrud'st thy offered aid, that I, accepting, END
BEGIN NOW At least might seem to hold all power of thee, END
BEGIN NOW Ambitious Spirit! and would'st be thought my God; END
BEGIN NOW And storm'st, refused, thinking to terrify END
BEGIN NOW Me to thy will! Desist (thou art discerned, END
BEGIN NOW And toil'st in vain), nor me in vain molest. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Fiend, now swoln with rage, replied:-- END
BEGIN NOW Then hear, O Son of David, virgin-born! END
BEGIN NOW For Son of God to me is yet in doubt. END
BEGIN NOW Of the Messiah I have heard foretold END
BEGIN NOW By all the Prophets; of thy birth, at length END
BEGIN NOW Announced by Gabriel, with the first I knew, END
BEGIN NOW And of the angelic song in Bethlehem field, END
BEGIN NOW On thy birth-night, that sung thee Saviour born. END
BEGIN NOW From that time seldom have I ceased to eye END
BEGIN NOW Thy infancy, thy childhood, and thy youth, END
BEGIN NOW Thy manhood last, though yet in private bred; END
BEGIN NOW Till, at the ford of Jordan, whither all END
BEGIN NOW Flocked to the Baptist, I among the rest END
BEGIN NOW (Though not to be baptized), by voice from Heaven END
BEGIN NOW Heard thee pronounced the Son of God beloved. END
BEGIN NOW Thenceforth I thought thee worth my nearer view END
BEGIN NOW And narrower scrutiny, that I might learn END
BEGIN NOW In what degree or meaning thou art called END
BEGIN NOW The Son of God, which bears no single sense. END
BEGIN NOW The Son of God I also am, or was; END
BEGIN NOW And, if I was, I am; relation stands: END
BEGIN NOW All men are Sons of God; yet thee I thought END
BEGIN NOW In some respect far higher so declared. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore I watched thy footsteps from that hour, END
BEGIN NOW And followed thee still on to this waste wild, END
BEGIN NOW Where, by all best conjectures, I collect END
BEGIN NOW Thou art to be my fatal enemy. END
BEGIN NOW Good reason, then, if I beforehand seek END
BEGIN NOW To understand my adversary, who END
BEGIN NOW And what he is; his wisdom, power, intent; END
BEGIN NOW By parle or composition, truce or league, END
BEGIN NOW To win him, or win from him what I can. END
BEGIN NOW And opportunity I here have had END
BEGIN NOW To try thee, sift thee, and confess have found thee END
BEGIN NOW Proof against all temptation, as a rock END
BEGIN NOW Of adamant and as a centre, firm END
BEGIN NOW To the utmost of mere man both wise and good, END
BEGIN NOW Not more; for honours, riches, kingdoms, glory, END
BEGIN NOW Have been before contemned, and may again. END
BEGIN NOW Therefore, to know what more thou art than man, END
BEGIN NOW Worth naming the Son of God by voice from Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW Another method I must now begin. END
BEGIN NOW So saying, he caught him up, and, without wing END
BEGIN NOW Of hippogrif, bore through the air sublime, END
BEGIN NOW Over the wilderness and o'er the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Till underneath them fair Jerusalem, END
BEGIN NOW The Holy City, lifted high her towers, END
BEGIN NOW And higher yet the glorious Temple reared END
BEGIN NOW Her pile, far off appearing like a mount END
BEGIN NOW Of alablaster, topt with golden spires: END
BEGIN NOW There, on the highest pinnacle, he set END
BEGIN NOW The Son of God, and added thus in scorn:-- END
BEGIN NOW There stand, if thou wilt stand; to stand upright END
BEGIN NOW Will ask thee skill. I to thy Father's house END
BEGIN NOW Have brought thee, and highest placed: highest is best. END
BEGIN NOW Now shew thy progeny; if not to stand, END
BEGIN NOW Cast thyself down. Safely, if Son of God; END
BEGIN NOW For it is written, 'He will give command END
BEGIN NOW Concerning thee to his Angels; in their hands END
BEGIN NOW They shall uplift thee, lest at any time END
BEGIN NOW Thou chance to dash thy foot against a stone.' END
BEGIN NOW To whom thus Jesus: "Also it is written, END
BEGIN NOW 'Tempt not the Lord thy God.'" He said, and stood; END
BEGIN NOW But Satan, smitten with amazement, fell. END
BEGIN NOW As when Earth's son, Antaeus (to compare END
BEGIN NOW Small things with greatest), in Irassa strove END
BEGIN NOW With Jove's Alcides, and, oft foiled, still rose, END
BEGIN NOW Receiving from his mother Earth new strength, END
BEGIN NOW Fresh from his fall, and fiercer grapple joined, END
BEGIN NOW Throttled at length in the air expired and fell, END
BEGIN NOW So, after many a foil, the Tempter proud, END
BEGIN NOW Renewing fresh assaults, amidst his pride END
BEGIN NOW Fell whence he stood to see his victor fall; END
BEGIN NOW And, as that Theban monster that proposed END
BEGIN NOW Her riddle, and him who solved it not devoured, END
BEGIN NOW That once found out and solved, for grief and spite END
BEGIN NOW Cast herself headlong from the Ismenian steep, END
BEGIN NOW So, strook with dread and anguish, fell the Fiend, END
BEGIN NOW And to his crew, that sat consulting, brought END
BEGIN NOW Joyless triumphals of his hoped success, END
BEGIN NOW Ruin, and desperation, and dismay, END
BEGIN NOW Who durst so proudly tempt the Son of God. END
BEGIN NOW So Satan fell; and straight a fiery globe END
BEGIN NOW Of Angels on full sail of wing flew nigh, END
BEGIN NOW Who on their plumy vans received Him soft END
BEGIN NOW From his uneasy station, and upbore, END
BEGIN NOW As on a floating couch, through the blithe air; END
BEGIN NOW Then, in a flowery valley, set him down END
BEGIN NOW On a green bank, and set before him spread END
BEGIN NOW A table of celestial food, divine END
BEGIN NOW Ambrosial fruits fetched from the Tree of Life, END
BEGIN NOW And from the Fount of Life ambrosial drink, END
BEGIN NOW That soon refreshed him wearied, and repaired END
BEGIN NOW What hunger, if aught hunger, had impaired, END
BEGIN NOW Or thirst; and, as he fed, Angelic quires END
BEGIN NOW Sung heavenly anthems of his victory END
BEGIN NOW Over temptation and the Tempter proud:-- END
BEGIN NOW True Image of the Father, whether throned END
BEGIN NOW In the bosom of bliss, and light of light END
BEGIN NOW Conceiving, or, remote from Heaven, enshrined END
BEGIN NOW In fleshly tabernacle and human form, END
BEGIN NOW Wandering the wilderness--whatever place, END
BEGIN NOW Habit, or state, or motion, still expressing END
BEGIN NOW The Son of God, with Godlike force endued END
BEGIN NOW Against the attempter of thy Father's throne END
BEGIN NOW And thief of Paradise! Him long of old END
BEGIN NOW Thou didst debel, and down from Heaven cast END
BEGIN NOW With all his army; now thou hast avenged END
BEGIN NOW Supplanted Adam, and, by vanquishing END
BEGIN NOW Temptation, hast regained lost Paradise, END
BEGIN NOW And frustrated the conquest fraudulent. END
BEGIN NOW He never more henceforth will dare set foot END
BEGIN NOW In paradise to tempt; his snares are broke. END
BEGIN NOW For, though that seat of earthly bliss be failed, END
BEGIN NOW A fairer Paradise is founded now END
BEGIN NOW For Adam and his chosen sons, whom thou, END
BEGIN NOW A Saviour, art come down to reinstall; END
BEGIN NOW Where they shall dwell secure, when time shall be, END
BEGIN NOW Of tempter and temptation without fear. END
BEGIN NOW But thou, Infernal Serpent! shalt not long END
BEGIN NOW Rule in the clouds. Like an autumnal star, END
BEGIN NOW Or lightning, thou shalt fall from Heaven, trod down END
BEGIN NOW Under his feet. For proof, ere this thou feel'st END
BEGIN NOW Thy wound (yet not thy last and deadliest wound) END
BEGIN NOW By this repulse received, and hold'st in Hell END
BEGIN NOW No triumph; in all her gates Abaddon rues END
BEGIN NOW Thy bold attempt. Hereafter learn with awe END
BEGIN NOW To dread the Son of God. He, all unarmed, END
BEGIN NOW Shall chase thee, with the terror of his voice, END
BEGIN NOW From thy demoniac holds, possession foul-- END
BEGIN NOW Thee and thy legions; yelling they shall fly, END
BEGIN NOW And beg to hide them in a herd of swine, END
BEGIN NOW Lest he command them down into the Deep, END
BEGIN NOW Bound, and to torment sent before their time. END
BEGIN NOW Hail, Son of the Most High, heir of both Worlds, END
BEGIN NOW Queller of Satan! On thy glorious work END
BEGIN NOW Now enter, and begin to save Mankind. END
BEGIN NOW Thus they the Son of God, our Saviour meek, END
BEGIN NOW Sung victor, and, from heavenly feast refreshed, END
BEGIN NOW Brought on his way with joy. He, unobserved, END
BEGIN NOW Home to his mother's house private returned. END
BEGIN NOW All I could see from where I stood END
BEGIN NOW The room is full of you!--As I came in END
BEGIN NOW Curse thee, Life, I will live with thee no more! END
BEGIN NOW God's World END
BEGIN NOW O world, I cannot hold thee close enough! END
BEGIN NOW I will be the gladdest thing END
BEGIN NOW Sorrow like a ceaseless rain END
BEGIN NOW I'll keep a little tavern END
BEGIN NOW Love has gone and left me and the days are all alike; END
BEGIN NOW I knew her for a little ghost END
BEGIN NOW The first rose on my rose-tree END
BEGIN NOW Let the little birds sing; END
BEGIN NOW All the dog-wood blossoms are underneath the tree! END
BEGIN NOW Death, I say, my heart is bowed END
BEGIN NOW Love, if I weep it will not matter, END
BEGIN NOW I said,--for Love was laggard, O, Love was slow to come,-- END
BEGIN NOW She is neither pink nor pale, END
BEGIN NOW Hard seeds of hate I planted END
BEGIN NOW I cannot but remember END
BEGIN NOW Thou art not lovelier than lilacs,--no, END
BEGIN NOW Time does not bring relief; you all have lied END
BEGIN NOW Mindful of you the sodden earth in spring, END
BEGIN NOW Not in this chamber only at my birth-- END
BEGIN NOW If I should learn, in some quite casual way, END
BEGIN NOW This door you might not open, and you did; END
BEGIN NOW All I could see from where I stood END
BEGIN NOW Was three long mountains and a wood; END
BEGIN NOW I turned and looked another way, END
BEGIN NOW And saw three islands in a bay. END
BEGIN NOW So with my eyes I traced the line END
BEGIN NOW Of the horizon, thin and fine, END
BEGIN NOW Straight around till I was come END
BEGIN NOW Back to where I'd started from; END
BEGIN NOW And all I saw from where I stood END
BEGIN NOW Was three long mountains and a wood. END
BEGIN NOW Over these things I could not see; END
BEGIN NOW These were the things that bounded me; END
BEGIN NOW And I could touch them with my hand, END
BEGIN NOW Almost, I thought, from where I stand. END
BEGIN NOW And all at once things seemed so small END
BEGIN NOW My breath came short, and scarce at all. END
BEGIN NOW But, sure, the sky is big, I said; END
BEGIN NOW Miles and miles above my head; END
BEGIN NOW So here upon my back I'll lie END
BEGIN NOW And look my fill into the sky. END
BEGIN NOW And so I looked, and, after all, END
BEGIN NOW The sky was not so very tall. END
BEGIN NOW The sky, I said, must somewhere stop, END
BEGIN NOW And--sure enough!--I see the top! END
BEGIN NOW The sky, I thought, is not so grand; END
BEGIN NOW I 'most could touch it with my hand! END
BEGIN NOW And reaching up my hand to try, END
BEGIN NOW I screamed to feel it touch the sky. END
BEGIN NOW I screamed, and--lo!--Infinity END
BEGIN NOW Came down and settled over me; END
BEGIN NOW Forced back my scream into my chest, END
BEGIN NOW Bent back my arm upon my breast, END
BEGIN NOW And, pressing of the Undefined END
BEGIN NOW The definition on my mind, END
BEGIN NOW Held up before my eyes a glass END
BEGIN NOW Through which my shrinking sight did pass END
BEGIN NOW Until it seemed I must behold END
BEGIN NOW Immensity made manifold; END
BEGIN NOW Whispered to me a word whose sound END
BEGIN NOW Deafened the air for worlds around, END
BEGIN NOW And brought unmuffled to my ears END
BEGIN NOW The gossiping of friendly spheres, END
BEGIN NOW The creaking of the tented sky, END
BEGIN NOW The ticking of Eternity. END
BEGIN NOW I saw and heard, and knew at last END
BEGIN NOW The How and Why of all things, past, END
BEGIN NOW And present, and forevermore. END
BEGIN NOW The Universe, cleft to the core, END
BEGIN NOW Lay open to my probing sense END
BEGIN NOW That, sick'ning, I would fain pluck thence END
BEGIN NOW But could not,--nay! But needs must suck END
BEGIN NOW At the great wound, and could not pluck END
BEGIN NOW My lips away till I had drawn END
BEGIN NOW All venom out.--Ah, fearful pawn! END
BEGIN NOW For my omniscience paid I toll END
BEGIN NOW In infinite remorse of soul. END
BEGIN NOW All sin was of my sinning, all END
BEGIN NOW Atoning mine, and mine the gall END
BEGIN NOW Of all regret. Mine was the weight END
BEGIN NOW Of every brooded wrong, the hate END
BEGIN NOW That stood behind each envious thrust, END
BEGIN NOW Mine every greed, mine every lust. END
BEGIN NOW And all the while for every grief, END
BEGIN NOW Each suffering, I craved relief END
BEGIN NOW With individual desire,-- END
BEGIN NOW Craved all in vain! And felt fierce fire END
BEGIN NOW About a thousand people crawl; END
BEGIN NOW Perished with each,--then mourned for all! END
BEGIN NOW A man was starving in Capri; END
BEGIN NOW He moved his eyes and looked at me; END
BEGIN NOW I felt his gaze, I heard his moan, END
BEGIN NOW And knew his hunger as my own. END
BEGIN NOW I saw at sea a great fog bank END
BEGIN NOW Between two ships that struck and sank; END
BEGIN NOW A thousand screams the heavens smote; END
BEGIN NOW And every scream tore through my throat. END
BEGIN NOW No hurt I did not feel, no death END
BEGIN NOW That was not mine; mine each last breath END
BEGIN NOW That, crying, met an answering cry END
BEGIN NOW From the compassion that was I. END
BEGIN NOW All suffering mine, and mine its rod; END
BEGIN NOW Mine, pity like the pity of God. END
BEGIN NOW Ah, awful weight! Infinity END
BEGIN NOW Pressed down upon the finite Me! END
BEGIN NOW My anguished spirit, like a bird, END
BEGIN NOW Beating against my lips I heard; END
BEGIN NOW Yet lay the weight so close about END
BEGIN NOW There was no room for it without. END
BEGIN NOW And so beneath the weight lay I END
BEGIN NOW And suffered death, but could not die. END
BEGIN NOW Long had I lain thus, craving death, END
BEGIN NOW When quietly the earth beneath END
BEGIN NOW Gave way, and inch by inch, so great END
BEGIN NOW At last had grown the crushing weight, END
BEGIN NOW Into the earth I sank till I END
BEGIN NOW Full six feet under ground did lie, END
BEGIN NOW And sank no more,--there is no weight END
BEGIN NOW Can follow here, however great. END
BEGIN NOW From off my breast I felt it roll, END
BEGIN NOW And as it went my tortured soul END
BEGIN NOW Burst forth and fled in such a gust END
BEGIN NOW That all about me swirled the dust. END
BEGIN NOW Deep in the earth I rested now; END
BEGIN NOW Cool is its hand upon the brow END
BEGIN NOW And soft its breast beneath the head END
BEGIN NOW Of one who is so gladly dead. END
BEGIN NOW And all at once, and over all END
BEGIN NOW The pitying rain began to fall; END
BEGIN NOW I lay and heard each pattering hoof END
BEGIN NOW Upon my lowly, thatched roof, END
BEGIN NOW And seemed to love the sound far more END
BEGIN NOW Than ever I had done before. END
BEGIN NOW For rain it hath a friendly sound END
BEGIN NOW To one who's six feet underground; END
BEGIN NOW And scarce the friendly voice or face: END
BEGIN NOW A grave is such a quiet place. END
BEGIN NOW The rain, I said, is kind to come END
BEGIN NOW And speak to me in my new home. END
BEGIN NOW I would I were alive again END
BEGIN NOW To kiss the fingers of the rain, END
BEGIN NOW To drink into my eyes the shine END
BEGIN NOW Of every slanting silver line, END
BEGIN NOW To catch the freshened, fragrant breeze END
BEGIN NOW From drenched and dripping apple-trees. END
BEGIN NOW For soon the shower will be done, END
BEGIN NOW And then the broad face of the sun END
BEGIN NOW Will laugh above the rain-soaked earth END
BEGIN NOW Until the world with answering mirth END
BEGIN NOW Shakes joyously, and each round drop END
BEGIN NOW Rolls, twinkling, from its grass-blade top. END
BEGIN NOW How can I bear it; buried here, END
BEGIN NOW While overhead the sky grows clear END
BEGIN NOW And blue again after the storm? END
BEGIN NOW O, multi-colored, multiform, END
BEGIN NOW Beloved beauty over me, END
BEGIN NOW That I shall never, never see END
BEGIN NOW Again! Spring-silver, autumn-gold, END
BEGIN NOW That I shall never more behold! END
BEGIN NOW Sleeping your myriad magics through, END
BEGIN NOW Close-sepulchred away from you! END
BEGIN NOW O God, I cried, give me new birth, END
BEGIN NOW And put me back upon the earth! END
BEGIN NOW Upset each cloud's gigantic gourd END
BEGIN NOW And let the heavy rain, down-poured END
BEGIN NOW In one big torrent, set me free, END
BEGIN NOW Washing my grave away from me! END
BEGIN NOW I ceased; and through the breathless hush END
BEGIN NOW That answered me, the far-off rush END
BEGIN NOW Of herald wings came whispering END
BEGIN NOW Like music down the vibrant string END
BEGIN NOW Of my ascending prayer, and--crash! END
BEGIN NOW Before the wild wind's whistling lash END
BEGIN NOW The startled storm-clouds reared on high END
BEGIN NOW And plunged in terror down the sky, END
BEGIN NOW And the big rain in one black wave END
BEGIN NOW Fell from the sky and struck my grave. END
BEGIN NOW I know not how such things can be; END
BEGIN NOW I only know there came to me END
BEGIN NOW A fragrance such as never clings END
BEGIN NOW To aught save happy living things; END
BEGIN NOW A sound as of some joyous elf END
BEGIN NOW Singing sweet songs to please himself, END
BEGIN NOW And, through and over everything, END
BEGIN NOW A sense of glad awakening. END
BEGIN NOW The grass, a-tiptoe at my ear, END
BEGIN NOW Whispering to me I could hear; END
BEGIN NOW I felt the rain's cool finger-tips END
BEGIN NOW Brushed tenderly across my lips, END
BEGIN NOW Laid gently on my sealed sight, END
BEGIN NOW And all at once the heavy night END
BEGIN NOW Fell from my eyes and I could see,-- END
BEGIN NOW A drenched and dripping apple-tree, END
BEGIN NOW A last long line of silver rain, END
BEGIN NOW A sky grown clear and blue again. END
BEGIN NOW And as I looked a quickening gust END
BEGIN NOW Of wind blew up to me and thrust END
BEGIN NOW Into my face a miracle END
BEGIN NOW Of orchard-breath, and with the smell,-- END
BEGIN NOW I know not how such things can be!-- END
BEGIN NOW I breathed my soul back into me. END
BEGIN NOW Ah! Up then from the ground sprang I END
BEGIN NOW And hailed the earth with such a cry END
BEGIN NOW As is not heard save from a man END
BEGIN NOW Who has been dead, and lives again. END
BEGIN NOW About the trees my arms I wound; END
BEGIN NOW Like one gone mad I hugged the ground; END
BEGIN NOW I raised my quivering arms on high; END
BEGIN NOW I laughed and laughed into the sky, END
BEGIN NOW Till at my throat a strangling sob END
BEGIN NOW Caught fiercely, and a great heart-throb END
BEGIN NOW Sent instant tears into my eyes; END
BEGIN NOW O God, I cried, no dark disguise END
BEGIN NOW Can e'er hereafter hide from me END
BEGIN NOW Thy radiant identity! END
BEGIN NOW Thou canst not move across the grass END
BEGIN NOW But my quick eyes will see Thee pass, END
BEGIN NOW Nor speak, however silently, END
BEGIN NOW But my hushed voice will answer Thee. END
BEGIN NOW I know the path that tells Thy way END
BEGIN NOW Through the cool eve of every day; END
BEGIN NOW God, I can push the grass apart END
BEGIN NOW And lay my finger on Thy heart! END
BEGIN NOW The world stands out on either side END
BEGIN NOW No wider than the heart is wide; END
BEGIN NOW Above the world is stretched the sky,-- END
BEGIN NOW No higher than the soul is high. END
BEGIN NOW The heart can push the sea and land END
BEGIN NOW Farther away on either hand; END
BEGIN NOW The soul can split the sky in two, END
BEGIN NOW And let the face of God shine through. END
BEGIN NOW But East and West will pinch the heart END
BEGIN NOW That can not keep them pushed apart; END
BEGIN NOW And he whose soul is flat--the sky END
BEGIN NOW Will cave in on him by and by. END
BEGIN NOW The room is full of you!--As I came in END
BEGIN NOW And closed the door behind me, all at once END
BEGIN NOW A something in the air, intangible, END
BEGIN NOW Yet stiff with meaning, struck my senses sick!-- END
BEGIN NOW Sharp, unfamiliar odors have destroyed END
BEGIN NOW Each other room's dear personality. END
BEGIN NOW The heavy scent of damp, funereal flowers,-- END
BEGIN NOW The very essence, hush-distilled, of Death-- END
BEGIN NOW Has strangled that habitual breath of home END
BEGIN NOW Whose expiration leaves all houses dead; END
BEGIN NOW And wheresoe'er I look is hideous change. END
BEGIN NOW Save here. Here 'twas as if a weed-choked gate END
BEGIN NOW Had opened at my touch, and I had stepped END
BEGIN NOW Into some long-forgot, enchanted, strange, END
BEGIN NOW Sweet garden of a thousand years ago END
BEGIN NOW And suddenly thought, "I have been here before! END
BEGIN NOW You are not here. I know that you are gone, END
BEGIN NOW And will not ever enter here again. END
BEGIN NOW And yet it seems to me, if I should speak, END
BEGIN NOW Your silent step must wake across the hall; END
BEGIN NOW If I should turn my head, that your sweet eyes END
BEGIN NOW Would kiss me from the door.--So short a time END
BEGIN NOW To teach my life its transposition to END
BEGIN NOW This difficult and unaccustomed key!-- END
BEGIN NOW The room is as you left it; your last touch-- END
BEGIN NOW A thoughtless pressure, knowing not itself END
BEGIN NOW As saintly--hallows now each simple thing; END
BEGIN NOW Hallows and glorifies, and glows between END
BEGIN NOW The dust's grey fingers like a shielded light. END
BEGIN NOW There is your book, just as you laid it down, END
BEGIN NOW Face to the table,--I cannot believe END
BEGIN NOW That you are gone!--Just then it seemed to me END
BEGIN NOW You must be here. I almost laughed to think END
BEGIN NOW How like reality the dream had been; END
BEGIN NOW Yet knew before I laughed, and so was still. END
BEGIN NOW That book, outspread, just as you laid it down! END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps you thought, "I wonder what comes next, END
BEGIN NOW And whether this or this will be the end"; END
BEGIN NOW So rose, and left it, thinking to return. END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps that chair, when you arose and passed END
BEGIN NOW Out of the room, rocked silently a while END
BEGIN NOW Ere it again was still. When you were gone END
BEGIN NOW Forever from the room, perhaps that chair, END
BEGIN NOW Stirred by your movement, rocked a little while, END
BEGIN NOW Silently, to and fro. . . END
BEGIN NOW And here are the last words your fingers wrote, END
BEGIN NOW Scrawled in broad characters across a page END
BEGIN NOW In this brown book I gave you. Here your hand, END
BEGIN NOW Guiding your rapid pen, moved up and down. END
BEGIN NOW Here with a looping knot you crossed a t", END
BEGIN NOW And here another like it, just beyond END
BEGIN NOW These two eccentric "e's". You were so small, END
BEGIN NOW And wrote so brave a hand! END
BEGIN NOW How strange it seems END
BEGIN NOW That of all words these are the words you chose! END
BEGIN NOW And yet a simple choice; you did not know END
BEGIN NOW You would not write again. If you had known-- END
BEGIN NOW But then, it does not matter,--and indeed END
BEGIN NOW If you had known there was so little time END
BEGIN NOW You would have dropped your pen and come to me END
BEGIN NOW And this page would be empty, and some phrase END
BEGIN NOW Other than this would hold my wonder now. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, since you could not know, and it befell END
BEGIN NOW That these are the last words your fingers wrote, END
BEGIN NOW There is a dignity some might not see END
BEGIN NOW In this, "I picked the first sweet-pea to-day. END
BEGIN NOW To-day! Was there an opening bud beside it END
BEGIN NOW You left until to-morrow?--O my love, END
BEGIN NOW The things that withered,--and you came not back! END
BEGIN NOW That day you filled this circle of my arms END
BEGIN NOW That now is empty. (O my empty life!) END
BEGIN NOW That day--that day you picked the first sweet-pea,-- END
BEGIN NOW And brought it in to show me! I recall END
BEGIN NOW With terrible distinctness how the smell END
BEGIN NOW Of your cool gardens drifted in with you. END
BEGIN NOW I know, you held it up for me to see END
BEGIN NOW And flushed because I looked not at the flower, END
BEGIN NOW But at your face; and when behind my look END
BEGIN NOW You saw such unmistakable intent END
BEGIN NOW You laughed and brushed your flower against my lips. END
BEGIN NOW (You were the fairest thing God ever made, END
BEGIN NOW I think.) And then your hands above my heart END
BEGIN NOW Drew down its stem into a fastening, END
BEGIN NOW And while your head was bent I kissed your hair. END
BEGIN NOW I wonder if you knew. (Beloved hands! END
BEGIN NOW Somehow I cannot seem to see them still. END
BEGIN NOW Somehow I cannot seem to see the dust END
BEGIN NOW In your bright hair.) What is the need of Heaven END
BEGIN NOW When earth can be so sweet?--If only God END
BEGIN NOW Had let us love,--and show the world the way! END
BEGIN NOW Strange cancellings must ink th' eternal books END
BEGIN NOW When love-crossed-out will bring the answer right! END
BEGIN NOW That first sweet-pea! I wonder where it is. END
BEGIN NOW It seems to me I laid it down somewhere, END
BEGIN NOW And yet,--I am not sure. I am not sure, END
BEGIN NOW Even, if it was white or pink; for then END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas much like any other flower to me, END
BEGIN NOW Save that it was the first. I did not know, END
BEGIN NOW Then, that it was the last. If I had known-- END
BEGIN NOW But then, it does not matter. Strange how few, END
BEGIN NOW After all's said and done, the things that are END
BEGIN NOW Of moment. END
BEGIN NOW Few indeed! When I can make END
BEGIN NOW Of ten small words a rope to hang the world! END
BEGIN NOW I had you and I have you now no more. END
BEGIN NOW There, there it dangles,--where's the little truth END
BEGIN NOW That can for long keep footing under that END
BEGIN NOW When its slack syllables tighten to a thought? END
BEGIN NOW Here, let me write it down! I wish to see END
BEGIN NOW Just how a thing like that will look on paper! END
BEGIN NOW *I had you and I have you now no more*. END
BEGIN NOW O little words, how can you run so straight END
BEGIN NOW Across the page, beneath the weight you bear? END
BEGIN NOW How can you fall apart, whom such a theme END
BEGIN NOW Has bound together, and hereafter aid END
BEGIN NOW In trivial expression, that have been END
BEGIN NOW So hideously dignified?--Would God END
BEGIN NOW That tearing you apart would tear the thread END
BEGIN NOW I strung you on! Would God--O God, my mind END
BEGIN NOW Stretches asunder on this merciless rack END
BEGIN NOW Of imagery! O, let me sleep a while! END
BEGIN NOW Would I could sleep, and wake to find me back END
BEGIN NOW In that sweet summer afternoon with you. END
BEGIN NOW Summer? 'Tis summer still by the calendar! END
BEGIN NOW How easily could God, if He so willed, END
BEGIN NOW Set back the world a little turn or two! END
BEGIN NOW Correct its griefs, and bring its joys again! END
BEGIN NOW We were so wholly one I had not thought END
BEGIN NOW That we could die apart. I had not thought END
BEGIN NOW That I could move,--and you be stiff and still! END
BEGIN NOW I think our heart-strings were, like warp and woof END
BEGIN NOW In some firm fabric, woven in and out; END
BEGIN NOW Your golden filaments in fair design END
BEGIN NOW Across my duller fibre. And to-day END
BEGIN NOW The shining strip is rent; the exquisite END
BEGIN NOW Fine pattern is destroyed; part of your heart END
BEGIN NOW Aches in my breast; part of my heart lies chilled END
BEGIN NOW In the damp earth with you. I have been torn END
BEGIN NOW In two, and suffer for the rest of me. END
BEGIN NOW What is my life to me? And what am I END
BEGIN NOW To life,--a ship whose star has guttered out? END
BEGIN NOW A Fear that in the deep night starts awake END
BEGIN NOW Perpetually, to find its senses strained END
BEGIN NOW Against the taut strings of the quivering air, END
BEGIN NOW Awaiting the return of some dread chord? END
BEGIN NOW Dark, Dark, is all I find for metaphor; END
BEGIN NOW All else were contrast,--save that contrast's wall END
BEGIN NOW Is down, and all opposed things flow together END
BEGIN NOW Into a vast monotony, where night END
BEGIN NOW And day, and frost and thaw, and death and life, END
BEGIN NOW Are synonyms. What now--what now to me END
BEGIN NOW Are all the jabbering birds and foolish flowers END
BEGIN NOW That clutter up the world? You were my song! END
BEGIN NOW Now, let discord scream! You were my flower! END
BEGIN NOW Now let the world grow weeds! For I shall not END
BEGIN NOW Plant things above your grave--(the common balm END
BEGIN NOW Of the conventional woe for its own wound!) END
BEGIN NOW Amid sensations rendered negative END
BEGIN NOW By your elimination stands to-day, END
BEGIN NOW Certain, unmixed, the element of grief; END
BEGIN NOW I sorrow; and I shall not mock my truth END
BEGIN NOW With travesties of suffering, nor seek END
BEGIN NOW To effigy its incorporeal bulk END
BEGIN NOW In little wry-faced images of woe. END
BEGIN NOW I cannot call you back; and I desire END
BEGIN NOW No utterance of my immaterial voice. END
BEGIN NOW I cannot even turn my face this way END
BEGIN NOW Or that, and say, "My face is turned to you"; END
BEGIN NOW I know not where you are, I do not know END
BEGIN NOW If Heaven hold you or if earth transmute, END
BEGIN NOW Body and soul, you into earth again; END
BEGIN NOW But this I know:--not for one second's space END
BEGIN NOW Shall I insult my sight with visionings END
BEGIN NOW Such as the credulous crowd so eager-eyed END
BEGIN NOW Beholds, self-conjured, in the empty air. END
BEGIN NOW Let the world wail! Let drip its easy tears! END
BEGIN NOW --What do I say? END
BEGIN NOW God! God!--God pity me! Am I gone mad END
BEGIN NOW That I should spit upon a rosary? END
BEGIN NOW Am I become so shrunken? Would to God END
BEGIN NOW I too might feel that frenzied faith whose touch END
BEGIN NOW Makes temporal the most enduring grief; END
BEGIN NOW Though it must walk a while, as is its wont, END
BEGIN NOW With wild lamenting! Would I too might weep END
BEGIN NOW Where weeps the world and hangs its piteous wreaths END
BEGIN NOW For its new dead! Not Truth, but Faith, it is END
BEGIN NOW That keeps the world alive. If all at once END
BEGIN NOW Faith were to slacken,--that unconscious faith END
BEGIN NOW Which must, I know, yet be the corner-stone END
BEGIN NOW Of all believing,--birds now flying fearless END
BEGIN NOW Across would drop in terror to the earth; END
BEGIN NOW Fishes would drown; and the all-governing reins END
BEGIN NOW Would tangle in the frantic hands of God END
BEGIN NOW And the worlds gallop headlong to destruction! END
BEGIN NOW O God, I see it now, and my sick brain END
BEGIN NOW Staggers and swoons! How often over me END
BEGIN NOW Flashes this breathlessness of sudden sight END
BEGIN NOW In which I see the universe unrolled END
BEGIN NOW Before me like a scroll and read thereon END
BEGIN NOW Chaos and Doom, where helpless planets whirl END
BEGIN NOW Dizzily round and round and round and round, END
BEGIN NOW Like tops across a table, gathering speed END
BEGIN NOW With every spin, to waver on the edge END
BEGIN NOW One instant--looking over--and the next END
BEGIN NOW To shudder and lurch forward out of sight-- END
BEGIN NOW Ah, I am worn out--I am wearied out-- END
BEGIN NOW It is too much--I am but flesh and blood, END
BEGIN NOW And I must sleep. Though you were dead again, END
BEGIN NOW I am but flesh and blood and I must sleep. END
BEGIN NOW Curse thee, Life, I will live with thee no more! END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast mocked me, starved me, beat my body sore! END
BEGIN NOW And all for a pledge that was not pledged by me, END
BEGIN NOW I have kissed thy crust and eaten sparingly END
BEGIN NOW That I might eat again, and met thy sneers END
BEGIN NOW With deprecations, and thy blows with tears,-- END
BEGIN NOW Aye, from thy glutted lash, glad, crawled away, END
BEGIN NOW As if spent passion were a holiday! END
BEGIN NOW And now I go. Nor threat, nor easy vow END
BEGIN NOW With me, whence fear and faith alike are flown; END
BEGIN NOW Lonely I came, and I depart alone, END
BEGIN NOW And know not where nor unto whom I go; END
BEGIN NOW But that thou canst not follow me I know. END
BEGIN NOW Thus I to Life, and ceased; but through my brain END
BEGIN NOW My thought ran still, until I spake again: END
BEGIN NOW Ah, but I go not as I came,--no trace END
BEGIN NOW Is mine to bear away of that old grace END
BEGIN NOW I brought! I have been heated in thy fires, END
BEGIN NOW Bent by thy hands, fashioned to thy desires, END
BEGIN NOW Thy mark is on me! I am not the same END
BEGIN NOW Nor ever more shall be, as when I came. END
BEGIN NOW Ashes am I of all that once I seemed. END
BEGIN NOW In me all's sunk that leapt, and all that dreamed END
BEGIN NOW Is wakeful for alarm,--oh, shame to thee, END
BEGIN NOW For the ill change that thou hast wrought in me, END
BEGIN NOW Who laugh no more nor lift my throat to sing! END
BEGIN NOW Ah, Life, I would have been a pleasant thing END
BEGIN NOW To have about the house when I was grown END
BEGIN NOW If thou hadst left my little joys alone! END
BEGIN NOW I asked of thee no favor save this one: END
BEGIN NOW That thou wouldst leave me playing in the sun! END
BEGIN NOW And this thou didst deny, calling my name END
BEGIN NOW Insistently, until I rose and came. END
BEGIN NOW I saw the sun no more.--It were not well END
BEGIN NOW So long on these unpleasant thoughts to dwell, END
BEGIN NOW Need I arise to-morrow and renew END
BEGIN NOW Again my hated tasks, but I am through END
BEGIN NOW With all things save my thoughts and this one night, END
BEGIN NOW So that in truth I seem already quite END
BEGIN NOW Free and remote from thee,--I feel no haste END
BEGIN NOW And no reluctance to depart; I taste END
BEGIN NOW Merely, with thoughtful mien, an unknown draught, END
BEGIN NOW That in a little while I shall have quaffed. END
BEGIN NOW Thus I to Life, and ceased, and slightly smiled, END
BEGIN NOW Looking at nothing; and my thin dreams filed END
BEGIN NOW Before me one by one till once again END
BEGIN NOW I set new words unto an old refrain: END
BEGIN NOW Treasures thou hast that never have been mine! END
BEGIN NOW Warm lights in many a secret chamber shine END
BEGIN NOW Of thy gaunt house, and gusts of song have blown END
BEGIN NOW Like blossoms out to me that sat alone! END
BEGIN NOW And I have waited well for thee to show END
BEGIN NOW If any share were mine,--and now I go! END
BEGIN NOW Nothing I leave, and if I naught attain END
BEGIN NOW I shall but come into mine own again! END
BEGIN NOW Thus I to Life, and ceased, and spake no more, END
BEGIN NOW But turning, straightway, sought a certain door END
BEGIN NOW In the rear wall. Heavy it was, and low END
BEGIN NOW And dark,--a way by which none e'er would go END
BEGIN NOW That other exit had, and never knock END
BEGIN NOW Was heard thereat,--bearing a curious lock END
BEGIN NOW Some chance had shown me fashioned faultily, END
BEGIN NOW Whereof Life held content the useless key, END
BEGIN NOW And great coarse hinges, thick and rough with rust, END
BEGIN NOW Whose sudden voice across a silence must, END
BEGIN NOW I knew, be harsh and horrible to hear,-- END
BEGIN NOW A strange door, ugly like a dwarf.--So near END
BEGIN NOW I came I felt upon my feet the chill END
BEGIN NOW Of acid wind creeping across the sill. END
BEGIN NOW So stood longtime, till over me at last END
BEGIN NOW Came weariness, and all things other passed END
BEGIN NOW To make it room; the still night drifted deep END
BEGIN NOW Like snow about me, and I longed for sleep. END
BEGIN NOW But, suddenly, marking the morning hour, END
BEGIN NOW Bayed the deep-throated bell within the tower! END
BEGIN NOW Startled, I raised my head,--and with a shout END
BEGIN NOW Laid hold upon the latch,--and was without. END
BEGIN NOW Ah, long-forgotten, well-remembered road, END
BEGIN NOW Leading me back unto my old abode, END
BEGIN NOW My father's house! There in the night I came, END
BEGIN NOW And found them feasting, and all things the same END
BEGIN NOW As they had been before. A splendour hung END
BEGIN NOW Upon the walls, and such sweet songs were sung END
BEGIN NOW As, echoing out of very long ago, END
BEGIN NOW Had called me from the house of Life, I know. END
BEGIN NOW So fair their raiment shone I looked in shame END
BEGIN NOW On the unlovely garb in which I came; END
BEGIN NOW Then straightway at my hesitancy mocked: END
BEGIN NOW It is my father's house!" I said and knocked; END
BEGIN NOW And the door opened. To the shining crowd END
BEGIN NOW Tattered and dark I entered, like a cloud, END
BEGIN NOW Seeing no face but his; to him I crept, END
BEGIN NOW And "Father!" I cried, and clasped his knees, and wept. END
BEGIN NOW Ah, days of joy that followed! All alone END
BEGIN NOW I wandered through the house. My own, my own, END
BEGIN NOW My own to touch, my own to taste and smell, END
BEGIN NOW All I had lacked so long and loved so well! END
BEGIN NOW None shook me out of sleep, nor hushed my song, END
BEGIN NOW Nor called me in from the sunlight all day long. END
BEGIN NOW I know not when the wonder came to me END
BEGIN NOW Of what my father's business might be, END
BEGIN NOW And whither fared and on what errands bent END
BEGIN NOW The tall and gracious messengers he sent. END
BEGIN NOW Yet one day with no song from dawn till night END
BEGIN NOW Wondering, I sat, and watched them out of sight. END
BEGIN NOW And the next day I called; and on the third END
BEGIN NOW Asked them if I might go,--but no one heard. END
BEGIN NOW Then, sick with longing, I arose at last END
BEGIN NOW And went unto my father,--in that vast END
BEGIN NOW Chamber wherein he for so many years END
BEGIN NOW Has sat, surrounded by his charts and spheres. END
BEGIN NOW Father, I said, "Father, I cannot play END
BEGIN NOW The harp that thou didst give me, and all day END
BEGIN NOW I sit in idleness, while to and fro END
BEGIN NOW About me thy serene, grave servants go; END
BEGIN NOW And I am weary of my lonely ease. END
BEGIN NOW Better a perilous journey overseas END
BEGIN NOW Away from thee, than this, the life I lead, END
BEGIN NOW To sit all day in the sunshine like a weed END
BEGIN NOW That grows to naught,--I love thee more than they END
BEGIN NOW Who serve thee most; yet serve thee in no way. END
BEGIN NOW Father, I beg of thee a little task END
BEGIN NOW To dignify my days,--'tis all I ask END
BEGIN NOW Forever, but forever, this denied, END
BEGIN NOW I perish. END
BEGIN NOW Child, my father's voice replied, END
BEGIN NOW All things thy fancy hath desired of me END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast received. I have prepared for thee END
BEGIN NOW Within my house a spacious chamber, where END
BEGIN NOW Are delicate things to handle and to wear, END
BEGIN NOW And all these things are thine. Dost thou love song? END
BEGIN NOW My minstrels shall attend thee all day long. END
BEGIN NOW Or sigh for flowers? My fairest gardens stand END
BEGIN NOW Open as fields to thee on every hand. END
BEGIN NOW And all thy days this word shall hold the same: END
BEGIN NOW No pleasure shalt thou lack that thou shalt name. END
BEGIN NOW But as for tasks--" he smiled, and shook his head; END
BEGIN NOW Thou hadst thy task, and laidst it by", he said. END
BEGIN NOW God's World END
BEGIN NOW O world, I cannot hold thee close enough! END
BEGIN NOW Thy winds, thy wide grey skies! END
BEGIN NOW Thy mists, that roll and rise! END
BEGIN NOW Thy woods, this autumn day, that ache and sag END
BEGIN NOW And all but cry with colour! That gaunt crag END
BEGIN NOW To crush! To lift the lean of that black bluff! END
BEGIN NOW World, World, I cannot get thee close enough! END
BEGIN NOW Long have I known a glory in it all, END
BEGIN NOW But never knew I this; END
BEGIN NOW Here such a passion is END
BEGIN NOW As stretcheth me apart,--Lord, I do fear END
BEGIN NOW Thou'st made the world too beautiful this year; END
BEGIN NOW My soul is all but out of me,--let fall END
BEGIN NOW No burning leaf; prithee, let no bird call. END
BEGIN NOW I will be the gladdest thing END
BEGIN NOW Under the sun! END
BEGIN NOW I will touch a hundred flowers END
BEGIN NOW And not pick one. END
BEGIN NOW I will look at cliffs and clouds END
BEGIN NOW With quiet eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Watch the wind bow down the grass, END
BEGIN NOW And the grass rise. END
BEGIN NOW And when lights begin to show END
BEGIN NOW Up from the town, END
BEGIN NOW I will mark which must be mine, END
BEGIN NOW And then start down! END
BEGIN NOW Sorrow like a ceaseless rain END
BEGIN NOW Beats upon my heart. END
BEGIN NOW People twist and scream in pain,-- END
BEGIN NOW Dawn will find them still again; END
BEGIN NOW This has neither wax nor wane, END
BEGIN NOW Neither stop nor start. END
BEGIN NOW People dress and go to town; END
BEGIN NOW I sit in my chair. END
BEGIN NOW All my thoughts are slow and brown: END
BEGIN NOW Standing up or sitting down END
BEGIN NOW Little matters, or what gown END
BEGIN NOW Or what shoes I wear. END
BEGIN NOW I'll keep a little tavern END
BEGIN NOW Below the high hill's crest, END
BEGIN NOW Wherein all grey-eyed people END
BEGIN NOW May set them down and rest. END
BEGIN NOW There shall be plates a-plenty, END
BEGIN NOW And mugs to melt the chill END
BEGIN NOW Of all the grey-eyed people END
BEGIN NOW Who happen up the hill. END
BEGIN NOW There sound will sleep the traveller, END
BEGIN NOW And dream his journey's end, END
BEGIN NOW But I will rouse at midnight END
BEGIN NOW The falling fire to tend. END
BEGIN NOW Aye, 'tis a curious fancy-- END
BEGIN NOW But all the good I know END
BEGIN NOW Was taught me out of two grey eyes END
BEGIN NOW A long time ago. END
BEGIN NOW Love has gone and left me and the days are all alike; END
BEGIN NOW Eat I must, and sleep I will,--and would that night were here! END
BEGIN NOW But ah!--to lie awake and hear the slow hours strike! END
BEGIN NOW Would that it were day again!--with twilight near! END
BEGIN NOW Love has gone and left me and I don't know what to do; END
BEGIN NOW This or that or what you will is all the same to me; END
BEGIN NOW But all the things that I begin I leave before I'm through,-- END
BEGIN NOW There's little use in anything as far as I can see. END
BEGIN NOW Love has gone and left me,--and the neighbors knock and borrow, END
BEGIN NOW And life goes on forever like the gnawing of a mouse,-- END
BEGIN NOW And to-morrow and to-morrow and to-morrow and to-morrow END
BEGIN NOW There's this little street and this little house. END
BEGIN NOW I knew her for a little ghost END
BEGIN NOW That in my garden walked; END
BEGIN NOW The wall is high--higher than most-- END
BEGIN NOW And the green gate was locked. END
BEGIN NOW And yet I did not think of that END
BEGIN NOW Till after she was gone-- END
BEGIN NOW I knew her by the broad white hat, END
BEGIN NOW All ruffled, she had on. END
BEGIN NOW By the dear ruffles round her feet, END
BEGIN NOW By her small hands that hung END
BEGIN NOW In their lace mitts, austere and sweet, END
BEGIN NOW Her gown's white folds among. END
BEGIN NOW I watched to see if she would stay, END
BEGIN NOW What she would do--and oh! END
BEGIN NOW She looked as if she liked the way END
BEGIN NOW I let my garden grow! END
BEGIN NOW She bent above my favourite mint END
BEGIN NOW With conscious garden grace, END
BEGIN NOW She smiled and smiled--there was no hint END
BEGIN NOW Of sadness in her face. END
BEGIN NOW She held her gown on either side END
BEGIN NOW To let her slippers show, END
BEGIN NOW And up the walk she went with pride, END
BEGIN NOW The way great ladies go. END
BEGIN NOW And where the wall is built in new END
BEGIN NOW And is of ivy bare END
BEGIN NOW She paused--then opened and passed through END
BEGIN NOW A gate that once was there. END
BEGIN NOW Falls the knocker of my door-- END
BEGIN NOW Neither loud nor soft, END
BEGIN NOW But as long accustomed, END
BEGIN NOW Under Sorrow's hand? END
BEGIN NOW Marigolds around the step END
BEGIN NOW And rosemary stand, END
BEGIN NOW And then comes Sorrow-- END
BEGIN NOW And what does Sorrow care END
BEGIN NOW For the rosemary END
BEGIN NOW Or the marigolds there? END
BEGIN NOW Are we kin? END
BEGIN NOW That so oft upon my door-- END
BEGIN NOW The first rose on my rose-tree END
BEGIN NOW Budded, bloomed, and shattered, END
BEGIN NOW During sad days when to me END
BEGIN NOW Nothing mattered. END
BEGIN NOW Grief of grief has drained me clean; END
BEGIN NOW Still it seems a pity END
BEGIN NOW No one saw,--it must have been END
BEGIN NOW Very pretty. END
BEGIN NOW Let the little birds sing; END
BEGIN NOW Let the little lambs play; END
BEGIN NOW Spring is here; and so 'tis spring;-- END
BEGIN NOW But not in the old way! END
BEGIN NOW I recall a place END
BEGIN NOW Where a plum-tree grew; END
BEGIN NOW There you lifted up your face, END
BEGIN NOW And blossoms covered you. END
BEGIN NOW If the little birds sing, END
BEGIN NOW And the little lambs play, END
BEGIN NOW Spring is here; and so 'tis spring-- END
BEGIN NOW But not in the old way! END
BEGIN NOW All the dog-wood blossoms are underneath the tree! END
BEGIN NOW Ere spring was going--ah, spring is gone! END
BEGIN NOW And there comes no summer to the like of you and me,-- END
BEGIN NOW Blossom time is early, but no fruit sets on. END
BEGIN NOW All the dog-wood blossoms are underneath the tree, END
BEGIN NOW Browned at the edges, turned in a day; END
BEGIN NOW And I would with all my heart they trimmed a mound for me, END
BEGIN NOW And weeds were tall on all the paths that led that way! END
BEGIN NOW Death, I say, my heart is bowed END
BEGIN NOW Unto thine,--O mother! END
BEGIN NOW This red gown will make a shroud END
BEGIN NOW Good as any other! END
BEGIN NOW (I, that would not wait to wear END
BEGIN NOW My own bridal things, END
BEGIN NOW In a dress dark as my hair END
BEGIN NOW Made my answerings. END
BEGIN NOW I, to-night, that till he came END
BEGIN NOW Could not, could not wait, END
BEGIN NOW In a gown as bright as flame END
BEGIN NOW Held for them the gate.) END
BEGIN NOW Death, I say, my heart is bowed END
BEGIN NOW Unto thine,--O mother! END
BEGIN NOW This red gown will make a shroud END
BEGIN NOW Good as any other! END
BEGIN NOW Love, if I weep it will not matter, END
BEGIN NOW And if you laugh I shall not care; END
BEGIN NOW Foolish am I to think about it, END
BEGIN NOW But it is good to feel you there. END
BEGIN NOW Love, in my sleep I dreamed of waking,-- END
BEGIN NOW White and awful the moonlight reached END
BEGIN NOW Over the floor, and somewhere, somewhere, END
BEGIN NOW There was a shutter loose,--it screeched! END
BEGIN NOW Swung in the wind,--and no wind blowing!-- END
BEGIN NOW I was afraid, and turned to you, END
BEGIN NOW Put out my hand to you for comfort,-- END
BEGIN NOW And you were gone! Cold, cold as dew, END
BEGIN NOW Under my hand the moonlight lay! END
BEGIN NOW Love, if you laugh I shall not care, END
BEGIN NOW But if I weep it will not matter,-- END
BEGIN NOW Ah, it is good to feel you there! END
BEGIN NOW I said,--for Love was laggard, O, Love was slow to come,-- END
BEGIN NOW I'll hear his step and know his step when I am warm in bed; END
BEGIN NOW But I'll never leave my pillow, though there be some END
BEGIN NOW As would let him in--and take him in with tears!" I said. END
BEGIN NOW I lay,--for Love was laggard, O, he came not until dawn,-- END
BEGIN NOW I lay and listened for his step and could not get to sleep; END
BEGIN NOW And he found me at my window with my big cloak on, END
BEGIN NOW All sorry with the tears some folks might weep! END
BEGIN NOW She is neither pink nor pale, END
BEGIN NOW And she never will be all mine; END
BEGIN NOW She learned her hands in a fairy-tale, END
BEGIN NOW And her mouth on a valentine. END
BEGIN NOW She has more hair than she needs; END
BEGIN NOW In the sun 'tis a woe to me! END
BEGIN NOW And her voice is a string of colored beads, END
BEGIN NOW Or steps leading into the sea. END
BEGIN NOW She loves me all that she can, END
BEGIN NOW And her ways to my ways resign; END
BEGIN NOW But she was not made for any man, END
BEGIN NOW And she never will be all mine. END
BEGIN NOW Hard seeds of hate I planted END
BEGIN NOW That should by now be grown,-- END
BEGIN NOW Rough stalks, and from thick stamens END
BEGIN NOW A poisonous pollen blown, END
BEGIN NOW And odors rank, unbreathable, END
BEGIN NOW From dark corollas thrown! END
BEGIN NOW At dawn from my damp garden END
BEGIN NOW I shook the chilly dew; END
BEGIN NOW The thin boughs locked behind me END
BEGIN NOW That sprang to let me through; END
BEGIN NOW The blossoms slept,--I sought a place END
BEGIN NOW Where nothing lovely grew. END
BEGIN NOW And there, when day was breaking, END
BEGIN NOW I knelt and looked around: END
BEGIN NOW The light was near, the silence END
BEGIN NOW Was palpitant with sound; END
BEGIN NOW I drew my hate from out my breast END
BEGIN NOW And thrust it in the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, ye so fiercely tended, END
BEGIN NOW Ye little seeds of hate! END
BEGIN NOW I bent above your growing END
BEGIN NOW Early and noon and late, END
BEGIN NOW Yet are ye drooped and pitiful,-- END
BEGIN NOW I cannot rear ye straight! END
BEGIN NOW The sun seeks out my garden, END
BEGIN NOW No nook is left in shade, END
BEGIN NOW No mist nor mold nor mildew END
BEGIN NOW Endures on any blade, END
BEGIN NOW Sweet rain slants under every bough: END
BEGIN NOW Ye falter, and ye fade. END
BEGIN NOW I cannot but remember END
BEGIN NOW When the year grows old-- END
BEGIN NOW How she disliked the cold! END
BEGIN NOW She used to watch the swallows END
BEGIN NOW Go down across the sky, END
BEGIN NOW And turn from the window END
BEGIN NOW With a little sharp sigh. END
BEGIN NOW And often when the brown leaves END
BEGIN NOW Were brittle on the ground, END
BEGIN NOW And the wind in the chimney END
BEGIN NOW Made a melancholy sound, END
BEGIN NOW She had a look about her END
BEGIN NOW That I wish I could forget-- END
BEGIN NOW The look of a scared thing END
BEGIN NOW Sitting in a net! END
BEGIN NOW Oh, beautiful at nightfall END
BEGIN NOW The soft spitting snow! END
BEGIN NOW And beautiful the bare boughs END
BEGIN NOW Rubbing to and fro! END
BEGIN NOW But the roaring of the fire, END
BEGIN NOW And the warmth of fur, END
BEGIN NOW And the boiling of the kettle END
BEGIN NOW Were beautiful to her! END
BEGIN NOW I cannot but remember END
BEGIN NOW When the year grows old-- END
BEGIN NOW How she disliked the cold! END
BEGIN NOW Thou art not lovelier than lilacs,--no, END
BEGIN NOW Nor honeysuckle; thou art not more fair END
BEGIN NOW Than small white single poppies,--I can bear END
BEGIN NOW Thy beauty; though I bend before thee, though END
BEGIN NOW From left to right, not knowing where to go, END
BEGIN NOW I turn my troubled eyes, nor here nor there END
BEGIN NOW Find any refuge from thee, yet I swear END
BEGIN NOW So has it been with mist,--with moonlight so. END
BEGIN NOW Like him who day by day unto his draught END
BEGIN NOW Of delicate poison adds him one drop more END
BEGIN NOW Till he may drink unharmed the death of ten, END
BEGIN NOW Even so, inured to beauty, who have quaffed END
BEGIN NOW Each hour more deeply than the hour before, END
BEGIN NOW I drink--and live--what has destroyed some men. END
BEGIN NOW Time does not bring relief; you all have lied END
BEGIN NOW Who told me time would ease me of my pain! END
BEGIN NOW I miss him in the weeping of the rain; END
BEGIN NOW I want him at the shrinking of the tide; END
BEGIN NOW The old snows melt from every mountain-side, END
BEGIN NOW And last year's leaves are smoke in every lane; END
BEGIN NOW But last year's bitter loving must remain END
BEGIN NOW Heaped on my heart, and my old thoughts abide! END
BEGIN NOW There are a hundred places where I fear END
BEGIN NOW To go,--so with his memory they brim! END
BEGIN NOW And entering with relief some quiet place END
BEGIN NOW Where never fell his foot or shone his face END
BEGIN NOW I say, "There is no memory of him here! END
BEGIN NOW And so stand stricken, so remembering him! END
BEGIN NOW Mindful of you the sodden earth in spring, END
BEGIN NOW And all the flowers that in the springtime grow, END
BEGIN NOW And dusty roads, and thistles, and the slow END
BEGIN NOW Rising of the round moon, all throats that sing END
BEGIN NOW The summer through, and each departing wing, END
BEGIN NOW And all the nests that the bared branches show, END
BEGIN NOW And all winds that in any weather blow, END
BEGIN NOW And all the storms that the four seasons bring. END
BEGIN NOW You go no more on your exultant feet END
BEGIN NOW Up paths that only mist and morning knew, END
BEGIN NOW Or watch the wind, or listen to the beat END
BEGIN NOW Of a bird's wings too high in air to view,-- END
BEGIN NOW But you were something more than young and sweet END
BEGIN NOW And fair,--and the long year remembers you. END
BEGIN NOW Not in this chamber only at my birth-- END
BEGIN NOW When the long hours of that mysterious night END
BEGIN NOW Were over, and the morning was in sight-- END
BEGIN NOW I cried, but in strange places, steppe and firth END
BEGIN NOW I have not seen, through alien grief and mirth; END
BEGIN NOW And never shall one room contain me quite END
BEGIN NOW Who in so many rooms first saw the light, END
BEGIN NOW Child of all mothers, native of the earth. END
BEGIN NOW So is no warmth for me at any fire END
BEGIN NOW To-day, when the world's fire has burned so low; END
BEGIN NOW I kneel, spending my breath in vain desire, END
BEGIN NOW At that cold hearth which one time roared so strong, END
BEGIN NOW And straighten back in weariness, and long END
BEGIN NOW To gather up my little gods and go. END
BEGIN NOW If I should learn, in some quite casual way, END
BEGIN NOW That you were gone, not to return again-- END
BEGIN NOW Read from the back-page of a paper, say, END
BEGIN NOW Held by a neighbor in a subway train, END
BEGIN NOW How at the corner of this avenue END
BEGIN NOW And such a street (so are the papers filled) END
BEGIN NOW A hurrying man--who happened to be you-- END
BEGIN NOW At noon to-day had happened to be killed, END
BEGIN NOW I should not cry aloud--I could not cry END
BEGIN NOW Aloud, or wring my hands in such a place-- END
BEGIN NOW I should but watch the station lights rush by END
BEGIN NOW With a more careful interest on my face, END
BEGIN NOW Or raise my eyes and read with greater care END
BEGIN NOW Where to store furs and how to treat the hair. END
BEGIN NOW This door you might not open, and you did; END
BEGIN NOW So enter now, and see for what slight thing END
BEGIN NOW You are betrayed. . . . Here is no treasure hid, END
BEGIN NOW No cauldron, no clear crystal mirroring END
BEGIN NOW The sought-for truth, no heads of women slain END
BEGIN NOW For greed like yours, no writhings of distress, END
BEGIN NOW But only what you see. . . . Look yet again-- END
BEGIN NOW An empty room, cobwebbed and comfortless. END
BEGIN NOW Yet this alone out of my life I kept END
BEGIN NOW Unto myself, lest any know me quite; END
BEGIN NOW And you did so profane me when you crept END
BEGIN NOW Unto the threshold of this room to-night END
BEGIN NOW That I must never more behold your face. END
BEGIN NOW This now is yours. I seek another place. END
BEGIN NOW A Child's Garden of Verses END
BEGIN NOW For the long nights you lay awake END
BEGIN NOW And watched for my unworthy sake: END
BEGIN NOW For your most comfortable hand END
BEGIN NOW That led me through the uneven land: END
BEGIN NOW For all the story-books you read: END
BEGIN NOW For all the pains you comforted: END
BEGIN NOW For all you pitied, all you bore, END
BEGIN NOW In sad and happy days of yore:-- END
BEGIN NOW My second Mother, my first Wife, END
BEGIN NOW The angel of my infant life-- END
BEGIN NOW From the sick child, now well and old, END
BEGIN NOW Take, nurse, the little book you hold! END
BEGIN NOW And grant it, Heaven, that all who read END
BEGIN NOW May find as dear a nurse at need, END
BEGIN NOW And every child who lists my rhyme, END
BEGIN NOW In the bright, fireside, nursery clime, END
BEGIN NOW May hear it in as kind a voice END
BEGIN NOW As made my childish days rejoice! END
BEGIN NOW VIII Foreign Lands END
BEGIN NOW XIII A Good Play END
BEGIN NOW XV Auntie's Skirts END
BEGIN NOW XVII The Land of Nod END
BEGIN NOW XVIII My Shadow END
BEGIN NOW XXII Marching Song END
BEGIN NOW XXIII The Cow END
BEGIN NOW XXIV The Happy Thought END
BEGIN NOW XXVI Keepsake Mill END
BEGIN NOW XXVII Good and Bad Children END
BEGIN NOW XXVIII Foreign Children END
BEGIN NOW XXIX The Sun Travels END
BEGIN NOW XXXI My Bed is a Boat END
BEGIN NOW XXXII The Moon END
BEGIN NOW XXXIII The Swing END
BEGIN NOW XXXIV Time to Rise END
BEGIN NOW XXXV Looking-Glass River END
BEGIN NOW XXXVI Fairy Bread END
BEGIN NOW XXXVII From a Railway Carriage END
BEGIN NOW XXXVIII Winter-Time END
BEGIN NOW XXXIX The Hayloft END
BEGIN NOW VIII Armies in the Fire END
BEGIN NOW VIII Historical Associations END
BEGIN NOW A Child's Garden of Verses END
BEGIN NOW In winter I get up at night END
BEGIN NOW And dress by yellow candle-light. END
BEGIN NOW In summer quite the other way, END
BEGIN NOW I have to go to bed by day. END
BEGIN NOW I have to go to bed and see END
BEGIN NOW The birds still hopping on the tree, END
BEGIN NOW Or hear the grown-up people's feet END
BEGIN NOW Still going past me in the street. END
BEGIN NOW And does it not seem hard to you, END
BEGIN NOW When all the sky is clear and blue, END
BEGIN NOW And I should like so much to play, END
BEGIN NOW To have to go to bed by day? END
BEGIN NOW It is very nice to think END
BEGIN NOW The world is full of meat and drink, END
BEGIN NOW With little children saying grace END
BEGIN NOW In every Christian kind of place. END
BEGIN NOW When I was down beside the sea END
BEGIN NOW To dig the sandy shore. END
BEGIN NOW My holes were empty like a cup. END
BEGIN NOW In every hole the sea came up, END
BEGIN NOW Till it could come no more. END
BEGIN NOW All night long and every night, END
BEGIN NOW When my mama puts out the light, END
BEGIN NOW I see the people marching by, END
BEGIN NOW As plain as day before my eye. END
BEGIN NOW Armies and emperor and kings, END
BEGIN NOW All carrying different kinds of things, END
BEGIN NOW And marching in so grand a way, END
BEGIN NOW You never saw the like by day. END
BEGIN NOW So fine a show was never seen END
BEGIN NOW At the great circus on the green; END
BEGIN NOW For every kind of beast and man END
BEGIN NOW Is marching in that caravan. END
BEGIN NOW As first they move a little slow, END
BEGIN NOW But still the faster on they go, END
BEGIN NOW And still beside me close I keep END
BEGIN NOW Until we reach the town of Sleep. END
BEGIN NOW A child should always say what's true END
BEGIN NOW And speak when he is spoken to, END
BEGIN NOW And behave mannerly at table; END
BEGIN NOW At least as far as he is able. END
BEGIN NOW The rain is falling all around, END
BEGIN NOW It falls on field and tree, END
BEGIN NOW It rains on the umbrellas here, END
BEGIN NOW And on the ships at sea. END
BEGIN NOW Three of us afloat in the meadow by the swing, END
BEGIN NOW Three of us abroad in the basket on the lea. END
BEGIN NOW Winds are in the air, they are blowing in the spring, END
BEGIN NOW And waves are on the meadow like the waves there are at sea. END
BEGIN NOW Where shall we adventure, to-day that we're afloat, END
BEGIN NOW Wary of the weather and steering by a star? END
BEGIN NOW Shall it be to Africa, a-steering of the boat, END
BEGIN NOW Hi! but here's a squadron a-rowing on the sea-- END
BEGIN NOW Cattle on the meadow a-charging with a roar! END
BEGIN NOW Quick, and we'll escape them, they're as mad as they can be, END
BEGIN NOW The wicket is the harbour and the garden is the shore. END
BEGIN NOW Up into the cherry tree END
BEGIN NOW Who should climb but little me? END
BEGIN NOW I held the trunk with both my hands END
BEGIN NOW And looked abroad in foreign lands. END
BEGIN NOW I saw the next door garden lie, END
BEGIN NOW Adorned with flowers, before my eye, END
BEGIN NOW And many pleasant places more END
BEGIN NOW That I had never seen before. END
BEGIN NOW I saw the dimpling river pass END
BEGIN NOW And be the sky's blue looking-glass; END
BEGIN NOW The dusty roads go up and down END
BEGIN NOW With people tramping in to town. END
BEGIN NOW If I could find a higher tree END
BEGIN NOW Farther and farther I should see, END
BEGIN NOW To where the grown-up river slips END
BEGIN NOW Into the sea among the ships, END
BEGIN NOW To where the roads on either hand END
BEGIN NOW Lead onward into fairy land, END
BEGIN NOW Where all the children dine at five, END
BEGIN NOW And all the playthings come alive. END
BEGIN NOW Whenever the moon and stars are set, END
BEGIN NOW Whenever the wind is high, END
BEGIN NOW All night long in the dark and wet, END
BEGIN NOW A man goes riding by. END
BEGIN NOW Late in the night when the fires are out, END
BEGIN NOW Why does he gallop and gallop about? END
BEGIN NOW Whenever the trees are crying aloud, END
BEGIN NOW And ships are tossed at sea, END
BEGIN NOW By, on the highway, low and loud, END
BEGIN NOW By at the gallop goes he. END
BEGIN NOW By at the gallop he goes, and then END
BEGIN NOW By he comes back at the gallop again. END
BEGIN NOW I should like to rise and go END
BEGIN NOW Where the golden apples grow;-- END
BEGIN NOW Where below another sky END
BEGIN NOW Parrot islands anchored lie, END
BEGIN NOW And, watched by cockatoos and goats, END
BEGIN NOW Lonely Crusoes building boats;-- END
BEGIN NOW Where in sunshine reaching out END
BEGIN NOW Eastern cities, miles about, END
BEGIN NOW Are with mosque and minaret END
BEGIN NOW Among sandy gardens set, END
BEGIN NOW And the rich goods from near and far END
BEGIN NOW Hang for sale in the bazaar;-- END
BEGIN NOW Where the Great Wall round China goes, END
BEGIN NOW And on one side the desert blows, END
BEGIN NOW And with the voice and bell and drum, END
BEGIN NOW Cities on the other hum;-- END
BEGIN NOW Where are forests hot as fire, END
BEGIN NOW Wide as England, tall as a spire, END
BEGIN NOW Full of apes and cocoa-nuts END
BEGIN NOW Where the knotty crocodile END
BEGIN NOW Lies and blinks in the Nile, END
BEGIN NOW And the red flamingo flies END
BEGIN NOW Hunting fish before his eyes;-- END
BEGIN NOW Where in jungles near and far, END
BEGIN NOW Man-devouring tigers are, END
BEGIN NOW Lying close and giving ear END
BEGIN NOW Lest the hunt be drawing near, END
BEGIN NOW Or a comer-by be seen END
BEGIN NOW Swinging in the palanquin;-- END
BEGIN NOW Where among the desert sands END
BEGIN NOW Some deserted city stands, END
BEGIN NOW All its children, sweep and prince, END
BEGIN NOW Grown to manhood ages since, END
BEGIN NOW Not a foot in street or house, END
BEGIN NOW Not a stir of child or mouse, END
BEGIN NOW And when kindly falls the night, END
BEGIN NOW In all the town no spark of light. END
BEGIN NOW There I'll come when I'm a man END
BEGIN NOW With a camel caravan; END
BEGIN NOW Light a fire in the gloom END
BEGIN NOW Of some dusty dining room; END
BEGIN NOW See the pictures on the walls, END
BEGIN NOW Heroes, fights and festivals; END
BEGIN NOW And in a corner find the toys END
BEGIN NOW Of speckled eggs the birdie sings END
BEGIN NOW And nests among the trees; END
BEGIN NOW The sailor sings of ropes and things END
BEGIN NOW In ships upon the seas. END
BEGIN NOW The children sing in Spain; END
BEGIN NOW The organ with the organ man END
BEGIN NOW Is singing in the rain. END
BEGIN NOW When I am grown to man's estate END
BEGIN NOW I shall be very proud and great, END
BEGIN NOW And tell the other girls and boys END
BEGIN NOW Not to meddle with my toys. END
BEGIN NOW We built a ship upon the stairs END
BEGIN NOW All made of the back-bedroom chairs, END
BEGIN NOW And filled it full of sofa pillows END
BEGIN NOW To go a-sailing on the billows. END
BEGIN NOW We took a saw and several nails, END
BEGIN NOW And water in the nursery pails; END
BEGIN NOW And Tom said, "Let us also take END
BEGIN NOW An apple and a slice of cake;"-- END
BEGIN NOW Which was enough for Tom and me END
BEGIN NOW To go a-sailing on, till tea. END
BEGIN NOW We sailed along for days and days, END
BEGIN NOW And had the very best of plays; END
BEGIN NOW But Tom fell out and hurt his knee, END
BEGIN NOW So there was no one left but me. END
BEGIN NOW Dark brown is the river, END
BEGIN NOW Golden is the sand. END
BEGIN NOW It flows along for ever, END
BEGIN NOW With trees on either hand. END
BEGIN NOW Green leaves a-floating, END
BEGIN NOW Castles of the foam, END
BEGIN NOW Boats of mine a-boating-- END
BEGIN NOW Where will all come home? END
BEGIN NOW On goes the river END
BEGIN NOW And out past the mill, END
BEGIN NOW Away down the valley, END
BEGIN NOW Away down the hill. END
BEGIN NOW Away down the river, END
BEGIN NOW A hundred miles or more, END
BEGIN NOW Other little children END
BEGIN NOW Shall bring my boats ashore. END
BEGIN NOW Auntie's Skirts END
BEGIN NOW Whenever Auntie moves around, END
BEGIN NOW Her dresses make a curious sound, END
BEGIN NOW They trail behind her up the floor, END
BEGIN NOW And trundle after through the door. END
BEGIN NOW When I was sick and lay a-bed, END
BEGIN NOW I had two pillows at my head, END
BEGIN NOW And all my toys beside me lay, END
BEGIN NOW To keep me happy all the day. END
BEGIN NOW And sometimes for an hour or so END
BEGIN NOW I watched my leaden soldiers go, END
BEGIN NOW With different uniforms and drills, END
BEGIN NOW Among the bed-clothes, through the hills; END
BEGIN NOW And sometimes sent my ships in fleets END
BEGIN NOW All up and down among the sheets; END
BEGIN NOW Or brought my trees and houses out, END
BEGIN NOW And planted cities all about. END
BEGIN NOW I was the giant great and still END
BEGIN NOW That sits upon the pillow-hill, END
BEGIN NOW And sees before him, dale and plain, END
BEGIN NOW The pleasant land of counterpane. END
BEGIN NOW From breakfast on through all the day END
BEGIN NOW At home among my friends I stay, END
BEGIN NOW But every night I go abroad END
BEGIN NOW Afar into the land of Nod. END
BEGIN NOW All by myself I have to go, END
BEGIN NOW With none to tell me what to do-- END
BEGIN NOW All alone beside the streams END
BEGIN NOW And up the mountain-sides of dreams. END
BEGIN NOW The strangest things are these for me, END
BEGIN NOW Both things to eat and things to see, END
BEGIN NOW And many frightening sights abroad END
BEGIN NOW Till morning in the land of Nod. END
BEGIN NOW Try as I like to find the way, END
BEGIN NOW I never can get back by day, END
BEGIN NOW Nor can remember plain and clear END
BEGIN NOW The curious music that I hear. END
BEGIN NOW I have a little shadow that goes in and out with me, END
BEGIN NOW And what can be the use of him is more than I can see. END
BEGIN NOW He is very, very like me from the heels up to the head; END
BEGIN NOW And I see him jump before me, when I jump into my bed. END
BEGIN NOW The funniest thing about him is the way he likes to grow-- END
BEGIN NOW Not at all like proper children, which is always very slow; END
BEGIN NOW For he sometimes shoots up taller like an india-rubber ball, END
BEGIN NOW And he sometimes goes so little that there's none of him at all. END
BEGIN NOW He hasn't got a notion of how children ought to play, END
BEGIN NOW And can only make a fool of me in every sort of way. END
BEGIN NOW He stays so close behind me, he's a coward you can see; END
BEGIN NOW I'd think shame to stick to nursie as that shadow sticks to me! END
BEGIN NOW One morning, very early, before the sun was up, END
BEGIN NOW I rose and found the shining dew on every buttercup; END
BEGIN NOW But my lazy little shadow, like an arrant sleepy-head, END
BEGIN NOW Had stayed at home behind me and was fast asleep in bed. END
BEGIN NOW Every night my prayers I say, END
BEGIN NOW And get my dinner every day; END
BEGIN NOW And every day that I've been good, END
BEGIN NOW I get an orange after food. END
BEGIN NOW The child that is not clean and neat, END
BEGIN NOW With lots of toys and things to eat, END
BEGIN NOW He is a naughty child, I'm sure-- END
BEGIN NOW Or else his dear papa is poor. END
BEGIN NOW I woke before the morning, I was happy all the day, END
BEGIN NOW I never said an ugly word, but smiled and stuck to play. END
BEGIN NOW And now at last the sun is going down behind the wood, END
BEGIN NOW And I am very happy, for I know that I've been good. END
BEGIN NOW My bed is waiting cool and fresh, with linen smooth and fair, END
BEGIN NOW And I must be off to sleepsin-by, and not forget my prayer. END
BEGIN NOW I know that, till to-morrow I shall see the sun arise, END
BEGIN NOW No ugly dream shall fright my mind, no ugly sight my eyes. END
BEGIN NOW But slumber hold me tightly till I waken in the dawn, END
BEGIN NOW And hear the thrushes singing in the lilacs round the lawn. END
BEGIN NOW The lights from the parlour and kitchen shone out END
BEGIN NOW Through the blinds and the windows and bars; END
BEGIN NOW And high overhead and all moving about, END
BEGIN NOW There were thousands of millions of stars. END
BEGIN NOW There ne'er were such thousands of leaves on a tree, END
BEGIN NOW Nor of people in church or the Park, END
BEGIN NOW As the crowds of the stars that looked down upon me, END
BEGIN NOW And that glittered and winked in the dark. END
BEGIN NOW The Dog, and the Plough, and the Hunter, and all, END
BEGIN NOW And the star of the sailor, and Mars, END
BEGIN NOW These shown in the sky, and the pail by the wall END
BEGIN NOW Would be half full of water and stars. END
BEGIN NOW They saw me at last, and they chased me with cries, END
BEGIN NOW And they soon had me packed into bed; END
BEGIN NOW But the glory kept shining and bright in my eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And the stars going round in my head. END
BEGIN NOW Bring the comb and play upon it! END
BEGIN NOW Marching, here we come! END
BEGIN NOW Willie cocks his highland bonnet, END
BEGIN NOW Johnnie beats the drum. END
BEGIN NOW Mary Jane commands the party, END
BEGIN NOW Peter leads the rear; END
BEGIN NOW Feet in time, alert and hearty, END
BEGIN NOW All in the most martial manner END
BEGIN NOW Marching double-quick; END
BEGIN NOW While the napkin, like a banner, END
BEGIN NOW Waves upon the stick! END
BEGIN NOW Here's enough of fame and pillage, END
BEGIN NOW Great commander Jane! END
BEGIN NOW Now that we've been round the village, END
BEGIN NOW Let's go home again. END
BEGIN NOW The friendly cow all red and white, END
BEGIN NOW I love with all my heart: END
BEGIN NOW She gives me cream with all her might, END
BEGIN NOW To eat with apple-tart. END
BEGIN NOW She wanders lowing here and there, END
BEGIN NOW And yet she cannot stray, END
BEGIN NOW All in the pleasant open air, END
BEGIN NOW The pleasant light of day; END
BEGIN NOW And blown by all the winds that pass END
BEGIN NOW And wet with all the showers, END
BEGIN NOW She walks among the meadow grass END
BEGIN NOW And eats the meadow flowers. END
BEGIN NOW The world is so full of a number of things, END
BEGIN NOW I'm sure we should all be as happy as kings. END
BEGIN NOW I saw you toss the kites on high END
BEGIN NOW And blow the birds about the sky; END
BEGIN NOW And all around I heard you pass, END
BEGIN NOW Like ladies' skirts across the grass-- END
BEGIN NOW O wind, a-blowing all day long, END
BEGIN NOW O wind, that sings so loud a song! END
BEGIN NOW I saw the different things you did, END
BEGIN NOW But always you yourself you hid. END
BEGIN NOW I felt you push, I heard you call, END
BEGIN NOW I could not see yourself at all-- END
BEGIN NOW O wind, a-blowing all day long, END
BEGIN NOW O wind, that sings so loud a song! END
BEGIN NOW O you that are so strong and cold, END
BEGIN NOW O blower, are you young or old? END
BEGIN NOW Are you a beast of field and tree, END
BEGIN NOW Or just a stronger child than me? END
BEGIN NOW O wind, a-blowing all day long, END
BEGIN NOW O wind, that sings so loud a song! END
BEGIN NOW Over the borders, a sin without pardon, END
BEGIN NOW Breaking the branches and crawling below, END
BEGIN NOW Out through the breach in the wall of the garden, END
BEGIN NOW Down by the banks of the river we go. END
BEGIN NOW Here is a mill with the humming of thunder, END
BEGIN NOW Here is the weir with the wonder of foam, END
BEGIN NOW Here is the sluice with the race running under-- END
BEGIN NOW Marvellous places, though handy to home! END
BEGIN NOW Sounds of the village grow stiller and stiller, END
BEGIN NOW Stiller the note of the birds on the hill; END
BEGIN NOW Dusty and dim are the eyes of the miller, END
BEGIN NOW Deaf are his ears with the moil of the mill. END
BEGIN NOW Years may go by, and the wheel in the river END
BEGIN NOW Wheel as it wheels for us, children, to-day, END
BEGIN NOW Wheel and keep roaring and foaming for ever END
BEGIN NOW Long after all of the boys are away. END
BEGIN NOW Home for the Indies and home from the ocean, END
BEGIN NOW Heroes and soldiers we all will come home; END
BEGIN NOW Still we shall find the old mill wheel in motion, END
BEGIN NOW Turning and churning that river to foam. END
BEGIN NOW You with the bean that I gave when we quarrelled, END
BEGIN NOW I with your marble of Saturday last, END
BEGIN NOW Honoured and old and all gaily apparelled, END
BEGIN NOW Here we shall meet and remember the past. END
BEGIN NOW Children, you are very little, END
BEGIN NOW And your bones are very brittle; END
BEGIN NOW If you would grow great and stately, END
BEGIN NOW You must try to walk sedately. END
BEGIN NOW You must still be bright and quiet, END
BEGIN NOW And content with simple diet; END
BEGIN NOW And remain, through all bewild'ring, END
BEGIN NOW Innocent and honest children. END
BEGIN NOW Happy hearts and happy faces, END
BEGIN NOW Happy play in grassy places-- END
BEGIN NOW That was how in ancient ages, END
BEGIN NOW Children grew to kings and sages. END
BEGIN NOW But the unkind and the unruly, END
BEGIN NOW And the sort who eat unduly, END
BEGIN NOW They must never hope for glory-- END
BEGIN NOW Theirs is quite a different story! END
BEGIN NOW Cruel children, crying babies, END
BEGIN NOW All grow up as geese and gabies, END
BEGIN NOW Hated, as their age increases, END
BEGIN NOW By their nephews and their nieces. END
BEGIN NOW Little frosty Eskimo, END
BEGIN NOW Oh! don't you wish that you were me? END
BEGIN NOW You have seen the scarlet trees END
BEGIN NOW And the lions over seas; END
BEGIN NOW You have eaten ostrich eggs, END
BEGIN NOW And turned the turtles off their legs. END
BEGIN NOW Such a life is very fine, END
BEGIN NOW But it's not so nice as mine: END
BEGIN NOW You must often as you trod, END
BEGIN NOW Have wearied NOT to be abroad. END
BEGIN NOW You have curious things to eat, END
BEGIN NOW I am fed on proper meat; END
BEGIN NOW You must dwell upon the foam, END
BEGIN NOW But I am safe and live at home. END
BEGIN NOW Little frosty Eskimo, END
BEGIN NOW Oh! don't you wish that you were me? END
BEGIN NOW The sun is not a-bed, when I END
BEGIN NOW At night upon my pillow lie; END
BEGIN NOW Still round the earth his way he takes, END
BEGIN NOW And morning after morning makes. END
BEGIN NOW While here at home, in shining day, END
BEGIN NOW We round the sunny garden play, END
BEGIN NOW Each little Indian sleepy-head END
BEGIN NOW Is being kissed and put to bed. END
BEGIN NOW And when at eve I rise from tea, END
BEGIN NOW Day dawns beyond the Atlantic Sea; END
BEGIN NOW And all the children in the west END
BEGIN NOW Are getting up and being dressed. END
BEGIN NOW My tea is nearly ready and the sun has left the sky. END
BEGIN NOW It's time to take the window to see Leerie going by; END
BEGIN NOW For every night at teatime and before you take your seat, END
BEGIN NOW With lantern and with ladder he comes posting up the street. END
BEGIN NOW Now Tom would be a driver and Maria go to sea, END
BEGIN NOW And my papa's a banker and as rich as he can be; END
BEGIN NOW But I, when I am stronger and can choose what I'm to do, END
BEGIN NOW O Leerie, I'll go round at night and light the lamps with you! END
BEGIN NOW For we are very lucky, with a lamp before the door, END
BEGIN NOW And Leerie stops to light it as he lights so many more; END
BEGIN NOW And oh! before you hurry by with ladder and with light; END
BEGIN NOW O Leerie, see a little child and nod to him to-night! END
BEGIN NOW My bed is like a little boat; END
BEGIN NOW Nurse helps me in when I embark; END
BEGIN NOW She girds me in my sailor's coat END
BEGIN NOW And starts me in the dark. END
BEGIN NOW At night I go on board and say END
BEGIN NOW Good-night to all my friends on shore; END
BEGIN NOW I shut my eyes and sail away END
BEGIN NOW And see and hear no more. END
BEGIN NOW And sometimes things to bed I take, END
BEGIN NOW As prudent sailors have to do; END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps a slice of wedding-cake, END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps a toy or two. END
BEGIN NOW All night across the dark we steer; END
BEGIN NOW But when the day returns at last, END
BEGIN NOW Safe in my room beside the pier, END
BEGIN NOW I find my vessel fast. END
BEGIN NOW The moon has a face like the clock in the hall; END
BEGIN NOW She shines on thieves on the garden wall, END
BEGIN NOW On streets and fields and harbour quays, END
BEGIN NOW And birdies asleep in the forks of the trees. END
BEGIN NOW The squalling cat and the squeaking mouse, END
BEGIN NOW The howling dog by the door of the house, END
BEGIN NOW The bat that lies in bed at noon, END
BEGIN NOW All love to be out by the light of the moon. END
BEGIN NOW But all of the things that belong to the day END
BEGIN NOW Cuddle to sleep to be out of her way; END
BEGIN NOW And flowers and children close their eyes END
BEGIN NOW Till up in the morning the sun shall arise. END
BEGIN NOW How do you like to go up in a swing, END
BEGIN NOW Up in the air so blue? END
BEGIN NOW Oh, I do think it the pleasantest thing END
BEGIN NOW Ever a child can do! END
BEGIN NOW Up in the air and over the wall, END
BEGIN NOW Till I can see so wide, END
BEGIN NOW River and trees and cattle and all END
BEGIN NOW Over the countryside-- END
BEGIN NOW Till I look down on the garden green, END
BEGIN NOW Down on the roof so brown-- END
BEGIN NOW Up in the air I go flying again, END
BEGIN NOW Up in the air and down! END
BEGIN NOW A birdie with a yellow bill END
BEGIN NOW Hopped upon my window sill, END
BEGIN NOW Cocked his shining eye and said: END
BEGIN NOW Ain't you 'shamed, you sleepy-head! END
BEGIN NOW Smooth it glides upon its travel, END
BEGIN NOW Here a wimple, there a gleam-- END
BEGIN NOW O the clean gravel! END
BEGIN NOW O the smooth stream! END
BEGIN NOW Sailing blossoms, silver fishes, END
BEGIN NOW Paven pools as clear as air-- END
BEGIN NOW How a child wishes END
BEGIN NOW To live down there! END
BEGIN NOW We can see our colored faces END
BEGIN NOW Floating on the shaken pool END
BEGIN NOW Down in cool places, END
BEGIN NOW Dim and very cool; END
BEGIN NOW Till a wind or water wrinkle, END
BEGIN NOW Dipping marten, plumping trout, END
BEGIN NOW Spreads in a twinkle END
BEGIN NOW And blots all out. END
BEGIN NOW See the rings pursue each other; END
BEGIN NOW All below grows black as night, END
BEGIN NOW Just as if mother END
BEGIN NOW Had blown out the light! END
BEGIN NOW Patience, children, just a minute-- END
BEGIN NOW See the spreading circles die; END
BEGIN NOW The stream and all in it END
BEGIN NOW Will clear by-and-by. END
BEGIN NOW Come up here, O dusty feet! END
BEGIN NOW Here is fairy bread to eat. END
BEGIN NOW Here in my retiring room, END
BEGIN NOW Children, you may dine END
BEGIN NOW On the golden smell of broom END
BEGIN NOW And the shade of pine; END
BEGIN NOW And when you have eaten well, END
BEGIN NOW Fairy stories hear and tell. END
BEGIN NOW Faster than fairies, faster than witches, END
BEGIN NOW Bridges and houses, hedges and ditches; END
BEGIN NOW And charging along like troops in a battle END
BEGIN NOW All through the meadows the horses and cattle: END
BEGIN NOW All of the sights of the hill and the plain END
BEGIN NOW Fly as thick as driving rain; END
BEGIN NOW And ever again, in the wink of an eye, END
BEGIN NOW Painted stations whistle by. END
BEGIN NOW Here is a child who clambers and scrambles, END
BEGIN NOW All by himself and gathering brambles; END
BEGIN NOW Here is a tramp who stands and gazes; END
BEGIN NOW And here is the green for stringing the daisies! END
BEGIN NOW Here is a cart run away in the road END
BEGIN NOW Lumping along with man and load; END
BEGIN NOW And here is a mill, and there is a river: END
BEGIN NOW Each a glimpse and gone forever! END
BEGIN NOW Late lies the wintry sun a-bed, END
BEGIN NOW A frosty, fiery sleepy-head; END
BEGIN NOW Blinks but an hour or two; and then, END
BEGIN NOW A blood-red orange, sets again. END
BEGIN NOW Before the stars have left the skies, END
BEGIN NOW At morning in the dark I rise; END
BEGIN NOW And shivering in my nakedness, END
BEGIN NOW By the cold candle, bathe and dress. END
BEGIN NOW Close by the jolly fire I sit END
BEGIN NOW To warm my frozen bones a bit; END
BEGIN NOW Or with a reindeer-sled, explore END
BEGIN NOW The colder countries round the door. END
BEGIN NOW When to go out, my nurse doth wrap END
BEGIN NOW Me in my comforter and cap; END
BEGIN NOW The cold wind burns my face, and blows END
BEGIN NOW Its frosty pepper up my nose. END
BEGIN NOW Black are my steps on silver sod; END
BEGIN NOW Thick blows my frosty breath abroad; END
BEGIN NOW And tree and house, and hill and lake, END
BEGIN NOW Are frosted like a wedding cake. END
BEGIN NOW Through all the pleasant meadow-side END
BEGIN NOW The grass grew shoulder-high, END
BEGIN NOW Till the shining scythes went far and wide END
BEGIN NOW And cut it down to dry. END
BEGIN NOW Those green and sweetly smelling crops END
BEGIN NOW They led in waggons home; END
BEGIN NOW And they piled them here in mountain tops END
BEGIN NOW For mountaineers to roam. END
BEGIN NOW The mice that in these mountains dwell, END
BEGIN NOW No happier are than I! END
BEGIN NOW Oh, what a joy to clamber there, END
BEGIN NOW Oh, what a place for play, END
BEGIN NOW With the sweet, the dim, the dusty air, END
BEGIN NOW The happy hills of hay! END
BEGIN NOW The coach is at the door at last; END
BEGIN NOW The eager children, mounting fast END
BEGIN NOW And kissing hands, in chorus sing: END
BEGIN NOW Good-bye, good-bye, to everything! END
BEGIN NOW To house and garden, field and lawn, END
BEGIN NOW The meadow-gates we swang upon, END
BEGIN NOW To pump and stable, tree and swing, END
BEGIN NOW Good-bye, good-bye, to everything! END
BEGIN NOW And fare you well for evermore, END
BEGIN NOW O ladder at the hayloft door, END
BEGIN NOW O hayloft where the cobwebs cling, END
BEGIN NOW Good-bye, good-bye, to everything! END
BEGIN NOW Crack goes the whip, and off we go; END
BEGIN NOW The trees and houses smaller grow; END
BEGIN NOW Last, round the woody turn we sing: END
BEGIN NOW Good-bye, good-bye, to everything! END
BEGIN NOW When the bright lamp is carried in, END
BEGIN NOW The sunless hours again begin; END
BEGIN NOW O'er all without, in field and lane, END
BEGIN NOW The haunted night returns again. END
BEGIN NOW Now we behold the embers flee END
BEGIN NOW About the firelit hearth; and see END
BEGIN NOW Our faces painted as we pass, END
BEGIN NOW Like pictures, on the window glass. END
BEGIN NOW Must we to bed indeed? Well then, END
BEGIN NOW Let us arise and go like men, END
BEGIN NOW And face with an undaunted tread END
BEGIN NOW The long black passage up to bed. END
BEGIN NOW Farewell, O brother, sister, sire! END
BEGIN NOW O pleasant party round the fire! END
BEGIN NOW The songs you sing, the tales you tell, END
BEGIN NOW Till far to-morrow, fare you well! END
BEGIN NOW All around the house is the jet-black night; END
BEGIN NOW It stares through the window-pane; END
BEGIN NOW It crawls in the corners, hiding from the light, END
BEGIN NOW And it moves with the moving flame. END
BEGIN NOW Now my little heart goes a beating like a drum, END
BEGIN NOW With the breath of the Bogies in my hair; END
BEGIN NOW And all around the candle the crooked shadows come, END
BEGIN NOW And go marching along up the stair. END
BEGIN NOW The shadow of the balusters, the shadow of the lamp, END
BEGIN NOW The shadow of the child that goes to bed-- END
BEGIN NOW All the wicked shadows coming tramp, tramp, tramp, END
BEGIN NOW With the black night overhead. END
BEGIN NOW Last, to the chamber where I lie END
BEGIN NOW My fearful footsteps patter nigh, END
BEGIN NOW And come out from the cold and gloom END
BEGIN NOW Into my warm and cheerful room. END
BEGIN NOW There, safe arrived, we turn about END
BEGIN NOW To keep the coming shadows out, END
BEGIN NOW And close the happy door at last END
BEGIN NOW On all the perils that we past. END
BEGIN NOW Then, when mamma goes by to bed, END
BEGIN NOW She shall come in with tip-toe tread, END
BEGIN NOW And see me lying warm and fast END
BEGIN NOW And in the land of Nod at last. END
BEGIN NOW When children are playing alone on the green, END
BEGIN NOW In comes the playmate that never was seen. END
BEGIN NOW When children are happy and lonely and good, END
BEGIN NOW The Friend of the Children comes out of the wood. END
BEGIN NOW Nobody heard him, and nobody saw, END
BEGIN NOW His is a picture you never could draw, END
BEGIN NOW But he's sure to be present, abroad or at home, END
BEGIN NOW When children are happy and playing alone. END
BEGIN NOW He lies in the laurels, he runs on the grass, END
BEGIN NOW He sings when you tinkle the musical glass; END
BEGIN NOW Whene'er you are happy and cannot tell why, END
BEGIN NOW The Friend of the Children is sure to be by! END
BEGIN NOW He loves to be little, he hates to be big, END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis he that inhabits the caves that you dig; END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis he when you play with your soldiers of tin END
BEGIN NOW That sides with the Frenchmen and never can win. END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis he, when at night you go off to your bed, END
BEGIN NOW Bids you go to sleep and not trouble your head; END
BEGIN NOW For wherever they're lying, in cupboard or shelf, END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis he will take care of your playthings himself! END
BEGIN NOW O it's I that am the captain of a tidy little ship, END
BEGIN NOW Of a ship that goes a sailing on the pond; END
BEGIN NOW And my ship it keeps a-turning all around and all about; END
BEGIN NOW But when I'm a little older, I shall find the secret out END
BEGIN NOW How to send my vessel sailing on beyond. END
BEGIN NOW For I mean to grow as little as the dolly at the helm, END
BEGIN NOW And the dolly I intend to come alive; END
BEGIN NOW And with him beside to help me, it's a-sailing I shall go, END
BEGIN NOW It's a-sailing on the water, when the jolly breezes blow END
BEGIN NOW And the vessel goes a divie-divie-dive. END
BEGIN NOW For beside the dolly sailor, I'm to voyage and explore, END
BEGIN NOW To land upon the island where no dolly was before, END
BEGIN NOW And to fire the penny cannon in the bow. END
BEGIN NOW Down by a shining water well END
BEGIN NOW I found a very little dell, END
BEGIN NOW No higher than my head. END
BEGIN NOW The heather and the gorse about END
BEGIN NOW In summer bloom were coming out, END
BEGIN NOW Some yellow and some red. END
BEGIN NOW I called the little pool a sea; END
BEGIN NOW The little hills were big to me; END
BEGIN NOW For I am very small. END
BEGIN NOW I made a boat, I made a town, END
BEGIN NOW I searched the caverns up and down, END
BEGIN NOW And named them one and all. END
BEGIN NOW And all about was mine, I said, END
BEGIN NOW The little sparrows overhead, END
BEGIN NOW The little minnows too. END
BEGIN NOW This was the world and I was king; END
BEGIN NOW For me the bees came by to sing, END
BEGIN NOW For me the swallows flew. END
BEGIN NOW I played there were no deeper seas, END
BEGIN NOW Nor any wider plains than these, END
BEGIN NOW Nor other kings than me. END
BEGIN NOW At last I heard my mother call END
BEGIN NOW Out from the house at evenfall, END
BEGIN NOW To call me home to tea. END
BEGIN NOW And I must rise and leave my dell, END
BEGIN NOW And leave my dimpled water well, END
BEGIN NOW And leave my heather blooms. END
BEGIN NOW Alas! and as my home I neared, END
BEGIN NOW How very big my nurse appeared. END
BEGIN NOW How great and cool the rooms! END
BEGIN NOW Summer fading, winter comes-- END
BEGIN NOW Frosty mornings, tingling thumbs, END
BEGIN NOW Window robins, winter rooks, END
BEGIN NOW And the picture story-books. END
BEGIN NOW Water now is turned to stone END
BEGIN NOW Nurse and I can walk upon; END
BEGIN NOW Still we find the flowing brooks END
BEGIN NOW In the picture story-books. END
BEGIN NOW All the pretty things put by, END
BEGIN NOW Wait upon the children's eye, END
BEGIN NOW Sheep and shepherds, trees and crooks, END
BEGIN NOW In the picture story-books. END
BEGIN NOW We may see how all things are END
BEGIN NOW Seas and cities, near and far, END
BEGIN NOW And the flying fairies' looks, END
BEGIN NOW In the picture story-books. END
BEGIN NOW How am I to sing your praise, END
BEGIN NOW Happy chimney-corner days, END
BEGIN NOW Sitting safe in nursery nooks, END
BEGIN NOW Reading picture story-books? END
BEGIN NOW These nuts, that I keep in the back of the nest, END
BEGIN NOW Where all my tin soldiers are lying at rest, END
BEGIN NOW Were gathered in Autumn by nursie and me END
BEGIN NOW In a wood with a well by the side of the sea. END
BEGIN NOW This whistle we made (and how clearly it sounds!) END
BEGIN NOW By the side of a field at the end of the grounds. END
BEGIN NOW Of a branch of a plane, with a knife of my own, END
BEGIN NOW It was nursie who made it, and nursie alone! END
BEGIN NOW The stone, with the white and the yellow and grey, END
BEGIN NOW We discovered I cannot tell HOW far away; END
BEGIN NOW And I carried it back although weary and cold, END
BEGIN NOW For though father denies it, I'm sure it is gold. END
BEGIN NOW But of all my treasures the last is the king, END
BEGIN NOW For there's very few children possess such a thing; END
BEGIN NOW And that is a chisel, both handle and blade, END
BEGIN NOW Which a man who was really a carpenter made. END
BEGIN NOW What are you able to build with your blocks? END
BEGIN NOW Castles and palaces, temples and docks. END
BEGIN NOW Rain may keep raining, and others go roam, END
BEGIN NOW But I can be happy and building at home. END
BEGIN NOW Let the sofa be mountains, the carpet be sea, END
BEGIN NOW There I'll establish a city for me: END
BEGIN NOW A kirk and a mill and a palace beside, END
BEGIN NOW And a harbour as well where my vessels may ride. END
BEGIN NOW Great is the palace with pillar and wall, END
BEGIN NOW A sort of a tower on the top of it all, END
BEGIN NOW And steps coming down in an orderly way END
BEGIN NOW To where my toy vessels lie safe in the bay. END
BEGIN NOW This one is sailing and that one is moored: END
BEGIN NOW Hark to the song of the sailors aboard! END
BEGIN NOW And see, on the steps of my palace, the kings END
BEGIN NOW Coming and going with presents and things! END
BEGIN NOW Now I have done with it, down let it go! END
BEGIN NOW All in a moment the town is laid low. END
BEGIN NOW Block upon block lying scattered and free, END
BEGIN NOW What is there left of my town by the sea? END
BEGIN NOW Yet as I saw it, I see it again, END
BEGIN NOW The kirk and the palace, the ships and the men, END
BEGIN NOW And as long as I live and where'er I may be, END
BEGIN NOW I'll always remember my town by the sea. END
BEGIN NOW At evening when the lamp is lit, END
BEGIN NOW Around the fire my parents sit; END
BEGIN NOW They sit at home and talk and sing, END
BEGIN NOW And do not play at anything. END
BEGIN NOW Now, with my little gun, I crawl END
BEGIN NOW All in the dark along the wall, END
BEGIN NOW And follow round the forest track END
BEGIN NOW Away behind the sofa back. END
BEGIN NOW There, in the night, where none can spy, END
BEGIN NOW All in my hunter's camp I lie, END
BEGIN NOW And play at books that I have read END
BEGIN NOW Till it is time to go to bed. END
BEGIN NOW These are the hills, these are the woods, END
BEGIN NOW These are my starry solitudes; END
BEGIN NOW And there the river by whose brink END
BEGIN NOW The roaring lions come to drink. END
BEGIN NOW I see the others far away END
BEGIN NOW As if in firelit camp they lay, END
BEGIN NOW And I, like to an Indian scout, END
BEGIN NOW Around their party prowled about. END
BEGIN NOW So when my nurse comes in for me, END
BEGIN NOW Home I return across the sea, END
BEGIN NOW And go to bed with backward looks END
BEGIN NOW At my dear land of Story-books. END
BEGIN NOW The lamps now glitter down the street; END
BEGIN NOW Faintly sound the falling feet; END
BEGIN NOW And the blue even slowly falls END
BEGIN NOW About the garden trees and walls. END
BEGIN NOW Now in the falling of the gloom END
BEGIN NOW The red fire paints the empty room: END
BEGIN NOW And warmly on the roof it looks, END
BEGIN NOW And flickers on the back of books. END
BEGIN NOW Armies march by tower and spire END
BEGIN NOW Of cities blazing, in the fire;-- END
BEGIN NOW Till as I gaze with staring eyes, END
BEGIN NOW The armies fade, the lustre dies. END
BEGIN NOW Then once again the glow returns; END
BEGIN NOW Again the phantom city burns; END
BEGIN NOW And down the red-hot valley, lo! END
BEGIN NOW The phantom armies marching go! END
BEGIN NOW Blinking embers, tell me true END
BEGIN NOW Where are those armies marching to, END
BEGIN NOW And what the burning city is END
BEGIN NOW That crumbles in your furnaces! END
BEGIN NOW When at home alone I sit END
BEGIN NOW And am very tired of it, END
BEGIN NOW I have just to shut my eyes END
BEGIN NOW To go sailing through the skies-- END
BEGIN NOW To go sailing far away END
BEGIN NOW To the pleasant Land of Play; END
BEGIN NOW To the fairy land afar END
BEGIN NOW Where the Little People are; END
BEGIN NOW Where the clover-tops are trees, END
BEGIN NOW And the rain-pools are the seas, END
BEGIN NOW And the leaves, like little ships, END
BEGIN NOW Sail about on tiny trips; END
BEGIN NOW And above the Daisy tree END
BEGIN NOW Through the grasses, END
BEGIN NOW High o'erhead the Bumble Bee END
BEGIN NOW Hums and passes. END
BEGIN NOW In that forest to and fro END
BEGIN NOW I can wander, I can go; END
BEGIN NOW See the spider and the fly, END
BEGIN NOW And the ants go marching by, END
BEGIN NOW Carrying parcels with their feet END
BEGIN NOW Down the green and grassy street. END
BEGIN NOW I can in the sorrel sit END
BEGIN NOW Where the ladybird alit. END
BEGIN NOW I can climb the jointed grass END
BEGIN NOW And on high END
BEGIN NOW See the greater swallows pass END
BEGIN NOW In the sky, END
BEGIN NOW And the round sun rolling by END
BEGIN NOW Heeding no such things as I. END
BEGIN NOW Through that forest I can pass END
BEGIN NOW Till, as in a looking-glass, END
BEGIN NOW Humming fly and daisy tree END
BEGIN NOW And my tiny self I see, END
BEGIN NOW Painted very clear and neat END
BEGIN NOW On the rain-pool at my feet. END
BEGIN NOW Should a leaflet come to land END
BEGIN NOW Drifting near to where I stand, END
BEGIN NOW Straight I'll board that tiny boat END
BEGIN NOW Round the rain-pool sea to float. END
BEGIN NOW Little thoughtful creatures sit END
BEGIN NOW On the grassy coasts of it; END
BEGIN NOW Little things with lovely eyes END
BEGIN NOW See me sailing with surprise. END
BEGIN NOW Some are clad in armour green-- END
BEGIN NOW (These have sure to battle been!)-- END
BEGIN NOW Some are pied with ev'ry hue, END
BEGIN NOW Black and crimson, gold and blue; END
BEGIN NOW Some have wings and swift are gone;-- END
BEGIN NOW But they all look kindly on. END
BEGIN NOW When my eyes I once again END
BEGIN NOW Open, and see all things plain: END
BEGIN NOW High bare walls, great bare floor; END
BEGIN NOW Great big knobs on drawer and door; END
BEGIN NOW Great big people perched on chairs, END
BEGIN NOW Stitching tucks and mending tears, END
BEGIN NOW Each a hill that I could climb, END
BEGIN NOW And talking nonsense all the time-- END
BEGIN NOW O dear me, END
BEGIN NOW That I could be END
BEGIN NOW A sailor on a the rain-pool sea, END
BEGIN NOW A climber in the clover tree, END
BEGIN NOW And just come back a sleepy-head, END
BEGIN NOW Late at night to go to bed. END
BEGIN NOW When the golden day is done, END
BEGIN NOW Through the closing portal, END
BEGIN NOW Child and garden, flower and sun, END
BEGIN NOW Vanish all things mortal. END
BEGIN NOW As the building shadows fall END
BEGIN NOW As the rays diminish, END
BEGIN NOW Under evening's cloak they all END
BEGIN NOW Roll away and vanish. END
BEGIN NOW Garden darkened, daisy shut, END
BEGIN NOW Child in bed, they slumber-- END
BEGIN NOW Glow-worm in the hallway rut, END
BEGIN NOW Mice among the lumber. END
BEGIN NOW In the darkness houses shine, END
BEGIN NOW Parents move the candles; END
BEGIN NOW Till on all the night divine END
BEGIN NOW Turns the bedroom handles. END
BEGIN NOW Till at last the day begins END
BEGIN NOW In the east a-breaking, END
BEGIN NOW In the hedges and the whins END
BEGIN NOW Sleeping birds a-waking. END
BEGIN NOW In the darkness shapes of things, END
BEGIN NOW Houses, trees and hedges, END
BEGIN NOW Clearer grow; and sparrow's wings END
BEGIN NOW Beat on window ledges. END
BEGIN NOW These shall wake the yawning maid; END
BEGIN NOW She the door shall open-- END
BEGIN NOW Finding dew on garden glade END
BEGIN NOW And the morning broken. END
BEGIN NOW There my garden grows again END
BEGIN NOW Green and rosy painted, END
BEGIN NOW As at eve behind the pane END
BEGIN NOW From my eyes it fainted. END
BEGIN NOW Just as it was shut away, END
BEGIN NOW Toy-like, in the even, END
BEGIN NOW Here I see it glow with day END
BEGIN NOW Under glowing heaven. END
BEGIN NOW Every path and every plot, END
BEGIN NOW Every blush of roses, END
BEGIN NOW Every blue forget-me-not END
BEGIN NOW Where the dew reposes, END
BEGIN NOW Up! they cry, "the day is come END
BEGIN NOW On the smiling valleys: END
BEGIN NOW We have beat the morning drum; END
BEGIN NOW Playmate, join your allies! END
BEGIN NOW Birds all the sunny day END
BEGIN NOW Flutter and quarrel END
BEGIN NOW Here in the arbour-like END
BEGIN NOW Tent of the laurel. END
BEGIN NOW Here in the fork END
BEGIN NOW The brown nest is seated; END
BEGIN NOW Four little blue eggs END
BEGIN NOW The mother keeps heated. END
BEGIN NOW While we stand watching her END
BEGIN NOW Staring like gabies, END
BEGIN NOW Safe in each egg are the END
BEGIN NOW Bird's little babies. END
BEGIN NOW Soon the frail eggs they shall END
BEGIN NOW Chip, and upspringing END
BEGIN NOW Make all the April woods END
BEGIN NOW Merry with singing. END
BEGIN NOW Younger than we are, END
BEGIN NOW O children, and frailer, END
BEGIN NOW Soon in the blue air they'll be, END
BEGIN NOW Singer and sailor. END
BEGIN NOW We, so much older, END
BEGIN NOW Taller and stronger, END
BEGIN NOW We shall look down on the END
BEGIN NOW Birdies no longer. END
BEGIN NOW They shall go flying END
BEGIN NOW With musical speeches END
BEGIN NOW High overhead in the END
BEGIN NOW Tops of the beeches. END
BEGIN NOW In spite of our wisdom END
BEGIN NOW And sensible talking, END
BEGIN NOW We on our feet must go END
BEGIN NOW Plodding and walking. END
BEGIN NOW All the names I know from nurse: END
BEGIN NOW Gardener's garters, Shepherd's purse, END
BEGIN NOW Bachelor's buttons, Lady's smock, END
BEGIN NOW Fairy places, fairy things, END
BEGIN NOW Fairy woods where the wild bee wings, END
BEGIN NOW Tiny trees for tiny dames-- END
BEGIN NOW These must all be fairy names! END
BEGIN NOW Tiny woods below whose boughs END
BEGIN NOW Shady fairies weave a house; END
BEGIN NOW Tiny tree-tops, rose or thyme, END
BEGIN NOW Where the braver fairies climb! END
BEGIN NOW Fair are grown-up people's trees, END
BEGIN NOW But the fairest woods are these; END
BEGIN NOW Where, if I were not so tall, END
BEGIN NOW I should live for good and all. END
BEGIN NOW Great is the sun, and wide he goes END
BEGIN NOW Through empty heaven with repose; END
BEGIN NOW And in the blue and glowing days END
BEGIN NOW More thick than rain he showers his rays. END
BEGIN NOW Though closer still the blinds we pull END
BEGIN NOW To keep the shady parlour cool, END
BEGIN NOW To slip his golden fingers through. END
BEGIN NOW The dusty attic spider-clad END
BEGIN NOW He, through the keyhole, maketh glad; END
BEGIN NOW And through the broken edge of tiles END
BEGIN NOW Into the laddered hay-loft smiles. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime his golden face around END
BEGIN NOW He bares to all the garden ground, END
BEGIN NOW And sheds a warm and glittering look END
BEGIN NOW Among the ivy's inmost nook. END
BEGIN NOW Above the hills, along the blue, END
BEGIN NOW Round the bright air with footing true, END
BEGIN NOW To please the child, to paint the rose, END
BEGIN NOW The gardener of the World, he goes. END
BEGIN NOW When the grass was closely mown, END
BEGIN NOW Walking on the lawn alone, END
BEGIN NOW In the turf a hole I found, END
BEGIN NOW And hid a soldier underground. END
BEGIN NOW Spring and daisies came apace; END
BEGIN NOW Grasses hide my hiding place; END
BEGIN NOW Grasses run like a green sea END
BEGIN NOW O'er the lawn up to my knee. END
BEGIN NOW Under grass alone he lies, END
BEGIN NOW Looking up with leaden eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Scarlet coat and pointed gun, END
BEGIN NOW To the stars and to the sun. END
BEGIN NOW When the grass is ripe like grain, END
BEGIN NOW When the scythe is stoned again, END
BEGIN NOW When the lawn is shaven clear, END
BEGIN NOW Then my hole shall reappear. END
BEGIN NOW I shall find him, never fear, END
BEGIN NOW I shall find my grenadier; END
BEGIN NOW But for all that's gone and come, END
BEGIN NOW He has lived, a little thing, END
BEGIN NOW In the grassy woods of spring; END
BEGIN NOW Done, if he could tell me true, END
BEGIN NOW Just as I should like to do. END
BEGIN NOW He has seen the starry hours END
BEGIN NOW And the springing of the flowers; END
BEGIN NOW And the fairy things that pass END
BEGIN NOW In the forests of the grass. END
BEGIN NOW In the silence he has heard END
BEGIN NOW Talking bee and ladybird, END
BEGIN NOW And the butterfly has flown END
BEGIN NOW O'er him as he lay alone. END
BEGIN NOW Not a word will he disclose, END
BEGIN NOW Not a word of all he knows. END
BEGIN NOW I must lay him on the shelf, END
BEGIN NOW And make up the tale myself. END
BEGIN NOW In the other gardens END
BEGIN NOW And all up the vale, END
BEGIN NOW From the autumn bonfires END
BEGIN NOW See the smoke trail! END
BEGIN NOW Pleasant summer over END
BEGIN NOW And all the summer flowers, END
BEGIN NOW The red fire blazes, END
BEGIN NOW The grey smoke towers. END
BEGIN NOW Sing a song of seasons! END
BEGIN NOW Something bright in all! END
BEGIN NOW Flowers in the summer, END
BEGIN NOW Fires in the fall! END
BEGIN NOW The gardener does not love to talk. END
BEGIN NOW He makes me keep the gravel walk; END
BEGIN NOW And when he puts his tools away, END
BEGIN NOW He locks the door and takes the key. END
BEGIN NOW Away behind the currant row, END
BEGIN NOW Where no one else but cook may go, END
BEGIN NOW Far in the plots, I see him dig, END
BEGIN NOW Old and serious, brown and big. END
BEGIN NOW He digs the flowers, green, red, and blue, END
BEGIN NOW Nor wishes to be spoken to. END
BEGIN NOW He digs the flowers and cuts the hay, END
BEGIN NOW And never seems to want to play. END
BEGIN NOW Silly gardener! summer goes, END
BEGIN NOW And winter comes with pinching toes, END
BEGIN NOW When in the garden bare and brown END
BEGIN NOW You must lay your barrow down. END
BEGIN NOW Well now, and while the summer stays, END
BEGIN NOW To profit by these garden days END
BEGIN NOW O how much wiser you would be END
BEGIN NOW To play at Indian wars with me! END
BEGIN NOW Dear Uncle Jim, this garden ground END
BEGIN NOW That now you smoke your pipe around, END
BEGIN NOW Has seen immortal actions done END
BEGIN NOW And valiant battles lost and won. END
BEGIN NOW Here we had best on tip-toe tread, END
BEGIN NOW While I for safety march ahead, END
BEGIN NOW For this is that enchanted ground END
BEGIN NOW Where all who loiter slumber sound. END
BEGIN NOW Here is the sea, here is the sand, END
BEGIN NOW Here is simple Shepherd's Land, END
BEGIN NOW Here are the fairy hollyhocks, END
BEGIN NOW And there are Ali Baba's rocks. END
BEGIN NOW But yonder, see! apart and high, END
BEGIN NOW Frozen Siberia lies; where I, END
BEGIN NOW Was bound by an enchanter's spell. END
BEGIN NOW If two may read aright END
BEGIN NOW These rhymes of old delight END
BEGIN NOW And house and garden play, END
BEGIN NOW You two, my cousins, and you only, may. END
BEGIN NOW You in a garden green END
BEGIN NOW With me were king and queen, END
BEGIN NOW Were hunter, soldier, tar, END
BEGIN NOW And all the thousand things that children are. END
BEGIN NOW Now in the elders' seat END
BEGIN NOW We rest with quiet feet, END
BEGIN NOW And from the window-bay END
BEGIN NOW We watch the children, our successors, play. END
BEGIN NOW Time was," the golden head END
BEGIN NOW Irrevocably said; END
BEGIN NOW But time which one can bind, END
BEGIN NOW While flowing fast away, leaves love behind. END
BEGIN NOW You too, my mother, read my rhymes END
BEGIN NOW For love of unforgotten times, END
BEGIN NOW And you may chance to hear once more END
BEGIN NOW The little feet along the floor. END
BEGIN NOW Chief of our aunts"--not only I, END
BEGIN NOW But all your dozen of nurselings cry-- END
BEGIN NOW What did the other children do? END
BEGIN NOW And what were childhood, wanting you? END
BEGIN NOW The red room with the giant bed END
BEGIN NOW Where none but elders laid their head; END
BEGIN NOW The little room where you and I END
BEGIN NOW Did for awhile together lie END
BEGIN NOW And, simple suitor, I your hand END
BEGIN NOW In decent marriage did demand; END
BEGIN NOW The great day nursery, best of all, END
BEGIN NOW With pictures pasted on the wall END
BEGIN NOW And leaves upon the blind-- END
BEGIN NOW A pleasant room wherein to wake END
BEGIN NOW And hear the leafy garden shake END
BEGIN NOW And rustle in the wind-- END
BEGIN NOW And pleasant there to lie in bed END
BEGIN NOW And see the pictures overhead-- END
BEGIN NOW The wars about Sebastopol, END
BEGIN NOW The grinning guns along the wall, END
BEGIN NOW The daring escalade, END
BEGIN NOW The plunging ships, the bleating sheep, END
BEGIN NOW The happy children ankle-deep END
BEGIN NOW And laughing as they wade: END
BEGIN NOW All these are vanished clean away, END
BEGIN NOW And the old manse is changed to-day; END
BEGIN NOW It wears an altered face END
BEGIN NOW And shields a stranger race. END
BEGIN NOW The river, on from mill to mill, END
BEGIN NOW Flows past our childhood's garden still; END
BEGIN NOW But ah! we children never more END
BEGIN NOW Shall watch it from the water-door! END
BEGIN NOW Below the yew--it still is there-- END
BEGIN NOW Our phantom voices haunt the air END
BEGIN NOW As we were still at play, END
BEGIN NOW And I can hear them call and say: END
BEGIN NOW Ah, far enough, my dear, END
BEGIN NOW Far, far enough from here-- END
BEGIN NOW Yet you have farther gone! END
BEGIN NOW Can I get there by candlelight? END
BEGIN NOW So goes the old refrain. END
BEGIN NOW I do not know--perchance you might-- END
BEGIN NOW But only, children, hear it right, END
BEGIN NOW Ah, never to return again! END
BEGIN NOW The eternal dawn, beyond a doubt, END
BEGIN NOW Shall break on hill and plain, END
BEGIN NOW And put all stars and candles out END
BEGIN NOW Ere we be young again. END
BEGIN NOW To you in distant India, these END
BEGIN NOW I send across the seas, END
BEGIN NOW Nor count it far across. END
BEGIN NOW For which of us forgets END
BEGIN NOW The Indian cabinets, END
BEGIN NOW The bones of antelope, the wings of albatross, END
BEGIN NOW The pied and painted birds and beans, END
BEGIN NOW The junks and bangles, beads and screens, END
BEGIN NOW The gods and sacred bells, END
BEGIN NOW And the loud-humming, twisted shells! END
BEGIN NOW The level of the parlour floor END
BEGIN NOW Was honest, homely, Scottish shore; END
BEGIN NOW But when we climbed upon a chair, END
BEGIN NOW Behold the gorgeous East was there! END
BEGIN NOW Be this a fable; and behold END
BEGIN NOW Me in the parlour as of old, END
BEGIN NOW And Minnie just above me set END
BEGIN NOW In the quaint Indian cabinet! END
BEGIN NOW Smiling and kind, you grace a shelf END
BEGIN NOW Too high for me to reach myself. END
BEGIN NOW Reach down a hand, my dear, and take END
BEGIN NOW These rhymes for old acquaintance' sake! END
BEGIN NOW Then you shall discover, that your name was printed down END
BEGIN NOW By the English printers, long before, in London town. END
BEGIN NOW In the great and busy city where the East and West are met, END
BEGIN NOW All the little letters did the English printer set; END
BEGIN NOW While you thought of nothing, and were still too young to play, END
BEGIN NOW Foreign people thought of you in places far away. END
BEGIN NOW Ay, and when you slept, a baby, over all the English lands END
BEGIN NOW Other little children took the volume in their hands; END
BEGIN NOW Other children questioned, in their homes across the seas: END
BEGIN NOW Who was little Louis, won't you tell us, mother, please? END
BEGIN NOW Now that you have spelt your lesson, lay it down and go and play, END
BEGIN NOW Watching all the mighty whalebones, lying buried by the breeze, END
BEGIN NOW Tiny sandy-pipers, and the huge Pacific seas. END
BEGIN NOW And remember in your playing, as the sea-fog rolls to you, END
BEGIN NOW Long ere you could read it, how I told you what to do; END
BEGIN NOW And that while you thought of no one, nearly half the world away END
BEGIN NOW Some one thought of Louis on the beach of Monterey! END
BEGIN NOW As from the house your mother sees END
BEGIN NOW You playing round the garden trees, END
BEGIN NOW So you may see, if you will look END
BEGIN NOW Through the windows of this book, END
BEGIN NOW Another child, far, far away, END
BEGIN NOW And in another garden, play. END
BEGIN NOW But do not think you can at all, END
BEGIN NOW By knocking on the window, call END
BEGIN NOW That child to hear you. He intent END
BEGIN NOW Is all on his play-business bent. END
BEGIN NOW He does not hear, he will not look, END
BEGIN NOW Nor yet be lured out of this book. END
BEGIN NOW For, long ago, the truth to say, END
BEGIN NOW He has grown up and gone away, END
BEGIN NOW And it is but a child of air END
BEGIN NOW That lingers in the garden there. END
BEGIN NOW It is an ancient Mariner, END
BEGIN NOW And he stoppeth one of three. END
BEGIN NOW By thy long grey beard and glittering eye, END
BEGIN NOW Now wherefore stopp'st thou me? END
BEGIN NOW The Bridegroom's doors are opened wide, END
BEGIN NOW And I am next of kin; END
BEGIN NOW The guests are met, the feast is set: END
BEGIN NOW May'st hear the merry din. END
BEGIN NOW He holds him with his skinny hand, END
BEGIN NOW There was a ship," quoth he. END
BEGIN NOW Hold off! unhand me, grey-beard loon! END
BEGIN NOW Eftsoons his hand dropt he. END
BEGIN NOW He holds him with his glittering eye-- END
BEGIN NOW The Wedding-Guest stood still, END
BEGIN NOW And listens like a three years child: END
BEGIN NOW The Mariner hath his will. END
BEGIN NOW The Wedding-Guest sat on a stone: END
BEGIN NOW He cannot chuse but hear; END
BEGIN NOW And thus spake on that ancient man, END
BEGIN NOW The bright-eyed Mariner. END
BEGIN NOW The ship was cheered, the harbour cleared, END
BEGIN NOW Merrily did we drop END
BEGIN NOW Below the kirk, below the hill, END
BEGIN NOW Below the light-house top. END
BEGIN NOW The Sun came up upon the left, END
BEGIN NOW Out of the sea came he! END
BEGIN NOW And he shone bright, and on the right END
BEGIN NOW Went down into the sea. END
BEGIN NOW Higher and higher every day, END
BEGIN NOW Till over the mast at noon-- END
BEGIN NOW The Wedding-Guest here beat his breast, END
BEGIN NOW For he heard the loud bassoon. END
BEGIN NOW The bride hath paced into the hall, END
BEGIN NOW Red as a rose is she; END
BEGIN NOW Nodding their heads before her goes END
BEGIN NOW The merry minstrelsy. END
BEGIN NOW The Wedding-Guest he beat his breast, END
BEGIN NOW Yet he cannot chuse but hear; END
BEGIN NOW And thus spake on that ancient man, END
BEGIN NOW The bright-eyed Mariner. END
BEGIN NOW And now the STORM-BLAST came, and he END
BEGIN NOW Was tyrannous and strong: END
BEGIN NOW He struck with his o'ertaking wings, END
BEGIN NOW And chased south along. END
BEGIN NOW With sloping masts and dipping prow, END
BEGIN NOW As who pursued with yell and blow END
BEGIN NOW Still treads the shadow of his foe END
BEGIN NOW And forward bends his head, END
BEGIN NOW The ship drove fast, loud roared the blast, END
BEGIN NOW And southward aye we fled. END
BEGIN NOW And now there came both mist and snow, END
BEGIN NOW And it grew wondrous cold: END
BEGIN NOW And ice, mast-high, came floating by, END
BEGIN NOW As green as emerald. END
BEGIN NOW And through the drifts the snowy clifts END
BEGIN NOW Did send a dismal sheen: END
BEGIN NOW Nor shapes of men nor beasts we ken-- END
BEGIN NOW The ice was all between. END
BEGIN NOW The ice was here, the ice was there, END
BEGIN NOW The ice was all around: END
BEGIN NOW It cracked and growled, and roared and howled, END
BEGIN NOW Like noises in a swound! END
BEGIN NOW At length did cross an Albatross: END
BEGIN NOW Thorough the fog it came; END
BEGIN NOW As if it had been a Christian soul, END
BEGIN NOW We hailed it in God's name. END
BEGIN NOW It ate the food it ne'er had eat, END
BEGIN NOW And round and round it flew. END
BEGIN NOW The ice did split with a thunder-fit; END
BEGIN NOW The helmsman steered us through! END
BEGIN NOW And a good south wind sprung up behind; END
BEGIN NOW The Albatross did follow, END
BEGIN NOW And every day, for food or play, END
BEGIN NOW Came to the mariners' hollo! END
BEGIN NOW In mist or cloud, on mast or shroud, END
BEGIN NOW It perched for vespers nine; END
BEGIN NOW Whiles all the night, through fog-smoke white, END
BEGIN NOW Glimmered the white Moon-shine. END
BEGIN NOW God save thee, ancient Mariner! END
BEGIN NOW From the fiends, that plague thee thus!-- END
BEGIN NOW Why look'st thou so?"--With my cross-bow END
BEGIN NOW I shot the ALBATROSS. END
BEGIN NOW The Sun now rose upon the right: END
BEGIN NOW Out of the sea came he, END
BEGIN NOW Still hid in mist, and on the left END
BEGIN NOW Went down into the sea. END
BEGIN NOW And the good south wind still blew behind END
BEGIN NOW But no sweet bird did follow, END
BEGIN NOW Nor any day for food or play END
BEGIN NOW Came to the mariners' hollo! END
BEGIN NOW And I had done an hellish thing, END
BEGIN NOW And it would work 'em woe: END
BEGIN NOW For all averred, I had killed the bird END
BEGIN NOW That made the breeze to blow. END
BEGIN NOW Ah wretch! said they, the bird to slay END
BEGIN NOW That made the breeze to blow! END
BEGIN NOW Nor dim nor red, like God's own head, END
BEGIN NOW The glorious Sun uprist: END
BEGIN NOW Then all averred, I had killed the bird END
BEGIN NOW That brought the fog and mist. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas right, said they, such birds to slay, END
BEGIN NOW That bring the fog and mist. END
BEGIN NOW The fair breeze blew, the white foam flew, END
BEGIN NOW The furrow followed free: END
BEGIN NOW We were the first that ever burst END
BEGIN NOW Into that silent sea. END
BEGIN NOW Down dropt the breeze, the sails dropt down, END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas sad as sad could be; END
BEGIN NOW And we did speak only to break END
BEGIN NOW The silence of the sea! END
BEGIN NOW All in a hot and copper sky, END
BEGIN NOW The bloody Sun, at noon, END
BEGIN NOW Right up above the mast did stand, END
BEGIN NOW No bigger than the Moon. END
BEGIN NOW Day after day, day after day, END
BEGIN NOW We stuck, nor breath nor motion; END
BEGIN NOW As idle as a painted ship END
BEGIN NOW Upon a painted ocean. END
BEGIN NOW Water, water, every where, END
BEGIN NOW And all the boards did shrink; END
BEGIN NOW Water, water, every where, END
BEGIN NOW Nor any drop to drink. END
BEGIN NOW The very deep did rot: O Christ! END
BEGIN NOW That ever this should be! END
BEGIN NOW Yea, slimy things did crawl with legs END
BEGIN NOW Upon the slimy sea. END
BEGIN NOW About, about, in reel and rout END
BEGIN NOW The death-fires danced at night; END
BEGIN NOW The water, like a witch's oils, END
BEGIN NOW Burnt green, and blue and white. END
BEGIN NOW And some in dreams assured were END
BEGIN NOW Of the spirit that plagued us so: END
BEGIN NOW Nine fathom deep he had followed us END
BEGIN NOW From the land of mist and snow. END
BEGIN NOW And every tongue, through utter drought, END
BEGIN NOW Was withered at the root; END
BEGIN NOW We could not speak, no more than if END
BEGIN NOW We had been choked with soot. END
BEGIN NOW Ah! well a-day! what evil looks END
BEGIN NOW Had I from old and young! END
BEGIN NOW Instead of the cross, the Albatross END
BEGIN NOW About my neck was hung. END
BEGIN NOW There passed a weary time. Each throat END
BEGIN NOW Was parched, and glazed each eye. END
BEGIN NOW A weary time! a weary time! END
BEGIN NOW How glazed each weary eye, END
BEGIN NOW When looking westward, I beheld END
BEGIN NOW A something in the sky. END
BEGIN NOW At first it seemed a little speck, END
BEGIN NOW And then it seemed a mist: END
BEGIN NOW It moved and moved, and took at last END
BEGIN NOW A certain shape, I wist. END
BEGIN NOW A speck, a mist, a shape, I wist! END
BEGIN NOW And still it neared and neared: END
BEGIN NOW As if it dodged a water-sprite, END
BEGIN NOW It plunged and tacked and veered. END
BEGIN NOW With throats unslaked, with black lips baked, END
BEGIN NOW We could not laugh nor wail; END
BEGIN NOW I bit my arm, I sucked the blood, END
BEGIN NOW And cried, A sail! a sail! END
BEGIN NOW With throats unslaked, with black lips baked, END
BEGIN NOW Agape they heard me call: END
BEGIN NOW Gramercy! they for joy did grin, END
BEGIN NOW And all at once their breath drew in, END
BEGIN NOW As they were drinking all. END
BEGIN NOW See! see! (I cried) she tacks no more! END
BEGIN NOW Hither to work us weal; END
BEGIN NOW Without a breeze, without a tide, END
BEGIN NOW She steadies with upright keel! END
BEGIN NOW The western wave was all a-flame END
BEGIN NOW The day was well nigh done! END
BEGIN NOW Almost upon the western wave END
BEGIN NOW Rested the broad bright Sun; END
BEGIN NOW When that strange shape drove suddenly END
BEGIN NOW And straight the Sun was flecked with bars, END
BEGIN NOW (Heaven's Mother send us grace!) END
BEGIN NOW As if through a dungeon-grate he peered, END
BEGIN NOW With broad and burning face. END
BEGIN NOW Alas! (thought I, and my heart beat loud) END
BEGIN NOW How fast she nears and nears! END
BEGIN NOW Are those her sails that glance in the Sun, END
BEGIN NOW Like restless gossameres! END
BEGIN NOW Are those her ribs through which the Sun END
BEGIN NOW Did peer, as through a grate? END
BEGIN NOW And is that Woman all her crew? END
BEGIN NOW Is that a DEATH? and are there two? END
BEGIN NOW Is DEATH that woman's mate? END
BEGIN NOW Her lips were red, her looks were free, END
BEGIN NOW Her locks were yellow as gold: END
BEGIN NOW Her skin was as white as leprosy, END
BEGIN NOW The Night-Mare LIFE-IN-DEATH was she, END
BEGIN NOW Who thicks man's blood with cold. END
BEGIN NOW The naked hulk alongside came, END
BEGIN NOW And the twain were casting dice; END
BEGIN NOW The game is done! I've won! I've won! END
BEGIN NOW Quoth she, and whistles thrice. END
BEGIN NOW The Sun's rim dips; the stars rush out: END
BEGIN NOW At one stride comes the dark; END
BEGIN NOW With far-heard whisper, o'er the sea. END
BEGIN NOW Off shot the spectre-bark. END
BEGIN NOW We listened and looked sideways up! END
BEGIN NOW Fear at my heart, as at a cup, END
BEGIN NOW My life-blood seemed to sip! END
BEGIN NOW The stars were dim, and thick the night, END
BEGIN NOW The steersman's face by his lamp gleamed white; END
BEGIN NOW From the sails the dew did drip-- END
BEGIN NOW Till clombe above the eastern bar END
BEGIN NOW The horned Moon, with one bright star END
BEGIN NOW Within the nether tip. END
BEGIN NOW One after one, by the star-dogged Moon END
BEGIN NOW Too quick for groan or sigh, END
BEGIN NOW Each turned his face with a ghastly pang, END
BEGIN NOW And cursed me with his eye. END
BEGIN NOW Four times fifty living men, END
BEGIN NOW (And I heard nor sigh nor groan) END
BEGIN NOW With heavy thump, a lifeless lump, END
BEGIN NOW They dropped down one by one. END
BEGIN NOW The souls did from their bodies fly,-- END
BEGIN NOW They fled to bliss or woe! END
BEGIN NOW And every soul, it passed me by, END
BEGIN NOW Like the whizz of my CROSS-BOW! END
BEGIN NOW I fear thee, ancient Mariner! END
BEGIN NOW I fear thy skinny hand! END
BEGIN NOW And thou art long, and lank, and brown, END
BEGIN NOW As is the ribbed sea-sand. END
BEGIN NOW I fear thee and thy glittering eye, END
BEGIN NOW And thy skinny hand, so brown."-- END
BEGIN NOW Fear not, fear not, thou Wedding-Guest! END
BEGIN NOW This body dropt not down. END
BEGIN NOW Alone, alone, all, all alone, END
BEGIN NOW Alone on a wide wide sea! END
BEGIN NOW And never a saint took pity on END
BEGIN NOW My soul in agony. END
BEGIN NOW The many men, so beautiful! END
BEGIN NOW And they all dead did lie: END
BEGIN NOW And a thousand thousand slimy things END
BEGIN NOW I looked upon the rotting sea, END
BEGIN NOW And drew my eyes away; END
BEGIN NOW I looked upon the rotting deck, END
BEGIN NOW And there the dead men lay. END
BEGIN NOW I looked to Heaven, and tried to pray: END
BEGIN NOW But or ever a prayer had gusht, END
BEGIN NOW A wicked whisper came, and made END
BEGIN NOW my heart as dry as dust. END
BEGIN NOW I closed my lids, and kept them close, END
BEGIN NOW And the balls like pulses beat; END
BEGIN NOW For the sky and the sea, and the sea and the sky END
BEGIN NOW Lay like a load on my weary eye, END
BEGIN NOW And the dead were at my feet. END
BEGIN NOW The cold sweat melted from their limbs, END
BEGIN NOW Nor rot nor reek did they: END
BEGIN NOW The look with which they looked on me END
BEGIN NOW Had never passed away. END
BEGIN NOW An orphan's curse would drag to Hell END
BEGIN NOW A spirit from on high; END
BEGIN NOW But oh! more horrible than that END
BEGIN NOW Is a curse in a dead man's eye! END
BEGIN NOW Seven days, seven nights, I saw that curse, END
BEGIN NOW And yet I could not die. END
BEGIN NOW The moving Moon went up the sky, END
BEGIN NOW And no where did abide: END
BEGIN NOW Softly she was going up, END
BEGIN NOW And a star or two beside. END
BEGIN NOW Her beams bemocked the sultry main, END
BEGIN NOW Like April hoar-frost spread; END
BEGIN NOW But where the ship's huge shadow lay, END
BEGIN NOW The charmed water burnt alway END
BEGIN NOW A still and awful red. END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the shadow of the ship, END
BEGIN NOW I watched the water-snakes: END
BEGIN NOW They moved in tracks of shining white, END
BEGIN NOW And when they reared, the elfish light END
BEGIN NOW Fell off in hoary flakes. END
BEGIN NOW Within the shadow of the ship END
BEGIN NOW I watched their rich attire: END
BEGIN NOW Blue, glossy green, and velvet black, END
BEGIN NOW They coiled and swam; and every track END
BEGIN NOW Was a flash of golden fire. END
BEGIN NOW O happy living things! no tongue END
BEGIN NOW Their beauty might declare: END
BEGIN NOW A spring of love gushed from my heart, END
BEGIN NOW And I blessed them unaware: END
BEGIN NOW Sure my kind saint took pity on me, END
BEGIN NOW And I blessed them unaware. END
BEGIN NOW The self same moment I could pray; END
BEGIN NOW And from my neck so free END
BEGIN NOW The Albatross fell off, and sank END
BEGIN NOW Like lead into the sea. END
BEGIN NOW Oh sleep! it is a gentle thing, END
BEGIN NOW Beloved from pole to pole! END
BEGIN NOW To Mary Queen the praise be given! END
BEGIN NOW She sent the gentle sleep from Heaven, END
BEGIN NOW That slid into my soul. END
BEGIN NOW The silly buckets on the deck, END
BEGIN NOW That had so long remained, END
BEGIN NOW I dreamt that they were filled with dew; END
BEGIN NOW And when I awoke, it rained. END
BEGIN NOW My lips were wet, my throat was cold, END
BEGIN NOW My garments all were dank; END
BEGIN NOW Sure I had drunken in my dreams, END
BEGIN NOW And still my body drank. END
BEGIN NOW I moved, and could not feel my limbs: END
BEGIN NOW I was so light--almost END
BEGIN NOW I thought that I had died in sleep, END
BEGIN NOW And was a blessed ghost. END
BEGIN NOW And soon I heard a roaring wind: END
BEGIN NOW It did not come anear; END
BEGIN NOW But with its sound it shook the sails, END
BEGIN NOW That were so thin and sere. END
BEGIN NOW The upper air burst into life! END
BEGIN NOW And a hundred fire-flags sheen, END
BEGIN NOW To and fro they were hurried about! END
BEGIN NOW And to and fro, and in and out, END
BEGIN NOW The wan stars danced between. END
BEGIN NOW And the coming wind did roar more loud, END
BEGIN NOW And the sails did sigh like sedge; END
BEGIN NOW And the rain poured down from one black cloud; END
BEGIN NOW The Moon was at its edge. END
BEGIN NOW The thick black cloud was cleft, and still END
BEGIN NOW The Moon was at its side: END
BEGIN NOW Like waters shot from some high crag, END
BEGIN NOW The lightning fell with never a jag, END
BEGIN NOW A river steep and wide. END
BEGIN NOW The loud wind never reached the ship, END
BEGIN NOW Yet now the ship moved on! END
BEGIN NOW Beneath the lightning and the Moon END
BEGIN NOW The dead men gave a groan. END
BEGIN NOW They groaned, they stirred, they all uprose, END
BEGIN NOW Nor spake, nor moved their eyes; END
BEGIN NOW It had been strange, even in a dream, END
BEGIN NOW To have seen those dead men rise. END
BEGIN NOW The helmsman steered, the ship moved on; END
BEGIN NOW Yet never a breeze up blew; END
BEGIN NOW The mariners all 'gan work the ropes, END
BEGIN NOW Where they were wont to do: END
BEGIN NOW They raised their limbs like lifeless tools-- END
BEGIN NOW We were a ghastly crew. END
BEGIN NOW The body of my brother's son, END
BEGIN NOW Stood by me, knee to knee: END
BEGIN NOW The body and I pulled at one rope, END
BEGIN NOW But he said nought to me. END
BEGIN NOW I fear thee, ancient Mariner! END
BEGIN NOW Be calm, thou Wedding-Guest! END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas not those souls that fled in pain, END
BEGIN NOW Which to their corses came again, END
BEGIN NOW But a troop of spirits blest: END
BEGIN NOW For when it dawned--they dropped their arms, END
BEGIN NOW And clustered round the mast; END
BEGIN NOW Sweet sounds rose slowly through their mouths, END
BEGIN NOW And from their bodies passed. END
BEGIN NOW Around, around, flew each sweet sound, END
BEGIN NOW Then darted to the Sun; END
BEGIN NOW Slowly the sounds came back again, END
BEGIN NOW Now mixed, now one by one. END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes a-dropping from the sky END
BEGIN NOW I heard the sky-lark sing; END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes all little birds that are, END
BEGIN NOW How they seemed to fill the sea and air END
BEGIN NOW With their sweet jargoning! END
BEGIN NOW And now 'twas like all instruments, END
BEGIN NOW Now like a lonely flute; END
BEGIN NOW And now it is an angel's song, END
BEGIN NOW That makes the Heavens be mute. END
BEGIN NOW It ceased; yet still the sails made on END
BEGIN NOW A pleasant noise till noon, END
BEGIN NOW A noise like of a hidden brook END
BEGIN NOW In the leafy month of June, END
BEGIN NOW That to the sleeping woods all night END
BEGIN NOW Singeth a quiet tune. END
BEGIN NOW Till noon we quietly sailed on, END
BEGIN NOW Yet never a breeze did breathe: END
BEGIN NOW Slowly and smoothly went the ship, END
BEGIN NOW Moved onward from beneath. END
BEGIN NOW Under the keel nine fathom deep, END
BEGIN NOW From the land of mist and snow, END
BEGIN NOW The spirit slid: and it was he END
BEGIN NOW That made the ship to go. END
BEGIN NOW The sails at noon left off their tune, END
BEGIN NOW And the ship stood still also. END
BEGIN NOW The Sun, right up above the mast, END
BEGIN NOW Had fixed her to the ocean: END
BEGIN NOW But in a minute she 'gan stir, END
BEGIN NOW With a short uneasy motion-- END
BEGIN NOW Backwards and forwards half her length END
BEGIN NOW With a short uneasy motion. END
BEGIN NOW Then like a pawing horse let go, END
BEGIN NOW She made a sudden bound: END
BEGIN NOW It flung the blood into my head, END
BEGIN NOW And I fell down in a swound. END
BEGIN NOW How long in that same fit I lay, END
BEGIN NOW I have not to declare; END
BEGIN NOW But ere my living life returned, END
BEGIN NOW I heard and in my soul discerned END
BEGIN NOW Two VOICES in the air. END
BEGIN NOW Is it he?" quoth one, "Is this the man? END
BEGIN NOW By him who died on cross, END
BEGIN NOW With his cruel bow he laid full low, END
BEGIN NOW The harmless Albatross. END
BEGIN NOW The spirit who bideth by himself END
BEGIN NOW In the land of mist and snow, END
BEGIN NOW He loved the bird that loved the man END
BEGIN NOW Who shot him with his bow. END
BEGIN NOW The other was a softer voice, END
BEGIN NOW As soft as honey-dew: END
BEGIN NOW Quoth he, "The man hath penance done, END
BEGIN NOW And penance more will do. END
BEGIN NOW But tell me, tell me! speak again, END
BEGIN NOW Thy soft response renewing-- END
BEGIN NOW What makes that ship drive on so fast? END
BEGIN NOW What is the OCEAN doing? END
BEGIN NOW Still as a slave before his lord, END
BEGIN NOW The OCEAN hath no blast; END
BEGIN NOW His great bright eye most silently END
BEGIN NOW Up to the Moon is cast-- END
BEGIN NOW If he may know which way to go; END
BEGIN NOW For she guides him smooth or grim END
BEGIN NOW See, brother, see! how graciously END
BEGIN NOW She looketh down on him. END
BEGIN NOW But why drives on that ship so fast, END
BEGIN NOW Without or wave or wind? END
BEGIN NOW The air is cut away before, END
BEGIN NOW And closes from behind. END
BEGIN NOW Fly, brother, fly! more high, more high END
BEGIN NOW Or we shall be belated: END
BEGIN NOW For slow and slow that ship will go, END
BEGIN NOW When the Mariner's trance is abated. END
BEGIN NOW I woke, and we were sailing on END
BEGIN NOW As in a gentle weather: END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas night, calm night, the Moon was high; END
BEGIN NOW The dead men stood together. END
BEGIN NOW All stood together on the deck, END
BEGIN NOW For a charnel-dungeon fitter: END
BEGIN NOW All fixed on me their stony eyes, END
BEGIN NOW That in the Moon did glitter. END
BEGIN NOW The pang, the curse, with which they died, END
BEGIN NOW Had never passed away: END
BEGIN NOW I could not draw my eyes from theirs, END
BEGIN NOW Nor turn them up to pray. END
BEGIN NOW And now this spell was snapt: once more END
BEGIN NOW I viewed the ocean green. END
BEGIN NOW And looked far forth, yet little saw END
BEGIN NOW Of what had else been seen-- END
BEGIN NOW Like one that on a lonesome road END
BEGIN NOW Doth walk in fear and dread, END
BEGIN NOW And having once turned round walks on, END
BEGIN NOW And turns no more his head; END
BEGIN NOW Because he knows, a frightful fiend END
BEGIN NOW Doth close behind him tread. END
BEGIN NOW But soon there breathed a wind on me, END
BEGIN NOW Nor sound nor motion made: END
BEGIN NOW Its path was not upon the sea, END
BEGIN NOW In ripple or in shade. END
BEGIN NOW It raised my hair, it fanned my cheek END
BEGIN NOW Like a meadow-gale of spring-- END
BEGIN NOW It mingled strangely with my fears, END
BEGIN NOW Yet it felt like a welcoming. END
BEGIN NOW Swiftly, swiftly flew the ship, END
BEGIN NOW Yet she sailed softly too: END
BEGIN NOW Sweetly, sweetly blew the breeze-- END
BEGIN NOW On me alone it blew. END
BEGIN NOW Oh! dream of joy! is this indeed END
BEGIN NOW The light-house top I see? END
BEGIN NOW Is this the hill? is this the kirk? END
BEGIN NOW Is this mine own countree! END
BEGIN NOW We drifted o'er the harbour-bar, END
BEGIN NOW And I with sobs did pray-- END
BEGIN NOW O let me be awake, my God! END
BEGIN NOW Or let me sleep alway. END
BEGIN NOW The harbour-bay was clear as glass, END
BEGIN NOW So smoothly it was strewn! END
BEGIN NOW And on the bay the moonlight lay, END
BEGIN NOW And the shadow of the moon. END
BEGIN NOW The rock shone bright, the kirk no less, END
BEGIN NOW That stands above the rock: END
BEGIN NOW The moonlight steeped in silentness END
BEGIN NOW The steady weathercock. END
BEGIN NOW And the bay was white with silent light, END
BEGIN NOW Till rising from the same, END
BEGIN NOW Full many shapes, that shadows were, END
BEGIN NOW In crimson colours came. END
BEGIN NOW A little distance from the prow END
BEGIN NOW Those crimson shadows were: END
BEGIN NOW I turned my eyes upon the deck-- END
BEGIN NOW Oh, Christ! what saw I there! END
BEGIN NOW Each corse lay flat, lifeless and flat, END
BEGIN NOW And, by the holy rood! END
BEGIN NOW A man all light, a seraph-man, END
BEGIN NOW On every corse there stood. END
BEGIN NOW This seraph band, each waved his hand: END
BEGIN NOW It was a heavenly sight! END
BEGIN NOW They stood as signals to the land, END
BEGIN NOW Each one a lovely light: END
BEGIN NOW This seraph-band, each waved his hand, END
BEGIN NOW No voice did they impart-- END
BEGIN NOW No voice; but oh! the silence sank END
BEGIN NOW Like music on my heart. END
BEGIN NOW But soon I heard the dash of oars; END
BEGIN NOW I heard the Pilot's cheer; END
BEGIN NOW My head was turned perforce away, END
BEGIN NOW And I saw a boat appear. END
BEGIN NOW The Pilot, and the Pilot's boy, END
BEGIN NOW I heard them coming fast: END
BEGIN NOW The dead men could not blast. END
BEGIN NOW I saw a third--I heard his voice: END
BEGIN NOW It is the Hermit good! END
BEGIN NOW He singeth loud his godly hymns END
BEGIN NOW That he makes in the wood. END
BEGIN NOW He'll shrieve my soul, he'll wash away END
BEGIN NOW The Albatross's blood. END
BEGIN NOW This Hermit good lives in that wood END
BEGIN NOW Which slopes down to the sea. END
BEGIN NOW How loudly his sweet voice he rears! END
BEGIN NOW He loves to talk with marineres END
BEGIN NOW That come from a far countree. END
BEGIN NOW He kneels at morn and noon and eve-- END
BEGIN NOW He hath a cushion plump: END
BEGIN NOW It is the moss that wholly hides END
BEGIN NOW The rotted old oak-stump. END
BEGIN NOW The skiff-boat neared: I heard them talk, END
BEGIN NOW Why this is strange, I trow! END
BEGIN NOW Where are those lights so many and fair, END
BEGIN NOW That signal made but now? END
BEGIN NOW Strange, by my faith!" the Hermit said-- END
BEGIN NOW And they answered not our cheer! END
BEGIN NOW The planks looked warped! and see those sails, END
BEGIN NOW How thin they are and sere! END
BEGIN NOW I never saw aught like to them, END
BEGIN NOW Unless perchance it were END
BEGIN NOW Brown skeletons of leaves that lag END
BEGIN NOW My forest-brook along; END
BEGIN NOW When the ivy-tod is heavy with snow, END
BEGIN NOW And the owlet whoops to the wolf below, END
BEGIN NOW That eats the she-wolf's young. END
BEGIN NOW Dear Lord! it hath a fiendish look-- END
BEGIN NOW (The Pilot made reply) END
BEGIN NOW I am a-feared"--"Push on, push on! END
BEGIN NOW Said the Hermit cheerily. END
BEGIN NOW The boat came closer to the ship, END
BEGIN NOW But I nor spake nor stirred; END
BEGIN NOW The boat came close beneath the ship, END
BEGIN NOW And straight a sound was heard. END
BEGIN NOW Under the water it rumbled on, END
BEGIN NOW Still louder and more dread: END
BEGIN NOW It reached the ship, it split the bay; END
BEGIN NOW The ship went down like lead. END
BEGIN NOW Stunned by that loud and dreadful sound, END
BEGIN NOW Which sky and ocean smote, END
BEGIN NOW Like one that hath been seven days drowned END
BEGIN NOW My body lay afloat; END
BEGIN NOW But swift as dreams, myself I found END
BEGIN NOW Within the Pilot's boat. END
BEGIN NOW Upon the whirl, where sank the ship, END
BEGIN NOW The boat spun round and round; END
BEGIN NOW And all was still, save that the hill END
BEGIN NOW Was telling of the sound. END
BEGIN NOW I moved my lips--the Pilot shrieked END
BEGIN NOW And fell down in a fit; END
BEGIN NOW The holy Hermit raised his eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And prayed where he did sit. END
BEGIN NOW I took the oars: the Pilot's boy, END
BEGIN NOW Laughed loud and long, and all the while END
BEGIN NOW His eyes went to and fro. END
BEGIN NOW Ha! ha!" quoth he, "full plain I see, END
BEGIN NOW The Devil knows how to row. END
BEGIN NOW And now, all in my own countree, END
BEGIN NOW I stood on the firm land! END
BEGIN NOW The Hermit stepped forth from the boat, END
BEGIN NOW And scarcely he could stand. END
BEGIN NOW O shrieve me, shrieve me, holy man! END
BEGIN NOW The Hermit crossed his brow. END
BEGIN NOW Say quick," quoth he, "I bid thee say-- END
BEGIN NOW What manner of man art thou? END
BEGIN NOW Forthwith this frame of mine was wrenched END
BEGIN NOW With a woeful agony, END
BEGIN NOW Which forced me to begin my tale; END
BEGIN NOW And then it left me free. END
BEGIN NOW Since then, at an uncertain hour, END
BEGIN NOW That agony returns; END
BEGIN NOW And till my ghastly tale is told, END
BEGIN NOW This heart within me burns. END
BEGIN NOW I pass, like night, from land to land; END
BEGIN NOW I have strange power of speech; END
BEGIN NOW That moment that his face I see, END
BEGIN NOW I know the man that must hear me: END
BEGIN NOW To him my tale I teach. END
BEGIN NOW What loud uproar bursts from that door! END
BEGIN NOW The wedding-guests are there: END
BEGIN NOW But in the garden-bower the bride END
BEGIN NOW And bride-maids singing are: END
BEGIN NOW And hark the little vesper bell, END
BEGIN NOW Which biddeth me to prayer! END
BEGIN NOW O Wedding-Guest! this soul hath been END
BEGIN NOW Alone on a wide wide sea: END
BEGIN NOW So lonely 'twas, that God himself END
BEGIN NOW Scarce seemed there to be. END
BEGIN NOW O sweeter than the marriage-feast, END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis sweeter far to me, END
BEGIN NOW To walk together to the kirk END
BEGIN NOW With a goodly company!-- END
BEGIN NOW To walk together to the kirk, END
BEGIN NOW And all together pray, END
BEGIN NOW While each to his great Father bends, END
BEGIN NOW Old men, and babes, and loving friends, END
BEGIN NOW And youths and maidens gay! END
BEGIN NOW Farewell, farewell! but this I tell END
BEGIN NOW To thee, thou Wedding-Guest! END
BEGIN NOW He prayeth well, who loveth well END
BEGIN NOW Both man and bird and beast. END
BEGIN NOW He prayeth best, who loveth best END
BEGIN NOW All things both great and small; END
BEGIN NOW For the dear God who loveth us END
BEGIN NOW He made and loveth all. END
BEGIN NOW The Mariner, whose eye is bright, END
BEGIN NOW Whose beard with age is hoar, END
BEGIN NOW Is gone: and now the Wedding-Guest END
BEGIN NOW Turned from the bridegroom's door. END
BEGIN NOW He went like one that hath been stunned, END
BEGIN NOW And is of sense forlorn: END
BEGIN NOW A sadder and a wiser man, END
BEGIN NOW He rose the morrow morn. END
BEGIN NOW Pondering shadows, colors, clouds END
