BEGIN NOW If you leave the gloom of London and you seek a glowing land, END
BEGIN NOW The cruel war was over -- oh, the triumph was so sweet, END
BEGIN NOW A pistol shot rings round and round the world, END
BEGIN NOW An angel was tired of heaven, as he lounged in the golden street, END
BEGIN NOW We couldn't sit and study for the law, END
BEGIN NOW New Year's Eve END
BEGIN NOW It's cruel cold on the water-front, silent and dark and drear, END
BEGIN NOW Say! You've struck a heap of trouble, END
BEGIN NOW There was a woman, and she was wise; woefully wise was she, END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas a year ago, and the moon was bright, END
BEGIN NOW You who have lived in the land, END
BEGIN NOW I wanted the gold, and I sought it, END
BEGIN NOW I scrabbled and mucked like a slave. END
BEGIN NOW Was it famine or scurvy -- I fought it; END
BEGIN NOW I hurled my youth into a grave. END
BEGIN NOW I wanted the gold, and I got it -- END
BEGIN NOW Came out with a fortune last fall, -- END
BEGIN NOW Yet somehow life's not what I thought it, END
BEGIN NOW And somehow the gold isn't all. END
BEGIN NOW No! There's the land. (Have you seen it?) END
BEGIN NOW It's the cussedest land that I know, END
BEGIN NOW From the big, dizzy mountains that screen it END
BEGIN NOW To the deep, deathlike valleys below. END
BEGIN NOW Some say God was tired when He made it; END
BEGIN NOW Some say it's a fine land to shun; END
BEGIN NOW Maybe; but there's some as would trade it END
BEGIN NOW For no land on earth -- and I'm one. END
BEGIN NOW You come to get rich (damned good reason); END
BEGIN NOW You feel like an exile at first; END
BEGIN NOW You hate it like hell for a season, END
BEGIN NOW And then you are worse than the worst. END
BEGIN NOW It grips you like some kinds of sinning; END
BEGIN NOW It twists you from foe to a friend; END
BEGIN NOW It seems it's been since the beginning; END
BEGIN NOW It seems it will be to the end. END
BEGIN NOW I've stood in some mighty-mouthed hollow END
BEGIN NOW That's plumb-full of hush to the brim; END
BEGIN NOW I've watched the big, husky sun wallow END
BEGIN NOW In crimson and gold, and grow dim, END
BEGIN NOW Till the moon set the pearly peaks gleaming, END
BEGIN NOW And the stars tumbled out, neck and crop; END
BEGIN NOW And I've thought that I surely was dreaming, END
BEGIN NOW With the peace o' the world piled on top. END
BEGIN NOW The summer -- no sweeter was ever; END
BEGIN NOW The sunshiny woods all athrill; END
BEGIN NOW The grayling aleap in the river, END
BEGIN NOW The bighorn asleep on the hill. END
BEGIN NOW The strong life that never knows harness; END
BEGIN NOW The wilds where the caribou call; END
BEGIN NOW The freshness, the freedom, the farness -- END
BEGIN NOW O God! how I'm stuck on it all. END
BEGIN NOW The winter! the brightness that blinds you, END
BEGIN NOW The white land locked tight as a drum, END
BEGIN NOW The cold fear that follows and finds you, END
BEGIN NOW The snows that are older than history, END
BEGIN NOW The woods where the weird shadows slant; END
BEGIN NOW The stillness, the moonlight, the mystery, END
BEGIN NOW I've bade 'em good-by -- but I can't. END
BEGIN NOW There's a land where the mountains are nameless, END
BEGIN NOW And the rivers all run God knows where; END
BEGIN NOW There are lives that are erring and aimless, END
BEGIN NOW And deaths that just hang by a hair; END
BEGIN NOW There are hardships that nobody reckons; END
BEGIN NOW There are valleys unpeopled and still; END
BEGIN NOW There's a land -- oh, it beckons and beckons, END
BEGIN NOW And I want to go back -- and I will. END
BEGIN NOW They're making my money diminish; END
BEGIN NOW I'm sick of the taste of champagne. END
BEGIN NOW Thank God! when I'm skinned to a finish END
BEGIN NOW I'll pike to the Yukon again. END
BEGIN NOW I'll fight -- and you bet it's no sham-fight; END
BEGIN NOW It's hell! -- but I've been there before; END
BEGIN NOW And it's better than this by a damsite -- END
BEGIN NOW So me for the Yukon once more. END
BEGIN NOW There's gold, and it's haunting and haunting; END
BEGIN NOW It's luring me on as of old; END
BEGIN NOW Yet it isn't the gold that I'm wanting END
BEGIN NOW So much as just finding the gold. END
BEGIN NOW It's the great, big, broad land 'way up yonder, END
BEGIN NOW It's the forests where silence has lease; END
BEGIN NOW It's the beauty that thrills me with wonder, END
BEGIN NOW It's the stillness that fills me with peace. END
BEGIN NOW There where the mighty mountains bare their fangs unto the moon, END
BEGIN NOW it's the lure of the timeless things, END
BEGIN NOW And to-night, oh, God of the trails untrod, END
BEGIN NOW how it whines in my heart-strings! END
BEGIN NOW With the raw-ribbed Wild that abhors all life, END
BEGIN NOW the Wild that would crush and rend, END
BEGIN NOW I have clinched and closed with the naked North, END
BEGIN NOW I have learned to defy and defend; END
BEGIN NOW Shoulder to shoulder we have fought it out -- END
BEGIN NOW yet the Wild must win in the end. END
BEGIN NOW I have flouted the Wild. I have followed its lure, END
BEGIN NOW fearless, familiar, alone; END
BEGIN NOW Even as lean wolf-dog goes down will I go down and die. END
BEGIN NOW The waves have a story to tell me, END
BEGIN NOW As I lie on the lonely beach; END
BEGIN NOW Chanting aloft in the pine-tops, END
BEGIN NOW The wind has a lesson to teach; END
BEGIN NOW But the stars sing an anthem of glory END
BEGIN NOW I cannot put into speech. END
BEGIN NOW The waves tell of ocean spaces, END
BEGIN NOW Of hearts that are wild and brave, END
BEGIN NOW Of populous city places, END
BEGIN NOW Of desolate shores they lave, END
BEGIN NOW Of men who sally in quest of gold END
BEGIN NOW To sink in an ocean grave. END
BEGIN NOW The wind is a mighty roamer; END
BEGIN NOW He bids me keep me free, END
BEGIN NOW Clean from the taint of the gold-lust, END
BEGIN NOW Hardy and pure as he; END
BEGIN NOW Cling with my love to nature, END
BEGIN NOW As a child to the mother-knee. END
BEGIN NOW But the stars throng out in their glory, END
BEGIN NOW And they sing of the God in man; END
BEGIN NOW They sing of the Mighty Master, END
BEGIN NOW Of the loom his fingers span, END
BEGIN NOW Where a star or a soul is a part of the whole, END
BEGIN NOW And weft in the wondrous plan. END
BEGIN NOW Here by the camp-fire's flicker, END
BEGIN NOW Deep in my blanket curled, END
BEGIN NOW I long for the peace of the pine-gloom, END
BEGIN NOW When the scroll of the Lord is unfurled, END
BEGIN NOW And the wind and the wave are silent, END
BEGIN NOW And world is singing to world. END
BEGIN NOW This is the law of the Yukon, and ever she makes it plain: END
BEGIN NOW Send me men girt for the combat, men who are grit to the core; END
BEGIN NOW Swift as the panther in triumph, fierce as the bear in defeat, END
BEGIN NOW Sired of a bulldog parent, steeled in the furnace heat. END
BEGIN NOW Send me the best of your breeding, lend me your chosen ones; END
BEGIN NOW Them will I take to my bosom, them will I call my sons; END
BEGIN NOW Them will I gild with my treasure, them will I glut with my meat; END
BEGIN NOW Wild and wide are my borders, stern as death is my sway; END
BEGIN NOW One by one I weeded them out, for all that I sought was -- Men. END
BEGIN NOW One by one I dismayed them, frighting them sore with my glooms; END
BEGIN NOW One by one I betrayed them unto my manifold dooms. END
BEGIN NOW Going outside with an escort, raving with lips all afoam, END
BEGIN NOW Writing a cheque for a million, driveling feebly of home; END
BEGIN NOW Lost like a louse in the burning... or else in the tented town END
BEGIN NOW Seeking a drunkard's solace, sinking and sinking down; END
BEGIN NOW Steeped in the slime at the bottom, dead to a decent world, END
BEGIN NOW Lost 'mid the human flotsam, far on the frontier hurled; END
BEGIN NOW Searching my uttermost valleys, fighting each step as they go, END
BEGIN NOW Shooting the wrath of my rapids, scaling my ramparts of snow; END
BEGIN NOW Ripping the guts of my mountains, looting the beds of my creeks, END
BEGIN NOW Them will I take to my bosom, and speak as a mother speaks. END
BEGIN NOW I am the land that listens, I am the land that broods; END
BEGIN NOW Steeped in eternal beauty, crystalline waters and woods. END
BEGIN NOW Long have I waited lonely, shunned as a thing accurst, END
BEGIN NOW Monstrous, moody, pathetic, the last of the lands and the first; END
BEGIN NOW Visioning camp-fires at twilight, sad with a longing forlorn, END
BEGIN NOW Feeling my womb o'er-pregnant with the seed of cities unborn. END
BEGIN NOW Wild and wide are my borders, stern as death is my sway, END
BEGIN NOW Them will I gild with my treasure, them will I glut with my meat. END
BEGIN NOW Lofty I stand from each sister land, patient and wearily wise, END
BEGIN NOW When men shall not rape my riches, and curse me and go away; END
BEGIN NOW Making a bawd of my bounty, fouling the hand that gave -- END
BEGIN NOW Till I rise in my wrath and I sweep on their path END
BEGIN NOW and I stamp them into a grave. END
BEGIN NOW Dreaming of men who will bless me, of women esteeming me good, END
BEGIN NOW Of children born in my borders of radiant motherhood, END
BEGIN NOW Of cities leaping to stature, of fame like a flag unfurled, END
BEGIN NOW As I pour the tide of my riches in the eager lap of the world. END
BEGIN NOW This is the Law of the Yukon, that only the Strong shall thrive; END
BEGIN NOW That surely the Weak shall perish, and only the Fit survive. END
BEGIN NOW Dissolute, damned and despairful, crippled and palsied and slain, END
BEGIN NOW The Parson's Son END
BEGIN NOW shoot up from the frozen zone, END
BEGIN NOW I'm one of the Arctic brotherhood, I'm an old-time pioneer. END
BEGIN NOW I came with the first -- O God! how I've cursed END
BEGIN NOW this Yukon -- but still I'm here. END
BEGIN NOW I've toiled and moiled for its gold. END
BEGIN NOW where the frost-fiend bit to the bone. END
BEGIN NOW Each one a brand of this devil's land, END
BEGIN NOW where I've played and I've lost the game, END
BEGIN NOW This mining is only a gamble; the worst is as good as the best; END
BEGIN NOW And I got in on Bonanza before the big rush began. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, those Dawson days, and the sin and the blaze, END
BEGIN NOW and the town all open wide! END
BEGIN NOW (If God made me in His likeness, sure He let the devil inside.) END
BEGIN NOW Money was just like dirt there, easy to get and to spend. END
BEGIN NOW Twenty years in the Yukon, struggling along its creeks; END
BEGIN NOW Roaming its giant valleys, scaling its god-like peaks; END
BEGIN NOW Bathed in its fiery sunsets, fighting its fiendish cold -- END
BEGIN NOW Twenty years in the Yukon... twenty years -- and I'm old. END
BEGIN NOW ... Come, Kit, your pony is saddled. END
BEGIN NOW I'm waiting, dear, in the court... END
BEGIN NOW ... Minnie, you devil, I'll kill you END
BEGIN NOW if you skip with that flossy sport... END
BEGIN NOW ... How much does it go to the pan, Bill?... END
BEGIN NOW play up, School, and play the game... END
BEGIN NOW ... Our Father, which art in heaven, hallowed be Thy name... END
BEGIN NOW and his blue lips ceased to moan, END
BEGIN NOW And the hunger-maddened malamutes had torn him flesh from bone._ END
BEGIN NOW Have you swept the visioned valley END
BEGIN NOW with the green stream streaking through it, END
BEGIN NOW Searched the Vastness for a something you have lost? END
BEGIN NOW Have you wandered in the wilderness, the sagebrush desolation, END
BEGIN NOW The bunch-grass levels where the cattle graze? END
BEGIN NOW Have you whistled bits of rag-time at the end of all creation, END
BEGIN NOW And learned to know the desert's little ways? END
BEGIN NOW Have you suffered, starved and triumphed, END
BEGIN NOW groveled down, yet grasped at glory, END
BEGIN NOW Grown bigger in the bigness of the whole? END
BEGIN NOW Let us probe the silent places, let us seek what luck betide us; END
BEGIN NOW Let us journey to a lonely land I know. END
BEGIN NOW _Ye who know the Lone Trail fain would follow it, END
BEGIN NOW Though it lead to glory or the darkness of the pit. END
BEGIN NOW Ye who take the Lone Trail, bid your love good-by; END
BEGIN NOW The Lone Trail, the Lone Trail follow till you die._ END
BEGIN NOW and they rob the corpse for its clothes. END
BEGIN NOW and the snows where your torn feet freeze, END
BEGIN NOW till the ways of the world are made plain. END
BEGIN NOW _Bid good-by to sweetheart, bid good-by to friend; END
BEGIN NOW The Lone Trail, the Lone Trail follow to the end. END
BEGIN NOW Tarry not, and fear not, chosen of the true; END
BEGIN NOW Lover of the Lone Trail, the Lone Trail waits for you._ END
BEGIN NOW We sleep in the sleep of ages, the bleak, barbarian pines; END
BEGIN NOW The gray moss drapes us like sages, and closer we lock our lines, END
BEGIN NOW Ours till the world be riven in the crash of the utter end; END
BEGIN NOW Wind of the East, Wind of the West, wandering to and fro, END
BEGIN NOW and our ancients crash and roar; END
BEGIN NOW to the peaks that tusk the sky, END
BEGIN NOW Sun, moon and stars give answer; shall we not staunchly stand, END
BEGIN NOW Even as now, forever, wards of the wilder strand, END
BEGIN NOW Sentinels of the stillness, lords of the last, lone land? END
BEGIN NOW They miss my little camp-fires, ever brightly, bravely gleaming END
BEGIN NOW In the womb of desolation, where was never man before; END
BEGIN NOW As comradeless I sought them, lion-hearted, loving, dreaming, END
BEGIN NOW And they hailed me as a comrade, and they loved me evermore. END
BEGIN NOW And now they're all a-crying, and it's no use me denying; END
BEGIN NOW The spell of them is on me and I'm helpless as a child; END
BEGIN NOW My heart is aching, aching, but I hear them, sleeping, waking; END
BEGIN NOW It's the Lure of Little Voices, it's the mandate of the Wild. END
BEGIN NOW I'm afraid to tell you, Honey, I can take no bitter leaving; END
BEGIN NOW But softly in the sleep-time from your love I'll steal away. END
BEGIN NOW Look at my face, toil-furrowed; look at my calloused hands; END
BEGIN NOW Master, I've done Thy bidding, wrought in Thy many lands -- END
BEGIN NOW Wrought for the little masters, big-bellied they be, and rich; END
BEGIN NOW And now, Big Master, I'm broken and bent and twisted and scarred, END
BEGIN NOW Whiskey and cards and women, they made me the devil's tool. END
BEGIN NOW I was just like a child with money; I flung it away with a curse, END
BEGIN NOW Then back to the woods repentant, back to the mill or the mine, END
BEGIN NOW I, the worker of workers, everything in my line. END
BEGIN NOW Everything hard but headwork (I'd no more brains than a kid), END
BEGIN NOW A brute with brute strength to labor, doing as I was bid; END
BEGIN NOW Living in camps with men-folk, a lonely and loveless life; END
BEGIN NOW Never knew kiss of sweetheart, never caress of wife. END
BEGIN NOW Down in the ditch building o'er me palaces fairer than dreams; END
BEGIN NOW Boring the rock to the ore-bed, driving the road through the fen, END
BEGIN NOW Master, I've filled my contract, wrought in Thy many lands; END
BEGIN NOW Not by my sins wilt Thou judge me, but by the work of my hands. END
BEGIN NOW Master, I've done Thy bidding, and the light is low in the west, END
BEGIN NOW Don't let him see you're funking, let him know with every clout, END
BEGIN NOW And grin. END
BEGIN NOW This life's a bally battle, and the same advice holds true END
BEGIN NOW Of grin. END
BEGIN NOW If you're up against it badly, then it's only one on you, END
BEGIN NOW So grin. END
BEGIN NOW Rise up in the morning with the will that, smooth or rough, END
BEGIN NOW You'll grin. END
BEGIN NOW Sink to sleep at midnight, and although you're feeling tough, END
BEGIN NOW Yet grin. END
BEGIN NOW Your trouble is that you don't know when you have had enough -- END
BEGIN NOW Don't give in. END
BEGIN NOW If Fate should down you, just get up and take another cuff; END
BEGIN NOW You may bank on it that there is no philosophy like bluff, END
BEGIN NOW And grin. END
BEGIN NOW The Shooting of Dan McGrew END
BEGIN NOW A bunch of the boys were whooping it up in the Malamute saloon; END
BEGIN NOW The kid that handles the music-box was hitting a jag-time tune; END
BEGIN NOW Back of the bar, in a solo game, sat Dangerous Dan McGrew, END
BEGIN NOW and scarcely the strength of a louse, END
BEGIN NOW Yet he tilted a poke of dust on the bar, END
BEGIN NOW and he called for drinks for the house. END
BEGIN NOW There was none could place the stranger's face, END
BEGIN NOW though we searched ourselves for a clue; END
BEGIN NOW There's men that somehow just grip your eyes, END
BEGIN NOW and hold them hard like a spell; END
BEGIN NOW And I turned my head -- and there watching him END
BEGIN NOW was the lady that's known as Lou. END
BEGIN NOW -- my God! but that man could play. END
BEGIN NOW the North Lights swept in bars? -- END
BEGIN NOW Then you've a haunch what the music meant... END
BEGIN NOW hunger and night and the stars. END
BEGIN NOW (God! how ghastly she looks through her rouge, -- END
BEGIN NOW the lady that's known as Lou.) END
BEGIN NOW of all that it once held dear; END
BEGIN NOW and it thrilled you through and through -- END
BEGIN NOW The music almost died away... then it burst like a pent-up flood; END
BEGIN NOW then the music stopped with a crash, END
BEGIN NOW and he spoke, and his voice was calm, END
BEGIN NOW and I'll bet my poke they're true, END
BEGIN NOW Then I ducked my head, and the lights went out, END
BEGIN NOW and two guns blazed in the dark, END
BEGIN NOW And a woman screamed, and the lights went up, END
BEGIN NOW and two men lay stiff and stark. END
BEGIN NOW of the lady that's known as Lou. END
BEGIN NOW and I'm not denying it's so. END
BEGIN NOW was the lady that's known as Lou. END
BEGIN NOW The Cremation of Sam McGee END
BEGIN NOW _There are strange things done in the midnight sun END
BEGIN NOW By the men who moil for gold; END
BEGIN NOW The Arctic trails have their secret tales END
BEGIN NOW That would make your blood run cold; END
BEGIN NOW The Northern Lights have seen queer sights, END
BEGIN NOW But the queerest they ever did see END
BEGIN NOW Was that night on the marge of Lake Lebarge END
BEGIN NOW I cremated Sam McGee._ END
BEGIN NOW On a Christmas Day we were mushing our way over the Dawson trail. END
BEGIN NOW Well, he seemed so low that I couldn't say no; END
BEGIN NOW then he says with a sort of moan: END
BEGIN NOW It's the cursed cold, and it's got right hold END
BEGIN NOW till I'm chilled clean through to the bone. END
BEGIN NOW You may tax your brawn and brains, END
BEGIN NOW in my heart how I cursed that load. END
BEGIN NOW In the long, long night, by the lone firelight, END
BEGIN NOW while the huskies, round in a ring, END
BEGIN NOW Howled out their woes to the homeless snows -- END
BEGIN NOW O God! how I loathed the thing. END
BEGIN NOW And every day that quiet clay seemed to heavy and heavier grow; END
BEGIN NOW such a blaze you seldom see; END
BEGIN NOW Then I made a hike, for I didn't like to hear him sizzle so; END
BEGIN NOW down my cheeks, and I don't know why; END
BEGIN NOW I do not know how long in the snow I wrestled with grisly fear; END
BEGIN NOW then the door I opened wide. END
BEGIN NOW and he said: "Please close that door. END
BEGIN NOW it's the first time I've been warm. END
BEGIN NOW _There are strange things done in the midnight sun END
BEGIN NOW By the men who moil for gold; END
BEGIN NOW The Arctic trails have their secret tales END
BEGIN NOW That would make your blood run cold; END
BEGIN NOW The Northern Lights have seen queer sights, END
BEGIN NOW But the queerest they ever did see END
BEGIN NOW Was that night on the marge of Lake Lebarge END
BEGIN NOW I cremated Sam McGee._ END
BEGIN NOW I haled me a woman from the street, END
BEGIN NOW Shameless, but, oh, so fair! END
BEGIN NOW I bade her sit in the model's seat END
BEGIN NOW And I painted her sitting there. END
BEGIN NOW I hid all trace of her heart unclean; END
BEGIN NOW I painted a babe at her breast; END
BEGIN NOW I painted her as she might have been END
BEGIN NOW If the Worst had been the Best. END
BEGIN NOW She laughed at my picture and went away. END
BEGIN NOW Then came, with a knowing nod, END
BEGIN NOW A connoisseur, and I heard him say; END
BEGIN NOW So I painted a halo round her hair, END
BEGIN NOW And I sold her and took my fee, END
BEGIN NOW And she hangs in the church of Saint Hillaire, END
BEGIN NOW Where you and all may see. END
BEGIN NOW I know a garden where the lilies gleam, END
BEGIN NOW And one who lingers in the sunshine there; END
BEGIN NOW She is than white-stoled lily far more fair, END
BEGIN NOW And oh, her eyes are heaven-lit with dream! END
BEGIN NOW I know a garret, cold and dark and drear, END
BEGIN NOW And one who toils and toils with tireless pen, END
BEGIN NOW Until his brave, sad eyes grow weary -- then END
BEGIN NOW He seeks the stars, pale, silent as a seer. END
BEGIN NOW And ah, it's strange; for, desolate and dim, END
BEGIN NOW Between these two there rolls an ocean wide; END
BEGIN NOW Yet he is in the garden by her side END
BEGIN NOW And she is in the garret there with him. END
BEGIN NOW It's fine to have a blow-out in a fancy restaurant, END
BEGIN NOW With terrapin and canvas-back and all the wine you want; END
BEGIN NOW To enjoy the flowers and music, watch the pretty women pass, END
BEGIN NOW Smoke a choice cigar, and sip the wealthy water in your glass. END
BEGIN NOW It's bully in a high-toned joint to eat and drink your fill, END
BEGIN NOW But it's quite another matter when you END
BEGIN NOW Pay the bill. END
BEGIN NOW It's great to go out every night on fun or pleasure bent; END
BEGIN NOW To wear your glad rags always and to never save a cent; END
BEGIN NOW To drift along regardless, have a good time every trip; END
BEGIN NOW To hit the high spots sometimes, and to let your chances slip; END
BEGIN NOW To know you're acting foolish, yet to go on fooling still, END
BEGIN NOW Till Nature calls a show-down, and you END
BEGIN NOW Pay the bill. END
BEGIN NOW Time has got a little bill -- get wise while yet you may, END
BEGIN NOW For the debit side's increasing in a most alarming way; END
BEGIN NOW So eat, drink and be merry, have a good time if you will, END
BEGIN NOW But God help you when the time comes, and you END
BEGIN NOW Foot the bill. END
BEGIN NOW One said: Thy life is thine to make or mar, END
BEGIN NOW To flicker feebly, or to soar, a star; END
BEGIN NOW It lies with thee -- the choice is thine, is thine, END
BEGIN NOW To hit the ties or drive thy auto-car. END
BEGIN NOW I answered Her: The choice is mine -- ah, no! END
BEGIN NOW We all were made or marred long, long ago. END
BEGIN NOW The parts are written; hear the super wail: END
BEGIN NOW Who is stage-managing this cosmic show? END
BEGIN NOW Blind fools of fate and slaves of circumstance, END
BEGIN NOW Life is a fiddler, and we all must dance. END
BEGIN NOW From gloom where mocks that will-o'-wisp, Free-will END
BEGIN NOW I heard a voice cry: "Say, give us a chance. END
BEGIN NOW Chance! Oh, there is no chance! The scene is set. END
BEGIN NOW Up with the curtain! Man, the marionette, END
BEGIN NOW Resumes his part. The gods will work the wires. END
BEGIN NOW They've got it all down fine, you bet, you bet! END
BEGIN NOW It's all decreed -- the mighty earthquake crash, END
BEGIN NOW The countless constellations' wheel and flash; END
BEGIN NOW The rise and fall of empires, war's red tide; END
BEGIN NOW The composition of your dinner hash. END
BEGIN NOW There's no haphazard in this world of ours. END
BEGIN NOW Cause and effect are grim, relentless powers. END
BEGIN NOW They rule the world. (A king was shot last night; END
BEGIN NOW Last night I held the joker and both bowers.) END
BEGIN NOW From out the mesh of fate our heads we thrust. END
BEGIN NOW We can't do what we would, but what we must. END
BEGIN NOW Heredity has got us in a cinch -- END
BEGIN NOW (Consoling thought when you've been on a bust".) END
BEGIN NOW Hark to the song where spheral voices blend: END
BEGIN NOW There's no beginning, never will be end. END
BEGIN NOW It makes us nutty; hang the astral chimes! END
BEGIN NOW The tables spread; come, let us dine, my friend. END
BEGIN NOW The Men That Don't Fit In END
BEGIN NOW There's a race of men that don't fit in, END
BEGIN NOW A race that can't stay still; END
BEGIN NOW So they break the hearts of kith and kin, END
BEGIN NOW And they roam the world at will. END
BEGIN NOW They range the field and they rove the flood, END
BEGIN NOW And they climb the mountain's crest; END
BEGIN NOW And they don't know how to rest. END
BEGIN NOW If they just went straight they might go far; END
BEGIN NOW They are strong and brave and true; END
BEGIN NOW But they're always tired of the things that are, END
BEGIN NOW And they want the strange and new. END
BEGIN NOW They say: "Could I find my proper groove, END
BEGIN NOW What a deep mark I would make! END
BEGIN NOW So they chop and change, and each fresh move END
BEGIN NOW Is only a fresh mistake. END
BEGIN NOW And each forgets, as he strips and runs END
BEGIN NOW With a brilliant, fitful pace, END
BEGIN NOW It's the steady, quiet, plodding ones END
BEGIN NOW Who win in the lifelong race. END
BEGIN NOW And each forgets that his youth has fled, END
BEGIN NOW Forgets that his prime is past, END
BEGIN NOW Till he stands one day, with a hope that's dead, END
BEGIN NOW In the glare of the truth at last. END
BEGIN NOW He has failed, he has failed; he has missed his chance; END
BEGIN NOW He has just done things by half. END
BEGIN NOW Life's been a jolly good joke on him, END
BEGIN NOW And now is the time to laugh. END
BEGIN NOW He was never meant to win; END
BEGIN NOW He's a rolling stone, and it's bred in the bone; END
BEGIN NOW He's a man who won't fit in. END
BEGIN NOW O'er the dark pines she sees the silver moon, END
BEGIN NOW And in the west, all tremulous, a star; END
BEGIN NOW And soothing sweet she hears the mellow tune END
BEGIN NOW Of cow-bells jangled in the fields afar. END
BEGIN NOW Quite listless, for her daily stent is done, END
BEGIN NOW She stands, sad exile, at her rose-wreathed door, END
BEGIN NOW And sends her love eternal with the sun END
BEGIN NOW That goes to gild the land she'll see no more. END
BEGIN NOW The grave, gaunt pines imprison her sad gaze, END
BEGIN NOW All still the sky and darkling drearily; END
BEGIN NOW She feels the chilly breath of dear, dead days END
BEGIN NOW Come sifting through the alders eerily. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, how the roses riot in their bloom! END
BEGIN NOW The curtains stir as with an ancient pain; END
BEGIN NOW Her old piano gleams from out the gloom END
BEGIN NOW And waits and waits her tender touch in vain. END
BEGIN NOW But now her hands like moonlight brush the keys END
BEGIN NOW With velvet grace -- melodious delight; END
BEGIN NOW And now a sad refrain from over seas END
BEGIN NOW Goes sobbing on the bosom of the night; END
BEGIN NOW And now she sings. (O! singer in the gloom, END
BEGIN NOW Voicing a sorrow we can ne'er express, END
BEGIN NOW Here in the Farness where we few have room END
BEGIN NOW Unshamed to show our love and tenderness, END
BEGIN NOW Our hearts will echo, till they beat no more, END
BEGIN NOW That song of sadness and of motherland; END
BEGIN NOW And, stretched in deathless love to England's shore, END
BEGIN NOW Some day she'll hearken and she'll understand.) END
BEGIN NOW A prima-donna in the shining past, END
BEGIN NOW But now a mother growing old and gray, END
BEGIN NOW She thinks of how she held a people fast END
BEGIN NOW In thrall, and gleaned the triumphs of a day. END
BEGIN NOW She sees a sea of faces like a dream; END
BEGIN NOW She sees herself a queen of song once more; END
BEGIN NOW She sees lips part in rapture, eyes agleam; END
BEGIN NOW She sings as never once she sang before. END
BEGIN NOW She sings a wild, sweet song that throbs with pain, END
BEGIN NOW The added pain of life that transcends art -- END
BEGIN NOW A song of home, a deep, celestial strain, END
BEGIN NOW The glorious swan-song of a dying heart. END
BEGIN NOW A lame tramp comes along the railway track, END
BEGIN NOW A grizzled dog whose day is nearly done; END
BEGIN NOW He passes, pauses, then comes slowly back END
BEGIN NOW And listens there -- an audience of one. END
BEGIN NOW She sings -- her golden voice is passion-fraught, END
BEGIN NOW As when she charmed a thousand eager ears; END
BEGIN NOW He listens trembling, and she knows it not, END
BEGIN NOW And down his hollow cheeks roll bitter tears. END
BEGIN NOW She ceases and is still, as if to pray; END
BEGIN NOW There is no sound, the stars are all alight -- END
BEGIN NOW Only a wretch who stumbles on his way, END
BEGIN NOW Only a vagrant sobbing in the night. END
BEGIN NOW There's a four-pronged buck a-swinging in the shadow of my cabin, END
BEGIN NOW But I tracked it by the river, and I trailed it in the cover, END
BEGIN NOW And I killed it on the mountain miles away. END
BEGIN NOW Now I've had my lazy supper, and the level sun is gleaming END
BEGIN NOW On the water where the silver salmon play; END
BEGIN NOW And I light my little corn-cob, and I linger, softly dreaming, END
BEGIN NOW In the twilight, of a land that's far away. END
BEGIN NOW Far away, so faint and far, is flaming London, fevered Paris, END
BEGIN NOW That I fancy I have gained another star; END
BEGIN NOW Far away the din and hurry, far away the sin and worry, END
BEGIN NOW Far away -- God knows they cannot be too far. END
BEGIN NOW Had I clutched like them my chances, END
BEGIN NOW learned their wisdom, crushed my fancies, END
BEGIN NOW Starved my soul and gone to business every day. END
BEGIN NOW I can couch me deep in clover, I can listen to the story END
BEGIN NOW Of the lazy, lapping water -- it is best. END
BEGIN NOW And the robin greets the dayspring with the rapture of a lover, END
BEGIN NOW I am happy, and I'll nevermore go back. END
BEGIN NOW For I know I'd just be longing for the little old log cabin, END
BEGIN NOW With the morning-glory clinging to the door, END
BEGIN NOW Till I loathed the city places, cursed the care on all the faces, END
BEGIN NOW So send me far from Lombard Street, and write me down a failure; END
BEGIN NOW Put a little in my purse and leave me free. END
BEGIN NOW I am one of you no longer; by the trails my feet have broken, END
BEGIN NOW The dizzy peaks I've scaled, the camp-fire's glow; END
BEGIN NOW so I've sent my klooch to town, END
BEGIN NOW And I know at the dawn she'll come reeling home END
BEGIN NOW with the bottles, one, two, three -- END
BEGIN NOW One for herself, to drown her shame, and two big bottles for me, END
BEGIN NOW To make me forget the thing I am and the man I used to be. END
BEGIN NOW but they could not keep me straight; END
BEGIN NOW swift staggering through the snow. END
BEGIN NOW When a man gits on his uppers in a hard-pan sort of town, END
BEGIN NOW An' he ain't got nothin' comin' an' he can't afford ter eat, END
BEGIN NOW An' he's in a fix for lodgin' an' he wanders up an' down, END
BEGIN NOW An' you'd fancy he'd been boozin', he's so locoed 'bout the feet; END
BEGIN NOW In the little ol' log cabin in the shadder of the pines. END
BEGIN NOW When he's on the blazin' desert an' his canteen's sprung a leak, END
BEGIN NOW Then he's like ter hev' a vision, as he settles down ter die, END
BEGIN NOW Of the little ol' log cabin an' the roses an' the vines. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, the little ol' log cabin, it's a solemn shinin' mark, END
BEGIN NOW When a feller gits ter sinnin' an' a-goin' ter the wall, END
BEGIN NOW An' folks don't understand him an' he's gropin' in the dark, END
BEGIN NOW An' he's sick of bein' cursed at an' he's longin' fer his call! END
BEGIN NOW When the sun of life's a-sinkin' you can see it 'way above, END
BEGIN NOW On the hill from out the shadder in a glory 'gin the sky, END
BEGIN NOW An' never leave its shelter, an' forget, an' love, an' rest. END
BEGIN NOW If you leave the gloom of London and you seek a glowing land, END
BEGIN NOW Where all except the flag is strange and new, END
BEGIN NOW For he's your younger brother, the one you sent away END
BEGIN NOW Because there wasn't room for him at home; END
BEGIN NOW And now he's quite contented, and he's glad he didn't stay, END
BEGIN NOW And he's building Britain's greatness o'er the foam. END
BEGIN NOW When the giant herd is moving at the rising of the sun, END
BEGIN NOW And the prairie is lit with rose and gold, END
BEGIN NOW And the camp is all abustle, and the busy day's begun, END
BEGIN NOW He leaps into the saddle sure and bold. END
BEGIN NOW And when the night-winds whisper and camp-fires flicker out, END
BEGIN NOW He is sleeping like a child beneath the stars. END
BEGIN NOW When the wattle-blooms are drooping in the sombre she-oak glade, END
BEGIN NOW And the breathless land is lying in a swoon, END
BEGIN NOW And he hears the bell-bird chime the Austral noon. END
BEGIN NOW The parrakeets are silent in the gum-tree by the creek; END
BEGIN NOW The ferny grove is sunshine-steeped and still; END
BEGIN NOW But the dew will gem the myrtle in the twilight ere he seek END
BEGIN NOW His little lonely cabin on the hill. END
BEGIN NOW Around the purple, vine-clad slope the argent river dreams; END
BEGIN NOW The roses almost hide the house from view; END
BEGIN NOW A snow-peak of the Winterberg in crimson splendor gleams; END
BEGIN NOW The shadow deepens down on the karroo. END
BEGIN NOW He seeks the lily-scented dusk beneath the orange tree; END
BEGIN NOW His pipe in silence glows and fades and glows; END
BEGIN NOW And then two little maids come out and climb upon his knee, END
BEGIN NOW And one is like the lily, one the rose. END
BEGIN NOW He sees his white sheep dapple o'er the green New Zealand plain, END
BEGIN NOW And where Vancouver's shaggy ramparts frown, END
BEGIN NOW You will find him toiling, toiling, in the south or in the west, END
BEGIN NOW A child of nature, fearless, frank, and free; END
BEGIN NOW You've a brother in the army, you've another in the Church; END
BEGIN NOW One of you is a diplomatic swell; END
BEGIN NOW You've had the pick of everything and left him in the lurch, END
BEGIN NOW And yet I think he's doing very well. END
BEGIN NOW I'm sure his life is happy, and he doesn't envy yours; END
BEGIN NOW I know he loves the land his pluck has won; END
BEGIN NOW And I fancy in the years unborn, while England's fame endures, END
BEGIN NOW She will come to bless with pride -- The Younger Son. END
BEGIN NOW The cruel war was over -- oh, the triumph was so sweet! END
BEGIN NOW We watched the troops returning, through our tears; END
BEGIN NOW And everyone was shouting for the Soldiers of the Queen, END
BEGIN NOW And the glory of an age was passing by. END
BEGIN NOW And then there came a shadow, swift and sudden, dark and drear; END
BEGIN NOW The bells were silent, not an echo stirred. END
BEGIN NOW The flags were drooping sullenly, the men forgot to cheer; END
BEGIN NOW We waited, and we never spoke a word. END
BEGIN NOW The sky grew darker, darker, till from out the gloomy rack END
BEGIN NOW There came a voice that checked the heart with dread: END
BEGIN NOW Tear down, tear down your bunting now, and hang up sable black; END
BEGIN NOW They are coming -- it's the Army of the Dead. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, the clammy brow of anguish! the livid, foam-flecked lips! END
BEGIN NOW The reeling ranks of ruin swept along! END
BEGIN NOW They left us on the veldt-side, but we felt we couldn't stop END
BEGIN NOW On this, our England's crowning festal day; END
BEGIN NOW We're the men of Magersfontein, we're the men of Spion Kop, END
BEGIN NOW Colenso -- we're the men who had to pay. END
BEGIN NOW Then cheer us for our glory now, and cheer us for our pain, END
BEGIN NOW And cheer us as ye never cheered before. END
BEGIN NOW And every eye was staring at the horror of the dead, END
BEGIN NOW The pity of the men who paid the price. END
BEGIN NOW A thousand flags were flaming where the sky and city meet; END
BEGIN NOW A thousand bells were thundering the joy. END
BEGIN NOW O God, in Thy great mercy, let us nevermore forget END
BEGIN NOW The graves they left behind, the bitter graves. END
BEGIN NOW A pistol shot rings round and round the world; END
BEGIN NOW In pitiful defeat a warrior lies. END
BEGIN NOW A last defiance to dark Death is hurled, END
BEGIN NOW A last wild challenge shocks the sunlit skies. END
BEGIN NOW Alone he falls, with wide, wan, woeful eyes: END
BEGIN NOW Eyes that could smile at death -- could not face shame. END
BEGIN NOW Alone, alone he paced his narrow room, END
BEGIN NOW In the bright sunshine of that Paris day; END
BEGIN NOW Saw in his thought the awful hand of doom; END
BEGIN NOW Saw in his dream his glory pass away; END
BEGIN NOW Tried in his heart, his weary heart, to pray: END
BEGIN NOW O God! who made me, give me strength to face END
BEGIN NOW The spectre of this bitter, black disgrace. END
BEGIN NOW The burn brawls darkly down the shaggy glen; END
BEGIN NOW The bee-kissed heather blooms around the door; END
BEGIN NOW He sees himself a barefoot boy again, END
BEGIN NOW Bending o'er page of legendary lore. END
BEGIN NOW He hears the pibroch, grips the red claymore, END
BEGIN NOW Runs with the Fiery Cross, a clansman true, END
BEGIN NOW Sworn kinsman of Rob Roy and Roderick Dhu. END
BEGIN NOW Eating his heart out with a wild desire, END
BEGIN NOW One day, behind his counter trim and neat, END
BEGIN NOW He hears a sound that sets his brain afire -- END
BEGIN NOW The Highlanders are marching down the street. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, how the pipes shrill out, the mad drums beat! END
BEGIN NOW On to the gates of Hell, my Gordons gay! END
BEGIN NOW He flings his hated yardstick away. END
BEGIN NOW He sees the sullen pass, high-crowned with snow, END
BEGIN NOW Where Afghans cower with eyes of gleaming hate. END
BEGIN NOW He hurls himself against the hidden foe. END
BEGIN NOW They try to rally -- ah, too late, too late! END
BEGIN NOW Again, defenseless, with fierce eyes that wait END
BEGIN NOW For death, he stands, like baited bull at bay, END
BEGIN NOW And flouts the Boers, that mad Majuba day. END
BEGIN NOW He sees again the murderous Soudan, END
BEGIN NOW Blood-slaked and rapine-swept. He seems to stand END
BEGIN NOW Upon the gory plain of Omdurman. END
BEGIN NOW Then Magersfontein, and supreme command END
BEGIN NOW Over his Highlanders. To shake his hand END
BEGIN NOW A King is proud, and princes call him friend. END
BEGIN NOW And glory crowns his life -- and now the end, END
BEGIN NOW The awful end. His eyes are dark with doom; END
BEGIN NOW He hears the shrapnel shrieking overhead; END
BEGIN NOW He sees the ravaged ranks, the flame-stabbed gloom. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, to have fallen! -- the battle-field his bed, END
BEGIN NOW With Wauchope and his glorious brother-dead. END
BEGIN NOW Why was he saved for this, for this? And now END
BEGIN NOW He raises the revolver to his brow. END
BEGIN NOW In many a Highland home, framed with rude art, END
BEGIN NOW You'll find his portrait, rough-hewn, stern and square; END
BEGIN NOW It's graven in the Fuyam fellah's heart; END
BEGIN NOW The Ghurka reads it at his evening prayer; END
BEGIN NOW The raw lands know it, where the fierce suns glare; END
BEGIN NOW The Dervish fears it. Honor to his name END
BEGIN NOW Who holds aloft the shield of England's fame. END
BEGIN NOW Mourn for our hero, men of Northern race! END
BEGIN NOW We do not know his sin; we only know END
BEGIN NOW His sword was keen. He laughed death in the face, END
BEGIN NOW And struck, for Empire's sake, a giant blow. END
BEGIN NOW His arm was strong. Ah! well they learnt, the foe END
BEGIN NOW The echo of his deeds is ringing yet -- END
BEGIN NOW Will ring for aye. All else... let us forget. END
BEGIN NOW An angel was tired of heaven, as he lounged in the golden street; END
BEGIN NOW So the Master stooped in His pity, and gave him a pass to go, END
BEGIN NOW The sexless singers of heaven chanted a fond farewell, END
BEGIN NOW Never was seen such an angel -- eyes of heavenly blue, END
BEGIN NOW Features that shamed Apollo, hair of a golden hue; END
BEGIN NOW The women simply adored him; his lips were like Cupid's bow; END
BEGIN NOW But he never ventured to use them -- and so they voted him slow. END
BEGIN NOW Till at last there came One Woman, a marvel of loveliness, END
BEGIN NOW And she whispered to him: "Do you love me? END
BEGIN NOW And he answered that woman, Yes. END
BEGIN NOW We couldn't sit and study for the law; END
BEGIN NOW The stagnation of a bank we couldn't stand; END
BEGIN NOW For our riot blood was surging, and we didn't need much urging END
BEGIN NOW To excitements and excesses that are banned. END
BEGIN NOW So we took to wine and drink and other things, END
BEGIN NOW And the devil in us struggled to be free; END
BEGIN NOW Till our friends rose up in wrath, and they pointed out the path, END
BEGIN NOW Oh, they shook us off and shipped us o'er the foam, END
BEGIN NOW To the larger lands that lure a man to roam; END
BEGIN NOW And we took the chance they gave END
BEGIN NOW Of a far and foreign grave, END
BEGIN NOW And we bade good-by for evermore to home. END
BEGIN NOW And some of us are climbing on the peak, END
BEGIN NOW And some of us are camping on the plain; END
BEGIN NOW By pine and palm you'll find us, with never claim to bind us, END
BEGIN NOW By track and trail you'll meet us once again. END
BEGIN NOW We are the fated serfs to freedom -- sky and sea; END
BEGIN NOW We have failed where slummy cities overflow; END
BEGIN NOW But the stranger ways of earth know our pride and know our worth, END
BEGIN NOW Yes, we go into the night as brave men go, END
BEGIN NOW Though our faces they be often streaked with woe; END
BEGIN NOW Yet we're hard as cats to kill, END
BEGIN NOW And our hearts are reckless still, END
BEGIN NOW And we've danced with death a dozen times or so. END
BEGIN NOW And you'll find us in Alaska after gold, END
BEGIN NOW And you'll find us herding cattle in the South. END
BEGIN NOW We like strong drink and fun, and, when the race is run, END
BEGIN NOW We often die with curses in our mouth. END
BEGIN NOW We are wild as colts unbroke, but never mean. END
BEGIN NOW Of our sins we've shoulders broad to bear the blame; END
BEGIN NOW But we'll never stay in town and we'll never settle down, END
BEGIN NOW And we'll never have an object or an aim. END
BEGIN NOW No, there's that in us that time can never tame; END
BEGIN NOW And life will always seem a careless game; END
BEGIN NOW And they'd better far forget -- END
BEGIN NOW Those who say they love us yet -- END
BEGIN NOW Forget, blot out with bitterness our name. END
BEGIN NOW New Year's Eve END
BEGIN NOW It's cruel cold on the water-front, silent and dark and drear; END
BEGIN NOW Only the black tide weltering, only the hissing snow; END
BEGIN NOW They're playing a tune in McGuffy's saloon, END
BEGIN NOW and it's cheery and bright in there END
BEGIN NOW They'll jeer at me, and they'll sneer at me, END
BEGIN NOW and they'll call me a whiskey soak; END
BEGIN NOW McGuffy is showing a bunch of the boys how Bob Fitzsimmons hit; END
BEGIN NOW The room is reeling round and round... END
BEGIN NOW O God! but I'm tired, I'm tired.... END
BEGIN NOW Of lives that would blend like an angel-song END
BEGIN NOW in the bliss of the coming years? END
BEGIN NOW but oh, I have suffered so! END
BEGIN NOW I can hear the dreadful hum END
BEGIN NOW Of the crowded court... See! the Judge looks down... END
BEGIN NOW _NOT GUILTY_, my Lord, I swear... END
BEGIN NOW Have a drink to the glad New Year, a drop before you go -- END
BEGIN NOW You darned old dirty hobo... My God! Here, boys! He's _DEAD!_ END
BEGIN NOW Say! You've struck a heap of trouble -- END
BEGIN NOW Bust in business, lost your wife; END
BEGIN NOW No one cares a cent about you, END
BEGIN NOW You don't care a cent for life; END
BEGIN NOW Hard luck has of hope bereft you, END
BEGIN NOW Health is failing, wish you'd die -- END
BEGIN NOW Why, you've still the sunshine left you END
BEGIN NOW And the big, blue sky. END
BEGIN NOW Sky so blue it makes you wonder END
BEGIN NOW If it's heaven shining through; END
BEGIN NOW Earth so smiling 'way out yonder, END
BEGIN NOW Sun so bright it dazzles you; END
BEGIN NOW Birds a-singing, flowers a-flinging END
BEGIN NOW All their fragrance on the breeze; END
BEGIN NOW Dancing shadows, green, still meadows -- END
BEGIN NOW Don't you mope, you've still got these. END
BEGIN NOW These, and none can take them from you; END
BEGIN NOW These, and none can weigh their worth. END
BEGIN NOW What! you're tired and broke and beaten? -- END
BEGIN NOW Why, you're rich -- you've got the earth! END
BEGIN NOW Yes, if you're a tramp in tatters, END
BEGIN NOW While the blue sky bends above END
BEGIN NOW You've got nearly all that matters -- END
BEGIN NOW You've got God, and God is love. END
BEGIN NOW There was a woman, and she was wise; woefully wise was she; END
BEGIN NOW There is no hope for such as I on earth, nor yet in Heaven; END
BEGIN NOW Unloved I live, unloved I die, unpitied, unforgiven; END
BEGIN NOW A loathed jade, I ply my trade, unhallowed and unshriven. END
BEGIN NOW Until they come, the nightly scum, with drunken eyes aflame; END
BEGIN NOW For life is not the thing we thought, and not the thing we plan; END
BEGIN NOW And Woman in a bitter world must do the best she can -- END
BEGIN NOW Must serve his need and ever feed the flame of his desire, END
BEGIN NOW Though be she loved for love alone, or be she loved for hire; END
BEGIN NOW For every man since life began is tainted with the mire. END
BEGIN NOW And though you know he love you so and set you on love's throne; END
BEGIN NOW And 'tis not wise to love too well, and this all women know. END
BEGIN NOW Wherefore, the wolf-pack having gorged upon the lamb, their prey, END
BEGIN NOW With velvet paws and flensing claws, a tigress roused to slay. END
BEGIN NOW One who in youth sought truest truth and found a devil's lies; END
BEGIN NOW A symbol of the sin of man, a human sacrifice. END
BEGIN NOW Yet shall I blame on man the shame? Could it be otherwise? END
BEGIN NOW Was I not born to walk in scorn where others walk in pride? END
BEGIN NOW The Maker marred, and, evil-starred, I drift upon His tide; END
BEGIN NOW And He alone shall judge His own, so I His judgment bide. END
BEGIN NOW Fate has written a tragedy; its name is "The Human Heart". END
BEGIN NOW The Theatre is the House of Life, Woman the mummer's part; END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas a year ago and the moon was bright END
BEGIN NOW (Oh, I remember so well, so well); END
BEGIN NOW I walked with my love in a sea of light, END
BEGIN NOW And the voice of my sweet was a silver bell. END
BEGIN NOW And sudden the moon grew strangely dull, END
BEGIN NOW And sudden my love had taken wing; END
BEGIN NOW I looked on the face of a grinning skull, END
BEGIN NOW I strained to my heart a ghastly thing. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas but fantasy, for my love lay still END
BEGIN NOW In my arms, with her tender eyes aglow, END
BEGIN NOW And she wondered why my lips were chill, END
BEGIN NOW Why I was silent and kissed her so. END
BEGIN NOW A year has gone and the moon is bright, END
BEGIN NOW A gibbous moon, like a ghost of woe; END
BEGIN NOW I sit by a new-made grave to-night, END
BEGIN NOW And my heart is broken -- it's strange, you know. END
BEGIN NOW Along the road to Anywhere, when each day had its story; END
BEGIN NOW When time was yet our vassal, and life's jest was still unstale; END
BEGIN NOW Alas! the road to Anywhere is pitfalled with disaster; END
BEGIN NOW There's hunger, want, and weariness, yet O we loved it so! END
BEGIN NOW As on we tramped exultantly, and no man was our master, END
BEGIN NOW The tragic road to Anywhere, such dear, dim years ago. END
BEGIN NOW You who have lived in the land, END
BEGIN NOW You who have trusted the trail, END
BEGIN NOW You who are strong to withstand, END
BEGIN NOW You who are swift to assail: END
BEGIN NOW _Songs have I sung to beguile, END
BEGIN NOW Vintage of desperate years, END
BEGIN NOW Hard as a harlot's smile, END
BEGIN NOW Bitter as unshed tears._ END
BEGIN NOW Little of joy or mirth, END
BEGIN NOW Little of ease I sing; END
BEGIN NOW Sagas of men of earth END
BEGIN NOW Humanly suffering, END
BEGIN NOW _Such as you all have done; END
BEGIN NOW Savagely faring forth, END
BEGIN NOW Sons of the midnight sun, END
BEGIN NOW Far in the land God forgot END
BEGIN NOW Glimmers the lure of your trail; END
BEGIN NOW Still in your lust are you taught END
BEGIN NOW Even to win is to fail. END
BEGIN NOW _Still you must follow and fight END
BEGIN NOW Under the vampire wing; END
BEGIN NOW There in the long, long night END
BEGIN NOW Hoping and vanquishing._ END
BEGIN NOW Reaping a barren gain; END
BEGIN NOW Scourged by desire, reconciled END
BEGIN NOW Unto disaster and pain; END
BEGIN NOW _These, my songs, are for you, END
BEGIN NOW You who are seared with the brand. END
BEGIN NOW God knows I have tried to be true; END
BEGIN NOW Please God you will understand._ END
BEGIN NOW with preface by Rolf Boldrewood END
BEGIN NOW on the subject has been supplied in sufficient quantity. END
BEGIN NOW But the maker of folksongs for our newborn nation requires END
BEGIN NOW a somewhat rare combination of gifts and experiences. END
BEGIN NOW adown the mountain spur, and followed the night-long moving, END
BEGIN NOW spectral-seeming herd 'in the droving days'. Amid such scarce END
BEGIN NOW like undiscovered gold, await the fortunate adventurer. END
BEGIN NOW this collection comprises the best bush ballads written END
BEGIN NOW since the death of Lindsay Gordon. END
BEGIN NOW A number of these verses are now published for the first time, END
BEGIN NOW to readers in Australasia. END
BEGIN NOW I have gathered these stories afar, END
BEGIN NOW In the wind and the rain, END
BEGIN NOW In the land where the cattle camps are, END
BEGIN NOW On the edge of the plain. END
BEGIN NOW On the overland routes of the west, END
BEGIN NOW When the watches were long, END
BEGIN NOW I have fashioned in earnest and jest END
BEGIN NOW These fragments of song. END
BEGIN NOW They are just the rude stories one hears END
BEGIN NOW In sadness and mirth, END
BEGIN NOW The records of wandering years, END
BEGIN NOW And scant is their worth END
BEGIN NOW Though their merits indeed are but slight, END
BEGIN NOW I shall not repine, END
BEGIN NOW If they give you one moment's delight, END
BEGIN NOW Old comrades of mine. END
BEGIN NOW Contents with First Lines: END
BEGIN NOW I have gathered these stories afar, END
BEGIN NOW The Man from Snowy River END
BEGIN NOW There was movement at the station, for the word had passed around END
BEGIN NOW You never heard tell of the story? END
BEGIN NOW I had written him a letter which I had, for want of better END
BEGIN NOW Conroy's Gap END
BEGIN NOW This was the way of it, don't you know -- END
BEGIN NOW The boys had come back from the races END
BEGIN NOW On Western plains, where shade is not, END
BEGIN NOW It was somewhere up the country, in a land of rock and scrub, END
BEGIN NOW The roving breezes come and go, the reed beds sweep and sway, END
BEGIN NOW Now this is the law of the Overland that all in the West obey, END
BEGIN NOW I bought a run a while ago, END
BEGIN NOW There came a stranger to Walgett town, END
BEGIN NOW The widow sought the lawyer's room with children three in tow, END
BEGIN NOW The Man from Ironbark END
BEGIN NOW It was the man from Ironbark who struck the Sydney town, END
BEGIN NOW I had ridden over hurdles up the country once or twice, END
BEGIN NOW _HIM_ going to ride for us! _HIM_ -- END
BEGIN NOW with the pants and the eyeglass and all. END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run END
BEGIN NOW The roving breezes come and go END
BEGIN NOW Frying Pan's Theology END
BEGIN NOW It was shearing-time at the Myall Lake, END
BEGIN NOW 'Only a pound,' said the auctioneer, END
BEGIN NOW 'He ought to be home,' said the old man, END
BEGIN NOW 'without there's something amiss. END
BEGIN NOW Little bush maiden, wondering-eyed, END
BEGIN NOW Out in the grey cheerless chill of the morning light, END
BEGIN NOW Let us cease our idle chatter, END
BEGIN NOW A Voice from the Town END
BEGIN NOW I thought, in the days of the droving, END
BEGIN NOW Roses ruddy and roses white, END
BEGIN NOW As I lie at rest on a patch of clover END
BEGIN NOW He came from 'further out', END
BEGIN NOW Did you ever hear tell of Chili? I was readin' the other day END
BEGIN NOW A Bushman's Song END
BEGIN NOW I'm travellin' down the Castlereagh, and I'm a station hand, END
BEGIN NOW There's never a stone at the sleeper's head, END
BEGIN NOW I served my time, in the days gone by, END
BEGIN NOW The bell is set a-ringing, and the engine gives a toot, END
BEGIN NOW The Wind's Message END
BEGIN NOW There came a whisper down the Bland between the dawn and dark, END
BEGIN NOW Johnson's Antidote END
BEGIN NOW Down along the Snakebite River, where the overlanders camp, END
BEGIN NOW I am the maid of the lustrous eyes END
BEGIN NOW The daylight is dying END
BEGIN NOW Oh, the new-chum went to the back block run, END
BEGIN NOW The shearers sat in the firelight, hearty and hale and strong, END
BEGIN NOW On the outer Barcoo where the churches are few, END
BEGIN NOW 'Aye,' said the boozer, 'I tell you it's true, sir, END
BEGIN NOW MacFierce'un came to Whiskeyhurst END
BEGIN NOW Come-by-Chance END
BEGIN NOW As I pondered very weary o'er a volume long and dreary -- END
BEGIN NOW Under the Shadow of Kiley's Hill END
BEGIN NOW This is the place where they all were bred; END
BEGIN NOW Born of a thoroughbred English race, END
BEGIN NOW The Swagman's Rest END
BEGIN NOW We buried old Bob where the bloodwoods wave END
BEGIN NOW The Man from Snowy River END
BEGIN NOW There was movement at the station, for the word had passed around END
BEGIN NOW All the tried and noted riders from the stations near and far END
BEGIN NOW Had mustered at the homestead overnight, END
BEGIN NOW For the bushmen love hard riding where the wild bush horses are, END
BEGIN NOW And the stock-horse snuffs the battle with delight. END
BEGIN NOW There was Harrison, who made his pile when Pardon won the cup, END
BEGIN NOW The old man with his hair as white as snow; END
BEGIN NOW But few could ride beside him when his blood was fairly up -- END
BEGIN NOW He would go wherever horse and man could go. END
BEGIN NOW And Clancy of the Overflow came down to lend a hand, END
BEGIN NOW No better horseman ever held the reins; END
BEGIN NOW And one was there, a stripling on a small and weedy beast, END
BEGIN NOW He was something like a racehorse undersized, END
BEGIN NOW And he bore the badge of gameness in his bright and fiery eye, END
BEGIN NOW And the proud and lofty carriage of his head. END
BEGIN NOW But still so slight and weedy, one would doubt his power to stay, END
BEGIN NOW For a long and tiring gallop -- lad, you'd better stop away, END
BEGIN NOW Those hills are far too rough for such as you.' END
BEGIN NOW So he waited sad and wistful -- only Clancy stood his friend -- END
BEGIN NOW 'I think we ought to let him come,' he said; END
BEGIN NOW 'I warrant he'll be with us when he's wanted at the end, END
BEGIN NOW For both his horse and he are mountain bred. END
BEGIN NOW 'He hails from Snowy River, up by Kosciusko's side, END
BEGIN NOW Where the hills are twice as steep and twice as rough, END
BEGIN NOW And the Snowy River riders on the mountains make their home, END
BEGIN NOW Where the river runs those giant hills between; END
BEGIN NOW I have seen full many horsemen since I first commenced to roam, END
BEGIN NOW But nowhere yet such horsemen have I seen.' END
BEGIN NOW So he went -- they found the horses by the big mimosa clump -- END
BEGIN NOW They raced away towards the mountain's brow, END
BEGIN NOW And the old man gave his orders, 'Boys, go at them from the jump, END
BEGIN NOW For never yet was rider that could keep the mob in sight, END
BEGIN NOW If once they gain the shelter of those hills.' END
BEGIN NOW So Clancy rode to wheel them -- he was racing on the wing END
BEGIN NOW Where the best and boldest riders take their place, END
BEGIN NOW Then they halted for a moment, while he swung the dreaded lash, END
BEGIN NOW But they saw their well-loved mountain full in view, END
BEGIN NOW Then fast the horsemen followed, where the gorges deep and black END
BEGIN NOW Resounded to the thunder of their tread, END
BEGIN NOW And upward, ever upward, the wild horses held their way, END
BEGIN NOW Where mountain ash and kurrajong grew wide; END
BEGIN NOW And the old man muttered fiercely, 'We may bid the mob good day, END
BEGIN NOW _NO_ man can hold them down the other side.' END
BEGIN NOW When they reached the mountain's summit, even Clancy took a pull, END
BEGIN NOW The wild hop scrub grew thickly, and the hidden ground was full END
BEGIN NOW Of wombat holes, and any slip was death. END
BEGIN NOW But the man from Snowy River let the pony have his head, END
BEGIN NOW And he swung his stockwhip round and gave a cheer, END
BEGIN NOW And he raced him down the mountain like a torrent down its bed, END
BEGIN NOW While the others stood and watched in very fear. END
BEGIN NOW He sent the flint stones flying, but the pony kept his feet, END
BEGIN NOW He cleared the fallen timber in his stride, END
BEGIN NOW And the man from Snowy River never shifted in his seat -- END
BEGIN NOW It was grand to see that mountain horseman ride. END
BEGIN NOW And he never drew the bridle till he landed safe and sound, END
BEGIN NOW At the bottom of that terrible descent. END
BEGIN NOW He was right among the horses as they climbed the further hill, END
BEGIN NOW And the watchers on the mountain standing mute, END
BEGIN NOW Then they lost him for a moment, where two mountain gullies met END
BEGIN NOW In the ranges, but a final glimpse reveals END
BEGIN NOW On a dim and distant hillside the wild horses racing yet, END
BEGIN NOW With the man from Snowy River at their heels. END
BEGIN NOW But his hardy mountain pony he could scarcely raise a trot, END
BEGIN NOW He was blood from hip to shoulder from the spur; END
BEGIN NOW But his pluck was still undaunted, and his courage fiery hot, END
BEGIN NOW For never yet was mountain horse a cur. END
BEGIN NOW And down by Kosciusko, where the pine-clad ridges raise END
BEGIN NOW Their torn and rugged battlements on high, END
BEGIN NOW And where around the Overflow the reedbeds sweep and sway END
BEGIN NOW To the breezes, and the rolling plains are wide, END
BEGIN NOW The man from Snowy River is a household word to-day, END
BEGIN NOW And the stockmen tell the story of his ride. END
BEGIN NOW You never heard tell of the story? END
BEGIN NOW Well, now, I can hardly believe! END
BEGIN NOW Never heard of the honour and glory END
BEGIN NOW But maybe you're only a Johnnie END
BEGIN NOW And don't know a horse from a hoe? END
BEGIN NOW Well, well, don't get angry, my sonny, END
BEGIN NOW But, really, a young un should know. END
BEGIN NOW They bred him out back on the 'Never', END
BEGIN NOW His mother was Mameluke breed. END
BEGIN NOW To the front -- and then stay there -- was ever END
BEGIN NOW The root of the Mameluke creed. END
BEGIN NOW He seemed to inherit their wiry END
BEGIN NOW Strong frames -- and their pluck to receive -- END
BEGIN NOW As hard as a flint and as fiery END
BEGIN NOW We ran him at many a meeting END
BEGIN NOW At crossing and gully and town, END
BEGIN NOW And nothing could give him a beating -- END
BEGIN NOW At least when our money was down. END
BEGIN NOW For weight wouldn't stop him, nor distance, END
BEGIN NOW Nor odds, though the others were fast, END
BEGIN NOW He'd race with a dogged persistence, END
BEGIN NOW And wear them all down at the last. END
BEGIN NOW At the Turon the Yattendon filly END
BEGIN NOW Led by lengths at the mile-and-a-half, END
BEGIN NOW And we all began to look silly, END
BEGIN NOW While _HER_ crowd were starting to laugh; END
BEGIN NOW But the old horse came faster and faster, END
BEGIN NOW His pluck told its tale, and his strength, END
BEGIN NOW He gained on her, caught her, and passed her, END
BEGIN NOW And won it, hands-down, by a length. END
BEGIN NOW And then we swooped down on Menindie END
BEGIN NOW To run for the President's Cup -- END
BEGIN NOW Oh! that's a sweet township -- a shindy END
BEGIN NOW To them is board, lodging, and sup. END
BEGIN NOW Eye-openers they are, and their system END
BEGIN NOW Is never to suffer defeat; END
BEGIN NOW It's 'win, tie, or wrangle' -- to best 'em END
BEGIN NOW You must lose 'em, or else it's 'dead heat'. END
BEGIN NOW We strolled down the township and found 'em END
BEGIN NOW At drinking and gaming and play; END
BEGIN NOW If sorrows they had, why they drowned 'em, END
BEGIN NOW And betting was soon under way. END
BEGIN NOW Their horses were good 'uns and fit 'uns, END
BEGIN NOW There was plenty of cash in the town; END
BEGIN NOW They backed their own horses like Britons, END
BEGIN NOW And, Lord! how _WE_ rattled it down! END
BEGIN NOW With gladness we thought of the morrow, END
BEGIN NOW We counted our wagers with glee, END
BEGIN NOW A simile homely to borrow -- END
BEGIN NOW 'There was plenty of milk in our tea.' END
BEGIN NOW You see we were green; and we never END
BEGIN NOW Had even a thought of foul play, END
BEGIN NOW Though we well might have known that the clever END
BEGIN NOW Division would 'put us away'. END
BEGIN NOW Experience 'docet', they tell us, END
BEGIN NOW At least so I've frequently heard, END
BEGIN NOW But, 'dosing' or 'stuffing', those fellows END
BEGIN NOW Were up to each move on the board: END
BEGIN NOW They got to his stall -- it is sinful END
BEGIN NOW To think what such villains would do -- END
BEGIN NOW And they gave him a regular skinful END
BEGIN NOW Of barley -- green barley -- to chew. END
BEGIN NOW He munched it all night, and we found him END
BEGIN NOW Next morning as full as a hog -- END
BEGIN NOW The girths wouldn't nearly meet round him; END
BEGIN NOW He looked like an overfed frog. END
BEGIN NOW We saw we were done like a dinner -- END
BEGIN NOW The odds were a thousand to one END
BEGIN NOW Against Pardon turning up winner, END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas cruel to ask him to run. END
BEGIN NOW We got to the course with our troubles, END
BEGIN NOW A crestfallen couple were we; END
BEGIN NOW And we heard the 'books' calling the doubles -- END
BEGIN NOW A roar like the surf of the sea; END
BEGIN NOW And over the tumult and louder END
BEGIN NOW Rang 'Any price Pardon, I lay!' END
BEGIN NOW Says Jimmy, 'The children of Judah END
BEGIN NOW Are out on the warpath to-day.' END
BEGIN NOW Three miles in three heats: -- Ah, my sonny, END
BEGIN NOW The horses in those days were stout, END
BEGIN NOW They had to run well to win money; END
BEGIN NOW I don't see such horses about. END
BEGIN NOW Your six-furlong vermin that scamper END
BEGIN NOW Half-a-mile with their feather-weight up; END
BEGIN NOW They wouldn't earn much of their damper END
BEGIN NOW In a race like the President's Cup. END
BEGIN NOW The first heat was soon set a-going; END
BEGIN NOW The Dancer went off to the front; END
BEGIN NOW The Don on his quarters was showing, END
BEGIN NOW With Pardon right out of the hunt. END
BEGIN NOW He rolled and he weltered and wallowed -- END
BEGIN NOW You'd kick your hat faster, I'll bet; END
BEGIN NOW They finished all bunched, and he followed END
BEGIN NOW All lathered and dripping with sweat. END
BEGIN NOW But troubles came thicker upon us, END
BEGIN NOW For while we were rubbing him dry END
BEGIN NOW The stewards came over to warn us: END
BEGIN NOW 'We hear you are running a bye! END
BEGIN NOW If Pardon don't spiel like tarnation END
BEGIN NOW And win the next heat -- if he can -- END
BEGIN NOW He'll earn a disqualification; END
BEGIN NOW Just think over _THAT_, now, my man!' END
BEGIN NOW Our money all gone and our credit, END
BEGIN NOW Our horse couldn't gallop a yard; END
BEGIN NOW And then people thought that _WE_ did it! END
BEGIN NOW It really was terribly hard. END
BEGIN NOW We were objects of mirth and derision END
BEGIN NOW To folk in the lawn and the stand, END
BEGIN NOW And the yells of the clever division END
BEGIN NOW Of 'Any price Pardon!' were grand. END
BEGIN NOW We still had a chance for the money, END
BEGIN NOW Two heats still remained to be run; END
BEGIN NOW If both fell to us -- why, my sonny, END
BEGIN NOW The clever division were done. END
BEGIN NOW And Pardon was better, we reckoned, END
BEGIN NOW His sickness was passing away, END
BEGIN NOW So he went to the post for the second END
BEGIN NOW And principal heat of the day. END
BEGIN NOW They're off and away with a rattle, END
BEGIN NOW Like dogs from the leashes let slip, END
BEGIN NOW And right at the back of the battle END
BEGIN NOW He followed them under the whip. END
BEGIN NOW They gained ten good lengths on him quickly END
BEGIN NOW He dropped right away from the pack; END
BEGIN NOW I tell you it made me feel sickly END
BEGIN NOW To see the blue jacket fall back. END
BEGIN NOW Our very last hope had departed -- END
BEGIN NOW We thought the old fellow was done, END
BEGIN NOW When all of a sudden he started END
BEGIN NOW To go like a shot from a gun. END
BEGIN NOW His chances seemed slight to embolden END
BEGIN NOW Our hearts; but, with teeth firmly set, END
BEGIN NOW We thought, 'Now or never! The old 'un END
BEGIN NOW May reckon with some of 'em yet.' END
BEGIN NOW Then loud rose the war-cry for Pardon; END
BEGIN NOW He swept like the wind down the dip, END
BEGIN NOW And over the rise by the garden, END
BEGIN NOW The jockey was done with the whip END
BEGIN NOW The field were at sixes and sevens -- END
BEGIN NOW The pace at the first had been fast -- END
BEGIN NOW And hope seemed to drop from the heavens, END
BEGIN NOW For Pardon was coming at last. END
BEGIN NOW And how he did come! It was splendid; END
BEGIN NOW He gained on them yards every bound, END
BEGIN NOW Stretching out like a greyhound extended, END
BEGIN NOW His girth laid right down on the ground. END
BEGIN NOW A shimmer of silk in the cedars END
BEGIN NOW As into the running they wheeled, END
BEGIN NOW And out flashed the whips on the leaders, END
BEGIN NOW For Pardon had collared the field. END
BEGIN NOW Then right through the ruck he came sailing -- END
BEGIN NOW I knew that the battle was won -- END
BEGIN NOW The son of Haphazard was failing, END
BEGIN NOW The Yattendon filly was done; END
BEGIN NOW He cut down the Don and the Dancer, END
BEGIN NOW He raced clean away from the mare -- END
BEGIN NOW He's in front! Catch him now if you can, sir! END
BEGIN NOW And up went my hat in the air! END
BEGIN NOW Then loud from the lawn and the garden END
BEGIN NOW Rose offers of 'Ten to one _ON!_' END
BEGIN NOW 'Who'll bet on the field? I back Pardon!' END
BEGIN NOW No use; all the money was gone. END
BEGIN NOW He came for the third heat light-hearted, END
BEGIN NOW A-jumping and dancing about; END
BEGIN NOW The others were done ere they started END
BEGIN NOW Crestfallen, and tired, and worn out. END
BEGIN NOW He won it, and ran it much faster END
BEGIN NOW Than even the first, I believe END
BEGIN NOW Oh, he was the daddy, the master, END
BEGIN NOW He showed 'em the method to travel -- END
BEGIN NOW The boy sat as still as a stone -- END
BEGIN NOW They never could see him for gravel; END
BEGIN NOW He came in hard-held, and alone. END
BEGIN NOW But he's old -- and his eyes are grown hollow; END
BEGIN NOW Like me, with my thatch of the snow; END
BEGIN NOW When he dies, then I hope I may follow, END
BEGIN NOW And go where the racehorses go. END
BEGIN NOW I don't want no harping nor singing -- END
BEGIN NOW Such things with my style don't agree; END
BEGIN NOW Where the hoofs of the horses are ringing END
BEGIN NOW There's music sufficient for me. END
BEGIN NOW And surely the thoroughbred horses END
BEGIN NOW Will rise up again and begin END
BEGIN NOW Fresh races on far-away courses, END
BEGIN NOW And p'raps they might let me slip in. END
BEGIN NOW It would look rather well the race-card on END
BEGIN NOW 'Mongst Cherubs and Seraphs and things, END
BEGIN NOW 'Angel Harrison's black gelding Pardon, END
BEGIN NOW Blue halo, white body and wings.' END
BEGIN NOW And if they have racing hereafter, END
BEGIN NOW (And who is to say they will not?) END
BEGIN NOW When the cheers and the shouting and laughter END
BEGIN NOW Proclaim that the battle grows hot; END
BEGIN NOW As they come down the racecourse a-steering, END
BEGIN NOW He'll rush to the front, I believe; END
BEGIN NOW And you'll hear the great multitude cheering END
BEGIN NOW I had written him a letter which I had, for want of better END
BEGIN NOW Knowledge, sent to where I met him down the Lachlan, years ago, END
BEGIN NOW He was shearing when I knew him, so I sent the letter to him, END
BEGIN NOW Just 'on spec', addressed as follows, 'Clancy, of The Overflow'. END
BEGIN NOW And an answer came directed in a writing unexpected, END
BEGIN NOW In my wild erratic fancy visions come to me of Clancy END
BEGIN NOW Gone a-droving 'down the Cooper' where the Western drovers go; END
BEGIN NOW And he sees the vision splendid of the sunlit plains extended, END
BEGIN NOW And at night the wond'rous glory of the everlasting stars. END
BEGIN NOW I am sitting in my dingy little office, where a stingy END
BEGIN NOW Ray of sunlight struggles feebly down between the houses tall, END
BEGIN NOW And the foetid air and gritty of the dusty, dirty city END
BEGIN NOW Through the open window floating, spreads its foulness over all END
BEGIN NOW And in place of lowing cattle, I can hear the fiendish rattle END
BEGIN NOW Of the tramways and the 'buses making hurry down the street, END
BEGIN NOW And the language uninviting of the gutter children fighting, END
BEGIN NOW Comes fitfully and faintly through the ceaseless tramp of feet. END
BEGIN NOW And the hurrying people daunt me, and their pallid faces haunt me END
BEGIN NOW And I somehow rather fancy that I'd like to change with Clancy, END
BEGIN NOW Like to take a turn at droving where the seasons come and go, END
BEGIN NOW Conroy's Gap END
BEGIN NOW This was the way of it, don't you know -- END
BEGIN NOW Ryan was 'wanted' for stealing sheep, END
BEGIN NOW And never a trooper, high or low, END
BEGIN NOW Could find him -- catch a weasel asleep! END
BEGIN NOW Till Trooper Scott, from the Stockman's Ford -- END
BEGIN NOW A bushman, too, as I've heard them tell -- END
BEGIN NOW Chanced to find him drunk as a lord END
BEGIN NOW D'you know the place? It's a wayside inn, END
BEGIN NOW A low grog-shanty -- a bushman trap, END
BEGIN NOW Hiding away in its shame and sin END
BEGIN NOW Under the shelter of Conroy's Gap -- END
BEGIN NOW Under the shade of that frowning range, END
BEGIN NOW The roughest crowd that ever drew breath -- END
BEGIN NOW Thieves and rowdies, uncouth and strange, END
BEGIN NOW Were mustered round at the Shadow of Death. END
BEGIN NOW The trooper knew that his man would slide END
BEGIN NOW Like a dingo pup, if he saw the chance; END
BEGIN NOW And with half a start on the mountain side END
BEGIN NOW Ryan would lead him a merry dance. END
BEGIN NOW Drunk as he was when the trooper came, END
BEGIN NOW To him that did not matter a rap -- END
BEGIN NOW Drunk or sober, he was the same, END
BEGIN NOW The boldest rider in Conroy's Gap. END
BEGIN NOW 'I want you, Ryan,' the trooper said, END
BEGIN NOW 'And listen to me, if you dare resist, END
BEGIN NOW So help me heaven, I'll shoot you dead!' END
BEGIN NOW He snapped the steel on his prisoner's wrist, END
BEGIN NOW And Ryan, hearing the handcuffs click, END
BEGIN NOW Recovered his wits as they turned to go, END
BEGIN NOW For fright will sober a man as quick END
BEGIN NOW As all the drugs that the doctors know. END
BEGIN NOW There was a girl in that rough bar END
BEGIN NOW Went by the name of Kate Carew, END
BEGIN NOW Quiet and shy as the bush girls are, END
BEGIN NOW But ready-witted and plucky, too. END
BEGIN NOW She loved this Ryan, or so they say, END
BEGIN NOW And passing by, while her eyes were dim END
BEGIN NOW With tears, she said in a careless way, END
BEGIN NOW 'The Swagman's round in the stable, Jim.' END
BEGIN NOW Spoken too low for the trooper's ear, END
BEGIN NOW Why should she care if he heard or not? END
BEGIN NOW Plenty of swagmen far and near, END
BEGIN NOW And yet to Ryan it meant a lot. END
BEGIN NOW That was the name of the grandest horse END
BEGIN NOW In all the district from east to west END
BEGIN NOW In every show ring, on every course END
BEGIN NOW They always counted the Swagman best. END
BEGIN NOW He was a wonder, a raking bay -- END
BEGIN NOW One of the grand old Snowdon strain -- END
BEGIN NOW One of the sort that could race and stay END
BEGIN NOW With his mighty limbs and his length of rein. END
BEGIN NOW Born and bred on the mountain side, END
BEGIN NOW He could race through scrub like a kangaroo, END
BEGIN NOW The girl herself on his back might ride, END
BEGIN NOW And the Swagman would carry her safely through. END
BEGIN NOW He would travel gaily from daylight's flush END
BEGIN NOW Till after the stars hung out their lamps, END
BEGIN NOW There was never his like in the open bush, END
BEGIN NOW And never his match on the cattle-camps. END
BEGIN NOW For faster horses might well be found END
BEGIN NOW On racing tracks, or a plain's extent, END
BEGIN NOW But few, if any, on broken ground END
BEGIN NOW Could see the way that the Swagman went. END
BEGIN NOW When this girl's father, old Jim Carew, END
BEGIN NOW Was droving out on the Castlereagh END
BEGIN NOW With Conroy's cattle, a wire came through END
BEGIN NOW To say that his wife couldn't live the day. END
BEGIN NOW And he was a hundred miles from home, END
BEGIN NOW As flies the crow, with never a track, END
BEGIN NOW Through plains as pathless as ocean's foam, END
BEGIN NOW He mounted straight on the Swagman's back. END
BEGIN NOW He left the camp by the sundown light, END
BEGIN NOW And the settlers out on the Marthaguy END
BEGIN NOW Awoke and heard, in the dead of night, END
BEGIN NOW A single horseman hurrying by. END
BEGIN NOW He crossed the Bogan at Dandaloo, END
BEGIN NOW And many a mile of the silent plain END
BEGIN NOW That lonely rider behind him threw END
BEGIN NOW Before they settled to sleep again. END
BEGIN NOW He rode all night and he steered his course END
BEGIN NOW By the shining stars with a bushman's skill, END
BEGIN NOW And every time that he pressed his horse END
BEGIN NOW The Swagman answered him gamely still. END
BEGIN NOW He neared his home as the east was bright, END
BEGIN NOW The doctor met him outside the town: END
BEGIN NOW 'Carew! How far did you come last night?' END
BEGIN NOW 'A hundred miles since the sun went down.' END
BEGIN NOW And his wife got round, and an oath he passed, END
BEGIN NOW So long as he or one of his breed END
BEGIN NOW Could raise a coin, though it took their last END
BEGIN NOW The Swagman never should want a feed. END
BEGIN NOW And Kate Carew, when her father died, END
BEGIN NOW She kept the horse and she kept him well: END
BEGIN NOW The pride of the district far and wide, END
BEGIN NOW He lived in style at the bush hotel. END
BEGIN NOW Such was the Swagman; and Ryan knew END
BEGIN NOW Nothing about could pace the crack; END
BEGIN NOW Little he'd care for the man in blue END
BEGIN NOW If once he got on the Swagman's back. END
BEGIN NOW But how to do it? A word let fall END
BEGIN NOW Gave him the hint as the girl passed by; END
BEGIN NOW Nothing but 'Swagman -- stable-wall; END
BEGIN NOW 'Go to the stable and mind your eye.' END
BEGIN NOW He caught her meaning, and quickly turned END
BEGIN NOW To the trooper: 'Reckon you'll gain a stripe END
BEGIN NOW By arresting me, and it's easily earned; END
BEGIN NOW Let's go to the stable and get my pipe, END
BEGIN NOW The Swagman has it.' So off they went, END
BEGIN NOW And soon as ever they turned their backs END
BEGIN NOW The girl slipped down, on some errand bent END
BEGIN NOW Behind the stable, and seized an axe. END
BEGIN NOW The trooper stood at the stable door END
BEGIN NOW While Ryan went in quite cool and slow, END
BEGIN NOW And then (the trick had been played before) END
BEGIN NOW The girl outside gave the wall a blow. END
BEGIN NOW Three slabs fell out of the stable wall -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas done 'fore ever the trooper knew -- END
BEGIN NOW And Ryan, as soon as he saw them fall, END
BEGIN NOW Mounted the Swagman and rushed him through. END
BEGIN NOW The trooper heard the hoof-beats ring END
BEGIN NOW In the stable yard, and he slammed the gate, END
BEGIN NOW But the Swagman rose with a mighty spring END
BEGIN NOW At the fence, and the trooper fired too late, END
BEGIN NOW As they raced away and his shots flew wide END
BEGIN NOW And Ryan no longer need care a rap, END
BEGIN NOW For never a horse that was lapped in hide END
BEGIN NOW Could catch the Swagman in Conroy's Gap. END
BEGIN NOW And that's the story. You want to know END
BEGIN NOW If Ryan came back to his Kate Carew; END
BEGIN NOW Of course he should have, as stories go, END
BEGIN NOW But the worst of it is, this story's true: END
BEGIN NOW And in real life it's a certain rule, END
BEGIN NOW Whatever poets and authors say END
BEGIN NOW Of high-toned robbers and all their school, END
BEGIN NOW These horsethief fellows aren't built that way. END
BEGIN NOW Come back! Don't hope it -- the slinking hound, END
BEGIN NOW He sloped across to the Queensland side, END
BEGIN NOW And sold the Swagman for fifty pound, END
BEGIN NOW And stole the money, and more beside. END
BEGIN NOW And took to drink, and by some good chance END
BEGIN NOW Was killed -- thrown out of a stolen trap. END
BEGIN NOW And that was the end of this small romance, END
BEGIN NOW The end of the story of Conroy's Gap. END
BEGIN NOW The boys had come back from the races END
BEGIN NOW All silent and down on their luck; END
BEGIN NOW They'd backed 'em, straight out and for places, END
BEGIN NOW But never a winner they struck. END
BEGIN NOW They lost their good money on Slogan, END
BEGIN NOW And fell, most uncommonly flat, END
BEGIN NOW When Partner, the pride of the Bogan, END
BEGIN NOW Was beaten by Aristocrat. END
BEGIN NOW And one said, 'I move that instanter END
BEGIN NOW We sell out our horses and quit, END
BEGIN NOW The brutes ought to win in a canter, END
BEGIN NOW Such trials they do when they're fit. END
BEGIN NOW The last one they ran was a snorter -- END
BEGIN NOW A gallop to gladden one's heart -- END
BEGIN NOW Two-twelve for a mile and a quarter, END
BEGIN NOW And finished as straight as a dart. END
BEGIN NOW 'And then when I think that they're ready END
BEGIN NOW To win me a nice little swag, END
BEGIN NOW They are licked like the veriest neddy -- END
BEGIN NOW They're licked from the fall of the flag. END
BEGIN NOW The mare held her own to the stable, END
BEGIN NOW She died out to nothing at that, END
BEGIN NOW And Partner he never seemed able END
BEGIN NOW To pace it with Aristocrat. END
BEGIN NOW 'And times have been bad, and the seasons END
BEGIN NOW Don't promise to be of the best; END
BEGIN NOW In short, boys, there's plenty of reasons END
BEGIN NOW For giving the racing a rest. END
BEGIN NOW The mare can be kept on the station -- END
BEGIN NOW Her breeding is good as can be -- END
BEGIN NOW But Partner, his next destination END
BEGIN NOW Is rather a trouble to me. END
BEGIN NOW 'We can't sell him here, for they know him END
BEGIN NOW As well as the clerk of the course; END
BEGIN NOW He's raced and won races till, blow him, END
BEGIN NOW He's done as a handicap horse. END
BEGIN NOW A jady, uncertain performer, END
BEGIN NOW They weight him right out of the hunt, END
BEGIN NOW And clap it on warmer and warmer END
BEGIN NOW Whenever he gets near the front. END
BEGIN NOW 'It's no use to paint him or dot him END
BEGIN NOW Or put any 'fake' on his brand, END
BEGIN NOW For bushmen are smart, and they'd spot him END
BEGIN NOW In any sale-yard in the land. END
BEGIN NOW The folk about here could all tell him, END
BEGIN NOW Could swear to each separate hair; END
BEGIN NOW Let us send him to Sydney and sell him, END
BEGIN NOW There's plenty of Jugginses there. END
BEGIN NOW 'We'll call him a maiden, and treat 'em END
BEGIN NOW To trials will open their eyes, END
BEGIN NOW We'll run their best horses and beat 'em, END
BEGIN NOW And then won't they think him a prize. END
BEGIN NOW I pity the fellow that buys him, END
BEGIN NOW He'll find in a very short space, END
BEGIN NOW No matter how highly he tries him, END
BEGIN NOW The beggar won't _RACE_ in a race.' END
BEGIN NOW Next week, under 'Seller and Buyer', END
BEGIN NOW Appeared in the _DAILY GAZETTE_: END
BEGIN NOW 'A racehorse for sale, and a flyer; END
BEGIN NOW Has never been started as yet; END
BEGIN NOW A trial will show what his pace is; END
BEGIN NOW The buyer can get him in light, END
BEGIN NOW And win all the handicap races. END
BEGIN NOW Apply here before Wednesday night.' END
BEGIN NOW He sold for a hundred and thirty, END
BEGIN NOW Because of a gallop he had END
BEGIN NOW One morning with Bluefish and Bertie, END
BEGIN NOW And donkey-licked both of 'em bad. END
BEGIN NOW And when the old horse had departed, END
BEGIN NOW The life on the station grew tame; END
BEGIN NOW The race-track was dull and deserted, END
BEGIN NOW The boys had gone back on the game. END
BEGIN NOW The winter rolled by, and the station END
BEGIN NOW Was green with the garland of spring END
BEGIN NOW A spirit of glad exultation END
BEGIN NOW Awoke in each animate thing. END
BEGIN NOW And all the old love, the old longing, END
BEGIN NOW Broke out in the breasts of the boys, END
BEGIN NOW The visions of racing came thronging END
BEGIN NOW With all its delirious joys. END
BEGIN NOW The rushing of floods in their courses, END
BEGIN NOW The rattle of rain on the roofs END
BEGIN NOW Recalled the fierce rush of the horses, END
BEGIN NOW The thunder of galloping hoofs. END
BEGIN NOW And soon one broke out: 'I can suffer END
BEGIN NOW No longer the life of a slug, END
BEGIN NOW The man that don't race is a duffer, END
BEGIN NOW Let's have one more run for the mug. END
BEGIN NOW 'Why, _EVERYTHING_ races, no matter END
BEGIN NOW Whatever its method may be: END
BEGIN NOW The waterfowl hold a regatta; END
BEGIN NOW The 'possums run heats up a tree; END
BEGIN NOW The emus are constantly sprinting END
BEGIN NOW A handicap out on the plain; END
BEGIN NOW It seems like all nature was hinting, END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis time to be at it again. END
BEGIN NOW 'The cockatoo parrots are talking END
BEGIN NOW Of races to far away lands; END
BEGIN NOW The native companions are walking END
BEGIN NOW A go-as-you-please on the sands; END
BEGIN NOW The little foals gallop for pastime; END
BEGIN NOW The wallabies race down the gap; END
BEGIN NOW Let's try it once more for the last time, END
BEGIN NOW Bring out the old jacket and cap. END
BEGIN NOW 'And now for a horse; we might try one END
BEGIN NOW Of those that are bred on the place, END
BEGIN NOW But I think it better to buy one, END
BEGIN NOW A horse that has proved he can race. END
BEGIN NOW Let us send down to Sydney to Skinner, END
BEGIN NOW A thorough good judge who can ride, END
BEGIN NOW And ask him to buy us a spinner END
BEGIN NOW To clean out the whole countryside.' END
BEGIN NOW They wrote him a letter as follows: END
BEGIN NOW 'We want you to buy us a horse; END
BEGIN NOW He must have the speed to catch swallows, END
BEGIN NOW And stamina with it of course. END
BEGIN NOW The price ain't a thing that'll grieve us, END
BEGIN NOW It's getting a bad 'un annoys END
BEGIN NOW The undersigned blokes, and believe us, END
BEGIN NOW We're yours to a cinder, 'the boys'.' END
BEGIN NOW He answered: 'I've bought you a hummer, END
BEGIN NOW A horse that has never been raced; END
BEGIN NOW I saw him run over the Drummer, END
BEGIN NOW He held him outclassed and outpaced. END
BEGIN NOW His breeding's not known, but they state he END
BEGIN NOW Is born of a thoroughbred strain, END
BEGIN NOW I paid them a hundred and eighty, END
BEGIN NOW And started the horse in the train.' END
BEGIN NOW They met him -- alas, that these verses END
BEGIN NOW Aren't up to the subject's demands -- END
BEGIN NOW Can't set forth their eloquent curses, END
BEGIN NOW They went in to meet him in gladness, END
BEGIN NOW They opened his box with delight -- END
BEGIN NOW A silent procession of sadness END
BEGIN NOW They crept to the station at night. END
BEGIN NOW And life has grown dull on the station, END
BEGIN NOW The boys are all silent and slow; END
BEGIN NOW Their work is a daily vexation, END
BEGIN NOW And sport is unknown to them now. END
BEGIN NOW Whenever they think how they stranded, END
BEGIN NOW They squeal just like guinea-pigs squeal; END
BEGIN NOW They bit their own hook, and were landed END
BEGIN NOW With fifty pounds loss on the deal. END
BEGIN NOW On Western plains, where shade is not, END
BEGIN NOW 'Neath summer skies of cloudless blue, END
BEGIN NOW Where all is dry and all is hot, END
BEGIN NOW There stands the town of Dandaloo -- END
BEGIN NOW A township where life's total sum END
BEGIN NOW Is sleep, diversified with rum. END
BEGIN NOW It's grass-grown streets with dust are deep, END
BEGIN NOW 'Twere vain endeavour to express END
BEGIN NOW The dreamless silence of its sleep, END
BEGIN NOW Its wide, expansive drunkenness. END
BEGIN NOW The yearly races mostly drew END
BEGIN NOW A lively crowd to Dandaloo. END
BEGIN NOW There came a sportsman from the East, END
BEGIN NOW The eastern land where sportsmen blow, END
BEGIN NOW And brought with him a speedy beast -- END
BEGIN NOW A speedy beast as horses go. END
BEGIN NOW He came afar in hope to 'do' END
BEGIN NOW The little town of Dandaloo. END
BEGIN NOW Now this was weak of him, I wot -- END
BEGIN NOW Exceeding weak, it seemed to me -- END
BEGIN NOW For we in Dandaloo were not END
BEGIN NOW The Jugginses we seemed to be; END
BEGIN NOW In fact, we rather thought we knew END
BEGIN NOW Our book by heart in Dandaloo. END
BEGIN NOW We held a meeting at the bar, END
BEGIN NOW And met the question fair and square -- END
BEGIN NOW 'We've stumped the country near and far END
BEGIN NOW To raise the cash for races here; END
BEGIN NOW We've got a hundred pounds or two -- END
BEGIN NOW Not half so bad for Dandaloo. END
BEGIN NOW 'And now, it seems, we have to be END
BEGIN NOW Cleaned out by this here Sydney bloke, END
BEGIN NOW With his imported horse; and he END
BEGIN NOW Will scoop the pool and leave us broke END
BEGIN NOW Shall we sit still, and make no fuss END
BEGIN NOW While this chap climbs all over us?' END
BEGIN NOW The races came to Dandaloo, END
BEGIN NOW And all the cornstalks from the West, END
BEGIN NOW On ev'ry kind of moke and screw, END
BEGIN NOW Came forth in all their glory drest. END
BEGIN NOW The stranger's horse, as hard as nails, END
BEGIN NOW Look'd fit to run for New South Wales. END
BEGIN NOW He won the race by half a length -- END
BEGIN NOW _QUITE_ half a length, it seemed to me -- END
BEGIN NOW But Dandaloo, with all its strength, END
BEGIN NOW Roared out 'Dead heat!' most fervently; END
BEGIN NOW And, after hesitation meet, END
BEGIN NOW The judge's verdict was 'Dead heat!' END
BEGIN NOW And many men there were could tell END
BEGIN NOW What gave the verdict extra force: END
BEGIN NOW The stewards, and the judge as well -- END
BEGIN NOW They all had backed the second horse. END
BEGIN NOW For things like this they sometimes do END
BEGIN NOW In larger towns than Dandaloo. END
BEGIN NOW They ran it off; the stranger won, END
BEGIN NOW Hands down, by near a hundred yards END
BEGIN NOW He smiled to think his troubles done; END
BEGIN NOW But Dandaloo held all the cards. END
BEGIN NOW They went to scale and -- cruel fate! -- END
BEGIN NOW His jockey turned out under-weight. END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps they'd tampered with the scale! END
BEGIN NOW I cannot tell. I only know END
BEGIN NOW It weighed him _OUT_ all right. I fail END
BEGIN NOW To paint that Sydney sportsman's woe. END
BEGIN NOW He said the stewards were a crew END
BEGIN NOW Of low-lived thieves in Dandaloo. END
BEGIN NOW He lifted up his voice, irate, END
BEGIN NOW And swore till all the air was blue; END
BEGIN NOW So then we rose to vindicate END
BEGIN NOW The dignity of Dandaloo. END
BEGIN NOW 'Look here,' said we, 'you must not poke END
BEGIN NOW Such oaths at us poor country folk.' END
BEGIN NOW We rode him softly on a rail, END
BEGIN NOW We shied at him, in careless glee, END
BEGIN NOW Some large tomatoes, rank and stale, END
BEGIN NOW And eggs of great antiquity -- END
BEGIN NOW Their wild, unholy fragrance flew END
BEGIN NOW About the town of Dandaloo. END
BEGIN NOW He left the town at break of day, END
BEGIN NOW He led his race-horse through the streets, END
BEGIN NOW And now he tells the tale, they say, END
BEGIN NOW To every racing man he meets. END
BEGIN NOW And Sydney sportsmen all eschew END
BEGIN NOW The atmosphere of Dandaloo. END
BEGIN NOW It was somewhere up the country, in a land of rock and scrub, END
BEGIN NOW That they formed an institution called the Geebung Polo Club. END
BEGIN NOW They were long and wiry natives from the rugged mountain side, END
BEGIN NOW And the horse was never saddled that the Geebungs couldn't ride; END
BEGIN NOW But their style of playing polo was irregular and rash -- END
BEGIN NOW They had mighty little science, but a mighty lot of dash: END
BEGIN NOW And they played on mountain ponies that were muscular and strong, END
BEGIN NOW and their manes and tails were long. END
BEGIN NOW And they used to train those ponies wheeling cattle in the scrub: END
BEGIN NOW It was somewhere down the country, in a city's smoke and steam, END
BEGIN NOW That a polo club existed, called 'The Cuff and Collar Team'. END
BEGIN NOW As a social institution 'twas a marvellous success, END
BEGIN NOW For the members were distinguished by exclusiveness and dress. END
BEGIN NOW So they started up the country in pursuit of sport and fame, END
BEGIN NOW Now my readers can imagine how the contest ebbed and flowed, END
BEGIN NOW When the Geebung boys got going it was time to clear the road; END
BEGIN NOW And the game was so terrific that ere half the time was gone END
BEGIN NOW A spectator's leg was broken -- just from merely looking on. END
BEGIN NOW For they waddied one another till the plain was strewn with dead, END
BEGIN NOW And the Cuff and Collar Captain, when he tumbled off to die, END
BEGIN NOW Was the last surviving player -- so the game was called a tie. END
BEGIN NOW So he scrambled on his pony for his last expiring chance, END
BEGIN NOW For he meant to make an effort to get victory to his side; END
BEGIN NOW By the old Campaspe River, where the breezes shake the grass, END
BEGIN NOW There's a row of little gravestones that the stockmen never pass, END
BEGIN NOW And on misty moonlit evenings, while the dingoes howl around, END
BEGIN NOW You can see their shadows flitting down that phantom polo ground; END
BEGIN NOW And the rattle of the mallets, and the rush of ponies' feet, END
BEGIN NOW Till the terrified spectator rides like blazes to the pub -- END
BEGIN NOW He's been haunted by the spectres of the Geebung Polo Club. END
BEGIN NOW The roving breezes come and go, the reed beds sweep and sway, END
BEGIN NOW The sleepy river murmurs low, and loiters on its way, END
BEGIN NOW It is the land of lots o' time along the Castlereagh. END
BEGIN NOW The old man's son had left the farm, he found it dull and slow, END
BEGIN NOW He drifted to the great North-west where all the rovers go. END
BEGIN NOW He's shearing here and fencing there, a kind of waif and stray, END
BEGIN NOW He's droving now with Conroy's sheep along the Castlereagh. END
BEGIN NOW Or tramping down the black soil flats across by Waddiwong, END
BEGIN NOW But all those little country towns would send the letter wrong, END
BEGIN NOW The mailman, if he's extra tired, would pass them in his sleep, END
BEGIN NOW It's safest to address the note to 'Care of Conroy's sheep', END
BEGIN NOW For five and twenty thousand head can scarcely go astray, END
BEGIN NOW You write to 'Care of Conroy's sheep along the Castlereagh'.' END
BEGIN NOW By rock and ridge and riverside the western mail has gone, END
BEGIN NOW Across the great Blue Mountain Range to take that letter on. END
BEGIN NOW A moment on the topmost grade while open fire doors glare, END
BEGIN NOW She pauses like a living thing to breathe the mountain air, END
BEGIN NOW Then launches down the other side across the plains away END
BEGIN NOW To bear that note to 'Conroy's sheep along the Castlereagh'. END
BEGIN NOW And now by coach and mailman's bag it goes from town to town, END
BEGIN NOW A speck upon the waste of plain the lonely mailman rides. END
BEGIN NOW Where fierce hot winds have set the pine and myall boughs asweep END
BEGIN NOW He hails the shearers passing by for news of Conroy's sheep. END
BEGIN NOW By big lagoons where wildfowl play and crested pigeons flock, END
BEGIN NOW By camp fires where the drovers ride around their restless stock, END
BEGIN NOW My letter chases Conroy's sheep along the Castlereagh. END
BEGIN NOW Now this is the law of the Overland that all in the West obey, END
BEGIN NOW A man must cover with travelling sheep a six-mile stage a day; END
BEGIN NOW but they camp where the grass is good; END
BEGIN NOW on the edge of the saltbush plains, END
BEGIN NOW 'tis written in white and black -- END
BEGIN NOW on the runs where the grass is dead, END
BEGIN NOW But they spread their sheep on a well-grassed run END
BEGIN NOW till they go with a two-mile spread. END
BEGIN NOW are willing the peace to keep, END
BEGIN NOW For the drovers learn how to use their hands END
BEGIN NOW when they go with the travelling sheep; END
BEGIN NOW Now Saltbush Bill was a drover tough, as ever the country knew, END
BEGIN NOW He had fought his way on the Great Stock Routes END
BEGIN NOW from the sea to the big Barcoo; END
BEGIN NOW He could tell when he came to a friendly run END
BEGIN NOW that gave him a chance to spread, END
BEGIN NOW with a mob that could scarcely creep, END
BEGIN NOW (When the kangaroos by the thousands starve, END
BEGIN NOW it is rough on the travelling sheep), END
BEGIN NOW 'or the half of the mob are done!' END
BEGIN NOW And they set to work on the straggling sheep, END
BEGIN NOW and with many a stockwhip crack END
BEGIN NOW They forced them in where the grass was dead END
BEGIN NOW in the space of the half-mile track; END
BEGIN NOW in the teeth of that Jackaroo. END
BEGIN NOW though the sheep ran loose the while, END
BEGIN NOW Now, the new chum fought for his honour's sake END
BEGIN NOW and the pride of the English race, END
BEGIN NOW they whispered to Saltbush Bill -- END
BEGIN NOW 'We have spread the sheep with a two-mile spread, END
BEGIN NOW and the grass it is something grand, END
BEGIN NOW You must stick to him, Bill, for another round END
BEGIN NOW for the pride of the Overland.' END
BEGIN NOW and glared on the brick-red loam, END
BEGIN NOW So the new chum rode to the homestead straight END
BEGIN NOW and he told them a story grand END
BEGIN NOW Of the desperate fight that he fought that day END
BEGIN NOW with the King of the Overland. END
BEGIN NOW And the tale went home to the Public Schools END
BEGIN NOW of the pluck of the English swell, END
BEGIN NOW were boxed on the Old Man Plain. END
BEGIN NOW with a curse and a stockwhip crack, END
BEGIN NOW They hunted them off on the road once more END
BEGIN NOW to starve on the half-mile track. END
BEGIN NOW And Saltbush Bill, on the Overland, will many a time recite END
BEGIN NOW How the best day's work that ever he did END
BEGIN NOW was the day that he lost the fight. END
BEGIN NOW I bought a run a while ago, END
BEGIN NOW On country rough and ridgy, END
BEGIN NOW Where wallaroos and wombats grow -- END
BEGIN NOW The grass is rather scant, it's true, END
BEGIN NOW But this a fair exchange is, END
BEGIN NOW The sheep can see a lovely view END
BEGIN NOW By climbing up the ranges. END
BEGIN NOW And She-oak Flat's the station's name, END
BEGIN NOW I'm not surprised at that, sirs: END
BEGIN NOW The oaks were there before I came, END
BEGIN NOW And I supplied the flat, sirs. END
BEGIN NOW A man would wonder how it's done, END
BEGIN NOW The stock so soon decreases -- END
BEGIN NOW They sometimes tumble off the run END
BEGIN NOW And break themselves to pieces. END
BEGIN NOW I've tried to make expenses meet, END
BEGIN NOW But wasted all my labours, END
BEGIN NOW The sheep the dingoes didn't eat END
BEGIN NOW Were stolen by the neighbours. END
BEGIN NOW They stole my pears -- my native pears -- END
BEGIN NOW Those thrice-convicted felons, END
BEGIN NOW And ravished from me unawares END
BEGIN NOW My crop of paddy-melons. END
BEGIN NOW And sometimes under sunny skies, END
BEGIN NOW Without an explanation, END
BEGIN NOW The Murrumbidgee used to rise END
BEGIN NOW And overflow the station. END
BEGIN NOW But this was caused (as now I know) END
BEGIN NOW When summer sunshine glowing END
BEGIN NOW Had melted all Kiandra's snow END
BEGIN NOW And set the river going. END
BEGIN NOW And in the news, perhaps you read: END
BEGIN NOW 'Stock passings. Puckawidgee, END
BEGIN NOW Fat cattle: Seven hundred head END
BEGIN NOW Swept down the Murrumbidgee; END
BEGIN NOW Their destination's quite obscure, END
BEGIN NOW But, somehow, there's a notion, END
BEGIN NOW Unless the river falls, they're sure END
BEGIN NOW To reach the Southern Ocean.' END
BEGIN NOW So after that I'll give it best; END
BEGIN NOW No more with Fate I'll battle. END
BEGIN NOW I'll let the river take the rest, END
BEGIN NOW For those were all my cattle. END
BEGIN NOW And with one comprehensive curse END
BEGIN NOW I close my brief narration, END
BEGIN NOW And advertise it in my verse -- END
BEGIN NOW There came a stranger to Walgett town, END
BEGIN NOW To Walgett town when the sun was low, END
BEGIN NOW And he carried a thirst that was worth a crown, END
BEGIN NOW Yet how to quench it he did not know; END
BEGIN NOW But he thought he might take those yokels down, END
BEGIN NOW The guileless yokels of Walgett town. END
BEGIN NOW They made him a bet in a private bar, END
BEGIN NOW In a private bar when the talk was high, END
BEGIN NOW And they bet him some pounds no matter how far END
BEGIN NOW He could pelt a stone, yet he could not shy END
BEGIN NOW A stone right over the river so brown, END
BEGIN NOW The Darling river at Walgett town. END
BEGIN NOW He knew that the river from bank to bank END
BEGIN NOW Was fifty yards, and he smiled a smile END
BEGIN NOW As he trundled down, but his hopes they sank END
BEGIN NOW For there wasn't a stone within fifty mile; END
BEGIN NOW For the saltbush plain and the open down END
BEGIN NOW Produce no quarries in Walgett town. END
BEGIN NOW The yokels laughed at his hopes o'erthrown, END
BEGIN NOW And he stood awhile like a man in a dream; END
BEGIN NOW Then out of his pocket he fetched a stone, END
BEGIN NOW And pelted it over the silent stream -- END
BEGIN NOW He had been there before: he had wandered down END
BEGIN NOW On a previous visit to Walgett town. END
BEGIN NOW The widow sought the lawyer's room with children three in tow, END
BEGIN NOW She told the lawyer man her tale in tones of deepest woe. END
BEGIN NOW Said she, 'My husband took to drink for pains in his inside, END
BEGIN NOW And never drew a sober breath from then until he died. END
BEGIN NOW 'He never drew a sober breath, he died without a will, END
BEGIN NOW And I must sell the bit of land the childer's mouths to fill. END
BEGIN NOW There's some is grown and gone away, but some is childer yet, END
BEGIN NOW And times is very bad indeed -- a livin's hard to get. END
BEGIN NOW And Fred is drovin' Conroy's sheep along the Castlereagh, END
BEGIN NOW And Charley's shearin' down the Bland, and Peter is away.' END
BEGIN NOW The lawyer wrote the details down in ink of legal blue -- END
BEGIN NOW 'There's Minnie, Susan, Christopher, they stop at home with you; END
BEGIN NOW There's Sarah, Frederick, and Charles, I'll write to them to-day, END
BEGIN NOW 'You'll have to furnish his consent to sell the bit of land.' END
BEGIN NOW The widow shuffled in her seat, 'Oh, don't you understand? END
BEGIN NOW I thought a lawyer ought to know -- I don't know what to say -- END
BEGIN NOW You'll have to do without him, boss, for Peter is away.' END
BEGIN NOW The mystery of Peter's life -- the man who was away. END
BEGIN NOW The Man from Ironbark END
BEGIN NOW It was the man from Ironbark who struck the Sydney town, END
BEGIN NOW He wandered over street and park, he wandered up and down. END
BEGIN NOW He loitered here, he loitered there, till he was like to drop, END
BEGIN NOW Until at last in sheer despair he sought a barber's shop. END
BEGIN NOW ''Ere! shave my beard and whiskers off, I'll be a man of mark, END
BEGIN NOW I'll go and do the Sydney toff up home in Ironbark.' END
BEGIN NOW The barber man was small and flash, as barbers mostly are, END
BEGIN NOW He wore a strike-your-fancy sash, he smoked a huge cigar: END
BEGIN NOW He was a humorist of note and keen at repartee, END
BEGIN NOW He laid the odds and kept a 'tote', whatever that may be, END
BEGIN NOW And when he saw our friend arrive, he whispered 'Here's a lark! END
BEGIN NOW Just watch me catch him all alive, this man from Ironbark.' END
BEGIN NOW There were some gilded youths that sat along the barber's wall, END
BEGIN NOW 'I'll make this bloomin' yokel think his bloomin' throat is cut.' END
BEGIN NOW 'I s'pose the flats is pretty green up there in Ironbark.' END
BEGIN NOW A grunt was all reply he got; he shaved the bushman's chin, END
BEGIN NOW Then made the water boiling hot and dipped the razor in. END
BEGIN NOW Upon the newly shaven skin it made a livid mark -- END
BEGIN NOW No doubt it fairly took him in -- the man from Ironbark. END
BEGIN NOW He fetched a wild up-country yell might wake the dead to hear, END
BEGIN NOW 'You've done for me! you dog, I'm beat! one hit before I go! END
BEGIN NOW I only wish I had a knife, you blessed murdering shark! END
BEGIN NOW But you'll remember all your life, the man from Ironbark.' END
BEGIN NOW He lifted up his hairy paw, with one tremendous clout END
BEGIN NOW He landed on the barber's jaw, and knocked the barber out. END
BEGIN NOW He set to work with tooth and nail, he made the place a wreck; END
BEGIN NOW He grabbed the nearest gilded youth, and tried to break his neck. END
BEGIN NOW And 'Murder! Bloody Murder!' yelled the man from Ironbark. END
BEGIN NOW A peeler man who heard the din came in to see the show; END
BEGIN NOW He tried to run the bushman in, but he refused to go. END
BEGIN NOW And when at last the barber spoke, and said, ''Twas all in fun -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Them barber chaps what keeps a tote, By George, I've had enough, END
BEGIN NOW That flowing beards are all the go way up in Ironbark. END
BEGIN NOW I had ridden over hurdles up the country once or twice, END
BEGIN NOW By the side of Snowy River with a horse they called 'The Ace'. END
BEGIN NOW And we brought him down to Sydney, and our rider Jimmy Rice, END
BEGIN NOW 'Are you ready?' said the starter, as we held the horses back, END
BEGIN NOW All ablazing with impatience, with excitement all aglow; END
BEGIN NOW Before us like a ribbon stretched the steeplechasing track, END
BEGIN NOW And the sun-rays glistened brightly on the chestnut and the black END
BEGIN NOW Well, I scarcely knew we'd started, I was stupid-like with wonder END
BEGIN NOW And we flew it like a hurdle, not a baulk and not a blunder, END
BEGIN NOW As we charged it all together, and it fairly whistled under, END
BEGIN NOW And then some were pulled behind me and a few shot out and led. END
BEGIN NOW So we ran for half the distance, and I'm making no pretences END
BEGIN NOW When I tell you I was feeling very nervous-like and queer, END
BEGIN NOW For those jockeys rode like demons; END
BEGIN NOW you would think they'd lost their senses END
BEGIN NOW Are there riders on Monaro? ----' but I never heard the rest. END
BEGIN NOW Let us mend the pace a little and we'll see who cries a crack.' END
BEGIN NOW So we raced away together, and we left the others standing, END
BEGIN NOW And the people cheered and shouted as we settled down to ride, END
BEGIN NOW And we clung beside the Quiver. At his taking off and landing END
BEGIN NOW I could see his scarlet nostril and his mighty ribs expanding, END
BEGIN NOW There was no one next or near me for the field was fairly slated, END
BEGIN NOW And he shook my hand and told me that in all his days he never END
BEGIN NOW Met a man who rode more gamely, and our last set to was prime, END
BEGIN NOW And we wired them on Monaro how we chanced to beat the Quiver. END
BEGIN NOW And they sent us back an answer, 'Good old sort from Snowy River: END
BEGIN NOW _HIM_ going to ride for us! _HIM_ -- END
BEGIN NOW with the pants and the eyeglass and all. END
BEGIN NOW Amateur! don't he just look it -- it's twenty to one on a fall. END
BEGIN NOW Ride! Don't tell _ME_ he can ride. END
BEGIN NOW With his pants just as loose as balloons, END
BEGIN NOW you mind that he don't clout you off -- END
BEGIN NOW and the splinters fly up from the rail. END
BEGIN NOW All you can do is to hold him and just let him jump as he likes, END
BEGIN NOW Fell at that wall once, he did, and it gave him a regular spread, END
BEGIN NOW he'll take first-class care he don't fall, END
BEGIN NOW And I think that's the lot -- but remember, END
BEGIN NOW Well, he's down safe as far as the start, END
BEGIN NOW and he seems to sit on pretty neat, END
BEGIN NOW Only his baggified breeches would ruinate anyone's seat -- END
BEGIN NOW They're away -- here they come -- the first fence, END
BEGIN NOW and he's head over heels for a crown! END
BEGIN NOW Good for the new chum, he's over, and two of the others are down! END
BEGIN NOW Now for the treble, my hearty -- By Jove, he can ride, after all; END
BEGIN NOW He hasn't much fear of a fall. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, good, that's the style -- come away! END
BEGIN NOW Rataplan's certain to beat you, unless you can give him the slip; END
BEGIN NOW Battleaxe, Battleaxe, yet -- and it's Battleaxe wins for a crown; END
BEGIN NOW Well, sir, you rode him just perfect -- END
BEGIN NOW I knew from the first you could ride. END
BEGIN NOW and them was the words that I said. END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run END
BEGIN NOW The roving breezes come and go END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run, END
BEGIN NOW The sleepy river murmurs low, END
BEGIN NOW And far away one dimly sees END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the stretch of forest trees -- END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the foothills dusk and dun -- END
BEGIN NOW The ranges sleeping in the sun END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis many years since first I came END
BEGIN NOW To Kiley's Run, END
BEGIN NOW More years than I would care to name END
BEGIN NOW Since I, a stripling, used to ride END
BEGIN NOW For miles and miles at Kiley's side, END
BEGIN NOW The while in stirring tones he told END
BEGIN NOW The stories of the days of old END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW I see the old bush homestead now END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run, END
BEGIN NOW Just nestled down beneath the brow END
BEGIN NOW Of one small ridge above the sweep END
BEGIN NOW Of river-flat, where willows weep END
BEGIN NOW And jasmine flowers and roses bloom, END
BEGIN NOW The air was laden with perfume END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW We lived the good old station life END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run, END
BEGIN NOW With little thought of care or strife. END
BEGIN NOW Old Kiley seldom used to roam, END
BEGIN NOW He liked to make the Run his home, END
BEGIN NOW The swagman never turned away END
BEGIN NOW With empty hand at close of day END
BEGIN NOW From Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW We kept a racehorse now and then END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run, END
BEGIN NOW And neighb'ring stations brought their men END
BEGIN NOW To meetings where the sport was free, END
BEGIN NOW And dainty ladies came to see END
BEGIN NOW Their champions ride; with laugh and song END
BEGIN NOW The old house rang the whole night long END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW The station hands were friends I wot END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run, END
BEGIN NOW A reckless, merry-hearted lot -- END
BEGIN NOW All splendid riders, and they knew END
BEGIN NOW The 'boss' was kindness through and through. END
BEGIN NOW Old Kiley always stood their friend, END
BEGIN NOW And so they served him to the end END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW But droughts and losses came apace END
BEGIN NOW To Kiley's Run, END
BEGIN NOW Till ruin stared him in the face; END
BEGIN NOW He toiled and toiled while lived the light, END
BEGIN NOW He dreamed of overdrafts at night: END
BEGIN NOW At length, because he could not pay, END
BEGIN NOW His bankers took the stock away END
BEGIN NOW From Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW Old Kiley stood and saw them go END
BEGIN NOW From Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW The well-bred cattle marching slow; END
BEGIN NOW His stockmen, mates for many a day, END
BEGIN NOW They wrung his hand and went away. END
BEGIN NOW Too old to make another start, END
BEGIN NOW Old Kiley died -- of broken heart, END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW The owner lives in England now END
BEGIN NOW Of Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW He knows a racehorse from a cow; END
BEGIN NOW But that is all he knows of stock: END
BEGIN NOW His chiefest care is how to dock END
BEGIN NOW Expenses, and he sends from town END
BEGIN NOW To cut the shearers' wages down END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW There are no neighbours anywhere END
BEGIN NOW Near Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW The hospitable homes are bare, END
BEGIN NOW The gardens gone; for no pretence END
BEGIN NOW Must hinder cutting down expense: END
BEGIN NOW The homestead that we held so dear END
BEGIN NOW Contains a half-paid overseer END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW All life and sport and hope have died END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW No longer there the stockmen ride; END
BEGIN NOW For sour-faced boundary riders creep END
BEGIN NOW On mongrel horses after sheep, END
BEGIN NOW Through ranges where, at racing speed, END
BEGIN NOW Old Kiley used to 'wheel the lead' END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW There runs a lane for thirty miles END
BEGIN NOW Through Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW On either side the herbage smiles, END
BEGIN NOW But wretched trav'lling sheep must pass END
BEGIN NOW Without a drink or blade of grass END
BEGIN NOW Thro' that long lane of death and shame: END
BEGIN NOW The weary drovers curse the name END
BEGIN NOW Of Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW The name itself is changed of late END
BEGIN NOW Of Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW They call it 'Chandos Park Estate'. END
BEGIN NOW The lonely swagman through the dark END
BEGIN NOW Must hump his swag past Chandos Park. END
BEGIN NOW The name is English, don't you see, END
BEGIN NOW The old name sweeter sounds to me END
BEGIN NOW Of 'Kiley's Run'. END
BEGIN NOW I cannot guess what fate will bring END
BEGIN NOW To Kiley's Run -- END
BEGIN NOW For chances come and changes ring -- END
BEGIN NOW I scarcely think 'twill always be END
BEGIN NOW Locked up to suit an absentee; END
BEGIN NOW And if he lets it out in farms END
BEGIN NOW His tenants soon will carry arms END
BEGIN NOW On Kiley's Run. END
BEGIN NOW Frying Pan's Theology END
BEGIN NOW Shock-headed blackfellow, END
BEGIN NOW Boy (on a pony). END
BEGIN NOW Snowflakes are falling END
BEGIN NOW So gentle and slow, END
BEGIN NOW Youngster says, 'Frying Pan, END
BEGIN NOW What makes it snow?' END
BEGIN NOW Frying Pan confident END
BEGIN NOW Makes the reply -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Shake 'em big flour bag END
BEGIN NOW Up in the sky!' END
BEGIN NOW 'What! when there's miles of it! END
BEGIN NOW Sur'ly that's brag. END
BEGIN NOW Who is there strong enough END
BEGIN NOW Shake such a bag?' END
BEGIN NOW 'What parson tellin' you, END
BEGIN NOW Tell you in Sunday-school? END
BEGIN NOW Big feller God! END
BEGIN NOW He drive His bullock dray, END
BEGIN NOW Then thunder go, END
BEGIN NOW He shake His flour bag -- END
BEGIN NOW Tumble down snow!' END
BEGIN NOW It was shearing-time at the Myall Lake, END
BEGIN NOW And there rose the sound thro' the livelong day END
BEGIN NOW Of the constant clash that the shear-blades make END
BEGIN NOW When the fastest shearers are making play, END
BEGIN NOW But there wasn't a man in the shearers' lines END
BEGIN NOW That could shear a sheep with the two Devines. END
BEGIN NOW They had rung the sheds of the east and west, END
BEGIN NOW Had beaten the cracks of the Walgett side, END
BEGIN NOW And the Cooma shearers had giv'n them best -- END
BEGIN NOW When they saw them shear, they were satisfied. END
BEGIN NOW From the southern slopes to the western pines END
BEGIN NOW They were noted men, were the two Devines. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas a wether flock that had come to hand, END
BEGIN NOW Great struggling brutes, that the shearers shirk, END
BEGIN NOW For the fleece was filled with the grass and sand, END
BEGIN NOW And seventy sheep was a big day's work. END
BEGIN NOW 'At a pound a hundred it's dashed hard lines END
BEGIN NOW To shear such sheep,' said the two Devines. END
BEGIN NOW But the shearers knew that they'd make a cheque END
BEGIN NOW When they came to deal with the station ewes; END
BEGIN NOW They were bare of belly and bare of neck END
BEGIN NOW With a fleece as light as a kangaroo's. END
BEGIN NOW 'We will show the boss how a shear-blade shines END
BEGIN NOW When we reach those ewes,' said the two Devines. END
BEGIN NOW But it chanced next day when the stunted pines END
BEGIN NOW Were swayed and stirred with the dawn-wind's breath, END
BEGIN NOW That a message came for the two Devines END
BEGIN NOW That their father lay at the point of death. END
BEGIN NOW So away at speed through the whispering pines END
BEGIN NOW Down the bridle track rode the two Devines. END
BEGIN NOW It was fifty miles to their father's hut, END
BEGIN NOW And the dawn was bright when they rode away; END
BEGIN NOW At the fall of night when the shed was shut END
BEGIN NOW And the men had rest from the toilsome day, END
BEGIN NOW To the shed once more through the dark'ning pines END
BEGIN NOW On their weary steeds came the two Devines. END
BEGIN NOW 'Well, you're back right sudden,' the super. said; END
BEGIN NOW 'Is the old man dead and the funeral done?' END
BEGIN NOW 'Well, no, sir, he ain't not exactly dead, END
BEGIN NOW But as good as dead,' said the eldest son -- END
BEGIN NOW 'And we couldn't bear such a chance to lose, END
BEGIN NOW So we came straight back to tackle the ewes.' END
BEGIN NOW They are shearing ewes at the Myall Lake, END
BEGIN NOW And the shed is merry the livelong day END
BEGIN NOW With the clashing sound that the shear-blades make END
BEGIN NOW When the fastest shearers are making play, END
BEGIN NOW And a couple of 'hundred and ninety-nines' END
BEGIN NOW Are the tallies made by the two Devines. END
BEGIN NOW 'Only a pound,' said the auctioneer, END
BEGIN NOW 'Only a pound; and I'm standing here END
BEGIN NOW Selling this animal, gain or loss. END
BEGIN NOW Only a pound for the drover's horse; END
BEGIN NOW One of the sort that was never afraid, END
BEGIN NOW One of the boys of the Old Brigade; END
BEGIN NOW Thoroughly honest and game, I'll swear, END
BEGIN NOW Only a little the worse for wear; END
BEGIN NOW Plenty as bad to be seen in town, END
BEGIN NOW Give me a bid and I'll knock him down; END
BEGIN NOW Sold as he stands, and without recourse, END
BEGIN NOW Give me a bid for the drover's horse.' END
BEGIN NOW Loitering there in an aimless way END
BEGIN NOW Somehow I noticed the poor old grey, END
BEGIN NOW Weary and battered and screwed, of course, END
BEGIN NOW Yet when I noticed the old grey horse, END
BEGIN NOW The rough bush saddle, and single rein END
BEGIN NOW Of the bridle laid on his tangled mane, END
BEGIN NOW Straightway the crowd and the auctioneer END
BEGIN NOW Seemed on a sudden to disappear, END
BEGIN NOW Melted away in a kind of haze, END
BEGIN NOW For my heart went back to the droving days. END
BEGIN NOW Back to the road, and I crossed again END
BEGIN NOW Over the miles of the saltbush plain -- END
BEGIN NOW The shining plain that is said to be END
BEGIN NOW The dried-up bed of an inland sea, END
BEGIN NOW Where the air so dry and so clear and bright END
BEGIN NOW Refracts the sun with a wondrous light, END
BEGIN NOW And out in the dim horizon makes END
BEGIN NOW The deep blue gleam of the phantom lakes. END
BEGIN NOW At dawn of day we would feel the breeze END
BEGIN NOW That stirred the boughs of the sleeping trees, END
BEGIN NOW And brought a breath of the fragrance rare END
BEGIN NOW That comes and goes in that scented air; END
BEGIN NOW For the trees and grass and the shrubs contain END
BEGIN NOW A dry sweet scent on the saltbush plain. END
BEGIN NOW For those that love it and understand, END
BEGIN NOW The saltbush plain is a wonderland. END
BEGIN NOW A wondrous country, where Nature's ways END
BEGIN NOW Were revealed to me in the droving days. END
BEGIN NOW We saw the fleet wild horses pass, END
BEGIN NOW And the kangaroos through the Mitchell grass, END
BEGIN NOW The emu ran with her frightened brood END
BEGIN NOW All unmolested and unpursued. END
BEGIN NOW But there rose a shout and a wild hubbub END
BEGIN NOW When the dingo raced for his native scrub, END
BEGIN NOW And he paid right dear for his stolen meals END
BEGIN NOW With the drover's dogs at his wretched heels. END
BEGIN NOW For we ran him down at a rattling pace, END
BEGIN NOW While the packhorse joined in the stirring chase. END
BEGIN NOW And a wild halloo at the kill we'd raise -- END
BEGIN NOW We were light of heart in the droving days. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas a drover's horse, and my hand again END
BEGIN NOW Made a move to close on a fancied rein. END
BEGIN NOW For I felt the swing and the easy stride END
BEGIN NOW Of the grand old horse that I used to ride END
BEGIN NOW In drought or plenty, in good or ill, END
BEGIN NOW That same old steed was my comrade still; END
BEGIN NOW The old grey horse with his honest ways END
BEGIN NOW Was a mate to me in the droving days. END
BEGIN NOW When we kept our watch in the cold and damp, END
BEGIN NOW If the cattle broke from the sleeping camp, END
BEGIN NOW Over the flats and across the plain, END
BEGIN NOW With my head bent down on his waving mane, END
BEGIN NOW Through the boughs above and the stumps below END
BEGIN NOW On the darkest night I could let him go END
BEGIN NOW At a racing speed; he would choose his course, END
BEGIN NOW And my life was safe with the old grey horse. END
BEGIN NOW But man and horse had a favourite job, END
BEGIN NOW When an outlaw broke from a station mob, END
BEGIN NOW With a right good will was the stockwhip plied, END
BEGIN NOW As the old horse raced at the straggler's side, END
BEGIN NOW And the greenhide whip such a weal would raise, END
BEGIN NOW We could use the whip in the droving days. END
BEGIN NOW 'Only a pound!' and was this the end -- END
BEGIN NOW Only a pound for the drover's friend. END
BEGIN NOW The drover's friend that had seen his day, END
BEGIN NOW And now was worthless, and cast away END
BEGIN NOW With a broken knee and a broken heart END
BEGIN NOW To be flogged and starved in a hawker's cart. END
BEGIN NOW Well, I made a bid for a sense of shame END
BEGIN NOW And the memories dear of the good old game. END
BEGIN NOW 'Thank you? Guinea! and cheap at that! END
BEGIN NOW Against you there in the curly hat! END
BEGIN NOW Only a guinea, and one more chance, END
BEGIN NOW Down he goes if there's no advance, END
BEGIN NOW Third, and the last time, one! two! three!' END
BEGIN NOW And the old grey horse was knocked down to me. END
BEGIN NOW And now he's wandering, fat and sleek, END
BEGIN NOW On the lucerne flats by the Homestead Creek; END
BEGIN NOW I dare not ride him for fear he'd fall, END
BEGIN NOW But he does a journey to beat them all, END
BEGIN NOW For though he scarcely a trot can raise, END
BEGIN NOW He can take me back to the droving days. END
BEGIN NOW 'He was always his mother's idol, since ever his father died; END
BEGIN NOW Away in the gloomy ranges, at the foot of an ironbark, END
BEGIN NOW The bonnie, winsome laddie was lying stiff and stark; END
BEGIN NOW For the Reckless mare had smashed him against a leaning limb, END
BEGIN NOW And his comely face was battered, and his merry eyes were dim. END
BEGIN NOW But the mother pined and faded, and cried, and took no rest, END
BEGIN NOW And rode each day to the ranges on her hopeless, weary quest. END
BEGIN NOW Seeking her loved one ever, she faded and pined away, END
BEGIN NOW 'I know that sooner or later I shall find my boy,' she said. END
BEGIN NOW But she came not home one evening, and they found her lying dead, END
BEGIN NOW Little bush maiden, wondering-eyed, END
BEGIN NOW Playing alone in the creek-bed dry, END
BEGIN NOW In the small green flat on every side END
BEGIN NOW Walled in by the Moonbi ranges high; END
BEGIN NOW Tell us the tale of your lonely life, END
BEGIN NOW 'Mid the great grey forests that know no change. END
BEGIN NOW 'I never have left my home,' she said, END
BEGIN NOW 'I have never been over the Moonbi Range. END
BEGIN NOW 'Father and mother are both long dead, END
BEGIN NOW And I live with granny in yon wee place.' END
BEGIN NOW 'Where are your father and mother?' we said. END
BEGIN NOW She puzzled awhile with thoughtful face, END
BEGIN NOW Then a light came into the shy brown eye, END
BEGIN NOW And she smiled, for she thought the question strange END
BEGIN NOW On a thing so certain -- 'When people die END
BEGIN NOW They go to the country over the range.' END
BEGIN NOW 'And what is this country like, my lass?' END
BEGIN NOW 'There are blossoming trees and pretty flowers, END
BEGIN NOW And shining creeks where the golden grass END
BEGIN NOW Is fresh and sweet from the summer showers. END
BEGIN NOW They never need work, nor want, nor weep; END
BEGIN NOW No troubles can come their hearts to estrange. END
BEGIN NOW Some summer night I shall fall asleep, END
BEGIN NOW And wake in the country over the range.' END
BEGIN NOW Child, you are wise in your simple trust, END
BEGIN NOW For the wisest man knows no more than you END
BEGIN NOW Ashes to ashes, and dust to dust: END
BEGIN NOW Our views by a range are bounded too; END
BEGIN NOW But we know that God hath this gift in store, END
BEGIN NOW That when we come to the final change, END
BEGIN NOW We shall meet with our loved ones gone before END
BEGIN NOW To the beautiful country over the range. END
BEGIN NOW 'Richard Bennison, a jockey, aged 14, while riding William Tell END
BEGIN NOW Out in the grey cheerless chill of the morning light, END
BEGIN NOW Out on the track where the night shades still lurk; END
BEGIN NOW Ere the first gleam of the sungod's returning light, END
BEGIN NOW Round come the race-horses early at work. END
BEGIN NOW Reefing and pulling and racing so readily, END
BEGIN NOW Close sit the jockey-boys holding them hard, END
BEGIN NOW 'Steady the stallion there -- canter him steadily, END
BEGIN NOW Don't let him gallop so much as a yard.' END
BEGIN NOW Fiercely he fights while the others run wide of him, END
BEGIN NOW Reefs at the bit that would hold him in thrall, END
BEGIN NOW Plunges and bucks till the boy that's astride of him END
BEGIN NOW Goes to the ground with a terrible fall. END
BEGIN NOW 'Stop him there! Block him there! Drive him in carefully, END
BEGIN NOW Lead him about till he's quiet and cool. END
BEGIN NOW Sound as a bell! though he's blown himself fearfully, END
BEGIN NOW Now let us pick up this poor little fool. END
BEGIN NOW 'Stunned? Oh, by Jove, I'm afraid it's a case with him; END
BEGIN NOW Ride for the doctor! keep bathing his head! END
BEGIN NOW Send for a cart to go down to our place with him' -- END
BEGIN NOW No use! One long sigh and the little chap's dead. END
BEGIN NOW Only a jockey-boy, foul-mouthed and bad you see, END
BEGIN NOW Ignorant, heathenish, gone to his rest. END
BEGIN NOW What did you do for him? -- bad was the best. END
BEGIN NOW Yearly you send your well-advertised hoard, END
BEGIN NOW But the poor jockey-boy -- shame on you, shame on you, END
BEGIN NOW 'Feed ye, my little ones' -- what said the Lord? END
BEGIN NOW Him ye held less than the outer barbarian, END
BEGIN NOW Left him to die in his ignorant sin; END
BEGIN NOW Have you no principles, humanitarian? END
BEGIN NOW Have you no precept -- 'go gather them in?' END
BEGIN NOW Knew he God's name? In his brutal profanity, END
BEGIN NOW That name was an oath -- out of many but one -- END
BEGIN NOW What did he get from our famed Christianity? END
BEGIN NOW Where has his soul -- if he had any -- gone? END
BEGIN NOW Fourteen years old, and what was he taught of it? END
BEGIN NOW What did he know of God's infinite grace? END
BEGIN NOW Draw the dark curtain of shame o'er the thought of it, END
BEGIN NOW Draw the shroud over the jockey-boy's face. END
BEGIN NOW Let us cease our idle chatter, END
BEGIN NOW Let the tears bedew our cheek, END
BEGIN NOW For a man from Tallangatta END
BEGIN NOW Has been missing for a week. END
BEGIN NOW Where the roaring flooded Murray END
BEGIN NOW Covered all the lower land, END
BEGIN NOW There he started in a hurry, END
BEGIN NOW With a bottle in his hand. END
BEGIN NOW And his fate is hid for ever, END
BEGIN NOW But the public seem to think END
BEGIN NOW That he slumbered by the river, END
BEGIN NOW 'Neath the influence of drink. END
BEGIN NOW And they scarcely seem to wonder END
BEGIN NOW That the river, wide and deep, END
BEGIN NOW Never woke him with its thunder, END
BEGIN NOW Never stirred him in his sleep. END
BEGIN NOW As the crashing logs came sweeping, END
BEGIN NOW And their tumult filled the air, END
BEGIN NOW Then M'Ginnis murmured, sleeping, END
BEGIN NOW ''Tis a wake in ould Kildare.' END
BEGIN NOW So the river rose and found him END
BEGIN NOW Sleeping softly by the stream, END
BEGIN NOW And the cruel waters drowned him END
BEGIN NOW Ere he wakened from his dream. END
BEGIN NOW And the blossom-tufted wattle, END
BEGIN NOW Blooming brightly on the lea, END
BEGIN NOW Saw M'Ginnis and the bottle END
BEGIN NOW Going drifting out to sea. END
BEGIN NOW A Voice from the Town END
BEGIN NOW A sequel to [Mowbray Morris's] 'A Voice from the Bush' END
BEGIN NOW I thought, in the days of the droving, END
BEGIN NOW Of steps I might hope to retrace, END
BEGIN NOW To be done with the bush and the roving END
BEGIN NOW And settle once more in my place. END
BEGIN NOW With a heart that was well nigh to breaking, END
BEGIN NOW In the long, lonely rides on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW I thought of the pleasure of taking END
BEGIN NOW The hand of a lady again. END
BEGIN NOW I am back into civilisation, END
BEGIN NOW Once more in the stir and the strife, END
BEGIN NOW But the old joys have lost their sensation -- END
BEGIN NOW The light has gone out of my life; END
BEGIN NOW The men of my time they have married, END
BEGIN NOW Made fortunes or gone to the wall; END
BEGIN NOW Too long from the scene I have tarried, END
BEGIN NOW And, somehow, I'm out of it all. END
BEGIN NOW For I go to the balls and the races END
BEGIN NOW A lonely companionless elf, END
BEGIN NOW And the ladies bestow all their graces END
BEGIN NOW On others less grey than myself; END
BEGIN NOW 'Midst youngsters that chatter and prate, END
BEGIN NOW And they call me 'the Man who was Someone END
BEGIN NOW Way back in the year Sixty-eight.' END
BEGIN NOW And I look, sour and old, at the dancers END
BEGIN NOW That swing to the strains of the band, END
BEGIN NOW And the ladies all give me the Lancers, END
BEGIN NOW No waltzes -- I quite understand. END
BEGIN NOW For matrons intent upon matching END
BEGIN NOW Their daughters with infinite push, END
BEGIN NOW Would scarce think him worthy the catching, END
BEGIN NOW The broken-down man from the bush. END
BEGIN NOW New partners have come and new faces, END
BEGIN NOW And I, of the bygone brigade, END
BEGIN NOW Sharply feel that oblivion my place is -- END
BEGIN NOW I must lie with the rest in the shade. END
BEGIN NOW And the youngsters, fresh-featured and pleasant, END
BEGIN NOW They live as we lived -- fairly fast; END
BEGIN NOW But I doubt if the men of the present END
BEGIN NOW Are as good as the men of the past. END
BEGIN NOW Of excitement and praise they are chary, END
BEGIN NOW There is nothing much good upon earth; END
BEGIN NOW Their watchword is _NIL ADMIRARI_, END
BEGIN NOW They are bored from the days of their birth. END
BEGIN NOW Where the life that we led was a revel END
BEGIN NOW They 'wince and relent and refrain' -- END
BEGIN NOW I could show them the road -- to the devil, END
BEGIN NOW Were I only a youngster again. END
BEGIN NOW I could show them the road where the stumps are END
BEGIN NOW The pleasures that end in remorse, END
BEGIN NOW And the game where the Devil's three trumps are, END
BEGIN NOW The woman, the card, and the horse. END
BEGIN NOW Shall the blind lead the blind -- shall the sower END
BEGIN NOW Of wind reap the storm as of yore? END
BEGIN NOW Though they get to their goal somewhat slower, END
BEGIN NOW They march where we hurried before. END
BEGIN NOW For the world never learns -- just as we did, END
BEGIN NOW They gallantly go to their fate, END
BEGIN NOW Unheeded all warnings, unheeded END
BEGIN NOW The maxims of elders sedate. END
BEGIN NOW As the husbandman, patiently toiling, END
BEGIN NOW Draws a harvest each year from the soil, END
BEGIN NOW So the fools grow afresh for the spoiling, END
BEGIN NOW And a new crop of thieves for the spoil. END
BEGIN NOW But a truce to this dull moralising, END
BEGIN NOW Let them drink while the drops are of gold, END
BEGIN NOW I have tasted the dregs -- 'twere surprising END
BEGIN NOW Were the new wine to me like the old; END
BEGIN NOW And I weary for lack of employment END
BEGIN NOW In idleness day after day, END
BEGIN NOW For the key to the door of enjoyment END
BEGIN NOW Is Youth -- and I've thrown it away. END
BEGIN NOW Roses ruddy and roses white, END
BEGIN NOW What are the joys that my heart discloses? END
BEGIN NOW Sitting alone in the fading light END
BEGIN NOW Memories come to me here to-night END
BEGIN NOW With the wonderful scent of the big red roses. END
BEGIN NOW Memories come as the daylight fades END
BEGIN NOW Down on the hearth where the firelight dozes; END
BEGIN NOW Flicker and flutter the lights and shades, END
BEGIN NOW And I see the face of a queen of maids END
BEGIN NOW Whose memory comes with the scent of roses. END
BEGIN NOW Visions arise of a scene of mirth, END
BEGIN NOW And a ball-room belle that superbly poses -- END
BEGIN NOW A queenly woman of queenly worth, END
BEGIN NOW And I am the happiest man on earth END
BEGIN NOW With a single flower from a bunch of roses. END
BEGIN NOW Only her memory lives to-night -- END
BEGIN NOW God in His wisdom her young life closes; END
BEGIN NOW Over her grave may the turf be light, END
BEGIN NOW Cover her coffin with roses white -- END
BEGIN NOW She was always fond of the big white roses. END
BEGIN NOW Such are the visions that fade away -- END
BEGIN NOW Man proposes and God disposes; END
BEGIN NOW Look in the glass and I see to-day END
BEGIN NOW Only an old man, worn and grey, END
BEGIN NOW Bending his head to a bunch of roses. END
BEGIN NOW As I lie at rest on a patch of clover END
BEGIN NOW In the Western Park when the day is done, END
BEGIN NOW I watch as the wild black swans fly over END
BEGIN NOW With their phalanx turned to the sinking sun; END
BEGIN NOW And I hear the clang of their leader crying END
BEGIN NOW To a lagging mate in the rearward flying, END
BEGIN NOW And they fade away in the darkness dying, END
BEGIN NOW Where the stars are mustering one by one. END
BEGIN NOW Oh! ye wild black swans, 'twere a world of wonder END
BEGIN NOW For a while to join in your westward flight, END
BEGIN NOW With the stars above and the dim earth under, END
BEGIN NOW Through the cooling air of the glorious night. END
BEGIN NOW As we swept along on our pinions winging, END
BEGIN NOW We should catch the chime of a church-bell ringing, END
BEGIN NOW Or the distant note of a torrent singing, END
BEGIN NOW Or the far-off flash of a station light. END
BEGIN NOW From the northern lakes with the reeds and rushes, END
BEGIN NOW Where the hills are clothed with a purple haze, END
BEGIN NOW Where the bell-birds chime and the songs of thrushes END
BEGIN NOW Make music sweet in the jungle maze, END
BEGIN NOW They will hold their course to the westward ever, END
BEGIN NOW Till they reach the banks of the old grey river, END
BEGIN NOW Where the waters wash, and the reed-beds quiver END
BEGIN NOW In the burning heat of the summer days. END
BEGIN NOW Oh! ye strange wild birds, will ye bear a greeting END
BEGIN NOW To the folk that live in that western land? END
BEGIN NOW Then for every sweep of your pinions beating, END
BEGIN NOW Ye shall bear a wish to the sunburnt band, END
BEGIN NOW To the stalwart men who are stoutly fighting END
BEGIN NOW With the heat and drought and the dust-storm smiting, END
BEGIN NOW Yet whose life somehow has a strange inviting, END
BEGIN NOW When once to the work they have put their hand. END
BEGIN NOW Facing it yet! Oh, my friend stout-hearted, END
BEGIN NOW What does it matter for rain or shine, END
BEGIN NOW For the hopes deferred and the gain departed? END
BEGIN NOW Nothing could conquer that heart of thine. END
BEGIN NOW And thy health and strength are beyond confessing END
BEGIN NOW As the only joys that are worth possessing. END
BEGIN NOW May the days to come be as rich in blessing END
BEGIN NOW As the days we spent in the auld lang syne. END
BEGIN NOW I would fain go back to the old grey river, END
BEGIN NOW To the old bush days when our hearts were light, END
BEGIN NOW But, alas! those days they have fled for ever, END
BEGIN NOW They are like the swans that have swept from sight. END
BEGIN NOW And I know full well that the strangers' faces END
BEGIN NOW Would meet us now in our dearest places; END
BEGIN NOW For our day is dead and has left no traces END
BEGIN NOW But the thoughts that live in my mind to-night. END
BEGIN NOW There are folk long dead, and our hearts would sicken -- END
BEGIN NOW We would grieve for them with a bitter pain, END
BEGIN NOW If the past could live and the dead could quicken, END
BEGIN NOW We then might turn to that life again. END
BEGIN NOW But on lonely nights we would hear them calling, END
BEGIN NOW We should hear their steps on the pathways falling, END
BEGIN NOW We should loathe the life with a hate appalling END
BEGIN NOW In our lonely rides by the ridge and plain. END
BEGIN NOW In the silent park is a scent of clover, END
BEGIN NOW And the distant roar of the town is dead, END
BEGIN NOW And I hear once more as the swans fly over END
BEGIN NOW Their far-off clamour from overhead. END
BEGIN NOW They are flying west, by their instinct guided, END
BEGIN NOW And for man likewise is his fate decided, END
BEGIN NOW And griefs apportioned and joys divided END
BEGIN NOW By a mighty power with a purpose dread. END
BEGIN NOW He came from 'further out', END
BEGIN NOW That land of heat and drought END
BEGIN NOW And dust and gravel. END
BEGIN NOW He got a touch of sun, END
BEGIN NOW And rested at the run END
BEGIN NOW Until his cure was done, END
BEGIN NOW And he could travel. END
BEGIN NOW When spring had decked the plain, END
BEGIN NOW He flitted off again END
BEGIN NOW As flit the swallows. END
BEGIN NOW And from that western land, END
BEGIN NOW When many months were spanned, END
BEGIN NOW A letter came to hand, END
BEGIN NOW Which read as follows: END
BEGIN NOW 'Dear sir, I take my pen END
BEGIN NOW In hopes that all your men END
BEGIN NOW And you are hearty. END
BEGIN NOW You think that I've forgot END
BEGIN NOW Your kindness, Mr. Scott, END
BEGIN NOW Oh, no, dear sir, I'm not END
BEGIN NOW That sort of party. END
BEGIN NOW 'You sometimes bet, I know, END
BEGIN NOW Well, now you'll have a show END
BEGIN NOW The 'books' to frighten. END
BEGIN NOW Up here at Wingadee END
BEGIN NOW We're training Strife, and he END
BEGIN NOW Is a all right 'un. END
BEGIN NOW 'Just now we're running byes, END
BEGIN NOW But, sir, first time he tries END
BEGIN NOW I'll send you word of. END
BEGIN NOW And running 'on the crook' END
BEGIN NOW Their measures we have took, END
BEGIN NOW It is the deadest hook END
BEGIN NOW You ever heard of. END
BEGIN NOW 'So when we lets him go, END
BEGIN NOW Why, then, I'll let you know, END
BEGIN NOW And you can have a show END
BEGIN NOW To put a mite on. END
BEGIN NOW Now, sir, my leave I'll take, END
BEGIN NOW Yours truly, William Blake. END
BEGIN NOW P.S. -- Make no mistake, END
BEGIN NOW By next week's _RIVERINE_ END
BEGIN NOW I saw my friend had been END
BEGIN NOW A bit too cunning. END
BEGIN NOW I read: 'The racehorse Strife END
BEGIN NOW And jockey William Fife END
BEGIN NOW Disqualified for life -- END
BEGIN NOW Suspicious running.' END
BEGIN NOW But though they spoilt his game, END
BEGIN NOW I reckon all the same END
BEGIN NOW I fairly ought to claim END
BEGIN NOW My friend a white 'un. END
BEGIN NOW For though he wasn't straight, END
BEGIN NOW His deeds would indicate END
BEGIN NOW His heart at any rate END
BEGIN NOW Was 'a all right 'un'. END
BEGIN NOW Did you ever hear tell of Chili? I was readin' the other day END
BEGIN NOW Of President Balmaceda and of how he was sent away. END
BEGIN NOW and then there's a truce declared, END
BEGIN NOW no odds were they small or great, END
BEGIN NOW Well, he was for Balmaceda, and after the war was done, END
BEGIN NOW And Balmaceda was beaten and his troops had been forced to run, END
BEGIN NOW The other man fetched his army and proceeded to do things brown, END
BEGIN NOW He marched 'em into the fortress and took command of the town. END
BEGIN NOW Cannon and guns and horses troopin' along the road, END
BEGIN NOW Rumblin' over the bridges, and never a foeman showed END
BEGIN NOW And there as they watched they noticed a flutter of crimson rag, END
BEGIN NOW And under their eyes he hoisted old Balmaceda's flag. END
BEGIN NOW Well, they sent him a civil message to say that the war was done, END
BEGIN NOW And them with their hundred cannon and him with a single gun: END
BEGIN NOW The odds were a trifle heavy -- but he wasn't the sort to flinch, END
BEGIN NOW They pounded his boat to pieces, they silenced his single gun, END
BEGIN NOW And captured the whole consignment, for none of 'em cared to run; END
BEGIN NOW They turn out the real Maginnis when it comes to an uphill fight. END
BEGIN NOW And General Alzereca was killed in the battle's front; END
BEGIN NOW A Bushman's Song END
BEGIN NOW I'm travellin' down the Castlereagh, and I'm a station hand, END
BEGIN NOW I'm handy with the ropin' pole, I'm handy with the brand, END
BEGIN NOW And I can ride a rowdy colt, or swing the axe all day, END
BEGIN NOW But there's no demand for a station-hand along the Castlereagh. END
BEGIN NOW So it's shift, boys, shift, for there isn't the slightest doubt END
BEGIN NOW That we've got to make a shift to the stations further out, END
BEGIN NOW With the pack-horse runnin' after, for he follows like a dog, END
BEGIN NOW We must strike across the country at the old jig-jog. END
BEGIN NOW He takes a lot of beatin', and the other day we tried, END
BEGIN NOW It was shift, boys, shift, for there wasn't the slightest doubt END
BEGIN NOW That I had to make him shift, for the money was nearly out; END
BEGIN NOW But he cantered home a winner, with the other one at the flog -- END
BEGIN NOW He's a red-hot sort to pick up with his old jig-jog. END
BEGIN NOW I asked a cove for shearin' once along the Marthaguy: END
BEGIN NOW 'We shear non-union here,' says he. 'I call it scab,' says I. END
BEGIN NOW I looked along the shearin' floor before I turned to go -- END
BEGIN NOW It was shift, boys, shift, for there wasn't the slightest doubt END
BEGIN NOW It was time to make a shift with the leprosy about. END
BEGIN NOW So I saddled up my horses, and I whistled to my dog, END
BEGIN NOW And I left his scabby station at the old jig-jog. END
BEGIN NOW I went to Illawarra, where my brother's got a farm, END
BEGIN NOW He has to ask his landlord's leave before he lifts his arm; END
BEGIN NOW The landlord owns the country side -- man, woman, dog, and cat, END
BEGIN NOW It was shift, boys, shift, for there wasn't the slightest doubt END
BEGIN NOW Their little landlord god and I would soon have fallen out; END
BEGIN NOW Was I to touch my hat to him? -- was I his bloomin' dog? END
BEGIN NOW So I makes for up the country at the old jig-jog. END
BEGIN NOW But it's time that I was movin', I've a mighty way to go END
BEGIN NOW Till I drink artesian water from a thousand feet below; END
BEGIN NOW Till I meet the overlanders with the cattle comin' down, END
BEGIN NOW So, it's shift, boys, shift, for there isn't the slightest doubt END
BEGIN NOW We've got to make a shift to the stations further out; END
BEGIN NOW The pack-horse runs behind us, for he follows like a dog, END
BEGIN NOW And we cross a lot of country at the old jig-jog. END
BEGIN NOW There's never a stone at the sleeper's head, END
BEGIN NOW There's never a fence beside, END
BEGIN NOW And the wandering stock on the grave may tread END
BEGIN NOW Unnoticed and undenied, END
BEGIN NOW But the smallest child on the Watershed END
BEGIN NOW Can tell you how Gilbert died. END
BEGIN NOW For he rode at dusk, with his comrade Dunn END
BEGIN NOW To the hut at the Stockman's Ford, END
BEGIN NOW In the waning light of the sinking sun END
BEGIN NOW They peered with a fierce accord. END
BEGIN NOW They were outlaws both -- and on each man's head END
BEGIN NOW Was a thousand pounds reward. END
BEGIN NOW They had taken toll of the country round, END
BEGIN NOW And the troopers came behind END
BEGIN NOW With a black that tracked like a human hound END
BEGIN NOW In the scrub and the ranges blind: END
BEGIN NOW He could run the trail where a white man's eye END
BEGIN NOW No sign of a track could find. END
BEGIN NOW He had hunted them out of the One Tree Hill END
BEGIN NOW And over the Old Man Plain, END
BEGIN NOW But they wheeled their tracks with a wild beast's skill, END
BEGIN NOW And they made for the range again. END
BEGIN NOW Then away to the hut where their grandsire dwelt, END
BEGIN NOW They rode with a loosened rein. END
BEGIN NOW And their grandsire gave them a greeting bold: END
BEGIN NOW 'Come in and rest in peace, END
BEGIN NOW No safer place does the country hold -- END
BEGIN NOW With the night pursuit must cease, END
BEGIN NOW And we'll drink success to the roving boys, END
BEGIN NOW And to hell with the black police.' END
BEGIN NOW But they went to death when they entered there, END
BEGIN NOW In the hut at the Stockman's Ford, END
BEGIN NOW For their grandsire's words were as false as fair -- END
BEGIN NOW They were doomed to the hangman's cord. END
BEGIN NOW He had sold them both to the black police END
BEGIN NOW For the sake of the big reward. END
BEGIN NOW In the depth of night there are forms that glide END
BEGIN NOW As stealthy as serpents creep, END
BEGIN NOW And around the hut where the outlaws hide END
BEGIN NOW They plant in the shadows deep, END
BEGIN NOW And they wait till the first faint flush of dawn END
BEGIN NOW Shall waken their prey from sleep. END
BEGIN NOW But Gilbert wakes while the night is dark -- END
BEGIN NOW A restless sleeper, aye, END
BEGIN NOW He has heard the sound of a sheep-dog's bark, END
BEGIN NOW And his horse's warning neigh, END
BEGIN NOW And he says to his mate, 'There are hawks abroad, END
BEGIN NOW And it's time that we went away.' END
BEGIN NOW Their rifles stood at the stretcher head, END
BEGIN NOW Their bridles lay to hand, END
BEGIN NOW They wakened the old man out of his bed, END
BEGIN NOW When they heard the sharp command: END
BEGIN NOW 'In the name of the Queen lay down your arms, END
BEGIN NOW Now, Dunn and Gilbert, stand!' END
BEGIN NOW Then Gilbert reached for his rifle true END
BEGIN NOW That close at his hand he kept, END
BEGIN NOW He pointed it straight at the voice and drew, END
BEGIN NOW But never a flash outleapt, END
BEGIN NOW For the water ran from the rifle breech -- END
BEGIN NOW It was drenched while the outlaws slept. END
BEGIN NOW Then he dropped the piece with a bitter oath, END
BEGIN NOW And he turned to his comrade Dunn: END
BEGIN NOW 'We are sold,' he said, 'we are dead men both, END
BEGIN NOW But there may be a chance for one; END
BEGIN NOW I'll stop and I'll fight with the pistol here, END
BEGIN NOW You take to your heels and run.' END
BEGIN NOW So Dunn crept out on his hands and knees END
BEGIN NOW In the dim, half-dawning light, END
BEGIN NOW And he made his way to a patch of trees, END
BEGIN NOW And vanished among the night, END
BEGIN NOW And the trackers hunted his tracks all day, END
BEGIN NOW But they never could trace his flight. END
BEGIN NOW But Gilbert walked from the open door END
BEGIN NOW In a confident style and rash; END
BEGIN NOW He heard at his side the rifles roar, END
BEGIN NOW And he heard the bullets crash. END
BEGIN NOW But he laughed as he lifted his pistol-hand, END
BEGIN NOW And he fired at the rifle flash. END
BEGIN NOW Then out of the shadows the troopers aimed END
BEGIN NOW At his voice and the pistol sound, END
BEGIN NOW With the rifle flashes the darkness flamed, END
BEGIN NOW He staggered and spun around, END
BEGIN NOW And they riddled his body with rifle balls END
BEGIN NOW As it lay on the blood-soaked ground. END
BEGIN NOW There's never a stone at the sleeper's head, END
BEGIN NOW There's never a fence beside, END
BEGIN NOW And the wandering stock on the grave may tread END
BEGIN NOW Unnoticed and undenied, END
BEGIN NOW But the smallest child on the Watershed END
BEGIN NOW Can tell you how Gilbert died. END
BEGIN NOW I served my time, in the days gone by, END
BEGIN NOW In the railway's clash and clang, END
BEGIN NOW And I worked my way to the end, and I END
BEGIN NOW Was the head of the 'Flying Gang'. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas a chosen band that was kept at hand END
BEGIN NOW In case of an urgent need, END
BEGIN NOW Was it south or north we were started forth, END
BEGIN NOW And away at our utmost speed. END
BEGIN NOW If word reached town that a bridge was down, END
BEGIN NOW The imperious summons rang -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Come out with the pilot engine sharp, END
BEGIN NOW And away with the flying gang.' END
BEGIN NOW Then a piercing scream and a rush of steam END
BEGIN NOW As the engine moved ahead, END
BEGIN NOW With a measured beat by the slum and street END
BEGIN NOW Of the busy town we fled, END
BEGIN NOW By the uplands bright and the homesteads white, END
BEGIN NOW With the rush of the western gale, END
BEGIN NOW And the pilot swayed with the pace we made END
BEGIN NOW As she rocked on the ringing rail. END
BEGIN NOW And the country children clapped their hands END
BEGIN NOW As the engine's echoes rang, END
BEGIN NOW But their elders said: 'There is work ahead END
BEGIN NOW When they send for the flying gang.' END
BEGIN NOW Then across the miles of the saltbush plain END
BEGIN NOW That gleamed with the morning dew, END
BEGIN NOW Where the grasses waved like the ripening grain END
BEGIN NOW The pilot engine flew, END
BEGIN NOW A fiery rush in the open bush END
BEGIN NOW Where the grade marks seemed to fly, END
BEGIN NOW And the order sped on the wires ahead, END
BEGIN NOW The pilot _MUST_ go by. END
BEGIN NOW The Governor's special must stand aside, END
BEGIN NOW And the fast express go hang, END
BEGIN NOW Let your orders be that the line is free END
BEGIN NOW For the boys of the flying gang. END
BEGIN NOW The bell is set a-ringing, and the engine gives a toot, END
BEGIN NOW There's five and thirty shearers here are shearing for the loot, END
BEGIN NOW So stir yourselves, you penners-up, and shove the sheep along, END
BEGIN NOW The musterers are fetching them a hundred thousand strong, END
BEGIN NOW And make your collie dogs speak up -- what would the buyers say END
BEGIN NOW In London if the wool was late this year from Castlereagh? END
BEGIN NOW The man that 'rung' the Tubbo shed is not the ringer here, END
BEGIN NOW That stripling from the Cooma side can teach him how to shear. END
BEGIN NOW They trim away the ragged locks, and rip the cutter goes, END
BEGIN NOW And leaves a track of snowy fleece from brisket to the nose; END
BEGIN NOW It's lovely how they peel it off with never stop nor stay, END
BEGIN NOW They're racing for the ringer's place this year at Castlereagh. END
BEGIN NOW The man that keeps the cutters sharp is growling in his cage, END
BEGIN NOW He's always in a hurry and he's always in a rage -- END
BEGIN NOW 'You clumsy-fisted mutton-heads, you'd turn a fellow sick, END
BEGIN NOW You pass yourselves as shearers, you were born to swing a pick. END
BEGIN NOW Another broken cutter here, that's two you've broke to-day, END
BEGIN NOW It's awful how such crawlers come to shear at Castlereagh.' END
BEGIN NOW The youngsters picking up the fleece enjoy the merry din, END
BEGIN NOW They throw the classer up the fleece, he throws it to the bin; END
BEGIN NOW The pressers standing by the rack are waiting for the wool, END
BEGIN NOW There's room for just a couple more, the press is nearly full; END
BEGIN NOW Now jump upon the lever, lads, and heave and heave away, END
BEGIN NOW Another bale of golden fleece is branded 'Castlereagh'. END
BEGIN NOW The Wind's Message END
BEGIN NOW There came a whisper down the Bland between the dawn and dark, END
BEGIN NOW Above the tossing of the pines, above the river's flow; END
BEGIN NOW It stirred the boughs of giant gums and stalwart ironbark; END
BEGIN NOW It drifted where the wild ducks played amid the swamps below; END
BEGIN NOW It brought a breath of mountain air from off the hills of pine, END
BEGIN NOW A scent of eucalyptus trees in honey-laden bloom; END
BEGIN NOW And drifting, drifting far away along the southern line END
BEGIN NOW It caught from leaf and grass and fern a subtle strange perfume. END
BEGIN NOW And others heard the whisper pass, but could not understand END
BEGIN NOW The magic of the breeze's breath that set their hearts aglow, END
BEGIN NOW Nor how the roving wind could bring across the Overland END
BEGIN NOW A sound of voices silent now and songs of long ago. END
BEGIN NOW The mighty rolling western plains are very fair to see, END
BEGIN NOW Where waving to the passing breeze the silver myalls stand, END
BEGIN NOW But fairer are the giant hills, all rugged though they be, END
BEGIN NOW From which the two great rivers rise that run along the Bland. END
BEGIN NOW Oh! rocky range and rugged spur and river running clear, END
BEGIN NOW The message that the breezes bring to call the wanderers home. END
BEGIN NOW And we shall live to see once more those sunny southern hills, END
BEGIN NOW And strike once more the bridle track that leads along the Bland. END
BEGIN NOW Johnson's Antidote END
BEGIN NOW Down along the Snakebite River, where the overlanders camp, END
BEGIN NOW Where the serpents are in millions, all of the most deadly stamp; END
BEGIN NOW Mixes up among the doughboys half-a-dozen poison-snakes: END
BEGIN NOW Where the wily free-selector walks in armour-plated pants, END
BEGIN NOW There it was that William Johnson sought his snake-bite antidote. END
BEGIN NOW Johnson was a free-selector, and his brain went rather queer, END
BEGIN NOW For the constant sight of serpents filled him with a deadly fear; END
BEGIN NOW Old goanna cure himself with eating little pfeller tree.' END
BEGIN NOW Thus it came to pass that Johnson, having got the tale by rote, END
BEGIN NOW Followed every stray goanna, seeking for the antidote. END
BEGIN NOW Saw him, happy and contented, lick his lips, as off he crept, END
BEGIN NOW While the bulging in his stomach showed where his opponent slept. END
BEGIN NOW 'Here it is, the Grand Elixir, greatest blessing ever known, END
BEGIN NOW Twenty thousand men in India die each year of snakes alone. END
BEGIN NOW Saved from sudden expiration, by my wondrous snakebite cure. END
BEGIN NOW It will bring me fame and fortune! In the happy days to be, END
BEGIN NOW Men of every clime and nation will be round to gaze on me -- END
BEGIN NOW Scientific men in thousands, men of mark and men of note, END
BEGIN NOW Rushing down the Mooki River, after Johnson's antidote. END
BEGIN NOW It will cure Delirium Tremens, when the patient's eyeballs stare END
BEGIN NOW At imaginary spiders, snakes which really are not there. END
BEGIN NOW Then he rushed to the museum, found a scientific man -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Trot me out a deadly serpent, just the deadliest you can; END
BEGIN NOW I intend to let him bite me, all the risk I will endure, END
BEGIN NOW Just to prove the sterling value of my wondrous snakebite cure. END
BEGIN NOW Even though an adder bit me, back to life again I'd float; END
BEGIN NOW Said the scientific person, 'If you really want to die, END
BEGIN NOW Give your dog the snakebite mixture, let the other fellow rip; END
BEGIN NOW Both the dogs were duly loaded with the poison-gland's contents; END
BEGIN NOW Johnson gave his dog the mixture, then sat down to wait events. END
BEGIN NOW 'Mark,' he said, 'in twenty minutes Stump'll be a-rushing round, END
BEGIN NOW While the other wretched creature lies a corpse upon the ground.' END
BEGIN NOW And the scientific person hurried off with utmost speed, END
BEGIN NOW Tested Johnson's drug and found it was a deadly poison-weed; END
BEGIN NOW Half a tumbler killed an emu, half a spoonful killed a goat, END
BEGIN NOW All the snakes on earth were harmless to that awful antidote. END
BEGIN NOW Down along the Mooki River, on the overlanders' camp, END
BEGIN NOW Where the serpents are in millions, all of the most deadly stamp, END
BEGIN NOW Somehow seems to dodge the subject of the snake-bite antidote. END
BEGIN NOW I am the maid of the lustrous eyes END
BEGIN NOW Of great fruition, END
BEGIN NOW Whom the sons of men that are over-wise END
BEGIN NOW Have called Ambition. END
BEGIN NOW And the world's success is the only goal END
BEGIN NOW I have within me; END
BEGIN NOW The meanest man with the smallest soul END
BEGIN NOW May woo and win me. END
BEGIN NOW For the lust of power and the pride of place END
BEGIN NOW To all I proffer. END
BEGIN NOW Wilt thou take thy part in the crowded race END
BEGIN NOW For what I offer? END
BEGIN NOW The choice is thine, and the world is wide -- END
BEGIN NOW Thy path is lonely. END
BEGIN NOW I may not lead and I may not guide -- END
BEGIN NOW I urge thee only. END
BEGIN NOW I am just a whip and a spur that smites END
BEGIN NOW To fierce endeavour. END
BEGIN NOW In the restless days and the sleepless nights END
BEGIN NOW I urge thee ever. END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt wake from sleep with a startled cry, END
BEGIN NOW In fright upleaping END
BEGIN NOW At a rival's step as it passes by END
BEGIN NOW Whilst thou art sleeping. END
BEGIN NOW Honour and truth shall be overthrown END
BEGIN NOW In fierce desire; END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt use thy friend as a stepping-stone END
BEGIN NOW To mount thee higher. END
BEGIN NOW When the curtain falls on the sordid strife END
BEGIN NOW That seemed so splendid, END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt look with pain on the wasted life END
BEGIN NOW That thou hast ended. END
BEGIN NOW Thou hast sold thy life for a guerdon small END
BEGIN NOW In fitful flashes; END
BEGIN NOW There has been reward -- but the end of all END
BEGIN NOW Is dust and ashes. END
BEGIN NOW For the night has come and it brings to naught END
BEGIN NOW Thy projects cherished, END
BEGIN NOW And thine epitaph shall in brass be wrought -- END
BEGIN NOW 'He lived and perished.' END
BEGIN NOW I wait for thee at the outer gate, END
BEGIN NOW My love, mine only; END
BEGIN NOW Wherefore tarriest thou so late END
BEGIN NOW While I am lonely. END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt seek my side with a footstep swift, END
BEGIN NOW In thee implanted END
BEGIN NOW Is the love of Art and the greatest gift END
BEGIN NOW That God has granted. END
BEGIN NOW And the world's concerns with its rights and wrongs END
BEGIN NOW Shall seem but small things -- END
BEGIN NOW Poet or painter, a singer of songs, END
BEGIN NOW Thine art is all things. END
BEGIN NOW For the wine of life is a woman's love END
BEGIN NOW To keep beside thee; END
BEGIN NOW But the love of Art is a thing above -- END
BEGIN NOW A star to guide thee. END
BEGIN NOW As the years go by with thy love of Art END
BEGIN NOW All undiminished, END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt end thy days with a quiet heart -- END
BEGIN NOW Thy work is finished. END
BEGIN NOW So the painter fashions a picture strong END
BEGIN NOW That fadeth never, END
BEGIN NOW And the singer singeth a wond'rous song END
BEGIN NOW That lives for ever. END
BEGIN NOW The daylight is dying END
BEGIN NOW Away in the west, END
BEGIN NOW The wild birds are flying END
BEGIN NOW In silence to rest; END
BEGIN NOW Where shadows are deep, END
BEGIN NOW They pass to its bondage -- END
BEGIN NOW The kingdom of sleep. END
BEGIN NOW And watched in their sleeping END
BEGIN NOW By stars in the height, END
BEGIN NOW They rest in your keeping, END
BEGIN NOW Oh, wonderful night. END
BEGIN NOW When night doth her glories END
BEGIN NOW Of starshine unfold, END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis then that the stories END
BEGIN NOW Of bush-land are told. END
BEGIN NOW Unnumbered I hold them END
BEGIN NOW In memories bright, END
BEGIN NOW But who could unfold them, END
BEGIN NOW Or read them aright? END
BEGIN NOW Beyond all denials END
BEGIN NOW The stars in their glories END
BEGIN NOW The breeze in the myalls END
BEGIN NOW Are part of these stories. END
BEGIN NOW The waving of grasses, END
BEGIN NOW The song of the river END
BEGIN NOW That sings as it passes END
BEGIN NOW For ever and ever, END
BEGIN NOW The hobble-chains' rattle, END
BEGIN NOW The calling of birds, END
BEGIN NOW The lowing of cattle END
BEGIN NOW Must blend with the words. END
BEGIN NOW Without these, indeed, you END
BEGIN NOW Would find it ere long, END
BEGIN NOW As though I should read you END
BEGIN NOW The words of a song END
BEGIN NOW That lamely would linger END
BEGIN NOW When lacking the rune, END
BEGIN NOW The voice of the singer, END
BEGIN NOW The lilt of the tune. END
BEGIN NOW But, as one half-hearing END
BEGIN NOW An old-time refrain, END
BEGIN NOW With memory clearing, END
BEGIN NOW Recalls it again, END
BEGIN NOW These tales, roughly wrought of END
BEGIN NOW The bush and its ways, END
BEGIN NOW May call back a thought of END
BEGIN NOW The wandering days, END
BEGIN NOW And, blending with each END
BEGIN NOW In the mem'ries that throng, END
BEGIN NOW There haply shall reach END
BEGIN NOW You some echo of song. END
BEGIN NOW Well, we grieve to disappoint you, and it makes us sad to hear END
BEGIN NOW That it wasn't cool and shady -- and there wasn't plenty beer, END
BEGIN NOW And the loony bullock snorted when you first came into view; END
BEGIN NOW Well, you know it's not so often that he sees a swell like you; END
BEGIN NOW Where the sunbaked earth was gasping like a creature in its pain END
BEGIN NOW You would find the grasses waving like a field of summer grain, END
BEGIN NOW But you found the bush was dismal and a land of no delight, END
BEGIN NOW Did you chance to hear a chorus in the shearers' huts at night? END
BEGIN NOW Than the little city urchins who would greet you with a curse? END
BEGIN NOW Is not such a life much better than the squalid street and square END
BEGIN NOW Did you hear no sweeter voices in the music of the bush END
BEGIN NOW Would you make it a tea-garden and on Sundays have a band END
BEGIN NOW Where the 'blokes' might take their 'donahs', END
BEGIN NOW with a 'public' close at hand? END
BEGIN NOW You had better stick to Sydney and make merry with the 'push', END
BEGIN NOW For the bush will never suit you, and you'll never suit the bush. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, the new-chum went to the back block run, END
BEGIN NOW But he should have gone there last week. END
BEGIN NOW He tramped ten miles with a loaded gun, END
BEGIN NOW But of turkey or duck he saw never a one, END
BEGIN NOW For he should have been there last week, END
BEGIN NOW They said, END
BEGIN NOW There were flocks of 'em there last week. END
BEGIN NOW He wended his way to a waterfall, END
BEGIN NOW And he should have gone there last week. END
BEGIN NOW He carried a camera, legs and all, END
BEGIN NOW But the day was hot, and the stream was small, END
BEGIN NOW For he should have gone there last week, END
BEGIN NOW They said. END
BEGIN NOW They drowned a man there last week. END
BEGIN NOW He went for a drive, and he made a start, END
BEGIN NOW Which should have been made last week, END
BEGIN NOW For the old horse died of a broken heart; END
BEGIN NOW So he footed it home and he dragged the cart -- END
BEGIN NOW But the horse was all right last week, END
BEGIN NOW They said. END
BEGIN NOW He trotted a match last week. END
BEGIN NOW So he asked the bushies who came from far END
BEGIN NOW To visit the town last week, END
BEGIN NOW If they'd dine with him, and they said 'Hurrah!' END
BEGIN NOW But there wasn't a drop in the whisky jar -- END
BEGIN NOW You should have been here last week, END
BEGIN NOW He said, END
BEGIN NOW I drank it all up last week! END
BEGIN NOW The shearers sat in the firelight, hearty and hale and strong, END
BEGIN NOW After the hard day's shearing, passing the joke along: END
BEGIN NOW where the skies like a furnace glow, END
BEGIN NOW And men from the Snowy River, the land of the frozen snow; END
BEGIN NOW He lingered over them fondly, because they recalled to mind END
BEGIN NOW Most of the names are easy -- short for a man to say. END
BEGIN NOW 'You've heard of Mungrybambone and the Gundabluey pine, END
BEGIN NOW But the rest of the shearers stopped him: END
BEGIN NOW 'For the sake of your jaw, go slow, END
BEGIN NOW On the outer Barcoo where the churches are few, END
BEGIN NOW And men of religion are scanty, END
BEGIN NOW On a road never cross'd 'cept by folk that are lost, END
BEGIN NOW One Michael Magee had a shanty. END
BEGIN NOW Now this Mike was the dad of a ten year old lad, END
BEGIN NOW Plump, healthy, and stoutly conditioned; END
BEGIN NOW He was strong as the best, but poor Mike had no rest END
BEGIN NOW For the youngster had never been christened. END
BEGIN NOW And his wife used to cry, 'If the darlin' should die END
BEGIN NOW Saint Peter would not recognise him.' END
BEGIN NOW But by luck he survived till a preacher arrived, END
BEGIN NOW Who agreed straightaway to baptise him. END
BEGIN NOW Now the artful young rogue, while they held their collogue, END
BEGIN NOW With his ear to the keyhole was listenin', END
BEGIN NOW And he muttered in fright, while his features turned white, END
BEGIN NOW 'What the divil and all is this christenin'?' END
BEGIN NOW He was none of your dolts, he had seen them brand colts, END
BEGIN NOW And it seemed to his small understanding, END
BEGIN NOW If the man in the frock made him one of the flock, END
BEGIN NOW It must mean something very like branding. END
BEGIN NOW So away with a rush he set off for the bush, END
BEGIN NOW While the tears in his eyelids they glistened -- END
BEGIN NOW ''Tis outrageous,' says he, 'to brand youngsters like me, END
BEGIN NOW I'll be dashed if I'll stop to be christened!' END
BEGIN NOW Like a young native dog he ran into a log, END
BEGIN NOW And his father with language uncivil, END
BEGIN NOW Never heeding the 'praste' cried aloud in his haste, END
BEGIN NOW 'Come out and be christened, you divil!' END
BEGIN NOW But he lay there as snug as a bug in a rug, END
BEGIN NOW And his parents in vain might reprove him, END
BEGIN NOW Till his reverence spoke (he was fond of a joke) END
BEGIN NOW 'I've a notion,' says he, 'that'll move him.' END
BEGIN NOW 'Poke a stick up the log, give the spalpeen a prog; END
BEGIN NOW Poke him aisy -- don't hurt him or maim him, END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis not long that he'll stand, I've the water at hand, END
BEGIN NOW As he rushes out this end I'll name him. END
BEGIN NOW 'Here he comes, and for shame! ye've forgotten the name -- END
BEGIN NOW Here the youngster ran out, and the priest gave a shout -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Take your chance, anyhow, wid 'Maginnis'!' END
BEGIN NOW As the howling young cub ran away to the scrub END
BEGIN NOW Where he knew that pursuit would be risky, END
BEGIN NOW The priest, as he fled, flung a flask at his head END
BEGIN NOW That was labelled '_MAGINNIS'S WHISKY_'! END
BEGIN NOW And Maginnis Magee has been made a J.P., END
BEGIN NOW And the one thing he hates more than sin is END
BEGIN NOW To be asked by the folk, who have heard of the joke, END
BEGIN NOW How he came to be christened 'Maginnis'! END
BEGIN NOW 'Aye,' said the boozer, 'I tell you it's true, sir, END
BEGIN NOW I once was a punter with plenty of pelf, END
BEGIN NOW But gone is my glory, I'll tell you the story END
BEGIN NOW How I stiffened my horse and got stiffened myself. END
BEGIN NOW ''Twas a mare called the Cracker, I came down to back her, END
BEGIN NOW But found she was favourite all of a rush, END
BEGIN NOW The folk just did pour on to lay six to four on, END
BEGIN NOW And several bookies were killed in the crush. END
BEGIN NOW 'It seems old Tomato was stiff, though a starter; END
BEGIN NOW They reckoned him fit for the Caulfield to keep. END
BEGIN NOW The Bloke and the Donah were scratched by their owner, END
BEGIN NOW He only was offered three-fourths of the sweep. END
BEGIN NOW 'We knew Salamander was slow as a gander, END
BEGIN NOW The mare could have beat him the length of the straight, END
BEGIN NOW And old Manumission was out of condition, END
BEGIN NOW And most of the others were running off weight. END
BEGIN NOW 'No doubt someone 'blew it', for everyone knew it, END
BEGIN NOW The bets were all gone, and I muttered in spite END
BEGIN NOW 'If I can't get a copper, by Jingo, I'll stop her, END
BEGIN NOW Let the public fall in, it will serve the brutes right.' END
BEGIN NOW 'I said to the jockey, 'Now, listen, my cocky, END
BEGIN NOW You watch as you're cantering down by the stand, END
BEGIN NOW I'll wait where that toff is and give you the office, END
BEGIN NOW You're only to win if I lift up my hand.' END
BEGIN NOW 'I then tried to back her -- 'What price is the Cracker?' END
BEGIN NOW 'Our books are all full, sir,' each bookie did swear; END
BEGIN NOW My mind, then, I made up, my fortune I played up END
BEGIN NOW I bet every shilling against my own mare. END
BEGIN NOW 'I strolled to the gateway, the mare in the straightway END
BEGIN NOW Was shifting and dancing, and pawing the ground, END
BEGIN NOW The boy saw me enter and wheeled for his canter, END
BEGIN NOW When a darned great mosquito came buzzing around. END
BEGIN NOW 'They breed 'em at Hexham, it's risky to vex 'em, END
BEGIN NOW They suck a man dry at a sitting, no doubt, END
BEGIN NOW But just as the mare passed, he fluttered my hair past, END
BEGIN NOW I lifted my hand, and I flattened him out. END
BEGIN NOW 'I was stunned when they started, the mare simply darted END
BEGIN NOW Away to the front when the flag was let fall, END
BEGIN NOW For none there could match her, and none tried to catch her -- END
BEGIN NOW She finished a furlong in front of them all. END
BEGIN NOW 'You bet that I went for the boy, whom I sent for END
BEGIN NOW The moment he weighed and came out of the stand -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Who paid you to win it? Come, own up this minute.' END
BEGIN NOW 'Lord love yer,' said he, 'why you lifted your hand.' END
BEGIN NOW ''Twas true, by St. Peter, that cursed 'muskeeter' END
BEGIN NOW Had broke me so broke that I hadn't a brown, END
BEGIN NOW And you'll find the best course is when dealing with horses END
BEGIN NOW To win when you're able, and _KEEP YOUR HANDS DOWN_. END
BEGIN NOW MacFierce'un came to Whiskeyhurst END
BEGIN NOW When summer days were hot, END
BEGIN NOW And bided there wi' Jock McThirst, END
BEGIN NOW A brawny brother Scot. END
BEGIN NOW Gude Faith! They made the whisky fly, END
BEGIN NOW Like Highland chieftains true, END
BEGIN NOW And when they'd drunk the beaker dry END
BEGIN NOW They sang 'We are nae fou!' END
BEGIN NOW 'There is nae folk like oor ain folk, END
BEGIN NOW Sae gallant and sae true.' END
BEGIN NOW They sang the only Scottish joke END
BEGIN NOW Which is, 'We are nae fou.' END
BEGIN NOW Said bold McThirst, 'Let Saxons jaw END
BEGIN NOW Aboot their great concerns, END
BEGIN NOW But bonny Scotland beats them a', END
BEGIN NOW The land o' cakes and Burns, END
BEGIN NOW The land o' partridge, deer, and grouse, END
BEGIN NOW Fill up your glass, I beg, END
BEGIN NOW There's muckle whusky i' the house, END
BEGIN NOW Forbye what's in the keg.' END
BEGIN NOW And here a hearty laugh he laughed, END
BEGIN NOW 'Just come wi' me, I beg.' END
BEGIN NOW MacFierce'un saw with pleasure daft END
BEGIN NOW A fifty-gallon keg. END
BEGIN NOW 'Losh, man, that's grand,' MacFierce'un cried, END
BEGIN NOW 'Saw ever man the like, END
BEGIN NOW Now, wi' the daylight, I maun ride END
BEGIN NOW To meet a Southron tyke, END
BEGIN NOW But I'll be back ere summer's gone, END
BEGIN NOW So bide for me, I beg, END
BEGIN NOW We'll make a grand assault upon END
BEGIN NOW Yon deevil of a keg.' END
BEGIN NOW MacFierce'un rode to Whiskeyhurst, END
BEGIN NOW When summer days were gone, END
BEGIN NOW And there he met with Jock McThirst END
BEGIN NOW Was greetin' all alone. END
BEGIN NOW 'McThirst what gars ye look sae blank? END
BEGIN NOW Have all yer wits gane daft? END
BEGIN NOW Has that accursed Southron bank END
BEGIN NOW Called up your overdraft? END
BEGIN NOW Is all your grass burnt up wi' drouth? END
BEGIN NOW Is wool and hides gone flat?' END
BEGIN NOW McThirst replied, 'Gude friend, in truth, END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis muckle waur than that.' END
BEGIN NOW 'Has sair misfortune cursed your life END
BEGIN NOW That you should weep sae free? END
BEGIN NOW Is harm upon your bonny wife, END
BEGIN NOW The children at your knee? END
BEGIN NOW Is scaith upon your house and hame?' END
BEGIN NOW McThirst upraised his head: END
BEGIN NOW 'My bairns hae done the deed of shame -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Twere better they were dead. END
BEGIN NOW 'To think my bonny infant son END
BEGIN NOW Should do the deed o' guilt -- END
BEGIN NOW Upon them both these words did bring END
BEGIN NOW A solemn silence deep, END
BEGIN NOW Gude faith, it is a fearsome thing END
BEGIN NOW To see two strong men weep. END
BEGIN NOW Come-by-Chance END
BEGIN NOW As I pondered very weary o'er a volume long and dreary -- END
BEGIN NOW Of each township, town, and village in the radius of the Act. END
BEGIN NOW And I learnt that Puckawidgee stands beside the Murrumbidgee, END
BEGIN NOW And that Booleroi and Bumble get their letters twice a year, END
BEGIN NOW Also that the post inspector, when he visited Collector, END
BEGIN NOW Closed the office up instanter, and re-opened Dungalear. END
BEGIN NOW But my languid mood forsook me, when I found a name that took me, END
BEGIN NOW Just an N which stood for northward, and the rest was all unsaid. END
BEGIN NOW Where the telegraph don't reach you nor the railways run to town. END
BEGIN NOW And one's letters and exchanges come by chance across the ranges, END
BEGIN NOW Under the Shadow of Kiley's Hill END
BEGIN NOW This is the place where they all were bred; END
BEGIN NOW Some of the rafters are standing still; END
BEGIN NOW Now they are scattered and lost and dead, END
BEGIN NOW Every one from the old nest fled, END
BEGIN NOW Out of the shadow of Kiley's Hill. END
BEGIN NOW Better it is that they ne'er came back -- END
BEGIN NOW Changes and chances are quickly rung; END
BEGIN NOW Now the old homestead is gone to rack, END
BEGIN NOW Green is the grass on the well-worn track END
BEGIN NOW Down by the gate where the roses clung. END
BEGIN NOW Gone is the garden they kept with care; END
BEGIN NOW Left to decay at its own sweet will, END
BEGIN NOW Fruit trees and flower beds eaten bare, END
BEGIN NOW Cattle and sheep where the roses were, END
BEGIN NOW Under the shadow of Kiley's Hill. END
BEGIN NOW Where are the children that throve and grew END
BEGIN NOW In the old homestead in days gone by? END
BEGIN NOW One is away on the far Barcoo END
BEGIN NOW Watching his cattle the long year through, END
BEGIN NOW Watching them starve in the droughts and die. END
BEGIN NOW One in the town where all cares are rife, END
BEGIN NOW Weary with troubles that cramp and kill, END
BEGIN NOW Fain would be done with the restless strife, END
BEGIN NOW Fain would go back to the old bush life, END
BEGIN NOW Back to the shadow of Kiley's Hill. END
BEGIN NOW One is away on the roving quest, END
BEGIN NOW Seeking his share of the golden spoil, END
BEGIN NOW Out in the wastes of the trackless west, END
BEGIN NOW Wandering ever he gives the best END
BEGIN NOW Of his years and strength to the hopeless toil. END
BEGIN NOW What of the parents? That unkept mound END
BEGIN NOW Shows where they slumber united still; END
BEGIN NOW Rough is their grave, but they sleep as sound END
BEGIN NOW Out on the range as on holy ground, END
BEGIN NOW Under the shadow of Kiley's Hill. END
BEGIN NOW Born of a thoroughbred English race, END
BEGIN NOW Well proportioned and closely knit, END
BEGIN NOW Neat of figure and handsome face, END
BEGIN NOW Always ready and always fit, END
BEGIN NOW Hard and wiry of limb and thew, END
BEGIN NOW That was the ne'er-do-well Jim Carew. END
BEGIN NOW One of the sons of the good old land -- END
BEGIN NOW Many a year since his like was known; END
BEGIN NOW Never a game but he took command, END
BEGIN NOW Never a sport but he held his own; END
BEGIN NOW Gained at his college a triple blue -- END
BEGIN NOW Good as they make them was Jim Carew. END
BEGIN NOW Came to grief -- was it card or horse? END
BEGIN NOW Nobody asked and nobody cared; END
BEGIN NOW Ship him away to the bush of course, END
BEGIN NOW Ne'er-do-well fellows are easily spared; END
BEGIN NOW Only of women a tolerable few END
BEGIN NOW Sorrowed at parting with Jim Carew. END
BEGIN NOW Gentleman Jim on the cattle camp, END
BEGIN NOW Sitting his horse with an easy grace; END
BEGIN NOW But the reckless living has left its stamp END
BEGIN NOW In the deep drawn lines of that handsome face, END
BEGIN NOW And a harder look in those eyes of blue: END
BEGIN NOW Prompt at a quarrel is Jim Carew. END
BEGIN NOW Billy the Lasher was out for gore -- END
BEGIN NOW Twelve-stone navvy with chest of hair, END
BEGIN NOW When he opened out with a hungry roar END
BEGIN NOW On a ten-stone man it was hardly fair; END
BEGIN NOW But his wife was wise if his face she knew END
BEGIN NOW By the time you were done with him, Jim Carew. END
BEGIN NOW Gentleman Jim in the stockmen's hut END
BEGIN NOW Works with them, toils with them, side by side; END
BEGIN NOW As to his past -- well, his lips are shut. END
BEGIN NOW 'Gentleman once,' say his mates with pride; END
BEGIN NOW And the wildest Cornstalk can ne'er outdo END
BEGIN NOW In feats of recklessness, Jim Carew. END
BEGIN NOW What should he live for? A dull despair! END
BEGIN NOW Drink is his master and drags him down, END
BEGIN NOW Water of Lethe that drowns all care. END
BEGIN NOW Gentleman Jim has a lot to drown, END
BEGIN NOW And he reigns as king with a drunken crew, END
BEGIN NOW Sinking to misery, Jim Carew. END
BEGIN NOW Such is the end of the ne'er-do-well -- END
BEGIN NOW Jimmy the Boozer, all down at heel; END
BEGIN NOW But he straightens up when he's asked to tell END
BEGIN NOW His name and race, and a flash of steel END
BEGIN NOW Still lightens up in those eyes of blue -- END
BEGIN NOW The Swagman's Rest END
BEGIN NOW We buried old Bob where the bloodwoods wave END
BEGIN NOW At the foot of the Eaglehawk; END
BEGIN NOW We fashioned a cross on the old man's grave, END
BEGIN NOW For fear that his ghost might walk; END
BEGIN NOW We carved his name on a bloodwood tree, END
BEGIN NOW With the date of his sad decease, END
BEGIN NOW And in place of 'Died from effects of spree', END
BEGIN NOW We wrote 'May he rest in peace'. END
BEGIN NOW For Bob was known on the Overland, END
BEGIN NOW A regular old bush wag, END
BEGIN NOW Tramping along in the dust and sand, END
BEGIN NOW Humping his well-worn swag. END
BEGIN NOW He would camp for days in the river-bed, END
BEGIN NOW And loiter and 'fish for whales'. END
BEGIN NOW 'I'm into the swagman's yard,' he said, END
BEGIN NOW 'And I never shall find the rails.' END
BEGIN NOW But he found the rails on that summer night END
BEGIN NOW For a better place -- or worse, END
BEGIN NOW As we watched by turns in the flickering light END
BEGIN NOW With an old black gin for nurse. END
BEGIN NOW The breeze came in with the scent of pine, END
BEGIN NOW The river sounded clear, END
BEGIN NOW When a change came on, and we saw the sign END
BEGIN NOW That told us the end was near. END
BEGIN NOW But he spoke in a cultured voice and low -- END
BEGIN NOW 'I fancy they've "sent the route"; END
BEGIN NOW I once was an army man, you know, END
BEGIN NOW Though now I'm a drunken brute; END
BEGIN NOW But bury me out where the bloodwoods wave, END
BEGIN NOW And if ever you're fairly stuck, END
BEGIN NOW Just take and shovel me out of the grave END
BEGIN NOW And, maybe, I'll bring you luck. END
BEGIN NOW 'For I've always heard --' here his voice fell weak, END
BEGIN NOW His strength was well-nigh sped, END
BEGIN NOW He gasped and struggled and tried to speak, END
BEGIN NOW Then fell in a moment -- dead. END
BEGIN NOW Thus ended a wasted life and hard, END
BEGIN NOW Of energies misapplied -- END
BEGIN NOW Old Bob was out of the 'swagman's yard' END
BEGIN NOW And over the Great Divide. END
BEGIN NOW The drought came down on the field and flock, END
BEGIN NOW And never a raindrop fell, END
BEGIN NOW Though the tortured moans of the starving stock END
BEGIN NOW Might soften a fiend from hell. END
BEGIN NOW And we thought of the hint that the swagman gave END
BEGIN NOW When he went to the Great Unseen -- END
BEGIN NOW We shovelled the skeleton out of the grave END
BEGIN NOW To see what his hint might mean. END
BEGIN NOW We dug where the cross and the grave posts were, END
BEGIN NOW We shovelled away the mould, END
BEGIN NOW When sudden a vein of quartz lay bare END
BEGIN NOW All gleaming with yellow gold. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas a reef with never a fault nor baulk END
BEGIN NOW That ran from the range's crest, END
BEGIN NOW And the richest mine on the Eaglehawk END
BEGIN NOW Is known as 'The Swagman's Rest'. END
BEGIN NOW THE LITERARY YEAR BOOK: "The immediate success of this END
BEGIN NOW SPECTATOR: "These lines have the true lyrical cry in them. END
BEGIN NOW Eloquent and ardent verses. END
BEGIN NOW about great rides, in which the lines gallop like the very hoofs END
BEGIN NOW of the horses. END
BEGIN NOW Mr. A. Patchett Martin, in LITERATURE (London): "In my opinion, END
BEGIN NOW and a dash of real tears in its composition. END
BEGIN NOW GLASGOW HERALD: "These ballads... are full of such go END
BEGIN NOW that the mere reading of them make the blood tingle.... END
BEGIN NOW But there are other things in Mr. Paterson's book besides END
BEGIN NOW mere racing and chasing, and each piece bears the mark END
BEGIN NOW of special local knowledge, feeling, and colour. END
BEGIN NOW The poet has also a note of pathos, which is always wholesome. END
BEGIN NOW and capital subjects... We turn to Mr. Paterson's roaring muse END
BEGIN NOW with instantaneous gratitude. END
