BEGIN NOW Old Mate! In the gusty old weather, END
BEGIN NOW When our hopes and our troubles were new, END
BEGIN NOW In the years spent in wearing out leather, END
BEGIN NOW I found you unselfish and true -- END
BEGIN NOW I have gathered these verses together END
BEGIN NOW For the sake of our friendship and you. END
BEGIN NOW You may think for awhile, and with reason, END
BEGIN NOW Though still with a kindly regret, END
BEGIN NOW That I've left it full late in the season END
BEGIN NOW To prove I remember you yet; END
BEGIN NOW But you'll never judge me by their treason END
BEGIN NOW Who profit by friends -- and forget. END
BEGIN NOW I remember, Old Man, I remember -- END
BEGIN NOW The tracks that we followed are clear -- END
BEGIN NOW The jovial last nights of December, END
BEGIN NOW The solemn first days of the year, END
BEGIN NOW Long tramps through the clearings and timber, END
BEGIN NOW Short partings on platform and pier. END
BEGIN NOW I can still feel the spirit that bore us, END
BEGIN NOW And often the old stars will shine -- END
BEGIN NOW I remember the last spree in chorus END
BEGIN NOW For the sake of that other Lang Syne, END
BEGIN NOW When the tracks lay divided before us, END
BEGIN NOW Your path through the future and mine. END
BEGIN NOW Through the frost-wind that cut like whip-lashes, END
BEGIN NOW Through the ever-blind haze of the drought -- END
BEGIN NOW And in fancy at times by the flashes END
BEGIN NOW Of light in the darkness of doubt -- END
BEGIN NOW I have followed the tent poles and ashes END
BEGIN NOW Of camps that we moved further out. END
BEGIN NOW You will find in these pages a trace of END
BEGIN NOW That side of our past which was bright, END
BEGIN NOW And recognise sometimes the face of END
BEGIN NOW A friend who has dropped out of sight -- END
BEGIN NOW I send them along in the place of END
BEGIN NOW The letters I promised to write. END
