BEGIN NOW Down the street as I was drifting with the city's human tide, END
BEGIN NOW of the days when the world was wide. END
BEGIN NOW When the North was hale in the march of Time, END
BEGIN NOW and the South and the West were new, END
BEGIN NOW and proud in the ranks of pride, END
BEGIN NOW Then a man could fight if his heart were bold, END
BEGIN NOW and win if his faith were true -- END
BEGIN NOW in the days when the world was wide. END
BEGIN NOW as 'twill never prevail again; END
BEGIN NOW They knew not whither, nor much they cared -- END
BEGIN NOW let Fate or the winds decide -- END
BEGIN NOW The worst of the Great Unknown they dared END
BEGIN NOW in the days when the world was wide. END
BEGIN NOW and old eyes glistened with pride -- END
BEGIN NOW When barbarous cities were paved with gold END
BEGIN NOW in the days when the world was wide. END
BEGIN NOW in the days when the world was wide. END
BEGIN NOW in the days when the world was wide. END
BEGIN NOW 'Where bound?' and 'What ship's that?' -- END
BEGIN NOW from the days when the world was wide. END
BEGIN NOW with the days when the world was wide? END
BEGIN NOW the sneer of a sneak hits hard; END
BEGIN NOW in the days when the world was wide. END
BEGIN NOW as they did when the world was wide. END
BEGIN NOW were traced since the days gone by. END
BEGIN NOW There was room in the long, free lines of the van END
BEGIN NOW to fight for it side by side -- END
BEGIN NOW There was beating-room for the heart of a man END
BEGIN NOW in the days when the world was wide. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW With its dull, brown days of a-shilling-an-hour END
BEGIN NOW the dreary year drags round: END
BEGIN NOW Is this the result of Old England's power? END
BEGIN NOW -- the bourne of the Outward Bound? END
BEGIN NOW We'll fight till the world grows wide!' END
BEGIN NOW They lie, the men who tell us in a loud decisive tone END
BEGIN NOW That want is here a stranger, and that misery's unknown; END
BEGIN NOW For where the nearest suburb and the city proper meet END
BEGIN NOW My window-sill is level with the faces in the street -- END
BEGIN NOW Drifting past, drifting past, END
BEGIN NOW To the beat of weary feet -- END
BEGIN NOW While I sorrow for the owners of those faces in the street. END
BEGIN NOW And cause I have to sorrow, in a land so young and fair, END
BEGIN NOW To see upon those faces stamped the marks of Want and Care; END
BEGIN NOW I look in vain for traces of the fresh and fair and sweet END
BEGIN NOW In sallow, sunken faces that are drifting through the street -- END
BEGIN NOW Drifting on, drifting on, END
BEGIN NOW To the scrape of restless feet; END
BEGIN NOW I can sorrow for the owners of the faces in the street. END
BEGIN NOW In hours before the dawning dims the starlight in the sky END
BEGIN NOW The wan and weary faces first begin to trickle by, END
BEGIN NOW Increasing as the moments hurry on with morning feet, END
BEGIN NOW Till like a pallid river flow the faces in the street -- END
BEGIN NOW Flowing in, flowing in, END
BEGIN NOW To the beat of hurried feet -- END
BEGIN NOW Ah! I sorrow for the owners of those faces in the street. END
BEGIN NOW The human river dwindles when 'tis past the hour of eight, END
BEGIN NOW Its waves go flowing faster in the fear of being late; END
BEGIN NOW But slowly drag the moments, whilst beneath the dust and heat END
BEGIN NOW The city grinds the owners of the faces in the street -- END
BEGIN NOW Grinding body, grinding soul, END
BEGIN NOW Yielding scarce enough to eat -- END
BEGIN NOW Oh! I sorrow for the owners of the faces in the street. END
BEGIN NOW And then the only faces till the sun is sinking down END
BEGIN NOW Are those of outside toilers and the idlers of the town, END
BEGIN NOW Save here and there a face that seems a stranger in the street, END
BEGIN NOW Tells of the city's unemployed upon his weary beat -- END
BEGIN NOW Drifting round, drifting round, END
BEGIN NOW To the tread of listless feet -- END
BEGIN NOW Ah! My heart aches for the owner of that sad face in the street. END
BEGIN NOW And when the hours on lagging feet have slowly dragged away, END
BEGIN NOW And sickly yellow gaslights rise to mock the going day, END
BEGIN NOW Then flowing past my window like a tide in its retreat, END
BEGIN NOW Again I see the pallid stream of faces in the street -- END
BEGIN NOW Ebbing out, ebbing out, END
BEGIN NOW To the drag of tired feet, END
BEGIN NOW Sinking down, sinking down, END
BEGIN NOW Battered wreck by tempests beat -- END
BEGIN NOW A dreadful, thankless trade is hers, that Woman of the Street. END
BEGIN NOW But, ah! to dreader things than these our fair young city comes, END
BEGIN NOW For in its heart are growing thick the filthy dens and slums, END
BEGIN NOW Where human forms shall rot away in sties for swine unmeet, END
BEGIN NOW And ghostly faces shall be seen unfit for any street -- END
BEGIN NOW Rotting out, rotting out, END
BEGIN NOW For the lack of air and meat -- END
BEGIN NOW In dens of vice and horror that are hidden from the street. END
BEGIN NOW I wonder would the apathy of wealthy men endure END
BEGIN NOW Were all their windows level with the faces of the Poor? END
BEGIN NOW The wrong things and the bad things END
BEGIN NOW And the sad things that we meet END
BEGIN NOW In the filthy lane and alley, and the cruel, heartless street. END
BEGIN NOW I left the dreadful corner where the steps are never still, END
BEGIN NOW And sought another window overlooking gorge and hill; END
BEGIN NOW But when the night came dreary with the driving rain and sleet, END
BEGIN NOW They haunted me -- the shadows of those faces in the street, END
BEGIN NOW Flitting by, flitting by, END
BEGIN NOW Flitting by with noiseless feet, END
BEGIN NOW Once I cried: 'Oh, God Almighty! if Thy might doth still endure, END
BEGIN NOW And, lo! with shops all shuttered I beheld a city's street, END
BEGIN NOW And in the warning distance heard the tramp of many feet, END
BEGIN NOW Coming near, coming near, END
BEGIN NOW To a drum's dull distant beat, END
BEGIN NOW And soon I saw the army that was marching down the street. END
BEGIN NOW Then, like a swollen river that has broken bank and wall, END
BEGIN NOW The human flood came pouring with the red flags over all, END
BEGIN NOW And kindled eyes all blazing bright with revolution's heat, END
BEGIN NOW And flashing swords reflecting rigid faces in the street. END
BEGIN NOW Pouring on, pouring on, END
BEGIN NOW To a drum's loud threatening beat, END
BEGIN NOW And the war-hymns and the cheering of the people in the street. END
BEGIN NOW And so it must be while the world goes rolling round its course, END
BEGIN NOW Shall its sad people miss awhile the terrors of the street -- END
BEGIN NOW The dreadful everlasting strife END
BEGIN NOW For scarcely clothes and meat END
BEGIN NOW In that pent track of living death -- the city's cruel street. END
BEGIN NOW The night too quickly passes END
BEGIN NOW And we are growing old, END
BEGIN NOW So let us fill our glasses END
BEGIN NOW And toast the Days of Gold; END
BEGIN NOW When finds of wondrous treasure END
BEGIN NOW Set all the South ablaze, END
BEGIN NOW And you and I were faithful mates END
BEGIN NOW All through the roaring days! END
BEGIN NOW Then stately ships came sailing END
BEGIN NOW From every harbour's mouth, END
BEGIN NOW And sought the land of promise END
BEGIN NOW That beaconed in the South; END
BEGIN NOW Then southward streamed their streamers END
BEGIN NOW And swelled their canvas full END
BEGIN NOW To speed the wildest dreamers END
BEGIN NOW E'er borne in vessel's hull. END
BEGIN NOW Their shining Eldorado, END
BEGIN NOW Beneath the southern skies, END
BEGIN NOW Was day and night for ever END
BEGIN NOW Before their eager eyes. END
BEGIN NOW The brooding bush, awakened, END
BEGIN NOW Was stirred in wild unrest, END
BEGIN NOW And all the year a human stream END
BEGIN NOW Went pouring to the West. END
BEGIN NOW The rough bush roads re-echoed END
BEGIN NOW The bar-room's noisy din, END
BEGIN NOW When troops of stalwart horsemen END
BEGIN NOW Dismounted at the inn. END
BEGIN NOW And oft the hearty greetings END
BEGIN NOW And hearty clasp of hands END
BEGIN NOW Would tell of sudden meetings END
BEGIN NOW Of friends from other lands; END
BEGIN NOW When, puzzled long, the new-chum END
BEGIN NOW Would recognise at last, END
BEGIN NOW Behind a bronzed and bearded skin, END
BEGIN NOW A comrade of the past. END
BEGIN NOW And when the cheery camp-fire END
BEGIN NOW Explored the bush with gleams, END
BEGIN NOW The camping-grounds were crowded END
BEGIN NOW With caravans of teams; END
BEGIN NOW Then home the jests were driven, END
BEGIN NOW And good old songs were sung, END
BEGIN NOW And choruses were given END
BEGIN NOW The strength of heart and lung. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, they were lion-hearted END
BEGIN NOW Who gave our country birth! END
BEGIN NOW Oh, they were of the stoutest sons END
BEGIN NOW From all the lands on earth! END
BEGIN NOW Oft when the camps were dreaming, END
BEGIN NOW And fires began to pale, END
BEGIN NOW Through rugged ranges gleaming END
BEGIN NOW Would come the Royal Mail. END
BEGIN NOW Behind six foaming horses, END
BEGIN NOW And lit by flashing lamps, END
BEGIN NOW Old 'Cobb and Co.'s', in royal state, END
BEGIN NOW Went dashing past the camps. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, who would paint a goldfield, END
BEGIN NOW And limn the picture right, END
BEGIN NOW As we have often seen it END
BEGIN NOW In early morning's light; END
BEGIN NOW The yellow mounds of mullock END
BEGIN NOW With spots of red and white, END
BEGIN NOW The scattered quartz that glistened END
BEGIN NOW Like diamonds in light; END
BEGIN NOW The azure line of ridges, END
BEGIN NOW The bush of darkest green, END
BEGIN NOW The little homes of calico END
BEGIN NOW That dotted all the scene. END
BEGIN NOW I hear the fall of timber END
BEGIN NOW From distant flats and fells, END
BEGIN NOW The pealing of the anvils END
BEGIN NOW As clear as little bells, END
BEGIN NOW The rattle of the cradle, END
BEGIN NOW The clack of windlass-boles, END
BEGIN NOW The flutter of the crimson flags END
BEGIN NOW Above the golden holes. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW Ah, then our hearts were bolder, END
BEGIN NOW And if Dame Fortune frowned END
BEGIN NOW Our swags we'd lightly shoulder END
BEGIN NOW And tramp to other ground. END
BEGIN NOW But golden days are vanished, END
BEGIN NOW And altered is the scene; END
BEGIN NOW The diggings are deserted, END
BEGIN NOW The camping-grounds are green; END
BEGIN NOW The flaunting flag of progress END
BEGIN NOW Is in the West unfurled, END
BEGIN NOW The mighty bush with iron rails END
BEGIN NOW Is tethered to the world. END
BEGIN NOW It is stuffy in the steerage where the second-classers sleep, END
BEGIN NOW In the cushioned cabins, aft, END
BEGIN NOW With saloons 'n' smoke-rooms, aft -- END
BEGIN NOW There is sheets 'n' best of tucker for the first-salooners, aft. END
BEGIN NOW Our beef is just like scrapin's from the inside of a hide, END
BEGIN NOW Say, cold fowl for luncheon, aft, END
BEGIN NOW Juicy grills an' toast 'n' cutlets -- tucker a-lor-frongsy, aft. END
BEGIN NOW They feed our women sep'rate, an' they make a blessed fuss, END
BEGIN NOW Just as if they couldn't trust 'em for to eat along with us! END
BEGIN NOW With their ferns an' mirrors, aft, END
BEGIN NOW With their flow'rs an' napkins, aft -- END
BEGIN NOW 'I'll assist you to an orange' -- 'Kindly pass the sugar', aft. END
BEGIN NOW We are shabby, rough, 'n' dirty, an' our feelin's out of tune, END
BEGIN NOW An' it's hard on fellers for'ard that was used to go saloon; END
BEGIN NOW For they'd understand him, aft, END
BEGIN NOW (He will miss the bath-rooms aft), END
BEGIN NOW Spite of all there's no denyin' that there's finer feelin's aft. END
BEGIN NOW With his cap an' spyglass, aft -- END
BEGIN NOW A careless, rovin', gay young spark as always travelled aft. END
BEGIN NOW There's a notice by the gangway, an' it seems to come amiss, END
BEGIN NOW For it says that second-classers 'ain't allowed abaft o' this'; END
BEGIN NOW An' there ought to be a notice for the fellows from abaft -- END
BEGIN NOW But the smell an' dirt's a warnin' to the first-salooners, aft; END
BEGIN NOW With their tooth and nail-brush, aft, END
BEGIN NOW With their cuffs 'n' collars, aft -- END
BEGIN NOW I want to breathe the mornin' breeze that blows against the boat, END
BEGIN NOW With their dressin'-cases, aft, END
BEGIN NOW With their swell pyjamas, aft -- END
BEGIN NOW Yes! the idle and the careless, they have ease an' comfort, aft. END
BEGIN NOW I feel so low an' wretched, as I mooch about the deck, END
BEGIN NOW That I'm ripe for jumpin' over -- an' I wish there was a wreck! END
BEGIN NOW We are driven to New Zealand to be shot out over there -- END
BEGIN NOW Scarce a shillin' in our pockets, nor a decent rag to wear, END
BEGIN NOW With the everlastin' worry lest we don't get into graft -- END
BEGIN NOW There is little left to land for if you cannot travel aft; END
BEGIN NOW No anxiety abaft, END
BEGIN NOW They have stuff to land with, aft -- END
BEGIN NOW Oh, there's little left to land for if you cannot travel aft; END
BEGIN NOW But it's grand at sea this mornin', an' Creation almost speaks, END
BEGIN NOW Sailin' past the Bay of Islands with its pinnacles an' peaks, END
BEGIN NOW With the sunny haze all round us an' the white-caps on the blue, END
BEGIN NOW An' we see the beauty for'ard, better than if we were aft; END
BEGIN NOW Spite of op'ra-glasses, aft; END
BEGIN NOW But, ah well, they're brothers aft -- END
BEGIN NOW Nature seems to draw us closer -- bring us nearer fore-'n'-aft. END
BEGIN NOW What's the use of bein' bitter? What's the use of gettin' mad? END
BEGIN NOW What's the use of bein' narrer just because yer luck is bad? END
BEGIN NOW We are used to bein' shabby -- we have got no overdraft -- END
BEGIN NOW We can laugh at troubles for'ard that they couldn't laugh at aft; END
BEGIN NOW (Keepin' up appearance, aft) END
BEGIN NOW There's anxiety an' worry in the breezy cabins aft. END
BEGIN NOW There'll be higher education for the toilin' starvin' clown, END
BEGIN NOW An' the rich an' educated shall be educated down; END
BEGIN NOW An' we all will meet amidships on this stout old earthly craft, END
BEGIN NOW An' there won't be any friction 'twixt the classes fore-'n'-aft. END
BEGIN NOW We'll be brothers, fore-'n'-aft! END
BEGIN NOW When the people work together, and there ain't no fore-'n'-aft. END
BEGIN NOW The Drover's Sweetheart END
BEGIN NOW An hour before the sun goes down END
BEGIN NOW Behind the ragged boughs, END
BEGIN NOW I go across the little run END
BEGIN NOW And bring the dusty cows; END
BEGIN NOW And once I used to sit and rest END
BEGIN NOW Beneath the fading dome, END
BEGIN NOW For there was one that I loved best END
BEGIN NOW Who'd bring the cattle home. END
BEGIN NOW Our yard is fixed with double bails, END
BEGIN NOW Round one the grass is green, END
BEGIN NOW The bush is growing through the rails, END
BEGIN NOW The spike is rusted in; END
BEGIN NOW And 'twas from there his freckled face END
BEGIN NOW Would turn and smile at me -- END
BEGIN NOW He'd milk a dozen in the race END
BEGIN NOW While I was milking three. END
BEGIN NOW I milk eleven cows myself END
BEGIN NOW Where once I milked but four; END
BEGIN NOW I set the dishes on the shelf END
BEGIN NOW And close the dairy door; END
BEGIN NOW And when the glaring sunlight fails END
BEGIN NOW And the fire shines through the cracks, END
BEGIN NOW I climb the broken stockyard rails END
BEGIN NOW And watch the bridle-tracks. END
BEGIN NOW He kissed me twice and once again END
BEGIN NOW And rode across the hill, END
BEGIN NOW The pint-pots and the hobble-chain END
BEGIN NOW I hear them jingling still; END
BEGIN NOW He'll come at night or not at all -- END
BEGIN NOW He left in dust and heat, END
BEGIN NOW And when the soft, cool shadows fall END
BEGIN NOW Is the best time to meet. END
BEGIN NOW And he is coming back again, END
BEGIN NOW He wrote to let me know, END
BEGIN NOW The floods were in the Darling then -- END
BEGIN NOW It seems so long ago; END
BEGIN NOW He'd come through miles of slush and mud, END
BEGIN NOW And it was weary work, END
BEGIN NOW The creeks were bankers, and the flood END
BEGIN NOW Was forty miles round Bourke. END
BEGIN NOW He said the floods had formed a block, END
BEGIN NOW The plains could not be crossed, END
BEGIN NOW And there was foot-rot in the flock END
BEGIN NOW And hundreds had been lost; END
BEGIN NOW The sheep were falling thick and fast END
BEGIN NOW A hundred miles from town, END
BEGIN NOW And when he reached the line at last END
BEGIN NOW He trucked the remnant down. END
BEGIN NOW And so he'll have to stand the cost; END
BEGIN NOW His luck was always bad, END
BEGIN NOW Instead of making more, he lost END
BEGIN NOW The money that he had; END
BEGIN NOW And how he'll manage, heaven knows END
BEGIN NOW (My eyes are getting dim), END
BEGIN NOW He says -- he says -- he don't -- suppose END
BEGIN NOW As if I wouldn't take his hand END
BEGIN NOW Without a golden glove -- END
BEGIN NOW Oh! Jack, you men won't understand END
BEGIN NOW How much a girl can love. END
BEGIN NOW I long to see his face once more -- END
BEGIN NOW Jack's dog! thank God, it's Jack! -- END
BEGIN NOW (I never thought I'd faint before) END
BEGIN NOW He's coming -- up -- the track. END
BEGIN NOW and the sheds were all cut out; END
BEGIN NOW The publican's words were short and few, END
BEGIN NOW and the publican's looks were black -- END
BEGIN NOW For time means tucker, and tramp you must, END
BEGIN NOW where the scrubs and plains are wide, END
BEGIN NOW they carry their swags Out Back. END
BEGIN NOW though he tramped for a year Out Back. END
BEGIN NOW In stifling noons when his back was wrung END
BEGIN NOW by its load, and the air seemed dead, END
BEGIN NOW and the scrubs were cold and black, END
BEGIN NOW He blamed himself in the year 'Too Late' -- END
BEGIN NOW in the heaviest hours of life -- END
BEGIN NOW and treacherous tongues attack -- END
BEGIN NOW It chanced one day, when the north wind blew END
BEGIN NOW in his face like a furnace-breath, END
BEGIN NOW A drover came, but the fringe of law was eastward many a mile; END
BEGIN NOW by his mouldering swag Out Back. END
BEGIN NOW _For time means tucker, and tramp they must, END
BEGIN NOW where the plains and scrubs are wide, END
BEGIN NOW With stinted stomachs and blistered feet END
BEGIN NOW must carry their swags Out Back._ END
BEGIN NOW The Free-Selector's Daughter END
BEGIN NOW A darling girl I thought her, END
BEGIN NOW And ere I left I swore I'd win END
BEGIN NOW The free-selector's daughter. END
BEGIN NOW I milked her father's cows a month, END
BEGIN NOW I brought the wood and water, END
BEGIN NOW I mended all the broken fence, END
BEGIN NOW Before I won the daughter. END
BEGIN NOW I listened to her father's yarns, END
BEGIN NOW I did just what I 'oughter', END
BEGIN NOW And what you'll have to do to win END
BEGIN NOW A free-selector's daughter. END
BEGIN NOW I broke my pipe and burnt my twist, END
BEGIN NOW And washed my mouth with water; END
BEGIN NOW I had a shave before I kissed END
BEGIN NOW The free-selector's daughter. END
BEGIN NOW Then, rising in the frosty morn, END
BEGIN NOW I brought the cows for Mary, END
BEGIN NOW And when I'd milked a bucketful END
BEGIN NOW I took it to the dairy. END
BEGIN NOW I poured the milk into the dish END
BEGIN NOW While Mary held the strainer, END
BEGIN NOW I summoned heart to speak my wish, END
BEGIN NOW And, oh! her blush grew plainer. END
BEGIN NOW I told her I must leave the place, END
BEGIN NOW I said that I would miss her; END
BEGIN NOW At first she turned away her face, END
BEGIN NOW And then she let me kiss her. END
BEGIN NOW I put the bucket on the ground, END
BEGIN NOW And in my arms I caught her: END
BEGIN NOW I'd give the world to hold again END
BEGIN NOW That free-selector's daughter! END
BEGIN NOW When you're camping in the mulga, and the rain is falling slow, END
BEGIN NOW While you nurse your rheumatism 'neath a patch of calico; END
BEGIN NOW Short of tucker or tobacco, short of sugar or of tea, END
BEGIN NOW For it cannot last for ever -- 'I will rise again!' says you. END
BEGIN NOW When you're dossing out in winter, in the darkness and the rain, END
BEGIN NOW Who are ye? Come, move on -- git out av this!' END
BEGIN NOW But it can't go on for ever -- 'I'll have money yet!' says you. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW Bother not about the morrow, for sufficient to the day END
BEGIN NOW Is the evil (rather more so). Put your trust in God and pray! END
BEGIN NOW Study well the ant, thou sluggard. Blessed are the meek and low. END
BEGIN NOW Andy's Gone With Cattle END
BEGIN NOW Our Andy's gone to battle now END
BEGIN NOW 'Gainst Drought, the red marauder; END
BEGIN NOW Our Andy's gone with cattle now END
BEGIN NOW Across the Queensland border. END
BEGIN NOW He's left us in dejection now; END
BEGIN NOW Our hearts with him are roving. END
BEGIN NOW It's dull on this selection now, END
BEGIN NOW Since Andy went a-droving. END
BEGIN NOW Who now shall wear the cheerful face END
BEGIN NOW In times when things are slackest? END
BEGIN NOW And who shall whistle round the place END
BEGIN NOW When Fortune frowns her blackest? END
BEGIN NOW Oh, who shall cheek the squatter now END
BEGIN NOW When he comes round us snarling? END
BEGIN NOW His tongue is growing hotter now END
BEGIN NOW Since Andy cross'd the Darling. END
BEGIN NOW The gates are out of order now, END
BEGIN NOW In storms the 'riders' rattle; END
BEGIN NOW For far across the border now END
BEGIN NOW Our Andy's gone with cattle. END
BEGIN NOW Poor Aunty's looking thin and white; END
BEGIN NOW And Uncle's cross with worry; END
BEGIN NOW And poor old Blucher howls all night END
BEGIN NOW Since Andy left Macquarie. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, may the showers in torrents fall, END
BEGIN NOW And all the tanks run over; END
BEGIN NOW And may the grass grow green and tall END
BEGIN NOW In pathways of the drover; END
BEGIN NOW And may good angels send the rain END
BEGIN NOW On desert stretches sandy; END
BEGIN NOW And when the summer comes again END
BEGIN NOW God grant 'twill bring us Andy. END
BEGIN NOW It chanced upon the very day we'd got the shearing done, END
BEGIN NOW A buggy brought a stranger to the West-o'-Sunday Run; END
BEGIN NOW He had a round and jolly face, and he was sleek and stout, END
BEGIN NOW He drove right up between the huts and called the super out. END
BEGIN NOW We chaps were smoking after tea, and heard the swell enquire END
BEGIN NOW For one as travelled by the name of 'Dunn of Nevertire'. END
BEGIN NOW There wasn't one of us but knew Jack Dunn of Nevertire. END
BEGIN NOW 'Jack Dunn of Nevertire,' he said; 'I was a mate of his; END
BEGIN NOW And now it's twenty years since I set eyes upon his phiz. END
BEGIN NOW There is no whiter man than Jack -- no straighter south the line, END
BEGIN NOW To help a mate in trouble Jack would go through flood and fire. END
BEGIN NOW Great Scott! and don't you know the name of Dunn of Nevertire? END
BEGIN NOW Long Jack from Nevertire; END
BEGIN NOW He stuck to me through thick and thin, Jack Dunn of Nevertire. END
BEGIN NOW 'I did a wild and foolish thing while Jack and I were mates, END
BEGIN NOW And I disgraced my guv'nor's name, an' wished to try the States. END
BEGIN NOW My lamps were turned to Yankee Land, for I'd some people there, END
BEGIN NOW And I was right when someone sent the money for my fare; END
BEGIN NOW I thought 'twas Dad until I took the trouble to enquire, END
BEGIN NOW And found that he who sent the stuff was Dunn of Nevertire, END
BEGIN NOW He'd won some money on a race -- Jack Dunn of Nevertire. END
BEGIN NOW 'Now I've returned, by Liverpool, a swell of Yankee brand, END
BEGIN NOW To reckon, guess, and kalkilate, 'n' wake my native land; END
BEGIN NOW There is no better land, I swear, in all the wide world round -- END
BEGIN NOW I smelt the bush a month before we touched King George's Sound! END
BEGIN NOW And now I've come to settle down, the top of my desire END
BEGIN NOW Is just to meet a mate o' mine called 'Dunn of Nevertire'. END
BEGIN NOW Was raised at Nevertire -- END
BEGIN NOW The town of Nevertire; END
BEGIN NOW He humped his bluey by the name of 'Dunn of Nevertire'. END
BEGIN NOW 'I've heard he's poor, and if he is, a proud old fool is he; END
BEGIN NOW But, spite of that, I'll find a way to fix the old gum-tree. END
BEGIN NOW I've bought a station in the North -- the best that could be had; END
BEGIN NOW I want no bully-brute to boss -- no crawling, sneaking liar -- END
BEGIN NOW My station super's name shall be 'Jack Dunn of Nevertire'! END
BEGIN NOW I guess he's known up Queensland way -- Jack Dunn of Nevertire.' END
BEGIN NOW The super said, while to his face a strange expression came: END
BEGIN NOW 'I THINK I've seen the man you want, I THINK I know the name; END
BEGIN NOW Had he a jolly kind of face, a free and careless way, END
BEGIN NOW Jack D. from Nevertire, END
BEGIN NOW They said I'd find him here, the cuss! -- Jack Dunn of Nevertire. END
BEGIN NOW 'I doubt it much,' the super said, and sadly puffed his briar, END
BEGIN NOW 'I guess he wears a pair of wings -- Jack Dunn of Nevertire; END
BEGIN NOW He caught a fever nursing me, Jack Dunn of Nevertire.' END
BEGIN NOW We took the stranger round to where a gum-tree stood alone, END
BEGIN NOW And in the grass beside the trunk he saw a granite stone; END
BEGIN NOW The names of Dunn and Nevertire were plainly written there -- END
BEGIN NOW 'I'm all broke up,' the stranger said, in sorrow and despair, END
BEGIN NOW 'I guess he has a wider run, the man that I require; END
BEGIN NOW He's got a river-frontage now, Jack Dunn of Nevertire; END
BEGIN NOW White Jack from Nevertire, END
BEGIN NOW I guess Saint Peter knew the name of 'Dunn of Nevertire'.' END
BEGIN NOW Rode out to Blackman's Run, END
BEGIN NOW His cap-peak and his sabre END
BEGIN NOW Were glancing in the sun. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas New Year's Eve, and slowly END
BEGIN NOW Across the ridges low END
BEGIN NOW The sad Old Year was drifting END
BEGIN NOW To where the old years go. END
BEGIN NOW The trooper's mind was reading END
BEGIN NOW The love-page of his life -- END
BEGIN NOW His love for Mary Wylie END
BEGIN NOW Ere she was Blackman's wife; END
BEGIN NOW He sorrowed for the sorrows END
BEGIN NOW Of the heart a rival won, END
BEGIN NOW For he knew that there was trouble END
BEGIN NOW Out there on Blackman's Run. END
BEGIN NOW The sapling shades had lengthened, END
BEGIN NOW The summer day was late, END
BEGIN NOW When Blackman met the trooper END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the homestead gate. END
BEGIN NOW And if the hand of trouble END
BEGIN NOW Can leave a lasting trace, END
BEGIN NOW The lines of care had come to stay END
BEGIN NOW On poor old Blackman's face. END
BEGIN NOW 'Not good day, Trooper Campbell, END
BEGIN NOW It's a bad, bad day for me -- END
BEGIN NOW You are of all the men on earth END
BEGIN NOW The one I wished to see. END
BEGIN NOW The great black clouds of trouble END
BEGIN NOW Above our homestead hang; END
BEGIN NOW That wild and reckless boy of mine END
BEGIN NOW Has joined M'Durmer's gang. END
BEGIN NOW 'Oh! save him, save him, Campbell! END
BEGIN NOW I beg in friendship's name! END
BEGIN NOW For if they take and hang him, END
BEGIN NOW The wife would die of shame. END
BEGIN NOW Could Mary or her sisters END
BEGIN NOW Hold up their heads again, END
BEGIN NOW And face a woman's malice END
BEGIN NOW Or claim the love of men? END
BEGIN NOW 'And if he does a murder END
BEGIN NOW 'Twere better we were dead. END
BEGIN NOW Don't take him, Trooper Campbell, END
BEGIN NOW If a price be on his head; END
BEGIN NOW But shoot him! shoot him, Campbell, END
BEGIN NOW When you meet him face to face, END
BEGIN NOW And save him from the gallows, END
BEGIN NOW And us from that disgrace.' END
BEGIN NOW 'Now, Tom,' cried Trooper Campbell, END
BEGIN NOW 'You know your words are wild. END
BEGIN NOW Though he is wild and reckless, END
BEGIN NOW Yet still he is your child; END
BEGIN NOW So bear up in your trouble, END
BEGIN NOW And meet it like a man, END
BEGIN NOW And tell the wife and daughters END
BEGIN NOW I'll save him if I can.' END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW The sad Australian sunset END
BEGIN NOW Had faded from the west; END
BEGIN NOW But night brings darker shadows END
BEGIN NOW To hearts that cannot rest; END
BEGIN NOW And Blackman's wife sat rocking END
BEGIN NOW And moaning in her chair. END
BEGIN NOW 'I cannot bear disgrace,' she moaned; END
BEGIN NOW 'Disgrace I cannot bear. END
BEGIN NOW 'In hardship and in trouble END
BEGIN NOW I struggled year by year END
BEGIN NOW To make my children better END
BEGIN NOW Than other children here. END
BEGIN NOW And if my son's a felon END
BEGIN NOW How can I show my face? END
BEGIN NOW I cannot bear disgrace; my God, END
BEGIN NOW I cannot bear disgrace! END
BEGIN NOW 'Ah, God in Heaven pardon! END
BEGIN NOW I'm selfish in my woe -- END
BEGIN NOW My boy is better-hearted END
BEGIN NOW Than many that I know. END
BEGIN NOW And I will face the world's disgrace, END
BEGIN NOW And, till his mother's dead, END
BEGIN NOW My foolish child shall find a place END
BEGIN NOW To lay his outlawed head.' END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW With a sad heart Trooper Campbell END
BEGIN NOW Rode back from Blackman's Run, END
BEGIN NOW Nor noticed aught about him END
BEGIN NOW Till thirteen miles were done; END
BEGIN NOW When, close beside a cutting, END
BEGIN NOW He heard the click of locks, END
BEGIN NOW And saw the rifle muzzles END
BEGIN NOW Were on him from the rocks. END
BEGIN NOW But suddenly a youth rode out, END
BEGIN NOW And, close by Campbell's side: END
BEGIN NOW 'Don't fire! don't fire, in heaven's name! END
BEGIN NOW It's Campbell, boys!' he cried. END
BEGIN NOW Then one by one in silence END
BEGIN NOW The levelled rifles fell, END
BEGIN NOW For who'd shoot Trooper Campbell END
BEGIN NOW Of those who knew him well? END
BEGIN NOW Oh, bravely sat old Campbell, END
BEGIN NOW No sign of fear showed he. END
BEGIN NOW He slowly drew his carbine; END
BEGIN NOW It rested by his knee. END
BEGIN NOW The outlaws' guns were lifted, END
BEGIN NOW But none the silence broke, END
BEGIN NOW Till steadfastly and firmly END
BEGIN NOW Old Trooper Campbell spoke. END
BEGIN NOW 'That boy that you would ruin END
BEGIN NOW Goes home with me, my men; END
BEGIN NOW Or some of us shall never END
BEGIN NOW Ride through the Gap again. END
BEGIN NOW You know old Trooper Campbell, END
BEGIN NOW And have you ever heard END
BEGIN NOW That bluff or lead could turn him, END
BEGIN NOW That e'er he broke his word? END
BEGIN NOW 'That reckless lad is playing END
BEGIN NOW A heartless villain's part; END
BEGIN NOW He knows that he is breaking END
BEGIN NOW His poor old mother's heart. END
BEGIN NOW He'll bring a curse upon himself; END
BEGIN NOW But 'tis not that alone, END
BEGIN NOW He'll bring dishonour to a name END
BEGIN NOW That I'D be proud to own. END
BEGIN NOW 'I speak to you, M'Durmer, -- END
BEGIN NOW If your heart's not hardened quite, END
BEGIN NOW And if you'd seen the trouble END
BEGIN NOW At Blackman's home this night, END
BEGIN NOW You'd help me now, M'Durmer -- END
BEGIN NOW I speak as man to man -- END
BEGIN NOW I swore to save that foolish lad, END
BEGIN NOW And I'll save him if I can.' END
BEGIN NOW 'Oh, take him!' said M'Durmer, END
BEGIN NOW 'He's got a horse to ride.' END
BEGIN NOW The youngster thought a moment, END
BEGIN NOW Then rode to Campbell's side -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Good-bye!' the outlaws shouted, END
BEGIN NOW As up the range they sped. END
BEGIN NOW Was all M'Durmer said. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW Then fast along the ridges END
BEGIN NOW Two bushmen rode a race, END
BEGIN NOW And the moonlight lent a glory END
BEGIN NOW To Trooper Campbell's face. END
BEGIN NOW And ere the new year's dawning END
BEGIN NOW They reached the home at last; END
BEGIN NOW And this is but a story END
BEGIN NOW Of trouble that is past! END
BEGIN NOW The colours of the setting sun END
BEGIN NOW Withdrew across the Western land -- END
BEGIN NOW He raised the sliprails, one by one, END
BEGIN NOW And shot them home with trembling hand; END
BEGIN NOW Her brown hands clung -- her face grew pale -- END
BEGIN NOW Ah! quivering chin and eyes that brim! -- END
BEGIN NOW One quick, fierce kiss across the rail, END
BEGIN NOW _Oh, he rides hard to race the pain END
BEGIN NOW Who rides from love, who rides from home; END
BEGIN NOW But he rides slowly home again, END
BEGIN NOW Whose heart has learnt to love and roam._ END
BEGIN NOW A hand upon the horse's mane, END
BEGIN NOW And one foot in the stirrup set, END
BEGIN NOW And, stooping back to kiss again, END
BEGIN NOW With 'Good-bye, Mary! don't you fret! END
BEGIN NOW When I come back' -- he laughed for her -- END
BEGIN NOW 'We do not know how soon 'twill be; END
BEGIN NOW I'll whistle as I round the spur -- END
BEGIN NOW You let the sliprails down for me.' END
BEGIN NOW She gasped for sudden loss of hope, END
BEGIN NOW As, with a backward wave to her, END
BEGIN NOW He cantered down the grassy slope END
BEGIN NOW And swiftly round the dark'ning spur. END
BEGIN NOW Black-pencilled panels standing high, END
BEGIN NOW And darkness fading into stars, END
BEGIN NOW And blurring fast against the sky, END
BEGIN NOW A faint white form beside the bars. END
BEGIN NOW And often at the set of sun, END
BEGIN NOW In winter bleak and summer brown, END
BEGIN NOW She'd steal across the little run, END
BEGIN NOW And shyly let the sliprails down. END
BEGIN NOW And listen there when darkness shut END
BEGIN NOW The nearer spur in silence deep; END
BEGIN NOW And when they called her from the hut END
BEGIN NOW Steal home and cry herself to sleep. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW {Some editions have four more lines here.} END
BEGIN NOW _And he rides hard to dull the pain END
BEGIN NOW Who rides from one that loves him best; END
BEGIN NOW And he rides slowly back again, END
BEGIN NOW Whose restless heart must rove for rest._ END
BEGIN NOW Now up and down the siding brown END
BEGIN NOW The great black crows are flyin', END
BEGIN NOW And down below the spur, I know, END
BEGIN NOW Another 'milker's' dyin'; END
BEGIN NOW The crops have withered from the ground, END
BEGIN NOW The tank's clay bed is glarin', END
BEGIN NOW But from my heart no tear nor sound, END
BEGIN NOW For I have gone past carin' -- END
BEGIN NOW _Past worryin' or carin', END
BEGIN NOW Past feelin' aught or carin'; END
BEGIN NOW But from my heart no tear nor sound, END
BEGIN NOW For I have gone past carin'._ END
BEGIN NOW Through Death and Trouble, turn about, END
BEGIN NOW Through hopeless desolation, END
BEGIN NOW Through flood and fever, fire and drought, END
BEGIN NOW And slavery and starvation; END
BEGIN NOW Through childbirth, sickness, hurt, and blight, END
BEGIN NOW And nervousness an' scarin', END
BEGIN NOW Through bein' left alone at night, END
BEGIN NOW I've got to be past carin'. END
BEGIN NOW _Past botherin' or carin', END
BEGIN NOW Past feelin' and past carin'; END
BEGIN NOW Through city cheats and neighbours' spite, END
BEGIN NOW I've come to be past carin'._ END
BEGIN NOW Our first child took, in days like these, END
BEGIN NOW A cruel week in dyin', END
BEGIN NOW All day upon her father's knees, END
BEGIN NOW Or on my poor breast lyin'; END
BEGIN NOW The tears we shed -- the prayers we said END
BEGIN NOW Were awful, wild -- despairin'! END
BEGIN NOW I've pulled three through, and buried two END
BEGIN NOW Since then -- and I'm past carin'. END
BEGIN NOW _I've grown to be past carin', END
BEGIN NOW Past worryin' and wearin'; END
BEGIN NOW I've pulled three through and buried two END
BEGIN NOW Since then, and I'm past carin'._ END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas ten years first, then came the worst, END
BEGIN NOW All for a dusty clearin', END
BEGIN NOW I thought, I thought my heart would burst END
BEGIN NOW When first my man went shearin'; END
BEGIN NOW He's drovin' in the great North-west, END
BEGIN NOW I don't know how he's farin'; END
BEGIN NOW For I, the one that loved him best, END
BEGIN NOW Have grown to be past carin'. END
BEGIN NOW _I've grown to be past carin' END
BEGIN NOW Past lookin' for or carin'; END
BEGIN NOW The girl that waited long ago, END
BEGIN NOW Has lived to be past carin'._ END
BEGIN NOW My eyes are dry, I cannot cry, END
BEGIN NOW I've got no heart for breakin', END
BEGIN NOW But where it was in days gone by, END
BEGIN NOW A dull and empty achin'. END
BEGIN NOW My last boy ran away from me, END
BEGIN NOW I know my temper's wearin', END
BEGIN NOW But now I only wish to be END
BEGIN NOW Beyond all signs of carin'. END
BEGIN NOW _Past wearyin' or carin', END
BEGIN NOW Past feelin' and despairin'; END
BEGIN NOW And now I only wish to be END
BEGIN NOW Beyond all signs of carin'._ END
BEGIN NOW Three bushmen one morning rode up to an inn, END
BEGIN NOW And one of them called for the drinks with a grin; END
BEGIN NOW They'd only returned from a trip to the North, END
BEGIN NOW And, eager to greet them, the landlord came forth. END
BEGIN NOW He absently poured out a glass of Three Star. END
BEGIN NOW And set down that drink with the rest on the bar. END
BEGIN NOW 'There, that is for Harry,' he said, 'and it's queer, END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis the very same glass that he drank from last year; END
BEGIN NOW His name's on the glass, you can read it like print, END
BEGIN NOW He scratched it himself with an old piece of flint; END
BEGIN NOW I remember his drink -- it was always Three Star' -- END
BEGIN NOW And the landlord looked out through the door of the bar. END
BEGIN NOW He looked at the horses, and counted but three: END
BEGIN NOW 'You were always together -- where's Harry?' cried he. END
BEGIN NOW Oh, sadly they looked at the glass as they said, END
BEGIN NOW 'You may put it away, for our old mate is dead;' END
BEGIN NOW But one, gazing out o'er the ridges afar, END
BEGIN NOW Said, 'We owe him a shout -- leave the glass on the bar.' END
BEGIN NOW They thought of the far-away grave on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW They thought of the comrade who came not again, END
BEGIN NOW They lifted their glasses, and sadly they said: END
BEGIN NOW 'We drink to the name of the mate who is dead.' END
BEGIN NOW And the sunlight streamed in, and a light like a star END
BEGIN NOW Seemed to glow in the depth of the glass on the bar. END
BEGIN NOW And still in that shanty a tumbler is seen, END
BEGIN NOW It stands by the clock, ever polished and clean; END
BEGIN NOW And often the strangers will read as they pass END
BEGIN NOW The name of a bushman engraved on the glass; END
BEGIN NOW And though on the shelf but a dozen there are, END
BEGIN NOW That glass never stands with the rest on the bar. END
BEGIN NOW When the caravans of wool-teams climbed the ranges from the West, END
BEGIN NOW It was built of bark and saplings, and was rather rough inside, END
BEGIN NOW As the bushmen called the landlord of the Shanty on the Rise. END
BEGIN NOW City swells who 'do the Royal' would have called the Shanty low, END
BEGIN NOW But 'twas better far and purer than some toney pubs I know; END
BEGIN NOW For the patrons of the Shanty had the principles of men, END
BEGIN NOW And the spieler, if he struck it, wasn't welcome there again. END
BEGIN NOW You could smoke and drink in quiet, yarn, or else soliloquise, END
BEGIN NOW With a decent lot of fellows in the Shanty on the Rise. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas the bullock-driver's haven when his team was on the road, END
BEGIN NOW Just to camp within a cooey of the Shanty for the night; END
BEGIN NOW And the bullock-bells were clanking from the marshes on the flats END
BEGIN NOW And we took a drop of something that was brought at our desire, END
BEGIN NOW As we stood with steaming moleskins in the kitchen by the fire. END
BEGIN NOW Oh! it roared upon a fireplace of the good, old-fashioned size, END
BEGIN NOW When the rain came down the chimney of the Shanty on the Rise. END
BEGIN NOW They got up a Christmas party in the Shanty long ago, END
BEGIN NOW While I camped with Jimmy Nowlett on the riverbank below; END
BEGIN NOW Poor old Jim was in his glory -- they'd elected him M.C., END
BEGIN NOW 'Mr. Nowlett, Mr. Swaller!' shouted Something-in-Disguise, END
BEGIN NOW As we walked into the parlour of the Shanty on the Rise. END
BEGIN NOW There is little real pleasure in the city where I am -- END
BEGIN NOW There's a swarry round the corner with its mockery and sham; END
BEGIN NOW But a fellow can be happy when around the room he whirls END
BEGIN NOW In a party up the country with the jolly country girls. END
BEGIN NOW Why, at times I almost fancied I was dancing on the skies, END
BEGIN NOW When I danced with Mary Carey in the Shanty on the Rise. END
BEGIN NOW Jimmy came to me and whispered, and I muttered, 'Go along!' END
BEGIN NOW But he shouted, 'Mr. Swaller will oblige us with a song!' END
BEGIN NOW And at first I said I wouldn't, and I shammed a little too, END
BEGIN NOW Till the girls began to whisper, 'Mr. Swallow, now, ah, DO!' END
BEGIN NOW So I sang a song of something 'bout the love that never dies, END
BEGIN NOW And the chorus shook the rafters of the Shanty on the Rise. END
BEGIN NOW Jimmy burst his concertina, and the bullock-drivers went END
BEGIN NOW For the corpse of Joe the Fiddler, who was sleeping in his tent; END
BEGIN NOW Joe was tired and had lumbago, and he wouldn't come, he said, END
BEGIN NOW But the case was very urgent, so they pulled him out of bed; END
BEGIN NOW Jim and I were rather quiet while escorting Mary home, END
BEGIN NOW That we heard the settlers'-matches rustle softly on the tree; END
BEGIN NOW I suppose the Shanty vanished from the ranges long ago, END
BEGIN NOW And the girls are mostly married to the chaps I used to know; END
BEGIN NOW And, upon the very centre of the greenest spot that lies END
BEGIN NOW In my fondest recollection, stands the Shanty on the Rise. END
BEGIN NOW White handkerchiefs wave from the short black pier END
BEGIN NOW As we glide to the grand old sea -- END
BEGIN NOW But the song of my heart is for none to hear END
BEGIN NOW If one of them waves for me. END
BEGIN NOW A roving, roaming life is mine, END
BEGIN NOW Ever by field or flood -- END
BEGIN NOW For not far back in my father's line END
BEGIN NOW Was a dash of the Gipsy blood. END
BEGIN NOW Flax and tussock and fern, END
BEGIN NOW Gum and mulga and sand, END
BEGIN NOW Reef and palm -- but my fancies turn END
BEGIN NOW Ever away from land; END
BEGIN NOW Strange wild cities in ancient state, END
BEGIN NOW Range and river and tree, END
BEGIN NOW Snow and ice. But my star of fate END
BEGIN NOW Is ever across the sea. END
BEGIN NOW A god-like ride on a thundering sea, END
BEGIN NOW When all but the stars are blind -- END
BEGIN NOW A desperate race from Eternity END
BEGIN NOW With a gale-and-a-half behind. END
BEGIN NOW A jovial spree in the cabin at night, END
BEGIN NOW A song on the rolling deck, END
BEGIN NOW A lark ashore with the ships in sight, END
BEGIN NOW Till -- a wreck goes down with a wreck. END
BEGIN NOW A smoke and a yarn on the deck by day, END
BEGIN NOW When life is a waking dream, END
BEGIN NOW And care and trouble so far away END
BEGIN NOW That out of your life they seem. END
BEGIN NOW A roving spirit in sympathy, END
BEGIN NOW Who has travelled the whole world o'er -- END
BEGIN NOW My heart forgets, in a week at sea, END
BEGIN NOW The trouble of years on shore. END
BEGIN NOW A rolling stone! -- 'tis a saw for slaves -- END
BEGIN NOW Philosophy false as old -- END
BEGIN NOW Wear out or break 'neath the feet of knaves, END
BEGIN NOW Or rot in your bed of mould! END
BEGIN NOW But I'D rather trust to the darkest skies END
BEGIN NOW And the wildest seas that roar, END
BEGIN NOW Or die, where the stars of Nations rise, END
BEGIN NOW In the stormy clouds of war. END
BEGIN NOW Cleave to your country, home, and friends, END
BEGIN NOW Die in a sordid strife -- END
BEGIN NOW You can count your friends on your finger ends END
BEGIN NOW In the critical hours of life. END
BEGIN NOW Sacrifice all for the family's sake, END
BEGIN NOW Bow to their selfish rule! END
BEGIN NOW Slave till your big soft heart they break -- END
BEGIN NOW The heart of the family fool. END
BEGIN NOW Domestic quarrels, and family spite, END
BEGIN NOW And your Native Land may be END
BEGIN NOW Controlled by custom, but, come what might, END
BEGIN NOW The rest of the world for me. END
BEGIN NOW I'd sail with money, or sail without! -- END
BEGIN NOW If your love be forced from home, END
BEGIN NOW And you dare enough, and your heart be stout, END
BEGIN NOW The world is your own to roam. END
BEGIN NOW I've never a love that can sting my pride, END
BEGIN NOW Nor a friend to prove untrue; END
BEGIN NOW For I leave my love ere the turning tide, END
BEGIN NOW And my friends are all too new. END
BEGIN NOW The curse of the Powers on a peace like ours, END
BEGIN NOW With its greed and its treachery -- END
BEGIN NOW A stranger's hand, and a stranger land, END
BEGIN NOW And the rest of the world for me! END
BEGIN NOW But why be bitter? The world is cold END
BEGIN NOW To one with a frozen heart; END
BEGIN NOW New friends are often so like the old, END
BEGIN NOW They seem of the past a part -- END
BEGIN NOW As a better part of the past appears, END
BEGIN NOW When enemies, parted long, END
BEGIN NOW Are come together in kinder years, END
BEGIN NOW With their better nature strong. END
BEGIN NOW I had a friend, ere my first ship sailed, END
BEGIN NOW A friend that I never deserved -- END
BEGIN NOW For the selfish strain in my blood prevailed END
BEGIN NOW As soon as my turn was served. END
BEGIN NOW And the memory haunts my heart with shame -- END
BEGIN NOW Or, rather, the pride that's there; END
BEGIN NOW In different guises, but soul the same, END
BEGIN NOW I meet him everywhere. END
BEGIN NOW I had a chum. When the times were tight END
BEGIN NOW We starved in Australian scrubs; END
BEGIN NOW We froze together in parks at night, END
BEGIN NOW And laughed together in pubs. END
BEGIN NOW And I often hear a laugh like his END
BEGIN NOW From a sense of humour keen, END
BEGIN NOW And catch a glimpse in a passing phiz END
BEGIN NOW Of his broad, good-humoured grin. END
BEGIN NOW And I had a love -- 'twas a love to prize -- END
BEGIN NOW But I never went back again . . . END
BEGIN NOW I have seen the light of her kind brown eyes END
BEGIN NOW In many a face since then. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW The sailors say 'twill be rough to-night, END
BEGIN NOW As they fasten the hatches down, END
BEGIN NOW The south is black, and the bar is white, END
BEGIN NOW And the drifting smoke is brown. END
BEGIN NOW The gold has gone from the western haze, END
BEGIN NOW The sea-birds circle and swarm -- END
BEGIN NOW But we shall have plenty of sunny days, END
BEGIN NOW And little enough of storm. END
BEGIN NOW The hill is hiding the short black pier, END
BEGIN NOW As the last white signal's seen; END
BEGIN NOW The points run in, and the houses veer, END
BEGIN NOW And the great bluff stands between. END
BEGIN NOW So darkness swallows each far white speck END
BEGIN NOW On many a wharf and quay. END
BEGIN NOW The night comes down on a restless deck, -- END
BEGIN NOW Grim cliffs -- and -- The Open Sea! END
BEGIN NOW It was somewhere in September, and the sun was going down, END
BEGIN NOW When I came, in search of 'copy', to a Darling-River town; END
BEGIN NOW 'Neath the public-house verandah I was resting on a bunk END
BEGIN NOW When a stranger rose before me, and he said that he was drunk; END
BEGIN NOW He apologised for speaking; there was no offence, he swore; END
BEGIN NOW But he somehow seemed to fancy that he'd seen my face before. END
BEGIN NOW 'No erfence,' he said. I told him that he needn't mention it, END
BEGIN NOW For I might have met him somewhere; I had travelled round a bit, END
BEGIN NOW And I knew a lot of fellows in the bush and in the streets -- END
BEGIN NOW But a fellow can't remember all the fellows that he meets. END
BEGIN NOW Very old and thin and dirty were the garments that he wore, END
BEGIN NOW Just a shirt and pair of trousers, and a boot, and nothing more; END
BEGIN NOW He was wringing-wet, and really in a sad and sinful plight, END
BEGIN NOW And his hat was in his left hand, and a bottle in his right. END
BEGIN NOW His brow was broad and roomy, but its lines were somewhat harsh, END
BEGIN NOW And a sensual mouth was hidden by a drooping, fair moustache; END
BEGIN NOW (His hairy chest was open to what poets call the 'wined', END
BEGIN NOW And I would have bet a thousand that his pants were gone behind). END
BEGIN NOW 'Only for the blanky horses walkin' over him all night.' END
BEGIN NOW He'd apparently been fighting, for his face was black-and-blue, END
BEGIN NOW And he looked as though the horses had been treading on him, too; END
BEGIN NOW It appeared that he mistook me for a long-lost mate of his -- END
BEGIN NOW One of whom I was the image, both in figure and in phiz -- END
BEGIN NOW (He'd have had a letter from him if the chap were living still, END
BEGIN NOW For they'd carried swags together from the Gulf to Broken Hill.) END
BEGIN NOW Sweeney yarned awhile and hinted that his folks were doing well, END
BEGIN NOW And he told me that his father kept the Southern Cross Hotel; END
BEGIN NOW And I wondered if his absence was regarded as a loss END
BEGIN NOW When he left the elder Sweeney -- landlord of the Southern Cross. END
BEGIN NOW He was born in Parramatta, and he said, with humour grim, END
BEGIN NOW That he'd like to see the city ere the liquor finished him, END
BEGIN NOW But he couldn't raise the money. He was damned if he could think END
BEGIN NOW I declined -- 'TWAS self-denial -- and I lectured him on booze, END
BEGIN NOW Using all the hackneyed arguments that preachers mostly use; END
BEGIN NOW Then a wise expression struggled with the bruises on his face, END
BEGIN NOW Though his argument had scarcely any bearing on the case: END
BEGIN NOW But he couldn't stay to argue, for his beer was nearly gone. END
BEGIN NOW He was glad, he said, to meet me, and he'd see me later on; END
BEGIN NOW He guessed he'd have to go and get his bottle filled again, END
BEGIN NOW And he gave a lurch and vanished in the darkness and the rain. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW And of afternoons in cities, when the rain is on the land, END
BEGIN NOW Visions come to me of Sweeney with his bottle in his hand, END
BEGIN NOW With the stormy night behind him, and the pub verandah-post -- END
BEGIN NOW And I wonder why he haunts me more than any other ghost. END
BEGIN NOW Still I see the shearers drinking at the township in the scrub, END
BEGIN NOW And the army praying nightly at the door of every pub, END
BEGIN NOW Well, perhaps, it isn't funny; there were links between us two -- END
BEGIN NOW And, perhaps, his face forewarned me of a face that I might see END
BEGIN NOW From a bitter cup reflected in the wretched days to be. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW I suppose he's tramping somewhere where the bushmen carry swags, END
BEGIN NOW Cadging round the wretched stations with his empty tucker-bags; END
BEGIN NOW And I fancy that of evenings, when the track is growing dim, END
BEGIN NOW Middleton's Rouseabout END
BEGIN NOW Tall and freckled and sandy, END
BEGIN NOW Face of a country lout; END
BEGIN NOW This was the picture of Andy, END
BEGIN NOW Middleton's Rouseabout. END
BEGIN NOW Type of a coming nation, END
BEGIN NOW In the land of cattle and sheep, END
BEGIN NOW Worked on Middleton's station, END
BEGIN NOW 'Pound a week and his keep.' END
BEGIN NOW On Middleton's wide dominions END
BEGIN NOW Plied the stockwhip and shears; END
BEGIN NOW Hadn't any opinions, END
BEGIN NOW Hadn't any 'idears'. END
BEGIN NOW Swiftly the years went over, END
BEGIN NOW Liquor and drought prevailed; END
BEGIN NOW Middleton went as a drover, END
BEGIN NOW After his station had failed. END
BEGIN NOW Type of a careless nation, END
BEGIN NOW Men who are soon played out, END
BEGIN NOW Middleton was: -- and his station END
BEGIN NOW Was bought by the Rouseabout. END
BEGIN NOW Flourishing beard and sandy, END
BEGIN NOW Tall and robust and stout; END
BEGIN NOW This is the picture of Andy, END
BEGIN NOW Middleton's Rouseabout. END
BEGIN NOW Now on his own dominions END
BEGIN NOW Works with his overseers; END
BEGIN NOW Hasn't any opinions, END
BEGIN NOW Hasn't any 'idears'. END
BEGIN NOW Across the stony ridges, END
BEGIN NOW Across the rolling plain, END
BEGIN NOW Young Harry Dale, the drover, END
BEGIN NOW Comes riding home again. END
BEGIN NOW And well his stock-horse bears him, END
BEGIN NOW And light of heart is he, END
BEGIN NOW And stoutly his old pack-horse END
BEGIN NOW Is trotting by his knee. END
BEGIN NOW Up Queensland way with cattle END
BEGIN NOW He travelled regions vast; END
BEGIN NOW And many months have vanished END
BEGIN NOW Since home-folk saw him last. END
BEGIN NOW He hums a song of someone END
BEGIN NOW He hopes to marry soon; END
BEGIN NOW And hobble-chains and camp-ware END
BEGIN NOW Keep jingling to the tune. END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the hazy dado END
BEGIN NOW Against the lower skies END
BEGIN NOW And yon blue line of ranges END
BEGIN NOW The homestead station lies. END
BEGIN NOW And thitherward the drover END
BEGIN NOW Jogs through the lazy noon, END
BEGIN NOW While hobble-chains and camp-ware END
BEGIN NOW Are jingling to a tune. END
BEGIN NOW An hour has filled the heavens END
BEGIN NOW With storm-clouds inky black; END
BEGIN NOW At times the lightning trickles END
BEGIN NOW Around the drover's track; END
BEGIN NOW But Harry pushes onward, END
BEGIN NOW His horses' strength he tries, END
BEGIN NOW In hope to reach the river END
BEGIN NOW Before the flood shall rise. END
BEGIN NOW The thunder from above him END
BEGIN NOW Goes rolling o'er the plain; END
BEGIN NOW And down on thirsty pastures END
BEGIN NOW In torrents falls the rain. END
BEGIN NOW And every creek and gully END
BEGIN NOW Sends forth its little flood, END
BEGIN NOW Till the river runs a banker, END
BEGIN NOW All stained with yellow mud. END
BEGIN NOW Now Harry speaks to Rover, END
BEGIN NOW The best dog on the plains, END
BEGIN NOW And to his hardy horses, END
BEGIN NOW And strokes their shaggy manes; END
BEGIN NOW 'We've breasted bigger rivers END
BEGIN NOW When floods were at their height END
BEGIN NOW Nor shall this gutter stop us END
BEGIN NOW From getting home to-night!' END
BEGIN NOW The thunder growls a warning, END
BEGIN NOW The ghastly lightnings gleam, END
BEGIN NOW As the drover turns his horses END
BEGIN NOW To swim the fatal stream. END
BEGIN NOW But, oh! the flood runs stronger END
BEGIN NOW Than e'er it ran before; END
BEGIN NOW The saddle-horse is failing, END
BEGIN NOW And only half-way o'er! END
BEGIN NOW When flashes next the lightning, END
BEGIN NOW The flood's grey breast is blank, END
BEGIN NOW And a cattle dog and pack-horse END
BEGIN NOW Are struggling up the bank. END
BEGIN NOW But in the lonely homestead END
BEGIN NOW The girl will wait in vain -- END
BEGIN NOW He'll never pass the stations END
BEGIN NOW In charge of stock again. END
BEGIN NOW The faithful dog a moment END
BEGIN NOW Sits panting on the bank, END
BEGIN NOW And then swims through the current END
BEGIN NOW To where his master sank. END
BEGIN NOW And round and round in circles END
BEGIN NOW He fights with failing strength, END
BEGIN NOW Till, borne down by the waters, END
BEGIN NOW The old dog sinks at length. END
BEGIN NOW Across the flooded lowlands END
BEGIN NOW And slopes of sodden loam END
BEGIN NOW The pack-horse struggles onward, END
BEGIN NOW And mud-stained, wet, and weary, END
BEGIN NOW Through ranges dark goes he; END
BEGIN NOW While hobble-chains and tinware END
BEGIN NOW Are sounding eerily. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW The floods are in the ocean, END
BEGIN NOW The stream is clear again, END
BEGIN NOW And now a verdant carpet END
BEGIN NOW Is stretched across the plain. END
BEGIN NOW But someone's eyes are saddened, END
BEGIN NOW And someone's heart still bleeds END
BEGIN NOW In sorrow for the drover END
BEGIN NOW Who sleeps among the reeds. END
BEGIN NOW They stood by the door of the Inn on the Rise; END
BEGIN NOW May Carney looked up in the bushranger's eyes: END
BEGIN NOW 'Oh! why did you come? -- it was mad of you, Jack; END
BEGIN NOW You know that the troopers are out on your track.' END
BEGIN NOW A laugh and a shake of his obstinate head -- END
BEGIN NOW 'I wanted a dance, and I'll chance it,' he said. END
BEGIN NOW Some twenty-odd bushmen had come to the 'ball', END
BEGIN NOW But Jack from his youth had been known to them all, END
BEGIN NOW And bushmen are soft where a woman is fair, END
BEGIN NOW So the love of May Carney protected him there; END
BEGIN NOW And all the short evening -- it seems like romance -- END
BEGIN NOW She danced with a bushranger taking his chance. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas midnight -- the dancers stood suddenly still, END
BEGIN NOW For hoofs had been heard on the side of the hill! END
BEGIN NOW Ben Duggan, the drover, along the hillside END
BEGIN NOW Came riding as only a bushman can ride. END
BEGIN NOW He sprang from his horse, to the shanty he sped -- END
BEGIN NOW 'The troopers are down in the gully!' he said. END
BEGIN NOW Quite close to the homestead the troopers were seen. END
BEGIN NOW 'Clear out and ride hard for the ranges, Jack Dean! END
BEGIN NOW Be quick!' said May Carney -- her hand on her heart -- END
BEGIN NOW 'We'll bluff them awhile, and 'twill give you a start.' END
BEGIN NOW He lingered a moment -- to kiss her, of course -- END
BEGIN NOW Then ran to the trees where he'd hobbled his horse. END
BEGIN NOW She ran to the gate, and the troopers were there -- END
BEGIN NOW The jingle of hobbles came faint on the air -- END
BEGIN NOW Then loudly she screamed: it was only to drown END
BEGIN NOW The treacherous clatter of slip-rails let down. END
BEGIN NOW But troopers are sharp, and she saw at a glance END
BEGIN NOW That someone was taking a desperate chance. END
BEGIN NOW They chased, and they shouted, 'Surrender, Jack Dean!' END
BEGIN NOW They called him three times in the name of the Queen. END
BEGIN NOW Then came from the darkness the clicking of locks; END
BEGIN NOW The crack of the rifles was heard in the rocks! END
BEGIN NOW A shriek and a shout, and a rush of pale men -- END
BEGIN NOW And there lay the bushranger, chancing it then. END
BEGIN NOW The sergeant dismounted and knelt on the sod -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Your bushranging's over -- make peace, Jack, with God!' END
BEGIN NOW The bushranger laughed -- not a word he replied, END
BEGIN NOW But turned to the girl who knelt down by his side. END
BEGIN NOW He gazed in her eyes as she lifted his head: END
BEGIN NOW 'Just kiss me -- my girl -- and -- I'll -- chance it,' he said. END
BEGIN NOW When the last rose-tint is fading on the distant mulga scrub, END
BEGIN NOW Then the Army prays for Watty at the entrance of his pub. END
BEGIN NOW Now, I often sit at Watty's when the night is very near, END
BEGIN NOW With a head that's full of jingles and the fumes of bottled beer, END
BEGIN NOW When the Army prays for Watty, I'm included in the prayer. END
BEGIN NOW Watty lounges in his arm-chair, in its old accustomed place, END
BEGIN NOW With a fatherly expression on his round and passive face; END
BEGIN NOW And his arms are clasped before him in a calm, contented way, END
BEGIN NOW And he nods his head and dozes when he hears the Army pray. END
BEGIN NOW And I wonder does he ponder on the distant years and dim, END
BEGIN NOW Or his chances over yonder, when the Army prays for him? END
BEGIN NOW Has he not a fear connected with the warm place down below, END
BEGIN NOW Where, according to good Christians, all the publicans should go? END
BEGIN NOW But his features give no token of a feeling in his breast, END
BEGIN NOW Save of peace that is unbroken and a conscience well at rest; END
BEGIN NOW And we guzzle as we guzzled long before the Army came, END
BEGIN NOW It would take a lot of praying -- lots of thumping on the drum -- END
BEGIN NOW But I love my fellow-sinners, and I hope, upon the whole, END
BEGIN NOW That the Army gets a hearing when it prays for Watty's soul. END
BEGIN NOW Day of ending for beginnings! END
BEGIN NOW Ocean hath another innings, END
BEGIN NOW Ocean hath another score; END
BEGIN NOW And the surges sing his winnings, END
BEGIN NOW And the surges shout his winnings, END
BEGIN NOW And the surges shriek his winnings, END
BEGIN NOW All along the sullen shore. END
BEGIN NOW Sing another dirge in wailing, END
BEGIN NOW For another vessel sailing END
BEGIN NOW With the shadow-ships at sea; END
BEGIN NOW Shadow-ships for ever sinking -- END
BEGIN NOW Shadow-ships whose pumps are clinking, END
BEGIN NOW And whose thirsty holds are drinking END
BEGIN NOW Pray for souls of ghastly, sodden END
BEGIN NOW Corpses, floating round untrodden END
BEGIN NOW Cliffs, where nought but sea-drift strays; END
BEGIN NOW Souls of dead men, in whose faces END
BEGIN NOW Of humanity no trace is -- END
BEGIN NOW Not a mark to show their races -- END
BEGIN NOW Floating round for days and days. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW Ocean's salty tongues are licking END
BEGIN NOW Round the faces of the drowned, END
BEGIN NOW And a cruel blade seems sticking END
BEGIN NOW Through my heart and turning round. END
BEGIN NOW Heaven! shall HIS ghastly, sodden END
BEGIN NOW Corpse float round for days and days? END
BEGIN NOW Shall it dash 'neath cliffs untrodden, END
BEGIN NOW Rocks where nought but sea-drift strays? END
BEGIN NOW God in heaven! hide the floating, END
BEGIN NOW Falling, rising, face from me; END
BEGIN NOW God in heaven! stay the gloating, END
BEGIN NOW Mocking singing of the sea! END
BEGIN NOW Jack Denver died on Talbragar when Christmas Eve began, END
BEGIN NOW And there was sorrow round the place, for Denver was a man; END
BEGIN NOW But big Ben Duggan saddled up, and galloped fast and far, END
BEGIN NOW To raise the longest funeral ever seen on Talbragar. END
BEGIN NOW _By station home END
BEGIN NOW And shearing shed END
BEGIN NOW Ben Duggan cried, 'Jack Denver's dead! END
BEGIN NOW He borrowed horses here and there, and rode all Christmas Eve, END
BEGIN NOW And scarcely paused a moment's time the mournful news to leave; END
BEGIN NOW He rode by lonely huts and farms, and when the day was done END
BEGIN NOW He turned his panting horse's head and rode to Ross's Run. END
BEGIN NOW No bushman in a single day had ridden half so far END
BEGIN NOW Since Johnson brought the doctor to his wife at Talbragar. END
BEGIN NOW _By diggers' camps END
BEGIN NOW Ben Duggan sped -- END
BEGIN NOW At each he cried, 'Jack Denver's dead! END
BEGIN NOW That night he passed the humpies of the splitters on the ridge, END
BEGIN NOW And roused the bullock-drivers camped at Belinfante's Bridge; END
BEGIN NOW And as he climbed the ridge again the moon shone on the rise; END
BEGIN NOW _At Blackman's Run END
BEGIN NOW Before the dawn, END
BEGIN NOW Ben Duggan cried, 'Poor Denver's gone! END
BEGIN NOW But in the gorge by Deadman's Gap the mountain shades were black, END
BEGIN NOW He saw too late, and then he heard the swift hoof's sudden jar, END
BEGIN NOW And big Ben Duggan ne'er again rode home to Talbragar. END
BEGIN NOW _'The wretch is drunk, END
BEGIN NOW And Denver's dead -- END
BEGIN NOW A burning shame!' the people said END
BEGIN NOW For thirty miles round Talbragar the boys rolled up in strength, END
BEGIN NOW And Denver had a funeral a good long mile in length; END
BEGIN NOW But some returning homeward found, by light of moon and star, END
BEGIN NOW Ben Duggan dying in the rocks, five miles from Talbragar. END
BEGIN NOW _They knelt around, END
BEGIN NOW He raised his head END
BEGIN NOW And faintly gasped, 'Jack Denver's dead, END
BEGIN NOW But one short hour before he died he woke to understand, END
BEGIN NOW They told him, when he asked them, that the funeral was 'grand'; END
BEGIN NOW And then there came into his eyes a strange victorious light, END
BEGIN NOW He smiled on them in triumph, and his great soul took its flight. END
BEGIN NOW How Duggan raised a funeral years back on Talbragar. END
BEGIN NOW _And far and wide END
BEGIN NOW When Duggan died, END
BEGIN NOW The bushmen of the western side END
BEGIN NOW while passion and pride are strong -- END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW to the tread of a mighty war, END
BEGIN NOW till the furthest hills vibrate, END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW that batter a coastal town, END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW in that glorious race to ride END
BEGIN NOW And strike for all that is true and strong, END
BEGIN NOW for all that is grand and brave, END
BEGIN NOW And all that ever shall be, so long as man has a soul to save. END
BEGIN NOW who'd ride with a stockman scout, END
BEGIN NOW like stockwhip amongst the gums -- END
BEGIN NOW And the 'straight' is reached and the field is 'gapped' END
BEGIN NOW and the hoof-torn sward grows red END
BEGIN NOW with the spirit and with the shades END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW All creeds and trades will have soldiers there -- END
BEGIN NOW give every class its due -- END
BEGIN NOW in the chase and the grim retreat -- END
BEGIN NOW They'll know the glory of victory -- and the grandeur of defeat. END
BEGIN NOW the facts that are hard to explain, END
BEGIN NOW and that was a scrub in the rear, END
BEGIN NOW And this was the point where the guards held out, END
BEGIN NOW and the enemy's lines were here.' END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW They'll tell the tales of the nights before END
BEGIN NOW and the tales of the ship and fort END
BEGIN NOW at the tales of our chivalry, END
BEGIN NOW And every boy will want to fight, no matter what cause it be -- END
BEGIN NOW When the children run to the doors and cry: END
BEGIN NOW 'Oh, mother, the troops are come!' END
BEGIN NOW no matter how low or mean, END
BEGIN NOW Will feel, when he hears the march, a touch END
BEGIN NOW of the man that he might have been. END
BEGIN NOW And this you learn from the libelled past, END
BEGIN NOW though its methods were somewhat rude -- END
BEGIN NOW and the crimes of the peace we boast, END
BEGIN NOW Out West, where the stars are brightest, END
BEGIN NOW Where the scorching north wind blows, END
BEGIN NOW And the bones of the dead gleam whitest, END
BEGIN NOW And the sun on a desert glows -- END
BEGIN NOW Yet within the selfish kingdom END
BEGIN NOW Where man starves man for gain, END
BEGIN NOW Where white men tramp for existence -- END
BEGIN NOW Wide lies the Great Grey Plain. END
BEGIN NOW No break in its awful horizon, END
BEGIN NOW No blur in the dazzling haze, END
BEGIN NOW Save where by the bordering timber END
BEGIN NOW The fierce, white heat-waves blaze, END
BEGIN NOW And out where the tank-heap rises END
BEGIN NOW Or looms when the sunlights wane, END
BEGIN NOW Till it seems like a distant mountain END
BEGIN NOW Low down on the Great Grey Plain. END
BEGIN NOW No sign of a stream or fountain, END
BEGIN NOW No spring on its dry, hot breast, END
BEGIN NOW No shade from the blazing noontide END
BEGIN NOW Where a weary man might rest. END
BEGIN NOW Whole years go by when the glowing END
BEGIN NOW Sky never clouds for rain -- END
BEGIN NOW Only the shrubs of the desert END
BEGIN NOW From the camp, while the rich man's dreaming, END
BEGIN NOW Come the 'traveller' and his mate, END
BEGIN NOW In the ghastly dawnlight seeming END
BEGIN NOW Like a swagman's ghost out late; END
BEGIN NOW And the horseman blurs in the distance, END
BEGIN NOW While still the stars remain, END
BEGIN NOW A low, faint dust-cloud haunting END
BEGIN NOW His track on the Great Grey Plain. END
BEGIN NOW And all day long from before them END
BEGIN NOW The mirage smokes away -- END
BEGIN NOW That daylight ghost of an ocean END
BEGIN NOW Creeps close behind all day END
BEGIN NOW With an evil, snake-like motion, END
BEGIN NOW As the waves of a madman's brain: END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis a phantom NOT like water END
BEGIN NOW Out there on the Great Grey Plain. END
BEGIN NOW There's a run on the Western limit END
BEGIN NOW Where a man lives like a beast, END
BEGIN NOW And a shanty in the mulga END
BEGIN NOW That stretches to the East; END
BEGIN NOW And the hopeless men who carry END
BEGIN NOW Their swags and tramp in pain -- END
BEGIN NOW The footmen must not tarry END
BEGIN NOW Out there on the Great Grey Plain. END
BEGIN NOW Out West, where the stars are brightest, END
BEGIN NOW Where the scorching north wind blows, END
BEGIN NOW And the bones of the dead seem whitest, END
BEGIN NOW And the sun on a desert glows -- END
BEGIN NOW Out back in the hungry distance END
BEGIN NOW That brave hearts dare in vain -- END
BEGIN NOW Where beggars tramp for existence -- END
BEGIN NOW There lies the Great Grey Plain. END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis a desert not more barren END
BEGIN NOW Than the Great Grey Plain of years, END
BEGIN NOW Where a fierce fire burns the hearts of men -- END
BEGIN NOW Dries up the fount of tears: END
BEGIN NOW Are crushed in a hell-born strife -- END
BEGIN NOW Where the souls of a race are murdered END
BEGIN NOW When I was up the country in the rough and early days, END
BEGIN NOW I used to work along ov Jimmy Nowlett's bullick-drays; END
BEGIN NOW Load provisions for the stations, an' we'd travel far and slow END
BEGIN NOW Through the plains an' 'cross the ranges in the days of long ago. END
BEGIN NOW _Then it's yoke up the bullicks and tramp beside 'em slow, END
BEGIN NOW An' saddle up yer horses an' a-ridin' we will go, END
BEGIN NOW To the bullick-drivin', cattle-drovin', END
BEGIN NOW Days o' long ago._ END
BEGIN NOW Once me and Jimmy Nowlett loaded timber for the town, END
BEGIN NOW But we hadn't gone a dozen mile before the rain come down, END
BEGIN NOW An' me an' Jimmy Nowlett an' the bullicks an' the dray END
BEGIN NOW Was cut off on some risin' ground while floods around us lay; END
BEGIN NOW An' we soon run short of tucker an' terbacca, which was bad, END
BEGIN NOW An' pertaters dipped in honey was the only tuck we had. END
BEGIN NOW An' half our bullicks perished when the drought was on the land, END
BEGIN NOW An' the burnin' heat that dazzles as it dances on the sand; END
BEGIN NOW But we pulled ourselves together, for we never used ter know END
BEGIN NOW What a feather bed was good for in those days o' long ago. END
BEGIN NOW But in spite ov barren ridges an' in spite ov mud an' heat, END
BEGIN NOW An' in spite of modern progress, and in spite of all their blow, END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas a better land to live in, in the days o' long ago. END
BEGIN NOW When the frosty moon was shinin' o'er the ranges like a lamp, END
BEGIN NOW An' a lot of bullick-drivers was a-campin' on the camp, END
BEGIN NOW When the fire was blazin' cheery an' the pipes was drawin' well, END
BEGIN NOW Then our songs we useter chorus an' our yarns we useter tell; END
BEGIN NOW An' we'd talk ov lands we come from, and ov chaps we useter know, END
BEGIN NOW Still we pauses at the shanty just to have a drop er cheer, END
BEGIN NOW Still I feels a kind ov pleasure when the campin'-ground is near; END
BEGIN NOW O'er the timber-truck for shelter in the days ov long ago. END
BEGIN NOW I have been a-driftin' back'ards with the changes ov the land, END
BEGIN NOW An' if I spoke ter bullicks now they wouldn't understand, END
BEGIN NOW But when Mary wakes me sudden in the night I'll often say: END
BEGIN NOW An' if Jimmy uses doubleyou instead of ar an' vee, END
BEGIN NOW An' if he drops his aitches, then you're sure to know it's he. END
BEGIN NOW An' yer won't forgit to arsk him if he still remembers Joe END
BEGIN NOW As knowed him up the country in the days o' long ago. END
BEGIN NOW _Then it's yoke up the bullicks and tramp beside 'em slow, END
BEGIN NOW An' saddle up yer horses an' a-ridin' we will go, END
BEGIN NOW To the bullick-drivin', cattle-drovin', END
BEGIN NOW Days o' long ago._ END
BEGIN NOW His old clay pipe stuck in his mouth, END
BEGIN NOW His hat pushed from his brow, END
BEGIN NOW His dress best fitted for the South -- END
BEGIN NOW I think I see him now; END
BEGIN NOW And when the city streets are still, END
BEGIN NOW And sleep upon me comes, END
BEGIN NOW I often dream that me an' Bill END
BEGIN NOW Are humpin' of our drums. END
BEGIN NOW I mind the time when first I came END
BEGIN NOW A stranger to the land; END
BEGIN NOW And I was stumped, an' sick, an' lame END
BEGIN NOW When Bill took me in hand. END
BEGIN NOW Old Bill was what a chap would call END
BEGIN NOW A friend in poverty, END
BEGIN NOW And he was very kind to all, END
BEGIN NOW And very good to me. END
BEGIN NOW We'd camp beneath the lonely trees END
BEGIN NOW And sit beside the blaze, END
BEGIN NOW A-nursin' of our wearied knees, END
BEGIN NOW A-smokin' of our clays. END
BEGIN NOW Or when we'd journeyed damp an' far, END
BEGIN NOW An' clouds were in the skies, END
BEGIN NOW We'd camp in some old shanty bar, END
BEGIN NOW And sit a-tellin' lies. END
BEGIN NOW Though time had writ upon his brow END
BEGIN NOW And rubbed away his curls, END
BEGIN NOW He always was -- an' may be now -- END
BEGIN NOW A favourite with the girls; END
BEGIN NOW I've heard bush-wimmin scream an' squall -- END
BEGIN NOW I've see'd 'em laugh until END
BEGIN NOW They could not do their work at all, END
BEGIN NOW He was the jolliest old pup END
BEGIN NOW As ever you did see, END
BEGIN NOW And often at some bush kick-up END
BEGIN NOW They'd make old Bill M.C. END
BEGIN NOW He'd make them dance and sing all night, END
BEGIN NOW He'd make the music hum, END
BEGIN NOW But he'd be gone at mornin' light END
BEGIN NOW A-humpin' of his drum. END
BEGIN NOW Though joys of which the poet rhymes END
BEGIN NOW I think we had some good old times END
BEGIN NOW Out on the wallaby. END
BEGIN NOW I took a wife and left off rum, END
BEGIN NOW An' camped beneath a roof; END
BEGIN NOW But Bill preferred to hump his drum END
BEGIN NOW A-paddin' of the hoof. END
BEGIN NOW The lazy, idle loafers what END
BEGIN NOW In toney houses camp END
BEGIN NOW Would call old Bill a drunken sot, END
BEGIN NOW A loafer, or a tramp; END
BEGIN NOW But if the dead should ever dance -- END
BEGIN NOW As poets say they will -- END
BEGIN NOW I think I'd rather take my chance END
BEGIN NOW His long life's-day is nearly o'er, END
BEGIN NOW Its shades begin to fall; END
BEGIN NOW He soon must mount his bluey for END
BEGIN NOW The last long tramp of all; END
BEGIN NOW I trust that when, in bush an' town, END
BEGIN NOW He's lived and learnt his fill, END
BEGIN NOW They'll let the golden slip-rails down END
BEGIN NOW For poor old Corny Bill. END
BEGIN NOW The rafters are open to sun, moon, and star, END
BEGIN NOW Thistles and nettles grow high in the bar -- END
BEGIN NOW The chimneys are crumbling, the log fires are dead, END
BEGIN NOW And green mosses spring from the hearthstone instead. END
BEGIN NOW The voices are silent, the bustle and din, END
BEGIN NOW For the railroad hath ruined the Cherry-tree Inn. END
BEGIN NOW Save the glimmer of stars, or the moon's pallid streams, END
BEGIN NOW And the sounds of the 'possums that camp on the beams, END
BEGIN NOW The bar-room is dark and the stable is still, END
BEGIN NOW For the coach comes no more over Cherry-tree Hill. END
BEGIN NOW No riders push on through the darkness to win END
BEGIN NOW The rest and the comfort of Cherry-tree Inn. END
BEGIN NOW I drift from my theme, for my memory strays END
BEGIN NOW To the carrying, digging, and bushranging days -- END
BEGIN NOW Far back to the seasons that I love the best, END
BEGIN NOW When a stream of wild diggers rushed into the west, END
BEGIN NOW But the 'rushes' grew feeble, and sluggish, and thin, END
BEGIN NOW Till scarcely a swagman passed Cherry-tree Inn. END
BEGIN NOW Do you think, my old mate (if it's thinking you be), END
BEGIN NOW Of the days when you tramped to the goldfields with me? END
BEGIN NOW Do you think of the day of our thirty-mile tramp, END
BEGIN NOW When never a fire could we light on the camp, END
BEGIN NOW And, weary and footsore and drenched to the skin, END
BEGIN NOW We tramped through the darkness to Cherry-tree Inn? END
BEGIN NOW Then I had a sweetheart and you had a wife, END
BEGIN NOW And Johnny was more to his mother than life; END
BEGIN NOW But we solemnly swore, ere that evening was done, END
BEGIN NOW That we'd never return till our fortunes were won. END
BEGIN NOW Next morning to harvests of folly and sin END
BEGIN NOW We tramped o'er the ranges from Cherry-tree Inn. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW The years have gone over with many a change, END
BEGIN NOW And there comes an old swagman from over the range, END
BEGIN NOW And faint 'neath the weight of his rain-sodden load, END
BEGIN NOW He suddenly thinks of the inn by the road. END
BEGIN NOW He tramps through the darkness the shelter to win, END
BEGIN NOW And reaches the ruins of Cherry-tree Inn. END
BEGIN NOW I am back from up the country -- very sorry that I went -- END
BEGIN NOW Seeking for the Southern poets' land whereon to pitch my tent; END
BEGIN NOW I have lost a lot of idols, which were broken on the track, END
BEGIN NOW Burnt a lot of fancy verses, and I'm glad that I am back. END
BEGIN NOW Further out may be the pleasant scenes of which our poets boast, END
BEGIN NOW But I think the country's rather more inviting round the coast. END
BEGIN NOW Anyway, I'll stay at present at a boarding-house in town, END
BEGIN NOW Drinking beer and lemon-squashes, taking baths and cooling down. END
BEGIN NOW 'Sunny plains'! Great Scott! -- those burning END
BEGIN NOW wastes of barren soil and sand END
BEGIN NOW With their everlasting fences stretching out across the land! END
BEGIN NOW Desolation where the crow is! Desert where the eagle flies, END
BEGIN NOW Turned from some infernal furnace on a plain devoid of grass. END
BEGIN NOW Where the God-forgotten hatter dreams of city life and beer. END
BEGIN NOW Treacherous tracks that trap the stranger, END
BEGIN NOW endless roads that gleam and glare, END
BEGIN NOW Dark and evil-looking gullies, hiding secrets here and there! END
BEGIN NOW Land of day and night -- no morning freshness, and no afternoon, END
BEGIN NOW When the great white sun in rising bringeth summer heat in June. END
BEGIN NOW Dismal country for the exile, when the shades begin to fall END
BEGIN NOW From the sad heart-breaking sunset, to the new-chum worst of all. END
BEGIN NOW Dreary land in rainy weather, with the endless clouds that drift END
BEGIN NOW O'er the bushman like a blanket that the Lord will never lift -- END
BEGIN NOW Ghastly fires in lonely humpies where the granite rocks are piled END
BEGIN NOW Land where gaunt and haggard women live alone and work like men, END
BEGIN NOW Till their husbands, gone a-droving, will return to them again: END
BEGIN NOW Homes of men! if home had ever such a God-forgotten place, END
BEGIN NOW Where the wild selector's children fly before a stranger's face. END
BEGIN NOW Home of tragedy applauded by the dingoes' dismal yell, END
BEGIN NOW Heaven of the shanty-keeper -- fitting fiend for such a hell -- END
BEGIN NOW I am back from up the country, up the country where I went END
BEGIN NOW Seeking for the Southern poets' land whereon to pitch my tent; END
BEGIN NOW I have shattered many idols out along the dusty track, END
BEGIN NOW Burnt a lot of fancy verses -- and I'm glad that I am back. END
BEGIN NOW I believe the Southern poets' dream will not be realised END
BEGIN NOW Till the plains are irrigated and the land is humanised. END
BEGIN NOW I intend to stay at present, as I said before, in town END
BEGIN NOW Drinking beer and lemon-squashes, taking baths and cooling down. END
BEGIN NOW I've got no spirits left to rise and smooth me achin' brow -- END
BEGIN NOW I'm too knocked up to light a fire and bile the billy now. END
BEGIN NOW through mud and slush 'n sleet; END
BEGIN NOW It's tramp an' tramp for tucker -- one everlastin' strife, END
BEGIN NOW An' wearin' out yer boots an' heart in the wastin' of yer life._ END
BEGIN NOW They whine o' lost an' wasted lives in idleness and crime -- END
BEGIN NOW I've wasted mine for twenty years, and grafted all the time END
BEGIN NOW And never drunk the stuff I earned, nor gambled when I shore -- END
BEGIN NOW But somehow when yer on the track yer life seems wasted more. END
BEGIN NOW There's twenty hungry beggars wild for any job this year, END
BEGIN NOW An' fifty might be at the shed while I am lyin' here. END
BEGIN NOW The sinews in my legs seem drawn, red-hot -- 'n that's the truth; END
BEGIN NOW The blessed rain is comin' too -- there's oceans in the sky, END
BEGIN NOW An' I suppose I must get up and rig the blessed fly; END
BEGIN NOW The heat is bad, the water's bad, the flies a crimson curse, END
BEGIN NOW The grub is bad, mosquitoes damned -- but rheumatism's worse. END
BEGIN NOW I wonder why poor blokes like me will stick so fast ter breath, END
BEGIN NOW Though Shakespeare says it is the fear of somethin' after death; END
BEGIN NOW But though Eternity be cursed with God's almighty curse -- END
BEGIN NOW What ever that same somethin' is I swear it can't be worse. END
BEGIN NOW A-wearin' out yer heart 'n soul in the wastin' of yer life._ END
BEGIN NOW Above the ashes straight and tall, END
BEGIN NOW Through ferns with moisture dripping, END
BEGIN NOW I climb beneath the sandstone wall, END
BEGIN NOW My feet on mosses slipping. END
BEGIN NOW Like ramparts round the valley's edge END
BEGIN NOW The tinted cliffs are standing, END
BEGIN NOW With many a broken wall and ledge, END
BEGIN NOW And many a rocky landing. END
BEGIN NOW And round about their rugged feet END
BEGIN NOW Deep ferny dells are hidden END
BEGIN NOW In shadowed depths, whence dust and heat END
BEGIN NOW Are banished and forbidden. END
BEGIN NOW The stream that, crooning to itself, END
BEGIN NOW Comes down a tireless rover, END
BEGIN NOW Flows calmly to the rocky shelf, END
BEGIN NOW And there leaps bravely over. END
BEGIN NOW Now pouring down, now lost in spray END
BEGIN NOW When mountain breezes sally, END
BEGIN NOW The water strikes the rock midway, END
BEGIN NOW And leaps into the valley. END
BEGIN NOW Now in the west the colours change, END
BEGIN NOW The blue with crimson blending; END
BEGIN NOW The sun is fast descending. END
BEGIN NOW And mellowed day comes o'er the place, END
BEGIN NOW And softens ragged edges; END
BEGIN NOW The rising moon's great placid face END
BEGIN NOW Looks gravely o'er the ledges. END
BEGIN NOW It was pleasant up the country, City Bushman, where you went, END
BEGIN NOW For you sought the greener patches and you travelled like a gent; END
BEGIN NOW Though you know the squalid city needn't keep you from the bush; END
BEGIN NOW But his back is growing rounder -- slaving for the absentee -- END
BEGIN NOW And his toiling wife is thinner than a country wife should be. END
BEGIN NOW For we noticed that the faces of the folks we chanced to meet END
BEGIN NOW Should have made a greater contrast to the faces in the street; END
BEGIN NOW And, in short, we think the bushman's being driven to the wall, END
BEGIN NOW And it's doubtful if his spirit will be 'loyal thro' it all'. END
BEGIN NOW Though the bush has been romantic and it's nice to sing about, END
BEGIN NOW There's a lot of patriotism that the land could do without -- END
BEGIN NOW Sort of BRITISH WORKMAN nonsense that shall perish in the scorn END
BEGIN NOW Of the drover who is driven and the shearer who is shorn, END
BEGIN NOW Of the struggling western farmers who have little time for rest, END
BEGIN NOW And are ruined on selections in the sheep-infested West; END
BEGIN NOW Droving songs are very pretty, but they merit little thanks END
BEGIN NOW From the people of a country in possession of the Banks. END
BEGIN NOW For the drought will go on drying while there's anything to dry, END
BEGIN NOW Then it rains until you'd fancy it would bleach the sunny sky -- END
BEGIN NOW Then it pelters out of reason, for the downpour day and night END
BEGIN NOW Nearly sweeps the population to the Great Australian Bight. END
BEGIN NOW It is up in Northern Queensland that the seasons do their best, END
BEGIN NOW But it's doubtful if you ever saw a season in the West; END
BEGIN NOW There are years without an autumn or a winter or a spring, END
BEGIN NOW In the bush my ears were opened to the singing of the bird, END
BEGIN NOW But the 'carol of the magpie' was a thing I never heard. END
BEGIN NOW Once the beggar roused my slumbers in a shanty, it is true, END
BEGIN NOW But I only heard him asking, 'Who the blanky blank are you?' END
BEGIN NOW Yes, I heard the shearers singing 'William Riley', out of tune, END
BEGIN NOW Saw 'em fighting round a shanty on a Sunday afternoon, END
BEGIN NOW But the bushman isn't always 'trapping brumbies in the night', END
BEGIN NOW Nor is he for ever riding when 'the morn is fresh and bright', END
BEGIN NOW And he isn't always singing in the humpies on the run -- END
BEGIN NOW And the camp-fire's 'cheery blazes' are a trifle overdone; END
BEGIN NOW We have grumbled with the bushmen round the fire on rainy days, END
BEGIN NOW When the smoke would blind a bullock and there wasn't any blaze, END
BEGIN NOW Save the blazes of our language, for we cursed the fire in turn END
BEGIN NOW Till the atmosphere was heated and the wood began to burn. END
BEGIN NOW Then we had to wring our blueys which were rotting in the swags, END
BEGIN NOW And we saw the sugar leaking through the bottoms of the bags, END
BEGIN NOW And we couldn't raise a chorus, for the toothache and the cramp, END
BEGIN NOW To be losing time and money through the foot-rot in the flock, END
BEGIN NOW And you wouldn't mind the beauties underneath the starry dome END
BEGIN NOW If you had a wife and children and a lot of bills at home. END
BEGIN NOW Did you ever guard the cattle when the night was inky-black, END
BEGIN NOW And it rained, and icy water trickled gently down your back END
BEGIN NOW Till your saddle-weary backbone fell a-aching to the roots END
BEGIN NOW Till a squatter's irate dummy cantered up to warn you off? END
BEGIN NOW Do you think the bush was better in the 'good old droving days', END
BEGIN NOW When the squatter ruled supremely as the king of western ways, END
BEGIN NOW When you got a slip of paper for the little you could earn, END
BEGIN NOW But were forced to take provisions from the station in return -- END
BEGIN NOW When you couldn't keep a chicken at your humpy on the run, END
BEGIN NOW While you 'rose up Willy Riley' -- in the days ere you were born? END
BEGIN NOW Ah! we read about the drovers and the shearers and the like END
BEGIN NOW Till we wonder why such happy and romantic fellows strike. END
BEGIN NOW Don't you fancy that the poets ought to give the bush a rest END
BEGIN NOW Ere they raise a just rebellion in the over-written West? END
BEGIN NOW Where the simple-minded bushman gets a meal and bed and rum END
BEGIN NOW Just by riding round reporting phantom flocks that never come; END
BEGIN NOW Where the idle shanty-keeper never fails to make a draw, END
BEGIN NOW And the dummy gets his tucker through provisions in the law; END
BEGIN NOW Where the labour-agitator -- when the shearers rise in might -- END
BEGIN NOW Makes his money sacrificing all his substance for The Right; END
BEGIN NOW Where the drovers and the shearers and the bushmen and the rest END
BEGIN NOW Never reach the Eldorado of the poets of the West. END
BEGIN NOW And you think the bush is purer and that life is better there, END
BEGIN NOW Of the awful 'city urchin who would greet you with a curse'. END
BEGIN NOW Do you think we're never jolly where the trams and buses rage? END
BEGIN NOW Did you hear the gods in chorus when 'Ri-tooral' held the stage? END
BEGIN NOW Did you catch a ring of sorrow in the city urchin's voice END
BEGIN NOW When they drink and flirt and so on in the glow of private bars? END
BEGIN NOW (And about that self-same attic -- Lord! wherever have you been? END
BEGIN NOW For the struggling needlewoman mostly keeps her attic clean.) END
BEGIN NOW But you'll find it very jolly with the cuff-and-collar push, END
BEGIN NOW And the city seems to suit you, while you rave about the bush. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW You'll admit that Up-the Country, more especially in drought, END
BEGIN NOW Isn't quite the Eldorado that the poets rave about, END
BEGIN NOW Yet at times we long to gallop where the reckless bushman rides END
BEGIN NOW In the wake of startled brumbies that are flying for their hides; END
BEGIN NOW And to hear the stockwhips rattle just like rifles in the trees! END
BEGIN NOW Long to feel the bridle-leather tugging strongly in the hand END
BEGIN NOW And to feel once more a little like a native of the land. END
BEGIN NOW And the ring of bitter feeling in the jingling of our rhymes END
BEGIN NOW Isn't suited to the country nor the spirit of the times. END
BEGIN NOW Let us go together droving, and returning, if we live, END
BEGIN NOW Try to understand each other while we reckon up the div. END
BEGIN NOW There are scenes in the distance where beauty is not, END
BEGIN NOW On the desolate flats where gaunt appletrees rot. END
BEGIN NOW Where the brooding old ridge rises up to the breeze END
BEGIN NOW From his dark lonely gullies of stringy-bark trees, END
BEGIN NOW There are voice-haunted gaps, ever sullen and strange, END
BEGIN NOW But Eurunderee lies like a gem in the range. END
BEGIN NOW Still I see in my fancy the dark-green and blue END
BEGIN NOW Of the box-covered hills where the five-corners grew; END
BEGIN NOW And the rugged old sheoaks that sighed in the bend END
BEGIN NOW O'er the lily-decked pools where the dark ridges end, END
BEGIN NOW And the scrub-covered spurs running down from the Peak END
BEGIN NOW To the deep grassy banks of Eurunderee Creek. END
BEGIN NOW On the knolls where the vineyards and fruit-gardens are END
BEGIN NOW There's a beauty that even the drought cannot mar; END
BEGIN NOW For I noticed it oft, in the days that are lost, END
BEGIN NOW As I trod on the siding where lingered the frost, END
BEGIN NOW When the shadows of night from the gullies were gone END
BEGIN NOW And the hills in the background were flushed by the dawn. END
BEGIN NOW I was there in late years, but there's many a change END
BEGIN NOW Where the Cudgegong River flows down through the range, END
BEGIN NOW For the curse of the town with the railroad had come, END
BEGIN NOW And the goldfields were dead. And the girl and the chum END
BEGIN NOW And the old home were gone, yet the oaks seemed to speak END
BEGIN NOW Of the hazy old days on Eurunderee Creek. END
BEGIN NOW And I stood by that creek, ere the sunset grew cold, END
BEGIN NOW When the leaves of the sheoaks are traced on the gold, END
BEGIN NOW And I thought of old things, and I thought of old folks, END
BEGIN NOW Till I sighed in my heart to the sigh of the oaks; END
BEGIN NOW For the years waste away like the waters that leak END
BEGIN NOW Through the pebbles and sand of Eurunderee Creek. END
BEGIN NOW Only one old post is standing -- END
BEGIN NOW Solid yet, but only one -- END
BEGIN NOW Where the milking, and the branding, END
BEGIN NOW And the slaughtering were done. END
BEGIN NOW Later years have brought dejection, END
BEGIN NOW Care, and sorrow; but we knew END
BEGIN NOW Happy days on that selection END
BEGIN NOW Then the light of day commencing END
BEGIN NOW Found us at the gully's head, END
BEGIN NOW Splitting timber for the fencing, END
BEGIN NOW Stripping bark to roof the shed. END
BEGIN NOW Hands and hearts the labour strengthened; END
BEGIN NOW Weariness we never knew, END
BEGIN NOW Even when the shadows lengthened END
BEGIN NOW Round the base of Bukaroo. END
BEGIN NOW There for days below the paddock END
BEGIN NOW How the wilderness would yield END
BEGIN NOW While we toiled to win the field. END
BEGIN NOW Bronzed hands we used to sully END
BEGIN NOW Till they were of darkest hue, END
BEGIN NOW 'Burning off' down in the gully END
BEGIN NOW At the back of Bukaroo. END
BEGIN NOW When we came the baby brother END
BEGIN NOW Left in haste his broken toys, END
BEGIN NOW Shouted to the busy mother: END
BEGIN NOW 'Here is dadda and the boys!' END
BEGIN NOW Strange it seems that she was able END
BEGIN NOW For the work that she would do; END
BEGIN NOW How she'd bustle round the table END
BEGIN NOW In the hut 'neath Bukaroo! END
BEGIN NOW When the cows were safely yarded, END
BEGIN NOW And the calves were in the pen, END
BEGIN NOW All the cares of day discarded, END
BEGIN NOW Closed we round the hut-fire then. END
BEGIN NOW Rang the roof with boyish laughter END
BEGIN NOW While the flames o'er-topped the flue; END
BEGIN NOW Happy days remembered after -- END
BEGIN NOW Far away from Bukaroo. END
BEGIN NOW But the years were full of changes, END
BEGIN NOW And a sorrow found us there; END
BEGIN NOW For our home amid the ranges END
BEGIN NOW Was not safe from searching Care. END
BEGIN NOW On he came, a silent creeper; END
BEGIN NOW And another mountain threw END
BEGIN NOW O'er our lives a shadow deeper END
BEGIN NOW Than the shade of Bukaroo. END
BEGIN NOW All the farm is disappearing; END
BEGIN NOW For the home has vanished now, END
BEGIN NOW Mountain scrub has choked the clearing, END
BEGIN NOW Hid the furrows of the plough. END
BEGIN NOW Nearer still the scrub is creeping END
BEGIN NOW Where the little garden grew; END
BEGIN NOW And the old folks now are sleeping END
BEGIN NOW At the foot of Bukaroo. END
BEGIN NOW The Fire at Ross's Farm END
BEGIN NOW The squatter saw his pastures wide END
BEGIN NOW The farmers moving to the west END
BEGIN NOW Selected on his run; END
BEGIN NOW Selectors took the water up END
BEGIN NOW And all the black soil round; END
BEGIN NOW The best grass-land the squatter had END
BEGIN NOW Was spoilt by Ross's Ground. END
BEGIN NOW Now many schemes to shift old Ross END
BEGIN NOW Had racked the squatter's brains, END
BEGIN NOW But Sandy had the stubborn blood END
BEGIN NOW Of Scotland in his veins; END
BEGIN NOW He held the land and fenced it in, END
BEGIN NOW He cleared and ploughed the soil, END
BEGIN NOW And year by year a richer crop END
BEGIN NOW Repaid him for his toil. END
BEGIN NOW Between the homes for many years END
BEGIN NOW The devil left his tracks: END
BEGIN NOW The squatter pounded Ross's stock, END
BEGIN NOW And Sandy pounded Black's. END
BEGIN NOW A well upon the lower run END
BEGIN NOW Was filled with earth and logs, END
BEGIN NOW And Black laid baits about the farm END
BEGIN NOW To poison Ross's dogs. END
BEGIN NOW It was, indeed, a deadly feud END
BEGIN NOW Of class and creed and race; END
BEGIN NOW But, yet, there was a Romeo END
BEGIN NOW And a Juliet in the case; END
BEGIN NOW And more than once across the flats, END
BEGIN NOW Young Robert Black was seen to ride END
BEGIN NOW With pretty Jenny Ross. END
BEGIN NOW One Christmas time, when months of drought END
BEGIN NOW Had parched the western creeks, END
BEGIN NOW The bush-fires started in the north END
BEGIN NOW And travelled south for weeks. END
BEGIN NOW At night along the river-side END
BEGIN NOW The scene was grand and strange -- END
BEGIN NOW The hill-fires looked like lighted streets END
BEGIN NOW Of cities in the range. END
BEGIN NOW The cattle-tracks between the trees END
BEGIN NOW Were like long dusky aisles, END
BEGIN NOW And on a sudden breeze the fire END
BEGIN NOW Would sweep along for miles; END
BEGIN NOW Like sounds of distant musketry END
BEGIN NOW It crackled through the brakes, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er the flat of silver grass END
BEGIN NOW It hissed like angry snakes. END
BEGIN NOW It leapt across the flowing streams END
BEGIN NOW And raced o'er pastures broad; END
BEGIN NOW It climbed the trees and lit the boughs END
BEGIN NOW And through the scrubs it roared. END
BEGIN NOW The bees fell stifled in the smoke END
BEGIN NOW Or perished in their hives, END
BEGIN NOW And with the stock the kangaroos END
BEGIN NOW Went flying for their lives. END
BEGIN NOW When, through the scrub-lands wide, END
BEGIN NOW Young Robert Black came riding home END
BEGIN NOW As only natives ride. END
BEGIN NOW He galloped to the homestead door END
BEGIN NOW And gave the first alarm: END
BEGIN NOW 'The fire is past the granite spur, END
BEGIN NOW 'And close to Ross's farm.' END
BEGIN NOW 'Now, father, send the men at once, END
BEGIN NOW They won't be wanted here; END
BEGIN NOW Poor Ross's wheat is all he has END
BEGIN NOW To pull him through the year.' END
BEGIN NOW 'Then let it burn,' the squatter said; END
BEGIN NOW 'I'd like to see it done -- END
BEGIN NOW I'd bless the fire if it would clear END
BEGIN NOW Selectors from the run. END
BEGIN NOW 'Go if you will,' the squatter said, END
BEGIN NOW 'You shall not take the men -- END
BEGIN NOW Go out and join your precious friends, END
BEGIN NOW And don't come here again.' END
BEGIN NOW 'I won't come back,' young Robert cried, END
BEGIN NOW And, reckless in his ire, END
BEGIN NOW He sharply turned his horse's head END
BEGIN NOW And galloped towards the fire. END
BEGIN NOW And there, for three long weary hours, END
BEGIN NOW Half-blind with smoke and heat, END
BEGIN NOW Old Ross and Robert fought the flames END
BEGIN NOW That neared the ripened wheat. END
BEGIN NOW The farmer's hand was nerved by fears END
BEGIN NOW Of danger and of loss; END
BEGIN NOW And Robert fought the stubborn foe END
BEGIN NOW For the love of Jenny Ross. END
BEGIN NOW But serpent-like the curves and lines END
BEGIN NOW Slipped past them, and between, END
BEGIN NOW Until they reached the bound'ry where END
BEGIN NOW The old coach-road had been. END
BEGIN NOW 'The track is now our only hope, END
BEGIN NOW There we must stand,' cried Ross, END
BEGIN NOW 'For nought on earth can stop the fire END
BEGIN NOW If once it gets across.' END
BEGIN NOW Then came a cruel gust of wind, END
BEGIN NOW And, with a fiendish rush, END
BEGIN NOW The flames leapt o'er the narrow path END
BEGIN NOW And lit the fence of brush. END
BEGIN NOW 'The crop must burn!' the farmer cried, END
BEGIN NOW 'We cannot save it now,' END
BEGIN NOW And down upon the blackened ground END
BEGIN NOW He dashed the ragged bough. END
BEGIN NOW But wildly, in a rush of hope, END
BEGIN NOW His heart began to beat, END
BEGIN NOW For o'er the crackling fire he heard END
BEGIN NOW The sound of horses' feet. END
BEGIN NOW 'Here's help at last,' young Robert cried, END
BEGIN NOW And even as he spoke END
BEGIN NOW The squatter with a dozen men END
BEGIN NOW Came racing through the smoke. END
BEGIN NOW Down on the ground the stockmen jumped END
BEGIN NOW And bared each brawny arm, END
BEGIN NOW They tore green branches from the trees END
BEGIN NOW And fought for Ross's farm; END
BEGIN NOW And when before the gallant band END
BEGIN NOW The beaten flames gave way, END
BEGIN NOW Two grimy hands in friendship joined -- END
BEGIN NOW A cloud of dust on the long white road, END
BEGIN NOW And the teams go creeping on END
BEGIN NOW Inch by inch with the weary load; END
BEGIN NOW And by the power of the green-hide goad END
BEGIN NOW The distant goal is won. END
BEGIN NOW With eyes half-shut to the blinding dust, END
BEGIN NOW And necks to the yokes bent low, END
BEGIN NOW The beasts are pulling as bullocks must; END
BEGIN NOW And the shining tires might almost rust END
BEGIN NOW While the spokes are turning slow. END
BEGIN NOW With face half-hid 'neath a broad-brimmed hat END
BEGIN NOW That shades from the heat's white waves, END
BEGIN NOW And shouldered whip with its green-hide plait, END
BEGIN NOW The driver plods with a gait like that END
BEGIN NOW Of his weary, patient slaves. END
BEGIN NOW He wipes his brow, for the day is hot, END
BEGIN NOW And spits to the left with spite; END
BEGIN NOW He shouts at 'Bally', and flicks at 'Scot', END
BEGIN NOW And raises dust from the back of 'Spot', END
BEGIN NOW And spits to the dusty right. END
BEGIN NOW He'll sometimes pause as a thing of form END
BEGIN NOW In front of a settler's door, END
BEGIN NOW And ask for a drink, and remark 'It's warm, END
BEGIN NOW Or say 'There's signs of a thunder-storm'; END
BEGIN NOW But he seldom utters more. END
BEGIN NOW But the rains are heavy on roads like these; END
BEGIN NOW And, fronting his lonely home, END
BEGIN NOW For weeks together the settler sees END
BEGIN NOW The teams bogged down to the axletrees, END
BEGIN NOW Or ploughing the sodden loam. END
BEGIN NOW And then when the roads are at their worst, END
BEGIN NOW The bushman's children hear END
BEGIN NOW The cruel blows of the whips reversed END
BEGIN NOW While bullocks pull as their hearts would burst, END
BEGIN NOW And bellow with pain and fear. END
BEGIN NOW And thus with little of joy or rest END
BEGIN NOW Are the long, long journeys done; END
BEGIN NOW And thus -- 'tis a cruel war at the best -- END
BEGIN NOW Is distance fought in the mighty West, END
BEGIN NOW And the lonely battles won. END
BEGIN NOW Cameron's Heart END
BEGIN NOW The diggings were just in their glory when Alister Cameron came, END
BEGIN NOW and spoke with respect of his kirk; END
BEGIN NOW He shunned all the girls in the camp, END
BEGIN NOW and they said he was proof to the dart -- END
BEGIN NOW That nothing but whisky and gaming had ever a place in his heart; END
BEGIN NOW A bit of a worn silver chain, and the portrait of Cameron's girl. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW It chanced in the first of the Sixties that Ally and I and McKean END
BEGIN NOW where it suddenly stopped, and hung still. END
BEGIN NOW I knew what was up in a moment when Cameron shouted to me: END
BEGIN NOW 'Climb up for your life by the footholes. END
BEGIN NOW And those were the last words he uttered. END
BEGIN NOW He groaned, for I heard him quite plain -- END
BEGIN NOW I wonder did Alister think of the scenes in the distance so dim, END
BEGIN NOW When you haven't got a billet, and the times are very slack, END
BEGIN NOW There is nothing that can spur you like the shame of going back; END
BEGIN NOW Crawling home with empty pockets, END
BEGIN NOW Going back hard-up; END
BEGIN NOW Oh! it's then you learn the meaning of humiliation's cup. END
BEGIN NOW When the place and you are strangers and you struggle all alone, END
BEGIN NOW And you have a mighty longing for the town where you are known; END
BEGIN NOW When your clothes are very shabby and the future's very black, END
BEGIN NOW There is nothing that can hurt you like the shame of going back. END
BEGIN NOW When we've fought the battle bravely and are beaten to the wall, END
BEGIN NOW And your heart is in the shadow of the shame of going back. END
BEGIN NOW When a beaten man's discovered with a bullet in his brain, END
BEGIN NOW But it very often happens that he'd lately got the sack, END
BEGIN NOW And his onward move was owing to the shame of going back. END
BEGIN NOW You will learn the bitter meaning of the shame of going back; END
BEGIN NOW Going home with empty pockets, END
BEGIN NOW Going home hard-up; END
BEGIN NOW Oh, you'll taste the bitter poison in humiliation's cup. END
BEGIN NOW I met Jack Ellis in town to-day -- END
BEGIN NOW Jack Ellis -- my old mate, Jack -- END
BEGIN NOW Ten years ago, from the Castlereagh, END
BEGIN NOW We carried our swags together away END
BEGIN NOW But times have altered since those old days, END
BEGIN NOW And the times have changed the men. END
BEGIN NOW Ah, well! there's little to blame or praise -- END
BEGIN NOW Jack Ellis and I have tramped long ways END
BEGIN NOW On different tracks since then. END
BEGIN NOW His hat was battered, his coat was green, END
BEGIN NOW The toes of his boots were through, END
BEGIN NOW But the pride was his! It was I felt mean -- END
BEGIN NOW I wished that my collar was not so clean, END
BEGIN NOW Nor the clothes I wore so new. END
BEGIN NOW He saw me first, and he knew 'twas I -- END
BEGIN NOW The holiday swell he met. END
BEGIN NOW Why have we no faith in each other? Ah, why? -- END
BEGIN NOW He made as though he would pass me by, END
BEGIN NOW For he thought that I might forget. END
BEGIN NOW He ought to have known me better than that, END
BEGIN NOW By the tracks we tramped far out -- END
BEGIN NOW The sweltering scrub and the blazing flat, END
BEGIN NOW When the heat came down through each old felt hat END
BEGIN NOW In the hell-born western drought. END
BEGIN NOW The cheques we made and the shanty sprees, END
BEGIN NOW The camps in the great blind scrub, END
BEGIN NOW The long wet tramps when the plains were seas, END
BEGIN NOW And the oracles worked in days like these END
BEGIN NOW For rum and tobacco and grub. END
BEGIN NOW Could I forget how we struck 'the same END
BEGIN NOW Old tale' in the nearer West, END
BEGIN NOW When the first great test of our friendship came -- END
BEGIN NOW But -- well, there's little to praise or blame END
BEGIN NOW If our mateship stood the test. END
BEGIN NOW 'Heads!' he laughed (but his face was stern) -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Tails!' and a friendly oath; END
BEGIN NOW We loved her fair, we had much to learn -- END
BEGIN NOW And each was stabbed to the heart in turn END
BEGIN NOW By the girl who -- loved us both. END
BEGIN NOW Or the last day lost on the lignum plain, END
BEGIN NOW When I staggered, half-blind, half-dead, END
BEGIN NOW With a burning throat and a tortured brain; END
BEGIN NOW And the tank when we came to the track again END
BEGIN NOW Was seventeen miles ahead. END
BEGIN NOW Then life seemed finished -- then death began END
BEGIN NOW As down in the dust I sank, END
BEGIN NOW But he stuck to his mate as a bushman can, END
BEGIN NOW Till I heard him saying, 'Bear up, old man!' END
BEGIN NOW In the shade by the mulga tank. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW He took my hand in a distant way END
BEGIN NOW (I thought how we parted last), END
BEGIN NOW And we seemed like men who have nought to say END
BEGIN NOW And who meet -- 'Good-day', and who part -- 'Good-day', END
BEGIN NOW Who never have shared the past. END
BEGIN NOW I asked him in for a drink with me -- END
BEGIN NOW Jack Ellis -- my old mate, Jack -- END
BEGIN NOW But his manner no longer was careless and free, END
BEGIN NOW He followed, but not with the grin that he END
BEGIN NOW Wore always in days Out Back. END
BEGIN NOW I tried to live in the past once more -- END
BEGIN NOW Or the present and past combine, END
BEGIN NOW But the days between I could not ignore -- END
BEGIN NOW I couldn't help notice the clothes he wore, END
BEGIN NOW And he couldn't but notice mine. END
BEGIN NOW He placed his glass on the polished bar, END
BEGIN NOW And he wouldn't fill up again; END
BEGIN NOW For he is prouder than most men are -- END
BEGIN NOW Jack Ellis and I have tramped too far END
BEGIN NOW On different tracks since then. END
BEGIN NOW He said that he had a mate to meet, END
BEGIN NOW And 'I'll see you again,' said he, END
BEGIN NOW Then he hurried away through the crowded street END
BEGIN NOW And the rattle of buses and scrape of feet END
BEGIN NOW Seemed suddenly loud to me. END
BEGIN NOW And I almost wished that the time were come END
BEGIN NOW When less will be left to Fate -- END
BEGIN NOW When boys will start on the track from home END
BEGIN NOW With equal chances, and no old chum END
BEGIN NOW Have more or less than his mate. END
BEGIN NOW He had offices in Sydney, not so many years ago, END
BEGIN NOW And his shingle bore the legend 'Peter Anderson and Co.', END
BEGIN NOW But his real name was Careless, as the fellows understood -- END
BEGIN NOW And his relatives decided that he wasn't any good. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas their gentle tongues that blasted any 'character' he had -- END
BEGIN NOW It was limited in number to a unit, was the Co. -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas a bosom chum of Peter and his Christian name was Joe. END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis a class of men belonging to these soul-forsaken years: END
BEGIN NOW Third-rate canvassers, collectors, journalists and auctioneers. END
BEGIN NOW They are never very shabby, they are never very spruce -- END
BEGIN NOW Going cheerfully and carelessly and smoothly to the deuce. END
BEGIN NOW Some are wanderers by profession, 'turning up' and gone as soon, END
BEGIN NOW Peter met you with the comic smile of one who knows you well, END
BEGIN NOW And is mighty glad to see you, and has got a joke to tell; END
BEGIN NOW Only cynical in cases where his own self was the jest, END
BEGIN NOW And the humour of his good yarns made atonement for the rest. END
BEGIN NOW (You can always furnish cheaply, when your cash or credit fails, END
BEGIN NOW With a packing-case, a hammer, and a pound of two-inch nails -- END
BEGIN NOW And, maybe, a drop of varnish and sienna, too, for tints, END
BEGIN NOW And a scrap or two of oilcloth, and a yard or two of chintz). END
BEGIN NOW The office was their haven, for they lived there when hard-up -- END
BEGIN NOW A 'daily' for a table cloth -- a jam tin for a cup; END
BEGIN NOW And if the landlord's bailiff happened round in times like these END
BEGIN NOW Till another portal boasted 'Peter Anderson and Co.' END
BEGIN NOW no one would have thought 'twas Joe! END
BEGIN NOW Gloriously drunk and happy, till they heard the roosters crow -- END
BEGIN NOW And the landlady and neighbours made complaints about the Co. END
BEGIN NOW But that life! it might be likened to a reckless drinking-song, END
BEGIN NOW For it can't go on for ever, and it never lasted long. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW Debt-collecting ruined Peter -- people talked him round too oft, END
BEGIN NOW He would ask him round the corner, and it seemed to him and her, END
BEGIN NOW And perhaps it pays in heaven, but on earth it doesn't pay. END
BEGIN NOW They got harder up than ever, and, to make it worse, the Co. END
BEGIN NOW Went more often round the corner than was good for him to go. END
BEGIN NOW 'I might live,' he said to Peter, 'but I haven't got the nerve -- END
BEGIN NOW Eat and drink and love they tell us, for to-morrow we may die, END
BEGIN NOW 'The death of such philosophy's the death I'm dying now. END
BEGIN NOW Pull yourself together, Peter; 'tis the dying wish of Joe END
BEGIN NOW That the business world shall honour Peter Anderson and Co. END
BEGIN NOW 'When you feel your life is sinking in a dull and useless course, END
BEGIN NOW See if you can raise a drink, old man, I'm feelin' mighty bad -- END
BEGIN NOW Or a joke to try on Peter -- or, perhaps, it was the rum. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW Yet, to show his heart was not of human decency bereft, END
BEGIN NOW Peter paid the undertaker. He got drunk on what was left; END
BEGIN NOW And the dying words of Joseph, ringing through his own despair, END
BEGIN NOW Peter 'pulled himself together' and he started business there. END
BEGIN NOW But his life was very lonely, and his heart was very sad, END
BEGIN NOW And no help to reformation was the company he had -- END
BEGIN NOW And a boundary-rider jogging out across the neighb'ring run END
BEGIN NOW Was attracted by a something that was blazing in the sun; END
BEGIN NOW And he found that it was Peter, lying peacefully at rest, END
BEGIN NOW With a bottle close beside him and the shingle on his breast. END
BEGIN NOW Well, they analysed the liquor, and it would appear that he END
BEGIN NOW Qualified his drink with something good for setting spirits free. END
BEGIN NOW On a lonely selection far out in the West END
BEGIN NOW An old woman works all the day without rest, END
BEGIN NOW And she croons, as she toils 'neath the sky's glassy dome, END
BEGIN NOW 'Sure I'll keep the ould place till the childer come home.' END
BEGIN NOW She mends all the fences, she grubs, and she ploughs, END
BEGIN NOW She drives the old horse and she milks all the cows, END
BEGIN NOW And she sings to herself as she thatches the stack, END
BEGIN NOW 'Sure I'll keep the ould place till the childer come back.' END
BEGIN NOW It is five weary years since her old husband died; END
BEGIN NOW And oft as he lay on his deathbed he sighed END
BEGIN NOW 'Sure one man can bring up ten children, he can, END
BEGIN NOW An' it's strange that ten sons cannot keep one old man.' END
BEGIN NOW Whenever the scowling old sundowners come, END
BEGIN NOW And cunningly ask if the master's at home, END
BEGIN NOW 'Be off,' she replies, 'with your blarney and cant, END
BEGIN NOW Or I'll call my son Andy; he's workin' beyant.' END
BEGIN NOW 'Git out,' she replies, though she trembles with fear, END
BEGIN NOW For she lives all alone and no neighbours are near; END
BEGIN NOW But she says to herself, when she's like to despond, END
BEGIN NOW That the boys are at work in the paddock beyond. END
BEGIN NOW Ah, none of her children need follow the plough, END
BEGIN NOW And some have grown rich in the city ere now; END
BEGIN NOW Yet she says: 'They might come when the shearing is done, END
BEGIN NOW And I'll keep the ould place if it's only for one.' END
BEGIN NOW Tall, and stout, and solid-looking, END
BEGIN NOW Yet a wreck; END
BEGIN NOW None would think Death's finger's hooking END
BEGIN NOW Him from deck. END
BEGIN NOW Cause of half the fun that's started -- END
BEGIN NOW Isn't like a broken-hearted, END
BEGIN NOW Ruined man. END
BEGIN NOW Walking-coat from tail to throat is END
BEGIN NOW Frayed and greened -- END
BEGIN NOW Like a man whose other coat is END
BEGIN NOW Being cleaned; END
BEGIN NOW Gone for ever round the edging END
BEGIN NOW Past repair -- END
BEGIN NOW Waistcoat pockets frayed with dredging END
BEGIN NOW After 'sprats' no longer there. END
BEGIN NOW Wearing summer boots in June, or END
BEGIN NOW Slippers worn and old -- END
BEGIN NOW Like a man whose other shoon are END
BEGIN NOW Getting soled. END
BEGIN NOW Pants? They're far from being recent -- END
BEGIN NOW But, perhaps, I'd better not -- END
BEGIN NOW Says they are the only decent END
BEGIN NOW Pair he's got. END
BEGIN NOW And his hat, I am afraid, is END
BEGIN NOW Past all lifting to the ladies END
BEGIN NOW By the brim. END
BEGIN NOW But, although he'd hardly strike a END
BEGIN NOW Girl, would Dan, END
BEGIN NOW Yet he wears his wreckage like a END
BEGIN NOW Once -- no matter how the rest dressed -- END
BEGIN NOW Up or down -- END
BEGIN NOW Once, they say, he was the best-dressed END
BEGIN NOW Man in town. END
BEGIN NOW Must have been before I knew him -- END
BEGIN NOW Now you'd scarcely care to meet END
BEGIN NOW And be noticed talking to him END
BEGIN NOW In the street. END
BEGIN NOW Drink the cause, and dissipation, END
BEGIN NOW That is clear -- END
BEGIN NOW Maybe friend or kind relation END
BEGIN NOW Cause of beer. END
BEGIN NOW And the talking fool, who never END
BEGIN NOW Reads or thinks, END
BEGIN NOW Says, from hearsay: 'Yes, he's clever; END
BEGIN NOW But, you know, he drinks.' END
BEGIN NOW Been an actor and a writer -- END
BEGIN NOW Doesn't whine -- END
BEGIN NOW Reckoned now the best reciter END
BEGIN NOW In his line. END
BEGIN NOW Takes the stage at times, and fills it -- END
BEGIN NOW Raise a sneer! -- his first line kills it, END
BEGIN NOW Where he lives, or how, or wherefore END
BEGIN NOW No one knows; END
BEGIN NOW Lost his real friends, and therefore END
BEGIN NOW Lost his foes. END
BEGIN NOW Had, no doubt, his own romances -- END
BEGIN NOW Met his fate; END
BEGIN NOW Tortured, doubtless, by the chances END
BEGIN NOW And the luck that comes too late. END
BEGIN NOW Now and then his boots are polished, END
BEGIN NOW Collar clean, END
BEGIN NOW And the worst grease stains abolished END
BEGIN NOW By ammonia or benzine: END
BEGIN NOW Hints of some attempt to shove him END
BEGIN NOW From the taps, END
BEGIN NOW Or of someone left to love him -- END
BEGIN NOW After all, he is a grafter, END
BEGIN NOW Earns his cheer -- END
BEGIN NOW Keeps the room in roars of laughter END
BEGIN NOW When he gets outside a beer. END
BEGIN NOW Yarns that would fall flat from others END
BEGIN NOW He can tell; END
BEGIN NOW How he spent his 'stuff', my brothers, END
BEGIN NOW You know well. END
BEGIN NOW Manner puts a man in mind of END
BEGIN NOW Old club balls and evening dress, END
BEGIN NOW Ugly with a handsome kind of END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW One of those we say of often, END
BEGIN NOW While hearts swell, END
BEGIN NOW Standing sadly by the coffin: END
BEGIN NOW 'He looks well.' END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW We may be -- so goes a rumour -- END
BEGIN NOW But we may not have the humour END
BEGIN NOW Of the man; END
BEGIN NOW Nor the sight -- well, deem it blindness, END
BEGIN NOW As the general public do -- END
BEGIN NOW And the love of human kindness, END
BEGIN NOW Or the GRIT to see it through! END
BEGIN NOW If you fancy that your people came of better stock than mine, END
BEGIN NOW If you hint of higher breeding by a word or by a sign, END
BEGIN NOW If you're proud because of fortune or the clever things you do -- END
BEGIN NOW If you think that your profession has the more gentility, END
BEGIN NOW And that you are condescending to be seen along with me; END
BEGIN NOW If you have a swell companion when you see me on the street, END
BEGIN NOW And you think that I'm too common for your toney friend to meet, END
BEGIN NOW So that I, in passing closely, fail to come within your view -- END
BEGIN NOW Then be blind to me for ever: I'm a prouder man than you! END
BEGIN NOW If your character be blameless, if your outward past be clean, END
BEGIN NOW 'Birds o' feather fly together': I'm a prouder bird than you! END
BEGIN NOW Keep your patronage for others! Gold and station cannot hide END
BEGIN NOW And my wall of pride is shattered: I am not so proud as you! END
BEGIN NOW The creek went down with a broken song, END
BEGIN NOW 'Neath the sheoaks high; END
BEGIN NOW The waters carried the song along, END
BEGIN NOW And the oaks a sigh. END
BEGIN NOW The song and the sigh went winding by, END
BEGIN NOW Went winding down; END
BEGIN NOW Circling the foot of the mountain high, END
BEGIN NOW And the hillside brown. END
BEGIN NOW They were hushed in the swamp of the Dead Man's Crime, END
BEGIN NOW Where the curlews cried; END
BEGIN NOW But they reached the river the self-same time, END
BEGIN NOW And there they died. END
BEGIN NOW And the creek of life goes winding on, END
BEGIN NOW And bears for ever, its course upon, END
BEGIN NOW A song and a sigh. END
BEGIN NOW So you're writing for a paper? Well, it's nothing very new END
BEGIN NOW To be writing yards of drivel for a tidy little screw; END
BEGIN NOW You are young and educated, and a clever chap you are, END
BEGIN NOW But you'll never run a paper like the CAMBAROORA STAR. END
BEGIN NOW Though in point of education I am nothing but a dunce, END
BEGIN NOW I myself -- you mayn't believe it -- helped to run a paper once END
BEGIN NOW With a chap on Cambaroora, by the name of Charlie Brown, END
BEGIN NOW And I'll tell you all about it if you'll take the story down. END
BEGIN NOW On a golden day in summer, when the sunrays were aslant, END
BEGIN NOW Brown arrived in Cambaroora with a little printing plant END
BEGIN NOW He had bought an empty humpy, and, instead of getting tight, END
BEGIN NOW And next day a sign of canvas, writ in characters of tar, END
BEGIN NOW Claimed the humpy as the office of the CAMBAROORA STAR. END
BEGIN NOW Well, I cannot read, that's honest, but I had a digger friend END
BEGIN NOW Who would read the paper to me from the title to the end; END
BEGIN NOW Once I showed it to a critic, and he said 'twas very fine, END
BEGIN NOW Though he wasn't long in finding glaring faults in every line; END
BEGIN NOW But it was a song of Freedom -- all the clever critic said END
BEGIN NOW So I went where Brown was working in his little hut hard by: END
BEGIN NOW And your principles is honest, Brown; I want to shake your hand, END
BEGIN NOW And if there's any lumping in connection with the STAR, END
BEGIN NOW Brown was every inch a digger (bronzed and bearded in the South), END
BEGIN NOW So we worked a little 'paddock' on a place they called the 'Bar', END
BEGIN NOW Well, I didn't shirk my promise, and I helped the thing, I guess, END
BEGIN NOW For she died on Cambaroora when the STAR began to go, END
BEGIN NOW And was buried like the diggers buried diggers long ago. END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW Many nights we'd sit together in the windy hut and fold, END
BEGIN NOW And I helped the thing a little when I struck a patch of gold; END
BEGIN NOW And we battled for the diggers as the papers seldom do, END
BEGIN NOW Though when the diggers errored, why, we touched the diggers too. END
BEGIN NOW And the diggers sent a nugget with their sympathy to Brown. END
BEGIN NOW Oft I sat and smoked beside him in the listening hours of night, END
BEGIN NOW Diggers then had little mercy for the loafer and the scamp -- END
BEGIN NOW If there wasn't law and order, there was justice in the camp; END
BEGIN NOW And the manly independence that is found where diggers are END
BEGIN NOW Had a sentinel to guard it in the CAMBAROORA STAR. END
BEGIN NOW And who only shepherd diggers till they track them to the 'find'. END
BEGIN NOW Charlie wrote a slinging leader, calling on his digger mates, END
BEGIN NOW It was nine o'clock next morning when the Chows began to swarm, END
BEGIN NOW Give three ringing cheers, my hearties, for the CAMBAROORA STAR.' END
BEGIN NOW But the Cambaroora petered, and the diggers' sun went down, END
BEGIN NOW And another sort of people came and settled in the town; END
BEGIN NOW The reefing was conducted by a syndicate or two, END
BEGIN NOW But his leaders went like thunder for their vested interests, END
BEGIN NOW And he fought for right and justice and he raved about the dawn END
BEGIN NOW Of the reign of Man and Reason till his ads. were all withdrawn. END
BEGIN NOW He was offered shares for nothing in the richest of the mines, END
BEGIN NOW And he could have made a fortune had he run on other lines; END
BEGIN NOW They abused him for his leaders, and they parodied his rhymes, END
BEGIN NOW And they told him that his paper was a mile behind the times. END
BEGIN NOW So we fought the battle bravely, and we did our very best END
BEGIN NOW Just to make the final issue quite as lively as the rest. END
BEGIN NOW And the swells in Cambaroora talked of feathers and of tar END
BEGIN NOW When they read the final issue of the CAMBAROORA STAR. END
BEGIN NOW But in vain we scraped together every penny we could get, END
BEGIN NOW Though we gave him ads. for nothing when the STAR began to boom: END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas a paltry bill for tucker, and the crawling, sneaking clown END
BEGIN NOW Sold the debt for twice its value to the men who hated Brown. END
BEGIN NOW I was digging up the river, and I swam the flooded bend END
BEGIN NOW With a little cash and comfort for my literary friend. END
BEGIN NOW Brown was sitting sad and lonely with his head bowed in despair, END
BEGIN NOW While a single tallow candle threw a flicker on his hair, END
BEGIN NOW And the gusty wind that whistled through the crannies of the door END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW Then he stood up on a sudden, with a face as pale as death, END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW Listen! Like the distant thunder of the rollers on the bar -- END
BEGIN NOW though it died when the sun went down; END
BEGIN NOW The river is high and the stream is strong, END
BEGIN NOW and the grass is green and tall, END
BEGIN NOW Let our enemies go by their old dull tracks, END
BEGIN NOW and theirs be the fault or shame END
BEGIN NOW It well may be that I saw too plain, and it may be I was blind; END
BEGIN NOW But I'll keep my face to the dawning light, END
BEGIN NOW though the devil may stand behind! END
BEGIN NOW Marshall's Mate END
BEGIN NOW You almost heard the surface bake, and saw the gum-leaves turn -- END
BEGIN NOW The tanks went dry on Ninety Mile, as tanks go dry out back, END
BEGIN NOW Too blind to see there was no shade, and too done-up to feel. END
BEGIN NOW And charcoaled on the canvas bag ('twas written pretty clear) END
BEGIN NOW 'Spread out as widely as you can each side the track,' said he; END
BEGIN NOW 'The first to find him make a smoke that all the rest can see.' END
BEGIN NOW We took the track and followed back where Crowbar followed fate, END
BEGIN NOW We found a dead man in the scrub -- but 'twas not Crowbar's mate. END
BEGIN NOW And no one, save the spirit of the sand-waste, fierce and lone, END
BEGIN NOW He'd scarcely closed his quiet eyes or drawn a sleeping breath -- END
BEGIN NOW A careless, roving scamp, that loved to laugh and drink and joke, END
BEGIN NOW The search was made as searches are (and often made in vain), END
BEGIN NOW And on the seventh day we saw a smoke across the plain; END
BEGIN NOW And when we gave it best at last, he said, 'I'LL see it through,' END
BEGIN NOW I'll see it so in twenty years, 'twill haunt me all my life -- END
BEGIN NOW I could not face his sister, and I could not face his wife. END
BEGIN NOW It's no use talking to me now -- I'm going back,' he said, END
BEGIN NOW 'I'm going back to find him, and I will -- alive or dead!' END
BEGIN NOW . . . . . END
BEGIN NOW He packed his horse with water and provisions for a week, END
BEGIN NOW And then, at sunset, crossed the plain, away from Dingo Creek. END
BEGIN NOW We watched him tramp beside the horse till we, as it grew late, END
BEGIN NOW Could not tell which was Bonypart and which was Marshall's mate. END
BEGIN NOW The dam went dry at Dingo Creek, and we were driven back, END
BEGIN NOW And none dared face the Ninety Mile when Crowbar took the track. END
BEGIN NOW They saw him at Dead Camel and along the Dry Hole Creeks -- END
BEGIN NOW But no one knew how Crowbar died -- the soul of Marshall knows! END
BEGIN NOW And now, way out on Dingo Creek, when winter days are late, END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the furthest two-rail fence, Colanne and Nevertire -- END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the furthest rabbit-proof, barbed wire and common wire -- END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the Land o' Break-o'-Day, and Sunset and the Dawn, END
BEGIN NOW The soul of Marshall and the soul of Marshall's mate have gone END
BEGIN NOW Unto that Loving, Laughing Land where life is fresh and clean -- END
BEGIN NOW Where the rivers flow all summer, and the grass is always green. END
BEGIN NOW The world has had enough of bards who wish that they were dead, END
BEGIN NOW 'Tis time the people passed a law to knock 'em on the head, END
BEGIN NOW They talk of peace and restfulness connected with the tomb. END
BEGIN NOW They say that man is made of dirt, and die, of course, he must; END
BEGIN NOW But, all the same, a man is made of pretty solid dust. END
BEGIN NOW There is a thing that they forget, so let it here be writ, END
BEGIN NOW That some are made of common mud, and some are made of GRIT; END
BEGIN NOW Some try to help the world along while others fret and fume END
BEGIN NOW And wish that they were slumbering in the silence of the tomb. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twixt mother's arms and coffin-gear a man has work to do! END
BEGIN NOW And if he does his very best he mostly worries through, END
BEGIN NOW And yet, as long as sheoaks sigh and wattle-blossoms bloom, END
BEGIN NOW The world shall hear the drivel of the poets of the tomb. END
BEGIN NOW And though the graveyard poets long to vanish from the scene, END
BEGIN NOW I notice that they mostly wish their resting-place kept green. END
BEGIN NOW Now, were I rotting underground, I do not think I'd care END
BEGIN NOW If wombats rooted on the mound or if the cows camped there; END
BEGIN NOW And should I have some feelings left when I have gone before, END
BEGIN NOW I think a ton of solid stone would hurt my feelings more. END
BEGIN NOW Such wormy songs of mouldy joys can give me no delight; END
BEGIN NOW I'll take my chances with the world, I'd rather live and fight. END
BEGIN NOW While you use your best endeavour to immortalise in verse END
BEGIN NOW You're a clever southern writer, scarce inferior to Bret Harte. END
BEGIN NOW If you sing of waving grasses when the plains are dry as bricks, END
BEGIN NOW And discover shining rivers where there's only mud and sticks; END
BEGIN NOW You are gracefully referred to as the 'young Australian Burns'. END
BEGIN NOW Your grammar's simply awful and your intellect is weak. END
BEGIN NOW Down the street as I was drifting with the city's human tide, END
BEGIN NOW Came a ghost, and for a moment walked in silence by my side -- END
BEGIN NOW Now my heart was hard and bitter, and a bitter spirit he, END
BEGIN NOW So I felt no great aversion to his ghostly company. END
BEGIN NOW When he'll gladly fly for succour to the bosom of the foe. END
BEGIN NOW 'Where Society is mighty, always truckle to her rule; END
BEGIN NOW Never send an 'i' undotted to the teacher of a school; END
BEGIN NOW Only fight a wrong or falsehood when the crowd is at your back, END
BEGIN NOW And, till Charity repay you, shut the purse, and let her pack; END
BEGIN NOW At the fools who would do other let your lip in scorn be curled, END
BEGIN NOW 'Ne'er assail the shaky ladders Fame has from her niches hung, END
BEGIN NOW Lest unfriendly heels above you grind your fingers from the rung; END
BEGIN NOW And the banter of the critic hurts his heart till it grows hard. END
BEGIN NOW At the fame your muse may offer let your lip in scorn be curled, END
BEGIN NOW Then he ceased and looked intently in my face, and nearer drew; END
BEGIN NOW But a sudden deep repugnance to his presence thrilled me through; END
BEGIN NOW Then I felt his breath was poison, by the shuddering of my soul, END
BEGIN NOW Then I guessed his purpose evil, by his lip in sneering curled, END
BEGIN NOW And I knew he slandered mankind, by my knowledge of the world. END
BEGIN NOW But he vanished as a purer brighter presence gained my side -- END
BEGIN NOW 'Heed him not! there's truth and friendship END
BEGIN NOW in this wondrous world,' she cried, END
BEGIN NOW And of those who cleave to virtue in their climbing for renown, END
BEGIN NOW Only they who faint or falter from the height are shaken down. END
BEGIN NOW At a cynic's baneful teaching let your lip in scorn be curled! END
BEGIN NOW 'Brotherhood and Love and Honour!' is the motto for the world.' END
