BEGIN NOW Joe Wilson's Mates Winnowed Verses END
BEGIN NOW in any distinctive sense. END
BEGIN NOW Arms, and the man I sing, who, forc'd by fate, END
BEGIN NOW And haughty Juno's unrelenting hate, END
BEGIN NOW Expell'd and exil'd, left the Trojan shore. END
BEGIN NOW Long labors, both by sea and land, he bore, END
BEGIN NOW And in the doubtful war, before he won END
BEGIN NOW The Latian realm, and built the destin'd town; END
BEGIN NOW His banish'd gods restor'd to rites divine, END
BEGIN NOW And settled sure succession in his line, END
BEGIN NOW From whence the race of Alban fathers come, END
BEGIN NOW And the long glories of majestic Rome. END
BEGIN NOW O Muse! the causes and the crimes relate; END
BEGIN NOW What goddess was provok'd, and whence her hate; END
BEGIN NOW For what offense the Queen of Heav'n began END
BEGIN NOW To persecute so brave, so just a man; END
BEGIN NOW Involv'd his anxious life in endless cares, END
BEGIN NOW Expos'd to wants, and hurried into wars! END
BEGIN NOW Can heav'nly minds such high resentment show, END
BEGIN NOW Or exercise their spite in human woe? END
BEGIN NOW Against the Tiber's mouth, but far away, END
BEGIN NOW An ancient town was seated on the sea; END
BEGIN NOW A Tyrian colony; the people made END
BEGIN NOW Stout for the war, and studious of their trade: END
BEGIN NOW Carthage the name; belov'd by Juno more END
BEGIN NOW Than her own Argos, or the Samian shore. END
BEGIN NOW Here stood her chariot; here, if Heav'n were kind, END
BEGIN NOW The seat of awful empire she design'd. END
BEGIN NOW Yet she had heard an ancient rumor fly, END
BEGIN NOW (Long cited by the people of the sky,) END
BEGIN NOW That times to come should see the Trojan race END
BEGIN NOW Her Carthage ruin, and her tow'rs deface; END
BEGIN NOW Nor thus confin'd, the yoke of sov'reign sway END
BEGIN NOW Should on the necks of all the nations lay. END
BEGIN NOW She ponder'd this, and fear'd it was in fate; END
BEGIN NOW Nor could forget the war she wag'd of late END
BEGIN NOW For conqu'ring Greece against the Trojan state. END
BEGIN NOW Besides, long causes working in her mind, END
BEGIN NOW And secret seeds of envy, lay behind; END
BEGIN NOW Deep graven in her heart the doom remain'd END
BEGIN NOW Of partial Paris, and her form disdain'd; END
BEGIN NOW The grace bestow'd on ravish'd Ganymed, END
BEGIN NOW Electra's glories, and her injur'd bed. END
BEGIN NOW Each was a cause alone; and all combin'd END
BEGIN NOW To kindle vengeance in her haughty mind. END
BEGIN NOW For this, far distant from the Latian coast END
BEGIN NOW She drove the remnants of the Trojan host; END
BEGIN NOW And sev'n long years th' unhappy wand'ring train END
BEGIN NOW Were toss'd by storms, and scatter'd thro' the main. END
BEGIN NOW Such time, such toil, requir'd the Roman name, END
BEGIN NOW Such length of labor for so vast a frame. END
BEGIN NOW Now scarce the Trojan fleet, with sails and oars, END
BEGIN NOW Had left behind the fair Sicilian shores, END
BEGIN NOW Ent'ring with cheerful shouts the wat'ry reign, END
BEGIN NOW And plowing frothy furrows in the main; END
BEGIN NOW When, lab'ring still with endless discontent, END
BEGIN NOW The Queen of Heav'n did thus her fury vent: END
BEGIN NOW Then am I vanquish'd? must I yield?" said she, END
BEGIN NOW And must the Trojans reign in Italy? END
BEGIN NOW So Fate will have it, and Jove adds his force; END
BEGIN NOW Nor can my pow'r divert their happy course. END
BEGIN NOW Could angry Pallas, with revengeful spleen, END
BEGIN NOW The Grecian navy burn, and drown the men? END
BEGIN NOW She, for the fault of one offending foe, END
BEGIN NOW The bolts of Jove himself presum'd to throw: END
BEGIN NOW With whirlwinds from beneath she toss'd the ship, END
BEGIN NOW And bare expos'd the bosom of the deep; END
BEGIN NOW Then, as an eagle gripes the trembling game, END
BEGIN NOW The wretch, yet hissing with her father's flame, END
BEGIN NOW She strongly seiz'd, and with a burning wound END
BEGIN NOW Transfix'd, and naked, on a rock she bound. END
BEGIN NOW But I, who walk in awful state above, END
BEGIN NOW The majesty of heav'n, the sister wife of Jove, END
BEGIN NOW For length of years my fruitless force employ END
BEGIN NOW Against the thin remains of ruin'd Troy! END
BEGIN NOW What nations now to Juno's pow'r will pray, END
BEGIN NOW Or off'rings on my slighted altars lay? END
BEGIN NOW Thus rag'd the goddess; and, with fury fraught. END
BEGIN NOW The restless regions of the storms she sought, END
BEGIN NOW Where, in a spacious cave of living stone, END
BEGIN NOW The tyrant Aeolus, from his airy throne, END
BEGIN NOW With pow'r imperial curbs the struggling winds, END
BEGIN NOW And sounding tempests in dark prisons binds. END
BEGIN NOW This way and that th' impatient captives tend, END
BEGIN NOW And, pressing for release, the mountains rend. END
BEGIN NOW High in his hall th' undaunted monarch stands, END
BEGIN NOW And shakes his scepter, and their rage commands; END
BEGIN NOW Which did he not, their unresisted sway END
BEGIN NOW Would sweep the world before them in their way; END
BEGIN NOW Earth, air, and seas thro' empty space would roll, END
BEGIN NOW And heav'n would fly before the driving soul. END
BEGIN NOW In fear of this, the Father of the Gods END
BEGIN NOW Confin'd their fury to those dark abodes, END
BEGIN NOW And lock'd 'em safe within, oppress'd with mountain loads; END
BEGIN NOW Impos'd a king, with arbitrary sway, END
BEGIN NOW To loose their fetters, or their force allay. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the suppliant queen her pray'rs address'd, END
BEGIN NOW And thus the tenor of her suit express'd: END
BEGIN NOW O Aeolus! for to thee the King of Heav'n END
BEGIN NOW The pow'r of tempests and of winds has giv'n; END
BEGIN NOW Thy force alone their fury can restrain, END
BEGIN NOW And smooth the waves, or swell the troubled main- END
BEGIN NOW A race of wand'ring slaves, abhorr'd by me, END
BEGIN NOW With prosp'rous passage cut the Tuscan sea; END
BEGIN NOW To fruitful Italy their course they steer, END
BEGIN NOW And for their vanquish'd gods design new temples there. END
BEGIN NOW Raise all thy winds; with night involve the skies; END
BEGIN NOW Sink or disperse my fatal enemies. END
BEGIN NOW Twice sev'n, the charming daughters of the main, END
BEGIN NOW Around my person wait, and bear my train: END
BEGIN NOW Succeed my wish, and second my design; END
BEGIN NOW The fairest, Deiopeia, shall be thine, END
BEGIN NOW And make thee father of a happy line. END
BEGIN NOW To this the god: "'T is yours, O queen, to will END
BEGIN NOW The work which duty binds me to fulfil. END
BEGIN NOW These airy kingdoms, and this wide command, END
BEGIN NOW Are all the presents of your bounteous hand: END
BEGIN NOW Yours is my sov'reign's grace; and, as your guest, END
BEGIN NOW I sit with gods at their celestial feast; END
BEGIN NOW Raise tempests at your pleasure, or subdue; END
BEGIN NOW Dispose of empire, which I hold from you. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and hurl'd against the mountain side END
BEGIN NOW His quiv'ring spear, and all the god applied. END
BEGIN NOW The raging winds rush thro' the hollow wound, END
BEGIN NOW And dance aloft in air, and skim along the ground; END
BEGIN NOW Then, settling on the sea, the surges sweep, END
BEGIN NOW Raise liquid mountains, and disclose the deep. END
BEGIN NOW South, East, and West with mix'd confusion roar, END
BEGIN NOW And roll the foaming billows to the shore. END
BEGIN NOW The cables crack; the sailors' fearful cries END
BEGIN NOW Ascend; and sable night involves the skies; END
BEGIN NOW And heav'n itself is ravish'd from their eyes. END
BEGIN NOW Loud peals of thunder from the poles ensue; END
BEGIN NOW Then flashing fires the transient light renew; END
BEGIN NOW The face of things a frightful image bears, END
BEGIN NOW And present death in various forms appears. END
BEGIN NOW Struck with unusual fright, the Trojan chief, END
BEGIN NOW With lifted hands and eyes, invokes relief; END
BEGIN NOW And, "Thrice and four times happy those," he cried, END
BEGIN NOW That under Ilian walls before their parents died! END
BEGIN NOW Tydides, bravest of the Grecian train! END
BEGIN NOW Why could not I by that strong arm be slain, END
BEGIN NOW And lie by noble Hector on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Or great Sarpedon, in those bloody fields END
BEGIN NOW Where Simois rolls the bodies and the shields END
BEGIN NOW Of heroes, whose dismember'd hands yet bear END
BEGIN NOW The dart aloft, and clench the pointed spear! END
BEGIN NOW Thus while the pious prince his fate bewails, END
BEGIN NOW Fierce Boreas drove against his flying sails, END
BEGIN NOW And rent the sheets; the raging billows rise, END
BEGIN NOW And mount the tossing vessels to the skies: END
BEGIN NOW Nor can the shiv'ring oars sustain the blow; END
BEGIN NOW The galley gives her side, and turns her prow; END
BEGIN NOW While those astern, descending down the steep, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' gaping waves behold the boiling deep. END
BEGIN NOW Three ships were hurried by the southern blast, END
BEGIN NOW And on the secret shelves with fury cast. END
BEGIN NOW Those hidden rocks th' Ausonian sailors knew: END
BEGIN NOW They call'd them Altars, when they rose in view, END
BEGIN NOW And show'd their spacious backs above the flood. END
BEGIN NOW Three more fierce Eurus, in his angry mood, END
BEGIN NOW Dash'd on the shallows of the moving sand, END
BEGIN NOW And in mid ocean left them moor'd aland. END
BEGIN NOW Orontes' bark, that bore the Lycian crew, END
BEGIN NOW (A horrid sight!) ev'n in the hero's view, END
BEGIN NOW From stem to stern by waves was overborne: END
BEGIN NOW The trembling pilot, from his rudder torn, END
BEGIN NOW Was headlong hurl'd; thrice round the ship was toss'd, END
BEGIN NOW Then bulg'd at once, and in the deep was lost; END
BEGIN NOW And here and there above the waves were seen END
BEGIN NOW Arms, pictures, precious goods, and floating men. END
BEGIN NOW The stoutest vessel to the storm gave way, END
BEGIN NOW And suck'd thro' loosen'd planks the rushing sea. END
BEGIN NOW Ilioneus was her chief: Alethes old, END
BEGIN NOW Achates faithful, Abas young and bold, END
BEGIN NOW Endur'd not less; their ships, with gaping seams, END
BEGIN NOW Admit the deluge of the briny streams. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime imperial Neptune heard the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of raging billows breaking on the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Displeas'd, and fearing for his wat'ry reign, END
BEGIN NOW He rear'd his awful head above the main, END
BEGIN NOW Serene in majesty; then roll'd his eyes END
BEGIN NOW Around the space of earth, and seas, and skies. END
BEGIN NOW He saw the Trojan fleet dispers'd, distress'd, END
BEGIN NOW By stormy winds and wintry heav'n oppress'd. END
BEGIN NOW Full well the god his sister's envy knew, END
BEGIN NOW And what her aims and what her arts pursue. END
BEGIN NOW He summon'd Eurus and the western blast, END
BEGIN NOW And first an angry glance on both he cast; END
BEGIN NOW Then thus rebuk'd: "Audacious winds! from whence END
BEGIN NOW This bold attempt, this rebel insolence? END
BEGIN NOW Is it for you to ravage seas and land, END
BEGIN NOW Unauthoriz'd by my supreme command? END
BEGIN NOW To raise such mountains on the troubled main? END
BEGIN NOW Whom I- but first 't is fit the billows to restrain; END
BEGIN NOW And then you shall be taught obedience to my reign. END
BEGIN NOW Hence! to your lord my royal mandate bear- END
BEGIN NOW The realms of ocean and the fields of air END
BEGIN NOW Are mine, not his. By fatal lot to me END
BEGIN NOW The liquid empire fell, and trident of the sea. END
BEGIN NOW His pow'r to hollow caverns is confin'd: END
BEGIN NOW There let him reign, the jailer of the wind, END
BEGIN NOW With hoarse commands his breathing subjects call, END
BEGIN NOW And boast and bluster in his empty hall. END
BEGIN NOW He spoke; and, while he spoke, he smooth'd the sea, END
BEGIN NOW Dispell'd the darkness, and restor'd the day. END
BEGIN NOW Cymothoe, Triton, and the sea-green train END
BEGIN NOW Of beauteous nymphs, the daughters of the main, END
BEGIN NOW Clear from the rocks the vessels with their hands: END
BEGIN NOW The god himself with ready trident stands, END
BEGIN NOW And opes the deep, and spreads the moving sands; END
BEGIN NOW Then heaves them off the shoals. Where'er he guides END
BEGIN NOW His finny coursers and in triumph rides, END
BEGIN NOW The waves unruffle and the sea subsides. END
BEGIN NOW As, when in tumults rise th' ignoble crowd, END
BEGIN NOW Mad are their motions, and their tongues are loud; END
BEGIN NOW And stones and brands in rattling volleys fly, END
BEGIN NOW And all the rustic arms that fury can supply: END
BEGIN NOW If then some grave and pious man appear, END
BEGIN NOW They hush their noise, and lend a list'ning ear; END
BEGIN NOW He soothes with sober words their angry mood, END
BEGIN NOW And quenches their innate desire of blood: END
BEGIN NOW So, when the Father of the Flood appears, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er the seas his sov'reign trident rears, END
BEGIN NOW Their fury falls: he skims the liquid plains, END
BEGIN NOW High on his chariot, and, with loosen'd reins, END
BEGIN NOW Majestic moves along, and awful peace maintains. END
BEGIN NOW The weary Trojans ply their shatter'd oars END
BEGIN NOW To nearest land, and make the Libyan shores. END
BEGIN NOW Within a long recess there lies a bay: END
BEGIN NOW An island shades it from the rolling sea, END
BEGIN NOW And forms a port secure for ships to ride; END
BEGIN NOW Broke by the jutting land, on either side, END
BEGIN NOW In double streams the briny waters glide. END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt two rows of rocks a sylvan scene END
BEGIN NOW Appears above, and groves for ever green: END
BEGIN NOW A grot is form'd beneath, with mossy seats, END
BEGIN NOW To rest the Nereids, and exclude the heats. END
BEGIN NOW Down thro' the crannies of the living walls END
BEGIN NOW The crystal streams descend in murm'ring falls: END
BEGIN NOW No haulsers need to bind the vessels here, END
BEGIN NOW Nor bearded anchors; for no storms they fear. END
BEGIN NOW Sev'n ships within this happy harbor meet, END
BEGIN NOW The thin remainders of the scatter'd fleet. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans, worn with toils, and spent with woes, END
BEGIN NOW Leap on the welcome land, and seek their wish'd repose. END
BEGIN NOW First, good Achates, with repeated strokes END
BEGIN NOW Of clashing flints, their hidden fire provokes: END
BEGIN NOW Short flame succeeds; a bed of wither'd leaves END
BEGIN NOW The dying sparkles in their fall receives: END
BEGIN NOW Caught into life, in fiery fumes they rise, END
BEGIN NOW And, fed with stronger food, invade the skies. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans, dropping wet, or stand around END
BEGIN NOW The cheerful blaze, or lie along the ground: END
BEGIN NOW Some dry their corn, infected with the brine, END
BEGIN NOW Then grind with marbles, and prepare to dine. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas climbs the mountain's airy brow, END
BEGIN NOW And takes a prospect of the seas below, END
BEGIN NOW If Capys thence, or Antheus he could spy, END
BEGIN NOW Or see the streamers of Caicus fly. END
BEGIN NOW No vessels were in view; but, on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Three beamy stags command a lordly train END
BEGIN NOW Of branching heads: the more ignoble throng END
BEGIN NOW Attend their stately steps, and slowly graze along. END
BEGIN NOW He stood; and, while secure they fed below, END
BEGIN NOW He took the quiver and the trusty bow END
BEGIN NOW Achates us'd to bear: the leaders first END
BEGIN NOW He laid along, and then the vulgar pierc'd; END
BEGIN NOW Nor ceas'd his arrows, till the shady plain END
BEGIN NOW Sev'n mighty bodies with their blood distain. END
BEGIN NOW For the sev'n ships he made an equal share, END
BEGIN NOW And to the port return'd, triumphant from the war. END
BEGIN NOW The jars of gen'rous wine (Acestes' gift, END
BEGIN NOW When his Trinacrian shores the navy left) END
BEGIN NOW He set abroach, and for the feast prepar'd, END
BEGIN NOW In equal portions with the ven'son shar'd. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while he dealt it round, the pious chief END
BEGIN NOW With cheerful words allay'd the common grief: END
BEGIN NOW Endure, and conquer! Jove will soon dispose END
BEGIN NOW To future good our past and present woes. END
BEGIN NOW With me, the rocks of Scylla you have tried; END
BEGIN NOW Th' inhuman Cyclops and his den defied. END
BEGIN NOW What greater ills hereafter can you bear? END
BEGIN NOW Resume your courage and dismiss your care, END
BEGIN NOW An hour will come, with pleasure to relate END
BEGIN NOW Your sorrows past, as benefits of Fate. END
BEGIN NOW Thro' various hazards and events, we move END
BEGIN NOW To Latium and the realms foredoom'd by Jove. END
BEGIN NOW Call'd to the seat (the promise of the skies) END
BEGIN NOW Where Trojan kingdoms once again may rise, END
BEGIN NOW Endure the hardships of your present state; END
BEGIN NOW Live, and reserve yourselves for better fate. END
BEGIN NOW These words he spoke, but spoke not from his heart; END
BEGIN NOW His outward smiles conceal'd his inward smart. END
BEGIN NOW The jolly crew, unmindful of the past, END
BEGIN NOW The quarry share, their plenteous dinner haste. END
BEGIN NOW Some strip the skin; some portion out the spoil; END
BEGIN NOW The limbs, yet trembling, in the caldrons boil; END
BEGIN NOW Some on the fire the reeking entrails broil. END
BEGIN NOW Stretch'd on the grassy turf, at ease they dine, END
BEGIN NOW Restore their strength with meat, and cheer their souls with END
BEGIN NOW wine. END
BEGIN NOW Their hunger thus appeas'd, their care attends END
BEGIN NOW The doubtful fortune of their absent friends: END
BEGIN NOW Alternate hopes and fears their minds possess, END
BEGIN NOW Whether to deem 'em dead, or in distress. END
BEGIN NOW Above the rest, Aeneas mourns the fate END
BEGIN NOW Of brave Orontes, and th' uncertain state END
BEGIN NOW The day, but not their sorrows, ended thus. END
BEGIN NOW When, from aloft, almighty Jove surveys END
BEGIN NOW Earth, air, and shores, and navigable seas, END
BEGIN NOW At length on Libyan realms he fix'd his eyes- END
BEGIN NOW Whom, pond'ring thus on human miseries, END
BEGIN NOW When Venus saw, she with a lowly look, END
BEGIN NOW Not free from tears, her heav'nly sire bespoke: END
BEGIN NOW O King of Gods and Men! whose awful hand END
BEGIN NOW Disperses thunder on the seas and land, END
BEGIN NOW Disposing all with absolute command; END
BEGIN NOW How could my pious son thy pow'r incense? END
BEGIN NOW Or what, alas! is vanish'd Troy's offense? END
BEGIN NOW Our hope of Italy not only lost, END
BEGIN NOW On various seas by various tempests toss'd, END
BEGIN NOW But shut from ev'ry shore, and barr'd from ev'ry coast. END
BEGIN NOW You promis'd once, a progeny divine END
BEGIN NOW Of Romans, rising from the Trojan line, END
BEGIN NOW In after times should hold the world in awe, END
BEGIN NOW And to the land and ocean give the law. END
BEGIN NOW How is your doom revers'd, which eas'd my care END
BEGIN NOW When Troy was ruin'd in that cruel war? END
BEGIN NOW Then fates to fates I could oppose; but now, END
BEGIN NOW When Fortune still pursues her former blow, END
BEGIN NOW What can I hope? What worse can still succeed? END
BEGIN NOW What end of labors has your will decreed? END
BEGIN NOW Antenor, from the midst of Grecian hosts, END
BEGIN NOW Could pass secure, and pierce th' Illyrian coasts, END
BEGIN NOW Where, rolling down the steep, Timavus raves END
BEGIN NOW And thro' nine channels disembogues his waves. END
BEGIN NOW At length he founded Padua's happy seat, END
BEGIN NOW And gave his Trojans a secure retreat; END
BEGIN NOW There fix'd their arms, and there renew'd their name, END
BEGIN NOW And there in quiet rules, and crown'd with fame. END
BEGIN NOW But we, descended from your sacred line, END
BEGIN NOW Entitled to your heav'n and rites divine, END
BEGIN NOW Are banish'd earth; and, for the wrath of one, END
BEGIN NOW Remov'd from Latium and the promis'd throne. END
BEGIN NOW Are these our scepters? these our due rewards? END
BEGIN NOW And is it thus that Jove his plighted faith regards? END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Father of th' immortal race, END
BEGIN NOW Smiling with that serene indulgent face, END
BEGIN NOW With which he drives the clouds and clears the skies, END
BEGIN NOW First gave a holy kiss; then thus replies: END
BEGIN NOW Daughter, dismiss thy fears; to thy desire END
BEGIN NOW The fates of thine are fix'd, and stand entire. END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt behold thy wish'd Lavinian walls; END
BEGIN NOW And, ripe for heav'n, when fate Aeneas calls, END
BEGIN NOW Then shalt thou bear him up, sublime, to me: END
BEGIN NOW No councils have revers'd my firm decree. END
BEGIN NOW And, lest new fears disturb thy happy state, END
BEGIN NOW Know, I have search'd the mystic rolls of Fate: END
BEGIN NOW Thy son (nor is th' appointed season far) END
BEGIN NOW In Italy shall wage successful war, END
BEGIN NOW Shall tame fierce nations in the bloody field, END
BEGIN NOW And sov'reign laws impose, and cities build, END
BEGIN NOW Till, after ev'ry foe subdued, the sun END
BEGIN NOW Thrice thro' the signs his annual race shall run: END
BEGIN NOW This is his time prefix'd. Ascanius then, END
BEGIN NOW Now call'd Iulus, shall begin his reign. END
BEGIN NOW He thirty rolling years the crown shall wear, END
BEGIN NOW Then from Lavinium shall the seat transfer, END
BEGIN NOW And, with hard labor, Alba Longa build. END
BEGIN NOW The throne with his succession shall be fill'd END
BEGIN NOW Three hundred circuits more: then shall be seen END
BEGIN NOW Ilia the fair, a priestess and a queen, END
BEGIN NOW Who, full of Mars, in time, with kindly throes, END
BEGIN NOW Shall at a birth two goodly boys disclose. END
BEGIN NOW The royal babes a tawny wolf shall drain: END
BEGIN NOW Then Romulus his grandsire's throne shall gain, END
BEGIN NOW Of martial tow'rs the founder shall become, END
BEGIN NOW The people Romans call, the city Rome. END
BEGIN NOW To them no bounds of empire I assign, END
BEGIN NOW Nor term of years to their immortal line. END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n haughty Juno, who, with endless broils, END
BEGIN NOW Earth, seas, and heav'n, and Jove himself turmoils; END
BEGIN NOW At length aton'd, her friendly pow'r shall join, END
BEGIN NOW To cherish and advance the Trojan line. END
BEGIN NOW The subject world shall Rome's dominion own, END
BEGIN NOW And, prostrate, shall adore the nation of the gown. END
BEGIN NOW An age is ripening in revolving fate END
BEGIN NOW When Troy shall overturn the Grecian state, END
BEGIN NOW And sweet revenge her conqu'ring sons shall call, END
BEGIN NOW To crush the people that conspir'd her fall. END
BEGIN NOW Then Caesar from the Julian stock shall rise, END
BEGIN NOW Whose empire ocean, and whose fame the skies END
BEGIN NOW Alone shall bound; whom, fraught with eastern spoils, END
BEGIN NOW Our heav'n, the just reward of human toils, END
BEGIN NOW Securely shall repay with rites divine; END
BEGIN NOW And incense shall ascend before his sacred shrine. END
BEGIN NOW Then dire debate and impious war shall cease, END
BEGIN NOW And the stern age be soften'd into peace: END
BEGIN NOW Then banish'd Faith shall once again return, END
BEGIN NOW And Vestal fires in hallow'd temples burn; END
BEGIN NOW And Remus with Quirinus shall sustain END
BEGIN NOW The righteous laws, and fraud and force restrain. END
BEGIN NOW Janus himself before his fane shall wait, END
BEGIN NOW And keep the dreadful issues of his gate, END
BEGIN NOW With bolts and iron bars: within remains END
BEGIN NOW Imprison'd Fury, bound in brazen chains; END
BEGIN NOW High on a trophy rais'd, of useless arms, END
BEGIN NOW He sits, and threats the world with vain alarms. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and sent Cyllenius with command END
BEGIN NOW To free the ports, and ope the Punic land END
BEGIN NOW To Trojan guests; lest, ignorant of fate, END
BEGIN NOW The queen might force them from her town and state. END
BEGIN NOW Down from the steep of heav'n Cyllenius flies, END
BEGIN NOW And cleaves with all his wings the yielding skies. END
BEGIN NOW Soon on the Libyan shore descends the god, END
BEGIN NOW Performs his message, and displays his rod: END
BEGIN NOW The surly murmurs of the people cease; END
BEGIN NOW And, as the fates requir'd, they give the peace: END
BEGIN NOW The queen herself suspends the rigid laws, END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans pities, and protects their cause. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime, in shades of night Aeneas lies: END
BEGIN NOW Care seiz'd his soul, and sleep forsook his eyes. END
BEGIN NOW But, when the sun restor'd the cheerful day, END
BEGIN NOW He rose, the coast and country to survey, END
BEGIN NOW Anxious and eager to discover more. END
BEGIN NOW It look'd a wild uncultivated shore; END
BEGIN NOW But, whether humankind, or beasts alone END
BEGIN NOW Possess'd the new-found region, was unknown. END
BEGIN NOW Beneath a ledge of rocks his fleet he hides: END
BEGIN NOW Tall trees surround the mountain's shady sides; END
BEGIN NOW The bending brow above a safe retreat provides. END
BEGIN NOW Arm'd with two pointed darts, he leaves his friends, END
BEGIN NOW And true Achates on his steps attends. END
BEGIN NOW Lo! in the deep recesses of the wood, END
BEGIN NOW Before his eyes his goddess mother stood: END
BEGIN NOW A huntress in her habit and her mien; END
BEGIN NOW Her dress a maid, her air confess'd a queen. END
BEGIN NOW Bare were her knees, and knots her garments bind; END
BEGIN NOW Loose was her hair, and wanton'd in the wind; END
BEGIN NOW Her hand sustain'd a bow; her quiver hung behind. END
BEGIN NOW She seem'd a virgin of the Spartan blood: END
BEGIN NOW With such array Harpalyce bestrode END
BEGIN NOW Her Thracian courser and outstripp'd the rapid flood. END
BEGIN NOW Ho, strangers! have you lately seen," she said, END
BEGIN NOW One of my sisters, like myself array'd, END
BEGIN NOW Who cross'd the lawn, or in the forest stray'd? END
BEGIN NOW A painted quiver at her back she bore; END
BEGIN NOW Varied with spots, a lynx's hide she wore; END
BEGIN NOW And at full cry pursued the tusky boar. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Venus: thus her son replied again: END
BEGIN NOW None of your sisters have we heard or seen, END
BEGIN NOW O virgin! or what other name you bear END
BEGIN NOW Above that style- O more than mortal fair! END
BEGIN NOW Your voice and mien celestial birth betray! END
BEGIN NOW If, as you seem, the sister of the day, END
BEGIN NOW Or one at least of chaste Diana's train, END
BEGIN NOW Let not an humble suppliant sue in vain; END
BEGIN NOW But tell a stranger, long in tempests toss'd, END
BEGIN NOW What earth we tread, and who commands the coast? END
BEGIN NOW Then on your name shall wretched mortals call, END
BEGIN NOW And offer'd victims at your altars fall. END
BEGIN NOW I dare not," she replied, "assume the name END
BEGIN NOW Of goddess, or celestial honors claim: END
BEGIN NOW For Tyrian virgins bows and quivers bear, END
BEGIN NOW And purple buskins o'er their ankles wear. END
BEGIN NOW Know, gentle youth, in Libyan lands you are- END
BEGIN NOW A people rude in peace, and rough in war. END
BEGIN NOW The rising city, which from far you see, END
BEGIN NOW Is Carthage, and a Tyrian colony. END
BEGIN NOW Phoenician Dido rules the growing state, END
BEGIN NOW Who fled from Tyre, to shun her brother's hate. END
BEGIN NOW Great were her wrongs, her story full of fate; END
BEGIN NOW Which I will sum in short. Sichaeus, known END
BEGIN NOW For wealth, and brother to the Punic throne, END
BEGIN NOW Possess'd fair Dido's bed; and either heart END
BEGIN NOW At once was wounded with an equal dart. END
BEGIN NOW Her father gave her, yet a spotless maid; END
BEGIN NOW Pygmalion then the Tyrian scepter sway'd: END
BEGIN NOW One who condemn'd divine and human laws. END
BEGIN NOW Then strife ensued, and cursed gold the cause. END
BEGIN NOW The monarch, blinded with desire of wealth, END
BEGIN NOW With steel invades his brother's life by stealth; END
BEGIN NOW Before the sacred altar made him bleed, END
BEGIN NOW And long from her conceal'd the cruel deed. END
BEGIN NOW Some tale, some new pretense, he daily coin'd, END
BEGIN NOW To soothe his sister, and delude her mind. END
BEGIN NOW At length, in dead of night, the ghost appears END
BEGIN NOW Of her unhappy lord: the specter stares, END
BEGIN NOW And, with erected eyes, his bloody bosom bares. END
BEGIN NOW The cruel altars and his fate he tells, END
BEGIN NOW And the dire secret of his house reveals, END
BEGIN NOW Then warns the widow, with her household gods, END
BEGIN NOW To seek a refuge in remote abodes. END
BEGIN NOW Last, to support her in so long a way, END
BEGIN NOW He shows her where his hidden treasure lay. END
BEGIN NOW Admonish'd thus, and seiz'd with mortal fright, END
BEGIN NOW The queen provides companions of her flight: END
BEGIN NOW They meet, and all combine to leave the state, END
BEGIN NOW Who hate the tyrant, or who fear his hate. END
BEGIN NOW They seize a fleet, which ready rigg'd they find; END
BEGIN NOW Nor is Pygmalion's treasure left behind. END
BEGIN NOW The vessels, heavy laden, put to sea END
BEGIN NOW With prosp'rous winds; a woman leads the way. END
BEGIN NOW I know not, if by stress of weather driv'n, END
BEGIN NOW Or was their fatal course dispos'd by Heav'n; END
BEGIN NOW At last they landed, where from far your eyes END
BEGIN NOW May view the turrets of new Carthage rise; END
BEGIN NOW There bought a space of ground, which (Byrsa call'd, END
BEGIN NOW From the bull's hide) they first inclos'd, and wall'd. END
BEGIN NOW But whence are you? what country claims your birth? END
BEGIN NOW What seek you, strangers, on our Libyan earth? END
BEGIN NOW To whom, with sorrow streaming from his eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And deeply sighing, thus her son replies: END
BEGIN NOW Could you with patience hear, or I relate, END
BEGIN NOW O nymph, the tedious annals of our fate! END
BEGIN NOW Thro' such a train of woes if I should run, END
BEGIN NOW The day would sooner than the tale be done! END
BEGIN NOW From ancient Troy, by force expell'd, we came- END
BEGIN NOW If you by chance have heard the Trojan name. END
BEGIN NOW On various seas by various tempests toss'd, END
BEGIN NOW At length we landed on your Libyan coast. END
BEGIN NOW The good Aeneas am I call'd- a name, END
BEGIN NOW While Fortune favor'd, not unknown to fame. END
BEGIN NOW My household gods, companions of my woes, END
BEGIN NOW With pious care I rescued from our foes. END
BEGIN NOW To fruitful Italy my course was bent; END
BEGIN NOW And from the King of Heav'n is my descent. END
BEGIN NOW With twice ten sail I cross'd the Phrygian sea; END
BEGIN NOW Fate and my mother goddess led my way. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce sev'n, the thin remainders of my fleet, END
BEGIN NOW From storms preserv'd, within your harbor meet. END
BEGIN NOW Myself distress'd, an exile, and unknown, END
BEGIN NOW Debarr'd from Europe, and from Asia thrown, END
BEGIN NOW In Libyan desarts wander thus alone. END
BEGIN NOW His tender parent could no longer bear; END
BEGIN NOW But, interposing, sought to soothe his care. END
BEGIN NOW Whoe'er you are- not unbelov'd by Heav'n, END
BEGIN NOW Since on our friendly shore your ships are driv'n- END
BEGIN NOW Have courage: to the gods permit the rest, END
BEGIN NOW And to the queen expose your just request. END
BEGIN NOW Now take this earnest of success, for more: END
BEGIN NOW Your scatter'd fleet is join'd upon the shore; END
BEGIN NOW The winds are chang'd, your friends from danger free; END
BEGIN NOW Or I renounce my skill in augury. END
BEGIN NOW Twelve swans behold in beauteous order move, END
BEGIN NOW And stoop with closing pinions from above; END
BEGIN NOW Whom late the bird of Jove had driv'n along, END
BEGIN NOW And thro' the clouds pursued the scatt'ring throng: END
BEGIN NOW Now, all united in a goodly team, END
BEGIN NOW They skim the ground, and seek the quiet stream. END
BEGIN NOW As they, with joy returning, clap their wings, END
BEGIN NOW And ride the circuit of the skies in rings; END
BEGIN NOW Not otherwise your ships, and ev'ry friend, END
BEGIN NOW Already hold the port, or with swift sails descend. END
BEGIN NOW No more advice is needful; but pursue END
BEGIN NOW The path before you, and the town in view. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, she turn'd, and made appear END
BEGIN NOW Her neck refulgent, and dishevel'd hair, END
BEGIN NOW Which, flowing from her shoulders, reach'd the ground. END
BEGIN NOW And widely spread ambrosial scents around: END
BEGIN NOW In length of train descends her sweeping gown; END
BEGIN NOW And, by her graceful walk, the Queen of Love is known. END
BEGIN NOW The prince pursued the parting deity END
BEGIN NOW With words like these: "Ah! whither do you fly? END
BEGIN NOW Unkind and cruel! to deceive your son END
BEGIN NOW In borrow'd shapes, and his embrace to shun; END
BEGIN NOW Never to bless my sight, but thus unknown; END
BEGIN NOW And still to speak in accents not your own. END
BEGIN NOW Against the goddess these complaints he made, END
BEGIN NOW But took the path, and her commands obey'd. END
BEGIN NOW They march, obscure; for Venus kindly shrouds END
BEGIN NOW With mists their persons, and involves in clouds, END
BEGIN NOW That, thus unseen, their passage none might stay, END
BEGIN NOW Or force to tell the causes of their way. END
BEGIN NOW This part perform'd, the goddess flies sublime END
BEGIN NOW To visit Paphos and her native clime; END
BEGIN NOW Where garlands, ever green and ever fair, END
BEGIN NOW With vows are offer'd, and with solemn pray'r: END
BEGIN NOW A hundred altars in her temple smoke; END
BEGIN NOW A thousand bleeding hearts her pow'r invoke. END
BEGIN NOW They climb the next ascent, and, looking down, END
BEGIN NOW Now at a nearer distance view the town. END
BEGIN NOW The prince with wonder sees the stately tow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW Which late were huts and shepherds' homely bow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW The gates and streets; and hears, from ev'ry part, END
BEGIN NOW The noise and busy concourse of the mart. END
BEGIN NOW The toiling Tyrians on each other call END
BEGIN NOW To ply their labor: some extend the wall; END
BEGIN NOW Some build the citadel; the brawny throng END
BEGIN NOW Or dig, or push unwieldly stones along. END
BEGIN NOW Some for their dwellings choose a spot of ground, END
BEGIN NOW Which, first design'd, with ditches they surround. END
BEGIN NOW Some laws ordain; and some attend the choice END
BEGIN NOW Of holy senates, and elect by voice. END
BEGIN NOW Here some design a mole, while others there END
BEGIN NOW Lay deep foundations for a theater; END
BEGIN NOW From marble quarries mighty columns hew, END
BEGIN NOW For ornaments of scenes, and future view. END
BEGIN NOW Such is their toil, and such their busy pains, END
BEGIN NOW As exercise the bees in flow'ry plains, END
BEGIN NOW When winter past, and summer scarce begun, END
BEGIN NOW Invites them forth to labor in the sun; END
BEGIN NOW Some lead their youth abroad, while some condense END
BEGIN NOW Their liquid store, and some in cells dispense; END
BEGIN NOW Some at the gate stand ready to receive END
BEGIN NOW The golden burthen, and their friends relieve; END
BEGIN NOW All with united force, combine to drive END
BEGIN NOW The lazy drones from the laborious hive: END
BEGIN NOW With envy stung, they view each other's deeds; END
BEGIN NOW The fragrant work with diligence proceeds. END
BEGIN NOW Thrice happy you, whose walls already rise! END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas said, and view'd, with lifted eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Their lofty tow'rs; then, entiring at the gate, END
BEGIN NOW Conceal'd in clouds (prodigious to relate) END
BEGIN NOW He mix'd, unmark'd, among the busy throng, END
BEGIN NOW Borne by the tide, and pass'd unseen along. END
BEGIN NOW Full in the center of the town there stood, END
BEGIN NOW Thick set with trees, a venerable wood. END
BEGIN NOW The Tyrians, landing near this holy ground, END
BEGIN NOW And digging here, a prosp'rous omen found: END
BEGIN NOW From under earth a courser's head they drew, END
BEGIN NOW Their growth and future fortune to foreshew. END
BEGIN NOW This fated sign their foundress Juno gave, END
BEGIN NOW Of a soil fruitful, and a people brave. END
BEGIN NOW Sidonian Dido here with solemn state END
BEGIN NOW Did Juno's temple build, and consecrate, END
BEGIN NOW Enrich'd with gifts, and with a golden shrine; END
BEGIN NOW But more the goddess made the place divine. END
BEGIN NOW On brazen steps the marble threshold rose, END
BEGIN NOW And brazen plates the cedar beams inclose: END
BEGIN NOW The rafters are with brazen cov'rings crown'd; END
BEGIN NOW The lofty doors on brazen hinges sound. END
BEGIN NOW What first Aeneas this place beheld, END
BEGIN NOW Reviv'd his courage, and his fear expell'd. END
BEGIN NOW For while, expecting there the queen, he rais'd END
BEGIN NOW His wond'ring eyes, and round the temple gaz'd, END
BEGIN NOW Admir'd the fortune of the rising town, END
BEGIN NOW The striving artists, and their arts' renown; END
BEGIN NOW He saw, in order painted on the wall, END
BEGIN NOW Whatever did unhappy Troy befall: END
BEGIN NOW The wars that fame around the world had blown, END
BEGIN NOW All to the life, and ev'ry leader known. END
BEGIN NOW There Agamemnon, Priam here, he spies, END
BEGIN NOW And fierce Achilles, who both kings defies. END
BEGIN NOW He stopp'd, and weeping said: "O friend! ev'n here END
BEGIN NOW The monuments of Trojan woes appear! END
BEGIN NOW Our known disasters fill ev'n foreign lands: END
BEGIN NOW See there, where old unhappy Priam stands! END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n the mute walls relate the warrior's fame, END
BEGIN NOW And Trojan griefs the Tyrians' pity claim. END
BEGIN NOW He said (his tears a ready passage find), END
BEGIN NOW Devouring what he saw so well design'd, END
BEGIN NOW And with an empty picture fed his mind: END
BEGIN NOW For there he saw the fainting Grecians yield, END
BEGIN NOW And here the trembling Trojans quit the field, END
BEGIN NOW Pursued by fierce Achilles thro' the plain, END
BEGIN NOW On his high chariot driving o'er the slain. END
BEGIN NOW The tents of Rhesus next his grief renew, END
BEGIN NOW By their white sails betray'd to nightly view; END
BEGIN NOW And wakeful Diomede, whose cruel sword END
BEGIN NOW The sentries slew, nor spar'd their slumb'ring lord, END
BEGIN NOW Then took the fiery steeds, ere yet the food END
BEGIN NOW Of Troy they taste, or drink the Xanthian flood. END
BEGIN NOW Elsewhere he saw where Troilus defied END
BEGIN NOW Achilles, and unequal combat tried; END
BEGIN NOW Then, where the boy disarm'd, with loosen'd reins, END
BEGIN NOW Was by his horses hurried o'er the plains, END
BEGIN NOW Hung by the neck and hair, and dragg'd around: END
BEGIN NOW The hostile spear, yet sticking in his wound, END
BEGIN NOW With tracks of blood inscrib'd the dusty ground. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the Trojan dames, oppress'd with woe, END
BEGIN NOW To Pallas' fane in long procession go, END
BEGIN NOW In hopes to reconcile their heav'nly foe. END
BEGIN NOW They weep, they beat their breasts, they rend their hair, END
BEGIN NOW And rich embroider'd vests for presents bear; END
BEGIN NOW But the stern goddess stands unmov'd with pray'r. END
BEGIN NOW Thrice round the Trojan walls Achilles drew END
BEGIN NOW The corpse of Hector, whom in fight he slew. END
BEGIN NOW Here Priam sues; and there, for sums of gold, END
BEGIN NOW The lifeless body of his son is sold. END
BEGIN NOW So sad an object, and so well express'd, END
BEGIN NOW Drew sighs and groans from the griev'd hero's breast, END
BEGIN NOW To see the figure of his lifeless friend, END
BEGIN NOW And his old sire his helpless hand extend. END
BEGIN NOW Himself he saw amidst the Grecian train, END
BEGIN NOW Mix'd in the bloody battle on the plain; END
BEGIN NOW And swarthy Memnon in his arms he knew, END
BEGIN NOW His pompous ensigns, and his Indian crew. END
BEGIN NOW Penthisilea there, with haughty grace, END
BEGIN NOW Leads to the wars an Amazonian race: END
BEGIN NOW In their right hands a pointed dart they wield; END
BEGIN NOW The left, for ward, sustains the lunar shield. END
BEGIN NOW Athwart her breast a golden belt she throws, END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the press alone provokes a thousand foes, END
BEGIN NOW And dares her maiden arms to manly force oppose. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while the Trojan prince employs his eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Fix'd on the walls with wonder and surprise, END
BEGIN NOW The beauteous Dido, with a num'rous train END
BEGIN NOW And pomp of guards, ascends the sacred fane. END
BEGIN NOW Such on Eurotas' banks, or Cynthus' height, END
BEGIN NOW Diana seems; and so she charms the sight, END
BEGIN NOW When in the dance the graceful goddess leads END
BEGIN NOW The choir of nymphs, and overtops their heads: END
BEGIN NOW Known by her quiver, and her lofty mien, END
BEGIN NOW She walks majestic, and she looks their queen; END
BEGIN NOW Latona sees her shine above the rest, END
BEGIN NOW And feeds with secret joy her silent breast. END
BEGIN NOW Such Dido was; with such becoming state, END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the crowd, she walks serenely great. END
BEGIN NOW Their labor to her future sway she speeds, END
BEGIN NOW And passing with a gracious glance proceeds; END
BEGIN NOW Then mounts the throne, high plac'd before the shrine: END
BEGIN NOW In crowds around, the swarming people join. END
BEGIN NOW She takes petitions, and dispenses laws, END
BEGIN NOW Hears and determines ev'ry private cause; END
BEGIN NOW Their tasks in equal portions she divides, END
BEGIN NOW And, where unequal, there by lots decides. END
BEGIN NOW Another way by chance Aeneas bends END
BEGIN NOW His eyes, and unexpected sees his friends, END
BEGIN NOW Antheus, Sergestus grave, Cloanthus strong, END
BEGIN NOW And at their backs a mighty Trojan throng, END
BEGIN NOW Whom late the tempest on the billows toss'd, END
BEGIN NOW And widely scatter'd on another coast. END
BEGIN NOW The prince, unseen, surpris'd with wonder stands, END
BEGIN NOW And longs, with joyful haste, to join their hands; END
BEGIN NOW But, doubtful of the wish'd event, he stays, END
BEGIN NOW And from the hollow cloud his friends surveys, END
BEGIN NOW Impatient till they told their present state, END
BEGIN NOW And where they left their ships, and what their fate, END
BEGIN NOW And why they came, and what was their request; END
BEGIN NOW For these were sent, commission'd by the rest, END
BEGIN NOW To sue for leave to land their sickly men, END
BEGIN NOW And gain admission to the gracious queen. END
BEGIN NOW Ent'ring, with cries they fill'd the holy fane; END
BEGIN NOW Then thus, with lowly voice, Ilioneus began: END
BEGIN NOW O queen! indulg'd by favor of the gods END
BEGIN NOW To found an empire in these new abodes, END
BEGIN NOW To build a town, with statutes to restrain END
BEGIN NOW The wild inhabitants beneath thy reign, END
BEGIN NOW We wretched Trojans, toss'd on ev'ry shore, END
BEGIN NOW From sea to sea, thy clemency implore. END
BEGIN NOW Forbid the fires our shipping to deface! END
BEGIN NOW Receive th' unhappy fugitives to grace, END
BEGIN NOW And spare the remnant of a pious race! END
BEGIN NOW We come not with design of wasteful prey, END
BEGIN NOW To drive the country, force the swains away: END
BEGIN NOW Nor such our strength, nor such is our desire; END
BEGIN NOW The vanquish'd dare not to such thoughts aspire. END
BEGIN NOW A land there is, Hesperia nam'd of old; END
BEGIN NOW The soil is fruitful, and the men are bold- END
BEGIN NOW Th' Oenotrians held it once- by common fame END
BEGIN NOW Now call'd Italia, from the leader's name. END
BEGIN NOW To that sweet region was our voyage bent, END
BEGIN NOW When winds and ev'ry warring element END
BEGIN NOW Disturb'd our course, and, far from sight of land, END
BEGIN NOW Cast our torn vessels on the moving sand: END
BEGIN NOW The sea came on; the South, with mighty roar, END
BEGIN NOW Dispers'd and dash'd the rest upon the rocky shore. END
BEGIN NOW Those few you see escap'd the Storm, and fear, END
BEGIN NOW Unless you interpose, a shipwreck here. END
BEGIN NOW What men, what monsters, what inhuman race, END
BEGIN NOW What laws, what barb'rous customs of the place, END
BEGIN NOW Shut up a desart shore to drowning men, END
BEGIN NOW And drive us to the cruel seas again? END
BEGIN NOW If our hard fortune no compassion draws, END
BEGIN NOW Nor hospitable rights, nor human laws, END
BEGIN NOW The gods are just, and will revenge our cause. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas was our prince: a juster lord, END
BEGIN NOW Or nobler warrior, never drew a sword; END
BEGIN NOW Observant of the right, religious of his word. END
BEGIN NOW If yet he lives, and draws this vital air, END
BEGIN NOW Nor we, his friends, of safety shall despair; END
BEGIN NOW Nor you, great queen, these offices repent, END
BEGIN NOW Which he will equal, and perhaps augment. END
BEGIN NOW We want not cities, nor Sicilian coasts, END
BEGIN NOW Where King Acestes Trojan lineage boasts. END
BEGIN NOW Permit our ships a shelter on your shores, END
BEGIN NOW Refitted from your woods with planks and oars, END
BEGIN NOW That, if our prince be safe, we may renew END
BEGIN NOW Our destin'd course, and Italy pursue. END
BEGIN NOW But if, O best of men, the Fates ordain END
BEGIN NOW That thou art swallow'd in the Libyan main, END
BEGIN NOW And if our young Iulus be no more, END
BEGIN NOW Dismiss our navy from your friendly shore, END
BEGIN NOW That we to good Acestes may return, END
BEGIN NOW And with our friends our common losses mourn. END
BEGIN NOW Thus spoke Ilioneus: the Trojan crew END
BEGIN NOW With cries and clamors his request renew. END
BEGIN NOW The modest queen a while, with downcast eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Ponder'd the speech; then briefly thus replies: END
BEGIN NOW Trojans, dismiss your fears; my cruel fate, END
BEGIN NOW And doubts attending an unsettled state, END
BEGIN NOW Force me to guard my coast from foreign foes. END
BEGIN NOW Who has not heard the story of your woes, END
BEGIN NOW The name and fortune of your native place, END
BEGIN NOW The fame and valor of the Phrygian race? END
BEGIN NOW We Tyrians are not so devoid of sense, END
BEGIN NOW Nor so remote from Phoebus' influence. END
BEGIN NOW Whether to Latian shores your course is bent, END
BEGIN NOW Or, driv'n by tempests from your first intent, END
BEGIN NOW You seek the good Acestes' government, END
BEGIN NOW Your men shall be receiv'd, your fleet repair'd, END
BEGIN NOW And sail, with ships of convoy for your guard: END
BEGIN NOW Or, would you stay, and join your friendly pow'rs END
BEGIN NOW To raise and to defend the Tyrian tow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW My wealth, my city, and myself are yours. END
BEGIN NOW And would to Heav'n, the Storm, you felt, would bring END
BEGIN NOW On Carthaginian coasts your wand'ring king. END
BEGIN NOW My people shall, by my command, explore END
BEGIN NOW The ports and creeks of ev'ry winding shore, END
BEGIN NOW And towns, and wilds, and shady woods, in quest END
BEGIN NOW Of so renown'd and so desir'd a guest. END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd in his mind the Trojan hero stood, END
BEGIN NOW And long'd to break from out his ambient cloud: END
BEGIN NOW Achates found it, and thus urg'd his way: END
BEGIN NOW From whence, O goddess-born, this long delay? END
BEGIN NOW What more can you desire, your welcome sure, END
BEGIN NOW Your fleet in safety, and your friends secure? END
BEGIN NOW One only wants; and him we saw in vain END
BEGIN NOW Oppose the Storm, and swallow'd in the main. END
BEGIN NOW Orontes in his fate our forfeit paid; END
BEGIN NOW The rest agrees with what your mother said. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had he spoken, when the cloud gave way, END
BEGIN NOW The mists flew upward and dissolv'd in day. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan chief appear'd in open sight, END
BEGIN NOW August in visage, and serenely bright. END
BEGIN NOW His mother goddess, with her hands divine, END
BEGIN NOW Had form'd his curling locks, and made his temples shine, END
BEGIN NOW And giv'n his rolling eyes a sparkling grace, END
BEGIN NOW And breath'd a youthful vigor on his face; END
BEGIN NOW Like polish'd ivory, beauteous to behold, END
BEGIN NOW Or Parian marble, when enchas'd in gold: END
BEGIN NOW Thus radiant from the circling cloud he broke, END
BEGIN NOW And thus with manly modesty he spoke: END
BEGIN NOW He whom you seek am I; by tempests toss'd, END
BEGIN NOW And sav'd from shipwreck on your Libyan coast; END
BEGIN NOW Presenting, gracious queen, before your throne, END
BEGIN NOW A prince that owes his life to you alone. END
BEGIN NOW Fair majesty, the refuge and redress END
BEGIN NOW Of those whom fate pursues, and wants oppress, END
BEGIN NOW You, who your pious offices employ END
BEGIN NOW To save the relics of abandon'd Troy; END
BEGIN NOW Receive the shipwreck'd on your friendly shore, END
BEGIN NOW With hospitable rites relieve the poor; END
BEGIN NOW Associate in your town a wand'ring train, END
BEGIN NOW And strangers in your palace entertain: END
BEGIN NOW What thanks can wretched fugitives return, END
BEGIN NOW Who, scatter'd thro' the world, in exile mourn? END
BEGIN NOW The gods, if gods to goodness are inclin'd; END
BEGIN NOW If acts of mercy touch their heav'nly mind, END
BEGIN NOW And, more than all the gods, your gen'rous heart. END
BEGIN NOW Conscious of worth, requite its own desert! END
BEGIN NOW In you this age is happy, and this earth, END
BEGIN NOW And parents more than mortal gave you birth. END
BEGIN NOW While rolling rivers into seas shall run, END
BEGIN NOW And round the space of heav'n the radiant sun; END
BEGIN NOW While trees the mountain tops with shades supply, END
BEGIN NOW Your honor, name, and praise shall never die. END
BEGIN NOW Whate'er abode my fortune has assign'd, END
BEGIN NOW Your image shall be present in my mind. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, he turn'd with pious haste, END
BEGIN NOW And joyful his expecting friends embrac'd: END
BEGIN NOW With his right hand Ilioneus was grac'd, END
BEGIN NOW Serestus with his left; then to his breast END
BEGIN NOW Cloanthus and the noble Gyas press'd; END
BEGIN NOW And so by turns descended to the rest. END
BEGIN NOW The Tyrian queen stood fix'd upon his face, END
BEGIN NOW Pleas'd with his motions, ravish'd with his grace; END
BEGIN NOW Admir'd his fortunes, more admir'd the man; END
BEGIN NOW Then recollected stood, and thus began: END
BEGIN NOW What fate, O goddess-born; what angry pow'rs END
BEGIN NOW Have cast you shipwrack'd on our barren shores? END
BEGIN NOW Are you the great Aeneas, known to fame, END
BEGIN NOW Who from celestial seed your lineage claim? END
BEGIN NOW The same Aeneas whom fair Venus bore END
BEGIN NOW To fam'd Anchises on th' Idaean shore? END
BEGIN NOW It calls into my mind, tho' then a child, END
BEGIN NOW When Teucer came, from Salamis exil'd, END
BEGIN NOW And sought my father's aid, to be restor'd: END
BEGIN NOW My father Belus then with fire and sword END
BEGIN NOW Invaded Cyprus, made the region bare, END
BEGIN NOW And, conqu'ring, finish'd the successful war. END
BEGIN NOW From him the Trojan siege I understood, END
BEGIN NOW The Grecian chiefs, and your illustrious blood. END
BEGIN NOW Your foe himself the Dardan valor prais'd, END
BEGIN NOW And his own ancestry from Trojans rais'd. END
BEGIN NOW Enter, my noble guest, and you shall find, END
BEGIN NOW If not a costly welcome, yet a kind: END
BEGIN NOW For I myself, like you, have been distress'd, END
BEGIN NOW Till Heav'n afforded me this place of rest; END
BEGIN NOW Like you, an alien in a land unknown, END
BEGIN NOW I learn to pity woes so like my own. END
BEGIN NOW She said, and to the palace led her guest; END
BEGIN NOW Then offer'd incense, and proclaim'd a feast. END
BEGIN NOW Nor yet less careful for her absent friends, END
BEGIN NOW Twice ten fat oxen to the ships she sends; END
BEGIN NOW Besides a hundred boars, a hundred lambs, END
BEGIN NOW With bleating cries, attend their milky dams; END
BEGIN NOW And jars of gen'rous wine and spacious bowls END
BEGIN NOW She gives, to cheer the sailors' drooping souls. END
BEGIN NOW Now purple hangings clothe the palace walls, END
BEGIN NOW And sumptuous feasts are made in splendid halls: END
BEGIN NOW On Tyrian carpets, richly wrought, they dine; END
BEGIN NOW With loads of massy plate the sideboards shine, END
BEGIN NOW And antique vases, all of gold emboss'd END
BEGIN NOW (The gold itself inferior to the cost), END
BEGIN NOW Of curious work, where on the sides were seen END
BEGIN NOW The fights and figures of illustrious men, END
BEGIN NOW From their first founder to the present queen. END
BEGIN NOW The good Aeneas, paternal care END
BEGIN NOW Iulus' absence could no longer bear, END
BEGIN NOW Dispatch'd Achates to the ships in haste, END
BEGIN NOW To give a glad relation of the past, END
BEGIN NOW And, fraught with precious gifts, to bring the boy, END
BEGIN NOW Snatch'd from the ruins of unhappy Troy: END
BEGIN NOW A robe of tissue, stiff with golden wire; END
BEGIN NOW An upper vest, once Helen's rich attire, END
BEGIN NOW From Argos by the fam'd adultress brought, END
BEGIN NOW With golden flow'rs and winding foliage wrought, END
BEGIN NOW Her mother Leda's present, when she came END
BEGIN NOW To ruin Troy and set the world on flame; END
BEGIN NOW The scepter Priam's eldest daughter bore, END
BEGIN NOW Her orient necklace, and the crown she wore END
BEGIN NOW Of double texture, glorious to behold, END
BEGIN NOW One order set with gems, and one with gold. END
BEGIN NOW Instructed thus, the wise Achates goes, END
BEGIN NOW And in his diligence his duty shows. END
BEGIN NOW But Venus, anxious for her son's affairs, END
BEGIN NOW New counsels tries, and new designs prepares: END
BEGIN NOW That Cupid should assume the shape and face END
BEGIN NOW Of sweet Ascanius, and the sprightly grace; END
BEGIN NOW Should bring the presents, in her nephew's stead, END
BEGIN NOW And in Eliza's veins the gentle poison shed: END
BEGIN NOW For much she fear'd the Tyrians, double-tongued, END
BEGIN NOW And knew the town to Juno's care belong'd. END
BEGIN NOW These thoughts by night her golden slumbers broke, END
BEGIN NOW And thus alarm'd, to winged Love she spoke: END
BEGIN NOW My son, my strength, whose mighty pow'r alone END
BEGIN NOW Controls the Thund'rer on his awful throne, END
BEGIN NOW To thee thy much-afflicted mother flies, END
BEGIN NOW And on thy succor and thy faith relies. END
BEGIN NOW Thou know'st, my son, how Jove's revengeful wife, END
BEGIN NOW By force and fraud, attempts thy brother's life; END
BEGIN NOW And often hast thou mourn'd with me his pains. END
BEGIN NOW Him Dido now with blandishment detains; END
BEGIN NOW But I suspect the town where Juno reigns. END
BEGIN NOW For this 't is needful to prevent her art, END
BEGIN NOW And fire with love the proud Phoenician's heart: END
BEGIN NOW A love so violent, so strong, so sure, END
BEGIN NOW As neither age can change, nor art can cure. END
BEGIN NOW How this may be perform'd, now take my mind: END
BEGIN NOW Ascanius by his father is design'd END
BEGIN NOW To come, with presents laden, from the port, END
BEGIN NOW To gratify the queen, and gain the court. END
BEGIN NOW I mean to plunge the boy in pleasing sleep, END
BEGIN NOW And, ravish'd, in Idalian bow'rs to keep, END
BEGIN NOW Or high Cythera, that the sweet deceit END
BEGIN NOW May pass unseen, and none prevent the cheat. END
BEGIN NOW Take thou his form and shape. I beg the grace END
BEGIN NOW But only for a night's revolving space: END
BEGIN NOW Thyself a boy, assume a boy's dissembled face; END
BEGIN NOW That when, amidst the fervor of the feast, END
BEGIN NOW The Tyrian hugs and fonds thee on her breast, END
BEGIN NOW And with sweet kisses in her arms constrains, END
BEGIN NOW Thou may'st infuse thy venom in her veins. END
BEGIN NOW The God of Love obeys, and sets aside END
BEGIN NOW His bow and quiver, and his plumy pride; END
BEGIN NOW He walks Iulus in his mother's sight, END
BEGIN NOW And in the sweet resemblance takes delight. END
BEGIN NOW The goddess then to young Ascanius flies, END
BEGIN NOW And in a pleasing slumber seals his eyes: END
BEGIN NOW Lull'd in her lap, amidst a train of Loves, END
BEGIN NOW She gently bears him to her blissful groves, END
BEGIN NOW Then with a wreath of myrtle crowns his head, END
BEGIN NOW And softly lays him on a flow'ry bed. END
BEGIN NOW Cupid meantime assum'd his form and face, END
BEGIN NOW Foll'wing Achates with a shorter pace, END
BEGIN NOW And brought the gifts. The queen already sate END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the Trojan lords, in shining state, END
BEGIN NOW High on a golden bed: her princely guest END
BEGIN NOW Was next her side; in order sate the rest. END
BEGIN NOW Then canisters with bread are heap'd on high; END
BEGIN NOW Th' attendants water for their hands supply, END
BEGIN NOW And, having wash'd, with silken towels dry. END
BEGIN NOW Next fifty handmaids in long order bore END
BEGIN NOW The censers, and with fumes the gods adore: END
BEGIN NOW Then youths, and virgins twice as many, join END
BEGIN NOW To place the dishes, and to serve the wine. END
BEGIN NOW The Tyrian train, admitted to the feast, END
BEGIN NOW Approach, and on the painted couches rest. END
BEGIN NOW All on the Trojan gifts with wonder gaze, END
BEGIN NOW But view the beauteous boy with more amaze, END
BEGIN NOW His rosy-color'd cheeks, his radiant eyes, END
BEGIN NOW His motions, voice, and shape, and all the god's disguise; END
BEGIN NOW Nor pass unprais'd the vest and veil divine, END
BEGIN NOW Which wand'ring foliage and rich flow'rs entwine. END
BEGIN NOW But, far above the rest, the royal dame, END
BEGIN NOW (Already doom'd to love's disastrous flame,) END
BEGIN NOW With eyes insatiate, and tumultuous joy, END
BEGIN NOW Beholds the presents, and admires the boy. END
BEGIN NOW The guileful god about the hero long, END
BEGIN NOW With children's play, and false embraces, hung; END
BEGIN NOW Then sought the queen: she took him to her arms END
BEGIN NOW With greedy pleasure, and devour'd his charms. END
BEGIN NOW Unhappy Dido little thought what guest, END
BEGIN NOW How dire a god, she drew so near her breast; END
BEGIN NOW But he, not mindless of his mother's pray'r, END
BEGIN NOW Works in the pliant bosom of the fair, END
BEGIN NOW And molds her heart anew, and blots her former care. END
BEGIN NOW The dead is to the living love resign'd; END
BEGIN NOW And all Aeneas enters in her mind. END
BEGIN NOW Now, when the rage of hunger was appeas'd, END
BEGIN NOW The meat remov'd, and ev'ry guest was pleas'd, END
BEGIN NOW The golden bowls with sparkling wine are crown'd, END
BEGIN NOW And thro' the palace cheerful cries resound. END
BEGIN NOW From gilded roofs depending lamps display END
BEGIN NOW Nocturnal beams, that emulate the day. END
BEGIN NOW A golden bowl, that shone with gems divine, END
BEGIN NOW The queen commanded to be crown'd with wine: END
BEGIN NOW The bowl that Belus us'd, and all the Tyrian line. END
BEGIN NOW Then, silence thro' the hall proclaim'd, she spoke: END
BEGIN NOW O hospitable Jove! we thus invoke, END
BEGIN NOW With solemn rites, thy sacred name and pow'r; END
BEGIN NOW Bless to both nations this auspicious hour! END
BEGIN NOW So may the Trojan and the Tyrian line END
BEGIN NOW In lasting concord from this day combine. END
BEGIN NOW Thou, Bacchus, god of joys and friendly cheer, END
BEGIN NOW And gracious Juno, both be present here! END
BEGIN NOW And you, my lords of Tyre, your vows address END
BEGIN NOW To Heav'n with mine, to ratify the peace. END
BEGIN NOW The goblet then she took, with nectar crown'd END
BEGIN NOW (Sprinkling the first libations on the ground,) END
BEGIN NOW And rais'd it to her mouth with sober grace; END
BEGIN NOW Then, sipping, offer'd to the next in place. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was Bitias whom she call'd, a thirsty soul; END
BEGIN NOW He took challenge, and embrac'd the bowl, END
BEGIN NOW With pleasure swill'd the gold, nor ceas'd to draw, END
BEGIN NOW Till he the bottom of the brimmer saw. END
BEGIN NOW The goblet goes around: Iopas brought END
BEGIN NOW His golden lyre, and sung what ancient Atlas taught: END
BEGIN NOW The various labors of the wand'ring moon, END
BEGIN NOW And whence proceed th' eclipses of the sun; END
BEGIN NOW Th' original of men and beasts; and whence END
BEGIN NOW The rains arise, and fires their warmth dispense, END
BEGIN NOW And fix'd and erring stars dispose their influence; END
BEGIN NOW What shakes the solid earth; what cause delays END
BEGIN NOW The summer nights and shortens winter days. END
BEGIN NOW With peals of shouts the Tyrians praise the song: END
BEGIN NOW Those peals are echo'd by the Trojan throng. END
BEGIN NOW Th' unhappy queen with talk prolong'd the night, END
BEGIN NOW And drank large draughts of love with vast delight; END
BEGIN NOW Of Priam much enquir'd, of Hector more; END
BEGIN NOW Then ask'd what arms the swarthy Memnon wore, END
BEGIN NOW What troops he landed on the Trojan shore; END
BEGIN NOW The steeds of Diomede varied the discourse, END
BEGIN NOW And fierce Achilles, with his matchless force; END
BEGIN NOW At length, as fate and her ill stars requir'd, END
BEGIN NOW To hear the series of the war desir'd. END
BEGIN NOW Relate at large, my godlike guest," she said, END
BEGIN NOW The Grecian stratagems, the town betray'd: END
BEGIN NOW The fatal issue of so long a war, END
BEGIN NOW Your flight, your wand'rings, and your woes, declare; END
BEGIN NOW For, since on ev'ry sea, on ev'ry coast, END
BEGIN NOW Your men have been distress'd, your navy toss'd, END
BEGIN NOW Sev'n times the sun has either tropic view'd, END
BEGIN NOW The winter banish'd, and the spring renew'd. END
BEGIN NOW All were attentive to the godlike man, END
BEGIN NOW When from his lofty couch he thus began: END
BEGIN NOW Great queen, what you command me to relate END
BEGIN NOW Renews the sad remembrance of our fate: END
BEGIN NOW An empire from its old foundations rent, END
BEGIN NOW And ev'ry woe the Trojans underwent; END
BEGIN NOW A peopled city made a desart place; END
BEGIN NOW All that I saw, and part of which I was: END
BEGIN NOW Not ev'n the hardest of our foes could hear, END
BEGIN NOW Nor stern Ulysses tell without a tear. END
BEGIN NOW And now the latter watch of wasting night, END
BEGIN NOW And setting stars, to kindly rest invite; END
BEGIN NOW But, since you take such int'rest in our woe, END
BEGIN NOW And Troy's disastrous end desire to know, END
BEGIN NOW I will restrain my tears, and briefly tell END
BEGIN NOW What in our last and fatal night befell. END
BEGIN NOW By destiny compell'd, and in despair, END
BEGIN NOW The Greeks grew weary of the tedious war, END
BEGIN NOW And by Minerva's aid a fabric rear'd, END
BEGIN NOW Which like a steed of monstrous height appear'd: END
BEGIN NOW The sides were plank'd with pine; they feign'd it made END
BEGIN NOW For their return, and this the vow they paid. END
BEGIN NOW Thus they pretend, but in the hollow side END
BEGIN NOW Selected numbers of their soldiers hide: END
BEGIN NOW With inward arms the dire machine they load, END
BEGIN NOW And iron bowels stuff the dark abode. END
BEGIN NOW In sight of Troy lies Tenedos, an isle END
BEGIN NOW (While Fortune did on Priam's empire smile) END
BEGIN NOW Renown'd for wealth; but, since, a faithless bay, END
BEGIN NOW Where ships expos'd to wind and weather lay. END
BEGIN NOW There was their fleet conceal'd. We thought, for Greece END
BEGIN NOW Their sails were hoisted, and our fears release. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans, coop'd within their walls so long, END
BEGIN NOW Unbar their gates, and issue in a throng, END
BEGIN NOW Like swarming bees, and with delight survey END
BEGIN NOW The camp deserted, where the Grecians lay: END
BEGIN NOW The quarters of the sev'ral chiefs they show'd; END
BEGIN NOW Here Phoenix, here Achilles, made abode; END
BEGIN NOW Here join'd the battles; there the navy rode. END
BEGIN NOW Part on the pile their wond'ring eyes employ: END
BEGIN NOW The pile by Pallas rais'd to ruin Troy. END
BEGIN NOW Thymoetes first ('t is doubtful whether hir'd, END
BEGIN NOW Or so the Trojan destiny requir'd) END
BEGIN NOW Mov'd that the ramparts might be broken down, END
BEGIN NOW To lodge the monster fabric in the town. END
BEGIN NOW But Capys, and the rest of sounder mind, END
BEGIN NOW The fatal present to the flames designed, END
BEGIN NOW Or to the wat'ry deep; at least to bore END
BEGIN NOW The hollow sides, and hidden frauds explore. END
BEGIN NOW The giddy vulgar, as their fancies guide, END
BEGIN NOW With noise say nothing, and in parts divide. END
BEGIN NOW Laocoon, follow'd by a num'rous crowd, END
BEGIN NOW Ran from the fort, and cried, from far, aloud: END
BEGIN NOW 'O wretched countrymen! what fury reigns? END
BEGIN NOW What more than madness has possess'd your brains? END
BEGIN NOW Think you the Grecians from your coasts are gone? END
BEGIN NOW And are Ulysses' arts no better known? END
BEGIN NOW This hollow fabric either must inclose, END
BEGIN NOW Within its blind recess, our secret foes; END
BEGIN NOW Or 't is an engine rais'd above the town, END
BEGIN NOW T' o'erlook the walls, and then to batter down. END
BEGIN NOW Somewhat is sure design'd, by fraud or force: END
BEGIN NOW Trust not their presents, nor admit the horse.' END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, against the steed he threw END
BEGIN NOW His forceful spear, which, hissing as flew, END
BEGIN NOW Pierc'd thro' the yielding planks of jointed wood, END
BEGIN NOW And trembling in the hollow belly stood. END
BEGIN NOW The sides, transpierc'd, return a rattling sound, END
BEGIN NOW And groans of Greeks inclos'd come issuing thro' the wound END
BEGIN NOW And, had not Heav'n the fall of Troy design'd, END
BEGIN NOW Or had not men been fated to be blind, END
BEGIN NOW Enough was said and done t'inspire a better mind. END
BEGIN NOW Then had our lances pierc'd the treach'rous wood, END
BEGIN NOW And Ilian tow'rs and Priam's empire stood. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime, with shouts, the Trojan shepherds bring END
BEGIN NOW A captive Greek, in bands, before the king; END
BEGIN NOW Taken to take; who made himself their prey, END
BEGIN NOW T' impose on their belief, and Troy betray; END
BEGIN NOW Fix'd on his aim, and obstinately bent END
BEGIN NOW To die undaunted, or to circumvent. END
BEGIN NOW About the captive, tides of Trojans flow; END
BEGIN NOW All press to see, and some insult the foe. END
BEGIN NOW Now hear how well the Greeks their wiles disguis'd; END
BEGIN NOW Behold a nation in a man compris'd. END
BEGIN NOW Trembling the miscreant stood, unarm'd and bound; END
BEGIN NOW He star'd, and roll'd his haggard eyes around, END
BEGIN NOW Then said: 'Alas! what earth remains, what sea END
BEGIN NOW Is open to receive unhappy me? END
BEGIN NOW What fate a wretched fugitive attends, END
BEGIN NOW Scorn'd by my foes, abandon'd by my friends?' END
BEGIN NOW He said, and sigh'd, and cast a rueful eye: END
BEGIN NOW Our pity kindles, and our passions die. END
BEGIN NOW We cheer youth to make his own defense, END
BEGIN NOW And freely tell us what he was, and whence: END
BEGIN NOW What news he could impart, we long to know, END
BEGIN NOW And what to credit from a captive foe. END
BEGIN NOW His fear at length dismiss'd, he said: 'Whate'er END
BEGIN NOW My fate ordains, my words shall be sincere: END
BEGIN NOW I neither can nor dare my birth disclaim; END
BEGIN NOW Greece is my country, Sinon is my name. END
BEGIN NOW Tho' plung'd by Fortune's pow'r in misery, END
BEGIN NOW 'T is not in Fortune's pow'r to make me lie. END
BEGIN NOW If any chance has hither brought the name END
BEGIN NOW Of Palamedes, not unknown to fame, END
BEGIN NOW Who suffer'd from the malice of the times, END
BEGIN NOW Accus'd and sentenc'd for pretended crimes, END
BEGIN NOW Because these fatal wars he would prevent; END
BEGIN NOW Whose death the wretched Greeks too late lament- END
BEGIN NOW Me, then a boy, my father, poor and bare END
BEGIN NOW Of other means, committed to his care, END
BEGIN NOW His kinsman and companion in the war. END
BEGIN NOW While Fortune favor'd, while his arms support END
BEGIN NOW The cause, and rul'd the counsels, of the court, END
BEGIN NOW I made some figure there; nor was my name END
BEGIN NOW Obscure, nor I without my share of fame. END
BEGIN NOW But when Ulysses, with fallacious arts, END
BEGIN NOW Had made impression in the people's hearts, END
BEGIN NOW And forg'd a treason in my patron's name END
BEGIN NOW (I speak of things too far divulg'd by fame), END
BEGIN NOW My kinsman fell. Then I, without support, END
BEGIN NOW In private mourn'd his loss, and left the court. END
BEGIN NOW Mad as I was, I could not bear his fate END
BEGIN NOW With silent grief, but loudly blam'd the state, END
BEGIN NOW And curs'd the direful author of my woes. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was told again; and hence my ruin rose. END
BEGIN NOW I threaten'd, if indulgent Heav'n once more END
BEGIN NOW Would land me safely on my native shore, END
BEGIN NOW His death with double vengeance to restore. END
BEGIN NOW This mov'd the murderer's hate; and soon ensued END
BEGIN NOW Th' effects of malice from a man so proud. END
BEGIN NOW Ambiguous rumors thro' the camp he spread, END
BEGIN NOW And sought, by treason, my devoted head; END
BEGIN NOW New crimes invented; left unturn'd no stone, END
BEGIN NOW To make my guilt appear, and hide his own; END
BEGIN NOW Till Calchas was by force and threat'ning wrought- END
BEGIN NOW But why- why dwell I on that anxious thought? END
BEGIN NOW If on my nation just revenge you seek, END
BEGIN NOW And 't is t' appear a foe, t' appear a Greek; END
BEGIN NOW Already you my name and country know; END
BEGIN NOW Assuage your thirst of blood, and strike the blow: END
BEGIN NOW My death will both the kingly brothers please, END
BEGIN NOW And set insatiate Ithacus at ease.' END
BEGIN NOW This fair unfinish'd tale, these broken starts, END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd expectations in our longing hearts: END
BEGIN NOW Unknowing as we were in Grecian arts. END
BEGIN NOW His former trembling once again renew'd, END
BEGIN NOW With acted fear, the villain thus pursued: END
BEGIN NOW 'Long had the Grecians (tir'd with fruitless care, END
BEGIN NOW And wearied with an unsuccessful war) END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd to raise the siege, and leave the town; END
BEGIN NOW And, had the gods permitted, they had gone; END
BEGIN NOW But oft the wintry seas and southern winds END
BEGIN NOW Withstood their passage home, and chang'd their minds. END
BEGIN NOW Portents and prodigies their souls amaz'd; END
BEGIN NOW But most, when this stupendous pile was rais'd: END
BEGIN NOW Then flaming meteors, hung in air, were seen, END
BEGIN NOW And thunders rattled thro' a sky serene. END
BEGIN NOW Dismay'd, and fearful of some dire event, END
BEGIN NOW Eurypylus t' enquire their fate was sent. END
BEGIN NOW He from the gods this dreadful answer brought: END
BEGIN NOW O Grecians, when the Trojan shores you sought, END
BEGIN NOW Your passage with a virgin's blood was bought: END
BEGIN NOW So must your safe return be bought again, END
BEGIN NOW And Grecian blood once more atone the main. END
BEGIN NOW The spreading rumor round the people ran; END
BEGIN NOW All fear'd, and each believ'd himself the man. END
BEGIN NOW Ulysses took th' advantage of their fright; END
BEGIN NOW Call'd Calchas, and produc'd in open sight: END
BEGIN NOW Then bade him name the wretch, ordain'd by fate END
BEGIN NOW The public victim, to redeem the state. END
BEGIN NOW Already some presag'd the dire event, END
BEGIN NOW And saw what sacrifice Ulysses meant. END
BEGIN NOW For twice five days the good old seer withstood END
BEGIN NOW Till, tir'd, with endless clamors and pursuit END
BEGIN NOW Of Ithacus, he stood no longer mute; END
BEGIN NOW But, as it was agreed, pronounc'd that I END
BEGIN NOW Was destin'd by the wrathful gods to die. END
BEGIN NOW All prais'd the sentence, pleas'd the storm should fall END
BEGIN NOW On one alone, whose fury threaten'd all. END
BEGIN NOW The dismal day was come; the priests prepare END
BEGIN NOW Their leaven'd cakes, and fillets for my hair. END
BEGIN NOW I follow'd nature's laws, and must avow END
BEGIN NOW I broke my bonds and fled the fatal blow. END
BEGIN NOW Hid in a weedy lake all night I lay, END
BEGIN NOW Secure of safety when they sail'd away. END
BEGIN NOW But now what further hopes for me remain, END
BEGIN NOW To see my friends, or native soil, again; END
BEGIN NOW My tender infants, or my careful sire, END
BEGIN NOW Whom they returning will to death require; END
BEGIN NOW Will perpetrate on them their first design, END
BEGIN NOW And take the forfeit of their heads for mine? END
BEGIN NOW Which, O! if pity mortal minds can move, END
BEGIN NOW If there be faith below, or gods above, END
BEGIN NOW If innocence and truth can claim desert, END
BEGIN NOW Ye Trojans, from an injur'd wretch avert.' END
BEGIN NOW False tears true pity move; the king commands END
BEGIN NOW To loose his fetters, and unbind his hands: END
BEGIN NOW Then adds these friendly words: 'Dismiss thy fears; END
BEGIN NOW Forget the Greeks; be mine as thou wert theirs. END
BEGIN NOW But truly tell, was it for force or guile, END
BEGIN NOW Or some religious end, you rais'd the pile?' END
BEGIN NOW Thus said the king. He, full of fraudful arts, END
BEGIN NOW This well-invented tale for truth imparts: END
BEGIN NOW 'Ye lamps of heav'n!' he said, and lifted high END
BEGIN NOW His hands now free, 'thou venerable sky! END
BEGIN NOW Inviolable pow'rs, ador'd with dread! END
BEGIN NOW Ye fatal fillets, that once bound this head! END
BEGIN NOW Ye sacred altars, from whose flames I fled! END
BEGIN NOW Be all of you adjur'd; and grant I may, END
BEGIN NOW Without a crime, th' ungrateful Greeks betray, END
BEGIN NOW Reveal the secrets of the guilty state, END
BEGIN NOW And justly punish whom I justly hate! END
BEGIN NOW But you, O king, preserve the faith you gave, END
BEGIN NOW If I, to save myself, your empire save. END
BEGIN NOW The Grecian hopes, and all th' attempts they made, END
BEGIN NOW Were only founded on Minerva's aid. END
BEGIN NOW But from the time when impious Diomede, END
BEGIN NOW And false Ulysses, that inventive head, END
BEGIN NOW Her fatal image from the temple drew, END
BEGIN NOW The sleeping guardians of the castle slew, END
BEGIN NOW Her virgin statue with their bloody hands END
BEGIN NOW Polluted, and profan'd her holy bands; END
BEGIN NOW From thence the tide of fortune left their shore, END
BEGIN NOW And ebb'd much faster than it flow'd before: END
BEGIN NOW Their courage languish'd, as their hopes decay'd; END
BEGIN NOW And Pallas, now averse, refus'd her aid. END
BEGIN NOW Nor did the goddess doubtfully declare END
BEGIN NOW Her alter'd mind and alienated care. END
BEGIN NOW When first her fatal image touch'd the ground, END
BEGIN NOW She sternly cast her glaring eyes around, END
BEGIN NOW That sparkled as they roll'd, and seem'd to threat: END
BEGIN NOW Her heav'nly limbs distill'd a briny sweat. END
BEGIN NOW Thrice from the ground she leap'd, was seen to wield END
BEGIN NOW Her brandish'd lance, and shake her horrid shield. END
BEGIN NOW Then Calchas bade our host for flight END
BEGIN NOW And hope no conquest from the tedious war, END
BEGIN NOW Till first they sail'd for Greece; with pray'rs besought END
BEGIN NOW Her injur'd pow'r, and better omens brought. END
BEGIN NOW And now their navy plows the wat'ry main, END
BEGIN NOW Yet soon expect it on your shores again, END
BEGIN NOW With Pallas pleas'd; as Calchas did ordain. END
BEGIN NOW But first, to reconcile the blue-ey'd maid END
BEGIN NOW For her stol'n statue and her tow'r betray'd, END
BEGIN NOW Warn'd by the seer, to her offended name END
BEGIN NOW We rais'd and dedicate this wondrous frame, END
BEGIN NOW So lofty, lest thro' your forbidden gates END
BEGIN NOW It pass, and intercept our better fates: END
BEGIN NOW For, once admitted there, our hopes are lost; END
BEGIN NOW And Troy may then a new Palladium boast; END
BEGIN NOW For so religion and the gods ordain, END
BEGIN NOW That, if you violate with hands profane END
BEGIN NOW Minerva's gift, your town in flames shall burn, END
BEGIN NOW (Which omen, O ye gods, on Graecia turn!) END
BEGIN NOW But if it climb, with your assisting hands, END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan walls, and in the city stands; END
BEGIN NOW Then Troy shall Argos and Mycenae burn, END
BEGIN NOW And the reverse of fate on us return.' END
BEGIN NOW With such deceits he gain'd their easy hearts, END
BEGIN NOW Too prone to credit his perfidious arts. END
BEGIN NOW What Diomede, nor Thetis' greater son, END
BEGIN NOW A thousand ships, nor ten years' siege, had done- END
BEGIN NOW False tears and fawning words the city won. END
BEGIN NOW A greater omen, and of worse portent, END
BEGIN NOW Did our unwary minds with fear torment, END
BEGIN NOW Concurring to produce the dire event. END
BEGIN NOW Laocoon, Neptune's priest by lot that year, END
BEGIN NOW With solemn pomp then sacrific'd a steer; END
BEGIN NOW When, dreadful to behold, from sea we spied END
BEGIN NOW Two serpents, rank'd abreast, the seas divide, END
BEGIN NOW And smoothly sweep along the swelling tide. END
BEGIN NOW Their flaming crests above the waves they show; END
BEGIN NOW Their bellies seem to burn the seas below; END
BEGIN NOW Their speckled tails advance to steer their course, END
BEGIN NOW And on the sounding shore the flying billows force. END
BEGIN NOW And now the strand, and now the plain they held; END
BEGIN NOW Their ardent eyes with bloody streaks were fill'd; END
BEGIN NOW Their nimble tongues they brandish'd as they came, END
BEGIN NOW And lick'd their hissing jaws, that sputter'd flame. END
BEGIN NOW We fled amaz'd; their destin'd way they take, END
BEGIN NOW And to Laocoon and his children make; END
BEGIN NOW And first around the tender boys they wind, END
BEGIN NOW Then with their sharpen'd fangs their limbs and bodies grind. END
BEGIN NOW The wretched father, running to their aid END
BEGIN NOW With pious haste, but vain, they next invade; END
BEGIN NOW Twice round his waist their winding volumes roll'd; END
BEGIN NOW And twice about his gasping throat they fold. END
BEGIN NOW The priest thus doubly chok'd, their crests divide, END
BEGIN NOW And tow'ring o'er his head in triumph ride. END
BEGIN NOW With both his hands he labors at the knots; END
BEGIN NOW His holy fillets the blue venom blots; END
BEGIN NOW His roaring fills the flitting air around. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, when an ox receives a glancing wound, END
BEGIN NOW He breaks his bands, the fatal altar flies, END
BEGIN NOW And with loud bellowings breaks the yielding skies. END
BEGIN NOW Their tasks perform'd, the serpents quit their prey, END
BEGIN NOW And to the tow'r of Pallas make their way: END
BEGIN NOW Couch'd at her feet, they lie protected there END
BEGIN NOW By her large buckler and protended spear. END
BEGIN NOW Amazement seizes all; the gen'ral cry END
BEGIN NOW Proclaims Laocoon justly doom'd to die, END
BEGIN NOW Whose hand the will of Pallas had withstood, END
BEGIN NOW And dared to violate the sacred wood. END
BEGIN NOW All vote t' admit the steed, that vows be paid END
BEGIN NOW And incense offer'd to th' offended maid. END
BEGIN NOW A spacious breach is made; the town lies bare; END
BEGIN NOW Some hoisting-levers, some the wheels prepare END
BEGIN NOW And fasten to the horse's feet; the rest END
BEGIN NOW With cables haul along th' unwieldly beast. END
BEGIN NOW Each on his fellow for assistance calls; END
BEGIN NOW At length the fatal fabric mounts the walls, END
BEGIN NOW Big with destruction. Boys with chaplets crown'd, END
BEGIN NOW And choirs of virgins, sing and dance around. END
BEGIN NOW Thus rais'd aloft, and then descending down, END
BEGIN NOW It enters o'er our heads, and threats the town. END
BEGIN NOW O sacred city, built by hands divine! END
BEGIN NOW O valiant heroes of the Trojan line! END
BEGIN NOW Four times he struck: as oft the clashing sound END
BEGIN NOW Of arms was heard, and inward groans rebound. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, mad with zeal, and blinded with our fate, END
BEGIN NOW We haul along the horse in solemn state; END
BEGIN NOW Then place the dire portent within the tow'r. END
BEGIN NOW Cassandra cried, and curs'd th' unhappy hour; END
BEGIN NOW Foretold our fate; but, by the god's decree, END
BEGIN NOW All heard, and none believ'd the prophecy. END
BEGIN NOW With branches we the fanes adorn, and waste, END
BEGIN NOW In jollity, the day ordain'd to be the last. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the rapid heav'ns roll'd down the light, END
BEGIN NOW And on the shaded ocean rush'd the night; END
BEGIN NOW Our men, secure, nor guards nor sentries held, END
BEGIN NOW But easy sleep their weary limbs compell'd. END
BEGIN NOW The Grecians had embark'd their naval pow'rs END
BEGIN NOW From Tenedos, and sought our well-known shores, END
BEGIN NOW Safe under covert of the silent night, END
BEGIN NOW And guided by th' imperial galley's light; END
BEGIN NOW When Sinon, favor'd by the partial gods, END
BEGIN NOW Unlock'd the horse, and op'd his dark abodes; END
BEGIN NOW Restor'd to vital air our hidden foes, END
BEGIN NOW Who joyful from their long confinement rose. END
BEGIN NOW Tysander bold, and Sthenelus their guide, END
BEGIN NOW And dire Ulysses down the cable slide: END
BEGIN NOW Then Thoas, Athamas, and Pyrrhus haste; END
BEGIN NOW Nor was the Podalirian hero last, END
BEGIN NOW Nor injur'd Menelaus, nor the fam'd END
BEGIN NOW Epeus, who the fatal engine fram'd. END
BEGIN NOW A nameless crowd succeed; their forces join END
BEGIN NOW T' invade the town, oppress'd with sleep and wine. END
BEGIN NOW Those few they find awake first meet their fate; END
BEGIN NOW Then to their fellows they unbar the gate. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was in the dead of night, when sleep repairs END
BEGIN NOW Our bodies worn with toils, our minds with cares, END
BEGIN NOW When Hector's ghost before my sight appears: END
BEGIN NOW A bloody shroud he seem'd, and bath'd in tears; END
BEGIN NOW Such as he was, when, by Pelides slain, END
BEGIN NOW Thessalian coursers dragg'd him o'er the plain. END
BEGIN NOW Swoln were his feet, as when the thongs were thrust END
BEGIN NOW Thro' the bor'd holes; his body black with dust; END
BEGIN NOW Unlike that Hector who return'd from toils END
BEGIN NOW Of war, triumphant, in Aeacian spoils, END
BEGIN NOW Or him who made the fainting Greeks retire, END
BEGIN NOW And launch'd against their navy Phrygian fire. END
BEGIN NOW His hair and beard stood stiffen'd with his gore; END
BEGIN NOW And all the wounds he for his country bore END
BEGIN NOW Now stream'd afresh, and with new purple ran. END
BEGIN NOW I wept to see the visionary man, END
BEGIN NOW And, while my trance continued, thus began: END
BEGIN NOW 'O light of Trojans, and support of Troy, END
BEGIN NOW Thy father's champion, and thy country's joy! END
BEGIN NOW O, long expected by thy friends! from whence END
BEGIN NOW Art thou so late return'd for our defense? END
BEGIN NOW Do we behold thee, wearied as we are END
BEGIN NOW With length of labors, and with toils of war? END
BEGIN NOW After so many fun'rals of thy own END
BEGIN NOW Art thou restor'd to thy declining town? END
BEGIN NOW But say, what wounds are these? What new disgrace END
BEGIN NOW Deforms the manly features of thy face?' END
BEGIN NOW To this the specter no reply did frame, END
BEGIN NOW But answer'd to the cause for which he came, END
BEGIN NOW And, groaning from the bottom of his breast, END
BEGIN NOW This warning in these mournful words express'd: END
BEGIN NOW 'O goddess-born! escape, by timely flight, END
BEGIN NOW The flames and horrors of this fatal night. END
BEGIN NOW The foes already have possess'd the wall; END
BEGIN NOW Troy nods from high, and totters to her fall. END
BEGIN NOW Enough is paid to Priam's royal name, END
BEGIN NOW More than enough to duty and to fame. END
BEGIN NOW If by a mortal hand my father's throne END
BEGIN NOW Could be defended, 't was by mine alone. END
BEGIN NOW Now Troy to thee commends her future state, END
BEGIN NOW And gives her gods companions of thy fate: END
BEGIN NOW From their assistance walls expect, END
BEGIN NOW Which, wand'ring long, at last thou shalt erect.' END
BEGIN NOW He said, and brought me, from their blest abodes, END
BEGIN NOW The venerable statues of the gods, END
BEGIN NOW With ancient Vesta from the sacred choir, END
BEGIN NOW The wreaths and relics of th' immortal fire. END
BEGIN NOW Now peals of shouts come thund'ring from afar, END
BEGIN NOW Cries, threats, and loud laments, and mingled war: END
BEGIN NOW The noise approaches, tho' our palace stood END
BEGIN NOW Aloof from streets, encompass'd with a wood. END
BEGIN NOW Louder, and yet more loud, I hear th' alarms END
BEGIN NOW Of human cries distinct, and clashing arms. END
BEGIN NOW Fear broke my slumbers; I no longer stay, END
BEGIN NOW But mount the terrace, thence the town survey, END
BEGIN NOW And hearken what the frightful sounds convey. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, when a flood of fire by wind is borne, END
BEGIN NOW Crackling it rolls, and mows the standing corn; END
BEGIN NOW Or deluges, descending on the plains, END
BEGIN NOW Sweep o'er the yellow year, destroy the pains END
BEGIN NOW Of lab'ring oxen and the peasant's gains; END
BEGIN NOW Unroot the forest oaks, and bear away END
BEGIN NOW Flocks, folds, and trees, and undistinguish'd prey: END
BEGIN NOW The shepherd climbs the cliff, and sees from far END
BEGIN NOW The wasteful ravage of the wat'ry war. END
BEGIN NOW Then Hector's faith was manifestly clear'd, END
BEGIN NOW And Grecian frauds in open light appear'd. END
BEGIN NOW The palace of Deiphobus ascends END
BEGIN NOW In smoky flames, and catches on his friends. END
BEGIN NOW Ucalegon burns next: the seas are bright END
BEGIN NOW With splendor not their own, and shine with Trojan light. END
BEGIN NOW New clamors and new clangors now arise, END
BEGIN NOW The sound of trumpets mix'd with fighting cries. END
BEGIN NOW With frenzy seiz'd, I run to meet th' alarms, END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd on death, resolv'd to die in arms, END
BEGIN NOW But first to gather friends, with them t' oppose END
BEGIN NOW (If fortune favor'd) and repel the foes; END
BEGIN NOW Spurr'd by my courage, by my country fir'd, END
BEGIN NOW With sense of honor and revenge inspir'd. END
BEGIN NOW Pantheus, Apollo's priest, a sacred name, END
BEGIN NOW Had scap'd the Grecian swords, and pass'd the flame: END
BEGIN NOW With relics loaden. to my doors he fled, END
BEGIN NOW And by the hand his tender grandson led. END
BEGIN NOW 'What hope, O Pantheus? whither can we run? END
BEGIN NOW Where make a stand? and what may yet be done?' END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had I said, when Pantheus, with a groan: END
BEGIN NOW 'Troy is no more, and Ilium was a town! END
BEGIN NOW The fatal day, th' appointed hour, is come, END
BEGIN NOW When wrathful Jove's irrevocable doom END
BEGIN NOW Transfers the Trojan state to Grecian hands. END
BEGIN NOW The fire consumes the town, the foe commands; END
BEGIN NOW And armed hosts, an unexpected force, END
BEGIN NOW Break from the bowels of the fatal horse. END
BEGIN NOW Within the gates, proud Sinon throws about END
BEGIN NOW The flames; and foes for entrance press without, END
BEGIN NOW With thousand others, whom I fear to name, END
BEGIN NOW More than from Argos or Mycenae came. END
BEGIN NOW To sev'ral posts their parties they divide; END
BEGIN NOW Some block the narrow streets, some scour the wide: END
BEGIN NOW The bold they kill, th' unwary they surprise; END
BEGIN NOW Who fights finds death, and death finds him who flies. END
BEGIN NOW The warders of the gate but scarce maintain END
BEGIN NOW Th' unequal combat, and resist in vain.' END
BEGIN NOW I heard; and Heav'n, that well-born souls inspires, END
BEGIN NOW Prompts me thro' lifted swords and rising fires END
BEGIN NOW To run where clashing arms and clamor calls, END
BEGIN NOW And rush undaunted to defend the walls. END
BEGIN NOW Ripheus and Iph'itus by my side engage, END
BEGIN NOW For valor one renown'd, and one for age. END
BEGIN NOW Dymas and Hypanis by moonlight knew END
BEGIN NOW My motions and my mien, and to my party drew; END
BEGIN NOW With young Coroebus, who by love was led END
BEGIN NOW To win renown and fair Cassandra's bed, END
BEGIN NOW And lately brought his troops to Priam's aid, END
BEGIN NOW Forewarn'd in vain by the prophetic maid. END
BEGIN NOW Whom when I saw resolv'd in arms to fall, END
BEGIN NOW And that one spirit animated all: END
BEGIN NOW 'Brave souls!' said I,- 'but brave, alas! in vain- END
BEGIN NOW Come, finish what our cruel fates ordain. END
BEGIN NOW You see the desp'rate state of our affairs, END
BEGIN NOW And heav'n's protecting pow'rs are deaf to pray'rs. END
BEGIN NOW The passive gods behold the Greeks defile END
BEGIN NOW Their temples, and abandon to the spoil END
BEGIN NOW Their own abodes: we, feeble few, conspire END
BEGIN NOW To save a sinking town, involv'd in fire. END
BEGIN NOW Then let us fall, but fall amidst our foes: END
BEGIN NOW Despair of life the means of living shows.' END
BEGIN NOW So bold a speech incourag'd their desire END
BEGIN NOW Of death, and added fuel to their fire. END
BEGIN NOW As hungry wolves, with raging appetite, END
BEGIN NOW Scour thro' the fields, nor fear the stormy night- END
BEGIN NOW Their whelps at home expect the promis'd food, END
BEGIN NOW And long to temper their dry chaps in blood- END
BEGIN NOW So rush'd we forth at once; resolv'd to die, END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd, in death, the last extremes to try. END
BEGIN NOW We leave the narrow lanes behind, and dare END
BEGIN NOW Th' unequal combat in the public square: END
BEGIN NOW Night was our friend; our leader was despair. END
BEGIN NOW What tongue can tell the slaughter of that night? END
BEGIN NOW What eyes can weep the sorrows and affright? END
BEGIN NOW An ancient and imperial city falls: END
BEGIN NOW The streets are fill'd with frequent funerals; END
BEGIN NOW Houses and holy temples float in blood, END
BEGIN NOW And hostile nations make a common flood. END
BEGIN NOW Not only Trojans fall; but, in their turn, END
BEGIN NOW The vanquish'd triumph, and the victors mourn. END
BEGIN NOW Ours take new courage from despair and night: END
BEGIN NOW Confus'd the fortune is, confus'd the fight. END
BEGIN NOW All parts resound with tumults, plaints, and fears; END
BEGIN NOW And grisly Death in sundry shapes appears. END
BEGIN NOW Androgeos fell among us, with his band, END
BEGIN NOW Who thought us Grecians newly come to land. END
BEGIN NOW 'From whence,' said he, 'my friends, this long delay? END
BEGIN NOW You loiter, while the spoils are borne away: END
BEGIN NOW Our ships are laden with the Trojan store; END
BEGIN NOW And you, like truants, come too late ashore.' END
BEGIN NOW He said, but soon corrected his mistake, END
BEGIN NOW Found, by the doubtful answers which we make: END
BEGIN NOW Amaz'd, he would have shunn'd th' unequal fight; END
BEGIN NOW But we, more num'rous, intercept his flight. END
BEGIN NOW As when some peasant, in a bushy brake, END
BEGIN NOW Has with unwary footing press'd a snake; END
BEGIN NOW He starts aside, astonish'd, when he spies END
BEGIN NOW His rising crest, blue neck, and rolling eyes; END
BEGIN NOW So from our arms surpris'd Androgeos flies. END
BEGIN NOW In vain; for him and his we compass'd round, END
BEGIN NOW Possess'd with fear, unknowing of the ground, END
BEGIN NOW And of their lives an easy conquest found. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Fortune on our first endeavor smil'd. END
BEGIN NOW Coroebus then, with youthful hopes beguil'd, END
BEGIN NOW Swoln with success, and a daring mind, END
BEGIN NOW This new invention fatally design'd. END
BEGIN NOW 'My friends,' said he, 'since Fortune shows the way, END
BEGIN NOW 'T is fit we should th' auspicious guide obey. END
BEGIN NOW For what has she these Grecian arms bestow'd, END
BEGIN NOW But their destruction, and the Trojans' good? END
BEGIN NOW Then change we shields, and their devices bear: END
BEGIN NOW Let fraud supply the want of force in war. END
BEGIN NOW They find us arms.' This said, himself he dress'd END
BEGIN NOW In dead Androgeos' spoils, his upper vest, END
BEGIN NOW His painted buckler, and his plumy crest. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Ripheus, Dymas, all the Trojan train, END
BEGIN NOW Lay down their own attire, and strip the slain. END
BEGIN NOW Mix'd with the Greeks, we go with ill presage, END
BEGIN NOW Flatter'd with hopes to glut our greedy rage; END
BEGIN NOW Unknown, assaulting whom we blindly meet, END
BEGIN NOW And strew with Grecian carcasses the street. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while their straggling parties we defeat, END
BEGIN NOW Some to the shore and safer ships retreat; END
BEGIN NOW And some, oppress'd with more ignoble fear, END
BEGIN NOW Remount the hollow horse, and pant in secret there. END
BEGIN NOW But, ah! what use of valor can be made, END
BEGIN NOW When heav'n's propitious pow'rs refuse their aid! END
BEGIN NOW Behold the royal prophetess, the fair END
BEGIN NOW Cassandra, dragg'd by her dishevel'd hair, END
BEGIN NOW Whom not Minerva's shrine, nor sacred bands, END
BEGIN NOW In safety could protect from sacrilegious hands: END
BEGIN NOW On heav'n she cast her eyes, she sigh'd, she cried- END
BEGIN NOW 'T was all she could- her tender arms were tied. END
BEGIN NOW So sad a sight Coroebus could not bear; END
BEGIN NOW But, fir'd with rage, distracted with despair, END
BEGIN NOW Amid the barb'rous ravishers he flew: END
BEGIN NOW Our leader's rash example we pursue. END
BEGIN NOW But storms of stones, from the proud temple's height, END
BEGIN NOW Pour down, and on our batter'd helms alight: END
BEGIN NOW We from our friends receiv'd this fatal blow, END
BEGIN NOW Who thought us Grecians, as we seem'd in show. END
BEGIN NOW They aim at the mistaken crests, from high; END
BEGIN NOW And ours beneath the pond'rous ruin lie. END
BEGIN NOW Then, mov'd with anger and disdain, to see END
BEGIN NOW Their troops dispers'd, the royal virgin free, END
BEGIN NOW The Grecians rally, and their pow'rs unite, END
BEGIN NOW With fury charge us, and renew the fight. END
BEGIN NOW The brother kings with Ajax join their force, END
BEGIN NOW And the whole squadron of Thessalian horse. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, when the rival winds their quarrel try, END
BEGIN NOW Contending for the kingdom of the sky, END
BEGIN NOW South, east, and west, on airy coursers borne; END
BEGIN NOW The whirlwind gathers, and the woods are torn: END
BEGIN NOW Then Nereus strikes the deep; the billows rise, END
BEGIN NOW And, mix'd with ooze and sand, pollute the skies. END
BEGIN NOW The troops we squander'd first again appear END
BEGIN NOW From several quarters, and enclose the rear. END
BEGIN NOW They first observe, and to the rest betray, END
BEGIN NOW Our diff'rent speech; our borrow'd arms survey. END
BEGIN NOW Oppress'd with odds, we fall; Coroebus first, END
BEGIN NOW At Pallas' altar, by Peneleus pierc'd. END
BEGIN NOW Then Ripheus follow'd, in th' unequal fight; END
BEGIN NOW Just of his word, observant of the right: END
BEGIN NOW Heav'n thought not so. Dymas their fate attends, END
BEGIN NOW With Hypanis, mistaken by their friends. END
BEGIN NOW Nor, Pantheus, thee, thy miter, nor the bands END
BEGIN NOW Of awful Phoebus, sav'd from impious hands. END
BEGIN NOW Ye Trojan flames, your testimony bear, END
BEGIN NOW What I perform'd, and what I suffer'd there; END
BEGIN NOW No sword avoiding in the fatal strife, END
BEGIN NOW Expos'd to death, and prodigal of life; END
BEGIN NOW Witness, ye heavens! I live not by my fault: END
BEGIN NOW I strove to have deserv'd the death I sought. END
BEGIN NOW But, when I could not fight, and would have died, END
BEGIN NOW Borne off to distance by the growing tide, END
BEGIN NOW Old Iphitus and I were hurried thence, END
BEGIN NOW With Pelias wounded, and without defense. END
BEGIN NOW New clamors from th' invested palace ring: END
BEGIN NOW We run to die, or disengage the king. END
BEGIN NOW So hot th' assault, so high the tumult rose, END
BEGIN NOW While ours defend, and while the Greeks oppose END
BEGIN NOW As all the Dardan and Argolic race END
BEGIN NOW Had been contracted in that narrow space; END
BEGIN NOW Or as all Ilium else were void of fear, END
BEGIN NOW And tumult, war, and slaughter, only there. END
BEGIN NOW Their targets in a tortoise cast, the foes, END
BEGIN NOW Secure advancing, to the turrets rose: END
BEGIN NOW Some mount the scaling ladders; some, more bold, END
BEGIN NOW Swerve upwards, and by posts and pillars hold; END
BEGIN NOW Their left hand gripes their bucklers in th' ascent, END
BEGIN NOW While with their right they seize the battlement. END
BEGIN NOW From their demolish'd tow'rs the Trojans throw END
BEGIN NOW Huge heaps of stones, that, falling, crush the foe; END
BEGIN NOW And heavy beams and rafters from the sides END
BEGIN NOW (Such arms their last necessity provides) END
BEGIN NOW And gilded roofs, come tumbling from on high, END
BEGIN NOW The marks of state and ancient royalty. END
BEGIN NOW The guards below, fix'd in the pass, attend END
BEGIN NOW The charge undaunted, and the gate defend. END
BEGIN NOW Renew'd in courage with recover'd breath, END
BEGIN NOW A second time we ran to tempt our death, END
BEGIN NOW To clear the palace from the foe, succeed END
BEGIN NOW The weary living, and revenge the dead. END
BEGIN NOW A postern door, yet unobserv'd and free, END
BEGIN NOW Join'd by the length of a blind gallery, END
BEGIN NOW To the king's closet led: a way well known END
BEGIN NOW To Hector's wife, while Priam held the throne, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' which she brought Astyanax, unseen, END
BEGIN NOW To cheer his grandsire and his grandsire's queen. END
BEGIN NOW Thro' this we pass, and mount the tow'r, from whence END
BEGIN NOW With unavailing arms the Trojans make defense. END
BEGIN NOW From this the trembling king had oft descried END
BEGIN NOW The Grecian camp, and saw their navy ride. END
BEGIN NOW Beams from its lofty height with swords we hew, END
BEGIN NOW Then, wrenching with our hands, th' assault renew; END
BEGIN NOW And, where the rafters on the columns meet, END
BEGIN NOW We push them headlong with our arms and feet. END
BEGIN NOW The lightning flies not swifter than the fall, END
BEGIN NOW Nor thunder louder than the ruin'd wall: END
BEGIN NOW Down goes the top at once; the Greeks beneath END
BEGIN NOW Are piecemeal torn, or pounded into death. END
BEGIN NOW Yet more succeed, and more to death are sent; END
BEGIN NOW We cease not from above, nor they below relent. END
BEGIN NOW Before the gate stood Pyrrhus, threat'ning loud, END
BEGIN NOW With glitt'ring arms conspicuous in the crowd. END
BEGIN NOW So shines, renew'd in youth, the crested snake, END
BEGIN NOW Who slept the winter in a thorny brake, END
BEGIN NOW And, casting off his slough when spring returns, END
BEGIN NOW Now looks aloft, and with new glory burns; END
BEGIN NOW Restor'd with poisonous herbs, his ardent sides END
BEGIN NOW Reflect the sun; and rais'd on spires he rides; END
BEGIN NOW High o'er the grass, hissing he rolls along, END
BEGIN NOW And brandishes by fits his forky tongue. END
BEGIN NOW Proud Periphas, and fierce Automedon, END
BEGIN NOW His father's charioteer, together run END
BEGIN NOW To force the gate; the Scyrian infantry END
BEGIN NOW Rush on in crowds, and the barr'd passage free. END
BEGIN NOW Ent'ring the court, with shouts the skies they rend; END
BEGIN NOW And flaming firebrands to the roofs ascend. END
BEGIN NOW Himself, among the foremost, deals his blows, END
BEGIN NOW And with his ax repeated strokes bestows END
BEGIN NOW On the strong doors; then all their shoulders ply, END
BEGIN NOW Till from the posts the brazen hinges fly. END
BEGIN NOW He hews apace; the double bars at length END
BEGIN NOW Yield to his ax and unresisted strength. END
BEGIN NOW A mighty breach is made: the rooms conceal'd END
BEGIN NOW Appear, and all the palace is reveal'd; END
BEGIN NOW The halls of audience, and of public state, END
BEGIN NOW And where the lonely queen in secret sate. END
BEGIN NOW Arm'd soldiers now by trembling maids are seen, END
BEGIN NOW With not a door, and scarce a space, between. END
BEGIN NOW The house is fill'd with loud laments and cries, END
BEGIN NOW And shrieks of women rend the vaulted skies; END
BEGIN NOW The fearful matrons run from place to place, END
BEGIN NOW And kiss the thresholds, and the posts embrace. END
BEGIN NOW The fatal work inhuman Pyrrhus plies, END
BEGIN NOW And all his father sparkles in his eyes; END
BEGIN NOW Nor bars, nor fighting guards, his force sustain: END
BEGIN NOW The bars are broken, and the guards are slain. END
BEGIN NOW In rush the Greeks, and all the apartments fill; END
BEGIN NOW Those few defendants whom they find, they kill. END
BEGIN NOW Not with so fierce a rage the foaming flood END
BEGIN NOW Roars, when he finds his rapid course withstood; END
BEGIN NOW Bears down the dams with unresisted sway, END
BEGIN NOW And sweeps the cattle and the cots away. END
BEGIN NOW These eyes beheld him when he march'd between END
BEGIN NOW The brother kings: I saw th' unhappy queen, END
BEGIN NOW The hundred wives, and where old Priam stood, END
BEGIN NOW To stain his hallow'd altar with his brood. END
BEGIN NOW The fifty nuptial beds (such hopes had he, END
BEGIN NOW So large a promise, of a progeny), END
BEGIN NOW The posts, of plated gold, and hung with spoils, END
BEGIN NOW Fell the reward of the proud victor's toils. END
BEGIN NOW Where'er the raging fire had left a space, END
BEGIN NOW The Grecians enter and possess the place. END
BEGIN NOW Perhaps you may of Priam's fate enquire. END
BEGIN NOW He, when he saw his regal town on fire, END
BEGIN NOW His ruin'd palace, and his ent'ring foes, END
BEGIN NOW On ev'ry side inevitable woes, END
BEGIN NOW In arms, disus'd, invests his limbs, decay'd, END
BEGIN NOW Like them, with age; a late and useless aid. END
BEGIN NOW His feeble shoulders scarce the weight sustain; END
BEGIN NOW Loaded, not arm'd, he creeps along with pain, END
BEGIN NOW Despairing of success, ambitious to be slain! END
BEGIN NOW Uncover'd but by heav'n, there stood in view END
BEGIN NOW An altar; near the hearth a laurel grew, END
BEGIN NOW Dodder'd with age, whose boughs encompass round END
BEGIN NOW The household gods, and shade the holy ground. END
BEGIN NOW Here Hecuba, with all her helpless train END
BEGIN NOW Of dames, for shelter sought, but sought in vain. END
BEGIN NOW Driv'n like a flock of doves along the sky, END
BEGIN NOW Their images they hug, and to their altars fly. END
BEGIN NOW The Queen, when she beheld her trembling lord, END
BEGIN NOW And hanging by his side a heavy sword, END
BEGIN NOW 'What rage,' she cried, 'has seiz'd my husband's mind? END
BEGIN NOW What arms are these, and to what use design'd? END
BEGIN NOW These times want other aids! Were Hector here, END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n Hector now in vain, like Priam, would appear. END
BEGIN NOW With us, one common shelter thou shalt find, END
BEGIN NOW Or in one common fate with us be join'd.' END
BEGIN NOW She said, and with a last salute embrac'd END
BEGIN NOW The poor old man, and by the laurel plac'd. END
BEGIN NOW Behold! Polites, one of Priam's sons, END
BEGIN NOW Pursued by Pyrrhus, there for safety runs. END
BEGIN NOW Thro' swords and foes, amaz'd and hurt, he flies END
BEGIN NOW Thro' empty courts and open galleries. END
BEGIN NOW Him Pyrrhus, urging with his lance, pursues, END
BEGIN NOW And often reaches, and his thrusts renews. END
BEGIN NOW The youth, transfix'd, with lamentable cries, END
BEGIN NOW Expires before his wretched parent's eyes: END
BEGIN NOW Whom gasping at his feet when Priam saw, END
BEGIN NOW The fear of death gave place to nature's law; END
BEGIN NOW And, shaking more with anger than with age, END
BEGIN NOW 'The gods,' said he, 'requite thy brutal rage! END
BEGIN NOW As sure they will, barbarian, sure they must, END
BEGIN NOW If there be gods in heav'n, and gods be just- END
BEGIN NOW Who tak'st in wrongs an insolent delight; END
BEGIN NOW With a son's death t' infect a father's sight. END
BEGIN NOW Not he, whom thou and lying fame conspire END
BEGIN NOW To call thee his- not he, thy vaunted sire, END
BEGIN NOW Thus us'd my wretched age: the gods he fear'd, END
BEGIN NOW The laws of nature and of nations heard. END
BEGIN NOW He cheer'd my sorrows, and, for sums of gold, END
BEGIN NOW The bloodless carcass of my Hector sold; END
BEGIN NOW Pitied the woes a parent underwent, END
BEGIN NOW And sent me back in safety from his tent.' END
BEGIN NOW This said, his feeble hand a javelin threw, END
BEGIN NOW Which, flutt'ring, seem'd to loiter as it flew: END
BEGIN NOW Just, and but barely, to the mark it held, END
BEGIN NOW And faintly tinkled on the brazen shield. END
BEGIN NOW Then Pyrrhus thus: 'Go thou from me to fate, END
BEGIN NOW And to my father my foul deeds relate. END
BEGIN NOW Now die!' With that he dragg'd the trembling sire, END
BEGIN NOW Slidd'ring thro' clotter'd blood and holy mire, END
BEGIN NOW (The mingled paste his murder'd son had made,) END
BEGIN NOW Haul'd from beneath the violated shade, END
BEGIN NOW And on the sacred pile the royal victim laid. END
BEGIN NOW His right hand held his bloody falchion bare, END
BEGIN NOW His left he twisted in his hoary hair; END
BEGIN NOW Then, with a speeding thrust, his heart he found: END
BEGIN NOW The lukewarm blood came rushing thro' the wound, END
BEGIN NOW And sanguine streams distain'd the sacred ground. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Priam fell, and shar'd one common fate END
BEGIN NOW With Troy in ashes, and his ruin'd state: END
BEGIN NOW He, who the scepter of all Asia sway'd, END
BEGIN NOW Whom monarchs like domestic slaves obey'd. END
BEGIN NOW On the bleak shore now lies th' abandon'd king, END
BEGIN NOW A headless carcass, and a nameless thing. END
BEGIN NOW Then, not before, I felt my cruddled blood END
BEGIN NOW Congeal with fear, my hair with horror stood: END
BEGIN NOW My father's image fill'd my pious mind, END
BEGIN NOW Lest equal years might equal fortune find. END
BEGIN NOW Again I thought on my forsaken wife, END
BEGIN NOW And trembled for my son's abandon'd life. END
BEGIN NOW I look'd about, but found myself alone, END
BEGIN NOW Deserted at my need! My friends were gone. END
BEGIN NOW Some spent with toil, some with despair oppress'd, END
BEGIN NOW Leap'd headlong from the heights; the flames consum'd the rest. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, wand'ring in my way, without a guide, END
BEGIN NOW The graceless Helen in the porch I spied END
BEGIN NOW Of Vesta's temple; there she lurk'd alone; END
BEGIN NOW Muffled she sate, and, what she could, unknown: END
BEGIN NOW But, by the flames that cast their blaze around, END
BEGIN NOW That common bane of Greece and Troy I found. END
BEGIN NOW For Ilium burnt, she dreads the Trojan sword; END
BEGIN NOW More dreads the vengeance of her injur'd lord; END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n by those gods who refug'd her abhorr'd. END
BEGIN NOW Trembling with rage, the strumpet I regard, END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd to give her guilt the due reward: END
BEGIN NOW 'Shall she triumphant sail before the wind, END
BEGIN NOW And leave in flames unhappy Troy behind? END
BEGIN NOW Shall she her kingdom and her friends review, END
BEGIN NOW In state attended with a captive crew, END
BEGIN NOW While unreveng'd the good old Priam falls, END
BEGIN NOW And Grecian fires consume the Trojan walls? END
BEGIN NOW For this the Phrygian fields and Xanthian flood END
BEGIN NOW Were swell'd with bodies, and were drunk with blood? END
BEGIN NOW 'T is true, a soldier can small honor gain, END
BEGIN NOW And boast no conquest, from a woman slain: END
BEGIN NOW Yet shall the fact not pass without applause, END
BEGIN NOW Of vengeance taken in so just a cause; END
BEGIN NOW The punish'd crime shall set my soul at ease, END
BEGIN NOW And murm'ring manes of my friends appease.' END
BEGIN NOW Thus while I rave, a gleam of pleasing light END
BEGIN NOW Spread o'er the place; and, shining heav'nly bright, END
BEGIN NOW My mother stood reveal'd before my sight END
BEGIN NOW Never so radiant did her eyes appear; END
BEGIN NOW Not her own star confess'd a light so clear: END
BEGIN NOW Great in her charms, as when on gods above END
BEGIN NOW She looks, and breathes herself into their love. END
BEGIN NOW She held my hand, the destin'd blow to break; END
BEGIN NOW Then from her rosy lips began to speak: END
BEGIN NOW 'My son, from whence this madness, this neglect END
BEGIN NOW Of my commands, and those whom I protect? END
BEGIN NOW Why this unmanly rage? Recall to mind END
BEGIN NOW Whom you forsake, what pledges leave behind. END
BEGIN NOW Look if your helpless father yet survive, END
BEGIN NOW Or if Ascanius or Creusa live. END
BEGIN NOW Around your house the greedy Grecians err; END
BEGIN NOW And these had perish'd in the nightly war, END
BEGIN NOW But for my presence and protecting care. END
BEGIN NOW Not Helen's face, nor Paris, was in fault; END
BEGIN NOW But by the gods was this destruction brought. END
BEGIN NOW Now cast your eyes around, while I dissolve END
BEGIN NOW The mists and films that mortal eyes involve, END
BEGIN NOW Purge from your sight the dross, and make you see END
BEGIN NOW The shape of each avenging deity. END
BEGIN NOW Enlighten'd thus, my just commands fulfil, END
BEGIN NOW Nor fear obedience to your mother's will. END
BEGIN NOW Where yon disorder'd heap of ruin lies, END
BEGIN NOW Stones rent from stones; where clouds of dust arise- END
BEGIN NOW Amid that smother Neptune holds his place, END
BEGIN NOW Below the wall's foundation drives his mace, END
BEGIN NOW And heaves the building from the solid base. END
BEGIN NOW Look where, in arms, imperial Juno stands END
BEGIN NOW Full in the Scaean gate, with loud commands, END
BEGIN NOW See! Pallas, of her snaky buckler proud, END
BEGIN NOW Bestrides the tow'r, refulgent thro' the cloud: END
BEGIN NOW See! Jove new courage to the foe supplies, END
BEGIN NOW And arms against the town the partial deities. END
BEGIN NOW Haste hence, my son; this fruitless labor end: END
BEGIN NOW Haste, where your trembling spouse and sire attend: END
BEGIN NOW Haste; and a mother's care your passage shall befriend.' END
BEGIN NOW She said, and swiftly vanish'd from my sight, END
BEGIN NOW Obscure in clouds and gloomy shades of night. END
BEGIN NOW I look'd, I listen'd; dreadful sounds I hear; END
BEGIN NOW And the dire forms of hostile gods appear. END
BEGIN NOW Troy sunk in flames I saw (nor could prevent), END
BEGIN NOW And Ilium from its old foundations rent; END
BEGIN NOW Rent like a mountain ash, which dar'd the winds, END
BEGIN NOW And stood the sturdy strokes of lab'ring hinds. END
BEGIN NOW About the roots the cruel ax resounds; END
BEGIN NOW The stumps are pierc'd with oft-repeated wounds: END
BEGIN NOW The war is felt on high; the nodding crown END
BEGIN NOW Now threats a fall, and throws the leafy honors down. END
BEGIN NOW To their united force it yields, tho' late, END
BEGIN NOW And mourns with mortal groans th' approaching fate: END
BEGIN NOW The roots no more their upper load sustain; END
BEGIN NOW But down she falls, and spreads a ruin thro' the plain. END
BEGIN NOW Descending thence, I scape thro' foes and fire: END
BEGIN NOW Before the goddess, foes and flames retire. END
BEGIN NOW Arriv'd at home, he, for whose only sake, END
BEGIN NOW Or most for his, such toils I undertake, END
BEGIN NOW The good Anchises, whom, by timely flight, END
BEGIN NOW I purpos'd to secure on Ida's height, END
BEGIN NOW Refus'd the journey, resolute to die END
BEGIN NOW And add his fun'rals to the fate of Troy, END
BEGIN NOW Rather than exile and old age sustain. END
BEGIN NOW 'Go you, whose blood runs warm in ev'ry vein. END
BEGIN NOW Had Heav'n decreed that I should life enjoy, END
BEGIN NOW Heav'n had decreed to save unhappy Troy. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is, sure, enough, if not too much, for one, END
BEGIN NOW Twice to have seen our Ilium overthrown. END
BEGIN NOW Make haste to save the poor remaining crew, END
BEGIN NOW And give this useless corpse a long adieu. END
BEGIN NOW These weak old hands suffice to stop my breath; END
BEGIN NOW At least the pitying foes will aid my death, END
BEGIN NOW To take my spoils, and leave my body bare: END
BEGIN NOW As for my sepulcher, let Heav'n take care. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is long since I, for my celestial wife END
BEGIN NOW Loath'd by the gods, have dragg'd a ling'ring life; END
BEGIN NOW Since ev'ry hour and moment I expire, END
BEGIN NOW Blasted from heav'n by Jove's avenging fire.' END
BEGIN NOW This oft repeated, he stood fix'd to die: END
BEGIN NOW Myself, my wife, my son, my family, END
BEGIN NOW Intreat, pray, beg, and raise a doleful cry- END
BEGIN NOW 'What, will he still persist, on death resolve, END
BEGIN NOW And in his ruin all his house involve!' END
BEGIN NOW He still persists his reasons to maintain; END
BEGIN NOW Our pray'rs, our tears, our loud laments, are vain. END
BEGIN NOW Urg'd by despair, again I go to try END
BEGIN NOW The fate of arms, resolv'd in fight to die: END
BEGIN NOW 'What hope remains, but what my death must give? END
BEGIN NOW Can I, without so dear a father, live? END
BEGIN NOW You term it prudence, what I baseness call: END
BEGIN NOW Could such a word from such a parent fall? END
BEGIN NOW If Fortune please, and so the gods ordain, END
BEGIN NOW That nothing should of ruin'd Troy remain, END
BEGIN NOW And you conspire with Fortune to be slain, END
BEGIN NOW The way to death is wide, th' approaches near: END
BEGIN NOW For soon relentless Pyrrhus will appear, END
BEGIN NOW Reeking with Priam's blood- the wretch who slew END
BEGIN NOW The son (inhuman) in the father's view, END
BEGIN NOW And then the sire himself to the dire altar drew. END
BEGIN NOW O goddess mother, give me back to Fate; END
BEGIN NOW Your gift was undesir'd, and came too late! END
BEGIN NOW Did you, for this, unhappy me convey END
BEGIN NOW Thro' foes and fires, to see my house a prey? END
BEGIN NOW Shall I my father, wife, and son behold, END
BEGIN NOW Welt'ring in blood, each other's arms infold? END
BEGIN NOW Haste! gird my sword, tho' spent and overcome: END
BEGIN NOW 'T is the last summons to receive our doom. END
BEGIN NOW I hear thee, Fate; and I obey thy call! END
BEGIN NOW Not unreveng'd the foe shall see my fall. END
BEGIN NOW Restore me to the yet unfinish'd fight: END
BEGIN NOW My death is wanting to conclude the night.' END
BEGIN NOW Arm'd once again, my glitt'ring sword I wield, END
BEGIN NOW While th' other hand sustains my weighty shield, END
BEGIN NOW And forth I rush to seek th' abandon'd field. END
BEGIN NOW I went; but sad Creusa stopp'd my way, END
BEGIN NOW And cross the threshold in my passage lay, END
BEGIN NOW Embrac'd my knees, and, when I would have gone, END
BEGIN NOW Shew'd me my feeble sire and tender son: END
BEGIN NOW 'If death be your design, at least,' said she, END
BEGIN NOW 'Take us along to share your destiny. END
BEGIN NOW If any farther hopes in arms remain, END
BEGIN NOW This place, these pledges of your love, maintain. END
BEGIN NOW To whom do you expose your father's life, END
BEGIN NOW Your son's, and mine, your now forgotten wife!' END
BEGIN NOW While thus she fills the house with clam'rous cries, END
BEGIN NOW Our hearing is diverted by our eyes: END
BEGIN NOW For, while I held my son, in the short space END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt our kisses and our last embrace; END
BEGIN NOW Strange to relate, from young Iulus' head END
BEGIN NOW A lambent flame arose, which gently spread END
BEGIN NOW Around his brows, and on his temples fed. END
BEGIN NOW Amaz'd, with running water we prepare END
BEGIN NOW To quench the sacred fire, and slake his hair; END
BEGIN NOW But old Anchises, vers'd in omens, rear'd END
BEGIN NOW His hands to heav'n, and this request preferr'd: END
BEGIN NOW 'If any vows, almighty Jove, can bend END
BEGIN NOW Thy will; if piety can pray'rs commend, END
BEGIN NOW Confirm the glad presage which thou art pleas'd to send.' END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had he said, when, on our left, we hear END
BEGIN NOW A peal of rattling thunder roll in air: END
BEGIN NOW There shot a streaming lamp along the sky, END
BEGIN NOW Which on the winged lightning seem'd to fly; END
BEGIN NOW From o'er the roof the blaze began to move, END
BEGIN NOW And, trailing, vanish'd in th' Idaean grove. END
BEGIN NOW It swept a path in heav'n, and shone a guide, END
BEGIN NOW Then in a steaming stench of sulphur died. END
BEGIN NOW The good old man with suppliant hands implor'd END
BEGIN NOW The gods' protection, and their star ador'd. END
BEGIN NOW 'Now, now,' said he, 'my son, no more delay! END
BEGIN NOW I yield, I follow where Heav'n shews the way. END
BEGIN NOW Keep, O my country gods, our dwelling place, END
BEGIN NOW And guard this relic of the Trojan race, END
BEGIN NOW This tender child! These omens are your own, END
BEGIN NOW And you can yet restore the ruin'd town. END
BEGIN NOW At least accomplish what your signs foreshow: END
BEGIN NOW I stand resign'd, and am prepar'd to go.' END
BEGIN NOW He said. The crackling flames appear on high. END
BEGIN NOW And driving sparkles dance along the sky. END
BEGIN NOW With Vulcan's rage the rising winds conspire, END
BEGIN NOW And near our palace roll the flood of fire. END
BEGIN NOW 'Haste, my dear father, ('t is no time to wait,) END
BEGIN NOW And load my shoulders with a willing freight. END
BEGIN NOW Whate'er befalls, your life shall be my care; END
BEGIN NOW One death, or one deliv'rance, we will share. END
BEGIN NOW My hand shall lead our little son; and you, END
BEGIN NOW My faithful consort, shall our steps pursue. END
BEGIN NOW Next, you, my servants, heed my strict commands: END
BEGIN NOW Without the walls a ruin'd temple stands, END
BEGIN NOW To Ceres hallow'd once; a cypress nigh END
BEGIN NOW Shoots up her venerable head on high, END
BEGIN NOW By long religion kept; there bend your feet, END
BEGIN NOW And in divided parties let us meet. END
BEGIN NOW Our country gods, the relics, and the bands, END
BEGIN NOW Hold you, my father, in your guiltless hands: END
BEGIN NOW In me 't is impious holy things to bear, END
BEGIN NOW Red as I am with slaughter, new from war, END
BEGIN NOW Till in some living stream I cleanse the guilt END
BEGIN NOW Of dire debate, and blood in battle spilt.' END
BEGIN NOW Thus, ord'ring all that prudence could provide, END
BEGIN NOW I clothe my shoulders with a lion's hide END
BEGIN NOW And yellow spoils; then, on my bending back, END
BEGIN NOW The welcome load of my dear father take; END
BEGIN NOW While on my better hand Ascanius hung, END
BEGIN NOW And with unequal paces tripp'd along. END
BEGIN NOW Creusa kept behind; by choice we stray END
BEGIN NOW Thro' ev'ry dark and ev'ry devious way. END
BEGIN NOW I, who so bold and dauntless, just before, END
BEGIN NOW The Grecian darts and shock of lances bore, END
BEGIN NOW At ev'ry shadow now am seiz'd with fear, END
BEGIN NOW Not for myself, but for the charge I bear; END
BEGIN NOW Till, near the ruin'd gate arriv'd at last, END
BEGIN NOW Secure, and deeming all the danger past, END
BEGIN NOW A frightful noise of trampling feet we hear. END
BEGIN NOW My father, looking thro' the shades, with fear, END
BEGIN NOW Cried out: 'Haste, haste, my son, the foes are nigh; END
BEGIN NOW Their swords and shining armor I descry.' END
BEGIN NOW Some hostile god, for some unknown offense, END
BEGIN NOW Had sure bereft my mind of better sense; END
BEGIN NOW For, while thro' winding ways I took my flight, END
BEGIN NOW And sought the shelter of the gloomy night, END
BEGIN NOW Alas! I lost Creusa: hard to tell END
BEGIN NOW If by her fatal destiny she fell, END
BEGIN NOW Or weary sate, or wander'd with affright; END
BEGIN NOW But she was lost for ever to my sight. END
BEGIN NOW I knew not, or reflected, till I meet END
BEGIN NOW My friends, at Ceres' now deserted seat. END
BEGIN NOW We met: not one was wanting; only she END
BEGIN NOW Deceiv'd her friends, her son, and wretched me. END
BEGIN NOW What mad expressions did my tongue refuse! END
BEGIN NOW Whom did I not, of gods or men, accuse! END
BEGIN NOW This was the fatal blow, that pain'd me more END
BEGIN NOW Than all I felt from ruin'd Troy before. END
BEGIN NOW Stung with my loss, and raving with despair, END
BEGIN NOW Abandoning my now forgotten care, END
BEGIN NOW Of counsel, comfort, and of hope bereft, END
BEGIN NOW My sire, my son, my country gods I left. END
BEGIN NOW In shining armor once again I sheathe END
BEGIN NOW My limbs, not feeling wounds, nor fearing death. END
BEGIN NOW Then headlong to the burning walls I run, END
BEGIN NOW And seek the danger I was forc'd to shun. END
BEGIN NOW I tread my former tracks; thro' night explore END
BEGIN NOW Each passage, ev'ry street I cross'd before. END
BEGIN NOW All things were full of horror and affright, END
BEGIN NOW And dreadful ev'n the silence of the night. END
BEGIN NOW Then to my father's house I make repair, END
BEGIN NOW With some small glimpse of hope to find her there. END
BEGIN NOW Instead of her, the cruel Greeks I met; END
BEGIN NOW The house was fill'd with foes, with flames beset. END
BEGIN NOW Driv'n on the wings of winds, whole sheets of fire, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' air transported, to the roofs aspire. END
BEGIN NOW From thence to Priam's palace I resort, END
BEGIN NOW And search the citadel and desart court. END
BEGIN NOW Then, unobserv'd, I pass by Juno's church: END
BEGIN NOW A guard of Grecians had possess'd the porch; END
BEGIN NOW There Phoenix and Ulysses watch prey, END
BEGIN NOW And thither all the wealth of Troy convey: END
BEGIN NOW The spoils which they from ransack'd houses brought, END
BEGIN NOW And golden bowls from burning altars caught, END
BEGIN NOW The tables of the gods, the purple vests, END
BEGIN NOW The people's treasure, and the pomp of priests. END
BEGIN NOW A rank of wretched youths, with pinion'd hands, END
BEGIN NOW And captive matrons, in long order stands. END
BEGIN NOW Then, with ungovern'd madness, I proclaim, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' all the silent street, Creusa's name: END
BEGIN NOW Creusa still I call; at length she hears, END
BEGIN NOW And sudden thro' the shades of night appears- END
BEGIN NOW Appears, no more Creusa, nor my wife, END
BEGIN NOW But a pale specter, larger than the life. END
BEGIN NOW I stood; like bristles rose my stiffen'd hair. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus the ghost began to soothe my grief END
BEGIN NOW 'Nor tears, nor cries, can give the dead relief. END
BEGIN NOW Desist, my much-lov'd lord,'t indulge your pain; END
BEGIN NOW You bear no more than what the gods ordain. END
BEGIN NOW My fates permit me not from hence to fly; END
BEGIN NOW Nor he, the great controller of the sky. END
BEGIN NOW Long wand'ring ways for you the pow'rs decree; END
BEGIN NOW On land hard labors, and a length of sea. END
BEGIN NOW Then, after many painful years are past, END
BEGIN NOW On Latium's happy shore you shall be cast, END
BEGIN NOW Where gentle Tiber from his bed beholds END
BEGIN NOW The flow'ry meadows, and the feeding folds. END
BEGIN NOW There end your toils; and there your fates provide END
BEGIN NOW A quiet kingdom, and a royal bride: END
BEGIN NOW There fortune shall the Trojan line restore, END
BEGIN NOW And you for lost Creusa weep no more. END
BEGIN NOW Fear not that I shall watch, with servile shame, END
BEGIN NOW Th' imperious looks of some proud Grecian dame; END
BEGIN NOW Or, stooping to the victor's lust, disgrace END
BEGIN NOW My goddess mother, or my royal race. END
BEGIN NOW And now, farewell! The parent of the gods END
BEGIN NOW Restrains my fleeting soul in her abodes: END
BEGIN NOW I trust our common issue to your care.' END
BEGIN NOW She said, and gliding pass'd unseen in air. END
BEGIN NOW I strove to speak: but horror tied my tongue; END
BEGIN NOW And thrice about her neck my arms I flung, END
BEGIN NOW And, thrice deceiv'd, on vain embraces hung. END
BEGIN NOW Light as an empty dream at break of day, END
BEGIN NOW Or as a blast of wind, she rush'd away. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having pass'd the night in fruitless pain, END
BEGIN NOW I to my longing friends return again, END
BEGIN NOW Amaz'd th' augmented number to behold, END
BEGIN NOW Of men and matrons mix'd, of young and old; END
BEGIN NOW A wretched exil'd crew together brought, END
BEGIN NOW With arms appointed, and with treasure fraught, END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd, and willing, under my command, END
BEGIN NOW To run all hazards both of sea and land. END
BEGIN NOW The Morn began, from Ida, to display END
BEGIN NOW Her rosy cheeks; and Phosphor led the day: END
BEGIN NOW Before the gates the Grecians took their post, END
BEGIN NOW And all pretense of late relief was lost. END
BEGIN NOW I yield to Fate, unwillingly retire, END
BEGIN NOW And, loaded, up the hill convey my sire. END
BEGIN NOW When Heav'n had overturn'd the Trojan state END
BEGIN NOW And Priam's throne, by too severe a fate; END
BEGIN NOW When ruin'd Troy became the Grecians' prey, END
BEGIN NOW And Ilium's lofty tow'rs in ashes lay; END
BEGIN NOW Warn'd by celestial omens, we retreat, END
BEGIN NOW To seek in foreign lands a happier seat. END
BEGIN NOW Near old Antandros, and at Ida's foot, END
BEGIN NOW The timber of the sacred groves we cut, END
BEGIN NOW And build our fleet; uncertain yet to find END
BEGIN NOW What place the gods for our repose assign'd. END
BEGIN NOW Friends daily flock; and scarce the kindly spring END
BEGIN NOW Began to clothe the ground, and birds to sing, END
BEGIN NOW When old Anchises summon'd all to sea: END
BEGIN NOW The crew my father and the Fates obey. END
BEGIN NOW With sighs and tears I leave my native shore, END
BEGIN NOW And empty fields, where Ilium stood before. END
BEGIN NOW My sire, my son, our less and greater gods, END
BEGIN NOW All sail at once, and cleave the briny floods. END
BEGIN NOW Against our coast appears a spacious land, END
BEGIN NOW Which once the fierce Lycurgus did command, END
BEGIN NOW (Thracia the name- the people bold in war; END
BEGIN NOW Vast are their fields, and tillage is their care,) END
BEGIN NOW A hospitable realm while Fate was kind, END
BEGIN NOW With Troy in friendship and religion join'd. END
BEGIN NOW I land; with luckless omens then adore END
BEGIN NOW Their gods, and draw a line along the shore; END
BEGIN NOW I lay the deep foundations of a wall, END
BEGIN NOW And Aenos, nam'd from me, the city call. END
BEGIN NOW To Dionaean Venus vows are paid, END
BEGIN NOW And all the pow'rs that rising labors aid; END
BEGIN NOW A bull on Jove's imperial altar laid. END
BEGIN NOW Not far, a rising hillock stood in view; END
BEGIN NOW Sharp myrtles on the sides, and cornels grew. END
BEGIN NOW There, while I went to crop the sylvan scenes, END
BEGIN NOW And shade our altar with their leafy greens, END
BEGIN NOW I pull'd a plant- with horror I relate END
BEGIN NOW A prodigy so strange and full of fate. END
BEGIN NOW The rooted fibers rose, and from the wound END
BEGIN NOW Black bloody drops distill'd upon the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Mute and amaz'd, my hair with terror stood; END
BEGIN NOW Fear shrunk my sinews, and congeal'd my blood. END
BEGIN NOW Mann'd once again, another plant I try: END
BEGIN NOW That other gush'd with the same sanguine dye. END
BEGIN NOW Then, fearing guilt for some offense unknown, END
BEGIN NOW With pray'rs and vows the Dryads I atone, END
BEGIN NOW With all the sisters of the woods, and most END
BEGIN NOW The God of Arms, who rules the Thracian coast, END
BEGIN NOW That they, or he, these omens would avert, END
BEGIN NOW Release our fears, and better signs impart. END
BEGIN NOW Clear'd, as I thought, and fully fix'd at length END
BEGIN NOW To learn the cause, I tugged with all my strength: END
BEGIN NOW I bent my knees against the ground; once more END
BEGIN NOW The violated myrtle ran with gore. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce dare I tell the sequel: from the womb END
BEGIN NOW Of wounded earth, and caverns of the tomb, END
BEGIN NOW A groan, as of a troubled ghost, renew'd END
BEGIN NOW My fright, and then these dreadful words ensued: END
BEGIN NOW 'Why dost thou thus my buried body rend? END
BEGIN NOW O spare the corpse of thy unhappy friend! END
BEGIN NOW Spare to pollute thy pious hands with blood: END
BEGIN NOW The tears distil not from the wounded wood; END
BEGIN NOW But ev'ry drop this living tree contains END
BEGIN NOW Is kindred blood, and ran in Trojan veins. END
BEGIN NOW O fly from this unhospitable shore, END
BEGIN NOW Warn'd by my fate; for I am Polydore! END
BEGIN NOW Here loads of lances, in my blood embrued, END
BEGIN NOW Again shoot upward, by my blood renew'd.' END
BEGIN NOW My falt'ring tongue and shiv'ring limbs declare END
BEGIN NOW My horror, and in bristles rose my hair. END
BEGIN NOW When Troy with Grecian arms was closely pent, END
BEGIN NOW Old Priam, fearful of the war's event, END
BEGIN NOW This hapless Polydore to Thracia sent: END
BEGIN NOW Loaded with gold, he sent his darling, far END
BEGIN NOW From noise and tumults, and destructive war, END
BEGIN NOW Committed to the faithless tyrant's care; END
BEGIN NOW Who, when he saw the pow'r of Troy decline, END
BEGIN NOW Forsook the weaker, with the strong to join; END
BEGIN NOW Broke ev'ry bond of nature and of truth, END
BEGIN NOW And murder'd, for his wealth, the royal youth. END
BEGIN NOW O sacred hunger of pernicious gold! END
BEGIN NOW What bands of faith can impious lucre hold? END
BEGIN NOW Now, when my soul had shaken off her fears, END
BEGIN NOW I call my father and the Trojan peers; END
BEGIN NOW Relate the prodigies of Heav'n, require END
BEGIN NOW What he commands, and their advice desire. END
BEGIN NOW All vote to leave that execrable shore, END
BEGIN NOW Polluted with the blood of Polydore; END
BEGIN NOW But, ere we sail, his fun'ral rites prepare, END
BEGIN NOW Then, to his ghost, a tomb and altars rear. END
BEGIN NOW In mournful pomp the matrons walk the round, END
BEGIN NOW With baleful cypress and blue fillets crown'd, END
BEGIN NOW With eyes dejected, and with hair unbound. END
BEGIN NOW Then bowls of tepid milk and blood we pour, END
BEGIN NOW And thrice invoke the soul of Polydore. END
BEGIN NOW Now, when the raging storms no longer reign, END
BEGIN NOW But southern gales invite us to the main, END
BEGIN NOW We launch our vessels, with a prosp'rous wind, END
BEGIN NOW And leave the cities and the shores behind. END
BEGIN NOW An island in th' Aegaean main appears; END
BEGIN NOW Neptune and wat'ry Doris claim it theirs. END
BEGIN NOW It floated once, till Phoebus fix'd the sides END
BEGIN NOW To rooted earth, and now it braves the tides. END
BEGIN NOW Here, borne by friendly winds, we come ashore, END
BEGIN NOW With needful ease our weary limbs restore, END
BEGIN NOW And the Sun's temple and his town adore. END
BEGIN NOW Anius, the priest and king, with laurel crown'd, END
BEGIN NOW His hoary locks with purple fillets bound, END
BEGIN NOW Who saw my sire the Delian shore ascend, END
BEGIN NOW Came forth with eager haste to meet his friend; END
BEGIN NOW Invites him to his palace; and, in sign END
BEGIN NOW Of ancient love, their plighted hands they join. END
BEGIN NOW Then to the temple of the god I went, END
BEGIN NOW And thus, before the shrine, my vows present: END
BEGIN NOW 'Give, O Thymbraeus, give a resting place END
BEGIN NOW To the sad relics of the Trojan race; END
BEGIN NOW A seat secure, a region of their own, END
BEGIN NOW A lasting empire, and a happier town. END
BEGIN NOW Where shall we fix? where shall our labors end? END
BEGIN NOW Whom shall we follow, and what fate attend? END
BEGIN NOW Let not my pray'rs a doubtful answer find; END
BEGIN NOW But in clear auguries unveil thy mind.' END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had I said: he shook the holy ground, END
BEGIN NOW The laurels, and the lofty hills around; END
BEGIN NOW And from the tripos rush'd a bellowing sound. END
BEGIN NOW Prostrate we fell; confess'd the present god, END
BEGIN NOW Who gave this answer from his dark abode: END
BEGIN NOW 'Undaunted youths, go, seek that mother earth END
BEGIN NOW From which your ancestors derive their birth. END
BEGIN NOW The soil that sent you forth, her ancient race END
BEGIN NOW In her old bosom shall again embrace. END
BEGIN NOW Thro' the wide world th' Aeneian house shall reign, END
BEGIN NOW And children's children shall the crown sustain.' END
BEGIN NOW Thus Phoebus did our future fates disclose: END
BEGIN NOW A mighty tumult, mix'd with joy, arose. END
BEGIN NOW All are concern'd to know what place the god END
BEGIN NOW Assign'd, and where determin'd our abode. END
BEGIN NOW My father, long revolving in his mind END
BEGIN NOW The race and lineage of the Trojan kind, END
BEGIN NOW Thus answer'd their demands: 'Ye princes, hear END
BEGIN NOW Your pleasing fortune, and dispel your fear. END
BEGIN NOW The fruitful isle of Crete, well known to fame, END
BEGIN NOW Sacred of old to Jove's imperial name, END
BEGIN NOW In the mid ocean lies, with large command, END
BEGIN NOW And on its plains a hundred cities stand. END
BEGIN NOW Another Ida rises there, and we END
BEGIN NOW From thence derive our Trojan ancestry. END
BEGIN NOW From thence, as 't is divulg'd by certain fame, END
BEGIN NOW To the Rhoetean shores old Teucrus came; END
BEGIN NOW There fix'd, and there the seat of empire chose, END
BEGIN NOW Ere Ilium and the Trojan tow'rs arose. END
BEGIN NOW In humble vales they built their soft abodes, END
BEGIN NOW Till Cybele, the mother of the gods, END
BEGIN NOW With tinkling cymbals charm'd th' Idaean woods, END
BEGIN NOW She secret rites and ceremonies taught, END
BEGIN NOW And to the yoke the savage lions brought. END
BEGIN NOW Let us the land which Heav'n appoints, explore; END
BEGIN NOW Appease the winds, and seek the Gnossian shore. END
BEGIN NOW If Jove assists the passage of our fleet, END
BEGIN NOW The third propitious dawn discovers Crete.' END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, the sacrifices, laid END
BEGIN NOW On smoking altars, to the gods he paid: END
BEGIN NOW A bull, to Neptune an oblation due, END
BEGIN NOW Another bull to bright Apollo slew; END
BEGIN NOW A milk-white ewe, the western winds to please, END
BEGIN NOW And one coal-black, to calm the stormy seas. END
BEGIN NOW Ere this, a flying rumor had been spread END
BEGIN NOW That fierce Idomeneus from Crete was fled, END
BEGIN NOW Expell'd and exil'd; that the coast was free END
BEGIN NOW From foreign or domestic enemy. END
BEGIN NOW We leave the Delian ports, and put to sea; END
BEGIN NOW By Naxos, fam'd for vintage, make our way; END
BEGIN NOW Then green Donysa pass; and sail in sight END
BEGIN NOW Of Paros' isle, with marble quarries white. END
BEGIN NOW We pass the scatter'd isles of Cyclades, END
BEGIN NOW That, scarce distinguish'd, seem to stud the seas. END
BEGIN NOW The shouts of sailors double near the shores; END
BEGIN NOW They stretch their canvas, and they ply their oars. END
BEGIN NOW 'All hands aloft! for Crete! for Crete!' they cry, END
BEGIN NOW And swiftly thro' the foamy billows fly. END
BEGIN NOW Full on the promis'd land at length we bore, END
BEGIN NOW With joy descending on the Cretan shore. END
BEGIN NOW With eager haste a rising town I frame, END
BEGIN NOW Which from the Trojan Pergamus I name: END
BEGIN NOW The name itself was grateful; I exhort END
BEGIN NOW To found their houses, and erect a fort. END
BEGIN NOW Our ships are haul'd upon the yellow strand; END
BEGIN NOW The youth begin to till the labor'd land; END
BEGIN NOW And I myself new marriages promote, END
BEGIN NOW Give laws, and dwellings I divide by lot; END
BEGIN NOW When rising vapors choke the wholesome air, END
BEGIN NOW And blasts of noisome winds corrupt the year; END
BEGIN NOW The trees devouring caterpillars burn; END
BEGIN NOW Parch'd was the grass, and blighted was the corn: END
BEGIN NOW Nor 'scape the beasts; for Sirius, from on high, END
BEGIN NOW With pestilential heat infects the sky: END
BEGIN NOW My men- some fall, the rest in fevers fry. END
BEGIN NOW Again my father bids me seek the shore END
BEGIN NOW Of sacred Delos, and the god implore, END
BEGIN NOW To learn what end of woes we might expect, END
BEGIN NOW And to what clime our weary course direct. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was night, when ev'ry creature, void of cares, END
BEGIN NOW The common gift of balmy slumber shares: END
BEGIN NOW The statues of my gods (for such they seem'd), END
BEGIN NOW Those gods whom I from flaming Troy redeem'd, END
BEGIN NOW Before me stood, majestically bright, END
BEGIN NOW Full in the beams of Phoebe's ent'ring light. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus they spoke, and eas'd my troubled mind: END
BEGIN NOW 'What from the Delian god thou go'st to find, END
BEGIN NOW He tells thee here, and sends us to relate. END
BEGIN NOW Those pow'rs are we, companions of thy fate, END
BEGIN NOW Who from the burning town by thee were brought, END
BEGIN NOW Thy fortune follow'd, and thy safety wrought. END
BEGIN NOW Thro' seas and lands as we thy steps attend, END
BEGIN NOW So shall our care thy glorious race befriend. END
BEGIN NOW An ample realm for thee thy fates ordain, END
BEGIN NOW A town that o'er the conquer'd world shall reign. END
BEGIN NOW Thou, mighty walls for mighty nations build; END
BEGIN NOW Nor let thy weary mind to labors yield: END
BEGIN NOW But change thy seat; for not the Delian god, END
BEGIN NOW Nor we, have giv'n thee Crete for our abode. END
BEGIN NOW A land there is, Hesperia call'd of old, END
BEGIN NOW (The soil is fruitful, and the natives bold- END
BEGIN NOW Th' Oenotrians held it once,) by later fame END
BEGIN NOW Now call'd Italia, from the leader's name. END
BEGIN NOW lasius there and Dardanus were born; END
BEGIN NOW From thence we came, and thither must return. END
BEGIN NOW Rise, and thy sire with these glad tidings greet. END
BEGIN NOW Search Italy; for Jove denies thee Crete.' END
BEGIN NOW Astonish'd at their voices and their sight, END
BEGIN NOW (Nor were they dreams, but visions of the night; END
BEGIN NOW I saw, I knew their faces, and descried, END
BEGIN NOW In perfect view, their hair with fillets tied;) END
BEGIN NOW I started from my couch; a clammy sweat END
BEGIN NOW On all my limbs and shiv'ring body sate. END
BEGIN NOW To heav'n I lift my hands with pious haste, END
BEGIN NOW And sacred incense in the flames I cast. END
BEGIN NOW Thus to the gods their perfect honors done, END
BEGIN NOW More cheerful, to my good old sire I run, END
BEGIN NOW And tell the pleasing news. In little space END
BEGIN NOW He found his error of the double race; END
BEGIN NOW Not, as before he deem'd, deriv'd from Crete; END
BEGIN NOW No more deluded by the doubtful seat: END
BEGIN NOW Then said: 'O son, turmoil'd in Trojan fate! END
BEGIN NOW Such things as these Cassandra did relate. END
BEGIN NOW This day revives within my mind what she END
BEGIN NOW Foretold of Troy renew'd in Italy, END
BEGIN NOW And Latian lands; but who could then have thought END
BEGIN NOW That Phrygian gods to Latium should be brought, END
BEGIN NOW Or who believ'd what mad Cassandra taught? END
BEGIN NOW Now let us go where Phoebus leads the way.' END
BEGIN NOW He said; and we with glad consent obey, END
BEGIN NOW Forsake the seat, and, leaving few behind, END
BEGIN NOW We spread our sails before the willing wind. END
BEGIN NOW Now from the sight of land our galleys move, END
BEGIN NOW With only seas around and skies above; END
BEGIN NOW When o'er our heads descends a burst of rain, END
BEGIN NOW And night with sable clouds involves the main; END
BEGIN NOW The ruffling winds the foamy billows raise; END
BEGIN NOW The scatter'd fleet is forc'd to sev'ral ways; END
BEGIN NOW The face of heav'n is ravish'd from our eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And in redoubled peals the roaring thunder flies. END
BEGIN NOW Cast from our course, we wander in the dark. END
BEGIN NOW No stars to guide, no point of land to mark. END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n Palinurus no distinction found END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the night and day; such darkness reign'd around. END
BEGIN NOW Three starless nights the doubtful navy strays, END
BEGIN NOW Without distinction, and three sunless days; END
BEGIN NOW The fourth renews the light, and, from our shrouds, END
BEGIN NOW We view a rising land, like distant clouds; END
BEGIN NOW The mountain-tops confirm the pleasing sight, END
BEGIN NOW And curling smoke ascending from their height. END
BEGIN NOW The canvas falls; their oars the sailors ply; END
BEGIN NOW From the rude strokes the whirling waters fly. END
BEGIN NOW At length I land upon the Strophades, END
BEGIN NOW Safe from the danger of the stormy seas. END
BEGIN NOW Those isles are compass'd by th' Ionian main, END
BEGIN NOW The dire abode where the foul Harpies reign, END
BEGIN NOW Forc'd by the winged warriors to repair END
BEGIN NOW To their old homes, and leave their costly fare. END
BEGIN NOW Monsters more fierce offended Heav'n ne'er sent END
BEGIN NOW From hell's abyss, for human punishment: END
BEGIN NOW With virgin faces, but with wombs obscene, END
BEGIN NOW Foul paunches, and with ordure still unclean; END
BEGIN NOW With claws for hands, and looks for ever lean. END
BEGIN NOW We landed at the port, and soon beheld END
BEGIN NOW Fat herds of oxen graze the flow'ry field, END
BEGIN NOW And wanton goats without a keeper stray'd. END
BEGIN NOW With weapons we the welcome prey invade, END
BEGIN NOW Then call the gods for partners of our feast, END
BEGIN NOW And Jove himself, the chief invited guest. END
BEGIN NOW We spread the tables on the greensward ground; END
BEGIN NOW We feed with hunger, and the bowls go round; END
BEGIN NOW When from the mountain-tops, with hideous cry, END
BEGIN NOW And clatt'ring wings, the hungry Harpies fly; END
BEGIN NOW They snatch the meat, defiling all they find, END
BEGIN NOW And, parting, leave a loathsome stench behind. END
BEGIN NOW Close by a hollow rock, again we sit, END
BEGIN NOW New dress the dinner, and the beds refit, END
BEGIN NOW Secure from sight, beneath a pleasing shade, END
BEGIN NOW Where tufted trees a native arbor made. END
BEGIN NOW Again the holy fires on altars burn; END
BEGIN NOW And once again the rav'nous birds return, END
BEGIN NOW Or from the dark recesses where they lie, END
BEGIN NOW Or from another quarter of the sky; END
BEGIN NOW With filthy claws their odious meal repeat, END
BEGIN NOW And mix their loathsome ordures with their meat. END
BEGIN NOW I bid my friends for vengeance then prepare, END
BEGIN NOW And with the hellish nation wage the war. END
BEGIN NOW They, as commanded, for the fight provide, END
BEGIN NOW And in the grass their glitt'ring weapons hide; END
BEGIN NOW Then, when along the crooked shore we hear END
BEGIN NOW Their clatt'ring wings, and saw the foes appear, END
BEGIN NOW Misenus sounds a charge: we take th' alarm, END
BEGIN NOW And our strong hands with swords and bucklers arm. END
BEGIN NOW In this new kind of combat all employ END
BEGIN NOW Their utmost force, the monsters to destroy. END
BEGIN NOW In vain- the fated skin is proof to wounds; END
BEGIN NOW And from their plumes the shining sword rebounds. END
BEGIN NOW At length rebuff'd, they leave their mangled prey, END
BEGIN NOW And their stretch'd pinions to the skies display. END
BEGIN NOW Yet one remain'd- the messenger of Fate: END
BEGIN NOW High on a craggy cliff Celaeno sate, END
BEGIN NOW And thus her dismal errand did relate: END
BEGIN NOW 'What! not contented with our oxen slain, END
BEGIN NOW Dare you with Heav'n an impious war maintain, END
BEGIN NOW And drive the Harpies from their native reign? END
BEGIN NOW Heed therefore what I say; and keep in mind END
BEGIN NOW What Jove decrees, what Phoebus has design'd, END
BEGIN NOW And I, the Furies' queen, from both relate- END
BEGIN NOW You seek th' Italian shores, foredoom'd by fate: END
BEGIN NOW Th' Italian shores are granted you to find, END
BEGIN NOW And a safe passage to the port assign'd. END
BEGIN NOW But know, that ere your promis'd walls you build, END
BEGIN NOW My curses shall severely be fulfill'd. END
BEGIN NOW Fierce famine is your lot for this misdeed, END
BEGIN NOW Reduc'd to grind the plates on which you feed.' END
BEGIN NOW She said, and to the neighb'ring forest flew. END
BEGIN NOW Our courage fails us, and our fears renew. END
BEGIN NOW Hopeless to win by war, to pray'rs we fall, END
BEGIN NOW And on th' offended Harpies humbly call, END
BEGIN NOW And whether gods or birds obscene they were, END
BEGIN NOW Our vows for pardon and for peace prefer. END
BEGIN NOW But old Anchises, off'ring sacrifice, END
BEGIN NOW And lifting up to heav'n his hands and eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Ador'd the greater gods: 'Avert,' said he, END
BEGIN NOW 'These omens; render vain this prophecy, END
BEGIN NOW And from th' impending curse a pious people free!' END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, he bids us put to sea; END
BEGIN NOW We loose from shore our haulsers, and obey, END
BEGIN NOW And soon with swelling sails pursue the wat'ry way. END
BEGIN NOW Amidst our course, Zacynthian woods appear; END
BEGIN NOW And next by rocky Neritos we steer: END
BEGIN NOW We fly from Ithaca's detested shore, END
BEGIN NOW And curse the land which dire Ulysses bore. END
BEGIN NOW At length Leucate's cloudy top appears, END
BEGIN NOW And the Sun's temple, which the sailor fears. END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd to breathe a while from labor past, END
BEGIN NOW Our crooked anchors from the prow we cast, END
BEGIN NOW And joyful to the little city haste. END
BEGIN NOW Here, safe beyond our hopes, our vows we pay END
BEGIN NOW To Jove, the guide and patron of our way. END
BEGIN NOW The customs of our country we pursue, END
BEGIN NOW And Trojan games on Actian shores renew. END
BEGIN NOW Our youth their naked limbs besmear with oil, END
BEGIN NOW And exercise the wrastlers' noble toil; END
BEGIN NOW Pleas'd to have sail'd so long before the wind, END
BEGIN NOW And left so many Grecian towns behind. END
BEGIN NOW The sun had now fulfill'd his annual course, END
BEGIN NOW And Boreas on the seas display'd his force: END
BEGIN NOW I fix'd upon the temple's lofty door END
BEGIN NOW The brazen shield which vanquish'd Abas bore; END
BEGIN NOW The verse beneath my name and action speaks: END
BEGIN NOW 'These arms Aeneas took from conqu'ring Greeks.' END
BEGIN NOW Then I command to weigh; the seamen ply END
BEGIN NOW Their sweeping oars; the smoking billows fly. END
BEGIN NOW The sight of high Phaeacia soon we lost, END
BEGIN NOW And skimm'd along Epirus' rocky coast. END
BEGIN NOW Then to Chaonia's port our course we bend, END
BEGIN NOW And, landed, to Buthrotus' heights ascend. END
BEGIN NOW Here wondrous things were loudly blaz'd fame: END
BEGIN NOW How Helenus reviv'd the Trojan name, END
BEGIN NOW And reign'd in Greece; that Priam's captive son END
BEGIN NOW Succeeded Pyrrhus in his bed and throne; END
BEGIN NOW And fair Andromache, restor'd by fate, END
BEGIN NOW Once more was happy in a Trojan mate. END
BEGIN NOW I leave my galleys riding in the port, END
BEGIN NOW And long to see the new Dardanian court. END
BEGIN NOW By chance, the mournful queen, before the gate, END
BEGIN NOW Then solemniz'd her former husband's fate. END
BEGIN NOW Green altars, rais'd of turf, with gifts she crown'd, END
BEGIN NOW And sacred priests in order stand around, END
BEGIN NOW And thrice the name of hapless Hector sound. END
BEGIN NOW The grove itself resembles Ida's wood; END
BEGIN NOW And Simois seem'd the well-dissembled flood. END
BEGIN NOW But when at nearer distance she beheld END
BEGIN NOW My shining armor and my Trojan shield, END
BEGIN NOW Astonish'd at the sight, the vital heat END
BEGIN NOW Forsakes her limbs; her veins no longer beat: END
BEGIN NOW She faints, she falls, and scarce recov'ring strength, END
BEGIN NOW Thus, with a falt'ring tongue, she speaks at length: END
BEGIN NOW 'Are you alive, O goddess-born?' she said, END
BEGIN NOW 'Or if a ghost, then where is Hector's shade?' END
BEGIN NOW At this, she cast a loud and frightful cry. END
BEGIN NOW With broken words I made this brief reply: END
BEGIN NOW 'All of me that remains appears in sight; END
BEGIN NOW I live, if living be to loathe the light. END
BEGIN NOW No phantom; but I drag a wretched life, END
BEGIN NOW My fate resembling that of Hector's wife. END
BEGIN NOW What have you suffer'd since you lost your lord? END
BEGIN NOW By what strange blessing are you now restor'd? END
BEGIN NOW Still are you Hector's? or is Hector fled, END
BEGIN NOW And his remembrance lost in Pyrrhus' bed?' END
BEGIN NOW With eyes dejected, in a lowly tone, END
BEGIN NOW After a modest pause she thus begun: END
BEGIN NOW 'O only happy maid of Priam's race, END
BEGIN NOW Whom death deliver'd from the foes' embrace! END
BEGIN NOW Commanded on Achilles' tomb to die, END
BEGIN NOW Not forc'd, like us, to hard captivity, END
BEGIN NOW Or in a haughty master's arms to lie. END
BEGIN NOW In Grecian ships unhappy we were borne, END
BEGIN NOW Endur'd the victor's lust, sustain'd the scorn: END
BEGIN NOW Thus I submitted to the lawless pride END
BEGIN NOW Of Pyrrhus, more a handmaid than a bride. END
BEGIN NOW Cloy'd with possession, he forsook my bed, END
BEGIN NOW And Helen's lovely daughter sought to wed; END
BEGIN NOW Then me to Trojan Helenus resign'd, END
BEGIN NOW And his two slaves in equal marriage join'd; END
BEGIN NOW Till young Orestes, pierc'd with deep despair, END
BEGIN NOW And longing to redeem the promis'd fair, END
BEGIN NOW Before Apollo's altar slew the ravisher. END
BEGIN NOW By Pyrrhus' death the kingdom we regain'd: END
BEGIN NOW At least one half with Helenus remain'd. END
BEGIN NOW Our part, from Chaon, he Chaonia calls, END
BEGIN NOW And names from Pergamus his rising walls. END
BEGIN NOW But you, what fates have landed on our coast? END
BEGIN NOW What gods have sent you, or what storms have toss'd? END
BEGIN NOW Does young Ascanius life and health enjoy, END
BEGIN NOW Sav'd from the ruins of unhappy Troy? END
BEGIN NOW O tell me how his mother's loss he bears, END
BEGIN NOW What hopes are promis'd from his blooming years, END
BEGIN NOW How much of Hector in his face appears?' END
BEGIN NOW She spoke; and mix'd her speech with mournful cries, END
BEGIN NOW And fruitless tears came trickling from her eyes. END
BEGIN NOW At length her lord descends upon the plain, END
BEGIN NOW In pomp, attended with a num'rous train; END
BEGIN NOW Receives his friends, and to the city leads, END
BEGIN NOW And tears of joy amidst his welcome sheds. END
BEGIN NOW Proceeding on, another Troy I see, END
BEGIN NOW Or, in less compass, Troy's epitome. END
BEGIN NOW A riv'let by the name of Xanthus ran, END
BEGIN NOW And I embrace the Scaean gate again. END
BEGIN NOW My friends in porticoes were entertain'd, END
BEGIN NOW And feasts and pleasures thro' the city reign'd. END
BEGIN NOW The tables fill'd the spacious hall around, END
BEGIN NOW And golden bowls with sparkling wine were crown'd. END
BEGIN NOW Two days we pass'd in mirth, till friendly gales, END
BEGIN NOW Blown from the supplied our swelling sails. END
BEGIN NOW Then to the royal seer I thus began: END
BEGIN NOW 'O thou, who know'st, beyond the reach of man, END
BEGIN NOW The laws of heav'n, and what the stars decree; END
BEGIN NOW Whom Phoebus taught unerring prophecy, END
BEGIN NOW From his own tripod, and his holy tree; END
BEGIN NOW Skill'd in the wing'd inhabitants of air, END
BEGIN NOW What auspices their notes and flights declare: END
BEGIN NOW O say- for all religious rites portend END
BEGIN NOW A happy voyage, and a prosp'rous end; END
BEGIN NOW And ev'ry power and omen of the sky END
BEGIN NOW Direct my course for destin'd Italy; END
BEGIN NOW But only dire Celaeno, from the gods, END
BEGIN NOW A dismal famine fatally forebodes- END
BEGIN NOW O say what dangers I am first to shun, END
BEGIN NOW What toils vanquish, and what course to run.' END
BEGIN NOW The prophet first with sacrifice adores END
BEGIN NOW The greater gods; their pardon then implores; END
BEGIN NOW Unbinds the fillet from his holy head; END
BEGIN NOW To Phoebus, next, my trembling steps he led, END
BEGIN NOW Full of religious doubts and awful dread. END
BEGIN NOW Then, with his god possess'd, before the shrine, END
BEGIN NOW These words proceeded from his mouth divine: END
BEGIN NOW 'O goddess-born, (for Heav'n's appointed will, END
BEGIN NOW With greater auspices of good than ill, END
BEGIN NOW Foreshows thy voyage, and thy course directs; END
BEGIN NOW Thy fates conspire, and Jove himself protects,) END
BEGIN NOW Of many things some few I shall explain, END
BEGIN NOW Teach thee to shun the dangers of the main, END
BEGIN NOW And how at length the promis'd shore to gain. END
BEGIN NOW The rest the fates from Helenus conceal, END
BEGIN NOW And Juno's angry pow'r forbids to tell. END
BEGIN NOW First, then, that happy shore, that seems so nigh, END
BEGIN NOW Will far from your deluded wishes fly; END
BEGIN NOW Long tracts of seas divide your hopes from Italy: END
BEGIN NOW For you must cruise along Sicilian shores, END
BEGIN NOW And stem the currents with your struggling oars; END
BEGIN NOW Then round th' Italian coast your navy steer; END
BEGIN NOW And, after this, to Circe's island veer; END
BEGIN NOW And, last, before your new foundations rise, END
BEGIN NOW Must pass the Stygian lake, and view the nether skies. END
BEGIN NOW Now mark the signs of future ease and rest, END
BEGIN NOW And bear them safely treasur'd in thy breast. END
BEGIN NOW When, in the shady shelter of a wood, END
BEGIN NOW And near the margin of a gentle flood, END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt behold a sow upon the ground, END
BEGIN NOW With thirty sucking young encompass'd round; END
BEGIN NOW The dam and offspring white as falling snow- END
BEGIN NOW These on thy city shall their name bestow, END
BEGIN NOW And there shall end thy labors and thy woe. END
BEGIN NOW Nor let the threaten'd famine fright thy mind, END
BEGIN NOW For Phoebus will assist, and Fate the way will find. END
BEGIN NOW Let not thy course to that ill coast be bent, END
BEGIN NOW Which fronts from far th' Epirian continent: END
BEGIN NOW Those parts are all by Grecian foes possess'd; END
BEGIN NOW The salvage Locrians here the shores infest; END
BEGIN NOW There fierce Idomeneus his city builds, END
BEGIN NOW And guards with arms the Salentinian fields; END
BEGIN NOW And on the mountain's brow Petilia stands, END
BEGIN NOW Which Philoctetes with his troops commands. END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n when thy fleet is landed on the shore, END
BEGIN NOW And priests with holy vows the gods adore, END
BEGIN NOW Then with a purple veil involve your eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Lest hostile faces blast the sacrifice. END
BEGIN NOW These rites and customs to the rest commend, END
BEGIN NOW That to your pious race they may descend. END
BEGIN NOW 'When, parted hence, the wind, that ready waits END
BEGIN NOW For Sicily, shall bear you to the straits END
BEGIN NOW Where proud Pelorus opes a wider way, END
BEGIN NOW Tack to the larboard, and stand off to sea: END
BEGIN NOW Veer starboard sea and land. Th' Italian shore END
BEGIN NOW And fair Sicilia's coast were one, before END
BEGIN NOW An earthquake caus'd the flaw: the roaring tides END
BEGIN NOW The passage broke that land from land divides; END
BEGIN NOW And where the lands retir'd, the rushing ocean rides. END
BEGIN NOW Distinguish'd by the straits, on either hand, END
BEGIN NOW Now rising cities in long order stand, END
BEGIN NOW And fruitful fields: so much can time invade END
BEGIN NOW The mold'ring work that beauteous Nature made. END
BEGIN NOW Far on the right, her dogs foul Scylla hides: END
BEGIN NOW Charybdis roaring on the left presides, END
BEGIN NOW And in her greedy whirlpool sucks the tides; END
BEGIN NOW Then spouts them from below: with fury driv'n, END
BEGIN NOW The waves mount up and wash the face of heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW But Scylla from her den, with open jaws, END
BEGIN NOW The sinking vessel in her eddy draws, END
BEGIN NOW Then dashes on the rocks. A human face, END
BEGIN NOW And virgin bosom, hides her tail's disgrace: END
BEGIN NOW Her parts obscene below the waves descend, END
BEGIN NOW With dogs inclos'd, and in a dolphin end. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is safer, then, to bear aloof to sea, END
BEGIN NOW And coast Pachynus, tho' with more delay, END
BEGIN NOW Than once to view misshapen Scylla near, END
BEGIN NOW And the loud yell of wat'ry wolves to hear. END
BEGIN NOW 'Besides, if faith to Helenus be due, END
BEGIN NOW And if prophetic Phoebus tell me true, END
BEGIN NOW Do not this precept of your friend forget, END
BEGIN NOW Which therefore more than once I must repeat: END
BEGIN NOW Above the rest, great Juno's name adore; END
BEGIN NOW Pay vows to Juno; Juno's aid implore. END
BEGIN NOW Let gifts be to the mighty queen design'd, END
BEGIN NOW And mollify with pray'rs her haughty mind. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, at the length, your passage shall be free, END
BEGIN NOW And you shall safe descend on Italy. END
BEGIN NOW Arriv'd at Cumae, when you view the flood END
BEGIN NOW Of black Avernus, and the sounding wood, END
BEGIN NOW The mad prophetic Sibyl you shall find, END
BEGIN NOW Dark in a cave, and on a rock reclin'd. END
BEGIN NOW She sings the fates, and, in her frantic fits, END
BEGIN NOW The notes and names, inscrib'd, to leafs commits. END
BEGIN NOW What she commits to leafs, in order laid, END
BEGIN NOW Before the cavern's entrance are display'd: END
BEGIN NOW Unmov'd they lie; but, if a blast of wind END
BEGIN NOW Without, or vapors issue from behind, END
BEGIN NOW The leafs are borne aloft in liquid air, END
BEGIN NOW And she resumes no more her museful care, END
BEGIN NOW Nor gathers from the rocks her scatter'd verse, END
BEGIN NOW Nor sets in order what the winds disperse. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, many not succeeding, most upbraid END
BEGIN NOW The madness of the visionary maid, END
BEGIN NOW And with loud curses leave the mystic shade. END
BEGIN NOW 'Think it not loss of time a while to stay, END
BEGIN NOW Tho' thy companions chide thy long delay; END
BEGIN NOW Tho' summon'd to the seas, tho' pleasing gales END
BEGIN NOW Invite thy course, and stretch thy swelling sails: END
BEGIN NOW But beg the sacred priestess to relate END
BEGIN NOW With willing words, and not to write thy fate. END
BEGIN NOW The fierce Italian people she will show, END
BEGIN NOW And all thy wars, and all thy future woe, END
BEGIN NOW And what thou may'st avoid, and what must undergo. END
BEGIN NOW She shall direct thy course, instruct thy mind, END
BEGIN NOW And teach thee how the happy shores to find. END
BEGIN NOW This is what Heav'n allows me to relate: END
BEGIN NOW Now part in peace; pursue thy better fate, END
BEGIN NOW And raise, by strength of arms, the Trojan state.' END
BEGIN NOW This when the priest with friendly voice declar'd, END
BEGIN NOW He gave me license, and rich gifts prepar'd: END
BEGIN NOW Bounteous of treasure, he supplied my want END
BEGIN NOW With heavy gold, and polish'd elephant; END
BEGIN NOW Then Dodonaean caldrons put on board, END
BEGIN NOW And ev'ry ship with sums of silver stor'd. END
BEGIN NOW A trusty coat of mail to me he sent, END
BEGIN NOW Thrice chain'd with gold, for use and ornament; END
BEGIN NOW The helm of Pyrrhus added to the rest, END
BEGIN NOW That flourish'd with a plume and waving crest. END
BEGIN NOW Nor was my sire forgotten, nor my friends; END
BEGIN NOW And large recruits he to my navy sends: END
BEGIN NOW Men, horses, captains, arms, and warlike stores; END
BEGIN NOW Supplies new pilots, and new sweeping oars. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime, my sire commands to hoist our sails, END
BEGIN NOW Lest we should lose the first auspicious gales. END
BEGIN NOW The prophet bless'd the parting crew, and last, END
BEGIN NOW With words like these, his ancient friend embrac'd: END
BEGIN NOW 'Old happy man, the care of gods above, END
BEGIN NOW Whom heav'nly Venus honor'd with her love, END
BEGIN NOW And twice preserv'd thy life, when Troy was lost, END
BEGIN NOW Behold from far the wish'd Ausonian coast: END
BEGIN NOW There land; but take a larger compass round, END
BEGIN NOW For that before is all forbidden ground. END
BEGIN NOW The shore that Phoebus has design'd for you, END
BEGIN NOW At farther distance lies, conceal'd from view. END
BEGIN NOW Go happy hence, and seek your new abodes, END
BEGIN NOW Blest in a son, and favor'd by the gods: END
BEGIN NOW For I with useless words prolong your stay, END
BEGIN NOW When southern gales have summon'd you away.' END
BEGIN NOW Nor less the queen our parting thence deplor'd, END
BEGIN NOW Nor was less bounteous than her Trojan lord. END
BEGIN NOW A noble present to my son she brought, END
BEGIN NOW A robe with flow'rs on golden tissue wrought, END
BEGIN NOW A phrygian vest; and loads with gifts beside END
BEGIN NOW Of precious texture, and of Asian pride. END
BEGIN NOW 'Accept,' she said, 'these monuments of love, END
BEGIN NOW Which in my youth with happier hands I wove: END
BEGIN NOW Regard these trifles for the giver's sake; END
BEGIN NOW 'T is the last present Hector's wife can make. END
BEGIN NOW Thou call'st my lost Astyanax to mind; END
BEGIN NOW In thee his features and his form I find: END
BEGIN NOW His eyes so sparkled with a lively flame; END
BEGIN NOW Such were his motions; such was all his frame; END
BEGIN NOW And ah! had Heav'n so pleas'd, his years had been the same.' END
BEGIN NOW With tears I took my last adieu, and said: END
BEGIN NOW 'Your fortune, happy pair, already made, END
BEGIN NOW Leaves you no farther wish. My diff'rent state, END
BEGIN NOW Avoiding one, incurs another fate. END
BEGIN NOW To you a quiet seat the gods allow: END
BEGIN NOW You have no shores to search, no seas to plow, END
BEGIN NOW Nor fields of flying Italy to chase: END
BEGIN NOW (Deluding visions, and a vain embrace!) END
BEGIN NOW You see another Simois, and enjoy END
BEGIN NOW The labor of your hands, another Troy, END
BEGIN NOW With better auspice than her ancient tow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW And less obnoxious to the Grecian pow'rs. END
BEGIN NOW If e'er the gods, whom I with vows adore, END
BEGIN NOW Conduct my steps to Tiber's happy shore; END
BEGIN NOW If ever I ascend the Latian throne, END
BEGIN NOW And build a city I may call my own; END
BEGIN NOW As both of us our birth from Troy derive, END
BEGIN NOW So let our kindred lines in concord live, END
BEGIN NOW And both in acts of equal friendship strive. END
BEGIN NOW Our fortunes, good or bad, shall be the same: END
BEGIN NOW The double Troy shall differ but in name; END
BEGIN NOW That what we now begin may never end, END
BEGIN NOW But long to late posterity descend.' END
BEGIN NOW Near the Ceraunian rocks our course we bore; END
BEGIN NOW The shortest passage to th' Italian shore. END
BEGIN NOW Now had the sun withdrawn his radiant light, END
BEGIN NOW And hills were hid in dusky shades of night: END
BEGIN NOW We land, and, on the bosom Of the ground, END
BEGIN NOW A safe retreat and a bare lodging found. END
BEGIN NOW Close by the shore we lay; the sailors keep END
BEGIN NOW Their watches, and the rest securely sleep. END
BEGIN NOW The night, proceeding on with silent pace, END
BEGIN NOW Stood in her noon, and view'd with equal face END
BEGIN NOW Her steepy rise and her declining race. END
BEGIN NOW Then wakeful Palinurus rose, to spy END
BEGIN NOW The face of heav'n, and the nocturnal sky; END
BEGIN NOW And listen'd ev'ry breath of air to try; END
BEGIN NOW Observes the stars, and notes their sliding course, END
BEGIN NOW The Pleiads, Hyads, and their wat'ry force; END
BEGIN NOW And both the Bears is careful to behold, END
BEGIN NOW And bright Orion, arm'd with burnish'd gold. END
BEGIN NOW Then, when he saw no threat'ning tempest nigh, END
BEGIN NOW But a sure promise of a settled sky, END
BEGIN NOW He gave the sign to weigh; we break our sleep, END
BEGIN NOW Forsake the pleasing shore, and plow the deep. END
BEGIN NOW And now the rising morn with rosy light END
BEGIN NOW Adorns the skies, and puts the stars to flight; END
BEGIN NOW When we from far, like bluish mists, descry END
BEGIN NOW The hills, and then the plains, of Italy. END
BEGIN NOW Achates first pronounc'd the joyful sound; END
BEGIN NOW Then, 'Italy!' the cheerful crew rebound. END
BEGIN NOW My sire Anchises crown'd a cup with wine, END
BEGIN NOW And, off'ring, thus implor'd the pow'rs divine: END
BEGIN NOW 'Ye gods, presiding over lands and seas, END
BEGIN NOW And you who raging winds and waves appease, END
BEGIN NOW Breathe on our swelling sails a prosp'rous wind, END
BEGIN NOW And smooth our passage to the port assign'd!' END
BEGIN NOW The gentle gales their flagging force renew, END
BEGIN NOW And now the happy harbor is in view. END
BEGIN NOW Minerva's temple then salutes our sight, END
BEGIN NOW Plac'd, as a landmark, on the mountain's height. END
BEGIN NOW We furl our sails, and turn the prows to shore; END
BEGIN NOW The curling waters round the galleys roar. END
BEGIN NOW The land lies open to the raging east, END
BEGIN NOW Then, bending like a bow, with rocks compress'd, END
BEGIN NOW Shuts out the storms; the winds and waves complain, END
BEGIN NOW And vent their malice on the cliffs in vain. END
BEGIN NOW The port lies hid within; on either side END
BEGIN NOW Two tow'ring rocks the narrow mouth divide. END
BEGIN NOW The temple, which aloft we view'd before, END
BEGIN NOW To distance flies, and seems to shun the shore. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce landed, the first omens I beheld END
BEGIN NOW Were four white steeds that cropp'd the flow'ry field. END
BEGIN NOW 'War, war is threaten'd from this foreign ground,' END
BEGIN NOW My father cried, 'where warlike steeds are found. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, since reclaim'd to chariots they submit, END
BEGIN NOW And bend to stubborn yokes, and champ the bit, END
BEGIN NOW Peace may succeed to war.' Our way we bend END
BEGIN NOW To Pallas, and the sacred hill ascend; END
BEGIN NOW There prostrate to the fierce virago pray, END
BEGIN NOW Whose temple was the landmark of our way. END
BEGIN NOW Each with a Phrygian mantle veil'd his head, END
BEGIN NOW And all commands of Helenus obey'd, END
BEGIN NOW And pious rites to Grecian Juno paid. END
BEGIN NOW These dues perform'd, we stretch our sails, and stand END
BEGIN NOW To sea, forsaking that suspected land. END
BEGIN NOW From hence Tarentum's bay appears in view, END
BEGIN NOW For Hercules renown'd, if fame be true. END
BEGIN NOW Just opposite, Lacinian Juno stands; END
BEGIN NOW Caulonian tow'rs, and Scylacaean strands, END
BEGIN NOW For shipwrecks fear'd. Mount Aetna thence we spy, END
BEGIN NOW Known by the smoky flames which cloud the sky. END
BEGIN NOW Far off we hear the waves with surly sound END
BEGIN NOW Invade the rocks, the rocks their groans rebound. END
BEGIN NOW The billows break upon the sounding strand, END
BEGIN NOW And roll the rising tide, impure with sand. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus Anchises, in experience old: END
BEGIN NOW ''T is that Charybdis which the seer foretold, END
BEGIN NOW And those the promis'd rocks! Bear off to sea!' END
BEGIN NOW With haste the frighted mariners obey. END
BEGIN NOW First Palinurus to the larboard veer'd; END
BEGIN NOW Then all the fleet by his example steer'd. END
BEGIN NOW To heav'n aloft on ridgy waves we ride, END
BEGIN NOW Then down to hell descend, when they divide; END
BEGIN NOW And thrice our galleys knock'd the stony ground, END
BEGIN NOW And thrice the hollow rocks return'd the sound, END
BEGIN NOW And thrice we saw the stars, that stood with dews around. END
BEGIN NOW The flagging winds forsook us, with the sun; END
BEGIN NOW And, wearied, on Cyclopian shores we run. END
BEGIN NOW The port capacious, and secure from wind, END
BEGIN NOW Is to the foot of thund'ring Aetna join'd. END
BEGIN NOW By turns a pitchy cloud she rolls on high; END
BEGIN NOW By turns hot embers from her entrails fly, END
BEGIN NOW And flakes of mounting flames, that lick the sky. END
BEGIN NOW Oft from her bowels massy rocks are thrown, END
BEGIN NOW And, shiver'd by the force, come piecemeal down. END
BEGIN NOW Oft liquid lakes of burning sulphur flow, END
BEGIN NOW Fed from the fiery springs that boil below. END
BEGIN NOW Enceladus, they say, transfix'd by Jove, END
BEGIN NOW With blasted limbs came tumbling from above; END
BEGIN NOW And, where he fell, th' avenging father drew END
BEGIN NOW This flaming hill, and on his body threw. END
BEGIN NOW As often as he turns his weary sides, END
BEGIN NOW He shakes the solid isle, and smoke the heavens hides. END
BEGIN NOW In shady woods we pass the tedious night, END
BEGIN NOW Where bellowing sounds and groans our souls affright, END
BEGIN NOW Of which no cause is offer'd to the sight; END
BEGIN NOW For not one star was kindled in the sky, END
BEGIN NOW Nor could the moon her borrow'd light supply; END
BEGIN NOW For misty clouds involv'd the firmament, END
BEGIN NOW The stars were muffled, and the moon was pent. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had the rising sun the day reveal'd, END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had his heat the pearly dews dispell'd, END
BEGIN NOW When from the woods there bolts, before our sight, END
BEGIN NOW Somewhat betwixt a mortal and a sprite, END
BEGIN NOW So thin, so ghastly meager, and so wan, END
BEGIN NOW So bare of flesh, he scarce resembled man. END
BEGIN NOW This thing, all tatter'd, seem'd from far t' implore END
BEGIN NOW Our pious aid, and pointed to the shore. END
BEGIN NOW We look behind, then view his shaggy beard; END
BEGIN NOW His clothes were tagg'd with thorns, and filth his limbs END
BEGIN NOW besmear'd; END
BEGIN NOW The rest, in mien, in habit, and in face, END
BEGIN NOW Appear'd a Greek, and such indeed he was. END
BEGIN NOW He cast on us, from far, a frightful view, END
BEGIN NOW Whom soon for Trojans and for foes he knew; END
BEGIN NOW Stood still, and paus'd; then all at once began END
BEGIN NOW To stretch his limbs, and trembled as he ran. END
BEGIN NOW Soon as approach'd, upon his knees he falls, END
BEGIN NOW And thus with tears and sighs for pity calls: END
BEGIN NOW 'Now, by the pow'rs above, and what we share END
BEGIN NOW From Nature's common gift, this vital air, END
BEGIN NOW O Trojans, take me hence! I beg no more; END
BEGIN NOW But bear me far from this unhappy shore. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is true, I am a Greek, and farther own, END
BEGIN NOW Among your foes besieg'd th' imperial town. END
BEGIN NOW For such demerits if my death be due, END
BEGIN NOW No more for this abandon'd life I sue; END
BEGIN NOW This only favor let my tears obtain, END
BEGIN NOW To throw me headlong in the rapid main: END
BEGIN NOW Since nothing more than death my crime demands, END
BEGIN NOW I die content, to die by human hands.' END
BEGIN NOW He said, and on his knees my knees embrac'd: END
BEGIN NOW I bade him boldly tell his fortune past, END
BEGIN NOW His present state, his lineage, and his name, END
BEGIN NOW Th' occasion of his fears, and whence he came. END
BEGIN NOW The good Anchises rais'd him with his hand; END
BEGIN NOW Who, thus encourag'd, answer'd our demand: END
BEGIN NOW 'From Ithaca, my native soil, I came END
BEGIN NOW To Troy; and Achaemenides my name. END
BEGIN NOW Me my poor father with Ulysses sent; END
BEGIN NOW (O had I stay'd, with poverty content!) END
BEGIN NOW But, fearful for themselves, my countrymen END
BEGIN NOW Left me forsaken in the Cyclops' den. END
BEGIN NOW The cave, tho' large, was dark; the dismal floor END
BEGIN NOW Was pav'd with mangled limbs and putrid gore. END
BEGIN NOW Our monstrous host, of more than human size, END
BEGIN NOW Erects his head, and stares within the skies; END
BEGIN NOW Bellowing his voice, and horrid is his hue. END
BEGIN NOW Ye gods, remove this plague from mortal view! END
BEGIN NOW The joints of slaughter'd wretches are his food; END
BEGIN NOW And for his wine he quaffs the streaming blood. END
BEGIN NOW These eyes beheld, when with his spacious hand END
BEGIN NOW He seiz'd two captives of our Grecian band; END
BEGIN NOW Stretch'd on his back, he dash'd against the stones END
BEGIN NOW Their broken bodies, and their crackling bones: END
BEGIN NOW With spouting blood the purple pavement swims, END
BEGIN NOW While the dire glutton grinds the trembling limbs. END
BEGIN NOW 'Not unreveng'd Ulysses bore their fate, END
BEGIN NOW Nor thoughtless of his own unhappy state; END
BEGIN NOW For, gorg'd with flesh, and drunk with human wine END
BEGIN NOW While fast asleep the giant lay supine, END
BEGIN NOW Snoring aloud, and belching from his maw END
BEGIN NOW His indigested foam, and morsels raw; END
BEGIN NOW We pray; we cast the lots, and then surround END
BEGIN NOW The monstrous body, stretch'd along the ground: END
BEGIN NOW Each, as he could approach him, lends a hand END
BEGIN NOW To bore his eyeball with a flaming brand. END
BEGIN NOW Beneath his frowning forehead lay his eye; END
BEGIN NOW For only one did the vast frame supply- END
BEGIN NOW But that a globe so large, his front it fill'd, END
BEGIN NOW Like the sun's disk or like a Grecian shield. END
BEGIN NOW The stroke succeeds; and down the pupil bends: END
BEGIN NOW This vengeance follow'd for our slaughter'd friends. END
BEGIN NOW But haste, unhappy wretches, haste to fly! END
BEGIN NOW Your cables cut, and on your oars rely! END
BEGIN NOW Such, and so vast as Polypheme appears, END
BEGIN NOW A hundred more this hated island bears: END
BEGIN NOW Like him, in caves they shut their woolly sheep; END
BEGIN NOW Like him, their herds on tops of mountains keep; END
BEGIN NOW Like him, with mighty strides, they stalk from steep to steep END
BEGIN NOW And now three moons their sharpen'd horns renew, END
BEGIN NOW Since thus, in woods and wilds, obscure from view, END
BEGIN NOW I drag my loathsome days with mortal fright, END
BEGIN NOW And in deserted caverns lodge by night; END
BEGIN NOW Oft from the rocks a dreadful prospect see END
BEGIN NOW Of the huge Cyclops, like a walking tree: END
BEGIN NOW From far I hear his thund'ring voice resound, END
BEGIN NOW And trampling feet that shake the solid ground. END
BEGIN NOW Cornels and salvage berries of the wood, END
BEGIN NOW And roots and herbs, have been my meager food. END
BEGIN NOW While all around my longing eyes I cast, END
BEGIN NOW I saw your happy ships appear at last. END
BEGIN NOW On those I fix'd my hopes, to these I run; END
BEGIN NOW 'T is all I ask, this cruel race to shun; END
BEGIN NOW What other death you please, yourselves bestow.' END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had he said, when on the mountain's brow END
BEGIN NOW We saw the giant shepherd stalk before END
BEGIN NOW His following flock, and leading to the shore: END
BEGIN NOW A monstrous bulk, deform'd, depriv'd of sight; END
BEGIN NOW His staff a trunk of pine, to guide his steps aright. END
BEGIN NOW His pond'rous whistle from his neck descends; END
BEGIN NOW His woolly care their pensive lord attends: END
BEGIN NOW This only solace his hard fortune sends. END
BEGIN NOW Soon as he reach'd the shore and touch'd the waves, END
BEGIN NOW From his bor'd eye the gutt'ring blood he laves: END
BEGIN NOW He gnash'd his teeth, and groan'd; thro' seas he strides, END
BEGIN NOW And scarce the topmost billows touch'd his sides. END
BEGIN NOW Seiz'd with a sudden fear, we run to sea, END
BEGIN NOW The cables cut, and silent haste away; END
BEGIN NOW The well-deserving stranger entertain; END
BEGIN NOW Then, buckling to the work, our oars divide the main. END
BEGIN NOW The giant harken'd to the dashing sound: END
BEGIN NOW But, when our vessels out of reach he found, END
BEGIN NOW He strided onward, and in vain essay'd END
BEGIN NOW Th' Ionian deep, and durst no farther wade. END
BEGIN NOW With that he roar'd aloud: the dreadful cry END
BEGIN NOW Shakes earth, and air, and seas; the billows fly END
BEGIN NOW Before the bellowing noise to distant Italy. END
BEGIN NOW The neigh'ring Aetna trembling all around, END
BEGIN NOW The winding caverns echo to the sound. END
BEGIN NOW His brother Cyclops hear the yelling roar, END
BEGIN NOW And, rushing down the mountains, crowd the shore. END
BEGIN NOW We saw their stern distorted looks, from far, END
BEGIN NOW And one-eyed glance, that vainly threaten'd war: END
BEGIN NOW A dreadful council, with their heads on high; END
BEGIN NOW (The misty clouds about their foreheads fly;) END
BEGIN NOW Not yielding to the tow'ring tree of Jove, END
BEGIN NOW Or tallest cypress of Diana's grove. END
BEGIN NOW New pangs of mortal fear our minds assail; END
BEGIN NOW We tug at ev'ry oar, and hoist up ev'ry sail, END
BEGIN NOW And take th' advantage of the friendly gale. END
BEGIN NOW Forewarn'd by Helenus, we strive to shun END
BEGIN NOW Charybdis' gulf, nor dare to Scylla run. END
BEGIN NOW An equal fate on either side appears: END
BEGIN NOW We, tacking to the left, are free from fears; END
BEGIN NOW For, from Pelorus' point, the North arose, END
BEGIN NOW And drove us back where swift Pantagias flows. END
BEGIN NOW His rocky mouth we pass, and make our way END
BEGIN NOW By Thapsus and Megara's winding bay. END
BEGIN NOW This passage Achaemenides had shown, END
BEGIN NOW Tracing the course which he before had run. END
BEGIN NOW Right o'er against Plemmyrium's wat'ry strand, END
BEGIN NOW There lies an isle once call'd th' Ortygian land. END
BEGIN NOW Alpheus, as old fame reports, has found END
BEGIN NOW From Greece a secret passage under ground, END
BEGIN NOW By love to beauteous Arethusa led; END
BEGIN NOW And, mingling here, they roll in the same sacred bed. END
BEGIN NOW As Helenus enjoin'd, we next adore END
BEGIN NOW Diana's name, protectress of the shore. END
BEGIN NOW With prosp'rous gales we pass the quiet sounds END
BEGIN NOW Of still Elorus, and his fruitful bounds. END
BEGIN NOW Then, doubling Cape Pachynus, we survey END
BEGIN NOW The rocky shore extended to the sea. END
BEGIN NOW The town of Camarine from far we see, END
BEGIN NOW And fenny lake, undrain'd by fate's decree. END
BEGIN NOW In sight of the Geloan fields we pass, END
BEGIN NOW And the large walls, where mighty Gela was; END
BEGIN NOW Then Agragas, with lofty summits crown'd, END
BEGIN NOW Long for the race of warlike steeds renown'd. END
BEGIN NOW We pass'd Selinus, and the palmy land, END
BEGIN NOW And widely shun the Lilybaean strand, END
BEGIN NOW Unsafe, for secret rocks and moving sand. END
BEGIN NOW At length on shore the weary fleet arriv'd, END
BEGIN NOW Which Drepanum's unhappy port receiv'd. END
BEGIN NOW Here, after endless labors, often toss'd END
BEGIN NOW By raging storms, and driv'n on ev'ry coast, END
BEGIN NOW My dear, dear father, spent with age, I lost: END
BEGIN NOW Ease of my cares, and solace of my pain, END
BEGIN NOW Sav'd thro' a thousand toils, but sav'd in vain END
BEGIN NOW The prophet, who my future woes reveal'd, END
BEGIN NOW Yet this, the greatest and the worst, conceal'd; END
BEGIN NOW And dire Celaeno, whose foreboding skill END
BEGIN NOW Denounc'd all else, was silent of the ill. END
BEGIN NOW This my last labor was. Some friendly god END
BEGIN NOW From thence convey'd us to your blest abode. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, to the list'ning queen, the royal guest END
BEGIN NOW His wand'ring course and all his toils express'd; END
BEGIN NOW And here concluding, he retir'd to rest. END
BEGIN NOW But anxious cares already seiz'd the queen: END
BEGIN NOW She fed within her veins a flame unseen; END
BEGIN NOW The hero's valor, acts, and birth inspire END
BEGIN NOW Her soul with love, and fan the secret fire. END
BEGIN NOW His words, his looks, imprinted in her heart, END
BEGIN NOW Improve the passion, and increase the smart. END
BEGIN NOW Now, when the purple morn had chas'd away END
BEGIN NOW The dewy shadows, and restor'd the day, END
BEGIN NOW Her sister first with early care she sought, END
BEGIN NOW And thus in mournful accents eas'd her thought: END
BEGIN NOW My dearest Anna, what new dreams affright END
BEGIN NOW My lab'ring soul! what visions of the night END
BEGIN NOW Disturb my quiet, and distract my breast END
BEGIN NOW With strange ideas of our Trojan guest! END
BEGIN NOW His worth, his actions, and majestic air, END
BEGIN NOW A man descended from the gods declare. END
BEGIN NOW Fear ever argues a degenerate kind; END
BEGIN NOW His birth is well asserted by his mind. END
BEGIN NOW Then, what he suffer'd, when by Fate betray'd! END
BEGIN NOW What brave attempts for falling Troy he made! END
BEGIN NOW Such were his looks, so gracefully he spoke, END
BEGIN NOW That, were I not resolv'd against the yoke END
BEGIN NOW Of hapless marriage, never to be curst END
BEGIN NOW With second love, so fatal was my first, END
BEGIN NOW To this one error I might yield again; END
BEGIN NOW For, since Sichaeus was untimely slain, END
BEGIN NOW This only man is able to subvert END
BEGIN NOW The fix'd foundations of my stubborn heart. END
BEGIN NOW And, to confess my frailty, to my shame, END
BEGIN NOW Somewhat I find within, if not the same, END
BEGIN NOW Too like the sparkles of my former flame. END
BEGIN NOW But first let yawning earth a passage rend, END
BEGIN NOW And let me thro' the dark abyss descend; END
BEGIN NOW First let avenging Jove, with flames from high, END
BEGIN NOW Drive down this body to the nether sky, END
BEGIN NOW Condemn'd with ghosts in endless night to lie, END
BEGIN NOW Before I break the plighted faith I gave! END
BEGIN NOW No! he who had my vows shall ever have; END
BEGIN NOW For, whom I lov'd on earth, I worship in the grave. END
BEGIN NOW She said: the tears ran gushing from her eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And stopp'd her speech. Her sister thus replies: END
BEGIN NOW O dearer than the vital air I breathe, END
BEGIN NOW Will you to grief your blooming years bequeath, END
BEGIN NOW Condemn'd to waste in woes your lonely life, END
BEGIN NOW Without the joys of mother or of wife? END
BEGIN NOW Think you these tears, this pompous train of woe, END
BEGIN NOW Are known or valued by the ghosts below? END
BEGIN NOW I grant that, while your sorrows yet were green, END
BEGIN NOW It well became a woman, and a queen, END
BEGIN NOW The vows of Tyrian princes to neglect, END
BEGIN NOW To scorn Hyarbas, and his love reject, END
BEGIN NOW With all the Libyan lords of mighty name; END
BEGIN NOW But will you fight against a pleasing flame! END
BEGIN NOW This little spot of land, which Heav'n bestows, END
BEGIN NOW On ev'ry side is hemm'd with warlike foes; END
BEGIN NOW Gaetulian cities here are spread around, END
BEGIN NOW And fierce Numidians there your frontiers bound; END
BEGIN NOW Here lies a barren waste of thirsty land, END
BEGIN NOW And there the Syrtes raise the moving sand; END
BEGIN NOW Barcaean troops besiege the narrow shore, END
BEGIN NOW And from the sea Pygmalion threatens more. END
BEGIN NOW Propitious Heav'n, and gracious Juno, lead END
BEGIN NOW This wand'ring navy to your needful aid: END
BEGIN NOW How will your empire spread, your city rise, END
BEGIN NOW From such a union, and with such allies? END
BEGIN NOW Implore the favor of the pow'rs above, END
BEGIN NOW And leave the conduct of the rest to love. END
BEGIN NOW Continue still your hospitable way, END
BEGIN NOW And still invent occasions of their stay, END
BEGIN NOW Till storms and winter winds shall cease to threat, END
BEGIN NOW And planks and oars repair their shatter'd fleet. END
BEGIN NOW These words, which from a friend and sister came, END
BEGIN NOW With ease resolv'd the scruples of her fame, END
BEGIN NOW And added fury to the kindled flame. END
BEGIN NOW Inspir'd with hope, the project they pursue; END
BEGIN NOW On ev'ry altar sacrifice renew: END
BEGIN NOW A chosen ewe of two years old they pay END
BEGIN NOW Preferring Juno's pow'r, for Juno ties END
BEGIN NOW The nuptial knot and makes the marriage joys. END
BEGIN NOW The beauteous queen before her altar stands, END
BEGIN NOW And holds the golden goblet in her hands. END
BEGIN NOW A milk-white heifer she with flow'rs adorns, END
BEGIN NOW And pours the ruddy wine betwixt her horns; END
BEGIN NOW And, while the priests with pray'r the gods invoke, END
BEGIN NOW She feeds their altars with Sabaean smoke, END
BEGIN NOW With hourly care the sacrifice renews, END
BEGIN NOW And anxiously the panting entrails views. END
BEGIN NOW What priestly rites, alas! what pious art, END
BEGIN NOW What vows avail to cure a bleeding heart! END
BEGIN NOW A gentle fire she feeds within her veins, END
BEGIN NOW Where the soft god secure in silence reigns. END
BEGIN NOW Sick with desire, and seeking him she loves, END
BEGIN NOW From street to street the raving Dido roves. END
BEGIN NOW So when the watchful shepherd, from the blind, END
BEGIN NOW Wounds with a random shaft the careless hind, END
BEGIN NOW Distracted with her pain she flies the woods, END
BEGIN NOW Bounds o'er the lawn, and seeks the silent floods, END
BEGIN NOW With fruitless care; for still the fatal dart END
BEGIN NOW Sticks in her side, and rankles in her heart. END
BEGIN NOW And now she leads the Trojan chief along END
BEGIN NOW The lofty walls, amidst the busy throng; END
BEGIN NOW Displays her Tyrian wealth, and rising town, END
BEGIN NOW Which love, without his labor, makes his own. END
BEGIN NOW This pomp she shows, to tempt her wand'ring guest; END
BEGIN NOW Her falt'ring tongue forbids to speak the rest. END
BEGIN NOW When day declines, and feasts renew the night, END
BEGIN NOW Still on his face she feeds her famish'd sight; END
BEGIN NOW She longs again to hear the prince relate END
BEGIN NOW His own adventures and the Trojan fate. END
BEGIN NOW He tells it o'er and o'er; but still in vain, END
BEGIN NOW For still she begs to hear it once again. END
BEGIN NOW The hearer on the speaker's mouth depends, END
BEGIN NOW And thus the tragic story never ends. END
BEGIN NOW Then, when they part, when Phoebe's paler light END
BEGIN NOW Withdraws, and falling stars to sleep invite, END
BEGIN NOW She last remains, when ev'ry guest is gone, END
BEGIN NOW Sits on the bed he press'd, and sighs alone; END
BEGIN NOW Absent, her absent hero sees and hears; END
BEGIN NOW Or in her bosom young Ascanius bears, END
BEGIN NOW And seeks the father's image in the child, END
BEGIN NOW If love by likeness might be so beguil'd. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the rising tow'rs are at a stand; END
BEGIN NOW No labors exercise the youthful band, END
BEGIN NOW Nor use of arts, nor toils of arms they know; END
BEGIN NOW The mole is left unfinish'd to the foe; END
BEGIN NOW The mounds, the works, the walls, neglected lie, END
BEGIN NOW Short of their promis'd heighth, that seem'd to threat the sky, END
BEGIN NOW But when imperial Juno, from above, END
BEGIN NOW Saw Dido fetter'd in the chains of love, END
BEGIN NOW Hot with the venom which her veins inflam'd, END
BEGIN NOW And by no sense of shame to be reclaim'd, END
BEGIN NOW With soothing words to Venus she begun: END
BEGIN NOW High praises, endless honors, you have won, END
BEGIN NOW And mighty trophies, with your worthy son! END
BEGIN NOW Two gods a silly woman have undone! END
BEGIN NOW Nor am I ignorant, you both suspect END
BEGIN NOW This rising city, which my hands erect: END
BEGIN NOW But shall celestial discord never cease? END
BEGIN NOW 'T is better ended in a lasting peace. END
BEGIN NOW You stand possess'd of all your soul desir'd: END
BEGIN NOW Poor Dido with consuming love is fir'd. END
BEGIN NOW Your Trojan with my Tyrian let us join; END
BEGIN NOW So Dido shall be yours, Aeneas mine: END
BEGIN NOW One common kingdom, one united line. END
BEGIN NOW Eliza shall a Dardan lord obey, END
BEGIN NOW And lofty Carthage for a dow'r convey. END
BEGIN NOW Then Venus, who her hidden fraud descried, END
BEGIN NOW Which would the scepter of the world misguide END
BEGIN NOW To Libyan shores, thus artfully replied: END
BEGIN NOW Who, but a fool, would wars with Juno choose, END
BEGIN NOW And such alliance and such gifts refuse, END
BEGIN NOW If Fortune with our joint desires comply? END
BEGIN NOW The doubt is all from Jove and destiny; END
BEGIN NOW Lest he forbid, with absolute command, END
BEGIN NOW To mix the people in one common land- END
BEGIN NOW Or will the Trojan and the Tyrian line END
BEGIN NOW In lasting leagues and sure succession join? END
BEGIN NOW But you, the partner of his bed and throne, END
BEGIN NOW May move his mind; my wishes are your own. END
BEGIN NOW Mine, said imperial Juno, "be the care; END
BEGIN NOW Time urges, now, to perfect this affair: END
BEGIN NOW Attend my counsel, and the secret share. END
BEGIN NOW When next the Sun his rising light displays, END
BEGIN NOW And gilds the world below with purple rays, END
BEGIN NOW The queen, Aeneas, and the Tyrian court END
BEGIN NOW Shall to the shady woods, for sylvan game, resort. END
BEGIN NOW There, while the huntsmen pitch their toils around, END
BEGIN NOW And cheerful horns from side to side resound, END
BEGIN NOW A pitchy cloud shall cover all the plain END
BEGIN NOW With hail, and thunder, and tempestuous rain; END
BEGIN NOW The fearful train shall take their speedy flight, END
BEGIN NOW Dispers'd, and all involv'd in gloomy night; END
BEGIN NOW One cave a grateful shelter shall afford END
BEGIN NOW To the fair princess and the Trojan lord. END
BEGIN NOW I will myself the bridal bed prepare, END
BEGIN NOW If you, to bless the nuptials, will be there: END
BEGIN NOW So shall their loves be crown'd with due delights, END
BEGIN NOW And Hymen shall be present at the rites. END
BEGIN NOW The Queen of Love consents, and closely smiles END
BEGIN NOW At her vain project, and discover'd wiles. END
BEGIN NOW The rosy morn was risen from the main, END
BEGIN NOW And horns and hounds awake the princely train: END
BEGIN NOW They issue early thro' the city gate, END
BEGIN NOW Where the more wakeful huntsmen ready wait, END
BEGIN NOW With nets, and toils, and darts, beside the force END
BEGIN NOW Of Spartan dogs, and swift Massylian horse. END
BEGIN NOW The Tyrian peers and officers of state END
BEGIN NOW For the slow queen in antechambers wait; END
BEGIN NOW Her lofty courser, in the court below, END
BEGIN NOW Who his majestic rider seems to know, END
BEGIN NOW Proud of his purple trappings, paws the ground, END
BEGIN NOW And champs the golden bit, and spreads the foam around. END
BEGIN NOW The queen at length appears; on either hand END
BEGIN NOW The brawny guards in martial order stand. END
BEGIN NOW A flow'r'd simar with golden fringe she wore, END
BEGIN NOW And at her back a golden quiver bore; END
BEGIN NOW Her flowing hair a golden caul restrains, END
BEGIN NOW A golden clasp the Tyrian robe sustains. END
BEGIN NOW Then young Ascanius, with a sprightly grace, END
BEGIN NOW Leads on the Trojan youth to view the chase. END
BEGIN NOW But far above the rest in beauty shines END
BEGIN NOW The great Aeneas, the troop he joins; END
BEGIN NOW Like fair Apollo, when he leaves the frost END
BEGIN NOW Of wint'ry Xanthus, and the Lycian coast, END
BEGIN NOW When to his native Delos he resorts, END
BEGIN NOW Ordains the dances, and renews the sports; END
BEGIN NOW Where painted Scythians, mix'd with Cretan bands, END
BEGIN NOW Before the joyful altars join their hands: END
BEGIN NOW Himself, on Cynthus walking, sees below END
BEGIN NOW The merry madness of the sacred show. END
BEGIN NOW Green wreaths of bays his length of hair inclose; END
BEGIN NOW A golden fillet binds his awful brows; END
BEGIN NOW His quiver sounds: not less the prince is seen END
BEGIN NOW In manly presence, or in lofty mien. END
BEGIN NOW Now had they reach'd the hills, and storm'd the seat END
BEGIN NOW Of salvage beasts, in dens, their last retreat. END
BEGIN NOW The cry pursues the mountain goats: they bound END
BEGIN NOW From rock to rock, and keep the craggy ground; END
BEGIN NOW Quite otherwise the stags, a trembling train, END
BEGIN NOW In herds unsingled, scour the dusty plain, END
BEGIN NOW And a long chase in open view maintain. END
BEGIN NOW The glad Ascanius, as his courser guides, END
BEGIN NOW Spurs thro' the vale, and these and those outrides. END
BEGIN NOW His horse's flanks and sides are forc'd to feel END
BEGIN NOW The clanking lash, and goring of the steel. END
BEGIN NOW Impatiently he views the feeble prey, END
BEGIN NOW Wishing some nobler beast to cross his way, END
BEGIN NOW And rather would the tusky boar attend, END
BEGIN NOW Or see the tawny lion downward bend. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime, the gath'ring clouds obscure the skies: END
BEGIN NOW From pole to pole the forky lightning flies; END
BEGIN NOW The rattling thunders roll; and Juno pours END
BEGIN NOW A wintry deluge down, and sounding show'rs. END
BEGIN NOW The company, dispers'd, to converts ride, END
BEGIN NOW And seek the homely cots, or mountain's hollow side. END
BEGIN NOW The rapid rains, descending from the hills, END
BEGIN NOW To rolling torrents raise the creeping rills. END
BEGIN NOW The queen and prince, as love or fortune guides, END
BEGIN NOW One common cavern in her bosom hides. END
BEGIN NOW Then first the trembling earth the signal gave, END
BEGIN NOW And flashing fires enlighten all the cave; END
BEGIN NOW Hell from below, and Juno from above, END
BEGIN NOW And howling nymphs, were conscious of their love. END
BEGIN NOW From this ill-omen'd hour in time arose END
BEGIN NOW Debate and death, and all succeeding woes. END
BEGIN NOW The queen, whom sense of honor could not move, END
BEGIN NOW No longer made a secret of her love, END
BEGIN NOW But call'd it marriage, by that specious name END
BEGIN NOW To veil the crime and sanctify the shame. END
BEGIN NOW The loud report thro' Libyan cities goes. END
BEGIN NOW Fame, the great ill, from small beginnings grows: END
BEGIN NOW Swift from the first; and ev'ry moment brings END
BEGIN NOW New vigor to her flights, new pinions to her wings. END
BEGIN NOW Soon grows the pigmy to gigantic size; END
BEGIN NOW Her feet on earth, her forehead in the skies. END
BEGIN NOW Inrag'd against the gods, revengeful Earth END
BEGIN NOW Produc'd her last of the Titanian birth. END
BEGIN NOW Swift is her walk, more swift her winged haste: END
BEGIN NOW A monstrous phantom, horrible and vast. END
BEGIN NOW As many plumes as raise her lofty flight, END
BEGIN NOW So many piercing eyes inlarge her sight; END
BEGIN NOW Millions of opening mouths to Fame belong, END
BEGIN NOW And ev'ry mouth is furnish'd with a tongue, END
BEGIN NOW And round with list'ning ears the flying plague is hung. END
BEGIN NOW She fills the peaceful universe with cries; END
BEGIN NOW No slumbers ever close her wakeful eyes; END
BEGIN NOW By day, from lofty tow'rs her head she shews, END
BEGIN NOW And spreads thro' trembling crowds disastrous news; END
BEGIN NOW With court informers haunts, and royal spies; END
BEGIN NOW Talk is her business, and her chief delight END
BEGIN NOW To tell of prodigies and cause affright. END
BEGIN NOW She fills the people's ears with Dido's name, END
BEGIN NOW Who, lost to honor and the sense of shame, END
BEGIN NOW Admits into her throne and nuptial bed END
BEGIN NOW A wand'ring guest, who from his country fled: END
BEGIN NOW Whole days with him she passes in delights, END
BEGIN NOW And wastes in luxury long winter nights, END
BEGIN NOW Forgetful of her fame and royal trust, END
BEGIN NOW Dissolv'd in ease, abandon'd to her lust. END
BEGIN NOW The goddess widely spreads the loud report, END
BEGIN NOW And flies at length to King Hyarba's court. END
BEGIN NOW When first possess'd with this unwelcome news END
BEGIN NOW Whom did he not of men and gods accuse? END
BEGIN NOW This prince, from ravish'd Garamantis born, END
BEGIN NOW A hundred temples did with spoils adorn, END
BEGIN NOW In Ammon's honor, his celestial sire; END
BEGIN NOW A hundred altars fed with wakeful fire; END
BEGIN NOW And, thro' his vast dominions, priests ordain'd, END
BEGIN NOW Whose watchful care these holy rites maintain'd. END
BEGIN NOW The gates and columns were with garlands crown'd, END
BEGIN NOW And blood of victim beasts enrich'd the ground. END
BEGIN NOW He, when he heard a fugitive could move END
BEGIN NOW The Tyrian princess, who disdain'd his love, END
BEGIN NOW His breast with fury burn'd, his eyes with fire, END
BEGIN NOW Mad with despair, impatient with desire; END
BEGIN NOW Then on the sacred altars pouring wine, END
BEGIN NOW He thus with pray'rs implor'd his sire divine: END
BEGIN NOW Great Jove! propitious to the Moorish race, END
BEGIN NOW Who feast on painted beds, with off'rings grace END
BEGIN NOW Thy temples, and adore thy pow'r divine END
BEGIN NOW With blood of victims, and with sparkling wine, END
BEGIN NOW Seest thou not this? or do we fear in vain END
BEGIN NOW Thy boasted thunder, and thy thoughtless reign? END
BEGIN NOW Do thy broad hands the forky lightnings lance? END
BEGIN NOW Thine are the bolts, or the blind work of chance? END
BEGIN NOW A wand'ring woman builds, within our state, END
BEGIN NOW A little town, bought at an easy rate; END
BEGIN NOW She pays me homage, and my grants allow END
BEGIN NOW A narrow space of Libyan lands to plow; END
BEGIN NOW Yet, scorning me, by passion blindly led, END
BEGIN NOW Admits a banish'd Trojan to her bed! END
BEGIN NOW And now this other Paris, with his train END
BEGIN NOW Of conquer'd cowards, must in Afric reign! END
BEGIN NOW (Whom, what they are, their looks and garb confess, END
BEGIN NOW Their locks with oil perfum'd, their Lydian dress.) END
BEGIN NOW He takes the spoil, enjoys the princely dame; END
BEGIN NOW And I, rejected I, adore an empty name. END
BEGIN NOW His vows, in haughty terms, he thus preferr'd, END
BEGIN NOW And held his altar's horns. The mighty Thund'rer heard; END
BEGIN NOW Then cast his eyes on Carthage, where he found END
BEGIN NOW The lustful pair in lawless pleasure drown'd, END
BEGIN NOW Lost in their loves, insensible of shame, END
BEGIN NOW And both forgetful of their better fame. END
BEGIN NOW He calls Cyllenius, and the god attends, END
BEGIN NOW By whom his menacing command he sends: END
BEGIN NOW Go, mount the western winds, and cleave the sky; END
BEGIN NOW Then, with a swift descent, to Carthage fly: END
BEGIN NOW There find the Trojan chief, who wastes his days END
BEGIN NOW In slothful not and inglorious ease, END
BEGIN NOW Nor minds the future city, giv'n by fate. END
BEGIN NOW To him this message from my mouth relate: END
BEGIN NOW 'Not so fair Venus hop'd, when twice she won END
BEGIN NOW Thy life with pray'rs, nor promis'd such a son. END
BEGIN NOW Hers was a hero, destin'd to command END
BEGIN NOW A martial race, and rule the Latian land, END
BEGIN NOW Who should his ancient line from Teucer draw, END
BEGIN NOW And on the conquer'd world impose the law.' END
BEGIN NOW If glory cannot move a mind so mean, END
BEGIN NOW Nor future praise from fading pleasure wean, END
BEGIN NOW Yet why should he defraud his son of fame, END
BEGIN NOW And grudge the Romans their immortal name! END
BEGIN NOW What are his vain designs! what hopes he more END
BEGIN NOW From his long ling'ring on a hostile shore, END
BEGIN NOW Regardless to redeem his honor lost, END
BEGIN NOW And for his race to gain th' Ausonian coast! END
BEGIN NOW Bid him with speed the Tyrian court forsake; END
BEGIN NOW With this command the slumb'ring warrior wake. END
BEGIN NOW Hermes obeys; with golden pinions binds END
BEGIN NOW His flying feet, and mounts the western winds: END
BEGIN NOW And, whether o'er the seas or earth he flies, END
BEGIN NOW With rapid force they bear him down the skies. END
BEGIN NOW But first he grasps within his awful hand END
BEGIN NOW The mark of sov'reign pow'r, his magic wand; END
BEGIN NOW With this he draws the ghosts from hollow graves; END
BEGIN NOW With this he drives them down the Stygian waves; END
BEGIN NOW With this he seals in sleep the wakeful sight, END
BEGIN NOW And eyes, tho' clos'd in death, restores to light. END
BEGIN NOW Thus arm'd, the god begins his airy race, END
BEGIN NOW And drives the racking clouds along the liquid space; END
BEGIN NOW Now sees the tops of Atlas, as he flies, END
BEGIN NOW Whose brawny back supports the starry skies; END
BEGIN NOW Atlas, whose head, with piny forests crown'd, END
BEGIN NOW Is beaten by the winds, with foggy vapors bound. END
BEGIN NOW Snows hide his shoulders; from beneath his chin END
BEGIN NOW The founts of rolling streams their race begin; END
BEGIN NOW A beard of ice on his large breast depends. END
BEGIN NOW Here, pois'd upon his wings, the god descends: END
BEGIN NOW Then, rested thus, he from the tow'ring height END
BEGIN NOW Plung'd downward, with precipitated flight, END
BEGIN NOW Lights on the seas, and skims along the flood. END
BEGIN NOW As waterfowl, who seek their fishy food, END
BEGIN NOW Less, and yet less, to distant prospect show; END
BEGIN NOW By turns they dance aloft, and dive below: END
BEGIN NOW Like these, the steerage of his wings he plies, END
BEGIN NOW And near the surface of the water flies, END
BEGIN NOW Till, having pass'd the seas, and cross'd the sands, END
BEGIN NOW He clos'd his wings, and stoop'd on Libyan lands: END
BEGIN NOW Where shepherds once were hous'd in homely sheds, END
BEGIN NOW Now tow'rs within the clouds advance their heads. END
BEGIN NOW Arriving there, he found the Trojan prince END
BEGIN NOW New ramparts raising for the town's defense. END
BEGIN NOW A purple scarf, with gold embroider'd o'er, END
BEGIN NOW (Queen Dido's gift,) about his waist he wore; END
BEGIN NOW A sword, with glitt'ring gems diversified, END
BEGIN NOW For ornament, not use, hung idly by his side. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus, with winged words, the god began, END
BEGIN NOW Resuming his own shape: "Degenerate man, END
BEGIN NOW Thou woman's property, what mak'st thou here, END
BEGIN NOW These foreign walls and Tyrian tow'rs to rear, END
BEGIN NOW Forgetful of thy own? All-pow'rful Jove, END
BEGIN NOW Who sways the world below and heav'n above, END
BEGIN NOW Has sent me down with this severe command: END
BEGIN NOW What means thy ling'ring in the Libyan land? END
BEGIN NOW If glory cannot move a mind so mean, END
BEGIN NOW Nor future praise from flitting pleasure wean, END
BEGIN NOW Regard the fortunes of thy rising heir: END
BEGIN NOW The promis'd crown let young Ascanius wear, END
BEGIN NOW To whom th' Ausonian scepter, and the state END
BEGIN NOW Of Rome's imperial name is ow'd by fate. END
BEGIN NOW So spoke the god; and, speaking, took his flight, END
BEGIN NOW Involv'd in clouds, and vanish'd out of sight. END
BEGIN NOW The pious prince was seiz'd with sudden fear; END
BEGIN NOW Mute was his tongue, and upright stood his hair. END
BEGIN NOW Revolving in his mind the stern command, END
BEGIN NOW He longs to fly, and loathes the charming land. END
BEGIN NOW What should he say? or how should he begin? END
BEGIN NOW What course, alas! remains to steer between END
BEGIN NOW Th' offended lover and the pow'rful queen? END
BEGIN NOW This way and that he turns his anxious mind, END
BEGIN NOW And all expedients tries, and none can find. END
BEGIN NOW Fix'd on the deed, but doubtful of the means, END
BEGIN NOW After long thought, to this advice he leans: END
BEGIN NOW Three chiefs he calls, commands them to repair END
BEGIN NOW The fleet, and ship their men with silent care; END
BEGIN NOW Some plausible pretense he bids them find, END
BEGIN NOW To color what in secret he design'd. END
BEGIN NOW Himself, meantime, the softest hours would choose, END
BEGIN NOW Before the love-sick lady heard the news; END
BEGIN NOW And move her tender mind, by slow degrees, END
BEGIN NOW To suffer what the sov'reign pow'r decrees: END
BEGIN NOW Jove will inspire him, when, and what to say. END
BEGIN NOW They hear with pleasure, and with haste obey. END
BEGIN NOW But soon the queen perceives the thin disguise: END
BEGIN NOW (What arts can blind a jealous woman's eyes!) END
BEGIN NOW She was the first to find the secret fraud, END
BEGIN NOW Before the fatal news was blaz'd abroad. END
BEGIN NOW Love the first motions of the lover hears, END
BEGIN NOW Quick to presage, and ev'n in safety fears. END
BEGIN NOW Nor impious Fame was wanting to report END
BEGIN NOW The ships repair'd, the Trojans' thick resort, END
BEGIN NOW And purpose to forsake the Tyrian court. END
BEGIN NOW Frantic with fear, impatient of the wound, END
BEGIN NOW And impotent of mind, she roves the city round. END
BEGIN NOW Less wild the Bacchanalian dames appear, END
BEGIN NOW When, from afar, their nightly god they hear, END
BEGIN NOW And howl about the hills, and shake the wreathy spear. END
BEGIN NOW At length she finds the dear perfidious man; END
BEGIN NOW Prevents his form'd excuse, and thus began: END
BEGIN NOW Base and ungrateful! could you hope to fly, END
BEGIN NOW And undiscover'd scape a lover's eye? END
BEGIN NOW Nor could my kindness your compassion move. END
BEGIN NOW Nor plighted vows, nor dearer bands of love? END
BEGIN NOW Or is the death of a despairing queen END
BEGIN NOW Not worth preventing, tho' too well foreseen? END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n when the wintry winds command your stay, END
BEGIN NOW You dare the tempests, and defy the sea. END
BEGIN NOW False as you are, suppose you were not bound END
BEGIN NOW To lands unknown, and foreign coasts to sound; END
BEGIN NOW Were Troy restor'd, and Priam's happy reign, END
BEGIN NOW Now durst you tempt, for Troy, the raging main? END
BEGIN NOW See whom you fly! am I the foe you shun? END
BEGIN NOW Now, by those holy vows, so late begun, END
BEGIN NOW By this right hand, (since I have nothing more END
BEGIN NOW To challenge, but the faith you gave before;) END
BEGIN NOW I beg you by these tears too truly shed, END
BEGIN NOW By the new pleasures of our nuptial bed; END
BEGIN NOW If ever Dido, when you most were kind, END
BEGIN NOW Were pleasing in your eyes, or touch'd your mind; END
BEGIN NOW By these my pray'rs, if pray'rs may yet have place, END
BEGIN NOW Pity the fortunes of a falling race. END
BEGIN NOW For you I have provok'd a tyrant's hate, END
BEGIN NOW Incens'd the Libyan and the Tyrian state; END
BEGIN NOW For you alone I suffer in my fame, END
BEGIN NOW Bereft of honor, and expos'd to shame. END
BEGIN NOW Whom have I now to trust, ungrateful guest? END
BEGIN NOW (That only name remains of all the rest!) END
BEGIN NOW What have I left? or whither can I fly? END
BEGIN NOW Must I attend Pygmalion's cruelty, END
BEGIN NOW Or till Hyarba shall in triumph lead END
BEGIN NOW A queen that proudly scorn'd his proffer'd bed? END
BEGIN NOW Had you deferr'd, at least, your hasty flight, END
BEGIN NOW And left behind some pledge of our delight, END
BEGIN NOW Some babe to bless the mother's mournful sight, END
BEGIN NOW Some young Aeneas, to supply your place, END
BEGIN NOW Whose features might express his father's face; END
BEGIN NOW I should not then complain to live bereft END
BEGIN NOW Of all my husband, or be wholly left. END
BEGIN NOW Here paus'd the queen. Unmov'd he holds his eyes, END
BEGIN NOW By Jove's command; nor suffer'd love to rise, END
BEGIN NOW Tho' heaving in his heart; and thus at length replies: END
BEGIN NOW Fair queen, you never can enough repeat END
BEGIN NOW Your boundless favors, or I own my debt; END
BEGIN NOW Nor can my mind forget Eliza's name, END
BEGIN NOW While vital breath inspires this mortal frame. END
BEGIN NOW This only let me speak in my defense: END
BEGIN NOW I never hop'd a secret flight from hence, END
BEGIN NOW Much less pretended to the lawful claim END
BEGIN NOW Of sacred nuptials, or a husband's name. END
BEGIN NOW For, if indulgent Heav'n would leave me free, END
BEGIN NOW And not submit my life to fate's decree, END
BEGIN NOW My choice would lead me to the Trojan shore, END
BEGIN NOW Those relics to review, their dust adore, END
BEGIN NOW And Priam's ruin'd palace to restore. END
BEGIN NOW But now the Delphian oracle commands, END
BEGIN NOW And fate invites me to the Latian lands. END
BEGIN NOW That is the promis'd place to which I steer, END
BEGIN NOW And all my vows are terminated there. END
BEGIN NOW If you, a Tyrian, and a stranger born, END
BEGIN NOW With walls and tow'rs a Libyan town adorn, END
BEGIN NOW Why may not we- like you, a foreign race- END
BEGIN NOW Like you, seek shelter in a foreign place? END
BEGIN NOW As often as the night obscures the skies END
BEGIN NOW With humid shades, or twinkling stars arise, END
BEGIN NOW Anchises' angry ghost in dreams appears, END
BEGIN NOW Chides my delay, and fills my soul with fears; END
BEGIN NOW And young Ascanius justly may complain END
BEGIN NOW Of his defrauded and destin'd reign. END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n now the herald of the gods appear'd: END
BEGIN NOW Waking I saw him, and his message heard. END
BEGIN NOW From Jove he came commission'd, heav'nly bright END
BEGIN NOW With radiant beams, and manifest to sight END
BEGIN NOW (The sender and the sent I both attest) END
BEGIN NOW These walls he enter'd, and those words express'd. END
BEGIN NOW Fair queen, oppose not what the gods command; END
BEGIN NOW Forc'd by my fate, I leave your happy land. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while he spoke, already she began, END
BEGIN NOW With sparkling eyes, to view the guilty man; END
BEGIN NOW From head to foot survey'd his person o'er, END
BEGIN NOW Nor longer these outrageous threats forebore: END
BEGIN NOW False as thou art, and, more than false, forsworn! END
BEGIN NOW Not sprung from noble blood, nor goddess-born, END
BEGIN NOW But hewn from harden'd entrails of a rock! END
BEGIN NOW And rough Hyrcanian tigers gave thee suck! END
BEGIN NOW Why should I fawn? what have I worse to fear? END
BEGIN NOW Did he once look, or lent a list'ning ear, END
BEGIN NOW Sigh'd when I sobb'd, or shed one kindly tear?- END
BEGIN NOW All symptoms of a base ungrateful mind, END
BEGIN NOW So foul, that, which is worse, 'tis hard to find. END
BEGIN NOW Of man's injustice why should I complain? END
BEGIN NOW The gods, and Jove himself, behold in vain END
BEGIN NOW Triumphant treason; yet no thunder flies, END
BEGIN NOW Nor Juno views my wrongs with equal eyes; END
BEGIN NOW Faithless is earth, and faithless are the skies! END
BEGIN NOW Justice is fled, and Truth is now no more! END
BEGIN NOW I sav'd the shipwrack'd exile on my shore; END
BEGIN NOW With needful food his hungry Trojans fed; END
BEGIN NOW I took the traitor to my throne and bed: END
BEGIN NOW Fool that I was- 't is little to repeat END
BEGIN NOW The rest- I stor'd and rigg'd his ruin'd fleet. END
BEGIN NOW I rave, I rave! A god's command he pleads, END
BEGIN NOW And makes Heav'n accessary to his deeds. END
BEGIN NOW Now Lycian lots, and now the Delian god, END
BEGIN NOW Now Hermes is employ'd from Jove's abode, END
BEGIN NOW To warn him hence; as if the peaceful state END
BEGIN NOW Of heav'nly pow'rs were touch'd with human fate! END
BEGIN NOW But go! thy flight no longer I detain- END
BEGIN NOW Go seek thy promis'd kingdom thro' the main! END
BEGIN NOW Yet, if the heav'ns will hear my pious vow, END
BEGIN NOW The faithless waves, not half so false as thou, END
BEGIN NOW Or secret sands, shall sepulchers afford END
BEGIN NOW To thy proud vessels, and their perjur'd lord. END
BEGIN NOW Then shalt thou call on injur'd Dido's name: END
BEGIN NOW Dido shall come in a black sulph'ry flame, END
BEGIN NOW When death has once dissolv'd her mortal frame; END
BEGIN NOW Shall smile to see the traitor vainly weep: END
BEGIN NOW Her angry ghost, arising from the deep, END
BEGIN NOW Shall haunt thee waking, and disturb thy sleep. END
BEGIN NOW At least my shade thy punishment shall know, END
BEGIN NOW And Fame shall spread the pleasing news below. END
BEGIN NOW Abruptly here she stops; then turns away END
BEGIN NOW Her loathing eyes, and shuns the sight of day. END
BEGIN NOW Amaz'd he stood, revolving in his mind END
BEGIN NOW What speech to frame, and what excuse to find. END
BEGIN NOW Her fearful maids their fainting mistress led, END
BEGIN NOW And softly laid her on her ivory bed. END
BEGIN NOW But good Aeneas, tho' he much desir'd END
BEGIN NOW To give that pity which her grief requir'd; END
BEGIN NOW Tho' much he mourn'd, and labor'd with his love, END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd at length, obeys the will of Jove; END
BEGIN NOW Reviews his forces: they with early care END
BEGIN NOW Unmoor their vessels, and for sea prepare. END
BEGIN NOW The fleet is soon afloat, in all its pride, END
BEGIN NOW And well-calk'd galleys in the harbor ride. END
BEGIN NOW Then oaks for oars they fell'd; or, as they stood, END
BEGIN NOW Of its green arms despoil'd the growing wood, END
BEGIN NOW Studious of flight. The beach is cover'd o'er END
BEGIN NOW With Trojan bands, that blacken all the shore: END
BEGIN NOW On ev'ry side are seen, descending down, END
BEGIN NOW Thick swarms of soldiers, loaden from the town. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, in battalia, march embodied ants, END
BEGIN NOW Fearful of winter, and of future wants, END
BEGIN NOW T' invade the corn, and to their cells convey END
BEGIN NOW The plunder'd forage of their yellow prey. END
BEGIN NOW The sable troops, along the narrow tracks, END
BEGIN NOW Scarce bear the weighty burthen on their backs: END
BEGIN NOW Some set their shoulders to the pond'rous grain; END
BEGIN NOW Some guard the spoil; some lash the lagging train; END
BEGIN NOW All ply their sev'ral tasks, and equal toil sustain. END
BEGIN NOW What pangs the tender breast of Dido tore, END
BEGIN NOW When, from the tow'r, she saw the cover'd shore, END
BEGIN NOW And heard the shouts of sailors from afar, END
BEGIN NOW Mix'd with the murmurs of the wat'ry war! END
BEGIN NOW All-pow'rful Love! what changes canst thou cause END
BEGIN NOW In human hearts, subjected to thy laws! END
BEGIN NOW Once more her haughty soul the tyrant bends: END
BEGIN NOW To pray'rs and mean submissions she descends. END
BEGIN NOW No female arts or aids she left untried, END
BEGIN NOW Nor counsels unexplor'd, before she died. END
BEGIN NOW Look, Anna! look! the Trojans crowd to sea; END
BEGIN NOW They spread their canvas, and their anchors weigh. END
BEGIN NOW The shouting crew their ships with garlands bind, END
BEGIN NOW Invoke the sea gods, and invite the wind. END
BEGIN NOW Could I have thought this threat'ning blow so near, END
BEGIN NOW My tender soul had been forewarn'd to bear. END
BEGIN NOW But do not you my last request deny; END
BEGIN NOW With yon perfidious man your int'rest try, END
BEGIN NOW And bring me news, if I must live or die. END
BEGIN NOW You are his fav'rite; you alone can find END
BEGIN NOW The dark recesses of his inmost mind: END
BEGIN NOW In all his trusted secrets you have part, END
BEGIN NOW And know the soft approaches to his heart. END
BEGIN NOW Haste then, and humbly seek my haughty foe; END
BEGIN NOW Tell him, I did not with the Grecians go, END
BEGIN NOW Nor did my fleet against his friends employ, END
BEGIN NOW Nor swore the ruin of unhappy Troy, END
BEGIN NOW Nor mov'd with hands profane his father's dust: END
BEGIN NOW Why should he then reject a just! END
BEGIN NOW Whom does he shun, and whither would he fly! END
BEGIN NOW Can he this last, this only pray'r deny! END
BEGIN NOW Let him at least his dang'rous flight delay, END
BEGIN NOW Wait better winds, and hope a calmer sea. END
BEGIN NOW The nuptials he disclaims I urge no more: END
BEGIN NOW Let him pursue the promis'd Latian shore. END
BEGIN NOW A short delay is all I ask him now; END
BEGIN NOW A pause of grief, an interval from woe, END
BEGIN NOW Till my soft soul be temper'd to sustain END
BEGIN NOW Accustom'd sorrows, and inur'd to pain. END
BEGIN NOW If you in pity grant this one request, END
BEGIN NOW My death shall glut the hatred of his breast. END
BEGIN NOW This mournful message pious Anna bears, END
BEGIN NOW And seconds with her own her sister's tears: END
BEGIN NOW But all her arts are still employ'd in vain; END
BEGIN NOW Again she comes, and is refus'd again. END
BEGIN NOW His harden'd heart nor pray'rs nor threat'nings move; END
BEGIN NOW Fate, and the god, had stopp'd his ears to love. END
BEGIN NOW As, when the winds their airy quarrel try, END
BEGIN NOW Justling from ev'ry quarter of the sky, END
BEGIN NOW This way and that the mountain oak they bend, END
BEGIN NOW His boughs they shatter, and his branches rend; END
BEGIN NOW With leaves and falling mast they spread the ground; END
BEGIN NOW The hollow valleys echo to the sound: END
BEGIN NOW Unmov'd, the royal plant their fury mocks, END
BEGIN NOW Or, shaken, clings more closely to the rocks; END
BEGIN NOW Far as he shoots his tow'ring head on high, END
BEGIN NOW So deep in earth his fix'd foundations lie. END
BEGIN NOW No less a storm the Trojan hero bears; END
BEGIN NOW Thick messages and loud complaints he hears, END
BEGIN NOW And bandied words, still beating on his ears. END
BEGIN NOW Sighs, groans, and tears proclaim his inward pains; END
BEGIN NOW But the firm purpose of his heart remains. END
BEGIN NOW The wretched queen, pursued by cruel fate, END
BEGIN NOW Begins at length the light of heav'n to hate, END
BEGIN NOW And loathes to live. Then dire portents she sees, END
BEGIN NOW To hasten on the death her soul decrees: END
BEGIN NOW Strange to relate! for when, before the shrine, END
BEGIN NOW She pours in sacrifice the purple wine, END
BEGIN NOW The purple wine is turn'd to putrid blood, END
BEGIN NOW And the white offer'd milk converts to mud. END
BEGIN NOW This dire presage, to her alone reveal'd, END
BEGIN NOW From all, and ev'n her sister, she conceal'd. END
BEGIN NOW A marble temple stood within the grove, END
BEGIN NOW Sacred to death, and to her murther'd love; END
BEGIN NOW That honor'd chapel she had hung around END
BEGIN NOW With snowy fleeces, and with garlands crown'd: END
BEGIN NOW Oft, when she visited this lonely dome, END
BEGIN NOW Strange voices issued from her husband's tomb; END
BEGIN NOW She thought she heard him summon her away, END
BEGIN NOW Invite her to his grave, and chide her stay. END
BEGIN NOW Hourly 't is heard, when with a boding note END
BEGIN NOW The solitary screech owl strains her throat, END
BEGIN NOW And, on a chimney's top, or turret's height, END
BEGIN NOW With songs obscene disturbs the silence of the night. END
BEGIN NOW Besides, old prophecies augment her fears; END
BEGIN NOW And stern Aeneas in her dreams appears, END
BEGIN NOW Disdainful as by day: she seems, alone, END
BEGIN NOW To wander in her sleep, thro' ways unknown, END
BEGIN NOW Guideless and dark; or, in a desart plain, END
BEGIN NOW To seek her subjects, and to seek in vain: END
BEGIN NOW Like Pentheus, when, distracted with his fear, END
BEGIN NOW He saw two suns, and double Thebes, appear; END
BEGIN NOW Or mad Orestes, when his mother's ghost END
BEGIN NOW Full in his face infernal torches toss'd, END
BEGIN NOW And shook her snaky locks: he shuns the sight, END
BEGIN NOW Flies o'er the stage, surpris'd with mortal fright; END
BEGIN NOW The Furies guard the door and intercept his flight. END
BEGIN NOW Now, sinking underneath a load of grief, END
BEGIN NOW From death alone she seeks her last relief; END
BEGIN NOW The time and means resolv'd within her breast, END
BEGIN NOW She to her mournful sister thus address'd END
BEGIN NOW (Dissembling hope, her cloudy front she clears, END
BEGIN NOW And a false vigor in her eyes appears): END
BEGIN NOW Rejoice! she said. "Instructed from above, END
BEGIN NOW My lover I shall gain, or lose my love. END
BEGIN NOW Nigh rising Atlas, next the falling sun, END
BEGIN NOW Long tracts of Ethiopian climates run: END
BEGIN NOW There a Massylian priestess I have found, END
BEGIN NOW Honor'd for age, for magic arts renown'd: END
BEGIN NOW Th' Hesperian temple was her trusted care; END
BEGIN NOW 'T was she supplied the wakeful dragon's fare. END
BEGIN NOW She poppy seeds in honey taught to steep, END
BEGIN NOW Reclaim'd his rage, and sooth'd him into sleep. END
BEGIN NOW She watch'd the golden fruit; her charms unbind END
BEGIN NOW The chains of love, or fix them on the mind: END
BEGIN NOW She stops the torrents, leaves the channel dry, END
BEGIN NOW Repels the stars, and backward bears the sky. END
BEGIN NOW The yawning earth rebellows to her call, END
BEGIN NOW Pale ghosts ascend, and mountain ashes fall. END
BEGIN NOW Witness, ye gods, and thou my better part, END
BEGIN NOW How loth I am to try this impious art! END
BEGIN NOW Within the secret court, with silent care, END
BEGIN NOW Erect a lofty pile, expos'd in air: END
BEGIN NOW Hang on the topmost part the Trojan vest, END
BEGIN NOW Spoils, arms, and presents, of my faithless guest. END
BEGIN NOW Next, under these, the bridal bed be plac'd, END
BEGIN NOW Where I my ruin in his arms embrac'd: END
BEGIN NOW All relics of the wretch are doom'd to fire; END
BEGIN NOW For so the priestess and her charms require. END
BEGIN NOW Thus far she said, and farther speech forbears; END
BEGIN NOW A mortal paleness in her face appears: END
BEGIN NOW Yet the mistrustless Anna could not find END
BEGIN NOW The secret fun'ral in these rites design'd; END
BEGIN NOW Nor thought so dire a rage possess'd her mind. END
BEGIN NOW Unknowing of a train conceal'd so well, END
BEGIN NOW She fear'd no worse than when Sichaeus fell; END
BEGIN NOW Therefore obeys. The fatal pile they rear, END
BEGIN NOW Within the secret court, expos'd in air. END
BEGIN NOW The cloven holms and pines are heap'd on high, END
BEGIN NOW And garlands on the hollow spaces lie. END
BEGIN NOW Sad cypress, vervain, yew, compose the wreath, END
BEGIN NOW And ev'ry baleful green denoting death. END
BEGIN NOW The queen, determin'd to the fatal deed, END
BEGIN NOW The spoils and sword he left, in order spread, END
BEGIN NOW And the man's image on the nuptial bed. END
BEGIN NOW And now (the sacred altars plac'd around) END
BEGIN NOW The priestess enters, with her hair unbound, END
BEGIN NOW And thrice invokes the pow'rs below the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Night, Erebus, and Chaos she proclaims, END
BEGIN NOW And threefold Hecate, with her hundred names, END
BEGIN NOW And three Dianas: next, she sprinkles round END
BEGIN NOW With feign'd Avernian drops the hallow'd ground; END
BEGIN NOW Culls hoary simples, found by Phoebe's light, END
BEGIN NOW With brazen sickles reap'd at noon of night; END
BEGIN NOW Then mixes baleful juices in the bowl, END
BEGIN NOW And cuts the forehead of a newborn foal, END
BEGIN NOW Robbing the mother's love. The destin'd queen END
BEGIN NOW Observes, assisting at the rites obscene; END
BEGIN NOW A leaven'd cake in her devoted hands END
BEGIN NOW She holds, and next the highest altar stands: END
BEGIN NOW One tender foot was shod, her other bare; END
BEGIN NOW Girt was her gather'd gown, and loose her hair. END
BEGIN NOW Thus dress'd, she summon'd, with her dying breath, END
BEGIN NOW The heav'ns and planets conscious of her death, END
BEGIN NOW And ev'ry pow'r, if any rules above, END
BEGIN NOW Who minds, or who revenges, injur'd love. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was dead of night, when weary bodies close END
BEGIN NOW Their eyes in balmy sleep and soft repose: END
BEGIN NOW The winds no longer whisper thro' the woods, END
BEGIN NOW Nor murm'ring tides disturb the gentle floods. END
BEGIN NOW The stars in silent order mov'd around; END
BEGIN NOW And Peace, with downy wings, was brooding on the ground END
BEGIN NOW The flocks and herds, and party-color'd fowl, END
BEGIN NOW Which haunt the woods, or swim the weedy pool, END
BEGIN NOW Stretch'd on the quiet earth, securely lay, END
BEGIN NOW Forgetting the past labors of the day. END
BEGIN NOW All else of nature's common gift partake: END
BEGIN NOW Unhappy Dido was alone awake. END
BEGIN NOW Nor sleep nor ease the furious queen can find; END
BEGIN NOW Sleep fled her eyes, as quiet fled her mind. END
BEGIN NOW Despair, and rage, and love divide her heart; END
BEGIN NOW Despair and rage had some, but love the greater part. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus she said within her secret mind: END
BEGIN NOW What shall I do? what succor can I find? END
BEGIN NOW Become a suppliant to Hyarba's pride, END
BEGIN NOW And take my turn, to court and be denied? END
BEGIN NOW Shall I with this ungrateful Trojan go, END
BEGIN NOW Forsake an empire, and attend a foe? END
BEGIN NOW Himself I refug'd, and his train reliev'd- END
BEGIN NOW 'T is true- but am I sure to be receiv'd? END
BEGIN NOW Can gratitude in Trojan souls have place! END
BEGIN NOW Laomedon still lives in all his race! END
BEGIN NOW Then, shall I seek alone the churlish crew, END
BEGIN NOW Or with my fleet their flying sails pursue? END
BEGIN NOW What force have I but those whom scarce before END
BEGIN NOW I drew reluctant from their native shore? END
BEGIN NOW Will they again embark at my desire, END
BEGIN NOW Once more sustain the seas, and quit their second Tyre? END
BEGIN NOW Rather with steel thy guilty breast invade, END
BEGIN NOW And take the fortune thou thyself hast made. END
BEGIN NOW Your pity, sister, first seduc'd my mind, END
BEGIN NOW Or seconded too well what I design'd. END
BEGIN NOW These dear-bought pleasures had I never known, END
BEGIN NOW Had I continued free, and still my own; END
BEGIN NOW Avoiding love, I had not found despair, END
BEGIN NOW But shar'd with salvage beasts the common air. END
BEGIN NOW Like them, a lonely life I might have led, END
BEGIN NOW Not mourn'd the living, nor disturb'd the dead. END
BEGIN NOW These thoughts she brooded in her anxious breast. END
BEGIN NOW On board, the Trojan found more easy rest. END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd to sail, in sleep he pass'd the night; END
BEGIN NOW And order'd all things for his early flight. END
BEGIN NOW To whom once more the winged god appears; END
BEGIN NOW His former youthful mien and shape he wears, END
BEGIN NOW And with this new alarm invades his ears: END
BEGIN NOW Sleep'st thou, O goddess-born! and canst thou drown END
BEGIN NOW Thy needful cares, so near a hostile town, END
BEGIN NOW Beset with foes; nor hear'st the western gales END
BEGIN NOW Invite thy passage, and inspire thy sails? END
BEGIN NOW She harbors in her heart a furious hate, END
BEGIN NOW And thou shalt find the dire effects too late; END
BEGIN NOW Fix'd on revenge, and obstinate to die. END
BEGIN NOW Haste swiftly hence, while thou hast pow'r to fly. END
BEGIN NOW The sea with ships will soon be cover'd o'er, END
BEGIN NOW And blazing firebrands kindle all the shore. END
BEGIN NOW Prevent her rage, while night obscures the skies, END
BEGIN NOW And sail before the purple morn arise. END
BEGIN NOW Who knows what hazards thy delay may bring? END
BEGIN NOW Woman's a various and a changeful thing. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Hermes in the dream; then took his flight END
BEGIN NOW Aloft in air unseen, and mix'd with night. END
BEGIN NOW Twice warn'd by the celestial messenger, END
BEGIN NOW The pious prince arose with hasty fear; END
BEGIN NOW Then rous'd his drowsy train without delay: END
BEGIN NOW Haste to your banks; your crooked anchors weigh, END
BEGIN NOW And spread your flying sails, and stand to sea. END
BEGIN NOW A god commands: he stood before my sight, END
BEGIN NOW And urg'd us once again to speedy flight. END
BEGIN NOW O sacred pow'r, what pow'r soe'er thou art, END
BEGIN NOW To thy blest orders I resign my heart. END
BEGIN NOW Lead thou the way; protect thy Trojan bands, END
BEGIN NOW And prosper the design thy will commands. END
BEGIN NOW He said: and, drawing forth his flaming sword, END
BEGIN NOW His thund'ring arm divides the many-twisted cord. END
BEGIN NOW An emulating zeal inspires his train: END
BEGIN NOW They run; they snatch; they rush into the main. END
BEGIN NOW With headlong haste they leave the desert shores, END
BEGIN NOW And brush the liquid seas with lab'ring oars. END
BEGIN NOW Aurora now had left her saffron bed, END
BEGIN NOW And beams of early light the heav'ns o'erspread, END
BEGIN NOW When, from a tow'r, the queen, with wakeful eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Saw day point upward from the rosy skies. END
BEGIN NOW She look'd to seaward; but the sea was void, END
BEGIN NOW And scarce in ken the sailing ships descried. END
BEGIN NOW Stung with despite, and furious with despair, END
BEGIN NOW She struck her trembling breast, and tore her hair. END
BEGIN NOW And shall th' ungrateful traitor go," she said, END
BEGIN NOW My land forsaken, and my love betray'd? END
BEGIN NOW Shall we not arm? not rush from ev'ry street, END
BEGIN NOW To follow, sink, and burn his perjur'd fleet? END
BEGIN NOW Haste, haul my galleys out! pursue the foe! END
BEGIN NOW Bring flaming brands! set sail, and swiftly row! END
BEGIN NOW What have I said? where am I? Fury turns END
BEGIN NOW My brain; and my distemper'd bosom burns. END
BEGIN NOW Then, when I gave my person and my throne, END
BEGIN NOW This hate, this rage, had been more timely shown. END
BEGIN NOW See now the promis'd faith, the vaunted name, END
BEGIN NOW The pious man, who, rushing thro' the flame, END
BEGIN NOW Preserv'd his gods, and to the Phrygian shore END
BEGIN NOW The burthen of his feeble father bore! END
BEGIN NOW I should have torn him piecemeal; strow'd in floods END
BEGIN NOW His scatter'd limbs, or left expos'd in woods; END
BEGIN NOW Destroy'd his friends and son; and, from the fire, END
BEGIN NOW Have set the reeking boy before the sire. END
BEGIN NOW Events are doubtful, which on battles wait: END
BEGIN NOW Yet where's the doubt, to souls secure of fate? END
BEGIN NOW My Tyrians, at their injur'd queen's command, END
BEGIN NOW Had toss'd their fires amid the Trojan band; END
BEGIN NOW At once extinguish'd all the faithless name; END
BEGIN NOW And I myself, in vengeance of my shame, END
BEGIN NOW Had fall'n upon the pile, to mend the fun'ral flame. END
BEGIN NOW Thou Sun, who view'st at once the world below; END
BEGIN NOW Thou Juno, guardian of the nuptial vow; END
BEGIN NOW Thou Hecate hearken from thy dark abodes! END
BEGIN NOW Ye Furies, fiends, and violated gods, END
BEGIN NOW All pow'rs invok'd with Dido's dying breath, END
BEGIN NOW Attend her curses and avenge her death! END
BEGIN NOW If so the Fates ordain, Jove commands, END
BEGIN NOW Th' ungrateful wretch should find the Latian lands, END
BEGIN NOW Yet let a race untam'd, and haughty foes, END
BEGIN NOW His peaceful entrance with dire arms oppose: END
BEGIN NOW Oppress'd with numbers in th' unequal field, END
BEGIN NOW His men discourag'd, and himself expell'd, END
BEGIN NOW Let him for succor sue from place to place, END
BEGIN NOW Torn from his subjects, and his son's embrace. END
BEGIN NOW First, let him see his friends in battle slain, END
BEGIN NOW And their untimely fate lament in vain; END
BEGIN NOW And when, at length, the cruel war shall cease, END
BEGIN NOW On hard conditions may he buy his peace: END
BEGIN NOW Nor let him then enjoy supreme command; END
BEGIN NOW But fall, untimely, by some hostile hand, END
BEGIN NOW And lie unburied on the barren sand! END
BEGIN NOW These are my pray'rs, and this my dying will; END
BEGIN NOW And you, my Tyrians, ev'ry curse fulfil. END
BEGIN NOW Perpetual hate and mortal wars proclaim, END
BEGIN NOW Against the prince, the people, and the name. END
BEGIN NOW These grateful off'rings on my grave bestow; END
BEGIN NOW Nor league, nor love, the hostile nations know! END
BEGIN NOW Now, and from hence, in ev'ry future age, END
BEGIN NOW When rage excites your arms, and strength supplies the rage END
BEGIN NOW Rise some avenger of our Libyan blood, END
BEGIN NOW With fire and sword pursue the perjur'd brood; END
BEGIN NOW Our arms, our seas, our shores, oppos'd to theirs; END
BEGIN NOW And the same hate descend on all our heirs! END
BEGIN NOW This said, within her anxious mind she weighs END
BEGIN NOW The means of cutting short her odious days. END
BEGIN NOW Then to Sichaeus' nurse she briefly said END
BEGIN NOW (For, when she left her country, hers was dead): END
BEGIN NOW Go, Barce, call my sister. Let her care END
BEGIN NOW The solemn rites of sacrifice prepare; END
BEGIN NOW The sheep, and all th' atoning off'rings bring, END
BEGIN NOW Sprinkling her body from the crystal spring END
BEGIN NOW With living drops; then let her come, and thou END
BEGIN NOW With sacred fillets bind thy hoary brow. END
BEGIN NOW Thus will I pay my vows to Stygian Jove, END
BEGIN NOW And end the cares of my disastrous love; END
BEGIN NOW Then cast the Trojan image on the fire, END
BEGIN NOW And, as that burns, my passions shall expire. END
BEGIN NOW The nurse moves onward, with officious care, END
BEGIN NOW And all the speed her aged limbs can bear. END
BEGIN NOW But furious Dido, with dark thoughts involv'd, END
BEGIN NOW Shook at the mighty mischief she resolv'd. END
BEGIN NOW With livid spots distinguish'd was her face; END
BEGIN NOW Red were her rolling eyes, and discompos'd her pace; END
BEGIN NOW Ghastly she gaz'd, with pain she drew her breath, END
BEGIN NOW And nature shiver'd at approaching death. END
BEGIN NOW Then swiftly to the fatal place she pass'd, END
BEGIN NOW And mounts the fun'ral pile with furious haste; END
BEGIN NOW Unsheathes the sword the Trojan left behind END
BEGIN NOW (Not for so dire an enterprise design'd). END
BEGIN NOW But when she view'd the garments loosely spread, END
BEGIN NOW Which once he wore, and saw the conscious bed, END
BEGIN NOW She paus'd, and with a sigh the robes embrac'd; END
BEGIN NOW Then on the couch her trembling body cast, END
BEGIN NOW Repress'd the ready tears, and spoke her last: END
BEGIN NOW Dear pledges of my love, while Heav'n so pleas'd, END
BEGIN NOW Receive a soul, of mortal anguish eas'd: END
BEGIN NOW My fatal course is finish'd; and I go, END
BEGIN NOW A glorious name, among the ghosts below. END
BEGIN NOW A lofty city by my hands is rais'd, END
BEGIN NOW Pygmalion punish'd, and my lord appeas'd. END
BEGIN NOW What could my fortune have afforded more, END
BEGIN NOW Had the false Trojan never touch'd my shore! END
BEGIN NOW Then kiss'd the couch; and, "Must I die," she said, END
BEGIN NOW And unreveng'd? 'T is doubly to be dead! END
BEGIN NOW Yet ev'n this death with pleasure I receive: END
BEGIN NOW On any terms, 't is better than to live. END
BEGIN NOW These flames, from far, may the false Trojan view; END
BEGIN NOW These boding omens his base flight pursue! END
BEGIN NOW She said, and struck; deep enter'd in her side END
BEGIN NOW The piercing steel, with reeking purple dyed: END
BEGIN NOW Clogg'd in the wound the cruel weapon stands; END
BEGIN NOW The spouting blood came streaming on her hands. END
BEGIN NOW Her sad attendants saw the deadly stroke, END
BEGIN NOW And with loud cries the sounding palace shook. END
BEGIN NOW Distracted, from the fatal sight they fled, END
BEGIN NOW And thro' the town the dismal rumor spread. END
BEGIN NOW First from the frighted court the yell began; END
BEGIN NOW Redoubled, thence from house to house it ran: END
BEGIN NOW The groans of men, with shrieks, laments, and cries END
BEGIN NOW Of mixing women, mount the vaulted skies. END
BEGIN NOW Not less the clamor, than if- ancient Tyre, END
BEGIN NOW Or the new Carthage, set by foes on fire- END
BEGIN NOW The rolling ruin, with their lov'd abodes, END
BEGIN NOW Involv'd the blazing temples of their gods. END
BEGIN NOW Her sister hears; and, furious with despair, END
BEGIN NOW She beats her breast, and rends her yellow hair, END
BEGIN NOW And, calling on Eliza's name aloud, END
BEGIN NOW Runs breathless to the place, and breaks the crowd. END
BEGIN NOW Was all that pomp of woe for this prepar'd; END
BEGIN NOW These fires, this fun'ral pile, these altars rear'd? END
BEGIN NOW Was all this train of plots contriv'd," said she, END
BEGIN NOW All only to deceive unhappy me? END
BEGIN NOW Which is the worst? Didst thou in death pretend END
BEGIN NOW To scorn thy sister, or delude thy friend? END
BEGIN NOW Thy summon'd sister, and thy friend, had come; END
BEGIN NOW One sword had serv'd us both, one common tomb: END
BEGIN NOW Was I to raise the pile, the pow'rs invoke, END
BEGIN NOW Not to be present at the fatal stroke? END
BEGIN NOW At once thou hast destroy'd thyself and me, END
BEGIN NOW Thy town, thy senate, and thy colony! END
BEGIN NOW Bring water; bathe the wound; while I in death END
BEGIN NOW Lay close my lips to hers, and catch the flying breath. END
BEGIN NOW This said, she mounts the pile with eager haste, END
BEGIN NOW And in her arms the gasping queen embrac'd; END
BEGIN NOW Her temples chaf'd; and her own garments tore, END
BEGIN NOW To stanch the streaming blood, and cleanse the gore. END
BEGIN NOW Thrice Dido tried to raise her drooping head, END
BEGIN NOW And, fainting thrice, fell grov'ling on the bed; END
BEGIN NOW Thrice op'd her heavy eyes, and sought the light, END
BEGIN NOW But, having found it, sicken'd at the sight, END
BEGIN NOW And clos'd her lids at last in endless night. END
BEGIN NOW Then Juno, grieving that she should sustain END
BEGIN NOW A death so ling'ring, and so full of pain, END
BEGIN NOW Sent Iris down, to free her from the strife END
BEGIN NOW Of lab'ring nature, and dissolve her life. END
BEGIN NOW For since she died, not doom'd by Heav'n's decree, END
BEGIN NOW Or her own crime, but human casualty, END
BEGIN NOW And rage of love, that plung'd her in despair, END
BEGIN NOW The Sisters had not cut the topmost hair, END
BEGIN NOW Which Proserpine and they can only know; END
BEGIN NOW Nor made her sacred to the shades below. END
BEGIN NOW Downward the various goddess took her flight, END
BEGIN NOW And drew a thousand colors from the light; END
BEGIN NOW Then stood above the dying lover's head, END
BEGIN NOW And said: "I thus devote thee to the dead. END
BEGIN NOW This off'ring to th' infernal gods I bear. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while she spoke, she cut the fatal hair: END
BEGIN NOW The struggling soul was loos'd, and life dissolv'd in air. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the Trojan cuts his wat'ry way, END
BEGIN NOW Fix'd on his voyage, thro' the curling sea; END
BEGIN NOW Then, casting back his eyes, with dire amaze, END
BEGIN NOW Sees on the Punic shore the mounting blaze. END
BEGIN NOW The cause unknown; yet his presaging mind END
BEGIN NOW The fate of Dido from the fire divin'd; END
BEGIN NOW He knew the stormy souls of womankind, END
BEGIN NOW What secret springs their eager passions move, END
BEGIN NOW How capable of death for injur'd love. END
BEGIN NOW Dire auguries from hence the Trojans draw; END
BEGIN NOW Till neither fires nor shining shores they saw. END
BEGIN NOW Now seas and skies their prospect only bound; END
BEGIN NOW An empty space above, a floating field around. END
BEGIN NOW But soon the heav'ns with shadows were o'erspread; END
BEGIN NOW A swelling cloud hung hov'ring o'er their head: END
BEGIN NOW Livid it look'd, the threat'ning of a storm: END
BEGIN NOW Then night and horror ocean's face deform. END
BEGIN NOW The pilot, Palinurus, cried aloud: END
BEGIN NOW What gusts of weather from that gath'ring cloud END
BEGIN NOW My thoughts presage! Ere yet the tempest roars, END
BEGIN NOW Stand to your tackle, mates, and stretch your oars; END
BEGIN NOW Contract your swelling sails, and luff to wind. END
BEGIN NOW The frighted crew perform the task assign'd. END
BEGIN NOW Then, to his fearless chief: "Not Heav'n," said he, END
BEGIN NOW Tho' Jove himself should promise Italy, END
BEGIN NOW Can stem the torrent of this raging sea. END
BEGIN NOW Mark how the shifting winds from west arise, END
BEGIN NOW And what collected night involves the skies! END
BEGIN NOW Nor can our shaken vessels live at sea, END
BEGIN NOW Much less against the tempest force their way. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is fate diverts our course, and fate we must obey. END
BEGIN NOW Not far from hence, if I observ'd aright END
BEGIN NOW The southing of the stars, and polar light, END
BEGIN NOW Sicilia lies, whose hospitable shores END
BEGIN NOW In safety we may reach with struggling oars. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas then replied: "Too sure I find END
BEGIN NOW We strive in vain against the seas and wind: END
BEGIN NOW Now shift your sails; what place can please me more END
BEGIN NOW Than what you promise, the Sicilian shore, END
BEGIN NOW Whose hallow'd earth Anchises' bones contains, END
BEGIN NOW And where a prince of Trojan lineage reigns? END
BEGIN NOW The course resolv'd, before the western wind END
BEGIN NOW They scud amain, and make the port assign'd. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime Acestes, from a lofty stand, END
BEGIN NOW Beheld the fleet descending on the land; END
BEGIN NOW And, not unmindful of his ancient race, END
BEGIN NOW Down from the cliff he ran with eager pace, END
BEGIN NOW And held the hero in a strict embrace. END
BEGIN NOW Of a rough Libyan bear the spoils he wore, END
BEGIN NOW And either hand a pointed jav'lin bore. END
BEGIN NOW His mother was a dame of Dardan blood; END
BEGIN NOW His sire Crinisus, a Sicilian flood. END
BEGIN NOW He welcomes his returning friends ashore END
BEGIN NOW With plenteous country cates and homely store. END
BEGIN NOW Now, when the following morn had chas'd away END
BEGIN NOW The flying stars, and light restor'd the day, END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas call'd the Trojan troops around, END
BEGIN NOW And thus bespoke them from a rising ground: END
BEGIN NOW Offspring of heav'n, divine Dardanian race! END
BEGIN NOW The sun, revolving thro' th' ethereal space, END
BEGIN NOW The shining circle of the year has fill'd, END
BEGIN NOW Since first this isle my father's ashes held: END
BEGIN NOW And now the rising day renews the year; END
BEGIN NOW A day for ever sad, for ever dear. END
BEGIN NOW This would I celebrate with annual games, END
BEGIN NOW With gifts on altars pil'd, and holy flames, END
BEGIN NOW Tho' banish'd to Gaetulia's barren sands, END
BEGIN NOW Caught on the Grecian seas, or hostile lands: END
BEGIN NOW But since this happy storm our fleet has driv'n END
BEGIN NOW (Not, as I deem, without the will of Heav'n) END
BEGIN NOW Upon these friendly shores and flow'ry plains, END
BEGIN NOW Which hide Anchises and his blest remains, END
BEGIN NOW Let us with joy perform his honors due, END
BEGIN NOW And pray for prosp'rous winds, our voyage to renew; END
BEGIN NOW Pray, that in towns and temples of our own, END
BEGIN NOW The name of great Anchises may be known, END
BEGIN NOW And yearly games may spread the gods' renown. END
BEGIN NOW Our sports Acestes, of the Trojan race, END
BEGIN NOW With royal gifts ordain'd, is pleas'd to grace: END
BEGIN NOW Two steers on ev'ry ship the king bestows; END
BEGIN NOW His gods and ours shall share your equal vows. END
BEGIN NOW Besides, if, nine days hence, the rosy morn END
BEGIN NOW Shall with unclouded light the skies adorn, END
BEGIN NOW That day with solemn sports I mean to grace: END
BEGIN NOW Light galleys on the seas shall run a wat'ry race; END
BEGIN NOW Some shall in swiftness for the goal contend, END
BEGIN NOW And others try the twanging bow to bend; END
BEGIN NOW The strong, with iron gauntlets arm'd, shall stand END
BEGIN NOW Oppos'd in combat on the yellow sand. END
BEGIN NOW Let all be present at the games prepar'd, END
BEGIN NOW And joyful victors wait the just reward. END
BEGIN NOW But now assist the rites, with garlands crown'd. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and first his brows with myrtle bound. END
BEGIN NOW Then Helymus, by his example led, END
BEGIN NOW And old Acestes, each adorn'd his head; END
BEGIN NOW Thus young Ascanius, with a sprightly grace, END
BEGIN NOW His temples tied, and all the Trojan race. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas then advanc'd amidst the train, END
BEGIN NOW By thousands follow'd thro' the flow'ry plain, END
BEGIN NOW To great Anchises' tomb; which when he found, END
BEGIN NOW He pour'd to Bacchus, on the hallow'd ground, END
BEGIN NOW Two bowls of sparkling wine, of milk two more, END
BEGIN NOW And two (from offer'd bulls) of purple gore, END
BEGIN NOW With roses then the sepulcher he strow'd END
BEGIN NOW And thus his father's ghost bespoke aloud: END
BEGIN NOW Hail, O ye holy manes! hail again, END
BEGIN NOW Paternal ashes, now review'd in vain! END
BEGIN NOW The gods permitted not, that you, with me, END
BEGIN NOW Should reach the promis'd shores of Italy, END
BEGIN NOW Or Tiber's flood, what flood soe'er it be. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had he finish'd, when, with speckled pride, END
BEGIN NOW A serpent from the tomb began to glide; END
BEGIN NOW His hugy bulk on sev'n high volumes roll'd; END
BEGIN NOW Blue was his breadth of back, but streak'd with scaly gold: END
BEGIN NOW Thus riding on his curls, he seem'd to pass END
BEGIN NOW A rolling fire along, and singe the grass. END
BEGIN NOW More various colors thro' his body run, END
BEGIN NOW Than Iris when her bow imbibes the sun. END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the rising altars, and around, END
BEGIN NOW The sacred monster shot along the ground; END
BEGIN NOW With harmless play amidst the bowls he pass'd, END
BEGIN NOW And with his lolling tongue assay'd the taste: END
BEGIN NOW Thus fed with holy food, the wondrous guest END
BEGIN NOW Within the hollow tomb retir'd to rest. END
BEGIN NOW The pious prince, surpris'd at what he view'd, END
BEGIN NOW The fun'ral honors with more zeal renew'd, END
BEGIN NOW Doubtful if this place's genius were, END
BEGIN NOW Or guardian of his father's sepulcher. END
BEGIN NOW Five sheep, according to the rites, he slew; END
BEGIN NOW As many swine, and steers of sable hue; END
BEGIN NOW New gen'rous wine he from the goblets pour'd. END
BEGIN NOW And call'd his father's ghost, from hell restor'd. END
BEGIN NOW The glad attendants in long order come, END
BEGIN NOW Off'ring their gifts at great Anchises' tomb: END
BEGIN NOW Some add more oxen: some divide the spoil; END
BEGIN NOW Some place the chargers on the grassy soil; END
BEGIN NOW Some blow the fires, and off entrails broil. END
BEGIN NOW Now came the day desir'd. The skies were bright END
BEGIN NOW With rosy luster of the rising light: END
BEGIN NOW The bord'ring people, rous'd by sounding fame END
BEGIN NOW Of Trojan feasts and great Acestes' name, END
BEGIN NOW The crowded shore with acclamations fill, END
BEGIN NOW Part to behold, and part to prove their skill. END
BEGIN NOW And first the gifts in public view they place, END
BEGIN NOW Green laurel wreaths, and palm, the victors' grace: END
BEGIN NOW Within the circle, arms and tripods lie, END
BEGIN NOW Ingots of gold and silver, heap'd on high, END
BEGIN NOW And vests embroider'd, of the Tyrian dye. END
BEGIN NOW The trumpet's clangor then the feast proclaims, END
BEGIN NOW And all prepare for their appointed games. END
BEGIN NOW Four galleys first, which equal rowers bear, END
BEGIN NOW Advancing, in the wat'ry lists appear. END
BEGIN NOW The speedy Dolphin, that outstrips the wind, END
BEGIN NOW Bore Mnestheus, author of the Memmian kind: END
BEGIN NOW Gyas the vast Chimaera's bulk commands, END
BEGIN NOW Which rising, like a tow'ring city stands; END
BEGIN NOW Three Trojans tug at ev'ry lab'ring oar; END
BEGIN NOW Three banks in three degrees the sailors bore; END
BEGIN NOW Beneath their sturdy strokes the billows roar. END
BEGIN NOW Sergesthus, who began the Sergian race, END
BEGIN NOW In the great Centaur took the leading place; END
BEGIN NOW Cloanthus on the sea-green Scylla stood, END
BEGIN NOW From whom Cluentius draws his Trojan blood. END
BEGIN NOW Far in the sea, against the foaming shore, END
BEGIN NOW There stands a rock: the raging billows roar END
BEGIN NOW Above his head in storms; but, when 't is clear, END
BEGIN NOW Uncurl their ridgy backs, and at his foot appear. END
BEGIN NOW In peace below the gentle waters run; END
BEGIN NOW The cormorants above lie basking in the sun. END
BEGIN NOW On this the hero fix'd an oak in sight, END
BEGIN NOW The mark to guide the mariners aright. END
BEGIN NOW To bear with this, the seamen stretch their oars; END
BEGIN NOW Then round the rock they steer, and seek the former shores. END
BEGIN NOW The lots decide their place. Above the rest, END
BEGIN NOW Each leader shining in his Tyrian vest; END
BEGIN NOW The common crew with wreaths of poplar boughs END
BEGIN NOW Their temples crown, and shade their sweaty brows: END
BEGIN NOW Besmear'd with oil, their naked shoulders shine. END
BEGIN NOW All take their seats, and wait the sounding sign: END
BEGIN NOW They gripe their oars; and ev'ry panting breast END
BEGIN NOW Is rais'd by turns with hope, by turns with fear depress'd. END
BEGIN NOW The clangor of the trumpet gives the sign; END
BEGIN NOW At once they start, advancing in a line: END
BEGIN NOW With shouts the sailors rend the starry skies; END
BEGIN NOW Lash'd with their oars, the smoky billows rise; END
BEGIN NOW Sparkles the briny main, and the vex'd ocean fries. END
BEGIN NOW Exact in time, with equal strokes they row: END
BEGIN NOW At once the brushing oars and brazen prow END
BEGIN NOW Dash up the sandy waves, and ope the depths below. END
BEGIN NOW Not fiery coursers, in a chariot race, END
BEGIN NOW Invade the field with half so swift a pace; END
BEGIN NOW Not the fierce driver with more fury lends END
BEGIN NOW The sounding lash, and, ere the stroke descends, END
BEGIN NOW Low to the wheels his pliant body bends. END
BEGIN NOW The partial crowd their hopes and fears divide, END
BEGIN NOW And aid with eager shouts the favor'd side. END
BEGIN NOW Cries, murmurs, clamors, with a mixing sound, END
BEGIN NOW From woods to woods, from hills to hills rebound. END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the loud applauses of the shore, END
BEGIN NOW Gyas outstripp'd the rest, and sprung before: END
BEGIN NOW Cloanthus, better mann'd, pursued him fast, END
BEGIN NOW But his o'er-masted galley check'd his haste. END
BEGIN NOW The Centaur and the Dolphin brush the brine END
BEGIN NOW With equal oars, advancing in a line; END
BEGIN NOW And now the mighty Centaur seems to lead, END
BEGIN NOW And now the speedy Dolphin gets ahead; END
BEGIN NOW Now board to board the rival vessels row, END
BEGIN NOW The billows lave the skies, and ocean groans below. END
BEGIN NOW They reach'd the mark. Proud Gyas and his train END
BEGIN NOW In triumph rode, the victors of the main; END
BEGIN NOW But, steering round, he charg'd his pilot stand END
BEGIN NOW More close to shore, and skim along the sand- END
BEGIN NOW Let others bear to sea!" Menoetes heard; END
BEGIN NOW But secret shelves too cautiously he fear'd, END
BEGIN NOW And, fearing, sought the deep; and still aloof he steer'd. END
BEGIN NOW With louder cries the captain call'd again: END
BEGIN NOW Bear to the rocky shore, and shun the main. END
BEGIN NOW He spoke, and, speaking, at his stern he saw END
BEGIN NOW The bold Cloanthus near the shelvings draw. END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the mark and him the Scylla stood, END
BEGIN NOW And in a closer compass plow'd the flood. END
BEGIN NOW He pass'd the mark; and, wheeling, got before: END
BEGIN NOW Gyas blasphem'd the gods, devoutly swore, END
BEGIN NOW Cried out for anger, and his hair he tore. END
BEGIN NOW Mindless of others' lives (so high was grown END
BEGIN NOW His rising rage) and careless of his own, END
BEGIN NOW Then hoisted up, and overboard he threw: END
BEGIN NOW This done, he seiz'd the helm; his fellows cheer'd, END
BEGIN NOW Turn'd short upon the shelfs, and madly steer'd. END
BEGIN NOW Hardly his head the plunging pilot rears, END
BEGIN NOW Clogg'd with his clothes, and cumber'd with his years: END
BEGIN NOW Now dropping wet, he climbs the cliff with pain. END
BEGIN NOW The crowd, that saw him fall and float again, END
BEGIN NOW Shout from the distant shore; and loudly laugh'd, END
BEGIN NOW To see his heaving breast disgorge the briny draught. END
BEGIN NOW The following Centaur, and the Dolphin's crew, END
BEGIN NOW Their vanish'd hopes of victory renew; END
BEGIN NOW While Gyas lags, they kindle in the race, END
BEGIN NOW To reach the mark. Sergesthus takes the place; END
BEGIN NOW Mnestheus pursues; and while around they wind, END
BEGIN NOW Comes up, not half his galley's length behind; END
BEGIN NOW Then, on the deck, amidst his mates appear'd, END
BEGIN NOW And thus their drooping courage he cheer'd: END
BEGIN NOW My friends, and Hector's followers heretofore, END
BEGIN NOW Exert your vigor; tug the lab'ring oar; END
BEGIN NOW Stretch to your strokes, my still unconquer'd crew, END
BEGIN NOW Whom from the flaming walls of Troy I drew. END
BEGIN NOW In this, our common int'rest, let me find END
BEGIN NOW That strength of hand, that courage of the mind, END
BEGIN NOW As when you stemm'd the strong Malean flood, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er the Syrtes' broken billows row'd. END
BEGIN NOW I seek not now the foremost palm to gain; END
BEGIN NOW Tho' yet- but, ah! that haughty wish is vain! END
BEGIN NOW Let those enjoy it whom the gods ordain. END
BEGIN NOW But to be last, the lags of all the race!- END
BEGIN NOW Redeem yourselves and me from that disgrace. END
BEGIN NOW Now, one and all, they tug amain; they row END
BEGIN NOW At the full stretch, and shake the brazen prow. END
BEGIN NOW The sea beneath 'em sinks; their lab'ring sides END
BEGIN NOW Are swell'd, and sweat runs gutt'ring down in tides. END
BEGIN NOW Chance aids their daring with unhop'd success; END
BEGIN NOW Sergesthus, eager with his beak to press END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the rival galley and the rock, END
BEGIN NOW Shuts up th' unwieldly Centaur in the lock. END
BEGIN NOW The vessel struck; and, with the dreadful shock, END
BEGIN NOW Her oars she shiver'd, and her head she broke. END
BEGIN NOW The trembling rowers from their banks arise, END
BEGIN NOW And, anxious for themselves, renounce the prize. END
BEGIN NOW With iron poles they heave her off the shores, END
BEGIN NOW And gather from the sea their floating oars. END
BEGIN NOW The crew of Mnestheus, with elated minds, END
BEGIN NOW Urge their success, and call the willing winds; END
BEGIN NOW Then ply their oars, and cut their liquid way END
BEGIN NOW In larger compass on the roomy sea. END
BEGIN NOW As, when the dove her rocky hold forsakes, END
BEGIN NOW Rous'd in a fright, her sounding wings she shakes; END
BEGIN NOW The cavern rings with clatt'ring; out she flies, END
BEGIN NOW And leaves her callow care, and cleaves the skies: END
BEGIN NOW At first she flutters; but at length she springs END
BEGIN NOW To smoother flight, and shoots upon her wings: END
BEGIN NOW So Mnestheus in the Dolphin cuts the sea; END
BEGIN NOW And, flying with a force, that force assists his way. END
BEGIN NOW Sergesthus in the Centaur soon he pass'd, END
BEGIN NOW Wedg'd in the rocky shoals, and sticking fast. END
BEGIN NOW In vain the victor he with cries implores, END
BEGIN NOW And practices to row with shatter'd oars. END
BEGIN NOW Then Mnestheus bears with Gyas, and outflies: END
BEGIN NOW The ship, without a pilot, yields the prize. END
BEGIN NOW Unvanquish'd Scylla now alone remains; END
BEGIN NOW Her he pursues, and all his vigor strains. END
BEGIN NOW Shouts from the fav'ring multitude arise; END
BEGIN NOW Applauding Echo to the shouts replies; END
BEGIN NOW Shouts, wishes, and applause run rattling thro' the skies. END
BEGIN NOW These clamors with disdain the Scylla heard, END
BEGIN NOW Much grudg'd the praise, but more the robb'd reward: END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd to hold their own, they mend their pace, END
BEGIN NOW All obstinate to die, or gain the race. END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd with success, the Dolphin swiftly ran; END
BEGIN NOW For they can conquer, who believe they can. END
BEGIN NOW Both urge their oars, and fortune both supplies, END
BEGIN NOW And both perhaps had shar'd an equal prize; END
BEGIN NOW When to the seas Cloanthus holds his hands, END
BEGIN NOW And succor from the wat'ry pow'rs demands: END
BEGIN NOW Gods of the liquid realms, on which I row! END
BEGIN NOW If, giv'n by you, the laurel bind my brow, END
BEGIN NOW Assist to make me guilty of my vow! END
BEGIN NOW A snow-white bull shall on your shore be slain; END
BEGIN NOW His offer'd entrails cast into the main, END
BEGIN NOW And ruddy wine, from golden goblets thrown, END
BEGIN NOW Your grateful gift and my return shall own. END
BEGIN NOW The choir of nymphs, and Phorcus, from below, END
BEGIN NOW With virgin Panopea, heard his vow; END
BEGIN NOW And old Portunus, with his breadth of hand, END
BEGIN NOW Push'd on, and sped the galley to the land. END
BEGIN NOW Swift as a shaft, or winged wind, she flies, END
BEGIN NOW And, darting to the port, obtains the prize. END
BEGIN NOW The herald summons all, and then proclaims END
BEGIN NOW Cloanthus conqu'ror of the naval games. END
BEGIN NOW The prince with laurel crowns the victor's head, END
BEGIN NOW And three fat steers are to his vessel led, END
BEGIN NOW The ship's reward; with gen'rous wine beside, END
BEGIN NOW And sums of silver, which the crew divide. END
BEGIN NOW The leaders are distinguish'd from the rest; END
BEGIN NOW The victor honor'd with a nobler vest, END
BEGIN NOW Where gold and purple strive in equal rows, END
BEGIN NOW And needlework its happy cost bestows. END
BEGIN NOW There Ganymede is wrought with living art, END
BEGIN NOW Chasing thro' Ida's groves the trembling hart: END
BEGIN NOW Breathless he seems, yet eager to pursue; END
BEGIN NOW When from aloft descends, in open view, END
BEGIN NOW The bird of Jove, and, sousing on his prey, END
BEGIN NOW With crooked talons bears the boy away. END
BEGIN NOW In vain, with lifted hands and gazing eyes, END
BEGIN NOW His guards behold him soaring thro' the skies, END
BEGIN NOW And dogs pursue his flight with imitated cries. END
BEGIN NOW Mnestheus the second victor was declar'd; END
BEGIN NOW And, summon'd there, the second prize he shard. END
BEGIN NOW A coat of mail, brave Demoleus bore, END
BEGIN NOW More brave Aeneas from his shoulders tore, END
BEGIN NOW In single combat on the Trojan shore: END
BEGIN NOW This was ordain'd for Mnestheus to possess; END
BEGIN NOW In war for his defense, for ornament in peace. END
BEGIN NOW Rich was the gift, and glorious to behold, END
BEGIN NOW But yet so pond'rous with its plates of gold, END
BEGIN NOW That scarce two servants could the weight sustain; END
BEGIN NOW Yet, loaded thus, Demoleus o'er the plain END
BEGIN NOW Pursued and lightly seiz'd the Trojan train. END
BEGIN NOW The third, succeeding to the last reward, END
BEGIN NOW Two goodly bowls of massy silver shar'd, END
BEGIN NOW With figures prominent, and richly wrought, END
BEGIN NOW And two brass caldrons from Dodona brought. END
BEGIN NOW Thus all, rewarded by the hero's hands, END
BEGIN NOW Their conqu'ring temples bound with purple bands; END
BEGIN NOW And now Sergesthus, clearing from the rock, END
BEGIN NOW Brought back his galley shatter'd with the shock. END
BEGIN NOW Forlorn she look'd, without an aiding oar, END
BEGIN NOW And, houted by the vulgar, made to shore. END
BEGIN NOW As when a snake, surpris'd upon the road, END
BEGIN NOW Is crush'd athwart her body by the load END
BEGIN NOW Of heavy wheels; or with a mortal wound END
BEGIN NOW Her belly bruis'd, and trodden to the ground: END
BEGIN NOW In vain, with loosen'd curls, she crawls along; END
BEGIN NOW Yet, fierce above, she brandishes her tongue; END
BEGIN NOW Glares with her eyes, and bristles with her scales; END
BEGIN NOW But, groveling in the dust, her parts unsound she trails: END
BEGIN NOW So slowly to the port the Centaur tends, END
BEGIN NOW But, what she wants in oars, with sails amends. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, for his galley sav'd, the grateful prince END
BEGIN NOW Is pleas'd th' unhappy chief to recompense. END
BEGIN NOW Pholoe, the Cretan slave, rewards his care, END
BEGIN NOW Beauteous herself, with lovely twins as fair. END
BEGIN NOW From thence his way the Trojan hero bent END
BEGIN NOW Into the neighb'ring plain, with mountains pent, END
BEGIN NOW Whose sides were shaded with surrounding wood. END
BEGIN NOW Full in the midst of this fair valley stood END
BEGIN NOW A native theater, which, rising slow END
BEGIN NOW By just degrees, o'erlook'd the ground below. END
BEGIN NOW High on a sylvan throne the leader sate; END
BEGIN NOW A num'rous train attend in solemn state. END
BEGIN NOW Here those that in the rapid course delight, END
BEGIN NOW Desire of honor and the prize invite. END
BEGIN NOW The rival runners without order stand; END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans mix'd with the Sicilian band. END
BEGIN NOW First Nisus, with Euryalus, appears; END
BEGIN NOW Euryalus a boy of blooming years, END
BEGIN NOW With sprightly grace and equal beauty crown'd; END
BEGIN NOW Nisus, for friendship to the youth renown'd. END
BEGIN NOW Diores next, of Priam's royal race, END
BEGIN NOW Then Salius joined with Patron, took their place; END
BEGIN NOW (But Patron in Arcadia had his birth, END
BEGIN NOW And Salius his from Arcananian earth;) END
BEGIN NOW Then two Sicilian youths- the names of these, END
BEGIN NOW Swift Helymus, and lovely Panopes: END
BEGIN NOW Both jolly huntsmen, both in forest bred, END
BEGIN NOW And owning old Acestes for their head; END
BEGIN NOW With sev'ral others of ignobler name, END
BEGIN NOW Whom time has not deliver'd o'er to fame. END
BEGIN NOW To these the hero thus his thoughts explain'd, END
BEGIN NOW In words which gen'ral approbation gain'd: END
BEGIN NOW One common largess is for all design'd, END
BEGIN NOW (The vanquish'd and the victor shall be join'd,) END
BEGIN NOW Two darts of polish'd steel and Gnosian wood, END
BEGIN NOW A silver-studded ax, alike bestow'd. END
BEGIN NOW The foremost three have olive wreaths decreed: END
BEGIN NOW The first of these obtains a stately steed, END
BEGIN NOW Adorn'd with trappings; and the next in fame, END
BEGIN NOW The quiver of an Amazonian dame, END
BEGIN NOW With feather'd Thracian arrows well supplied: END
BEGIN NOW A golden belt shall gird his manly side, END
BEGIN NOW Which with a sparkling diamond shall be tied. END
BEGIN NOW The third this Grecian helmet shall content. END
BEGIN NOW He said. To their appointed base they went; END
BEGIN NOW With beating hearts th' expected sign receive, END
BEGIN NOW And, starting all at once, the barrier leave. END
BEGIN NOW Spread out, as on the winged winds, they flew, END
BEGIN NOW And seiz'd the distant goal with greedy view. END
BEGIN NOW Shot from the crowd, swift Nisus all o'erpass'd; END
BEGIN NOW Nor storms, nor thunder, equal half his haste. END
BEGIN NOW The next, but tho' the next, yet far disjoin'd, END
BEGIN NOW Came Salius, and Euryalus behind; END
BEGIN NOW Then Helymus, whom young Diores plied, END
BEGIN NOW Step after step, and almost side by side, END
BEGIN NOW His shoulders pressing; and, in longer space, END
BEGIN NOW Had won, or left at least a dubious race. END
BEGIN NOW Now, spent, the goal they almost reach at last, END
BEGIN NOW When eager Nisus, hapless in his haste, END
BEGIN NOW Slipp'd first, and, slipping, fell upon the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Soak'd with the blood of oxen newly slain. END
BEGIN NOW The careless victor had not mark'd his way; END
BEGIN NOW But, treading where the treach'rous puddle lay, END
BEGIN NOW His heels flew up; and on the grassy floor END
BEGIN NOW He fell, besmear'd with filth and holy gore. END
BEGIN NOW Not mindless then, Euryalus, of thee, END
BEGIN NOW Nor of the sacred bonds of amity, END
BEGIN NOW He strove th' immediate rival's hope to cross, END
BEGIN NOW And caught the foot of Salius as he rose. END
BEGIN NOW So Salius lay extended on the plain; END
BEGIN NOW Euryalus springs out, the prize to gain, END
BEGIN NOW And leaves the crowd: applauding peals attend END
BEGIN NOW The victor to the goal, who vanquish'd by his friend. END
BEGIN NOW Next Helymus; and then Diores came, END
BEGIN NOW By two misfortunes made the third in fame. END
BEGIN NOW But Salius enters, and, exclaiming loud END
BEGIN NOW For justice, deafens and disturbs the crowd; END
BEGIN NOW Urges his cause may in the court be heard; END
BEGIN NOW And pleads the prize is wrongfully conferr'd. END
BEGIN NOW But favor for Euryalus appears; END
BEGIN NOW His blooming beauty, with his tender tears, END
BEGIN NOW Had brib'd the judges for the promis'd prize. END
BEGIN NOW Besides, Diores fills the court with cries, END
BEGIN NOW Who vainly reaches at the last reward, END
BEGIN NOW If the first palm on Salius be conferr'd. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus the prince: "Let no disputes arise: END
BEGIN NOW Where fortune plac'd it, I award the prize. END
BEGIN NOW But fortune's errors give me leave to mend, END
BEGIN NOW At least to pity my deserving friend. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and, from among the spoils, he draws END
BEGIN NOW (Pond'rous with shaggy mane and golden paws) END
BEGIN NOW A lion's hide: to Salius this he gives. END
BEGIN NOW Nisus with envy sees the gift, and grieves. END
BEGIN NOW If such rewards to vanquish'd men are due. END
BEGIN NOW He said, "and falling is to rise by you, END
BEGIN NOW What prize may Nisus from your bounty claim, END
BEGIN NOW Who merited the first rewards and fame? END
BEGIN NOW In falling, both an equal fortune tried; END
BEGIN NOW Would fortune for my fall so well provide! END
BEGIN NOW With this he pointed to his face, and show'd END
BEGIN NOW His hand and all his habit smear'd with blood. END
BEGIN NOW Th' indulgent father of the people smil'd, END
BEGIN NOW And caus'd to be produc'd an ample shield, END
BEGIN NOW Of wondrous art, by Didymaon wrought, END
BEGIN NOW Long since from Neptune's bars in triumph brought. END
BEGIN NOW This giv'n to Nisus, he divides the rest, END
BEGIN NOW And equal justice in his gifts express'd. END
BEGIN NOW The race thus ended, and rewards bestow'd, END
BEGIN NOW Once more the princes bespeaks th' attentive crowd: END
BEGIN NOW If there he here whose dauntless courage dare END
BEGIN NOW In gauntlet-fight, with limbs and body bare, END
BEGIN NOW His opposite sustain in open view, END
BEGIN NOW Stand forth the champion, and the games renew. END
BEGIN NOW Two prizes I propose, and thus divide: END
BEGIN NOW A bull with gilded horns, and fillets tied, END
BEGIN NOW Shall be the portion of the conqu'ring chief; END
BEGIN NOW A sword and helm shall cheer the loser's grief. END
BEGIN NOW Then haughty Dares in the lists appears; END
BEGIN NOW Stalking he strides, his head erected bears: END
BEGIN NOW His nervous arms the weighty gauntlet wield, END
BEGIN NOW And loud applauses echo thro' the field. END
BEGIN NOW Dares alone in combat us'd to stand END
BEGIN NOW The match of mighty Paris, hand to hand; END
BEGIN NOW The same, at Hector's fun'rals, undertook END
BEGIN NOW Gigantic Butes, of th' Amycian stock, END
BEGIN NOW And, by the stroke of his resistless hand, END
BEGIN NOW Stretch'd the vast bulk upon the yellow sand. END
BEGIN NOW Such Dares was; and such he strode along, END
BEGIN NOW And drew the wonder of the gazing throng. END
BEGIN NOW His brawny back and ample breast he shows, END
BEGIN NOW His lifted arms around his head he throws, END
BEGIN NOW And deals in whistling air his empty blows. END
BEGIN NOW His match is sought; but, thro' the trembling band, END
BEGIN NOW Not one dares answer to the proud demand. END
BEGIN NOW Presuming of his force, with sparkling eyes END
BEGIN NOW Already he devours the promis'd prize. END
BEGIN NOW He claims the bull with awless insolence, END
BEGIN NOW And having seiz'd his horns, accosts the prince: END
BEGIN NOW If none my matchless valor dares oppose, END
BEGIN NOW Permit me, chief, permit without delay, END
BEGIN NOW To lead this uncontended gift away. END
BEGIN NOW The crowd assents, and with redoubled cries END
BEGIN NOW For the proud challenger demands the prize. END
BEGIN NOW Acestes, fir'd with just disdain, to see END
BEGIN NOW The palm usurp'd without a victory, END
BEGIN NOW Reproach'd Entellus thus, who sate beside, END
BEGIN NOW And heard and saw, unmov'd, the Trojan's pride: END
BEGIN NOW Once, but in vain, a champion of renown, END
BEGIN NOW So tamely can you bear the ravish'd crown, END
BEGIN NOW A prize in triumph borne before your sight, END
BEGIN NOW And shun, for fear, the danger of the fight? END
BEGIN NOW Where is our Eryx now, the boasted name, END
BEGIN NOW The god who taught your thund'ring arm the game? END
BEGIN NOW Where now your baffled honor? Where the spoil END
BEGIN NOW That fill'd your house, and fame that fill'd our isle? END
BEGIN NOW Entellus, thus: "My soul is still the same, END
BEGIN NOW Unmov'd with fear, and mov'd with martial fame; END
BEGIN NOW But my chill blood is curdled in my veins, END
BEGIN NOW And scarce the shadow of a man remains. END
BEGIN NOW O could I turn to that fair prime again, END
BEGIN NOW That prime of which this boaster is so vain, END
BEGIN NOW The brave, who this decrepid age defies, END
BEGIN NOW Should feel my force, without the promis'd prize. END
BEGIN NOW He said; and, rising at the word, he threw END
BEGIN NOW Two pond'rous gauntlets down in open view; END
BEGIN NOW Gauntlets which Eryx wont in fight to wield, END
BEGIN NOW And sheathe his hands with in the listed field. END
BEGIN NOW With fear and wonder seiz'd, the crowd beholds END
BEGIN NOW The gloves of death, with sev'n distinguish'd folds END
BEGIN NOW Of tough bull hides; the space within is spread END
BEGIN NOW With iron, or with loads of heavy lead: END
BEGIN NOW Dares himself was daunted at the sight, END
BEGIN NOW Renounc'd his challenge, and refus'd to fight. END
BEGIN NOW Astonish'd at their weight, the hero stands, END
BEGIN NOW And pois'd the pond'rous engines in his hands. END
BEGIN NOW What had your wonder," said Entellus, been, END
BEGIN NOW Had you the gauntlets of Alcides seen, END
BEGIN NOW Or view'd the stern debate on this unhappy green! END
BEGIN NOW These which I bear your brother Eryx bore, END
BEGIN NOW Still mark'd with batter'd brains and mingled gore. END
BEGIN NOW With these he long sustain'd th' Herculean arm; END
BEGIN NOW And these I wielded while my blood was warm, END
BEGIN NOW This languish'd frame while better spirits fed, END
BEGIN NOW Ere age unstrung my nerves, or time o'ersnow'd my head. END
BEGIN NOW But if the challenger these arms refuse, END
BEGIN NOW And cannot wield their weight, or dare not use; END
BEGIN NOW If great Aeneas and Acestes join END
BEGIN NOW In his request, these gauntlets I resign; END
BEGIN NOW Let us with equal arms perform the fight, END
BEGIN NOW And let him leave to fear, since I resign my right. END
BEGIN NOW This said, Entellus for the strife prepares; END
BEGIN NOW Stripp'd of his quilted coat, his body bares; END
BEGIN NOW Compos'd of mighty bones and brawn he stands, END
BEGIN NOW A goodly tow'ring object on the sands. END
BEGIN NOW Then just Aeneas equal arms supplied, END
BEGIN NOW Which round their shoulders to their wrists they tied. END
BEGIN NOW Both on the tiptoe stand, at full extent, END
BEGIN NOW Their arms aloft, their bodies inly bent; END
BEGIN NOW Their heads from aiming blows they bear afar; END
BEGIN NOW With clashing gauntlets then provoke the war. END
BEGIN NOW One on his youth and pliant limbs relies; END
BEGIN NOW One on his sinews and his giant size. END
BEGIN NOW The last is stiff with age, his motion slow; END
BEGIN NOW He heaves for breath, he staggers to and fro, END
BEGIN NOW And clouds of issuing smoke his nostrils loudly blow. END
BEGIN NOW Yet equal in success, they ward, they strike; END
BEGIN NOW Their ways are diff'rent, but their art alike. END
BEGIN NOW Before, behind, the blows are dealt; around END
BEGIN NOW Their hollow sides the rattling thumps resound. END
BEGIN NOW A storm of strokes, well meant, with fury flies, END
BEGIN NOW And errs about their temples, ears, and eyes. END
BEGIN NOW Nor always errs; for oft the gauntlet draws END
BEGIN NOW A sweeping stroke along the crackling jaws. END
BEGIN NOW Heavy with age, Entellus stands his ground, END
BEGIN NOW But with his warping body wards the wound. END
BEGIN NOW His hand and watchful eye keep even pace; END
BEGIN NOW While Dares traverses and shifts his place, END
BEGIN NOW And, like a captain who beleaguers round END
BEGIN NOW Some strong-built castle on a rising ground, END
BEGIN NOW Views all th' approaches with observing eyes: END
BEGIN NOW This and that other part in vain he tries, END
BEGIN NOW And more on industry than force relies. END
BEGIN NOW With hands on high, Entellus threats the foe; END
BEGIN NOW But Dares watch'd the motion from below, END
BEGIN NOW And slipp'd aside, and shunn'd the long descending blow. END
BEGIN NOW Entellus wastes his forces on the wind, END
BEGIN NOW And, thus deluded of the stroke design'd, END
BEGIN NOW Headlong and heavy fell; his ample breast END
BEGIN NOW And weighty limbs his ancient mother press'd. END
BEGIN NOW So falls a hollow pine, that long had stood END
BEGIN NOW On Ida's height, or Erymanthus' wood, END
BEGIN NOW Torn from the roots. The diff'ring nations rise, END
BEGIN NOW And shouts and mingled murmurs rend the skies, END
BEGIN NOW Acestus runs with eager haste, to raise END
BEGIN NOW The fall'n companion of his youthful days. END
BEGIN NOW Dauntless he rose, and to the fight return'd; END
BEGIN NOW With shame his glowing cheeks, his eyes with fury burn'd. END
BEGIN NOW Disdain and conscious virtue fir'd his breast, END
BEGIN NOW And with redoubled force his foe he press'd. END
BEGIN NOW He lays on load with either hand, amain, END
BEGIN NOW And headlong drives the Trojan o'er the plain; END
BEGIN NOW Nor stops, nor stays; nor rest nor breath allows; END
BEGIN NOW But storms of strokes descend about his brows, END
BEGIN NOW A rattling tempest, and a hail of blows. END
BEGIN NOW But now the prince, who saw the wild increase END
BEGIN NOW Of wounds, commands the combatants to cease, END
BEGIN NOW And bounds Entellus' wrath, and bids the peace. END
BEGIN NOW First to the Trojan, spent with toil, he came, END
BEGIN NOW And sooth'd his sorrow for the suffer'd shame. END
BEGIN NOW What fury seiz'd my friend? The gods," said he, END
BEGIN NOW To him propitious, and averse to thee, END
BEGIN NOW Have giv'n his arm superior force to thine. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is madness to contend with strength divine. END
BEGIN NOW The gauntlet fight thus ended, from the shore END
BEGIN NOW His faithful friends unhappy Dares bore: END
BEGIN NOW His mouth and nostrils pour'd a purple flood, END
BEGIN NOW And pounded teeth came rushing with his blood. END
BEGIN NOW Faintly he stagger'd thro' the hissing throng, END
BEGIN NOW And hung his head, and trail'd his legs along. END
BEGIN NOW The sword and casque are carried by his train; END
BEGIN NOW But with his foe the palm and ox remain. END
BEGIN NOW The champion, then, before Aeneas came, END
BEGIN NOW Proud of his prize, but prouder of his fame: END
BEGIN NOW O goddess-born, and you, Dardanian host, END
BEGIN NOW Mark with attention, and forgive my boast; END
BEGIN NOW Learn what I was, by what remains; and know END
BEGIN NOW From what impending fate you sav'd my foe. END
BEGIN NOW Sternly he spoke, and then confronts the bull; END
BEGIN NOW And, on his ample forehead aiming full, END
BEGIN NOW The deadly stroke, descending, pierc'd the skull. END
BEGIN NOW Down drops the beast, nor needs a second wound, END
BEGIN NOW But sprawls in pangs of death, and spurns the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Then, thus: "In Dares' stead I offer this. END
BEGIN NOW Eryx, accept a nobler sacrifice; END
BEGIN NOW Take the last gift my wither'd arms can yield: END
BEGIN NOW Thy gauntlets I resign, and here renounce the field. END
BEGIN NOW This done, Aeneas orders, for the close, END
BEGIN NOW The strife of archers with contending bows. END
BEGIN NOW The mast Sergesthus' shatter'd galley bore END
BEGIN NOW With his own hands he raises on the shore. END
BEGIN NOW A flutt'ring dove upon the top they tie, END
BEGIN NOW The living mark at which their arrows fly. END
BEGIN NOW The rival archers in a line advance, END
BEGIN NOW Their turn of shooting to receive from chance. END
BEGIN NOW A helmet holds their names; the lots are drawn: END
BEGIN NOW On the first scroll was read Hippocoon. END
BEGIN NOW The people shout. Upon the next was found END
BEGIN NOW Young Mnestheus, late with naval honors crown'd. END
BEGIN NOW The third contain'd Eurytion's noble name, END
BEGIN NOW Thy brother, Pandarus, and next in fame, END
BEGIN NOW Whom Pallas urg'd the treaty to confound, END
BEGIN NOW And send among the Greeks a feather'd wound. END
BEGIN NOW Acestes in the bottom last remain'd, END
BEGIN NOW Whom not his age from youthful sports restrain'd. END
BEGIN NOW Soon all with vigor bend their trusty bows, END
BEGIN NOW And from the quiver each his arrow chose. END
BEGIN NOW Hippocoon's was the first: with forceful sway END
BEGIN NOW It flew, and, whizzing, cut the liquid way. END
BEGIN NOW Fix'd in the mast the feather'd weapon stands: END
BEGIN NOW The fearful pigeon flutters in her bands, END
BEGIN NOW And the tree trembled, and the shouting cries END
BEGIN NOW Of the pleas'd people rend the vaulted skies. END
BEGIN NOW Then Mnestheus to the head his arrow drove, END
BEGIN NOW With lifted eyes, and took his aim above, END
BEGIN NOW But made a glancing shot, and missed the dove; END
BEGIN NOW Yet miss'd so narrow, that he cut the cord END
BEGIN NOW Which fasten'd by the foot the flitting bird. END
BEGIN NOW The captive thus releas'd, away she flies, END
BEGIN NOW And beats with clapping wings the yielding skies. END
BEGIN NOW His bow already bent, Eurytion stood; END
BEGIN NOW And, having first invok'd his brother god, END
BEGIN NOW His winged shaft with eager haste he sped. END
BEGIN NOW The fatal message reach'd her as she fled: END
BEGIN NOW She leaves her life aloft; she strikes the ground, END
BEGIN NOW And renders back the weapon in the wound. END
BEGIN NOW Acestes, grudging at his lot, remains, END
BEGIN NOW Without a prize to gratify his pains. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, shooting upward, sends his shaft, to show END
BEGIN NOW An archer's art, and boast his twanging bow. END
BEGIN NOW The feather'd arrow gave a dire portent, END
BEGIN NOW And latter augurs judge from this event. END
BEGIN NOW Chaf'd by the speed, it fir'd; and, as it flew, END
BEGIN NOW A trail of following flames ascending drew: END
BEGIN NOW Kindling they mount, and mark the shiny way; END
BEGIN NOW Across the skies as falling meteors play, END
BEGIN NOW And vanish into wind, or in a blaze decay. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans and Sicilians wildly stare, END
BEGIN NOW And, trembling, turn their wonder into pray'r. END
BEGIN NOW The Dardan prince put on a smiling face, END
BEGIN NOW And strain'd Acestes with a close embrace; END
BEGIN NOW Then, hon'ring him with gifts above the rest, END
BEGIN NOW Turn'd the bad omen, nor his fears confess'd. END
BEGIN NOW The gods," said he, "this miracle have wrought, END
BEGIN NOW And order'd you the prize without the lot. END
BEGIN NOW Accept this goblet, rough with figur'd gold, END
BEGIN NOW Which Thracian Cisseus gave my sire of old: END
BEGIN NOW This pledge of ancient amity receive, END
BEGIN NOW Which to my second sire I justly give. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and, with the trumpets' cheerful sound, END
BEGIN NOW Proclaim'd him victor, and with laurel-crown'd. END
BEGIN NOW Nor good Eurytion envied him the prize, END
BEGIN NOW Tho' he transfix'd the pigeon in the skies. END
BEGIN NOW Who cut the line, with second gifts was grac'd; END
BEGIN NOW The third was his whose arrow pierc'd the mast. END
BEGIN NOW The chief, before the games were wholly done, END
BEGIN NOW Call'd Periphantes, tutor to his son, END
BEGIN NOW And whisper'd thus: "With speed Ascanius find; END
BEGIN NOW And, if his childish troop be ready join'd, END
BEGIN NOW On horseback let him grace his grandsire's day, END
BEGIN NOW And lead his equals arm'd in just array. END
BEGIN NOW He said; and, calling out, the cirque he clears. END
BEGIN NOW The crowd withdrawn, an open plain appears. END
BEGIN NOW And now the noble youths, of form divine, END
BEGIN NOW Advance before their fathers, in a line; END
BEGIN NOW The riders grace the steeds; the steeds with glory shine. END
BEGIN NOW Thus marching on in military pride, END
BEGIN NOW Shouts of applause resound from side to side. END
BEGIN NOW Their casques adorn'd with laurel wreaths they wear, END
BEGIN NOW Each brandishing aloft a cornel spear. END
BEGIN NOW Some at their backs their gilded quivers bore; END
BEGIN NOW Their chains of burnish'd gold hung down before. END
BEGIN NOW Three graceful troops they form'd upon the green; END
BEGIN NOW Three graceful leaders at their head were seen; END
BEGIN NOW Twelve follow'd ev'ry chief, and left a space between. END
BEGIN NOW The first young Priam led; a lovely boy, END
BEGIN NOW Whose grandsire was th' unhappy king of Troy; END
BEGIN NOW His race in after times was known to fame, END
BEGIN NOW New honors adding to the Latian name; END
BEGIN NOW And well the royal boy his Thracian steed became. END
BEGIN NOW White were the fetlocks of his feet before, END
BEGIN NOW And on his front a snowy star he bore. END
BEGIN NOW Then beauteous Atys, with Iulus bred, END
BEGIN NOW Of equal age, the second squadron led. END
BEGIN NOW The last in order, but the first in place, END
BEGIN NOW First in the lovely features of his face, END
BEGIN NOW Rode fair Ascanius on a fiery steed, END
BEGIN NOW Queen Dido's gift, and of the Tyrian breed. END
BEGIN NOW Sure coursers for the rest the king ordains, END
BEGIN NOW With golden bits adorn'd, and purple reins. END
BEGIN NOW The pleas'd spectators peals of shouts renew, END
BEGIN NOW And all the parents in the children view; END
BEGIN NOW Their make, their motions, and their sprightly grace, END
BEGIN NOW And hopes and fears alternate in their face. END
BEGIN NOW Th' unfledg'd commanders and their martial train END
BEGIN NOW First make the circuit of the sandy plain END
BEGIN NOW Around their sires, and, at th' appointed sign, END
BEGIN NOW Drawn up in beauteous order, form a line. END
BEGIN NOW The second signal sounds, the troop divides END
BEGIN NOW In three distinguish'd parts, with three distinguish'd guides END
BEGIN NOW Again they close, and once again disjoin; END
BEGIN NOW In troop to troop oppos'd, and line to line. END
BEGIN NOW They meet; they wheel; they throw their darts afar END
BEGIN NOW With harmless rage and well-dissembled war. END
BEGIN NOW Then in a round the mingled bodies run: END
BEGIN NOW Flying they follow, and pursuing shun; END
BEGIN NOW Broken, they break; and, rallying, they renew END
BEGIN NOW In other forms the military shew. END
BEGIN NOW At last, in order, undiscern'd they join, END
BEGIN NOW And march together in a friendly line. END
BEGIN NOW And, as the Cretan labyrinth of old, END
BEGIN NOW With wand'ring ways and many a winding fold, END
BEGIN NOW Involv'd the weary feet, without redress, END
BEGIN NOW In a round error, which denied recess; END
BEGIN NOW So fought the Trojan boys in warlike play, END
BEGIN NOW Turn'd and return'd, and still a diff'rent way. END
BEGIN NOW Thus dolphins in the deep each other chase END
BEGIN NOW In circles, when they swim around the wat'ry race. END
BEGIN NOW This game, these carousels, Ascanius taught; END
BEGIN NOW And, building Alba, to the Latins brought; END
BEGIN NOW Shew'd what he learn'd: the Latin sires impart END
BEGIN NOW To their succeeding sons the graceful art; END
BEGIN NOW From these imperial Rome receiv'd the game, END
BEGIN NOW Which Troy, the youths the Trojan troop, they name. END
BEGIN NOW Thus far the sacred sports they celebrate: END
BEGIN NOW But Fortune soon resum'd her ancient hate; END
BEGIN NOW For, while they pay the dead his annual dues, END
BEGIN NOW Those envied rites Saturnian Juno views; END
BEGIN NOW And sends the goddess of the various bow, END
BEGIN NOW To try new methods of revenge below; END
BEGIN NOW Supplies the winds to wing her airy way, END
BEGIN NOW Where in the port secure the navy lay. END
BEGIN NOW Swiftly fair Iris down her arch descends, END
BEGIN NOW And, undiscern'd, her fatal voyage ends. END
BEGIN NOW She saw the gath'ring crowd; and, gliding thence, END
BEGIN NOW The desart shore, and fleet without defense. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan matrons, on the sands alone, END
BEGIN NOW With sighs and tears Anchises' death bemoan; END
BEGIN NOW Then, turning to the sea their weeping eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Their pity to themselves renews their cries. END
BEGIN NOW Alas! said one, "what oceans yet remain END
BEGIN NOW For us to sail! what labors to sustain! END
BEGIN NOW All take the word, and, with a gen'ral groan, END
BEGIN NOW Implore the gods for peace, and places of their own. END
BEGIN NOW The goddess, great in mischief, views their pains, END
BEGIN NOW And in a woman's form her heav'nly limbs restrains. END
BEGIN NOW In face and shape old Beroe she became, END
BEGIN NOW Doryclus' wife, a venerable dame, END
BEGIN NOW Once blest with riches, and a mother's name. END
BEGIN NOW Thus chang'd, amidst the crying crowd she ran, END
BEGIN NOW Mix'd with the matrons, and these words began: END
BEGIN NOW O wretched we, whom not the Grecian pow'r, END
BEGIN NOW Nor flames, destroy'd, in Troy's unhappy hour! END
BEGIN NOW O wretched we, reserv'd by cruel fate, END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the ruins of the sinking state! END
BEGIN NOW Now sev'n revolving years are wholly run, END
BEGIN NOW Since this improsp'rous voyage we begun; END
BEGIN NOW Since, toss'd from shores to shores, from lands to lands, END
BEGIN NOW Inhospitable rocks and barren sands, END
BEGIN NOW Wand'ring in exile thro' the stormy sea, END
BEGIN NOW We search in vain for flying Italy. END
BEGIN NOW Now cast by fortune on this kindred land, END
BEGIN NOW What should our rest and rising walls withstand, END
BEGIN NOW Or hinder here to fix our banish'd band? END
BEGIN NOW O country lost, and gods redeem'd in vain, END
BEGIN NOW If still in endless exile we remain! END
BEGIN NOW Shall we no more the Trojan walls renew, END
BEGIN NOW Or streams of some dissembled Simois view! END
BEGIN NOW Haste, join with me, th' unhappy fleet consume! END
BEGIN NOW Cassandra bids; and I declare her doom. END
BEGIN NOW In sleep I saw her; she supplied my hands END
BEGIN NOW (For this I more than dreamt) with flaming brands: END
BEGIN NOW 'With these,' said she, 'these wand'ring ships destroy: END
BEGIN NOW These are your fatal seats, and this your Troy.' END
BEGIN NOW Time calls you now; the precious hour employ: END
BEGIN NOW Slack not the good presage, while Heav'n inspires END
BEGIN NOW Our minds to dare, and gives the ready fires. END
BEGIN NOW See! Neptune's altars minister their brands: END
BEGIN NOW The god is pleas'd; the god supplies our hands. END
BEGIN NOW Then from the pile a flaming fire she drew, END
BEGIN NOW And, toss'd in air, amidst the galleys threw. END
BEGIN NOW Wrapp'd in amaze, the matrons wildly stare: END
BEGIN NOW Then Pyrgo, reverenc'd for her hoary hair, END
BEGIN NOW Pyrgo, the nurse of Priam's num'rous race: END
BEGIN NOW No Beroe this, tho' she belies her face! END
BEGIN NOW What terrors from her frowning front arise! END
BEGIN NOW Behold a goddess in her ardent eyes! END
BEGIN NOW What rays around her heav'nly face are seen! END
BEGIN NOW Mark her majestic voice, and more than mortal mien! END
BEGIN NOW Beroe but now I left, whom, pin'd with pain, END
BEGIN NOW Her age and anguish from these rites detain, END
BEGIN NOW She said. The matrons, seiz'd with new amaze, END
BEGIN NOW Roll their malignant eyes, and on the navy gaze. END
BEGIN NOW They fear, and hope, and neither part obey: END
BEGIN NOW They hope the fated land, but fear the fatal way. END
BEGIN NOW The goddess, having done her task below, END
BEGIN NOW Mounts up on equal wings, and bends her painted bow. END
BEGIN NOW Struck with the sight, and seiz'd with rage divine, END
BEGIN NOW The matrons prosecute their mad design: END
BEGIN NOW They shriek aloud; they snatch, with impious hands, END
BEGIN NOW The food of altars; fires and flaming brands. END
BEGIN NOW Green boughs and saplings, mingled in their haste, END
BEGIN NOW And smoking torches, on the ships they cast. END
BEGIN NOW The flame, unstopp'd at first, more fury gains, END
BEGIN NOW And Vulcan rides at large with loosen'd reins: END
BEGIN NOW Triumphant to the painted sterns he soars, END
BEGIN NOW And seizes, in this way, the banks and crackling oars. END
BEGIN NOW Eumelus was the first the news to bear, END
BEGIN NOW While yet they crowd the rural theater. END
BEGIN NOW Then, what they hear, is witness'd by their eyes: END
BEGIN NOW A storm of sparkles and of flames arise. END
BEGIN NOW Ascanius took th' alarm, while yet he led END
BEGIN NOW His early warriors on his prancing steed, END
BEGIN NOW And, spurring on, his equals soon o'erpass'd; END
BEGIN NOW Nor could his frighted friends reclaim his haste. END
BEGIN NOW Soon as the royal youth appear'd in view, END
BEGIN NOW He sent his voice before him as he flew: END
BEGIN NOW What madness moves you, matrons, to destroy END
BEGIN NOW The last remainders of unhappy Troy! END
BEGIN NOW Not hostile fleets, but your own hopes, you burn, END
BEGIN NOW And on your friends your fatal fury turn. END
BEGIN NOW Behold your own Ascanius!" While he said, END
BEGIN NOW He drew his glitt'ring helmet from his head, END
BEGIN NOW In which the youths to sportful arms he led. END
BEGIN NOW By this, Aeneas and his train appear; END
BEGIN NOW And now the women, seiz'd with shame and fear, END
BEGIN NOW Dispers'd, to woods and caverns take their flight, END
BEGIN NOW Abhor their actions, and avoid the light; END
BEGIN NOW Their friends acknowledge, and their error find, END
BEGIN NOW And shake the goddess from their alter'd mind. END
BEGIN NOW Not so the raging fires their fury cease, END
BEGIN NOW But, lurking in the seams, with seeming peace, END
BEGIN NOW Work on their way amid the smold'ring tow, END
BEGIN NOW Sure in destruction, but in motion slow. END
BEGIN NOW The silent plague thro' the green timber eats, END
BEGIN NOW Down to the keels, and upward to the sails, END
BEGIN NOW The fire descends, or mounts, but still prevails; END
BEGIN NOW Nor buckets pour'd, nor strength of human hand, END
BEGIN NOW Can the victorious element withstand. END
BEGIN NOW The pious hero rends his robe, and throws END
BEGIN NOW To heav'n his hands, and with his hands his vows. END
BEGIN NOW O Jove," he cried, "if pray'rs can yet have place; END
BEGIN NOW If thou abhorr'st not all the Dardan race; END
BEGIN NOW If any spark of pity still remain; END
BEGIN NOW If gods are gods, and not invok'd in vain; END
BEGIN NOW Yet spare the relics of the Trojan train! END
BEGIN NOW Yet from the flames our burning vessels free, END
BEGIN NOW Or let thy fury fall alone on me! END
BEGIN NOW At this devoted head thy thunder throw, END
BEGIN NOW And send the willing sacrifice below! END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had he said, when southern storms arise: END
BEGIN NOW From pole to pole the forky lightning flies; END
BEGIN NOW Loud rattling shakes the mountains and the plain; END
BEGIN NOW Heav'n bellies downward, and descends in rain. END
BEGIN NOW Whole sheets of water from the clouds are sent, END
BEGIN NOW Which, hissing thro' the planks, the flames prevent, END
BEGIN NOW And stop the fiery pest. Four ships alone END
BEGIN NOW Burn to the waist, and for the fleet atone. END
BEGIN NOW But doubtful thoughts the hero's heart divide; END
BEGIN NOW If he should still in Sicily reside, END
BEGIN NOW Forgetful of his fates, or tempt the main, END
BEGIN NOW In hope the promis'd Italy to gain. END
BEGIN NOW Then Nautes, old and wise, to whom alone END
BEGIN NOW The will of Heav'n by Pallas was foreshown; END
BEGIN NOW Vers'd in portents, experienc'd, and inspir'd END
BEGIN NOW To tell events, and what the fates requir'd; END
BEGIN NOW Thus while he stood, to neither part inclin'd, END
BEGIN NOW With cheerful words reliev'd his lab'ring mind: END
BEGIN NOW O goddess-born, resign'd in ev'ry state, END
BEGIN NOW With patience bear, with prudence push your fate. END
BEGIN NOW By suff'ring well, our Fortune we subdue; END
BEGIN NOW Fly when she frowns, and, when she calls, pursue. END
BEGIN NOW Your friend Acestes is of Trojan kind; END
BEGIN NOW To him disclose the secrets of your mind: END
BEGIN NOW Trust in his hands your old and useless train; END
BEGIN NOW Too num'rous for the ships which yet remain: END
BEGIN NOW The feeble, old, indulgent of their ease, END
BEGIN NOW The dames who dread the dangers of the seas, END
BEGIN NOW The shock of battle with your foes by land. END
BEGIN NOW Here you may build a common town for all, END
BEGIN NOW And, from Acestes' name, Acesta call. END
BEGIN NOW The reasons, with his friend's experience join'd, END
BEGIN NOW Encourag'd much, but more disturb'd his mind. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was dead of night; when to his slumb'ring eyes END
BEGIN NOW His father's shade descended from the skies, END
BEGIN NOW And thus he spoke: "O more than vital breath, END
BEGIN NOW Lov'd while I liv'd, and dear ev'n after death; END
BEGIN NOW O son, in various toils and troubles toss'd, END
BEGIN NOW The King of Heav'n employs my careful ghost END
BEGIN NOW On his commands: the god, who sav'd from fire END
BEGIN NOW Your flaming fleet, and heard your just desire. END
BEGIN NOW The wholesome counsel of your friend receive, END
BEGIN NOW And here the coward train and woman leave: END
BEGIN NOW The chosen youth, and those who nobly dare, END
BEGIN NOW Transport, to tempt the dangers of the war. END
BEGIN NOW The stern Italians will their courage try; END
BEGIN NOW Rough are their manners, and their minds are high. END
BEGIN NOW But first to Pluto's palace you shall go, END
BEGIN NOW And seek my shade among the blest below: END
BEGIN NOW For not with impious ghosts my soul remains, END
BEGIN NOW Nor suffers with the damn'd perpetual pains, END
BEGIN NOW But breathes the living air of soft Elysian plains. END
BEGIN NOW The chaste Sibylla shall your steps convey, END
BEGIN NOW And blood of offer'd victims free the way. END
BEGIN NOW There shall you know what realms the gods assign, END
BEGIN NOW And learn the fates and fortunes of your line. END
BEGIN NOW But now, farewell! I vanish with the night, END
BEGIN NOW And feel the blast of heav'n's approaching light. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and mix'd with shades, and took his airy flight. END
BEGIN NOW Whither so fast?" the filial duty cried; END
BEGIN NOW And why, ah why, the wish'd embrace denied? END
BEGIN NOW He said, and rose; as holy zeal inspires, END
BEGIN NOW He rakes hot embers, and renews the fires; END
BEGIN NOW His country gods and Vesta then adores END
BEGIN NOW With cakes and incense, and their aid implores. END
BEGIN NOW Next, for his friends and royal host he sent, END
BEGIN NOW Reveal'd his vision, and the gods' intent, END
BEGIN NOW With his own purpose. All, without delay, END
BEGIN NOW The will of Jove, and his desires obey. END
BEGIN NOW They list with women each degenerate name, END
BEGIN NOW Who dares not hazard life for future fame. END
BEGIN NOW These they cashier: the brave remaining few, END
BEGIN NOW Oars, banks, and cables, half consum'd, renew. END
BEGIN NOW The prince designs a city with the plow; END
BEGIN NOW The lots their sev'ral tenements allow. END
BEGIN NOW This part is nam'd from Ilium, that from Troy, END
BEGIN NOW And the new king ascends the throne with joy; END
BEGIN NOW A chosen senate from the people draws; END
BEGIN NOW Appoints the judges, and ordains the laws. END
BEGIN NOW Then, on the top of Eryx, they begin END
BEGIN NOW A rising temple to the Paphian queen. END
BEGIN NOW Anchises, last, is honor'd as a god; END
BEGIN NOW A priest is added, annual gifts bestow'd, END
BEGIN NOW And groves are planted round his blest abode. END
BEGIN NOW Nine days they pass in feasts, their temples crown'd; END
BEGIN NOW And fumes of incense in the fanes abound. END
BEGIN NOW Then from the south arose a gentle breeze END
BEGIN NOW That curl'd the smoothness of the glassy seas; END
BEGIN NOW The rising winds a ruffling gale afford, END
BEGIN NOW And call the merry mariners aboard. END
BEGIN NOW Now loud laments along the shores resound, END
BEGIN NOW Of parting friends in close embraces bound. END
BEGIN NOW The trembling women, the degenerate train, END
BEGIN NOW Who shunn'd the frightful dangers of the main, END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n those desire to sail, and take their share END
BEGIN NOW Of the rough passage and the promis'd war: END
BEGIN NOW Whom good Aeneas cheers, and recommends END
BEGIN NOW To their new master's care his fearful friends. END
BEGIN NOW On Eryx's altars three fat calves he lays; END
BEGIN NOW A lamb new-fallen to the stormy seas; END
BEGIN NOW Then slips his haulsers, and his anchors weighs. END
BEGIN NOW High on the deck the godlike hero stands, END
BEGIN NOW With olive crown'd, a charger in his hands; END
BEGIN NOW Then cast the reeking entrails in the brine, END
BEGIN NOW And pour'd the sacrifice of purple wine. END
BEGIN NOW Fresh gales arise; with equal strokes they vie, END
BEGIN NOW And brush the buxom seas, and o'er the billows fly. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the mother goddess, full of fears, END
BEGIN NOW To Neptune thus address'd, with tender tears: END
BEGIN NOW The pride of Jove's imperious queen, the rage, END
BEGIN NOW The malice which no suff'rings can assuage, END
BEGIN NOW Compel me to these pray'rs; since neither fate, END
BEGIN NOW Nor time, nor pity, can remove her hate: END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n Jove is thwarted by his haughty wife; END
BEGIN NOW Still vanquish'd, yet she still renews the strife. END
BEGIN NOW As if 't were little to consume the town END
BEGIN NOW Which aw'd the world, and wore th' imperial crown, END
BEGIN NOW She prosecutes the ghost of Troy with pains, END
BEGIN NOW And gnaws, ev'n to the bones, the last remains. END
BEGIN NOW Let her the causes of her hatred tell; END
BEGIN NOW But you can witness its effects too well. END
BEGIN NOW You saw the storm she rais'd on Libyan floods, END
BEGIN NOW That mix'd the mounting billows with the clouds; END
BEGIN NOW When, bribing Aeolus, she shook the main, END
BEGIN NOW And mov'd rebellion in your wat'ry reign. END
BEGIN NOW With fury she possess'd the Dardan dames, END
BEGIN NOW To burn their fleet with execrable flames, END
BEGIN NOW And forc'd Aeneas, when his ships were lost, END
BEGIN NOW To leave his foll'wers on a foreign coast. END
BEGIN NOW For what remains, your godhead I implore, END
BEGIN NOW And trust my son to your protecting pow'r. END
BEGIN NOW If neither Jove's nor Fate's decree withstand, END
BEGIN NOW Secure his passage to the Latian land. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus the mighty Ruler of the Main: END
BEGIN NOW What may not Venus hope from Neptune's reign? END
BEGIN NOW My kingdom claims your birth; my late defense END
BEGIN NOW Of your indanger'd fleet may claim your confidence. END
BEGIN NOW Nor less by land than sea my deeds declare END
BEGIN NOW How much your lov'd Aeneas is my care. END
BEGIN NOW Thee, Xanthus, and thee, Simois, I attest. END
BEGIN NOW Your Trojan troops when proud Achilles press'd, END
BEGIN NOW And drove before him headlong on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW And dash'd against the walls the trembling train; END
BEGIN NOW When floods were fill'd with bodies of the slain; END
BEGIN NOW When crimson Xanthus, doubtful of his way, END
BEGIN NOW Stood up on ridges to behold the sea; END
BEGIN NOW (New heaps came tumbling in, and chok'd his way;) END
BEGIN NOW When your Aeneas fought, but fought with odds END
BEGIN NOW Of force unequal, and unequal gods; END
BEGIN NOW I spread a cloud before the victor's sight, END
BEGIN NOW Sustain'd the vanquish'd, and secur'd his flight; END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n then secur'd him, when I sought with joy END
BEGIN NOW The vow'd destruction of ungrateful Troy. END
BEGIN NOW My will's the same: fair goddess, fear no more, END
BEGIN NOW Your fleet shall safely gain the Latian shore; END
BEGIN NOW Their lives are giv'n; one destin'd head alone END
BEGIN NOW Shall perish, and for multitudes atone. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having arm'd with hopes her anxious mind, END
BEGIN NOW His finny team Saturnian Neptune join'd, END
BEGIN NOW Then adds the foamy bridle to their jaws, END
BEGIN NOW And to the loosen'd reins permits the laws. END
BEGIN NOW High on the waves his azure car he guides; END
BEGIN NOW Its axles thunder, and the sea subsides, END
BEGIN NOW And the smooth ocean rolls her silent tides. END
BEGIN NOW The tempests fly before their father's face, END
BEGIN NOW Trains of inferior gods his triumph grace, END
BEGIN NOW And monster whales before their master play, END
BEGIN NOW And choirs of Tritons crowd the wat'ry way. END
BEGIN NOW The marshal'd pow'rs in equal troops divide END
BEGIN NOW To right and left; the gods his better side END
BEGIN NOW Inclose, and on the worse the Nymphs and Nereids ride. END
BEGIN NOW Now smiling hope, with sweet vicissitude, END
BEGIN NOW Within the hero's mind his joys renew'd. END
BEGIN NOW He calls to raise the masts, the sheets display; END
BEGIN NOW The cheerful crew with diligence obey; END
BEGIN NOW They scud before the wind, and sail in open sea. END
BEGIN NOW Ahead of all the master pilot steers; END
BEGIN NOW And, as he leads, the following navy veers. END
BEGIN NOW The steeds of Night had travel'd half the sky, END
BEGIN NOW The drowsy rowers on their benches lie, END
BEGIN NOW When the soft God of Sleep, with easy flight, END
BEGIN NOW Descends, and draws behind a trail of light. END
BEGIN NOW Thou, Palinurus, art his destin'd prey; END
BEGIN NOW To thee alone he takes his fatal way. END
BEGIN NOW Dire dreams to thee, and iron sleep, he bears; END
BEGIN NOW And, lighting on thy prow, the form of Phorbas wears. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus the traitor god began his tale: END
BEGIN NOW The winds, my friend, inspire a pleasing gale; END
BEGIN NOW The ships, without thy care, securely sail. END
BEGIN NOW Now steal an hour of sweet repose; and I END
BEGIN NOW Will take the rudder and thy room supply. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the yawning pilot, half asleep: END
BEGIN NOW Me dost thou bid to trust the treach'rous deep, END
BEGIN NOW The harlot smiles of her dissembling face, END
BEGIN NOW And to her faith commit the Trojan race? END
BEGIN NOW Shall I believe the Siren South again, END
BEGIN NOW And, oft betray'd, not know the monster main? END
BEGIN NOW He said: his fasten'd hands the rudder keep, END
BEGIN NOW And, fix'd on heav'n, his eyes repel invading sleep. END
BEGIN NOW The god was wroth, and at his temples threw END
BEGIN NOW A branch in Lethe dipp'd, and drunk with Stygian dew: END
BEGIN NOW The pilot, vanquish'd by the pow'r divine, END
BEGIN NOW Soon clos'd his swimming eyes, and lay supine. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce were his limbs extended at their length, END
BEGIN NOW The god, insulting with superior strength, END
BEGIN NOW Fell heavy on him, plung'd him in the sea, END
BEGIN NOW And, with the stern, the rudder tore away. END
BEGIN NOW Headlong he fell, and, struggling in the main, END
BEGIN NOW Cried out for helping hands, but cried in vain. END
BEGIN NOW The victor daemon mounts obscure in air, END
BEGIN NOW While the ship sails without the pilot's care. END
BEGIN NOW On Neptune's faith the floating fleet relies; END
BEGIN NOW But what the man forsook, the god supplies, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er the dang'rous deep secure the navy flies; END
BEGIN NOW Glides by the Sirens' cliffs, a shelfy coast, END
BEGIN NOW Long infamous for ships and sailors lost, END
BEGIN NOW And white with bones. Th' impetuous ocean roars, END
BEGIN NOW And rocks rebellow from the sounding shores. END
BEGIN NOW The watchful hero felt the knocks, and found END
BEGIN NOW The tossing vessel sail'd on shoaly ground. END
BEGIN NOW Sure of his pilot's loss, he takes himself END
BEGIN NOW The helm, and steers aloof, and shuns the shelf. END
BEGIN NOW Inly he griev'd, and, groaning from the breast, END
BEGIN NOW Deplor'd his death; and thus his pain express'd: END
BEGIN NOW For faith repos'd on seas, and on the flatt'ring sky, END
BEGIN NOW Thy naked corpse is doom'd on shores unknown to lie. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and wept; then spread his sails before END
BEGIN NOW The winds, and reach'd at length the Cumaean shore: END
BEGIN NOW Their anchors dropp'd, his crew the vessels moor. END
BEGIN NOW They turn their heads to sea, their sterns to land, END
BEGIN NOW And greet with greedy joy th' Italian strand. END
BEGIN NOW Some strike from clashing flints their fiery seed; END
BEGIN NOW Some gather sticks, the kindled flames to feed, END
BEGIN NOW Or search for hollow trees, and fell the woods, END
BEGIN NOW Or trace thro' valleys the discover'd floods. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, while their sev'ral charges they fulfil, END
BEGIN NOW The pious prince ascends the sacred hill END
BEGIN NOW Where Phoebus is ador'd; and seeks the shade END
BEGIN NOW Which hides from sight his venerable maid. END
BEGIN NOW Deep in a cave the Sibyl makes abode; END
BEGIN NOW Thence full of fate returns, and of the god. END
BEGIN NOW Thro' Trivia's grove they walk; and now behold, END
BEGIN NOW And enter now, the temple roof'd with gold. END
BEGIN NOW When Daedalus, to fly the Cretan shore, END
BEGIN NOW His heavy limbs on jointed pinions bore, END
BEGIN NOW (The first who sail'd in air,) 't is sung by Fame, END
BEGIN NOW To the Cumaean coast at length he came, END
BEGIN NOW And here alighting, built this costly frame. END
BEGIN NOW Inscrib'd to Phoebus, here he hung on high END
BEGIN NOW The steerage of his wings, that cut the sky: END
BEGIN NOW Then o'er the lofty gate his art emboss'd END
BEGIN NOW Androgeos' death, and off'rings to his ghost; END
BEGIN NOW Sev'n youths from Athens yearly sent, to meet END
BEGIN NOW The fate appointed by revengeful Crete. END
BEGIN NOW And next to those the dreadful urn was plac'd, END
BEGIN NOW In which the destin'd names by lots were cast: END
BEGIN NOW The mournful parents stand around in tears, END
BEGIN NOW And rising Crete against their shore appears. END
BEGIN NOW There too, in living sculpture, might be seen END
BEGIN NOW The mad affection of the Cretan queen; END
BEGIN NOW Then how she cheats her bellowing lover's eye; END
BEGIN NOW The rushing leap, the doubtful progeny, END
BEGIN NOW The lower part a beast, a man above, END
BEGIN NOW The monument of their polluted love. END
BEGIN NOW Not far from thence he grav'd the wondrous maze, END
BEGIN NOW A thousand doors, a thousand winding ways: END
BEGIN NOW Here dwells the monster, hid from human view, END
BEGIN NOW Not to be found, but by the faithful clew; END
BEGIN NOW Till the kind artist, mov'd with pious grief, END
BEGIN NOW Lent to the loving maid this last relief, END
BEGIN NOW And all those erring paths describ'd so well END
BEGIN NOW That Theseus conquer'd and the monster fell. END
BEGIN NOW Here hapless Icarus had found his part, END
BEGIN NOW Had not the father's grief restrain'd his art. END
BEGIN NOW He twice assay'd to cast his son in gold; END
BEGIN NOW Twice from his hands he dropp'd the forming mold. END
BEGIN NOW All this with wond'ring eyes Aeneas view'd; END
BEGIN NOW Each varying object his delight renew'd: END
BEGIN NOW Eager to read the rest- Achates came, END
BEGIN NOW And by his side the mad divining dame, END
BEGIN NOW The priestess of the god, Deiphobe her name. END
BEGIN NOW Time suffers not," she said, "to feed your eyes END
BEGIN NOW With empty pleasures; haste the sacrifice. END
BEGIN NOW Sev'n bullocks, yet unyok'd, for Phoebus choose, END
BEGIN NOW And for Diana sev'n unspotted ewes. END
BEGIN NOW This said, the servants urge the sacred rites, END
BEGIN NOW While to the temple she the prince invites. END
BEGIN NOW A spacious cave, within its farmost part, END
BEGIN NOW Was hew'd and fashion'd by laborious art END
BEGIN NOW Thro' the hill's hollow sides: before the place, END
BEGIN NOW A hundred doors a hundred entries grace; END
BEGIN NOW As many voices issue, and the sound END
BEGIN NOW Of Sybil's words as many times rebound. END
BEGIN NOW Now to the mouth they come. Aloud she cries: END
BEGIN NOW This is the time; enquire your destinies. END
BEGIN NOW He comes; behold the god!" Thus while she said, END
BEGIN NOW (And shiv'ring at the sacred entry stay'd,) END
BEGIN NOW Her color chang'd; her face was not the same, END
BEGIN NOW And hollow groans from her deep spirit came. END
BEGIN NOW Her hair stood up; convulsive rage possess'd END
BEGIN NOW Her trembling limbs, and heav'd her lab'ring breast. END
BEGIN NOW Greater than humankind she seem'd to look, END
BEGIN NOW And with an accent more than mortal spoke. END
BEGIN NOW Her staring eyes with sparkling fury roll; END
BEGIN NOW When all the god came rushing on her soul. END
BEGIN NOW Swiftly she turn'd, and, foaming as she spoke: END
BEGIN NOW Why this delay?" she cried- "the pow'rs invoke! END
BEGIN NOW Thy pray'rs alone can open this abode; END
BEGIN NOW She said no more. The trembling Trojans hear, END
BEGIN NOW O'erspread with a damp sweat and holy fear. END
BEGIN NOW The prince himself, with awful dread possess'd, END
BEGIN NOW His vows to great Apollo thus address'd: END
BEGIN NOW Indulgent god, propitious pow'r to Troy, END
BEGIN NOW Swift to relieve, unwilling to destroy, END
BEGIN NOW Directed by whose hand the Dardan dart END
BEGIN NOW Pierc'd the proud Grecian's only mortal part: END
BEGIN NOW Thus far, by fate's decrees and thy commands, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' ambient seas and thro' devouring sands, END
BEGIN NOW Our exil'd crew has sought th' Ausonian ground; END
BEGIN NOW And now, at length, the flying coast is found. END
BEGIN NOW Thus far the fate of Troy, from place to place, END
BEGIN NOW With fury has pursued her wand'ring race. END
BEGIN NOW Here cease, ye pow'rs, and let your vengeance end: END
BEGIN NOW Troy is no more, and can no more offend. END
BEGIN NOW And thou, O sacred maid, inspir'd to see END
BEGIN NOW Th' event of things in dark futurity; END
BEGIN NOW Give me what Heav'n has promis'd to my fate, END
BEGIN NOW To conquer and command the Latian state; END
BEGIN NOW To fix my wand'ring gods, and find a place END
BEGIN NOW For the long exiles of the Trojan race. END
BEGIN NOW Then shall my grateful hands a temple rear END
BEGIN NOW To the twin gods, with vows and solemn pray'r; END
BEGIN NOW And annual rites, and festivals, and games, END
BEGIN NOW Shall be perform'd to their auspicious names. END
BEGIN NOW Nor shalt thou want thy honors in my land; END
BEGIN NOW For there thy faithful oracles shall stand, END
BEGIN NOW Preserv'd in shrines; and ev'ry sacred lay, END
BEGIN NOW Which, by thy mouth, Apollo shall convey: END
BEGIN NOW All shall be treasur'd by a chosen train END
BEGIN NOW Of holy priests, and ever shall remain. END
BEGIN NOW But O! commit not thy prophetic mind END
BEGIN NOW To flitting leaves, the sport of ev'ry wind, END
BEGIN NOW Lest they disperse in air our empty fate; END
BEGIN NOW Write not, but, what the pow'rs ordain, relate. END
BEGIN NOW Struggling in vain, impatient of her load, END
BEGIN NOW And lab'ring underneath the pond'rous god, END
BEGIN NOW The more she strove to shake him from her breast, END
BEGIN NOW With more and far superior force he press'd; END
BEGIN NOW Commands his entrance, and, without control, END
BEGIN NOW Usurps her organs and inspires her soul. END
BEGIN NOW Now, with a furious blast, the hundred doors END
BEGIN NOW Ope of themselves; a rushing whirlwind roars END
BEGIN NOW Within the cave, and Sibyl's voice restores: END
BEGIN NOW Escap'd the dangers of the wat'ry reign, END
BEGIN NOW Yet more and greater ills by land remain. END
BEGIN NOW The coast, so long desir'd (nor doubt th' event), END
BEGIN NOW Thy troops shall reach, but, having reach'd, repent. END
BEGIN NOW Wars, horrid wars, I view- a field of blood, END
BEGIN NOW And Tiber rolling with a purple flood. END
BEGIN NOW Simois nor Xanthus shall be wanting there: END
BEGIN NOW A new Achilles shall in arms appear, END
BEGIN NOW And he, too, goddess-born. Fierce Juno's hate, END
BEGIN NOW Added to hostile force, shall urge thy fate. END
BEGIN NOW To what strange nations shalt not thou resort, END
BEGIN NOW Driv'n to solicit aid at ev'ry court! END
BEGIN NOW The cause the same which Ilium once oppress'd; END
BEGIN NOW A foreign mistress, and a foreign guest. END
BEGIN NOW But thou, secure of soul, unbent with woes, END
BEGIN NOW The more thy fortune frowns, the more oppose. END
BEGIN NOW The dawnings of thy safety shall be shown END
BEGIN NOW From whence thou least shalt hope, a Grecian town. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, from the dark recess, the Sibyl spoke, END
BEGIN NOW And the resisting air the thunder broke; END
BEGIN NOW The cave rebellow'd, and the temple shook. END
BEGIN NOW Th' ambiguous god, who rul'd her lab'ring breast, END
BEGIN NOW In these mysterious words his mind express'd; END
BEGIN NOW Some truths reveal'd, in terms involv'd the rest. END
BEGIN NOW At length her fury fell, her foaming ceas'd, END
BEGIN NOW And, ebbing in her soul, the god decreas'd. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus the chief: "No terror to my view, END
BEGIN NOW No frightful face of danger can be new. END
BEGIN NOW Inur'd to suffer, and resolv'd to dare, END
BEGIN NOW The Fates, without my pow'r, shall be without my care. END
BEGIN NOW This let me crave, since near your grove the road END
BEGIN NOW To hell lies open, and the dark abode END
BEGIN NOW Which Acheron surrounds, th' innavigable flood; END
BEGIN NOW Conduct me thro' the regions void of light, END
BEGIN NOW And lead me longing to my father's sight. END
BEGIN NOW For him, a thousand dangers I have sought, END
BEGIN NOW And, rushing where the thickest Grecians fought, END
BEGIN NOW Safe on my back the sacred burthen brought. END
BEGIN NOW He, for my sake, the raging ocean tried, END
BEGIN NOW And wrath of Heav'n, my still auspicious guide, END
BEGIN NOW And bore beyond the strength decrepid age supplied. END
BEGIN NOW Oft, since he breath'd his last, in dead of night END
BEGIN NOW His reverend image stood before my sight; END
BEGIN NOW Enjoin'd to seek, below, his holy shade; END
BEGIN NOW Conducted there by your unerring aid. END
BEGIN NOW But you, if pious minds by pray'rs are won, END
BEGIN NOW Oblige the father, and protect the son. END
BEGIN NOW Yours is the pow'r; nor Proserpine in vain END
BEGIN NOW Has made you priestess of her nightly reign. END
BEGIN NOW If Orpheus, arm'd with his enchanting lyre, END
BEGIN NOW The ruthless king with pity could inspire, END
BEGIN NOW And from the shades below redeem his wife; END
BEGIN NOW If Pollux, off'ring his alternate life, END
BEGIN NOW Could free his brother, and can daily go END
BEGIN NOW By turns aloft, by turns descend below- END
BEGIN NOW Why name I Theseus, or his greater friend, END
BEGIN NOW Who trod the downward path, and upward could ascend? END
BEGIN NOW Not less than theirs from Jove my lineage came; END
BEGIN NOW My mother greater, my descent the same. END
BEGIN NOW So pray'd the Trojan prince, and, while he pray'd, END
BEGIN NOW His hand upon the holy altar laid. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus replied the prophetess divine: END
BEGIN NOW O goddess-born of great Anchises' line, END
BEGIN NOW The gates of hell are open night and day; END
BEGIN NOW Smooth the descent, and easy is the way: END
BEGIN NOW But to return, and view the cheerful skies, END
BEGIN NOW In this the task and mighty labor lies. END
BEGIN NOW To few great Jupiter imparts this grace, END
BEGIN NOW And those of shining worth and heav'nly race. END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt those regions and our upper light, END
BEGIN NOW Deep forests and impenetrable night END
BEGIN NOW Possess the middle space: th' infernal bounds END
BEGIN NOW Cocytus, with his sable waves, surrounds. END
BEGIN NOW But if so dire a love your soul invades, END
BEGIN NOW As twice below to view the trembling shades; END
BEGIN NOW If you so hard a toil will undertake, END
BEGIN NOW As twice to pass th' innavigable lake; END
BEGIN NOW Receive my counsel. In the neighb'ring grove END
BEGIN NOW There stands a tree; the queen of Stygian Jove END
BEGIN NOW Claims it her own; thick woods and gloomy night END
BEGIN NOW Conceal the happy plant from human sight. END
BEGIN NOW One bough it bears; but (wondrous to behold!) END
BEGIN NOW The ductile rind and leaves of radiant gold: END
BEGIN NOW This from the vulgar branches must be torn, END
BEGIN NOW And to fair Proserpine the present borne, END
BEGIN NOW Ere leave be giv'n to tempt the nether skies. END
BEGIN NOW The first thus rent a second will arise, END
BEGIN NOW And the same metal the same room supplies. END
BEGIN NOW Look round the wood, with lifted eyes, to see END
BEGIN NOW The lurking gold upon the fatal tree: END
BEGIN NOW Then rend it off, as holy rites command; END
BEGIN NOW The willing metal will obey thy hand, END
BEGIN NOW Following with ease, if favor'd by thy fate, END
BEGIN NOW Thou art foredoom'd to view the Stygian state: END
BEGIN NOW If not, no labor can the tree constrain; END
BEGIN NOW And strength of stubborn arms and steel are vain. END
BEGIN NOW Besides, you know not, while you here attend, END
BEGIN NOW Th' unworthy fate of your unhappy friend: END
BEGIN NOW Breathless he lies; and his unburied ghost, END
BEGIN NOW Depriv'd of fun'ral rites, pollutes your host. END
BEGIN NOW Pay first his pious dues; and, for the dead, END
BEGIN NOW Two sable sheep around his hearse be led; END
BEGIN NOW Then, living turfs upon his body lay: END
BEGIN NOW This done, securely take the destin'd way, END
BEGIN NOW To find the regions destitute of day. END
BEGIN NOW She said, and held her peace. Aeneas went END
BEGIN NOW Sad from the cave, and full of discontent, END
BEGIN NOW Unknowing whom the sacred Sibyl meant. END
BEGIN NOW Achates, the companion of his breast, END
BEGIN NOW Goes grieving by his side, with equal cares oppress'd. END
BEGIN NOW Walking, they talk'd, and fruitlessly divin'd END
BEGIN NOW What friend the priestess by those words design'd. END
BEGIN NOW But soon they found an object to deplore: END
BEGIN NOW Misenus lay extended the shore; END
BEGIN NOW Son of the God of Winds: none so renown'd END
BEGIN NOW The warrior trumpet in the field to sound; END
BEGIN NOW With breathing brass to kindle fierce alarms, END
BEGIN NOW And rouse to dare their fate in honorable arms. END
BEGIN NOW He serv'd great Hector, and was ever near, END
BEGIN NOW Not with his trumpet only, but his spear. END
BEGIN NOW But by Pelides' arms when Hector fell, END
BEGIN NOW He chose Aeneas; and he chose as well. END
BEGIN NOW Swoln with applause, and aiming still at more, END
BEGIN NOW He now provokes the sea gods from the shore; END
BEGIN NOW With envy Triton heard the martial sound, END
BEGIN NOW And the bold champion, for his challenge, drown'd; END
BEGIN NOW Then cast his mangled carcass on the strand: END
BEGIN NOW The gazing crowd around the body stand. END
BEGIN NOW All weep; but most Aeneas mourns his fate, END
BEGIN NOW And hastens to perform the funeral state. END
BEGIN NOW In altar-wise, a stately pile they rear; END
BEGIN NOW The basis broad below, and top advanc'd in air. END
BEGIN NOW An ancient wood, fit for the work design'd, END
BEGIN NOW (The shady covert of the salvage kind,) END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans found: the sounding ax is plied; END
BEGIN NOW Firs, pines, and pitch trees, and the tow'ring pride END
BEGIN NOW Of forest ashes, feel the fatal stroke, END
BEGIN NOW And piercing wedges cleave the stubborn oak. END
BEGIN NOW Huge trunks of trees, fell'd from the steepy crown END
BEGIN NOW Of the bare mountains, roll with ruin down. END
BEGIN NOW Arm'd like the rest the Trojan prince appears, END
BEGIN NOW And by his pious labor urges theirs. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while he wrought, revolving in his mind END
BEGIN NOW The ways to compass what his wish design'd, END
BEGIN NOW He cast his eyes upon the gloomy grove, END
BEGIN NOW And then with vows implor'd the Queen of Love: END
BEGIN NOW O may thy pow'r, propitious still to me, END
BEGIN NOW Conduct my steps to find the fatal tree, END
BEGIN NOW In this deep forest; since the Sibyl's breath END
BEGIN NOW Foretold, alas! too true, Misenus' death. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had he said, when, full before his sight, END
BEGIN NOW Two doves, descending from their airy flight, END
BEGIN NOW Secure upon the grassy plain alight. END
BEGIN NOW He knew his mother's birds; and thus he pray'd: END
BEGIN NOW Be you my guides, with your auspicious aid, END
BEGIN NOW And lead my footsteps, till the branch be found, END
BEGIN NOW Whose glitt'ring shadow gilds the sacred ground. END
BEGIN NOW And thou, great parent, with celestial care, END
BEGIN NOW In this distress be present to my pray'r! END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, he stopp'd with watchful sight, END
BEGIN NOW Observing still the motions of their flight, END
BEGIN NOW What course they took, what happy signs they shew. END
BEGIN NOW They fed, and, flutt'ring, by degrees withdrew END
BEGIN NOW Still farther from the place, but still in view: END
BEGIN NOW Hopping and flying, thus they led him on END
BEGIN NOW To the slow lake, whose baleful stench to shun END
BEGIN NOW They wing'd their flight aloft; then, stooping low, END
BEGIN NOW Perch'd on the double tree that bears the golden bough. END
BEGIN NOW Thro' the green leafs the glitt'ring shadows glow; END
BEGIN NOW As, on the sacred oak, the wintry mistletoe, END
BEGIN NOW Where the proud mother views her precious brood, END
BEGIN NOW And happier branches, which she never sow'd. END
BEGIN NOW Such was the glitt'ring; such the ruddy rind, END
BEGIN NOW And dancing leaves, that wanton'd in the wind. END
BEGIN NOW He seiz'd the shining bough with griping hold, END
BEGIN NOW And rent away, with ease, the ling'ring gold; END
BEGIN NOW Then to the Sibyl's palace bore the prize. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the Trojan troops, with weeping eyes, END
BEGIN NOW To dead Misenus pay his obsequies. END
BEGIN NOW First, from the ground a lofty pile they rear, END
BEGIN NOW Of pitch trees, oaks, and pines, and unctuous fir: END
BEGIN NOW The fabric's front with cypress twigs they strew, END
BEGIN NOW And stick the sides with boughs of baleful yew. END
BEGIN NOW The topmost part his glitt'ring arms adorn; END
BEGIN NOW Warm waters, then, in brazen caldrons borne, END
BEGIN NOW Are pour'd to wash his body, joint by joint, END
BEGIN NOW And fragrant oils the stiffen'd limbs anoint. END
BEGIN NOW With groans and cries Misenus they deplore: END
BEGIN NOW Then on a bier, with purple cover'd o'er, END
BEGIN NOW The breathless body, thus bewail'd, they lay, END
BEGIN NOW And fire the pile, their faces turn'd away- END
BEGIN NOW Such reverend rites their fathers us'd to pay. END
BEGIN NOW Pure oil and incense on the fire they throw, END
BEGIN NOW And fat of victims, which his friends bestow. END
BEGIN NOW These gifts the greedy flames to dust devour; END
BEGIN NOW Then on the living coals red wine they pour; END
BEGIN NOW And, last, the relics by themselves dispose, END
BEGIN NOW Which in a brazen urn the priests inclose. END
BEGIN NOW Old Corynaeus compass'd thrice the crew, END
BEGIN NOW And dipp'd an olive branch in holy dew; END
BEGIN NOW Which thrice he sprinkled round, and thrice aloud END
BEGIN NOW Invok'd the dead, and then dismissed the crowd. END
BEGIN NOW But good Aeneas order'd on the shore END
BEGIN NOW A stately tomb, whose top a trumpet bore, END
BEGIN NOW A soldier's fauchion, and a seaman's oar. END
BEGIN NOW Thus was his friend interr'd; and deathless fame END
BEGIN NOW Still to the lofty cape consigns his name. END
BEGIN NOW These rites perform'd, the prince, without delay, END
BEGIN NOW Hastes to the nether world his destin'd way. END
BEGIN NOW Deep was the cave; and, downward as it went END
BEGIN NOW From the wide mouth, a rocky rough descent; END
BEGIN NOW And here th' access a gloomy grove defends, END
BEGIN NOW And there th' unnavigable lake extends, END
BEGIN NOW O'er whose unhappy waters, void of light, END
BEGIN NOW No bird presumes to steer his airy flight; END
BEGIN NOW Such deadly stenches from the depths arise, END
BEGIN NOW And steaming sulphur, that infects the skies. END
BEGIN NOW From hence the Grecian bards their legends make, END
BEGIN NOW And give the name Avernus to the lake. END
BEGIN NOW Four sable bullocks, in the yoke untaught, END
BEGIN NOW For sacrifice the pious hero brought. END
BEGIN NOW The priestess pours the wine betwixt their horns; END
BEGIN NOW Then cuts the curling hair; that first oblation burns, END
BEGIN NOW Invoking Hecate hither to repair: END
BEGIN NOW A pow'rful name in hell and upper air. END
BEGIN NOW The sacred priests with ready knives bereave END
BEGIN NOW The beasts of life, and in full bowls receive END
BEGIN NOW The streaming blood: a lamb to Hell and Night END
BEGIN NOW (The sable wool without a streak of white) END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas offers; and, by fate's decree, END
BEGIN NOW A barren heifer, Proserpine, to thee, END
BEGIN NOW With holocausts he Pluto's altar fills; END
BEGIN NOW Sev'n brawny bulls with his own hand he kills; END
BEGIN NOW Then on the broiling entrails oil he pours; END
BEGIN NOW Which, ointed thus, the raging flame devours. END
BEGIN NOW Late the nocturnal sacrifice begun, END
BEGIN NOW Nor ended till the next returning sun. END
BEGIN NOW Then earth began to bellow, trees to dance, END
BEGIN NOW And howling dogs in glimm'ring light advance, END
BEGIN NOW Ere Hecate came. "Far hence be souls profane! END
BEGIN NOW The Sibyl cried, "and from the grove abstain! END
BEGIN NOW Now, Trojan, take the way thy fates afford; END
BEGIN NOW Assume thy courage, and unsheathe thy sword. END
BEGIN NOW She said, and pass'd along the gloomy space; END
BEGIN NOW The prince pursued her steps with equal pace. END
BEGIN NOW Ye realms, yet unreveal'd to human sight, END
BEGIN NOW Ye gods who rule the regions of the night, END
BEGIN NOW Ye gliding ghosts, permit me to relate END
BEGIN NOW The mystic wonders of your silent state! END
BEGIN NOW Obscure they went thro' dreary shades, that led END
BEGIN NOW Along the waste dominions of the dead. END
BEGIN NOW Thus wander travelers in woods by night, END
BEGIN NOW By the moon's doubtful and malignant light, END
BEGIN NOW When Jove in dusky clouds involves the skies, END
BEGIN NOW And the faint crescent shoots by fits before their eyes. END
BEGIN NOW Just in the gate and in the jaws of hell, END
BEGIN NOW Revengeful Cares and sullen Sorrows dwell, END
BEGIN NOW And pale Diseases, and repining Age, END
BEGIN NOW Want, Fear, and Famine's unresisted rage; END
BEGIN NOW Here Toils, and Death, and Death's half-brother, Sleep, END
BEGIN NOW Forms terrible to view, their sentry keep; END
BEGIN NOW With anxious Pleasures of a guilty mind, END
BEGIN NOW Deep Frauds before, and open Force behind; END
BEGIN NOW The Furies' iron beds; and Strife, that shakes END
BEGIN NOW Her hissing tresses and unfolds her snakes. END
BEGIN NOW Full in the midst of this infernal road, END
BEGIN NOW An elm displays her dusky arms abroad: END
BEGIN NOW The God of Sleep there hides his heavy head, END
BEGIN NOW And empty dreams on ev'ry leaf are spread. END
BEGIN NOW Of various forms unnumber'd specters more, END
BEGIN NOW Centaurs, and double shapes, besiege the door. END
BEGIN NOW Before the passage, horrid Hydra stands, END
BEGIN NOW And Briareus with all his hundred hands; END
BEGIN NOW Gorgons, Geryon with his triple frame; END
BEGIN NOW And vain Chimaera vomits empty flame. END
BEGIN NOW The chief unsheath'd his shining steel, prepar'd, END
BEGIN NOW Tho' seiz'd with sudden fear, to force the guard, END
BEGIN NOW Off'ring his brandish'd weapon at their face; END
BEGIN NOW Had not the Sibyl stopp'd his eager pace, END
BEGIN NOW And told him what those empty phantoms were: END
BEGIN NOW Forms without bodies, and impassive air. END
BEGIN NOW Hence to deep Acheron they take their way, END
BEGIN NOW Whose troubled eddies, thick with ooze and clay, END
BEGIN NOW Are whirl'd aloft, and in Cocytus lost. END
BEGIN NOW There Charon stands, who rules the dreary coast- END
BEGIN NOW A sordid god: down from his hoary chin END
BEGIN NOW A length of beard descends, uncomb'd, unclean; END
BEGIN NOW His eyes, like hollow furnaces on fire; END
BEGIN NOW A girdle, foul with grease, binds his obscene attire. END
BEGIN NOW He spreads his canvas; with his pole he steers; END
BEGIN NOW The freights of flitting ghosts in his thin bottom bears. END
BEGIN NOW He look'd in years; yet in his years were seen END
BEGIN NOW A youthful vigor and autumnal green. END
BEGIN NOW An airy crowd came rushing where he stood, END
BEGIN NOW Which fill'd the margin of the fatal flood: END
BEGIN NOW Husbands and wives, boys and unmarried maids, END
BEGIN NOW And mighty heroes' more majestic shades, END
BEGIN NOW And youths, intomb'd before their fathers' eyes, END
BEGIN NOW With hollow groans, and shrieks, and feeble cries. END
BEGIN NOW Thick as the leaves in autumn strow the woods, END
BEGIN NOW Or fowls, by winter forc'd, forsake the floods, END
BEGIN NOW And wing their hasty flight to happier lands; END
BEGIN NOW Such, and so thick, the shiv'ring army stands, END
BEGIN NOW And press for passage with extended hands. END
BEGIN NOW Now these, now those, the surly boatman bore: END
BEGIN NOW The rest he drove to distance from the shore. END
BEGIN NOW The hero, who beheld with wond'ring eyes END
BEGIN NOW The tumult mix'd with shrieks, laments, and cries, END
BEGIN NOW Ask'd of his guide, what the rude concourse meant; END
BEGIN NOW Why to the shore the thronging people bent; END
BEGIN NOW What forms of law among the ghosts were us'd; END
BEGIN NOW Why some were ferried o'er, and some refus'd. END
BEGIN NOW Son of Anchises, offspring of the gods, END
BEGIN NOW The Sibyl said, "you see the Stygian floods, END
BEGIN NOW The sacred stream which heav'n's imperial state END
BEGIN NOW Attests in oaths, and fears to violate. END
BEGIN NOW The ghosts rejected are th' unhappy crew END
BEGIN NOW Depriv'd of sepulchers and fun'ral due: END
BEGIN NOW The boatman, Charon; those, the buried host, END
BEGIN NOW He ferries over to the farther coast; END
BEGIN NOW Nor dares his transport vessel cross the waves END
BEGIN NOW With such whose bones are not compos'd in graves. END
BEGIN NOW A hundred years they wander on the shore; END
BEGIN NOW At length, their penance done, are wafted o'er. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan chief his forward pace repress'd, END
BEGIN NOW Revolving anxious thoughts within his breast, END
BEGIN NOW He saw his friends, who, whelm'd beneath the waves, END
BEGIN NOW Their fun'ral honors claim'd, and ask'd their quiet graves. END
BEGIN NOW The lost Leucaspis in the crowd he knew, END
BEGIN NOW And the brave leader of the Lycian crew, END
BEGIN NOW Whom, on the Tyrrhene seas, the tempests met; END
BEGIN NOW The sailors master'd, and the ship o'erset. END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the spirits, Palinurus press'd, END
BEGIN NOW Yet fresh from life, a new-admitted guest, END
BEGIN NOW Who, while he steering view'd the stars, and bore END
BEGIN NOW His course from Afric to the Latian shore, END
BEGIN NOW Fell headlong down. The Trojan fix'd his view, END
BEGIN NOW And scarcely thro' the gloom the sullen shadow knew. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus the prince: "What envious pow'r, O friend, END
BEGIN NOW Brought your lov'd life to this disastrous end? END
BEGIN NOW For Phoebus, ever true in all he said, END
BEGIN NOW Has in your fate alone my faith betray'd. END
BEGIN NOW The god foretold you should not die, before END
BEGIN NOW You reach'd, secure from seas, th' Italian shore. END
BEGIN NOW Is this th' unerring pow'r?" The ghost replied; END
BEGIN NOW Nor Phoebus flatter'd, nor his answers lied; END
BEGIN NOW Nor envious gods have sent me to the deep: END
BEGIN NOW But, while the stars and course of heav'n I keep, END
BEGIN NOW My wearied eyes were seiz'd with fatal sleep. END
BEGIN NOW I fell; and, with my weight, the helm constrain'd END
BEGIN NOW Was drawn along, which yet my gripe retain'd. END
BEGIN NOW Now by the winds and raging waves I swear, END
BEGIN NOW Your safety, more than mine, was then my care; END
BEGIN NOW Lest, of the guide bereft, the rudder lost, END
BEGIN NOW Your ship should run against the rocky coast. END
BEGIN NOW Three blust'ring nights, borne by the southern blast, END
BEGIN NOW I floated, and discover'd land at last: END
BEGIN NOW High on a mounting wave my head I bore, END
BEGIN NOW Forcing my strength, and gath'ring to the shore. END
BEGIN NOW Panting, but past the danger, now I seiz'd END
BEGIN NOW The craggy cliffs, and my tir'd members eas'd. END
BEGIN NOW While, cumber'd with my dropping clothes, I lay, END
BEGIN NOW The cruel nation, covetous of prey, END
BEGIN NOW Stain'd with my blood th' unhospitable coast; END
BEGIN NOW And now, by winds and waves, my lifeless limbs are toss'd: END
BEGIN NOW Which O avert, by yon ethereal light, END
BEGIN NOW Which I have lost for this eternal night! END
BEGIN NOW Or, if by dearer ties you may be won, END
BEGIN NOW By your dead sire, and by your living son, END
BEGIN NOW Redeem from this reproach my wand'ring ghost; END
BEGIN NOW Or with your navy seek the Velin coast, END
BEGIN NOW And in a peaceful grave my corpse compose; END
BEGIN NOW Or, if a nearer way your mother shows, END
BEGIN NOW Without whose aid you durst not undertake END
BEGIN NOW This frightful passage o'er the Stygian lake, END
BEGIN NOW Lend to this wretch your hand, and waft him o'er END
BEGIN NOW To the sweet banks of yon forbidden shore. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had he said, the prophetess began: END
BEGIN NOW What hopes delude thee, miserable man? END
BEGIN NOW Think'st thou, thus unintomb'd, to cross the floods, END
BEGIN NOW To view the Furies and infernal gods, END
BEGIN NOW And visit, without leave, the dark abodes? END
BEGIN NOW Attend the term of long revolving years; END
BEGIN NOW Fate, and the dooming gods, are deaf to tears. END
BEGIN NOW This comfort of thy dire misfortune take: END
BEGIN NOW The wrath of Heav'n, inflicted for thy sake, END
BEGIN NOW With vengeance shall pursue th' inhuman coast, END
BEGIN NOW Till they propitiate thy offended ghost, END
BEGIN NOW And raise a tomb, with vows and solemn pray'r; END
BEGIN NOW And Palinurus' name the place shall bear. END
BEGIN NOW This calm'd his cares; sooth'd with his future fame, END
BEGIN NOW And pleas'd to hear his propagated name. END
BEGIN NOW Now nearer to the Stygian lake they draw: END
BEGIN NOW Whom, from the shore, the surly boatman saw; END
BEGIN NOW Observ'd their passage thro' the shady wood, END
BEGIN NOW And mark'd their near approaches to the flood. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus he call'd aloud, inflam'd with wrath: END
BEGIN NOW Mortal, whate'er, who this forbidden path END
BEGIN NOW In arms presum'st to tread, I charge thee, stand, END
BEGIN NOW And tell thy name, and bus'ness in the land. END
BEGIN NOW Know this, the realm of night- the Stygian shore: END
BEGIN NOW My boat conveys no living bodies o'er; END
BEGIN NOW Nor was I pleas'd great Theseus once to bear, END
BEGIN NOW Who forc'd a passage with his pointed spear, END
BEGIN NOW Nor strong Alcides- men of mighty fame, END
BEGIN NOW And from th' immortal gods their lineage came. END
BEGIN NOW In fetters one the barking porter tied, END
BEGIN NOW And took him trembling from his sov'reign's side: END
BEGIN NOW Two sought by force to seize his beauteous bride. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the Sibyl thus: "Compose thy mind; END
BEGIN NOW Nor frauds are here contriv'd, nor force design'd. END
BEGIN NOW Still may the dog the wand'ring troops constrain END
BEGIN NOW Of airy ghosts, and vex the guilty train, END
BEGIN NOW And with her grisly lord his lovely queen remain. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan chief, whose lineage is from Jove, END
BEGIN NOW Much fam'd for arms, and more for filial love, END
BEGIN NOW Is sent to seek his sire in your Elysian grove. END
BEGIN NOW If neither piety, nor Heav'n's command, END
BEGIN NOW Can gain his passage to the Stygian strand, END
BEGIN NOW This fatal present shall prevail at least. END
BEGIN NOW Then shew'd the shining bough, conceal'd within her vest. END
BEGIN NOW No more was needful: for the gloomy god END
BEGIN NOW Stood mute with awe, to see the golden rod; END
BEGIN NOW Admir'd the destin'd off'ring to his queen- END
BEGIN NOW A venerable gift, so rarely seen. END
BEGIN NOW His fury thus appeas'd, he puts to land; END
BEGIN NOW The ghosts forsake their seats at his command: END
BEGIN NOW He clears the deck, receives the mighty freight; END
BEGIN NOW The leaky vessel groans beneath the weight. END
BEGIN NOW Slowly she sails, and scarcely stems the tides; END
BEGIN NOW The pressing water pours within her sides. END
BEGIN NOW His passengers at length are wafted o'er, END
BEGIN NOW Expos'd, in muddy weeds, upon the miry shore. END
BEGIN NOW No sooner landed, in his den they found END
BEGIN NOW The triple porter of the Stygian sound, END
BEGIN NOW Grim Cerberus, who soon began to rear END
BEGIN NOW His crested snakes, and arm'd his bristling hair. END
BEGIN NOW The prudent Sibyl had before prepar'd END
BEGIN NOW A sop, in honey steep'd, to charm the guard; END
BEGIN NOW Which, mix'd with pow'rful drugs, she cast before END
BEGIN NOW His greedy grinning jaws, just op'd to roar. END
BEGIN NOW With three enormous mouths he gapes; and straight, END
BEGIN NOW With hunger press'd, devours the pleasing bait. END
BEGIN NOW Long draughts of sleep his monstrous limbs enslave; END
BEGIN NOW He reels, and, falling, fills the spacious cave. END
BEGIN NOW The keeper charm'd, the chief without delay END
BEGIN NOW Pass'd on, and took th' irremeable way. END
BEGIN NOW Before the gates, the cries of babes new born, END
BEGIN NOW Whom fate had from their tender mothers torn, END
BEGIN NOW Assault his ears: then those, whom form of laws END
BEGIN NOW Condemn'd to die, when traitors judg'd their cause. END
BEGIN NOW Nor want they lots, nor judges to review END
BEGIN NOW The wrongful sentence, and award a new. END
BEGIN NOW Minos, the strict inquisitor, appears; END
BEGIN NOW And lives and crimes, with his assessors, hears. END
BEGIN NOW Round in his urn the blended balls he rolls, END
BEGIN NOW Absolves the just, and dooms the guilty souls. END
BEGIN NOW The next, in place and punishment, are they END
BEGIN NOW Who prodigally throw their souls away; END
BEGIN NOW Fools, who, repining at their wretched state, END
BEGIN NOW And loathing anxious life, suborn'd their fate. END
BEGIN NOW With late repentance now they would retrieve END
BEGIN NOW The bodies they forsook, and wish to live; END
BEGIN NOW Their pains and poverty desire to bear, END
BEGIN NOW To view the light of heav'n, and breathe the vital air: END
BEGIN NOW But fate forbids; the Stygian floods oppose, END
BEGIN NOW And with circling streams the captive souls inclose. END
BEGIN NOW Not far from thence, the Mournful Fields appear END
BEGIN NOW So call'd from lovers that inhabit there. END
BEGIN NOW The souls whom that unhappy flame invades, END
BEGIN NOW In secret solitude and myrtle shades END
BEGIN NOW Make endless moans, and, pining with desire, END
BEGIN NOW Lament too late their unextinguish'd fire. END
BEGIN NOW Here Procris, Eriphyle here he found, END
BEGIN NOW Baring her breast, yet bleeding with the wound END
BEGIN NOW Made by her son. He saw Pasiphae there, END
BEGIN NOW With Phaedra's ghost, a foul incestuous pair. END
BEGIN NOW There Laodamia, with Evadne, moves, END
BEGIN NOW Unhappy both, but loyal in their loves: END
BEGIN NOW Caeneus, a woman once, and once a man, END
BEGIN NOW But ending in the sex she first began. END
BEGIN NOW Not far from these Phoenician Dido stood, END
BEGIN NOW Fresh from her wound, her bosom bath'd in blood; END
BEGIN NOW Whom when the Trojan hero hardly knew, END
BEGIN NOW Obscure in shades, and with a doubtful view, END
BEGIN NOW (Doubtful as he who sees, thro' dusky night, END
BEGIN NOW Or thinks he sees, the moon's uncertain light,) END
BEGIN NOW With tears he first approach'd the sullen shade; END
BEGIN NOW And, as his love inspir'd him, thus he said: END
BEGIN NOW Unhappy queen! then is the common breath END
BEGIN NOW Of rumor true, in your reported death, END
BEGIN NOW And I, alas! the cause? By Heav'n, I vow, END
BEGIN NOW And all the pow'rs that rule the realms below, END
BEGIN NOW Unwilling I forsook your friendly state, END
BEGIN NOW Commanded by the gods, and forc'd by fate- END
BEGIN NOW Those gods, that fate, whose unresisted might END
BEGIN NOW Have sent me to these regions void of light, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' the vast empire of eternal night. END
BEGIN NOW Nor dar'd I to presume, that, press'd with grief, END
BEGIN NOW My flight should urge you to this dire relief. END
BEGIN NOW Stay, stay your steps, and listen to my vows: END
BEGIN NOW 'T is the last interview that fate allows! END
BEGIN NOW In vain he thus attempts her mind to move END
BEGIN NOW With tears, and pray'rs, and late-repenting love. END
BEGIN NOW Disdainfully she look'd; then turning round, END
BEGIN NOW But fix'd her eyes unmov'd upon the ground, END
BEGIN NOW And what he says and swears, regards no more END
BEGIN NOW Than the deaf rocks, when the loud billows roar; END
BEGIN NOW But whirl'd away, to shun his hateful sight, END
BEGIN NOW Hid in the forest and the shades of night; END
BEGIN NOW Then sought Sichaeus thro' the shady grove, END
BEGIN NOW Who answer'd all her cares, and equal'd all her love. END
BEGIN NOW Some pious tears the pitying hero paid, END
BEGIN NOW And follow'd with his eyes the flitting shade, END
BEGIN NOW Then took the forward way, by fate ordain'd, END
BEGIN NOW And, with his guide, the farther fields attain'd, END
BEGIN NOW Where, sever'd from the rest, the warrior souls remain'd. END
BEGIN NOW Tydeus he met, with Meleager's race, END
BEGIN NOW The pride of armies, and the soldiers' grace; END
BEGIN NOW And pale Adrastus with his ghastly face. END
BEGIN NOW Of Trojan chiefs he view'd a num'rous train, END
BEGIN NOW All much lamented, all in battle slain; END
BEGIN NOW Glaucus and Medon, high above the rest, END
BEGIN NOW Antenor's sons, and Ceres' sacred priest. END
BEGIN NOW And proud Idaeus, Priam's charioteer, END
BEGIN NOW Who shakes his empty reins, and aims his airy spear. END
BEGIN NOW The gladsome ghosts, in circling troops, attend END
BEGIN NOW And with unwearied eyes behold their friend; END
BEGIN NOW Delight to hover near, and long to know END
BEGIN NOW What bus'ness brought him to the realms below. END
BEGIN NOW But Argive chiefs, and Agamemnon's train, END
BEGIN NOW When his refulgent arms flash'd thro' the shady plain, END
BEGIN NOW Fled from his well-known face, with wonted fear, END
BEGIN NOW As when his thund'ring sword and pointed spear END
BEGIN NOW Drove headlong to their ships, and glean'd the routed rear. END
BEGIN NOW They rais'd a feeble cry, with trembling notes; END
BEGIN NOW But the weak voice deceiv'd their gasping throats. END
BEGIN NOW Here Priam's son, Deiphobus, he found, END
BEGIN NOW Whose face and limbs were one continued wound: END
BEGIN NOW Dishonest, with lopp'd arms, the youth appears, END
BEGIN NOW Spoil'd of his nose, and shorten'd of his ears. END
BEGIN NOW He scarcely knew him, striving to disown END
BEGIN NOW His blotted form, and blushing to be known; END
BEGIN NOW And therefore first began: "O Tsucer's race, END
BEGIN NOW Who durst thy faultless figure thus deface? END
BEGIN NOW What heart could wish, what hand inflict, this dire disgrace? END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas fam'd, that in our last and fatal night END
BEGIN NOW Your single prowess long sustain'd the fight, END
BEGIN NOW Till tir'd, not forc'd, a glorious fate you chose, END
BEGIN NOW And fell upon a heap of slaughter'd foes. END
BEGIN NOW But, in remembrance of so brave a deed, END
BEGIN NOW A tomb and fun'ral honors I decreed; END
BEGIN NOW Thrice call'd your manes on the Trojan plains: END
BEGIN NOW The place your armor and your name retains. END
BEGIN NOW Your body too I sought, and, had I found, END
BEGIN NOW Design'd for burial in your native ground. END
BEGIN NOW The ghost replied: "Your piety has paid END
BEGIN NOW All needful rites, to rest my wand'ring shade; END
BEGIN NOW But cruel fate, and my more cruel wife, END
BEGIN NOW To Grecian swords betray'd my sleeping life. END
BEGIN NOW These are the monuments of Helen's love: END
BEGIN NOW The shame I bear below, the marks I bore above. END
BEGIN NOW You know in what deluding joys we pass'd END
BEGIN NOW The night that was by Heav'n decreed our last: END
BEGIN NOW For, when the fatal horse, descending down, END
BEGIN NOW Pregnant with arms, o'erwhelm'd th' unhappy town END
BEGIN NOW She feign'd nocturnal orgies; left my bed, END
BEGIN NOW And, mix'd with Trojan dames, the dances led END
BEGIN NOW Then, waving high her torch, the signal made, END
BEGIN NOW Which rous'd the Grecians from their ambuscade. END
BEGIN NOW With watching overworn, with cares oppress'd, END
BEGIN NOW Unhappy I had laid me down to rest, END
BEGIN NOW And heavy sleep my weary limbs possess'd. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime my worthy wife our arms mislaid, END
BEGIN NOW And from beneath my head my sword convey'd; END
BEGIN NOW The door unlatch'd, and, with repeated calls, END
BEGIN NOW Invites her former lord within my walls. END
BEGIN NOW Thus in her crime her confidence she plac'd, END
BEGIN NOW And with new treasons would redeem the past. END
BEGIN NOW What need I more? Into the room they ran, END
BEGIN NOW And meanly murther'd a defenseless man. END
BEGIN NOW Ulysses, basely born, first led the way. END
BEGIN NOW Avenging pow'rs! with justice if I pray, END
BEGIN NOW That fortune be their own another day! END
BEGIN NOW But answer you; and in your turn relate, END
BEGIN NOW What brought you, living, to the Stygian state: END
BEGIN NOW Driv'n by the winds and errors of the sea, END
BEGIN NOW Or did you Heav'n's superior doom obey? END
BEGIN NOW Or tell what other chance conducts your way, END
BEGIN NOW To view with mortal eyes our dark retreats, END
BEGIN NOW Tumults and torments of th' infernal seats. END
BEGIN NOW While thus in talk the flying hours they pass, END
BEGIN NOW The sun had finish'd more than half his race: END
BEGIN NOW And they, perhaps, in words and tears had spent END
BEGIN NOW The little time of stay which Heav'n had lent; END
BEGIN NOW But thus the Sibyl chides their long delay: END
BEGIN NOW Night rushes down, and headlong drives the day: END
BEGIN NOW 'T is here, in different paths, the way divides; END
BEGIN NOW The right to Pluto's golden palace guides; END
BEGIN NOW The left to that unhappy region tends, END
BEGIN NOW Which to the depth of Tartarus descends; END
BEGIN NOW The seat of night profound, and punish'd fiends. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus Deiphobus: "O sacred maid, END
BEGIN NOW Forbear to chide, and be your will obey'd! END
BEGIN NOW Lo! to the secret shadows I retire, END
BEGIN NOW To pay my penance till my years expire. END
BEGIN NOW Proceed, auspicious prince, with glory crown'd, END
BEGIN NOW And born to better fates than I have found. END
BEGIN NOW He said; and, while he said, his steps he turn'd END
BEGIN NOW To secret shadows, and in silence mourn'd. END
BEGIN NOW The hero, looking on the left, espied END
BEGIN NOW A lofty tow'r, and strong on ev'ry side END
BEGIN NOW With treble walls, which Phlegethon surrounds, END
BEGIN NOW Whose fiery flood the burning empire bounds; END
BEGIN NOW And, press'd betwixt the rocks, the bellowing noise resounds END
BEGIN NOW Wide is the fronting gate, and, rais'd on high END
BEGIN NOW With adamantine columns, threats the sky. END
BEGIN NOW Vain is the force of man, and Heav'n's as vain, END
BEGIN NOW To crush the pillars which the pile sustain. END
BEGIN NOW Sublime on these a tow'r of steel is rear'd; END
BEGIN NOW And dire Tisiphone there keeps the ward, END
BEGIN NOW Girt in her sanguine gown, by night and day, END
BEGIN NOW Observant of the souls that pass the downward way. END
BEGIN NOW From hence are heard the groans of ghosts, the pains END
BEGIN NOW Of sounding lashes and of dragging chains. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan stood astonish'd at their cries, END
BEGIN NOW And ask'd his guide from whence those yells arise; END
BEGIN NOW And what the crimes, and what the tortures were, END
BEGIN NOW And loud laments that rent the liquid air. END
BEGIN NOW She thus replied: "The chaste and holy race END
BEGIN NOW Are all forbidden this polluted place. END
BEGIN NOW But Hecate, when she gave to rule the woods, END
BEGIN NOW Then led me trembling thro' these dire abodes, END
BEGIN NOW And taught the tortures of th' avenging gods. END
BEGIN NOW These are the realms of unrelenting fate; END
BEGIN NOW And awful Rhadamanthus rules the state. END
BEGIN NOW He hears and judges each committed crime; END
BEGIN NOW Enquires into the manner, place, and time. END
BEGIN NOW The conscious wretch must all his acts reveal, END
BEGIN NOW (Loth to confess, unable to conceal), END
BEGIN NOW From the first moment of his vital breath, END
BEGIN NOW To his last hour of unrepenting death. END
BEGIN NOW Straight, o'er the guilty ghost, the Fury shakes END
BEGIN NOW The sounding whip and brandishes her snakes, END
BEGIN NOW And the pale sinner, with her sisters, takes. END
BEGIN NOW Then, of itself, unfolds th' eternal door; END
BEGIN NOW With dreadful sounds the brazen hinges roar. END
BEGIN NOW You see, before the gate, what stalking ghost END
BEGIN NOW Commands the guard, what sentries keep the post. END
BEGIN NOW More formidable Hydra stands within, END
BEGIN NOW Whose jaws with iron teeth severely grin. END
BEGIN NOW The gaping gulf low to the center lies, END
BEGIN NOW And twice as deep as earth is distant from the skies. END
BEGIN NOW The rivals of the gods, the Titan race, END
BEGIN NOW Here, sing'd with lightning, roll within th' unfathom'd space. END
BEGIN NOW Here lie th' Alaean twins, (I saw them both,) END
BEGIN NOW Enormous bodies, of gigantic growth, END
BEGIN NOW Who dar'd in fight the Thund'rer to defy, END
BEGIN NOW Affect his heav'n, and force him from the sky. END
BEGIN NOW Salmoneus, suff'ring cruel pains, I found, END
BEGIN NOW For emulating Jove; the rattling sound END
BEGIN NOW Of mimic thunder, and the glitt'ring blaze END
BEGIN NOW Of pointed lightnings, and their forky rays. END
BEGIN NOW Thro' Elis and the Grecian towns he flew; END
BEGIN NOW Th' audacious wretch four fiery coursers drew: END
BEGIN NOW He wav'd a torch aloft, and, madly vain, END
BEGIN NOW Sought godlike worship from a servile train. END
BEGIN NOW Ambitious fool! with horny hoofs to pass END
BEGIN NOW O'er hollow arches of resounding brass, END
BEGIN NOW To rival thunder in its rapid course, END
BEGIN NOW And imitate inimitable force! END
BEGIN NOW But he, the King of Heav'n, obscure on high, END
BEGIN NOW Bar'd his red arm, and, launching from the sky END
BEGIN NOW His writhen bolt, not shaking empty smoke, END
BEGIN NOW Down to the deep abyss the flaming felon strook. END
BEGIN NOW There Tityus was to see, who took his birth END
BEGIN NOW From heav'n, his nursing from the foodful earth. END
BEGIN NOW Here his gigantic limbs, with large embrace, END
BEGIN NOW Infold nine acres of infernal space. END
BEGIN NOW A rav'nous vulture, in his open'd side, END
BEGIN NOW Her crooked beak and cruel talons tried; END
BEGIN NOW Still for the growing liver digg'd his breast; END
BEGIN NOW The growing liver still supplied the feast; END
BEGIN NOW Still are his entrails fruitful to their pains: END
BEGIN NOW Th' immortal hunger lasts, th' immortal food remains. END
BEGIN NOW Ixion and Perithous I could name, END
BEGIN NOW And more Thessalian chiefs of mighty fame. END
BEGIN NOW High o'er their heads a mold'ring rock is plac'd, END
BEGIN NOW That promises a fall, and shakes at ev'ry blast. END
BEGIN NOW They lie below, on golden beds display'd; END
BEGIN NOW And genial feasts with regal pomp are made. END
BEGIN NOW The Queen of Furies by their sides is set, END
BEGIN NOW And snatches from their mouths th' untasted meat, END
BEGIN NOW Which if they touch, her hissing snakes she rears, END
BEGIN NOW Tossing her torch, and thund'ring in their ears. END
BEGIN NOW Then they, who brothers' better claim disown, END
BEGIN NOW Expel their parents, and usurp the throne; END
BEGIN NOW Defraud their clients, and, to lucre sold, END
BEGIN NOW Sit brooding on unprofitable gold; END
BEGIN NOW Who dare not give, and ev'n refuse to lend END
BEGIN NOW To their poor kindred, or a wanting friend. END
BEGIN NOW Vast is the throng of these; nor less the train END
BEGIN NOW Of lustful youths, for foul adult'ry slain: END
BEGIN NOW Hosts of deserters, who their honor sold, END
BEGIN NOW And basely broke their faith for bribes of gold. END
BEGIN NOW All these within the dungeon's depth remain, END
BEGIN NOW Despairing pardon, and expecting pain. END
BEGIN NOW Ask not what pains; nor farther seek to know END
BEGIN NOW Their process, or the forms of law below. END
BEGIN NOW Some roll a weighty stone; some, laid along, END
BEGIN NOW And bound with burning wires, on spokes of wheels are hung END
BEGIN NOW Unhappy Theseus, doom'd for ever there, END
BEGIN NOW Is fix'd by fate on his eternal chair; END
BEGIN NOW And wretched Phlegyas warns the world with cries END
BEGIN NOW (Could warning make the world more just or wise): END
BEGIN NOW 'Learn righteousness, and dread th' avenging deities.' END
BEGIN NOW To tyrants others have their country sold, END
BEGIN NOW Imposing foreign lords, for foreign gold; END
BEGIN NOW Some have old laws repeal'd, new statutes made, END
BEGIN NOW Not as the people pleas'd, but as they paid; END
BEGIN NOW With incest some their daughters' bed profan'd: END
BEGIN NOW All dar'd the worst of ills, and, what they dar'd, attain'd. END
BEGIN NOW Had I a hundred mouths, a hundred tongues, END
BEGIN NOW And throats of brass, inspir'd with iron lungs, END
BEGIN NOW I could not half those horrid crimes repeat, END
BEGIN NOW Nor half the punishments those crimes have met. END
BEGIN NOW But let us haste our voyage to pursue: END
BEGIN NOW The walls of Pluto's palace are in view; END
BEGIN NOW The gate, and iron arch above it, stands END
BEGIN NOW On anvils labor'd by the Cyclops' hands. END
BEGIN NOW Before our farther way the Fates allow, END
BEGIN NOW Here must we fix on high the golden bough. END
BEGIN NOW She said: and thro' the gloomy shades they pass'd, END
BEGIN NOW And chose the middle path. Arriv'd at last, END
BEGIN NOW The prince with living water sprinkled o'er END
BEGIN NOW His limbs and body; then approach'd the door, END
BEGIN NOW Possess'd the porch, and on the front above END
BEGIN NOW He fix'd the fatal bough requir'd by Pluto's love. END
BEGIN NOW These holy rites perform'd, they took their way END
BEGIN NOW Where long extended plains of pleasure lay: END
BEGIN NOW The verdant fields with those of heav'n may vie, END
BEGIN NOW With ether vested, and a purple sky; END
BEGIN NOW The blissful seats of happy souls below. END
BEGIN NOW Stars of their own, and their own suns, they know; END
BEGIN NOW Their airy limbs in sports they exercise, END
BEGIN NOW And on the green contend the wrestler's prize. END
BEGIN NOW Some in heroic verse divinely sing; END
BEGIN NOW Others in artful measures led the ring. END
BEGIN NOW The Thracian bard, surrounded by the rest, END
BEGIN NOW There stands conspicuous in his flowing vest; END
BEGIN NOW His flying fingers, and harmonious quill, END
BEGIN NOW Strikes sev'n distinguish'd notes, and sev'n at once they fill. END
BEGIN NOW Here found they Tsucer's old heroic race, END
BEGIN NOW Born better times and happier years to grace. END
BEGIN NOW Assaracus and Ilus here enjoy END
BEGIN NOW Perpetual fame, with him who founded Troy. END
BEGIN NOW The chief beheld their chariots from afar, END
BEGIN NOW Their shining arms, and coursers train'd to war: END
BEGIN NOW Their lances fix'd in earth, their steeds around, END
BEGIN NOW Free from their harness, graze the flow'ry ground. END
BEGIN NOW The love of horses which they had, alive, END
BEGIN NOW And care of chariots, after death survive. END
BEGIN NOW Some cheerful souls were feasting on the plain; END
BEGIN NOW Some did the song, and some the choir maintain, END
BEGIN NOW Beneath a laurel shade, where mighty Po END
BEGIN NOW Mounts up to woods above, and hides his head below. END
BEGIN NOW Here patriots live, who, for their country's good, END
BEGIN NOW In fighting fields, were prodigal of blood: END
BEGIN NOW Priests of unblemish'd lives here make abode, END
BEGIN NOW And poets worthy their inspiring god; END
BEGIN NOW And searching wits, of more mechanic parts, END
BEGIN NOW Who grac'd their age with new-invented arts: END
BEGIN NOW Those who to worth their bounty did extend, END
BEGIN NOW And those who knew that bounty to commend. END
BEGIN NOW The heads of these with holy fillets bound, END
BEGIN NOW And all their temples were with garlands crown'd. END
BEGIN NOW To these the Sibyl thus her speech address'd, END
BEGIN NOW And first to him surrounded by the rest END
BEGIN NOW (Tow'ring his height, and ample was his breast): END
BEGIN NOW Say, happy souls, divine Musaeus, say, END
BEGIN NOW Where lives Anchises, and where lies our way END
BEGIN NOW To find the hero, for whose only sake END
BEGIN NOW We sought the dark abodes, and cross'd the bitter lake? END
BEGIN NOW To this the sacred poet thus replied: END
BEGIN NOW In no fix'd place the happy souls reside. END
BEGIN NOW In groves we live, and lie on mossy beds, END
BEGIN NOW By crystal streams, that murmur thro' the meads: END
BEGIN NOW But pass yon easy hill, and thence descend; END
BEGIN NOW The path conducts you to your journey's end. END
BEGIN NOW This said, he led them up the mountain's brow, END
BEGIN NOW And shews them all the shining fields below. END
BEGIN NOW They wind the hill, and thro' the blissful meadows go. END
BEGIN NOW But old Anchises, in a flow'ry vale, END
BEGIN NOW Review'd his muster'd race, and took the tale: END
BEGIN NOW Those happy spirits, which, ordain'd by fate, END
BEGIN NOW For future beings and new bodies wait- END
BEGIN NOW With studious thought observ'd th' illustrious throng, END
BEGIN NOW In nature's order as they pass'd along: END
BEGIN NOW Their names, their fates, their conduct, and their care, END
BEGIN NOW In peaceful senates and successful war. END
BEGIN NOW He, when Aeneas on the plain appears, END
BEGIN NOW Meets him with open arms, and falling tears. END
BEGIN NOW Welcome, he said, "the gods' undoubted race! END
BEGIN NOW O long expected to my dear embrace! END
BEGIN NOW Once more 't is giv'n me to behold your face! END
BEGIN NOW The love and pious duty which you pay END
BEGIN NOW Have pass'd the perils of so hard a way. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is true, computing times, I now believ'd END
BEGIN NOW The happy day approach'd; nor are my hopes deceiv'd. END
BEGIN NOW What length of lands, what oceans have you pass'd; END
BEGIN NOW What storms sustain'd, and on what shores been cast? END
BEGIN NOW How have I fear'd your fate! but fear'd it most, END
BEGIN NOW When love assail'd you, on the Libyan coast. END
BEGIN NOW To this, the filial duty thus replies: END
BEGIN NOW Your sacred ghost before my sleeping eyes END
BEGIN NOW Appear'd, and often urg'd this painful enterprise. END
BEGIN NOW After long tossing on the Tyrrhene sea, END
BEGIN NOW My navy rides at anchor in the bay. END
BEGIN NOW But reach your hand, O parent shade, nor shun END
BEGIN NOW The dear embraces of your longing son! END
BEGIN NOW He said; and falling tears his face bedew: END
BEGIN NOW Then thrice around his neck his arms he threw; END
BEGIN NOW And thrice the flitting shadow slipp'd away, END
BEGIN NOW Like winds, or empty dreams that fly the day. END
BEGIN NOW Now, in a secret vale, the Trojan sees END
BEGIN NOW A sep'rate grove, thro' which a gentle breeze END
BEGIN NOW Plays with a passing breath, and whispers thro' the trees; END
BEGIN NOW And, just before the confines of the wood, END
BEGIN NOW The gliding Lethe leads her silent flood. END
BEGIN NOW About the boughs an airy nation flew, END
BEGIN NOW Thick as the humming bees, that hunt the golden dew; END
BEGIN NOW In summer's heat on tops of lilies feed, END
BEGIN NOW And creep within their bells, to suck the balmy seed: END
BEGIN NOW The winged army roams the fields around; END
BEGIN NOW The rivers and the rocks remurmur to the sound. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas wond'ring stood, then ask'd the cause END
BEGIN NOW Which to the stream the crowding people draws. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus the sire: "The souls that throng the flood END
BEGIN NOW Are those to whom, by fate, are other bodies ow'd: END
BEGIN NOW In Lethe's lake they long oblivion taste, END
BEGIN NOW Of future life secure, forgetful of the past. END
BEGIN NOW Long has my soul desir'd this time and place, END
BEGIN NOW To set before your sight your glorious race, END
BEGIN NOW That this presaging joy may fire your mind END
BEGIN NOW To seek the shores by destiny design'd."- END
BEGIN NOW O father, can it be, that souls sublime END
BEGIN NOW Return to visit our terrestrial clime, END
BEGIN NOW And that the gen'rous mind, releas'd by death, END
BEGIN NOW Can covet lazy limbs and mortal breath? END
BEGIN NOW Anchises then, in order, thus begun END
BEGIN NOW To clear those wonders to his godlike son: END
BEGIN NOW Know, first, that heav'n, and earth's compacted frame, END
BEGIN NOW And flowing waters, and the starry flame, END
BEGIN NOW And both the radiant lights, one common soul END
BEGIN NOW Inspires and feeds, and animates the whole. END
BEGIN NOW This active mind, infus'd thro' all the space, END
BEGIN NOW Unites and mingles with the mighty mass. END
BEGIN NOW Hence men and beasts the breath of life obtain, END
BEGIN NOW And birds of air, and monsters of the main. END
BEGIN NOW Th' ethereal vigor is in all the same, END
BEGIN NOW And every soul is fill'd with equal flame; END
BEGIN NOW As much as earthy limbs, and gross allay END
BEGIN NOW Of mortal members, subject to decay, END
BEGIN NOW Blunt not the beams of heav'n and edge of day. END
BEGIN NOW From this coarse mixture of terrestrial parts, END
BEGIN NOW Desire and fear by turns possess their hearts, END
BEGIN NOW And grief, and joy; nor can the groveling mind, END
BEGIN NOW In the dark dungeon of the limbs confin'd, END
BEGIN NOW Assert the native skies, or own its heav'nly kind: END
BEGIN NOW Nor death itself can wholly wash their stains; END
BEGIN NOW But long-contracted filth ev'n in the soul remains. END
BEGIN NOW The relics of inveterate vice they wear, END
BEGIN NOW And spots of sin obscene in ev'ry face appear. END
BEGIN NOW For this are various penances enjoin'd; END
BEGIN NOW And some are hung to bleach upon the wind, END
BEGIN NOW Some plung'd in waters, others purg'd in fires, END
BEGIN NOW Till all the dregs are drain'd, and all the rust expires. END
BEGIN NOW All have their manes, and those manes bear: END
BEGIN NOW The few, so cleans'd, to these abodes repair, END
BEGIN NOW And breathe, in ample fields, the soft Elysian air. END
BEGIN NOW Then are they happy, when by length of time END
BEGIN NOW The scurf is worn away of each committed crime; END
BEGIN NOW No speck is left of their habitual stains, END
BEGIN NOW But the pure ether of the soul remains. END
BEGIN NOW But, when a thousand rolling years are past, END
BEGIN NOW (So long their punishments and penance last,) END
BEGIN NOW Whole droves of minds are, by the driving god, END
BEGIN NOW Compell'd to drink the deep Lethaean flood, END
BEGIN NOW In large forgetful draughts to steep the cares END
BEGIN NOW Of their past labors, and their irksome years, END
BEGIN NOW That, unrememb'ring of its former pain, END
BEGIN NOW The soul may suffer mortal flesh again. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, the father spirit leads END
BEGIN NOW The priestess and his son thro' swarms of shades, END
BEGIN NOW And takes a rising ground, from thence to see END
BEGIN NOW The long procession of his progeny. END
BEGIN NOW Survey, pursued the sire, "this airy throng, END
BEGIN NOW As, offer'd to thy view, they pass along. END
BEGIN NOW These are th' Italian names, which fate will join END
BEGIN NOW With ours, and graff upon the Trojan line. END
BEGIN NOW Observe the youth who first appears in sight, END
BEGIN NOW And holds the nearest station to the light, END
BEGIN NOW Already seems to snuff the vital air, END
BEGIN NOW And leans just forward, on a shining spear: END
BEGIN NOW Silvius is he, thy last-begotten race, END
BEGIN NOW But first in order sent, to fill thy place; END
BEGIN NOW An Alban name, but mix'd with Dardan blood, END
BEGIN NOW Born in the covert of a shady wood: END
BEGIN NOW Him fair Lavinia, thy surviving wife, END
BEGIN NOW Shall breed in groves, to lead a solitary life. END
BEGIN NOW In Alba he shall fix his royal seat, END
BEGIN NOW And, born a king, a race of kings beget. END
BEGIN NOW Then Procas, honor of the Trojan name, END
BEGIN NOW Capys, and Numitor, of endless fame. END
BEGIN NOW A second Silvius after these appears; END
BEGIN NOW Silvius Aeneas, for thy name he bears; END
BEGIN NOW For arms and justice equally renown'd, END
BEGIN NOW Who, late restor'd, in Alba shall be crown'd. END
BEGIN NOW How great they look! how vig'rously they wield END
BEGIN NOW Their weighty lances, and sustain the shield! END
BEGIN NOW But they, who crown'd with oaken wreaths appear, END
BEGIN NOW Shall Gabian walls and strong Fidena rear; END
BEGIN NOW Nomentum, Bola, with Pometia, found; END
BEGIN NOW And raise Collatian tow'rs on rocky ground. END
BEGIN NOW All these shall then be towns of mighty fame, END
BEGIN NOW Tho' now they lie obscure, and lands without a name. END
BEGIN NOW See Romulus the great, born to restore END
BEGIN NOW The crown that once his injur'd grandsire wore. END
BEGIN NOW This prince a priestess of your blood shall bear, END
BEGIN NOW And like his sire in arms he shall appear. END
BEGIN NOW Two rising crests, his royal head adorn; END
BEGIN NOW Born from a god, himself to godhead born: END
BEGIN NOW His sire already signs him for the skies, END
BEGIN NOW And marks the seat amidst the deities. END
BEGIN NOW Auspicious chief! thy race, in times to come, END
BEGIN NOW Shall spread the conquests of imperial Rome- END
BEGIN NOW Rome, whose ascending tow'rs shall heav'n invade, END
BEGIN NOW Involving earth and ocean in her shade; END
BEGIN NOW High as the Mother of the Gods in place, END
BEGIN NOW And proud, like her, of an immortal race. END
BEGIN NOW Then, when in pomp she makes the Phrygian round, END
BEGIN NOW With golden turrets on her temples crown'd; END
BEGIN NOW A hundred gods her sweeping train supply; END
BEGIN NOW Her offspring all, and all command the sky. END
BEGIN NOW Now fix your sight, and stand intent, to see END
BEGIN NOW Your Roman race, and Julian progeny. END
BEGIN NOW The mighty Caesar waits his vital hour, END
BEGIN NOW Impatient for the world, and grasps his promis'd pow'r. END
BEGIN NOW But next behold the youth of form divine, END
BEGIN NOW Ceasar himself, exalted in his line; END
BEGIN NOW Augustus, promis'd oft, and long foretold, END
BEGIN NOW Sent to the realm that Saturn rul'd of old; END
BEGIN NOW Born to restore a better age of gold. END
BEGIN NOW Afric and India shall his pow'r obey; END
BEGIN NOW He shall extend his propagated sway END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the solar year, without the starry way, END
BEGIN NOW Where Atlas turns the rolling heav'ns around, END
BEGIN NOW And his broad shoulders with their lights are crown'd. END
BEGIN NOW At his foreseen approach, already quake END
BEGIN NOW The Caspian kingdoms and Maeotian lake: END
BEGIN NOW Their seers behold the tempest from afar, END
BEGIN NOW And threat'ning oracles denounce the war. END
BEGIN NOW Nile hears him knocking at his sev'nfold gates, END
BEGIN NOW And seeks his hidden spring, and fears his nephew's fates. END
BEGIN NOW Nor Hercules more lands or labors knew, END
BEGIN NOW Not tho' the brazen-footed hind he slew, END
BEGIN NOW Freed Erymanthus from the foaming boar, END
BEGIN NOW And dipp'd his arrows in Lernaean gore; END
BEGIN NOW Nor Bacchus, turning from his Indian war, END
BEGIN NOW By tigers drawn triumphant in his car, END
BEGIN NOW From Nisus' top descending on the plains, END
BEGIN NOW With curling vines around his purple reins. END
BEGIN NOW And doubt we yet thro' dangers to pursue END
BEGIN NOW The paths of honor, and a crown in view? END
BEGIN NOW But what's the man, who from afar appears? END
BEGIN NOW His head with olive crown'd, his hand a censer bears, END
BEGIN NOW His hoary beard and holy vestments bring END
BEGIN NOW His lost idea back: I know the Roman king. END
BEGIN NOW He shall to peaceful Rome new laws ordain, END
BEGIN NOW Call'd from his mean abode a scepter to sustain. END
BEGIN NOW Him Tullus next in dignity succeeds, END
BEGIN NOW An active prince, and prone to martial deeds. END
BEGIN NOW He shall his troops for fighting fields prepare, END
BEGIN NOW Disus'd to toils, and triumphs of the war. END
BEGIN NOW By dint of sword his crown he shall increase, END
BEGIN NOW And scour his armor from the rust of peace. END
BEGIN NOW Whom Ancus follows, with a fawning air, END
BEGIN NOW But vain within, and proudly popular. END
BEGIN NOW Next view the Tarquin kings, th' avenging sword END
BEGIN NOW Of Brutus, justly drawn, and Rome restor'd. END
BEGIN NOW He first renews the rods and ax severe, END
BEGIN NOW And gives the consuls royal robes to wear. END
BEGIN NOW His sons, who seek the tyrant to sustain, END
BEGIN NOW And long for arbitrary lords again, END
BEGIN NOW With ignominy scourg'd, in open sight, END
BEGIN NOW He dooms to death deserv'd, asserting public right. END
BEGIN NOW Unhappy man, to break the pious laws END
BEGIN NOW Of nature, pleading in his children's cause! END
BEGIN NOW Howeer the doubtful fact is understood, END
BEGIN NOW 'T is love of honor, and his country's good: END
BEGIN NOW The consul, not the father, sheds the blood. END
BEGIN NOW Behold Torquatus the same track pursue; END
BEGIN NOW And, next, the two devoted Decii view: END
BEGIN NOW The Drusian line, Camillus loaded home END
BEGIN NOW With standards well redeem'd, and foreign foes o'ercome END
BEGIN NOW The pair you see in equal armor shine, END
BEGIN NOW Now, friends below, in close embraces join; END
BEGIN NOW But, when they leave the shady realms of night, END
BEGIN NOW And, cloth'd in bodies, breathe your upper light, END
BEGIN NOW With mortal hate each other shall pursue: END
BEGIN NOW What wars, what wounds, what slaughter shall ensue! END
BEGIN NOW From Alpine heights the father first descends; END
BEGIN NOW His daughter's husband in the plain attends: END
BEGIN NOW His daughter's husband arms his eastern friends. END
BEGIN NOW Embrace again, my sons, be foes no more; END
BEGIN NOW Nor stain your country with her children's gore! END
BEGIN NOW And thou, the first, lay down thy lawless claim, END
BEGIN NOW Thou, of my blood, who bearist the Julian name! END
BEGIN NOW Another comes, who shall in triumph ride, END
BEGIN NOW And to the Capitol his chariot guide, END
BEGIN NOW From conquer'd Corinth, rich with Grecian spoils. END
BEGIN NOW And yet another, fam'd for warlike toils, END
BEGIN NOW On Argos shall impose the Roman laws, END
BEGIN NOW And on the Greeks revenge the Trojan cause; END
BEGIN NOW Shall drag in chains their Achillean race; END
BEGIN NOW Shall vindicate his ancestors' disgrace, END
BEGIN NOW And Pallas, for her violated place. END
BEGIN NOW Great Cato there, for gravity renown'd, END
BEGIN NOW And conqu'ring Cossus goes with laurels crown'd. END
BEGIN NOW Who can omit the Gracchi? who declare END
BEGIN NOW The Scipios' worth, those thunderbolts of war, END
BEGIN NOW The double bane of Carthage? Who can see END
BEGIN NOW Without esteem for virtuous poverty, END
BEGIN NOW Severe Fabricius, or can cease t' admire END
BEGIN NOW The plowman consul in his coarse attire? END
BEGIN NOW Tir'd as I am, my praise the Fabii claim; END
BEGIN NOW And thou, great hero, greatest of thy name, END
BEGIN NOW Ordain'd in war to save the sinking state, END
BEGIN NOW And, by delays, to put a stop to fate! END
BEGIN NOW Let others better mold the running mass END
BEGIN NOW Of metals, and inform the breathing brass, END
BEGIN NOW And soften into flesh a marble face; END
BEGIN NOW Plead better at the bar; describe the skies, END
BEGIN NOW And when the stars descend, and when they rise. END
BEGIN NOW But, Rome, 't is thine alone, with awful sway, END
BEGIN NOW To rule mankind, and make the world obey, END
BEGIN NOW Disposing peace and war by thy own majestic way; END
BEGIN NOW To tame the proud, the fetter'd slave to free: END
BEGIN NOW These are imperial arts, and worthy thee. END
BEGIN NOW He paus'd; and, while with wond'ring eyes they view'd END
BEGIN NOW The passing spirits, thus his speech renew'd: END
BEGIN NOW See great Marcellus! how, untir'd in toils, END
BEGIN NOW He moves with manly grace, how rich with regal spoils! END
BEGIN NOW He, when his country, threaten'd with alarms, END
BEGIN NOW Requires his courage and his conqu'ring arms, END
BEGIN NOW Shall more than once the Punic bands affright; END
BEGIN NOW Shall kill the Gaulish king in single fight; END
BEGIN NOW Then to the Capitol in triumph move, END
BEGIN NOW And the third spoils shall grace Feretrian Jove. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas here beheld, of form divine, END
BEGIN NOW A godlike youth in glitt'ring armor shine, END
BEGIN NOW With great Marcellus keeping equal pace; END
BEGIN NOW But gloomy were his eyes, dejected was his face. END
BEGIN NOW He saw, and, wond'ring, ask'd his airy guide, END
BEGIN NOW What and of whence was he, who press'd the hero's side: END
BEGIN NOW His son, or one of his illustrious name? END
BEGIN NOW How like the former, and almost the same! END
BEGIN NOW Observe the crowds that compass him around; END
BEGIN NOW All gaze, and all admire, and raise a shouting sound: END
BEGIN NOW But hov'ring mists around his brows are spread, END
BEGIN NOW And night, with sable shades, involves his head. END
BEGIN NOW Seek not to know," the ghost replied with tears, END
BEGIN NOW The sorrows of thy sons in future years. END
BEGIN NOW This youth (the blissful vision of a day) END
BEGIN NOW Shall just be shown on earth, and snatch'd away. END
BEGIN NOW The gods too high had rais'd the Roman state, END
BEGIN NOW Were but their gifts as permanent as great. END
BEGIN NOW What groans of men shall fill the Martian field! END
BEGIN NOW How fierce a blaze his flaming pile shall yield! END
BEGIN NOW What fun'ral pomp shall floating Tiber see, END
BEGIN NOW When, rising from his bed, he views the sad solemnity! END
BEGIN NOW No youth shall equal hopes of glory give, END
BEGIN NOW No youth afford so great a cause to grieve; END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan honor, and the Roman boast, END
BEGIN NOW Admir'd when living, and ador'd when lost! END
BEGIN NOW Mirror of ancient faith in early youth! END
BEGIN NOW Undaunted worth, inviolable truth! END
BEGIN NOW No foe, unpunish'd, in the fighting field END
BEGIN NOW Shall dare thee, foot to foot, with sword and shield; END
BEGIN NOW Much less in arms oppose thy matchless force, END
BEGIN NOW When thy sharp spurs shall urge thy foaming horse. END
BEGIN NOW Ah! couldst thou break thro' fate's severe decree, END
BEGIN NOW A new Marcellus shall arise in thee! END
BEGIN NOW Full canisters of fragrant lilies bring, END
BEGIN NOW Mix'd with the purple roses of the spring; END
BEGIN NOW Let me with fun'ral flow'rs his body strow; END
BEGIN NOW This gift which parents to their children owe, END
BEGIN NOW This unavailing gift, at least, I may bestow! END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, he led the hero round END
BEGIN NOW The confines of the blest Elysian ground; END
BEGIN NOW Which when Anchises to his son had shown, END
BEGIN NOW And fir'd his mind to mount the promis'd throne, END
BEGIN NOW He tells the future wars, ordain'd by fate; END
BEGIN NOW The strength and customs of the Latian state; END
BEGIN NOW The prince, and people; and forearms his care END
BEGIN NOW With rules, to push his fortune, or to bear. END
BEGIN NOW Two gates the silent house of Sleep adorn; END
BEGIN NOW Of polish'd ivory this, that of transparent horn: END
BEGIN NOW True visions thro' transparent horn arise; END
BEGIN NOW Thro' polish'd ivory pass deluding lies. END
BEGIN NOW Of various things discoursing as he pass'd, END
BEGIN NOW Anchises hither bends his steps at last. END
BEGIN NOW Then, thro' the gate of iv'ry, he dismiss'd END
BEGIN NOW His valiant offspring and divining guest. END
BEGIN NOW Straight to the ships Aeneas his way, END
BEGIN NOW Embark'd his men, and skimm'd along the sea, END
BEGIN NOW Still coasting, till he gain'd Cajeta's bay. END
BEGIN NOW At length on oozy ground his galleys moor; END
BEGIN NOW Their heads are turn'd to sea, their sterns to shore. END
BEGIN NOW And thou, O matron of immortal fame, END
BEGIN NOW Here dying, to the shore hast left thy name; END
BEGIN NOW Cajeta still the place is call'd from thee, END
BEGIN NOW The nurse of great Aeneas' infancy. END
BEGIN NOW Here rest thy bones in rich Hesperia's plains; END
BEGIN NOW Thy name ('t is all a ghost can have) remains. END
BEGIN NOW Now, when the prince her fun'ral rites had paid, END
BEGIN NOW He plow'd the Tyrrhene seas with sails display'd. END
BEGIN NOW From land a gentle breeze arose by night, END
BEGIN NOW Serenely shone the stars, the moon was bright, END
BEGIN NOW And the sea trembled with her silver light. END
BEGIN NOW Now near the shelves of Circe's shores they run, END
BEGIN NOW (Circe the rich, the daughter of the Sun,) END
BEGIN NOW A dang'rous coast: the goddess wastes her days END
BEGIN NOW In joyous songs; the rocks resound her lays: END
BEGIN NOW In spinning, or the loom, she spends the night, END
BEGIN NOW And cedar brands supply her father's light. END
BEGIN NOW From hence were heard, rebellowing to the main, END
BEGIN NOW The roars of lions that refuse the chain, END
BEGIN NOW The grunts of bristled boars, and groans of bears, END
BEGIN NOW And herds of howling wolves that stun the sailors' ears. END
BEGIN NOW These from their caverns, at the close of night, END
BEGIN NOW Fill the sad isle with horror and affright. END
BEGIN NOW Darkling they mourn their fate, whom Circe's pow'r, END
BEGIN NOW (That watch'd the moon and planetary hour,) END
BEGIN NOW With words and wicked herbs from humankind END
BEGIN NOW Had alter'd, and in brutal shapes confin'd. END
BEGIN NOW Which monsters lest the Trojans' pious host END
BEGIN NOW Should bear, or touch upon th' inchanted coast, END
BEGIN NOW Propitious Neptune steer'd their course by night END
BEGIN NOW With rising gales that sped their happy flight. END
BEGIN NOW Supplied with these, they skim the sounding shore, END
BEGIN NOW And hear the swelling surges vainly roar. END
BEGIN NOW Now, when the rosy morn began to rise, END
BEGIN NOW And wav'd her saffron streamer thro' the skies; END
BEGIN NOW When Thetis blush'd in purple not her own, END
BEGIN NOW And from her face the breathing winds were blown, END
BEGIN NOW A sudden silence sate upon the sea, END
BEGIN NOW And sweeping oars, with struggling, urge their way. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan, from the main, beheld a wood, END
BEGIN NOW Which thick with shades and a brown horror stood: END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the trees the Tiber took his course, END
BEGIN NOW With whirlpools dimpled; and with downward force, END
BEGIN NOW That drove the sand along, he took his way, END
BEGIN NOW And roll'd his yellow billows to the sea. END
BEGIN NOW About him, and above, and round the wood, END
BEGIN NOW The birds that haunt the borders of his flood, END
BEGIN NOW That bath'd within, or basked upon his side, END
BEGIN NOW To tuneful songs their narrow throats applied. END
BEGIN NOW The captain gives command; the joyful train END
BEGIN NOW Glide thro' the gloomy shade, and leave the main. END
BEGIN NOW Now, Erato, thy poet's mind inspire, END
BEGIN NOW And fill his soul with thy celestial fire! END
BEGIN NOW Relate what Latium was; her ancient kings; END
BEGIN NOW Declare the past and state of things, END
BEGIN NOW When first the Trojan fleet Ausonia sought, END
BEGIN NOW And how the rivals lov'd, and how they fought. END
BEGIN NOW These are my theme, and how the war began, END
BEGIN NOW And how concluded by the godlike man: END
BEGIN NOW For I shall sing of battles, blood, and rage, END
BEGIN NOW Which princes and their people did engage; END
BEGIN NOW And haughty souls, that, mov'd with mutual hate, END
BEGIN NOW In fighting fields pursued and found their fate; END
BEGIN NOW That rous'd the Tyrrhene realm with loud alarms, END
BEGIN NOW And peaceful Italy involv'd in arms. END
BEGIN NOW A larger scene of action is display'd; END
BEGIN NOW And, rising hence, a greater work is weigh'd. END
BEGIN NOW Latinus, old and mild, had long possess'd END
BEGIN NOW The Latin scepter, and his people blest: END
BEGIN NOW His father Faunus; a Laurentian dame END
BEGIN NOW His mother; fair Marica was her name. END
BEGIN NOW But Faunus came from Picus: Picus drew END
BEGIN NOW His birth from Saturn, if records be true. END
BEGIN NOW Thus King Latinus, in the third degree, END
BEGIN NOW Had Saturn author of his family. END
BEGIN NOW But this old peaceful prince, as Heav'n decreed, END
BEGIN NOW Was blest with no male issue to succeed: END
BEGIN NOW His sons in blooming youth were snatch'd by fate; END
BEGIN NOW One only daughter heir'd the royal state. END
BEGIN NOW Fir'd with her love, and with ambition led, END
BEGIN NOW The neighb'ring princes court her nuptial bed. END
BEGIN NOW Among the crowd, but far above the rest, END
BEGIN NOW Young Turnus to the beauteous maid address'd. END
BEGIN NOW Turnus, for high descent and graceful mien, END
BEGIN NOW Was first, and favor'd by the Latian queen; END
BEGIN NOW With him she strove to join Lavinia's hand, END
BEGIN NOW But dire portents the purpos'd match withstand. END
BEGIN NOW Deep in the palace, of long growth, there stood END
BEGIN NOW A laurel's trunk, a venerable wood; END
BEGIN NOW Where rites divine were paid; whose holy hair END
BEGIN NOW Was kept and cut with superstitious care. END
BEGIN NOW This plant Latinus, when his town he wall'd, END
BEGIN NOW Then found, and from the tree Laurentum call'd; END
BEGIN NOW And last, in honor of his new abode, END
BEGIN NOW He vow'd the laurel to the laurel's god. END
BEGIN NOW It happen'd once (a boding prodigy!) END
BEGIN NOW A swarm of bees, that cut the liquid sky, END
BEGIN NOW (Unknown from whence they took their airy flight,) END
BEGIN NOW Upon the topmost branch in clouds alight; END
BEGIN NOW There with their clasping feet together clung, END
BEGIN NOW And a long cluster from the laurel hung. END
BEGIN NOW An ancient augur prophesied from hence: END
BEGIN NOW Behold on Latian shores a foreign prince! END
BEGIN NOW From the same parts of heav'n his navy stands, END
BEGIN NOW To the same parts on earth; his army lands; END
BEGIN NOW The town he conquers, and the tow'r commands. END
BEGIN NOW Yet more, when fair Lavinia fed the fire END
BEGIN NOW Before the gods, and stood beside her sire, END
BEGIN NOW (Strange to relate!) the flames, involv'd in smoke END
BEGIN NOW Of incense, from the sacred altar broke, END
BEGIN NOW Caught her dishevel'd hair and rich attire; END
BEGIN NOW From thence the fuming trail began to spread END
BEGIN NOW And lambent glories danc'd about her head. END
BEGIN NOW This new portent the seer with wonder views, END
BEGIN NOW Then pausing, thus his prophecy renews: END
BEGIN NOW The nymph, who scatters flaming fires around, END
BEGIN NOW Shall shine with honor, shall herself be crown'd; END
BEGIN NOW But, caus'd by her irrevocable fate, END
BEGIN NOW War shall the country waste, and change the state. END
BEGIN NOW Latinus, frighted with this dire ostent, END
BEGIN NOW For counsel to his father Faunus went, END
BEGIN NOW And sought the shades renown'd for prophecy END
BEGIN NOW Which near Albunea's sulph'rous fountain lie. END
BEGIN NOW To these the Latian and the Sabine land END
BEGIN NOW Fly, when distress'd, and thence relief demand. END
BEGIN NOW The priest on skins of off'rings takes his ease, END
BEGIN NOW And nightly visions in his slumber sees; END
BEGIN NOW A swarm of thin aerial shapes appears, END
BEGIN NOW And, flutt'ring round his temples, deafs his ears: END
BEGIN NOW These he consults, the future fates to know, END
BEGIN NOW From pow'rs above, and from the fiends below. END
BEGIN NOW Here, for the gods' advice, Latinus flies, END
BEGIN NOW Off'ring a hundred sheep for sacrifice: END
BEGIN NOW Their woolly fleeces, as the rites requir'd, END
BEGIN NOW He laid beneath him, and to rest retir'd. END
BEGIN NOW No sooner were his eyes in slumber bound, END
BEGIN NOW When, from above, a more than mortal sound END
BEGIN NOW Invades his ears; and thus the vision spoke: END
BEGIN NOW Seek not, my seed, in Latian bands to yoke END
BEGIN NOW Our fair Lavinia, nor the gods provoke. END
BEGIN NOW A foreign son upon thy shore descends, END
BEGIN NOW Whose martial fame from pole to pole extends. END
BEGIN NOW His race, in arms and arts of peace renown'd, END
BEGIN NOW Not Latium shall contain, nor Europe bound: END
BEGIN NOW 'T is theirs whate'er the sun surveys around. END
BEGIN NOW These answers, in the silent night receiv'd, END
BEGIN NOW The king himself divulg'd, the land believ'd: END
BEGIN NOW The fame thro' all the neighb'ring nations flew, END
BEGIN NOW When now the Trojan navy was in view. END
BEGIN NOW Beneath a shady tree, the hero spread END
BEGIN NOW His table on the turf, with cakes of bread; END
BEGIN NOW And, with his chiefs, on forest fruits he fed. END
BEGIN NOW They sate; and, (not without the god's command,) END
BEGIN NOW Their homely fare dispatch'd, the hungry band END
BEGIN NOW Invade their trenchers next, and soon devour, END
BEGIN NOW To mend the scanty meal, their cakes of flour. END
BEGIN NOW Ascanius this observ'd, and smiling said: END
BEGIN NOW See, we devour the plates on which we fed. END
BEGIN NOW The speech had omen, that the Trojan race END
BEGIN NOW Should find repose, and this the time and place. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas took the word, and thus replies, END
BEGIN NOW Confessing fate with wonder in his eyes: END
BEGIN NOW All hail, O earth! all hail, my household gods! END
BEGIN NOW Behold the destin'd place of your abodes! END
BEGIN NOW For thus Anchises prophesied of old, END
BEGIN NOW And this our fatal place of rest foretold: END
BEGIN NOW 'When, on a foreign shore, instead of meat, END
BEGIN NOW By famine forc'd, your trenchers you shall eat, END
BEGIN NOW Then ease your weary Trojans will attend, END
BEGIN NOW And the long labors of your voyage end. END
BEGIN NOW Remember on that happy coast to build, END
BEGIN NOW And with a trench inclose the fruitful field.' END
BEGIN NOW This was that famine, this the fatal place END
BEGIN NOW Which ends the wand'ring of our exil'd race. END
BEGIN NOW Then, on to-morrow's dawn, your care employ, END
BEGIN NOW To search the land, and where the cities lie, END
BEGIN NOW And what the men; but give this day to joy. END
BEGIN NOW Now pour to Jove; and, after Jove is blest, END
BEGIN NOW Call great Anchises to the genial feast: END
BEGIN NOW Crown high the goblets with a cheerful draught; END
BEGIN NOW Enjoy the present hour; adjourn the future thought. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, the hero bound his brows END
BEGIN NOW With leafy branches, then perform'd his vows; END
BEGIN NOW Adoring first the genius of the place, END
BEGIN NOW Then Earth, the mother of the heav'nly race, END
BEGIN NOW The nymphs, and native godheads yet unknown, END
BEGIN NOW And Night, and all the stars that gild her sable throne, END
BEGIN NOW And ancient Cybel, and Idaean Jove, END
BEGIN NOW And last his sire below, and mother queen above. END
BEGIN NOW Then heav'n's high monarch thunder'd thrice aloud, END
BEGIN NOW And thrice he shook aloft a golden cloud. END
BEGIN NOW Soon thro' the joyful camp a rumor flew, END
BEGIN NOW The time was come their city to renew. END
BEGIN NOW Then ev'ry brow with cheerful green is crown'd, END
BEGIN NOW The feasts are doubled, and the bowls go round. END
BEGIN NOW When next the rosy morn disclos'd the day, END
BEGIN NOW The scouts to sev'ral parts divide their way, END
BEGIN NOW To learn the natives' names, their towns explore, END
BEGIN NOW The coasts and trendings of the crooked shore: END
BEGIN NOW Here Tiber flows, and here Numicus stands; END
BEGIN NOW Here warlike Latins hold the happy lands. END
BEGIN NOW The pious chief, who sought by peaceful ways END
BEGIN NOW To found his empire, and his town to raise, END
BEGIN NOW A hundred youths from all his train selects, END
BEGIN NOW And to the Latian court their course directs, END
BEGIN NOW (The spacious palace where their prince resides,) END
BEGIN NOW And all their heads with wreaths of olive hides. END
BEGIN NOW They go commission'd to require a peace, END
BEGIN NOW And carry presents to procure access. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while they speed their pace, the prince designs END
BEGIN NOW His new-elected seat, and draws the lines. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans round the place a rampire cast, END
BEGIN NOW And palisades about the trenches plac'd. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the train, proceeding on their way, END
BEGIN NOW From far the town and lofty tow'rs survey; END
BEGIN NOW At length approach the walls. Without the gate, END
BEGIN NOW They see the boys and Latian youth debate END
BEGIN NOW The martial prizes on the dusty plain: END
BEGIN NOW Some drive the cars, and some the coursers rein; END
BEGIN NOW Some bend the stubborn bow for victory, END
BEGIN NOW And some with darts their active sinews try. END
BEGIN NOW A posting messenger, dispatch'd from hence, END
BEGIN NOW Of this fair troop advis'd their aged prince, END
BEGIN NOW That foreign men of mighty stature came; END
BEGIN NOW Uncouth their habit, and unknown their name. END
BEGIN NOW The king ordains their entrance, and ascends END
BEGIN NOW His regal seat, surrounded by his friends. END
BEGIN NOW The palace built by Picus, vast and proud, END
BEGIN NOW Supported by a hundred pillars stood, END
BEGIN NOW And round incompass'd with a rising wood. END
BEGIN NOW The pile o'erlook'd the town, and drew the sight; END
BEGIN NOW Surpris'd at once with reverence and delight. END
BEGIN NOW There kings receiv'd the marks of sov'reign pow'r; END
BEGIN NOW In state the monarchs march'd; the lictors bore END
BEGIN NOW Their awful axes and the rods before. END
BEGIN NOW Here the tribunal stood, the house of pray'r, END
BEGIN NOW And here the sacred senators repair; END
BEGIN NOW All at large tables, in long order set, END
BEGIN NOW A ram their off'ring, and a ram their meat. END
BEGIN NOW Above the portal, carv'd in cedar wood, END
BEGIN NOW Plac'd in their ranks, their godlike grandsires stood; END
BEGIN NOW Old Saturn, with his crooked scythe, on high; END
BEGIN NOW And Italus, that led the colony; END
BEGIN NOW And ancient Janus, with his double face, END
BEGIN NOW And bunch of keys, the porter of the place. END
BEGIN NOW There good Sabinus, planter of the vines, END
BEGIN NOW On a short pruning hook his head reclines, END
BEGIN NOW And studiously surveys his gen'rous wines; END
BEGIN NOW Then warlike kings, who for their country fought, END
BEGIN NOW And honorable wounds from battle brought. END
BEGIN NOW Around the posts hung helmets, darts, and spears, END
BEGIN NOW And captive chariots, axes, shields, and bars, END
BEGIN NOW And broken beaks of ships, the trophies of their wars. END
BEGIN NOW Above the rest, as chief of all the band, END
BEGIN NOW Was Picus plac'd, a buckler in his hand; END
BEGIN NOW His other wav'd a long divining wand. END
BEGIN NOW Girt in his Gabin gown the hero sate, END
BEGIN NOW Yet could not with his art avoid his fate: END
BEGIN NOW For Circe long had lov'd the youth in vain, END
BEGIN NOW Till love, refus'd, converted to disdain: END
BEGIN NOW Then, mixing pow'rful herbs, with magic art, END
BEGIN NOW She chang'd his form, who could not change his heart; END
BEGIN NOW Constrain'd him in a bird, and made him fly, END
BEGIN NOW With party-color'd plumes, a chatt'ring pie. END
BEGIN NOW In this high temple, on a chair of state, END
BEGIN NOW The seat of audience, old Latinus sate; END
BEGIN NOW Then gave admission to the Trojan train; END
BEGIN NOW And thus with pleasing accents he began: END
BEGIN NOW Tell me, ye Trojans, for that name you own, END
BEGIN NOW Nor is your course upon our coasts unknown- END
BEGIN NOW Say what you seek, and whither were you bound: END
BEGIN NOW Were you by stress of weather cast aground? END
BEGIN NOW (Such dangers as on seas are often seen, END
BEGIN NOW And oft befall to miserable men,) END
BEGIN NOW Or come, your shipping in our ports to lay, END
BEGIN NOW Spent and disabled in so long a way? END
BEGIN NOW Say what you want: the Latians you shall find END
BEGIN NOW Not forc'd to goodness, but by will inclin'd; END
BEGIN NOW For, since the time of Saturn's holy reign, END
BEGIN NOW His hospitable customs we retain. END
BEGIN NOW I call to mind (but time the tale has worn) END
BEGIN NOW Th' Arunci told, that Dardanus, tho' born END
BEGIN NOW On Latian plains, yet sought the Phrygian shore, END
BEGIN NOW And Samothracia, Samos call'd before. END
BEGIN NOW From Tuscan Coritum he claim'd his birth; END
BEGIN NOW But after, when exempt from mortal earth, END
BEGIN NOW From thence ascended to his kindred skies, END
BEGIN NOW A god, and, as a god, augments their sacrifice, END
BEGIN NOW He said. Ilioneus made this reply: END
BEGIN NOW O king, of Faunus' royal family! END
BEGIN NOW Nor wintry winds to Latium forc'd our way, END
BEGIN NOW Nor did the stars our wand'ring course betray. END
BEGIN NOW Willing we sought your shores; and, hither bound, END
BEGIN NOW The port, so long desir'd, at length we found; END
BEGIN NOW From our sweet homes and ancient realms expell'd; END
BEGIN NOW Great as the greatest that the sun beheld. END
BEGIN NOW The god began our line, who rules above; END
BEGIN NOW And, as our race, our king descends from Jove: END
BEGIN NOW And hither are we come, by his command, END
BEGIN NOW To crave admission in your happy land. END
BEGIN NOW How dire a tempest, from Mycenae pour'd, END
BEGIN NOW Our plains, our temples, and our town devour'd; END
BEGIN NOW What was the waste of war, what fierce alarms END
BEGIN NOW Shook Asia's crown with European arms; END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n such have heard, if any such there be, END
BEGIN NOW Whose earth is bounded by the frozen sea; END
BEGIN NOW And such as, born beneath the burning sky END
BEGIN NOW And sultry sun, betwixt the tropics lie. END
BEGIN NOW From that dire deluge, thro' the wat'ry waste, END
BEGIN NOW Such length of years, such various perils past, END
BEGIN NOW At last escap'd, to Latium we repair, END
BEGIN NOW To beg what you without your want may spare: END
BEGIN NOW The common water, and the common air; END
BEGIN NOW Sheds which ourselves will build, and mean abodes, END
BEGIN NOW Fit to receive and serve our banish'd gods. END
BEGIN NOW Nor our admission shall your realm disgrace, END
BEGIN NOW Nor length of time our gratitude efface. END
BEGIN NOW Besides, what endless honor you shall gain, END
BEGIN NOW To save and shelter Troy's unhappy train! END
BEGIN NOW Now, by my sov'reign, and his fate, I swear, END
BEGIN NOW Renown'd for faith in peace, for force in war; END
BEGIN NOW Oft our alliance other lands desir'd, END
BEGIN NOW And, what we seek of you, of us requir'd. END
BEGIN NOW Despite not then, that in our hands we bear END
BEGIN NOW These holy boughs, sue with words of pray'r. END
BEGIN NOW Fate and the gods, by their supreme command, END
BEGIN NOW Have doom'd our ships to seek the Latian land. END
BEGIN NOW To these abodes our fleet Apollo sends; END
BEGIN NOW Here Dardanus was born, and hither tends; END
BEGIN NOW Where Tuscan Tiber rolls with rapid force, END
BEGIN NOW And where Numicus opes his holy source. END
BEGIN NOW Besides, our prince presents, with his request, END
BEGIN NOW Some small remains of what his sire possess'd. END
BEGIN NOW This golden charger, snatch'd from burning Troy, END
BEGIN NOW Anchises did in sacrifice employ; END
BEGIN NOW This royal robe and this tiara wore END
BEGIN NOW Old Priam, and this golden scepter bore END
BEGIN NOW In full assemblies, and in solemn games; END
BEGIN NOW These purple vests were weav'd by Dardan dames. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while he spoke, Latinus roll'd around END
BEGIN NOW His eyes, and fix'd a while upon the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Intent he seem'd, and anxious in his breast; END
BEGIN NOW Not by the scepter mov'd, or kingly vest, END
BEGIN NOW But pond'ring future things of wondrous weight; END
BEGIN NOW Succession, empire, and his daughter's fate. END
BEGIN NOW On these he mus'd within his thoughtful mind, END
BEGIN NOW And then revolv'd what Faunus had divin'd. END
BEGIN NOW This was the foreign prince, by fate decreed END
BEGIN NOW To share his scepter, and Lavinia's bed; END
BEGIN NOW This was the race that sure portents foreshew END
BEGIN NOW To sway the world, and land and sea subdue. END
BEGIN NOW At length he rais'd his cheerful head, and spoke: END
BEGIN NOW The pow'rs," said he, "the pow'rs we both invoke, END
BEGIN NOW To you, and yours, and mine, propitious be, END
BEGIN NOW And firm our purpose with their augury! END
BEGIN NOW Have what you ask; your presents I receive; END
BEGIN NOW Land, where and when you please, with ample leave; END
BEGIN NOW Partake and use my kingdom as your own; END
BEGIN NOW All shall be yours, while I command the crown: END
BEGIN NOW And, if my wish'd alliance please your king, END
BEGIN NOW Tell him he should not send the peace, but bring. END
BEGIN NOW Then let him not a friend's embraces fear; END
BEGIN NOW The peace is made when I behold him here. END
BEGIN NOW Besides this answer, tell my royal guest, END
BEGIN NOW I add to his commands my own request: END
BEGIN NOW One only daughter heirs my crown and state, END
BEGIN NOW Whom not our oracles, nor Heav'n, nor fate, END
BEGIN NOW Nor frequent prodigies, permit to join END
BEGIN NOW With any native of th' Ausonian line. END
BEGIN NOW A foreign son-in-law shall come from far END
BEGIN NOW (Such is our doom), a chief renown'd in war, END
BEGIN NOW Whose race shall bear aloft the Latian name, END
BEGIN NOW And thro' the conquer'd world diffuse our fame. END
BEGIN NOW Himself to be the man the fates require, END
BEGIN NOW I firmly judge, and, what I judge, desire. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and then on each bestow'd a steed. END
BEGIN NOW Three hundred horses, in high stables fed, END
BEGIN NOW Stood ready, shining all, and smoothly dress'd: END
BEGIN NOW Of these he chose the fairest and the best, END
BEGIN NOW To mount the Trojan troop. At his command END
BEGIN NOW The steeds caparison'd with purple stand, END
BEGIN NOW With golden trappings, glorious to behold, END
BEGIN NOW And champ betwixt their teeth the foaming gold. END
BEGIN NOW Then to his absent guest the king decreed END
BEGIN NOW A pair of coursers born of heav'nly breed, END
BEGIN NOW Who from their nostrils breath'd ethereal fire; END
BEGIN NOW Whom Circe stole from her celestial sire, END
BEGIN NOW By substituting mares produc'd on earth, END
BEGIN NOW Whose wombs conceiv'd a more than mortal birth. END
BEGIN NOW These draw the chariot which Latinus sends, END
BEGIN NOW And the rich present to the prince commends. END
BEGIN NOW Sublime on stately steeds the Trojans borne, END
BEGIN NOW To their expecting lord with peace return. END
BEGIN NOW But jealous Juno, from Pachynus' height, END
BEGIN NOW As she from Argos took her airy flight, END
BEGIN NOW Beheld with envious eyes this hateful sight. END
BEGIN NOW She saw the Trojan and his joyful train END
BEGIN NOW Descend upon the shore, desert the main, END
BEGIN NOW Design a town, and, with unhop'd success, END
BEGIN NOW Th' embassadors return with promis'd peace. END
BEGIN NOW Then, pierc'd with pain, she shook her haughty head, END
BEGIN NOW Sigh'd from her inward soul, and thus she said: END
BEGIN NOW O hated offspring of my Phrygian foes! END
BEGIN NOW O fates of Troy, which Juno's fates oppose! END
BEGIN NOW Could they not fall unpitied on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW But slain revive, and, taken, scape again? END
BEGIN NOW When execrable Troy in ashes lay, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' fires and swords and seas they forc'd their way. END
BEGIN NOW Then vanquish'd Juno must in vain contend, END
BEGIN NOW Her rage disarm'd, her empire at an end. END
BEGIN NOW Breathless and tir'd, is all my fury spent? END
BEGIN NOW Or does my glutted spleen at length relent? END
BEGIN NOW As if 't were little from their town to chase, END
BEGIN NOW I thro' the seas pursued their exil'd race; END
BEGIN NOW Ingag'd the heav'ns, oppos'd the stormy main; END
BEGIN NOW But billows roar'd, and tempests rag'd in vain. END
BEGIN NOW What have my Scyllas and my Syrtes done, END
BEGIN NOW When these they overpass, and those they shun? END
BEGIN NOW On Tiber's shores they land, secure of fate, END
BEGIN NOW Triumphant o'er the storms and Juno's hate. END
BEGIN NOW Mars could in mutual blood the Centaurs bathe, END
BEGIN NOW And Jove himself gave way to Cynthia's wrath, END
BEGIN NOW Who sent the tusky boar to Calydon; END
BEGIN NOW (What great offense had either people done?) END
BEGIN NOW But I, the consort of the Thunderer, END
BEGIN NOW Have wag'd a long and unsuccessful war, END
BEGIN NOW With various arts and arms in vain have toil'd, END
BEGIN NOW And by a mortal man at length am foil'd. END
BEGIN NOW If native pow'r prevail not, shall I doubt END
BEGIN NOW To seek for needful succor from without? END
BEGIN NOW If Jove and Heav'n my just desires deny, END
BEGIN NOW Hell shall the pow'r of Heav'n and Jove supply. END
BEGIN NOW Grant that the Fates have firm'd, by their decree, END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan race to reign in Italy; END
BEGIN NOW At least I can defer the nuptial day, END
BEGIN NOW And with protracted wars the peace delay: END
BEGIN NOW With blood the dear alliance shall be bought, END
BEGIN NOW And both the people near destruction brought; END
BEGIN NOW So shall the son-in-law and father join, END
BEGIN NOW With ruin, war, and waste of either line. END
BEGIN NOW O fatal maid, thy marriage is endow'd END
BEGIN NOW With Phrygian, Latian, and Rutulian blood! END
BEGIN NOW Bellona leads thee to thy lover's hand; END
BEGIN NOW Another queen brings forth another brand, END
BEGIN NOW To burn with foreign fires another land! END
BEGIN NOW A second Paris, diff'ring but in name, END
BEGIN NOW Shall fire his country with a second flame. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, she sinks beneath the ground, END
BEGIN NOW With furious haste, and shoots the Stygian sound, END
BEGIN NOW To rouse Alecto from th' infernal seat END
BEGIN NOW Of her dire sisters, and their dark retreat. END
BEGIN NOW This Fury, fit for her intent, she chose; END
BEGIN NOW One who delights in wars and human woes. END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n Pluto hates his own misshapen race; END
BEGIN NOW Her sister Furies fly her hideous face; END
BEGIN NOW So frightful are the forms the monster takes, END
BEGIN NOW So fierce the hissings of her speckled snakes. END
BEGIN NOW Her Juno finds, and thus inflames her spite: END
BEGIN NOW O virgin daughter of eternal Night, END
BEGIN NOW Give me this once thy labor, to sustain END
BEGIN NOW My right, and execute my just disdain. END
BEGIN NOW Let not the Trojans, with a feign'd pretense END
BEGIN NOW Of proffer'd peace, delude the Latian prince. END
BEGIN NOW Expel from Italy that odious name, END
BEGIN NOW And let not Juno suffer in her fame. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is thine to ruin realms, o'erturn a state, END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the dearest friends to raise debate, END
BEGIN NOW And kindle kindred blood to mutual hate. END
BEGIN NOW Thy hand o'er towns the fun'ral torch displays, END
BEGIN NOW And forms a thousand ills ten thousand ways. END
BEGIN NOW Now shake, out thy fruitful breast, the seeds END
BEGIN NOW Of envy, discord, and of cruel deeds: END
BEGIN NOW Confound the peace establish'd, and prepare END
BEGIN NOW Their souls to hatred, and their hands to war. END
BEGIN NOW Smear'd as she was with black Gorgonian blood, END
BEGIN NOW The Fury sprang above the Stygian flood; END
BEGIN NOW And on her wicker wings, sublime thro' night, END
BEGIN NOW She to the Latian palace took her flight: END
BEGIN NOW There sought the queen's apartment, stood before END
BEGIN NOW The peaceful threshold, and besieg'd the door. END
BEGIN NOW Restless Amata lay, her swelling breast END
BEGIN NOW Fir'd with disdain for Turnus dispossess'd, END
BEGIN NOW And the new nuptials of the Trojan guest. END
BEGIN NOW From her black bloody locks the Fury shakes END
BEGIN NOW Her darling plague, the fav'rite of her snakes; END
BEGIN NOW With her full force she threw the poisonous dart, END
BEGIN NOW And fix'd it deep within Amata's heart, END
BEGIN NOW That, thus envenom'd, she might kindle rage, END
BEGIN NOW And sacrifice to strife her house husband's age. END
BEGIN NOW Unseen, unfelt, the fiery serpent skims END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt her linen and her naked limbs; END
BEGIN NOW His baleful breath inspiring, as he glides, END
BEGIN NOW Now like a chain around her neck he rides, END
BEGIN NOW Now like a fillet to her head repairs, END
BEGIN NOW And with his circling volumes folds her hairs. END
BEGIN NOW At first the silent venom slid with ease, END
BEGIN NOW And seiz'd her cooler senses by degrees; END
BEGIN NOW Then, ere th' infected mass was fir'd too far, END
BEGIN NOW In plaintive accents she began the war, END
BEGIN NOW And thus bespoke her husband: "Shall," she said, END
BEGIN NOW A wand'ring prince enjoy Lavinia's bed? END
BEGIN NOW If nature plead not in a parent's heart, END
BEGIN NOW Pity my tears, and pity her desert. END
BEGIN NOW I know, my dearest lord, the time will come, END
BEGIN NOW You in vain, reverse your cruel doom; END
BEGIN NOW The faithless pirate soon will set to sea, END
BEGIN NOW And bear the royal virgin far away! END
BEGIN NOW A guest like him, a Trojan guest before, END
BEGIN NOW In shew of friendship sought the Spartan shore, END
BEGIN NOW And ravish'd Helen from her husband bore. END
BEGIN NOW Think on a king's inviolable word; END
BEGIN NOW And think on Turnus, her once plighted lord: END
BEGIN NOW To this false foreigner you give your throne, END
BEGIN NOW And wrong a friend, a kinsman, and a son. END
BEGIN NOW Resume your ancient care; and, if the god END
BEGIN NOW Your sire, and you, resolve on foreign blood, END
BEGIN NOW Know all are foreign, in a larger sense, END
BEGIN NOW Not born your subjects, or deriv'd from hence. END
BEGIN NOW Then, if the line of Turnus you retrace, END
BEGIN NOW He springs from Inachus of Argive race. END
BEGIN NOW But when she saw her reasons idly spent, END
BEGIN NOW And could not move him from his fix'd intent, END
BEGIN NOW She flew to rage; for now the snake possess'd END
BEGIN NOW Her vital parts, and poison'd all her breast; END
BEGIN NOW She raves, she runs with a distracted pace, END
BEGIN NOW And fills with horrid howls the public place. END
BEGIN NOW And, as young striplings whip the top for sport, END
BEGIN NOW On the smooth pavement of an empty court; END
BEGIN NOW The wooden engine flies and whirls about, END
BEGIN NOW Admir'd, with clamors, of the beardless rout; END
BEGIN NOW They lash aloud; each other they provoke, END
BEGIN NOW And lend their little souls at ev'ry stroke: END
BEGIN NOW Thus fares the queen; and thus her fury blows END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the crowd, and kindles as she goes. END
BEGIN NOW Nor yet content, she strains her malice more, END
BEGIN NOW And adds new ills to those contriv'd before: END
BEGIN NOW She flies the town, and, mixing with a throng END
BEGIN NOW Of madding matrons, bears the bride along, END
BEGIN NOW Wand'ring thro' woods and wilds, and devious ways, END
BEGIN NOW And with these arts the Trojan match delays. END
BEGIN NOW She feign'd the rites of Bacchus; cried aloud, END
BEGIN NOW And to the buxom god the virgin vow'd. END
BEGIN NOW Evoe! O Bacchus!" thus began the song; END
BEGIN NOW And "Evoe!" answer'd all the female throng. END
BEGIN NOW O virgin! worthy thee alone!" she cried; END
BEGIN NOW O worthy thee alone!" the crew replied. END
BEGIN NOW For thee she feeds her hair, she leads thy dance, END
BEGIN NOW And with thy winding ivy wreathes her lance. END
BEGIN NOW Like fury seiz'd the rest; the progress known, END
BEGIN NOW All seek the mountains, and forsake the town: END
BEGIN NOW All, clad in skins of beasts, the jav'lin bear, END
BEGIN NOW Give to the wanton winds their flowing hair, END
BEGIN NOW And shrieks and shoutings rend the suff'ring air. END
BEGIN NOW The queen herself, inspir'd with rage divine, END
BEGIN NOW Shook high above her head a flaming pine; END
BEGIN NOW Then roll'd her haggard eyes around the throng, END
BEGIN NOW And sung, in Turnus' name, the nuptial song: END
BEGIN NOW Io, ye Latian dames! if any here END
BEGIN NOW Hold your unhappy queen, Amata, dear; END
BEGIN NOW If there be here," she said, who dare maintain END
BEGIN NOW My right, nor think the name of mother vain; END
BEGIN NOW Unbind your fillets, loose your flowing hair, END
BEGIN NOW And orgies and nocturnal rites prepare. END
BEGIN NOW Amata's breast the Fury thus invades, END
BEGIN NOW And fires with rage, amid the sylvan shades; END
BEGIN NOW Then, when she found her venom spread so far, END
BEGIN NOW The royal house embroil'd in civil war, END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd on her dusky wings, she cleaves the skies, END
BEGIN NOW And seeks the palace where young Turnus lies. END
BEGIN NOW His town, as fame reports, was built of old END
BEGIN NOW By Danae, pregnant with almighty gold, END
BEGIN NOW Who fled her father's rage, and, with a train END
BEGIN NOW Of following Argives, thro' the stormy main, END
BEGIN NOW Driv'n by the southern blasts, was fated here to reign. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was Ardua once; now Ardea's name it bears; END
BEGIN NOW Once a fair city, now consum'd with years. END
BEGIN NOW Here, in his lofty palace, Turnus lay, END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the confines of the night and day, END
BEGIN NOW Secure in sleep. The Fury laid aside END
BEGIN NOW Her looks and limbs, and with new methods tried END
BEGIN NOW The foulness of th' infernal form to hide. END
BEGIN NOW Propp'd on a staff, she takes a trembling mien: END
BEGIN NOW Her face is furrow'd, and her front obscene; END
BEGIN NOW Deep-dinted wrinkles on her cheek she draws; END
BEGIN NOW Sunk are her eyes, and toothless are her jaws; END
BEGIN NOW Her hoary hair with holy fillets bound, END
BEGIN NOW Her temples with an olive wreath are crown'd. END
BEGIN NOW Old Chalybe, who kept the sacred fane END
BEGIN NOW Of Juno, now she seem'd, and thus began, END
BEGIN NOW Appearing in a dream, to rouse the careless man: END
BEGIN NOW Shall Turnus then such endless toil sustain END
BEGIN NOW In fighting fields, and conquer towns in vain? END
BEGIN NOW Win, for a Trojan head to wear the prize, END
BEGIN NOW Usurp thy crown, enjoy thy victories? END
BEGIN NOW The bride and scepter which thy blood has bought, END
BEGIN NOW The king transfers; and foreign heirs are sought. END
BEGIN NOW Go now, deluded man, and seek again END
BEGIN NOW New toils, new dangers, on the dusty plain. END
BEGIN NOW Repel the Tuscan foes; their city seize; END
BEGIN NOW Protect the Latians in luxurious ease. END
BEGIN NOW This dream all-pow'rful Juno sends; I bear END
BEGIN NOW Her mighty mandates, and her words you hear. END
BEGIN NOW Haste; arm your Ardeans; issue to the plain; END
BEGIN NOW With fate to friend, assault the Trojan train: END
BEGIN NOW Their thoughtless chiefs, their painted ships, that lie END
BEGIN NOW In Tiber's mouth, with fire and sword destroy. END
BEGIN NOW The Latian king, unless he shall submit, END
BEGIN NOW Own his old promise, and his new forget- END
BEGIN NOW Let him, in arms, the pow'r of Turnus prove, END
BEGIN NOW And learn to fear whom he disdains to love. END
BEGIN NOW For such is Heav'n's command." The youthful prince END
BEGIN NOW With scorn replied, and made this bold defense: END
BEGIN NOW You tell me, mother, what I knew before: END
BEGIN NOW The Phrygian fleet is landed on the shore. END
BEGIN NOW I neither fear nor will provoke the war; END
BEGIN NOW My fate is Juno's most peculiar care. END
BEGIN NOW But time has made you dote, and vainly tell END
BEGIN NOW Of arms imagin'd in your lonely cell. END
BEGIN NOW Go; be the temple and the gods your care; END
BEGIN NOW Permit to men the thought of peace and war. END
BEGIN NOW These haughty words Alecto's rage provoke, END
BEGIN NOW And frighted Turnus trembled as she spoke. END
BEGIN NOW Her eyes grow stiffen'd, and with sulphur burn; END
BEGIN NOW Her hideous looks and hellish form return; END
BEGIN NOW Her curling snakes with hissings fill the place, END
BEGIN NOW And open all the furies of her face: END
BEGIN NOW Then, darting fire from her malignant eyes, END
BEGIN NOW She cast him backward as he strove to rise, END
BEGIN NOW And, ling'ring, sought to frame some new replies. END
BEGIN NOW High on her head she rears two twisted snakes, END
BEGIN NOW Her chains she rattles, and her whip she shakes; END
BEGIN NOW And, churning bloody foam, thus loudly speaks: END
BEGIN NOW Behold whom time has made to dote, and tell END
BEGIN NOW Of arms imagin'd in her lonely cell! END
BEGIN NOW Behold the Fates' infernal minister! END
BEGIN NOW War, death, destruction, in my hand I bear. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, her smold'ring torch, impress'd END
BEGIN NOW With her full force, she plung'd into his breast. END
BEGIN NOW Aghast he wak'd; and, starting from his bed, END
BEGIN NOW Cold sweat, in clammy drops, his limbs o'erspread. END
BEGIN NOW Arms! arms!" he cries: "my sword and shield prepare! END
BEGIN NOW He breathes defiance, blood, and mortal war. END
BEGIN NOW So, when with crackling flames a caldron fries, END
BEGIN NOW The bubbling waters from the bottom rise: END
BEGIN NOW Above the brims they force their fiery way; END
BEGIN NOW Black vapors climb aloft, and cloud the day. END
BEGIN NOW The peace polluted thus, a chosen band END
BEGIN NOW He first commissions to the Latian land, END
BEGIN NOW In threat'ning embassy; then rais'd the rest, END
BEGIN NOW To meet in arms th' intruding Trojan guest, END
BEGIN NOW To force the foes from the Lavinian shore, END
BEGIN NOW And Italy's indanger'd peace restore. END
BEGIN NOW Himself alone an equal match he boasts, END
BEGIN NOW To fight the Phrygian and Ausonian hosts. END
BEGIN NOW The gods invok'd, the Rutuli prepare END
BEGIN NOW Their arms, and warn each other to the war. END
BEGIN NOW His beauty these, and those his blooming age, END
BEGIN NOW The rest his house and his own fame ingage. END
BEGIN NOW While Turnus urges thus his enterprise, END
BEGIN NOW The Stygian Fury to the Trojans flies; END
BEGIN NOW New frauds invents, and takes a steepy stand, END
BEGIN NOW Which overlooks the vale with wide command; END
BEGIN NOW Where fair Ascanius and his youthful train, END
BEGIN NOW With horns and hounds, a hunting match ordain, END
BEGIN NOW And pitch their toils around the shady plain. END
BEGIN NOW The Fury fires the pack; they snuff, they vent, END
BEGIN NOW And feed their hungry nostrils with the scent. END
BEGIN NOW 'Twas of a well-grown stag, whose antlers rise END
BEGIN NOW High o'er his front; his beams invade the skies. END
BEGIN NOW From this light cause th' infernal maid prepares END
BEGIN NOW The country churls to mischief, hate, and wars. END
BEGIN NOW The stately beast the two Tyrrhidae bred, END
BEGIN NOW Snatch'd from his dams, and the tame youngling fed. END
BEGIN NOW Their father Tyrrheus did his fodder bring, END
BEGIN NOW Tyrrheus, chief ranger to the Latian king: END
BEGIN NOW Their sister Silvia cherish'd with her care END
BEGIN NOW The little wanton, and did wreaths prepare END
BEGIN NOW To hang his budding horns, with ribbons tied END
BEGIN NOW His tender neck, and comb'd his silken hide, END
BEGIN NOW And bathed his body. Patient of command END
BEGIN NOW In time he grew, and, growing us'd to hand, END
BEGIN NOW He waited at his master's board for food; END
BEGIN NOW Then sought his salvage kindred in the wood, END
BEGIN NOW Where grazing all the day, at night he came END
BEGIN NOW To his known lodgings, and his country dame. END
BEGIN NOW This household beast, that us'd the woodland grounds, END
BEGIN NOW Was view'd at first by the young hero's hounds, END
BEGIN NOW As down the stream he swam, to seek retreat END
BEGIN NOW In the cool waters, and to quench his heat. END
BEGIN NOW Ascanius young, and eager of his game, END
BEGIN NOW Soon bent his bow, uncertain in his aim; END
BEGIN NOW But the dire fiend the fatal arrow guides, END
BEGIN NOW Which pierc'd his bowels thro' his panting sides. END
BEGIN NOW The bleeding creature issues from the floods, END
BEGIN NOW Possess'd with fear, and seeks his known abodes, END
BEGIN NOW His old familiar hearth and household gods. END
BEGIN NOW He falls; he fills the house with heavy groans, END
BEGIN NOW Implores their pity, and his pain bemoans. END
BEGIN NOW Young Silvia beats her breast, and cries aloud END
BEGIN NOW For succor from the clownish neighborhood: END
BEGIN NOW The churls assemble; for the fiend, who lay END
BEGIN NOW In the close woody covert, urg'd their way. END
BEGIN NOW One with a brand yet burning from the flame, END
BEGIN NOW Arm'd with a knotty club another came: END
BEGIN NOW Whate'er they catch or find, without their care, END
BEGIN NOW Their fury makes an instrument of war. END
BEGIN NOW Tyrrheus, the foster father of the beast, END
BEGIN NOW Then clench'd a hatchet in his horny fist, END
BEGIN NOW But held his hand from the descending stroke, END
BEGIN NOW And left his wedge within the cloven oak, END
BEGIN NOW To whet their courage and their rage provoke. END
BEGIN NOW And now the goddess, exercis'd in ill, END
BEGIN NOW Who watch'd an hour to work her impious will, END
BEGIN NOW Ascends the roof, and to her crooked horn, END
BEGIN NOW Such as was then by Latian shepherds borne, END
BEGIN NOW Adds all her breath: the rocks and woods around, END
BEGIN NOW And mountains, tremble at th' infernal sound. END
BEGIN NOW The sacred lake of Trivia from afar, END
BEGIN NOW The Veline fountains, and sulphureous Nar, END
BEGIN NOW Shake at the baleful blast, the signal of the war. END
BEGIN NOW Young mothers wildly stare, with fear possess'd, END
BEGIN NOW And strain their helpless infants to their breast. END
BEGIN NOW The clowns, a boist'rous, rude, ungovern'd crew, END
BEGIN NOW With furious haste to the loud summons flew. END
BEGIN NOW The pow'rs of Troy, then issuing on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW With fresh recruits their youthful chief sustain: END
BEGIN NOW Not theirs a raw and unexperienc'd train, END
BEGIN NOW But a firm body of embattled men. END
BEGIN NOW At first, while fortune favor'd neither side, END
BEGIN NOW The fight with clubs and burning brands was tried; END
BEGIN NOW But now, both parties reinforc'd, the fields END
BEGIN NOW Are bright with flaming swords and brazen shields. END
BEGIN NOW A shining harvest either host displays, END
BEGIN NOW And shoots against the sun with equal rays. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, when a black-brow'd gust begins to rise, END
BEGIN NOW White foam at first on the curl'd ocean fries; END
BEGIN NOW Then roars the main, the billows mount the skies; END
BEGIN NOW Till, by the fury of the storm full blown, END
BEGIN NOW The muddy bottom o'er the clouds is thrown. END
BEGIN NOW First Almon falls, old Tyrrheus' eldest care, END
BEGIN NOW Pierc'd with an arrow from the distant war: END
BEGIN NOW Fix'd in his throat the flying weapon stood, END
BEGIN NOW And stopp'd his breath, and drank his vital blood END
BEGIN NOW Huge heaps of slain around the body rise: END
BEGIN NOW Among the rest, the rich Galesus lies; END
BEGIN NOW A good old man, while peace he preach'd in vain, END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the madness of th' unruly train: END
BEGIN NOW Five herds, five bleating flocks, his pastures fill'd; END
BEGIN NOW His lands a hundred yoke of oxen till'd. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, while in equal scales their fortune stood END
BEGIN NOW The Fury bath'd them in each other's blood; END
BEGIN NOW Then, having fix'd the fight, exulting flies, END
BEGIN NOW And bears fulfill'd her promise to the skies. END
BEGIN NOW To Juno thus she speaks: "Behold! It is done, END
BEGIN NOW The blood already drawn, the war begun; END
BEGIN NOW The discord is complete; nor can they cease END
BEGIN NOW The dire debate, nor you command the peace. END
BEGIN NOW Now, since the Latian and the Trojan brood END
BEGIN NOW Have tasted vengeance and the sweets of blood; END
BEGIN NOW Speak, and my pow'r shall add this office more: END
BEGIN NOW The neighb'ing nations of th' Ausonian shore END
BEGIN NOW Shall hear the dreadful rumor, from afar, END
BEGIN NOW Of arm'd invasion, and embrace the war. END
BEGIN NOW Then Juno thus: "The grateful work is done, END
BEGIN NOW The seeds of discord sow'd, the war begun; END
BEGIN NOW Frauds, fears, and fury have possess'd the state, END
BEGIN NOW And fix'd the causes of a lasting hate. END
BEGIN NOW A bloody Hymen shall th' alliance join END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the Trojan and Ausonian line: END
BEGIN NOW But thou with speed to night and hell repair; END
BEGIN NOW For not the gods, nor angry Jove, will bear END
BEGIN NOW Thy lawless wand'ring walks in upper air. END
BEGIN NOW Leave what remains to me." Saturnia said: END
BEGIN NOW The sullen fiend her sounding wings display'd, END
BEGIN NOW Unwilling left the light, and sought the nether shade. END
BEGIN NOW In midst of Italy, well known to fame, END
BEGIN NOW There lies a lake (Amsanctus is the name) END
BEGIN NOW Below the lofty mounts: on either side END
BEGIN NOW Thick forests the forbidden entrance hide. END
BEGIN NOW Full in the center of the sacred wood END
BEGIN NOW An arm arises of the Stygian flood, END
BEGIN NOW Which, breaking from beneath with bellowing sound, END
BEGIN NOW Whirls the black waves and rattling stones around. END
BEGIN NOW Here Pluto pants for breath from out his cell, END
BEGIN NOW And opens wide the grinning jaws of hell. END
BEGIN NOW To this infernal lake the Fury flies; END
BEGIN NOW Here hides her hated head, and frees the lab'ring skies. END
BEGIN NOW Saturnian Juno now, with double care, END
BEGIN NOW Attends the fatal process of the war. END
BEGIN NOW The clowns, return'd, from battle bear the slain, END
BEGIN NOW Implore the gods, and to their king complain. END
BEGIN NOW The corps of Almon and the rest are shown; END
BEGIN NOW Shrieks, clamors, murmurs, fill the frighted town. END
BEGIN NOW Ambitious Turnus in the press appears, END
BEGIN NOW And, aggravating crimes, augments their fears; END
BEGIN NOW Proclaims his private injuries aloud, END
BEGIN NOW A solemn promise made, and disavow'd; END
BEGIN NOW A foreign son is sought, and a mix'd mungril brood. END
BEGIN NOW Then they, whose mothers, frantic with their fear, END
BEGIN NOW In woods and wilds the flags of Bacchus bear, END
BEGIN NOW And lead his dances with dishevel'd hair, END
BEGIN NOW Increase the clamor, and the war demand, END
BEGIN NOW (Such was Amata's interest in the land,) END
BEGIN NOW Against the public sanctions of the peace, END
BEGIN NOW Against all omens of their ill success. END
BEGIN NOW With fates averse, the rout in arms resort, END
BEGIN NOW To force their monarch, and insult the court. END
BEGIN NOW But, like a rock unmov'd, a rock that braves END
BEGIN NOW The raging tempest and the rising waves- END
BEGIN NOW Propp'd on himself he stands; his solid sides END
BEGIN NOW Wash off the seaweeds, and the sounding tides- END
BEGIN NOW So stood the pious prince, unmov'd, and long END
BEGIN NOW Sustain'd the madness of the noisy throng. END
BEGIN NOW But, when he found that Juno's pow'r prevail'd, END
BEGIN NOW And all the methods of cool counsel fail'd, END
BEGIN NOW He calls the gods to witness their offense, END
BEGIN NOW Disclaims the war, asserts his innocence. END
BEGIN NOW Hurried by fate," he cries, "and borne before END
BEGIN NOW A furious wind, we have the faithful shore. END
BEGIN NOW O more than madmen! you yourselves shall bear END
BEGIN NOW The guilt of blood and sacrilegious war: END
BEGIN NOW Thou, Turnus, shalt atone it by thy fate, END
BEGIN NOW And pray to Heav'n for peace, but pray too late. END
BEGIN NOW For me, my stormy voyage at an end, END
BEGIN NOW I to the port of death securely tend. END
BEGIN NOW The fun'ral pomp which to your kings you pay, END
BEGIN NOW Is all I want, and all you take away. END
BEGIN NOW He said no more, but, in his walls confin'd, END
BEGIN NOW Shut out the woes which he too well divin'd END
BEGIN NOW Nor with the rising storm would vainly strive, END
BEGIN NOW But left the helm, and let the vessel drive. END
BEGIN NOW A solemn custom was observ'd of old, END
BEGIN NOW Which Latium held, and now the Romans hold, END
BEGIN NOW Their standard when in fighting fields they rear END
BEGIN NOW Against the fierce Hyrcanians, or declare END
BEGIN NOW The Scythian, Indian, or Arabian war; END
BEGIN NOW Or from the boasting Parthians would regain END
BEGIN NOW Their eagles, lost in Carrhae's bloody plain. END
BEGIN NOW Two gates of steel (the name of Mars they bear, END
BEGIN NOW And still are worship'd with religious fear) END
BEGIN NOW Before his temple stand: the dire abode, END
BEGIN NOW And the fear'd issues of the furious god, END
BEGIN NOW Are fenc'd with brazen bolts; without the gates, END
BEGIN NOW The wary guardian Janus doubly waits. END
BEGIN NOW Then, when the sacred senate votes the wars, END
BEGIN NOW The Roman consul their decree declares, END
BEGIN NOW And in his robes the sounding gates unbars. END
BEGIN NOW The youth in military shouts arise, END
BEGIN NOW And the loud trumpets break the yielding skies. END
BEGIN NOW These rites, of old by sov'reign princes us'd, END
BEGIN NOW Were the king's office; but the king refus'd, END
BEGIN NOW Deaf to their cries, nor would the gates unbar END
BEGIN NOW Of sacred peace, or loose th' imprison'd war; END
BEGIN NOW But hid his head, and, safe from loud alarms, END
BEGIN NOW Abhorr'd the wicked ministry of arms. END
BEGIN NOW Then heav'n's imperious queen shot down from high: END
BEGIN NOW At her approach the brazen hinges fly; END
BEGIN NOW The gates are forc'd, and ev'ry falling bar; END
BEGIN NOW And, like a tempest, issues out the war. END
BEGIN NOW The peaceful cities of th' Ausonian shore, END
BEGIN NOW Lull'd in their ease, and undisturb'd before, END
BEGIN NOW Are all on fire; and some, with studious care, END
BEGIN NOW Their restiff steeds in sandy plains prepare; END
BEGIN NOW Some their soft limbs in painful marches try, END
BEGIN NOW And war is all their wish, and arms the gen'ral cry. END
BEGIN NOW Part scour the rusty shields with seam; and part END
BEGIN NOW New grind the blunted ax, and point the dart: END
BEGIN NOW With joy they view the waving ensigns fly, END
BEGIN NOW And hear the trumpet's clangor pierce the sky. END
BEGIN NOW Five cities forge their arms: th' Atinian pow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW Antemnae, Tibur with her lofty tow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW Ardea the proud, the Crustumerian town: END
BEGIN NOW All these of old were places of renown. END
BEGIN NOW Some hammer helmets for the fighting field; END
BEGIN NOW Some twine young sallows to support the shield; END
BEGIN NOW The croslet some, and some the cuishes mold, END
BEGIN NOW With silver plated, and with ductile gold. END
BEGIN NOW The rustic honors of the scythe and share END
BEGIN NOW Give place to swords and plumes, the pride of war. END
BEGIN NOW Old fauchions are new temper'd in the fires; END
BEGIN NOW The sounding trumpet ev'ry soul inspires. END
BEGIN NOW The word is giv'n; with eager speed they lace END
BEGIN NOW The shining headpiece, and the shield embrace. END
BEGIN NOW The neighing steeds are to the chariot tied; END
BEGIN NOW The trusty weapon sits on ev'ry side. END
BEGIN NOW And now the mighty labor is begun END
BEGIN NOW Ye Muses, open all your Helicon. END
BEGIN NOW Sing you the chiefs that sway'd th' Ausonian land, END
BEGIN NOW Their arms, and armies under their command; END
BEGIN NOW What warriors in our ancient clime were bred; END
BEGIN NOW What soldiers follow'd, and what heroes led. END
BEGIN NOW For well you know, and can record alone, END
BEGIN NOW What fame to future times conveys but darkly down. END
BEGIN NOW Mezentius first appear'd upon the plain: END
BEGIN NOW Scorn sate upon his brows, and sour disdain, END
BEGIN NOW Defying earth and heav'n. Etruria lost, END
BEGIN NOW He brings to Turnus' aid his baffled host. END
BEGIN NOW The charming Lausus, full of youthful fire, END
BEGIN NOW Rode in the rank, and next his sullen sire; END
BEGIN NOW To Turnus only second in the grace END
BEGIN NOW Of manly mien, and features of the face. END
BEGIN NOW A skilful horseman, and a huntsman bred, END
BEGIN NOW With fates averse a thousand men he led: END
BEGIN NOW His sire unworthy of so brave a son; END
BEGIN NOW Himself well worthy of a happier throne. END
BEGIN NOW Next Aventinus drives his chariot round END
BEGIN NOW The Latian plains, with palms and laurels crown'd. END
BEGIN NOW Proud of his steeds, he smokes along the field; END
BEGIN NOW His father's hydra fills his ample shield: END
BEGIN NOW A hundred serpents hiss about the brims; END
BEGIN NOW The son of Hercules he justly seems END
BEGIN NOW By his broad shoulders and gigantic limbs; END
BEGIN NOW Of heav'nly part, and part of earthly blood, END
BEGIN NOW A mortal woman mixing with a god. END
BEGIN NOW For strong Alcides, after he had slain END
BEGIN NOW The triple Geryon, drove from conquer'd Spain END
BEGIN NOW His captive herds; and, thence in triumph led, END
BEGIN NOW On Tuscan Tiber's flow'ry banks they fed. END
BEGIN NOW The priestess Rhea found, and forc'd to love. END
BEGIN NOW For arms, his men long piles and jav'lins bore; END
BEGIN NOW And poles with pointed steel their foes in battle gore. END
BEGIN NOW Like Hercules himself his son appears, END
BEGIN NOW In salvage pomp; a lion's hide he wears; END
BEGIN NOW About his shoulders hangs the shaggy skin; END
BEGIN NOW The teeth and gaping jaws severely grin. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, like the god his father, homely dress'd, END
BEGIN NOW He strides into the hall, a horrid guest. END
BEGIN NOW Then two twin brothers from fair Tibur came, END
BEGIN NOW (Which from their brother Tiburs took the name,) END
BEGIN NOW Fierce Coras and Catillus, void of fear: END
BEGIN NOW Arm'd Argive horse they led, and in the front appear. END
BEGIN NOW Like cloud-born Centaurs, from the mountain's height END
BEGIN NOW With rapid course descending to the fight; END
BEGIN NOW They rush along; the rattling woods give way; END
BEGIN NOW The branches bend before their sweepy sway. END
BEGIN NOW Nor was Praeneste's founder wanting there, END
BEGIN NOW Whom fame reports the son of Mulciber: END
BEGIN NOW Found in the fire, and foster'd in the plains, END
BEGIN NOW A shepherd and a king at once he reigns, END
BEGIN NOW And leads to Turnus' aid his country swains. END
BEGIN NOW His own Praeneste sends a chosen band, END
BEGIN NOW With those who plow Saturnia's Gabine land; END
BEGIN NOW Besides the succor which cold Anien yields, END
BEGIN NOW The rocks of Hernicus, and dewy fields, END
BEGIN NOW Anagnia fat, and Father Amasene- END
BEGIN NOW A num'rous rout, but all of naked men: END
BEGIN NOW Nor arms they wear, nor swords and bucklers wield, END
BEGIN NOW Nor drive the chariot thro' the dusty field, END
BEGIN NOW But whirl from leathern slings huge balls of lead, END
BEGIN NOW And spoils of yellow wolves adorn their head; END
BEGIN NOW The left foot naked, when they march to fight, END
BEGIN NOW But in a bull's raw hide they sheathe the right. END
BEGIN NOW Messapus next, (great Neptune was his sire,) END
BEGIN NOW Secure of steel, and fated from the fire, END
BEGIN NOW In pomp appears, and with his ardor warms END
BEGIN NOW A heartless train, unexercis'd in arms: END
BEGIN NOW The just Faliscans he to battle brings, END
BEGIN NOW And those who live where Lake Ciminia springs; END
BEGIN NOW And where Feronia's grove and temple stands, END
BEGIN NOW Who till Fescennian or Flavinian lands. END
BEGIN NOW All these in order march, and marching sing END
BEGIN NOW The warlike actions of their sea-born king; END
BEGIN NOW Like a long team of snowy swans on high, END
BEGIN NOW Which clap their wings, and cleave the liquid sky, END
BEGIN NOW When, homeward from their wat'ry pastures borne, END
BEGIN NOW They sing, and Asia's lakes their notes return. END
BEGIN NOW Not one who heard their music from afar, END
BEGIN NOW Would think these troops an army train'd to war, END
BEGIN NOW But flocks of fowl, that, when the tempests roar, END
BEGIN NOW With their hoarse gabbling seek the silent shore. END
BEGIN NOW Then Clausus came, who led a num'rous band END
BEGIN NOW Of troops embodied from the Sabine land, END
BEGIN NOW And, in himself alone, an army brought. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was he, the noble Claudian race begot, END
BEGIN NOW The Claudian race, ordain'd, in times to come, END
BEGIN NOW To share the greatness of imperial Rome. END
BEGIN NOW He led the Cures forth, of old renown, END
BEGIN NOW Mutuscans from their olive-bearing town, END
BEGIN NOW And all th' Eretian pow'rs; besides a band END
BEGIN NOW That follow'd from Velinum's dewy land, END
BEGIN NOW And Amiternian troops, of mighty fame, END
BEGIN NOW And mountaineers, that from Severus came, END
BEGIN NOW And from the craggy cliffs of Tetrica, END
BEGIN NOW And those where yellow Tiber takes his way, END
BEGIN NOW And where Himella's wanton waters play. END
BEGIN NOW Casperia sends her arms, with those that lie END
BEGIN NOW By Fabaris, and fruitful Foruli: END
BEGIN NOW The warlike aids of Horta next appear, END
BEGIN NOW And the cold Nursians come to close the rear, END
BEGIN NOW Mix'd with the natives born of Latine blood, END
BEGIN NOW Whom Allia washes with her fatal flood. END
BEGIN NOW Not thicker billows beat the Libyan main, END
BEGIN NOW When pale Orion sets in wintry rain; END
BEGIN NOW Nor thicker harvests on rich Hermus rise, END
BEGIN NOW Or Lycian fields, when Phoebus burns the skies, END
BEGIN NOW Than stand these troops: their bucklers ring around; END
BEGIN NOW Their trampling turns the turf, and shakes the solid ground. END
BEGIN NOW High in his chariot then Halesus came, END
BEGIN NOW A foe by birth to Troy's unhappy name: END
BEGIN NOW From Agamemnon born- to Turnus' aid END
BEGIN NOW A thousand men the youthful hero led, END
BEGIN NOW Who till the Massic soil, for wine renown'd, END
BEGIN NOW And fierce Auruncans from their hilly ground, END
BEGIN NOW And those who live by Sidicinian shores, END
BEGIN NOW And where with shoaly fords Vulturnus roars, END
BEGIN NOW Cales' and Osca's old inhabitants, END
BEGIN NOW And rough Saticulans, inur'd to wants: END
BEGIN NOW Light demi-lances from afar they throw, END
BEGIN NOW Fasten'd with leathern thongs, to gall the foe. END
BEGIN NOW Short crooked swords in closer fight they wear; END
BEGIN NOW And on their warding arm light bucklers bear. END
BEGIN NOW Nor Oebalus, shalt thou be left unsung, END
BEGIN NOW From nymph Semethis and old Telon sprung, END
BEGIN NOW Who then in Teleboan Capri reign'd; END
BEGIN NOW But that short isle th' ambitious youth disdain'd, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er Campania stretch'd his ample sway, END
BEGIN NOW Where swelling Sarnus seeks the Tyrrhene sea; END
BEGIN NOW O'er Batulum, and where Abella sees, END
BEGIN NOW From her high tow'rs, the harvest of her trees. END
BEGIN NOW And these (as was the Teuton use of old) END
BEGIN NOW Wield brazen swords, and brazen bucklers hold; END
BEGIN NOW Sling weighty stones, when from afar they fight; END
BEGIN NOW Their casques are cork, a covering thick and light. END
BEGIN NOW Next these in rank, the warlike Ufens went, END
BEGIN NOW And led the mountain troops that Nursia sent. END
BEGIN NOW The rude Equicolae his rule obey'd; END
BEGIN NOW Hunting their sport, and plund'ring was their trade. END
BEGIN NOW In arms they plow'd, to battle still prepar'd: END
BEGIN NOW Their soil was barren, and their hearts were hard. END
BEGIN NOW Umbro the priest the proud Marrubians led, END
BEGIN NOW By King Archippus sent to Turnus' aid, END
BEGIN NOW And peaceful olives crown'd his hoary head. END
BEGIN NOW His wand and holy words, the viper's rage, END
BEGIN NOW And venom'd wounds of serpents could assuage. END
BEGIN NOW He, when he pleas'd with powerful juice to steep END
BEGIN NOW Their temples, shut their eyes in pleasing sleep. END
BEGIN NOW But vain were Marsian herbs, and magic art, END
BEGIN NOW To cure the wound giv'n by the Dardan dart: END
BEGIN NOW Yet his untimely fate th' Angitian woods END
BEGIN NOW In sighs remurmur'd to the Fucine floods. END
BEGIN NOW The son of fam'd Hippolytus was there, END
BEGIN NOW Fam'd as his sire, and, as his mother, fair; END
BEGIN NOW Whom in Egerian groves Aricia bore, END
BEGIN NOW And nurs'd his youth along the marshy shore, END
BEGIN NOW Where great Diana's peaceful altars flame, END
BEGIN NOW In fruitful fields; and Virbius was his name. END
BEGIN NOW Hippolytus, as old records have said, END
BEGIN NOW Was by his stepdam sought to share her bed; END
BEGIN NOW But, when no female arts his mind could move, END
BEGIN NOW She turn'd to furious hate her impious love. END
BEGIN NOW Torn by wild horses on the sandy shore, END
BEGIN NOW Another's crimes th' unhappy hunter bore, END
BEGIN NOW Glutting his father's eyes with guiltless gore. END
BEGIN NOW But chaste Diana, who his death deplor'd, END
BEGIN NOW With Aesculapian herbs his life restor'd. END
BEGIN NOW Then Jove, who saw from high, with just disdain, END
BEGIN NOW The dead inspir'd with vital breath again, END
BEGIN NOW Struck to the center, with his flaming dart, END
BEGIN NOW Th' unhappy founder of the godlike art. END
BEGIN NOW But Trivia kept in secret shades alone END
BEGIN NOW Her care, Hippolytus, to fate unknown; END
BEGIN NOW And call'd him Virbius in th' Egerian grove, END
BEGIN NOW Where then he liv'd obscure, but safe from Jove. END
BEGIN NOW For this, from Trivia's temple and her wood END
BEGIN NOW Are coursers driv'n, who shed their master's blood, END
BEGIN NOW Affrighted by the monsters of the flood. END
BEGIN NOW His son, the second Virbius, yet retain'd END
BEGIN NOW His father's art, and warrior steeds he rein'd. END
BEGIN NOW Amid the troops, and like the leading god, END
BEGIN NOW High o'er the rest in arms the graceful Turnus rode: END
BEGIN NOW A triple of plumes his crest adorn'd, END
BEGIN NOW On which with belching flames Chimaera burn'd: END
BEGIN NOW The more the kindled combat rises high'r, END
BEGIN NOW The more with fury burns the blazing fire. END
BEGIN NOW Fair Io grac'd his shield; but Io now END
BEGIN NOW With horns exalted stands, and seems to low- END
BEGIN NOW A noble charge! Her keeper by her side, END
BEGIN NOW To watch her walks, his hundred eyes applied; END
BEGIN NOW And on the brims her sire, the wat'ry god, END
BEGIN NOW Roll'd from a silver urn his crystal flood. END
BEGIN NOW A cloud of foot succeeds, and fills the fields END
BEGIN NOW With swords, and pointed spears, and clatt'ring shields; END
BEGIN NOW Of Argives, and of old Sicanian bands, END
BEGIN NOW And those who plow the rich Rutulian lands; END
BEGIN NOW Auruncan youth, and those Sacrana yields, END
BEGIN NOW And the proud Labicans, with painted shields, END
BEGIN NOW And those who near Numician streams reside, END
BEGIN NOW And those whom Tiber's holy forests hide, END
BEGIN NOW Or Circe's hills from the main land divide; END
BEGIN NOW Where Ufens glides along the lowly lands, END
BEGIN NOW Or the black water of Pomptina stands. END
BEGIN NOW Last, from the Volscians fair Camilla came, END
BEGIN NOW And led her warlike troops, a warrior dame; END
BEGIN NOW Unbred to spinning, in the loom unskill'd, END
BEGIN NOW She chose the nobler Pallas of the field. END
BEGIN NOW Mix'd with the first, the fierce virago fought, END
BEGIN NOW Sustain'd the toils of arms, the danger sought, END
BEGIN NOW Outstripp'd the winds in speed upon the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Flew o'er the fields, nor hurt the bearded grain: END
BEGIN NOW She swept the seas, and, as she skimm'd along, END
BEGIN NOW Her flying feet unbath'd on billows hung. END
BEGIN NOW Men, boys, and women, stupid with surprise, END
BEGIN NOW Where'er she passes, fix their wond'ring eyes: END
BEGIN NOW Longing they look, and, gaping at the sight, END
BEGIN NOW Devour her o'er and o'er with vast delight; END
BEGIN NOW Her purple habit sits with such a grace END
BEGIN NOW On her smooth shoulders, and so suits her face; END
BEGIN NOW Her head with ringlets of her hair is crown'd, END
BEGIN NOW And in a golden caul the curls are bound. END
BEGIN NOW She shakes her myrtle jav'lin; and, behind, END
BEGIN NOW Her Lycian quiver dances in the wind. END
BEGIN NOW When Turnus had assembled all his pow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW His standard planted on Laurentum's tow'rs; END
BEGIN NOW When now the sprightly trumpet, from afar, END
BEGIN NOW Had giv'n the signal of approaching war, END
BEGIN NOW Had rous'd the neighing steeds to scour the fields, END
BEGIN NOW While the fierce riders clatter'd on their shields; END
BEGIN NOW Trembling with rage, the Latian youth prepare END
BEGIN NOW To join th' allies, and headlong rush to war. END
BEGIN NOW Fierce Ufens, and Messapus, led the crowd, END
BEGIN NOW With bold Mezentius, who blasphem'd aloud. END
BEGIN NOW These thro' the country took their wasteful course, END
BEGIN NOW The fields to forage, and to gather force. END
BEGIN NOW Then Venulus to Diomede they send, END
BEGIN NOW To beg his aid Ausonia to defend, END
BEGIN NOW Declare the common danger, and inform END
BEGIN NOW The Grecian leader of the growing storm: END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas, landed on the Latian coast, END
BEGIN NOW With banish'd gods, and with a baffled host, END
BEGIN NOW Yet now aspir'd to conquest of the state, END
BEGIN NOW And claim'd a title from the gods and fate; END
BEGIN NOW What num'rous nations in his quarrel came, END
BEGIN NOW And how they spread his formidable name. END
BEGIN NOW What he design'd, what mischief might arise, END
BEGIN NOW If fortune favor'd his first enterprise, END
BEGIN NOW Was left for him to weigh, whose equal fears, END
BEGIN NOW And common interest, was involv'd in theirs. END
BEGIN NOW While Turnus and th' allies thus urge the war, END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan, floating in a flood of care, END
BEGIN NOW Beholds the tempest which his foes prepare. END
BEGIN NOW This way and that he turns his anxious mind; END
BEGIN NOW Thinks, and rejects the counsels he design'd; END
BEGIN NOW Explores himself in vain, in ev'ry part, END
BEGIN NOW And gives no rest to his distracted heart. END
BEGIN NOW So, when the sun by day, or moon by night, END
BEGIN NOW Strike on the polish'd brass their trembling light, END
BEGIN NOW The glitt'ring species here and there divide, END
BEGIN NOW And cast their dubious beams from side to side; END
BEGIN NOW Now on the walls, now on the pavement play, END
BEGIN NOW And to the ceiling flash the glaring day. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was night; and weary nature lull'd asleep END
BEGIN NOW The birds of air, and fishes of the deep, END
BEGIN NOW And beasts, and mortal men. The Trojan chief END
BEGIN NOW Was laid on Tiber's banks, oppress'd with grief, END
BEGIN NOW And found in silent slumber late relief. END
BEGIN NOW Then, thro' the shadows of the poplar wood, END
BEGIN NOW Arose the father of the Roman flood; END
BEGIN NOW An azure robe was o'er his body spread, END
BEGIN NOW A wreath of shady reeds adorn'd his head: END
BEGIN NOW Thus, manifest to sight, the god appear'd, END
BEGIN NOW And with these pleasing words his sorrow cheer'd: END
BEGIN NOW Undoubted offspring of ethereal race, END
BEGIN NOW O long expected in this promis'd place! END
BEGIN NOW Who thro' the foes hast borne thy banish'd gods, END
BEGIN NOW Restor'd them to their hearths, and old abodes; END
BEGIN NOW This is thy happy home, the clime where fate END
BEGIN NOW Ordains thee to restore the Trojan state. END
BEGIN NOW Fear not! The war shall end in lasting peace, END
BEGIN NOW And all the rage of haughty Juno cease. END
BEGIN NOW And that this nightly vision may not seem END
BEGIN NOW Th' effect of fancy, or an idle dream, END
BEGIN NOW A sow beneath an oak shall lie along, END
BEGIN NOW All white herself, and white her thirty young. END
BEGIN NOW When thirty rolling years have run their race, END
BEGIN NOW Thy son Ascanius, on this empty space, END
BEGIN NOW Shall build a royal town, of lasting fame, END
BEGIN NOW Which from this omen shall receive the name. END
BEGIN NOW Time shall approve the truth. For what remains, END
BEGIN NOW And how with sure success to crown thy pains, END
BEGIN NOW With patience next attend. A banish'd band, END
BEGIN NOW Driv'n with Evander from th' Arcadian land, END
BEGIN NOW Have planted here, and plac'd on high their walls; END
BEGIN NOW Their town the founder Pallanteum calls, END
BEGIN NOW Deriv'd from Pallas, his great-grandsire's name: END
BEGIN NOW But the fierce Latians old possession claim, END
BEGIN NOW With war infesting the new colony. END
BEGIN NOW These make thy friends, and on their aid rely. END
BEGIN NOW To thy free passage I submit my streams. END
BEGIN NOW Wake, son of Venus, from thy pleasing dreams; END
BEGIN NOW And, when the setting stars are lost in day, END
BEGIN NOW To Juno's pow'r thy just devotion pay; END
BEGIN NOW With sacrifice the wrathful queen appease: END
BEGIN NOW Her pride at length shall fall, her fury cease. END
BEGIN NOW When thou return'st victorious from the war, END
BEGIN NOW Perform thy vows to me with grateful care. END
BEGIN NOW The god am I, whose yellow water flows END
BEGIN NOW Around these fields, and fattens as it goes: END
BEGIN NOW Tiber my name; among the rolling floods END
BEGIN NOW Renown'd on earth, esteem'd among the gods. END
BEGIN NOW This is my certain seat. In times to come, END
BEGIN NOW My waves shall wash the walls of mighty Rome. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and plung'd below. While yet he spoke, END
BEGIN NOW His dream Aeneas and his sleep forsook. END
BEGIN NOW He rose, and looking up, beheld the skies END
BEGIN NOW With purple blushing, and the day arise. END
BEGIN NOW Then water in his hollow palm he took END
BEGIN NOW From Tiber's flood, and thus the pow'rs bespoke: END
BEGIN NOW Laurentian nymphs, by whom the streams are fed, END
BEGIN NOW And Father Tiber, in thy sacred bed END
BEGIN NOW Receive Aeneas, and from danger keep. END
BEGIN NOW Whatever fount, whatever holy deep, END
BEGIN NOW Conceals thy wat'ry stores; where'er they rise, END
BEGIN NOW And, bubbling from below, salute the skies; END
BEGIN NOW Thou, king of horned floods, whose plenteous urn END
BEGIN NOW Suffices fatness to the fruitful corn, END
BEGIN NOW For this thy kind compassion of our woes, END
BEGIN NOW Shalt share my morning song and ev'ning vows. END
BEGIN NOW But, O be present to thy people's aid, END
BEGIN NOW And firm the gracious promise thou hast made! END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, two galleys from his stores, END
BEGIN NOW With care he chooses, mans, and fits with oars. END
BEGIN NOW Now on the shore the fatal swine is found. END
BEGIN NOW Wondrous to tell!- She lay along the ground: END
BEGIN NOW Her well-fed offspring at her udders hung; END
BEGIN NOW She white herself, and white her thirty young. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas takes the mother and her brood, END
BEGIN NOW And all on Juno's altar are bestow'd. END
BEGIN NOW The foll'wing night, and the succeeding day, END
BEGIN NOW Propitious Tiber smooth'd his wat'ry way: END
BEGIN NOW He roll'd his river back, and pois'd he stood, END
BEGIN NOW A gentle swelling, and a peaceful flood. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans mount their ships; they put from shore, END
BEGIN NOW Borne on the waves, and scarcely dip an oar. END
BEGIN NOW Shouts from the land give omen to their course, END
BEGIN NOW And the pitch'd vessels glide with easy force. END
BEGIN NOW The woods and waters wonder at the gleam END
BEGIN NOW Of shields, and painted ships that stem the stream. END
BEGIN NOW One summer's night and one whole day they pass END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the greenwood shades, and cut the liquid glass. END
BEGIN NOW The fiery sun had finish'd half his race, END
BEGIN NOW Look'd back, and doubted in the middle space, END
BEGIN NOW When they from far beheld the rising tow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW The tops of sheds, and shepherds' lowly bow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW Thin as they stood, which, then of homely clay, END
BEGIN NOW Now rise in marble, from the Roman sway. END
BEGIN NOW These cots (Evander's kingdom, mean and poor) END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan saw, and turn'd his ships to shore. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was on a solemn day: th' Arcadian states, END
BEGIN NOW The king and prince, without the city gates, END
BEGIN NOW Then paid their off'rings in a sacred grove END
BEGIN NOW To Hercules, the warrior son of Jove. END
BEGIN NOW Thick clouds of rolling smoke involve the skies, END
BEGIN NOW And fat of entrails on his altar fries. END
BEGIN NOW But, when they saw the ships that stemm'd the flood, END
BEGIN NOW And glitter'd thro' the covert of the wood, END
BEGIN NOW They rose with fear, and left th' unfinish'd feast, END
BEGIN NOW Till dauntless Pallas reassur'd the rest END
BEGIN NOW To pay the rites. Himself without delay END
BEGIN NOW A jav'lin seiz'd, and singly took his way; END
BEGIN NOW Then gain'd a rising ground, and call'd from far: END
BEGIN NOW Resolve me, strangers, whence, and what you are; END
BEGIN NOW Your bus'ness here; and bring you peace or war? END
BEGIN NOW High on the stern Aeneas his stand, END
BEGIN NOW And held a branch of olive in his hand, END
BEGIN NOW While thus he spoke: "The Phrygians' arms you see, END
BEGIN NOW Expell'd from Troy, provok'd in Italy END
BEGIN NOW By Latian foes, with war unjustly made; END
BEGIN NOW At first affianc'd, and at last betray'd. END
BEGIN NOW This message bear: 'The Trojans and their chief END
BEGIN NOW Bring holy peace, and beg the king's relief.' END
BEGIN NOW Struck with so great a name, and all on fire, END
BEGIN NOW The youth replies: "Whatever you require, END
BEGIN NOW Your fame exacts. Upon our shores descend. END
BEGIN NOW A welcome guest, and, what you wish, a friend. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and, downward hasting to the strand, END
BEGIN NOW Embrac'd the stranger prince, and join'd his hand. END
BEGIN NOW Conducted to the grove, Aeneas broke END
BEGIN NOW The silence first, and thus the king bespoke: END
BEGIN NOW Best of the Greeks, to whom, by fate's command, END
BEGIN NOW I bear these peaceful branches in my hand, END
BEGIN NOW Undaunted I approach you, tho' I know END
BEGIN NOW Your birth is Grecian, and your land my foe; END
BEGIN NOW From Atreus tho' your ancient lineage came, END
BEGIN NOW And both the brother kings your kindred claim; END
BEGIN NOW Yet, my self-conscious worth, your high renown, END
BEGIN NOW Your virtue, thro' the neighb'ring nations blown, END
BEGIN NOW Our fathers' mingled blood, Apollo's voice, END
BEGIN NOW Have led me hither, less by need than choice. END
BEGIN NOW Our founder Dardanus, as fame has sung, END
BEGIN NOW And Greeks acknowledge, from Electra sprung: END
BEGIN NOW Electra from the loins of Atlas came; END
BEGIN NOW Atlas, whose head sustains the starry frame. END
BEGIN NOW Your sire is Mercury, whom long before END
BEGIN NOW On cold Cyllene's top fair Maia bore. END
BEGIN NOW Maia the fair, on fame if we rely, END
BEGIN NOW Was Atlas' daughter, who sustains the sky. END
BEGIN NOW Thus from one common source our streams divide; END
BEGIN NOW Ours is the Trojan, yours th' Areadian side. END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd by these hopes, I sent no news before, END
BEGIN NOW Nor ask'd your leave, nor did your faith implore; END
BEGIN NOW But come, without a pledge, my own ambassador. END
BEGIN NOW The same Rutulians, who with arms pursue END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan race, are equal foes to you. END
BEGIN NOW Our host expell'd, what farther force can stay END
BEGIN NOW The victor troops from universal sway? END
BEGIN NOW Then will they stretch their pow'r athwart the land, END
BEGIN NOW And either sea from side to side command. END
BEGIN NOW Receive our offer'd faith, and give us thine; END
BEGIN NOW Ours is a gen'rous and experienc'd line: END
BEGIN NOW We want not hearts nor bodies for the war; END
BEGIN NOW In council cautious, and in fields we dare. END
BEGIN NOW He said; and while spoke, with piercing eyes END
BEGIN NOW Evander view'd the man with vast surprise, END
BEGIN NOW Pleas'd with his action, ravish'd with his face: END
BEGIN NOW Then answer'd briefly, with a royal grace: END
BEGIN NOW O valiant leader of the Trojan line, END
BEGIN NOW In whom the features of thy father shine, END
BEGIN NOW How I recall Anchises! how I see END
BEGIN NOW His motions, mien, and all my friend, in thee! END
BEGIN NOW Long tho' it be, 't is fresh within my mind, END
BEGIN NOW When Priam to his sister's court design'd END
BEGIN NOW A welcome visit, with a friendly stay, END
BEGIN NOW And thro' th' Arcadian kingdom took his way. END
BEGIN NOW Then, past a boy, the callow down began END
BEGIN NOW To shade my chin, and call me first a man. END
BEGIN NOW I saw the shining train with vast delight, END
BEGIN NOW And Priam's goodly person pleas'd my sight: END
BEGIN NOW But great Anchises, far above the rest, END
BEGIN NOW With awful wonder fir'd my youthful breast. END
BEGIN NOW I long'd to join in friendship's holy bands END
BEGIN NOW Our mutual hearts, and plight our mutual hands. END
BEGIN NOW I first accosted him: I sued, I sought, END
BEGIN NOW And, with a loving force, to Pheneus brought. END
BEGIN NOW He gave me, when at length constrain'd to go, END
BEGIN NOW A Lycian quiver and a Gnossian bow, END
BEGIN NOW A vest embroider'd, glorious to behold, END
BEGIN NOW And two rich bridles, with their bits of gold, END
BEGIN NOW Which my son's coursers in obedience hold. END
BEGIN NOW The league you ask, I offer, as your right; END
BEGIN NOW And, when to-morrow's sun reveals the light, END
BEGIN NOW With swift supplies you shall be sent away. END
BEGIN NOW Now celebrate with us this solemn day, END
BEGIN NOW Whose holy rites admit no long delay. END
BEGIN NOW Honor our annual feast; and take your seat, END
BEGIN NOW With friendly welcome, at a homely treat. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, the bowls (remov'd for fear) END
BEGIN NOW The youths replac'd, and soon restor'd the cheer. END
BEGIN NOW On sods of turf he set the soldiers round: END
BEGIN NOW A maple throne, rais'd higher from the ground, END
BEGIN NOW Receiv'd the Trojan chief; and, o'er the bed, END
BEGIN NOW A lion's shaggy hide for ornament they spread. END
BEGIN NOW The loaves were serv'd in canisters; the wine END
BEGIN NOW In bowls; the priest renew'd the rites divine: END
BEGIN NOW Broil'd entrails are their food, and beef's continued chine. END
BEGIN NOW But when the rage of hunger was repress'd, END
BEGIN NOW Thus spoke Evander to his royal guest: END
BEGIN NOW These rites, these altars, and this feast, O king, END
BEGIN NOW From no vain fears or superstition spring, END
BEGIN NOW Or blind devotion, or from blinder chance, END
BEGIN NOW Or heady zeal, or brutal ignorance; END
BEGIN NOW But, sav'd from danger, with a grateful sense, END
BEGIN NOW The labors of a god we recompense. END
BEGIN NOW See, from afar, yon rock that mates the sky, END
BEGIN NOW About whose feet such heaps of rubbish lie; END
BEGIN NOW Such indigested ruin; bleak and bare, END
BEGIN NOW How desart now it stands, expos'd in air! END
BEGIN NOW 'T was once a robber's den, inclos'd around END
BEGIN NOW With living stone, and deep beneath the ground. END
BEGIN NOW The monster Cacus, more than half a beast, END
BEGIN NOW This hold, impervious to the sun, possess'd. END
BEGIN NOW The pavement ever foul with human gore; END
BEGIN NOW Heads, and their mangled members, hung the door. END
BEGIN NOW Vulcan this plague begot; and, like his sire, END
BEGIN NOW Black clouds he belch'd, and flakes of livid fire. END
BEGIN NOW Time, long expected, eas'd us of our load, END
BEGIN NOW And brought the needful presence of a god. END
BEGIN NOW Th' avenging force of Hercules, from Spain, END
BEGIN NOW Arriv'd in triumph, from Geryon slain: END
BEGIN NOW Thrice liv'd the giant, and thrice liv'd in vain. END
BEGIN NOW His prize, the lowing herds, Alcides drove END
BEGIN NOW Near Tiber's bank, to graze the shady grove. END
BEGIN NOW Allur'd with hope of plunder, and intent END
BEGIN NOW By force to rob, by fraud to circumvent, END
BEGIN NOW The brutal Cacus, as by chance they stray'd, END
BEGIN NOW Four oxen thence, and four fair kine convey'd; END
BEGIN NOW And, lest the printed footsteps might be seen, END
BEGIN NOW He dragg'd 'em backwards to his rocky den. END
BEGIN NOW The tracks averse a lying notice gave, END
BEGIN NOW And led the searcher backward from the cave. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the herdsman hero shifts his place, END
BEGIN NOW To find fresh pasture and untrodden grass. END
BEGIN NOW The beasts, who miss'd their mates, fill'd all around END
BEGIN NOW With bellowings, and the rocks restor'd the sound. END
BEGIN NOW One heifer, who had heard her love complain, END
BEGIN NOW Roar'd from the cave, and made the project vain. END
BEGIN NOW Alcides found the fraud; with rage he shook, END
BEGIN NOW And toss'd about his head his knotted oak. END
BEGIN NOW Swift as the winds, or Scythian arrows' flight, END
BEGIN NOW He clomb, with eager haste, th' aerial height. END
BEGIN NOW Then first we saw the monster mend his pace; END
BEGIN NOW Fear his eyes, and paleness in his face, END
BEGIN NOW Confess'd the god's approach. Trembling he springs, END
BEGIN NOW As terror had increas'd his feet with wings; END
BEGIN NOW Nor stay'd for stairs; but down the depth he threw END
BEGIN NOW His body, on his back the door he drew END
BEGIN NOW (The door, a rib of living rock; with pains END
BEGIN NOW His father hew'd it out, and bound with iron chains): END
BEGIN NOW He broke the heavy links, the mountain clos'd, END
BEGIN NOW And bars and levers to his foe oppos'd. END
BEGIN NOW The wretch had hardly made his dungeon fast; END
BEGIN NOW The fierce avenger came with bounding haste; END
BEGIN NOW Survey'd the mouth of the forbidden hold, END
BEGIN NOW And here and there his raging eyes he roll'd. END
BEGIN NOW He gnash'd his teeth; and thrice he compass'd round END
BEGIN NOW With winged speed the circuit of the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Thrice at the cavern's mouth he pull'd in vain, END
BEGIN NOW And, panting, thrice desisted from his pain. END
BEGIN NOW A pointed flinty rock, all bare and black, END
BEGIN NOW Grew gibbous from behind the mountain's back; END
BEGIN NOW Owls, ravens, all ill omens of the night, END
BEGIN NOW Here built their nests, and hither wing'd their flight. END
BEGIN NOW The leaning head hung threat'ning o'er the flood, END
BEGIN NOW And nodded to the left. The hero stood END
BEGIN NOW Adverse, with planted feet, and, from the right, END
BEGIN NOW Tugg'd at the solid stone with all his might. END
BEGIN NOW Thus heav'd, the fix'd foundations of the rock END
BEGIN NOW Gave way; heav'n echo'd at the rattling shock. END
BEGIN NOW Tumbling, it chok'd the flood: on either side END
BEGIN NOW The banks leap backward, and the streams divide; END
BEGIN NOW The sky shrunk upward with unusual dread, END
BEGIN NOW And trembling Tiber div'd beneath his bed. END
BEGIN NOW The court of Cacus stands reveal'd to sight; END
BEGIN NOW The cavern glares with new-admitted light. END
BEGIN NOW So the pent vapors, with a rumbling sound, END
BEGIN NOW Heave from below, and rend the hollow ground; END
BEGIN NOW A sounding flaw succeeds; and, from on high, END
BEGIN NOW The gods with hate beheld the nether sky: END
BEGIN NOW The ghosts repine at violated night, END
BEGIN NOW And curse th' invading sun, and sicken at the sight. END
BEGIN NOW The graceless monster, caught in open day, END
BEGIN NOW Inclos'd, and in despair to fly away, END
BEGIN NOW Howls horrible from underneath, and fills END
BEGIN NOW His hollow palace with unmanly yells. END
BEGIN NOW The hero stands above, and from afar END
BEGIN NOW Plies him with darts, and stones, and distant war. END
BEGIN NOW He, from his nostrils huge mouth, expires END
BEGIN NOW Black clouds of smoke, amidst his father's fires, END
BEGIN NOW Gath'ring, with each repeated blast, the night, END
BEGIN NOW To make uncertain aim, and erring sight. END
BEGIN NOW The wrathful god then plunges from above, END
BEGIN NOW And, where in thickest waves the sparkles drove, END
BEGIN NOW There lights; and wades thro' fumes, and gropes his way, END
BEGIN NOW Half sing'd, half stifled, till he grasps his prey. END
BEGIN NOW The monster, spewing fruitless flames, he found; END
BEGIN NOW He squeez'd his throat; he writh'd his neck around, END
BEGIN NOW And in a knot his crippled members bound; END
BEGIN NOW Then from their sockets tore his burning eyes: END
BEGIN NOW Roll'd on a heap, the breathless robber lies. END
BEGIN NOW The doors, unbarr'd, receive the rushing day, END
BEGIN NOW And thoro' lights disclose the ravish'd prey. END
BEGIN NOW The bulls, redeem'd, breathe open air again. END
BEGIN NOW Next, by the feet, they drag him from his den. END
BEGIN NOW The wond'ring neighborhood, with glad surprise, END
BEGIN NOW Behold his shagged breast, his giant size, END
BEGIN NOW His mouth that flames no more, and his extinguish'd eyes. END
BEGIN NOW From that auspicious day, with rites divine, END
BEGIN NOW We worship at the hero's holy shrine. END
BEGIN NOW Potitius first ordain'd these annual vows: END
BEGIN NOW As priests, were added the Pinarian house, END
BEGIN NOW Who rais'd this altar in the sacred shade, END
BEGIN NOW Where honors, ever due, for ever shall be paid. END
BEGIN NOW For these deserts, and this high virtue shown, END
BEGIN NOW Ye warlike youths, your heads with garlands crown: END
BEGIN NOW Fill high the goblets with a sparkling flood, END
BEGIN NOW And with deep draughts invoke our common god. END
BEGIN NOW This said, a double wreath Evander twin'd, END
BEGIN NOW And poplars black and white his temples bind. END
BEGIN NOW Then brims his ample bowl. With like design END
BEGIN NOW The rest invoke the gods, with sprinkled wine. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the sun descended from the skies, END
BEGIN NOW And the bright evening star began to rise. END
BEGIN NOW And now the priests, Potitius at their head, END
BEGIN NOW In skins of beasts involv'd, the long procession led; END
BEGIN NOW Held high the flaming tapers in their hands, END
BEGIN NOW As custom had prescrib'd their holy bands; END
BEGIN NOW Then with a second course the tables load, END
BEGIN NOW And with full chargers offer to the god. END
BEGIN NOW The Salii sing, and cense his altars round END
BEGIN NOW With Saban smoke, their heads with poplar bound- END
BEGIN NOW One choir of old, another of the young, END
BEGIN NOW To dance, and bear the burthen of the song. END
BEGIN NOW The lay records the labors, and the praise, END
BEGIN NOW And all th' immortal acts of Hercules: END
BEGIN NOW First, how the mighty babe, when swath'd in bands, END
BEGIN NOW The serpents strangled with his infant hands; END
BEGIN NOW Then, as in years and matchless force he grew, END
BEGIN NOW Th' Oechalian walls, and Trojan, overthrew. END
BEGIN NOW Besides, a thousand hazards they relate, END
BEGIN NOW Procur'd by Juno's and Eurystheus' hate: END
BEGIN NOW Thy hands, unconquer'd hero, could subdue END
BEGIN NOW The cloud-born Centaurs, and the monster crew: END
BEGIN NOW Nor thy resistless arm the bull withstood, END
BEGIN NOW Nor he, the roaring terror of the wood. END
BEGIN NOW The triple porter of the Stygian seat, END
BEGIN NOW With lolling tongue, lay fawning at thy feet, END
BEGIN NOW And, seiz'd with fear, forgot his mangled meat. END
BEGIN NOW Th' infernal waters trembled at thy sight; END
BEGIN NOW Thee, god, no face of danger could affright; END
BEGIN NOW Not huge Typhoeus, nor th' unnumber'd snake, END
BEGIN NOW Increas'd with hissing heads, in Lerna's lake. END
BEGIN NOW Hail, Jove's undoubted son! an added grace END
BEGIN NOW To heav'n and the great author of thy race! END
BEGIN NOW Receive the grateful off'rings which we pay, END
BEGIN NOW And smile propitious on thy solemn day! END
BEGIN NOW In numbers thus they sung; above the rest, END
BEGIN NOW The den and death of Cacus crown the feast. END
BEGIN NOW The woods to hollow vales convey the sound, END
BEGIN NOW The vales to hills, and hills the notes rebound. END
BEGIN NOW The rites perform'd, the cheerful train retire. END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt young Pallas and his aged sire, END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan pass'd, the city to survey, END
BEGIN NOW And pleasing talk beguil'd the tedious way. END
BEGIN NOW The stranger cast around his curious eyes, END
BEGIN NOW New objects viewing still, with new surprise; END
BEGIN NOW With greedy joy enquires of various things, END
BEGIN NOW And acts and monuments of ancient kings. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus the founder of the Roman tow'rs: END
BEGIN NOW These woods were first the seat of sylvan pow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW Of Nymphs and Fauns, and salvage men, who took END
BEGIN NOW Their birth from trunks of trees and stubborn oak. END
BEGIN NOW Nor laws they knew, nor manners, nor the care END
BEGIN NOW Of lab'ring oxen, or the shining share, END
BEGIN NOW Nor arts of gain, nor what they gain'd to spare. END
BEGIN NOW Their exercise the chase; the running flood END
BEGIN NOW Supplied their thirst, the trees supplied their food. END
BEGIN NOW Then Saturn came, who fled the pow'r of Jove, END
BEGIN NOW Robb'd of his realms, and banish'd from above. END
BEGIN NOW The men, dispers'd on hills, to towns he brought, END
BEGIN NOW And laws ordain'd, and civil customs taught, END
BEGIN NOW And Latium call'd the land where safe he lay END
BEGIN NOW From his unduteous son, and his usurping sway. END
BEGIN NOW With his mild empire, peace and plenty came; END
BEGIN NOW And hence the golden times deriv'd their name. END
BEGIN NOW A more degenerate and discolor'd age END
BEGIN NOW Succeeded this, with avarice and rage. END
BEGIN NOW Th' Ausonians then, and bold Sicanians came; END
BEGIN NOW And Saturn's empire often chang'd the name. END
BEGIN NOW Then kings, gigantic Tybris, and the rest, END
BEGIN NOW With arbitrary sway the land oppress'd: END
BEGIN NOW For Tiber's flood was Albula before, END
BEGIN NOW Till, from the tyrant's fate, his name it bore. END
BEGIN NOW I last arriv'd, driv'n from my native home END
BEGIN NOW By fortune's pow'r, and fate's resistless doom. END
BEGIN NOW Long toss'd on seas, I sought this happy land, END
BEGIN NOW Warn'd by my mother nymph, and call'd by Heav'n's command. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, walking on, he spoke, and shew'd the gate, END
BEGIN NOW Since call'd Carmental by the Roman state; END
BEGIN NOW Where stood an altar, sacred to the name END
BEGIN NOW Of old Carmenta, the prophetic dame, END
BEGIN NOW Who to her son foretold th' Aenean race, END
BEGIN NOW Sublime in fame, and Rome's imperial place: END
BEGIN NOW Then shews the forest, which, in after times, END
BEGIN NOW Fierce Romulus for perpetrated crimes END
BEGIN NOW A sacred refuge made; with this, the shrine END
BEGIN NOW Where Pan below the rock had rites divine: END
BEGIN NOW Then tells of Argus' death, his murder'd guest, END
BEGIN NOW Whose grave and tomb his innocence attest. END
BEGIN NOW Thence, to the steep Tarpeian rock he leads; END
BEGIN NOW Now roof'd with gold, then thatch'd with homely reeds. END
BEGIN NOW A reverent fear (such superstition reigns END
BEGIN NOW Among the rude) ev'n then possess'd the swains. END
BEGIN NOW Some god, they knew- what god, they could not tell- END
BEGIN NOW Did there amidst the sacred horror dwell. END
BEGIN NOW Th' Arcadians thought him Jove; and said they saw END
BEGIN NOW The mighty Thund'rer with majestic awe, END
BEGIN NOW Who took his shield, and dealt his bolts around, END
BEGIN NOW And scatter'd tempests on the teeming ground. END
BEGIN NOW Then saw two heaps of ruins, (once they stood END
BEGIN NOW Two stately towns, on either side the flood,) END
BEGIN NOW Saturnia's and Janicula's remains; END
BEGIN NOW And either place the founder's name retains. END
BEGIN NOW Discoursing thus together, they resort END
BEGIN NOW Where poor Evander kept his country court. END
BEGIN NOW They view'd the ground of Rome's litigious hall; END
BEGIN NOW (Once oxen low'd, where now the lawyers bawl;) END
BEGIN NOW Then, stooping, thro' the narrow gate they press'd, END
BEGIN NOW When thus the king bespoke his Trojan guest: END
BEGIN NOW Mean as it is, this palace, and this door, END
BEGIN NOW Receiv'd Alcides, then a conqueror. END
BEGIN NOW Dare to be poor; accept our homely food, END
BEGIN NOW Which feasted him, and emulate a god. END
BEGIN NOW Then underneath a lowly roof he led END
BEGIN NOW The weary prince, and laid him on a bed; END
BEGIN NOW The stuffing leaves, with hides of bears o'erspread. END
BEGIN NOW Now Night had shed her silver dews around, END
BEGIN NOW And with her sable wings embrac'd the ground, END
BEGIN NOW When love's fair goddess, anxious for her son, END
BEGIN NOW (New tumults rising, and new wars begun,) END
BEGIN NOW Couch'd with her husband in his golden bed, END
BEGIN NOW With these alluring words invokes his aid; END
BEGIN NOW And, that her pleasing speech his mind may move, END
BEGIN NOW Inspires each accent with the charms of love: END
BEGIN NOW While cruel fate conspir'd with Grecian pow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW To level with the ground the Trojan tow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW I ask'd not aid th' unhappy to restore, END
BEGIN NOW Nor did the succor of thy skill implore; END
BEGIN NOW Nor urg'd the labors of my lord in vain, END
BEGIN NOW A sinking empire longer to sustain, END
BEGIN NOW Tho'much I ow'd to Priam's house, and more END
BEGIN NOW The dangers of Aeneas did deplore. END
BEGIN NOW But now, by Jove's command, and fate's decree, END
BEGIN NOW His race is doom'd to reign in Italy: END
BEGIN NOW With humble suit I beg thy needful art, END
BEGIN NOW O still propitious pow'r, that rules my heart! END
BEGIN NOW A mother kneels a suppliant for her son. END
BEGIN NOW By Thetis and Aurora thou wert won END
BEGIN NOW To forge impenetrable shields, and grace END
BEGIN NOW With fated arms a less illustrious race. END
BEGIN NOW Behold, what haughty nations are combin'd END
BEGIN NOW Against the relics of the Phrygian kind, END
BEGIN NOW With fire and sword my people to destroy, END
BEGIN NOW And conquer Venus twice, in conqu'ring Troy. END
BEGIN NOW She said; and straight her arms, of snowy hue, END
BEGIN NOW About her unresolving husband threw. END
BEGIN NOW Her soft embraces soon infuse desire; END
BEGIN NOW His bones and marrow sudden warmth inspire; END
BEGIN NOW And all the godhead feels the wonted fire. END
BEGIN NOW Not half so swift the rattling thunder flies, END
BEGIN NOW Or forky lightnings flash along the skies. END
BEGIN NOW The goddess, proud of her successful wiles, END
BEGIN NOW And conscious of her form, in secret smiles. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus the pow'r, obnoxious to her charms, END
BEGIN NOW Panting, and half dissolving in her arms: END
BEGIN NOW Why seek you reasons for a cause so just, END
BEGIN NOW Or your own beauties or my love distrust? END
BEGIN NOW Long since, had you requir'd my helpful hand, END
BEGIN NOW Th' artificer and art you might command, END
BEGIN NOW To labor arms for Troy: nor Jove, nor fate, END
BEGIN NOW Confin'd their empire to so short a date. END
BEGIN NOW And, if you now desire new wars to wage, END
BEGIN NOW My skill I promise, and my pains engage. END
BEGIN NOW Whatever melting metals can conspire, END
BEGIN NOW Or breathing bellows, or the forming fire, END
BEGIN NOW Is freely yours: your anxious fears remove, END
BEGIN NOW And think no task is difficult to love. END
BEGIN NOW Trembling he spoke; and, eager of her charms, END
BEGIN NOW He snatch'd the willing goddess to his arms; END
BEGIN NOW Till in her lap infus'd, he lay possess'd END
BEGIN NOW Of full desire, and sunk to pleasing rest. END
BEGIN NOW Now when the Night her middle race had rode, END
BEGIN NOW And his first slumber had refresh'd the god- END
BEGIN NOW The time when early housewives leave the bed; END
BEGIN NOW When living embers on the hearth they spread, END
BEGIN NOW Supply the lamp, and call the maids to rise- END
BEGIN NOW With yawning mouths, and with half-open'd eyes, END
BEGIN NOW They ply the distaff by the winking light, END
BEGIN NOW And to their daily labor add the night: END
BEGIN NOW Thus frugally they earn their children's bread, END
BEGIN NOW And uncorrupted keep the nuptial bed- END
BEGIN NOW Not less concern'd, nor at a later hour, END
BEGIN NOW Rose from his downy couch the forging pow'r. END
BEGIN NOW Sacred to Vulcan's name, an isle there lay, END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt Sicilia's coasts and Lipare, END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd high on smoking rocks; and, deep below, END
BEGIN NOW In hollow caves the fires of Aetna glow. END
BEGIN NOW The Cyclops here their heavy hammers deal; END
BEGIN NOW Loud strokes, and hissings of tormented steel, END
BEGIN NOW Are heard around; the boiling waters roar, END
BEGIN NOW And smoky flames thro' fuming tunnels soar. END
BEGIN NOW Hether the Father of the Fire, by night, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' the brown air precipitates his flight. END
BEGIN NOW On their eternal anvils here he found END
BEGIN NOW The brethren beating, and the blows go round. END
BEGIN NOW A load of pointless thunder now there lies END
BEGIN NOW Before their hands, to ripen for the skies: END
BEGIN NOW These darts, for angry Jove, they daily cast; END
BEGIN NOW Consum'd on mortals with prodigious waste. END
BEGIN NOW Three rays of writhen rain, of fire three more, END
BEGIN NOW Of winged southern winds and cloudy store END
BEGIN NOW As many parts, the dreadful mixture frame; END
BEGIN NOW And fears are added, and avenging flame. END
BEGIN NOW Inferior ministers, for Mars, repair END
BEGIN NOW His broken axletrees and blunted war, END
BEGIN NOW And send him forth again with furbish'd arms, END
BEGIN NOW To wake the lazy war with trumpets' loud alarms. END
BEGIN NOW The rest refresh the scaly snakes that fold END
BEGIN NOW The shield of Pallas, and renew their gold. END
BEGIN NOW Full on the crest the Gorgon's head they place, END
BEGIN NOW With eyes that roll in death, and with distorted face. END
BEGIN NOW My sons," said Vulcan, "set your tasks aside; END
BEGIN NOW Your strength and master-skill must now be tried. END
BEGIN NOW Arms for a hero forge; arms that require END
BEGIN NOW Your force, your speed, and all your forming fire. END
BEGIN NOW He said. They set their former work aside, END
BEGIN NOW And their new toils with eager haste divide. END
BEGIN NOW A flood of molten silver, brass, and gold, END
BEGIN NOW And deadly steel, in the large furnace roll'd; END
BEGIN NOW Of this, their artful hands a shield prepare, END
BEGIN NOW Alone sufficient to sustain the war. END
BEGIN NOW Sev'n orbs within a spacious round they close: END
BEGIN NOW One stirs the fire, and one the bellows blows. END
BEGIN NOW The hissing steel is in the smithy drown'd; END
BEGIN NOW The grot with beaten anvils groans around. END
BEGIN NOW By turns their arms advance, in equal time; END
BEGIN NOW By turns their hands descend, and hammers chime. END
BEGIN NOW They turn the glowing mass with crooked tongs; END
BEGIN NOW The fiery work proceeds, with rustic songs. END
BEGIN NOW While, at the Lemnian god's command, they urge END
BEGIN NOW Their labors thus, and ply th' Aeolian forge, END
BEGIN NOW The cheerful morn salutes Evander's eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And songs of chirping birds invite to rise. END
BEGIN NOW He leaves his lowly bed: his buskins meet END
BEGIN NOW Above his ankles; sandals sheathe his feet: END
BEGIN NOW He sets his trusty sword upon his side, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er his shoulder throws a panther's hide. END
BEGIN NOW Two menial dogs before their master press'd. END
BEGIN NOW Thus clad, and guarded thus, he seeks his kingly guest. END
BEGIN NOW Mindful of promis'd aid, he mends his pace, END
BEGIN NOW But meets Aeneas in the middle space. END
BEGIN NOW Young Pallas did his father's steps attend, END
BEGIN NOW And true Achates waited on his friend. END
BEGIN NOW They join their hands; a secret seat they choose; END
BEGIN NOW Th' Arcadian first their former talk renews: END
BEGIN NOW Undaunted prince, I never can believe END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan empire lost, while you survive. END
BEGIN NOW Command th' assistance of a faithful friend; END
BEGIN NOW But feeble are the succors I can send. END
BEGIN NOW Our narrow kingdom here the Tiber bounds; END
BEGIN NOW That other side the Latian state surrounds, END
BEGIN NOW Insults our walls, and wastes our fruitful grounds. END
BEGIN NOW But mighty nations I prepare, to join END
BEGIN NOW Their arms with yours, and aid your just design. END
BEGIN NOW You come, as by your better genius sent, END
BEGIN NOW And fortune seems to favor your intent. END
BEGIN NOW Not far from hence there stands a hilly town, END
BEGIN NOW Of ancient building, and of high renown, END
BEGIN NOW Torn from the Tuscans by the Lydian race, END
BEGIN NOW Who gave the name of Caere to the place, END
BEGIN NOW Once Agyllina call'd. It flourish'd long, END
BEGIN NOW In pride of wealth and warlike people strong, END
BEGIN NOW Till curs'd Mezentius, in a fatal hour, END
BEGIN NOW Assum'd the crown, with arbitrary pow'r. END
BEGIN NOW What words can paint those execrable times, END
BEGIN NOW The subjects' suff'rings, and the tyrant's crimes! END
BEGIN NOW That blood, those murthers, O ye gods, replace END
BEGIN NOW On his own head, and on his impious race! END
BEGIN NOW The living and the dead at his command END
BEGIN NOW Were coupled, face to face, and hand to hand, END
BEGIN NOW Till, chok'd with stench, in loath'd embraces tied, END
BEGIN NOW The ling'ring wretches pin'd away and died. END
BEGIN NOW Thus plung'd in ills, and meditating more- END
BEGIN NOW The people's patience, tir'd, no longer bore END
BEGIN NOW The raging monster; but with arms beset END
BEGIN NOW His house, and vengeance and destruction threat. END
BEGIN NOW They fire his palace: while the flame ascends, END
BEGIN NOW They force his guards, and execute his friends. END
BEGIN NOW He cleaves the crowd, and, favor'd by the night, END
BEGIN NOW To Turnus' friendly court directs his flight. END
BEGIN NOW By just revenge the Tuscans set on fire, END
BEGIN NOW With arms, their king to punishment require: END
BEGIN NOW Their num'rous troops, now muster'd on the strand, END
BEGIN NOW My counsel shall submit to your command. END
BEGIN NOW Their navy swarms upon the coasts; they cry END
BEGIN NOW To hoist their anchors, but the gods deny. END
BEGIN NOW An ancient augur, skill'd in future fate, END
BEGIN NOW With these foreboding words restrains their hate: END
BEGIN NOW 'Ye brave in arms, ye Lydian blood, the flow'r END
BEGIN NOW Of Tuscan youth, and choice of all their pow'r, END
BEGIN NOW Whom just revenge against Mezentius arms, END
BEGIN NOW To seek your tyrant's death by lawful arms; END
BEGIN NOW Know this: no native of our land may lead END
BEGIN NOW This pow'rful people; seek a foreign head.' END
BEGIN NOW Aw'd with these words, in camps they still abide, END
BEGIN NOW And wait with longing looks their promis'd guide. END
BEGIN NOW Tarchon, the Tuscan chief, to me has sent END
BEGIN NOW Their crown, and ev'ry regal ornament: END
BEGIN NOW The people join their own with his desire; END
BEGIN NOW And all my conduct, as their king, require. END
BEGIN NOW But the chill blood that creeps within my veins, END
BEGIN NOW And age, and listless limbs unfit for pains, END
BEGIN NOW And a soul conscious of its own decay, END
BEGIN NOW Have forc'd me to refuse imperial sway. END
BEGIN NOW My Pallas were more fit to mount the throne, END
BEGIN NOW And should, but he's a Sabine mother's son, END
BEGIN NOW And half a native; but, in you, combine END
BEGIN NOW A manly vigor, and a foreign line. END
BEGIN NOW Where Fate and smiling Fortune shew the way, END
BEGIN NOW Pursue the ready path to sov'reign sway. END
BEGIN NOW The staff of my declining days, my son, END
BEGIN NOW Shall make your good or ill success his own; END
BEGIN NOW In fighting fields from you shall learn to dare, END
BEGIN NOW And serve the hard apprenticeship of war; END
BEGIN NOW Your matchless courage and your conduct view, END
BEGIN NOW And early shall begin t' admire and copy you. END
BEGIN NOW Besides, two hundred horse he shall command; END
BEGIN NOW Tho' few, a warlike and well-chosen band. END
BEGIN NOW These in my name are listed; and my son END
BEGIN NOW As many more has added in his own. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had he said; Achates and his guest, END
BEGIN NOW With downcast eyes, their silent grief express'd; END
BEGIN NOW Who, short of succors, and in deep despair, END
BEGIN NOW Shook at the dismal prospect of the war. END
BEGIN NOW But his bright mother, from a breaking cloud, END
BEGIN NOW To cheer her issue, thunder'd thrice aloud; END
BEGIN NOW Thrice forky lightning flash'd along the sky, END
BEGIN NOW And Tyrrhene trumpets thrice were heard on high. END
BEGIN NOW Then, gazing up, repeated peals they hear; END
BEGIN NOW And, in a heav'n serene, refulgent arms appear: END
BEGIN NOW Redd'ning the skies, and glitt'ring all around, END
BEGIN NOW The temper'd metals clash, and yield a silver sound. END
BEGIN NOW The rest stood trembling, struck with awe divine; END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas only, conscious to the sign, END
BEGIN NOW Presag'd th' event, and joyful view'd, above, END
BEGIN NOW Th' accomplish'd promise of the Queen of Love. END
BEGIN NOW Then, to th' Arcadian king: "This prodigy END
BEGIN NOW (Dismiss your fear) belongs alone to me. END
BEGIN NOW Heav'n calls me to the war: th' expected sign END
BEGIN NOW Is giv'n of promis'd aid, and arms divine. END
BEGIN NOW My goddess mother, whose indulgent care END
BEGIN NOW Foresaw the dangers of the growing war, END
BEGIN NOW This omen gave, when bright Vulcanian arms, END
BEGIN NOW Fated from force of steel by Stygian charms, END
BEGIN NOW Suspended, shone on high: she then foreshow'd END
BEGIN NOW Approaching fights, and fields to float in blood. END
BEGIN NOW Turnus shall dearly pay for faith forsworn; END
BEGIN NOW And corps, and swords, and shields, on Tiber borne, END
BEGIN NOW Shall choke his flood: now sound the loud alarms; END
BEGIN NOW And, Latian troops, prepare your perjur'd arms. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and, rising from his homely throne, END
BEGIN NOW The solemn rites of Hercules begun, END
BEGIN NOW And on his altars wak'd the sleeping fires; END
BEGIN NOW Then cheerful to his household gods retires; END
BEGIN NOW There offers chosen sheep. Th' Arcadian king END
BEGIN NOW And Trojan youth the same oblations bring. END
BEGIN NOW Next, of his men and ships he makes review; END
BEGIN NOW Draws out the best and ablest of the crew. END
BEGIN NOW Down with the falling stream the refuse run, END
BEGIN NOW To raise with joyful news his drooping son. END
BEGIN NOW Steeds are prepar'd to mount the Trojan band, END
BEGIN NOW Who wait their leader to the Tyrrhene land. END
BEGIN NOW A sprightly courser, fairer than the rest, END
BEGIN NOW The king himself presents his royal guest: END
BEGIN NOW A lion's hide his back and limbs infold, END
BEGIN NOW Precious with studded work, and paws of gold. END
BEGIN NOW Fame thro' the little city spreads aloud END
BEGIN NOW Th' intended march, amid the fearful crowd: END
BEGIN NOW The matrons beat their breasts, dissolve in tears, END
BEGIN NOW And double their devotion in their fears. END
BEGIN NOW The war at hand appears with more affright, END
BEGIN NOW And rises ev'ry moment to the sight. END
BEGIN NOW Then old Evander, with a close embrace, END
BEGIN NOW Strain'd his departing friend; and tears o'erflow his face. END
BEGIN NOW Would Heav'n," said he, "my strength and youth recall, END
BEGIN NOW Such as I was beneath Praeneste's wall; END
BEGIN NOW Then when I made the foremost foes retire, END
BEGIN NOW And set whole heaps of conquer'd shields on fire; END
BEGIN NOW When Herilus in single fight I slew, END
BEGIN NOW Whom with three lives Feronia did endue; END
BEGIN NOW And thrice I sent him to the Stygian shore, END
BEGIN NOW Till the last ebbing soul return'd no more- END
BEGIN NOW Such if I stood renew'd, not these alarms, END
BEGIN NOW Nor death, should rend me from my Pallas' arms; END
BEGIN NOW Nor proud Mezentius, thus unpunish'd, boast END
BEGIN NOW His rapes and murthers on the Tuscan coast. END
BEGIN NOW Ye gods, and mighty Jove, in pity bring END
BEGIN NOW Relief, and hear a father and a king! END
BEGIN NOW If fate and you reserve these eyes, to see END
BEGIN NOW My son return with peace and victory; END
BEGIN NOW If the lov'd boy shall bless his father's sight; END
BEGIN NOW If we shall meet again with more delight; END
BEGIN NOW Then draw my life in length; let me sustain, END
BEGIN NOW In hopes of his embrace, the worst of pain. END
BEGIN NOW But if your hard decrees- which, O! I dread- END
BEGIN NOW Have doom'd to death his undeserving head; END
BEGIN NOW This, O this very moment, let me die! END
BEGIN NOW While hopes and fears in equal balance lie; END
BEGIN NOW While, yet possess'd of all his youthful charms, END
BEGIN NOW I strain him close within these aged arms; END
BEGIN NOW Before that fatal news my soul shall wound! END
BEGIN NOW He said, and, swooning, sunk upon the ground. END
BEGIN NOW His servants bore him off, and softly laid END
BEGIN NOW His languish'd limbs upon his homely bed. END
BEGIN NOW The horsemen march; the gates are open'd wide; END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas at their head, Achates by his side. END
BEGIN NOW Next these, the Trojan leaders rode along; END
BEGIN NOW Last follows in the rear th' Arcadian throng. END
BEGIN NOW Young Pallas shone conspicuous o'er the rest; END
BEGIN NOW Gilded his arms, embroider'd was his vest. END
BEGIN NOW So, from the seas, exerts his radiant head END
BEGIN NOW The star by whom the lights of heav'n are led; END
BEGIN NOW Shakes from his rosy locks the pearly dews, END
BEGIN NOW Dispels the darkness, and the day renews. END
BEGIN NOW The trembling wives the walls and turrets crowd, END
BEGIN NOW And follow, with their eyes, the dusty cloud, END
BEGIN NOW Which winds disperse by fits, and shew from far END
BEGIN NOW The blaze of arms, and shields, and shining war. END
BEGIN NOW The troops, drawn up in beautiful array, END
BEGIN NOW O'er heathy plains pursue the ready way. END
BEGIN NOW Repeated peals of shouts are heard around; END
BEGIN NOW The neighing coursers answer to the sound, END
BEGIN NOW And shake with horny hoofs the solid ground. END
BEGIN NOW A greenwood shade, for long religion known, END
BEGIN NOW Stands by the streams that wash the Tuscan town, END
BEGIN NOW Incompass'd round with gloomy hills above, END
BEGIN NOW Which add a holy horror to the grove. END
BEGIN NOW The first inhabitants of Grecian blood, END
BEGIN NOW That sacred forest to Silvanus vow'd, END
BEGIN NOW The guardian of their flocks and fields; and pay END
BEGIN NOW Their due devotions on his annual day. END
BEGIN NOW Not far from hence, along the river's side, END
BEGIN NOW In tents secure, the Tuscan troops abide, END
BEGIN NOW By Tarchon led. Now, from a rising ground, END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas cast his wond'ring eyes around, END
BEGIN NOW And all the Tyrrhene army had in sight, END
BEGIN NOW Stretch'd on the spacious plain from left to right. END
BEGIN NOW Thether his warlike train the Trojan led, END
BEGIN NOW Refresh'd his men, and wearied horses fed. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the mother goddess, crown'd with charms, END
BEGIN NOW Breaks thro' the clouds, and brings the fated arms. END
BEGIN NOW Within a winding vale she finds her son, END
BEGIN NOW On the cool river's banks, retir'd alone. END
BEGIN NOW She shews her heav'nly form without disguise, END
BEGIN NOW And gives herself to his desiring eyes. END
BEGIN NOW Behold, she said, "perform'd in ev'ry part, END
BEGIN NOW My promise made, and Vulcan's labor'd art. END
BEGIN NOW Now seek, secure, the Latian enemy, END
BEGIN NOW And haughty Turnus to the field defy. END
BEGIN NOW She said; and, having first her son embrac'd, END
BEGIN NOW The radiant arms beneath an oak she plac'd, END
BEGIN NOW Proud of the gift, he roll'd his greedy sight END
BEGIN NOW Around the work, and gaz'd with vast delight. END
BEGIN NOW He lifts, he turns, he poises, and admires END
BEGIN NOW The crested helm, that vomits radiant fires: END
BEGIN NOW His hands the fatal sword and corslet hold, END
BEGIN NOW One keen with temper'd steel, one stiff with gold: END
BEGIN NOW Both ample, flaming both, and beamy bright; END
BEGIN NOW So shines a cloud, when edg'd with adverse light. END
BEGIN NOW He shakes the pointed spear, and longs to try END
BEGIN NOW The plated cuishes on his manly thigh; END
BEGIN NOW But most admires the shield's mysterious mold, END
BEGIN NOW And Roman triumphs rising on the gold: END
BEGIN NOW For these, emboss'd, the heav'nly smith had wrought END
BEGIN NOW (Not in the rolls of future fate untaught) END
BEGIN NOW The wars in order, and the race divine END
BEGIN NOW Of warriors issuing from the Julian line. END
BEGIN NOW The cave of Mars was dress'd with mossy greens: END
BEGIN NOW There, by the wolf, were laid the martial twins. END
BEGIN NOW Intrepid on her swelling dugs they hung; END
BEGIN NOW The foster dam loll'd out her fawning tongue: END
BEGIN NOW They suck'd secure, while, bending back her head, END
BEGIN NOW She lick'd their tender limbs, and form'd them as they fed. END
BEGIN NOW Not far from thence new Rome appears, with games END
BEGIN NOW Projected for the rape of Sabine dames. END
BEGIN NOW The pit resounds with shrieks; a war succeeds, END
BEGIN NOW For breach of public faith, and unexampled deeds. END
BEGIN NOW Here for revenge the Sabine troops contend; END
BEGIN NOW The Romans there with arms the prey defend. END
BEGIN NOW Wearied with tedious war, at length they cease; END
BEGIN NOW And both the kings and kingdoms plight the peace. END
BEGIN NOW The friendly chiefs before Jove's altar stand, END
BEGIN NOW Both arm'd, with each a charger in his hand: END
BEGIN NOW A fatted sow for sacrifice is led, END
BEGIN NOW With imprecations on the perjur'd head. END
BEGIN NOW Near this, the traitor Metius, stretch'd between END
BEGIN NOW Four fiery steeds, is dragg'd along the green, END
BEGIN NOW By Tullus' doom: the brambles drink his blood, END
BEGIN NOW And his torn limbs are left the vulture's food. END
BEGIN NOW There, Porsena to Rome proud Tarquin brings, END
BEGIN NOW And would by force restore the banish'd kings. END
BEGIN NOW One tyrant for his fellow-tyrant fights; END
BEGIN NOW The Roman youth assert their native rights. END
BEGIN NOW Before the town the Tuscan army lies, END
BEGIN NOW To win by famine, or by fraud surprise. END
BEGIN NOW Their king, half-threat'ning, half-disdaining stood, END
BEGIN NOW While Cocles broke the bridge, and stemm'd the flood. END
BEGIN NOW The captive maids there tempt the raging tide, END
BEGIN NOW Scap'd from their chains, with Cloelia for their guide. END
BEGIN NOW High on a rock heroic Manlius stood, END
BEGIN NOW To guard the temple, and the temple's god. END
BEGIN NOW Then Rome was poor; and there you might behold END
BEGIN NOW The palace thatch'd with straw, now roof'd with gold. END
BEGIN NOW The silver goose before the shining gate END
BEGIN NOW There flew, and, by her cackle, sav'd the state. END
BEGIN NOW She told the Gauls' approach; th' approaching Gauls, END
BEGIN NOW Obscure in night, ascend, and seize the walls. END
BEGIN NOW The gold dissembled well their yellow hair, END
BEGIN NOW And golden chains on their white necks they wear. END
BEGIN NOW Gold are their vests; long Alpine spears they wield, END
BEGIN NOW And their left arm sustains a length of shield. END
BEGIN NOW Hard by, the leaping Salian priests advance; END
BEGIN NOW And naked thro' the streets the mad Luperci dance, END
BEGIN NOW In caps of wool; the targets dropp'd from heav'n. END
BEGIN NOW Here modest matrons, in soft litters driv'n, END
BEGIN NOW To pay their vows in solemn pomp appear, END
BEGIN NOW And odorous gums in their chaste hands they bear. END
BEGIN NOW Far hence remov'd, the Stygian seats are seen; END
BEGIN NOW Pains of the damn'd, and punish'd Catiline END
BEGIN NOW Hung on a rock- the traitor; and, around, END
BEGIN NOW The Furies hissing from the nether ground. END
BEGIN NOW Apart from these, the happy souls he draws, END
BEGIN NOW And Cato's holy ghost dispensing laws. END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the quarters flows a golden sea; END
BEGIN NOW But foaming surges there in silver play. END
BEGIN NOW The dancing dolphins with their tails divide END
BEGIN NOW The glitt'ring waves, and cut the precious tide. END
BEGIN NOW Amid the main, two mighty fleets engage END
BEGIN NOW Their brazen beaks, oppos'd with equal rage. END
BEGIN NOW Actium surveys the well-disputed prize; END
BEGIN NOW Leucate's wat'ry plain with foamy billows fries. END
BEGIN NOW Young Caesar, on the stern, in armor bright, END
BEGIN NOW Here leads the Romans and their gods to fight: END
BEGIN NOW His beamy temples shoot their flames afar, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er his head is hung the Julian star. END
BEGIN NOW Agrippa seconds him, with prosp'rous gales, END
BEGIN NOW And, with propitious gods, his foes assails: END
BEGIN NOW A naval crown, that binds his manly brows, END
BEGIN NOW The happy fortune of the fight foreshows. END
BEGIN NOW Rang'd on the line oppos'd, Antonius brings END
BEGIN NOW Barbarian aids, and troops of Eastern kings; END
BEGIN NOW Th' Arabians near, and Bactrians from afar, END
BEGIN NOW Of tongues discordant, and a mingled war: END
BEGIN NOW And, rich in gaudy robes, amidst the strife, END
BEGIN NOW Moving they fight; with oars and forky prows END
BEGIN NOW The froth is gather'd, and the water glows. END
BEGIN NOW It seems, as if the Cyclades again END
BEGIN NOW Were rooted up, and justled in the main; END
BEGIN NOW Or floating mountains floating mountains meet; END
BEGIN NOW Such is the fierce encounter of the fleet. END
BEGIN NOW Fireballs are thrown, and pointed jav'lins fly; END
BEGIN NOW The fields of Neptune take a purple dye. END
BEGIN NOW The queen herself, amidst the loud alarms, END
BEGIN NOW With cymbals toss'd her fainting soldiers warms- END
BEGIN NOW Fool as she was! who had not yet divin'd END
BEGIN NOW Her cruel fate, nor saw the snakes behind. END
BEGIN NOW Her country gods, the monsters of the sky, END
BEGIN NOW Great Neptune, Pallas, and Love's Queen defy: END
BEGIN NOW The dog Anubis barks, but barks in vain, END
BEGIN NOW Nor longer dares oppose th' ethereal train. END
BEGIN NOW Mars in the middle of the shining shield END
BEGIN NOW Is grav'd, and strides along the liquid field. END
BEGIN NOW The Dirae souse from heav'n with swift descent; END
BEGIN NOW And Discord, dyed in blood, with garments rent, END
BEGIN NOW Divides the prease: her steps Bellona treads, END
BEGIN NOW And shakes her iron rod above their heads. END
BEGIN NOW This seen, Apollo, from his Actian height, END
BEGIN NOW Pours down his arrows; at whose winged flight END
BEGIN NOW And soft Sabaeans quit the wat'ry field. END
BEGIN NOW The fatal mistress hoists her silken sails, END
BEGIN NOW And, shrinking from the fight, invokes the gales. END
BEGIN NOW Aghast she looks, and heaves her breast for breath, END
BEGIN NOW Panting, and pale with fear of future death. END
BEGIN NOW The god had figur'd her as driv'n along END
BEGIN NOW By winds and waves, and scudding thro' the throng. END
BEGIN NOW Just opposite, sad Nilus opens wide END
BEGIN NOW His arms and ample bosom to the tide, END
BEGIN NOW And spreads his mantle o'er the winding coast, END
BEGIN NOW In which he wraps his queen, and hides the flying host. END
BEGIN NOW The victor to the gods his thanks express'd, END
BEGIN NOW And Rome, triumphant, with his presence bless'd. END
BEGIN NOW Three hundred temples in the town he plac'd; END
BEGIN NOW With spoils and altars ev'ry temple grac'd. END
BEGIN NOW Three shining nights, and three succeeding days, END
BEGIN NOW The fields resound with shouts, the streets with praise, END
BEGIN NOW The domes with songs, the theaters with plays. END
BEGIN NOW All altars flame: before each altar lies, END
BEGIN NOW Drench'd in his gore, the destin'd sacrifice. END
BEGIN NOW Great Caesar sits sublime upon his throne, END
BEGIN NOW Before Apollo's porch of Parian stone; END
BEGIN NOW Accepts the presents vow'd for victory, END
BEGIN NOW And hangs the monumental crowns on high. END
BEGIN NOW Vast crowds of vanquish'd nations march along, END
BEGIN NOW Various in arms, in habit, and in tongue. END
BEGIN NOW Here, Mulciber assigns the proper place END
BEGIN NOW For Carians, and th' ungirt Numidian race; END
BEGIN NOW Then ranks the Thracians in the second row, END
BEGIN NOW With Scythians, expert in the dart and bow. END
BEGIN NOW And here the tam'd Euphrates humbly glides, END
BEGIN NOW And there the Rhine submits her swelling tides, END
BEGIN NOW And proud Araxes, whom no bridge could bind; END
BEGIN NOW The Danes' unconquer'd offspring march behind, END
BEGIN NOW And Morini, the last of humankind. END
BEGIN NOW These figures, on the shield divinely wrought, END
BEGIN NOW By Vulcan labor'd, and by Venus brought, END
BEGIN NOW With joy and wonder fill the hero's thought. END
BEGIN NOW Unknown the names, he yet admires the grace, END
BEGIN NOW And bears aloft the fame and fortune of his race. END
BEGIN NOW While these affairs in distant places pass'd, END
BEGIN NOW The various Iris Juno sends with haste, END
BEGIN NOW To find bold Turnus, who, with anxious thought, END
BEGIN NOW The secret shade of his great grandsire sought. END
BEGIN NOW Retir'd alone she found the daring man, END
BEGIN NOW And op'd her rosy lips, and thus began: END
BEGIN NOW What none of all the gods could grant thy vows, END
BEGIN NOW That, Turnus, this auspicious day bestows. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas, gone to seek th' Arcadian prince, END
BEGIN NOW Has left the Trojan camp without defense; END
BEGIN NOW And, short of succors there, employs his pains END
BEGIN NOW In parts remote to raise the Tuscan swains. END
BEGIN NOW Now snatch an hour that favors thy designs; END
BEGIN NOW Unite thy forces, and attack their lines. END
BEGIN NOW This said, on equal wings she pois'd her weight, END
BEGIN NOW And form'd a radiant rainbow in her flight. END
BEGIN NOW The Daunian hero lifts his hands eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And thus invokes the goddess as she flies: END
BEGIN NOW Iris, the grace of heav'n, what pow'r divine END
BEGIN NOW Has sent thee down, thro' dusky clouds to shine? END
BEGIN NOW See, they divide; immortal day appears, END
BEGIN NOW And glitt'ring planets dancing in their spheres! END
BEGIN NOW With joy, these happy omens I obey, END
BEGIN NOW And follow to the war the god that leads the way. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, as by the brook he stood, END
BEGIN NOW He scoop'd the water from the crystal flood; END
BEGIN NOW Then with his hands the drops to heav'n he throws, END
BEGIN NOW And loads the pow'rs above with offer'd vows. END
BEGIN NOW Now march the bold confed'rates thro' the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Well hors'd, well clad; a rich and shining train. END
BEGIN NOW Messapus leads the van; and, in the rear, END
BEGIN NOW The sons of Tyrrheus in bright arms appear. END
BEGIN NOW In the main battle, with his flaming crest, END
BEGIN NOW The mighty Turnus tow'rs above the rest. END
BEGIN NOW Silent they move, majestically slow, END
BEGIN NOW Like ebbing Nile, or Ganges in his flow. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans view the dusty cloud from far, END
BEGIN NOW And the dark menace of the distant war. END
BEGIN NOW Caicus from the rampire saw it rise, END
BEGIN NOW Black'ning the fields, and thick'ning thro' the skies. END
BEGIN NOW Then to his fellows thus aloud he calls: END
BEGIN NOW What rolling clouds, my friends, approach the walls? END
BEGIN NOW Arm! arm! and man the works! prepare your spears END
BEGIN NOW And pointed darts! the Latian host appears. END
BEGIN NOW Thus warn'd, they shut their gates; with shouts ascend END
BEGIN NOW The bulwarks, and, secure, their foes attend: END
BEGIN NOW For their wise gen'ral, with foreseeing care, END
BEGIN NOW Had charg'd them not to tempt the doubtful war, END
BEGIN NOW Nor, tho' provok'd, in open fields advance, END
BEGIN NOW But close within their lines attend their chance. END
BEGIN NOW Unwilling, yet they keep the strict command, END
BEGIN NOW And sourly wait in arms the hostile band. END
BEGIN NOW The fiery Turnus flew before the rest: END
BEGIN NOW A piebald steed of Thracian strain he press'd; END
BEGIN NOW His helm of massy gold, and crimson was his crest. END
BEGIN NOW With twenty horse to second his designs, END
BEGIN NOW An unexpected foe, he fac'd the lines. END
BEGIN NOW Is there," he said, "in arms, who bravely dare END
BEGIN NOW His leader's honor and his danger share? END
BEGIN NOW Then spurring on, his brandish'd dart he threw, END
BEGIN NOW In sign of war: applauding shouts ensue. END
BEGIN NOW Behind the rampires and the battle shun, END
BEGIN NOW He rides around the camp, with rolling eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And stops at ev'ry post, and ev'ry passage tries. END
BEGIN NOW So roams the nightly wolf about the fold: END
BEGIN NOW Wet with descending show'rs, and stiff with cold, END
BEGIN NOW He howls for hunger, and he grins for pain, END
BEGIN NOW (His gnashing teeth are exercis'd in vain,) END
BEGIN NOW And, impotent of anger, finds no way END
BEGIN NOW In his distended paws to grasp the prey. END
BEGIN NOW The mothers listen; but the bleating lambs END
BEGIN NOW Securely swig the dug, beneath the dams. END
BEGIN NOW Thus ranges eager Turnus o'er the plain. END
BEGIN NOW Sharp with desire, and furious with disdain; END
BEGIN NOW Surveys each passage with a piercing sight, END
BEGIN NOW To force his foes in equal field to fight. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while he gazes round, at length he spies, END
BEGIN NOW Where, fenc'd with strong redoubts, their navy lies, END
BEGIN NOW Close underneath the walls; the washing tide END
BEGIN NOW Secures from all approach this weaker side. END
BEGIN NOW He takes the wish'd occasion, fills his hand END
BEGIN NOW With ready fires, and shakes a flaming brand. END
BEGIN NOW Urg'd by his presence, ev'ry soul is warm'd, END
BEGIN NOW And ev'ry hand with kindled firs is arm'd. END
BEGIN NOW From the fir'd pines the scatt'ring sparkles fly; END
BEGIN NOW Fat vapors, mix'd with flames, involve the sky. END
BEGIN NOW What pow'r, O Muses, could avert the flame END
BEGIN NOW Which threaten'd, in the fleet, the Trojan name? END
BEGIN NOW Tell: for the fact, thro' length of time obscure, END
BEGIN NOW Is hard to faith; yet shall the fame endure. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is said that, when the chief prepar'd his flight, END
BEGIN NOW And fell'd his timber from Mount Ida's height, END
BEGIN NOW The grandam goddess then approach'd her son, END
BEGIN NOW And with a mother's majesty begun: END
BEGIN NOW Grant me," she said, "the sole request I bring, END
BEGIN NOW Since conquer'd heav'n has own'd you for its king. END
BEGIN NOW On Ida's brows, for ages past, there stood, END
BEGIN NOW With firs and maples fill'd, a shady wood; END
BEGIN NOW And on the summit rose a sacred grove, END
BEGIN NOW Where I was worship'd with religious love. END
BEGIN NOW Those woods, that holy grove, my long delight, END
BEGIN NOW I gave the Trojan prince, to speed his flight. END
BEGIN NOW Now, fill'd with fear, on their behalf I come; END
BEGIN NOW Let neither winds o'erset, nor waves intomb END
BEGIN NOW The floating forests of the sacred pine; END
BEGIN NOW But let it be their safety to be mine. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus replied her awful son, who rolls END
BEGIN NOW The radiant stars, and heav'n and earth controls: END
BEGIN NOW How dare you, mother, endless date demand END
BEGIN NOW For vessels molded by a mortal hand? END
BEGIN NOW What then is fate? Shall bold Aeneas ride, END
BEGIN NOW Of safety certain, on th' uncertain tide? END
BEGIN NOW Yet, what I can, I grant; when, wafted o'er, END
BEGIN NOW The chief is landed on the Latian shore, END
BEGIN NOW Whatever ships escape the raging storms, END
BEGIN NOW At my command shall change their fading forms END
BEGIN NOW To nymphs divine, and plow the wat'ry way, END
BEGIN NOW Like Dotis and the daughters of the sea. END
BEGIN NOW To seal his sacred vow, by Styx he swore, END
BEGIN NOW The lake of liquid pitch, the dreary shore, END
BEGIN NOW And Phlegethon's innavigable flood, END
BEGIN NOW And the black regions of his brother god. END
BEGIN NOW He said; and shook the skies with his imperial nod. END
BEGIN NOW And now at length the number'd hours were come, END
BEGIN NOW Prefix'd by fate's irrevocable doom, END
BEGIN NOW When the great Mother of the Gods was free END
BEGIN NOW To save her ships, and finish Jove's decree. END
BEGIN NOW First, from the quarter of the morn, there sprung END
BEGIN NOW A light that sign'd the heav'ns, and shot along; END
BEGIN NOW Then from a cloud, fring'd round with golden fires, END
BEGIN NOW Were timbrels heard, and Berecynthian choirs; END
BEGIN NOW And, last, a voice, with more than mortal sounds, END
BEGIN NOW Both hosts, in arms oppos'd, with equal horror wounds: END
BEGIN NOW O Trojan race, your needless aid forbear, END
BEGIN NOW And know, my ships are my peculiar care. END
BEGIN NOW With greater ease the bold Rutulian may, END
BEGIN NOW With hissing brands, attempt to burn the sea, END
BEGIN NOW Than singe my sacred pines. But you, my charge, END
BEGIN NOW Loos'd from your crooked anchors, launch at large, END
BEGIN NOW Exalted each a nymph: forsake the sand, END
BEGIN NOW And swim the seas, at Cybele's command. END
BEGIN NOW No sooner had the goddess ceas'd to speak, END
BEGIN NOW When, lo! th' obedient ships their haulsers break; END
BEGIN NOW And, strange to tell, like dolphins, in the main END
BEGIN NOW They plunge their prows, and dive, and spring again: END
BEGIN NOW As many beauteous maids the billows sweep, END
BEGIN NOW As rode before tall vessels on the deep. END
BEGIN NOW The foes, surpris'd with wonder, stood aghast; END
BEGIN NOW Messapus curb'd his fiery courser's haste; END
BEGIN NOW Old Tiber roar'd, and, raising up his head, END
BEGIN NOW Call'd back his waters to their oozy bed. END
BEGIN NOW Turnus alone, undaunted, bore the shock, END
BEGIN NOW And with these words his trembling troops bespoke: END
BEGIN NOW These monsters for the Trojans' fate are meant, END
BEGIN NOW And are by Jove for black presages sent. END
BEGIN NOW He takes the cowards' last relief away; END
BEGIN NOW For fly they cannot, and, constrain'd to stay, END
BEGIN NOW Must yield unfought, a base inglorious prey. END
BEGIN NOW The liquid half of all the globe is lost; END
BEGIN NOW Heav'n shuts the seas, and we secure the coast. END
BEGIN NOW Theirs is no more than that small spot of ground END
BEGIN NOW Which myriads of our martial men surround. END
BEGIN NOW Their fates I fear not, or vain oracles. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was giv'n to Venus they should cross the seas, END
BEGIN NOW And land secure upon the Latian plains: END
BEGIN NOW Their promis'd hour is pass'd, and mine remains. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is in the fate of Turnus to destroy, END
BEGIN NOW With sword and fire, the faithless race of Troy. END
BEGIN NOW Shall such affronts as these alone inflame END
BEGIN NOW The Grecian brothers, and the Grecian name? END
BEGIN NOW My cause and theirs is one; a fatal strife, END
BEGIN NOW And final ruin, for a ravish'd wife. END
BEGIN NOW Was 't not enough, that, punish'd for the crime, END
BEGIN NOW They fell; but will they fall a second time? END
BEGIN NOW One would have thought they paid enough before, END
BEGIN NOW To curse the costly sex, and durst offend no more. END
BEGIN NOW Can they securely trust their feeble wall, END
BEGIN NOW A slight partition, a thin interval, END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt their fate and them; when Troy, tho' built END
BEGIN NOW By hands divine, yet perish'd by their guilt? END
BEGIN NOW Lend me, for once, my friends, your valiant hands, END
BEGIN NOW Less than a thousand ships will end this war, END
BEGIN NOW Nor Vulcan needs his fated arms prepare. END
BEGIN NOW Let all the Tuscans, all th' Arcadians, join! END
BEGIN NOW Nor these, nor those, shall frustrate my design. END
BEGIN NOW Let them not fear the treasons of the night, END
BEGIN NOW The robb'd Palladium, the pretended flight: END
BEGIN NOW Our onset shall be made in open light. END
BEGIN NOW No wooden engine shall their town betray; END
BEGIN NOW Fires they shall have around, but fires by day. END
BEGIN NOW No Grecian babes before their camp appear, END
BEGIN NOW Now, since the sun is rolling to the west, END
BEGIN NOW Give we the silent night to needful rest: END
BEGIN NOW Refresh your bodies, and your arms prepare; END
BEGIN NOW The morn shall end the small remains of war. END
BEGIN NOW The post of honor to Messapus falls, END
BEGIN NOW To keep the nightly guard, to watch the walls, END
BEGIN NOW To pitch the fires at distances around, END
BEGIN NOW And close the Trojans in their scanty ground. END
BEGIN NOW Twice seven Rutulian captains ready stand, END
BEGIN NOW And twice seven hundred horse these chiefs command; END
BEGIN NOW All clad in shining arms the works invest, END
BEGIN NOW Each with a radiant helm and waving crest. END
BEGIN NOW Stretch'd at their length, they press the grassy ground; END
BEGIN NOW They laugh, they sing, (the jolly bowls go round,) END
BEGIN NOW With lights and cheerful fires renew the day, END
BEGIN NOW And pass the wakeful night in feasts and play. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans, from above, their foes beheld, END
BEGIN NOW And with arm'd legions all the rampires fill'd. END
BEGIN NOW Seiz'd with affright, their gates they first explore; END
BEGIN NOW Join works to works with bridges, tow'r to tow'r: END
BEGIN NOW Thus all things needful for defense abound. END
BEGIN NOW Mnestheus and brave Seresthus walk the round, END
BEGIN NOW Commission'd by their absent prince to share END
BEGIN NOW The common danger, and divide the care. END
BEGIN NOW The soldiers draw their lots, and, as they fall, END
BEGIN NOW By turns relieve each other on the wall. END
BEGIN NOW Nigh where the foes their utmost guards advance, END
BEGIN NOW To watch the gate was warlike Nisus' chance. END
BEGIN NOW His father Hyrtacus of noble blood; END
BEGIN NOW His mother was a huntress of the wood, END
BEGIN NOW And sent him to the wars. Well could he bear END
BEGIN NOW His lance in fight, and dart the flying spear, END
BEGIN NOW But better skill'd unerring shafts to send. END
BEGIN NOW Beside him stood Euryalus, his friend: END
BEGIN NOW Euryalus, than whom the Trojan host END
BEGIN NOW No fairer face, or sweeter air, could boast- END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had the down to shade his cheeks begun. END
BEGIN NOW One was their care, and their delight was one: END
BEGIN NOW One common hazard in the war they shar'd, END
BEGIN NOW And now were both by choice upon the guard. END
BEGIN NOW Then Nisus thus: "Or do the gods inspire END
BEGIN NOW This warmth, or make we gods of our desire? END
BEGIN NOW A gen'rous ardor boils within my breast, END
BEGIN NOW Eager of action, enemy to rest: END
BEGIN NOW This urges me to fight, and fires my mind END
BEGIN NOW To leave a memorable name behind. END
BEGIN NOW Thou see'st the foe secure; how faintly shine END
BEGIN NOW Their scatter'd fires! the most, in sleep supine END
BEGIN NOW Along the ground, an easy conquest lie: END
BEGIN NOW The wakeful few the fuming flagon ply; END
BEGIN NOW All hush'd around. Now hear what I revolve- END
BEGIN NOW A thought unripe- and scarcely yet resolve. END
BEGIN NOW Our absent prince both camp and council mourn; END
BEGIN NOW By message both would hasten his return: END
BEGIN NOW If they confer what I demand on thee, END
BEGIN NOW (For fame is recompense enough for me,) END
BEGIN NOW Methinks, beneath yon hill, I have espied END
BEGIN NOW A way that safely will my passage guide. END
BEGIN NOW Euryalus stood list'ning while he spoke, END
BEGIN NOW With love of praise and noble envy struck; END
BEGIN NOW Then to his ardent friend expos'd his mind: END
BEGIN NOW All this, alone, and leaving me behind! END
BEGIN NOW Am I unworthy, Nisus, to be join'd? END
BEGIN NOW Thinkist thou I can my share of glory yield, END
BEGIN NOW Or send thee unassisted to the field? END
BEGIN NOW Not so my father taught my childhood arms; END
BEGIN NOW Born in a siege, and bred among alarms! END
BEGIN NOW Nor is my youth unworthy of my friend, END
BEGIN NOW Nor of the heav'n-born hero I attend. END
BEGIN NOW The thing call'd life, with ease I can disclaim, END
BEGIN NOW And think it over-sold to purchase fame. END
BEGIN NOW Then Nisus thus: "Alas! thy tender years END
BEGIN NOW Would minister new matter to my fears. END
BEGIN NOW So may the gods, who view this friendly strife, END
BEGIN NOW Restore me to thy lov'd embrace with life, END
BEGIN NOW Condemn'd to pay my vows, (as sure I trust,) END
BEGIN NOW This thy request is cruel and unjust. END
BEGIN NOW But if some chance- as many chances are, END
BEGIN NOW And doubtful hazards, in the deeds of war- END
BEGIN NOW If one should reach my head, there let it fall, END
BEGIN NOW And spare thy life; I would not perish all. END
BEGIN NOW Thy bloomy youth deserves a longer date: END
BEGIN NOW Live thou to mourn thy love's unhappy fate; END
BEGIN NOW To bear my mangled body from the foe, END
BEGIN NOW Or buy it back, and fun'ral rites bestow. END
BEGIN NOW Or, if hard fortune shall those dues deny, END
BEGIN NOW Thou canst at least an empty tomb supply. END
BEGIN NOW O let not me the widow's tears renew! END
BEGIN NOW Nor let a mother's curse my name pursue: END
BEGIN NOW Thy pious parent, who, for love of thee, END
BEGIN NOW Forsook the coasts of friendly Sicily, END
BEGIN NOW Her age committing to the seas and wind, END
BEGIN NOW When ev'ry weary matron stay'd behind. END
BEGIN NOW To this, Euryalus: "You plead in vain, END
BEGIN NOW And but protract the cause you cannot gain. END
BEGIN NOW No more delays, but haste!" With that, he wakes END
BEGIN NOW The nodding watch; each to his office takes. END
BEGIN NOW The guard reliev'd, the gen'rous couple went END
BEGIN NOW To find the council at the royal tent. END
BEGIN NOW All creatures else forgot their daily care, END
BEGIN NOW And sleep, the common gift of nature, share; END
BEGIN NOW Except the Trojan peers, who wakeful sate END
BEGIN NOW In nightly council for th' indanger'd state. END
BEGIN NOW They vote a message to their absent chief, END
BEGIN NOW Shew their distress, and beg a swift relief. END
BEGIN NOW Amid the camp a silent seat they chose, END
BEGIN NOW Remote from clamor, and secure from foes. END
BEGIN NOW On their left arms their ample shields they bear, END
BEGIN NOW The right reclin'd upon the bending spear. END
BEGIN NOW Now Nisus and his friend approach the guard, END
BEGIN NOW And beg admission, eager to be heard: END
BEGIN NOW Th' affair important, not to be deferr'd. END
BEGIN NOW Ascanius bids 'em be conducted in, END
BEGIN NOW Ord'ring the more experienc'd to begin. END
BEGIN NOW Then Nisus thus: "Ye fathers, lend your ears; END
BEGIN NOW Nor judge our bold attempt beyond our years. END
BEGIN NOW The foe, securely drench'd in sleep and wine, END
BEGIN NOW Neglect their watch; the fires but thinly shine; END
BEGIN NOW And where the smoke in cloudy vapors flies, END
BEGIN NOW Cov'ring the plain, and curling to the skies, END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt two paths, which at the gate divide, END
BEGIN NOW Close by the sea, a passage we have spied, END
BEGIN NOW Which will our way to great Aeneas guide. END
BEGIN NOW Expect each hour to see him safe again, END
BEGIN NOW Loaded with spoils of foes in battle slain. END
BEGIN NOW Snatch we the lucky minute while we may; END
BEGIN NOW Nor can we be mistaken in the way; END
BEGIN NOW For, hunting in the vale, we both have seen END
BEGIN NOW The rising turrets, and the stream between, END
BEGIN NOW And know the winding course, with ev'ry ford. END
BEGIN NOW He ceas'd; and old Alethes took the word: END
BEGIN NOW Our country gods, in whom our trust we place, END
BEGIN NOW Will yet from ruin save the Trojan race, END
BEGIN NOW While we behold such dauntless worth appear END
BEGIN NOW In dawning youth, and souls so void of fear. END
BEGIN NOW Then into tears of joy the father broke; END
BEGIN NOW Each in his longing arms by turns he took; END
BEGIN NOW Panted and paus'd; and thus again he spoke: END
BEGIN NOW Ye brave young men, what equal gifts can we, END
BEGIN NOW In recompense of such desert, decree? END
BEGIN NOW The greatest, sure, and best you can receive, END
BEGIN NOW The gods and your own conscious worth will give. END
BEGIN NOW The rest our grateful gen'ral will bestow, END
BEGIN NOW And young Ascanius till his manhood owe. END
BEGIN NOW And I, whose welfare in my father lies, END
BEGIN NOW Ascanius adds, "by the great deities, END
BEGIN NOW By my dear country, by my household gods, END
BEGIN NOW By hoary Vesta's rites and dark abodes, END
BEGIN NOW Adjure you both, (on you my fortune stands; END
BEGIN NOW That and my faith I plight into your hands,) END
BEGIN NOW Make me but happy in his safe return, END
BEGIN NOW Whose wanted presence I can only mourn; END
BEGIN NOW Your common gift shall two large goblets be END
BEGIN NOW Of silver, wrought with curious imagery, END
BEGIN NOW And high emboss'd, which, when old Priam reign'd, END
BEGIN NOW My conqu'ring sire at sack'd Arisba gain'd; END
BEGIN NOW And more, two tripods cast in antic mold, END
BEGIN NOW With two great talents of the finest gold; END
BEGIN NOW Beside a costly bowl, ingrav'd with art, END
BEGIN NOW Which Dido gave, when first she gave her heart. END
BEGIN NOW But, if in conquer'd Italy we reign, END
BEGIN NOW When spoils by lot the victor shall obtain- END
BEGIN NOW Thou saw'st the courser by proud Turnus press'd: END
BEGIN NOW That, Nisus, and his arms, and nodding crest, END
BEGIN NOW And shield, from chance exempt, shall be thy share: END
BEGIN NOW Twelve lab'ring slaves, twelve handmaids young and fair END
BEGIN NOW All clad in rich attire, and train'd with care; END
BEGIN NOW And, last, a Latian field with fruitful plains, END
BEGIN NOW And a large portion of the king's domains. END
BEGIN NOW But thou, whose years are more to mine allied- END
BEGIN NOW No fate my vow'd affection shall divide END
BEGIN NOW From thee, heroic youth! Be wholly mine; END
BEGIN NOW Take full possession; all my soul is thine. END
BEGIN NOW One faith, one fame, one fate, shall both attend; END
BEGIN NOW My life's companion, and my bosom friend: END
BEGIN NOW My peace shall be committed to thy care, END
BEGIN NOW And to thy conduct my concerns in war. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus the young Euryalus replied: END
BEGIN NOW Whatever fortune, good or bad, betide, END
BEGIN NOW The same shall be my age, as now my youth; END
BEGIN NOW No time shall find me wanting to my truth. END
BEGIN NOW This only from your goodness let me gain END
BEGIN NOW (And, this ungranted, all rewards are vain) END
BEGIN NOW Of Priam's royal race my mother came- END
BEGIN NOW And sure the best that ever bore the name- END
BEGIN NOW Whom neither Troy nor Sicily could hold END
BEGIN NOW From me departing, but, o'erspent and old, END
BEGIN NOW My fate she follow'd. Ignorant of this END
BEGIN NOW (Whatever) danger, neither parting kiss, END
BEGIN NOW Nor pious blessing taken, her I leave, END
BEGIN NOW And in this only act of all my life deceive. END
BEGIN NOW By this right hand and conscious Night I swear, END
BEGIN NOW My soul so sad a farewell could not bear. END
BEGIN NOW Be you her comfort; fill my vacant place END
BEGIN NOW (Permit me to presume so great a grace) END
BEGIN NOW Support her age, forsaken and distress'd. END
BEGIN NOW That hope alone will fortify my breast END
BEGIN NOW Against the worst of fortunes, and of fears. END
BEGIN NOW He said. The mov'd assistants melt in tears. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus Ascanius, wonderstruck to see END
BEGIN NOW That image of his filial piety: END
BEGIN NOW So great beginnings, in so green an age, END
BEGIN NOW Exact the faith which I again ingage. END
BEGIN NOW Thy mother all the dues shall justly claim, END
BEGIN NOW Creusa had, and only want the name. END
BEGIN NOW Whate'er event thy bold attempt shall have, END
BEGIN NOW 'T is merit to have borne a son so brave. END
BEGIN NOW Now by my head, a sacred oath, I swear, END
BEGIN NOW (My father us'd it,) what, returning here END
BEGIN NOW Crown'd with success, I for thyself prepare, END
BEGIN NOW That, if thou fail, shall thy lov'd mother share. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and weeping, while he spoke the word, END
BEGIN NOW From his broad belt he drew a shining sword, END
BEGIN NOW Magnificent with gold. Lycaon made, END
BEGIN NOW And in an ivory scabbard sheath'd the blade. END
BEGIN NOW This was his gift. Great Mnestheus gave his friend END
BEGIN NOW A lion's hide, his body to defend; END
BEGIN NOW And good Alethes furnish'd him, beside, END
BEGIN NOW With his own trusty helm, of temper tried. END
BEGIN NOW Thus arm'd they went. The noble Trojans wait END
BEGIN NOW Their issuing forth, and follow to the gate END
BEGIN NOW With prayers and vows. Above the rest appears END
BEGIN NOW Ascanius, manly far beyond his years, END
BEGIN NOW And messages committed to their care, END
BEGIN NOW Which all in winds were lost, and flitting air. END
BEGIN NOW The trenches first they pass'd; then took their way END
BEGIN NOW Where their proud foes in pitch'd pavilions lay; END
BEGIN NOW To many fatal, ere themselves were slain. END
BEGIN NOW They found the careless host dispers'd upon the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Who, gorg'd, and drunk with wine, supinely snore. END
BEGIN NOW Unharness'd chariots stand along the shore: END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the wheels and reins, the goblet by, END
BEGIN NOW A medley of debauch and war, they lie. END
BEGIN NOW Observing Nisus shew'd his friend the sight: END
BEGIN NOW Behold a conquest gain'd without a fight. END
BEGIN NOW Occasion offers, and I stand prepar'd; END
BEGIN NOW There lies our way; be thou upon the guard, END
BEGIN NOW And look around, while I securely go, END
BEGIN NOW And hew a passage thro' the sleeping foe. END
BEGIN NOW Softly he spoke; then striding took his way, END
BEGIN NOW With his drawn sword, where haughty Rhamnes lay; END
BEGIN NOW His head rais'd high on tapestry beneath, END
BEGIN NOW And heaving from his breast, he drew his breath; END
BEGIN NOW A king and prophet, by King Turnus lov'd: END
BEGIN NOW But fate by prescience cannot be remov'd. END
BEGIN NOW Him and his sleeping slaves he slew; then spies END
BEGIN NOW Where Remus, with his rich retinue, lies. END
BEGIN NOW His armor-bearer first, and next he kills END
BEGIN NOW His charioteer, intrench'd betwixt the wheels END
BEGIN NOW And his lov'd horses; last invades their lord; END
BEGIN NOW Full on his neck he drives the fatal sword: END
BEGIN NOW The gasping head flies off; a purple flood END
BEGIN NOW Flows from the trunk, that welters in the blood, END
BEGIN NOW Which, by the spurning heels dispers'd around, END
BEGIN NOW The bed besprinkles and bedews the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Lamus the bold, and Lamyrus the strong, END
BEGIN NOW He slew, and then Serranus fair and young. END
BEGIN NOW From dice and wine the youth retir'd to rest, END
BEGIN NOW And puff'd the fumy god from out his breast: END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n then he dreamt of drink and lucky play- END
BEGIN NOW More lucky, had it lasted till the day. END
BEGIN NOW The famish'd lion thus, with hunger bold, END
BEGIN NOW O'erleaps the fences of the nightly fold, END
BEGIN NOW And tears the peaceful flocks: with silent awe END
BEGIN NOW Trembling they lie, and pant beneath his paw. END
BEGIN NOW Nor with less rage Euryalus employs END
BEGIN NOW The wrathful sword, or fewer foes destroys; END
BEGIN NOW But on th' ignoble crowd his fury flew; END
BEGIN NOW He Fadus, Hebesus, and Rhoetus slew. END
BEGIN NOW Oppress'd with heavy sleep the former fell, END
BEGIN NOW But Rhoetus wakeful, and observing all: END
BEGIN NOW Behind a spacious jar he slink'd for fear; END
BEGIN NOW The fatal iron found and reach'd him there; END
BEGIN NOW For, as he rose, it pierc'd his naked side, END
BEGIN NOW And, reeking, thence return'd in crimson dyed. END
BEGIN NOW The wound pours out a stream of wine and blood; END
BEGIN NOW The purple soul comes floating in the flood. END
BEGIN NOW Now, where Messapus quarter'd, they arrive. END
BEGIN NOW The fires were fainting there, and just alive; END
BEGIN NOW The warrior-horses, tied in order, fed. END
BEGIN NOW Nisus observ'd the discipline, and said: END
BEGIN NOW Our eager thirst of blood may both betray; END
BEGIN NOW And see the scatter'd streaks of dawning day, END
BEGIN NOW Foe to nocturnal thefts. No more, my friend; END
BEGIN NOW Here let our glutted execution end. END
BEGIN NOW A lane thro' slaughter'd bodies we have made. END
BEGIN NOW The bold Euryalus, tho' loth, obey'd. END
BEGIN NOW Of arms, and arras, and of plate, they find END
BEGIN NOW A precious load; but these they leave behind. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, fond of gaudy spoils, the boy would stay END
BEGIN NOW To make the rich caparison his prey, END
BEGIN NOW Which on the steed of conquer'd Rhamnes lay. END
BEGIN NOW Nor did his eyes less longingly behold END
BEGIN NOW The girdle-belt, with nails of burnish'd gold. END
BEGIN NOW This present Caedicus the rich bestow'd END
BEGIN NOW On Remulus, when friendship first they vow'd, END
BEGIN NOW And, absent, join'd in hospitable ties: END
BEGIN NOW He, dying, to his heir bequeath'd the prize; END
BEGIN NOW Till, by the conqu'ring Ardean troops oppress'd, END
BEGIN NOW He fell; and they the glorious gift possess'd. END
BEGIN NOW These glitt'ring spoils (now made the victor's gain) END
BEGIN NOW He to his body suits, but suits in vain: END
BEGIN NOW Messapus' helm he finds among the rest, END
BEGIN NOW And laces on, and wears the waving crest. END
BEGIN NOW Proud of their conquest, prouder of their prey, END
BEGIN NOW They leave the camp, and take the ready way. END
BEGIN NOW But far they had not pass'd, before they spied END
BEGIN NOW Three hundred horse, with Volscens for their guide. END
BEGIN NOW The queen a legion to King Turnus sent; END
BEGIN NOW But the swift horse the slower foot prevent, END
BEGIN NOW And now, advancing, sought the leader's tent. END
BEGIN NOW They saw the pair; for, thro' the doubtful shade, END
BEGIN NOW His shining helm Euryalus betray'd, END
BEGIN NOW On which the moon with full reflection play'd. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is not for naught," cried Volscens from the crowd, END
BEGIN NOW These men go there;" then rais'd his voice aloud: END
BEGIN NOW Stand! stand! why thus in arms? And whither bent? END
BEGIN NOW From whence, to whom, and on what errand sent? END
BEGIN NOW Silent they scud away, and haste their flight END
BEGIN NOW To neighb'ring woods, and trust themselves to night. END
BEGIN NOW The speedy horse all passages belay, END
BEGIN NOW And spur their smoking steeds to cross their way, END
BEGIN NOW And watch each entrance of the winding wood. END
BEGIN NOW Black was the forest: thick with beech it stood, END
BEGIN NOW Horrid with fern, and intricate with thorn; END
BEGIN NOW Few paths of human feet, or tracks of beasts, were worn. END
BEGIN NOW The darkness of the shades, his heavy prey, END
BEGIN NOW And fear, misled the younger from his way. END
BEGIN NOW But Nisus hit the turns with happier haste, END
BEGIN NOW And, thoughtless of his friend, the forest pass'd, END
BEGIN NOW And Alban plains, from Alba's name so call'd, END
BEGIN NOW Where King Latinus then his oxen stall'd; END
BEGIN NOW Till, turning at the length, he stood his ground, END
BEGIN NOW And miss'd his friend, and cast his eyes around: END
BEGIN NOW Ah wretch!" he cried, "where have I left behind END
BEGIN NOW Th' unhappy youth? where shall I hope to find? END
BEGIN NOW Or what way take?" Again he ventures back, END
BEGIN NOW And treads the mazes of his former track. END
BEGIN NOW He winds the wood, and, list'ning, hears the noise END
BEGIN NOW Of tramping coursers, and the riders' voice. END
BEGIN NOW The sound approach'd; and suddenly he view'd END
BEGIN NOW The foes inclosing, and his friend pursued, END
BEGIN NOW Forelaid and taken, while he strove in vain END
BEGIN NOW The shelter of the friendly shades to gain. END
BEGIN NOW What should he next attempt? what arms employ, END
BEGIN NOW What fruitless force, to free the captive boy? END
BEGIN NOW Or desperate should he rush and lose his life, END
BEGIN NOW With odds oppress'd, in such unequal strife? END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd at length, his pointed spear he shook; END
BEGIN NOW And, casting on the moon a mournful look: END
BEGIN NOW Guardian of groves, and goddess of the night, END
BEGIN NOW Fair queen," he said, "direct my dart aright. END
BEGIN NOW If e'er my pious father, for my sake, END
BEGIN NOW Did grateful off'rings on thy altars make, END
BEGIN NOW Or I increas'd them with my sylvan toils, END
BEGIN NOW And hung thy holy roofs with savage spoils, END
BEGIN NOW Give me to scatter these." Then from his ear END
BEGIN NOW He pois'd, and aim'd, and launch'd the trembling spear. END
BEGIN NOW The deadly weapon, hissing from the grove, END
BEGIN NOW Impetuous on the back of Sulmo drove; END
BEGIN NOW Pierc'd his thin armor, drank his vital blood, END
BEGIN NOW And in his body left the broken END
BEGIN NOW He staggers round; his eyeballs roll in death, END
BEGIN NOW And with short sobs he gasps away his breath. END
BEGIN NOW All stand amaz'd- a second jav'lin flies END
BEGIN NOW With equal strength, and quivers thro' the skies. END
BEGIN NOW This thro' thy temples, Tagus, forc'd the way, END
BEGIN NOW And in the brainpan warmly buried lay. END
BEGIN NOW Fierce Volscens foams with rage, and, gazing round, END
BEGIN NOW Descried not him who gave the fatal wound, END
BEGIN NOW Nor knew to fix revenge: "But thou," he cries, END
BEGIN NOW Shalt pay for both," and at the pris'ner flies END
BEGIN NOW With his drawn sword. Then, struck with deep despair, END
BEGIN NOW That cruel sight the lover could not bear; END
BEGIN NOW But from his covert rush'd in open view, END
BEGIN NOW And sent his voice before him as he flew: END
BEGIN NOW Me! me!" he cried- "turn all your swords alone END
BEGIN NOW On me- the fact confess'd, the fault my own. END
BEGIN NOW He neither could nor durst, the guiltless youth: END
BEGIN NOW Ye moon and stars, bear witness to the truth! END
BEGIN NOW His only crime (if friendship can offend) END
BEGIN NOW Is too much love to his unhappy friend. END
BEGIN NOW Too late he speaks: the sword, which fury guides, END
BEGIN NOW Driv'n with full force, had pierc'd his tender sides. END
BEGIN NOW Down fell the beauteous youth: the yawning wound END
BEGIN NOW Gush'd out a purple stream, and stain'd the ground. END
BEGIN NOW His snowy neck reclines upon his breast, END
BEGIN NOW Like a fair flow'r by the keen share oppress'd; END
BEGIN NOW Like a white poppy sinking on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Whose heavy head is overcharg'd with rain. END
BEGIN NOW Despair, and rage, and vengeance justly vow'd, END
BEGIN NOW Drove Nisus headlong on the hostile crowd. END
BEGIN NOW Volscens he seeks; on him alone he bends: END
BEGIN NOW Borne back and bor'd by his surrounding friends, END
BEGIN NOW Onward he press'd, and kept him still in sight; END
BEGIN NOW Then whirl'd aloft his sword with all his might: END
BEGIN NOW Th' unerring steel descended while he spoke, END
BEGIN NOW Piered his wide mouth, and thro' his weazon broke. END
BEGIN NOW Dying, he slew; and, stagg'ring on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW With swimming eyes he sought his lover slain; END
BEGIN NOW Then quiet on his bleeding bosom fell, END
BEGIN NOW Content, in death, to be reveng'd so well. END
BEGIN NOW O happy friends! for, if my verse can give END
BEGIN NOW Immortal life, your fame shall ever live, END
BEGIN NOW Fix'd as the Capitol's foundation lies, END
BEGIN NOW And spread, where'er the Roman eagle flies! END
BEGIN NOW The conqu'ring party first divide the prey, END
BEGIN NOW Then their slain leader to the camp convey. END
BEGIN NOW With wonder, as they went, the troops were fill'd, END
BEGIN NOW To see such numbers whom so few had kill'd. END
BEGIN NOW Serranus, Rhamnes, and the rest, they found: END
BEGIN NOW Vast crowds the dying and the dead surround; END
BEGIN NOW And the yet reeking blood o'erflows the ground. END
BEGIN NOW All knew the helmet which Messapus lost, END
BEGIN NOW But mourn'd a purchase that so dear had cost. END
BEGIN NOW Now rose the ruddy morn from Tithon's bed, END
BEGIN NOW And with the dawn of day the skies o'erspread; END
BEGIN NOW Nor long the sun his daily course withheld, END
BEGIN NOW But added colors to the world reveal'd: END
BEGIN NOW When early Turnus, wak'ning with the light, END
BEGIN NOW All clad in armor, calls his troops to fight. END
BEGIN NOW His martial men with fierce harangue he fir'd, END
BEGIN NOW And his own ardor in their souls inspir'd. END
BEGIN NOW This done- to give new terror to his foes, END
BEGIN NOW The heads of Nisus and his friend he shows, END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd high on pointed spears- a ghastly sight: END
BEGIN NOW Loud peals of shouts ensue, and barbarous delight. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the Trojans run, where danger calls; END
BEGIN NOW They line their trenches, and they man their walls. END
BEGIN NOW In front extended to the left they stood; END
BEGIN NOW Safe was the right, surrounded by the flood. END
BEGIN NOW But, casting from their tow'rs a frightful view, END
BEGIN NOW They saw the faces, which too well they knew, END
BEGIN NOW Tho' then disguis'd in death, and smear'd all o'er END
BEGIN NOW With filth obscene, and dropping putrid gore. END
BEGIN NOW Soon hasty fame thro' the sad city bears END
BEGIN NOW The mournful message to the mother's ears. END
BEGIN NOW An icy cold benumbs her limbs; she shakes; END
BEGIN NOW Her cheeks the blood, her hand the web forsakes. END
BEGIN NOW She runs the rampires round amidst the war, END
BEGIN NOW Nor fears the flying darts; she rends her hair, END
BEGIN NOW And fills with loud laments the liquid air. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, then, my lov'd Euryalus appears! END
BEGIN NOW Thus looks the prop my declining years! END
BEGIN NOW Was't on this face my famish'd eyes I fed? END
BEGIN NOW Ah! how unlike the living is the dead! END
BEGIN NOW And could'st thou leave me, cruel, thus alone? END
BEGIN NOW Not one kind kiss from a departing son! END
BEGIN NOW No look, no last adieu before he went, END
BEGIN NOW In an ill-boding hour to slaughter sent! END
BEGIN NOW Cold on the ground, and pressing foreign clay, END
BEGIN NOW To Latian dogs and fowls he lies a prey! END
BEGIN NOW Nor was I near to close his dying eyes, END
BEGIN NOW To wash his wounds, to weep his obsequies, END
BEGIN NOW To call about his corpse his crying friends, END
BEGIN NOW Or spread the mantle (made for other ends) END
BEGIN NOW On his dear body, which I wove with care, END
BEGIN NOW Nor did my daily pains or nightly labor spare. END
BEGIN NOW Where shall I find his corpse? what earth sustains END
BEGIN NOW His trunk dismember'd, and his cold remains? END
BEGIN NOW For this, alas! I left my needful ease, END
BEGIN NOW Expos'd my life to winds and winter seas! END
BEGIN NOW If any pity touch Rutulian hearts, END
BEGIN NOW Here empty all your quivers, all your darts; END
BEGIN NOW Or, if they fail, thou, Jove, conclude my woe, END
BEGIN NOW And send me thunderstruck to shades below! END
BEGIN NOW Her shrieks and clamors pierce the Trojans' ears, END
BEGIN NOW Unman their courage, and augment their fears; END
BEGIN NOW Nor young Ascanius could the sight sustain, END
BEGIN NOW Nor old Ilioneus his tears restrain, END
BEGIN NOW But Actor and Idaeus jointly sent, END
BEGIN NOW To bear the madding mother to her tent. END
BEGIN NOW And now the trumpets terribly, from far, END
BEGIN NOW With rattling clangor, rouse the sleepy war. END
BEGIN NOW The soldiers' shouts succeed the brazen sounds; END
BEGIN NOW And heav'n, from pole to pole, the noise rebounds. END
BEGIN NOW The Volscians bear their shields upon their head, END
BEGIN NOW And, rushing forward, form a moving shed. END
BEGIN NOW These fill the ditch; those pull the bulwarks down: END
BEGIN NOW Some raise the ladders; others scale the town. END
BEGIN NOW But, where void spaces on the walls appear, END
BEGIN NOW Or thin defense, they pour their forces there. END
BEGIN NOW With poles and missive weapons, from afar, END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans keep aloof the rising war. END
BEGIN NOW Taught, by their ten years' siege, defensive fight, END
BEGIN NOW They roll down ribs of rocks, an unresisted weight, END
BEGIN NOW To break the penthouse with the pond'rous blow, END
BEGIN NOW Which yet the patient Volscians undergo: END
BEGIN NOW But could not bear th' unequal combat long; END
BEGIN NOW For, where the Trojans find the thickest throng, END
BEGIN NOW The ruin falls: their shatter'd shields give way, END
BEGIN NOW And their crush'd heads become an easy prey. END
BEGIN NOW They shrink for fear, abated of their rage, END
BEGIN NOW Nor longer dare in a blind fight engage; END
BEGIN NOW Contented now to gall them from below END
BEGIN NOW With darts and slings, and with the distant bow. END
BEGIN NOW Elsewhere Mezentius, terrible to view, END
BEGIN NOW A blazing pine within the trenches threw. END
BEGIN NOW But brave Messapus, Neptune's warlike son, END
BEGIN NOW Broke down the palisades, the trenches won, END
BEGIN NOW And loud for ladders calls, to scale the town. END
BEGIN NOW Calliope, begin! Ye sacred Nine, END
BEGIN NOW Inspire your poet in his high design, END
BEGIN NOW To sing what slaughter manly Turnus made, END
BEGIN NOW What souls he sent below the Stygian shade, END
BEGIN NOW What fame the soldiers with their captain share, END
BEGIN NOW And the vast circuit of the fatal war; END
BEGIN NOW For you in singing martial facts excel; END
BEGIN NOW You best remember, and alone can tell. END
BEGIN NOW There stood a tow'r, amazing to the sight, END
BEGIN NOW Built up of beams, and of stupendous height: END
BEGIN NOW Art, and the nature of the place, conspir'd END
BEGIN NOW To furnish all the strength that war requir'd. END
BEGIN NOW To level this, the bold Italians join; END
BEGIN NOW The wary Trojans obviate their design; END
BEGIN NOW With weighty stones o'erwhelm their troops below, END
BEGIN NOW Shoot thro' the loopholes, and sharp jav'lins throw. END
BEGIN NOW Turnus, the chief, toss'd from his thund'ring hand END
BEGIN NOW Against the wooden walls, a flaming brand: END
BEGIN NOW It stuck, the fiery plague; the winds were high; END
BEGIN NOW The planks were season'd, and the timber dry. END
BEGIN NOW Contagion caught the posts; it spread along, END
BEGIN NOW Scorch'd, and to distance drove the scatter'd throng. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans fled; the fire pursued amain, END
BEGIN NOW Still gath'ring fast upon the trembling train; END
BEGIN NOW Till, crowding to the corners of the wall, END
BEGIN NOW Down the defense and the defenders fall. END
BEGIN NOW The mighty flaw makes heav'n itself resound: END
BEGIN NOW The dead and dying Trojans strew the ground. END
BEGIN NOW The tow'r, that follow'd on the fallen crew, END
BEGIN NOW Whelm'd o'er their heads, and buried whom it slew: END
BEGIN NOW Some stuck upon the darts themselves had sent; END
BEGIN NOW All the same equal ruin underwent. END
BEGIN NOW Young Lycus and Helenor only scape; END
BEGIN NOW Sav'd- how, they know not- from the steepy leap. END
BEGIN NOW Helenor, elder of the two: by birth, END
BEGIN NOW On one side royal, one a son of earth, END
BEGIN NOW Whom to the Lydian king Licymnia bare, END
BEGIN NOW (A privilege which none but freemen share). END
BEGIN NOW Slight were his arms, a sword and silver shield: END
BEGIN NOW No marks of honor charg'd its empty field. END
BEGIN NOW Light as he fell, so light the youth arose, END
BEGIN NOW And rising, found himself amidst his foes; END
BEGIN NOW Nor flight was left, nor hopes to force his way. END
BEGIN NOW Embolden'd by despair, he stood at bay; END
BEGIN NOW And- like a stag, whom all the troop surrounds END
BEGIN NOW Of eager huntsmen and invading hounds- END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd on death, he dissipates his fears, END
BEGIN NOW And bounds aloft against the pointed spears: END
BEGIN NOW So dares the youth, secure of death; and throws END
BEGIN NOW His dying body on his thickest foes. END
BEGIN NOW But Lycus, swifter of his feet by far, END
BEGIN NOW Runs, doubles, winds and turns, amidst the war; END
BEGIN NOW Springs to the walls, and leaves his foes behind, END
BEGIN NOW And snatches at the beam he first can find; END
BEGIN NOW Looks up, and leaps aloft at all the stretch, END
BEGIN NOW In hopes the helping hand of some kind friend to reach. END
BEGIN NOW But Turnus follow'd hard his hunted prey END
BEGIN NOW (His spear had almost reach'd him in the way, END
BEGIN NOW Short of his reins, and scarce a span behind) END
BEGIN NOW Fool! said the chief, "tho' fleeter than the wind, END
BEGIN NOW Couldst thou presume to scape, when I pursue? END
BEGIN NOW He said, and downward by the feet he drew END
BEGIN NOW Vast ruins come along, rent from the smoking walls. END
BEGIN NOW Thus on some silver swan, or tim'rous hare, END
BEGIN NOW Jove's bird comes sousing down from upper air; END
BEGIN NOW Her crooked talons truss the fearful prey: END
BEGIN NOW Then out of sight she soars, and wings her way. END
BEGIN NOW So seizes the grim wolf the tender lamb, END
BEGIN NOW In vain lamented by the bleating dam. END
BEGIN NOW Then rushing onward with a barb'rous cry, END
BEGIN NOW The troops of Turnus to the combat fly. END
BEGIN NOW Toss'd firebrands to the steepy turrets throw. END
BEGIN NOW Ilioneus, as bold Lucetius came END
BEGIN NOW To force the gate, and feed the kindling flame, END
BEGIN NOW Roll'd down the fragment of a rock so right, END
BEGIN NOW It crush'd him double underneath the weight. END
BEGIN NOW Two more young Liger and Asylas slew: END
BEGIN NOW To bend the bow young Liger better knew; END
BEGIN NOW Asylas best the pointed jav'lin threw. END
BEGIN NOW Brave Caeneus laid Ortygius on the plain; END
BEGIN NOW The victor Caeneus was by Turnus slain. END
BEGIN NOW By the same hand, Clonius and Itys fall, END
BEGIN NOW Sagar, and Ida, standing on the wall. END
BEGIN NOW From Capys' arms his fate Privernus found: END
BEGIN NOW Hurt by Themilla first-but slight the wound- END
BEGIN NOW His shield thrown by, to mitigate the smart, END
BEGIN NOW He clapp'd his hand upon the wounded part: END
BEGIN NOW The second shaft came swift and unespied, END
BEGIN NOW And pierc'd his hand, and nail'd it to his side, END
BEGIN NOW Transfix'd his breathing lungs and beating heart: END
BEGIN NOW The soul came issuing out, and hiss'd against the dart. END
BEGIN NOW The son of Arcens shone amid the rest, END
BEGIN NOW In glitt'ring armor and a purple vest, END
BEGIN NOW (Fair was his face, his eyes inspiring love,) END
BEGIN NOW Bred by his father in the Martian grove, END
BEGIN NOW Where the fat altars of Palicus flame, END
BEGIN NOW And send in arms to purchase early fame. END
BEGIN NOW Him when he spied from far, the Tuscan king END
BEGIN NOW Laid by the lance, and took him to the sling, END
BEGIN NOW Thrice whirl'd the thong around his head, and threw: END
BEGIN NOW The heated lead half melted as it flew; END
BEGIN NOW It pierc'd his hollow temples and his brain; END
BEGIN NOW The youth came tumbling down, and spurn'd the plain. END
BEGIN NOW Then young Ascanius, who, before this day, END
BEGIN NOW Was wont in woods to shoot the savage prey, END
BEGIN NOW First bent in martial strife the twanging bow, END
BEGIN NOW And exercis'd against a human foe- END
BEGIN NOW With this bereft Numanus of his life, END
BEGIN NOW Who Turnus' younger sister took to wife. END
BEGIN NOW Proud of his realm, and of his royal bride, END
BEGIN NOW Vaunting before his troops, and lengthen'd with a stride, END
BEGIN NOW In these insulting terms the Trojans he defied: END
BEGIN NOW Twice-conquer'd cowards, now your shame is shown- END
BEGIN NOW Coop'd up a second time within your town! END
BEGIN NOW Who dare not issue forth in open field, END
BEGIN NOW But hold your walls before you for a shield. END
BEGIN NOW Thus threat you war? thus our alliance force? END
BEGIN NOW What gods, what madness, hether steer'd your course? END
BEGIN NOW You shall not find the sons of Atreus here, END
BEGIN NOW Nor need the frauds of sly Ulysses fear. END
BEGIN NOW Strong from the cradle, of a sturdy brood, END
BEGIN NOW We bear our newborn infants to the flood; END
BEGIN NOW There bath'd amid the stream, our boys we hold, END
BEGIN NOW With winter harden'd, and inur'd to cold. END
BEGIN NOW They wake before the day to range the wood, END
BEGIN NOW Kill ere they eat, nor taste unconquer'd food. END
BEGIN NOW No sports, but what belong to war, they know: END
BEGIN NOW To break the stubborn colt, to bend the bow. END
BEGIN NOW Our youth, of labor patient, earn their bread; END
BEGIN NOW Hardly they work, with frugal diet fed. END
BEGIN NOW From plows and harrows sent to seek renown, END
BEGIN NOW They fight in fields, and storm the shaken town. END
BEGIN NOW No part of life from toils of war is free, END
BEGIN NOW No change in age, or diff'rence in degree. END
BEGIN NOW We plow and till in arms; our oxen feel, END
BEGIN NOW Instead of goads, the spur and pointed steel; END
BEGIN NOW Th' inverted lance makes furrows in the plain. END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n time, that changes all, yet changes us in vain: END
BEGIN NOW The body, not the mind; nor can control END
BEGIN NOW Th' immortal vigor, or abate the soul. END
BEGIN NOW Our helms defend the young, disguise the gray: END
BEGIN NOW We live by plunder, and delight in prey. END
BEGIN NOW Your vests embroider'd with rich purple shine; END
BEGIN NOW In sloth you glory, and in dances join. END
BEGIN NOW Your vests have sweeping sleeves; with female pride END
BEGIN NOW Your turbants underneath your chins are tied. END
BEGIN NOW Go, Phrygians, to your Dindymus again! END
BEGIN NOW Go, less than women, in the shapes of men! END
BEGIN NOW Go, mix'd with eunuchs, in the Mother's rites, END
BEGIN NOW Where with unequal sound the flute invites; END
BEGIN NOW Sing, dance, and howl, by turns, in Ida's shade: END
BEGIN NOW Resign the war to men, who know the martial trade! END
BEGIN NOW This foul reproach Ascanius could not hear END
BEGIN NOW With patience, or a vow'd revenge forbear. END
BEGIN NOW At the full stretch of both his hands he drew, END
BEGIN NOW And almost join'd the horns of the tough yew. END
BEGIN NOW But, first, before the throne of Jove he stood, END
BEGIN NOW And thus with lifted hands invok'd the god: END
BEGIN NOW My first attempt, great Jupiter, succeed! END
BEGIN NOW An annual off'ring in thy grove shall bleed; END
BEGIN NOW A snow-white steer, before thy altar led, END
BEGIN NOW Who, like his mother, bears aloft his head, END
BEGIN NOW Butts with his threat'ning brows, and bellowing stands, END
BEGIN NOW And dares the fight, and spurns the yellow sands. END
BEGIN NOW Jove bow'd the heav'ns, and lent a gracious ear, END
BEGIN NOW And thunder'd on the left, amidst the clear. END
BEGIN NOW Sounded at once the bow; and swiftly flies END
BEGIN NOW The feather'd death, and hisses thro' the skies. END
BEGIN NOW The steel thro' both his temples forc'd the way: END
BEGIN NOW Extended on the ground, Numanus lay. END
BEGIN NOW Go now, vain boaster, and true valor scorn! END
BEGIN NOW The Phrygians, twice subdued, yet make this third return. END
BEGIN NOW Ascanius said no more. The Trojans shake END
BEGIN NOW The heav'ns with shouting, and new vigor take. END
BEGIN NOW Apollo then bestrode a golden cloud, END
BEGIN NOW To view the feats of arms, and fighting crowd; END
BEGIN NOW And thus the beardless victor he bespoke aloud: END
BEGIN NOW Advance, illustrious youth, increase in fame, END
BEGIN NOW And wide from east to west extend thy name; END
BEGIN NOW Offspring of gods thyself; and Rome shall owe END
BEGIN NOW To thee a race of demigods below. END
BEGIN NOW This is the way to heav'n: the pow'rs divine END
BEGIN NOW From this beginning date the Julian line. END
BEGIN NOW To thee, to them, and their victorious heirs, END
BEGIN NOW The conquer'd war is due, and the vast world is theirs. END
BEGIN NOW Troy is too narrow for thy name." He said, END
BEGIN NOW And plunging downward shot his radiant head; END
BEGIN NOW Dispell'd the breathing air, that broke his flight: END
BEGIN NOW Shorn of his beams, a man to mortal sight. END
BEGIN NOW Old Butes' form he took, Anchises' squire, END
BEGIN NOW Now left, to rule Ascanius, by his sire: END
BEGIN NOW His wrinkled visage, and his hoary hairs, END
BEGIN NOW His mien, his habit, and his arms, he wears, END
BEGIN NOW And thus salutes the boy, too forward for his years: END
BEGIN NOW Suffice it thee, thy father's worthy son, END
BEGIN NOW The warlike prize thou hast already won. END
BEGIN NOW The god of archers gives thy youth a part END
BEGIN NOW Of his own praise, nor envies equal art. END
BEGIN NOW Now tempt the war no more." He said, and flew END
BEGIN NOW Obscure in air, and vanish'd from their view. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans, by his arms, their patron know, END
BEGIN NOW And hear the twanging of his heav'nly bow. END
BEGIN NOW Then duteous force they use, and Phoebus' name, END
BEGIN NOW To keep from fight the youth too fond of fame. END
BEGIN NOW Undaunted, they themselves no danger shun; END
BEGIN NOW From wall to wall the shouts and clamors run. END
BEGIN NOW They bend their bows; they whirl their slings around; END
BEGIN NOW Heaps of spent arrows fall, and strew the ground; END
BEGIN NOW And helms, and shields, and rattling arms resound. END
BEGIN NOW The combat thickens, like the storm that flies END
BEGIN NOW From westward, when the show'ry Kids arise; END
BEGIN NOW Or patt'ring hail comes pouring on the main, END
BEGIN NOW When Jupiter descends in harden'd rain, END
BEGIN NOW Or bellowing clouds burst with a stormy sound, END
BEGIN NOW And with an armed winter strew the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Pand'rus and Bitias, thunderbolts of war, END
BEGIN NOW Whom Hiera to bold Alcanor bare END
BEGIN NOW On Ida's top, two youths of height and size END
BEGIN NOW Like firs that on their mother mountain rise, END
BEGIN NOW Presuming on their force, the gates unbar, END
BEGIN NOW And of their own accord invite the war. END
BEGIN NOW With fates averse, against their king's command, END
BEGIN NOW Arm'd, on the right and on the left they stand, END
BEGIN NOW And flank the passage: shining steel they wear, END
BEGIN NOW And waving crests above their heads appear. END
BEGIN NOW Thus two tall oaks, that Padus' banks adorn, END
BEGIN NOW Lift up to heav'n their leafy heads unshorn, END
BEGIN NOW And, overpress'd with nature's heavy load, END
BEGIN NOW Dance to the whistling winds, and at each other nod. END
BEGIN NOW In flows a tide of Latians, when they see END
BEGIN NOW The gate set open, and the passage free; END
BEGIN NOW Bold Quercens, with rash Tmarus, rushing on, END
BEGIN NOW Equicolus, that in bright armor shone, END
BEGIN NOW And Haemon first; but soon repuls'd they fly, END
BEGIN NOW Or in the well-defended pass they die. END
BEGIN NOW These with success are fir'd, and those with rage, END
BEGIN NOW And each on equal terms at length ingage. END
BEGIN NOW Drawn from their lines, and issuing on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans hand to hand the fight maintain. END
BEGIN NOW Fierce Turnus in another quarter fought, END
BEGIN NOW When suddenly th' unhop'd-for news was brought, END
BEGIN NOW The foes had left the fastness of their place, END
BEGIN NOW Prevail'd in fight, and had his men in chase. END
BEGIN NOW He quits th' attack, and, to prevent their fate, END
BEGIN NOW Runs where the giant brothers guard the gate. END
BEGIN NOW The first he met, Antiphates the brave, END
BEGIN NOW But base-begotten on a Theban slave, END
BEGIN NOW Sarpedon's son, he slew: the deadly dart END
BEGIN NOW Found passage thro' his breast, and pierc'd his heart. END
BEGIN NOW Fix'd in the wound th' Italian cornel stood, END
BEGIN NOW Warm'd in his lungs, and in his vital blood. END
BEGIN NOW Aphidnus next, and Erymanthus dies, END
BEGIN NOW And Meropes, and the gigantic size END
BEGIN NOW Of Bitias, threat'ning with his ardent eyes. END
BEGIN NOW Not by the feeble dart he fell oppress'd END
BEGIN NOW (A dart were lost within that roomy breast), END
BEGIN NOW But from a knotted lance, large, heavy, strong, END
BEGIN NOW Which roar'd like thunder as it whirl'd along: END
BEGIN NOW Not two bull hides th' impetuous force withhold, END
BEGIN NOW Nor coat of double mail, with scales of gold. END
BEGIN NOW Down sunk the monster bulk and press'd the ground; END
BEGIN NOW His arms and clatt'ring shield on the vast body sound, END
BEGIN NOW Not with less ruin than the Bajan mole, END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd on the seas, the surges to control- END
BEGIN NOW At once comes tumbling down the rocky wall; END
BEGIN NOW Prone to the deep, the stones disjointed fall END
BEGIN NOW Of the vast pile; the scatter'd ocean flies; END
BEGIN NOW Black sands, discolor'd froth, and mingled mud arise: END
BEGIN NOW The frighted billows roll, and seek the shores; END
BEGIN NOW Then trembles Prochyta, then Ischia roars: END
BEGIN NOW Typhoeus, thrown beneath, by Jove's command, END
BEGIN NOW Astonish'd at the flaw that shakes the land, END
BEGIN NOW Soon shifts his weary side, and, scarce awake, END
BEGIN NOW With wonder feels the weight press lighter on his back. END
BEGIN NOW The warrior god the Latian troops inspir'd, END
BEGIN NOW New strung their sinews, and their courage fir'd, END
BEGIN NOW But chills the Trojan hearts with cold affright: END
BEGIN NOW Then black despair precipitates their flight. END
BEGIN NOW When Pandarus beheld his brother kill'd, END
BEGIN NOW The town with fear and wild confusion fill'd, END
BEGIN NOW He turns the hinges of the heavy gate END
BEGIN NOW With both his hands, and adds his shoulders to the weight END
BEGIN NOW Some happier friends within the walls inclos'd; END
BEGIN NOW The rest shut out, to certain death expos'd: END
BEGIN NOW Fool as he was, and frantic in his care, END
BEGIN NOW T' admit young Turnus, and include the war! END
BEGIN NOW He thrust amid the crowd, securely bold, END
BEGIN NOW Like a fierce tiger pent amid the fold. END
BEGIN NOW Too late his blazing buckler they descry, END
BEGIN NOW And sparkling fires that shot from either eye, END
BEGIN NOW His mighty members, and his ample breast, END
BEGIN NOW His rattling armor, and his crimson crest. END
BEGIN NOW Far from that hated face the Trojans fly, END
BEGIN NOW All but the fool who sought his destiny. END
BEGIN NOW Mad Pandarus steps forth, with vengeance vow'd END
BEGIN NOW For Bitias' death, and threatens thus aloud: END
BEGIN NOW These are not Ardea's walls, nor this the town END
BEGIN NOW Amata proffers with Lavinia's crown: END
BEGIN NOW 'T is hostile earth you tread. Of hope bereft, END
BEGIN NOW No means of safe return by flight are left. END
BEGIN NOW To whom, with count'nance calm, and soul sedate, END
BEGIN NOW Thus Turnus: "Then begin, and try thy fate: END
BEGIN NOW My message to the ghost of Priam bear; END
BEGIN NOW Tell him a new Achilles sent thee there. END
BEGIN NOW A lance of tough ground ash the Trojan threw, END
BEGIN NOW Rough in the rind, and knotted as it grew: END
BEGIN NOW With his full force he whirl'd it first around; END
BEGIN NOW But the soft yielding air receiv'd the wound: END
BEGIN NOW Imperial Juno turn'd the course before, END
BEGIN NOW And fix'd the wand'ring weapon in the door. END
BEGIN NOW But hope not thou," said Turnus, "when I strike, END
BEGIN NOW To shun thy fate: our force is not alike, END
BEGIN NOW Nor thy steel temper'd by the Lemnian god. END
BEGIN NOW Then rising, on his utmost stretch he stood, END
BEGIN NOW And aim'd from high: the full descending blow END
BEGIN NOW Cleaves the broad front and beardless cheeks in two. END
BEGIN NOW Down sinks the giant with a thund'ring sound: END
BEGIN NOW His pond'rous limbs oppress the trembling ground; END
BEGIN NOW Blood, brains, and foam gush from the gaping wound: END
BEGIN NOW Scalp, face, and shoulders the keen steel divides, END
BEGIN NOW And the shar'd visage hangs on equal sides. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojans fly from their approaching fate; END
BEGIN NOW And, had the victor then secur'd the gate, END
BEGIN NOW And to his troops without unclos'd the bars, END
BEGIN NOW One lucky day had ended all his wars. END
BEGIN NOW But boiling youth, and blind desire of blood, END
BEGIN NOW Push'd on his fury, to pursue the crowd. END
BEGIN NOW Hamstring'd behind, unhappy Gyges died; END
BEGIN NOW Then Phalaris is added to his side. END
BEGIN NOW The pointed jav'lins from the dead he drew, END
BEGIN NOW And their friends' arms against their fellows threw. END
BEGIN NOW Strong Halys stands in vain; weak Phlegys flies; END
BEGIN NOW Saturnia, still at hand, new force and fire supplies. END
BEGIN NOW Then Halius, Prytanis, Alcander fall- END
BEGIN NOW Ingag'd against the foes who scal'd the wall: END
BEGIN NOW But, whom they fear'd without, they found within. END
BEGIN NOW At last, tho' late, by Lynceus he was seen. END
BEGIN NOW He calls new succors, and assaults the prince: END
BEGIN NOW But weak his force, and vain is their defense. END
BEGIN NOW Turn'd to the right, his sword the hero drew, END
BEGIN NOW And at one blow the bold aggressor slew. END
BEGIN NOW He joints the neck; and, with a stroke so strong, END
BEGIN NOW The helm flies off, and bears the head along. END
BEGIN NOW Next him, the huntsman Amycus he kill'd, END
BEGIN NOW In darts invenom'd and in poison skill'd. END
BEGIN NOW Then Clytius fell beneath his fatal spear, END
BEGIN NOW And Creteus, whom the Muses held so dear: END
BEGIN NOW He fought with courage, and he sung the fight; END
BEGIN NOW Arms were his bus'ness, verses his delight. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan chiefs behold, with rage and grief, END
BEGIN NOW Their slaughter'd friends, and hasten their relief. END
BEGIN NOW Bold Mnestheus rallies first the broken train, END
BEGIN NOW Whom brave Seresthus and his troop sustain. END
BEGIN NOW To save the living, and revenge the dead, END
BEGIN NOW Against one warrior's arms all Troy they led. END
BEGIN NOW O, void of sense and courage!" Mnestheus cried, END
BEGIN NOW Where can you hope your coward heads to hide? END
BEGIN NOW Ah! where beyond these rampires can you run? END
BEGIN NOW One man, and in your camp inclos'd, you shun! END
BEGIN NOW Shall then a single sword such slaughter boast, END
BEGIN NOW And pass unpunish'd from a num'rous host? END
BEGIN NOW Forsaking honor, and renouncing fame, END
BEGIN NOW Your gods, your country, and your king you shame! END
BEGIN NOW This just reproach their virtue does excite: END
BEGIN NOW They stand, they join, they thicken to the fight. END
BEGIN NOW Now Turnus doubts, and yet disdains to yield, END
BEGIN NOW But with slow paces measures back the field, END
BEGIN NOW And inches to the walls, where Tiber's tide, END
BEGIN NOW Washing the camp, defends the weaker side. END
BEGIN NOW The more he loses, they advance the more, END
BEGIN NOW And tread in ev'ry step he trod before. END
BEGIN NOW They shout: they bear him back; and, whom by might END
BEGIN NOW They cannot conquer, they oppress with weight. END
BEGIN NOW As, compass'd with a wood of spears around, END
BEGIN NOW The lordly lion still maintains his ground; END
BEGIN NOW Grins horrible, retires, and turns again; END
BEGIN NOW Threats his distended paws, and shakes his mane; END
BEGIN NOW He loses while in vain he presses on, END
BEGIN NOW Nor will his courage let him dare to run: END
BEGIN NOW So Turnus fares, and, unresolved of flight, END
BEGIN NOW Yet twice, inrag'd, the combat he renews, END
BEGIN NOW Twice breaks, and twice his broken foes pursues. END
BEGIN NOW But now they swarm, and, with fresh troops supplied, END
BEGIN NOW Come rolling on, and rush from ev'ry side: END
BEGIN NOW Nor Juno, who sustain'd his arms before, END
BEGIN NOW Dares with new strength suffice th' exhausted store; END
BEGIN NOW For Jove, with sour commands, sent Iris down, END
BEGIN NOW To force th' invader from the frighted town. END
BEGIN NOW With labor spent, no longer can he wield END
BEGIN NOW The heavy fanchion, or sustain the shield, END
BEGIN NOW O'erwhelm'd with darts, which from afar they fling: END
BEGIN NOW The weapons round his hollow temples ring; END
BEGIN NOW His golden helm gives way, with stony blows END
BEGIN NOW Batter'd, and flat, and beaten to his brows. END
BEGIN NOW His crest is rash'd away; his ample shield END
BEGIN NOW Is falsified, and round with jav'lins fill'd. END
BEGIN NOW The foe, now faint, the Trojans overwhelm; END
BEGIN NOW And Mnestheus lays hard load upon his helm. END
BEGIN NOW Sick sweat succeeds; he drops at ev'ry pore; END
BEGIN NOW With driving dust his cheeks are pasted o'er; END
BEGIN NOW Shorter and shorter ev'ry gasp he takes; END
BEGIN NOW And vain efforts and hurtless blows he makes. END
BEGIN NOW Plung'd in the flood, and made the waters fly. END
BEGIN NOW The yellow god the welcome burthen bore, END
BEGIN NOW And wip'd the sweat, and wash'd away the gore; END
BEGIN NOW Then gently wafts him to the farther coast, END
BEGIN NOW And sends him safe to cheer his anxious host. END
BEGIN NOW The gates of heav'n unfold: Jove summons all END
BEGIN NOW The gods to council in the common hall. END
BEGIN NOW Sublimely seated, he surveys from far END
BEGIN NOW The fields, the camp, the fortune of the war, END
BEGIN NOW And all th' inferior world. From first to last, END
BEGIN NOW The sov'reign senate in degrees are plac'd. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus th' almighty sire began: "Ye gods, END
BEGIN NOW Natives or denizens of blest abodes, END
BEGIN NOW From whence these murmurs, and this change of mind, END
BEGIN NOW This backward fate from what was first design'd? END
BEGIN NOW Why this protracted war, when my commands END
BEGIN NOW Pronounc'd a peace, and gave the Latian lands? END
BEGIN NOW What fear or hope on either part divides END
BEGIN NOW Our heav'ns, and arms our powers on diff'rent sides? END
BEGIN NOW A lawful time of war at length will come, END
BEGIN NOW (Nor need your haste anticipate the doom), END
BEGIN NOW When Carthage shall contend the world with Rome, END
BEGIN NOW Shall force the rigid rocks and Alpine chains, END
BEGIN NOW And, like a flood, come pouring on the plains. END
BEGIN NOW Then is your time for faction and debate, END
BEGIN NOW For partial favor, and permitted hate. END
BEGIN NOW Let now your immature dissension cease; END
BEGIN NOW Sit quiet, and compose your souls to peace. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Jupiter in few unfolds the charge; END
BEGIN NOW But lovely Venus thus replies at large: END
BEGIN NOW O pow'r immense, eternal energy, END
BEGIN NOW (For to what else protection can we fly?) END
BEGIN NOW Seest thou the proud Rutulians, how they dare END
BEGIN NOW In fields, unpunish'd, and insult my care? END
BEGIN NOW How lofty Turnus vaunts amidst his train, END
BEGIN NOW In shining arms, triumphant on the plain? END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n in their lines and trenches they contend, END
BEGIN NOW And scarce their walls the Trojan troops defend: END
BEGIN NOW The town is fill'd with slaughter, and o'erfloats, END
BEGIN NOW With a red deluge, their increasing moats. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas, ignorant, and far from thence, END
BEGIN NOW Has left a camp expos'd, without defense. END
BEGIN NOW This endless outrage shall they still sustain? END
BEGIN NOW Shall Troy renew'd be forc'd and fir'd again? END
BEGIN NOW A second siege my banish'd issue fears, END
BEGIN NOW And a new Diomede in arms appears. END
BEGIN NOW One more audacious mortal will be found; END
BEGIN NOW And I, thy daughter, wait another wound. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, if with fates averse, without thy leave, END
BEGIN NOW The Latian lands my progeny receive, END
BEGIN NOW Bear they the pains of violated law, END
BEGIN NOW And thy protection from their aid withdraw. END
BEGIN NOW But, if the gods their sure success foretell; END
BEGIN NOW If those of heav'n consent with those of hell, END
BEGIN NOW To promise Italy; who dare debate END
BEGIN NOW The pow'r of Jove, or fix another fate? END
BEGIN NOW What should I tell of tempests on the main, END
BEGIN NOW Of Aeolus usurping Neptune's reign? END
BEGIN NOW Of Iris sent, with Bacchanalian heat END
BEGIN NOW T' inspire the matrons, and destroy the fleet? END
BEGIN NOW Now Juno to the Stygian sky descends, END
BEGIN NOW Solicits hell for aid, and arms the fiends. END
BEGIN NOW That new example wanted yet above: END
BEGIN NOW An act that well became the wife of Jove! END
BEGIN NOW Alecto, rais'd by her, with rage inflames END
BEGIN NOW The peaceful bosoms of the Latian dames. END
BEGIN NOW Imperial sway no more exalts my mind; END
BEGIN NOW (Such hopes I had indeed, while Heav'n was kind;) END
BEGIN NOW Now let my happier foes possess my place, END
BEGIN NOW Whom Jove prefers before the Trojan race; END
BEGIN NOW And conquer they, whom you with conquest grace. END
BEGIN NOW Since you can spare, from all your wide command, END
BEGIN NOW No spot of earth, no hospitable land, END
BEGIN NOW Which may my wand'ring fugitives receive; END
BEGIN NOW (Since haughty Juno will not give you leave;) END
BEGIN NOW Then, father, (if I still may use that name,) END
BEGIN NOW By ruin'd Troy, yet smoking from the flame, END
BEGIN NOW I beg you, let Ascanius, by my care, END
BEGIN NOW Be freed from danger, and dismiss'd the war: END
BEGIN NOW Inglorious let him live, without a crown. END
BEGIN NOW The father may be cast on coasts unknown, END
BEGIN NOW Struggling with fate; but let me save the son. END
BEGIN NOW Mine is Cythera, mine the Cyprian tow'rs: END
BEGIN NOW In those recesses, and those sacred bow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW Obscurely let him rest; his right resign END
BEGIN NOW To promis'd empire, and his Julian line. END
BEGIN NOW Then Carthage may th' Ausonian towns destroy, END
BEGIN NOW Nor fear the race of a rejected boy. END
BEGIN NOW What profits it my son to scape the fire, END
BEGIN NOW Arm'd with his gods, and loaded with his sire; END
BEGIN NOW To pass the perils of the seas and wind; END
BEGIN NOW Evade the Greeks, and leave the war behind; END
BEGIN NOW To reach th' Italian shores; if, after all, END
BEGIN NOW Our second Pergamus is doom'd to fall? END
BEGIN NOW Much better had he curb'd his high desires, END
BEGIN NOW And hover'd o'er his ill-extinguish'd fires. END
BEGIN NOW To Simois' banks the fugitives restore, END
BEGIN NOW And give them back to war, and all the woes before. END
BEGIN NOW Deep indignation swell'd Saturnia's heart: END
BEGIN NOW And must I own," she said, "my secret smart- END
BEGIN NOW What with more decence were in silence kept, END
BEGIN NOW And, but for this unjust reproach, had slept? END
BEGIN NOW Did god or man your fav'rite son advise, END
BEGIN NOW With war unhop'd the Latians to surprise? END
BEGIN NOW By fate, you boast, and by the gods' decree, END
BEGIN NOW He left his native land for Italy! END
BEGIN NOW Confess the truth; by mad Cassandra, more END
BEGIN NOW Than Heav'n inspir'd, he sought a foreign shore! END
BEGIN NOW Did I persuade to trust his second Troy END
BEGIN NOW To the raw conduct of a beardless boy, END
BEGIN NOW With walls unfinish'd, which himself forsakes, END
BEGIN NOW And thro' the waves a wand'ring voyage takes? END
BEGIN NOW When have I urg'd him meanly to demand END
BEGIN NOW The Tuscan aid, and arm a quiet land? END
BEGIN NOW Did I or Iris give this mad advice, END
BEGIN NOW Or made the fool himself the fatal choice? END
BEGIN NOW You think it hard, the Latians should destroy END
BEGIN NOW With swords your Trojans, and with fires your Troy! END
BEGIN NOW Hard and unjust indeed, for men to draw END
BEGIN NOW Their native air, nor take a foreign law! END
BEGIN NOW That Turnus is permitted still to live, END
BEGIN NOW To whom his birth a god and goddess give! END
BEGIN NOW But yet is just and lawful for your line END
BEGIN NOW To drive their fields, and force with fraud to join; END
BEGIN NOW Realms, not your own, among your clans divide, END
BEGIN NOW And from the bridegroom tear the promis'd bride; END
BEGIN NOW Petition, while you public arms prepare; END
BEGIN NOW Pretend a peace, and yet provoke a war! END
BEGIN NOW 'T was giv'n to you, your darling son to shroud, END
BEGIN NOW And, for a man, obtend an empty cloud. END
BEGIN NOW From flaming fleets you turn'd the fire away, END
BEGIN NOW And chang'd the ships to daughters of the sea. END
BEGIN NOW But is my crime- the Queen of Heav'n offends, END
BEGIN NOW If she presume to save her suff'ring friends! END
BEGIN NOW Your son, not knowing what his foes decree, END
BEGIN NOW You say, is absent: absent let him be. END
BEGIN NOW Yours is Cythera, yours the Cyprian tow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW The soft recesses, and the sacred bow'rs. END
BEGIN NOW Why do you then these needless arms prepare, END
BEGIN NOW And thus provoke a people prone to war? END
BEGIN NOW Did I with fire the Trojan town deface, END
BEGIN NOW Or hinder from return your exil'd race? END
BEGIN NOW Was I the cause of mischief, or the man END
BEGIN NOW Whose lawless lust the fatal war began? END
BEGIN NOW Think on whose faith th' adult'rous youth relied; END
BEGIN NOW Who promis'd, who procur'd, the Spartan bride? END
BEGIN NOW When all th' united states of Greece combin'd, END
BEGIN NOW To purge the world of the perfidious kind, END
BEGIN NOW Then was your time to fear the Trojan fate: END
BEGIN NOW Your quarrels and complaints are now too late. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Juno. Murmurs rise, with mix'd applause, END
BEGIN NOW Just as they favor or dislike the cause. END
BEGIN NOW So winds, when yet unfledg'd in woods they lie, END
BEGIN NOW In whispers first their tender voices try, END
BEGIN NOW Then issue on the main with bellowing rage, END
BEGIN NOW And storms to trembling mariners presage. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus to both replied th' imperial god, END
BEGIN NOW Who shakes heav'n's axles with his awful nod. END
BEGIN NOW (When he begins, the silent senate stand END
BEGIN NOW With rev'rence, list'ning to the dread command: END
BEGIN NOW The clouds dispel; the winds their breath restrain; END
BEGIN NOW And the hush'd waves lie flatted on the main.) END
BEGIN NOW Celestials, your attentive ears incline! END
BEGIN NOW Since, said the god, "the Trojans must not join END
BEGIN NOW In wish'd alliance with the Latian line; END
BEGIN NOW Since endless jarrings and immortal hate END
BEGIN NOW Tend but to discompose our happy state; END
BEGIN NOW The war henceforward be resign'd to fate: END
BEGIN NOW Each to his proper fortune stand or fall; END
BEGIN NOW Equal and unconcern'd I look on all. END
BEGIN NOW Rutulians, Trojans, are the same to me; END
BEGIN NOW And both shall draw the lots their fates decree. END
BEGIN NOW Let these assault, if Fortune be their friend; END
BEGIN NOW And, if she favors those, let those defend: END
BEGIN NOW The Fates will find their way." The Thund'rer said, END
BEGIN NOW And shook the sacred honors of his head, END
BEGIN NOW Attesting Styx, th' inviolable flood, END
BEGIN NOW And the black regions of his brother god. END
BEGIN NOW Trembled the poles of heav'n, and earth confess'd the nod. END
BEGIN NOW This end the sessions had: the senate rise, END
BEGIN NOW And to his palace wait their sov'reign thro' the skies. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime, intent upon their siege, the foes END
BEGIN NOW Within their walls the Trojan host inclose: END
BEGIN NOW They wound, they kill, they watch at ev'ry gate; END
BEGIN NOW Renew the fires, and urge their happy fate. END
BEGIN NOW Th' Aeneans wish in vain their wanted chief, END
BEGIN NOW Hopeless of flight, more hopeless of relief. END
BEGIN NOW Thin on the tow'rs they stand; and ev'n those few END
BEGIN NOW A feeble, fainting, and dejected crew. END
BEGIN NOW Yet in the face of danger some there stood: END
BEGIN NOW The two bold brothers of Sarpedon's blood, END
BEGIN NOW Asius and Acmon; both th' Assaraci; END
BEGIN NOW Young Haemon, and tho' young, resolv'd to die. END
BEGIN NOW With these were Clarus and Thymoetes join'd; END
BEGIN NOW Tibris and Castor, both of Lycian kind. END
BEGIN NOW From Acmon's hands a rolling stone there came, END
BEGIN NOW So large, it half deserv'd a mountain's name: END
BEGIN NOW Strong-sinew'd was the youth, and big of bone; END
BEGIN NOW His brother Mnestheus could not more have done, END
BEGIN NOW Or the great father of th' intrepid son. END
BEGIN NOW Some firebrands throw, some flights of arrows send; END
BEGIN NOW And some with darts, and some with stones defend. END
BEGIN NOW Amid the press appears the beauteous boy, END
BEGIN NOW The care of Venus, and the hope of Troy. END
BEGIN NOW His lovely face unarm'd, his head was bare; END
BEGIN NOW In ringlets o'er his shoulders hung his hair. END
BEGIN NOW His forehead circled with a diadem; END
BEGIN NOW Distinguish'd from the crowd, he shines a gem, END
BEGIN NOW Enchas'd in gold, or polish'd iv'ry set, END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the meaner foil of sable jet. END
BEGIN NOW Nor Ismarus was wanting to the war, END
BEGIN NOW Directing pointed arrows from afar, END
BEGIN NOW And death with poison arm'd- in Lydia born, END
BEGIN NOW Where plenteous harvests the fat fields adorn; END
BEGIN NOW Where proud Pactolus floats the fruitful lands, END
BEGIN NOW And leaves a rich manure of golden sands. END
BEGIN NOW There Capys, author of the Capuan name, END
BEGIN NOW And there was Mnestheus too, increas'd in fame, END
BEGIN NOW Since Turnus from the camp he cast with shame. END
BEGIN NOW Thus mortal war was wag'd on either side. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the hero cuts the nightly tide: END
BEGIN NOW For, anxious, from Evander when he went, END
BEGIN NOW He sought the Tyrrhene camp, and Tarchon's tent; END
BEGIN NOW Expos'd the cause of coming to the chief; END
BEGIN NOW His name and country told, and ask'd relief; END
BEGIN NOW Propos'd the terms; his own small strength declar'd; END
BEGIN NOW What vengeance proud Mezentius had prepar'd: END
BEGIN NOW What Turnus, bold and violent, design'd; END
BEGIN NOW Then shew'd the slipp'ry state of humankind, END
BEGIN NOW And fickle fortune; warn'd him to beware, END
BEGIN NOW And to his wholesome counsel added pray'r. END
BEGIN NOW Tarchon, without delay, the treaty signs, END
BEGIN NOW And to the Trojan troops the Tuscan joins. END
BEGIN NOW They soon set sail; nor now the fates withstand; END
BEGIN NOW Their forces trusted with a foreign hand. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas leads; upon his stern appear END
BEGIN NOW Two lions carv'd, which rising Ida bear- END
BEGIN NOW Ida, to wand'ring Trojans ever dear. END
BEGIN NOW Under their grateful shade Aeneas sate, END
BEGIN NOW Revolving war's events, and various fate. END
BEGIN NOW His left young Pallas kept, fix'd to his side, END
BEGIN NOW And oft of winds enquir'd, and of the tide; END
BEGIN NOW Oft of the stars, and of their wat'ry way; END
BEGIN NOW And what he suffer'd both by land and sea. END
BEGIN NOW Now, sacred sisters, open all your spring! END
BEGIN NOW The Tuscan leaders, and their army sing, END
BEGIN NOW Which follow'd great Aeneas to the war: END
BEGIN NOW Their arms, their numbers, and their names declare. END
BEGIN NOW A thousand youths brave Massicus obey, END
BEGIN NOW Borne in the Tiger thro' the foaming sea; END
BEGIN NOW From Asium brought, and Cosa, by his care: END
BEGIN NOW For arms, light quivers, bows and shafts, they bear. END
BEGIN NOW Fierce Abas next: his men bright armor wore; END
BEGIN NOW His stern Apollo's golden statue bore. END
BEGIN NOW Six hundred Populonia sent along, END
BEGIN NOW All skill'd in martial exercise, and strong. END
BEGIN NOW Three hundred more for battle Ilva joins, END
BEGIN NOW An isle renown'd for steel, and unexhausted mines. END
BEGIN NOW Asylas on his prow the third appears, END
BEGIN NOW Who heav'n interprets, and the wand'ring stars; END
BEGIN NOW From offer'd entrails prodigies expounds, END
BEGIN NOW And peals of thunder, with presaging sounds. END
BEGIN NOW A thousand spears in warlike order stand, END
BEGIN NOW Sent by the Pisans under his command. END
BEGIN NOW Fair Astur follows in the wat'ry field, END
BEGIN NOW Proud of his manag'd horse and painted shield. END
BEGIN NOW Gravisca, noisome from the neighb'ring fen, END
BEGIN NOW And his own Caere, sent three hundred men; END
BEGIN NOW With those which Minio's fields and Pyrgi gave, END
BEGIN NOW All bred in arms, unanimous, and brave. END
BEGIN NOW Thou, Muse, the name of Cinyras renew, END
BEGIN NOW And brave Cupavo follow'd but by few; END
BEGIN NOW Whose helm confess'd the lineage of the man, END
BEGIN NOW And bore, with wings display'd, a silver swan. END
BEGIN NOW Love was the fault of his fam'd ancestry, END
BEGIN NOW Whose forms and fortunes in his ensigns fly. END
BEGIN NOW For Cycnus lov'd unhappy Phaeton, END
BEGIN NOW And sung his loss in poplar groves, alone, END
BEGIN NOW Beneath the sister shades, to soothe his grief. END
BEGIN NOW Heav'n heard his song, and hasten'd his relief, END
BEGIN NOW And chang'd to snowy plumes his hoary hair, END
BEGIN NOW And wing'd his flight, to chant aloft in air. END
BEGIN NOW His son Cupavo brush'd the briny flood: END
BEGIN NOW Upon his stern a brawny Centaur stood, END
BEGIN NOW Who heav'd a rock, and, threat'ning still to throw, END
BEGIN NOW With lifted hands alarm'd the seas below: END
BEGIN NOW They seem'd to fear the formidable sight, END
BEGIN NOW And roll'd their billows on, to speed his flight. END
BEGIN NOW Ocnus was next, who led his native train END
BEGIN NOW Of hardy warriors thro' the wat'ry plain: END
BEGIN NOW The son of Manto by the Tuscan stream, END
BEGIN NOW From whence the Mantuan town derives the name- END
BEGIN NOW An ancient city, but of mix'd descent: END
BEGIN NOW Three sev'ral tribes compose the government; END
BEGIN NOW Four towns are under each; but all obey END
BEGIN NOW The Mantuan laws, and own the Tuscan sway. END
BEGIN NOW Hate to Mezentius arm'd five hundred more, END
BEGIN NOW Whom Mincius from his sire Benacus bore: END
BEGIN NOW Mincius, with wreaths of reeds his forehead cover'd o'er. END
BEGIN NOW These grave Auletes leads: a hundred sweep END
BEGIN NOW With stretching oars at once the glassy deep. END
BEGIN NOW Him and his martial train the Triton bears; END
BEGIN NOW High on his poop the sea-green god appears: END
BEGIN NOW Frowning he seems his crooked shell to sound, END
BEGIN NOW And at the blast the billows dance around. END
BEGIN NOW A hairy man above the waist he shows; END
BEGIN NOW A porpoise tail beneath his belly grows; END
BEGIN NOW And ends a fish: his breast the waves divides, END
BEGIN NOW And froth and foam augment the murm'ring tides. END
BEGIN NOW Full thirty ships transport the chosen train END
BEGIN NOW For Troy's relief, and scour the briny main. END
BEGIN NOW Now was the world forsaken by the sun, END
BEGIN NOW And Phoebe half her nightly race had run. END
BEGIN NOW The careful chief, who never clos'd his eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Himself the rudder holds, the sails supplies. END
BEGIN NOW A choir of Nereids meet him on the flood, END
BEGIN NOW Once his own galleys, hewn from Ida's wood; END
BEGIN NOW But now, as many nymphs, the sea they sweep, END
BEGIN NOW As rode, before, tall vessels on the deep. END
BEGIN NOW They know him from afar; and in a ring END
BEGIN NOW Inclose the ship that bore the Trojan king. END
BEGIN NOW Cymodoce, whose voice excell'd the rest, END
BEGIN NOW Above the waves advanc'd her snowy breast; END
BEGIN NOW Her right hand stops the stern; her left divides END
BEGIN NOW The curling ocean, and corrects the tides. END
BEGIN NOW She spoke for all the choir, and thus began END
BEGIN NOW With pleasing words to warn th' unknowing man: END
BEGIN NOW Sleeps our lov'd lord? O goddess-born, awake! END
BEGIN NOW Spread ev'ry sail, pursue your wat'ry track, END
BEGIN NOW And haste your course. Your navy once were we, END
BEGIN NOW From Ida's height descending to the sea; END
BEGIN NOW Till Turnus, as at anchor fix'd we stood, END
BEGIN NOW Presum'd to violate our holy wood. END
BEGIN NOW Then, loos'd from shore, we fled his fires profane END
BEGIN NOW (Unwillingly we broke our master's chain), END
BEGIN NOW And since have sought you thro' the Tuscan main. END
BEGIN NOW The mighty Mother chang'd our forms to these, END
BEGIN NOW And gave us life immortal in the seas. END
BEGIN NOW But young Ascanius, in his camp distress'd, END
BEGIN NOW By your insulting foes is hardly press'd. END
BEGIN NOW Th' Arcadian horsemen, and Etrurian host, END
BEGIN NOW Advance in order on the Latian coast: END
BEGIN NOW To cut their way the Daunian chief designs, END
BEGIN NOW Before their troops can reach the Trojan lines. END
BEGIN NOW Thou, when the rosy morn restores the light, END
BEGIN NOW First arm thy soldiers for th' ensuing fight: END
BEGIN NOW Thyself the fated sword of Vulcan wield, END
BEGIN NOW And bear aloft th' impenetrable shield. END
BEGIN NOW To-morrow's sun, unless my skill be vain, END
BEGIN NOW Shall see huge heaps of foes in battle slain. END
BEGIN NOW Parting, she spoke; and with immortal force END
BEGIN NOW Push'd on the vessel in her wat'ry course; END
BEGIN NOW For well she knew the way. Impell'd behind, END
BEGIN NOW The ship flew forward, and outstripp'd the wind. END
BEGIN NOW The rest make up. Unknowing of the cause, END
BEGIN NOW The chief admires their speed, and happy omens draws. END
BEGIN NOW Then thus he pray'd, and fix'd on heav'n his eyes: END
BEGIN NOW Hear thou, great Mother of the deities. END
BEGIN NOW With turrets crown'd! (on Ida's holy hill END
BEGIN NOW Fierce tigers, rein'd and curb'd, obey thy will.) END
BEGIN NOW Firm thy own omens; lead us on to fight; END
BEGIN NOW And let thy Phrygians conquer in thy right. END
BEGIN NOW He said no more. And now renewing day END
BEGIN NOW Had chas'd the shadows of the night away. END
BEGIN NOW He charg'd the soldiers, with preventing care, END
BEGIN NOW Their flags to follow, and their arms prepare; END
BEGIN NOW Warn'd of th' ensuing fight, and bade 'em hope the war. END
BEGIN NOW Now, his lofty poop, he view'd below END
BEGIN NOW His camp incompass'd, and th' inclosing foe. END
BEGIN NOW His blazing shield, imbrac'd, he held on high; END
BEGIN NOW The camp receive the sign, and with loud shouts reply. END
BEGIN NOW Hope arms their courage: from their tow'rs they throw END
BEGIN NOW Their darts with double force, and drive the foe. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, at the signal giv'n, the cranes arise END
BEGIN NOW Before the stormy south, and blacken all the skies. END
BEGIN NOW King Turnus wonder'd at the fight renew'd, END
BEGIN NOW Till, looking back, the Trojan fleet he view'd, END
BEGIN NOW The seas with swelling canvas cover'd o'er, END
BEGIN NOW And the swift ships descending on the shore. END
BEGIN NOW The Latians saw from far, with dazzled eyes, END
BEGIN NOW The radiant crest that seem'd in flames to rise, END
BEGIN NOW And dart diffusive fires around the field, END
BEGIN NOW And the keen glitt'ring the golden shield. END
BEGIN NOW Thus threat'ning comets, when by night they rise, END
BEGIN NOW Shoot sanguine streams, and sadden all the skies: END
BEGIN NOW So Sirius, flashing forth sinister lights, END
BEGIN NOW Pale humankind with plagues and with dry famine fright: END
BEGIN NOW Yet Turnus with undaunted mind is bent END
BEGIN NOW To man the shores, and hinder their descent, END
BEGIN NOW And thus awakes the courage of his friends: END
BEGIN NOW What you so long have wish'd, kind Fortune sends; END
BEGIN NOW In ardent arms to meet th' invading foe: END
BEGIN NOW You find, and find him at advantage now. END
BEGIN NOW Yours is the day: you need but only dare; END
BEGIN NOW Your swords will make you masters of the war. END
BEGIN NOW Your sires, your sons, your houses, and your lands, END
BEGIN NOW And dearest wifes, are all within your hands. END
BEGIN NOW Be mindful of the race from whence you came, END
BEGIN NOW And emulate in arms your fathers' fame. END
BEGIN NOW Now take the time, while stagg'ring yet they stand END
BEGIN NOW With feet unfirm, and prepossess the strand: END
BEGIN NOW Fortune befriends the bold." Nor more he said, END
BEGIN NOW But balanc'd whom to leave, and whom to lead; END
BEGIN NOW Then these elects, the landing to prevent; END
BEGIN NOW And those he leaves, to keep the city pent. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the Trojan sends his troops ashore: END
BEGIN NOW Some are by boats expos'd, by bridges more. END
BEGIN NOW With lab'ring oars they bear along the strand, END
BEGIN NOW Where the tide languishes, and leap aland. END
BEGIN NOW Tarchon observes the coast with careful eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And, where no ford he finds, no water fries, END
BEGIN NOW Nor billows with unequal murmurs roar, END
BEGIN NOW But smoothly slide along, and swell the shore, END
BEGIN NOW That course he steer'd, and thus he gave command: END
BEGIN NOW Here ply your oars, and at all hazard land: END
BEGIN NOW Force on the vessel, that her keel may wound END
BEGIN NOW This hated soil, and furrow hostile ground. END
BEGIN NOW Let me securely land- I ask no more; END
BEGIN NOW Then sink my ships, or shatter on the shore. END
BEGIN NOW This fiery speech inflames his fearful friends: END
BEGIN NOW They tug at ev'ry oar, and ev'ry stretcher bends; END
BEGIN NOW They run their ships aground; the vessels knock, END
BEGIN NOW (Thus forc'd ashore,) and tremble with the shock. END
BEGIN NOW Tarchon's alone was lost, that stranded stood, END
BEGIN NOW Stuck on a bank, and beaten by the flood: END
BEGIN NOW She breaks her back; the loosen'd sides give way, END
BEGIN NOW And plunge the Tuscan soldiers in the sea. END
BEGIN NOW Their broken oars and floating planks withstand END
BEGIN NOW Their passage, while they labor to the land, END
BEGIN NOW And ebbing tides bear back upon th' uncertain sand. END
BEGIN NOW Now Turnus leads his troops without delay, END
BEGIN NOW Advancing to the margin of the sea. END
BEGIN NOW The trumpets sound: Aeneas first assail'd END
BEGIN NOW The clowns new-rais'd and raw, and soon prevail'd. END
BEGIN NOW Great Theron fell, an omen of the fight; END
BEGIN NOW Great Theron, large of limbs, of giant height. END
BEGIN NOW He first in open field defied the prince: END
BEGIN NOW But armor scal'd with gold was no defense END
BEGIN NOW Against the fated sword, which open'd wide END
BEGIN NOW His plated shield, and pierc'd his naked side. END
BEGIN NOW Next, Lichas fell, who, not like others born, END
BEGIN NOW Was from his wretched mother ripp'd and torn; END
BEGIN NOW Sacred, O Phoebus, from his birth to thee; END
BEGIN NOW For his beginning life from biting steel was free. END
BEGIN NOW Not far from him was Gyas laid along, END
BEGIN NOW Of monstrous bulk; with Cisseus fierce and strong: END
BEGIN NOW Vain bulk and strength! for, when the chief assail'd, END
BEGIN NOW Nor valor nor Herculean arms avail'd, END
BEGIN NOW Nor their fam'd father, wont in war to go END
BEGIN NOW With great Alcides, while he toil'd below. END
BEGIN NOW The noisy Pharos next receiv'd his death: END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas writh'd his dart, and stopp'd his bawling breath. END
BEGIN NOW Then wretched Cydon had receiv'd his doom, END
BEGIN NOW Who courted Clytius in his beardless bloom, END
BEGIN NOW And sought with lust obscene polluted joys: END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan sword had curd his love of boys, END
BEGIN NOW Had not his sev'n bold brethren stopp'd the course END
BEGIN NOW Of the fierce champions, with united force. END
BEGIN NOW Sev'n darts were thrown at once; and some rebound END
BEGIN NOW From his bright shield, some on his helmet sound: END
BEGIN NOW The rest had reach'd him; but his mother's care END
BEGIN NOW Prevented those, and turn'd aside in air. END
BEGIN NOW The prince then call'd Achates, to supply END
BEGIN NOW The spears that knew the way to victory- END
BEGIN NOW Those fatal weapons, which, inur'd to blood, END
BEGIN NOW In Grecian bodies under Ilium stood: END
BEGIN NOW Not one of those my hand shall toss in vain END
BEGIN NOW Against our foes, on this contended plain. END
BEGIN NOW He said; then seiz'd a mighty spear, and threw; END
BEGIN NOW Which, wing'd with fate, thro' Maeon's buckler flew, END
BEGIN NOW Pierc'd all the brazen plates, and reach'd his heart: END
BEGIN NOW He stagger'd with intolerable smart. END
BEGIN NOW Alcanor saw; and reach'd, but reach'd in vain, END
BEGIN NOW His helping hand, his brother to sustain. END
BEGIN NOW A second spear, which kept the former course, END
BEGIN NOW From the same hand, and sent with equal force, END
BEGIN NOW His right arm pierc'd, and holding on, bereft END
BEGIN NOW His use of both, and pinion'd down his left. END
BEGIN NOW Then Numitor from his dead brother drew END
BEGIN NOW Th' ill-omen'd spear, and at the Trojan threw: END
BEGIN NOW Preventing fate directs the lance awry, END
BEGIN NOW Which, glancing, only mark'd Achates' thigh. END
BEGIN NOW In pride of youth the Sabine Clausus came, END
BEGIN NOW And, from afar, at Dryops took his aim. END
BEGIN NOW The spear flew hissing thro' the middle space, END
BEGIN NOW And pierc'd his throat, directed at his face; END
BEGIN NOW It stopp'd at once the passage of his wind, END
BEGIN NOW And the free soul to flitting air resign'd: END
BEGIN NOW His forehead was the first that struck the ground; END
BEGIN NOW Lifeblood and life rush'd mingled thro' the wound. END
BEGIN NOW He slew three brothers of the Borean race, END
BEGIN NOW And three, whom Ismarus, their native place, END
BEGIN NOW Had sent to war, but all the sons of Thrace. END
BEGIN NOW Halesus, next, the bold Aurunci leads: END
BEGIN NOW The son of Neptune to his aid succeeds, END
BEGIN NOW Conspicuous on his horse. On either hand, END
BEGIN NOW These fight to keep, and those to win, the land. END
BEGIN NOW With mutual blood th' Ausonian soil is dyed, END
BEGIN NOW While on its borders each their claim decide. END
BEGIN NOW As wintry winds, contending in the sky, END
BEGIN NOW With equal force of lungs their titles try: END
BEGIN NOW They rage, they roar; the doubtful rack of heav'n END
BEGIN NOW Stands without motion, and the tide undriv'n: END
BEGIN NOW Each bent to conquer, neither side to yield, END
BEGIN NOW They long suspend the fortune of the field. END
BEGIN NOW Both armies thus perform what courage can; END
BEGIN NOW Foot set to foot, and mingled man to man. END
BEGIN NOW But, in another part, th' Arcadian horse END
BEGIN NOW With ill success ingage the Latin force: END
BEGIN NOW For, where th' impetuous torrent, rushing down, END
BEGIN NOW Huge craggy stones and rooted trees had thrown, END
BEGIN NOW They left their coursers, and, unus'd to fight END
BEGIN NOW On foot, were scatter'd in a shameful flight. END
BEGIN NOW Pallas, who with disdain and grief had view'd END
BEGIN NOW His foes pursuing, and his friends pursued, END
BEGIN NOW Us'd threat'nings mix'd with pray'rs, his last resource, END
BEGIN NOW With these to move their minds, with those to fire their force END
BEGIN NOW Which way, companions? whether would you run? END
BEGIN NOW By you yourselves, and mighty battles won, END
BEGIN NOW By my great sire, by his establish'd name, END
BEGIN NOW And early promise of my future fame; END
BEGIN NOW By my youth, emulous of equal right END
BEGIN NOW To share his honors- shun ignoble flight! END
BEGIN NOW Trust not your feet: your hands must hew way END
BEGIN NOW Thro' yon black body, and that thick array: END
BEGIN NOW 'T is thro' that forward path that we must come; END
BEGIN NOW There lies our way, and that our passage home. END
BEGIN NOW Nor pow'rs above, nor destinies below END
BEGIN NOW Oppress our arms: with equal strength we go, END
BEGIN NOW With mortal hands to meet a mortal foe. END
BEGIN NOW See on what foot we stand: a scanty shore, END
BEGIN NOW The sea behind, our enemies before; END
BEGIN NOW No passage left, unless we swim the main; END
BEGIN NOW Or, forcing these, the Trojan trenches gain. END
BEGIN NOW This said, he strode with eager haste along, END
BEGIN NOW And bore amidst the thickest of the throng. END
BEGIN NOW Lagus, the first he met, with fate to foe, END
BEGIN NOW Had heav'd a stone of mighty weight, to throw: END
BEGIN NOW Stooping, the spear descended on his chine, END
BEGIN NOW Just where the bone distinguished either loin: END
BEGIN NOW It stuck so fast, so deeply buried lay, END
BEGIN NOW That scarce the victor forc'd the steel away. END
BEGIN NOW Hisbon came on: but, while he mov'd too slow END
BEGIN NOW To wish'd revenge, the prince prevents his blow; END
BEGIN NOW For, warding his at once, at once he press'd, END
BEGIN NOW And plung'd the fatal weapon in his breast. END
BEGIN NOW Then lewd Anchemolus he laid in dust, END
BEGIN NOW Who stain'd his stepdam's bed with impious lust. END
BEGIN NOW And, after him, the Daucian twins were slain, END
BEGIN NOW Laris and Thymbrus, on the Latian plain; END
BEGIN NOW So wondrous like in feature, shape, and size, END
BEGIN NOW As caus'd an error in their parents' eyes- END
BEGIN NOW Grateful mistake! but soon the sword decides END
BEGIN NOW The nice distinction, and their fate divides: END
BEGIN NOW For Thymbrus' head was lopp'd; and Laris' hand, END
BEGIN NOW Dismember'd, sought its owner on the strand: END
BEGIN NOW The trembling fingers yet the fauchion strain, END
BEGIN NOW And threaten still th' intended stroke in vain. END
BEGIN NOW Now, to renew the charge, th' Arcadians came: END
BEGIN NOW Sight of such acts, and sense of honest shame, END
BEGIN NOW And grief, with anger mix'd, their minds inflame. END
BEGIN NOW Then, with a casual blow was Rhoeteus slain, END
BEGIN NOW Who chanc'd, as Pallas threw, to cross the plain: END
BEGIN NOW The flying spear was after Ilus sent; END
BEGIN NOW But Rhoeteus happen'd on a death unmeant: END
BEGIN NOW From Teuthras and from Tyres while he fled, END
BEGIN NOW The lance, athwart his body, laid him dead: END
BEGIN NOW Roll'd from his chariot with a mortal wound, END
BEGIN NOW And intercepted fate, he spurn'd the ground. END
BEGIN NOW As when, in summer, welcome winds arise, END
BEGIN NOW The watchful shepherd to the forest flies, END
BEGIN NOW And fires the midmost plants; contagion spreads, END
BEGIN NOW And catching flames infect the neighb'ring heads; END
BEGIN NOW Around the forest flies the furious blast, END
BEGIN NOW And all the leafy nation sinks at last, END
BEGIN NOW And Vulcan rides in triumph o'er the waste; END
BEGIN NOW The pastor, pleas'd with his dire victory, END
BEGIN NOW Beholds the satiate flames in sheets ascend the sky: END
BEGIN NOW So Pallas' troops their scatter'd strength unite, END
BEGIN NOW And, pouring on their foes, their prince delight. END
BEGIN NOW Halesus came, fierce with desire of blood; END
BEGIN NOW But first collected in his arms he stood: END
BEGIN NOW Advancing then, he plied the spear so well, END
BEGIN NOW Ladon, Demodocus, and Pheres fell. END
BEGIN NOW Around his head he toss'd his glitt'ring brand, END
BEGIN NOW And from Strymonius hew'd his better hand, END
BEGIN NOW Held up to guard his throat; then hurl'd a stone END
BEGIN NOW At Thoas' ample front, and pierc'd the bone: END
BEGIN NOW It struck beneath the space of either eye; END
BEGIN NOW And blood, and mingled brains, together fly. END
BEGIN NOW Deep skill'd in future fates, Halesus' sire END
BEGIN NOW Did with the youth to lonely groves retire: END
BEGIN NOW But, when the father's mortal race was run, END
BEGIN NOW Dire destiny laid hold upon the son, END
BEGIN NOW And haul'd him to the war, to find, beneath END
BEGIN NOW Th' Evandrian spear, a memorable death. END
BEGIN NOW Pallas th' encounter seeks, but, ere he throws, END
BEGIN NOW To Tuscan Tiber thus address'd his vows: END
BEGIN NOW O sacred stream, direct my flying dart, END
BEGIN NOW And give to pass the proud Halesus' heart! END
BEGIN NOW His arms and spoils thy holy oak shall bear. END
BEGIN NOW Pleas'd with the bribe, the god receiv'd his pray'r: END
BEGIN NOW For, while his shield protects a friend distress'd, END
BEGIN NOW The dart came driving on, and pierc'd his breast. END
BEGIN NOW But Lausus, no small portion of the war, END
BEGIN NOW Permits not panic fear to reign too far, END
BEGIN NOW Caus'd by the death of so renown'd a knight; END
BEGIN NOW But by his own example cheers the fight. END
BEGIN NOW Fierce Abas first he slew; Abas, the stay END
BEGIN NOW Of Trojan hopes, and hindrance of the day. END
BEGIN NOW The Phrygian troops escap'd the Greeks in vain: END
BEGIN NOW They, and their mix'd allies, now load the plain. END
BEGIN NOW To the rude shock of war both armies came; END
BEGIN NOW Their leaders equal, and their strength the same. END
BEGIN NOW The rear so press'd the front, they could not wield END
BEGIN NOW Their angry weapons, to dispute the field. END
BEGIN NOW Here Pallas urges on, and Lausus there: END
BEGIN NOW Of equal youth and beauty both appear, END
BEGIN NOW But both by fate forbid to breathe their native air. END
BEGIN NOW Their congress in the field great Jove withstands: END
BEGIN NOW Both doom'd to fall, but fall by greater hands. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime Juturna warns the Daunian chief END
BEGIN NOW Of Lausus' danger, urging swift relief. END
BEGIN NOW With his driv'n chariot he divides the crowd, END
BEGIN NOW And, making to his friends, thus calls aloud: END
BEGIN NOW Let none presume his needless aid to join; END
BEGIN NOW Retire, and clear the field; the fight is mine: END
BEGIN NOW To this right hand is Pallas only due; END
BEGIN NOW O were his father here, my just revenge to view! END
BEGIN NOW From the forbidden space his men retir'd. END
BEGIN NOW Pallas their awe, and his stern words, admir'd; END
BEGIN NOW Survey'd him o'er and o'er with wond'ring sight, END
BEGIN NOW Struck with his haughty mien, and tow'ring height. END
BEGIN NOW Then to the king: "Your empty vaunts forbear; END
BEGIN NOW Success I hope, and fate I cannot fear; END
BEGIN NOW Alive or dead, I shall deserve a name; END
BEGIN NOW Jove is impartial, and to both the same. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and to the void advanc'd his pace: END
BEGIN NOW Pale horror sate on each Arcadian face. END
BEGIN NOW Then Turnus, from his chariot leaping light, END
BEGIN NOW Address'd himself on foot to single fight. END
BEGIN NOW And, as a lion- when he spies from far END
BEGIN NOW A bull that seems to meditate the war, END
BEGIN NOW Bending his neck, and spurning back the sand- END
BEGIN NOW Runs roaring downward from his hilly stand: END
BEGIN NOW Imagine eager Turnus not more slow, END
BEGIN NOW To rush from high on his unequal foe. END
BEGIN NOW Young Pallas, when he saw the chief advance END
BEGIN NOW Within due distance of his flying lance, END
BEGIN NOW Prepares to charge him first, resolv'd to try END
BEGIN NOW If fortune would his want of force supply; END
BEGIN NOW And thus to Heav'n and Hercules address'd: END
BEGIN NOW Alcides, once on earth Evander's guest, END
BEGIN NOW His son adjures you by those holy rites, END
BEGIN NOW That hospitable board, those genial nights; END
BEGIN NOW Assist my great attempt to gain this prize, END
BEGIN NOW And let proud Turnus view, with dying eyes, END
BEGIN NOW His ravish'd spoils." 'T was heard, the vain request; END
BEGIN NOW Alcides mourn'd, and stifled sighs within his breast. END
BEGIN NOW Then Jove, to soothe his sorrow, thus began: END
BEGIN NOW Short bounds of life are set to mortal man. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is virtue's work alone to stretch the narrow span. END
BEGIN NOW So many sons of gods, in bloody fight, END
BEGIN NOW Around the walls of Troy, have lost the light: END
BEGIN NOW My own Sarpedon fell beneath his foe; END
BEGIN NOW Nor I, his mighty sire, could ward the blow. END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n Turnus shortly shall resign his breath, END
BEGIN NOW And stands already on the verge of death. END
BEGIN NOW This said, the god permits the fatal fight, END
BEGIN NOW But from the Latian fields averts his sight. END
BEGIN NOW Now with full force his spear young Pallas threw, END
BEGIN NOW And, having thrown, his shining fauchion drew END
BEGIN NOW The steel just graz'd along the shoulder joint, END
BEGIN NOW And mark'd it slightly with the glancing point, END
BEGIN NOW Fierce Turnus first to nearer distance drew, END
BEGIN NOW And pois'd his pointed spear, before he threw: END
BEGIN NOW Then, as the winged weapon whizz'd along, END
BEGIN NOW See now," said he, "whose arm is better strung. END
BEGIN NOW The spear kept on the fatal course, unstay'd END
BEGIN NOW By plates of ir'n, which o'er the shield were laid: END
BEGIN NOW Thro' folded brass and tough bull hides it pass'd, END
BEGIN NOW His corslet pierc'd, and reach'd his heart at last. END
BEGIN NOW In vain the youth tugs at the broken wood; END
BEGIN NOW The soul comes issuing with the vital blood: END
BEGIN NOW He falls; his arms upon his body sound; END
BEGIN NOW And with his bloody teeth he bites the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Turnus bestrode the corpse: "Arcadians, hear, END
BEGIN NOW Said he; "my message to your master bear: END
BEGIN NOW Such as the sire deserv'd, the son I send; END
BEGIN NOW It costs him dear to be the Phrygians' friend. END
BEGIN NOW The lifeless body, tell him, I bestow, END
BEGIN NOW Unask'd, to rest his wand'ring ghost below. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and trampled down with all the force END
BEGIN NOW Of his left foot, and spurn'd the wretched corse; END
BEGIN NOW Then snatch'd the shining belt, with gold inlaid; END
BEGIN NOW The belt Eurytion's artful hands had made, END
BEGIN NOW Where fifty fatal brides, express'd to sight, END
BEGIN NOW All in the compass of one mournful night, END
BEGIN NOW Depriv'd their bridegrooms of returning light. END
BEGIN NOW In an ill hour insulting Turnus tore END
BEGIN NOW Those golden spoils, and in a worse he wore. END
BEGIN NOW O mortals, blind in fate, who never know END
BEGIN NOW To bear high fortune, or endure the low! END
BEGIN NOW The time shall come, when Turnus, but in vain, END
BEGIN NOW Shall wish untouch'd the trophies of the slain; END
BEGIN NOW Shall wish the fatal belt were far away, END
BEGIN NOW And curse the dire remembrance of the day. END
BEGIN NOW The sad Arcadians, from th' unhappy field, END
BEGIN NOW Bear back the breathless body on a shield. END
BEGIN NOW O grace and grief of war! at once restor'd, END
BEGIN NOW With praises, to thy sire, at once deplor'd! END
BEGIN NOW One day first sent thee to the fighting field, END
BEGIN NOW Beheld whole heaps of foes in battle kill'd; END
BEGIN NOW One day beheld thee dead, and borne upon thy shield. END
BEGIN NOW This dismal news, not from uncertain fame, END
BEGIN NOW But sad spectators, to the hero came: END
BEGIN NOW His friends upon the brink of ruin stand, END
BEGIN NOW Unless reliev'd by his victorious hand. END
BEGIN NOW He whirls his sword around, without delay, END
BEGIN NOW And hews thro' adverse foes an ample way, END
BEGIN NOW To find fierce Turnus, of his conquest proud: END
BEGIN NOW Evander, Pallas, all that friendship ow'd END
BEGIN NOW To large deserts, are present to his eyes; END
BEGIN NOW His plighted hand, and hospitable ties. END
BEGIN NOW Four sons of Sulmo, four whom Ufens bred, END
BEGIN NOW He took in fight, and living victims led, END
BEGIN NOW To please the ghost of Pallas, and expire, END
BEGIN NOW In sacrifice, before his fun'ral fire. END
BEGIN NOW At Magus next he threw: he stoop'd below END
BEGIN NOW The flying spear, and shunn'd the promis'd blow; END
BEGIN NOW Then, creeping, clasp'd the hero's knees, and pray'd: END
BEGIN NOW By young Iulus, by thy father's shade, END
BEGIN NOW O spare my life, and send me back to see END
BEGIN NOW My longing sire, and tender progeny! END
BEGIN NOW A lofty house I have, and wealth untold, END
BEGIN NOW In silver ingots, and in bars of gold: END
BEGIN NOW All these, and sums besides, which see no day, END
BEGIN NOW The ransom of this one poor life shall pay. END
BEGIN NOW If I survive, will Troy the less prevail? END
BEGIN NOW A single soul's too light to turn the scale. END
BEGIN NOW He said. The hero sternly thus replied: END
BEGIN NOW Thy bars and ingots, and the sums beside, END
BEGIN NOW Leave for thy children's lot. Thy Turnus broke END
BEGIN NOW All rules of war by one relentless stroke, END
BEGIN NOW When Pallas fell: so deems, nor deems alone END
BEGIN NOW My father's shadow, but my living son. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, of kind remorse bereft, END
BEGIN NOW He seiz'd his helm, and dragg'd him with his left; END
BEGIN NOW Then with his right hand, while his neck he wreath'd, END
BEGIN NOW Up to the hilts his shining fauchion sheath'd. END
BEGIN NOW Apollo's priest, Emonides, was near; END
BEGIN NOW His holy fillets on his front appear; END
BEGIN NOW Glitt'ring in arms, he shone amidst the crowd; END
BEGIN NOW Much of his god, more of his purple, proud. END
BEGIN NOW Him the fierce Trojan follow'd thro' the field: END
BEGIN NOW The holy coward fell; and, forc'd to yield, END
BEGIN NOW The prince stood o'er the priest, and, at one blow, END
BEGIN NOW Sent him an off'ring to the shades below. END
BEGIN NOW His arms Seresthus on his shoulders bears, END
BEGIN NOW Design'd a trophy to the God of Wars. END
BEGIN NOW Vulcanian Caeculus renews the fight, END
BEGIN NOW And Umbro, born upon the mountains' height. END
BEGIN NOW The champion cheers his troops t' encounter those, END
BEGIN NOW And seeks revenge himself on other foes. END
BEGIN NOW At Anxur's shield he drove; and, at the blow, END
BEGIN NOW Both shield and arm to ground together go. END
BEGIN NOW Anxur had boasted much of magic charms, END
BEGIN NOW And thought he wore impenetrable arms, END
BEGIN NOW So made by mutter'd spells; and, from the spheres, END
BEGIN NOW Had life secur'd, in vain, for length of years. END
BEGIN NOW Then Tarquitus the field triumph trod; END
BEGIN NOW A nymph his mother, his sire a god. END
BEGIN NOW Exulting in bright arms, he braves the prince: END
BEGIN NOW With his protended lance he makes defense; END
BEGIN NOW Bears back his feeble foe; then, pressing on, END
BEGIN NOW Arrests his better hand, and drags him down; END
BEGIN NOW Stands o'er the prostrate wretch, and, as he lay, END
BEGIN NOW Vain tales inventing, and prepar'd to pray, END
BEGIN NOW Mows off his head: the trunk a moment stood, END
BEGIN NOW Then sunk, and roll'd along the sand in blood. END
BEGIN NOW The vengeful victor thus upbraids the slain: END
BEGIN NOW Lie there, proud man, unpitied, on the plain; END
BEGIN NOW Lie there, inglorious, and without a tomb, END
BEGIN NOW Far from thy mother and thy native home, END
BEGIN NOW Exposed to savage beasts, and birds of prey, END
BEGIN NOW Or thrown for food to monsters of the sea. END
BEGIN NOW On Lycas and Antaeus next he ran, END
BEGIN NOW Two chiefs of Turnus, and who led his van. END
BEGIN NOW They fled for fear; with these, he chas'd along END
BEGIN NOW Camers the yellow-lock'd, and Numa strong; END
BEGIN NOW Both great in arms, and both were fair and young. END
BEGIN NOW Camers was son to Volscens lately slain, END
BEGIN NOW In wealth surpassing all the Latian train, END
BEGIN NOW And in Amycla fix'd his silent easy reign. END
BEGIN NOW And, as Aegaeon, when with heav'n he strove, END
BEGIN NOW Stood opposite in arms to mighty Jove; END
BEGIN NOW Mov'd all his hundred hands, provok'd the war, END
BEGIN NOW Defied the forky lightning from afar; END
BEGIN NOW At fifty mouths his flaming breath expires, END
BEGIN NOW And flash for flash returns, and fires for fires; END
BEGIN NOW In his right hand as many swords he wields, END
BEGIN NOW And takes the thunder on as many shields: END
BEGIN NOW With strength like his, the Trojan hero stood; END
BEGIN NOW And soon the fields with falling corps were strow'd, END
BEGIN NOW When once his fauchion found the taste of blood. END
BEGIN NOW With fury scarce to be conceiv'd, he flew END
BEGIN NOW Against Niphaeus, whom four coursers drew. END
BEGIN NOW They, when they see the fiery chief advance, END
BEGIN NOW And pushing at their chests his pointed lance, END
BEGIN NOW Wheel'd with so swift a motion, mad with fear, END
BEGIN NOW They threw their master headlong from the chair. END
BEGIN NOW They stare, they start, nor stop their course, before END
BEGIN NOW They bear the bounding chariot to the shore. END
BEGIN NOW Now Lucagus and Liger scour the plains, END
BEGIN NOW With two white steeds; but Liger holds the reins, END
BEGIN NOW And Lucagus the lofty seat maintains: END
BEGIN NOW Bold brethren both. The former wav'd in air END
BEGIN NOW His flaming sword: Aeneas couch'd his spear, END
BEGIN NOW Unus'd to threats, and more unus'd to fear. END
BEGIN NOW Then Liger thus: "Thy confidence is vain END
BEGIN NOW To scape from hence, as from the Trojan plain: END
BEGIN NOW Nor these the steeds which Diomede bestrode, END
BEGIN NOW Nor this the chariot where Achilles rode; END
BEGIN NOW Nor Venus' veil is here, near Neptune's shield; END
BEGIN NOW Thy fatal hour is come, and this the field. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Liger vainly vaunts: the Trojan END
BEGIN NOW Return'd his answer with his flying spear. END
BEGIN NOW As Lucagus, to lash his horses, bends, END
BEGIN NOW Prone to the wheels, and his left foot protends, END
BEGIN NOW Prepar'd for fight; the fatal dart arrives, END
BEGIN NOW And thro' the borders of his buckler drives; END
BEGIN NOW Pass'd thro' and pierc'd his groin: the deadly wound, END
BEGIN NOW Cast from his chariot, roll'd him on the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Whom thus the chief upbraids with scornful spite: END
BEGIN NOW Blame not the slowness of your steeds in flight; END
BEGIN NOW Vain shadows did not force their swift retreat; END
BEGIN NOW But you yourself forsake your empty seat. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and seiz'd at once the loosen'd rein; END
BEGIN NOW For Liger lay already on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW By the same shock: then, stretching out his hands, END
BEGIN NOW The recreant thus his wretched life demands: END
BEGIN NOW Now, by thyself, O more than mortal man! END
BEGIN NOW By her and him from whom thy breath began, END
BEGIN NOW Who form'd thee thus divine, I beg thee, spare END
BEGIN NOW This forfeit life, and hear thy suppliant's pray'r. END
BEGIN NOW Thus much he spoke, and more he would have said; END
BEGIN NOW But the stern hero turn'd aside his head, END
BEGIN NOW And cut him short: "I hear another man; END
BEGIN NOW You talk'd not thus before the fight began. END
BEGIN NOW Now take your turn; and, as a brother should, END
BEGIN NOW Attend your brother to the Stygian flood. END
BEGIN NOW Then thro' his breast his fatal sword he sent, END
BEGIN NOW And the soul issued at the gaping vent. END
BEGIN NOW As storms the skies, and torrents tear the ground, END
BEGIN NOW Thus rag'd the prince, and scatter'd deaths around. END
BEGIN NOW At length Ascanius and the Trojan train END
BEGIN NOW Broke from the camp, so long besieg'd in vain. END
BEGIN NOW Held conference with his queen, and thus began: END
BEGIN NOW My sister goddess, and well-pleasing wife, END
BEGIN NOW Still think you Venus' aid supports the strife- END
BEGIN NOW Sustains her Trojans- or themselves, alone, END
BEGIN NOW With inborn valor force their fortune on? END
BEGIN NOW How fierce in fight, with courage undecay'd! END
BEGIN NOW Judge if such warriors want immortal aid. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the goddess with the charming eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Soft in her tone, submissively replies: END
BEGIN NOW Why, O my sov'reign lord, whose frown I fear, END
BEGIN NOW And cannot, unconcern'd, your anger bear; END
BEGIN NOW Why urge you thus my grief? when, if I still END
BEGIN NOW (As once I was) were mistress of your will, END
BEGIN NOW From your almighty pow'r your pleasing wife END
BEGIN NOW Might gain the grace of length'ning Turnus' life, END
BEGIN NOW Securely snatch him from the fatal fight, END
BEGIN NOW And give him to his aged father's sight. END
BEGIN NOW Now let him perish, since you hold it good, END
BEGIN NOW And glut the Trojans with his pious blood. END
BEGIN NOW Yet from our lineage he derives his name, END
BEGIN NOW And, in the fourth degree, from god Pilumnus came; END
BEGIN NOW Yet he devoutly pays you rites divine, END
BEGIN NOW And offers daily incense at your shrine. END
BEGIN NOW Then shortly thus the sov'reign god replied: END
BEGIN NOW Since in my pow'r and goodness you confide, END
BEGIN NOW If for a little space, a lengthen'd span, END
BEGIN NOW You beg reprieve for this expiring man, END
BEGIN NOW I grant you leave to take your Turnus hence END
BEGIN NOW From instant fate, and can so far dispense. END
BEGIN NOW But, if some secret meaning lies beneath, END
BEGIN NOW To save the short-liv'd youth from destin'd death, END
BEGIN NOW Or if a farther thought you entertain, END
BEGIN NOW To change the fates; you feed your hopes in vain. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the goddess thus, with weeping eyes: END
BEGIN NOW And what if that request, your tongue denies, END
BEGIN NOW Your heart should grant; and not a short reprieve, END
BEGIN NOW But length of certain life, to Turnus give? END
BEGIN NOW Now speedy death attends the guiltless youth, END
BEGIN NOW If my presaging soul divines with truth; END
BEGIN NOW Which, O! I wish, might err thro' causeless fears, END
BEGIN NOW And you (for you have pow'r) prolong his years! END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, involv'd in clouds, she flies, END
BEGIN NOW And drives a storm before her thro' the skies. END
BEGIN NOW Swift she descends, alighting on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Where the fierce foes a dubious fight maintain. END
BEGIN NOW Of air condens'd a specter soon she made; END
BEGIN NOW And, what Aeneas was, such seem'd the shade. END
BEGIN NOW Adorn'd with Dardan arms, the phantom bore END
BEGIN NOW His head aloft; a plumy crest he wore; END
BEGIN NOW This hand appear'd a shining sword to wield, END
BEGIN NOW And that sustain'd an imitated shield. END
BEGIN NOW With manly mien he stalk'd along the ground, END
BEGIN NOW Nor wanted voice belied, nor vaunting sound. END
BEGIN NOW (Thus haunting ghosts appear to waking sight, END
BEGIN NOW Or dreadful visions in our dreams by night.) END
BEGIN NOW The specter seems the Daunian chief to dare, END
BEGIN NOW And flourishes his empty sword in air. END
BEGIN NOW At this, advancing, Turnus hurl'd his spear: END
BEGIN NOW The phantom wheel'd, and seem'd to fly for fear. END
BEGIN NOW Deluded Turnus thought the Trojan fled, END
BEGIN NOW And with vain hopes his haughty fancy fed. END
BEGIN NOW Whether, O coward?" (thus he calls aloud, END
BEGIN NOW Nor found he spoke to wind, and chas'd a cloud,) END
BEGIN NOW Why thus forsake your bride! Receive from me END
BEGIN NOW The fated land you sought so long by sea. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and, brandishing at once his blade, END
BEGIN NOW With eager pace pursued the flying shade. END
BEGIN NOW By chance a ship was fasten'd to the shore, END
BEGIN NOW Which from old Clusium King Osinius bore: END
BEGIN NOW The plank was ready laid for safe ascent; END
BEGIN NOW For shelter there the trembling shadow bent, END
BEGIN NOW And skipp't and skulk'd, and under hatches went. END
BEGIN NOW Exulting Turnus, with regardless haste, END
BEGIN NOW Ascends the plank, and to the galley pass'd. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had he reach'd the prow: Saturnia's hand END
BEGIN NOW The haulsers cuts, and shoots the ship from land. END
BEGIN NOW With wind in poop, the vessel plows the sea, END
BEGIN NOW And measures back with speed her former way. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime Aeneas seeks his absent foe, END
BEGIN NOW And sends his slaughter'd troops to shades below. END
BEGIN NOW The guileful phantom now forsook the shroud, END
BEGIN NOW And flew sublime, and vanish'd in a cloud. END
BEGIN NOW Too late young Turnus the delusion found, END
BEGIN NOW Far on the sea, still making from the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Then, thankless for a life redeem'd by shame, END
BEGIN NOW With sense of honor stung, and forfeit fame, END
BEGIN NOW Fearful besides of what in fight had pass'd, END
BEGIN NOW His hands and haggard eyes to heav'n he cast; END
BEGIN NOW O Jove!" he cried, "for what offense have END
BEGIN NOW Deserv'd to bear this endless infamy? END
BEGIN NOW Whence am I forc'd, and whether am I borne? END
BEGIN NOW How, and with what reproach, shall I return? END
BEGIN NOW Shall ever I behold the Latian plain, END
BEGIN NOW Or see Laurentum's lofty tow'rs again? END
BEGIN NOW What will they say of their deserting chief END
BEGIN NOW The war was mine: I fly from their relief; END
BEGIN NOW I led to slaughter, and in slaughter leave; END
BEGIN NOW And ev'n from hence their dying groans receive. END
BEGIN NOW Here, overmatch'd in fight, in heaps they lie; END
BEGIN NOW There, scatter'd o'er the fields, ignobly fly. END
BEGIN NOW Gape wide, O earth, and draw me down alive! END
BEGIN NOW Or, O ye pitying winds, a wretch relieve! END
BEGIN NOW On sands or shelves the splitting vessel drive; END
BEGIN NOW Or set me shipwrack'd on some desart shore, END
BEGIN NOW Where no Rutulian eyes may see me more, END
BEGIN NOW Unknown to friends, or foes, or conscious Fame, END
BEGIN NOW Lest she should follow, and my flight proclaim. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Turnus rav'd, and various fates revolv'd: END
BEGIN NOW The choice was doubtful, but the death resolv'd. END
BEGIN NOW And now the sword, and now the sea took place, END
BEGIN NOW That to revenge, and this to purge disgrace. END
BEGIN NOW Sometimes he thought to swim the stormy main, END
BEGIN NOW By stretch of arms the distant shore to gain. END
BEGIN NOW Thrice he the sword assay'd, and thrice the flood; END
BEGIN NOW But Juno, mov'd with pity, both withstood. END
BEGIN NOW And thrice repress'd his rage; strong gales supplied, END
BEGIN NOW And push'd the vessel o'er the swelling tide. END
BEGIN NOW At length she lands him on his native shores, END
BEGIN NOW And to his father's longing arms restores. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime, by Jove's impulse, Mezentius arm'd, END
BEGIN NOW Succeeding Turnus, with his ardor warm'd END
BEGIN NOW His fainting friends, reproach'd their shameful flight, END
BEGIN NOW Repell'd the victors, and renew'd the fight. END
BEGIN NOW Against their king the Tuscan troops conspire; END
BEGIN NOW Such is their hate, and such their fierce desire END
BEGIN NOW Of wish'd revenge: on him, and him alone, END
BEGIN NOW All hands employ'd, and all their darts are thrown. END
BEGIN NOW He, like a solid rock by seas inclos'd, END
BEGIN NOW To raging winds and roaring waves oppos'd, END
BEGIN NOW From his proud summit looking down, disdains END
BEGIN NOW Their empty menace, and unmov'd remains. END
BEGIN NOW Beneath his feet fell haughty Hebrus dead, END
BEGIN NOW Then Latagus, and Palmus as he fled. END
BEGIN NOW At Latagus a weighty stone he flung: END
BEGIN NOW His face was flatted, and his helmet rung. END
BEGIN NOW But Palmus from behind receives his wound; END
BEGIN NOW Hamstring'd he falls, and grovels on the ground: END
BEGIN NOW His crest and armor, from his body torn, END
BEGIN NOW Thy shoulders, Lausus, and thy head adorn. END
BEGIN NOW Evas and Mimas, both of Troy, he slew. END
BEGIN NOW Mimas his birth from fair Theano drew, END
BEGIN NOW Born on that fatal night, when, big with fire, END
BEGIN NOW The queen produc'd young Paris to his sire: END
BEGIN NOW But Paris in the Phrygian fields was slain, END
BEGIN NOW Unthinking Mimas on the Latian plain. END
BEGIN NOW And, as a savage boar, on mountains bred, END
BEGIN NOW With forest mast and fatt'ning marshes fed, END
BEGIN NOW When once he sees himself in toils inclos'd, END
BEGIN NOW By huntsmen and their eager hounds oppos'd- END
BEGIN NOW He whets his tusks, and turns, and dares the war; END
BEGIN NOW Th' invaders dart their jav'lins from afar: END
BEGIN NOW All keep aloof, and safely shout around; END
BEGIN NOW But none presumes to give a nearer wound: END
BEGIN NOW He frets and froths, erects his bristled hide, END
BEGIN NOW And shakes a grove of lances from his side: END
BEGIN NOW Not otherwise the troops, with hate inspir'd, END
BEGIN NOW And just revenge against the tyrant fir'd, END
BEGIN NOW Their darts with clamor at a distance drive, END
BEGIN NOW And only keep the languish'd war alive. END
BEGIN NOW From Coritus came Acron to the fight, END
BEGIN NOW Who left his spouse betroth'd, and unconsummate night. END
BEGIN NOW Mezentius sees him thro' the squadrons ride, END
BEGIN NOW Proud of the purple favors of his bride. END
BEGIN NOW Then, as a hungry lion, who beholds END
BEGIN NOW A gamesome goat, who frisks about the folds, END
BEGIN NOW Or beamy stag, that grazes on the plain- END
BEGIN NOW He runs, he roars, he shakes his rising mane, END
BEGIN NOW He grins, and opens wide his greedy jaws; END
BEGIN NOW The prey lies panting underneath his paws: END
BEGIN NOW He fills his famish'd maw; his mouth runs o'er END
BEGIN NOW With unchew'd morsels, while he churns the gore: END
BEGIN NOW So proud Mezentius rushes on his foes, END
BEGIN NOW And first unhappy Acron overthrows: END
BEGIN NOW Stretch'd at his length, he spurns the swarthy ground; END
BEGIN NOW The lance, besmear'd with blood, lies broken in the wound. END
BEGIN NOW Then with disdain the haughty victor view'd END
BEGIN NOW Orodes flying, nor the wretch pursued, END
BEGIN NOW But, running, gain'd th' advantage of the ground: END
BEGIN NOW Then turning short, he met him face to face, END
BEGIN NOW To give his victor the better grace. END
BEGIN NOW Orodes falls, equal fight oppress'd: END
BEGIN NOW Mezentius fix'd his foot upon his breast, END
BEGIN NOW And rested lance; and thus aloud he cries: END
BEGIN NOW Lo! here the champion of my rebels lies! END
BEGIN NOW The fields around with Io Paean! ring; END
BEGIN NOW And peals of shouts applaud the conqu'ring king. END
BEGIN NOW At this the vanquish'd, with his dying breath, END
BEGIN NOW Thus faintly spoke, and prophesied in death: END
BEGIN NOW Nor thou, proud man, unpunish'd shalt remain: END
BEGIN NOW Like death attends thee on this fatal plain. END
BEGIN NOW Then, sourly smiling, thus the king replied: END
BEGIN NOW For what belongs to me, let Jove provide; END
BEGIN NOW But die thou first, whatever chance ensue. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and from the wound the weapon drew. END
BEGIN NOW A hov'ring mist came swimming o'er his sight, END
BEGIN NOW And seal'd his eyes in everlasting night. END
BEGIN NOW By Caedicus, Alcathous was slain; END
BEGIN NOW Sacrator laid Hydaspes on the plain; END
BEGIN NOW Orses the strong to greater strength must yield; END
BEGIN NOW He, with Parthenius, were by Rapo kill'd. END
BEGIN NOW Then brave Messapus Ericetes slew, END
BEGIN NOW Who from Lycaon's blood his lineage drew. END
BEGIN NOW But from his headstrong horse his fate he found, END
BEGIN NOW Who threw his master, as he made a bound: END
BEGIN NOW The chief, alighting, stuck him to the ground; END
BEGIN NOW Then Clonius, hand to hand, on foot assails: END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan sinks, and Neptune's son prevails. END
BEGIN NOW Agis the Lycian, stepping forth with pride, END
BEGIN NOW To single fight the boldest foe defied; END
BEGIN NOW Whom Tuscan Valerus by force o'ercame, END
BEGIN NOW And not belied his mighty father's fame. END
BEGIN NOW Salius to death the great Antronius sent: END
BEGIN NOW But the same fate the victor underwent, END
BEGIN NOW Slain by Nealces' hand, well-skill'd to throw END
BEGIN NOW The flying dart, and draw the far-deceiving bow. END
BEGIN NOW Thus equal deaths are dealt with equal chance; END
BEGIN NOW By turns they quit their ground, by turns advance: END
BEGIN NOW Victors and vanquish'd, in the various field, END
BEGIN NOW Nor wholly overcome, nor wholly yield. END
BEGIN NOW The gods from heav'n survey the fatal strife, END
BEGIN NOW And mourn the miseries of human life. END
BEGIN NOW Above the rest, two goddesses appear END
BEGIN NOW Concern'd for each: here Venus, Juno there. END
BEGIN NOW Amidst the crowd, infernal Ate shakes END
BEGIN NOW Her scourge aloft, and crest of hissing snakes. END
BEGIN NOW Once more the proud Mezentius, with disdain, END
BEGIN NOW Brandish'd his spear, and rush'd into the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Where tow'ring in the midmost rank she stood, END
BEGIN NOW Like tall Orion stalking o'er the flood. END
BEGIN NOW (When with his brawny breast he cuts the waves, END
BEGIN NOW His shoulders scarce the topmost billow laves), END
BEGIN NOW Or like a mountain ash, whose roots are spread, END
BEGIN NOW Deep fix'd in earth; in clouds he hides his head. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan prince beheld him from afar, END
BEGIN NOW And dauntless undertook the doubtful war. END
BEGIN NOW Collected in his strength, and like a rock, END
BEGIN NOW Pois'd on his base, Mezentius stood the shock. END
BEGIN NOW He stood, and, measuring first with careful eyes END
BEGIN NOW The space his spear could reach, aloud he cries: END
BEGIN NOW My strong right hand, and sword, assist my stroke! END
BEGIN NOW (Those only gods Mezentius will invoke.) END
BEGIN NOW His armor, from the Trojan pirate torn, END
BEGIN NOW By my triumphant Lausus shall be worn. END
BEGIN NOW He said; and with his utmost force he threw END
BEGIN NOW The massy spear, which, hissing as it flew, END
BEGIN NOW Reach'd the celestial shield, that stopp'd the course; END
BEGIN NOW But, glancing thence, the yet unbroken force END
BEGIN NOW Took a new bent obliquely, and betwixt END
BEGIN NOW The side and bowels fam'd Anthores fix'd. END
BEGIN NOW Anthores had from Argos travel'd far, END
BEGIN NOW Alcides' friend, and brother of the war; END
BEGIN NOW Till, tir'd with toils, fair Italy he chose, END
BEGIN NOW And in Evander's palace sought repose. END
BEGIN NOW Now, falling by another's wound, his eyes END
BEGIN NOW He cast to heav'n, on Argos thinks, and dies. END
BEGIN NOW The pious Trojan then his jav'lin sent; END
BEGIN NOW The shield gave way; thro' treble plates it went END
BEGIN NOW Of solid brass, of linen trebly roll'd, END
BEGIN NOW And three bull hides which round the buckler fold. END
BEGIN NOW All these it pass'd, resistless in the course, END
BEGIN NOW Transpierc'd his thigh, and spent its dying force. END
BEGIN NOW The gaping wound gush'd out a crimson flood. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan, glad with sight of hostile blood, END
BEGIN NOW His faunchion drew, to closer fight address'd, END
BEGIN NOW And with new force his fainting foe oppress'd. END
BEGIN NOW His father's peril Lausus view'd with grief; END
BEGIN NOW He sigh'd, he wept, he ran to his relief. END
BEGIN NOW And here, heroic youth, 't is here I must END
BEGIN NOW To thy immortal memory be just, END
BEGIN NOW And sing an act so noble and so new, END
BEGIN NOW Posterity will scarce believe 't is true. END
BEGIN NOW Pain'd with his wound, and useless for the fight, END
BEGIN NOW The father sought to save himself by flight: END
BEGIN NOW Incumber'd, slow he dragg'd the spear along, END
BEGIN NOW Which pierc'd his thigh, and in his buckler hung. END
BEGIN NOW The pious youth, resolv'd on death, below END
BEGIN NOW The lifted sword springs forth to face the foe; END
BEGIN NOW Protects his parent, and prevents the blow. END
BEGIN NOW Shouts of applause ran ringing thro' the field, END
BEGIN NOW To see the son the vanquish'd father shield. END
BEGIN NOW All, fir'd with gen'rous indignation, strive, END
BEGIN NOW And with a storm of darts to distance drive END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan chief, who, held at bay from far, END
BEGIN NOW On his Vulcanian orb sustain'd the war. END
BEGIN NOW As, when thick hail comes rattling in the wind, END
BEGIN NOW The plowman, passenger, and lab'ring hind END
BEGIN NOW For shelter to the neighb'ring covert fly, END
BEGIN NOW Or hous'd, or safe in hollow caverns lie; END
BEGIN NOW But, that o'erblown, when heav'n above 'em smiles, END
BEGIN NOW Return to travel, and renew their toils: END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas thus, o'erwhelmed on ev'ry side, END
BEGIN NOW The storm of darts, undaunted, did abide; END
BEGIN NOW And thus to Lausus loud with friendly threat'ning cried: END
BEGIN NOW Why wilt thou rush to certain death, and rage END
BEGIN NOW In rash attempts, beyond thy tender age, END
BEGIN NOW Betray'd by pious love?" Nor, thus forborne, END
BEGIN NOW The youth desists, but with insulting scorn END
BEGIN NOW Provokes the ling'ring prince, whose patience, tir'd, END
BEGIN NOW Gave place; and all his breast with fury fir'd. END
BEGIN NOW For now the Fates prepar'd their sharpen'd shears; END
BEGIN NOW And lifted high the flaming sword appears, END
BEGIN NOW Which, full descending with a frightful sway, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' shield and corslet forc'd th' impetuous way, END
BEGIN NOW And buried deep in his fair bosom lay. END
BEGIN NOW The purple streams thro' the thin armor strove, END
BEGIN NOW And drench'd th' imbroider'd coat his mother wove; END
BEGIN NOW And life at length forsook his heaving heart, END
BEGIN NOW Loth from so sweet a mansion to depart. END
BEGIN NOW But when, with blood and paleness all o'erspread, END
BEGIN NOW The pious prince beheld young Lausus dead, END
BEGIN NOW He griev'd; he wept; the sight an image brought END
BEGIN NOW Of his own filial love, a sadly pleasing thought: END
BEGIN NOW Then stretch'd his hand to hold him up, and said: END
BEGIN NOW Poor hapless youth! what praises can be paid END
BEGIN NOW To love so great, to such transcendent store END
BEGIN NOW Of early worth, and sure presage of more? END
BEGIN NOW Accept whate'er Aeneas can afford; END
BEGIN NOW Untouch'd thy arms, untaken be thy sword; END
BEGIN NOW And all that pleas'd thee living, still remain END
BEGIN NOW Inviolate, and sacred to the slain. END
BEGIN NOW Thy body on thy parents I bestow, END
BEGIN NOW To rest thy soul, at least, if shadows know, END
BEGIN NOW Or have a sense of human things below. END
BEGIN NOW There to thy fellow ghosts with glory tell: END
BEGIN NOW ''T was by the great Aeneas hand I fell.' END
BEGIN NOW With this, his distant friends he beckons near, END
BEGIN NOW Provokes their duty, and prevents their fear: END
BEGIN NOW Himself assists to lift him from the ground, END
BEGIN NOW With clotted locks, and blood that well'd from out the wound. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime, his father, now no father, stood, END
BEGIN NOW And wash'd his wounds by Tiber's yellow flood: END
BEGIN NOW Oppress'd with anguish, panting, and o'erspent, END
BEGIN NOW His fainting limbs against an oak he leant. END
BEGIN NOW A bough his brazen helmet did sustain; END
BEGIN NOW His heavier arms lay scatter'd on the plain: END
BEGIN NOW A chosen train of youth around him stand; END
BEGIN NOW His drooping head was rested on his hand: END
BEGIN NOW His grisly beard his pensive bosom sought; END
BEGIN NOW And all on Lausus ran his restless thought. END
BEGIN NOW Careful, concern'd his danger to prevent, END
BEGIN NOW He much enquir'd, and many a message sent END
BEGIN NOW To warn him from the field- alas! in vain! END
BEGIN NOW Behold, his mournful followers bear him slain! END
BEGIN NOW O'er his broad shield still gush'd the yawning wound, END
BEGIN NOW And drew a bloody trail along the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Far off he heard their cries, far off divin'd END
BEGIN NOW The dire event, with a foreboding mind. END
BEGIN NOW With dust he sprinkled first his hoary head; END
BEGIN NOW Then both his lifted hands to heav'n he spread; END
BEGIN NOW Last, the dear corpse embracing, thus he said: END
BEGIN NOW What joys, alas! could this frail being give, END
BEGIN NOW That I have been so covetous to live? END
BEGIN NOW To see my son, and such a son, resign END
BEGIN NOW His life, a ransom for preserving mine! END
BEGIN NOW And am I then preserv'd, and art thou lost? END
BEGIN NOW How much too dear has that redemption cost! END
BEGIN NOW 'T is now my bitter banishment I feel: END
BEGIN NOW This is a wound too deep for time to heal. END
BEGIN NOW My guilt thy growing virtues did defame; END
BEGIN NOW My blackness blotted thy unblemish'd name. END
BEGIN NOW Chas'd from a throne, abandon'd, and exil'd END
BEGIN NOW For foul misdeeds, were punishments too mild: END
BEGIN NOW I ow'd my people these, and, from their hate, END
BEGIN NOW With less resentment could have borne my fate. END
BEGIN NOW And yet I live, and yet sustain the sight END
BEGIN NOW Of hated men, and of more hated light: END
BEGIN NOW But will not long." With that he rais'd from ground END
BEGIN NOW His fainting limbs, that stagger'd with his wound; END
BEGIN NOW Yet, with a mind resolv'd, and unappall'd END
BEGIN NOW With pains or perils, for his courser call'd END
BEGIN NOW Well-mouth'd, well-manag'd, whom himself did dress END
BEGIN NOW With daily care, and mounted with success; END
BEGIN NOW His aid in arms, his ornament in peace. END
BEGIN NOW Soothing his courage with a gentle stroke, END
BEGIN NOW The steed seem'd sensible, while thus he spoke: END
BEGIN NOW O Rhoebus, we have liv'd too long for me- END
BEGIN NOW If life and long were terms that could agree! END
BEGIN NOW This day thou either shalt bring back the head END
BEGIN NOW And bloody trophies of the Trojan dead; END
BEGIN NOW This day thou either shalt revenge my woe, END
BEGIN NOW For murther'd Lausus, on his cruel foe; END
BEGIN NOW Or, if inexorable fate deny END
BEGIN NOW Our conquest, with thy conquer'd master die: END
BEGIN NOW For, after such a lord, rest secure, END
BEGIN NOW Thou wilt no foreign reins, or Trojan load endure. END
BEGIN NOW He said; and straight th' officious courser kneels, END
BEGIN NOW To take his wonted weight. His hands he fills END
BEGIN NOW With pointed jav'lins; on his head he lac'd END
BEGIN NOW His glitt'ring helm, which terribly was grac'd END
BEGIN NOW With waving horsehair, nodding from afar; END
BEGIN NOW Then spurr'd his thund'ring steed amidst the war. END
BEGIN NOW Love, anguish, wrath, and grief, to madness wrought, END
BEGIN NOW Despair, and secret shame, and conscious thought END
BEGIN NOW Of inborn worth, his lab'ring soul oppress'd, END
BEGIN NOW Roll'd in his eyes, and rag'd within his breast. END
BEGIN NOW Then loud he call'd Aeneas thrice by name: END
BEGIN NOW The loud repeated voice to glad Aeneas came. END
BEGIN NOW Great Jove," he said, "and the far-shooting god, END
BEGIN NOW Inspire thy mind to make thy challenge good! END
BEGIN NOW He spoke no more; but hasten'd, void of fear, END
BEGIN NOW And threaten'd with his long protended spear. END
BEGIN NOW To whom Mezentius thus: "Thy vaunts are vain. END
BEGIN NOW My Lausus lies extended on the plain: END
BEGIN NOW He's lost! thy conquest is already won; END
BEGIN NOW The wretched sire is murther'd in the son. END
BEGIN NOW Nor fate I fear, but all the gods defy. END
BEGIN NOW Forbear thy threats: my bus'ness is to die; END
BEGIN NOW But first receive this parting legacy. END
BEGIN NOW He said; and straight a whirling dart he sent; END
BEGIN NOW Another after, and another went. END
BEGIN NOW Round in a spacious ring he rides the field, END
BEGIN NOW And vainly plies th' impenetrable shield. END
BEGIN NOW Thrice rode he round; and thrice Aeneas wheel'd, END
BEGIN NOW Turn'd as he turn'd: the golden orb withstood END
BEGIN NOW The strokes, and bore about an iron wood. END
BEGIN NOW Impatient of delay, and weary grown, END
BEGIN NOW Still to defend, and to defend alone, END
BEGIN NOW To wrench the darts which in his buckler light, END
BEGIN NOW Urg'd and o'er-labor'd in unequal fight; END
BEGIN NOW At length resolv'd, he throws with all his force END
BEGIN NOW Full at the temples of the warrior horse. END
BEGIN NOW Just where the stroke was aim'd, th' unerring spear END
BEGIN NOW Made way, and stood transfix'd thro' either ear. END
BEGIN NOW Seiz'd with unwonted pain, surpris'd with fright, END
BEGIN NOW The wounded steed curvets, and, rais'd upright, END
BEGIN NOW Lights on his feet before; his hoofs behind END
BEGIN NOW Spring up in air aloft, and lash the wind. END
BEGIN NOW Down comes the rider headlong from his height: END
BEGIN NOW His horse came after with unwieldy weight, END
BEGIN NOW And, flound'ring forward, pitching on his head, END
BEGIN NOW His lord's incumber'd shoulder overlaid. END
BEGIN NOW From either host, the mingled shouts and cries END
BEGIN NOW Of Trojans and Rutulians rend the skies. END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas, hast'ning, wav'd his fatal sword END
BEGIN NOW High o'er his head, with this reproachful word: END
BEGIN NOW Now; where are now thy vaunts, the fierce disdain END
BEGIN NOW Of proud Mezentius, and the lofty strain? END
BEGIN NOW Struggling, and wildly staring on the skies, END
BEGIN NOW With scarce recover'd sight he thus replies: END
BEGIN NOW Why these insulting words, this waste of breath, END
BEGIN NOW To souls undaunted, and secure of death? END
BEGIN NOW 'T is no dishonor for the brave to die, END
BEGIN NOW Nor came I here with hope victory; END
BEGIN NOW Nor ask I life, nor fought with that design: END
BEGIN NOW As I had us'd my fortune, use thou thine. END
BEGIN NOW My dying son contracted no such band; END
BEGIN NOW The gift is hateful from his murd'rer's hand. END
BEGIN NOW For this, this only favor let me sue, END
BEGIN NOW If pity can to conquer'd foes be due: END
BEGIN NOW Refuse it not; but let my body have END
BEGIN NOW The last retreat of humankind, a grave. END
BEGIN NOW Too well I know th' insulting people's hate; END
BEGIN NOW Protect me from their vengeance after fate: END
BEGIN NOW This refuge for my poor remains provide, END
BEGIN NOW And lay my much-lov'd Lausus by my side. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and to the sword his throat applied. END
BEGIN NOW The crimson stream distain'd his arms around, END
BEGIN NOW And the disdainful soul came rushing thro' the wound. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce had the rosy Morning rais'd her head END
BEGIN NOW Above the waves, and left her wat'ry bed; END
BEGIN NOW The pious chief, whom double cares attend END
BEGIN NOW For his unburied soldiers and his friend, END
BEGIN NOW Yet first to Heav'n perform'd a victor's vows: END
BEGIN NOW He bar'd an ancient oak of all her boughs; END
BEGIN NOW Then on a rising ground the trunk he plac'd, END
BEGIN NOW Which with the spoils of his dead foe he grac'd. END
BEGIN NOW The coat of arms by proud Mezentius worn, END
BEGIN NOW Now on a naked snag in triumph borne, END
BEGIN NOW Was hung on high, and glitter'd from afar, END
BEGIN NOW A trophy sacred to the God of War. END
BEGIN NOW Above his arms, fix'd on the leafless wood, END
BEGIN NOW Appear'd his plumy crest, besmear'd with blood: END
BEGIN NOW His brazen buckler on the left was seen; END
BEGIN NOW Truncheons of shiver'd lances hung between; END
BEGIN NOW And on the right was placed his corslet, bor'd; END
BEGIN NOW And to the neck was tied his unavailing sword. END
BEGIN NOW A crowd of chiefs inclose the godlike man, END
BEGIN NOW Who thus, conspicuous in the midst, began: END
BEGIN NOW Our toils, my friends, are crown'd with sure success; END
BEGIN NOW The greater part perform'd, achieve the less. END
BEGIN NOW Now follow cheerful to the trembling town; END
BEGIN NOW Press but an entrance, and presume it won. END
BEGIN NOW Fear is no more, for fierce Mezentius lies, END
BEGIN NOW As the first fruits of war, a sacrifice. END
BEGIN NOW Turnus shall fall extended on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW And, in this omen, is already slain. END
BEGIN NOW Prepar'd in arms, pursue your happy chance; END
BEGIN NOW That none unwarn'd may plead his ignorance, END
BEGIN NOW And I, at Heav'n's appointed hour, may find END
BEGIN NOW Your warlike ensigns waving in the wind. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime the rites and fun'ral pomps prepare, END
BEGIN NOW Due to your dead companions of the war: END
BEGIN NOW The last respect the living can bestow, END
BEGIN NOW To shield their shadows from contempt below. END
BEGIN NOW That conquer'd earth be theirs, for which they fought, END
BEGIN NOW And which for us with their own blood they bought; END
BEGIN NOW But first the corpse of our unhappy friend END
BEGIN NOW To the sad city of Evander send, END
BEGIN NOW Who, not inglorious, in his age's bloom, END
BEGIN NOW Was hurried hence by too severe a doom. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, weeping while he spoke, he took his way, END
BEGIN NOW Where, new in death, lamented Pallas lay. END
BEGIN NOW Acoetes watch'd the corpse; whose youth deserv'd END
BEGIN NOW The father's trust; and now the son he serv'd END
BEGIN NOW With equal faith, but less auspicious care. END
BEGIN NOW Th' attendants of the slain his sorrow share. END
BEGIN NOW A troop of Trojans mix'd with these appear, END
BEGIN NOW And mourning matrons with dishevel'd hair. END
BEGIN NOW Soon as the prince appears, they raise a cry; END
BEGIN NOW All beat their breasts, and echoes rend the sky. END
BEGIN NOW They rear his drooping forehead from the ground; END
BEGIN NOW But, when Aeneas view'd the grisly wound END
BEGIN NOW Which Pallas in his manly bosom bore, END
BEGIN NOW And the fair flesh distain'd with purple gore; END
BEGIN NOW First, melting into tears, the pious man END
BEGIN NOW Deplor'd so sad a sight, then thus began: END
BEGIN NOW Unhappy youth! when Fortune gave the rest END
BEGIN NOW Of my full wishes, she refus'd the best! END
BEGIN NOW She came; but brought not thee along, to bless END
BEGIN NOW My longing eyes, and share in my success: END
BEGIN NOW She grudg'd thy safe return, the triumphs due END
BEGIN NOW To prosp'rous valor, in the public view. END
BEGIN NOW Not thus I promis'd, when thy father lent END
BEGIN NOW Thy needless succor with a sad consent; END
BEGIN NOW Embrac'd me, parting for th' Etrurian land, END
BEGIN NOW And sent me to possess a large command. END
BEGIN NOW He warn'd, and from his own experience told, END
BEGIN NOW Our foes were warlike, disciplin'd, and bold. END
BEGIN NOW And now perhaps, in hopes of thy return, END
BEGIN NOW Rich odors on his loaded altars burn, END
BEGIN NOW While we, with vain officious pomp, prepare END
BEGIN NOW To send him back his portion of the war, END
BEGIN NOW A bloody breathless body, which can owe END
BEGIN NOW No farther debt, but to the pow'rs below. END
BEGIN NOW The wretched father, ere his race is run, END
BEGIN NOW Shall view the fun'ral honors of his son. END
BEGIN NOW These are my triumphs of the Latian war, END
BEGIN NOW Fruits of my plighted faith and boasted care! END
BEGIN NOW And yet, unhappy sire, thou shalt not see END
BEGIN NOW A son whose death disgrac'd his ancestry; END
BEGIN NOW Thou shalt not blush, old man, however griev'd: END
BEGIN NOW Thy Pallas no dishonest wound receiv'd. END
BEGIN NOW He died no death to make thee wish, too late, END
BEGIN NOW Thou hadst not liv'd to see his shameful fate: END
BEGIN NOW But what a champion has th' Ausonian coast, END
BEGIN NOW And what a friend hast thou, Ascanius, lost! END
BEGIN NOW Thus having mourn'd, he gave the word around, END
BEGIN NOW To raise the breathless body from the ground; END
BEGIN NOW And chose a thousand horse, the flow'r of all END
BEGIN NOW His warlike troops, to wait the funeral, END
BEGIN NOW To bear him back and share Evander's grief: END
BEGIN NOW A well-becoming, but a weak relief. END
BEGIN NOW Of oaken twigs they twist an easy bier, END
BEGIN NOW Then on their shoulders the sad burden rear. END
BEGIN NOW The body on this rural hearse is borne: END
BEGIN NOW Strew'd leaves and funeral greens the bier adorn. END
BEGIN NOW All pale he lies, and looks a lovely flow'r, END
BEGIN NOW New cropp'd by virgin hands, to dress the bow'r: END
BEGIN NOW Unfaded yet, but yet unfed below, END
BEGIN NOW No more to mother earth or the green stern shall owe. END
BEGIN NOW Then two fair vests, of wondrous work and cost, END
BEGIN NOW Of purple woven, and with gold emboss'd, END
BEGIN NOW For ornament the Trojan hero brought, END
BEGIN NOW Which with her hands Sidonian Dido wrought. END
BEGIN NOW One vest array'd the corpse; and one they spread END
BEGIN NOW O'er his clos'd eyes, and wrapp'd around his head, END
BEGIN NOW That, when the yellow hair in flame should fall, END
BEGIN NOW The catching fire might burn the golden caul. END
BEGIN NOW Besides, the spoils of foes in battle slain, END
BEGIN NOW When he descended on the Latian plain; END
BEGIN NOW Arms, trappings, horses, by the hearse are led END
BEGIN NOW In long array- th' achievements of the dead. END
BEGIN NOW Then, pinion'd with their hands behind, appear END
BEGIN NOW Th' unhappy captives, marching in the rear, END
BEGIN NOW Appointed off'rings in the victor's name, END
BEGIN NOW To sprinkle with their blood the fun'ral flame. END
BEGIN NOW Inferior trophies by the chiefs are borne; END
BEGIN NOW Gauntlets and helms their loaded hands adorn; END
BEGIN NOW And fair inscriptions fix'd, and titles read END
BEGIN NOW Of Latian leaders conquer'd by the dead. END
BEGIN NOW Acoetes on his pupil's corpse attends, END
BEGIN NOW With feeble steps, supported by his friends. END
BEGIN NOW Pausing at ev'ry pace, in sorrow drown'd, END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt their arms he sinks upon the ground; END
BEGIN NOW Where grov'ling while he lies in deep despair, END
BEGIN NOW He beats his breast, and rends his hoary hair. END
BEGIN NOW The champion's chariot next is seen to roll, END
BEGIN NOW Besmear'd with hostile blood, and honorably foul. END
BEGIN NOW To close the pomp, Aethon, the steed of state, END
BEGIN NOW Is led, the fun'rals of his lord to wait. END
BEGIN NOW Stripp'd of his trappings, with a sullen pace END
BEGIN NOW He walks; and the big tears run rolling down his face. END
BEGIN NOW The lance of Pallas, and the crimson crest, END
BEGIN NOW Are borne behind: the victor seiz'd the rest. END
BEGIN NOW The march begins: the trumpets hoarsely sound; END
BEGIN NOW The pikes and lances trail along the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Thus while the Trojan and Arcadian horse END
BEGIN NOW To Pallantean tow'rs direct their course, END
BEGIN NOW In long procession rank'd, the pious chief END
BEGIN NOW Stopp'd in the rear, and gave a vent to grief: END
BEGIN NOW The public care," he said, "which war attends, END
BEGIN NOW Diverts our present woes, at least suspends. END
BEGIN NOW Peace with the manes of great Pallas dwell! END
BEGIN NOW Hail, holy relics! and a last farewell! END
BEGIN NOW He said no more, but, inly thro' he mourn'd, END
BEGIN NOW Restrained his tears, and to the camp return'd. END
BEGIN NOW Now suppliants, from Laurentum sent, demand END
BEGIN NOW A truce, with olive branches in their hand; END
BEGIN NOW Obtest his clemency, and from the plain END
BEGIN NOW Beg leave to draw the bodies of their slain. END
BEGIN NOW They plead, that none those common rites deny END
BEGIN NOW To conquer'd foes that in fair battle die. END
BEGIN NOW All cause of hate was ended in their death; END
BEGIN NOW Nor could he war with bodies void of breath. END
BEGIN NOW A king, they hop'd, would hear a king's request, END
BEGIN NOW Whose son he once was call'd, and once his guest. END
BEGIN NOW Their suit, which was too just to be denied, END
BEGIN NOW The hero grants, and farther thus replied: END
BEGIN NOW O Latian princes, how severe a fate END
BEGIN NOW In causeless quarrels has involv'd your state, END
BEGIN NOW And arm'd against an unoffending man, END
BEGIN NOW Who sought your friendship ere the war began! END
BEGIN NOW You beg a truce, which I would gladly give, END
BEGIN NOW Not only for the slain, but those who live. END
BEGIN NOW I came not hither but by Heav'n's command, END
BEGIN NOW And sent by fate to share the Latian land. END
BEGIN NOW Nor wage I wars unjust: your king denied END
BEGIN NOW My proffer'd friendship, and my promis'd bride; END
BEGIN NOW Left me for Turnus. Turnus then should try END
BEGIN NOW His cause in arms, to conquer or to die. END
BEGIN NOW My right and his are in dispute: the slain END
BEGIN NOW Fell without fault, our quarrel to maintain. END
BEGIN NOW In equal arms let us alone contend; END
BEGIN NOW And let him vanquish, whom his fates befriend. END
BEGIN NOW This is the way (so tell him) to possess END
BEGIN NOW The royal virgin, and restore the peace. END
BEGIN NOW Bear this message back, with ample leave, END
BEGIN NOW That your slain friends may fun'ral rites receive. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said- th' embassadors, amaz'd, END
BEGIN NOW Stood mute a while, and on each other gaz'd. END
BEGIN NOW Drances, their chief, who harbor'd in his breast END
BEGIN NOW Long hate to Turnus, as his foe profess'd, END
BEGIN NOW Broke silence first, and to the godlike man, END
BEGIN NOW With graceful action bowing, thus began: END
BEGIN NOW Auspicious prince, in arms a mighty name, END
BEGIN NOW But yet whose actions far transcend your fame; END
BEGIN NOW Would I your justice or your force express, END
BEGIN NOW Thought can but equal; and all words are less. END
BEGIN NOW Your answer we shall thankfully relate, END
BEGIN NOW And favors granted to the Latian state. END
BEGIN NOW If wish'd success our labor shall attend, END
BEGIN NOW Think peace concluded, and the king your friend: END
BEGIN NOW Let Turnus leave the realm to your command, END
BEGIN NOW And seek alliance in some other land: END
BEGIN NOW Build you the city which your fates assign; END
BEGIN NOW We shall be proud in the great work to join. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Drances; and his words so well persuade END
BEGIN NOW The rest impower'd, that soon a truce is made. END
BEGIN NOW Twelve days the term allow'd: and, during those, END
BEGIN NOW Latians and Trojans, now no longer foes, END
BEGIN NOW Mix'd in the woods, for fun'ral piles prepare END
BEGIN NOW To fell the timber, and forget the war. END
BEGIN NOW Loud axes thro' the groaning groves resound; END
BEGIN NOW Oak, mountain ash, and poplar spread the ground; END
BEGIN NOW First fall from high; and some the trunks receive END
BEGIN NOW In loaden wains; with wedges some they cleave. END
BEGIN NOW And now the fatal news by Fame is blown END
BEGIN NOW Thro' the short circuit of th' Arcadian town, END
BEGIN NOW Of Pallas slain- by Fame, which just before END
BEGIN NOW His triumphs on distended pinions bore. END
BEGIN NOW Rushing from out the gate, the people stand, END
BEGIN NOW Each with a fun'ral flambeau in his hand. END
BEGIN NOW Wildly they stare, distracted with amaze: END
BEGIN NOW The fields are lighten'd with a fiery blaze, END
BEGIN NOW That cast a sullen splendor on their friends, END
BEGIN NOW The marching troop which their dead prince attends. END
BEGIN NOW Both parties meet: they raise a doleful cry; END
BEGIN NOW The matrons from the walls with shrieks reply, END
BEGIN NOW And their mix'd mourning rends the vaulted sky. END
BEGIN NOW The town is fill'd with tumult and with tears, END
BEGIN NOW Till the loud clamors reach Evander's ears: END
BEGIN NOW Forgetful of his state, he runs along, END
BEGIN NOW With a disorder'd pace, and cleaves the throng; END
BEGIN NOW Falls on the corpse; and groaning there he lies, END
BEGIN NOW With silent grief, that speaks but at his eyes. END
BEGIN NOW Short sighs and sobs succeed; till sorrow breaks END
BEGIN NOW A passage, and at once he weeps and speaks: END
BEGIN NOW O Pallas! thou hast fail'd thy plighted word, END
BEGIN NOW To fight with caution, not to tempt the sword! END
BEGIN NOW I warn'd thee, but in vain; for well I knew END
BEGIN NOW What perils youthful ardor would pursue, END
BEGIN NOW That boiling blood would carry thee too far, END
BEGIN NOW Young as thou wert in dangers, raw to war! END
BEGIN NOW O curst essay of arms, disastrous doom, END
BEGIN NOW Prelude of bloody fields, and fights to come! END
BEGIN NOW Hard elements of unauspicious war, END
BEGIN NOW Vain vows to Heav'n, and unavailing care! END
BEGIN NOW Thrice happy thou, dear partner of my bed, END
BEGIN NOW Whose holy soul the stroke of Fortune fled, END
BEGIN NOW Praescious of ills, and leaving me behind, END
BEGIN NOW To drink the dregs of life by fate assign'd! END
BEGIN NOW Beyond the goal of nature I have gone: END
BEGIN NOW My Pallas late set out, but reach'd too soon. END
BEGIN NOW If, for my league against th' Ausonian state, END
BEGIN NOW Amidst their weapons I had found my fate, END
BEGIN NOW (Deserv'd from them,) then I had been return'd END
BEGIN NOW A breathless victor, and my son had mourn'd. END
BEGIN NOW Yet will I not my Trojan friend upbraid, END
BEGIN NOW Nor grudge th' alliance I so gladly made. END
BEGIN NOW 'T was not his fault, my Pallas fell so young, END
BEGIN NOW But my own crime, for having liv'd too long. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, since the gods had destin'd him to die, END
BEGIN NOW At least he led the way to victory: END
BEGIN NOW First for his friends he won the fatal shore, END
BEGIN NOW And sent whole herds of slaughter'd foes before; END
BEGIN NOW A death too great, too glorious to deplore. END
BEGIN NOW Nor will I add new honors to thy grave, END
BEGIN NOW Content with those the Trojan hero gave: END
BEGIN NOW That funeral pomp thy Phrygian friends design'd, END
BEGIN NOW In which the Tuscan chiefs and army join'd. END
BEGIN NOW Great spoils and trophies, gain'd by thee, they bear: END
BEGIN NOW Then let thy own achievements be thy share. END
BEGIN NOW Even thou, O Turnus, hadst a trophy stood, END
BEGIN NOW Whose mighty trunk had better grac'd the wood, END
BEGIN NOW If Pallas had arriv'd, with equal length END
BEGIN NOW Of years, to match thy bulk with equal strength. END
BEGIN NOW But why, unhappy man, dost thou detain END
BEGIN NOW These troops, to view the tears thou shedd'st in vain? END
BEGIN NOW Go, friends, this message to your lord relate: END
BEGIN NOW Tell him, that, if I bear my bitter fate, END
BEGIN NOW And, after Pallas' death, live ling'ring on, END
BEGIN NOW 'T is to behold his vengeance for my son. END
BEGIN NOW I stay for Turnus, whose devoted head END
BEGIN NOW Is owing to the living and the dead. END
BEGIN NOW My son and I expect it from his hand; END
BEGIN NOW 'T is all that he can give, or we demand. END
BEGIN NOW Joy is no more; but I would gladly go, END
BEGIN NOW To greet my Pallas with such news below. END
BEGIN NOW The morn had now dispell'd the shades of night, END
BEGIN NOW Restoring toils, when she restor'd the light. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan king and Tuscan chief command END
BEGIN NOW To raise the piles along the winding strand. END
BEGIN NOW Their friends convey the dead fun'ral fires; END
BEGIN NOW Black smold'ring smoke from the green wood expires; END
BEGIN NOW The light of heav'n is chok'd, and the new day retires. END
BEGIN NOW Then thrice around the kindled piles they go END
BEGIN NOW (For ancient custom had ordain'd it so) END
BEGIN NOW Thrice horse and foot about the fires are led; END
BEGIN NOW And thrice, with loud laments, they hail the dead. END
BEGIN NOW Tears, trickling down their breasts, bedew the ground, END
BEGIN NOW And drums and trumpets mix their mournful sound. END
BEGIN NOW Amid the blaze, their pious brethren throw END
BEGIN NOW The spoils, in battle taken from the foe: END
BEGIN NOW Helms, bits emboss'd, and swords of shining steel; END
BEGIN NOW One casts a target, one a chariot wheel; END
BEGIN NOW Some to their fellows their own arms restore: END
BEGIN NOW The fauchions which in luckless fight they bore, END
BEGIN NOW Their bucklers pierc'd, their darts bestow'd in vain, END
BEGIN NOW And shiver'd lances gather'd from the plain. END
BEGIN NOW Whole herds of offer'd bulls, about the fire, END
BEGIN NOW And bristled boars, and woolly sheep expire. END
BEGIN NOW Around the piles a careful troop attends, END
BEGIN NOW To watch the wasting flames, and weep their burning friends; END
BEGIN NOW Ling'ring along the shore, till dewy night END
BEGIN NOW New decks the face of heav'n with starry light. END
BEGIN NOW The conquer'd Latians, with like pious care, END
BEGIN NOW Piles without number for their dead prepare. END
BEGIN NOW Part in the places where they fell are laid; END
BEGIN NOW And part are to the neighb'ring fields convey'd. END
BEGIN NOW The corps of kings, and captains of renown, END
BEGIN NOW Borne off in state, are buried in the town; END
BEGIN NOW The rest, unhonor'd, and without a name, END
BEGIN NOW Are cast a common heap to feed the flame. END
BEGIN NOW Trojans and Latians vie with like desires END
BEGIN NOW To make the field of battle shine with fires, END
BEGIN NOW And the promiscuous blaze to heav'n aspires. END
BEGIN NOW Now had the morning thrice renew'd the light, END
BEGIN NOW And thrice dispell'd the shadows of the night, END
BEGIN NOW When those who round the wasted fires remain, END
BEGIN NOW Perform the last sad office to the slain. END
BEGIN NOW They rake the yet warm ashes from below; END
BEGIN NOW These, and the bones unburn'd, in earth bestow; END
BEGIN NOW These relics with their country rites they grace, END
BEGIN NOW And raise a mount of turf to mark the place. END
BEGIN NOW But, in the palace of the king, appears END
BEGIN NOW A scene more solemn, and a pomp of tears. END
BEGIN NOW Maids, matrons, widows, mix their common moans; END
BEGIN NOW Orphans their sires, and sires lament their sons. END
BEGIN NOW All in that universal sorrow share, END
BEGIN NOW And curse the cause of this unhappy war: END
BEGIN NOW A broken league, a bride unjustly sought, END
BEGIN NOW A crown usurp'd, which with their blood is bought! END
BEGIN NOW These are the crimes with which they load the name END
BEGIN NOW Of Turnus, and on him alone exclaim: END
BEGIN NOW Let him who lords it o'er th' Ausonian land END
BEGIN NOW Engage the Trojan hero hand to hand: END
BEGIN NOW His is the gain; our lot is but to serve; END
BEGIN NOW 'T is just, the sway he seeks, he should deserve. END
BEGIN NOW This Drances aggravates; and adds, with spite: END
BEGIN NOW His foe expects, and dares him to the fight. END
BEGIN NOW Nor Turnus wants a party, to support END
BEGIN NOW His cause and credit in the Latian court. END
BEGIN NOW His former acts secure his present fame, END
BEGIN NOW And the queen shades him with her mighty name. END
BEGIN NOW While thus their factious minds with fury burn, END
BEGIN NOW The legates from th' Aetolian prince return: END
BEGIN NOW Sad news they bring, that, after all the cost END
BEGIN NOW And care employ'd, their embassy is lost; END
BEGIN NOW That Diomedes refus'd his aid in war, END
BEGIN NOW Unmov'd with presents, and as deaf to pray'r. END
BEGIN NOW Some new alliance must elsewhere be sought, END
BEGIN NOW Or peace with Troy on hard conditions bought. END
BEGIN NOW Latinus, sunk in sorrow, finds too late, END
BEGIN NOW A foreign son is pointed out by fate; END
BEGIN NOW And, till Aeneas shall Lavinia wed, END
BEGIN NOW The wrath of Heav'n is hov'ring o'er his head. END
BEGIN NOW The gods, he saw, espous'd the juster side, END
BEGIN NOW When late their titles in the field were tried: END
BEGIN NOW Witness the fresh laments, and fun'ral tears undried. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, full of anxious thought, he summons all END
BEGIN NOW The Latian senate to the council hall. END
BEGIN NOW The princes come, commanded by their head, END
BEGIN NOW And crowd the paths that to the palace lead. END
BEGIN NOW Supreme in pow'r, and reverenc'd for his years, END
BEGIN NOW He takes the throne, and in the midst appears. END
BEGIN NOW Majestically sad, he sits in state, END
BEGIN NOW And bids his envoys their success relate. END
BEGIN NOW When Venulus began, the murmuring sound END
BEGIN NOW Was hush'd, and sacred silence reign'd around. END
BEGIN NOW We have," said he, "perform'd your high command, END
BEGIN NOW And pass'd with peril a long tract of land: END
BEGIN NOW We reach'd the place desir'd; with wonder fill'd, END
BEGIN NOW The Grecian tents and rising tow'rs beheld. END
BEGIN NOW Great Diomede has compass'd round with walls END
BEGIN NOW The city, which Argyripa he calls, END
BEGIN NOW From his own Argos nam'd. We touch'd, with joy, END
BEGIN NOW The royal hand that raz'd unhappy Troy. END
BEGIN NOW When introduc'd, our presents first we bring, END
BEGIN NOW Then crave an instant audience from the king. END
BEGIN NOW His leave obtain'd, our native soil we name, END
BEGIN NOW And tell th' important cause for which we came. END
BEGIN NOW Attentively he heard us, while we spoke; END
BEGIN NOW Then, with soft accents, and a pleasing look, END
BEGIN NOW Made this return: 'Ausonian race, of old END
BEGIN NOW Renown'd for peace, and for an age of gold, END
BEGIN NOW What madness has your alter'd minds possess'd, END
BEGIN NOW To change for war hereditary rest, END
BEGIN NOW Solicit arms unknown, and tempt the sword, END
BEGIN NOW A needless ill your ancestors abhorr'd? END
BEGIN NOW We- for myself I speak, and all the name END
BEGIN NOW Of Grecians, who to Troy's destruction came, END
BEGIN NOW Omitting those who were in battle slain, END
BEGIN NOW Or borne by rolling Simois to the main- END
BEGIN NOW Not one but suffer'd, and too dearly bought END
BEGIN NOW The prize of honor which in arms he sought; END
BEGIN NOW Some doom'd to death, and some in exile driv'n. END
BEGIN NOW Outcasts, abandon'd by the care of Heav'n; END
BEGIN NOW So worn, so wretched, so despis'd a crew, END
BEGIN NOW As ev'n old Priam might with pity view. END
BEGIN NOW Witness the vessels by Minerva toss'd END
BEGIN NOW In storms; the vengeful Capharean coast; END
BEGIN NOW Th' Euboean rocks! the prince, whose brother led END
BEGIN NOW Our armies to revenge his injur'd bed, END
BEGIN NOW Have seen Charybdis and the Cyclops' den. END
BEGIN NOW Why should I name Idomeneus, in vain END
BEGIN NOW Restor'd to scepters, and expell'd again? END
BEGIN NOW Or young Achilles, by his rival slain? END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n he, the King of Men, the foremost name END
BEGIN NOW Of all the Greeks, and most renown'd by fame, END
BEGIN NOW The proud revenger of another's wife, END
BEGIN NOW Yet by his own adult'ress lost his life; END
BEGIN NOW Fell at his threshold; and the spoils of Troy END
BEGIN NOW The foul polluters of his bed enjoy. END
BEGIN NOW The gods have envied me the sweets of life, END
BEGIN NOW My much lov'd country, and my more lov'd wife: END
BEGIN NOW Banish'd from both, I mourn; while in the sky, END
BEGIN NOW Transform'd to birds, my lost companions fly: END
BEGIN NOW Hov'ring about the coasts, they make their moan, END
BEGIN NOW And cuff the cliffs with pinions not their own. END
BEGIN NOW What squalid specters, in the dead of night, END
BEGIN NOW Break my short sleep, and skim before my sight! END
BEGIN NOW I might have promis'd to myself those harms, END
BEGIN NOW Mad as I was, when I, with mortal arms, END
BEGIN NOW Presum'd against immortal pow'rs to move, END
BEGIN NOW And violate with wounds the Queen of Love. END
BEGIN NOW Such arms this hand shall never more employ; END
BEGIN NOW No hate remains with me to ruin'd Troy. END
BEGIN NOW I war not with its dust; nor am I glad END
BEGIN NOW To think of past events, or good or bad. END
BEGIN NOW Your presents I return: whate'er you bring END
BEGIN NOW To buy my friendship, send the Trojan king. END
BEGIN NOW We met in fight; I know him, to my cost: END
BEGIN NOW With what a whirling force his lance he toss'd! END
BEGIN NOW Heav'ns! what a spring was in his arm, to throw! END
BEGIN NOW How high he held his shield, and rose at ev'ry blow! END
BEGIN NOW Had Troy produc'd two more his match in might, END
BEGIN NOW They would have chang'd the fortune of the fight: END
BEGIN NOW Th' invasion of the Greeks had been return'd, END
BEGIN NOW Our empire wasted, and our cities burn'd. END
BEGIN NOW The long defense the Trojan people made, END
BEGIN NOW The war protracted, and the siege delay'd, END
BEGIN NOW Were due to Hector's and this hero's hand: END
BEGIN NOW Both brave alike, and equal in command; END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas, not inferior in the field, END
BEGIN NOW In pious reverence to the gods excell'd. END
BEGIN NOW Make peace, ye Latians, and avoid with care END
BEGIN NOW Th' impending dangers of a fatal war.' END
BEGIN NOW He said no more; but, with this cold excuse, END
BEGIN NOW Refus'd th' alliance, and advis'd a truce. END
BEGIN NOW Thus Venulus concluded his report. END
BEGIN NOW A jarring murmur fill'd the factious court: END
BEGIN NOW As, when a torrent rolls with rapid force, END
BEGIN NOW And dashes o'er the stones that stop the course, END
BEGIN NOW The flood, constrain'd within a scanty space, END
BEGIN NOW Roars horrible along th' uneasy race; END
BEGIN NOW White foam in gath'ring eddies floats around; END
BEGIN NOW The rocky shores rebellow to the sound. END
BEGIN NOW The murmur ceas'd: then from his lofty throne END
BEGIN NOW The king invok'd the gods, and thus begun: END
BEGIN NOW I wish, ye Latins, what we now debate END
BEGIN NOW Had been resolv'd before it was too late. END
BEGIN NOW Much better had it been for you and me, END
BEGIN NOW Unforc'd by this our last necessity, END
BEGIN NOW To have been earlier wise, than now to call END
BEGIN NOW A council, when the foe surrounds the wall. END
BEGIN NOW O citizens, we wage unequal war, END
BEGIN NOW With men not only Heav'n's peculiar care, END
BEGIN NOW But Heav'n's own race; unconquer'd in the field, END
BEGIN NOW Or, conquer'd, yet unknowing how to yield. END
BEGIN NOW What hopes you had in Diomedes, lay down: END
BEGIN NOW Our hopes must center on ourselves alone. END
BEGIN NOW Yet those how feeble, and, indeed, how vain, END
BEGIN NOW You see too well; nor need my words explain. END
BEGIN NOW Vanquish'd without resource; laid flat by fate; END
BEGIN NOW Factions within, a foe without the gate! END
BEGIN NOW Not but I grant that all perform'd their parts END
BEGIN NOW With manly force, and with undaunted hearts: END
BEGIN NOW With our united strength the war we wag'd; END
BEGIN NOW With equal numbers, equal arms, engag'd. END
BEGIN NOW You see th' event.- Now hear what I propose, END
BEGIN NOW To save our friends, and satisfy our foes. END
BEGIN NOW A tract of land the Latins have possess'd END
BEGIN NOW Along the Tiber, stretching to the west, END
BEGIN NOW Which now Rutulians and Auruncans till, END
BEGIN NOW And their mix'd cattle graze the fruitful hill. END
BEGIN NOW Those mountains fill'd with firs, that lower land, END
BEGIN NOW If you consent, the Trojan shall command, END
BEGIN NOW Call'd into part of what is ours; and there, END
BEGIN NOW On terms agreed, the common country share. END
BEGIN NOW There let'em build and settle, if they please; END
BEGIN NOW Unless they choose once more to cross the seas, END
BEGIN NOW In search of seats remote from Italy, END
BEGIN NOW And from unwelcome inmates set us free. END
BEGIN NOW Then twice ten galleys let us build with speed, END
BEGIN NOW Or twice as many more, if more they need. END
BEGIN NOW Materials are at hand; a well-grown wood END
BEGIN NOW Runs equal with the margin of the flood: END
BEGIN NOW Let them the number and the form assign; END
BEGIN NOW The care and cost of all the stores be mine. END
BEGIN NOW To treat the peace, a hundred senators END
BEGIN NOW Shall be commission'd hence with ample pow'rs, END
BEGIN NOW With olive the presents they shall bear, END
BEGIN NOW A purple robe, a royal iv'ry chair, END
BEGIN NOW And all the marks of sway that Latian monarchs wear, END
BEGIN NOW And sums of gold. Among yourselves debate END
BEGIN NOW This great affair, and save the sinking state. END
BEGIN NOW Then Drances took the word, who grudg'd, long since, END
BEGIN NOW The rising glories of the Daunian prince. END
BEGIN NOW Factious and rich, bold at the council board, END
BEGIN NOW But cautious in the field, he shunn'd the sword; END
BEGIN NOW A close caballer, and tongue-valiant lord. END
BEGIN NOW Noble his mother was, and near the throne; END
BEGIN NOW But, what his father's parentage, unknown. END
BEGIN NOW He rose, and took th' advantage of the times, END
BEGIN NOW To load young Turnus with invidious crimes. END
BEGIN NOW Such truths, O king," said he, "your words contain, END
BEGIN NOW As strike the sense, and all replies are vain; END
BEGIN NOW Nor are your loyal subjects now to seek END
BEGIN NOW What common needs require, but fear to speak. END
BEGIN NOW Let him give leave of speech, that haughty man, END
BEGIN NOW Whose pride this unauspicious war began; END
BEGIN NOW For whose ambition (let me dare to say, END
BEGIN NOW Fear set apart, tho' death is in my way) END
BEGIN NOW The plains of Latium run with blood around. END
BEGIN NOW So many valiant heroes bite the ground; END
BEGIN NOW Dejected grief in ev'ry face appears; END
BEGIN NOW A town in mourning, and a land in tears; END
BEGIN NOW While he, th' undoubted author of our harms, END
BEGIN NOW The man who menaces the gods with arms, END
BEGIN NOW Yet, after all his boasts, forsook the fight, END
BEGIN NOW And sought his safety in ignoble flight. END
BEGIN NOW Now, best of kings, since you propose to send END
BEGIN NOW Such bounteous presents to your Trojan friend; END
BEGIN NOW Add yet a greater at our joint request, END
BEGIN NOW One which he values more than all the rest: END
BEGIN NOW Give him the fair Lavinia for his bride; END
BEGIN NOW With that alliance let the league be tied, END
BEGIN NOW And for the bleeding land a lasting peace provide. END
BEGIN NOW Let insolence no longer awe the throne; END
BEGIN NOW But, with a father's right, bestow your own. END
BEGIN NOW For this maligner of the general good, END
BEGIN NOW If still we fear his force, he must be woo'd; END
BEGIN NOW His haughty godhead we with pray'rs implore, END
BEGIN NOW Your scepter to release, and our just rights restore. END
BEGIN NOW O cursed cause of all our ills, must we END
BEGIN NOW Wage wars unjust, and fall in fight, for thee! END
BEGIN NOW What right hast thou to rule the Latian state, END
BEGIN NOW And send us out to meet our certain fate? END
BEGIN NOW 'T is a destructive war: from Turnus' hand END
BEGIN NOW Our peace and public safety we demand. END
BEGIN NOW Let the fair bride to the brave chief remain; END
BEGIN NOW If not, the peace, without the pledge, is vain. END
BEGIN NOW Turnus, I know you think me not your friend, END
BEGIN NOW Nor will I much with your belief contend: END
BEGIN NOW I beg your greatness not to give the law END
BEGIN NOW In others' realms, but, beaten, to withdraw. END
BEGIN NOW Pity your own, or pity our estate; END
BEGIN NOW Nor twist our fortunes with your sinking fate. END
BEGIN NOW Your interest is, the war should never cease; END
BEGIN NOW But we have felt enough to wish the peace: END
BEGIN NOW A land exhausted to the last remains, END
BEGIN NOW Depopulated towns, and driven plains. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, if desire of fame, and thirst of pow'r, END
BEGIN NOW A beauteous princess, with a crown in dow'r, END
BEGIN NOW So fire your mind, in arms assert your right, END
BEGIN NOW And meet your foe, who dares you to the fight. END
BEGIN NOW Mankind, it seems, is made for you alone; END
BEGIN NOW We, but the slaves who mount you to the throne: END
BEGIN NOW A base ignoble crowd, without a name, END
BEGIN NOW Unwept, unworthy, of the fun'ral flame, END
BEGIN NOW By duty bound to forfeit each his life, END
BEGIN NOW That Turnus may possess a royal wife. END
BEGIN NOW Permit not, mighty man, so mean a crew END
BEGIN NOW Should share such triumphs, and detain from you END
BEGIN NOW The post of honor, your undoubted due. END
BEGIN NOW Rather alone your matchless force employ, END
BEGIN NOW To merit what alone you must enjoy. END
BEGIN NOW These words, so full of malice mix'd with art, END
BEGIN NOW Inflam'd with rage the youthful hero's heart. END
BEGIN NOW Then, groaning from the bottom of his breast, END
BEGIN NOW He heav'd for wind, and thus his wrath express'd: END
BEGIN NOW You, Drances, never want a stream of words, END
BEGIN NOW Then, when the public need requires our swords. END
BEGIN NOW First in the council hall to steer the state, END
BEGIN NOW And ever foremost in a tongue-debate, END
BEGIN NOW While our strong walls secure us from the foe, END
BEGIN NOW Ere yet with blood our ditches overflow: END
BEGIN NOW But let the potent orator declaim, END
BEGIN NOW And with the brand of coward blot my name; END
BEGIN NOW Free leave is giv'n him, when his fatal hand END
BEGIN NOW Has cover'd with more corps the sanguine strand, END
BEGIN NOW And high as mine his tow'ring trophies stand. END
BEGIN NOW If any doubt remains, who dares the most, END
BEGIN NOW Let us decide it at the Trojan's cost, END
BEGIN NOW And issue both abreast, where honor calls- END
BEGIN NOW Foes are not far to seek without the walls- END
BEGIN NOW Unless his noisy tongue can only fight, END
BEGIN NOW And feet were giv'n him but to speed his flight. END
BEGIN NOW I beaten from the field? I forc'd away? END
BEGIN NOW Had he but ev'n beheld the fight, his eyes END
BEGIN NOW Had witness'd for me what his tongue denies: END
BEGIN NOW What heaps of Trojans by this hand were slain, END
BEGIN NOW And how the bloody Tiber swell'd the main. END
BEGIN NOW All saw, but he, th' Arcadian troops retire END
BEGIN NOW In scatter'd squadrons, and their prince expire. END
BEGIN NOW The giant brothers, in their camp, have found, END
BEGIN NOW I was not forc'd with ease to quit my ground. END
BEGIN NOW Not such the Trojans tried me, when, inclos'd, END
BEGIN NOW I singly their united arms oppos'd: END
BEGIN NOW First forc'd an entrance thro' their thick array; END
BEGIN NOW Then, glutted with their slaughter, freed my way. END
BEGIN NOW 'T is a destructive war? So let it be, END
BEGIN NOW But to the Phrygian pirate, and to thee! END
BEGIN NOW Meantime proceed to fill the people's ears END
BEGIN NOW With false reports, their minds with panic fears: END
BEGIN NOW Extol the strength of a twice-conquer'd race; END
BEGIN NOW Our foes encourage, and our friends debase. END
BEGIN NOW Believe thy fables, and the Trojan town END
BEGIN NOW Triumphant stands; the Grecians are o'erthrown; END
BEGIN NOW Suppliant at Hector's feet Achilles lies, END
BEGIN NOW And Diomede from fierce Aeneas flies. END
BEGIN NOW Say rapid Aufidus with awful dread END
BEGIN NOW Runs backward from the sea, and hides his head, END
BEGIN NOW When the great Trojan on his bank appears; END
BEGIN NOW For that's as true as thy dissembled fears END
BEGIN NOW Of my revenge. Dismiss that vanity: END
BEGIN NOW Thou, Drances, art below a death from me. END
BEGIN NOW Let that vile soul in that vile body rest; END
BEGIN NOW The lodging is well worthy of the guest. END
BEGIN NOW Now, royal father, to the present state END
BEGIN NOW Of our affairs, and of this high debate: END
BEGIN NOW If in your arms thus early you diffide, END
BEGIN NOW And think your fortune is already tried; END
BEGIN NOW If one defeat has brought us down so low, END
BEGIN NOW As never more in fields to meet the foe; END
BEGIN NOW Then I conclude for peace: 't is time to treat, END
BEGIN NOW And lie like vassals at the victor's feet. END
BEGIN NOW But, O! if any ancient blood remains, END
BEGIN NOW One drop of all our fathers', in our veins, END
BEGIN NOW That man would I prefer before the rest, END
BEGIN NOW Who dar'd his death with an undaunted breast; END
BEGIN NOW Who comely fell, by no dishonest wound, END
BEGIN NOW To shun that sight, and, dying, gnaw'd the ground. END
BEGIN NOW But, if we still have fresh recruits in store, END
BEGIN NOW If our confederates can afford us more; END
BEGIN NOW If the contended field we bravely fought, END
BEGIN NOW And not a bloodless victory was bought; END
BEGIN NOW Their losses equal'd ours; and, for their slain, END
BEGIN NOW With equal fires they fill'd the shining plain; END
BEGIN NOW Why thus, unforc'd, should we so tamely yield, END
BEGIN NOW And, ere the trumpet sounds, resign the field? END
BEGIN NOW Good unexpected, evils unforeseen, END
BEGIN NOW Appear by turns, as fortune shifts the scene: END
BEGIN NOW Some, rais'd aloft, come tumbling down amain; END
BEGIN NOW Then fall so hard, they bound and rise again. END
BEGIN NOW If Diomede refuse his aid to lend, END
BEGIN NOW The great Messapus yet remains our friend: END
BEGIN NOW Tolumnius, who foretells events, is ours; END
BEGIN NOW Th' Italian chiefs and princes join their pow'rs: END
BEGIN NOW Nor least in number, nor in name the last, END
BEGIN NOW Your own brave subjects have your cause embrac'd END
BEGIN NOW Above the rest, the Volscian Amazon END
BEGIN NOW Contains an army in herself alone, END
BEGIN NOW And heads a squadron, terrible to sight, END
BEGIN NOW With glitt'ring shields, in brazen armor bright. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, if the foe a single fight demand, END
BEGIN NOW And I alone the public peace withstand; END
BEGIN NOW If you consent, he shall not be refus'd, END
BEGIN NOW Nor find a hand to victory unus'd. END
BEGIN NOW This new Achilles, let him take the field, END
BEGIN NOW With fated armor, and Vulcanian shield! END
BEGIN NOW For you, my royal father, and my fame, END
BEGIN NOW I, Turnus, not the least of all my name, END
BEGIN NOW Devote my soul. He calls me hand to hand, END
BEGIN NOW And I alone will answer his demand. END
BEGIN NOW Drances shall rest secure, and neither share END
BEGIN NOW The danger, nor divide the prize of war. END
BEGIN NOW While they debate, nor these nor those will yield, END
BEGIN NOW Aeneas draws his forces to the field, END
BEGIN NOW And moves his camp. The scouts with flying speed END
BEGIN NOW Return, and thro' the frighted city spread END
BEGIN NOW Th' unpleasing news, the Trojans are descried, END
BEGIN NOW In battle marching by the river side, END
BEGIN NOW And bending to the town. They take th' alarm: END
BEGIN NOW Some tremble, some are bold; all in confusion arm. END
BEGIN NOW Th' impetuous youth press forward to the field; END
BEGIN NOW They clash the sword, and clatter on the shield: END
BEGIN NOW The fearful matrons raise a screaming cry; END
BEGIN NOW Old feeble men with fainter groans reply; END
BEGIN NOW A jarring sound results, and mingles in the sky, END
BEGIN NOW Like that of swans remurm'ring to the floods, END
BEGIN NOW Or birds of diff'ring kinds in hollow woods. END
BEGIN NOW Turnus th' occasion takes, and cries aloud: END
BEGIN NOW Talk on, ye quaint haranguers of the crowd: END
BEGIN NOW Declaim in praise of peace, when danger calls, END
BEGIN NOW And the fierce foes in arms approach the walls. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and, turning short, with speedy pace, END
BEGIN NOW Casts back a scornful glance, and quits the place: END
BEGIN NOW Thou, Volusus, the Volscian troops command END
BEGIN NOW To mount; and lead thyself our Ardean band. END
BEGIN NOW Messapus and Catillus, post your force END
BEGIN NOW Along the fields, to charge the Trojan horse. END
BEGIN NOW Some guard the passes, others man the wall; END
BEGIN NOW Drawn up in arms, the rest attend my call. END
BEGIN NOW They swarm from ev'ry quarter of the town, END
BEGIN NOW And with disorder'd haste the rampires crown. END
BEGIN NOW Good old Latinus, when he saw, too late, END
BEGIN NOW The gath'ring storm just breaking on the state, END
BEGIN NOW Dismiss'd the council till a fitter time, END
BEGIN NOW And own'd his easy temper as his crime, END
BEGIN NOW Who, forc'd against his reason, had complied END
BEGIN NOW To break the treaty for the promis'd bride. END
BEGIN NOW Some help to sink new trenches; others aid END
BEGIN NOW To ram the stones, or raise the palisade. END
BEGIN NOW Hoarse trumpets sound th' alarm; around the walls END
BEGIN NOW Runs a distracted crew, whom their last labor calls. END
BEGIN NOW A sad procession in the streets is seen, END
BEGIN NOW Of matrons, that attend the mother queen: END
BEGIN NOW High in her chair she sits, and, at her side, END
BEGIN NOW With downcast eyes, appears the fatal bride. END
BEGIN NOW They mount the cliff, where Pallas' temple stands; END
BEGIN NOW Pray'rs in their mouths, and presents in their hands, END
BEGIN NOW With censers first they fume the sacred shrine, END
BEGIN NOW Then in this common supplication join: END
BEGIN NOW O patroness of arms, unspotted maid, END
BEGIN NOW Propitious hear, and lend thy Latins aid! END
BEGIN NOW Break short the pirate's lance; pronounce his fate, END
BEGIN NOW And lay the Phrygian low before the gate. END
BEGIN NOW Now Turnus arms for fight. His back and breast END
BEGIN NOW Well-temper'd steel and scaly brass invest: END
BEGIN NOW The cuishes which his brawny thighs infold END
BEGIN NOW Are mingled metal damask'd o'er with gold. END
BEGIN NOW His faithful fauchion sits upon his side; END
BEGIN NOW Nor casque, nor crest, his manly features hide: END
BEGIN NOW But, bare to view, amid surrounding friends, END
BEGIN NOW With godlike grace, he from the tow'r descends. END
BEGIN NOW Exulting in his strength, he seems to dare END
BEGIN NOW His absent rival, and to promise war. END
BEGIN NOW Freed from his keepers, thus, with broken reins, END
BEGIN NOW The wanton courser prances o'er the plains, END
BEGIN NOW Or in the pride of youth o'erleaps the mounds, END
BEGIN NOW And snuffs the females in forbidden grounds. END
BEGIN NOW Or seeks his wat'ring in the well-known flood, END
BEGIN NOW To quench his thirst, and cool his fiery blood: END
BEGIN NOW He swims luxuriant in the liquid plain, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er his shoulder flows his waving mane: END
BEGIN NOW He neighs, he snorts, he bears his head on high; END
BEGIN NOW Before his ample chest the frothy waters fly. END
BEGIN NOW Soon as the prince appears without the gate, END
BEGIN NOW The Volscians, with their virgin leader, wait END
BEGIN NOW His last commands. Then, with a graceful mien, END
BEGIN NOW Lights from her lofty steed the warrior queen: END
BEGIN NOW Her squadron imitates, and each descends; END
BEGIN NOW Whose common suit Camilla thus commends: END
BEGIN NOW If sense of honor, if a soul secure END
BEGIN NOW Of inborn worth, that can all tests endure, END
BEGIN NOW Can promise aught, or on itself rely END
BEGIN NOW Greatly to dare, to conquer or to die; END
BEGIN NOW Then, I alone, sustain'd by these, will meet END
BEGIN NOW The Tyrrhene troops, and promise their defeat. END
BEGIN NOW Ours be the danger, ours the sole renown: END
BEGIN NOW You, gen'ral, stay behind, and guard the town: END
BEGIN NOW Turnus a while stood mute, with glad surprise, END
BEGIN NOW And on the fierce virago fix'd his eyes; END
BEGIN NOW Then thus return'd: "O grace of Italy, END
BEGIN NOW With what becoming thanks can I reply? END
BEGIN NOW Not only words lie lab'ring in my breast, END
BEGIN NOW But thought itself is by thy praise oppress'd. END
BEGIN NOW Yet rob me not of all; but let me join END
BEGIN NOW My toils, my hazard, and my fame, with thine. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan, not in stratagem unskill'd, END
BEGIN NOW Sends his light horse before to scour the field: END
BEGIN NOW Himself, thro' steep ascents and thorny brakes, END
BEGIN NOW A larger compass to the city takes. END
BEGIN NOW This news my scouts confirm, and I prepare END
BEGIN NOW To foil his cunning, and his force to dare; END
BEGIN NOW With chosen foot his passage to forelay, END
BEGIN NOW And place an ambush in the winding way. END
BEGIN NOW Thou, with thy Volscians, face the Tuscan horse; END
BEGIN NOW The brave Messapus shall thy troops inforce END
BEGIN NOW With those of Tibur, and the Latian band, END
BEGIN NOW Subjected all to thy supreme command. END
BEGIN NOW This said, he warns Messapus to the war, END
BEGIN NOW Then ev'ry chief exhorts with equal care. END
BEGIN NOW All thus encourag'd, his own troops he joins, END
BEGIN NOW And hastes to prosecute his deep designs. END
BEGIN NOW Inclos'd with hills, a winding valley lies, END
BEGIN NOW By nature form'd for fraud, and fitted for surprise. END
BEGIN NOW A narrow track, by human steps untrode, END
BEGIN NOW Leads, thro' perplexing thorns, to this obscure abode. END
BEGIN NOW High o'er the vale a steepy mountain stands, END
BEGIN NOW Whence the surveying sight the nether ground commands. END
BEGIN NOW The top is level, an offensive seat END
BEGIN NOW Of war; and from the war a safe retreat: END
BEGIN NOW For, on the right and left, is room to press END
BEGIN NOW The foes at hand, or from afar distress; END
BEGIN NOW To drive 'em headlong downward, and to pour END
BEGIN NOW On their descending backs a stony show'r. END
BEGIN NOW Thither young Turnus took the well-known way, END
BEGIN NOW Possess'd the pass, and in blind ambush lay. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime Latonian Phoebe, from the skies, END
BEGIN NOW Beheld th' approaching war with hateful eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And call'd the light-foot Opis to her aid, END
BEGIN NOW Her most belov'd and ever-trusty maid; END
BEGIN NOW Then with a sigh began: "Camilla goes END
BEGIN NOW To meet her death amidst her fatal foes: END
BEGIN NOW The nymphs I lov'd of all my mortal train, END
BEGIN NOW Invested with Diana's arms, in vain. END
BEGIN NOW Nor is my kindness for the virgin new: END
BEGIN NOW 'T was born with her; and with her years it grew. END
BEGIN NOW Her father Metabus, when forc'd away END
BEGIN NOW From old Privernum, for tyrannic sway, END
BEGIN NOW Snatch'd up, and sav'd from his prevailing foes, END
BEGIN NOW This tender babe, companion of his woes. END
BEGIN NOW Casmilla was her mother; but he drown'd END
BEGIN NOW One hissing letter in a softer sound, END
BEGIN NOW And call'd Camilla. Thro' the woods he flies; END
BEGIN NOW Wrapp'd in his robe the royal infant lies. END
BEGIN NOW His foes in sight, he mends his weary pace; END
BEGIN NOW With shout and clamors they pursue the chase. END
BEGIN NOW The banks of Amasene at length he gains: END
BEGIN NOW The raging flood his farther flight restrains, END
BEGIN NOW Rais'd o'er the borders with unusual rains. END
BEGIN NOW Prepar'd to plunge into the stream, he fears, END
BEGIN NOW Not for himself, but for the charge he bears. END
BEGIN NOW Anxious, he stops a while, and thinks in haste; END
BEGIN NOW Then, desp'rate in distress, resolves at last. END
BEGIN NOW A knotty lance of well-boil'd oak he bore; END
BEGIN NOW The middle part with cork he cover'd o'er: END
BEGIN NOW He clos'd the child within the hollow space; END
BEGIN NOW With twigs of bending osier bound the case; END
BEGIN NOW Then pois'd the spear, heavy with human weight, END
BEGIN NOW And thus invok'd my favor for the freight: END
BEGIN NOW 'Accept, great goddess of the woods,' he said, END
BEGIN NOW 'Sent by her sire, this dedicated maid! END
BEGIN NOW Thro' air she flies a suppliant to thy shrine; END
BEGIN NOW And the first weapons that she knows, are thine.' END
BEGIN NOW He said; and with full force the spear he threw: END
BEGIN NOW Above the sounding waves Camilla flew. END
BEGIN NOW Then, press'd by foes, he stemm'd the stormy tide, END
BEGIN NOW And gain'd, by stress of arms, the farther side. END
BEGIN NOW His fasten'd spear he pull'd from out the ground, END
BEGIN NOW And, victor of his vows, his infant nymph unbound; END
BEGIN NOW Nor, after that, in towns which walls inclose, END
BEGIN NOW Would trust his hunted life amidst his foes; END
BEGIN NOW But, rough, in open air he chose to lie; END
BEGIN NOW Earth was his couch, his cov'ring was the sky. END
BEGIN NOW On hills unshorn, or in a desart den, END
BEGIN NOW He shunn'd the dire society of men. END
BEGIN NOW A shepherd's solitary life he led; END
BEGIN NOW His daughter with the milk of mares he fed. END
BEGIN NOW The dugs of bears, and ev'ry salvage beast, END
BEGIN NOW He drew, and thro' her lips the liquor press'd. END
BEGIN NOW The little Amazon could scarcely go: END
BEGIN NOW He loads her with a quiver and a bow; END
BEGIN NOW And, that she might her stagg'ring steps command, END
BEGIN NOW He with a slender jav'lin fills her hand. END
BEGIN NOW Her flowing hair no golden fillet bound; END
BEGIN NOW Nor swept her trailing robe the dusty ground. END
BEGIN NOW Instead of these, a tiger's hide o'erspread END
BEGIN NOW Her back and shoulders, fasten'd to her head. END
BEGIN NOW The flying dart she first attempts to fling, END
BEGIN NOW And round her tender temples toss'd the sling; END
BEGIN NOW Then, as her strength with years increas'd, began END
BEGIN NOW To pierce aloft in air the soaring swan, END
BEGIN NOW And from the clouds to fetch the heron and the crane. END
BEGIN NOW The Tuscan matrons with each other vied, END
BEGIN NOW To bless their rival sons with such a bride; END
BEGIN NOW But she disdains their love, to share with me END
BEGIN NOW The sylvan shades and vow'd virginity. END
BEGIN NOW And, O! I wish, contented with my cares END
BEGIN NOW Of salvage spoils, she had not sought the wars! END
BEGIN NOW Then had she been of my celestial train, END
BEGIN NOW And shunn'd the fate that dooms her to be slain. END
BEGIN NOW But since, opposing Heav'n's decree, she goes END
BEGIN NOW To find her death among forbidden foes, END
BEGIN NOW Haste with these arms, and take thy steepy flight. END
BEGIN NOW Where, with the gods, averse, the Latins fight. END
BEGIN NOW This bow to thee, this quiver I bequeath, END
BEGIN NOW This chosen arrow, to revenge her death: END
BEGIN NOW By whate'er hand Camilla shall be slain, END
BEGIN NOW Or of the Trojan or Italian train, END
BEGIN NOW Let him not pass unpunish'd from the plain. END
BEGIN NOW Then, in a hollow cloud, myself will aid END
BEGIN NOW To bear the breathless body of my maid: END
BEGIN NOW Unspoil'd shall be her arms, and unprofan'd END
BEGIN NOW Her holy limbs with any human hand, END
BEGIN NOW And in a marble tomb laid in her native land. END
BEGIN NOW She said. The faithful nymph descends from high END
BEGIN NOW With rapid flight, and cuts the sounding sky: END
BEGIN NOW Black clouds and stormy winds around her body fly. END
BEGIN NOW By this, the Trojan and the Tuscan horse, END
BEGIN NOW Drawn up in squadrons, with united force, END
BEGIN NOW Approach the walls: the sprightly coursers bound, END
BEGIN NOW Press forward on their bits, and shift their ground. END
BEGIN NOW Shields, arms, and spears flash horribly from far; END
BEGIN NOW And the fields glitter with a waving war. END
BEGIN NOW Oppos'd to these, come on with furious force END
BEGIN NOW Messapus, Coras, and the Latian horse; END
BEGIN NOW These in the body plac'd, on either hand END
BEGIN NOW Sustain'd and clos'd by fair Camilla's band. END
BEGIN NOW Advancing in a line, they couch their spears; END
BEGIN NOW And less and less the middle space appears. END
BEGIN NOW Thick smoke obscures the field; and scarce are seen END
BEGIN NOW The neighing coursers, and the shouting men. END
BEGIN NOW In distance of their darts they stop their course; END
BEGIN NOW Then man to man they rush, and horse to horse. END
BEGIN NOW The face of heav'n their flying jav'lins hide, END
BEGIN NOW And deaths unseen are dealt on either side. END
BEGIN NOW Tyrrhenus, and Aconteus, void of fear, END
BEGIN NOW By mettled coursers borne in full career, END
BEGIN NOW Meet first oppos'd; and, with a mighty shock, END
BEGIN NOW Their horses' heads against each other knock. END
BEGIN NOW Far from his steed is fierce Aconteus cast, END
BEGIN NOW As with an engine's force, or lightning's blast: END
BEGIN NOW He rolls along in blood, and breathes his last. END
BEGIN NOW The Latin squadrons take a sudden fright, END
BEGIN NOW And sling their shields behind, to save their backs in flight END
BEGIN NOW Spurring at speed to their own walls they drew; END
BEGIN NOW Close in the rear the Tuscan troops pursue, END
BEGIN NOW And urge their flight: Asylas leads the chase; END
BEGIN NOW Till, seiz'd, with shame, they wheel about and face, END
BEGIN NOW Receive their foes, and raise a threat'ning cry. END
BEGIN NOW The Tuscans take their turn to fear and fly. END
BEGIN NOW So swelling surges, with a thund'ring roar, END
BEGIN NOW Driv'n on each other's backs, insult the shore, END
BEGIN NOW Bound o'er the rocks, incroach upon the land, END
BEGIN NOW And far upon the beach eject the sand; END
BEGIN NOW Then backward, with a swing, they take their way, END
BEGIN NOW Repuls'd from upper ground, and seek their mother sea; END
BEGIN NOW With equal hurry quit th' invaded shore, END
BEGIN NOW And swallow back the sand and stones they spew'd before. END
BEGIN NOW Twice were the Tuscans masters of the field, END
BEGIN NOW Twice by the Latins, in their turn, repell'd. END
BEGIN NOW Asham'd at length, to the third charge they ran; END
BEGIN NOW Both hosts resolv'd, and mingled man to man. END
BEGIN NOW Now dying groans are heard; the fields are strow'd END
BEGIN NOW With falling bodies, and are drunk with blood. END
BEGIN NOW Arms, horses, men, on heaps together lie: END
BEGIN NOW Confus'd the fight, and more confus'd the cry. END
BEGIN NOW Orsilochus, who durst not press too near END
BEGIN NOW Strong Remulus, at distance drove his spear, END
BEGIN NOW And stuck the steel beneath his horse's ear. END
BEGIN NOW The fiery steed, impatient of the wound, END
BEGIN NOW Curvets, and, springing upward with a bound, END
BEGIN NOW His helpless lord cast backward on the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Catillus pierc'd Iolas first; then drew END
BEGIN NOW His reeking lance, and at Herminius threw, END
BEGIN NOW The mighty champion of the Tuscan crew. END
BEGIN NOW His neck and throat unarm'd, his head was bare, END
BEGIN NOW But shaded with a length of yellow hair: END
BEGIN NOW Secure, he fought, expos'd on ev'ry part, END
BEGIN NOW A spacious mark for swords, and for the flying dart. END
BEGIN NOW Across the shoulders came the feather'd wound; END
BEGIN NOW Transfix'd he fell, and doubled to the ground. END
BEGIN NOW The sands with streaming blood are sanguine dyed, END
BEGIN NOW And death with honor sought on either side. END
BEGIN NOW Resistless thro' the war Camilla rode, END
BEGIN NOW In danger unappall'd, and pleas'd with blood. END
BEGIN NOW One side was bare for her exerted breast; END
BEGIN NOW One shoulder with her painted quiver press'd. END
BEGIN NOW Now from afar her fatal jav'lins play; END
BEGIN NOW Now with her ax's edge she hews her way: END
BEGIN NOW Diana's arms upon her shoulder sound; END
BEGIN NOW And when, too closely press'd, she quits the ground, END
BEGIN NOW From her bent bow she sends a backward wound. END
BEGIN NOW Her maids, in martial pomp, on either side, END
BEGIN NOW Larina, Tulla, fierce Tarpeia, ride: END
BEGIN NOW Italians all; in peace, their queen's delight; END
BEGIN NOW In war, the bold companions of the fight. END
BEGIN NOW So march'd the Tracian Amazons of old, END
BEGIN NOW When Thermodon with bloody billows roll'd: END
BEGIN NOW Such troops as these in shining arms were seen, END
BEGIN NOW When Theseus met in fight their maiden queen: END
BEGIN NOW Such to the field Penthisilea led, END
BEGIN NOW From the fierce virgin when the Grecians fled; END
BEGIN NOW With such, return'd triumphant from the war, END
BEGIN NOW Her maids with cries attend the lofty car; END
BEGIN NOW They clash with manly force their moony shields; END
BEGIN NOW With female shouts resound the Phrygian fields. END
BEGIN NOW Who foremost, and who last, heroic maid, END
BEGIN NOW On the cold earth were by thy courage laid? END
BEGIN NOW Thy spear, of mountain ash, Eumenius first, END
BEGIN NOW With fury driv'n, from side to side transpierc'd: END
BEGIN NOW A purple stream came spouting from the wound; END
BEGIN NOW Bath'd in his blood he lies, and bites the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Liris and Pegasus at once she slew: END
BEGIN NOW The former, as the slacken'd reins he drew END
BEGIN NOW Of his faint steed; the latter, as he stretch'd END
BEGIN NOW His arm to prop his friend, the jav'lin reach'd. END
BEGIN NOW By the same weapon, sent from the same hand, END
BEGIN NOW Both fall together, and both spurn the sand. END
BEGIN NOW Amastrus next is added to the slain: END
BEGIN NOW The rest in rout she follows o'er the plain: END
BEGIN NOW And Chromis, at full speed her fury shun. END
BEGIN NOW Of all her deadly darts, not one she lost; END
BEGIN NOW Each was attended with a Trojan ghost. END
BEGIN NOW Young Ornithus bestrode a hunter steed, END
BEGIN NOW Swift for the chase, and of Apulian breed. END
BEGIN NOW Him from afar she spied, in arms unknown: END
BEGIN NOW O'er his broad back an ox's hide was thrown; END
BEGIN NOW His helm a wolf, whose gaping jaws were spread END
BEGIN NOW A cov'ring for his cheeks, and grinn'd around his head, END
BEGIN NOW He clench'd within his hand an iron prong, END
BEGIN NOW And tower'd above the rest, conspicuous in the throng. END
BEGIN NOW Him soon she singled from the flying train, END
BEGIN NOW And slew with ease; then thus insults the slain: END
BEGIN NOW Vain hunter, didst thou think thro' woods to chase END
BEGIN NOW The savage herd, a vile and trembling race? END
BEGIN NOW Here cease thy vaunts, and own my victory: END
BEGIN NOW A woman warrior was too strong for thee. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, if the ghosts demand the conqu'ror's name, END
BEGIN NOW Confessing great Camilla, save thy shame. END
BEGIN NOW Then Butes and Orsilochus she slew, END
BEGIN NOW The bulkiest bodies of the Trojan crew; END
BEGIN NOW But Butes breast to breast: the spear descends END
BEGIN NOW Above the gorget, where his helmet ends, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er the shield which his left side defends. END
BEGIN NOW Orsilochus and she their courses ply: END
BEGIN NOW He seems to follow, and she seems to fly; END
BEGIN NOW But in a narrower ring she makes the race; END
BEGIN NOW And then he flies, and she pursues the chase. END
BEGIN NOW Gath'ring at length on her deluded foe, END
BEGIN NOW She swings her ax, and rises to the blow END
BEGIN NOW Full on the helm behind, with such a sway END
BEGIN NOW The weapon falls, the riven steel gives way: END
BEGIN NOW He groans, he roars, he sues in vain for grace; END
BEGIN NOW Brains, mingled with his blood, besmear his face. END
BEGIN NOW Astonish'd Aunus just arrives by chance, END
BEGIN NOW To see his fall; nor farther dares advance; END
BEGIN NOW But, fixing on the horrid maid his eye, END
BEGIN NOW He stares, and shakes, and finds it vain to fly; END
BEGIN NOW Yet, like a true Ligurian, born to cheat, END
BEGIN NOW (At least while fortune favor'd his deceit,) END
BEGIN NOW Cries out aloud: "What courage have you shown, END
BEGIN NOW Who trust your courser's strength, and not your own? END
BEGIN NOW Forego the vantage of your horse, alight, END
BEGIN NOW And then on equal terms begin the fight: END
BEGIN NOW It shall be seen, weak woman, what you can, END
BEGIN NOW When, foot to foot, you combat with a man, END
BEGIN NOW He said. She glows with anger and disdain, END
BEGIN NOW Dismounts with speed to dare him on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW And leaves her horse at large among her train; END
BEGIN NOW With her drawn sword defies him to the field, END
BEGIN NOW And, marching, lifts aloft her maiden shield. END
BEGIN NOW The youth, who thought his cunning did succeed, END
BEGIN NOW Reins round his horse, and urges all his speed; END
BEGIN NOW Adds the remembrance of the spur, and hides END
BEGIN NOW The goring rowels in his bleeding sides. END
BEGIN NOW Vain fool, and coward!" cries the lofty maid, END
BEGIN NOW Caught in the train which thou thyself hast laid! END
BEGIN NOW On others practice thy Ligurian arts; END
BEGIN NOW Thin stratagems and tricks of little hearts END
BEGIN NOW Are lost on me: nor shalt thou safe retire, END
BEGIN NOW With vaunting lies, to thy fallacious sire. END
BEGIN NOW At this, so fast her flying feet she sped, END
BEGIN NOW That soon she strain'd beyond his horse's head: END
BEGIN NOW Then turning short, at once she seiz'd the rein, END
BEGIN NOW And laid the boaster grov'ling on the plain. END
BEGIN NOW Not with more ease the falcon, from above, END
BEGIN NOW Trusses in middle air the trembling dove, END
BEGIN NOW Then plumes the prey, in her strong pounces bound: END
BEGIN NOW The feathers, foul with blood, come tumbling to the ground. END
BEGIN NOW Now mighty Jove, from his superior height, END
BEGIN NOW With his broad eye surveys th' unequal fight. END
BEGIN NOW He fires the breast of Tarchon with disdain, END
BEGIN NOW And sends him to redeem th' abandon'd plain. END
BEGIN NOW Betwixt the broken ranks the Tuscan rides, END
BEGIN NOW And these encourages, and those he chides; END
BEGIN NOW Recalls each leader, by his name, from flight; END
BEGIN NOW Renews their ardor, and restores the fight. END
BEGIN NOW What panic fear has seiz'd your souls? O shame, END
BEGIN NOW O brand perpetual of th' Etrurian name! END
BEGIN NOW Cowards incurable, a woman's hand END
BEGIN NOW Drives, breaks, and scatters your ignoble band! END
BEGIN NOW Now cast away the sword, and quit the shield! END
BEGIN NOW What use of weapons which you dare not wield? END
BEGIN NOW Not thus you fly your female foes by night, END
BEGIN NOW Nor shun the feast, when the full bowls invite; END
BEGIN NOW When to fat off'rings the glad augur calls, END
BEGIN NOW And the shrill hornpipe sounds to bacchanals. END
BEGIN NOW These are your studied cares, your lewd delight: END
BEGIN NOW Swift to debauch, but slow to manly fight. END
BEGIN NOW Thus having said, he spurs amid the foes, END
BEGIN NOW Not managing the life he meant to lose. END
BEGIN NOW The first he found he seiz'd with headlong haste, END
BEGIN NOW In his strong gripe, and clasp'd around the waist; END
BEGIN NOW 'T was Venulus, whom from his horse he tore, END
BEGIN NOW And, laid athwart his own, in triumph bore. END
BEGIN NOW Loud shouts ensue; the Latins turn their eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And view th' unusual sight with vast surprise. END
BEGIN NOW The fiery Tarchon, flying o'er the plains, END
BEGIN NOW Press'd in his arms the pond'rous prey sustains; END
BEGIN NOW Then, with his shorten'd spear, explores around END
BEGIN NOW His jointed arms, to fix a deadly wound. END
BEGIN NOW Nor less the captive struggles for his life: END
BEGIN NOW He writhes his body to prolong the strife, END
BEGIN NOW And, fencing for his naked throat, exerts END
BEGIN NOW His utmost vigor, and the point averts. END
BEGIN NOW So stoops the yellow eagle from on high, END
BEGIN NOW And bears a speckled serpent thro' the sky, END
BEGIN NOW Fast'ning his crooked talons on the prey: END
BEGIN NOW The pris'ner hisses thro' the liquid way; END
BEGIN NOW Resists the royal hawk; and, tho' oppress'd, END
BEGIN NOW She fights in volumes, and erects her crest: END
BEGIN NOW Turn'd to her foe, she stiffens ev'ry scale, END
BEGIN NOW And shoots her forky tongue, and whisks her threat'ning tail. END
BEGIN NOW Against the victor, all defense is weak: END
BEGIN NOW Th' imperial bird still plies her with his beak; END
BEGIN NOW He tears her bowels, and her breast he gores; END
BEGIN NOW Then claps his pinions, and securely soars. END
BEGIN NOW Thus, thro' the midst of circling enemies, END
BEGIN NOW Strong Tarchon snatch'd and bore away his prize. END
BEGIN NOW The Tyrrhene troops, that shrunk before, now press END
BEGIN NOW The Latins, and presume the like success. END
BEGIN NOW Then Aruns, doom'd to death, his arts assay'd, END
BEGIN NOW To murther, unespied, the Volscian maid: END
BEGIN NOW This way and that his winding course he bends, END
BEGIN NOW And, whereso'er she turns, her steps attends. END
BEGIN NOW When she retires victorious from the chase, END
BEGIN NOW He wheels about with care, and shifts his place; END
BEGIN NOW When, rushing on, she seeks her foes flight, END
BEGIN NOW He keeps aloof, but keeps her still in sight: END
BEGIN NOW He threats, and trembles, trying ev'ry way, END
BEGIN NOW Unseen to kill, and safely to betray. END
BEGIN NOW Chloreus, the priest of Cybele, from far, END
BEGIN NOW Glitt'ring in Phrygian arms amidst the war, END
BEGIN NOW Was by the virgin view'd. The steed he press'd END
BEGIN NOW Was proud with trappings, and his brawny chest END
BEGIN NOW With scales of gilded brass was cover'd o'er; END
BEGIN NOW A robe of Tyrian dye the rider wore. END
BEGIN NOW With deadly wounds he gall'd the distant foe; END
BEGIN NOW Gnossian his shafts, and Lycian was his bow: END
BEGIN NOW A golden helm his front and head surrounds END
BEGIN NOW A gilded quiver from his shoulder sounds. END
BEGIN NOW Gold, weav'd with linen, on his thighs he wore, END
BEGIN NOW With flowers of needlework distinguish'd o'er, END
BEGIN NOW With golden buckles bound, and gather'd up before. END
BEGIN NOW Him the fierce maid beheld with ardent eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Fond and ambitious of so rich a prize, END
BEGIN NOW Or that the temple might his trophies hold, END
BEGIN NOW Or else to shine herself in Trojan gold. END
BEGIN NOW Blind in her haste, she chases him alone. END
BEGIN NOW And seeks his life, regardless of her own. END
BEGIN NOW This lucky moment the sly traitor chose: END
BEGIN NOW Then, starting from his ambush, up he rose, END
BEGIN NOW And threw, but first to Heav'n address'd his vows: END
BEGIN NOW O patron of Socrates' high abodes, END
BEGIN NOW Phoebus, the ruling pow'r among the gods, END
BEGIN NOW Whom first we serve, whole woods of unctuous pine END
BEGIN NOW Are fell'd for thee, and to thy glory shine; END
BEGIN NOW By thee protected with our naked soles, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' flames unsing'd we march, and tread the kindled coals END
BEGIN NOW Give me, propitious pow'r, to wash away END
BEGIN NOW The stains of this dishonorable day: END
BEGIN NOW Nor spoils, nor triumph, from the fact I claim, END
BEGIN NOW But with my future actions trust my fame. END
BEGIN NOW Let me, by stealth, this female plague o'ercome, END
BEGIN NOW And from the field return inglorious home. END
BEGIN NOW Apollo heard, and, granting half his pray'r, END
BEGIN NOW Shuffled in winds the rest, and toss'd in empty air. END
BEGIN NOW He gives the death desir'd; his safe return END
BEGIN NOW By southern tempests to the seas is borne. END
BEGIN NOW Now, when the jav'lin whizz'd along the skies, END
BEGIN NOW Both armies on Camilla turn'd their eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Directed by the sound. Of either host, END
BEGIN NOW Th' unhappy virgin, tho' concern'd the most, END
BEGIN NOW Was only deaf; so greedy was she bent END
BEGIN NOW On golden spoils, and on her prey intent; END
BEGIN NOW Till in her pap the winged weapon stood END
BEGIN NOW Infix'd, and deeply drunk the purple blood. END
BEGIN NOW Her sad attendants hasten to sustain END
BEGIN NOW Their dying lady, drooping on the plain. END
BEGIN NOW Far from their sight the trembling Aruns flies, END
BEGIN NOW With beating heart, and fear confus'd with joys; END
BEGIN NOW Nor dares he farther to pursue his blow, END
BEGIN NOW Or ev'n to bear the sight of his expiring foe. END
BEGIN NOW As, when the wolf has torn a bullock's hide END
BEGIN NOW At unawares, or ranch'd a shepherd's side, END
BEGIN NOW Conscious of his audacious deed, he flies, END
BEGIN NOW And claps his quiv'ring tail between his thighs: END
BEGIN NOW So, speeding once, the wretch no more attends, END
BEGIN NOW But, spurring forward, herds among his friends. END
BEGIN NOW She wrench'd the jav'lin with her dying hands, END
BEGIN NOW But wedg'd within her breast the weapon stands; END
BEGIN NOW The wood she draws, the steely point remains; END
BEGIN NOW She staggers in her seat with agonizing pains: END
BEGIN NOW (A gath'ring mist o'erclouds her cheerful eyes, END
BEGIN NOW And from her cheeks the rosy color flies:) END
BEGIN NOW Then turns to her, whom of her female train END
BEGIN NOW She trusted most, and thus she speaks with pain: END
BEGIN NOW Acca, 't is past! he swims before my sight, END
BEGIN NOW Inexorable Death; and claims his right. END
BEGIN NOW Bear my last words to Turnus; fly with speed, END
BEGIN NOW And bid him timely to my charge succeed, END
BEGIN NOW Repel the Trojans, and the town relieve: END
BEGIN NOW Farewell! and in this kiss my parting breath receive. END
BEGIN NOW She said, and, sliding, sunk upon the plain: END
BEGIN NOW Dying, her open'd hand forsakes the rein; END
BEGIN NOW Short, and more short, she pants; by slow degrees END
BEGIN NOW Her mind the passage from her body frees. END
BEGIN NOW She drops her sword; she nods her plumy crest, END
BEGIN NOW Her drooping head declining on her breast: END
BEGIN NOW In the last sigh her struggling soul expires, END
BEGIN NOW And, murm'ring with disdain, to Stygian sounds retires. END
BEGIN NOW A shout, that struck the golden stars, ensued; END
BEGIN NOW Despair and rage the languish'd fight renew'd. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan troops and Tuscans, in a line, END
BEGIN NOW Advance to charge; the mix'd Arcadians join. END
BEGIN NOW But Cynthia's maid, high seated, from afar END
BEGIN NOW Surveys the field, and fortune of the war, END
BEGIN NOW Unmov'd a while, till, prostrate on the plain, END
BEGIN NOW Welt'ring in blood, she sees Camilla slain, END
BEGIN NOW And, round her corpse, of friends and foes a fighting train. END
BEGIN NOW Then, from the bottom of her breast, she drew END
BEGIN NOW A mournful sigh, and these sad words ensue: END
BEGIN NOW Too dear a fine, ah much lamented maid, END
BEGIN NOW For warring with the Trojans, thou hast paid! END
BEGIN NOW Nor aught avail'd, in this unhappy strife, END
BEGIN NOW Diana's sacred arms, to save thy life. END
BEGIN NOW Yet unreveng'd thy goddess will not leave END
BEGIN NOW Her vot'ry's death, nor; with vain sorrow grieve. END
BEGIN NOW Branded the wretch, and be his name abhorr'd; END
BEGIN NOW But after ages shall thy praise record. END
BEGIN NOW Th' inglorious coward soon shall press the plain: END
BEGIN NOW Thus vows thy queen, and thus the Fates ordain. END
BEGIN NOW High o'er the field there stood a hilly mound, END
BEGIN NOW Sacred the place, and spread with oaks around, END
BEGIN NOW Where, in a marble tomb, Dercennus lay, END
BEGIN NOW A king that once in Latium bore the sway. END
BEGIN NOW The beauteous Opis thither bent her flight, END
BEGIN NOW To mark the traitor Aruns from the height. END
BEGIN NOW Him in refulgent arms she soon espied, END
BEGIN NOW Swoln with success; and loudly thus she cried: END
BEGIN NOW Thy backward steps, vain boaster, are too late; END
BEGIN NOW Turn like a man, at length, and meet thy fate. END
BEGIN NOW Charg'd with my message, to Camilla go, END
BEGIN NOW And say I sent thee to the shades below, END
BEGIN NOW An honor undeserv'd from Cynthia's bow. END
BEGIN NOW She said, and from her quiver chose with speed END
BEGIN NOW The winged shaft, predestin'd for the deed; END
BEGIN NOW Then to the stubborn yew her strength applied, END
BEGIN NOW Till the far distant horns approach'd on either side. END
BEGIN NOW The bowstring touch'd her breast, so strong she drew; END
BEGIN NOW Whizzing in air the fatal arrow flew. END
BEGIN NOW At once the twanging bow and sounding dart END
BEGIN NOW The traitor heard, and felt the point within his heart. END
BEGIN NOW Him, beating with his heels in pangs of death, END
BEGIN NOW His flying friends to foreign fields bequeath. END
BEGIN NOW The conqu'ring damsel, with expanded wings, END
BEGIN NOW The welcome message to her mistress brings. END
BEGIN NOW Their leader lost, the Volscians quit the field, END
BEGIN NOW And, unsustain'd, the chiefs of Turnus yield. END
BEGIN NOW The frighted soldiers, when their captains fly, END
BEGIN NOW More on their speed than on their strength rely. END
BEGIN NOW Confus'd in flight, they bear each other down, END
BEGIN NOW And spur their horses headlong to the town. END
BEGIN NOW Driv'n by their foes, and to their fears resign'd, END
BEGIN NOW Not once they turn, but take their wounds behind. END
BEGIN NOW These drop the shield, and those the lance forego, END
BEGIN NOW Or on their shoulders bear the slacken'd bow. END
BEGIN NOW The hoofs of horses, with a rattling sound, END
BEGIN NOW Beat short and thick, and shake the rotten ground. END
BEGIN NOW Black clouds of dust come rolling in the sky, END
BEGIN NOW And o'er the darken'd walls and rampires fly. END
BEGIN NOW The trembling matrons, from their lofty stands, END
BEGIN NOW Rend heav'n with female shrieks, and wring their hands. END
BEGIN NOW All pressing on, pursuers and pursued, END
BEGIN NOW Are crush'd in crowds, a mingled multitude. END
BEGIN NOW Some happy few escape: the throng too late END
BEGIN NOW Rush on for entrance, till they choke the gate. END
BEGIN NOW Ev'n in the sight of home, the wretched sire END
BEGIN NOW Looks on, and sees his helpless son expire. END
BEGIN NOW Then, in a fright, the folding gates they close, END
BEGIN NOW But leave their friends excluded with their foes. END
BEGIN NOW The vanquish'd cry; the victors loudly shout; END
BEGIN NOW 'T is terror all within, and slaughter all without. END
BEGIN NOW Blind in their fear, they bounce against the wall, END
BEGIN NOW Or, to the moats pursued, precipitate their fall. END
BEGIN NOW The Latian virgins, valiant with despair, END
BEGIN NOW Arm'd on the tow'rs, the common danger share: END
BEGIN NOW So much of zeal their country's cause inspir'd; END
BEGIN NOW So much Camilla's great example fir'd. END
BEGIN NOW Poles, sharpen'd in the flames, from high they throw, END
BEGIN NOW With imitated darts, to gall the foe. END
BEGIN NOW Their lives for godlike freedom they bequeath, END
BEGIN NOW And crowd each other to be first in death. END
BEGIN NOW Meantime to Turnus, ambush'd in the shade, END
BEGIN NOW With heavy tidings came th' unhappy maid: END
BEGIN NOW The Volscians overthrown, Camilla kill'd; END
BEGIN NOW The foes, entirely masters of the field, END
BEGIN NOW Like a resistless flood, come rolling on: END
BEGIN NOW The cry goes off the plain, and thickens to the town. END
BEGIN NOW Inflam'd with rage, (for so the Furies fire END
BEGIN NOW The Daunian's breast, and so the Fates require,) END
BEGIN NOW He leaves the hilly pass, the woods in vain END
BEGIN NOW Possess'd, and downward issues on the plain. END
BEGIN NOW Scarce was he gone, when to the straits, now freed END
BEGIN NOW From secret foes, the Trojan troops succeed. END
BEGIN NOW Thro' the black forest and the ferny brake, END
BEGIN NOW Unknowingly secure, their way they take; END
BEGIN NOW From the rough mountains to the plain descend, END
BEGIN NOW And there, in order drawn, their line extend. END
BEGIN NOW Both armies now in open fields are seen; END
BEGIN NOW Nor far the distance of the space between. END
BEGIN NOW Both to the city bend. Aeneas sees, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' smoking fields, his hast'ning enemies; END
BEGIN NOW And Turnus views the Trojans in array, END
BEGIN NOW And hears th' approaching horses proudly neigh. END
BEGIN NOW Soon had their hosts in bloody battle join'd; END
BEGIN NOW But westward to the sea the sun declin'd. END
BEGIN NOW Intrench'd before the town both armies lie, END
BEGIN NOW While Night with sable wings involves the sky. END
BEGIN NOW When Turnus saw the Latins leave the field, END
BEGIN NOW Their armies broken, and their courage quell'd, END
BEGIN NOW Himself become the mark of public spite, END
BEGIN NOW His honor question'd for the promis'd fight; END
BEGIN NOW The more he was with vulgar hate oppress'd, END
BEGIN NOW The more his fury boil'd within his breast: END
BEGIN NOW He rous'd his vigor for the last debate, END
BEGIN NOW And rais'd his haughty soul to meet his fate. END
BEGIN NOW As, when the swains the Libyan lion chase, END
BEGIN NOW He makes a sour retreat, nor mends his pace; END
BEGIN NOW But, if the pointed jav'lin pierce his side, END
BEGIN NOW The lordly beast returns with double pride: END
BEGIN NOW He wrenches out the steel, he roars for pain; END
BEGIN NOW His sides he lashes, and erects his mane: END
BEGIN NOW So Turnus fares; his eyeballs flash with fire, END
BEGIN NOW Thro' his wide nostrils clouds of smoke expire. END
BEGIN NOW Trembling with rage, around the court he ran, END
BEGIN NOW At length approach'd the king, and thus began: END
BEGIN NOW No more excuses or delays: I stand END
BEGIN NOW In arms prepar'd to combat, hand to hand, END
BEGIN NOW This base deserter of his native land. END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan, by his word, is bound to take END
BEGIN NOW The same conditions which himself did make. END
BEGIN NOW Renew the truce; the solemn rites prepare, END
BEGIN NOW And to my single virtue trust the war. END
BEGIN NOW The Latians unconcern'd shall see the fight; END
BEGIN NOW This arm unaided shall assert your right: END
BEGIN NOW Then, if my prostrate body press the plain, END
BEGIN NOW To him the crown and beauteous bride remain. END
BEGIN NOW To whom the king sedately thus replied: END
BEGIN NOW Brave youth, the more your valor has been tried, END
BEGIN NOW The more becomes it us, with due respect, END
BEGIN NOW To weigh the chance of war, which you neglect. END
BEGIN NOW You want not wealth, or a successive throne, END
BEGIN NOW Or cities which your arms have made your own: END
BEGIN NOW My towns and treasures are at your command, END
BEGIN NOW And stor'd with blooming beauties is my land; END
BEGIN NOW Laurentum more than one Lavinia sees, END
BEGIN NOW Unmarried, fair, of noble families. END
BEGIN NOW Now let me speak, and you with patience hear, END
BEGIN NOW Things which perhaps may grate a lover's ear, END
BEGIN NOW But sound advice, proceeding from a heart END
BEGIN NOW Sincerely yours, and free from fraudful art. END
BEGIN NOW The gods, by signs, have manifestly shown, END
BEGIN NOW No prince Italian born should heir my throne: END
BEGIN NOW Oft have our augurs, in prediction skill'd, END
BEGIN NOW And oft our priests, foreign son reveal'd. END
BEGIN NOW Yet, won by worth that cannot be withstood, END
BEGIN NOW Brib'd by my kindness to my kindred blood, END
BEGIN NOW Urg'd by my wife, who would not be denied, END
BEGIN NOW I promis'd my Lavinia for your bride: END
BEGIN NOW Her from her plighted lord by force I took; END
BEGIN NOW All ties of treaties, and of honor, broke: END
BEGIN NOW On your account I wag'd an impious war- END
BEGIN NOW With what success, 't is needless to declare; END
BEGIN NOW I and my subjects feel, and you have had your share. END
BEGIN NOW Twice vanquish'd while in bloody fields we strive, END
BEGIN NOW Scarce in our walls we keep our hopes alive: END
BEGIN NOW The rolling flood runs warm with human gore; END
BEGIN NOW The bones of Latians blanch the neighb'ring shore. END
BEGIN NOW Why put I not an end to this debate, END
BEGIN NOW Still unresolv'd, and still a slave to fate? END
BEGIN NOW If Turnus' death a lasting peace can give, END
BEGIN NOW Why should I not procure it whilst you live? END
BEGIN NOW Should I to doubtful arms your youth betray, END
BEGIN NOW What would my kinsmen the Rutulians say? END
BEGIN NOW And, should you fall in fight, (which Heav'n defend!) END
BEGIN NOW How curse the cause which hasten'd to his end END
BEGIN NOW The daughter's lover and the father's friend? END
BEGIN NOW Weigh in your mind the various chance of war; END
BEGIN NOW Pity your parent's age, and ease his care. END
BEGIN NOW Such balmy words he pour'd, but all in vain: END
BEGIN NOW The proffer'd med'cine but provok'd the pain. END
BEGIN NOW The wrathful youth, disdaining the relief, END
BEGIN NOW With intermitting sobs thus vents his grief: END
BEGIN NOW The care, O best of fathers, which you take END
BEGIN NOW For my concerns, at my desire forsake. END
BEGIN NOW Permit me not to languish out my days, END
BEGIN NOW But make the best exchange of life for praise. END
BEGIN NOW This arm, this lance, can well dispute the prize; END
BEGIN NOW And the blood follows, where the weapon flies. END
BEGIN NOW His goddess mother is not near, to shroud END
BEGIN NOW The flying coward with an empty cloud. END
BEGIN NOW But now the queen, who fear'd for Turnus' life, END
BEGIN NOW And loath'd the hard conditions of the strife, END
BEGIN NOW Held him by force; and, dying in his death, END
BEGIN NOW In these sad accents gave her sorrow breath: END
BEGIN NOW O Turnus, I adjure thee by these tears, END
BEGIN NOW And whate'er price Amata's honor bears END
BEGIN NOW Within thy breast, since thou art all my hope, END
BEGIN NOW My sickly mind's repose, my sinking age's prop; END
BEGIN NOW Since on the safety of thy life alone END
BEGIN NOW Depends Latinus, and the Latian throne: END
BEGIN NOW Refuse me not this one, this only pray'r, END
BEGIN NOW To waive the combat, and pursue the war. END
BEGIN NOW Whatever chance attends this fatal strife, END
BEGIN NOW Think it includes, in thine, Amata's life. END
BEGIN NOW I cannot live a slave, or see my throne END
BEGIN NOW Usurp'd by strangers or a Trojan son. END
BEGIN NOW At this, a flood of tears Lavinia shed; END
BEGIN NOW A crimson blush her beauteous face o'erspread, END
BEGIN NOW Varying her cheeks by turns with white and red. END
BEGIN NOW The driving colors, never at a stay, END
BEGIN NOW Run here and there, and flush, and fade away. END
BEGIN NOW Delightful change! Thus Indian iv'ry shows, END
BEGIN NOW Which with the bord'ring paint of purple glows; END
BEGIN NOW Or lilies damask'd by the neighb'ring rose. END
BEGIN NOW The lover gaz'd, and, burning with desire, END
BEGIN NOW The more he look'd, the more he fed the fire: END
BEGIN NOW Revenge, and jealous rage, and secret spite, END
BEGIN NOW Roll in his breast, and rouse him to the fight. END
BEGIN NOW Then fixing on the queen his ardent eyes, END
BEGIN NOW Firm to his first intent, he thus replies: END
BEGIN NOW O mother, do not by your tears prepare END
BEGIN NOW Such boding omens, and prejudge the war. END
BEGIN NOW Resolv'd on fight, I am no longer free END
BEGIN NOW To shun my death, if Heav'n my death decree. END
BEGIN NOW Then turning to the herald, thus pursues: END
BEGIN NOW Go, greet the Trojan with ungrateful news; END
BEGIN NOW Denounce from me, that, when to-morrow's light END
BEGIN NOW Shall gild the heav'ns, he need not urge the fight; END
BEGIN NOW The Trojan and Rutulian troops no more END
BEGIN NOW Shall dye, with mutual blood, the Latian shore: END
BEGIN NOW Our single swords the quarrel shall decide, END
BEGIN NOW And to the victor be the beauteous bride. END
BEGIN NOW He said, and striding on, with speedy pace, END
BEGIN NOW He sought his coursers of the Thracian race. END
BEGIN NOW At his approach they toss their heads on high, END
BEGIN NOW And, proudly neighing, promise victory. END
BEGIN NOW The sires of these Orythia sent from far, END
BEGIN NOW To grace Pilumnus, when he went to war. END
BEGIN NOW The drifts of Thracian snows were scarce so white, END
BEGIN NOW Nor northern winds in fleetness match'd their flight. END
BEGIN NOW Officious grooms stand ready by his side; END
BEGIN NOW And some with combs their flowing manes divide, END
BEGIN NOW And others stroke their chests and gently soothe their pride. END
BEGIN NOW He sheath'd his limbs in arms; a temper'd mass END
BEGIN NOW Of golden metal those, and mountain brass. END
BEGIN NOW Then to his head his glitt'ring helm he tied, END
BEGIN NOW And girt his faithful fauchion to his side. END
BEGIN NOW In his Aetnaean forge, the God of Fire END
BEGIN NOW That fauchion labor'd for the hero's sire; END
BEGIN NOW Immortal keenness on the blade bestow'd, END
BEGIN NOW And plung'd it hissing in the Stygian flood. END
BEGIN NOW Propp'd on a pillar, which the ceiling bore, END
BEGIN NOW Was plac'd the lance Auruncan Actor wore; END
BEGIN NOW Which with such force he brandish'd in his hand, END
BEGIN NOW The tough ash trembled like an osier wand: END
BEGIN NOW Then cried: "O pond'rous spoil of Actor slain, END
BEGIN NOW And never yet by Turnus toss'd in vain, END
BEGIN NOW Fail not this day thy wonted force; but go, END
BEGIN NOW Sent by this hand, to pierce the Trojan foe! END
BEGIN NOW Give me to tear his corslet from his breast, END
BEGIN NOW And from that eunuch head to rend the crest; END
BEGIN NOW Dragg'd in the dust, his frizzled hair to soil, END
BEGIN NOW Hot from the vexing ir'n, and smear'd with fragrant oil! END
BEGIN NOW Thus while he raves, from his wide nostrils flies END
BEGIN NOW A fiery steam, and sparkles from his eyes. END
BEGIN NOW So fares the bull in his lov'd female's sight: END
BEGIN NOW Proudly he bellows, and preludes the fight; END
BEGIN NOW He tries his goring horns against a tree, END
BEGIN NOW And meditates his absent enemy; END
BEGIN NOW He pushes at the winds; he digs the strand END
BEGIN NOW With his black hoofs, and spurns the yellow sand. END
BEGIN NOW Nor less the Trojan, in his Lemnian arms, END
BEGIN NOW To future fight his manly courage warms: END
BEGIN NOW He whets his fury, and with joy prepares END
BEGIN NOW To terminate at once the ling'ring wars; END
BEGIN NOW To cheer his chiefs and tender son, relates END
BEGIN NOW What Heav'n had promis'd, and expounds the fates. END
BEGIN NOW Then to the Latian king he sends, to cease END
BEGIN NOW The rage of arms, and ratify the peace. END
BEGIN NOW The morn ensuing, from the mountain's height, END
BEGIN NOW Had scarcely spread the skies with rosy light; END
BEGIN NOW Th' ethereal coursers, bounding from the sea, END
BEGIN NOW From out their flaming nostrils breath'd the day; END
BEGIN NOW When now the Trojan and Rutulian guard, END
BEGIN NOW In friendly labor join'd, the list prepar'd. END
